INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('catapult', '[\'kætəpʌlt]', 'n.弹弩；发射机 v.发射', '1. The boy surrendered the catapult to the teacher. 那孩子把弹弓交给了老师。 2. The child broke his neighbor\'s window with a catapult. 这孩子用绷弓子打碎了邻居家的玻璃。 3. The catapult shot hundred-pound rocks at the enemy. 弩炮向敌人发射了上百磅石块。 4. In the crash the driver (was) catapulted through the windscreen. 在事故中司机从挡风玻璃中(被)弹了出来。', '过去式: catapulted 过去分词: catapulted 现在分词: catapulting 第三人称单数: catapults');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plenary', '[\'pliːnəri]', 'adj.充分的；完全的；全体出席的 n.全体会议', '1. He is a diplomat with plenary powers. 他是一位具有极权的外交家。 2. He was given plenary powers to negotiate with the rebels. 在同反叛者谈判时，他被授予绝对的权利。 3. They will hold a plenary session next week. 下周他们将召开全体会议。 4. I\'ll be at the plenary session of the conference. 我将出席大会的全体会议。 5. A children\'s choir sings during the opening plenary. 一个儿童合唱团在开幕式全会中演唱。', '副词: plenarily 名词: plenariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ensconce', '[ɪn\'skɑːns]', 'v.安顿下来；安置；隐藏', '1. We have ensconce ourselves in the most beautiful villa in the south of france. 我们在法国南部最美丽的别墅里安顿下来。 2. It makes use of peculiar UV coating way to ensconce the color inside the lens. 它是利用UV特殊涂料方式将镜片的颜色藏在镜片里面的方式生产的。 3. to ensconce oneself in an armchair 使自己安坐在扶手椅内 4. Against that time do I ensconce me here, 为抵抗那一天我就躲在这里', '过去式: ensconced 过去分词: ensconced 现在分词: ensconcing 第三人称单数: ensconces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rejoin', '[ˌriː\'dʒɔɪn]', 'v.（使）再结合；再加入；反驳', '1. She should strain a point to rejoin him. 她应该克服成见同他再次结合。 2. They may decide whether they want to rejoin the community. 他们可以决定是否愿意重新加入这个团体。 3. She make a detour and rejoin us on the other side of the wood. 她绕道在树林的另一边与我们重新会合。 4. \"You\'re wrong!\"she rejoined. “你错了!”她答道。', '过去式: rejoined 过去分词: rejoined 现在分词: rejoining 第三人称单数: rejoins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vanquish', '[\'væŋkwɪʃ]', 'v.征服；克服；击败', '1. It is no honor for an eagle to vanquish a dove. 老鹰胜鸽,不足为荣。 2. Our army has vanquished the enemy. 我们的军队已经彻底击败了敌人。', '形容词: vanquishable 名词: vanquisher 过去式: vanquished 过去分词: vanquished 现在分词: vanquishing 第三人称单数: vanquishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('communal', '[kə\'mjuːnl]', 'adj.公有的；公社的；共有的', '1. The Plains Indian has a plentiful and regular supply of meat and skins by the communal buffalo hunting. 大草原的印第安人猎取公有的牛而常得到很多肉和皮。 2. In college we had a communal kitchen. 念大学时，我们有共有的厨房。', '副词: communally 名词: communality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revert', '[rɪ\'vɜːrt]', 'vi.恢复；回复；归还', '1. You should try not to revert to your old eating habits. 你应该尽力不要恢复到你过去的饮食习惯。 2. He reverted to smoking when under stress. 他因受到压力又恢复了吸烟的习惯。 3. We\'ll revert to your enquiry as soon as fresh supplies are available. 一旦有货，我们就回复你方询价。 4. If he dies without leaving an heir, his lands will revert to the state. 如果他死后无继承人，其土地将复归国家所有。', '形容词: revertible 名词: reverter 过去式: reverted 过去分词: reverted 现在分词: reverting 第三人称单数: reverts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('condescend', '[ˌkɑːndɪ\'send]', 'v.屈尊；俯就；怀着优越感对待', '1. He occasionally condescended to take bribes. 他偶尔也自贬身价接受贿赂。 2. Mr. Smith sometimes condescends to help his wife with the housework. 史密斯先生有时屈尊帮他的妻子做家务。', '名词: condescender 过去式: condescended 过去分词: condescended 现在分词: condescending 第三人称单数: condescends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debility', '[dɪ\'bɪləti]', 'n.虚弱；衰弱', '1. After her operation she suffered from general debility. 她在手术后感到全身虚弱。', '名词复数: debilities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crab', '[kræb]', 'n.蟹；阴虱；爱争吵的人；[植]山楂子 v.捕蟹；使横行；批评；抱怨', '1. All the shops on the seafront had crab for sale. 海滨地区的全部商店都出售蟹。 2. A crab was left stranded on the beach when the tide ebbed. 退潮时，一只蟹被困留在沙滩上。 3. My neighbor is such an old crab. 我的邻居可真是个爱争吵的人。', '名词: crabber 过去式: crabbed 过去分词: crabbed 现在分词: crabbing 第三人称单数: crabs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immaculate', '[ɪ\'mækjələt]', 'adj.洁白的；无瑕疵的；无过失的', '1. He wore an immaculate uniform for the date. 他穿着整洁的制服去约会。 2. No matter how many guests were present, the great house was always immaculate. 不论有多少宾客，这幢大房子总是显得异常洁净。 3. It\'s an immaculate performance. 那是一场完美的演出。 4. Timing and technique were immaculate. 时间选择和方法都是非常完美的。', '副词: immaculately 名词: immaculateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apex', '[\'eɪpeks]', 'n.顶点；最高点；尖端', '1. The apex of the greater tuberosity was determined by placing a marker on the superiormost area of the greater tuberosity. 在大结节的上级放置一个标记以确定大结节的顶点。 2. As I neared the apex of the turn, a big pickup truck came around in my side of the road. 当我接近顶点的又一个大卡车来到我身边周围的道路。 3. So Andrew began to diversify, creating the Apex Security division and a videography service. 于是，安德鲁开始多元发展，创设了尖端通讯保险部门以及一项电视录象制作的服务。', '名词复数: apexes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rancid', '[\'rænsɪd]', 'adj.有腐臭油脂味的；腐臭的；令人作呕的', '1. The grocer took back the rancid butter. 杂货店老板拿回了有腐臭油脂味的黄油。 2. There was a rancid smell coming from the kitchen. 有一股腐臭味从厨房传来。', '名词: rancidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flare', '[fler]', 'n.闪光；闪光信号；[天]耀斑；(衣裙等)张开 v.闪光；闪耀；爆发；张开', '1. The flare of the match lit up his face. 火柴的光照亮了他的脸。 2. He stood ready to fire a warning flare. 他站着准备发出警告信号。 3. One possibility is that the blast was like an ultra-powerful solar flare. 一种可能的原因是这种爆炸很像有超级能量的太阳耀斑。 4. These flows occurred after violently unstable magnetic reconnection events above the Sun produced the flare. 这些在太阳表面上空剧烈而又不稳定的磁重联事件会产生耀斑。 5. A gust of wind made the candles flare. 一阵风吹得烛光摇曳。', '过去式: flared 过去分词: flared 现在分词: flaring 第三人称单数: flares');
