INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accomplished', '[ə\'kɑːmplɪʃt]', 'adj.完成的；有成就的；娴熟的；有造诣的；有教养的 动词accomplish的过去式和过去分词.', '1. Openings and closings were all accomplished with majestic rituality. 开幕和闭幕都是用隆重的仪式来完成的。 2. John is an accomplished scholar. 约翰是个有成就的学者。 3. Together this series is among the most moving and accomplished autobiographies-in-paint. 总的来讲，这一系列中的作品属于销售量最好以及手笔最娴熟的自传体油画。 4. She is an accomplished performer. 她是一个很有造诣的表演者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('realign', '[ˌriːə\'laɪn]', 'v.重新编制；重新排列；重新结盟', '1. The company is planning to realign its sales operations. 这家公司计划重新调整其销售经营。 2. McDonald\'s efforts to realign itself with the changing marketing environment appear to be paying off. 麦当劳对改变行销环境自我重新编制的努力出现了回馈。 3. The company is planning to realign its sales operations. 这家公司计划重新调整其销售经营。 4. These commands will realign a field in 10 minutes if intended. 这些指令，会在意愿后的10分钟内将能量场重新校准排序。', '名词: realignment 过去式: realigned 过去分词: realigned 现在分词: realigning 第三人称单数: realigns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('turmoil', '[\'tɜːrmɔɪl]', 'n.混乱；骚动', '1. The London Stock Exchange is in turmoil today. 今天伦敦证券市场一片混乱。 2. I couldn\'t think; my mind was in a complete turmoil. 我无法思考，我的脑子里一片混乱。 3. In the turmoil resulting from the collision, the arrested man broke loose and ran off. 在撞车引起的一片混乱中，那个被捕的人挣脱逃走了。 4. The whole city was in a turmoil, and people came running from all directions. 全城骚动起来,人们从四面八方跑来了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vibrant', '[\'vaɪbrənt]', 'adj.震颤的；响亮的；充满活力的；精力充沛的；(色彩)鲜明的', '1. The leaves were vibrant in the breeze. 叶子在微风中抖动。 2. His vibrant voice commove the air. 他响亮的声音振动了空气。 3. The city is vibrant with life. 这城市充满生机。 4. She was vibrant with health and enthusiasm. 她健康活泼生气勃勃。', '副词: vibrantly 名词: vibrancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('superimpose', '[ˌsuːpərɪm\'poʊz]', 'vt.置于某物之上；添加', '1. Westerners should not superimpose its value judgement on China. 西方人不应该把他们的价值观强加于中国。 2. I think you ought to superimpose the great trust of mine on your heart. 我想你应该牢记住我对你的重托。 3. She superimposed her own interpretation when she retold the story. 重复故事的时候，她加入了自己的解释。', '形容词: superimposable 名词: superimposition 过去式: superimposed 过去分词: superimposed 现在分词: superimposing 第三人称单数: superimposes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acclaim', '[ə\'kleɪm]', 'n.喝采；欢呼；赞同 v.欢呼；喝采；称赞', '1. Her performance won her much critical acclaim. 她的表演大获评论界赞颂。 2. He was welcomed with great acclaim. 他受到十分热烈的欢迎。 3. Every four years such acclaim would echo. 这种欢呼，每四年都会来一次。 4. The novel received great acclaim. 这本小说备受赞扬。 5. The whole city turned out to acclaim the winning team. 人们倾城而出为获胜的队欢呼喝彩。', '名词: acclaimer 过去式: acclaimed 过去分词: acclaimed 现在分词: acclaiming 第三人称单数: acclaims');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ragged', '[\'ræɡɪd]', 'adj.衣衫褴褛的；粗糙的；刺耳的；（外形）不规则的；不完美的', '1. The poor boy was ashamed of his ragged cloths. 这个穷孩子为自己的破衣服感到难为情。 2. The ragged man drags a waggon of rag fragments. 那个衣衫褴褛的人拉着一货车破布碎片。 3. Ragged cuts heal slowly and often poorly. 粗糙的伤口愈合慢，而且不好。 4. The spiders lie on their sides, translucent and ragged, their legs drying in knots. 蜘蛛们侧躺着，身体半透明而且粗糙，腿干枯关节突起。', '副词: raggedly 名词: raggedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bizarre', '[bɪ\'zɑːr]', 'adj.奇异的；怪诞的', '1. The building was of bizarre construction. 这建筑构造奇异。 2. She got herself up in a bizarre outfit. 她穿了一套古怪的套装 3. Its bizarre quality was not lost on us. 我们没有被那种异乎寻常的气氛弄得晕头转向。 4. His bizarre behavior attracted our attention. 他怪诞的行为吸引了我们的注意力。', '副词: bizarrely 名词: bizarreness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adorn', '[ə\'dɔːrn]', 'v.装饰；佩戴', '1. Some of Dem Bones open the big trunks and take out jewels and ropes of pearls and adorn themselves. 一些德国马克的骨头打开大箱子，并采取了珠宝和绳索的珍珠和装饰自己。 2. A shiny gold, rimless frame with brown, gradient lenses is wrapped in delicate gold rhinestones that adorn the temple. 闪亮的金色，棕色无框框架，梯度镜头是包裹微妙的金色人造钻石装饰眼镜脚。 3. She likes to adorn herself with jewels. 她喜欢佩戴珠宝。 4. Have the nearsighted patient of astigmatism, can you adorn invisible glasses? 患有散光的近视患者，能佩戴隐形眼镜吗？', '名词: adorner 过去式: adorned 过去分词: adorned 现在分词: adorning 第三人称单数: adorns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('veracious', '[və\'reɪʃəs]', 'adj.诚实的；精确的', '1. Miss Stackpole was a strictly veracious reporter. 斯坦克波尔小姐是一丝不苟、实事求是的记者。 2. Practice shows it fast, veracious and effective. 实践证明该处理方法快速、准确、有效。 3. We need to make a veracious evaluation. 我们需要事先作出准确的估计。 4. He is very veracious, he never lies. 他很诚实，从不说谎。', '副词: veraciously 名词: veraciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chisel', '[\'tʃɪzl]', 'n.凿子 v.雕；凿；欺骗', '1. She used a chisel to prise off the lid. 她用凿子来把盖子凿开。 2. He works with a file, a chisel, and an awl. 他工作起来又用锉刀，又用凿子，又用锥子。 3. He chiseled that rock into the figure of a woman. 他把那块石头凿成一个女人像。 4. He has chiseled me out of $5. 他骗去了我五块钱。', '名词: chiseler 过去式: chiseled/chiselled 过去分词: chiseled/chiselled 现在分词: chiseling/chiselling 第三人称单数: chisels/chisels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vindicate', '[\'vɪndɪkeɪt]', 'v.证明无辜；证明 ... 正确；维护（权利等）；<废>报仇', '1. I consider that I\'ve been completely vindicated. 我认为已经证实了我完全无辜。 2. The report of the committee vindicated him. 委员会的报告说明他是清白的。 3. The report fully vindicated the unions. 这份报告充分说明工会是正确的。 4. He tried hard to vindicate his honor. 他拼命维护自己的名誉。', '名词: vindicator 过去式: vindicated 过去分词: vindicated 现在分词: vindicating 第三人称单数: vindicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hearten', '[\'hɑːrtn]', 'vt.鼓励；激励；振作', '1. This good news will hearten you. 这个好消息将激励你。 2. I will go first to hearten thee. 我要先让你振作起来。 3. Nobody can hearten him after his wife died. 他的妻子死后，没有人可以使他振作起来。', '过去式: heartened 过去分词: heartened 现在分词: heartening 第三人称单数: heartens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('huckster', '[\'hʌkstər]', 'n.小商人；叫卖的小贩；商业广告员 v.贩卖；叫卖；强行推销', '1. They tried to huckster red socks to me. 他们企图强行向我推销红色短袜。 2. I don\'t think it\'s necessary for us to huckster the date. 我认为我们没必要在日期问题上没完没了的争论。 3. This usually involves buying something and the only thing here growing is the huckster’s bank account. 这类故事往往涉及到买一些东西，与此同时，小贩们银行帐户里的存款却在上涨。 4. In Eastwood\'s wily hands, Nowak is a master of disguise who becomes a radio DJ, a rodeo clown or a Vegas-style huckster to nail his target. 演技一流的奇连伊士活，他演活了纽瓦克一角，为了捕捉目标，易容为电台DJ、掷索套的小丑或在维加斯的小贩等；', '名词: hucksterism 过去式: huckstered 过去分词: huckstered 现在分词: huckstering 第三人称单数: hucksters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('torpor', '[\'tɔːrpər]', 'n.麻木；无感觉；不活泼', '1. The shock of the icy air ended Claire\'s torpor. 一种冰凉的寒风使克莱尔从麻木状况中恢复过来。 2. Now its torpor may remain undisturbed. 如今，这片宁静将不会被打扰了。 3. Then Marguerite lapsed into a sort of torpor. 接着玛格丽特迷迷糊糊睡着了。 4. In the heat they sank into a state of torpor. 炎热的天气使得他们委靡不振。', '形容词: torporific');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('checkered', '[\'tʃekəd]', 'adj.分成方格的；色彩多样的；有大变化的 动词checker的过去式和过去分词.', '1. A family with a checkered past. 一个有着波折历史的家族 2. A checkered career. 充满波折的经历', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('artifacts', '[\'ɑːrtɪfækts]', 'n.人工制品；史前古器物 名词artifact的复数形式. =artefacts.', '1. One can trace ancient practices through the study of artifacts. 经由研究人工制品可以探查出古代的惯例。 2. Indeed ,the multiplication of its artifacts may even be what makes it meaningfuI. 的确，人工制品的增加甚至会成为使之有意义的原因。 3. Excavations this year may reveal ancient artifacts. 今年的挖掘可能会发现史前古器物。 4. These artifacts can be the spoils of war, unlike gold and equipment. 这些史前古器物会在战争中受损，而不像金币和装备一样。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ungrudging', '[ʌn\'grʌdʒɪŋ]', 'adj.慷慨的；情愿的', '1. In the preparation of this manuscript I have received ungrudging help from several friends. 在准备这份手稿的过程中，我得到了几个朋友的慷慨帮助。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pseudonym', '[\'suːdənɪm]', 'n.假名；笔名', '1. * Samuel Clemens\' pseudonym was Mark Twain. *塞缪尔克莱门斯\'假名是马克吐温。 2. No one knew that he was operating under a pseudonym, 没人知道他一直在使用假名。 3. She writes under a pseudonym. 她用笔名发表作品。 4. She also writes under the pseudonym of Barbara Vine. 她也用芭芭拉 瓦因的化名从事写作。', '形容词: pseudonymous 副词: pseudonymously 名词: pseudonymousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('treasurer', '[\'treʒərər]', 'n.会计；出纳员；司库', '1. His father was treasurer of the club. 他父亲曾任俱乐部的会计。 2. The treasurer misappropriated the society\'s funds. 那会计盗用了协会的基金。 3. Please send remittance to the treasurer. 请将汇款送出纳员。 4. We suggest mr.smith for the post of treasurer. 我们提议史密斯先生担任出纳员。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('numerology', '[ˌnuːmə\'rɑːlədʒi]', 'n.命理学；数字命理学', '1. Much of the impetus for my research stems from the field of Numerology. 在我研究的过程中，许多进展都源于数字命理学这个领域。 2. You explain that the ancient Chinese were great mathematicians and believers in numerology. 你解释古老中国人是了不起的数学家和信徒在命理学方面。', '形容词: numerological 名词: numerologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('balk', '[bɔːk]', 'v.阻止；突然停止；退缩；拒绝 n.障碍；错误；失败 n.梁木 [棒球]佯投； 犯规动作； [游戏]开球区.', '1. Professor Xu Benli, of the Shanghai University of Sport, says successful sportspeople should not balk at turning over half of their earnings. 上海体育学院徐本力教授表示，功成名就的运动员不应拒绝上缴一半的收入。 2. The high price is a balk to me. 对我来说，价格太高是一个障碍。 3. There are small holes in the balk of a field, where crabs and fish accumulate in the rainy season. 田间的梁木上有小洞口，螃蟹和鱼在雨季的时候会聚集在里面。 4. A player with ball in hand must play from the balk. 拿球的选手必须从开球区开始打。', '名词: balker');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('soulful', '[\'soʊlfl]', 'adj.深情的；充满感情的', '1. I thought she got a lovely voice, very soulful and melancholy. 我觉得她的嗓音可爱，非常深情和忧郁。 2. He gave his girlfriend a soulful kiss before the part on the platform. 分手以前他在月台给他的女朋友一个深情的吻。 3. My dog gave me a soulful look when I scolded her. 我骂小狗时，它用充满感情的眼神看着我。', '副词: soulfully 名词: soulfulness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saliva', '[sə\'laɪvə]', 'n.唾液', '1. Saliva is secretion of the salivary glands. 唾液是唾液腺的分泌物。 2. Saliva helps one chew and digest food. 唾液能帮助咀嚼和消化食物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('novelty', '[\'nɑːvlti]', 'n.【C】新奇；小装饰 n.【U】新奇的事物；新奇的经验', '1. The novelty of his surroundings soon wore off. 他对环境的新奇感不久就淡薄了。 2. The demand is for quality, variety and novelty. 现在需求的是质量、花式品种和新颖性。 3. I bought some novelties on the boardwalk. 我在海滨人行道上买了一些新颖的小玩意儿。 4. Upon the whole the novelty attracted him. 总的说来，这个新奇的事物吸引着他。', '名词复数: novelties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impute', '[ɪm\'pjuːt]', 'v.归罪于；负责任；嫁祸', '1. I impute his failure to laziness. 我把他的失败归咎于他的懒惰。 2. They imputed the accident to the driver\'s carelessness. 他们把事故归咎于驾驶员的疏忽。 3. Don\'t impute to me that you failed. 不要把失败的责任推到我身上。 4. He was innocent of the crime imputed to him. 对于所加在他身上的罪，他是无辜的。', '过去式: imputed 过去分词: imputed 现在分词: imputing 第三人称单数: imputes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ringlet', '[\'rɪŋlət]', 'n.小环；小圈；卷发', '1. The child\'s hair fell in ringlets. 小孩的卷发自然下垂 2. Her hair hung down in ringlets. 她的头发呈许多小发卷下垂着。', '形容词: ringleted');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antagonize', '[æn\'tæɡənaɪz]', 'v.使…对抗', '1. It would be dangerous to antagonize him. 招惹他可危险。 2. They were always careful not to antagonize rural voters. 他们总是小心翼翼不引起乡村选民的反感。', '过去式: antagonized 过去分词: antagonized 现在分词: antagonizing 第三人称单数: antagonizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monotony', '[mə\'nɑːtəni]', 'n.单调；枯燥；单调无味', '1. I work with monotony. 我工作很单调。 2. The radio relieves the monotony of everyday life. 收音机缓解了我们日常生活的单调状况。 3. But the days succeeded each other with despairing monotony. 一天一天就这样枯燥无味地过去了。 4. The sheer monotony of the job is exhausting. 工作单调乏味，让人干起来浑身没劲儿。', '名词复数: monotonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fissure', '[\'fɪʃər]', 'n.裂缝；裂沟；分裂 v.裂开；分裂', '1. There is a fissure on the wall. 墙上有条裂缝。 2. Just ahead of us there was a huge fissure. 离我们不远处，出现一个大裂缝。 3. Though we all got out to examine the fissure, he remained in the car. 我们纷纷下车察看那个大裂缝，他却呆在车上。 4. An easier way to pull off a successful bribe is by using the Chrono Chasm, Fissure, or Rift Powers. 一个比较容易成功贿赂的方法是时空裂口，裂沟和裂缝能力。', '过去式: fissured 过去分词: fissured 现在分词: fissuring 第三人称单数: fissures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('novice', '[\'nɑːvɪs]', 'n.新手；新信徒', '1. He is a novice at swimming. 他是一个游泳新手。 2. I\'m a complete novice at skiing. 滑雪我完全是个新手。 3. The novice\'s expectation is inherently unrealistic and uninformed. 新手的期望大多是不现实和零散的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anchor', '[\'æŋkər]', 'n.锚；锚状物；依靠；新闻节目主播；压阵队员 v.抛锚；停泊；用锚系住；担任（广播电视新闻节目）的主持人', '1. The ship dragged its anchor during the night. 夜里,船把锚拖动了。 2. Hope is his only anchor. 希望是他唯一的依靠。 3. He was then doing the anchor. 他当时正主持新闻广播节目。 4. The anchor man in a relay team runs last. 接力队中的主力跑最后一棒。 5. The ship was anchored off the shore. 船在海岸处抛了锚。', '过去式: anchored 过去分词: anchored 现在分词: anchoring 第三人称单数: anchors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stubborn', '[\'stʌbərn]', 'adj.顽固的；倔强的；难对付的', '1. That stubborn man always cleaves to his idea. 那固执的人不愿改变想法。 2. The child has a stubborn temper. 这个小孩脾气执拗。 3. This detergent can remove stubborn stains. 这种去污剂能去除难洗的污渍。 4. I have a stubborn cold and cough day and night. 我得了很难治的感冒，日夜咳嗽。', '副词: stubbornly 比较级: stubborner 最高级: stubbornest 名词: stubbornness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extrapolate', '[ɪk\'stræpəleɪt]', 'v.推测；推知', '1. It is best if you can extrapolate this data. 最好是能够外推此数据。 2. The market conditions simply may not extrapolate. 市势根本不可以推测。 3. It is possible to extrapolate future developments from current trends. 从当前的趋势可以推知未来的发展。 4. One can extrapolate the size of the building from the measurements of an average room. 从一间屋子的量度可以推断出整座建筑物的大小。', '形容词: extrapolative 名词: extrapolation 过去式: extrapolated 过去分词: extrapolated 现在分词: extrapolating 第三人称单数: extrapolates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trigger', '[\'trɪɡər]', 'v.使发生；触发；使运行 n.扳机；起因', '1. Price increases will trigger off demands for wage increases. 价格上涨会激发人们增长工资的要求。 2. The odour of food may trigger people\'s appetite. 食物的香味能引起人的食欲。 3. A detonator is used to trigger an explosive device. 雷管用来引爆爆炸装置。 4. I pulled the trigger and the gun went off. 我一扣扳机，枪就响了。', '过去式: triggered 过去分词: triggered 现在分词: triggering 第三人称单数: triggers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shoal', '[ʃoʊl]', 'adj.浅的 n.浅水处；沙洲；鱼群；一大群 v.（使)变浅；群聚', '1. In the shoal water, we could see shoals of tiny fish darting about. 在浅水区，我们看到一群小鱼在游来游去。 2. The boat struck a shoal and fetched up all standing. 那艘船撞上浅滩突然停了下来。 3. I waded in the shoal almost a mile before I got to dry land. 我在浅滩中涉水几乎一英里远才到了陆地。 4. The ship ported sharply to the left to avoid a shoal. 船猛烈向左转以躲避一鱼群。 5. The fishmen shoal the narrow part of a river to fish. 渔夫使河道狭窄处水变浅以便捕鱼。', '过去式: shoaled 过去分词: shoaled 现在分词: shoaling 第三人称单数: shoals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aggrandize', '[ə\'grænˌdaɪz]', 'vt.增加；夸大；提高 =aggrandise(英).', '1. Indeed, it should be pointed out that although women status were greatly improved, we can not aggrandize the improvement. 当然，应该指出的是，妇女的地位尽管在罗马后期有了很大的提高，但我们不能夸大这种提高。 2. Indeed, it should be pointed out that although women status were greatly improved, we can not aggrandize the improvement. 当然，应该指出的是，妇女的地位尽管在罗马后期有了很大的提高，但我们不能夸大这种提高。', '名词: aggrandizement 过去式: aggrandized 过去分词: aggrandized 现在分词: aggrandizing 第三人称单数: aggrandizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antenna', '[æn\'tenə]', 'n.触角；天线', '1. Its ears were small, cup-shaped antennae. 它的耳朵很小,是杯子形状的触角。 2. Its antenna has reached every aspect of social life. 它的触角已经伸向社会生活的每个方面。 3. Extended the radio antenna. 把收音机的天线拉到最长 4. You should fix the television antenna before receiving programs. 接收节目前，你应该先装天线。', '形容词: antennal 名词复数: antennae');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('partition', '[pɑːr\'tɪʃn]', 'n.划分；隔离物 vt.区分；隔开；分割', '1. The key to resolve the problem is elaborate partition for time and manpower. 关键的解决这人问题的方法是把时间和人力精心划分。 2. I could hear what he was saying on the phone through the partition. 我能隔着墙听见他在电话里说了些什么。 3. Our office is comparted by a partition board. 我们的办公室用一个隔扇分成两部分。 4. There is a plywood partition between the two rooms. 两个房子中间有一个夹板墙。 5. The workers partition a room into three parts. 工人们把一间房间分成三部分。', '名词: partitioner 过去式: partitioned 过去分词: partitioned 现在分词: partitioning 第三人称单数: partitions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cite', '[saɪt]', 'vt.引用；传讯；表扬；举(例)', '1. The lawyer cited a previous case to support his argument. 律师引用了以前的案例来支持他的论点。 2. It\'s no use citing the Bible to somebody who doesn\'t believe in God. 对不信上帝的人引用圣经的话是没用的。 3. I\'ll just cite some figures for comparison. 我要引用一些数字作比较。 4. He was cited for contempt of court. 他因蔑视法庭而被传讯。', '形容词: citable 过去式: cited 过去分词: cited 现在分词: citing 第三人称单数: cites');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contain', '[kən\'teɪn]', 'vt.容纳；包含；抑制；克制 vi.自制', '1. The atlas contains forty maps. 这个地图集有四十幅地图。 2. Does each cup contain the same amount of milk? 每个杯子里的牛奶都一样多吗? 3. This book contains all the information you need. 这本书包含你所需的一切资料。 4. I could hardly contain my curiosity. 我简直无法克制我的好奇心 5. She couldn\'t contain herself for joy. 她高兴地难以自制。', '形容词: containable 过去式: contained 过去分词: contained 现在分词: containing 第三人称单数: contains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evasive', '[ɪ\'veɪsɪv]', 'adj.逃避的；难以捉摸的；闪烁其词的', '1. Stephen didn\'t want to see his sister, so he quickly took evasive action and hid under the bed. 斯蒂芬不愿见他的姐姐，便立即采取规避动作，藏到床底下去了。 2. His eyes gleamed with a smart, evasive light. 他那对眼睛闪耀着一种灵活的难以捉摸的光芒。 3. His evasive reply prompted me to ask him another question. 他闪烁其词的回答促使我提出又一个问题。 4. You can tell from his evasive language that he\'s got something to hide. 从他的闪烁其词能看出他分明是在掩饰什么。', '副词: evasively 名词: evasiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entreat', '[ɪn\'triːt]', 'v.恳求；乞求；请求', '1. He entreated her not to be angry. 他恳求她不要发怒。 2. She was not accustomed to entreat. 她不习惯于乞求于人。 3. They gathered outside the palace to entreat favours of the king. 他们聚集在宫廷外面，请求国王施以恩典。', '副词: entreatingly 异体字: intreat 名词: entreatment 过去式: entreated 过去分词: entreated 现在分词: entreating 第三人称单数: entreats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fragrant', '[\'freɪɡrənt]', 'adj.芬香的；馥郁的', '1. The aspic is one kind of strongly fragrant purple blue color floret. 薰衣草是一种馥郁的紫蓝色的小花。 2. Fragrant fruit juice is the best drink to entertain guests in the four seasons. 香气馥郁的果露饮料是四季酬宾美物。', '副词: fragrantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deduce', '[dɪ\'duːs]', 'vt.演绎；推断', '1. He will deduce a conclusion from premises. 从前提推导出结论。 2. If a = b and b = c, we can deduce that a = c. 设a = b，b = c，可以推断a=c。 3. The police were able to deduce where the fugitive was hiding. 警方成功地推断出那逃亡者躲藏的地方。', '形容词: deducible 过去式: deduced 过去分词: deduced 现在分词: deducing 第三人称单数: deduces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reminder', '[rɪ\'maɪndər]', 'n.提醒物；提示；催单', '1. These ruins are an eloquent reminder of the horrors of war. 这些废墟形象地提醒人们不要忘记战争的恐怖。 2. This has been a timely reminder of the need for constant care. 这件事适时地提醒我们要时时谨慎。 3. She placed it in the drawer as a reminder of her resolve. 她将它放在抽屉里,以此来不断提醒自己下的决心。 4. I\'ve got another reminder from the library. 我又收到图书馆催促还书的信函。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('damp', '[dæmp]', 'adj.潮湿的；有湿气的；沮丧的 n.湿气；潮湿 vt.使潮湿；使扫兴 vi.变潮湿', '1. Damp wood doesn\'t burn well. 潮湿的木头不好烧。 2. The building was cold and damp. 这房子又冷又湿。 3. The cheese molded in the damp cellar. 乳酪在潮湿的地下室中长了霉。 4. The party was a bit of a damp squib. 这次聚会有些扫兴。 5. The air of this room is impregnated with damp. 这房间充满着湿气。 6. Damp the cloth before you clean the windows. 在擦玻璃窗之前,把揩布弄湿。 7. Nothing could damp down my passion. 任何事情都不能磨灭我的激情。', '形容词: dampish 副词: damply 比较级: damper 最高级: dampest 名词: dampness 过去式: damped 过去分词: damped 现在分词: damping 第三人称单数: damps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('needlework', '[\'niːdlwɜːrk]', 'n.针线活；缝纫手艺', '1. This schoolgirl likes to do some needlework. 这个女学生喜欢做针线活。 2. In those ancient stores,the needlework is the required course for girls. 在古老故事里，女红是女子的必修课程。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remit', '[\'riːmɪt]', 'vt.汇出；提交；宽恕；免除；延迟 vi.汇款；缓和；减轻 n.移交事项', '1. He remitted some money to his mother. 他给他母亲寄了一些钱。 2. Remit the interest to her new address. 将利息寄到她的新地址 3. You will have to remit this problem to a higher authority. 你得把这个问题提交给上一级。 4. God would not remit your sins. 上帝不会宽恕你的罪恶。 5. Enclosed is our bill; please remit. 随函寄上账单,请寄款。', '形容词: remittable 名词: remitment 过去式: remitted 过去分词: remitted 现在分词: remitting 第三人称单数: remits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cursory', '[\'kɜːrsəri]', 'adj.匆匆忙忙的；草率的；粗略的', '1. He had given the report a cursory reading. 他草草看了一遍这份报告。 2. He signed with only a cursory glance at the report. 他只草草看了一眼报告就签了名。 3. After a cursory examination, he was released. 经过粗略的检查，他被释放。', '副词: cursorily 名词: cursoriness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('iodine', '[aɪədaɪn]', 'n.碘；碘酒', '1. Lack of iodine is a common cause of trouble. 缺碘是造成麻烦的常见原因。 2. Iodine tends to localize in the thyroid. 碘容易集于甲状腺。 3. The nurse bathed his wound with iodine. 护士在他的伤口上涂碘酒。 4. It smarts when iodine is put on a cut. 碘酒涂在伤口上真杀得慌。', '简写符号: I');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contingent', '[kən\'tɪndʒənt]', 'n.代表团；小分队；偶然的事情 adj.取决于；经验主义的；不可预知的', '1. The largest contingent was from the United States. 最大的会议代表团来自美国。 2. A large contingent from Japan was present at the conference. 来自日本的一个大代表团出席了会议。 3. A contingent of 400 Thebans remained. 一支400名的提佛人的小分队也留了下来。 4. The naval contingent was expected to come. 我们期望海军分遣队到来。 5. Our arrival time is contingent on the weather. 我们的抵达时间取决于天气情况。', '副词: contingently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('philately', '[fɪ\'lætəli]', 'n.集邮', '1. I liked philately three years ago. 三年前我喜欢上了集邮。 2. Ive always thought philately would be an interesting hobby. 我总是认为集邮是一项有趣的嗜好。', '形容词: philatelic 副词: philatelically 名词: philatelist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('full-fledged', '[fʊl fledʒd]', 'adj.羽毛丰满的；成熟的；完全有资格的 =fully-fledged(英).', '1. Let them soften and develop their full color indoors. 让它们在室内变软并且发育到成熟的颜色。 2. Fat is not accumulated as quickly as it is in full frown male deer. 脂肪的积累不如完全成熟的雄鹿快。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enslave', '[ɪn\'sleɪv]', 'vt.使做奴隶；使处于奴役的状态', '1. Someone was enslaved to her. 有人做了她的奴隶。 2. He is enslaved by love. 他正沉溺于爱情。 3. Her beauty enslaved many young men. 她的美貌倾倒了很多男青年。 4. Education makes people easy to govern but impossible to enslave. 教育使人容易去管理，但不可能去奴役。', '名词: enslavement 过去式: enslaved 过去分词: enslaved 现在分词: enslaving 第三人称单数: enslaves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('damn', '[dæm]', 'int.该死；讨厌 vt.使失败；诅咒；批评 vi.诅咒 n.诅咒；丝毫 adj.该死的；可恶的 adv.非常；极其', '1. Damn! I\'ve broken one of my nails. 该死！我弄断了一个指甲。 2. I made the damn doctors tell me. 我让那些讨厌的医生告诉了我。 3. Oh, damn the dirty swine to hell. 让那卑鄙的畜生见鬼去吧。 4. The book was damned by the critics. 这本书受到批评家的指责。 5. I don\'t give a damn. 我一点也不在乎。 6. \"Week in and week out, we had to write that damn paper.\" 我们都要写那该死的文章。 7. You know damn well what I mean. 你非常明白我的意思。', '副词: damningly 过去式: damned 过去分词: damned 现在分词: damning 第三人称单数: damns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('provision', '[prə\'vɪʒn]', 'n.食品；粮食；供应；规定；条款；预备；【经】准备金 vt.向 ... 供应食物', '1. We set out with enough provisions. 我们带上足够的食品出发了。 2. Provision of shelter was the Red Crosss main concern for the disaster victims. 为灾民提供避难处是 红十字会的主要工作。 3. The present law makes no provision for this. 现行的法律对此未作任何规定。 4. Both sides should act according to the provisions of the agreement. 双方都应按协议条款办事。 5. They provisioned the ship for a long voyage. 他们为远航的船只准备了食品和必需品。', '名词: provisioner 过去式: provisioned 过去分词: provisioned 现在分词: provisioning 第三人称单数: provisions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('telling', '[\'telɪŋ]', 'adj.有效的；显著的 动词tell的现在分词形式.', '1. History is the most telling witness. 历史是最好的见证。 2. He made a very telling speech about their mistakes. 他就他们的错误作了有力的发言。 3. A more telling criticism is that he reduces ethics to interpersonal relationships. 一个更有力的批评是他把道德规范简化为人际关系。', '副词: tellingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demonstrate', '[\'demənstreɪt]', 'vt.证明；演示；示范 vi.示威', '1. How can you demonstrate to us that your story is true? 你怎样才能向我们证明你所说的属实呢? 2. Realized benefits demonstrate good practice. 已实现的利益证明好的实践。 3. You have to demonstrate how to operate the computer. 你得演示一下如何使用这台计算机。 4. The students are demonstrating a chemical law in the laboratory. 学生们正在实验室里演示一条化学定理。 5. The workers marched through the streets with flags and banners to demonstrate against the rising cost of living . 工人们在街上游行，手执旗帜示威抗议生活费用的高涨。', '过去式: demonstrated 过去分词: demonstrated 现在分词: demonstrating 第三人称单数: demonstrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('toxic', '[\'tɑːksɪk]', 'adj.有毒的', '1. The factory had been sending out toxic fumes. 这家工厂一直在排放有毒的废气。 2. The toxic gas is extremely dangerous. 有毒的汽体是非常地危险的。 3. Too much toxic waste is being dumped at sea. 太多的有毒废料在向大海里倾倒。', '副词: toxically 名词: toxin');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monopolize', '[mə\'nɑːpəlaɪz]', 'v.独占；垄断 =monopolise(英).', '1. She tried to monopolize his time. 她想独占他的时间。 2. She tended to monopolize the conversation. 她说个没完,使别人插不上嘴。 3. The service providers monopolize the market. 服务行业垄断了市场。 4. First, the government will monopolize the land level development. 首先，政府将垄断土地的一级开发。', '名词: monopolization 过去式: monopolized 过去分词: monopolized 现在分词: monopolizing 第三人称单数: monopolizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('croon', '[kruːn]', 'v.低声歌唱；低吟；轻哼 n.低吟声；轻哼声', '1. She gently crooned a lullaby. 她轻声哼唱了一支摇篮曲。 2. The man was crooning soft words of encouragement to his wife. 这个人正柔情地对妻子说着一些鼓励的甜言蜜语。 3. Don\'t be startled by the smiling, white-haired man who croon \"Merry Christmas\" to you. 当你见到那向你低声哼着“圣诞快乐”面带笑容的白发老人时，不要感到吃惊。 4. Streisand\'s fans shelled out a total of $14,694,750 to hear Babs croon 1999 away. 仅1999一年中史翠珊的歌迷就花了%2414,694,750,来倾听她的浅唱低吟。', '名词: crooner 过去式: crooned 过去分词: crooned 现在分词: crooning 第三人称单数: croons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parallelism', '[\'pærəlelɪzəm]', 'n.平行；相似', '1. The parallelism in the classification of organisms and phytocoenoses is realized. 人们已认识到生物分类和植物群落分类是平行的。 2. Brackets shall be spaced at proper intervals to provide rigidity and parallelism. 平台之间应该有适当的空间间隔，这样有利于提高坚硬性和平行性。 3. I think he exaggerates the parallelism between the two cases. 我认为他夸大了两件事的相似之处。 4. There is a certain parallelism here between France and America. 这种情况，法国和美国是有点相似。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ennoble', '[ɪ\'noʊbl]', 'v.授予爵位；使高贵 vt.使杰出；使尊贵', '1. Ennoble a prime minister for distinguished service. 因其杰出的功劳授予总理爵位 2. His character has been ennobled by all his sufferings. 他受尽苦难，却志节弥高。', '名词: ennoblement 过去式: ennobled 过去分词: ennobled 现在分词: ennobling 第三人称单数: ennobles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stouthearted', '[\'stɑʊt\'hɑːtɪd]', 'adj.勇敢地；无畏的', '1. Robin Hood was a man with a stoutheart. 罗宾汉是一个勇敢的人。 2. He was artful and treacherous, and stouthearted soldier. 他是一个狡猾、奸诈而坚强的战士。 3. When I called, you answered me; you made me bold and stouthearted. 我呼求的日子,你就应允我,鼓励我,使我心里有能力。 4. A stalwart knight,a stouthearted fellow who had an active career in the army. 勇敢的骑士,一个在军队中有着活跃的事业的、刚毅的人。', '副词: stoutheartedly 名词: stoutheartedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tranquility', '[træŋ\'kwɪlətɪ]', 'n.宁静；平静；稳定', '1. I like the tranquility of night. 我喜爱夜晚的宁静。 2. Fame and tranquility can never be bedfellows. 名声很宁静永远不能是同床者。 3. The city was finally restored to tranquility. 这座城市最后恢复了平静。 4. So that takes more meditations with peace and tranquility. 因此那需要更多平静的思考。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('laity', '[\'leɪəti]', 'n.普通信徒；外行人', '1. The new proposals affect both clergy and laity. 新的建议与神职人员和俗人都有关系。 2. Thus, his preaching was directed at not only the laity, but the clergy as well. 因此，他的讲道面向的不只是世俗之人，也面向神职人员。 3. As they are possessed by all beings in the universe, they exist in the mind of the laity. 当他们被宇宙里一切存在拥有时候，它们就存在于外行人的头脑中。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brook', '[brʊk]', 'n.小河；溪 vt.(常用于否定句或疑问句)容忍；忍受', '1. He jumped his pony across the brook. 他使小马驹跳过了小河。 2. Before we drink much at a brook,it is well to know its source. 溪畔畅饮前，最好知其源。 3. By the brook, the cook looked through a cookbook before making hooked cookies. 在溪边，厨子在做钩形饼干之前查阅了一本食谱。 4. He will not brook any interference. 他不会容忍他人的任何干涉。', '过去式: brooked 过去分词: brooked 现在分词: brooking 第三人称单数: brooks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bogus', '[\'boʊɡəs]', 'adj.假的；伪造的', '1. The telegram turned out to have been bogus. 电报原来是假的。 2. Everything else was bogus, only money was genuine. 什么也是假的，只有钱是真的。 3. More than a quarter of the names on the list were found to be duplicates or bogus. 选票上超过四分之一的名字被查出是重复的或是伪造的。 4. Bogus payslips are produced along with faked time-cards and workers are drilled on the correct answers to questions. 伪造的工资单和假的工作时间卡一并俱全，工人们还练习了被问问题时的正确答案。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emboss', '[ɪm\'bɔːs]', 'vt.加浮雕花纹于；使凸出；装饰', '1. He carried a leather briefcase embossed with his initials. 他带着一个饰有浮凸的姓名首字母的皮公事包。 2. Can you read the addresses embossed on the notepaper? 你能看出凸印在信纸上的地址吗？', '名词: embosser 过去式: embossed 过去分词: embossed 现在分词: embossing 第三人称单数: embosses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bully', '[\'bʊli]', 'n.欺凌弱小者；开球 vt.恐吓；威胁；欺负', '1. The little girl stood up to a bully. 小女孩勇敢地对付暴徒。 2. The bully whacked my brother with a stick. 那恶棍用棒头狠揍我兄弟。 3. Leave that little girl alone, you big bully! 离那小姑娘远点儿, 你这个大坏蛋! 4. You are not discreet; you mustn\'t bully me. 你真不客气，你休想恐吓我。', '名词复数: bullies 过去式: bullied 过去分词: bullied 现在分词: bullying 第三人称单数: bullies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enfeeble', '[ɪn\'fiːbl]', 'vt.使衰弱', '1. He was enfeebled by a long illness. 他因长期患病而虚弱无力。 2. The boy was enfeebled by the cold. 那个男孩因感冒而虚弱无力。', '名词: enfeeblement 过去式: enfeebled 过去分词: enfeebled 现在分词: enfeebling 第三人称单数: enfeebles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exotic', '[ɪɡ\'zɑːtɪk]', 'adj.外来的；异国的；奇异的；脱衣舞的', '1. Exotic pets are the in thing right now. 外国宠物眼下很时髦。 2. The film retains much of the book\'s exotic flavour. 这部电影保存了原著的许多异国情调。 3. The taste of this exotic dish puts me off. 这道异国菜肴的味道令我望而却步。 4. The exotic atmosphere will fascinate you. 这里的异国情调风格将会把您深深地迷住。', '副词: exotically 名词: exoticness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('syllabus', '[\'sɪləbəs]', 'n.大纲；摘要', '1. These cannot be the required books on the syllabus. 这些不能是教学大纲中的必读书籍。 2. The new syllabus will be put into effect this year. 今年起开始实施新的教学大纲。 3. The language syllabus needs to be completely overhauled. 那个语言教学大纲需全面修订。 4. The professor is passing out the course syllabus. 教授正在派发课程摘要。', '名词复数: syllabuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kidney', '[\'kɪdni]', 'n.肾；腰子；类型', '1. Each man has a pair of kidneys. 每个人有一对肾脏。 2. Joe has also heard of kidney stones. 乔也听人提到过肾结石。 3. Those two brothers are men of the same kidney. 这两兄弟是同一类型的人。', '名词复数: kidneys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tombstone', '[\'tuːmstoʊn]', 'n.墓碑', '1. A tombstone stands in front of her tomb. 她墓前立着一块墓碑。 2. I saw a tombstone bearing the date 1602. 我见到一块刻有1602年字样的墓碑。 3. He asked the mason to make him a tombstone. 他要求这个石匠给他做一块墓碑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('restored', '[rɪ\'stɔːd]', 'adj.恢复的', '1. He feels completely restored to health after a period of intensive care. 通过一段时间的精心照顾，他感到身体完全康复了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compact', '[\'kɑːmpækt]', 'adj.紧密的；紧凑的；简洁的 vt.使简洁；使装满；压实 n.合约条约；梳妆粉盒；<美>小型汽车', '1. He received a compact package. 他收到一个扎得很紧的包裹。 2. As writers, they like a structure that is compact. 写文章的时候，他们喜欢采用紧凑的结构。 3. Regulator shall be corrosion resistant, compact and lightweight. 这种调节阀应该是耐腐蚀的，紧凑的和轻型的。 4. We\'d love to buy a compact car. 我们想买一辆简洁的车。 5. The kids are try to compact the sand into the mold. 孩子们正在设法把这沙土堆积到模子里。 6. You should sign your name on the right side of the compact. 你应该在合约的右边签上你的名字。', '副词: compactly 名词: compactness 过去式: compacted 过去分词: compacted 现在分词: compacting 第三人称单数: compacts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gall', '[ɡɔːl]', 'v.擦伤；烦恼；激怒；羞辱 n.胆汁；苦味；怨恨；<口>厚颜无耻 n.伤痛处 n.虫瘿', '1. The saddle galled the horse\'s back. 马鞍擦伤了马背。 2. That remark galls. 那句话使人恼怒。 3. It galled him to have to ask for a loan. 必须向人借钱使他感到羞辱。 4. The medicine is as bitter as gall. 这药像胆汁一样苦。', '过去式: galled 过去分词: galled 现在分词: galling 第三人称单数: galls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('undulate', '[\'ʌndʒəleɪt]', 'adj.波动的；起伏的 v.(使) 波动；(使) 起伏；(使) 震动', '1. We soon see a field of wheat undulate in the breeze. 我们很快看到一片在微风中起伏的麦田。', '形容词: undulatory 过去式: undulated 过去分词: undulated 现在分词: undulating 第三人称单数: undulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concentric', '[kən\'sentrɪk]', 'adj.同中心的；同轴的', '1. Concentric circles are parallel. 同心圆是平行的。 2. The centres of concentric circles coincide. 同心圆的圆心是一个。 3. The curvature of the film is concentric with the mirror behind the meniscus. 胶片的曲率是和弯月透镜后面的反射镜同心的。 4. It consists of a pair of concentric cylinder. 它由一对同轴的圆筒组成。', '副词: concentrically 异体字: concentrical 名词: concentricity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eliminate', '[ɪ\'lɪmɪneɪt]', 'v.除去；剔除；忽略；淘汰', '1. You must eliminate an unknown quantity. 你必须消去一个未知数。 2. Let us eliminate all uncertain on thought. 让我们从思想上消除一切疑惑。 3. We must eliminate unnecessary steps and get directly to the point. 我们必须忽略不必要的步骤,直接切入主题。 4. Their team was eliminated in the first round. 他们队在第一轮就被淘汰了。', '形容词: eliminative 名词: elimination 过去式: eliminated 过去分词: eliminated 现在分词: eliminating 第三人称单数: eliminates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unkempt', '[ˌʌn\'kempt]', 'adj.乱蓬蓬的；不整洁的', '1. The old man was shabby and unkempt. 老头蓬头垢面，衣衫褴褛。 2. Their faces were unkempt, their clothing sloppy. 他们仍然仪容不整，衣服也都是遢里邋遢的。 3. During the owners\' absence the lawn became dreadfully unkempt. 主人们不在的时候，草地变得凌乱不堪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coarsen', '[\'kɔːrsn]', 'v.（使）变粗', '1. The sea air coarsened her skin. 海上的空气使她的皮肤粗糙了。', '过去式: coarsened 过去分词: coarsened 现在分词: coarsening 第三人称单数: coarsens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ferocious', '[fə\'roʊʃəs]', 'adj.残忍的；凶猛的；极度的', '1. The ferocious chieftain was executed. 那个凶残的匪首被处决了。 2. I could catch the glare of their ferocious eyes. 我连它们那残忍的眼睛中的灼灼目光都看清楚了。 3. Both tigers and leopards are ferocious beasts. 虎豹都是凶猛的野兽。 4. The oncoming force of the typhoon was ferocious. 这次台风来势凶猛。', '副词: ferociously 名词: ferociousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deracinate', '[ˌdiː\'ræsɪneɪt]', 'v.根除；灭绝；使孤立', '1. The school should balance the exam effect, not only stimulate students to learn but also deracinate the action of cheat. 语言表达上注意一些过度衔接，一些句子可精练一下，注意句式变换。 2. DERACINATE DELETE RACE IN ATE KFC 在吃方面灭绝我们的民族食品 3. strengthen supervision and check, deracinate various \"protecting umbrellas\"; 加大监督、检查力度，根除各种“保护伞”； 4. to deracinate a tree 把一棵树连根拔起', '名词: deracination 过去式: deracinated 过去分词: deracinated 现在分词: deracinating 第三人称单数: deracinates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('holograph', '[\'hɑːləɡræf]', 'n.亲笔文件；全息照片 adj.亲笔的', '1. On the theory of language holograph? 何为语言全息论? 2. Autograph is not Han Han\'s holograph, however Han father forges! 签名不是韩寒的亲笔，而是韩爸爸伪造的！ 3. The frequency domain, the holograph and related concepts have all been used. 频率域、全息及有关的概念都已采用。 4. Holograph will or us also holographic will. 亲笔遗嘱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carat', '[\'kærət]', 'n.克拉；开(以纯金为24开表示金含量的单位) =karat.', '1. You can shop for 24 carat gold jewelry. 你可以选购24克拉的金首饰。 2. Stones jump in price at the carat mark. 一克拉以上和一克拉以下钻石的价钱差别很大。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defy', '[dɪ\'faɪ]', 'vt.藐视；挑衅；反抗', '1. The pine trees defy severe cold. 松树不畏严寒。 2. If you defy the law, you will be sent to prison. 如果你蔑视法律，你将被送入监狱。 3. He defined the order of the court. 他蔑视法庭的命令。 4. He won\'t allow anyone to defy his ministerial authority. 他不允许任何人挑衅他的教长权威。', '过去式: defied 过去分词: defied 现在分词: defying 第三人称单数: defies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('molar', '[\'moʊlər]', 'adj.磨碎的；臼齿的；[物]质量上的；[化]摩尔的 n.臼齿；磨牙', '1. The elephant grinds its food with/between its powerful molars. 象用其强有力的臼齿嚼碎食物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('finesse', '[fɪ\'nes]', 'n.技巧；策略；偷牌 v.用计谋处理；偷牌', '1. Paul played the sonata with great finesse. 保罗以丰富的技巧弹奏了这部奏鸣曲。 2. It was a disappointing performance which lacked finesse. 那场演出缺乏技巧,令人失望。 3. Paul handled the meeting with great finesse. 保罗极其巧妙地掌握着会议。 4. A shrewd diplomat must be a master of finesse. 一个精明的外交官必定是位手腕高手。 5. He finessed his way through the exam. 他用巧计通过考试。', '过去式: finessed 过去分词: finessed 现在分词: finessing 第三人称单数: finesses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intrigue', '[ɪn\'triːɡ]', 'vt.欺骗；激起 ... 的兴趣 vi.密谋 n.阴谋；私通；复杂的事', '1. The shapes of clouds intrigue me. 云的形状激起我的兴趣。 2. She was intriguing with her sister against her mother. 她和妹妹串通捣鬼和母亲作对。 3. Some of the members had been intriguing to get the secretary dismissed. 有些人一直密谋想让老板把秘书解雇。 4. I\'ll never intrigue against my friends 我决不会对我的朋友耍阴谋，施诡计。 5. It is said that he is a master of intrigue. 据说他是搞阴谋诡计的老手。', '副词: intriguingly 名词: intriguer 过去式: intrigued 过去分词: intrigued 现在分词: intriguing 第三人称单数: intrigues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amend', '[ə\'mend]', 'vt.修正；改进', '1. They decided to amend the bill. 他们决定修正这条议案。 2. Please amend your copy of the contract accordingly. 请将你的合同文本作相应的修正。 3. Since you insist, I must amend the letter of credit. 既然你坚持，我就只好修改信用证。 4. I would advise you to amend your manners. 我劝你改正你的态度', '过去式: amended 过去分词: amended 现在分词: amending 第三人称单数: amends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('salve', '[sælv]', 'n.药膏；缓解物；慰藉 v.涂软膏；安慰；抢救', '1. The salve will heal slight burns. 这药膏能治疗轻微烧伤。 2. This kind of salve is used on wounds. 这种药膏用在伤口处。 3. This is an inevitable result of the cheap credit that has been applied as a salve for the financial crisis. 这是为了缓解金融危机而发放廉价信贷的必然结果。 4. She paid the repair bill as a salve to her conscience. 她付了维修费以减轻内疚感。 5. He took them presents to salve his conscience. 他给他们带去礼物，以使自己良心稍安。', '名词: salvor 过去式: salved 过去分词: salved 现在分词: salving 第三人称单数: salves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apprehend', '[ˌæprɪ\'hend]', 'v.理解；忧虑；逮捕；拘押', '1. I can\'t apprehend your meaning. 我不明白你的意思。 2. He can\'t apprehend the real nature of change. 他不能理解变革的真实性质。 3. Do you apprehend there will be any difficulty? 你怕有任何困难吗？ 4. This will help them to apprehend the rapist. 这将有助于警察逮捕强奸犯。', '过去式: apprehended 过去分词: apprehended 现在分词: apprehending 第三人称单数: apprehends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sufficient', '[sə\'fɪʃnt]', 'adj.足够的；充分的', '1. The money I have saved is sufficient for buying a car. 我所存的钱足以买一辆汽车。 2. I doubt whether they really have sufficient manpower. 我怀疑他们是否真有足够的人力。 3. There is sufficient food for everybody. 有足够的饭菜供大家吃。 4. We must work hard, but equally we must get sufficient rest. 我们必须努力工作,但同时也要有充分的休息。', '副词: sufficiently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('matrix', '[\'meɪtrɪks]', 'n.矩阵；发源地；基质；母体；子宫；(人或社会成长发展的）社会环境、政治局势；线路网；道路网；[地]杂基；矩阵转接电路；唱片模板', '1. The square matrix is called a diagonal matrix. 该方矩阵称为对角矩阵。 2. How do I multiply a matrix by a vector? 我怎么用一个矩阵乘以一个向量呢? 3. A term sometimes applied to a stylus in a thermal matrix printer. 有时用来指热敏点阵打印机的触针的一个术语。', '名词复数: matrices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wend', '[wend]', 'v.行；走；去；往；向；前进', '1. I meet up with another writer and we wend our way through downtown. 我与另一位作家会合，慢慢蜿蜒穿过市中心。 2. Someone will secort you to the border then you must wend by yourself. 有人送你到边境，然后你必须自己走了。 3. My mother was washing dishes when I wend home yesterday evening. 昨天晚上我回家的时候，我妈妈正在洗碗。', '过去式: wended 过去分词: wended 现在分词: wending 第三人称单数: wends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glib', '[ɡlɪb]', 'adj.能说善道的；圆滑的', '1. A glib salesman sells her a set of dish that she does not want. 一位言词伶俐的推销员卖给她一套本来她不要的碟子。 2. The fellow has a very glib tongue. 这家伙嘴油得很。 3. The spokesman\'s answer was just too glib. 发言人的回答太圆滑了。', '副词: glibly 比较级: glibber 最高级: glibbest 名词: glibness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('piteous', '[\'pɪtiəs]', 'adj.哀怨的；可怜的；凄惨的', '1. We heard piteous sounds of suffering and pain. 我们听到可怜的痛苦受难的呻吟。 2. The politician found the piteous cries of the starving children unbearable. 这个政治家发现饥饿的孩子们可怜的哭声让人不忍心听下去。', '副词: piteously 名词: piteousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('egregious', '[ɪ\'ɡriːdʒiəs]', 'adj.恶名昭彰的；过份的；非常的', '1. The story seemed too egregious to be believed. 这故事似乎离奇得令人难以置信。 2. What an egregious example was here! 现摆着一个多么触目惊心的例子啊！ 3. If it\'s really , it\'s very egregious message. 如果这是真的，这肯定是非常惊人的消息。 4. That on the outer side was, one may say, on an egregious scale. 外边的那座可以说是规模异乎寻常。', '副词: egregiously 名词: egregiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hieroglyphic', '[ˌhaɪərə\'ɡlɪfɪk]', 'adj.象形文字的；用象形文字书写的；潦草难懂的 n.象形文字；难辨别的书写', '1. Dongba is an ancient hieroglyphic language. 东巴文是一种古老的象形文字。 2. There is no indication that script had as many ideograms as the hieroglyphic had. 没有迹象表明这种文字是拥有很多表意文字，就如那些象形文字一样。 3. His write is so bad it just looks like hieroglyphic to me. 他写的糟透了，对我来说就像天书一样。', '副词: hieroglyphically 异体字: hieroglyphical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cauterize', '[\'kɔːtəraɪz]', 'v.烧灼；腐蚀 =cauterise(英）.', '1. Laser beams may cauterize and heal ulcers. 激光束可以烧灼和愈合溃疡。', '名词: cauterization 过去式: cauterized 过去分词: cauterized 现在分词: cauterizing 第三人称单数: cauterizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sear', '[sɪr]', 'vt.使 ... 干枯；烤焦；用强烈的感情影响 vi.变得干枯 adj.枯萎的；烤焦的 n.烤焦的痕迹', '1. The cold wind seared all the flowers. 冷风使所有的花都枯萎了。 2. A cloth was seared by the heat of the oven. 一块布被烤箱烧焦了。 3. The novel is a searing indictment of urban poverty. 这部小说是对城市贫困的震撼心灵的控诉。 4. The terrible experience is seared into my memory. 那次可怕的经历铭刻在我的记忆中。 5. The autumn breeze blows down sear leaves. 秋风吹落枯萎的树叶。 6. That sear face has a Japanese name, from the old time of Japan, it had already play the piano in the old music classroom. 那张烤焦的脸有个日本名字，从日据时代就开始在老旧的教室里弹琴。', '过去式: seared 过去分词: seared 现在分词: searing 第三人称单数: sears');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marsh', '[mɑːrʃ]', 'n.沼泽；湿地 Marsh：马什（人名）.', '1. There are a lot of frogs in the marsh. 沼泽里有许多青蛙。 2. Be careful not to get stuck in the marsh. 小心别陷进沼泽里。 3. No retrieval romps in the marsh. 在湿地不好游戏。 4. At the mouth of the river, there is a large area of marsh. 这条河流的入口有一大片湿地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proclamation', '[ˌprɑːklə\'meɪʃn]', 'n.宣言；公布；文告', '1. Lincoln\'s Emancipation Proclamation emancipated slaves in the Confederate states. 林肯的解放宣言解放了南部联邦的奴隶。 2. Five score years ago, a great American, in whose symbolic shadow we stand today, signed the Emancipation Proclamation. 在一百年以前，有位伟大的美国人签署了奴隶解放宣言，而今天我们正是立足于他所象征的影像下。 3. At least the government should have come to some agreement with our party prior to the Proclamation. 至少政府在公布决议之前应和我党达成一些共识。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cape', '[keɪp]', 'n.岬；海角 n.披肩', '1. Rudolf was rounding a bleak, dangerous cape. 鲁道夫正在绕过一个荒凉险峻的海岬。 2. The cape extends far into the ocean. 那海岬伸向海洋远处。 3. My favorite movie is Cape No. 7. 我最喜欢的电影是”海角七号”。 4. The man has a red cape. 这人有一件红色的斗篷。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sparse', '[spɑːrs]', 'adj.稀少的；稀疏的', '1. This is a country of sparse population. 这是个人口稀少的小国。 2. Species that were once sparse started to carpet the plots. 曾经稀少的物种开始遍布草原。 3. His pink scalp gleamed through his sparse hair. 他发红的头皮在稀疏的头发下泛微光。 4. The sparse vegetation will only feed a small population of animals. 稀疏的植物只能喂少量的动物族群。', '副词: sparsely 比较级: sparser 最高级: sparsest 名词: sparseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('divestiture', '[də\'vestətʃə]', 'n.脱衣；剥夺财产或权利；夺去称号', '1. The divestiture takes place two years later on January 1, 1984. 这项法令于2年后的1984年1月1日执行。 2. You are confronted with a merger, acquisition, or divestiture. 您面临着合并、收购或资产剥离。 3. Finally it made research that AHP applied in the course of divestiture. 最后还对层次分析法在资产剥离中的应用研究。 4. The court found divestiture to be necessary in preventing a monopoly. 法庭发现在防止垄断方面进行资产剥离是必要的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('instate', '[ɪn\'steɪt]', 'vt.任命', '1. After some brainstorming, he will decide to instate a Facial Hair Tax. 针对这场资产转移，杜双华是通过海外投资公司来实现的。 2. In general, if choosing between instate schools, or choosing based on cost, KU is a strong contender. 相比同一个州内的其他学校和费用而言，堪萨斯大学都是很强的竞争者。 3. Palmer assures him that when he does become President, he will instate Mason to a high position of power. 帕默向他保证，等他当上总统，他会任命梅森一个位高权重的职位。 4. Those purposes were influenced to the proposals infuriated Russia, despite Washington instate . 这些行为激怒了俄国。', '过去式: instated 过去分词: instated 现在分词: instating 第三人称单数: instates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pulp', '[pʌlp]', 'n.果肉；纸浆；木髓；牙髓；低级刊物 v.使成为浆状；除去 ... 的果肉；把...制成纸浆', '1. A banana is mainly pulp, except for its skin. 香蕉除了果皮之外，主要是果肉。 2. The pulp of mango tastes very sweet and soft. 芒果的果肉尝起来很甜且很软。 3. A thin film formed on the surface of the pulp. 纸浆表面结了一层膜。 4. Critics reviled the novel as unsophisticated pulp. 批评家把这部小说贬为不成熟的低级品。 5. Their feet have pulped the wet mud to a mire. 他们的脚把湿泥踩成了泥潭。', '形容词: pulpous 名词: pulpiness 过去式: pulped 过去分词: pulped 现在分词: pulping 第三人称单数: pulps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sanity', '[\'sænəti]', 'n.神智健全；头脑清楚', '1. We have to do it in order to keep our sanity. 我们这么做是为了保持心智健全。 2. Sanity and happiness are an impossible combination. 睿智和幸福是无法兼得的。 3. She lost her sanity when she heard of that news. 当她听到这个消息时,便发狂了。 4. Sanity of judgment has never deserted him. 他从未失去明达的判断力。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peril', '[\'perəl]', 'n.危险；冒险 vt.冒险', '1. These birds are able to survive the perils of the Arctic winter. 这些鸟能在北极寒冷的冬天里生存。 2. The ship was in imminent peril of being wrecked. 那条船马上就有失事的危险。 3. You had better not invest so much money at your peril. 你最好不要冒险投资这么多。 4. He made the experiment at his peril. 他冒险做这个试验。 5. Do you think I am going to peril my reputation for you? 你以为我会为你拿我的名誉冒险?', '过去式: periled/perilled 过去分词: periled/perilled 现在分词: periling/perilling 第三人称单数: perils/perils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parse', '[pɑːrs]', 'v.从语法上分析 n.从语法上分析', '1. I simply couldn\'t parse what you just said. 我完全无法对你刚说的话作语法分析。 2. Let him construe the letter into English, and parse it over perfectly. 让他把信件逐字翻译成英文，并且完美地对它作语法分析。 3. A parse of a sentential form is the construction of a derivation and possibly a syntax tree for it. 句型的分析是某个推导(或许是其语法树)的构造过程。', '名词: parser 过去式: parsed 过去分词: parsed 现在分词: parsing 第三人称单数: parses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consistent', '[kən\'sɪstənt]', 'adj.始终如一的；持续的；一致的', '1. She is a consistent girl in her feeling. 在感情方面她是个始终如一的女孩。 2. Our aim is to ensure a consistent growth. 我们的目标是确保持续的增长。 3. Your conduct is not consistent with what you say. 你的言行不一致。', '副词: consistently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conceit', '[kən\'siːt]', 'n.自负；个人观点；幻想；字字珠玑；好评', '1. This young man is full of conceit. 这个年轻人非常自负。 2. No one admires a man who is full of conceit. 没有人喜欢一个十分自负的人。 3. He jotted down his conceits of his idle hours. 他记下闲暇时自己想到的一些念头。 4. I don\'t have much conceit of his poems. 我对他的诗作没有什么好评。', '过去式: conceited 过去分词: conceited 现在分词: conceiting 第三人称单数: conceits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embitter', '[ɪm\'bɪtər]', 'vt.使受苦；使难受；加苦味于', '1. The loss of all his money embitter the old man. 失去全部的钱，使这位老人甚为痛苦。 2. I was embittered by repeated failures. 我因屡次失败而苦恼。 3. The news embittered him. 这个消息使他陷入痛苦。', '名词: embitterment 过去式: embittered 过去分词: embittered 现在分词: embittering 第三人称单数: embitters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('depose', '[dɪ\'poʊz]', 'v.废黜；罢免；（通常以书面）证明；作证（尤指在法庭宣誓）；放下', '1. The head of state was deposed by the army. 国家元首被军队废黜了。 2. The council of the tribe also had the power to depose both sachems and chiefs. 部落会议也有罢免首领和酋帅的权利。 3. A witness must depose to such facts as are within his own knowledge. 证人必须宣誓证明他所知道的事实。 4. Investigators will depose the witness behind closed doors. 调查员们将让证人们在关闭的门后宣誓作证。', '形容词: deposable 过去式: deposed 过去分词: deposed 现在分词: deposing 第三人称单数: deposes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debunk', '[ˌdiː\'bʌŋk]', 'v.揭穿真相；暴露', '1. A lot of people used to believe that, but now it\'s been completely debunked. 过去很多人相信那种想法，但现已真相大白。', '名词: debunker 过去式: debunked 过去分词: debunked 现在分词: debunking 第三人称单数: debunks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verbatim', '[vɜː\'beɪtɪm]', 'adj.逐字的 adv.逐字地', '1. It was nothing but a verbatim translation. 这只不过是逐字的直译罢了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vindictive', '[vɪn\'dɪktɪv]', 'adj.有报仇心的；怀恨的；惩罚的', '1. It is not right to harbor vindictive feelings. 怀有报复的念头是不对的。 2. The vindictive little girl threw stones at me. 那个充满报复心的小女孩拿石头扔我。 3. I have no vindictive feelings about it. 我对此没有恶意。', '副词: vindictively 名词: vindictiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swoop', '[swuːp]', 'v.抓取；猛扑；突然袭击 n.俯冲；攫取；突然袭击', '1. The robber swooped up the banknotes. 劫匪把钞票一把抢走了。 2. The eagle poised in mid-air ready to swoop on its prey. 那鹰在半空中盘旋准备扑向猎物。 3. The owl swooped down on the mouse. 那只猫头鹰向着老鼠猛扑下来。 4. We decided to swoop down upon the enemy there. 我们决定突袭驻在那里的敌人。 5. The plane made a swoop over the city. 那架飞机突然向这座城市猛降下来。', '过去式: swooped 过去分词: swooped 现在分词: swooping 第三人称单数: swoops');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antecedence', '[ˌæntə\'siːdəns]', 'n.居先；在先', '1. Creative thinking is the antecedence of design. 创新性设计，必须有创新性思维。 2. Why concept antecedence?What\'s the soul for their concept? 为什么要“理念先行”?北外网院理念的精髓是什么? 3. Electric power is the antecedence to the development of the national economic. 国家经济的发展,电力是先行。 4. It has an important effect on the antecedence tunnel and results in displacement and stress increase when the later tunnel is excavated. 后行隧道开挖对先行隧道围岩的受力变形有很大影响，后行隧道开挖导致先行隧道洞周位移和应力大幅度增大；', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('certainty', '[\'sɜːrtnti]', 'n.确定；确实的事情', '1. I can say with certainty that this is true. 我可以很确定地说这是真实的。 2. Too great certainty destroys certainty itself. 过于确定就会破坏确定本身。', '名词复数: certainties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('facilities', '[fə\'sɪlɪtɪz]', 'n.设施；设备；工具 名词facility的复数形式.', '1. The sports facilities are superb in this city. 这个城市的运动设施是一流的。 2. These facilities have benefited the whole town. 这些设施使全城受益。 3. The college has excellent sporting facilities. 这所学院有极好的体育设备。 4. She had no cooking facilities in the room. 她房间里没有烧煮设备。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('opaque', '[oʊ\'peɪk]', 'adj.不透明的；难懂的', '1. This is an opaque cup. 这是一个不透明的杯子。 2. The window is made of opaque glass. 这扇窗是用不透明的玻璃做的。 3. The report was written in long, opaque sentences. 报告中的句子又长又难懂。 4. Their intentions remained opaque. 他们的意图仍然令人费解。', '副词: opaquely 名词: opaqueness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unjustly', '[ˌʌn\'dʒʌstli]', 'adv.不公正；不法地', '1. It\'s unfair to devalue anyone\'s work unjustly. 不公正地贬低任何人的工作都是不公平的。 2. I must resist those who punish me unjustly. 对那些不公正地惩罚我的人，我也只得去反抗。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cosmic', '[\'kɑːzmɪk]', 'adj.宇宙的；广大无边的；无限的', '1. I have mystical visions and cosmic vibrations. 我有神秘的幻觉和宇宙的震波。 2. I\'m pure, so I\'m more in touch with cosmic forces. 因为我纯洁，所以我能更好的接触宇宙的力量。', '副词: cosmically 异体字: cosmical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('renunciate', '[rɪ\'nʌnsɪeɪt]', 'v.放弃；抛弃；宣布中止', '1. And because he has renounced his impurities, he is called a renunciate. 在灭除污垢之后，他被称为出家人。 2. Enduring patience is the highest austerity. \"Nibbana is supreme,\" say the Buddhas. He is not a true monk who harms another, nor a true renunciate who oppresses others. 诸佛说：“忍辱是最好的德行，涅盘至上。”出家人不会伤害他人，伤人者不是沙门。 3. the renunciate should sit concentrating the mind upon Me as the Ultimate Goal. 出家人应该静坐冥想于“我”并把“我”作为人生的终极目标。 4. Whether one lives in his home as a grhastha or in the forest as a renunciate, as long as he exclaims, “Ha Gauranga!” 无论是在家的居士还是在森林里的弃绝者，他只要高呼：“哈，高浪伽！”', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('weed', '[wiːd]', 'n.杂草；野草 n.衣服；丧服 vi.除草；清除；淘汰', '1. The garden is choked with weeds. 花园杂草丛生。 2. She knelt down to pull a weed from the flower bed. 她跪下来拔除花圃上的杂草。 3. There are so many weeds in his field! 他的田里有那么多野草！ 4. He pulled off his coat and started to weed with us. 他脱去上装，开始和我们一起除草。', '过去式: weeded 过去分词: weeded 现在分词: weeding 第三人称单数: weeds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discomfit', '[dɪs\'kʌmfɪt]', 'vt. 使懊恼； 挫败； <古>征服 n. 挫败', '1. He was discomfited by the unexpected questions. 意料不到的问题使得他十分尴尬。', '过去式: discomfited 过去分词: discomfited 现在分词: discomfiting 第三人称单数: discomfits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('convey', '[kən\'veɪ]', 'vt.表达；传达；运输；转移', '1. I find it hard to convey my feelings in word. 我觉得难以用言语表达我的感情。 2. Word will suffice to convey his grief. 他的悲伤足以用言辞表达。 3. A vibrating membrane in the ear helps to convey sounds to the brain. 耳膜的振动帮助声音传送到大脑。 4. This train conveys both passengers and goods. 这趟列车客货均载。', '形容词: conveyable 过去式: conveyed 过去分词: conveyed 现在分词: conveying 第三人称单数: conveys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embryonic', '[ˌembri\'ɑːnɪk]', 'adj.胚胎的；萌芽期的', '1. Embryonic stem cells are totipotent. 胚胎干细胞是两性的。 2. Market economy was in its embryonic stages as early as feudalist society. 市场经济，在封建社会时期就有了萌芽。 3. The plan, as yet, only exists in embryonic form. 这个计划迄今为止还只是在酝酿之中。', '副词: embryonically 异体字: embryonal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tribulation', '[ˌtrɪbju\'leɪʃn]', 'n.苦难；灾难', '1. He bore his tribulations bravely. 他勇敢地忍受着困苦。 2. After many trial and tribulation, we finally reach our destination. 经过了许多考验和磨难之后,我们终於到达了目的地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('splurge', '[splɜːrdʒ]', 'n.挥霍；炫耀 v.挥霍；乱花', '1. I had a splurge and bought two new suits. 我大手大脚花了一笔钱买了两套新衣服。 2. The victory meeting should be one without any splurge . 庆功会应该开成一个毫不炫耀摆阔的会。 3. She won 100 and then splurged it all on new clothes. 她赢了100英镑，都挥霍在买新衣服上了。', '形容词: splurgy 过去式: splurged 过去分词: splurged 现在分词: splurging 第三人称单数: splurges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abnegation', '[ˌæbnɪ\'ɡeɪʃn]', 'n.克己；自制；放弃', '1. The convent is supreme egoism having for its result supreme abnegation. 修院表现的是极端的自私，而结果是极端的克己。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unsettle', '[ˌʌn\'setl]', 'v.使(某人)不安或担忧；使动摇', '1. Seafood unsettles my stomach. 我一吃海鲜胃就不舒服。 2. Living alone unsettled his nerves. 他独自生活，情绪很不稳定。 3. More traditional fears also unsettle China\'s neighbours. 还有更多的遗传的恐惧令中国的邻国不安。 4. Nothing can unsettle his resolution. 什么也动摇不了他的决心。', '副词: unsettlingly 名词: unsettlement 过去式: unsettled 过去分词: unsettled 现在分词: unsettling 第三人称单数: unsettles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prate', '[preɪt]', 'v.唠唠叨叨的讲；闲聊 n.唠叨；多嘴；无聊话', '1. Listen to him prating on about nothing. 听他瞎唠叨。 2. Pen walked on, listening to his companion\'s prate, wondering, amused, and puzzled. 潘一路走去，听他同伴喋喋不休，觉得又惊讶有趣，又有些困惑不解。 3. However, his query and pursue have never been a prate. 但他的质问和追索并未因此失于空泛。', '副词: pratingly 名词: prater 过去式: prated 过去分词: prated 现在分词: prating 第三人称单数: prates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gnaw', '[nɔː]', 'v.咬；折磨；侵蚀', '1. Rats gnawed off the lid of the box. 老鼠咬开了盒盖。 2. The rat gnawed a hole through the wall. 耗子在墙上啃了一个洞。 3. These desires gnawed away at us constantly. 这些欲望不断地折磨我们。 4. Self-doubt began to gnaw away at her confidence. 对自己的怀疑渐渐吞噬了她的自信心。', '名词: gnawer 过去式: gnawed 过去分词: gnawed 现在分词: gnawing 第三人称单数: gnaws');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skittish', '[\'skɪtɪʃ]', 'adj.胆小的；易受惊的；轻佻的', '1. The skittish deer was frightened by the hikers. 这只易受惊的鹿被登山客给吓著了。 2. She gets very skittish when her boy-friend is around. 她男朋友在场时，她就显得格外轻佻。', '副词: skittishly 名词: skittishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deft', '[deft]', 'adj.敏捷熟练的；灵巧的', '1. She is deft at dealing with reporters. 她善於与记者周旋。 2. Sister Irene was a tall, deft woman in her early thirties. 艾琳修女是个三十出头、精明能干的高个妇女。 3. With deft fingers she untangled the wire. 她用灵巧的手指解开了金属线。 4. My sister is a clever and deft person who can make pretty dresses. 姐姐是个心灵手巧的人，做的衣服很漂亮。', '副词: deftly 比较级: defter 最高级: deftest 名词: deftness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spatula', '[\'spætʃələ]', 'n.铲；抹刀；压舌片', '1. He scraped the mixture out of the bowl with a plastic spatula. 他用塑料铲把盆里的混合料刮了出来。 2. She levelled the surface of the cake mixture with a metal spatula. 她用金属铲抹平了蛋糕配料。 3. Lightly press down on the omelet with the spatula to seal it together. 轻轻地用抹刀按压鸡蛋卷，使封口更加严密。', '形容词: spatular');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invective', '[ɪn\'vektɪv]', 'n.恶言漫骂；臭骂 adj.漫骂的；恶言的', '1. He retorted the invective on her. 他用恶言讽刺还击她。 2. The gesture infuriated him and he let out a stream of invective. 那种姿态把他激怒了，于是他破口大骂。 3. He had expected criticism but not the invective which greeted his proposal. 他期望迎接他的提议的是批评而不是痛骂。 4. They are full of antagonism as well as invective rhetoric. 文章中充满了尖锐的对立，甚至是谩骂。', '副词: invectively 名词: invectiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irredeemable', '[ˌɪrɪ\'diːməbl]', 'adj.（指政府年金；债券或股票等）不能藉偿还而终止的；（指纸币)不能兑换成硬币的；不能恢复的；不能挽救的', '1. He is an irredeemable optimist. Nothing daunts him. 他就是这麽一个不可救药的乐天派，任何事情都难不倒他。 2. The idea that someone is an irredeemable loss seems incredibly brutal. 说某人无可救药似乎相当残忍。', '副词: irredeemably');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('virtuous', '[\'vɜːrtʃuəs]', 'adj.有品德的；有德行的；贞洁的', '1. She always tried to lead a virtuous life. 她一直想要过一种高洁的生活。 2. My uncle is always proud of having a virtuous wife. 叔叔一直为娶到一位贤德的妻子而骄傲。 3. I do not know if she is virtuous, but she is ugly, and with a woman that is half the battle. 我不知道她以往是否贞洁,但她容貌丑陋,对一个女人来说,这等于大势已定了。', '副词: virtuously 名词: virtuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transplantation', '[ˌtrænzplɑːn\'teɪʃn]', 'n.移植；移植法', '1. Cord blood transplantation is not without risks, however. 然而，脐带血移植也不是毫无风险。 2. Corneal transplantation operation makes the blindman to see again. 角膜移植手术使这位盲人重见光明。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fetter', '[\'fetər]', 'v.为 ... 上脚镣；束缚；限制 n.脚镣；桎梏', '1. He was fettered by his family and could not travel any longer. 他被家庭束缚，不能再到处去旅游了。 2. You may imprison my body, but you could not fetter my mind. 你可以禁锢我的身体，却束缚不了我的心灵。 3. This does not mean that we wish to fetter the trade union movement. 这并不意味着我们想限制工会运动。 4. The prisoner was put into the jail with fetters. 这个犯人被戴上脚镣投进了监狱。', '过去式: fettered 过去分词: fettered 现在分词: fettering 第三人称单数: fetters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insubstantial', '[ˌɪnsəb\'stænʃl]', 'adj.脆弱的；无实体的；非实质的', '1. Finite personalities are insubstantial fragments of this engulfing spiritual unity. 有限的人格是这种兼容并包的精神统一的非实体的碎片。', '名词: insubstantiality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('denunciate', '[dɪ\'nʌnsɪˌeɪt]', 'vt.(=denounce)公开指责；公然抨击；谴责', '1. When this story is seen by internet friends at Zhang\'s blog and some wet sites, thousands of internet friends denunciate their bad behavior. 这个故事被网友在张的博克及一些网站看到后，成千上万的网友指责他们的行为。 2. to denounce; to condemn; to denunciate 声讨', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cohabit', '[koʊ\'hæbɪt]', 'v.同居', '1. She refused to cohabit with him before the wedding. 她拒绝在婚礼前与他同居。 2. They were cohabiting for three years before their marriage. 他们同居了三年才结婚。', '形容词: cohabitational 名词: cohabitant 过去式: cohabited 过去分词: cohabited 现在分词: cohabiting 第三人称单数: cohabits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hem', '[hem]', 'n.褶边 vt.缝边；包围；约束', '1. The hem on her skirt needs sewing. 她裙子上的褶边需要缝一缝。 2. The hem of her dress was stained. 她的礼服的褶边弄脏了。 3. Can you help me to hem the skirt? 你能帮我给裙子缝边吗？ 4. The enemy troops were hemming us in. 敌军把我们包围了。', '名词: hemmer 过去式: hemmed 过去分词: hemmed 现在分词: hemming 第三人称单数: hems');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flippant', '[\'flɪpənt]', 'adj.轻率的；没礼貌的；[古]能说会道的', '1. John was offended by the doctor\'s flippant attitude. 约翰被医生轻率的态度而激怒。 2. He is content to draw the most flippant of morals from the story. 他满足于从故事中引出最轻率的教训。 3. He just gave me a flippant answer. 他漫不经心随口给了我一个答案。 4. She is flippant in her behavior. 她举止轻佻。', '副词: flippantly 名词: flippancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adventitious', '[ˌædven\'tɪʃəs]', 'adj.偶然的；外来的；[生]不定的', '1. The adventitious birth of our fourth child completely changed our plan. 第四个孩子偶然的出生，完全改变了我们的计画。 2. As a successful advertiser , he realized it and advised his boss to catch this adventitious and advantageous chance. 作为一名成功的广告人，维克多认识到这一点并建议他的老板抓住这个外来的有利的时机。', '副词: adventitiously 名词: adventitiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('memoir', '[\'memwɑːr]', 'n.传记；实录 (复数）memoirs: 回忆录；自传；学术论文集.', '1. The president\'s memoir disinterred a past era. 总统的回忆录重现了一个过去的时代。 2. She wrote a memoir of her stay in France. 她写了一篇旅法记事录。 3. At the end of his career in politics, he retired and wrote his memoirs. 他的从政生涯一结束便隐退写起了自己的回忆录。 4. His autobiography, or rather memoirs, is ready for publication. 他的自传，或者说是回忆录，即刻就要出版。', '名词: memoirist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('casual', '[\'kæʒuəl]', 'adj.非正式的；漫不经心的；偶然的；临时的；休闲的 n.便装；临时工', '1. He was wearing casual clothes. 他穿着便服。 2. The plan grew out of a casual conversation. 这个计划出自于一次非正式的谈话。 3. He sidled past, trying to seem casual. 他悄悄地溜了过去,竭力装作漫不经心的样子。 4. She is casual about winning the prize. 她对获奖漫不经心。', '副词: casually 名词: casualness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('derivative', '[dɪ\'rɪvətɪv]', 'n.派生物；衍生字；导数 adj.派生的；(贬)非独创的；庸乏的', '1. They spoke a derivative of the Malay language. 他们说一种从马来语派生的语言。 2. ‘Happiness\' is a derivative of ‘happy\'. happiness 是 happy 的派生词。 3. The derivative of the step is the impulse. 阶梯的导数就是脉冲。 4. Progress in the studies on new derivative atomic spectrometry was reviewed. 摘要本文评介了导数测量技术在原子光谱分析中的应用研究进展。 5. Derivative works are far more complicated. 派生作品更加复杂。', '副词: derivatively 名词: derivativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reckon', '[\'rekən]', 'v.计算；认为；估计', '1. Did you reckon in the cost of the taxi? 你把出租车费算进去了吗？ 2. You should reckon in the cost of fuel. 你应当把燃料费计算在内。 3. They reckon the book as one of his best works. 他们认为这本书是他的优秀作品之一。 4. The news won\'t worry her, I reckon. 我看这消息不会使她不安。', '过去式: reckoned 过去分词: reckoned 现在分词: reckoning 第三人称单数: reckons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oligarchy', '[\'ɑːləɡɑːrki]', 'n.寡头政治；寡头集团；寡头统治的国家', '1. The only secure basis for oligarchy is collectivism. 寡头政体的唯一可靠基础是集体主义。 2. The financial oligarchy is the real ruler of capitalist monopolies. 金融寡头是垄断资本主义的真正统治者。', '形容词: oligarchic 名词复数: oligarchies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infatuation', '[ɪnˌfætʃu\'eɪʃn]', 'n.迷恋', '1. His infatuation with her lasted six months. 他对她迷恋了半年。 2. He finally recovered from an absurd infatuation. 他终于从荒唐的迷恋中醒悟过来。 3. This is only a passing infatuation, not to be taken too seriously. 这仅仅是一时的恋情，不必过於认真。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('penumbra', '[pə\'nʌmbrə]', 'n.半阴影；边缘部分', '1. Vaapad is a path that leads through the penumbra of the dark side. 瓦帕德就是一条游走于明暗面之间的道路。', '形容词: penumbral 名词复数: penumbrae');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('collaborate', '[kə\'læbəreɪt]', 'vi.合作；通敌', '1. She collaborated with her sister/She and her sister collaborated on a biography of their father. 她和姐姐合作写父亲的传记。 2. We would ask you to collaborate with us. 我们愿意请你们和我们合作。 3. This supplier and I collaborate on certain points. 我与供应商有数方面或以上的合作。', '形容词: collaborative 名词: collaboration 过去式: collaborated 过去分词: collaborated 现在分词: collaborating 第三人称单数: collaborates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('continent', '[\'kɒntɪnənt]', 'n.大陆；洲；(the Continent)欧洲大陆', '1. The discovery of the new continent is usually referred to Columbus. 人们通常认为新大陆是哥伦布发现的。 2. There are seven continents in the world. 世界上有七大洲。 3. Asia is the largest continent on Earth. 亚洲是地球上最大的洲。 4. Many people embark at Dover for the Continent. 许多前往欧洲大陆的人都在多佛搭船。', '副词: continently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jostle', '[\'dʒɑːsl]', 'v.推；挤；争夺；争抢 n.推；撞；挤', '1. The youths jostled against an old lady on the pavement. 那些青年人在人行道上推推搡搡挤着了一个老太太。 2. The advertisers are jostling for the public\'s attention. 广告商们竞相吸引公众的注意力。', '名词: jostler 过去式: jostled 过去分词: jostled 现在分词: jostling 第三人称单数: jostles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('engaging', '[ɪn\'ɡeɪdʒɪŋ]', 'adj.动人的；迷人的；有魅力的 动词engage的现在分词.', '1. Her kindness, recommended by so pretty a face, was engaging. 她那可爱的脸蛋上浮泛的善意是动人的。 2. A person engaging in the activity of programming is referred to as a programmer. 动人的在规画的活动中的一个人被称为一个程序师。 3. Many people were attracted by her engaging smile. 许多人被她迷人的微笑所吸引了。 4. They are engaging in a duel of words. 他们双方在斗嘴。', '副词: engagingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pervade', '[pər\'veɪd]', 'vt.弥漫；遍及；蔓延', '1. The smell of baked apple pies pervaded the house. 房子里弥漫着烤苹果馅饼的香味。 2. We are all pervaded with a sense of disaster. 我们普遍有大祸降临的感觉。 3. Her work is pervaded by nostalgia for a past age. 她的作品充满了怀旧之情。 4. Revolutionary ideas pervaded the whole land. 革命思想遍及全国。', '名词: pervader 过去式: pervaded 过去分词: pervaded 现在分词: pervading 第三人称单数: pervades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vestige', '[\'vestɪdʒ]', 'n.丝毫；遗迹；痕迹；退化的器官', '1. There is not a vestige of truth in the report. 该报告毫无真实性。 2. There had not a vestige of the abbey remains. 修道院的遗迹已荡然无存。 3. Some upright stones in wild place are the vestige of ancient religion. 荒原上一些直立的石块是古老宗教的遗迹。 4. Every vestige has been swept away. 一切痕迹都被一扫而光。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ornithology', '[ˌɔːrnɪ\'θɑːlədʒi]', 'n.鸟类学', '1. He found his vocation in ornithology. 他发现自己适于专攻鸟类学。', '形容词: ornithologic 副词: ornithologically 名词: ornithologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('daredevil', '[\'derdevl]', 'adj.蛮勇的 n.鲁莽大胆的人；冒失的人', '1. Don\'t try any of those daredevil stunts. 不要耍那些天不怕地不怕的绝招. 2. Why does David do these daredevil deeds? 为什么戴维做出这些胆大妄为的事情？ 3. He\'s a daredevil on the racing-track. 他在跑道上十分胆大鲁莽。 4. The 45-year-old daredevil was taken into custody at the top. 这名45岁的猛男在楼顶被逮捕。', '名词: daredevilry');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('encomium', '[en\'koʊmiəm]', 'n.赞颂；颂辞', '1. He pronounced a splendid encomium upon her in the forum. 他在广场上为她作了华丽的赞颂。', '名词复数: encomiums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tread', '[tred]', 'n.步法；踏面；胎面花纹；鞋底 v.踩；行走；践踏；(鸟类)交配', '1. We heard his heavy tread on the staircase. 我们听到了他走在楼梯上沉重的脚步声。 2. We would hear the heavy, monotonous tread of the approaching bull. 我们能听到越来越近的公牛那沉重单调的蹄音。 3. Check your tire pressure and tread. 经常检查轮胎气压和胎面。 4. Driving with worn tread(s) can be dangerous. 轮胎胎面磨损的汽车开著有危险。 5. The cattle had trodden a path to the pond. 牛群踩出了一条通往池塘的小径。', '形容词: treadless 过去式: trod 过去分词: trodden/trod 现在分词: treading 第三人称单数: treads');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('convex', '[\'kɒnveks]', 'adj.中凸的；凸圆的；凸面的 n.凸状；凸面体；凸透镜', '1. Light can be collected with the convex. 凸透镜具有聚集光线的作用。 2. A convex lens is used to concentrate rays of light. 凸透镜用于聚集光线。', '副词: convexly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('espy', '[e\'spaɪ]', 'v.(从远处等)突然看到；窥见', '1. In all this serenity of ocean it is seldom that we espy so much as another ship. 在这一片无比宁静的大海上，我们就连一艘其他的船只也难得见到。 2. The Imperial Palace noted the history. There\'re many antiques which we could espy the great culture. 故宫记录着中国的历史。我们可以通过如此多的古物看到中国伟大的文化。', '过去式: espied 过去分词: espied 现在分词: espying 第三人称单数: espies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impunity', '[ɪm\'pjuːnəti]', 'n.不受惩罚；免罚', '1. One cannot commit crimes with impunity. 一个人不能犯了罪不受惩罚。 2. The days of impunity seem to be over. 免受惩罚的日子似乎已经完结。', '名词复数: impunities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ironclad', '[\'aɪərnklæd]', 'adj.坚固的；装铁甲的 n.铁甲舰', '1. A series of ironclad facts put him to silence. 一系列铁的事实驳得他哑口无言。 2. Actually, these selection rules are not ironclad. 实际上,这些选择规则并不是严格的。 3. Their epithetic lies can not cover ironclad fact. 伪善的谎言掩盖不了铁的事实。 4. That is an ironclad fact that is beyond controversy. 这是铁的事实，无庸置辩。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insolent', '[\'ɪnsələnt]', 'adj.粗野的；无礼的；厚颜的；无耻的', '1. My boss is so rude and insolent that I can\'t do with him. 我的老板是那样的粗野无礼，叫我无法忍受。 2. He was insolent in his manner. 他态度傲慢无礼。 3. It was insolent of them to demand special treatment. 他们要求给予特殊待遇,脸皮真厚。', '副词: insolently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('protest', '[\'proʊtest]', 'n.抗议；反对 v.抗议；反对；申明；断言', '1. Half a million people held a mass protest against racism last night. 昨晚50万人举行了大规模的抗议活动反对种族歧视。 2. Some delegates walked out in a show of protest. 有几位代表退出会场以示抗议。 3. The minister resigned in protest against the decision. 这位部长为反对那项决策而辞职。 4. They protested to the mayor that the taxes were too high. 他们向市长提出抗议说税款过高。', '副词: protestingly 名词: protester 过去式: protested 过去分词: protested 现在分词: protesting 第三人称单数: protests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nicotine', '[\'nɪkətiːn]', 'n.尼古丁', '1. Smokers who inhale are likely to become addicted to nicotine. 吸烟的人容易对尼古丁上瘾。 2. When people smoke, the nicotine goes right into the blood stream. 当人们抽烟时，尼古丁就直接进入血液之中。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('savvy', '[\'sævi]', 'v.理解 n.理解能力；悟性；常识 adj.机智的；有常识的', '1. Keep your mouth shut! Savvy? 闭上嘴! 懂吗? 2. He is a banker known for financial savvy. 作为一名银行家,他以精通金融著称。 3. My daugther has a good savvy in music. 我女儿在音乐上很有悟性。 4. To make our citizenry more savvy in general knowledge and current affairs will take time and sustained efforts. 要培养新加坡人对时事和常识的认识，需要时间和长期的努力。', '副词: savvily 比较级: savvier 最高级: savviest 过去式: savvied 过去分词: savvied 现在分词: savvying 第三人称单数: savvies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anthropoid', '[\'ænθrəpɔɪd]', 'adj.像人类的；类人猿的', '1. Man evolved from the anthropoid ape. 人是从类人猿进化而来的。 2. The gorilla is the strongest of the anthropoid animals. 大猩猩是最强的类人猿动物。', '形容词: anthropoidal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wink', '[wɪŋk]', 'n.眨眼；使眼色；瞬间 v.眨眼；使眼色；闪烁', '1. She did not understand the significance of my wink. 她没有领会我眨眼的意思。 2. He tipped me the wink not to buy at that price. 他眨眼暗示我按那个价格就不要买。 3. I\'ll tip you the wink when it\'s safe to come in. 可以安全进来时，我会向你使眼色的。 4. Then in the wink of an eye, the eight old men all turn into five- or six-year-old children. 说着,八位老者一眨眼工夫,忽然全变成五六岁的儿童了。 5. She winked at me. 她向我眨眼。', '过去式: winked 过去分词: winked 现在分词: winking 第三人称单数: winks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concise', '[kən\'saɪs]', 'adj.简明的；简要的', '1. His article is concise and comprehensive. 他的文章言简意赅。 2. I like the new concise dictionary very much. 我很喜欢这部新的简明词典。 3. I gave a concise answer to this. 我对于此事给了一个简要的答复。 4. He gave a concise and firm summary of our position. 他扼要而坚定地阐述了我方的立场。', '副词: concisely 名词: conciseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rampage', '[\'ræmpeɪdʒ]', 'n.暴怒；狂暴行为 v.狂暴地乱冲', '1. He went on the rampage after an argument with his wife. 与他妻子争吵之后,他暴跳如雷。 2. The capture tiger is on the rampage for several days. 捕获的老虎几天来一直处于狂躁不安中。 3. We must fight a global war to control this mosquito rampage. 我们必须在全球范围内展开这场控制虫害的战争。 4. The mob rampaged through the village. 这伙暴徒在村中横冲直撞。', '名词: rampager 过去式: rampaged 过去分词: rampaged 现在分词: rampaging 第三人称单数: rampages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indifferent', '[ɪn\'dɪfrənt]', 'adj.漠不关心的；无关紧要的；平凡的；中立的', '1. He is indifferent to the result of the exam. 他对考试结果漠不关心。 2. She seems indifferent, but deep down she\'s very pleased. 她貌似无动於衷，其实心里非常高兴。 3. Many one or little one is indifferent to me. 多一个或少一个对我是无关紧要的。 4. It was utterly indifferent to her who he was. 封她来说，他是谁，根本是无关紧要的事。', '副词: indifferently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cow', '[kaʊ]', 'n.母牛；雌象；雌鲸；雌犀牛；<俚><贬>女人 v.恐吓', '1. The cow has produced a calf. 这母牛生了一头小牛。 2. Do you know how to milk a cow? 你知道怎么挤牛奶吗？ 3. I\'m sure it was deliberately done to cow us. 我确信,这一事件经过精心策划,目的是恐吓我们。', '形容词: cowy 副词: cowedly 过去式: cowed 过去分词: cowed 现在分词: cowing 第三人称单数: cows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hedge', '[hedʒ]', 'n.树篱；篱笆；障碍；防护物；套期保值；推诿 v.用树篱围；避免直接回答；两面下注', '1. They managed to wriggle their way through the thick hedge. 他们设法钻过了厚厚的树篱。 2. There is an opening in the hedge. 这篱笆上有个洞。 3. There is a hedge of spectators along the sidewalk. 沿着人行道形成了一道观众障碍。 4. Buying a house is the best hedge against inflation. 购买房子是防止通货膨胀的最佳保障。 5. Mr. Green began to hedge his courtyard in last year. 去年格林先生开始把他的庭院用篱笆围起来。', '形容词: hedgy 名词: hedger 过去式: hedged 过去分词: hedged 现在分词: hedging 第三人称单数: hedges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abridge', '[ə\'brɪdʒ]', 'v.删节；缩短；限制', '1. He decide to abridge his stay here after he receive a letter from home. 他接到家信后决定缩短在这里的逗留时间。 2. This is an abridged edition of \"war and peace\". 这是“战争与和平”的节略版。 3. It was abridged from the original work. 这是原书的节录本。', '名词: abridger 过去式: abridged 过去分词: abridged 现在分词: abridging 第三人称单数: abridges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adulate', '[\'ædʒəˌleɪt]', 'vt.奉承；谄媚', '1. They are fools who adulate every decision of their leaders. 对领导的每个决定一味奉承的人是蠢材。', '形容词: adulatory 名词: adulator 过去式: adulated 过去分词: adulated 现在分词: adulating 第三人称单数: adulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prudent', '[\'pruːdnt]', 'adj.谨慎的；有远见的；精明的', '1. Young as he was, he was prudent. 他虽然如此年轻，却很慎重。 2. We should be modest and prudent. 我们应该谦虚谨慎。 3. Prudent man always fits his standard of living to his budget. 谨慎的人总是使他的生活水平符合他的收支预算。 4. It\'s prudent to take a thick coat in cold weather when you go out. 在寒冷的天气下外出时带上件厚外套是谨慎的。', '副词: prudently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('simper', '[\'sɪmpər]', 'v.傻笑；假笑；傻笑着说 n.傻笑；假笑', '1. They leer, they simper at her shame: Gay. 他们斜视着这个乞丐；他在别人的斜视中抬起了头。 2. High bright-ness,small volume,and simper. 超高亮度，体积小，更简约。 3. How long should we simper like this? 我们还要像这样傻笑多久？ 4. They leer , they simper at her shame: Gay. 他们斜视着这个乞丐；他在别人的斜视中抬起了头。', '副词: simperingly 名词: simperer 过去式: simpered 过去分词: simpered 现在分词: simpering 第三人称单数: simpers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('balmy', '[\'bɑːmi]', 'adj.芳香的；温和的；<俚>疯狂的；古怪的', '1. We can still spray appropriately balmy agent or deodorant. 我们还可适当喷洒芳香剂或除臭剂。 2. The air was warm and balmy. 天气温暖宜人。 3. This balmy weather is a herald of spring. 这种温和的天气是春天的预兆。 4. I’m sure the neighbours must have thought I was balmy yelling about shoes! 我敢说邻居们一定以为我是在冲鞋子大吼大叫呢！', '副词: balmily 比较级: balmier 最高级: balmiest 名词: balminess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('installment', '[ɪn\'stɔːlmənt]', 'n.分期付款；部分；分册 n.安装；安置', '1. We will pay for houses by monthly installments. 我们将按月分期付款买房。 2. Buy goods on the installment plan has become epidemic in recent year. 近几年来，用分期付款的办法购物十分流行。 3. The last installment will be split into two movies. 故事的最后一部分将会拍成两部电影。 4. The installment of the new system took an hour. 安装新系统花了一个小时。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prepossessing', '[ˌpriːpə\'zesɪŋ]', 'adj.给人良好印象的；有魅力的 动词prepossess的现在分词形式.', '1. Clean clothes and good manners are prepossessing. 清洁的衣服和良好的举止能给人以好感。 2. He was not a prepossessing sight. 他长相不怎么样。 3. The appearance of Frank Cowperwood at this time was, to say the least, prepossessing and satisfactory. 法兰克·柯帕乌这个时候的相貌,至少是讨人欢喜,令人满意的。', '副词: prepossessingly 名词: prepossessingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hallucination', '[həˌluːsɪ\'neɪʃn]', 'n.幻觉；幻想', '1. High temperatures can cause hallucination. 高烧可使人产生幻觉。 2. An hallucination began to trouble him. 一种幻觉开始折磨他。 3. It is a collective hallucination. 这是一种群体的幻想。', '形容词: hallucinational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spite', '[spaɪt]', 'n.恶意；怨恨 v.刁难；惹怒；冒犯', '1. I\'m sure he took my parking space just out of spite. 我认为他侵占我的停车位肯定是有意和我作对。 2. They trampled his flowers out of spite. 他们出于恶意踩了他的花。 3. There is no gall or spite in my soul. 我内心对谁都没有怨恨或恶意。 4. He took my best toy just out of spite! 他仅仅出于怨恨拿走了我最好的玩具！ 5. The bad children left the room dirty to spite their maid. 那些坏孩子把房间弄脏来刁难女佣人。', '过去式: spited 过去分词: spited 现在分词: spiting 第三人称单数: spites');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bureaucracy', '[bjʊ\'rɑːkrəsi]', 'n.官僚制度；官僚主义；官僚', '1. All this is a product of corrupt bureaucracy. 这一切都是腐朽的官僚制度的产物。 2. The bureaucracy has become ossified. 官僚主义已变得僵化了。 3. The dead hand of bureaucracy is slowing our progress. 官僚主义的流毒拖慢了我们的进步。 4. You will find a lot of bureaucracy in this company. 你会在这个公司看到很严重的官僚作风。', '名词复数: bureaucracies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irrigate', '[\'ɪrɪɡeɪt]', 'vi.进行灌溉 vt.灌溉；[医]冲洗', '1. They are irrigating with water. 他们正用水灌溉土地。 2. We have irrigated the desert area to make it fertile. 我们已经灌溉了荒芜地区使它肥沃。 3. They have built canals to irrigate the desert. 他们建造成水渠以灌溉沙漠。 4. They irrigate their crops with water from this river. 他们引这条河里的水灌溉庄稼。', '形容词: irrigational 名词: irrigation 过去式: irrigated 过去分词: irrigated 现在分词: irrigating 第三人称单数: irrigates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consensus', '[kən\'sensəs]', 'n.一致；同意；共识', '1. The two parties have reached a consensus. 这两个政党达成了一致意见。 2. It would be a good idea to predict which proposal is most likely to achieve consensus. 不妨研究一下哪项提案最有可能获得一致同意。 3. Yet the events of the past two years have called that consensus in question. 然而,过去两年来发生的各种事件使人们对这一共识产生了疑虑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('burgeon', '[\'bɜːrdʒən]', 'v.发芽；萌芽；迅速发展 n.芽；嫩枝', '1. Seeds begin to burgeon at the commencement of spring. 春天来临时种子开始发芽。 2. In these days the oaks shall burn in the forest glades, and acorns shall burgeon on the lime trees\' boughs. 在那些日子里，橡树会在林间空地里燃烧，橡子会在酸橙树的主枝上萌芽。 3. She burgeoned into a fine actress. 她迅速成长为一名优秀的女演员。 4. We hope that the festival will burgeon out slowly but steadily. 我们希望这欢乐的日子将逐步稳定的发展下去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hobble', '[\'hɑːbl]', 'v.蹒跚；跛行 n.蹒跚', '1. This may hobble the bull in the future. 这些可能会使得这头牛在未来步履蹒跚。 2. The old man hobbled along (the road) with the aid of his stick. 那老汉拄著拐杖一瘸一拐地走著。 3. I hurt my foot,and had to hobble home. 我的脚受了伤，只好一拐一拐地走回家。', '名词: hobbler 过去式: hobbled 过去分词: hobbled 现在分词: hobbling 第三人称单数: hobbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deterioration', '[dɪˌtɪriə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.恶化；退化；变坏', '1. This sped the deterioration of health. 这加速健康日益恶化。 2. The deterioration of soil structure is difficult to remedy. 土壤结构的恶化很难挽回。 3. I definitely felt a deterioration in vigor. 我自感体力已退化了。 4. The food undergoes no deterioration in the tropics. 这种食品在热带地方不会变质。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('facet', '[\'fæsɪt]', 'n.小平面；方面；刻面', '1. They beat us in every facet of the game. 他们在比赛的每个小层面都打败了我们。 2. He has perfected himself in every facet of his job. 他已使自己对工作的各个方面都得心应手。 3. Locomotion is merely one facet of action. 移动只是行动的一个方面而已。 4. Being a well-paid business woman is only one facet of her life. 高薪阶层职业妇女的身份只是她生活的一个方面。', '形容词: faceted');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illustrate', '[\'ɪləstreɪt]', 'vt.说明；（为书）作插图；图解 vi.举例说明；发亮', '1. He pointed at the diagram to illustrate his point. 他指着图表来说明他的论点。 2. In this section, I\'ll illustrate some of these differences. 在这一节,我将举例说明一些不同之处。 3. Our textbook is very well illustrated. 我们的课本插图丰富。 4. This chart is used to illustrate all the changes. 这张图片用来解释所有的变化。', '形容词: illustratable 名词: illustrator 过去式: illustrated 过去分词: illustrated 现在分词: illustrating 第三人称单数: illustrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('restore', '[rɪ\'stɔːr]', 'vt.恢复；归还；复原', '1. The military government promised to restore democracy within one year. 军人政府答应在一年内重新建立民主体制。 2. Drastic measures will have to be taken to restore order. 为恢复秩序必须采取严厉措施。 3. The police must try to restore order. 警方必须努力恢复治安。 4. The new manager\'s job is to restore the company to profitability. 新经理的工作是让这家公司能恢复盈利状况。', '名词: restorer 过去式: restored 过去分词: restored 现在分词: restoring 第三人称单数: restores');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nonviable', '[nɒn\'vaɪəbəl]', 'adj.不能生长发育的；不可行的', '1. Premature expulsion of a nonviable fetus from the uterus. 流产不能成活的胎儿过早地从子宫中分娩出来 2. All nonviable tissue, both osseous and soft tissue, should be removed. 所有无活性的组织，包括骨组织和软组织，都应清除。 3. Abortion is defined as termination of pregnancy resulting in expulsion of an immature, nonviable fetus. 妊娠终止导致未成熟的、无法成活的胎儿被排出体外称为流产。 4. The survey commissioned by the Dutch government reports that doctors now kill about 15 nonviable newborns a year. 荷兰政府授权进行的那项调查表明，目前医生每年大约要处死15个不能存活的新生儿。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gadget', '[\'ɡædʒɪt]', 'n.小机件；小玩意儿；小巧的机械', '1. This gadget can perform many different functions. 这种机器具有多种功能。 2. The gadget will lighten the goods you burden. 这个装置会减轻你背负货物的重量。 3. The gadget is simply marvelous! 这玩意儿简直好极了！ 4. This gadget isn\'t much good. 这小机械没什么用处。', '副词: gadgety');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expedient', '[ɪk\'spiːdiənt]', 'adj.权宜的；有用的 n.权宜之计；临时手段', '1. Einstein found it expedient to use in the creation of his theories. 爱因斯坦发现这种本性在他理论的创建中是有用的。 2. It was expedient to retire gracefully. 体面的让步可算是权宜之计。 3. But that would be crassly expedient. 但那将是一个愚蠢的权宜之计。', '副词: expediently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inundate', '[\'ɪnʌndeɪt]', 'v.浸水；向泛滥；淹没', '1. Police say rescue officials are worried that water from a choked river could inundate towns near the epicenter. 警方称救援人员担心堵塞的河流一旦决堤将会淹没震中附近地区的乡镇。 2. The course changes frequently, and the area is so flat that a small change in the level of the river may inundate a considerable area. 河道变化多端，下游地区却很平坦，水位少许上涨河流就会淹没一大片土地。', '形容词: inundatory 名词: inundation 过去式: inundated 过去分词: inundated 现在分词: inundating 第三人称单数: inundates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grovel', '[\'ɡrɑːvl]', 'v.趴；匍匐；卑躬屈膝', '1. Then he began to grovel and wail, \"I deserve to die!\" 这时他趴倒在地嚎叫道“我该死”。 2. You will just have to grovel to the bank manager for a loan. 你只得低声下气地向银行经理借贷。 3. We\'ll never grovel at the feet of the conqueror. 我们永远不会向征服者屈膝。', '副词: grovelingly 名词: groveler 过去式: groveled/grovelled 过去分词: groveled/grovelled 现在分词: groveling/grovelling 第三人称单数: grovels/grovels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reverberate', '[rɪ\'vɜːbəreɪt]', 'v.回响；反响；反射', '1. The room reverberated with the noise of the shot. 房间里回响著枪声。 2. The roar of the train reverberated in the tunnel. 火车的轰隆声在隧道里回荡。 3. Echoes of cries of pain reverberate my heart. 痛苦喊叫的回声在我心中回荡。 4. The white walls of the house coldly reverberate the lunar radiance. 粉白的墙冷冷地反射着月亮的清辉。', '名词: reverberator 过去式: reverberated 过去分词: reverberated 现在分词: reverberating 第三人称单数: reverberates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('caucus', '[\'kɔːkəs]', 'n.干部会议；政党高层会议 vi.开干部会议', '1. To assemble in or hold a caucus. 召集干部会议，召开干部会议 2. To assemble or canvass(members of a caucus). 集合选票，拉选票集合或拉（组织委员会成员）选票 3. It kept the Democratic caucus from fragmenting. 它也使得民主党的核心小组避免了土崩瓦解的危险。 4. In Maine, the Republican Party is holding a caucus. 在美国缅因州，共和党团会议的投票活动正在如火如荼地开展。', '名词复数: caucuses 过去式: caucused/caucussed 过去分词: caucused/caucussed 现在分词: caucusing/caucussing 第三人称单数: caucuses/caucusses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('architect', '[\'ɑːrkɪtekt]', 'n.建筑师 n.【喻】缔造者；创造者', '1. He is known as a successful architect. 他以成功的建筑师闻名。 2. The author of the guidebook is an architect by profession. 该旅行指南的作者任职建筑师。 3. The architect was given/presented with a blank cheque to design a new city centre. 设计师被授予全权设计一个新的城市中心区。 4. He was one of the architects of the republic. 他是这个共和国的缔造者之一。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harsh', '[hɑːrʃ]', 'adj.粗糙的；严厉的，严酷的；刺耳的；使人不舒服的；大约的', '1. Yorke himself has a harsh face. 约克本人长着张粗糙的脸。 2. The punishment was too harsh for him. 这种惩罚对他来说太严厉了。 3. He had deliberately made his voice harsh. 他故意嘶哑着嗓门。', '副词: harshly 比较级: harsher 最高级: harshest 名词: harshness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nominal', '[\'nɑːmɪnl]', 'adj.名义上的；象征性的；名词性的 n.名词词组', '1. He is only the nominal head of the country. 他只是那个国家名义上的元首。 2. He remained in nominal control of the business for another ten years. 他名义上又掌管了这家公司十年。 3. She charged only a nominal fee for her work. 她为所做的工作只收取象征性的费用。 4. Such a nominal phrase mainly acts as the subject or object in a sentence. 这样的名词性词组在句子中主要充当主语和宾语。', '副词: nominally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slippage', '[\'slɪpɪdʒ]', 'n.下滑；滑移；动力传动损耗', '1. Such slight slippage does not constitute a trend. 这样轻微的下滑不会构成趋势。 2. Another consideration is slippage, which might occur at a clamp or joint. 另外一个要考虑的问题是滑移。滑移可能产生于夹紧或联结处。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tally', '[\'tæli]', 'n.帐；记分；一致；标签 vt.计算；记录；使一致 vi.计算；记分；一致', '1. Don\'t forget to keep a careful tally of what you spend. 别忘了仔细记下你的开支帐目。 2. You can buy on tally in this shop. 在这家商店里可以赊购。 3. He added to his tally in the last minute. 他在比赛最后一分钟又得了分。 4. All the figures tally with the projected total. 合计和预算的总额一致。 5. The tally of computation and observation is in a good agreement. 将计算值与实测资料比较，结果表明符合程度良好。 6. The tally of computation and observation is in a good agreement. 将计算值与实测资料比较，结果表明符合程度良好。', '名词复数: tallies 过去式: tallied 过去分词: tallied 现在分词: tallying 第三人称单数: tallies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gazetteer', '[ˌɡæzə\'tɪr]', 'n.地名辞典；公报作者；新闻记者', '1. The entire \"Geographia\" is the first atlas and gazetteer. 全部《地理学》可说是第一本地图集和地名辞典。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expository', '[ɪk\'spɑːzətɔːri]', 'adj.说明的；解释的 =expositive.', '1. His language at such points generally seems to be explainable primarily in terms of his expository objectives. 在这点上他的语言似乎对于所解释的对象是解说性的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revive', '[rɪ\'vaɪv]', 'vt.使重生；恢复精神；唤醒 vi.复生', '1. We tried to revive him but without avail. 我们试图使他苏醒,但没有成功。 2. The flowers will revive in water. 这些花在水中会再活。 3. Revive your spirit and add shine to your hair. 重振你的精神，给你的头发增添光亮。 4. We need something to revive our hopes. 我们需要一些什么东西来重新恢复我们的希望。', '形容词: revivable 名词: reviver 过去式: revived 过去分词: revived 现在分词: reviving 第三人称单数: revives');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abjure', '[əb\'dʒʊr]', 'v.发誓弃绝；公开放弃', '1. They were compelled to abjure their faith. 他们被迫发誓放弃自己的信仰。 2. The conqueror tried to make the natives abjure their religion. 征服者试著让当地人宣誓放弃他们的宗教。 3. Second, I am not stating that the US should abjure action forever. 其次，我没有说美国应当永远不采取行动。 4. THESEUS Either to die the death, or to abjure For ever the society of men. 忒修斯：不是受死刑，便是永远和男人隔绝。因此，美丽的赫米娅，仔细问一问你自己的心愿吧！', '名词: abjuration 过去式: abjured 过去分词: abjured 现在分词: abjuring 第三人称单数: abjures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surrogate', '[\'sɜːrəɡət]', 'n.代理人；代用品；代孕者 adj.替代的', '1. I do not know if your company has surrogate in our country. 我不知道贵公司在我国是否有代理。 2. In addition, the patient or surrogate may correct any historical misinformation at this time. 病人或代诉者还可在此时纠正病史中的一些错误信息。 3. Fiction is a poor surrogate for real experience. 小说中的事远逊于实际体验。 4. The youngest child of Michael Jackson was borned by a surrogate. 迈克尔杰克逊最小的孩子是由一位代孕母亲所生的。 5. She saw him as a sort of surrogate father. 在她心目中，他仿佛是能替代父亲角色的人。', '过去式: surrogated 过去分词: surrogated 现在分词: surrogating 第三人称单数: surrogates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('undesirable', '[ˌʌndɪ\'zaɪərəbl]', 'adj.不受欢迎的；不良的；不合意的；讨厌的 n.不受欢迎的人；不良分子', '1. Big cuts in education are very undesirable. 教育经费的大幅度削减是极不受欢迎的。 2. She is declared an undesirable alien and deport. 她被宣布是不受欢迎的外国人并被驱逐出境。 3. The drug has no undesirable side-effects. 这种药没有什么不良的副作用。 4. Basically apply to the dysmenorrhoea patient with uterine undesirable development. 主要适用于子宫发育不良的痛经患者。 5. Big cuts in education are very undesirable. 教育经费的大幅度削减是极不受欢迎的。', '副词: undesirably 名词: undesirability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verdict', '[\'vɜːrdɪkt]', 'n.裁决；定论', '1. The jury announced their verdict. 陪审团做出了裁决。 2. The jury brought in a verdict of guilty. 陪审团作出有罪的裁决。 3. \"A science fiction cannot not be regarded as a mere entertainment, but in fact it tells the reader much more.\" \"科幻小说不能简单地看成是供消遣的，而实际上它给读者展示更深刻的内容。\" 4. They have had the verdict of the electors. 他们已经知道了选举人的决定。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fraudulent', '[\'frɔːdʒələnt]', 'adj.欺诈的；不正的；不诚实的', '1. This geographic split could be a serious problem for Mexico, if any strife develops in the south over the perception that the election was fraudulent. 假如南方对选举存在欺诈的看法的争吵不断升级，这种地域分歧会成为墨西哥的严重问题。', '副词: fraudulently 名词: fraudulence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cherubic', '[tʃə\'ruːbɪk]', 'adj.天使般的；无邪的；可爱的', '1. The cherubic feather falls in my front. 天使的羽毛降落在我的面前。 2. In appearance, Donahue was stocky, and had a cherubic face which made him look younger than the forty-nine he was. 唐纳休身材短粗，有一张娃娃脸，看上去比他四十九岁的年龄要年轻一些。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indices', '[\'ɪndɪsiːz]', 'n.目录；指数；符号；指示器；参见号 名词index的复数。.', '1. Paraffins have high diesel indices. 链烷烃的柴油指数最高。 2. Unweighted indices are simple arithmetic or geometric averages. 不加权的指数指简单算术平均或几何平均数。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('weird', '[wɪrd]', 'adj.离奇的；古怪的；怪异的 n.命运；预言者', '1. He looks like nothing on earth in those weird clothes. 他穿著奇装异服难看极了。 2. Jane, I found that guy somewhat weird. 珍妮, 我发觉那家伙有点古怪。 3. That was really a weird movie. 那部电影真怪异! 4. I heard weird shrieks in the darkness. 我在黑暗中听到奇怪的尖叫声。', '副词: weirdly 比较级: weirder 最高级: weirdest 名词: weirdness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heterodox', '[\'hetərədɑːks]', 'adj.异端的；非正统的', '1. His opinions have always been distinctly heterodox. 他的观点时常带有明显的异端色彩。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petition', '[pə\'tɪʃn]', 'n.请愿书；祈求；申请 vi.请愿；祈求 vt.向 ... 请愿，请求', '1. Many subscribers\' names are in the petition. 请愿书上有很多签名者的名字。 2. They signed a petition in support of the workers\' demands. 他们在请愿书上签名，支持工人的请求。 3. She made a silent petition to God for help. 她默默地祈求上帝给予帮助。 4. She filed a petition for divorce. 她提出了离婚申请。 5. I can petition for Junie\'s custody. 我可以申请做琼妮的监护人。 6. She petitioned her neighbor to turn down the radio. 她请求邻居把收音机关小点声。', '形容词: petitionary 名词: petitioner 过去式: petitioned 过去分词: petitioned 现在分词: petitioning 第三人称单数: petitions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lobe', '[loʊb]', 'n.圆形突出部；耳垂；裂片', '1. Senator Kennedy\'s *(tumor) is the left *(parietal) lobe of brain. 肯尼迪的肿瘤在大脑左边顶骨的圆形突出处。 2. Mike wants to get his lobe lanced. 迈克想在耳垂上穿个孔。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compound', '[\'kɑːmpaʊnd]', 'n.化合物；复合词；复合物 n.院子(用围墙圈起来的场地） adj.化合的；【语】（词语等）复合的；【植】复合的；【动】群体的 vt.混合；调合；使严重；私了；【经】以复利计算 vi.妥协', '1. Water is a compound of hydrogen and oxygen. 水是氢和氧的化合物。 2. \'Bus conductor\', \'dark-haired\' and \'policeman\' are compounds. bus conductor,dark-haired和policeman都是复合词。 3. Medicines are usually compounds. 药品通常是复合物。 4. All prisoners were frog-marched (out) into the compound. 犯人都被迫反剪双臂(出来)进入院子。 5. \"Fingerprint\" is a compound word. “Fingerprint”（指纹）是一个复合词。 6. He compounded various ingredients into an effective drug. 他将各种成分混合成一种有效的药物。 7. He compounded with his creditors for a remission of what he owed. 他和他的债权人谈妥免除其债务。', '形容词: compoundable 名词: compounder 过去式: compounded 过去分词: compounded 现在分词: compounding 第三人称单数: compounds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('phony', '[\'foʊniː]', 'adj.假的；伪造的；欺骗的 n.假货；赝品；骗子 suf.表声音', '1. The Miss Blogger champion is a phony. 博客小姐的冠军是假的。 2. Surprisingly, several of the 100 Yuan bank notes were phony. 这几张百元大钞竟然是假的。 3. He is using a phony credit card. 他使用的是伪造的信用卡。 4. That pint-sized, phony Flutemaster and his annoying friends are back on the Pirate Ship. 那个小骗子魔笛手，还有他那些讨厌的朋友们又回到了海盗船。', '副词: phonily 名词: phoniness 名词复数: phonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cinder', '[\'sɪndər]', 'n.煤渣；灰烬', '1. Clear out yesterday\'s cinders before you make the fire. 生火前先把昨天的炉渣清除干净。 2. At least 50,000 acres have been burnt to a cinder. 至少五万亩土地被烧成焦土。', '形容词: cindery 过去式: cindered 过去分词: cindered 现在分词: cindering 第三人称单数: cinders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corpuscle', '[\'kɔːrpʌsl]', 'n.血球；活细胞；微粒', '1. From the blood corpuscle count we can see that the ill man\'s red corpuscles of the blood are not enough for his healthy need. 从血球计算中我们可以看出这个病人的红血球不能满足身体的需要。', '形容词: corpuscular');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('languid', '[\'læŋɡwɪd]', 'adj.不活泼的；无精打采的；迟缓的', '1. The incredible summer heat and humidity made us all feel languid. 夏天超乎想像的热气与湿度让大家都觉得无精打采。 2. I was angry with his languid movements. 我被他那懒洋洋的动作激怒了。 3. He speaks with a languid drawl. 他慢吞吞拉着长调说话。', '副词: languidly 名词: languidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unprecedented', '[ʌn\'presɪdentɪd]', 'adj.空前的；前所未有的', '1. We are seeing unemployment on an unprecedented scale. 我们现在正经历规模空前的失业现象。 2. His statement made an unprecedented splash. 他的声明引起了空前的轰动。 3. The air crash caused an unprecedented number of deaths. 这次空难的死亡人数是空前的。 4. Some economists showed their anxiety on unprecedented level of unemployment. 一些经济学家对失业率达到前所未有的程度表示忧虑。', '副词: unprecedentedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resuscitate', '[rɪ\'sʌsɪteɪt]', 'v.使复活；使苏醒；使复兴 v.恢复；复兴', '1. Why did South Korea “resuscitate” Chinese Characters? 韩国为什么\"恢复\"汉字？ 2. The soul, going down stream in this gulf, may become a corpse. Who shall resuscitate it? 漂在那深渊里的心灵可以变成尸体,将来谁使它复活呢? 3. He had a heart attack and all attempts to resuscitate him failed. 他的心脏病发作，所有抢救他的努力都失败了。 4. We must work out a practicable plan for resuscitating our country. 我们必须制定一项切实可行的计划以使我们的国家复兴起来。 5. The character in the picture has the ability to purify and resuscitate. 图中的字符有能力净化和复苏。', '形容词: resuscitable 名词: resuscitation 过去式: resuscitated 过去分词: resuscitated 现在分词: resuscitating 第三人称单数: resuscitates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abdicate', '[\'æbdɪkeɪt]', 'vt.正式放弃；让位 vi.退位；辞职', '1. He was forced to abdicate his claim on the property. 他被迫放弃要求财产的权利。 2. He\'s abdicated all responsibility in the affair. 他已经放弃了这件事中的一切职责。 3. The king was forced to abdicate his throne. 国王被迫逊位。 4. King Edward VIII abdicated in 1936. 英王爱德华八世于1936年退位。', '形容词: abdicable 名词: abdication 过去式: abdicated 过去分词: abdicated 现在分词: abdicating 第三人称单数: abdicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accommodate', '[ə\'kɑːmədeɪt]', 'vt.供给住宿；使适应；容纳；提供；顾及；调解 vi.适应；调节', '1. This hotel can accommodate up to 500 guests. 这旅馆可供500位来宾住宿。 2. We must accommodate ourselves to circumstances. 我们必须适应环境。 3. One flat can accommodate a family of five. 一套单元房可容纳一个五口之家。 4. The bank is accommodating its customers more than it used to. 这家银行现在给客户贷款比以前多了。 5. Her eyes took a while to accommodate to the darkness. 过了一会儿，她的眼睛才能适应黑暗。', '形容词: accommodative 名词: accommodativeness 过去式: accommodated 过去分词: accommodated 现在分词: accommodating 第三人称单数: accommodates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tonsorial', '[tɒn\'soʊrɪəl]', 'adj.理发师的；理发的', '1. Thus he justified himself in sitting down in here after his tonsorial treatment. 享受了理发师的服务后，他就觉得自己有权利在那里坐下了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('razor', '[\'reɪzər]', 'n.剃刀', '1. He shaved his face with a razor. 他用剃刀刮脸。 2. He was honing his razor although it\'s very sharp. 尽管他的剃刀十分锋利了，可他还是不停地磨它。 3. This electric razor is our latest promotion. 这种电剃刀是我们的最新产品。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boulder', '[\'boʊldər]', 'n.大圆石；巨砾', '1. He was unable to budge the boulder. 他搬不动那块大圆石。 2. We hear the sound of the river rush past boulder below. 我们听到河水奔腾而过大圆石的声音。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('downplay', '[ˌdaʊn\'pleɪ]', 'v.低估；对…轻描淡写；不予重视', '1. Which does he downplay or ignore altogether? 又轻描淡写或完全忽略了哪些? 2. Mill seems to downplay the importance and terribleness of death. 表面上看来，密尔轻视死的重要性与恐怖性。 3. The pro-Olympics lobby tends to downplay the disadvantages. 争取申奥的游说团体倾向忽视不利因素。 4. As for Mr. Ross, he tends to downplay the record and his space achievements. 至于罗斯上校本人，并不怎么以自己的太空记录和太空成就沾沾自喜。', '过去式: downplayed 过去分词: downplayed 现在分词: downplaying 第三人称单数: downplays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demise', '[dɪ\'maɪz]', 'n.死亡；转让房产；让位 v.让渡；遗赠；转让；死亡', '1. This loss led to the demise of the business. 这一损失导致了公司的倒闭。 2. Upon his demise his house passed to his son. 他故世后，房子便传给了儿子。 3. The demise of the old man\'s property cause much dispute upon his death. 老人死时，财产的让渡问题引起许多争执。', '形容词: demisable 过去式: demised 过去分词: demised 现在分词: demising 第三人称单数: demises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('windbag', '[\'wɪndbæɡ]', 'n.[音]风囊；<俚>饶舌之人；啰嗦的人', '1. Everyone knows he\'s a real windbag. 大家都知道他是个啰嗦的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defoliant', '[ˌdiː\'foʊliənt]', 'n. <美>脱叶剂； 落叶剂', '1. Defoliant: Chemical dust or spray applied to plants to cause their leaves to drop off prematurely. 落叶剂:落叶剂是一种化学粉剂或喷洒剂，施于植物以使树叶提早掉落。 2. The crash had spilled a noxious defoliant into the planet\'s ecology, ravaging the native flora. 这次坠毁将一种有害的落叶剂洒入星球的生态系统中，破坏着当地的植物群。 3. Vietnamese victims of Agent Orange, a poisonous defoliant used by America in the war, are still seeking compensation. 落叶剂（美军在越战中使用的一种落叶毒素）的越南受害者仍在要求获得赔偿。 4. Defoliant : Chemical dust or spray applied to plants to cause their leaves to drop off prematurely. 落叶剂:落叶剂是一种化学粉剂或喷洒剂,施于植物以使树叶提早掉落。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snarl', '[snɑːrl]', 'v.吼叫；嚎叫；咆哮；怒骂 v.纠缠；混乱 n.咆哮 n.混乱；缠结', '1. The tiger snarled frighteningly. 老虎发出可怕的吼声。 2. The dog snarled at the milkman. 那条狗对着送牛奶的人低声吠叫。 3. He snarled himself hoarse. 他咆哮得嗓子都哑了 4. Her hair is snarled. 她的头发缠结在一起。 5. At the seaside we could hear the snarl of the waves. 在海滨我们可以听见波涛的咆哮。 6. My knitting was in a terrible snarl. 我织的东西都乱成一团了。', '形容词: snarly 副词: snarlingly 名词: snarler 过去式: snarled 过去分词: snarled 现在分词: snarling 第三人称单数: snarls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spendthrift', '[\'spendθrɪft]', 'n.浪费的人 adj.浪费的；挥霍无度的', '1. My mother warned me about marrying a spendthrift. 我妈妈告诫我，不要与挥霍金钱的人结婚。 2. It is hard to imagine the consumers returning to their spendthrift ways anytime soon. 很难想像消费者短期内会恢复以往挥霍无度的生活方式。 3. My dad observed my spendthrift ways and often said that money burned a hole in my pocket. 父亲看我挥霍金钱的方式，常说钱把我的口袋烧了一个洞。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sop', '[sɑːp]', 'n.贿赂；面包片；湿软食物；安慰物 v.浸透；泡；吸 SOP. abbr.标准操作程序（=standard operating procedure ）', '1. Please sop up the water with a mop. 请用拖把把水吸干。', '过去式: sopped 过去分词: sopped 现在分词: sopping 第三人称单数: sops');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('augment', '[ɔːɡ\'ment]', 'vt.增加 n.增加；补充物', '1. They hit upon another idea to augment their income. 他们又想出一个增加收入的办法。 2. Hotel workers depend on tips to augment their usually small salaries. 饭店的工作人员主要靠小费来增加他平时微薄的收入。 3. He augments his income by teaching in the evenings. 他晚上去教书以增加收入。 4. They hit upon another idea to augment their income. 他们又想出一个增加收入的办法。', '形容词: augmentable 名词: augmenter 过去式: augmented 过去分词: augmented 现在分词: augmenting 第三人称单数: augments');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grievance', '[\'ɡriːvəns]', 'n.委屈；冤情；苦况', '1. The idea makes me feel a sense of grievance. 我突然感到很委屈。 2. He will not easily forget his grievance. 他不会轻易忘掉他的委屈。 3. He used the occasion to express all his old grievance against the chairman. 他利用那机会表达了对主席积压已久的怨气。 4. A committee was set up to look into the workers\' grievances. 成立了一个委员会来调查工人的不满。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('magnanimity', '[ˌmæɡnə\'nɪməti]', 'n.宽大；雅量；高尚', '1. She accepted the criticism with magnanimity. 她很大度地接受了批评。 2. The soldiers treated their prisoners with magnanimity. 士兵们宽大为怀对待俘虏。 3. Her demeanor attests her magnanimity and confidence. 她的风度证名了她的大度和自信。', '名词复数: magnanimities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flask', '[flæsk]', 'n.细颈瓶；烧瓶；小水瓶', '1. A balloon is mysteriously \"sucked\" into a flask. 一个气球神秘地被吸进了一个细颈瓶。 2. Please carry a flask with you at all times during the hike. 在徒步旅行期间请随身携带一个长颈瓶。 3. The graduation is marked on the side of the flask. 烧瓶侧面有刻度标志。 4. A flask, conjured from thin air, was thrust into his shaking hand by Hermione. 赫敏将一个凭空变出来的烧瓶塞在了他颤抖着的手里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oblation', '[ə\'bleɪʃən]', 'n.供奉；奉献；祭品', '1. Each family has their own ancestor for oblation. 谁家也不缺个祖宗来供奉。 2. The tenth of this seventh month is the Day of Atonement, when you shall hold a sacred assembly and mortify yourselves and offer an oblation to the LORD. 还有七月初十是赎罪节，是你们应召集圣会的日子，要克己苦身，并给上主奉献一火祭。', '形容词: oblational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sport', '[spɔːrt]', 'n.运动；体育 vi.嬉戏；炫耀；戏弄 adj.运动的；户外穿戴的', '1. Baseball is more popular than any other sport in Japan. 在日本，棒球比其他任何运动都受人欢迎。 2. Football is my favorite sport. 足球是我最喜欢的运动。 3. Sport is being debased by commercialism. 体育运动的价值受商业化的影响而逐渐下降。 4. This sport event attracted many advertisers. 这个体育项目吸引了许多广告客户。 5. Don\'t sport with her， she\'s an old-fashioned girl. 别跟她开玩笑,她是个古板的姑娘。 6. Jump into the extreme sport of Skydiving. 跳转到极限运动的跳伞运动。', '形容词: sportful 副词: sportfully 名词: sportfulness 过去式: sported 过去分词: sported 现在分词: sporting 第三人称单数: sports');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('signal', '[\'sɪɡnəl]', 'n.信号；标志 v.(发信号)通知、表示 adj.显著的', '1. A red lamp is often a danger signal. 红灯常常是危险的信号。 2. I corrected my watch by the time signal. 我按报时信号校正我的表。 3. I\'ve called several times, but I keep getting a busy signal. 我打了好几次了,可是一直是忙音。 4. We live too far from the city to get a strong television signal. 我们住的地方离城里太远, 不能收到清晰的电视图像。 5. The police signalled the traffic to move forward slowly. 警察向来往车辆打信号，示意缓慢前行。 6. People speak of Mark Twain as a signal humourous writer. 人们称马克·吐温为杰出的幽默作家。', '名词: signaler 过去式: signaled/signalled 过去分词: signaled/signalled 现在分词: signaling/signalling 第三人称单数: signals/signals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perfidious', '[pər\'fɪdiəs]', 'adj.不忠的；背信弃义的', '1. Your perfidious gossip is malicious and dangerous. 你说的那些背信弃义的话是很刻毒险恶的。', '副词: perfidiously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('doggo', '[\'dɔːɡoʊ]', 'adv.隐藏着；躲起来', '1. The frightened boy lay doggo in his tent. 吓怀了的男孩躲在帐篷里。 2. Promise to lie absolutely doggo, or I shan\'t say anything. 答应我不声张，否则我什么话也不对你说。 3. Promise to lie absolutely doggo,or I shan\'t say anything. 答应我不声张，否则我什么话也不对你说。 4. The escaped prisoners lay doggo in a haystack until the searchers had gone away. 越狱的囚犯们一直躲在干草堆里，直到搜寻者离去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('percussionist', '[pər\'kʌʃənɪst]', 'n.[音]敲击乐器乐师', '1. He was a percussionist, working first in theatre, and it showed. 他是个打击乐手，最初在剧场工作，这个本领在电影中展示过。 2. A percussionist is someone who plays drums or other percussion instruments. 打击乐家是打鼓或其它打击乐器的演奏家。 3. For many years I practiced these techniques as a professional percussionist in jazz and new music. 许多年来作为一个职业的爵士乐和新音乐演奏者我不断实践着。 4. Eric : There is going to be a guitarist and a percussionist playing live music tonight. 埃瑞克：我们今晚会有乐队表演。乐队里有两个成员，吉他手和鼓手。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lag', '[læɡ]', 'v.落后；减退；缓慢进行 n.落后；时间间隔', '1. Some of the runners in the race began to lag. 参加比赛的运动员中有一些开始落後了。 2. The children always lag behind when we go for a walk. 我们出去散步时，孩子们总是落在后面。 3. Interest lags in such matters. 对这类事情的兴趣慢慢减少了。 4. It takes a lot of time to catch up with a cultural lag. 文化的落后需要长时间才能赶上。', '名词: lagger 过去式: lagged 过去分词: lagged 现在分词: lagging 第三人称单数: lags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obstinacy', '[\'ɒbstɪnəsi]', 'n.顽固；(病痛等)难治', '1. Sheer obstinacy prevented her from apologizing. 她固执得就是不道歉。', '名词复数: obstinacies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nag', '[næɡ]', 'vt.不断唠叨；指责；困扰，使…烦恼 n.小马；驽马；竞赛马', '1. Don\'t nag me! 别在我面前唠叨！ 2. She nagged him into doing what she wanted. 她向他唠叨，使他不得不去做她所要的事。 3. The problem had been nagging me for weeks. 那问题把我困扰了几个星期. 4. I have never seen a nag like this one. 我从来没见过这样的矮小马。', '副词: naggingly 名词: nagger 过去式: nagged 过去分词: nagged 现在分词: nagging 第三人称单数: nags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subsidy', '[\'sʌbsədi]', 'n.津贴；补助金', '1. It\'s the old and the poor who suffer worst when subsidies are cut. 补助津贴一削减，最吃苦头的就是那些老人和贫民。 2. She qualifies for the unemployment subsidy . 她有权获得失业补贴。 3. The townsfolk can\'t understand why the Royal Shakespeare Company needs a subsidy. 市民不明白王室莎士比亚公司为什么需要一个补助金。', '名词复数: subsidies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embrace', '[ɪm\'breɪs]', 'v.拥抱；包含；包围；接受；信奉 n.拥抱', '1. We embraced each other. 我们互相拥抱。 2. She held out her arms to embrace the little girl. 她伸出双臂来拥抱那个小女孩。 3. Many subjects are embraced in an encyclopedia. 百科全书中包含许多科目。 4. We allowed the warm water to embrace us. 我们让温水包围我们 5. He enfolded the child in an affectionate embrace. 他疼爱得把孩子紧紧搂在怀里。', '形容词: embraceable 名词: embracement 过去式: embraced 过去分词: embraced 现在分词: embracing 第三人称单数: embraces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avalanche', '[\'ævəlæntʃ]', 'n.雪崩；大量 v.雪崩', '1. The avalanche whelmed the small mountain village. 雪崩淹没了小山村。 2. Three climbers are safe after the avalanche. 雪崩过后，三个登山者平安无事。 3. He was buried by an avalanche and had to be dug out. 他遇雪崩被埋住了，得把他挖出来。 4. What a precarious situation we were in when the avalanche started! 雪崩发生的时候我们的处境多么危险啊！ 5. Higher still the snow was ready to avalanche. 在更高处积雪随时都会崩塌。', '过去式: avalanched 过去分词: avalanched 现在分词: avalanching 第三人称单数: avalanches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acrid', '[\'ækrɪd]', 'adj.苦味的；辛辣的；尖刻的', '1. An acrid brown gum resin is now used mainly in veterinary medicine. 一种苦味棕色的树胶树脂现在主要用于兽用药物。 2. The acrid smell carried across the table. 一股辛辣的味道在桌子周围弥漫开来。 3. This is an acrid and pungent substance. 这是一种辛辣而带刺激性的物质。 4. There is an acrid tone to your remarks. 你说这些话的口气带有讥刺意味。', '副词: acridly 名词: acridity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('innocence', '[\'ɪnəsns]', 'n.无罪；清白；无知；天真无邪', '1. She affirmed her innocence. 她坚称自己无罪。 2. He died protesting his innocence to the last. 他至死都坚称自己无罪。 3. He tried to convince me of his innocence. 他试图使我相信他是清白的。 4. Innocence is bliss. 无知便是福。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frugal', '[\'fruːɡl]', 'adj.节俭的；省钱的', '1. As far as oil energy is concerned, we cannot be too frugal. 就石油能源而言，我们愈节省愈好。 2. They lived a very frugal existence, avoiding all luxuries. 他们生活非常俭朴，力避奢侈。 3. The frugal boy rarely spends money. 那节俭的孩子很少花钱。 4. My mother was also a frugal woman. 我的妈妈也是一位节俭的女人。', '副词: frugally 名词: frugality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('benison', '[\'benɪzən]', 'n.祝福；祝祷', '1. If you can find blessedness, my benison is that I can see you will be happy in faraway country. 假若你得到幸福,那么我的祝福就是在相隔千万里的遥远国度看你开怀。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abase', '[ə\'beɪs]', 'v.降低 ... 的地位；降低 ... 的品格；贬低', '1. The president is not willing to abase himself before the nation. 总统不愿在全国人民面前降低自己的威信。', '名词: abasement 过去式: abased 过去分词: abased 现在分词: abasing 第三人称单数: abases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entrance', '[\'entrəns]', 'n.入口；进入；登场；进入权 vt.使入迷；使狂喜', '1. There is an entrance just around the corner. 拐角处有个入口。 2. I\'ll meet you at the entrance of the zoo tomorrow. 明天我会在动物园的入口处和你见面。 3. A lighthouse marks the entrance to the harbour. 灯塔是进入海港航道的标志。 4. The actress makes her entrance in Act 3. 女演员在第三幕登场。 5. Her beauty entirely entrances him. 她的美丽完全使他入迷了。', '副词: entrancingly 名词: entrancement 过去式: entranced 过去分词: entranced 现在分词: entrancing 第三人称单数: entrances');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disciple', '[dɪ\'saɪpl]', 'n.弟子；门徒；信徒', '1. The sage asked this disciple to wait. 智者让这个弟子等一会儿。 2. Matthew had just been called as a disciple. 马太刚被呼召作耶稣的门徒。 3. I\'m putting my shirt on Devil\'s Disciple to win the next race. 我这所有的钱都押在魔鬼门徒这匹马，指望它赢下一场比赛上了。 4. He was an ardent disciple of Gandhi. 他是甘地的忠实信徒。', '名词: discipleship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exodus', '[\'eksədəs]', 'n.大批的离去 Exodus：（《圣经·旧约》中的）出埃及记.', '1. A massive exodus of doctors is forcing the government to recruit from abroad. 大批医生的离去迫使政府从国外雇用医生。 2. Even in August, when a mass.holiday exodus leaves Milan virtually deserted, the small square outside the church bustles with activity. 即使到了八月份，当大批游客的离去使米兰变得萧条起来时，这个教堂外面的小广场上依然熙熙攘攘。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anterior', '[æn\'tɪriər]', 'adj.前面的；前部的；较早的', '1. The anterior skin of the concha was left intact and its redundancy was corrected by its own viscoelastic property. 住院后接受经耳后切口，切除耳壳纺椎形软骨而完成耳朵整形手术，外耳前面的皮肤仍然保持完整。 2. Then inspect the anterior shoulders and shoulder girdles for symmetry, noting any atrophy, swelling, or deformity. 然后检查前面的肩膀和与之相对的另一边看是否有萎缩，肿胀或变形。 3. The patient was referred to our clinic due to suspected anterior encephalocele. 患者因怀疑前部的脑膨出来我处就诊。 4. The forked bone anterior to the breastbone of most birds,formed by the fusion of the clavicles. 鸟胸的叉骨，如愿骨大多数鸟胸骨前部的叉形骨，因锁骨合并形成的。', '副词: anteriorly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invidious', '[ɪn\'vɪdiəs]', 'adj.惹人反感的；招人嫉妒的', '1. The officer feared the invidious accusations. 这个警官担心会招致人们不满的指控。 2. She’d put herself in an invidious position. 她陷入了招人嫉妒的情境。', '副词: invidiously 名词: invidiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deport', '[dɪ\'pɔːrt]', 'vt.驱逐出境；持...举止', '1. Even if they didn\'t put her in jail, they would deport her. 即使他们不把她关入监狱,他们也会把她驱逐出境。 2. We deport aliens who slip across our borders. 我们把偷渡入境的外国人驱逐出境。 3. It’s important to teach a child how to deport himself in public. 教会小孩在公众场合如何举止得体十分重要。', '过去式: deported 过去分词: deported 现在分词: deporting 第三人称单数: deports');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('twinge', '[twɪndʒ]', 'n.(生理；心理上的)剧痛；刺痛 v.（使）感到剧痛', '1. I feel a twinge in my back now and again. 我不时感到背痛。 2. But each time again there was a horrid twinge of conscience. 但同时，每一次又都要承受良心上的煎熬。 3. Remembering that promise. I felt a twinge of guilt. 忆起那个承诺。罪恶刺痛了我。 4. The letter still gives him a twinge when he thinks of it. 他一想起那封信就会感到一阵刺痛。', '过去式: twinged 过去分词: twinged 现在分词: twinging 第三人称单数: twinges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tilt', '[tɪlt]', 'vt.(使)倾斜 vi.抨击；争论 n.倾斜；车盖；以全速；(小舟、车辆、地摊等的)帐蓬', '1. Don\'t tilt your chair back so far, it might fall over. 别把椅子一个劲向后倾斜，它会翻倒的。 2. If you tilt the table,the dishes will slide off onto the floor. 如果你使桌子倾斜，碟子就会滑到地板上。 3. The table top suddenly tilted and all the plates and glasses crashed onto the floor. 桌面突然翘起，所有的盘子和玻璃制品都滑落到地板上打碎了。 4. Tilt pump downward and remove from engine. 将泵向下倾斜，从引擎移出。 5. He is bold enough to tilt at social injustices. 他敢于抨击社会上的不公正现象。 6. Such a tilt is unusual in the solar system. 这样的倾斜在太阳系中不常见。', '名词: tilter 过去式: tilted 过去分词: tilted 现在分词: tilting 第三人称单数: tilts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('faddish', '[\'fædɪʃ]', 'adj.流行一时的；时尚的', '1. This sang was faddish temporarily. 这首歌曾风行一时。 2. There was, to be sure, a faddish aspect to this enthusiasm. 在这个热潮中，肯定有赶时髦的成分。 3. Dial get online to say, begin since thenceforth faddish. 拨号上网一说，从那时起开始风行。 4. The current society is just evolved into a faddish society. 摘要当代社会正在演化为时尚化社会。', '副词: faddishly 名词: faddishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agronomy', '[ə\'ɡrɒnəmi]', 'n.农业经济学；农艺学', '1. Now he heads the agronomy department. 现在他担任农艺系系主任。', '形容词: agronomic 名词: agronomist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lymphatic', '[lɪm\'fætɪk]', 'adj.淋巴的；淋巴性的；无力的 n.淋巴腺；淋巴管', '1. The tourniquet should occlude venous and lymphatic return. 止血带应阻断静脉及淋巴回流。 2. The lacteals of villi are part of the lymphatic system. 绒毛的乳糜管是淋巴系统的一部分。 3. On medicine, according to the origin of haemal cell, haemal tumour cent is lymphatic sex tumour and pith sex tumour. 在医学上，根据血液细胞的来源，将血液肿瘤分为淋巴性肿瘤和髓性肿瘤。 4. A nest of metastatic infiltrating ductal carcinoma from breast is seen in a dilated lymphatic channel in the lung. 肺扩张的淋巴管可见来自乳腺浸润性导管癌转移灶。', '副词: lymphatically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glowing', '[\'ɡloʊɪŋ]', 'adj.灼热的；热情的；强烈的 动词glow的现在分词.', '1. She has a tanned and glowing face. 她的脸色黑里泛红。 2. Beat the glowing metal into a dagger. 把灼热的金属锻造成匕首 3. He gave a glowing description of that grand villa. 他热情地描述了那幢豪华的别墅。 4. The poet paints the simple country life in glowing colours, and is clearly against living in a city. 这位诗人颂扬乡村的简朴生活，显然他不赞同居住在城市中。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frequency', '[\'friːkwənsi]', 'n.频繁；频率', '1. Accidents on that highway are happening with increasing frequency. 那条高速公路上车祸发生得越来越频繁。 2. Accidents are happening with increasing frequency. 事故正在愈加频繁地发生。 3. He wrote to both with tolerable frequency. 他和他们通信，相当频繁。 4. He varied the transmission frequency. 他变换了无线电传送的频率。', '名词复数: frequencies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('constituent', '[kən\'stʃuənt]', 'n.成分；选民；构成物 adj.构成的；组织的；立宪的', '1. Do you know the constituents of the mixture? 你知道这种混合物的成分吗？ 2. Punctuality is an important constituent of good character. 准时是优良品格的一个重要成分。 3. Last week, a constituent contacted me and asked me to help him construe an article contained within the constitution. 上星期，一位选民跟我联系，让我帮他解释一下宪法中包含的某则条款。 4. The chemical dissolves into its constituent parts when heated. 该化学药剂加热时会分解成其组成的分子。', '副词: constituently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('manipulate', '[mə\'nɪpjuleɪt]', 'vt.操纵；操作；控制；利用；(巧妙地)处理；篡改', '1. A clever politician know how to manipulate public opinion. 聪明的政客知道如何操纵公众舆论。 2. He is one of those who manipulate the market. 他是操纵市场者之一。 3. Do you know how to manipulate a computer ? 你知道怎样操作计算机吗? 4. She uses her charm to manipulate people. 她利用其魅力左右他人。', '形容词: manipulatable 副词: manipulatively 名词: manipulability 过去式: manipulated 过去分词: manipulated 现在分词: manipulating 第三人称单数: manipulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('propriety', '[prə\'praɪəti]', 'n.适当；正当；得体 (复数）proprieties:礼节； 礼仪.', '1. I doubt the propriety of doing so. 我怀疑这样做是否适当。 2. The students in our school can be admitted propriety by No.1 Middle School. 我校学生中考可被华师一高中部适当优惠录取。 3. In propriety of classification, however, the people of a country are not to be counted in its wealth. 然而，按照正当的分类，一个国家的人民不应算作这个国家的财富。 4. Ellen ignored all things contrary to her ideas of propriety and tried to teach Scarlett to do the same, but with poor success. 对于那些自认为不正当的事情爱伦总是不屑一顾，并且想教导思嘉也这样做，可是没有多大效果。 5. China is a country of courtesy and propriety. 中华民族是个讲究礼仪的国家。', '名词复数: proprieties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('studied', '[\'stʌdid]', 'adj.故意的；有学问的 动词study的过去式和过去分词.', '1. She spoke with studied politeness. 她故作有礼地讲话。 2. The bishop gave his hand quickly, made his little studied bow. 主教连忙伸出手去，很矜持的欠了欠身。', '副词: studiedly 名词: studiedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swipe', '[swaɪp]', 'v.重击；猛打；<非正式>偷窃；在解码器上刮刷（信用卡等卡） n.重击；猛打；<非正式>尖刻的评论', '1. He swiped at the ball and missed it. 他向球猛击，但未打中。 2. He swiped at the dog with his stick, but missed. 他用手杖向那条狗打去，但没打中。 3. He swiped the ball into the grandstand. 他把球打到看台上去了。 4. Please swipe your card to enter. 请刷卡进门。 5. He had a swipe at the ball. 他重击了一下球。', '过去式: swiped 过去分词: swiped 现在分词: swiping 第三人称单数: swipes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pathos', '[\'peɪθɑːs]', 'n.感伤；悲怅；悲情', '1. He had hearty distaste for songs of pathos. 他极不爱听感伤歌曲。 2. Its tone is rather of an obvious pathos. 它的基调流露出十分明显的凄怆。 3. Every word he uttered was full of pathos and sublimity. 他发出的每一个声音都充满着悲怅和崇高。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remission', '[rɪ\'mɪʃn]', 'n.宽恕；赦免；（疾病等）减轻；豁免；减刑', '1. Remission of sins is promised to those who repent. 悔过自新的人会得到宽恕。 2. Now where remission of these is, there is no more offering for sin. 这些罪过既已赦免，就不用再为罪献祭了。 3. This is his second remission from his illness. 这是他的病情第二次得到缓解。 4. The company gained remission from tax payments. 这家公司获准免税。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scar', '[skɑːr]', 'n.疤痕；伤痕；断崖 v.结疤；痊愈', '1. He has a scar running across his left cheek. 他左脸上有一道很长的疤痕。 2. The scar flawed her beauty. 这伤疤损害了她的美貌。 3. The cut in her hand has healed completely, without leaving a scar. 她手上的刀伤完全愈合了,没有留下一点伤痕。 4. In that heart, where there had been a wound, there was a scar. 在他的心上，从前有过一条伤口，后来只剩下一条伤痕。 5. The wound gradually scarred over. 伤口渐渐愈合。', '过去式: scarred 过去分词: scarred 现在分词: scarring 第三人称单数: scars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stammer', '[\'stæmər]', 'vi.口吃；结巴 vt.结结巴巴地说 n.结巴；口吃', '1. His stammer rendered him unfit for a teaching job. 他的口吃毛病使他不宜担任教职。 2. She is always ragging Tom about his stammer. 她总是拿汤姆的口吃开玩笑。 3. I had a speech impediment, commonly referred to as a stutter or stammer. 我患有语言障碍，就是通常所指的口吃或者是结巴。 4. If you have a stammer a little bit in the middle where it does not matter to continue to read, and then come back to repeat. 如果中间有结巴的地方也不要紧，继续读下去，然后再回来重读。 5. Before Tony could stammer out his thanks,she walked away. 没等托尼结结巴巴地说出一声谢谢，她已经走开了。 6. I had a speech impediment, commonly referred to as a stutter or stammer. 我患有语言障碍，就是通常所指的口吃或者是结巴。', '副词: stammeringly 名词: stammerer 过去式: stammered 过去分词: stammered 现在分词: stammering 第三人称单数: stammers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('formidable', '[\'fɔːrmɪdəbl]', 'adj.强大的；可怕的；难对付的', '1. He was one of the most formidable intellects of his time. 他是该时代的盖世奇才。 2. His mother is a most formidable lady. 他的母亲是个最令人生畏的妇人。 3. They climbed up the last part of the mountain in formidable weather conditions. 他们在恶劣的天气条件下登上了山的顶峰。 4. Martin is formidable. His left hook is devastating. 马丁很难对付，他的左钩拳极有威力。', '副词: formidably 名词: formidability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grotto', '[\'ɡrɑːtoʊ]', 'n.洞穴；岩穴', '1. Currently the grotto is not accessible. 一般来说洞穴是不可进入。 2. We reached a beautiful grotto, whose entrance was almost hid by the vines. 我们到达了一个美丽的洞穴,洞的进口几乎被藤蔓遮掩著。 3. The cry proceeded from the grotto. 那声音是从地洞那面传过来的。 4. Here is the most eye-catching Binglingsi Grotto. 这里最引人注目的就是炳灵寺石窟。', '名词复数: grottoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lacerate', '[\'læsəreɪt]', 'vt.撕裂；伤害 adj.被撕裂的；裂成碎片的；受伤的', '1. The sharp stones lacerated his feet. 尖石把他的脚划伤了。', '过去式: lacerated 过去分词: lacerated 现在分词: lacerating 第三人称单数: lacerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scalpel', '[\'skælpəl]', 'n.手术刀；解剖刀', '1. A scalpel is a surgical instrument. 手术刀是外科器械。 2. This is the scalpel which Norman Bethune used in those days. 这是当年白求恩大夫用的手术刀。 3. In the biology lesson, the teacher dissected a frog with a scalpel. 生物课上老师用手术刀解剖了一只青蛙。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pugnacious', '[pʌɡ\'neɪʃəs]', 'adj.好斗的', '1. When he was a child, he was pugnacious and fought with everyone. 他小时候很好斗, 跟每个人都打过架。', '副词: pugnaciously 名词: pugnaciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('listless', '[\'lɪstləs]', 'adj.无精打采的', '1. Because of the death of his mother he is listless all day. 因为母亲的去世，他整天无精打采的。 2. She was very listless after her illness. 她病后懒洋洋的。 3. People are always listless on summer afternoons. 夏天的午后，人们总是无精打采的。 4. Many people feel listless on rainy days. 许多人碰到下雨天就无精打采。', '副词: listlessly 名词: listlessness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deluge', '[\'deljuːdʒ]', 'n.大洪水；暴雨；泛滥 v.泛滥；大量涌入', '1. Disturbed by the sounds of mankind, the gods, led by Enlil, set forth a deluge. 被人类的声音所扰乱，众神，在恩利尔的带领下，发起了一场大洪水。 2. You could see him now, in this deluge of distraction. 现在你在这混乱的暴雨中，能够看见他。 3. Hundreds of children were crushed as the floors collapsed in a deluge of falling bricks and concrete. 随着楼层的垮塌，数以百计的儿童被掩埋在如暴雨般跌落的砖块和水泥之下。 4. The deluge of spare cash has two main sources. 游资泛滥的原因有两点。 5. The deluge of spare cash has two main sources. 游资泛滥的原因有两点。', '过去式: deluged 过去分词: deluged 现在分词: deluging 第三人称单数: deluges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disenchant', '[ˌdɪsɪn\'tʃænt]', 'vt.唤醒；使不再着迷；使不抱幻想', '1. Her arrogance has disenchanted many of her former admirers. 她为人高傲，追求过她的许多人都已不再迷恋她了。', '副词: disenchantingly 名词: disenchanter 过去式: disenchanted 过去分词: disenchanted 现在分词: disenchanting 第三人称单数: disenchants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('relic', '[\'relɪk]', 'n.神圣的遗物；遗迹；纪念物', '1. This stone axe is a relic of ancient times. 这把石斧是古代的遗物。 2. Gold is still a barbaric relic whose value rises only when inflation is high. 黄金仍然只是未开化时代的遗物，其价值只在通涨高企时才会上升。 3. The calorie is a historical relic. 卡是历史的遗迹。 4. The building stands as the last remaining relic of the town\'s cotton industry. 这座建筑物是小镇棉纺业仅存的遗迹。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preliterate', '[priː\'lɪtərɪt]', 'adj.无文字记录的；文字以前的 n.无文字记录时期的人', '1. Having no written language;preliterate. 没有文字的没有书面语言的;有文字记裁前的 2. Having no written language; preliterate. 没有文字的没有书面语言的；有文字记裁前的 3. Such fetishes were, and still are, worshipped in many preliterate societies. 在许多文字出现之前或无文字的社会里，这样的偶像曾经和仍然受到人们的顶礼膜拜。 4. Similar tales were told by various preliterate peoples in Asia, Africa, and the Americas. 在亚洲、非洲和美洲各国，文字出现之前，也有相似的传说。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('steward', '[\'stuːərd]', 'n.乘务员；管家；干事；管理员 v.做乘务员；管理', '1. His neighbor is a chief steward. 他的邻居是一个乘务员领班。 2. We thanked the steward for his good service. 我们感谢了乘务员所提供的优质服务。 3. Sometimes he sent his house steward in his place. 有时他派管家替他去。 4. The stewards will inspect the course to see if racing is possible. 那些干事将检视赛马场看是否适宜比赛。 5. He was selected to steward a team. 他被指派经管球队。', '名词: stewardship 过去式: stewarded 过去分词: stewarded 现在分词: stewarding 第三人称单数: stewards');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reek', '[riːk]', 'n.恶臭；水蒸汽 v.放出恶臭；有 ... 气味；明显带有', '1. Do you smell the reek of stale tobacco? 你闻到发霉烟草的臭味了吗？ 2. They live amid reek and squalor. 他们生活在臭气熏天的污浊环境中。 3. His breath reeked of tobacco. 他口中带有烟草的臭味。 4. They reek of death and corruption. 它们身上散发出腐烂的死亡的气息。', '形容词: reeky 名词: reeker 过去式: reeked 过去分词: reeked 现在分词: reeking 第三人称单数: reeks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('testimony', '[\'testɪmoʊni]', 'n.证明；证据', '1. His hearty laughter is testimony of his happiness. 他尽情的欢笑可以证明他很幸福。 2. Nothing could refute her testimony that the driver was drunk. 她关于那个司机已经喝醉的证词无可辩驳。 3. The witness is giving false testimony. 那个证人在作伪证。 4. The statement is confirmed by testimony. 这个说法由证据所证实了。', '名词复数: testimonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pharmaceutical', '[ˌfɑːrmə\'suːtɪkl]', 'adj.制药的；配药的 n.药品；成药', '1. Her brother is interested in pharmaceutical botany. 她的哥哥对药草感兴趣。 2. The pharmaceutical company is only a subsidiary of the corporation. 这家制药公司只是这个集团的一个子公司。 3. She has donated money to establish a pharmaceutical laboratory. 她捐款成立了一个药剂实验室。 4. The quality detection of pharmaceutical production is very important. 药品生产质量的检测是非常重要的。', '副词: pharmaceutically 异体字: pharmaceutic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cosmopolitanism', '[ˌkɒzmə\'pɒlətənˌɪzəm]', 'n.世界大同主义；四海一家', '1. Chinese internationalism and cosmopolitanism grew constantly and were a permanent facet of the culture, with only short intervals of relative isolationism. 中国的帝国主义和世界大同主义继续膨胀，并成为只是有着较短时期相对孤立主义的文化的永恒面。 2. Travellers have long extolled its cosmopolitanism and vibrancy. 世界各地的游客们盛赞广场的四海一家味道和热情活跃。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distract', '[dɪ\'strækt]', 'vt.分散；转移；分心；困扰', '1. The film managed to distract me from these problems for a while. 这部影片分散了我的注意力，让我暂时忘记了这些难题。 2. It was all a ploy to distract attention from his real aims. 那纯粹是障眼法，用以分散人们对他真正意图的注意力。 3. We must change our route to distract the attention of the enemy. 我们必须改变行军路线以转移敌人的注意力。 4. Once she gets involved in a research, nothing can distract her mind from it. 她一旦潜心钻研某一课题,任何事情都无法使她分心。', '形容词: distractive 副词: distractingly 过去式: distracted 过去分词: distracted 现在分词: distracting 第三人称单数: distracts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('odds', '[ɑːdz]', 'n.机率；可能性；差别；投注赔率；让步；优势', '1. The odds are against us. 我们成功的机会很小。 2. His odds are very poor after he sprained his wrist. 他扭伤了手腕，获胜的可能性极小。 3. It makes no odds whether Henry goes or stays. 亨利去也好留也好都没有什么关系。 4. The horse was running at odds of ten to one. 那匹马参赛赔率是十比一。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('patriotism', '[\'peɪtriətɪzəm]', 'n.爱国主义；爱国心', '1. They did evil under the veil of patriotism. 他们在爱国主义的幌子下作恶。 2. Excessive patriotism can lead to xenophobia. 爱国主义过了头即可导致仇视一切外国人。 3. Her patriotism has bound her to her motherland. 她的爱国心使她和祖国紧密联系在。 4. Patriotism is sometimes a factor, but economic interest is certainly a much more important consideration. 爱国心有时也是一个因素，但是经济利益当然是更为重要的需要考虑的事项。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stigmatize', '[\'stɪɡmətaɪz]', 'vt. 污蔑； 使蒙上污名 vt. <古> 打上烙印', '1. They stigmatize these propositions as \"stifling\". 他们贬称这些命题 \"沉闷\"。 2. To mark with disgrace or infamy;stigmatize. 记号指示有脱漏的地方。 3. We did write, we did stigmatize. 我们写过，我们也斥责过。 4. We will stigmatize everyone who doesn\'t meet the goal. 我们将贬低没有实现这个目标的任何人。', '名词: stigmatization 过去式: stigmatized 过去分词: stigmatized 现在分词: stigmatizing 第三人称单数: stigmatizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lachrymose', '[\'lækrɪmoʊs]', 'adj.爱哭的；引人落泪的；哀痛的', '1. Yesterday\'s film is very lachrymose. 昨晚的电影真是催人泪下。 2. It is said that women are charactered with lachrymose. 人们认为爱哭是女人的特点. 3. It\'s think that lachrymose is one of the women\'s characteristics. 人们认为爱哭是女人的特点. 4. He was by turns devout and obscene, merry and lachrymose. 他时而虔诚时而淫秽，时而欢天喜地，时而凄然泪下。', '副词: lachrymosely 名词: lachrymosity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('smirch', '[smɜːtʃ]', 'n.污点 vt.玷污', '1. This eradicator can wipe off hard washing smirch. 这种去污剂能去除难洗的污渍。 2. This action smirch the true meaning of love . Maybe everyone has the different view about this,this is juts my view. 这种行为真的沾污了爱情真正的意义;也许每个人对待这方面的看法都不一样;这只是我的看法. 3. Despite its unavoidable pity and smirch due to historical limitations, its unigue comments played a vital part in strengthening its status in media. 虽然该报无法回避历史局限性带来的遗憾和污点，但其独有的评述特点，对巩固其在当时新闻媒体中的地位起到了一定作用。 4. Drakowen stood above the fallen Ardan, an evil smirch across his now malformed face. 德拉科文站在倒下的阿登之上，他难看的脸上显示出恶魔的污迹。', '过去式: smirched 过去分词: smirched 现在分词: smirching 第三人称单数: smirches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cozen', '[\'kʌzən]', 'v.欺；骗；瞒', '1. The clever salesman cozened the old lady into buying his goods. 聪明的推销员诱使老太太买下了他的东西。 2. The old man cozened me into giving him some money. 那老头哄骗我给了他一些钱。', '名词: cozener 过去式: cozened 过去分词: cozened 现在分词: cozening 第三人称单数: cozens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('legible', '[\'ledʒəbl]', 'adj.清晰的；易读的；可辨认的', '1. Then he sat down next to Voisin and began to write, carefully, without hurry, a thin legible hand. 他不慌不忙，认认真真地写下一串纤细而清晰的字迹。 2. It was also decided that the value would be indicated clearly in a readily legible manner and that certain tactile features would be included. 它也被决定价值会以不迟疑清晰的样子被清楚地指出而且特定的触觉特征会被包括在内。 3. Judicious use of white space and legible fonts is important so that these signposts remain clearly evident and distinct. 明智地使用空白的空间和易读的字体很重要，这样将使标志保持清晰独特。', '副词: legibly 名词: legibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rebuff', '[rɪ\'bʌf]', 'n.断然拒绝；漠不关心 v.严厉拒绝；冷落', '1. Her kindness to him was met with a cruel rebuff. 她一片好心却遭到他冷酷的拒绝。 2. His rebuff thoroughly deflated me. 他的断然拒绝使我心灰意懒。 3. He rebuffed all my offers of friendship. 他拒绝了我的一切友好表示。', '过去式: rebuffed 过去分词: rebuffed 现在分词: rebuffing 第三人称单数: rebuffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cane', '[keɪn]', 'n.手杖；细长的茎；藤条 vt.以杖击；以藤编制的', '1. He offered to strike the boy with his cane. 他威胁要用手杖打那个男孩。 2. He walks along briskly, twirl his cane in the air. 他一边轻快地走著，一边用手杖在空中旋转。 3. The blow of the cane stung the boy\'s fingers. 藤条的抽打使那男孩的手指感到刺痛。 4. She thrashed the children with a cane. 她用藤条痛打孩子们。 5. They cane our palms according to our marks. 他们根据我们的分数来打手心。', '名词: caner 过去式: caned 过去分词: caned 现在分词: caning 第三人称单数: canes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ruffian', '[\'rʌfiən]', 'n.恶棍 adj.残暴的', '1. That ruffian is capable of any crime. 那个恶棍什么勾当都做得出来。 2. The mere thought of the ruffian made her shudder. 她一想到那个恶棍就不寒而栗。', '形容词: ruffianly 名词: ruffianism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('phobia', '[\'foʊbiə]', 'n.恐怖病；恐怖症', '1. Sometimes, the result of extreme paranoia is a phobia. 有时，这种极度偏执狂的结果便是恐怖症。 2. A phobia is an excessive or unreasonable fear of a specific object or situation that is generally considered harmless. 恐怖症是一种过分的或者过度的对某个特定的事物或者场景的恐惧，而这个事物和场景通常被认为是无害的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recital', '[rɪ\'saɪtl]', 'n.背诵；吟诵；详述 n.独奏会；独唱会', '1. She gave us a boring recital of all her troubles. 她乏味地向我们详述了她所有的麻烦。 2. We went to a harp recital last night. 昨晚我们去听竖琴独奏会。 3. At the end of the semester year, the music teacher decided to organize a piano recital for her students and she sent flyers to them to participate. 学期末时，音乐老师决定为她的学生们举办一场钢琴独奏会。 4. Tickets are not sold out for the recital. 独唱会的票都卖完了。', '名词: recitalist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crudity', '[\'kruːdəti]', 'n.天然状态；粗糙；粗鲁', '1. I\'d never met such crudity before. 我从未见过这样粗鲁的行径。 2. The crudity of her language shocked him. 她粗鄙的语言使他感到震惊。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pantechnicon', '[pæn\'teknɪkən]', 'n.家具仓库；家具搬运车', '1. But, it is a such carpentry factories that take shape, the factory director\'s desk still is placed in a corner of pantechnicon, be the same as room office with 4 administrator; 可是，就是这样一个初具规模的木器厂，厂长的办公桌仍然摆在家具仓库的一个角落，与四名治理人员同室办公； 2. panel pantechnicon 大型仓库', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('canyon', '[\'kænjən]', 'n.峡谷', '1. A canyon usually has a river flowing through it. 峡谷常常有河流经过其中。 2. Arizona is famous for the Grand Canyon. 亚利桑那州因科罗拉多大峡谷而著名。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fraught', '[frɔːt]', 'adj.充满的；伴随的；忧伤的；忧虑的', '1. The journey was fraught with difficulties. 旅途充满艰辛。 2. The expedition into the jungle was fraught with danger. 到原始森林去探险充满了危险。 3. There\'s no need to look so fraught! 用不着那么愁眉苦脸的。 4. Next week will be particularly fraught as we\'ve just lost our secretary. 我们的秘书刚刚辞职,下星期特别令人担心。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clay', '[kleɪ]', 'n.黏土；泥土', '1. Clay is a plastic substance. 黏土是可塑物质。 2. Clay soil retains water. 黏土能保持水分。 3. Bricks and dishes are made from various kinds of clay. 砖和盘子由各种粘土制成。 4. It was said that the first man was moulded from clay by some kind of god. 据传，第一个人是某个神用泥土造出来的。', '形容词: clayey');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('guzzle', '[\'ɡʌzl]', 'v.狂饮；大量消耗', '1. He\'s always guzzling. 他总是大吃大喝的。', '名词: guzzler 过去式: guzzled 过去分词: guzzled 现在分词: guzzling 第三人称单数: guzzles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confront', '[kən\'frʌnt]', 'vt.对抗；遭遇；面临', '1. We must confront future with optimism. 我们必须乐观地面对未来。 2. You must confront your problems. 你必须面对自己的问题。 3. It\'s no use to confront your boss. 对抗你的老板是没有用的。 4. A soldier often has to confront danger. 士兵常常要身临险境。', '名词: confronter 过去式: confronted 过去分词: confronted 现在分词: confronting 第三人称单数: confronts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shiftless', '[\'ʃɪftləs]', 'adj.无计谋的；不中用的；无能的', '1. A lazy or shiftless person, especially one who seeks to live solely by the support of others. 懒鬼，游手好闲的人一个懒惰或得过且过的人，尤指靠别人施舍过生活的人', '副词: shiftlessly 名词: shiftlessness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conciliate', '[kən\'sɪlɪˌeɪt]', 'vt.安抚；调和；取悦于', '1. They tried to conciliate the natives with presents. 他们用礼物来博得土著人的好感。 2. He wanted to explain and conciliate her. 他要向她解释，劝慰她。 3. They are both trying hard to conciliate one another. 双方都在拼命想取得谅解。 4. It is hard to conciliate their views. 他们的看法殊难调和。', '形容词: conciliable 名词: conciliation 过去式: conciliated 过去分词: conciliated 现在分词: conciliating 第三人称单数: conciliates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('congeal', '[kən\'dʒiːl]', 'v.(使)凝结；凝固', '1. Gear lubricants may congeal and channel in cold weather. 天气冷时齿轮润滑油可能凝结而形成凹槽。', '形容词: congealable 名词: congealer 过去式: congealed 过去分词: congealed 现在分词: congealing 第三人称单数: congeals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insecticide', '[ɪn\'sektɪsaɪd]', 'n.杀虫剂', '1. The gardener sprayed insecticide on the flowers. 那园丁给花喷洒了杀虫剂。 2. The pad is impregnated with insecticide. 垫子上满是杀虫剂。', '形容词: insecticidal 副词: insecticidally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sensible', '[\'sensəbl]', 'adj.明智的；合情理的；可觉察的；实际的 n.可感知物', '1. To wink at rudeness in children is not sensible. 对小孩粗鲁的行为视若无睹是不明智的。 2. That sounds very sensible to me. 我觉得这很合理。 3. Saving your presence, I don\'t think the suggestion is very sensible. 请恕我直言，我认为这个建议不太合情理。 4. Her distress was sensible from her manner. 她的悲痛从她的态度上可觉察到。 5. The world of dreams is our real world whilst we are sleeping because our attention then lapses from the sensible world. 在睡眠中梦见的世界便是我们的真实世界，因为那时我们的注意力已从可感知世界转移开。', '副词: sensibly 名词: sensibleness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alliterate', '[ə\'lɪtəˌreɪt]', 'v.（使）押头韵', '1. The four T\'s alliterate well. 这四个T头韵押得有韵味。 2. The four T\'s alliterate well. 这四个T头韵押得有韵味。 3. the letter with which they alliterate 他们使用头韵法所用的字母', '过去式: alliterated 过去分词: alliterated 现在分词: alliterating 第三人称单数: alliterates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mitigate', '[\'mɪtɪɡeɪt]', 'vt.减轻；缓和', '1. The judge said that nothing could mitigate the cruelty with which the stepmother had treated the girl. 法官说没有任何理由可以把那个继母残忍虐待女孩的罪责减轻。 2. Her words mitigated my suffering. 她的话减轻了我的痛苦。 3. The government is trying to mitigate the effects of inflation. 政府正试图缓和通货膨胀的影响。', '形容词: mitigable 名词: mitigation 过去式: mitigated 过去分词: mitigated 现在分词: mitigating 第三人称单数: mitigates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('simultaneous', '[ˌsaɪml\'teɪniəs]', 'adj.同时发生的；同步的', '1. The explosion was timed to be simultaneous with the plane\'s take-off. 爆炸的时间定在飞机起飞的时刻。 2. The simultaneous demonstrations are held in London and New York. 在伦敦和纽约同时举行示威游行。 3. There were several simultaneous attacks by the rebels. 反叛者同时发动了几起攻击。 4. Her work as a simultaneous translator requires strong powers of concentration. 作为同步翻译员，她的工作需要极大的专注力。', '副词: simultaneously 名词: simultaneousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bench', '[bentʃ]', 'n.长凳；工作台；法官', '1. This bench is made of elm. 这条长凳是榆木制的。 2. An old man sat on the park bench and fed the pigeon. 一位老人坐在公园的长凳上喂鸽子。 3. A young woman, of sullen aspect, was sitting alone on the bench. 一个面色忧郁的年轻女人独自坐在长凳上。 4. I\'m glad the new trainee is keen but I wish he\'d stop hanging around my bench and getting in my hair. 新来的受训者很敏捷，我很满意，不过我希望他别再我工作台周围闲荡，使我觉得烦恼。', '过去式: benched 过去分词: benched 现在分词: benching 第三人称单数: benches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('faction', '[\'fækʃn]', 'n.内讧；小集团；派系斗争', '1. The country is afflicted with faction. 这个国家正遭受内讧。 2. A faction in our club tried to make the president resign. 在我们派别的内讧试图让总统辞职。 3. The faction from the extreme left is trying to elbow its way into power by short-cutting the democratic process. 这个极左小集团试图通过走民主程序的捷径，设法挤进有影响的机构。', '形容词: factional 副词: factionally 名词: factionalism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hack', '[hæk]', 'n.劈或砍；乱踢；咳嗽 n.供出租的马车；雇佣文人；（美口）出租车 vt.非法侵入(他人计算机系统) vi.劈或砍；咳嗽', '1. She gave Scarlett a glare as she saw her look longingly at the hack. 嬷嬷看见思嘉仍在恋恋不舍地打量那辆出租马车，便恶狠狠地瞪了她一眼。 2. The publisher paid his hacks low. 出版商付给他雇佣的文人很低的费用。 3. He was a literary hack, naturally fast in pace and brilliant in action. 他是个雇佣文人，不过天生下笔千言，很有些才气而已。 4. That party hack is just in politics for the money. 那位政客从政的目的只是为了钱。 5. He was hacking at a tree. 他正在砍树。', '形容词: hackable 过去式: hacked 过去分词: hacked 现在分词: hacking 第三人称单数: hacks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abysmal', '[ə\'bɪzməl]', 'adj.深不可测的；极坏的；完全的', '1. Woeful souls are wailing in an abysmal pond. 悲伤的灵魂在无底的深潭里嚎啕。 2. Although there is an abysmal lack of educational software, the number of computers in schools expands rapidly. 虽然教学上用的软件十分紧缺，学校的计算机数量却迅速增加。 3. The film was so abysmal that I fell asleep. 电影太糟糕,看得我睡着了。 4. Despite this, in many developing countries, the literacy rate for women is abysmal. 尽管如此，许多发展中国家的妇女识字率却令人叹息。', '副词: abysmally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mammal', '[\'mæml]', 'n.哺乳动物', '1. The bat is the only mammal that can fly. 蝙蝠是唯一会飞的哺乳动物。 2. Is a meadow more complex than a mammal brain? 草地较之哺乳动物的大脑更复杂吗？', '形容词: mammalian');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hegemony', '[hɪ\'dʒemoʊni]', 'n.霸权；领导权', '1. It was a struggle between the United States and Japan for hegemony in the Far East. 这是一个美国与日本争夺远东霸权的会议。 2. British seapower, after two centuries of hegemony , vanished from the Indian Ocean. 掌握了两个世纪霸权的英国海军，在印度洋上销声匿迹了。 3. The Hegemony Theory advanced by Antonio Gramsci, to some extent, illustrated the rationality and the necessity of the leadership seized by the Communist Party of China. 摘要葛兰西的霸权理论在一定程度上解释了中国共产党夺取领导权的合理性与必然性。', '形容词: hegemonic 名词: hegemonism 名词复数: hegemonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boycott', '[\'bɔɪkɑːt]', 'vt.抵制（贸易）；拒绝参加', '1. He urged all citizens to boycott Korean goods. 他呼吁所有民众联手抵制韩国货。 2. We boycott all products tested on animals. 我们抵制用动物做产品实验。 3. We boycott some country because it hurts our ego. 我们抵制某国货，因为他伤了我们的面子。 4. We are determined to boycott them. 我们决定拒绝跟他们来往。', '名词: boycotter 过去式: boycotted 过去分词: boycotted 现在分词: boycotting 第三人称单数: boycotts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('testiness', '[\'testɪnɪs]', 'n.易怒；暴躁', '1. The world is that sweetness, but I\'m this testiness, it\'s not good, not good. 世界如此美妙我却如此暴躁这样不好，不好。 2. Afterwards, Obama advisers were quick to highlight Mr McCain\'s testiness. 事后，奥巴马的顾问们迅速刻意提到麦凯恩的暴躁。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thermal', '[\'θɜːrml]', 'adj.热的；热量的；保热的 n.上升的热气流', '1. An improved thermal head boosts image quality. 经过改进的热敏头,提高了图像质量。 2. The thermal energy has become more and more important. 热能变得越来越重要了。 3. These are thermal units. 这是热量单位。 4. My mother has bought the thermal underwear for me. 我妈妈已经给我买了保暖内衣。 5. While flying, you feel a weak thermal. 当飞行中，你感觉到一个微弱的热气流。', '副词: thermally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('olfactory', '[ɑːl\'fæktəri]', 'adj.嗅觉的', '1. It arouses their olfactory sense. 这唤起了他们的嗅觉。 2. He is to develop a sensor to substitute for the olfactory abilities of dogs. 克罗克将研制一种传感器用以代替狗的嗅觉功能。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('backset', '[\'bæk]', 'n.倒退；逆流；涡流', '1. Resisting the balance backset current boiling point, the ones that reduce and brake oil volatilize effectively. 搞平衡回流沸点,有效减少刹车油的挥发。 2. Backset spinning process will have a bright future if the limitation of spinning is breaken. 涡流纺纱克服其仅能纷长绒棉一定号数的局限性，提高其制成率后，将会有很大的发展前景。 3. The backset current of the transferred agricultural labor force, and the phenomena of the “pleasant worker neglect” all proved this fact. 转移农村劳动力的回流、“民工荒”现象都佐证了这个事实。 4. This mesh belt without magnetic , general in hardness,apply to thefood industry extensively , the mechanical backset welding, electronic circuit board, purging equipement etc. 该网带无磁性，硬度一致，广泛用于食品工业，机械回流焊、电子线路板、清洗设备等。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('atonal', '[eɪ\'toʊnl]', 'adj.(音乐)无调的；不成调的', '1. There is great atonal music and terrible atonal music. 无调性音乐中既有宏伟动人之作,又有糟得吓人之作。', '副词: atonally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bucolic', '[bjuː\'kɑːlɪk]', 'adj.乡村的；田园的；牧羊的；牧民的', '1. It is a bucolic refuge in the midst of a great bustling city. 它是处在繁华的大城市之中的世外桃源。 2. A few gentleman farmers with plenty of money can still escape to the bucolic life. 只有少数殷实的绅士仍然可以避居乡间过着田园生活。', '副词: bucolically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evolve', '[i\'vɑːlv]', 'v.(使)逐步形成；(使)逐步演变；进化', '1. The American constitution was planned; the British constitution evolved. 美国宪法是精心制定的，英国宪法是约定俗成的。 2. He has evolved a new theory after many years of research. 他经过多年的研究，逐渐总结出了新的理论。 3. If women do not evolve, men definitely will change. 女人一成不变，男人一定会变。 4. Why did humans evolve to walk upright? 人类为何进化到了直立行走的姿态?', '形容词: evolvable 名词: evolvement 过去式: evolved 过去分词: evolved 现在分词: evolving 第三人称单数: evolves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distort', '[dɪ\'stɔːrt]', 'vt.歪曲；扭曲；变形 vi.歪曲', '1. The reporter distorted the facts. 记者们歪曲了事实。 2. How dare he distort the facts so brazenly! 他怎么敢如此肆无忌惮地歪曲事实！ 3. The government was accused of having systematically distorted the protester\'s case. 政府因为有计划地歪曲抗议者的观点而受到责难。 4. This journalist distorted the spokesman\'s remarks. 这名记者曲解了该发言人的话。 5. The bias of a reporter can easily distort the news. 记者的偏见很容易歪曲新闻的报导。', '名词: distorter 过去式: distorted 过去分词: distorted 现在分词: distorting 第三人称单数: distorts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cushion', '[\'kʊʃn]', 'n.垫子；橡皮软垫；缓冲 vt.加垫褥；放在垫子上；保护；减缓；为 ... 装垫子', '1. He covered the cushion with new material. 他给靠垫蒙上了新的料子。 2. She embroidered the cushion with flowers. 她把垫子绣上了花。 3. A hovercraft rides on a cushion of air. 气垫船悬浮在气垫上行驶. 4. The bush acted as a cushion to my fall. 这灌木在我摔下时起了缓冲作用。 5. We are going to cushion the rocking chair so that it is more comfortable. 我们要在摇椅上铺软垫，那么就会更舒适了。', '形容词: cushiony 过去式: cushioned 过去分词: cushioned 现在分词: cushioning 第三人称单数: cushions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('belabor', '[bɪ\'leɪbə]', 'vt.痛击；痛斥；冗长地解释', '1. To belabor(an issue or a subject). 对（问题或主题）作过多说明 2. I won’t belabor the point more than this. 我对这个问题的看法就阐述至此。 3. We won\'t belabor the theory and background. 我们不会就理论和背景做太多的论述。 4. He seems to be looking for a man of straw to belabor. 他看来在找一个假想的敌人来加以痛打。', '过去式: belabored 过去分词: belabored 现在分词: belaboring 第三人称单数: belabors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clamor', '[\'klæmə]', 'n.喧嚷；大声的要求 v.喧嚷；大声要求', '1. A clamor in the press for pollution control. 在报纸上对污染控制的呼吁 2. A din; a clamor. 喧闹; 吵闹 3. They made a clamor for reform. 他们强烈要求改革。 4. The clamor of traffic gave me a headache. 交通噪音让我头痛。', '名词: clamorer 过去式: clamored 过去分词: clamored 现在分词: clamoring 第三人称单数: clamors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chore', '[tʃɔːr]', 'n.讨厌的工作；琐事；家务', '1. She finds shopping a chore. 她认为买东西是烦人的事。 2. It\'s such a chore to change diapers. 换尿布真是一件讨厌的事。 3. Shopping isn\'t a chore, it\'s recreation. 购物不是一件琐事，而是休闲。 4. All this was done to relieve women of household chores. 这一切都是为了把妇女从家务劳动中解放出来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('airborne', '[\'erbɔːrn]', 'adj.空运的；空中传播的；起飞后在飞行中', '1. Some doubt Kirlin can get them airborne. 有人怀疑柯林不可能把飞机空运过来。 2. The airborne forces however met hard fortune. 但是，空降部队遇到了不幸的命运。 3. There is no evidence that the disease is airborne. 目前并无证据显示疾病是由空气传播。 4. Using coke in iron ore reduction produces copious quantities of airborne particulates. 炼铁过程中使用焦炭，会在空中形成大量的悬浮粒子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beatific', '[ˌbiːə\'tɪfɪk]', 'adj.祝福的；快乐的；慈祥的', '1. In beatific sound of close friends,I became his happy bride. 在亲朋好友的祝福声中，我做了他的幸福的新娘。 2. All parents wish their children could have a safe and beatific life. 父母都渴望他们的孩子们平安快乐。 3. The angels in the painting have beatific smiles. 油画中的天使有着安详的笑容。', '副词: beatifically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extirpation', '[ˌekstə\'peɪʃn]', 'n.消减；根除；毁减；[医]摘除', '1. Complete extirpation of the rumor was performed via an extraoral approach. 治疗方式探外手术，经口外切线将肿瘤分割摘除。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fail-safe', '[feɪl seɪf]', 'n.自动防故障装置 adj.故障自动保险的；能组织军事攻击的；万无一失的', '1. At present, absolutely safe schemes are being investigated and compared. 目前，万无一失的方案正在探索和比较中。', '过去式: fail-safed 过去分词: fail-safed 现在分词: fail-safing 第三人称单数: fail-safes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('toy', '[tɔɪ]', 'n.玩具', '1. He was appointed to superintend the toy department. 他获任玩具部的负责人。 2. The child clutched his toy. 那个孩子紧抓着他的玩具不放。', '过去式: toyed 过去分词: toyed 现在分词: toying 第三人称单数: toys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rent', '[rent]', 'n.租金 v.租用；出租 动词rend的过去式和过去分词.', '1. The rent is due at the end of each quarter. 缴纳租金以每季度末为期限。 2. They let the house to me at a rent of 100 dollars a month. 他们把房子租给我，每月租金一百美元。 3. I rent a room from her. 我向她租了一个房间。 4. I\'d like to rent a car for just one day. 我想租一部车，一天即可。', '形容词: rentable 名词: rentability 过去式: rented 过去分词: rented 现在分词: renting 第三人称单数: rents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distal', '[\'dɪstl]', 'adj.末梢部的', '1. The distal duodenum and jejunum remain on the right side of the spine . 远端十二指肠及空肠仍处于脊椎右侧。 2. There is no correspondence between evolved modules and distal behaviors. 神经网络的模块与机器人的终端行为之间没有一一对应的关系。', '副词: distally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intertwine', '[ˌɪntər\'twaɪn]', 'v.纠缠；缠绕；编结', '1. His fingers intertwined with hers. 他的手指勾著她的手指。', '名词: intertwinement 过去式: intertwined 过去分词: intertwined 现在分词: intertwining 第三人称单数: intertwines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retiring', '[rɪ\'taɪərɪŋ]', 'adj.退休的；退役的；腼腆的；不爱交际的 动词retire的现在分词.', '1. I can\'t disappoint my public by retiring. 我可不能退休，否则大家会失望的。 2. Some people find retiring difficult, but he has taken it all in his stride. 有些人觉得退休生活很艰难,但他轻而易举地适应了。 3. Retiring early from his job freed him to join several local clubs. 他早早退休，摆脱了工作的羁绊而加入了当地的几个俱乐部。 4. He pitched for ten years before retiring. 退役前他当了十年投手。', '副词: retiringly 名词: retiringness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invigilate', '[ɪn\'vɪdʒɪleɪt]', 'v.监考；监督', '1. The invigilators and markers can\'t refuse to invigilate and mark in the designated site of the field test. 监评人员无正当理由不得拒绝至指定术科测试场地担任监评工作。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gobble', '[\'ɡɑːbl]', 'vt.狼吞虎咽；很快用完；发出咯咯叫声 n.咯咯叫声', '1. As he was still hungry, he gobbled up a second sandwich. 因为还饿，他又狼吞虎咽地吃了第二块三明治。 2. She gobbled up all the relevant information. 她如饥似渴地收集一切有关的信息。 3. The government seems to gobble up the taxpayers\' money. 政府似乎大笔大笔地乱花纳税人的税款。', '过去式: gobbled 过去分词: gobbled 现在分词: gobbling 第三人称单数: gobbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('encomiastic', '[enˌkoʊmɪ\'æstɪk]', 'adj.赞颂的；阿谀的', '1. Since 90 time metaphase, globalization became the heat that people argues stage by stage, to the research manner of this problem, encomiast has, the; 自90年代中期以来,全球化逐步成为了人们争论的热点,对此问题的研究态度,赞美者有之,诅咒者也有之; 2. encomiast n. 宣读或写作颂辞之人;赞美者;阿谀者', 'none');
