INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('daub', '[dɔːb]', 'v.涂抹；乱画 n.涂抹；涂料；拙劣的画', '1. The next procedure is to daub a layer of mortar on the wall. 下一道手续是在墙面上涂抹一层沙浆。 2. I am not a good painter but I like to daub. 我不是个好画家，但我喜欢涂鸦。 3. The children were encouraged to daub the colors in liberally. 他们鼓励孩子随意大胆地涂色。 4. Some cheeses have a special recipe for this daub. 有些奶酪有特别的磨擦方法。', '名词: dauber 过去式: daubed 过去分词: daubed 现在分词: daubing 第三人称单数: daubs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('caricature', '[\'kærɪkətʃər]', 'n.讽刺画；讽刺；歪曲；笨拙的模仿 v.画成漫画；讽刺；使滑稽化', '1. His caricature flintily lashes current political high-up. 他的漫画无情地讽刺了当今的政界要人。 2. His caricature flintily lashes current political high-up. 他的漫画无情地讽刺了当今的政界要人。 3. His caricature satirized modern political V.I.P sharply. 他的漫画无情地讽刺了当今的政界要人。 4. He had unfairly presented a caricature of my views. 他歪曲了我的观点。 5. His caricature flintily lashes current political high-up. 他的漫画无情地讽刺了当今的政界要人。', '名词: caricaturist 过去式: caricatured 过去分词: caricatured 现在分词: caricaturing 第三人称单数: caricatures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('setback', '[\'setbæk]', 'n.挫折；失败；退步', '1. He met with many a setback in his lifetime. 他一生中遭到过许多挫折。 2. This setback has drained away my keenness. 这次挫折削弱了我的热情。 3. Undaunted by his first setback, he decided to try once more. 不为最初的失败而动摇，他决定再试一次。 4. This latest arrest was just one minor setback. 最近的逮捕只不过是一个小小的退步。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('precept', '[\'priːsept]', 'n.道德箴言；规则；训诫', '1. Example is better than precept. 身教胜于言传。 2. Just follow these few basic precepts and you won\'t go far wrong in life. 只要按这几条格言行事，你一生就不会出大错。 3. In the Anglo-American system, of course, precedent is a fundamental precept. 当然，在英美法系中，先例是基本的规则。 4. There is no moral precept that does not have something inconvenient about it. 任何一条道德戒律在奉行时都会引起不便。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gulch', '[ɡʌltʃ]', 'n.冲沟；激流峡谷', '1. Fixed several terrain exploits in Warsong Gulch. 修正数个战歌峡谷地形。 2. Loess gulch nearing Hui Ning hsien. Feb. 13. 2月13日，会宁县附近的黄土峡谷。 3. He\'s the sheriff at Twin Gulch, Idaho, and I\'m his deputy. 他是爱达荷州特温加尔奇的治安官，我是他的副手。 4. A deep gully cut by an intermittent stream; a dry gulch. 旱谷被断断续续的河水断开的山谷；干涸的沟壑', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dabbler', '[\'dæblə]', 'n.戏水者；业余家；半玩半认真做的人', '1. A dabbler in an art or a field of knowledge. 浅薄的涉猎者在艺术或知识领域里的涉猎者 2. The moon lake is crowded with dabbler in this summer evening. 在这个夏日的黄昏戏水者云集于月湖。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shrug', '[ʃrʌɡ]', 'n.耸肩 v.耸肩；不理会', '1. She gave a shrug of her shoulders. 她耸了耸肩膀。 2. She gave a shrug and walked away. 她耸了耸肩就离开了。 3. I would answer with a shrug of my shoulders. 我总是耸耸肩回答。 4. They would shrug their shoulders, and treat you like a child. 他们一定会耸耸肩膀,把你当作孩子看待!', '过去式: shrugged 过去分词: shrugged 现在分词: shrugging 第三人称单数: shrugs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('querulous', '[\'kwerələs]', 'adj.抱怨的；发牢骚的；爱挑剔的', '1. The child\'s querulous questions were driving me crazy. 那小孩所抱怨的问题快令我发疯了。 2. He was also petty, unreasonably querulous, and mean. 他还是个气量狭窄，无事生非，平庸刻薄的人。 3. Helpfully, the party\'s backbenchers are not proving particularly querulous. 还好，工党的普通议员被证明并不特别爱发牢骚。 4. He was not one who was inclined to be querulous. 他并不是爱吹毛求疵的人。', '副词: querulously 名词: querulousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debacle', '[deɪ\'bɑːkl]', 'n.惨败；溃逃；灾难；狂流', '1. His first performance was a debacle: the audience booed him off the stage. 他的首场演出一败涂地，观众发出嘘声把他轰下了台。 2. The debacle at Waterloo signaled the end of Napoleon\'s power. 滑铁卢的溃败暗示拿破仑政权的结束。 3. Many men were shot or captured in the debacle. 败军在溃逃时有很多人被击毙或俘虏。 4. Bernabo Bocca, chairman of the Italian hoteliers\' association, described the results as a debacle. 意大利酒店经营者协会主席博卡认为结果是灾难性的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frolicsome', '[\'frɑːlɪksəm]', 'adj.爱闹着玩的；嬉戏的', '1. Frolicsome students celebrated their graduation with parties and practical jokes. 欢乐的学生们用聚会和恶作剧来庆祝他们的毕业 2. One that is playful or frolicsome. 嬉戏的或开玩笑的人', 'none');
