INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kindred', '[\'kɪndrəd]', 'n.家人和亲戚；相似；亲戚关系 adj.同族的；同类的；血缘的', '1. Most of his kindred still live in Ireland. 他的亲戚大部分仍住在爱尔兰。 2. Only a few of his kindred were present at his funeral. 只有少数亲戚参加了他的葬礼。 3. English and Dutch are kindred languages. 英语和荷兰语是同源的语言. 4. We immediately realized that we were kindred spirits. 我们马上发觉彼此志同道合。', '名词: kindredness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disembody', '[ˌdɪsɪm\'bɒdɪ]', 'vt.使由肉体脱离', '1. Disembodied voices could be heard in the darkness. 在黑暗中听见了人声，却看不见人影。 2. Let us suppose that you or I, brethren, shall become a free and disembody spirit. 诸兄弟，让我们假设你或我将变成脱离了躯壳的自由精灵。', '名词: disembodiment 过去式: disembodied 过去分词: disembodied 现在分词: disembodying 第三人称单数: disembodies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hurricane', '[\'hɜːrəkən]', 'n.飓风；暴风', '1. The hurricane destroyed the whole village. 飓风把整个村子都毁掉了。 2. The hurricane screamed outside. 外面飓风呼啸著。 3. The hurricane has a speed of 73 miles per hour. 飓风每小时73英里。 4. The radio alerted the citizens to prepare for the hurricane. 电台警告市民们作好预防暴风准备。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defined', '[dɪ\'faɪnd]', 'adj.有定义的；明确的，确定的，清晰的；轮廓分明的 v.规定；限定；定义；解释（动词define的过去式和过去分词）', '1. The mountain was sharply defined against the eastern sky. 那座山在东方天空的衬托下显得轮廓分明。 2. The powers of the police need to be clearly defined. 必须对警方的权限作出明确的规定。 3. The powers of a judge are defined by law. 法官的权限是由法律规定的。 4. When boundaries between countries are not clearly defined, there is usually trouble. 国与国之间的边界未明确划定时，通常会发生纠纷。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('generator', '[\'dʒenəreɪtər]', 'n.发电机；发生器', '1. The propeller turns a small D.C. generator. 螺旋桨带动一个小型直流发电机。 2. If you have, then The Idea Generator is for you. 如果你有，那么发电机理念是为你。 3. Let\'s purify air with a negative ion generator. 我们用负离子发生器净化一下空气吧。 4. Well, it\'s essentially a random number generator. 好，基本上就是一个随机数发生器。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('veto', '[\'viːtoʊ]', 'n.否决；否决权 v.否决', '1. Will they interpose their veto again? 他们还会再次否决吗? 2. An abstention is not regarded as a veto. 弃权不视为否决。 3. Mr Bush\'s veto does not kill stem-cell research. 布什的否决没有彻底封杀干细胞研究。 4. They carried the ministerial veto. 他们行使了内阁否决权。 5. The president last week vetoed the tax cut. 总统上个星期否决了减税法案。', '名词: vetoer 名词复数: vetoes 过去式: vetoed 过去分词: vetoed 现在分词: vetoing 第三人称单数: vetoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sacred', '[\'seɪkrɪd]', 'adj.神圣的；受尊重的', '1. In India the cow is a sacred animal. 在印度，牛是神圣的动物。 2. We use them to protect our sacred grounds. 我们使用它们来保卫我们神圣的土地。 3. Nothing is sacred to these wild youths. 这些狂野的年轻人什么都不尊重。 4. This area was hallowed by sacred memories. 这个地区由于宗教上的纪念意义而被视为圣地。', '副词: sacredly 名词: sacredness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hexagon', '[\'heksəɡɑːn]', 'adj.六角形的 n.六角形；六边形', '1. The library with the hexagon shape always attracts students. 这个六角形形状的图书馆总是吸引着学生们。 2. The church tower likes a huge hexagon. 教堂的钟楼像一个大的六边形。 3. Perfect hexagon is the most compact grouping of wires. 精确的六角形是最密实的钢丝束。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wizardry', '[\'wɪzərdri]', 'n.魔术；巫术；绝技', '1. He wants to attend a school for wizardry. 他想要进入一所魔法学校。 2. I don\'t know you\'ve been studying wizardry. 我还不知道你学过法术呢。 3. He is a pianist with technical wizardry. 他是一个拥有专业技巧的天才钢琴家。', '名词复数: wizardries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conundrum', '[kə\'nʌndrəm]', 'n.谜语；难题', '1. I\'m going to tell you why this conundrum exists. 我打算告诉你们为什么这个谜题存在。 2. Let me tell you what science has done with the conundrum. 让我告诉你们科学与谜题曾有的关系。 3. It\'s a conundrum as it is. 这本来就是一道难题。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extemporize', '[ɪk\'stempəraɪz]', 'v.即席演说；即兴演奏；当场作成 =extemporise（英）.', '1. He had to extemporize because he had forgotten to bring his notes. 他因为忘了带讲稿，只好即席发言。', '名词: extemporization 过去式: extemporized 过去分词: extemporized 现在分词: extemporizing 第三人称单数: extemporizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('postpone', '[poʊ\'spoʊn]', 'vt.延期；推迟', '1. The weather being bad, we had to postpone our trip. 因为天气不好,我们不得不延期出行。 2. She did not postpone her departure. 她不再延迟她的行期。 3. Can we postpone the meeting till tomorrow? 我们可以把会议延到明天吗? 4. The commander decided to postpone the big push until the spring. 指挥官决定把大规模的进攻推迟到春天进行。', '形容词: postponable 名词: postponement 过去式: postponed 过去分词: postponed 现在分词: postponing 第三人称单数: postpones');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expatiate', '[ɪk\'speɪʃieɪt]', 'v.详述；细说；漫游', '1. His deep knowledge of the historical background enabled him to expatiate upon the significance of the movement. 他对于历史背景的深刻了解使他能够详细阐述这场运动的意义。 2. The chairman expatiated for two hours on his plans for the company. 董事长用两小时阐述了公司的规划。', '名词: expatiation 过去式: expatiated 过去分词: expatiated 现在分词: expatiating 第三人称单数: expatiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('roster', '[\'rɑːstər]', 'n.值勤表；花名册', '1. One has to wonder what the Rockets stand to gain by keeping him on their roster. 你必须知道火箭为什么让他留在他们的花名册里。 2. The NRF has failed to fill its roster, and has been informally cut back. 北约反应部队没能填满它的花名册，并且被非正式地削减规模。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('autocracy', '[ɔː\'tɑːkrəsi]', 'n.独裁政治；独裁政府', '1. There is no sanction for autocracy. 没有人赞成独裁统治。 2. Autocracy often causes the people to revolt. 独裁统治常常引起人民的反抗。 3. The revolution caused the overthrow of the autocracy. 这场革命导致了独裁政体的结束。', '名词复数: autocracies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clinch', '[klɪntʃ]', 'v.钉牢；紧抓；扭住对手；最终解决 n.揪扭；拥抱；固定', '1. We realize that it is not easy to clinch the medals. 大家意识到想夺取奖牌已经不是那么容易了。 2. Mike Bryan talked about getting the chance to clinch the victory. 麦克布莱恩表达了拥抱胜利的喜悦。 3. The boxers clinch and the referee have to separate them. 拳击手扭抱在一起，裁判让他们分开。 4. We clinched the agreement with a handshake. 我们握手达成协议。 5. When the police came the fighters were in a clinch. 警察到来时，打架的人正扭成一团。', '过去式: clinched 过去分词: clinched 现在分词: clinching 第三人称单数: clinches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appreciable', '[ə\'priːʃəbl]', 'adj.可感知的；可评估的；很可观的', '1. There is no appreciable difference between the two. 两者之间没有什么可感知的区别。 2. I think that human exertion will have no appreciable effect upon humanity. 我想人类的努力对人性没有可评价的效果。 3. The increase in salary will be appreciable. 薪水的增加将很可观.', '副词: appreciably');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('profiteer', '[ˌprɒfɪ\'tɪər]', 'v.牟取暴利 n.获暴利的人；奸商', '1. Over the ocean, an American profiteer fine-tunes his anticipated raid on United, craving to dip into the revenue streams unleashed by Ferguson. 在大洋彼岸，一名美国奸商正在伺机入侵曼联，此举无非是觊觎弗格森为曼联创造的源源不断的财富。', '过去式: profiteered 过去分词: profiteered 现在分词: profiteering 第三人称单数: profiteers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ginger', '[\'dʒɪndʒər]', 'n.姜；姜根；精力；深棕色 vt.用姜调味；使 ... 活泼', '1. He offered me some ginger snaps. 他请我吃些姜脆饼。 2. Would you like me to bring some ginger? 您希望我拿些姜来吗? 3. Do you like ginger beer? 你喜欢姜汁啤酒吗？ 4. The root ginger should be crushed up before it is added to the boiling jam. 姜根在加入煮沸的果酱中前必须碾碎后喂小孩子吃。 5. Some dancing would ginger up the party. 跳跳舞就可以使聚会活跃起来。', '形容词: gingery 过去式: gingered 过去分词: gingered 现在分词: gingering 第三人称单数: gingers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('noncommittal', '[ˌnɒnkə\'mɪtəl]', 'adj.态度暧昧的；含糊的', '1. I asked him if he approved of our plan,but he was noncommittal. 我问他是否赞同我们的计划，但他态度不明朗。 2. Harry gave a noncommittal grunt. 哈利含糊地咕噜了一句。', '副词: noncommittally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lineal', '[\'lɪniəl]', 'adj.直系的；嫡系的；直线的', '1. He is a lineal descendant of the company\'s founder. 他是公司创始人的直系后裔。 2. The lineal development of history should be carefully studied and analyzed. 必须认真学习和分析历史的纵向发展。', '副词: lineally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('manipulative', '[mə\'nɪpjəleɪtɪv]', 'adj.巧妙处理的；操纵的；用手控制的', '1. He\'s extremely manipulative, so don\'t let him persuade you. 别听他的，他这个人很会摆布人。 2. Thus, it is evident that gossip has a strong manipulative potential. 由此看来,流言显然具有很强的操纵力。 3. This position needs good manipulative ability and certain quality awareness. 这个职位需要有较强的动手能力和一定的质量意识。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pauper', '[\'pɔːpər]', 'n.乞丐；贫民；穷人', '1. He guards the sleep of his pauper master if he were a prince. 即使主人是乞丐，他也会像守护王子一样伴随着主人。 2. The King disguised himself in a pauper\'s clothes. 国王穿上贫儿的衣服以掩盖身份。 3. A pauper has as much a right to learn as a king. 穷人和国王一样均有受教育的权利。 4. Becoming a richer,that is the best way to help pauper. 帮助穷人的最好办法', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solidify', '[sə\'lɪdɪfaɪ]', 'v.变固体；凝固；变坚定；使团结', '1. Extreme cold will solidify water. 极冷会使水凝结。 2. The mixture solidifies into toffee. 这种混合物凝结之后就成了太妃糖。 3. Vague objections to the system solidified into firm opposition. 先前对这一制度不大明朗的反对演变成了坚决的抵制。', '名词: solidification 过去式: solidified 过去分词: solidified 现在分词: solidifying 第三人称单数: solidifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abscond', '[əb\'skɑːnd]', 'v.潜逃；逃匿', '1. He absconded from the country. 他已潜逃出境。 2. He absconded from the bank with all the money. 他拿走了银行的全部现金，潜逃无踪。 3. He attempted to abscond from the punishment. 他企图逃避惩罚。 4. You can not abscond from your responsibilities. 你不能逃避你的职责。', '名词: absconder 过去式: absconded 过去分词: absconded 现在分词: absconding 第三人称单数: absconds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disseminate', '[dɪ\'semɪneɪt]', 'vt.散播；公开；宣传', '1. They use the press to disseminate right-wing views. 他们利用报刊来传播右翼观点。 2. It is illegal to disseminate lies. 散布谣言是非法的。 3. It is essential to widely disseminate these ideas among young people. 在青年里面应该广泛地宣传这些思想。', '名词: dissemination 过去式: disseminated 过去分词: disseminated 现在分词: disseminating 第三人称单数: disseminates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('backdrop', '[\'bækdrɑːp]', 'n.背景幕；背景', '1. The events of the 1930s provided the backdrop for the film. 二十世纪三十年代的一些事件为这部电影提供了背景。 2. What showed on the ceremony backdrop was just Dafen Art Museum. 颁奖现场主背景板上所展示的正是大芬美术馆。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sundry', '[\'sʌndri]', 'adj.各种各样的；杂七杂八的 n.（sundries）杂物；杂项', '1. We can see the rich man on sundry occasions. 我们能在各种场合见到那个富豪。 2. My wallet is filled with sundry items. 我的钱包装满了各种杂七杂八的东西。 3. There\'s an item on the hotel bill for sundries. 酒店账单上有一个杂物项目。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pedagogue', '[\'pedəɡɑːɡ]', 'n.教师；教育者；学究 =pedagog.', '1. One of the most important duties of a pedagogue is to teach the pupil how to practice correctly. 指导学生以正确的方法练习是教师最重要的任务之一。', '形容词: pedagoguish');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seasoning', '[\'siːzənɪŋ]', 'n.调料', '1. This sauce uses mushroom as its seasoning. 这调味酱用蘑菇作调料。 2. The leaves of this plant can be used as a seasoning. 这种植物的叶子，可用作调料。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('persnickety', '[pər\'snɪkəti]', 'adj.势利的；挑剔的', '1. He hey hey one happy, say: Not so persnickety! 他嘿嘿一乐，说：别那么小气嘛！ 2. No one is willing to contact with such a persnickety guy. 对于这样小气的人;谁也不愿意和他打交道. 3. A lot of persnickety bubble had on the hand, defeated with respect to desquamate, what element does the body lack? 手上起了很多小气泡，破了就脱皮了，是不是身体缺什么元素了？ 4. Li Yue disposition is persnickety very, play make a person bad to understand more. 李越性情很是小气，处事多让人不好理解。', '名词: persnicketiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spiny', '[\'spaɪni]', 'adj.多刺的；尖刺状的；困难的；麻烦的', '1. This is the Asiatic ornamental shrub with spiny branches and pink or red blossoms. 这就是亚洲的一种观赏灌木，具有多刺的枝和粉红色或红色的花。', '比较级: spinier 最高级: spiniest 名词: spininess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('winding', '[\'waɪndɪŋ]', 'n.卷；线圈 adj.蜿蜒的；弯曲的', '1. The winder will consist of an air expanded winding mandrel. 卷取机由气动胀缩卷筒组成。 2. It adopts double working position for winding,unwinding and sealing. 双工位放料和收卷，双工位封口。 3. As the winding insulation has aged,the value is close to zero. 由于绕组的绝缘老化,其数值接近于零。 4. Still they lead me back to the long and winding road. 但它们仍然但我回到这条漫长又蜿蜒的路上，', '副词: windingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sham', '[ʃæm]', 'n.假；赝品；骗子；枕头套 adj.假的；伪造的 v.假装；学样子', '1. His love was a sham; he only wanted her money. 他爱她是假的，他只想要她的钱。 2. She claims to know all about computers but really she\'s a sham. 她自称精通计算机，其实她是假充内行。 3. Are these real diamonds or only sham? 这些是真的钻石还是赝品? 4. He a man! Hell! He was a hollow sham. 他是男子汉？见鬼！他是个虚伪的骗子。 5. They cunningly played the game of sham peace. 他们狡滑地玩弄假和平的把戏。 6. He\'s only shamming. 他只是假装而已。', '名词: shammer 过去式: shammed 过去分词: shammed 现在分词: shamming 第三人称单数: shams');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('belch', '[beltʃ]', 'v.打嗝；喷出', '1. He gave a loud belch. 他打了一个响嗝。 2. Plant chimneys belch out dense smoke. 工厂的烟囱冒出滚滚浓烟。', '过去式: belched 过去分词: belched 现在分词: belching 第三人称单数: belches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saturnine', '[\'sætərnaɪn]', 'adj.忧郁的；铅中毒的；受土星影响的；沉默寡言的；讥讽的', '1. The saturnine faces of the judges. 法官们那阴沉的脸色 2. Do not be misled by his saturnine contenance. 别被他阴郁的外表欺骗了。 3. Just how bad is the saturnine Hogwarts professor? 这位阴沉的霍格沃兹教授究竟有多邪恶？ 4. My former roommate was a saturnine scholar who said very little and smiled rarely. 我前一位室友是一位沉默的学者，他很少说话也很少笑。', '副词: saturninely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('celebrated', '[\'selɪbreɪtɪd]', 'adj.著名的；声誉卓著的 动词celebrate的过去式和过去分词.', '1. The celebrated violinist was mobbed by the audience. 观众团团围住了这位著名的小提琴演奏家。 2. This is celebrated as the Onam festival in Kerala, where he is also called Maveli. 这在印度西南部喀拉拉邦著名的奥南节也有庆祝，他也被称为玛瓦利。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dribble', '[\'drɪbl]', 'vt.使 ... 慢慢流下；运球；细流；流口水 n.少量；细流', '1. Dribble the oil into the beaten egg yolks. 往打匀的蛋黄里一滴滴加油. 2. He dribbled (the ball) past the goalie to score. 他带球越过守门员射门得分。 3. Babies often dribble at the mouth. 婴儿常会在嘴角流口水。 4. He wiped a dribble of milk from his chin with a handkerchief. 他用手帕擦去淌在下巴上的一点牛奶。', '名词: dribbler 过去式: dribbled 过去分词: dribbled 现在分词: dribbling 第三人称单数: dribbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chameleon', '[kə\'miːliən]', 'n.变色龙；善变的人；轻浮的人', '1. The chameleon can take on the colours of its background. 变色龙可将身体颜色变得与周围环境相同。 2. The chameleon rambled slowly down the branch. 那只变色龙沿着枝条慢慢往下爬。 3. He\'s a chameleon with no opinions of his own. 他是一个自己没有主张、反复无常的人。 4. He is something of a political chameleon. 他有点像政治上的变色龙。', '形容词: chameleonic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elevate', '[\'elɪveɪt]', 'vt.举起；提拔；素养提升；鼓舞 vi.变高', '1. They had the attempt to elevate Anderson to the presidency. 他们企图把安德逊抬上总统宝座。 2. He used a couple of bolsters to elevate his head. 他用两个垫枕垫头。 3. They had the attempt to elevate Anderson to the presidency. 他们企图把安德逊抬上总统宝座。 4. Reading good books elevates your mind. 阅读好书使人思想高尚。', '过去式: elevated 过去分词: elevated 现在分词: elevating 第三人称单数: elevates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coerce', '[koʊ\'ɜːrs]', 'vt.强制；威胁', '1. You can\'t coerce her into obedience. 你不能强制她服从。 2. Do you think there is any way that we can coerce them otherwise? 你认为我们有什么办法强迫他们不那样吗? 3. His plan was to resist every effort to coerce him to the last ditch. 他的计划就是要同那欺凌他的力量抵抗到底。 4. The policy of the prohibition against using tortures to coerce a statement is provided clearly and definitely. 严禁逼供信政策明确规定了公安机关及其人员在讯问过程中不得刑讯逼供。', '形容词: coercible 名词: coercer 过去式: coerced 过去分词: coerced 现在分词: coercing 第三人称单数: coerces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('certification', '[ˌsɜːrtɪfɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.证明；认证；证书；鉴定', '1. In 2001, there were four schools asking for LEED certification. 在2001年，仅有四所学校申请LEED证明。 2. We\'ve had ISO certification for a long time. 我们早就通过iso认证了。 3. Please select at least one certification authority. 请选择至少一个证书颁发机构。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extrovert', '[\'ekstrəvɜːrt]', 'n.性格外向的人 =extravert.', '1. Extrovert prefer lively conversation to brood on the meaning of life. 性格外向的人喜欢高谈阔论，而不愿思索人生的意义。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antiquity', '[æn\'tɪkwəti]', 'n.古代；古物；古迹', '1. The culture of antiquity was rediscovered. 古代文化重见天日。 2. Animals and plants of remote antiquity turned to fossils. 远古的动植物变成了化石。 3. There are many legends about the heroes of antiquity. 有许多关于古代英雄的传说。 4. The Roman legion was the ultimate military formation of antiquity. 罗马的军团是古代异常强大的军事作战团队。', '名词复数: antiquities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fumble', '[\'fʌmbl]', 'vi.摸索；笨手笨脚地做 vt.笨拙地做；弄乱；失球 n.摸索；失球；漏接球', '1. Want to have patience, want to fumble slowly. 要有耐心，要慢慢摸索。 2. You fumble to find your passport when you cross a frontier. 当你出境时，要摸索着寻找护照。', '名词: fumbler 过去式: fumbled 过去分词: fumbled 现在分词: fumbling 第三人称单数: fumbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jog', '[dʒɑːɡ]', 'v.慢跑；轻推；（使）颠簸前行 n.慢跑；轻推；颠簸', '1. He goes jogging every night. 他每晚慢跑。 2. You jogged my elbow and spoiled what I was drawing. 你撞到了我的手肘，弄坏了我正在画的图画。 3. The wagon jogged along on the rough road. 马车沿着崎岖不平的道路颠簸前行。 4. I go for a jog in the park every morning. 每天早晨我在公园里慢跑。', '名词: jogger 过去式: jogged 过去分词: jogged 现在分词: jogging 第三人称单数: jogs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ensemble', '[ɑːn\'sɑːmbl]', 'n.全体；剧团；联合演出人员；合奏曲；系综', '1. Based on the ensemble learning method, the outliers are learned and deleted from the training corpus. 本研究采用基于系综学习的野点学习方法剔除网页中的噪声样本，有效地提高了文本分类的性能。 2. The systematical state distributions and the related thermodynamic formulaeare by the ensemble theory of statistical mechanics. 用统计力学的系综理论，研究体系的状态分布以及有关的热力学公式。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delve', '[delv]', 'vi.探究；挖掘；搜索', '1. She had started to delve into her father\'s distant past. 她开始探究她父亲久已逝去的岁月。 2. He delves into lots of old books and papers for the fact. 他钻研许多古书与文件,以寻找事实。 3. We need to delve more deeply into these questions. 这些是我们想进一步了解的。 4. But someday，I want to learn how to do something before I delve into something else. 但也许有一天在我要进入这些领域前,我想我会深入地去学习。', '名词: delver 过去式: delved 过去分词: delved 现在分词: delving 第三人称单数: delves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cohesive', '[koʊ\'hiːsɪv]', 'adj.粘性的；有结合性的；有粘聚性的', '1. I would use a cohesive glue to weld the tubes to each other. 我会用粘胶把这些电子管粘起来。 2. He skillfully fuses these fragments into a cohesive whole. 他巧妙地把这些片断合并成连贯的整体。 3. They do not see themselves as a cohesive group. 他们不认为他们自己是有凝聚力的一群。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clipper', '[\'klɪpər]', 'n.修剪工；大剪刀；理发剪；（十九世纪的）快速帆船；移动很快的人或物', '1. You need handkerchiefs, soap and a nail clipper. 你需要手绢，肥皂和指甲刀。 2. Shall I use the clipper on the back? 要不要我用理发推子理后面的头发？ 3. The pirate ship boarded the clipper. 海盗船强行靠近快艇。 4. The length of the clipper from stem to stern is thirty-six feet. 这艘快船从船头到船尾全长36英尺。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plot', '[plɑːt]', 'n.情节；阴谋；图；(小块)土地 v.密谋；绘图；计划；标示位置', '1. The plot thickens. 情节复杂起来了。 2. They are brewing a plot behind the scenes. 他们正在幕后策划一个阴谋。 3. The silly ending robs the plot of any credibility. 这愚蠢的结尾使得整个情节变得一点都不可信。 4. The reporter was killed because he tried to expose a plot. 这名记者因为试图揭露一个阴谋而被杀害。 5. They are plotting how to murder him. 他们在密谋如何杀害他。', '名词: plotlessness 过去式: plotted 过去分词: plotted 现在分词: plotting 第三人称单数: plots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('esophagus', '[i\'sɑːfəɡəs]', 'n.食道', '1. Stomach or can esophagus problem affect a heart? 胃或者食道问题会不会影响到心脏？ 2. Lipomas of the esophagus are rare benign tumors. 摘要食道脂肪瘤是罕见的良性肿瘤。', '形容词: esophageal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('succor', '[\'sʌkə]', 'n.救援；援助者', '1. To rescue live peoples is still the most important and the first work in the succor. 救人仍然是救援工作的重中之重。', '形容词: succorable 名词: succorer 过去式: succored 过去分词: succored 现在分词: succoring 第三人称单数: succors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('attire', '[ə\'taɪər]', 'n.服装；盛装 v.穿衣；打扮', '1. They imposed through their magnifcent attire. 他们靠华丽的服装来行骗。 2. Her attention was attracted by his peculiar attire. 他那奇特的服装引起了她的注意。 3. The boys and girls go to the dance in elegant attire, and dance away the evening to the music of a live band. 男孩们和女孩们都身着盛装去参加舞会，随着乐队的现场伴奏翩翩起舞，度过一个美好的夜晚。 4. During the long-held tradition of Las Fallas, many participants don medieval attire. 许多参与者在法雅节期间穿上中世纪的盛装是长期以来传统。 5. Nor was he dressed himself like a bridegroom, but in strange disordered attire. 他自己打扮得也不象个新郎，身上穿得邋里邋遢的。', '过去式: attired 过去分词: attired 现在分词: attiring 第三人称单数: attires');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nadir', '[\'neɪdɪr]', 'n.最低点；[天]天底', '1. The demand for this product will reach its nadir within two years. 对此产品的需求在两年内将达到最低点。 2. The nadir of fertility appears to be 1.3 children per woman. 生育率的最低点为每个妇女1. 3. It felt as if we had traveled from nadir to zenith. 感觉上我们好像已从天底走到了天顶。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rivulet', '[\'rɪvjələt]', 'n.小河；小溪', '1. The school is located near the rivulet. 学校坐落在小河附近。 2. It reminds you of a placid rivulet. 它使人想起一条平静的溪流。 3. They passed the dry bed of a rivulet. 他们跨过了一道干涸的河床。 4. Tadpoles can be found in this rivulet. 这条小溪里能见到蝌蚪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('byline', '[\'baɪlaɪn]', 'n.(报刊等的文章开头或结尾）标出作者名字的一行', '1. \"The Times\" ran a wrap-up under the byline of Walter. 《泰晤士报》连续刊载一篇署名为沃尔特的新闻摘要报道。 2. The mode,alteration,order and quotation of signature are all concerned with the right of byline. 署名方式、署名变更、署名次序及引文标示,都涉及署名权问题。', '名词: byliner 过去式: bylined 过去分词: bylined 现在分词: bylining 第三人称单数: bylines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cult', '[kʌlt]', 'n.宗教膜拜仪式；异教；狂热崇拜；个人崇拜', '1. The cult of the Virgin Mary was extremely popular. 对圣母马利亚的膜拜当时非常流行。 2. The cult of sun worship is probably the most primitive one. 太阳崇拜仪式或许是最为原始的一种。 3. So this cult has been causing all the trouble? 那么就是这邪教导致了一切的麻烦? 4. This is an essential feature of a cult. 这是邪教的一大特征。', '形容词: cultic 名词: cultism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hurdle', '[\'hɜːrdl]', 'n.栏干；障碍 [计算机] 障碍. vt.跨越某物', '1. I defy you to jump that high hurdle. 我倒要看看你能不能跳过那高栏。 2. His horse fell as it jumped the last hurdle. 他的马在跨跃最后一个跳栏时跌倒了。 3. Software may turn out to be a bigger hurdle. 软件可能成为更大的障碍。 4. You have to hurdle to London and get the intelligence back. 你得克服困难到达伦敦把那份情报取回来。', '名词: hurdler 过去式: hurdled 过去分词: hurdled 现在分词: hurdling 第三人称单数: hurdles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('devastate', '[\'devəsteɪt]', 'vt.毁坏；使荒芜；使震惊', '1. They intended to devastate the town at one stroke. 他们企图一举摧毁全城。 2. Our Embassy was devastated by three bombs of NATO. 我们的使馆被北约的三枚炸弹炸毁了。 3. The country was devastated by a long war. 该国因遭到长期战争的破坏而荒废。 4. I was devastated by the news of the wreck. 我获悉失事的消息感到十分震惊。', '副词: devastatingly 名词: devastation 过去式: devastated 过去分词: devastated 现在分词: devastating 第三人称单数: devastates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conifer', '[\'kɑːnɪfər]', 'n.针叶树', '1. In conifer orchards new stumps should be removed. 在针叶树的种子园，新的伐桩应予除掉。 2. They are large evergreen conifer trees, ranging from 23m to 32m high. 它们是 23 米到 32 米高的大型的常绿针叶树。', '形容词: coniferous');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comity', '[\'kɒmətɪ]', 'n.友谊；礼让', '1. Don\'t think to be just pure comity with you. 不想和你只是单纯的友谊。 2. We harvested the spirit to also harvest the comity. 我们收获了精神也收获了友谊。 3. No comity by which a democratic society must live had broken down. 一个民主社会所赖以生存的崇尚礼让的风气败坏了。 4. Sometimes comity is regarded as a stimulus to the pattern of behaviour. 礼让有时被视作行为模式的一个促进因素。', '名词复数: comities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tamper', '[\'tæmpər]', 'v.干预；玩弄；贿赂；篡改', '1. By allowing the sacred mystery to unfold without trying to tamper with it, we can move through anything with much more ease and simplicity. 让恐惧的迷雾散开，不要去干预，这样的话，度过任何事情我们就能带着多的多的从容和简单。 2. It is dangerous for children to tamper with gunpowder. 孩子们玩弄火药是危险的。 3. You shouldn\'t tamper with a jury. 你不应该贿赂陪审团。', '名词: tamperer 过去式: tampered 过去分词: tampered 现在分词: tampering 第三人称单数: tampers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('iterate', '[\'ɪtəreɪt]', 'v.反复说；重做；[计]迭代', '1. Let me iterate that we have absolutely no plans to increase taxation. 让我再一次重申我们绝对没有增税的计划。', '过去式: iterated 过去分词: iterated 现在分词: iterating 第三人称单数: iterates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preponderant', '[prɪ\'pɑːndərənt]', 'adj.占优势的；主要的；压倒性的', '1. Melancholy is the preponderant mood of the poem. 忧郁的感情是该诗的基调。', '副词: preponderantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('modish', '[\'moʊdɪʃ]', 'adj.流行的；时髦的', '1. She is always crazy at modish things. 她疯狂热爱流行物品。 2. Some of the country\'s dowager opera houses have been refitted with modish new finery. 近来,一些老式剧院又被重新装修得新潮时尚。 3. If you want to live a free life, you can\'t always be modish. 如果你想过自在的生活，就不能时时打扮时髦。', '副词: modishly 名词: modishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hypotenuse', '[haɪ\'pɑːtənuːs]', 'n.(直角三角形的)斜边', '1. The hypotenuse is the longest side of a right triangle. 直角三角形的斜边是直角三角形中最长的边。', '异体字: hypothenuse');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('withdraw', '[wɪð\'drɔː]', 'vt.撤回；取回；撤退；提款 vi.撤退；退缩；走开', '1. In view of members reservation and request for further information, the Administration agreed to withdraw the item. 鉴于委员有所保留,并要求取得进一步资料,政府当局同意撤回该项目。 2. He wanted to withdraw his name from the guest list. 他想从客人名单中撤出自己的名字。 3. I\'d like to withdraw some money from my account. 我想从户头里提出一些钱。 4. The troops have been withdrawn from the danger area. 部队已经撤出危险地带。 5. Tell the men to withdraw from their new position. 告诉那些人从新的阵地上撤出。', '形容词: withdrawable 名词: withdrawer 过去式: withdrew 过去分词: withdrawn 现在分词: withdrawing 第三人称单数: withdraws');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drizzle', '[\'drɪzl]', 'vi.下毛毛雨 vt.细雨般地洒下 n.细雨', '1. It had been drizzling all day. 下了一整天的毛毛雨。 2. It\'s going to snow drizzle tomorrow. 明天要下毛毛雨。 3. Drizzle the lemon juice over the fish. 在鱼上洒点柠檬汁。 4. The dew on the branches drizzled our hair and shoulders. 枝头上的露珠润湿了我们的头发和双肩。 5. Would you like to go for a walk in the drizzle? 想去毛毛雨里散会儿步吗？', '形容词: drizzly 过去式: drizzled 过去分词: drizzled 现在分词: drizzling 第三人称单数: drizzles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('therapeutic', '[ˌθerə\'pjuːtɪk]', 'adj.治疗的', '1. Mourning can have a therapeutic function that we ignore at our peril. 悲痛可以有一种治疗的功能，即让我们忽略我们的风险。 2. Cupping is the method of applying a cup in which a partial vacuum is created over an acupoint for therapeutic purpose. 拔罐法是指使罐紧吸于穴位上进行治疗的方法。', '副词: therapeutically 异体字: therapeutical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('provender', '[\'prɒvəndə]', 'n.刍草；粮秣；食物', '1. Even proudest horse will have to bear his own provender. 再高傲的马也得自己驮草料。 2. If others are the machines to provide this provender, they are the machines to read it. 如果说别人是供给此种食物的机器，他们就是阅读机器。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('formality', '[fɔːr\'mæləti]', 'n.礼节；程序；拘谨', '1. She didn\'t like the formality of the party. 她不喜欢宴会拘泥的礼节。 2. The rigid formality of the place suffocated her. 这个地方呆板的礼节压制着她。 3. I found the formality of the occasion irritating. 我觉得这种场合的繁文缛节十分讨厌。 4. You should go through the legal formality. 你应该办理合法手续。', '名词复数: formalities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cuticle', '[\'kjuːtɪkl]', 'n.表皮；外皮；角质层', '1. The old cuticle is digested by molting fluid. 旧表皮被蜕皮液消化。 2. Don\'t cut too much of my cuticle. 我指甲旁的表皮不要剪得太深。 3. The reform has hardly made a scratch upon the cuticle of affairs . 改革几乎还没有触到事物的表皮。 4. Fortunately the cut didn\'t reach the cuticle. 庆幸的是伤口没有触到角质层。', '形容词: cuticular');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expertise', '[ˌekspɜːr\'tiːz]', 'n.专门知识；专门技术；专家的意见', '1. He has the expertise in the management of hotels. 他有酒店管理知识。 2. I have no sewing expertise 我没有缝纫方面的知识。 3. We were amazed at his expertise on the ski slopes. 他斜坡滑雪的技能使我们赞叹不已。 4. The company is eager to develop its own expertise in the area of computer programming. 该公司希望能在计算机程序领域开发出自己的专门技术。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('portfolio', '[pɔːrt\'foʊlioʊ]', 'n.文件夹；公事包；作品集；投资组合；（大臣或）部长职务', '1. He went through drawer after drawer and eventually searched out a dusty portfolio. 他一个一个抽屉查找，后来终于找出了一份沾满灰尘的文件夹。 2. The artist showed us a portfolio of her drawings. 艺术家给我们展示了她的绘画代表作品。 3. My stockbroker manages my portfolio for me. 我的证券经纪人替我管理投资组合。 4. She resigned her portfolio. 她辞去了大臣职务。', '名词复数: portfolios');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('torso', '[\'tɔːrsoʊ]', 'n.躯干；残缺的东西；人体的躯干雕塑像', '1. These core muscles lie deep within the torso. 这些核心肌肉位于躯干的深层部位。 2. Kicking involves the torso as well as the legs and feet. 踢腿包括躯干，腿和脚的动作。', '名词复数: torsos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('superlative', '[suː\'pɜːrlətɪv]', 'adj.最上的；高超的；过度的 n.最高级的言辞；极致；完璧', '1. We went to a superlative restaurant. 我们去了一家最好的餐馆。 2. This is a superlative conference. 这是一个最高级会议。 3. She is a versatile and superlative actress. 她是位多才多艺、演技高超的女演员。 4. Superlative drinking is harmful to the health. 饮酒过度对身体有害。 5. I know the rules of the superlative of adjectives. 我了解形容词最高级的规律。', '副词: superlatively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concur', '[kən\'kɜːr]', 'v.意见相同；同时发生', '1. I concur with him in many points. 我和他在许多论点上意见是一致的。 2. Did all the members concur in getting a bank loan? 委员们是否都同意向银行贷款。 3. She has expressed her opposition to the plan, and I fully concur . 她对计划表示反对 4. Wealth and happiness do not always concur. 财富与幸福并非总是并存的。', '过去式: concurred 过去分词: concurred 现在分词: concurring 第三人称单数: concurs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('offspring', '[\'ɔːfsprɪŋ]', 'n.后代；子孙；产物', '1. His offspring are diligent and intelligent. 他的后代既勤奋又聪明。 2. The hybrid offspring of a zebra and a horse. 杂交斑马斑马与马杂交的后代 3. His offspring inherit the estate. 他的孩子继承了房地产。 4. How do parents pass genes on to their offspring? 父母是怎样把基因遗传给自己的子女的？', '名词复数: offspring');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obtainable', '[əb\'teɪnəbl]', 'adj.能获得的；可得到的；能达到的', '1. The flowers are no longer obtainable. 那花再也得不到了。 2. The timetable is obtainable post-free from the airline office. 航班时刻表可以向航空公司免费索取。 3. The periodical is obtainable on the very first day of every month. 这本杂志每月一号出版。 4. This always sets ultimate limit to the noise performance obtainable. 它常常规定可能达到的噪声性能的基本限度。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beverage', '[\'bevərɪdʒ]', 'n.饮料', '1. What beverage would you like? 你想喝什么饮料？ 2. The bar steward is accountable to the beverage manager. 酒吧间服务员要对餐饮部经理负责。 3. He never drinks alcoholic beverage. 他从不喝含酒精的饮料。 4. The beverage is often colored with caramel. 这种饮料常用焦糖染色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sneer', '[snɪr]', 'n.冷笑；嘲笑 v.嘲笑；冷笑', '1. Ambreene favored him with a disbelieving sneer. 艾布瑞妮回以一个不相信的冷笑。 2. Defiance gleamed in Casey\'s eye, a sneer curled Casey\'s lip. 轻蔑在凯西眼中闪现，冷笑在凯西唇边出现。 3. The remark was, of course, a sneer. 这话当然是一种嘲笑。 4. It\'s not polite to jeer or sneer. 嘲笑别人是不礼貌的。 5. The remark was, of course, a sneer. 这话当然是一种嘲笑。', '形容词: sneerful 副词: sneeringly 名词: sneerer 过去式: sneered 过去分词: sneered 现在分词: sneering 第三人称单数: sneers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slag', '[slæɡ]', 'n.熔渣；矿渣；<英俚> 荡妇 v.(英）严厉批评', '1. Some come off in the form of gases and others collect as slag. 有的化成气体跑掉了，有的结成了熔渣。 2. Some possibility exists to use the slag from the smeltery. 存在利用这家冶炼厂的矿渣的某种可能性。 3. Now he\'s left, she\'s always slagging off her old boss. 因原老板已走了，她就一个劲儿地褒贬他。', '形容词: slaggy 过去式: slagged 过去分词: slagged 现在分词: slagging 第三人称单数: slags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('genuine', '[\'dʒenjuɪn]', 'adj.真诚的；真正的；真实的；地道的', '1. He has a genuine desire to help us. 他真心诚意地愿意帮助我们。 2. A genuine friend will not desert you in time of adversity. 真正的朋友不会在患难时弃你而去。 3. It appears to be genuine, but I have my suspicions (about it). 这看来好像是真的，不过我(对此)有怀疑。 4. Viewed from the outside, the company seemed genuine. 从外表上看，这家公司倒像是真的。', '副词: genuinely 名词: genuineness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('colt', '[koʊlt]', 'n.小马；无经验的年轻人 Colt. n.柯尔特公司(美国著名的制枪厂商)', '1. This colt is only two months old. 这只小雄驹只有两个月大。 2. The colt shied at the fence and refused to jump over it. 这马驹到障碍物前害怕不敢跳过去。 3. Jim is still a colt at this job. 对这个工作来说,吉姆还是个新手。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ostensible', '[ɑː\'stensəbl]', 'adj.表面的；假装的', '1. The ostensible reason wasn\'t the real reason. 表面上的理由并不是真正的理由。 2. His ostensible purpose was charity,his real goal popularity. 他表面的目的是做善事，实际目标是获得声望。 3. He resigned his secretaryship on the ostensible ground of health. 他借口身体不好，辞去书记的职务。', '副词: ostensibly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quarantine', '[\'kwɔːrəntiːn]', 'n.隔离；检疫期间；封锁交通；四十天 vt.检疫；停止交涉 vi.检疫', '1. Quarantine restriction have been lifted on import animal from that country. 对来自那个国家的进口动物的检疫隔离限制已被解除。 2. The quarantine is now abolished. 这项检疫隔离措施现已取消。 3. He had been kept in quarantine for a week. 他接受了一星期的检疫隔离。 4. Dengue is difficult to diagnose and impossible to quarantine. 登革热很难被诊断出来也不可能被隔离。 5. He had been kept in quarantine for a week. 他接受了一星期的检疫隔离。', '形容词: quarantinable 过去式: quarantined 过去分词: quarantined 现在分词: quarantining 第三人称单数: quarantines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forsake', '[fər\'seɪk]', 'v.放弃；断念；抛弃', '1. Because he chose to forsake eternal life for knowledge. 因为他为了选择知识而放弃了永生。 2. Forsake your greed, abandon your appetites of ostentation. 除去你的贪心，放弃你所炫耀的爱好。 3. Forsake learning, and you will ruin yourself. 抛弃了学问便是毁了你们自己。 4. She pleaded with her husband not to forsake her. 她恳求丈夫不要抛弃她。', '过去式: forsook 过去分词: forsaken 现在分词: forsaking 第三人称单数: forsakes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interregnum', '[ˌɪntə\'reɡnəm]', 'n.空位期；过渡期；间歇', '1. He shared Clifford\'s concern about the interregnum. 他同克利福德对新旧总统的交替期都抱有忧虑。 2. There is no interregnum between the death of one sovereign and the accession of the next. 君主死亡与下一君主继位之间不得有任何空位期。 3. The interregnum of 1932-1933, the long stretch between the election and the actual transfer of power, was disastrous for the U. 1932年至1933年的漫长的选举和政权更迭产生的政治空白给美国经济留下了灾难性的后果。', '形容词: interregnal 名词复数: interregnums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tined', '[taɪnd]', 'adj.尖端的；有齿的；有叉的 动词tine的过去式和过去分词.', '1. The comedy tine was cut out as being off side. 笑料由于低级趣味而被删去。 2. Is it a part- tine job you are after? 你要找的是不是非全日性的工作？', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('critical', '[\'krɪtɪkl]', 'adj.批评的；挑剔的；决定性的；危险的 adj.临界的', '1. It is difficult enough to be critical of our own mistakes. 对我们自己的错误采取批评的态度确实非常困难。 2. She viewed the findings with a critical eye. 她以批评的眼光看待这些研究结果。 3. Our clients are very critical on quality. 我们的客户对商品的质量是很挑剔的。 4. Joint strategic maneuver is critical. 联合战略行动是决定性的。 5. These materials become quite soft and flexible above critical temperature. 这些材料在临界温度以上变得十分柔软和易于弯曲。', '副词: critically 名词: criticalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('premise', '[\'premɪs]', 'n.前提 vt.预述；提论；假设', '1. I wonder whether the whole premise is right. 我怀疑整个前提是否正确。 2. We must act on the premise that the worst can happen. 我们必须在可能发生最坏事态的前提下行动。 3. British justice works on the premise that an accused person is innocent until he\'s proved guilty. 英国司法运作的前提是被告在被证明有罪之前是清白的。 4. You had better premise your argument with a little historical knowledge. 你最好引述一些历史知识作为你立论的前提。', '过去式: premised 过去分词: premised 现在分词: premising 第三人称单数: premises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maudlin', '[\'mɔːdlɪn]', 'adj.容易流泪的；感伤的；醉后好哭的', '1. The company were in that maudlin mood when a little wit goes a great way. 这些人充满着伤感情调，一点点打趣的话也会使大家感到很愉快。 2. We saw a maudlin movie about an orphan who lost his parents in the war. 我们看了部令人落泪的电影，内容是有关一个在战争中失去父母的孤儿。 3. He always becomes maudlin after he\'s had a few drinks. 他喝了几杯酒后总是变得多愁善感。', '副词: maudlinly 名词: maudlinness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expropriate', '[eks\'proʊprieɪt]', 'v.征用；没收；剥夺；侵占（他人财产）', '1. The new government expropriated his estate for military purposes. 新政府将他的地产征作军用。 2. She was expropriated (of her land). 她的(土地的)所有权已遭剥夺。 3. He expropriated the jewels from the bank\'s safe. 他非法将他人的珠宝从银行保险箱中取走。', '形容词: expropriatory 名词: expropriation 过去式: expropriated 过去分词: expropriated 现在分词: expropriating 第三人称单数: expropriates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indignation', '[ˌɪndɪɡ\'neɪʃn]', 'n.愤怒；愤慨；义愤', '1. He could scarcely keep in his indignation. 他愤怒得难以自持。 2. Moral indignation is jealousy with a halo. 道德上的愤怒是萦绕着光环的嫉妒。 3. The atrocity caused widespread indignation. 那暴行引起了普遍的愤慨。 4. Such a humiliation filled me with indignation. 这种污辱使我感到极其愤慨。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snare', '[sner]', 'n.陷阱；诱惑；圈套；勒除器 vt.以陷阱捕获；诱惑', '1. The rabbit struggled to escape from the snare. 兔子挣扎着要逃出陷阱。 2. Their promises are a snare and a delusion. 他们的诺言是一种圈套，也是一种欺骗。 3. I used to snare small birds such as sparrows. 我曾常用罗网捕捉麻雀等小鸟。', '名词: snarer 过去式: snared 过去分词: snared 现在分词: snaring 第三人称单数: snares');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infliction', '[ɪn\'flɪkʃn]', 'n.(强加于人身的)痛苦；刑罚', '1. Is the unending infliction of pain also required? 非得施以永无休止的痛苦才行吗？ 2. Now he\'s suing for a variety of reasons, including defamation and reckless infliction of emotional distress. 现在他要以数种理由提出告诉，包括诽谤以及鲁莽造成其精神上的痛苦。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stout', '[staʊt]', 'adj.强壮的；肥胖的；牢固的；坚定的 n.烈啤酒', '1. Hope is a slender reed for a stout man to lean on. 希望是壮汉依靠的一根纤细的芦苇。 2. The stout old man waddled across the road. 那粗壮的老人摇摇摆摆地穿过大路。 3. He became stout as he grew older. 随着年龄的增长，他发胖了。 4. The balloon was tied down to a stout stake. 气球被拴在一个结实的木桩上。 5. This stout has a slight chocolate flavor. 这种烈性啤酒有点巧克力的味道。', '形容词: stoutish 副词: stoutly 比较级: stouter 最高级: stoutest 名词: stoutness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('presage', '[\'presɪdʒ]', 'n.预感；预兆；预知 v.预兆；预示；预言', '1. Suddenly he had a presage about the near danger. 他突然对即将到来的危险有了一种预感。 2. It\'s a presage of doom. 这是世界末日的预兆。 3. Such incidents often presage war. 那样的事件常成为战争的前兆。 4. Those black clouds presage a storm. 那乌云预示着暴风雨将要来临。', '形容词: presageful 过去式: presaged 过去分词: presaged 现在分词: presaging 第三人称单数: presages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disposition', '[ˌdɪspə\'zɪʃn]', 'n.性情；倾向；安排；处置；控制；[计算机] 配置情况', '1. She has a calm and introverted disposition. 她性格文静内向。 2. Joanna had a gentle retiring disposition. 乔安娜性格温柔而腼腆。 3. The child had a placid disposition. 这个孩子性情温和。 4. They showed a disposition to sign the contract. 他们表示有签订合同的意愿。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infantry', '[\'ɪnfəntri]', 'n.步兵；步兵部队', '1. We have less infantry than the enemy. 我们的步兵比敌军少。 2. The infantry is an important part of the army. 步兵是军队中的一个重要的组成部分。 3. The infantry are defending well. 步兵防守甚佳。 4. The infantry is equipped with new weapons. 步兵部队装备了新武器。', '名词复数: infantries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whim', '[wɪm]', 'n.一时的兴致；奇想', '1. I bought the encyclopedia on a whim. 我凭一时的兴致买了这本百科全书。 2. That suggestion was no whim of the moment. 那个建议可不是一时的突发奇想。 3. She bought that dress on a whim. 她一时心血来潮就买了那件连衣裙。 4. He dotes on his grandchildren and indulges their every whim. 他溺爱自己的孙辈,并且满足他们的任何想法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repertoire', '[\'repərtwɑːr]', 'n.全部节目；全部才能', '1. A repertoire of tricks will astound the esteemed public. 全部节目将使尊敬的观众惊心动魄。 2. That tune is not in my repertoire. 我演出的节目中没有这个曲子。 3. He has a wide repertoire of dirty jokes. 他一肚子下流笑话. 4. Julia has a vast repertoire of smiles. 朱莉娅具有驾御各式微笑的本领。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stimulus', '[\'stɪmjuləs]', 'n.刺激；刺激品；激励', '1. One wants the stimulus of sympathy. 一个人总需要趣味相投、志同道合的朋友互相鼓励。 2. The nutrient in the soil acts as a stimulus to growth. 土壤中的养分能促进植物生长。 3. Her words of praise were a stimulus for people to work harder. 她赞扬的话鼓舞人们工作更努力。', '名词复数: stimuli');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('equine', '[\'iːkwaɪn]', 'adj.马的；似马的 n.马；马科', '1. Donkeys are related to horses, and both are part of the equine family. 驴是马的近亲，两者都是马科家庭的一员。 2. One could say she is the equine equivalent of me and vice versa. 你可以说她就是我象马的等同体，反过来也是如此。 3. For the most part, there is a fairly consistent pattern in the development of an equine from foalhood to old age. 在极大程度上，马从小马驹到老马的发展有一个相当一致的模范。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adept', '[ə\'dept]', 'adj.熟练的；老练的 n.名手；专家', '1. He was astonishingly adept at manipulating the big machine. 他操作这台大机器熟练得惊人。 2. Like any culturally adept traveler, the tribe has changed its appearance throughout its history. 就像任何聪明熟练的旅行老鸟，从历史上到如今这个部族一直不断地改变自己的面貌。 3. It may not have the best table manners, but this strange looking creature is certainly a very adept and unusual percussionist, which should help provide Nick with a good beat. 也许它的吃相并不雅观，但这种相貌奇特的动物肯定是一位老练的打击乐高手，能为尼克提供一些不错的素材。 4. Many became adept, and thousands of fires were extinguished before they took hold. 其中有很多人成了专家，几千颗烧夷弹还没有燃烧，火势头就被扑灭了。', '副词: adeptly 名词: adeptness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tardy', '[\'tɑːrdi]', 'adj.迟到的；缓慢的；迟缓的', '1. He was tardy for the meeting. 那次开会他迟到了。 2. The teacher gave the tardy student what for. 老师痛斥了迟到的学生。 3. His boss was dissatisfied with his tardy progress. 老板对他缓慢的进度不满意。 4. She is so forgetful and tardy with work. 她这人就是爱忘事，做什么事情总是拖拖拉拉的。', '副词: tardily 比较级: tardier 最高级: tardiest 名词: tardiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cadaver', '[kə\'dævər]', 'n.尸体；死尸', '1. Examination of a cadaver is to determine the cause of death. 尸体解剖是为了确认死亡原因。', '形容词: cadaveric');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mite', '[maɪt]', 'n.小虫；小家伙；极少量', '1. It takes about one hour for the mite to bury itself in the skin. 螨虫需要花费一个小时才能将自己埋藏到皮肤之下。 2. Poor little mite! 可怜的小家伙！ 3. He is a mite taller than I. 他比我高一点点。 4. I offer a mite of comfort to him. 我给了他一点安慰。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conceive', '[kən\'siːv]', 'v.设想；想出；怀孕', '1. I cannot conceive of him as a genius. 我不能设想他会是一个天才。 2. I cannot conceive that he would wish to harm us. 我不能想像他会伤害我们。 3. I can not conceive of anything funnier than that . 我想不出有比那更有趣的东西。 4. She was told she couldn\'t conceive. 她得知自己不能怀孕。', '形容词: conceivable 副词: conceivably 名词: conceivability 过去式: conceived 过去分词: conceived 现在分词: conceiving 第三人称单数: conceives');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retainer', '[rɪ\'teɪnər]', 'n.保持者；仆人；定位器 [牙科]牙架. n.（律师、顾问等的）聘金', '1. The retainer in his family was very honest. 他家里的那位仆人很诚实。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('leniency', '[\'liːniənsi]', 'n.宽大；不严厉；仁慈', '1. The accused craved for leniency. 被告恳求宽大处理。 2. The judge showed leniency to the prisoner . 法官对该囚犯给予宽大处理。', '名词复数: leniencies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rehabilitate', '[ˌriːə\'bɪlɪteɪt]', 'vt.使恢复；修复；改造', '1. He was set free and rehabilitated as chief engineer. 他被释放并恢复总工程师职务。 2. Our disgraced teacher was publicly rehabilitated by school authorities. 学校当局为我们的蒙受耻辱的老师公开恢复了名誉。 3. There was no money to rehabilitate the tower. 没有资金修复那座塔。 4. Does prison help rehabilitate criminals? 监狱能帮助改造罪犯吗?', '形容词: rehabilitatable 名词: rehabilitation 过去式: rehabilitated 过去分词: rehabilitated 现在分词: rehabilitating 第三人称单数: rehabilitates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demeanour', '[dɪ\'miːnər]', 'n.举止；态度；行为 =demeanor(美).', '1. He doesn\'t get upset and his demeanour never changes. 他并没不高兴，他的举止从未改变。 2. His demeanour has always been that of a perfect gentleman. 他的举止始终是属于正人君子的模样。 3. The girl has a quiet, modest demeanour. 这个女孩子的态度娴静而谦逊。 4. His smile disappeared, and he assumed a severe and reprehending demeanour. 他的笑容不见了，态度变得严厉起来，显出要斥责人的样子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('composer', '[kəm\'poʊzər]', 'n.创作者（尤指乐曲的）', '1. The composer kicked the music around for a while, trying it out. 作曲者把这个曲子随便哼了一会儿，看看行不行。 2. A jazz musician or composer. 爵士乐演奏家或作曲家 3. He\'s a composer of serious music. I like his music a lot. 他是个庄严音乐的作曲家，我非常喜欢他创作的曲子。 4. His dual role as a composer and a conductor made him very busy. 他作曲家和指挥家的双重身份使他非常繁忙。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('covet', '[\'kʌvət]', 'v.觊觎；垂涎；贪图', '1. Mr Appleby does not covet power. 艾波比先生不觊觎权力。 2. We do not covet anything from any nation. 我们不觊觎任何国家的任何东西。 3. We covet what we see every day. 我们垂涎每天看到的东西。 4. Never covet what is not yours, for it is a sin to steal a pin. 不是自己的东西就不要妄想，即使是偷一根针也是一种罪过。', '形容词: covetable 副词: covetingly 名词: coveter 过去式: coveted 过去分词: coveted 现在分词: coveting 第三人称单数: covets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sportive', '[\'spɔːtɪv]', 'adj.爱玩的；爱好运动的', '1. To behave or converse in a sportive or playful way. 不认真地做以开玩笑的或戏谑的方式举动或交谈 2. I\'m a goodlooking and sportive man, very caresss. 我是个英俊开朗的人，同时十分寂寞。 3. For sportive words and utt\'ring foolish things. 只会插科打诨，说些无聊的蠢事。 4. Notizie sui nuovi modelli, auto sportive e d\'epoca. 网站简介: Contiene informazioni sul mondo delle auto.', '副词: sportively 名词: sportiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('underscore', '[ˌʌndər\'skɔːr]', 'vt.划线于；强调；提供伴奏乐 n.下划线；影片伴奏乐', '1. Let me underscore two of many reasons for this concern. 值得担忧的原因很多，让我着重说明其中两点。 2. Please underscore the word three times for emphasis. 为了强调起见，请在该词下面划三条线。 3. Let me underscore that you should focus on an important problem. 让我强调一下：你必须关注于某一重要问题。 4. These results underscore the importance of context in studies of social capital. 这些结果强调了社会资本研究中环境的重要性。 5. They must begin with a letter or the underscore character 开始部分必须为一个字母或是下划线', '过去式: underscored 过去分词: underscored 现在分词: underscoring 第三人称单数: underscores');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dither', '[\'dɪðər]', 'n.抖；发抖；兴奋 v.发抖；犹豫不决', '1. The sight of the policeman made the murderer all of a dither. 一见到警察，那个谋杀者吓得浑身发抖。 2. Stop dithering about which film you want to see or you\'ll miss them both! 到底看哪一部影片，别再犹豫了，不然的话，两部影片你都要耽误了！', '过去式: dithered 过去分词: dithered 现在分词: dithering 第三人称单数: dithers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('penicillin', '[ˌpenɪ\'sɪlɪn]', 'n.青霉素', '1. He gave me a second shot of penicillin. 他又给我打了一针青霉素。 2. The nurse injected penicillin into her arm. 护士给她的胳膊注射了青霉素。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dominant', '[\'dɑːmɪnənt]', 'adj.主要的；占优势的；显性的 n.主宰者；显性基因', '1. Peace was the dominant theme of the conference. 和平是大会的首要议题。 2. He is a dominant leader in our university. 他是我们学校最主要的一位领导。 3. The right hand is dominant in most people. 大多数人的右手是优势手。 4. The company can\'t preserve its dominant position in the market. 该公司在市场上不能让自己保持优势地位。 5. We should be the dominant of ourselves. 我们要做自己的主宰者。', '副词: dominantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('siege', '[siːdʒ]', 'n.包围；围攻', '1. The town was forced to yield after a long siege. 该城受长期围困而被迫弃守。 2. He was smitten with Mary\'s attractions and laid siege to her heart. 他被玛丽的魅力迷惑，对她苦缠不休。 3. The citizens sallied out in an attempt to break the siege. 市民们进行突击，试图冲破包围。 4. He captained the siege of Berlin. 他指挥了围攻柏林的战役。', '过去式: sieged 过去分词: sieged 现在分词: sieging 第三人称单数: sieges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('racketeer', '[ˌrækə\'tɪr]', 'n.敲诈者；获取不正当钱财的人', '1. Al Capone was a famous racketeer in Chicago. 阿尔卡彭是在芝加哥的一位有名敲诈者。', '过去式: racketeered 过去分词: racketeered 现在分词: racketeering 第三人称单数: racketeers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sybarite', '[\'sɪbəˌraɪt]', 'n.沉于奢侈逸乐者；爱奢侈享乐的人 Sybarite. n.锡巴里斯的人', '1. The sybarite (or sensualist) thinks that he\'s living, but he\'s nothing but a puppet without a will to be free, a foolish slave that exhibits his own chains. 纵欲好色者认为他是在享受生活，但如果没有自由的意愿，他不比傀儡更多些什么，一个愚蠢的奴隶在展示着他自己的枷锁。 2. sybarite: 奢侈逸乐的人。', '名词: sybaritism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('penitent', '[\'penɪtənt]', 'adj.忏悔的；悔悟的 n.改过迁善的人；忏悔的人；悔罪者', '1. Since he has been penitent,I don\'t think he will do that again. 既然他已经忏悔了，我认为他不会再那样做了。 2. They all appeared very penitent and begged hard for their lives. 他们一个个表示悔罪，苦苦地哀求饶命。 3. A penitent\'s prayer is an undeniable ambassador. 一个忏悔者的祷告是令人无法拒绝的使者。', '副词: penitently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tremendous', '[trə\'mendəs]', 'adj.巨大的；惊人的', '1. He has a tremendous hold over his younger brother. 他对他弟弟很有影响。 2. She does her work with tremendous vigour. 她工作起来干劲十足。 3. The discovery caused a tremendous commotion in the scientific world. 那项发现在科学界引起极大的震动。 4. We got a tremendous surprise when she arrived. 她的到来使我们大吃一惊。', '副词: tremendously 名词: tremendousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ingredient', '[ɪn\'ɡriːdiənt]', 'n.成分；原料；配料；因素', '1. Coconut is a basic ingredient for many curries. 椰子是多种咖喱菜的基本成分。 2. Mix all the ingredients in a bowl. 将原料放在盆里调匀. 3. There is a list of ingredients on the side of the packet. 包装袋的边上印有所含配料表。 4. Humor is an effective ingredient of a speech. 幽默是演讲中效果极佳的一个因素。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jab', '[dʒæb]', 'v.刺；戳；猛击 n.戳；刺；猛击 <口>注射', '1. The vet jabbed (at) the dog with a needle. 兽医给狗扎针。 2. Be careful with that umbrella you nearly jabbed my eye out! 小心那把伞－－你差一点把我的眼睛戳出来。 3. Be careful with that umbrella. You nearly jabbed my eye out! 小心那把伞，你差一点把我的眼睛戳出来。 4. A thrust or jab does less damage but increases your attack range. 前刺或前戳，杀伤力小，但攻击范围大。 5. Have you had your cholera jabs yet? 你打霍乱预防针了吗？', '过去式: jabbed 过去分词: jabbed 现在分词: jabbing 第三人称单数: jabs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('containment', '[kən\'teɪnmənt]', 'n.控制；遏制政策；容积', '1. To solve the deficit problem, containment of public expenditure is necessary. 为解决财赤问题,控制公共开支是必须的。 2. Officials say the fire is about 40 percent containment. 官员表示大概控制了大火的40%25。 3. Through the collective embargo and \"the complete sanction,\" finally, the U.S. formed the containment policy toward Cuba. 通过对古巴的完全禁运和“集体制裁”，最终形成了对古巴的遏制政策。 4. Downer also commented on China-U.S. relations, saying Australia has never been concerned that Washington is pursuing a policy of containment toward Beijing. 唐纳也对美中关系发表评论。他说，澳大利亚从不担心华盛顿对北京采取遏制政策。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('satanic', '[sə\'tænɪk]', 'adj.恶魔的；撒旦的', '1. This was seen as a sort of Satanic conspiracy. 这被看作是一个恶魔的阴谋。', '副词: satanically 异体字: satanical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arctic', '[\'ɑːrktɪk]', 'adj.北极的；极寒的 n.北极圈；北极', '1. The polar bear\'s habitat is the icy waters of the Arctic. 北极熊的栖息地是冰冷的北极海域。 2. I guess there are much less people in the Arctic regions than here. 我想北极地区的人要比这里的少得多。 3. We can\'t stand this arctic weather. 我们受不了这种严寒的天气。 4. Wilderness forests give way to arctic tundra in the Far North. 原生森林一直延伸到极远的北方始由极地草原取代。 5. It is very cold in the Arctic Circle all the year. 北极圈内终年寒冷。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intimate', '[\'ɪntɪmət]', 'adj.亲密的；私人的；关系紧密的 vt.暗示；透露 n.密友', '1. She was so kind as to forgive her intimate friend who had betrayed her when she was in a great difficulty. 她如此善良,竟能原谅在她处境最艰难时背叛她的挚友。 2. The magazine published intimate details of their affair. 这本杂志刊登出了他们恋情的私密细节。 3. Island communities commonly feel an intimate connection with the sea and with seafarers. 岛国的居民一般都会感觉自己与海洋和水手之间存在着紧密的联系。 4. He stated what others had only dared to intimate. 他说出了别人只敢暗示的话。 5. Sir Reginald was known to his intimates as \"Porky\". 雷金纳德爵士的至交都叫他“胖子”。', '副词: intimately 名词: intimateness 过去式: intimated 过去分词: intimated 现在分词: intimating 第三人称单数: intimates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sedative', '[\'sedətɪv]', 'adj.使安静的；使镇静的 n.镇静剂；能使安静的东西', '1. Barbiturates are used for their calming, sedative effects. 巴比妥酸盐类具有镇静、安神作用。 2. The doctor gave her a sedative medicine and she then slept for eight hours. 医生给她一种镇静药后她睡了八小时。 3. The doctor gave him a sedative to help him sleep. 医生给了他镇静剂帮助他入睡。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('violet', '[\'vaɪələt]', 'n.紫罗兰；紫色 adj.紫色的', '1. The violet is a dainty spring flower. 紫罗兰是娇艳的春花。 2. She planted some violets in the garden. 她在花园里种了一些紫罗兰。 3. Red and violet are at opposite ends of the spectrum. 红色和紫色位于光谱相对的两端。 4. People thind violet is a dignified color. 人们认为紫色是高贵的颜色。 5. Violet romance and white pure be in harmony became tender dreamland. 紫的浪漫和白的纯洁融成了温柔的梦乡。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unexceptionable', '[ˌʌnɪk\'sepʃənəbl]', 'adj.〈正式或文〉无可挑剔的；无可指责的', '1. This is an unexceptionable comment. 这是个无懈可击的观点。 2. Mr. Weston was a man of unexceptionable character, easy fortune. 韦斯顿先生人品出众，广有钱财。 3. Mr. Weston was a man of unexceptionable character, easy fortune, suitable age, and pleasant manners. 魏斯吞先生有无可非议的品德、富裕的家产、合适的年龄和愉快的态度。 4. Such examples are unexceptionable, but care should be taken that this usage does not cause ambiguities. 这样的例子是无懈可击的，但应该小心谨慎以使这种用法不致于引起模棱两可。', '副词: unexceptionably 名词: unexceptionableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('halting', '[\'hɔːltɪŋ]', 'adj.跛的；踌躇的 动词halt的现在分词形式.', '1. Two quarrelled dogs come halting home . 两狗打架，跛着回家。 2. Shyness made the girl speak in a halting manner. 因害羞那姑娘说话结结巴巴。 3. If people often interrupt, your tempo may be too slow or halting. 如果人们总是打断你，你的语速就显得太慢或犹疑不决。', '副词: haltingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('creek', '[kriːk]', 'n.小湾；小溪 Creek. n.克里克族；克里克人；克里克语', '1. It will be absolutely necessary that the place you may select have a small harbor, creek, or bay, into which my corvette can enter and remain at anchor. 你挑选的地方务必要有一个小港，小溪或小湾，可以让我的帆船进去抛锚。 2. There are often wild ducks swimming in the creek. 小溪中常有野鸭戏水。 3. Eddie\'s going to lure Courtney down to Muddy Creek. 艾迪去把卡特妮引诱下来使小溪污浊。 4. The area was originally occupied by the native Creek and Cherokee Indians who had lived in the region for centuries. 几世纪以来，这里原先是当地印第安克里克族和切罗基族的居住地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spawn', '[spɔːn]', 'n.卵；产物；后代；结果 vt.产卵；种菌丝于；产生；造成 vi.产卵；大量生产', '1. I found a mass of spawn in the fish before cooking. 烧鱼前，我发现鱼里有很多鱼籽。 2. But bellicose intercontinental ballistic missiles were not the only spawn of Sputnik\'s launch.There was also the satellite itself. 洲际弹道导弹不是太空竞赛的唯一产物，卫星也是。 3. As a result, the mature female mud crab can spawn, though the number of eggs laid is affected. 结果表明精英的人工移植不会破坏成熟雌蟹纳精囊的内环境，其内精子具正常受精能力。 4. Many sea fishes spawn in rivers. 许多海洋鱼类是在淡水河里产卵的。 5. Probably this spawn was not fertilized. 这大概是产卵不受精。', '名词: spawner 过去式: spawned 过去分词: spawned 现在分词: spawning 第三人称单数: spawns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('soak', '[soʊk]', 'vt.使浸透；吸入；浸洗；<俚>使喝醉；敲竹杠 vi.浸泡；渗透；渗入；<俚>酗酒 n.浸；湿透；<俚>酒鬼', '1. She soaked the shirt in soapy water. 她把衬衫浸透在肥皂水中。 2. The kind of plant doesn\'t soak the sewage up. 这种植物没有吸入污水。 3. He likes to soak himself in a warm bath. 他喜欢泡洗热水澡。 4. They really soak the tourists in that restaurant. 他们在那家餐厅真的把观光客当成冤大头。 5. Leave the apricots to soak for 20 minutes. 把杏子浸泡20分钟。 6. Give the clothes a long soak before washing. 洗之前先将衣服多泡一些时间。', '名词: soaker 过去式: soaked 过去分词: soaked 现在分词: soaking 第三人称单数: soaks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('precursor', '[priː\'kɜːrsər]', 'n.先驱；前任；前兆；[生物]前体，前驱体', '1. The precursor of the modern car was a horseless carriage with a petrol engine. 现代汽车的前身是不用马拉的，装有汽油发动机的车子。 2. Her precursor as school principal was an eminent educator. 她任校长前是一位卓越的教育家。 3. Opposition by colonists to unfair taxation by the British was a precursor of the Revolution. 殖民地居民对英国不公正税收的反抗预示着革命的到来。 4. Lysine is a precursor of certain alkaloids. 赖氨酸是某些生物碱的前体。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fastness', '[\'fæstnəs]', 'n.要塞；城堡；坚固；不褪色；快速；偏远的地方', '1. We guarantee the fastness of these dyes. 我们担保这些染料不褪色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carapace', '[\'kærəpeɪs]', 'n.(蟹或龟等的)甲壳；壳', '1. He tickled gently at its glossy carapace,but the stubborn beetle would not budge. 他轻轻地搔着甲虫光滑的壳，但这只固执的甲虫就是不动。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crouch', '[kraʊtʃ]', 'v.蹲下；屈膝 n.蹲伏；蜷缩', '1. He crouched down among the tangled foliage. 他蹲下把身子藏在紊乱的叶丛中。 2. They crouch, back to back, in a sort of hut of fate. 他们彼此背靠着背，蹲在一种黑洞似的命运里。 3. They did not crouch under the oppression. 他们受压迫而不屈服。 4. He chuckled, said, \"Very convincing,\" and then suddenly sank into a crouch, his muscles coiled like a spring. 他咯咯地笑着说,“很有说服力，”然后突然蹲伏下来，他的肌肉就像个收紧的弹簧。', '过去式: crouched 过去分词: crouched 现在分词: crouching 第三人称单数: crouches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('claim', '[kleɪm]', 'n.要求；要求权；主张；断言；声称；要求物 vt.要求；请求；主张；声称；断言', '1. The matter claimed our serious attention. 这件事需要我们认真注意。 2. Did you claim on the insurance after your car accident? 出了车祸后，你向保险公司要求赔偿了吗？ 3. The government would not even consider his claim for money. 政府甚至不考虑他的赔款要求。 4. He set up a claim to the throne. 他自称王位是属于他的。', '形容词: claimable 名词: claimer 过去式: claimed 过去分词: claimed 现在分词: claiming 第三人称单数: claims');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prone', '[proʊn]', 'adj.易于 ... 的；有 ... 倾向的；俯卧的', '1. He was prone to anger. 他易于发怒。 2. The child is rather accident-prone. 那个小孩很容易出事儿。 3. People are more prone to make mistakes when they are tired. 人们疲劳时更容易出差错。 4. He\'s probably prone to domestic violence. 他也许有家庭暴力的倾向。', '副词: pronely 名词: proneness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('speculative', '[\'spekjələtɪv]', 'adj.推测的；推理的；思索的；投机的', '1. The report is highly speculative and should be ignored. 那个报道推测的成分很大，不应理会。 2. The inaccessibility of this remote region, now called Amazonia, meant that long-held theories about the early days of the river and surrounding forest were speculative at best. 而现在称为亚马逊流域的这个偏远地区难以进入，也意味著长期以来关于早期河流与周围森林的理论，顶多是靠推测的。 3. The other case which is excluded is the case of speculative demand. 另一个未谈的情况是投机的需要。 4. If this plays out as a gulf hurricane there is speculative energy galore to go along with it. 如果这演奏因为那里海湾飓风是投机的能量丰盛去与它一起。', '副词: speculatively 名词: speculativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('badinage', '[ˌbædən\'ɑːʒ]', 'n.打趣；开玩笑；嘲弄', '1. For all the forced badinage, it was an awkward meal. 大家尽管勉强地说说笑笑，这顿饭依旧吃得很别扭。 2. Sometimes we girls badinage together: “We will not watch the football game, unless there is a handsome man. 之类，反正除了看帅哥，欣赏帅哥在场地上奔跑的样子就没有别的。 3. As Carrie listened to this and much more of similar familiar Badinage among the men and girls, she instinctively withdrew into herself. 当嘉莉听到男女工人这样随便放肆地打趣揶揄时,她本能地和他们拉开了距离。 4. At El Sordo\'s camp Pilar exchanges badinage with Joaquin, a young man who wanted to be a bullfighter before the war, while Jordan confers with the leader. 在“聋子”的营地，趁着乔丹同那位队长商议的空当，皮拉尔跟华金相互打趣起来。华金是个年轻小伙子，战前曾想当名斗牛士。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('touching', '[\'tʌtʃɪŋ]', 'adj.动人的；感人的 prep.关于；有关 动词touch的现在分词.', '1. This is the most touching story I have ever heard. 这是我听到过的最动人的故事。 2. His farewell speech was very touching. 他的告别演讲非常感人。 3. She asked many question touching my family and school. 她问了我许多关于家庭和学校的问题。 4. He wrote a article touching a environment pollution. 他写了一篇有关环境污染的文章。 5. The two wires were touching. 那两条金属线搭在一起了。（《牛津高阶英汉双解词典》）', '副词: touchingly 名词: touchingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mistimed', '[\'mɪstaɪmd]', 'adj.不合时机的', '1. They mistimed the war by three years. 他们把战争爆发的时间搞错了三年。 2. She mistimed the marathon runner. 她给马拉松运动员计时时出现了计时错误。 3. The basketball team mistimed the final play and lost the game. 这个篮球队因比赛时间安排不当而输了一场 4. The horse completely mistimed the jump and threw its rider. 这匹马起跳完全不是时候，把骑手摔了下来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evaluation', '[ɪˌvælju\'eɪʃn]', 'n.估价；评价', '1. The product needs an expert evaluation. 这种产品需要专家评估。 2. We need to carry out a proper evaluation of the new system. 我们需要对这套新体系做出一个正确的评价。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repine', '[rɪ\'paɪn]', 'vi.不满；心中抱怨；向往', '1. He repined against his unhappy lot. 他自叹命运多舛。', '名词: repiner 过去式: repined 过去分词: repined 现在分词: repining 第三人称单数: repines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('devoted', '[dɪ\'voʊtɪd]', 'adj.投入的；深爱的；全心全意的 动词devote的过去式和过去分词.', '1. He lived a life devoted entirely to sensual pleasure. 他一生耽于肉欲。 2. He is very devoted to our cause. 他非常忠实于我们的目标。 3. She was devoted to her mother and looked after her for many years. 她深爱着她的母亲并照顾了她很多年。 4. It is in being humble that our love becomes real, devoted and ardent. 因着谦卑我们的爱才变得真实，投入和充满热情。 5. He devoted himself entirely to music. 他将一生奉献给了音乐。', '副词: devotedly 名词: devotedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aggression', '[ə\'ɡreʃn]', 'n.进攻；侵犯；侵害；侵略', '1. For a dog,an erect tail indicates aggression. 对狗而言，竖立起来的尾巴表示进攻。 2. Aggression gives us a great deal of suffering for our own mind. 这种进攻性的心态给我们的心灵带来了非常大的痛苦。 3. Retaliation only escalates a bully\'s aggression. 报复只会助长欺凌者的侵犯气焰。 4. You should learn what to do in case of an act of aggression. 你应该学习如何应对侵犯行为。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deter', '[dɪ\'tɜːr]', 'vt.阻止；威慑；威吓', '1. No difficulty can deter us from trying it again. 没有困难可以阻止我们再试一次。 2. The extreme cold deterred him from going out. 极度寒冷使他打消外出的念头。 3. It\'s this edge that gives newclear weapons their power to deter. 正是这个优势赋予了核武器威慑力量。 4. The fact that we have the big bombs will deter our enemies from attacking us 我们拥有这种重型炸弹的事实威慑住敌人不敢向我们进攻。', '形容词: deterrable 名词: determent 过去式: deterred 过去分词: deterred 现在分词: deterring 第三人称单数: deters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('penchant', '[\'pentʃənt]', 'n.喜好(倾向)', '1. She has a penchant for Indian food. 她爱吃印度食物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prominent', '[\'prɑːmɪnənt]', 'adj.显著的；杰出的；突出的', '1. That school is prominent in baseball. 那个学校以棒球著称。 2. Virginia Woolf is one of the most prominent writers in English literature. 弗吉尼亚·尔夫是英国文学史中一名重要的作家。 3. Einstein was a prominent scientist. 爱因斯坦是一位卓越的科学家。 4. She is having a lean, gaunt frame with prominent bones. 他骨瘦如柴的身材又细又瘦,骨骼突出的', '副词: prominently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('superficial', '[ˌsuːpər\'fɪʃl]', 'adj.表面的；肤浅的', '1. Superficial scratches can be easily removed. 表面的划痕很容易擦掉。 2. A superficial injury is not serious. 表面的伤不太严重。 3. This is only superficial prosperity. 这只是表面繁荣。 4. He is too superficial to appreciate great literature like this. 他太肤浅，无法欣赏这类文学巨著。', '副词: superficially 名词: superficiality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lint', '[lɪnt]', 'n.绷带用麻布；线头', '1. He cut his hand, which I did up with mercurochrome, lint and bandages. 他割破了手，我用红药水，绒布和绷带替他包扎起来。', '形容词: lintless');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sophistication', '[səˌfɪstɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.老练；精明；复杂；精密；有教养；诡辩；强词夺理', '1. Despite her scruffy clothes, there was an air of sophistication about her. 尽管她衣衫褴褛，但神态老练世故。 2. He combined curious qualities of naivete with incisive wit and worldly sophistication. 他把天真质朴的奇怪品质同锐利的机智和老练的世故结合了起来。 3. The result is a city huge on taste, sophistication and culinary pleasures. 这座城市对复杂的烹饪和美食有着极其浓厚的兴趣。 4. I have tried often to search behind the sophistication of years for the enchantment I so easily found in those gifts. 在经历了成年后的复杂生活后，我多次试图弄清楚为什么当年她送给我的礼物一下子就让我陶醉了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('champion', '[\'tʃæmpiən]', 'n.拥护者；冠军；优胜者；勇士 vt.拥护；保卫；为 ... 而斗争', '1. He is a champion of women\'s rights. 他是妇女权利的卫士. 2. He is the undisputed champion. 他是无可争辩的冠军。 3. He is a champion at writing familiar essays. 他是写小品文的好手。 4. Every absurdity have a champion to defend it. 任何谬论都拥有拥护它的斗士。 5. He is forced to champion unpopular causes. 他被迫去支持一些不得人心的事业。', '过去式: championed 过去分词: championed 现在分词: championing 第三人称单数: champions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('admire', '[əd\'maɪər]', 'vt.钦佩；赞美；羡慕；欣赏', '1. You may not like him, but you have got to admire his persistence. 你可以不喜欢他，但你不得不佩服他那种坚韧不拔的精神。 2. We admire him for his righteousness. 我们钦佩他的正直。 3. You had better admire others more than criticize if you want to be popular. 如果你想要更受人欢迎,尽量多赞美、少批评。 4. Visitors admire Beijing for its beauty. 观光者赞赏北京的美丽。', '副词: admiringly 名词: admirer 过去式: admired 过去分词: admired 现在分词: admiring 第三人称单数: admires');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corpulent', '[\'kɔːrpjələnt]', 'adj.肥胖的', '1. Sitting behind the window was a corpulent woman with a face of steel. 那窗口后面坐着一个面如镔铁的胖妇女。', '副词: corpulently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('movement', '[\'muːvmənt]', 'n.活动；运动；动作；[音]乐章', '1. If you did so, you would lose the movement of the knee. 如果你这样做,你的膝关节就不能活动了。 2. Loose clothing gives you greater freedom of movement. 衣服宽松，可以活动自如。 3. The Trade Union Movement works to obtain higher wages and better conditions. 工会运动旨在争取更高的工资和更好的工作条件。 4. The leadership of the movement are in agreement on this issue. 这一运动的领导层对这个问题的看法一致。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nipping', '[\'nɪpɪŋ]', 'adj.尖酸的；刺骨的 动词nip的现在分词形式.', '1. Airs romped around him, nipping and eager airs, they are coming, waves. 微风围着他嫡戏，砭人肌肤的凛例的风，波浪涌上来了。', '副词: nippingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sterile', '[\'sterəl]', 'adj.贫瘠的；无生气的；无生育能力的；无结果的；无菌的', '1. Sterile land does produce good crops. 贫瘠的土地也能出产优质的庄稼。 2. Mostly the mountains were still sterile. 大多数山仍然光秃秃的。 3. Their relationship had grown sterile over the years. 随着岁月的流逝，他们的关系变得了无生气。 4. Medical tests showed that he was sterile. 医学检查表明他没有生育能力。', '副词: sterilely 名词: sterileness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emancipate', '[ɪ\'mænsɪpeɪt]', 'vt.释放；解放', '1. Women have been struggling to emancipate from old restrictions of various kinds. 妇女们一直在为摆脱各种旧束缚而斗争。 2. We must emancipate the primary productive forces. 我们必须解放第一生产力。 3. We must emancipate our thinking in a bold way. 我们必须大胆解放思想。 4. We must emancipate our minds and think independently. 解放思想，独立思考。', '形容词: emancipative 名词: emancipator 过去式: emancipated 过去分词: emancipated 现在分词: emancipating 第三人称单数: emancipates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('despot', '[\'despɑːt]', 'n.暴君；专制者', '1. The despot gassed the rebellious tribes. 这位暴君用毒气攻击叛乱的部落。 2. Russia\'s Peter the Great was a cruel despot. 俄国的彼得大帝就是一个残酷无情的暴君。 3. That emperor was a cruel despot. 那个皇帝是个残酷的专制君主。 4. The despot claimed to be the chosen instrument of divine providence. 专制者声称自己是上天选定的统治工具。', '形容词: despotic 副词: despotically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oak', '[oʊk]', 'n.橡树；橡木', '1. The birds nested in the oak tree. 鸟在橡树上筑巢。 2. Pine wood saws more easily than oak. 松树要比橡树容易锯。 3. The wine is left to mature in oak barrels. 葡萄酒在橡木桶中陈酿。 4. There was a triptych of pale oak. 有一个浅灰色的三联橡木雕刻。', '形容词: oaken');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accommodating', '[ə\'kɑːmədeɪtɪŋ]', 'adj.乐于助人的 动词accommodate的现在分词形式.', '1. They are very accommodating to foreign visitors. 他们非常乐意帮助外国访客。 2. He was accommodating enough to give me a free ride. 他乐于给人方便,让我免费搭了次车。', '副词: accommodatingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ponder', '[\'pɑːndər]', 'v.沉思；考虑', '1. You should pause and ponder now. 你现在应该停下来仔细考虑一下。 2. He pondered long and deeply over the question. 他对该问题作了长时间的深思。 3. We pondered whether to tell her. 我们考虑是否要告诉她。 4. He pondered for some minutes before giving an answer. 他思考了几分钟才作答复。', '名词: ponderer 过去式: pondered 过去分词: pondered 现在分词: pondering 第三人称单数: ponders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distraught', '[dɪ\'strɔːt]', 'adj.心烦意乱；忧心如焚的；发狂的', '1. She sounded absolutely distraught. 听上去她完全心慌意乱。 2. Hunt was distraught after learning of Cech\'s condition. 亨特在听说切赫的伤势后心烦意乱. 3. Her distraught mother had spent all night waiting by the phone. 她母亲忧心如焚，在电话旁守了一个晚上。 4. She was distraught with worry. 她担心得几乎要发疯了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pervious', '[\'pɜːvɪəs]', 'adj.可渗透的；能接受的；能理解的', '1. I\'m afraid he\'s not pervious to our proposal. 恐怕他不会接受我们的建议。 2. Young people are readily pervious to new ideas. 青年人乐意接受新思想。 3. Underground water that is held in the soil and in pervious rocks. 土壤和能渗透的岩石中含有的地下的水。 4. Having a reference (from current or pervious job) is a must. 须有推荐信。', '副词: perviously 名词: perviousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brawl', '[brɔːl]', 'n.争吵；大声的吵闹 vi.争吵；大声喊；哗哗流', '1. He shall not get so angry. What we have gotten here is more like a brawl than a debate. 他不应该那么生气的。这里的样子不像在讨论而像是在吵架。 2. He is a timid boy; it\'s impossible for him to brawl with anyone. 他是一个胆小的男孩，他不可能和任何人吵架。 3. The young men had nothing better to do than brawl in the streets. 那些年轻人除了在街上打架外没更好的事干。 4. The river brawled over the rapids. 河水哗哗地流过湍滩。', '副词: brawlingly 名词: brawler 过去式: brawled 过去分词: brawled 现在分词: brawling 第三人称单数: brawls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('languish', '[\'læŋɡwɪʃ]', 'v.衰弱无力；失去活力；受苦；憔悴', '1. Shares now languish around $13 per share. 股价现在衰弱到了每股%2413左右。 2. The housing market continues to languish. 房地产市场继续低迷。 3. My interest in music has languished slightly. 我对音乐的兴趣有点减退。 4. The flower languished from lack of water. 花因缺水而枯萎。', '副词: languishingly 名词: languisher 过去式: languished 过去分词: languished 现在分词: languishing 第三人称单数: languishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('magpie', '[\'mæɡpaɪ]', 'n.喜鹊；（美口）爱饶舌的人；（英口）爱收集或储藏东西的人', '1. Now and then a magpie would call. 不时会有喜鹊鸣叫。 2. This young man is really a magpie. 这个年轻人真是饶舌。 3. No one wants to sit next to Miss Yates at the Sewing Meeting; she chatters like a magpie, all the time. 在缝纫联谊会上，谁也不想坐在耶茨小姐身边; 她整天喋喋不休。 4. A born magpie, Mandy collects any object that catches her eye. 曼迪是天生的收藏家，她收集见到的所有东西。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('squeeze', '[skwiːz]', 'v.挤压；塞进；压榨；设法腾出 n.挤压；少量；拥挤；严控；财政困难', '1. Kara squeezed the bottle, and the water rushed out. 卡拉挤压着那个瓶子,水一下子喷了出来。 2. It took some ingenuity to squeeze all the furniture into the little room. 把全部家具都塞进那个小房间是很费了一番心思的。 3. Supermarkets are accused of squeezing both customers and suppliers. 超市因压榨顾客和供货商而遭到指控。 4. I can squeeze a meeting in early tomorrow morning. 我可以在明天清早挤出时间开个会。 5. He gave my hand a gentle squeeze. 他握着我的手,轻轻捏了捏。', '形容词: squeezable 名词: squeezer 过去式: squeezed 过去分词: squeezed 现在分词: squeezing 第三人称单数: squeezes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('procurement', '[prə\'kjʊrmənt]', 'n.采购；获得；促成', '1. He is in charge of the procurement of materials. 他负责物资的采购。 2. This is the government procurement not commercial. 这是政府采购，不是商业采购。 3. Obtain project resources in accordance with a procurement plan. 按采购计划获得项目资源。 4. Procurement is the process of obtaining goods by the OCOG through purchase or VIK. 采购是奥组委通过购买或实物赞助形式获得物资的过程。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('refurbish', '[ˌriː\'fɜːrbɪʃ]', 'vt.刷新；擦亮；再磨光', '1. The flat will be refurbished for the new tenants. 这套房间将重新粉刷以接纳新房客。 2. Our house will be refurbished in the near future. 我们的房子最近将进行翻修。 3. She refurbished all the pots and pans. 她将所有的锅碗瓢盆都擦拭一新。', '名词: refurbishment 过去式: refurbished 过去分词: refurbished 现在分词: refurbishing 第三人称单数: refurbishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chaos', '[\'keɪɑːs]', 'n.混乱；无秩序；混沌', '1. The wintry weather has caused chaos on the roads. 因风雪交加,道路上混乱不堪。 2. After the failure of the electricity supplies, the city was in chaos. 电力供应中断,城市陷于混乱之中。 3. Without rules, people would live in a state of chaos. 若无规则,人们将在混乱状态中生活。 4. Chaos often breeds life, when order breeds habit. 混沌常常孕育着生命，而秩序会产生习惯。', '形容词: chaotic 副词: chaotically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('habitat', '[\'hæbɪtæt]', 'n.栖息地；产地', '1. The moth\'s habitat is being destroyed and it has nearly died out. 这种蛾子因栖息地正受到破坏，几乎绝种了。 2. The polar bear\'s habitat is the icy waters of the Arctic. 北极熊的栖息地是冰冷的北极海域。 3. I prefer to see animals in their natural habitat, rather than in zoos. 我宁愿观赏居住在自然栖息地里的动物，而不愿看关在动物园里的动物。 4. That country is the habitat of heroin. 那个国家是海洛因的产地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plight', '[plaɪt]', 'n.困境；苦境 n.誓约 vt.宣誓；订婚', '1. The Government seems to be closing its eyes to the plight of the unemployed. 政府似乎对失业者的困境熟视无睹。 2. The television pictures brought home to us all the plight of the refugees. 我们从电视上知道了难民所处的一切困境。 3. The plight of the refugees really wrung my heart. 难民处境惨苦真叫我牵肠割肚。 4. The plight of the refugees arouses the compassionate old man. 难民的困苦唤醒了那位有同情心的老人。 5. I plight that I will always be faithful to my work. 我发誓我会一直忠诚于我的工作。', '名词: plighter 过去式: plighted 过去分词: plighted 现在分词: plighting 第三人称单数: plights');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spatter', '[\'spætər]', 'v.溅；滴下；洒；诬蔑 n.泼溅的污迹', '1. The bus spatter them with mud as it pass in the rain. 公共汽车在雨中驶过，溅了他们一身泥。 2. We heard the rain spattering down on the roof of the hut. 我们听到雨滴滴答答打在小屋的顶上。 3. Don\'t spatter the soup onto the table. 别把汤洒到餐桌上。 4. Her feet sent back a continual spatter of mud. 她的后脚不断溅起泥浆。', '过去式: spattered 过去分词: spattered 现在分词: spattering 第三人称单数: spatters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dainty', '[\'deɪnti]', 'adj.小巧精致的；优美的；讲究的；可口的 n.适口的食物', '1. She collected some dainty porcelain. 她收集一些轻巧精致的瓷器。 2. The little girl wore a dainty dress. 小姑娘穿着一件漂亮的连衣裙。 3. The gentleman really is as dainty as a woman. 先生真是娇嫩得象女人一样。 4. Mr Su is a dainty eater. 苏先生是讲究饮食的人。 5. There were dainties of every kind on the table. 桌子上放着各式各样的精美食品。', '副词: daintily 比较级: daintier 最高级: daintiest 名词: daintiness 名词复数: dainties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('icon', '[\'aɪkɑːn]', 'n.偶像；象征；[计算机]图标', '1. An icon is something that somebody else makes you. 偶像是别人加到你头上的。 2. Britney\'s success has made her an icon to millions of fans all over the world. 布兰妮的成功使她成了全球歌迷心中的偶像。 3. He is most famous for his Westerns, and became an enduring American icon. 他最为人称道的是其主演的西部片,而且成为了美国人永远的偶像。 4. Koalas are considered an Australian national icon. 无尾熊被视为是澳洲的国家象征。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('taking', '[\'teɪkɪŋ]', 'n.取得；捕获；售得金额 adj.迷人的；会传染的 动词take的现在分词.', '1. what a taking smile! 多迷人的微笑啊！', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('iniquity', '[ɪ\'nɪkwəti]', 'n.邪恶；不公正；罪行', '1. He thought of New York as a den of iniquity. 他认为纽约是个藏污纳垢之处。 2. The iniquity of the transaction aroused general indignation. 这笔交易的不公引起了普遍的愤怒。 3. He had plumbed the very depths of iniquity. 他已经深测了罪恶的深渊。 4. God has found out the iniquity of your servants. 神已经查出你仆人们的罪孽了。', '名词复数: iniquities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hoarse', '[hɔːrs]', 'adj.沙哑的；嘶哑的；刺耳的', '1. The hoarse tenor singer mucked up the recital. 沙哑的男高音把音乐会搞砸了。 2. Tom whooped until he was hoarse, but it was of no use. 汤姆直喊得嗓子都哑了也无济于事。 3. We shouted ourselves hoarse at the football match. 足球比赛时我们把嗓子都喊哑了。 4. After you were gone, I heard hoarse and angry screams; 你走后,我听见一阵刺耳狂暴的嘶叫;', '副词: hoarsely 比较级: hoarser 最高级: hoarsest 名词: hoarseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('influx', '[\'ɪnflʌks]', 'n.流入；河口；汇集；涌入', '1. This influx of money could be exaggerating the market\'s gyrations. 大量资金的流入会夸大市场的回旋余地。 2. The country simply cannot absorb this influx of refugees. 这个国家实在没有能力接纳这么多涌入的难民。 3. There was a sudden influx of goods onto the market. 大批商品一下子涌入市场。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whimsy', '[\'wɪmzi]', 'n.怪念头；异想天开；心情浮动；反复无常', '1. He had a whimsy about flying to the moon. 他有个想飞上月球的怪念头。 2. Some show cars are pure whimsy, confections dreamed up by young designers at play. 展出的车型中有些纯属异想天开，只是年轻设计师们闲来无事的凭空想像。 3. We marvel at the whimsy of the devastation. 我们对灾难的反复无常感到吃惊。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pertinent', '[\'pɜːrtnənt]', 'adj.中肯的；相关的；切题的；恰当的', '1. The expert made some pertinent comments on the scheme. 那专家对规划提出了一些中肯的意见。 2. He raised several pertinent questions. 他提了几个有关的问题。 3. The lawyer wanted to know all the details pertinent to the case. 律师想知道与该案有关的全部细节。 4. His answer was highly pertinent to the question. 他的回答非常切题。', '副词: pertinently 名词: pertinence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wane', '[weɪn]', 'n.衰落；亏缺；变弱 v.变小；亏缺；呈下弦', '1. The empire was on the wane after its period of prosperity. 帝国经过全盛以后逐渐衰落。 2. By now the power of the Roman Empire was on the wane. 到这时，罗马帝国已日益衰败。 3. Why should the moon have wax and wane? 为什么一定会月有阴晴圆缺? 4. The sick man\'s strength is on the wane. 病人的体力越来越弱。 5. As time went on, so their hopes began to wane. 随着时间的消逝，他们的希望开始变得渺茫。', '过去式: waned 过去分词: waned 现在分词: waning 第三人称单数: wanes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fertile', '[\'fɜːrtl]', 'adj.肥沃的；富饶的；能繁殖的；多产的；（创造力）丰富的', '1. There are fertile fields in the Nile Delta. 尼罗河三角洲土地肥沃。 2. We have irrigated the desert area to make it fertile. 我们已经灌溉了荒芜地区使它肥沃。 3. It was a pleasant fertile spot, well wooded and rich in pasture. 那是一个富饶的，使人愉快的地方，材木苍然，牧草丰富。 4. This fertile land bears the hopes of the farmers. 这块富饶的土地,孕育着庄稼人的希望！', '副词: fertilely 名词: fertileness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harangue', '[hə\'ræŋ]', 'v.慷慨激昂地劝说；做长篇演说 n.长篇激烈演说', '1. He walked to the front of the stage and began to harangue the audience. 他走到台前，开始对听众慷慨陈辞。 2. He plans to harangue his fellow students and persuade them to walk out of the classroom. 他计划对他的同学慷慨陈词以说服他们罢课。 3. The harangue is very serious. 那篇长篇演说很郑重其事。 4. We had to listen to a long harangue about nothing. 我们不得不去听了空洞的长篇大论。', '名词: haranguer 过去式: harangued 过去分词: harangued 现在分词: haranguing 第三人称单数: harangues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stance', '[stæns]', 'n.立场；态度；站立姿势', '1. He maintains a rigidly right-wing political stance. 他坚持僵硬的右派政治立场。 2. You must choose to take a united stance. 你们必须选择来采取一致的立场。 3. What is your stance on corporal punishment? 你对体罚持什么态度? 4. He has changed his stance on monetary union. 他已经改变了对货币联盟的态度。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interloper', '[\'ɪntərloʊpər]', 'n.闯入者；干涉他人事务者；无执照营业者', '1. She felt like an interloper in her own family. 她感到在自己家里像个外人。 2. Security guards were stationed at the door to deal with any interlopers. 门口已设警卫人员以阻止闯入的人。', '动词: interlope');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tackle', '[\'tækl]', 'v.处理；对付；阻截(对方球员)；与…交涉 n.滑车；用具；铲球；(美式足球)拦截手', '1. Can you suggest how we might tackle the problem? 我们怎样处理这问题，你能给出个主意吗? 2. I suggested to him that we should tackle the problem another way. 我向他建议我们用另一种方式处理这个问题。 3. I\'ll tackle the boss for a raise. 我将与老板交涉要求增加薪水。 4. If Bill is late again I will tackle him about it . 如果彼尔再迟到的话，我就得和他开诚布公地谈谈了。 5. The cupboard was stuffed with old fishing tackle. 小橱里塞满了旧的钓鱼用具。', '名词: tackler 过去式: tackled 过去分词: tackled 现在分词: tackling 第三人称单数: tackles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delicate', '[\'delɪkət]', 'adj.微妙的；精美的；纤细的；脆弱的；敏锐的；美味的', '1. The international situation is very delicate at present. 目前的国际形势极其微妙。 2. He persecuted me with various delicate questions. 他用种种微妙的问题把我难倒了。 3. She wears a dress with delicate lace. 她穿了一件带有精致花边的裙子。 4. Don\'t grasp at the delicate branch, or you may break it. 不要去抓这嫩枝,你会把它折断的。', '副词: delicately 名词: delicateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inscrutable', '[ɪn\'skruːtəbl]', 'adj.难以了解的；不能预测的', '1. The riddle remains inscrutable to us. 那个谜对我们仍然是不可解的。 2. It is a most inscrutable and unmitigated staggerer. 这倒是一个难以理解和无法弄清楚的难题。 3. His inscrutable face does not show what he is thinking. 他那神秘莫测的面孔看不出在想什么。', '副词: inscrutably 名词: inscrutability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bout', '[baʊt]', 'n.回合；一场；一阵；发作；（摔跤等）比赛', '1. There are three rounds in an amateur boxing bout. 一场业余拳击比赛打三个回合。 2. He had a long bout of illness last year. 他去年生了一场拖了很久的病。 3. She has bouts of hard work followed by long periods of inactivity. 她总是努力干上一阵，然后一呆就是很长时间。 4. He suffers from frequent bouts of depression. 他患多发性抑郁症。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indebted', '[ɪn\'detɪd]', 'adj.受惠的；负债的', '1. I am greatly indebted to you for your kindness. 我非常感激您的恩惠。 2. He is indebted to his memory for his jest and to his imagination for his fact. 他的诙谐有赖于记忆力，而其事实则有来于想象力。 3. The restaurant is heavily indebted to the bank. 这家餐馆欠银行很多债务。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mariner', '[\'mærɪnər]', 'n.海员；水手', '1. A smooth sea never makes a skillful mariner . 风平浪静练不出好水手。 2. There are more than 50 mariners on this ship. 船上有五十多名水手。 3. The mariner followed the sea for fifty years. 这名水手在海上工作了50年之久。 4. He wished to be a mariner when he was a child. 当他还是一个孩子时，希望成为一名水手。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stymie', '[\'staɪmi]', 'vt. 使 ... 处于困难境地； 妨碍', '1. Social stigmas attached to homosexuality and bisexuality stymie public health efforts and allow the virus to spread rapidly in many parts of the region. 社会不齿同性恋与双性恋也妨碍公共卫生行动，让病毒得以在该区域的许多地方快速散播。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('equator', '[ɪ\'kweɪtər]', 'n.赤道', '1. The equator is an imaginary line. 赤道是一条实际上并不存在的线。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('devolve', '[dɪ\'vɑːlv]', 'v.委任；移交；退化', '1. We devolve this affair on you, so do as you see fit. 我们把这件事全托付给你了，你看着办吧。 2. We devolve your company as a single agent in China. 我们将委托贵公司作为我公司在中国的独家业务代理。 3. While he\'s ill, most of his work will devolve on me. 在他生病期间，他的大部分工作将移交给我。 4. More power is to be devolved to regional government. 要将更多的权力交给地方政府。', '名词: devolvement 过去式: devolved 过去分词: devolved 现在分词: devolving 第三人称单数: devolves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rhinestone', '[\'raɪnstoʊn]', 'n.莱茵石(一种透明无色的钻石仿制品)，水钻', '1. She often wears that cheap showy rhinestone bracelet. 她经常戴那个廉价艳丽的水晶手镯。', '形容词: rhinestoned');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('husband', '[\'hʌzbənd]', 'n.丈夫', '1. My husband is a stamp collector. 我丈夫是个集邮者。 2. Mary accused her husband of snore too loudly. 玛丽指责她丈夫打呼噜太响。', '过去式: husbanded 过去分词: husbanded 现在分词: husbanding 第三人称单数: husbands');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assure', '[ə\'ʃʊr]', 'vt.使确信；使放心；确保', '1. Her success as an actress was now assured. 她当演员很成功，已毋庸置疑了。 2. They tried to assure him of their willingness to work. 他们尽力使他相信他们乐意工作。 3. I can assure you that your son will be happy here. 我可以向你保证，你儿子在这里会很快乐的。 4. They were assured that everything possible was being done. 已经向他们保证，凡是可能做的都做到了。', '形容词: assurable 名词: assurer 过去式: assured 过去分词: assured 现在分词: assuring 第三人称单数: assures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('environs', '[ɪn\'vaɪrənz]', 'n.郊外；郊区 名词environ的复数形式.', '1. Oxford and its environs are worth a visit. 牛津城及其郊区值得一游。 2. The environs of Vienna are very beautiful. 维也纳郊区很美丽。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('silversmith', '[\'sɪlvərsmɪθ]', 'n.银匠', '1. He was apprenticed to a master silversmith. 他跟银匠师傅拜师学艺。 2. He apprenticed for ten years under a master silversmith. 他在一名银匠师傅手下当了10年学徒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wicked', '[\'wɪkɪd]', 'adj.坏的；邪恶的；缺德的 adv.极端地；非常地 vt.吸收', '1. He had a wicked glint in his eyes. 他眼睛里闪着坏坏的神色。 2. This wicked fellow needs to be locked up. 需要把这个坏家伙关押起来。 3. The wicked fairy bewitched the prince and turned him into a frog. 邪恶的女妖对王子施魔法，将他变成一只青蛙。 4. It\'s a wicked waste of money. 这样浪费金钱简直是罪恶。 5. The rejection was a wicked blow to her pride. 这一拒绝严重伤害了她的自尊心。 6. Cotton textiles can wick away perspiration. 棉织品可以吸汗。', '副词: wickedly 比较级: wickeder 最高级: wickedest 名词: wickedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('replete', '[rɪ\'pliːt]', 'adj.充满的；饱食的', '1. His story was replete with falsehood. 他的报导充满了虚伪。 2. He is longing for a home replete with warmth and comfort. 他渴望有个充满温暖、舒适的家。 3. He was replete with food and drink. 他吃喝得饱饱的。 4. It was a big meal and we all felt replete. 这是丰盛的一餐，我们都吃得很饱。', '名词: repleteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ambivalent', '[æm\'bɪvələnt]', 'adj.矛盾的；摇摆不定的', '1. He has an ambivalent attitude towards her. 他对她怀着矛盾的心情。 2. Although she professed fear of the Russians, she seemed to have ambivalent feelings toward Philby himself. 虽然她承认害怕俄国人，然而她似乎对菲尔比本人有一种矛盾的感情。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gum', '[ɡʌm]', 'n.牙床；树胶；齿龈；粘性物质 v.搞砸；用牙床嚼；以树胶粘合', '1. He has some sore swellings on his gum. 他牙床肿痛。 2. The tree is covered with gum. 树上涂有树胶。 3. Heart attack patients usually have gum diseases! 心脏病患者通常患有齿龈疾病。 4. We can stick these pictures into the book with gum. 我们可用胶水把这几张画粘贴在书里。 5. You\'ll gum up the jobs if you do it this way. 你这样做会把事情搞砸。', '过去式: gummed 过去分词: gummed 现在分词: gumming 第三人称单数: gums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('faculty', '[\'fæklti]', 'n.（大学的）系或院；全体教员；才能；能力', '1. He is the dean of the Faculty of Medicine. 他是医学院院长。 2. We haven\'t set up the Faculty of Law in our university. 我们学校还没下设法学院。 3. Both faculty and students oppose the measures. 全体教师和学生都反对这种方法。 4. She has the faculty to learn languages easily. 她有轻而易举学会语言的才能。', '名词复数: faculties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scale', '[skeɪl]', 'n.刻度；等级，规模；音阶；量程；天枰，磅秤；鳞片，鳞状物 v.攀登；按比例决定；称重；刮鳞；剥落', '1. How much does it read on the scale? 刻度显示的是多少? 2. The force of the wind is measured on a standard scale of 0-12. 风力是按0-12级标准等级测量的。 3. The fifth note of a scale is called a dominant. 音阶的第五音被称为属音。 4. It takes courage and strength to scale these cliffs. 攀登这些悬崖需要勇气和力量。', '形容词: scalelike 过去式: scaled 过去分词: scaled 现在分词: scaling 第三人称单数: scales');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('smite', '[smaɪt]', 'v.重击；折磨；迷惑', '1. He was smitten with Mary\'s attractions and laid siege to her heart. 他被玛丽的魅力迷惑，对她苦缠不休。 2. The hero smote the giant with his sword. 英雄用剑猛劈巨人。 3. The thief\'s conscience smote him. 那个贼突然良心发现。', '名词: smiter 过去式: smote 过去分词: smitten/smote 现在分词: smiting 第三人称单数: smites');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indict', '[ɪn\'daɪt]', 'v.起诉；控告；指控', '1. He grew anxious over the possibility that the Justice Department might now indict him for perjury. 他越来越担心司法部现在可能起诉他作伪证。 2. The Q&A session, which was audiotaped, came about two months prior to the child\'s initial appearance before the grand jury that later voted to indict Jackson on ten felony counts. 录音的问答单元的出现要比男孩在以十项罪名起诉杰克逊大陪审团面前的最初露面早两个月。 3. The police can\'t find any valid evidence to indict him for murder. 警察找不到有效的证据来控告他谋杀。', '名词: indictee 过去式: indicted 过去分词: indicted 现在分词: indicting 第三人称单数: indicts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('turbulent', '[\'tɜːrbjələnt]', 'adj.狂暴的；骚动的；动荡的；汹涌的', '1. He was born in that turbulent period of history. 他出生在那个动荡的历史时期。 2. In the turbulent war age, he guides the elf to know the death aright. 在动荡的战争年代，他导引精灵们正确认识死亡。 3. The oarsman was feathering through the turbulent waves. 划桨者正平掠过汹涌的波浪。 4. The Rhosili is a turbulent, swift-flowing river, full of dangerous rapids and currents. 罗西里是一条汹涌的迅速滚滚的河，充满着危险的险滩和湍流。', '副词: turbulently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cuff', '[kʌf]', 'n.袖口；<俚>手铐 n.巴掌 v.为...上袖口；带手铐 v.轻拍；掴', '1. The dress pattern doesn\'t really explain how the cuff joins onto the sleeve. 这个裙样没有真正地示明袖口是怎样与袖子连接在一起的。 2. This old jumper of mine is frayed at the sleeve cuff. 我的这件毛织上衣的袖口已经磨损了。 3. He gave the pickpocket a good cuff. 他给那扒手狠狠一巴掌。 4. The convict had his hands cuffed behind his back. 罪犯的手被铐在后面。 5. She cuffed the dog when she found it on the chair. 她发觉狗跳到椅子上,便轻轻打了它一下。', '过去式: cuffed 过去分词: cuffed 现在分词: cuffing 第三人称单数: cuffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('annexation', '[ˌænek\'seɪʃn]', 'n.并吞；附加；并吞物；附加物', '1. It is worth noting that historical records also show that Japan, the Japanese annexation in the Ryukyu Islands, Japan\'s territory is not met. 值得注意的是，日本史料记录亦显示，日本在并吞琉球群岛后，钓鱼台仍不属日本领土。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prudence', '[\'pruːdns]', 'n.审慎；深谋远虑；节俭', '1. He acted with prudence. 他谨慎行事。 2. Rashness attends youth, as prudence does old age. 鲁莽伴随青年，谨慎不离老人。 3. One can rely on the prudence of his decisions. 他所作的决定, 总是非常英明的，值得信赖。 4. A lack of prudence may lead to financial problems. 不注重节俭可能导致经济问题。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vouch', '[vaʊtʃ]', 'v.担保；保证；证明；确定 [律]传唤（某人）出庭作证.', '1. Let him in, I\'ll vouch for the man. 让这人进来，我愿替他担保。 2. Be that as it may, we do not vouch for his ability to pay. 不管怎样，对他的付款能力我们不愿作出担保。 3. We are ready to vouch for the truth of the report. 我们愿意保证这一报导的真实性。 4. I can vouch for the fact that he is a good worker. 我保证他是好员工。', '过去式: vouched 过去分词: vouched 现在分词: vouching 第三人称单数: vouches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('personification', '[pərˌsɑːnɪfɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.拟人；化身；典型；具体化', '1. Besides, this sort of dexterous hand can match up with the effect of personification both in external shape and the range of movement. 实验结果表明，该仿人灵巧手具有很好的柔顺性，并且整体外形和手指关节的运动范围均能达到拟人的效果。 2. He is the personification of honesty. 他是诚实的化身。 3. He looked the personification of misery. 他那副样子可谓是苦难的典型。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sandal', '[\'sændl]', 'n.凉鞋 n.檀香木', '1. She wears sandals every day in summer. 夏天她每天都穿凉鞋。', '形容词: sandaled');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insensate', '[ɪn\'senˌseɪt]', 'adj.无感觉的；无情的', '1. Insensate stones without words but sentimental, spirit it is for cultivation. 顽石不语亦有情,怡神冶性是精灵。 2. Corneous layer is formed by the horny protein cell of insensate active. 角质层是由无生命活性的角朊细胞构成的。 3. Hence the saying: When Sheng Gong preaches, insensate stone will nod in agreement. “生公说法，顽石点头”，就指这件事。 4. Screw Cat Troupe, Insensate Stone Troupe, Taichung Young Man Opera Shop, Army Honor Guard. 螺丝猫剧团、顽石剧团、东海青年歌剧坊、陆军仪队。', '副词: insensately 名词: insensateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jeopardize', '[\'dʒepərdaɪz]', 'vt.危及；使处于危险境地；影响', '1. If you are rude to the boss, it may jeopardize your chance of success. 如果你对老板没有礼貌，那也许会危及你事业的成功。 2. Overworking can jeopardize your health. 工作过量可能会危及你的健康。 3. Being late so often will jeopardize your chances for promotion. 这么常迟到会危及你升迁的机会。 4. Soldiers jeopardize their lives in war. 士兵们在战争中使他们的生命陷入险境。', '过去式: jeopardized 过去分词: jeopardized 现在分词: jeopardizing 第三人称单数: jeopardizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('raptorial', '[ræp\'toʊrɪəl]', 'adj.捕食生物的；猛禽类的', '1. Morphological Characteristics and Function of Raptorial Tarsometatarsus 猛禽类跗跖骨形态特征与功能的分析 2. a predatory bird; the rapacious wolf; raptorial birds; ravening wolves; a vulturine taste for offal 猛禽；贪婪的狼；猛禽；掠食的狼；对内脏的贪婪嗜好 3. a predatory bird; the rapacious wolf; raptorial birds; ravening wolves; a vulturine taste for offal. 猛禽；贪婪的狼；猛禽；掠食的狼；对内脏的贪婪嗜好。 4. (2) Body weight and raptorial appendages weight are correlate with fighting ability. (2)体童、捕脚重与打斗能力有关。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('omit', '[ə\'mɪt]', 'vt.省略；遗漏；忘记；删去', '1. In writing telegrams omit superfluous words. 写电报稿要省去不必要的文字。 2. I could omit the overseas section at this point. 我可以暂时把海外部分省略掉。 3. Don\'t omit his name from the list. 名单上不要遗漏了他的名字。 4. Don\'t omit locking the door. 别忘了锁门。', '过去式: omitted 过去分词: omitted 现在分词: omitting 第三人称单数: omits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entail', '[ɪn\'teɪl]', 'vt.使必需；带来；限定继承 n.限定继承权', '1. This job entails a lot of hard work. 这项工作需要十分努力。 2. It will entail driving a long distance every day. 这意味着每天都要长途开车。 3. The alteration would entail an expenditure of 50 pounds. 此项改变将带来为数五十英磅的花费。 4. He would have sold the property long ago had it not been entailed. 这些财产若非限定继承的话，他早就卖掉了。 5. You allude perhaps to the entail of this estate. 你大概是说产业的继承权问题。', '名词: entailment 过去式: entailed 过去分词: entailed 现在分词: entailing 第三人称单数: entails');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kudos', '[\'kuːdɑːs]', 'n.光荣；荣誉；称赞', '1. She did most of the work,but all the kudos went to him. 工作大部分是她做的，可是荣誉都归他了。 2. He received kudos from everyone on his performance. 他的表演受到大家的称赞。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mutate', '[\'mjuːteɪt]', 'vi.变异；突变 vt.使变异；使突变', '1. In the Darwinian run, the body code would mutate over time. 在与达尔文主义有关的这条线中，躯体代码将随着时间的推移而变异。 2. While it\'s only a single strand right now, it can mutate into other strands. 而这仅是一个单链，现在，它可以变异成其他方面。 3. Living machines reproduce, but as they do they mutate. 没错，活的机器会繁殖，但是，它也会突变。 4. Exposure to UV rays can mutate your cells and cause cancer. 暴露在紫外光下会使你的细胞突变，引起癌症。 5. In the Darwinian run, the body code would mutate over time. 在与达尔文主义有关的这条线中，躯体代码将随着时间的推移而变异。', '形容词: mutative 过去式: mutated 过去分词: mutated 现在分词: mutating 第三人称单数: mutates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('supple', '[\'sʌpl]', 'adj.柔软的；逢迎的；灵活的 vt.使柔软；使柔顺 vi.变柔软；变柔顺', '1. I picture my spine supple and flexible. 我想像我的脊椎是柔软弹性的。 2. The leather I tanned is supple and durable. 我鞣制的皮革特别柔韧耐用。 3. Exercise keeps you supple. 经常锻炼可使身体灵活。 4. She has a supple mind. 她头脑灵活。 5. It had simply made her sympathetic and supple. 它只是使她变得随和柔顺而已。', '副词: supply 比较级: suppler 最高级: supplest 名词: suppleness 过去式: suppled 过去分词: suppled 现在分词: suppling 第三人称单数: supples');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lave', '[leɪv]', 'v.洗涤；洗掉；如沐春风；洗澡 n.剩余物', '1. I lave done my duty. 我已尽了我的责任。 2. She will never lave home; she is too tied to her mother\'s apron strings. 她永远也离不开家; 她太依赖她的母亲了。', '过去式: laved 过去分词: laved 现在分词: laving 第三人称单数: laves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('versatile', '[\'vɜːrsətl]', 'adj.多才多艺的；通用的；多功能的', '1. Versatile actors can play all kinds of roles. 多才多艺的演员能演各种类型的角色。 2. He is one of the most versatile actors. 他是最多才多艺的演员之一。 3. These cotton towels are quite versatile for this reason. 鉴于这点,这些毛巾都是通用的。 4. I bought a versatile kitchen machine last month. 我上个月买了一部多功能的厨房用机器.', '副词: versatilely 名词: versatility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perambulate', '[pə\'ræmbjuleɪt]', 'vt.巡行；巡视 vi.漫步', '1. Via spot perambulate, extraction convict footmark. 经现场勘查,提取罪犯足迹一枚。 2. Every evening the local people perambulate around the park. 每天晚上，当地居民常在这公园里散步。 3. In spot perambulate, discovered the footmark of similar socks. 现场勘查中,发现了类似着袜的足迹。 4. Once Qianlong emperor perambulate here, Ciming for \"golden Taiwan afterglow. 有一次乾隆皇帝巡行到此，赐名为“金台夕照”。', '形容词: perambulatory 名词: perambulation 过去式: perambulated 过去分词: perambulated 现在分词: perambulating 第三人称单数: perambulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exemplary', '[ɪɡ\'zempləri]', 'adj.可仿效的；模范的', '1. Saintly individuals who lead exemplary lives imbue their environments with the holiness that accrues from their spiritual practices. 圣洁的个体通过他们从精神实践中产生的神圣来引导可仿效的生命浸透他们的环境。 2. And this exemplary treatment of herself by herself constitutes her presence. 这种作为模范的自我待遇，正构成了她的风度。', '副词: exemplarily 名词: exemplariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('touchy', '[\'tʌtʃi]', 'adj.易怒的；难以取悦的；敏感的', '1. He\'s an extremely touchy character and you have to handle him with kid gloves. 他是一个极易因小事而生气的人，因而你得温和灵巧地对待他。 2. He\'s a little touchy about his weight. 他对自己的体重感到有点儿苦恼。 3. He is in a particularly touchy mood today. 他今天情绪特别不好。 4. The mines are touchy as hell. 地雷非常灵敏，一有触动便会爆炸。', '副词: touchily 比较级: touchier 最高级: touchiest 名词: touchiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('magnify', '[\'mæɡnɪfaɪ]', 'v.放大；夸大', '1. I want to magnify my mother\'s picture. 我想放大我母亲的照片。 2. Magnify the magnitude of the magnetism. 放大磁性的大小。 3. He is inclined to magnify difficulties. 他老是爱夸大困难。 4. These groups and individuals magnify hate crimes by blacks in order to back their social agenda. 这些团体和个人为了给自己提出的社会议题造舆论而极力夸大黑人的攻击性犯罪。', '过去式: magnified 过去分词: magnified 现在分词: magnifying 第三人称单数: magnifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('airtight', '[\'ertaɪt]', 'adj.密封的；不透气的；无懈可击的', '1. The goods are to be sent in airtight package. 这批货物应密封包装运送。 2. We need an airtight bottle to keep this expensive medicine dry. 我们需要一个密封罐以便使这昂贵的药维持干燥。 3. Store tea in an airtight container away from strong smells. 把茶叶贮存在不透风的罐子里，避开异味。 4. He had an airtight alibi for that night. 他有无懈可击的证据证明那一夜他不在犯罪现场。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bin', '[bɪn]', 'n.箱柜；仓；垃圾箱 vt.放入箱内', '1. They\'re putting them into a white bin. 他们把它们放进一个白色的箱柜里。 2. I bought a bread bin for my family. 我给家里买了一个面包箱。 3. Chuck it in the bin! 把它扔到垃圾桶里去！ 4. Please put all your sweet wrappers in the bin. 请把你们的糖纸都放进垃圾箱里去。 5. Do you need to keep these letters or shall we bin them? 你需要保存这些信件吗，还是干脆把它们扔掉?', '过去式: binned 过去分词: binned 现在分词: binning 第三人称单数: bins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meditate', '[\'medɪteɪt]', 'v.沉思；冥想；考虑；计划', '1. He meditates on his past life. 他沉思着过去的生活。 2. These fields had subtle aromas that I loved to sit and meditate in. 这些田野散发淡淡的芳香，我喜欢坐在那里冥想。 3. I hope you can meditate it before you make decision . 我希望你做决定前仔细考虑一下。 4. Clever people should meditate on the problems before acting. 聪明的人应该是在采取行动前先仔细考虑一下。', '名词: meditator 过去式: meditated 过去分词: meditated 现在分词: meditating 第三人称单数: meditates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surrealism', '[sə\'riːəlɪzəm]', 'n.超现实主义', '1. My picture was inspired by my favourite style of art surrealism. 我的作品来源于我最喜欢的超现实主义。 2. The first thoughts that came to my mind were how to relate his works to Surrealism. 第一个浮现在我的内心思想的想法是该如何使他的工厂和超现实主义产生关联。', '名词: surrealist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abusive', '[ə\'bjuːsɪv]', 'adj.辱骂的；诅咒的；虐待的；滥用的', '1. If your partner is abusive and alcoholic, then you have a part of your unconscious that is abusive and alcoholic. 如果你的伙伴是好辱骂的并酗酒的，那么你就有好辱骂且酗酒的无意识部分。 2. Such slaves were energetically abusive. 这类奴隶在能量上是虐待的。 3. Intent is what separates the constructive from the abusive. 意图是区分建设性和虐待的因素。 4. The result of the abusive useing ecological resources is ecocide. 对生态资源滥用的结果是生态毁灭。', '副词: abusively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('euphoria', '[juː\'fɔːriə]', 'n.幸福愉快感', '1. A drug that tends to produce euphoria. 欣快剂有助于导致欣快的一种药剂 2. A feeling of excitement or euphoria. 兴奋或兴高采烈的感觉 3. A preparation from the leaves and seed capsules of the cannabis plant, smoked, chewed, eaten, or infused and drunk to obtain mild euphoria. 印度大麻从大麻植物的树叶和种囊中提取的一种制剂，通过吸烟、嚼咀、吞食或注射以得到适度精神快感', '形容词: euphoric 副词: euphorically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ideology', '[ˌaɪdi\'ɑːlədʒi]', 'n.意识形态；空论；观念学', '1. An obsolete ideology can hamper an economy. 过时的意识形态会束缚经济。 2. Nothing lay outside the scheme of our ideology. 我们的意识形态领域包罗万象。 3. Consensus came at the cost of ideology. 共识是通过放弃意识形态立场而获得的。 4. His attitude to ownership is rooted in communist ideology. 他的所有制观点源自共产主义思想。', '名词: ideologist 名词复数: ideologies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slug', '[slʌɡ]', 'n.蛞蝓；鼻涕虫；动作缓慢的人 n.子弹；铅字条；[物]斯勒格（质量单位） n.重击 v.加铅字条于；用力打', '1. The small garden slug can stretch its body to enter worm holes. 渺小的庭院蛞蝓能把身体伸长而钻进虫子洞里。 2. I raised a fist to slug Eddie. 我举拳重击埃迪。', '过去式: slugged 过去分词: slugged 现在分词: slugging 第三人称单数: slugs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entirety', '[ɪn\'taɪərəti]', 'n.全部', '1. He devoted the entirety of his life to medical research. 他把毕生精力贡献给医学研究工作。 2. You must examine the matter in its entirety. 你应该全面地看这件事。', '名词复数: entireties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sentry', '[\'sentri]', 'n.卫兵；哨兵', '1. No one was excluded from sentry duty. 人人都得站岗放哨。 2. Paul has just come off sentry. 保罗刚退哨。 3. The sentry had orders to shoot on sight. 哨兵奉命一发现有动静就立即开枪。 4. The sentry was praised for his alertness in his post. 哨兵因他站岗时的机警而被称赞。', '名词复数: sentries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cineaste', '[\'sɪniæst]', 'n.热爱电影者；电影制作人员', '1. Foreign Cineaste of the Year 法兰西文化奖年度外国制作者 2. French Cineaste of the Year 法兰西文化奖年度法国制作者 3. cineast n. =cinéaste', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muster', '[\'mʌstər]', 'v.集合；鼓起 n.集合；检阅；集合人员；点名册', '1. Go and muster all the men you can find. 去集合所有你能找到的人。 2. The troops mustered on the hill. 部队在小山上集合。 3. You\'d better muster your courage and never give up. 你最好鼓起勇气,永不放弃。 4. He mustered all his courage to take part in the game. 他鼓起全部的勇气参加比赛。 5. There was a muster of all the guards. 全体卫兵进行了一次集合。', '过去式: mustered 过去分词: mustered 现在分词: mustering 第三人称单数: musters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snicker', '[\'snɪkər]', 'vi.窃笑 n.窃笑', '1. Could it be a sexual signal, some snicker. 有人窃笑，它会不会是一个求爱信号。 2. The shuffle and snicker become the comedian\'s trademark. 搅和与窃笑成为那个戏剧演员的标志。 3. Could it be a sexual signal, some snicker. 有人窃笑，它会不会是一个求爱信号。 4. The shuffle and snicker become the comedian\'s trademark. 搅和与窃笑成为那个戏剧演员的标志。', '副词: snickeringly 过去式: snickered 过去分词: snickered 现在分词: snickering 第三人称单数: snickers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parry', '[\'pæri]', 'v.挡开武器或打击；挡开；回避 n.挡开；回避', '1. He prefers to parry rather than duck and sway. 他喜欢闪避胜过弯腰和摇摆。 2. He could no longer parry the fierce attacks of the latter by simple avoidance. 他不能光是用逃避来抵挡后者的凶猛的攻击了。 3. The bad news is that the U.N. is too weak to parry this challenge. 但坏的方面是联合国的力量太弱了，无法适当处理这个挑战。 4. Mrs Clinton finds this hard to parry. 克林顿夫人发现这一次很难招架。 5. The parry is the main defensive skill,often followed by the counter-riposte. 挡、避是主要的防守技术，通常防守中紧跟反还击。', '名词复数: parries 过去式: parried 过去分词: parried 现在分词: parrying 第三人称单数: parries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('generality', '[ˌdʒenə\'ræləti]', 'n.一般性；概论；大部分', '1. This method of analysis has generality. 分析方法具有一般性。 2. An account of such generality is of little value. 这种一般性描述没有什么价值。 3. This generality is subject to the particular facts. 这一个概论是以特别的事实为主题。 4. The generality of Swedes are blond. 瑞典人大部分是金发的。', '名词复数: generalities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('melody', '[\'melədi]', 'n.旋律；曲子；曲调；美妙的音乐', '1. The melody still rang in her ears. 那个旋律仍然在她的耳际荡。 2. The organist played a famous melody. 这位管风琴手演奏了一首著名的曲子。 3. He played a delightful melody on his flute. 他用笛子吹奏了欢快的曲调。 4. The song has plaintive melody. 这首歌曲的曲调悲伤。', '名词复数: melodies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('digress', '[daɪ\'ɡres]', 'v.走向岔道；离开本题；扯到枝节上', '1. I\'ll tell you a funny story,if I may digress for a moment. 如果我可以暂时离开一下话题，我将讲一个有趣的故事给你听。 2. Don\'t digress from the subject when lecturing. 讲课时不要扯到枝节上。', '过去式: digressed 过去分词: digressed 现在分词: digressing 第三人称单数: digresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('liberality', '[ˌlɪbə\'ræləti]', 'n.慷慨；心胸开阔', '1. Liberality is not giving much, but giving wisely. 慷慨并不是给予很多，而是给予得很明智。 2. She firmly relied on the liberality of his intentions. 她坚定地寄希望于他的慷慨打算。 3. He exhibits a spirit of liberality and reasonableness. 他表现出心胸开阔和通情达理的气魄。 4. The Tang Dynasty is a period remarkable for its liberality. 唐朝是一段以开明著称的时期。', '名词复数: liberalities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vivid', '[\'vɪvɪd]', 'adj.生动的；鲜艳的；栩栩如生的', '1. This place conjures up vivid memories. 这个地方使人回忆起许多生动的往事。 2. My daughter is a child with vivid imagination. 我女儿是一个想象力活跃的孩子。 3. This girl gave a vivid description of the event. 那女孩对这件事作了一番生动的描述。 4. Only the vivid red hair ever stood out. 只有鲜艳的红头发非常令人注目。', '副词: vividly 比较级: vivider 最高级: vividest 名词: vividness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bray', '[breɪ]', 'n.驴叫声；喇叭声 v.叫；嘶叫；响；粗声地说', '1. The bray of the donkey absorbed us. 驴叫声吸引了我们。 2. That was when a loud bray made me about-face once more. 就在这时，一只驴子的大叫声使我再次转过头来。 3. Every ass loves to hear himself bray. 每只驴子都爱自已叫。 4. If a donkey bray at you,don\'t bray at him. [谚]别和蠢人一般见识。', '过去式: brayed 过去分词: brayed 现在分词: braying 第三人称单数: brays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foul', '[faʊl]', 'adj.恶臭的；邪恶的；污秽的；恶劣的；犯规的 n.犯规 v.弄脏；妨碍；犯规', '1. He opened the window to let out the foul air. 他打开窗户，放出污浊的空气。 2. The foul weather spoiled our vacation. 恶劣的天气把我们的假期糟踏了。 3. She has a foul temper. 她脾气暴躁。 4. The ball was foul. 这球犯规了。 5. The forward made a foul in the penalty area. 前锋在禁区内犯规了。 6. Owners who allow their dogs to foul the footpath will be fined. 主人若放任狗弄脏人行道将受处罚。', '副词: foully 比较级: fouler 最高级: foulest 名词: foulness 过去式: fouled 过去分词: fouled 现在分词: fouling 第三人称单数: fouls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impasse', '[\'ɪmpæs]', 'n.僵局；死路', '1. But the political impasse lingers. 但政治僵局却依然持续。 2. We often reach an impasse in our thinking. 我们在思维过程中常常会陷入僵局。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distention', '[dɪ\'stenʃən]', 'n.膨胀', '1. Do you have a gastric distention? 你胃部作胀吗? 2. It lines hollow organs capable of considerable distention. 它所衬的中空器官具有一定的扩张能力。 3. Duct ectasia is characterized by distention of subareolar ducts. 导管扩张以乳晕下导管的扩张为特征. 4. An abnormal distention of body tissues caused by retention of air. 气肿因空气滞留而引起的体组织的不正常的扩张', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('explicable', '[ɪk\'splɪkəbl]', 'adj.可解释的；可说明的', '1. His conduct is not explicable. 他的行为无法解释。 2. His behaviour is only explicable in terms of his recent illness. 他的行为只能用他最近患病来解释。 3. The delay is partly explicable by the road works. 延误的部份原因是道路施工。 4. The sudden increase in sales is easily explicable. 销售额的突然增加是很容易理解的。', '副词: explicably');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('particularize', '[pər\'tɪkjələraɪz]', 'v.详细说明；列举；大书特书', '1. Introduce the system structure design of virtual multi-channel analyzer, particularize the functions of every modules and its software implementation method. 介绍了虚拟多道分析系统的系统结构设计，详细说明了虚拟多道各模块的功能及其软件实现方法。', '名词: particularization 过去式: particularized 过去分词: particularized 现在分词: particularizing 第三人称单数: particularizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bottleneck', '[\'bɑːtlnek]', 'n.瓶颈 v.阻塞；妨碍 adj.狭窄的', '1. TV talk show has entered a bottleneck period, gradually chug. 目前电视谈话节目已经进入了一个瓶颈期，问题逐渐彰显。', '过去式: bottlenecked 过去分词: bottlenecked 现在分词: bottlenecking 第三人称单数: bottlenecks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('green', '[ɡriːn]', 'adj.绿色的；长满绿色植物的；环保的；无经验的；未成熟的 n.绿色；草地 vi.变绿 vt.使…变绿；使…恢复活力 Green. n.格林(姓氏)', '1. The paper turned green as if by magic. 这纸魔术般地变成了绿色。 2. The green fields came into sight. 一片绿色的田野展现在眼前。 3. The country is very green in spring. 春天的时候，乡村一片青葱碧绿。 4. Starch is an unharmful and green material. 淀粉化学品是一种有利于环保的绿色物质。 5. Green was the predominant color in the forest. 绿色是森林的主色调。 6. Our lawn grass does not green up until the middle of May. 我们的草坪要到五月中旬才变绿。 7. Mr. Green spoke highly of our city. 格林先生很称赞我们的城市。', '副词: greenly 比较级: greener 最高级: greenest 名词: greenness 过去式: greened 过去分词: greened 现在分词: greening 第三人称单数: greens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grease', '[ɡriːs]', 'n.油脂 vt.用油脂涂；上油；贿赂', '1. Mother smeared grease on her hands. 母亲用油脂涂沫了双手。 2. The engine was covered in grease. 发动机上有层油脂。 3. I use the floor cleaner to remove grease. 我用地板除垢剂清除油污。 4. You\'re supposed to grease the pan first. 你应该先往锅里加点儿油。', '形容词: greaseless 过去式: greased 过去分词: greased 现在分词: greasing 第三人称单数: greases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amicable', '[\'æmɪkəbl]', 'adj.友好的；和睦的', '1. We came to an amicable agreement. 我们达成了友好的协议。 2. Especially when you\'ve established a long-term good business relationship with us,it is usually much easier to handle the disputes through amicable negotiations. 尤其当我们双方之间建立了长期友好的贸易关系以后，通过友好协商来解决争议就更容易了。 3. Unwedding ceremony acknowledges their shared life and marks their amicable separation. 离婚仪式承认彼此曾经共同拥有的生活，并且表示出他们彼此和睦的分离。', '副词: amicably 名词: amicability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beset', '[bɪ\'set]', 'vt.包围；困扰；镶嵌', '1. Buck was beset by three huskies, and in a trice his head and shoulders were ripped and slashed. 三只赫斯基狗包围了巴克，瞬息间便咬破了他的头和肩膀。 2. The country was beset with many problems. 这个国家被许多困难所困扰。 3. But a new threat faces a population already beset by hardship. 但这些已经被困境困扰的人民还面临着新的威胁。 4. The crown was beset with diamonds and jewels. 皇冠上镶嵌着钻石和珠宝。', '名词: besetment 过去式: beset 过去分词: beset 现在分词: besetting 第三人称单数: besets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('competence', '[\'kɑːmpɪtəns]', 'n.能力；胜任；管辖权', '1. Competence is prerequisite to promotion. 能力是升职的先决条件。 2. I doubt his competence to do the work. 我怀疑他是否有能力做那件工作。 3. No one doubts her competence as a teacher. 谁也不怀疑她能胜任教师工作。 4. It has beyond the competence of the court. 它已经超出法院的权限。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aloof', '[ə\'luːf]', 'adj.疏远的；冷淡的 adv.远离地', '1. She had always kept herself aloof from the boys in class. 她一直和班上的男同学保持疏远的关系。 2. It would assist England immeasurably if this hitherto aloof character could inspire some sympathy. 如果他迄今所表现出来的冷淡的性格能够赢得一些同情的话也许会对英格兰队有所帮助。', '副词: aloofly 名词: aloofness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reliance', '[rɪ\'laɪəns]', 'n.信赖；所信赖的人或物', '1. I place complete reliance on his judgment. 我完全信赖他的判断。 2. I have no reliance about his assurance. 我不信赖他的保证。 3. Don\'t place too much reliance on what he said. 对他所说的话不要过于信赖。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exceptional', '[ɪk\'sepʃənl]', 'adj.异常的；例外的；特别的；杰出的', '1. Forestry has advanced with exceptional speed. 植树造林以罕见的速度得到了发展。 2. By no means are these cases exceptional. 这些例子绝不是例外。 3. This weather is exceptional for June. 六月里这样的天气是反常的。 4. We\'ve enjoyed an exceptional run of fine weather recently. 我们这里最近天气好极了。', '副词: exceptionally 名词: exceptionality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tribunal', '[traɪ\'bjuːnl]', 'n.法庭；法院；法官席；裁决', '1. The tribunal will convene tomorrow. 法庭将于明日开庭。 2. He was brought before the tribunal for trial. 他被送到法庭受审。 3. The case has been remitted from the appeal court to a lesser tribunal. 此案已由上诉法庭转给下级法庭处理。 4. The states had no recourse but to await the verdict of the high tribunal. 各州没有追索权，只能坐待高级法院的判决。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elusive', '[i\'luːsɪv]', 'adj.难懂的；难捉摸的；难找的；逃避的', '1. Number is a crucial but elusive concept in English teaching and learning. 数是英语教学中的一个关键而又难以捉摸的概念。 2. The Abominable Snowman who haunts the imagination of climbers in the Himalayas is hardly more elusive. 常使喜马拉雅山的攀登者浮想联翩的雪人也不比此更难以捉摸。 3. Men like to pursue an elusive woman, like a cake of wet soap in a bathtub- even men who hate bath. 男人们喜欢追逐那些象浴缸里的湿肥皂般难以捉摸的女人，即使是讨厌洗澡的男人也无不如此。 4. He spent a year prospecting for the elusive metal. 他花了一年的功夫去勘探那种很难到手的金属。', '副词: elusively 名词: elusiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deranged', '[dɪ\'reɪndʒd]', 'adj.疯狂的 动词derange的过去式和过去分词.', '1. This thriller portrays the exploits of a deranged serial-killer. 该部惊悚片描绘了一个疯狂的连环杀手的作案经过。 2. He made up for his lack of personal charm by an almost deranged relentlessness. 这种几乎疯狂的执着弥补了他个人魅力的缺乏。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frieze', '[friːz]', 'n.横饰带；带状雕刻；檐壁；一种厚粗绒', '1. The friezes round the top of the wall are delicate. 墙顶的横条很精致。 2. The Corinthian painter\'s primary ornamental device was the animal frieze. 科林斯画家最初的装饰图案是动物形象的装饰带。 3. The most interesting ornamentation is found on a frieze and an arch-stone. 最有趣的装饰是发现雕刻的柱子和一个石头牌楼。 4. He was dressed in a frieze tunic, blue trousers and big, torn, high boots. 这家伙穿一件粗呢女外衣，蓝色裤子，一双裂开了的骑兵大靴子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overshadow', '[ˌoʊvər\'ʃædoʊ]', 'v.遮阴；使不快乐或减少乐趣；使黯然失色', '1. Large oak trees overshadow the garden. 高大的栎树把花园遮得很暗。 2. They traveled to a village overshadowed by mountains. 他们旅游到了一个被山影笼罩的村庄。 3. His recent death overshadowed the family gathering. 他最近去世给家庭聚会蒙上了阴影。 4. Her new book will overshadow all her earlier ones. 她的这部新作将会使她的早期作品黯然失色。', '过去式: overshadowed 过去分词: overshadowed 现在分词: overshadowing 第三人称单数: overshadows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subjective', '[səb\'dʒektɪv]', 'adj.主观的', '1. His arguments were never subjective. 他的论点从来不是主观的。 2. He took a subjective view of the problem. 他用主观的方法看问题。 3. Grading of oral tests is quite subjective. 口语考试的打分是相当主观的。', '副词: subjectively 名词: subjectiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indemnity', '[ɪn\'demnəti]', 'n.保证；赔偿；保险', '1. The bank can issue a letter of indemnity to the shipper. 银行可向承运人出具保证函。 2. He have to pay an indemnity of&100. 他必须支付100英镑的赔偿。 3. The victorious nations are demanding huge indemnities from their former enemies. 战胜国要求战败国交付巨额赔款。 4. Indemnity can be deducted from the salary of laborer. 赔偿金额可以从劳动者的工资扣除。', '名词复数: indemnities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('buck', '[bʌk]', 'n.<俚>一美元 n.钱；雄鹿；雄兔；(鹿皮等)制物；<美口>年轻男子 v.马弓背踢后腿挑起；抵制；振作', '1. People want to make a quick buck. 人人都想赚容易钱。 2. The buck shook his antlers ferociously. 那雄鹿猛烈地摇动他的鹿角。 3. The buck jumped into the woods before the hunter raised his gun. 还没等猎人举起枪来那只雄鹿就跳进了树林。 4. Both buck and doe have a little gait and both their eyelids palpitate. 雄兔脚扑朔，雌兔眼迷离。 5. The horse may still buck, but now the peeler can start topping it off. 虽然那匹马还会猛然弯背跃起，但现在驯马者可以结束对它的驯服工作了。', '名词: bucker 过去式: bucked 过去分词: bucked 现在分词: bucking 第三人称单数: bucks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prodigal', '[\'prɑːdɪɡl]', 'adj.挥霍的；(物产等)丰富的；慷慨的 n.挥霍者', '1. I hate the prodigal administration. 我痛恨铺张浪费的行政机关。 2. They are prodigal in their expenditures. 他们挥霍无度。 3. Destinies are very fatal for several and too prodigal or too protecting for others. 对于一部分人，命运是残酷无晴的，而对于另一部分人，又过于慷慨或过于爱护。 4. The prodigal handouts should continue 这些慷慨的施舍必须继续下去。 5. Those prodigals were put into prison. 那些挥霍者被关进监狱。', '副词: prodigally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frantic', '[\'fræntɪk]', 'adj.疯狂的；狂乱的；急忙的', '1. That noise is driving me frantic. 那种噪音真要把我弄疯了。 2. The child\'s parents were frantic when she did not return home on time. 那孩子没有按时回家，她父母都要急疯了。 3. Don\'t drive him frantic by worrying him with endless questions. 不要以无穷尽的问题困扰他而使他狂乱。 4. She was frantic with worry. 她愁得要命。', '副词: frantically 名词: franticness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('putter', '[\'pʌtər]', 'n.(高尔夫球的)轻击棒；轻击者 v.慢条斯理地工作；闲逛', '1. I like a putter that looks and feels good. 我喜欢那种看起来握起来都很好的轻击棒。 2. He gave me an aluminum putter that I use today. 他送了我一根打高尔夫球的轻击棒，我到今天还在用。 3. If he retains his faith in his ability to holes out, then he remains a good putter. 要是他保持有能力将高尔夫球打入穴中的那种信心，那么他仍然是个好的高尔夫球轻击手。 4. Although it is very old, the car can putter along on the flat. 尽管车已很旧，它还能在平坦的路面上慢慢地跑跑。', '名词: putterer 过去式: puttered 过去分词: puttered 现在分词: puttering 第三人称单数: putters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flatulent', '[\'flætʃələnt]', 'adj.肠胃气胀的；自负的；浮夸的', '1. Grandma: Now Ed, remember, when you yell you get flatulent. 凯特：我说艾德，你这么大声嚷嚷会发胃病的。 2. Indications: Stomach-ache, indigestion, hyperacidity, heartburn, flatulent and spasmodic. 主治： 胃痛、胃酸过多、胃灼热、胃气胀及肠胃痉挛等。 3. We\'ve got some great stuff coming your way, so download this app now and let the fun flatulent fun begin! 我们已经有了一些伟大的东西来您的方式，所以下载这个程序，并让现在的乐趣空虚的乐趣开始了！ 4. Bees sup honey from flowers and feel thankful when leaving. But flatulent butterfly think flowers shold thank her. 1蜜蜂从花中啜蜜，离开时营营地道谢。／浮夸的蝴蝶却相信花是应该向他道谢的。。', '副词: flatulently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('analogous', '[ə\'næləɡəs]', 'adj.类似的', '1. The human heart is analogous to a pump. 人的心脏和泵类似。 2. Brains and computers are often considered analogous. 人脑和电脑常被认为是类似的。', '副词: analogously 名词: analogousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('filth', '[fɪlθ]', 'n.污秽；淫秽图片、书刊等', '1. The black pigs rootled for filth. 这些黑猪用鼻翻拱垃圾。 2. The gutters were choked with filth. 街沟中淤积着污物。 3. Go and wash that filth off your hand. 去把你手上的脏东西洗掉。 4. You put filth in my child`s mouth. 你教会了我的孩子讲污秽的话.', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('butt', '[bʌt]', 'n.烟蒂；屁股；枪托 n.笑柄；靶垛 n.大酒桶 n.抵撞 v.插嘴；顶撞', '1. He stamped his butt on the floor. 他在地板上踩灭了他的烟蒂。 2. My sister says he has a hairy butt. 我姐姐说他屁股上长满了毛。 3. He was clubbed to death with a butt of a gun. 他是被人用枪托殴打致死的。 4. It was be a butt of the joke on my history. 这在我的历史中真是一个天大的笑柄。 5. The water butt catches the overflow from this pipe. 大水桶盛接管子里流出的东西。 6. He gave me a butt on the stomach. 他在我腹部撞了一下。 7. Don\'t butt in like that when I\'m speaking. 我讲话时别这样打断我的话。', '名词: butter 过去式: butted 过去分词: butted 现在分词: butting 第三人称单数: butts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('groom', '[ɡruːm]', 'n.新郎；马夫；王室侍从者 v.打扮；梳理毛发；培养；准备（滑雪）赛道', '1. Her groom was much older than she was. 她的新郎比她大很多。 2. The bride and groom made a lovely couple. 新娘和新郎是天作之合的一对。 3. The groom returned to the carriage. 马夫回到马车那儿。 4. He groomed himself carefully for the party. 他为晚会仔细地打扮了一番。', '名词: groomer 过去式: groomed 过去分词: groomed 现在分词: grooming 第三人称单数: grooms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stoop', '[stuːp]', 'n.佝偻；弯腰；屈尊；俯冲 v.弯腰；屈服；佝偻；屈尊；降格；俯冲', '1. The old woman walked with a stoop. 老太太伛偻而行。 2. Try not to walk with such a stoop. 尽量不要驼着背走路。 3. She has always walked with a stoop. 她总是弯腰走路。 4. The hawk descend in a vertical stoop on its quarry. 鹰向它的猎物直冲而下。 5. She stooped low to look under the bed. 她弯下腰看床底下。', '过去式: stooped 过去分词: stooped 现在分词: stooping 第三人称单数: stoops');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('denture', '[\'dentʃər]', 'n.假牙；齿列', '1. You should leave your denture in your mouth all day. 你应该整天戴着你的假牙。 2. The gums must heal for at least one mouth before the denture is begun. 先拔后牙，让伤口愈合一个月以后，再做假牙。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illuminati', '[ɪˌluːmə\'neɪtaɪ]', 'n.先觉者；智者；光照派', '1. The top of the Great Seal pyramid shows an eye-in-triangle, which has been associated with Sirius, the Eye of God, the pineal gland, and the Illuminati. 大封印金字塔展现了一只三角形眼睛，与天狼星有关联，神的眼睛，松果体和先觉者。 2. Believers say the Illuminati is so effective, they\'ve erased almost all evidence of their existence. 相信这个理论的人说，光照派非常厉害，他们把所有关于他们存在的证据都销毁了。 3. The supposed goals of the Illuminati range from simple world domination to preparing the Earth for extraterrestrial colonization. 关于光照派的目标的猜想也非常多，从简单的统治世界到在地球上为外星殖民做准备，不一而足。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debouch', '[dɪ\'buːʃ]', 'v.流出；进入(开阔地区)', '1. The army debouched from the mountains into a wide plain. 军队从山里开出，进入宽阔平原。 2. The stream debouches into the estuary. 这条河流入河口湾。', '过去式: debouched 过去分词: debouched 现在分词: debouching 第三人称单数: debouches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resound', '[rɪ\'zaʊnd]', 'v.(使)回响；鸣响；驰名', '1. The sonorous voice of the priest resounded in the church. 教士那圆润低沉的声音在教堂里回响。 2. The whole building resounded the siren\'s warning. 整个大楼回响着警报声。 3. His fame resounded all over the world. 他名扬全球。 4. His name will resound through ages. 他的名字将万古流芳。', '形容词: resounding 副词: resoundingly 过去式: resounded 过去分词: resounded 现在分词: resounding 第三人称单数: resounds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remove', '[rɪ\'muːv]', 'v.消除；脱掉；免除；搬迁', '1. He removed the mud from his shoes. 他去掉鞋上的泥。 2. How can we remove the husk of the grains? 我们怎样去掉谷物的外皮？ 3. Come and remove your wet coat. 过来把你的湿上衣脱掉。 4. She asked me to remove my shnes. 她让我把鞋脱掉。', '名词: remover 过去式: removed 过去分词: removed 现在分词: removing 第三人称单数: removes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accrue', '[ə\'kruː]', 'vi.自然增加；积累；生成 vt.积累', '1. Ability to think clearly will accrue to you from good habits of study. 你的思考能力将因良好的学习习惯而自然增进。 2. Knowledge will accrue to you from reading. 读书能增加知识。 3. Substantial profits accrue when sales take off. 当销售额突飞猛进之后，可观的利润就开始自然累积。 4. Interest will accrue if you keep your money in a savings account . 把钱存在储蓄帐户里就会生息. 5. When you nurture yourself, you accrue tremendous spin-off benefits. 当你悉心照料你自己，你的身体就会产生巨大的好处。', '名词: accruement 过去式: accrued 过去分词: accrued 现在分词: accruing 第三人称单数: accrues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scorching', '[\'skɔːrtʃɪŋ]', 'adj.灼热的 动车scorch的现在分词.', '1. The scorching heat was beginning to get her down. 灼热的天气使她开始感到疲倦。 2. I spent my day on the scorching hot dust of the road. 我在大路灼热的尘土上消磨了一天。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tempestuous', '[tem\'pestʃuəs]', 'adj.有暴风雨的；剧烈的', '1. Their ship was sailing dangerously in the tempestuous sea. 他们的船在浪急风高的海上危险地航行着。 2. She burst into a tempestuous fit of anger. 她勃然大怒。', '副词: tempestuously 名词: tempestuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illicit', '[ɪ\'lɪsɪt]', 'adj.非法的；违禁的；不正当的', '1. The police chief was talking about the illicit sale of drugs. 警长在讲毒品的非法贩卖。 2. Illicit trades should be outlawed. 非法交易应被取缔。 3. He makes a lot of money by traffic illicit merchandise. 他做违禁商品买卖赚了许多钱。 4. He had an illicit association with Jane. 他和简曾有过不正当关系。', '副词: illicitly 名词: illicitness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prefigure', '[ˌpriː\'fɪɡjər]', 'v.预示；预想', '1. Few writers care to prefigure the future. 很少有作家对预测将来感兴趣。 2. To prefigure indistinctly; foreshadow. 隐约预示；预示 3. To prefigure indistinctly;foreshadow. 隐约预示；预示 4. To represent by an image,a form,or a model; symbolize or prefigure. 象征用形象、形式或模型来表示；象征或预示。', '形容词: prefigurative 副词: prefiguratively 名词: prefigurativeness 过去式: prefigured 过去分词: prefigured 现在分词: prefiguring 第三人称单数: prefigures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('caustic', '[\'kɔːstɪk]', 'adj.腐蚀性的；刻薄的；[物]焦散的 n.腐蚀物；[物]焦散曲面', '1. He opened his mouth to make a caustic retort. 他张嘴开始进行刻薄的反击。 2. The caustic remark dented her ego. 那种尖利刻薄的话语伤害了她的自尊心。', '副词: caustically 名词: causticity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apologize', '[ə\'pɑːlədʒaɪz]', 'vi.道歉；赔罪', '1. He apologizes to her for not going to her party. 他因未出席她的派对向她表示歉意。 2. I apologize if I hurt your feelings. 如果我伤害了你的感情,那我道歉。 3. You must apologize to him for your fault. 你必须为你的过失向他赔罪。', '名词: apologizer 过去式: apologized 过去分词: apologized 现在分词: apologizing 第三人称单数: apologizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rotten', '[\'rɑːtn]', 'adj.腐烂的；腐朽的；<口>极坏的；讨厌的 adv.非常', '1. One smell of the rotten meat was enough! 这腐烂的肉闻一下就够受的了。 2. This place has an odious smell; something must be rotten. 这个地方有一股臭味，一定有东西腐烂了。 3. The wood was so rotten that you could put your finger through it. 这木料腐朽了,你可以用手指戳穿它。 4. They are contaminating the minds of our young people with these rotten ideas. 他们正用这些腐朽的思想污染着我们青年人的头脑。 5. The child is spoiled rotten. 这个小孩被宠坏了。', '副词: rottenly 比较级: rottener 最高级: rottenest 名词: rottenness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oversee', '[ˌoʊvər\'siː]', 'vt.监督；监管；监视', '1. Government must help oversee this recalibration. 政府必须帮助监督这次调整。 2. He will now oversee global manufacturing and productivity. 他现在将监督全球制造业和生产力。 3. You must employ someone to oversee the project. 你得雇个人监督这一工程。 4. He proposes an import tsar to oversee the scrutiny of Chinese goods. 他建议成立一个专门监管中国货物的进口管理机构。', '过去式: oversaw 过去分词: overseen 现在分词: overseeing 第三人称单数: oversees');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tuxedo', '[tʌk\'siːdoʊ]', 'n.（男士无尾半正式）晚礼服', '1. John looked fit to kill in his tuxedo. 约翰穿上晚礼服，显得十分英俊。 2. The groom wears a formal suit or tuxedo. 新郎则穿着一套正式的西装或无尾晚礼服。 3. At a formal occasion, it is necessary for men to wear a tuxedo. 在一个正式的场合中,男仕们穿着无尾晚礼服是必要的。', '形容词: tuxedoed 名词复数: tuxedos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('serene', '[sə\'riːn]', 'adj.安详的；宁静的；平静的 Serene. adj.尊贵的', '1. His serene smile calmed all of us down. 他脸上安详的微笑使我们都冷静下来。 2. The story took place in a serene summer night. 故事发生在一个宁静的夏夜。 3. It was a beautiful morning, calm and serene. 那是一个宁静、明媚的早晨。 4. Light music fills my heart with serene joyfulness. 轻音乐能带给我平静的欢乐。', '副词: serenely 名词: sereneness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marble', '[\'mɑːrbl]', 'n.大理石；弹子，弹珠 vt.使有大理石的花纹', '1. This table is made of marble. 这个桌子是大理石的。 2. Michelangelo carved in marble. 米开朗琪罗在大理石上雕刻。 3. There are many perpendicular marble columns in Greek temples. 希腊庙宇有很多垂直的大理石柱。 4. My little son has many marbles. 我的小儿子有许多弹珠。', '形容词: marbly 过去式: marbled 过去分词: marbled 现在分词: marbling 第三人称单数: marbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('notability', '[ˌnoʊtə\'bɪlətɪ]', 'n.著名；显著；名人', '1. The condition of traffic is very convenient, notability superiority to the zone. 交通条件便利，区位优势显著。 2. In addition, the system can draw the relevance picture of experiment data, and make variance analysis and verification of notability of these data. 另外该系统实现了仿真试验数据关系图形的绘制及仿真试验数据的方差分析和因素显著性检验等功能。', '名词复数: notabilities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('careworn', '[\'kerwɔːrn]', 'adj.疲倦的；饱经忧患的；忧心忡忡的', '1. The old woman had a careworn look on her face. 老妇脸上露出忧心忡忡的神色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ordeal', '[ɔːr\'diːl]', 'n.严酷的考验；痛苦的经验；神裁法', '1. Through this ordeal Heng lay stiff and silent. 在这个严酷的考验中，恒一直僵硬地躺着，默不作声。 2. Once there we saw that the ordeal must have been great. 从前我们觉得严酷的考验一定是很伟大的。 3. I\'d hate to go through such a terrible ordeal again. 我不想再受这种痛苦的经验。 4. Excessive choices quickly stop being a benefit and become an ordeal. 过多的选择很快就丧失了它的优势，而成为一种痛苦的经验。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rivet', '[\'rɪvɪt]', 'n.铆钉 v.铆接；固定；钉牢；集中；吸引', '1. Can I fasten these metal plates with rivets? 我可以用铆钉把这些金属板固定在一起吗？ 2. They riveted the steel beams together. 他们把钢梁铆接在一起。 3. We stood riveted to the spot. 我们寸步不移的站在那儿。 4. Her eyes were riveted on his face. 她的眼睛盯着他的脸。', '名词: riveter 过去式: riveted 过去分词: riveted 现在分词: riveting 第三人称单数: rivets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prissy', '[\'prɪsi]', 'adj.谨小慎微的；神经质的；为小事挂虑的', '1. Remember, Aunt Hester is a bit on the prissy side. 记住，海斯特阿姨有点谨小慎微。 2. Flats like these are really cute but they are too prissy. 像这样的平底鞋是很可爱，不够大方。 3. I would never ever wear dresses because I thought they were too prissy. 我永远不会穿衣服，因为我以为他们是太神经质。', '副词: prissily 比较级: prissier 最高级: prissiest 名词: prissiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solicitous', '[sə\'lɪsɪtəs]', 'adj.热切的；焦虑的；挂念的；关心的', '1. I am solicitous of his help. 我渴得到他的帮助。 2. He was very solicitous for her safe return. 他心神不定 3. She was very solicitous for our welfare. 她非常挂念我们的福利问题。 4. We are all solicitous about his health. 我们都为他的身体担心。', '副词: solicitously 名词: solicitousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('credence', '[\'kriːdns]', 'n.信任；相信；祭器台', '1. I attach little credence to what she says. 我对她的话姑妄听之。 2. Historical evidence lends credence to his theory. 史学根据使他的理论更为可信。 3. Don\'t give credence to all the gossip you hear. 不要相信你听到的闲话。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('redoubtable', '[rɪ\'daʊtəbl]', 'adj.可怕的；引起恐慌的；可敬畏的', '1. The redoubtable American woman played her part. 可敬的美国妇女作出了其贡献。', '副词: redoubtably');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surrender', '[sə\'rendər]', 'v.投降；屈服；放弃 n.投降；屈服；放弃', '1. It was shameful of them to surrender. 他们投降是可耻的。 2. We would rather die than surrender. 我们宁死而不投降。 3. They surrendered to the enemy. 他们向敌人投降了。 4. We can never surrender to him. 而我们绝对不能够屈服。 5. The garrison was starved into surrender. 卫戍部队因遭到断粮而投降。', '过去式: surrendered 过去分词: surrendered 现在分词: surrendering 第三人称单数: surrenders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blight', '[blaɪt]', 'n.枯萎病；导致破坏的因素 v.(使）枯萎；摧毁', '1. Blight is a disease incident to plants. 植物容易患枯萎病。 2. The apple crop was wiped out by blight. 枯萎病使苹果全无收成。 3. There is a blight on all his efforts. 他的一切努力都遭到挫折。 4. The accident cast a blight on our happiness. 那场意外事故使我们的幸福生活蒙上了一层阴影。 5. Too much rain may blight the garden with mold. 雨水太多会令花园因长真菌而枯萎。', '过去式: blighted 过去分词: blighted 现在分词: blighting 第三人称单数: blights');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spate', '[speɪt]', 'n.泛滥；洪水；突然的一阵', '1. After the storm all the rivers were in spate. 暴雨过后河水都上涨了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inveigh', '[ɪn\'veɪ]', 'v.痛骂；猛烈抨击；强烈抗议', '1. The speaker was inveighing against the evils of drink. 发言人正在猛烈抨击喝酒的害处。', '名词: inveigher 过去式: inveighed 过去分词: inveighed 现在分词: inveighing 第三人称单数: inveighs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pummel', '[\'pʌml]', 'v.猛击；(用拳)接连地打；打击', '1. Intense hurricane winds pummel the shoreline. 强烈的飓风吹打着海岸。 2. I am dying for a chance to pummel that guy. 我很想要有一个机会打那家伙。 3. The child pummelled his mother angrily as she carried him home. 那孩子因其母带他回家而生气地捶打著母亲。 4. On the other hand, Mr Obama correctly reckons that the attractive tax cuts Mr. McCain proposes could pummel the federal budget. 另一方面，奥巴马认为麦凯恩提出的诱人的减税提案可能给联邦预算连续打击，一点不错。', '过去式: pummeled/pummelled 过去分词: pummeled/pummelled 现在分词: pummeling/pummelling 第三人称单数: pummels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plain', '[pleɪn]', 'adj.清楚的；简单的；坦白的；平常的；朴素的；纯的 n.平原；广阔的区域 adv.完全地；纯粹地', '1. It was plain to everyone that she was not happy. 她并不幸福,这是明摆着的事实。 2. The restaurant serves plain home-made meals. 那个餐馆供应简单的家常菜。 3. She was admired for her plain speaking. 她说话坦白,这一点令人钦佩。 4. Most people see great men as wizards; however, they are just plain people. 大多数人觉得伟人是奇才,然而,他们只不过是平常人。 5. The wind whipped across the plain. 大风扫过平原。 6. Beck went plain crazy with anger on the day when he received his Dear John from his girlfriend. 贝克收到他女朋友的绝交信的那天简直都气疯了。', '副词: plainly 比较级: plainer 最高级: plainest 名词: plainness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lobby', '[\'lɑːbi]', 'n.大厅；民众接待厅；游说议员者 v.游说', '1. I waited for her in the lobby of theatre yesterday. 昨天我在戏院的大厅等她。 2. The film star held court in the hotel lobby. 这位电影明星在旅馆的大厅里接见了影迷。 3. The anti-nuclear lobby is becoming stronger. 向议员游说的反核群众声势渐强。 4. The group tried to lobby the bill through. 这个集团企图通过游说议员通过该项法案。', '名词: lobbyer 名词复数: lobbies 过去式: lobbied 过去分词: lobbied 现在分词: lobbying 第三人称单数: lobbies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heretic', '[\'herətɪk]', 'n.异教徒 adj.异端的；异教的（=heretical)', '1. He was regarded as heretic by the common people. 他被大众视为异教徒。 2. On one occasion he hanged twenty heretics, including a minister, at a single heat. 有一次他一下子绞死了20个异教徒，包括一位牧师在内。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grateful', '[\'ɡreɪtfl]', 'adj.感激的；令人愉快的', '1. I can\'t express how grateful I am. 我说不出我有多么感激。 2. These refugees are very grateful to the government\'s succor. 这些难民非常感激政府的救援。 3. I am grateful for all your past kindness. 多蒙关照,万分感激。 4. I\'d be grateful if you should let me know as soon as possible. 你若能让我尽快知道,我会很感激的。', '副词: gratefully 名词: gratefulness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anarchy', '[\'ænərki]', 'n.无政府状态；混乱', '1. The country was thrown into a state of anarchy. 这国家那时一下子陷入无政府状态。 2. If law and order break down, anarchy will result. 法治一垮，就会出现无政府状态。 3. Anarchy was rampant after the dictator died. 独裁者死后政治混乱猖獗。 4. Any system that cedes those rights will lead to anarchy. 任何割让那些权利的体制都将导致政治混乱。', '名词复数: anarchies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('valediction', '[ˌvælɪ\'dɪkʃn]', 'n.告别；告别演说；告别辞', '1. I came here just for a valediction. 我来仅仅是向你告别。 2. He gave a touching valediction at graduation. 他在毕业典礼上发表了动人的告别辞。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('simile', '[\'sɪməli]', 'n.直喻；明喻', '1. \"The baby is as cute as an angel\" is a simile. “孩子像天使一般可爱”是句直喻。 2. A simile has at least two layers of meaning. 明喻修辞至少有两层含义。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scuttle', '[\'skʌtl]', 'n.煤斗；天窗 v.凿沉；急走；快跑', '1. Basically use at window of housetop scuttle, balcony. 主要用于屋顶天窗、阳台窗。 2. The children scuttle across the street. 我看见他急匆匆地穿街而过。 3. The spectators scuttled for shelter when it began to rain. 一下起雨来，观众就纷纷找地方躲避。', '过去式: scuttled 过去分词: scuttled 现在分词: scuttling 第三人称单数: scuttles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inviolable', '[ɪn\'vaɪələbl]', 'adj.不可侵犯的；不可亵渎的', '1. The people possess inviolable rights. 人民享有不可侵犯的权利。 2. Basic law or tradition was considered inviolable. 基本法律或传统被认为神圣不可侵犯。', '副词: inviolably 名词: inviolability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coda', '[\'koʊdə]', 'n.乐章结尾部；(小说、戏剧等的）结局部分', '1. The coda to this last movement is borrowed from two humanists. 这个最后乐章的完结部来源于两个人文主义者。 2. The Coda features the tune combined with an evocative countermelody in the piano. 结尾部分的特征在于结合了钢琴的对位旋律。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('press', '[pres]', 'v.按；压；逼迫；强迫服役；征用 n.新闻界；出版社；报刊；新闻舆论；压；熨烫机；印刷机', '1. Please press the controller to turn the machine on. 请按控制器来开机。 2. Press this button in case of fire. 遇火灾时按下此钮。 3. The book is crumpled and needs press. 书皱了需要压一压。 4. Press firmly on the wound to stop the bleeding. 用力压住伤口止血。 5. He denied that he had leaked the news to the press. 他否认曾将这则消息泄漏给新闻界。', '过去式: pressed 过去分词: pressed 现在分词: pressing 第三人称单数: presses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clemency', '[\'klemənsi]', 'n.仁慈；宽厚，宽容，忍让；(气候)温和，温暖，和善；仁慈的举动，宽厚的举动', '1. He appealed to the judge for clemency. 他乞求法官开恩。 2. They addressed to the governor a plea for clemency. 他们向州长提出了宽刑的申辩书。', '名词复数: clemencies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('doctrinaire', '[ˌdɑːktrə\'ner]', 'n.教条主义者 adj.教条主义的；空谈理论的', '1. Today\'s economists tend to be open-minded about content, but doctrinaire about form. 目前经济学家对内容更包容，但教条主义者却关心形式。 2. And they do not like coming across as doctrinaire and mean-spirited. 况且他们也不愿意留给人们的印象就是死板守旧和铁石心肠。 3. The world needs a less doctrinaire approach to foreign capital flows. 我们需要一种不那么教条的方法来对待外资流动。 4. Don\'t be so doctrinaire about things. 别那样用理论去解释（判断）事物。', '名词: doctrinairism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assess', '[ə\'ses]', 'v.评定；评估；估算', '1. He can quickly assess a person\'s character. 他能很快地评定出某人的品质。 2. How do you assess your students? 你如何评估学生们？ 3. We will assess the damages caused by the flood. 我们将对洪灾造成的损失进行评估。 4. She looked at the house and assessed its market value. 她看了看房子并估算了其市场价值。', '形容词: assessable 过去式: assessed 过去分词: assessed 现在分词: assessing 第三人称单数: assesses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interjection', '[ˌɪntər\'dʒekʃn]', 'n.感叹词；插入语；插话', '1. Crikey is an interjection that is used to express surprise or amazement. 是感叹词，表示意外或惊讶。', '形容词: interjectional 副词: interjectionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('progeny', '[\'prɑːdʒəni]', 'n.子孙；结果', '1. He appeared, surrounded by his numerous progeny. 他出现时，子女前呼后拥不计其数。 2. Progeny of the sea often appear grotesque or fantastic. 海洋的子孙显得奇怪或荒谬。 3. Their main operations is distribution of product, transfer of progeny and imparting of technique. 以产品销售、成果转让、技术培训等为主要业务。', '名词复数: progeny');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('titular', '[\'tɪtʃələr]', 'adj.名义上的；由有称号或头衔的人持有的；从标题而来的 n.拥有称号的人', '1. He will never be a titular leader. 他永远不会成为一个有名无实的领袖。 2. The Queen is titular head of the Church of England. 英国女王是英国国教名义上的领袖。 3. Its titular head is a person whose whereabouts nobody knows. 它的名义首脑是个动向去处谁都不知道的人。 4. O\'Connor gave up his titular possessions and conducted business in America. 欧康纳放弃了他由头衔而拥有的财产,然后去美国经商了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('asinine', '[\'æsɪnaɪn]', 'adj.驴的；像驴的；愚蠢的', '1. I hope you win their appeal and throw this asinine verdict out. 我希望你可以赢得这场官事，把这个莫名其妙的判决推翻。 2. Admitting that cheating happened and then saying the voting was fair is asinine. 承认了投票有误却坚持说结果是公平的是愚蠢的做法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('censor', '[\'sensər]', 'n.检查员；监察官 vt.检查', '1. They had to accept the blue pencil of the censor. 他们不得不接受检查员的修改。 2. Don\'t write anything that will bother the censor. 你可别写什么给检查员找麻烦的话。 3. A white censor was standing over me. 有一个白人监察官在监视着我。 4. The censor insisted on excising the passage from the film. 电影审查员坚持剪去影片的这一段。 5. It is not constitutional to censor the press. 审查新闻是违反宪法的。', '形容词: censorable 过去式: censored 过去分词: censored 现在分词: censoring 第三人称单数: censors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ethereal', '[i\'θɪriəl]', 'adj.天上的；飘逸的；精致的；飘渺的；乙醚的', '1. The scientists were reduced to silence, to tears of an ethereal sort. 科学家们都无法言语，留下了超越现实的泪水。 2. She has an ethereal beauty. 她有一种微妙飘逸之美。 3. The music has an ethereal quality. 这段乐曲给人一种飘渺的感觉。', '副词: ethereally 名词: ethereality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('zone', '[zoʊn]', 'n.地域；地带；地区', '1. They are pulling their troops out of the battle zone. 他们正把部队调离战区。 2. They have declared their country a, nuclear-free zone. 他们宣布本国为无核区。 3. Most of China is in the temperate zone. 中国的大部分地区在温带。 4. Some people live in Torrid Zone. 有些人生活在热带。', '过去式: zoned 过去分词: zoned 现在分词: zoning 第三人称单数: zones');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interplay', '[\'ɪntərpleɪ]', 'n.相互影响', '1. The exhibits also show the interplay of the LAPD and Hollywood. 该展览也向我们展示了洛杉矶警署和好莱坞之间的关系。 2. The story of our lives is the interplay of the bucket and the dipper. 我们的生活里充满了桶和舀水杯的交织。 3. The interplay between these elements is intriguing, and draws us in. 这些要素的交互作用十分引人入胜,也深深吸引着我们。 4. She examines the interplay between changing gender divisions and urban change. 她研究性别差异的变化和城市变化之间的相互影响。', '过去式: interplayed 过去分词: interplayed 现在分词: interplaying 第三人称单数: interplays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('understate', '[ˌʌndər\'steɪt]', 'v.轻描淡写地说；少说', '1. To call this a security hole is to understate the point woefully. 不幸的是,将它称之为安全性漏洞是轻描淡写的说法。 2. It would be a mistake to understate the seriousness of the problem. 对问题严重性的轻描淡写是错误的。 3. Factory managers understate their potential output. 工厂的管理人员少报他们的潜在产量。 4. She refuses on principle to understate her income for taxation purposes. 她出于道德上的动机,不愿为了少纳税而少报收入。', '过去式: understated 过去分词: understated 现在分词: understating 第三人称单数: understates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('folksy', '[\'foʊksi]', 'adj.朴素的；不做作的；亲切的；谦虚的', '1. His speeches are folksy and witty. 他的演讲既通俗又风趣。 2. They wanted the store to have a folksy small-town image. 他们希望这家商店具有小城镇那种朴实热情的形象。 3. His folksy manner has endeared him to his neighbors. 他平易近人的态度使他受到邻居们的喜爱。', '副词: folksily 比较级: folksier 最高级: folksiest 名词: folksiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drawbridge', '[\'drɔːbrɪdʒ]', 'n.吊桥', '1. The chains clanked as the drawbridge opened. 吊桥放下时，铁链发出叮当声。 2. We will construct a drawbridge across the gorge. 我们要建造一座横跨山峡的吊桥。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('significant', '[sɪɡ\'nɪfɪkənt]', 'adj.重要的；有意义的；意味深长的；显著的', '1. The question under discussion is significant. 讨论中的问题是重要的。 2. Economic conditions are significant in many ways. 经济条件在许多方面都是很重要的。 3. All of us want our lives to be significant. 我们每个人都希望我们的人生是有意义的。 4. It was truly a significant conversation. 这是非常有意义的谈话。', '副词: significantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unimpeachable', '[ˌʌnɪm\'piːtʃəbl]', 'adj.无懈可击的；无可指责的；可靠的', '1. Your testimony on this matter is hardly unimpeachable. 在这个问题上你的辩驳很难说是无懈可击的。 2. Willoughby Pattern is a man of unimpeachable honour. 威洛比·帕忒恩是个无可指责的高尚的人。 3. This is the market rule which is unimpeachable. 这是可靠的市场规律。', '副词: unimpeachably');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('miser', '[\'maɪzər]', 'n.守财奴；吝啬鬼', '1. Soon Mary discovered she had married a miser. 不久，玛丽发现她嫁给了一个守财奴。 2. The miser gloated over his gold. 守财奴心满意足地望着他的金子。 3. The selfish old miser had a cold nature. 这个自私的老吝啬鬼生性冷酷。 4. That miser told over his money every night. 那个吝啬鬼每天晚上都要把他的钱数一遍。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vestment', '[\'vestmənt]', 'n.(尤指牧师的)法衣；官服；礼服', '1. The priest wore a purple vestment to conduct the funeral services. 牧师穿上紫色法衣主持葬礼仪式。', '形容词: vestmental');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scarf', '[skɑːrf]', 'n.围巾', '1. The price of this scarf is below ten dollars. 这条围巾价格不到10美元。 2. She twisted the long scarf round her head. 她把那条长围巾围在头上。 3. She threw a scarf over her shoulders. 她在肩上披上一块肩巾。', '名词: scarfer 名词复数: scarves 过去式: scarfed 过去分词: scarfed 现在分词: scarfing 第三人称单数: scarfs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('permeable', '[\'pɜːrmiəbl]', 'adj.可渗透的；可穿透的', '1. The skin of amphibians is permeable to water. 两栖动物的皮肤是透水的。 2. Permeable pavement is not very good for roads with a lot of traffic. 可渗透的路面对高运输量的马路并不有效。', '副词: permeably');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rubicund', '[\'ruːbɪkənd]', 'adj.红的；透红的', '1. His rubicund face expressed consternation and fatigue. 他那红通的脸显得又惊惶又疲乏。 2. Passepartout, usually so rubicund, was fairly white with suspense. 路路通因为过分激动，一向红润的面孔都气得发白了。 3. Regular use helps dark, coarse skin become soft, fair and rubicund. 令肌肤白皙红润，柔嫩舒爽。 4. The companion, Miss Clark, was a woman of sixty, a stout cheery woman with a beaming rubicund face. 妻子的看护，克拉克小姐，是个六十岁的女人，是个结实而快乐的女人有一张红润光洁的脸。', '名词: rubicundity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('domination', '[ˌdɒmɪ\'neɪʃn]', 'n.支配；控制；管辖 （复数）dominations:[宗]主天使.', '1. The defeated army must assent to the domination of the victors. 被打败的军队必须同意胜利军队的支配。 2. At this point, we could not say that it was the male domination. 再者，从表层上来看，行使支配权者多为男性，但这并不意味着男人是完全支配女人的。 3. His domination by his brother made him very angry. 他被他哥哥所控制，这使他非常气愤。 4. They threw off the yoke of domination. 他们摆脱了控制。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repository', '[rɪ\'pɑːzətɔːri]', 'n.容器；仓库；贮藏室；智囊', '1. My diary is the repository of all my hopes and plans. 我在日记中记载著我的一切希望和计划。 2. A library is a repository of medicine for the mind. 图书馆是治疗精神之病院。 3. There is no comparable repository of our tradition. 那是我们无与伦比的传统智慧宝库。 4. The repository is the official archive of our work. 库是我们的正式的档案。', '名词复数: repositories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ogle', '[\'oʊɡl]', 'v.抛媚眼 n.眉目传情', '1. Most women dislike being ogled (at). 多数女子都讨厌让人色迷迷地盯著。 2. She ogled me when handed me a glass of wine. 她在把酒杯递到我手上时对我做了个媚眼。 3. He likes to ogle at the pretty girls. 他爱盯着漂亮的女孩子。 4. Don\'t ogle at other girls in front of your girlfriend. It\'ll make her jealous. 在你女朋友的面前最好不要跟别的女人眉来眼去，这样会让她忌妒。', '名词: ogler 过去式: ogled 过去分词: ogled 现在分词: ogling 第三人称单数: ogles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('budge', '[bʌdʒ]', 'v. 移动； 妥协 n. 羔皮 adj. <古>浮夸的； 庄严的', '1. A cell can budge, however, only if it is able to synthesize a cytoskeleton, the network of fibers that gives it structural support. 可是细胞要想移动，它就必须合成细胞骨架，利用这种纤维网络才可支撑其结构。 2. Negotiations with the People\'s Alliance for Democracy have begun, but its leaders say they won\'t budge and will fight to the death. 同人民民主联盟的磋商已经开始，但是民盟领导人表示他们不会妥协，相反，他们会奋战到死。', '过去式: budged 过去分词: budged 现在分词: budging 第三人称单数: budges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('refute', '[rɪ\'fjuːt]', 'vt.驳斥；反驳；驳倒', '1. As for the Flat Earth theory, I believe I could refute it. 至于地平学说，我相信我能驳斥它。 2. Historical facts refute such a fallacy. 历史事实驳斥了这种谎言。 3. He had hardly finished when someone rose to refute his points. 他还没全说完，就有人起来反驳他的论点。 4. Nothing could refute her testimony that the driver was drunk. 她关于那个司机已经喝醉的证词无可辩驳。', '形容词: refutable 副词: refutably 名词: refutability 过去式: refuted 过去分词: refuted 现在分词: refuting 第三人称单数: refutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('soggy', '[\'sɑːɡi]', 'adj.湿而软的；潮湿的；湿透的；乏味的', '1. In the soggy ground his footsteps made the smallest sounds. 他的脚步在潮湿的地上几乎没有声音。 2. It rained last night and the earth was still soggy now. 昨夜下了雨, 现在地面还湿着。 3. The ground was soggy after the heavy rain. 大雨过后, 地面湿透了。 4. Moisten the soil, but do not make it muddy and soggy. 濡湿的土壤,但不泥泞,使其浸湿。', '副词: soggily 比较级: soggier 最高级: soggiest 名词: sogginess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sway', '[sweɪ]', 'v.摇动；摇摆；支配；影响；说服，使相信 n.摇摆；支配；影响', '1. The branches of the trees were swaying in the wind. 树枝在风中摇晃。 2. Smokestacks are known to sway in the wind if they are not rigid enough. 如果烟囱没有足够的刚度；它就会在风中摇摆。 3. Do you sway your hips when you walk ? 你走路时摆动臀部吗? 4. His power sways the world. 他称霸天下。 5. sway of the ferry made him feel sick. 渡船摇摇晃晃,他感到恶心。', '副词: swayingly 名词: swayer 过去式: swayed 过去分词: swayed 现在分词: swaying 第三人称单数: sways');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('otiose', '[\'oʊʃioʊs]', 'adj.没有用的；不必要的；多余的', '1. Because he does not know the skill of fishing, light has fishing rod is otiose. 因为他不懂钓鱼的技巧，光有鱼竿是没有用的。', '副词: otiosely 名词: otiosity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crochet', '[kroʊ\'ʃeɪ]', 'n.钩针编织；钩针织物 v.用钩针编织', '1. She is good at crochet. 她擅长钩针编织。 2. Can you show me some hand crochet article, please? 你能拿些手钩针编织品给我看看吗? 3. We have a very wide selection of hand crochet articles. 我们的手钩针编织品有很大的选择余地。 4. I asked her to crochet a shawl for me. 我请求她给我钩一条围巾。', '过去式: crocheted 过去分词: crocheted 现在分词: crocheting 第三人称单数: crochets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evenhanded', '[\'iːvən\'hændɪd]', 'adj.公平的；公平无私的', '1. Abstruse and evenhanded universe, clinging and firing metagalaxy. 宇宙邃允，银河执火。 2. Become aware quite to this author insufficient evenhanded. 对此笔者颇觉不够公允。 3. Compare abroad, our country starts to the research of evenhanded value later. 相比国外,我国对公允价值的研究起步较晚。 4. How to assure to execute the law judgement evenhanded of the branch? 如何保证执法部门的判断公允？', '副词: evenhandedly 名词: evenhandedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mores', '[\'mɔːreɪz]', 'n.风俗习惯；道德观念', '1. He wrote of the ideas and mores of the time. 他写下了很多当时的社会观点和社会风俗。 2. The mores of that village are hard to believe. 那村子的习俗让人难以置信。 3. Many blame these changes on the decay of traditional mores. 许多人把这些变化归罪与传统道德观念的衰退。 4. Changing social mores have placed stresses on long-term relationships. 不断变化的社会道德观念使人们开始重视长期的婚姻关系。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('navigate', '[\'nævɪɡeɪt]', 'vi.航行；驾驶；操纵 vt.航行；驾驶；横渡；<口>设法穿过，走过，经过', '1. The river became too narrow and shallow to navigate. 河道变得又窄又浅，无法航行。 2. Many captains depend on electronic devices to navigate their ships. 许多船长依靠电子仪器来驾驶他们的船。 3. Hyperlinks make it much easier to navigate through a document. 超链接使到你在文档中更容易的操纵。 4. The large ship could not navigate the river. 那艘大轮船不能在河里航行。', '过去式: navigated 过去分词: navigated 现在分词: navigating 第三人称单数: navigates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extremist', '[ɪk\'striːmɪst]', 'n.极端主义者；过激分子 adj.极端的', '1. The assassin was adjudged an extremist. 那个行刺者被认为是个极端主义分子。 2. When it comes to talking about patriotism, he\'s an extremist. 一谈到爱国主义，他就很偏激。 3. The extremists have formed a splinter group outside the main party. 那些极端主义者在大党外已组成了分裂出来的小派别。 4. He was blacklisted because of his extremist views. 他因观点偏激而被列入黑名单。', '名词: extremism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tatty', '[\'tæti]', 'adj.不整洁的；破烂的；简陋的；廉价艳丽的', '1. You\'d better change out of those tatty old jeans. 你最好改变一下，不穿那些破旧的牛仔裤。 2. There were a lot of guest houses which were very tatty. 那儿有许多简陋的宾馆。', '比较级: tattier 最高级: tattiest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chuck', '[tʃʌk]', 'n.抛掷；卡盘；咯咯声 v.扔；抛掷；撵走；咯咯叫', '1. The product is hand-operated independent chuck,with cylindrical center mount. 该产品是手动的单动卡盘，短圆柱连接型。 2. I\'m going to chuck out this stuff. 我想把这东西扔了。 3. Don\'t chuck pieces of paper about. 别把纸扔得到处都是。 4. I must chuck out all those old magazines. 我必须把所有的旧杂志处理掉。', '过去式: chucked 过去分词: chucked 现在分词: chucking 第三人称单数: chucks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glucose', '[\'ɡluːkoʊs]', 'n.葡萄糖', '1. Glucose has a simple sugar molecule. 葡萄糖含有单糖分子。 2. We injected the glucose into the patient\'s vein. 我们给病人的静脉里注射了葡萄糖。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('livid', '[\'lɪvɪd]', 'adj.铅色的；苍白的；暴怒的', '1. Livid lightning streaked the sky. 乌青色的闪电划破了天空。 2. Her face turned livid with rage. 她气得脸色铁青。 3. The jailor brought up another livid prisoner. 那个狱卒又带来了一个面无人色的犯人。 4. He\'d be livid if he found out what you\'re doing. 要是他知道了你干的事,他准得大发雷霆。', '副词: lividly 名词: lividity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nepotism', '[\'nepətɪzəm]', 'n.裙带关系；任人唯亲', '1. The congressman lashed the president for his nepotism. 国会议员抨击总统搞裙带关系。 2. He was guilty of nepotism and corruption. 他犯了任人唯亲和贪污腐败的罪。', '形容词: nepotistic 名词: nepotist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preface', '[\'prefəs]', 'n. 序文； 绪言； 前言 v.作序，写前言；以…开始', '1. That dictionary has a preface, not a foreword. 那部词典有一篇序文，不是前言。 2. The preface contained an acknowledgment of those who had helped her. 绪言中包含她对那些帮助过她的人的致谢声明。 3. Can you sort me out on how to write this preface? 你能对怎样写这个前言给我提点建议吗？ 4. The preface of this diary recounted her life. 这本日记的前言叙述了她的生活。 5. Several pages of closely reasoned argument preface her account of the war. 她那部关于战争的著述之前有几页论证严谨的序言。', '名词: prefacer 过去式: prefaced 过去分词: prefaced 现在分词: prefacing 第三人称单数: prefaces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aspersion', '[ə\'spɜːʒən]', 'n.洒(尤指洒圣水)；诽谤；中伤', '1. We cast no aspersion on the man or his program.Mr.Obama, in his short career, has not strongly associated himself with any policy idea. 我们无意诽谤这个人或他的计划，然而奥巴马先生在他短暂的职业生涯里，从未对任何政策主张表现过强烈支持的态度。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obloquy', '[\'ɑːbləkwi]', 'n.漫骂；叱骂；毁谤', '1. I have had enough obloquy for one lifetime. 我一辈子受够了诽谤。 2. Few words carry stronger obloquy than slumlord. 甚少有比贫民窟主更具有贬义的词汇了。 3. I resent the obloquy that you are casting upon my reputation. 我怨恨你对我的名誉横加诽谤。 4. The absence of presumptuous self-conceit in Tito made him feel all the more defenseless under prospective obloquy. 蒂托由于缺乏自以为是的傲气，因此在声名扫地的前景之下更加显得束手无策。', '名词复数: obloquies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inimical', '[ɪ\'nɪmɪkl]', 'adj.有害的；不友善的', '1. Lack of ambition is inimical to success. 没有抱负,则难以成功。 2. His policies are inimical to academic freedom. 他的政策不利于学术自由。', '副词: inimically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cougar', '[\'kuːɡər]', 'n.美洲狮；美洲豹；（追求年轻帅哥的）熟女', '1. I saw a cougar slinking toward its prey. 我看到一只美洲狮正在潜随猎物。 2. That man was on the prod and as dangerous as a cornered cougar. 那人大发雷霆，危险得如同一头被困的美洲豹。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transport', '[\'trænspɔːrt]', 'n.运输；心醉 v.运输；传播；流放；激动', '1. The goods have been cased up for transport. 货物已装箱待运。 2. London Transport run extra trains during the rush-hour. 伦敦运输公司在交通高峰时 间增开加班列车。 3. Please find alternative means of transport. 请另外找一个运输方法。 4. The transport of goods by air is very expensive. 空运货物费用十分昂贵。 5. A helicopter was used to transport the wounded. 一架直升飞机被用来运送伤员。', '形容词: transportable 名词: transportability 过去式: transported 过去分词: transported 现在分词: transporting 第三人称单数: transports');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fertilize', '[\'fɜːrtəlaɪz]', 'v.施肥；使肥沃；使丰富；[生]使受精；使受粉', '1. I help my father fertilize the crops. 我帮助父亲给农作物施肥。 2. And farmers can use camel west waste to fertilize their crops. 农民能用骆驼的粪便来给农作物施肥。 3. Fertilizer is a substance put on land to fertilize it. 肥料是施在地里使之肥沃的物质。 4. Reading will fertilize his vocabulary. 阅读会丰富他的词汇。', '形容词: fertilizable 过去式: fertilized 过去分词: fertilized 现在分词: fertilizing 第三人称单数: fertilizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comprehensible', '[ˌkɑːmprɪ\'hensəbl]', 'adj.可理解的；易懂的', '1. It is comprehensible to ordinary minds . 这是普通人都能理解的。 2. It is based on the faith that nature is comprehensible. 这基于一种信仰，那就是自然是可理解的。 3. Our aim is to make the students\' speech comprehensible. 我们的目的是使学生的讲话被人理解。 4. His French was barely comprehensible. 他的法语很难让人明白。', '副词: comprehensibly 名词: comprehensibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overdue', '[ˌoʊvər\'duː]', 'adj.过期的；未兑的；迟到的', '1. Now they are overdue and I shall have to pay a fine. 现在它们过期了,我不得不付罚款。 2. The library called in all overdue books. 图书馆要求把所有逾期未还的书收回。 3. Payment is now four days overdue. 付款期已超过四天了。 4. Your payment is 6 months overdue in total. 贵公司的应付款项总计已过期6个月。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tinge', '[tɪndʒ]', 'n.淡色；些微气味(常与with连用)；一丝痕迹 v.微染', '1. There is a tinge of red in her cheeks. 她双颊红润。 2. There was a faint pink tinge to the sky. 天空略带一点淡淡的粉红色。 3. There was a tinge of sadness in her voice. 她的声音中有几分伤感。 4. I feel touching my face a tinge of warmth from an unseen light. 我感觉迎面拂来一丝不知发自什么光体的暖意。 5. Her hair is tinged with Grey. 她的头发有些花白。', '过去式: tinged 过去分词: tinged 现在分词: tingeing/tinging 第三人称单数: tinges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('regale', '[rɪ\'ɡeɪl]', 'v.盛情招待；尽情吃喝；使快乐 n.款待', '1. They will regale the guests with a feast. 他们将以盛宴款待宾客。 2. We regaled ourselves on caviar and champagne. 我们尽情地享用鱼子酱和香槟酒. 3. She regaled us with an account of her school-days. 她讲她上学时的往事把我们逗得不亦乐乎。 4. New media is in the pace in this regale is more fast. 新媒体在这场盛宴中的步伐更为快速。', '名词: regalement 过去式: regaled 过去分词: regaled 现在分词: regaling 第三人称单数: regales');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elaboration', '[ɪˌlæbə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.详细阐述；精心制作；精致；周密；【报】精编', '1. The decoration has reached an extravagant degree of elaboration. 那装潢已精致到了奢华的地步。 2. This crop circle is an elaboration on the basic pentagram shape with moon shapes protruding from each point of the star. 这个麦田怪圈里有个精致的五角星，每个角上有个突出的月亮。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clairvoyant', '[kleə\'vɔɪənt]', 'adj.千里眼的；透视的；有洞察力的 n.有洞察力的人；千里眼', '1. Those who are clairvoyant have often come to understand past lives. 那些能透视的人们已经常能理解死去的生命。 2. Love is blind, but friendship is clairvoyant. 爱是盲目的，友谊则能洞察一切。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('roe', '[roʊ]', 'n.鱼卵；鱼子；獐鹿', '1. Salmon roe is marketed as analogous to caviar. 鲑鱼卵被作为鱼子酱的类似产品推向市场。 2. We will serve smoked cod\'s roe at the dinner. 宴会上我们将上一道熏鳕鱼子。 3. Such guards also protect against fraying by roe deer. 这种保护措施还可防止獐鹿摩擦损伤。', '名词复数: roe');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acronym', '[\'ækrənɪm]', 'n.首字母缩略词', '1. Could you tell me what this acronym stands for? 您能告诉我这些缩写的大写字母代表什么意思吗? 2. ASDIC is an acronym for antisubmarine detection investigation committee. “ASDIC”是“反潜艇侦查调查委员会”的缩写形式。', '形容词: acronymic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obedient', '[ə\'biːdiənt]', 'adj.服从的；顺从的', '1. I was no longer a sweet obedient little boy. 我不再是一个可爱的顺从的小男孩。 2. She is an obedient girl and always obeys her parents. 她是个顺从的孩子，总是服从父母。', '副词: obediently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abound', '[ə\'baʊnd]', 'v.富于；充满', '1. Most of her poems abound in imagery. 她的诗歌大多数富于形象。 2. The myths and traditions of India abound with references. 印度神话和传统充满了参考价值。 3. A very different world will abound as this comes to be so. 一个非常不同的世界将充满着这一切，当这实现。', '过去式: abounded 过去分词: abounded 现在分词: abounding 第三人称单数: abounds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bane', '[beɪn]', 'n.祸害；祸根', '1. We must beware of the bane that the Tao of sage caused. 我们对圣人之道所带给我们的祸害,一定要小心谨慎以对。 2. University reform had long been his bugbear, and now was his bane. 大学改革早就是使他头痛的事情，如今更成为他的祸害了。 3. Avarice is the bane to happiness. 贪婪是损毁幸福的祸根。 4. Drink was the bane of his life. 酗酒是他一生的祸根。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('persecute', '[\'pɜːrsɪkjuːt]', 'vt.迫害；烦扰；为难', '1. They persecute those who do not conform to their idea. 他们迫害那些不信奉他们思想的人。 2. They came to America after being persecuted for their religious beliefs. 他们是在他们因宗教信仰而受到迫害之后来到美洲的。 3. Once the affair became public, he was persecuted by the press. 事情公开後，他便受到新闻界的纠缠。 4. He persecuted me with various delicate questions. 他用种种微妙的问题把我难倒了。', '形容词: persecutive 名词: persecutee 过去式: persecuted 过去分词: persecuted 现在分词: persecuting 第三人称单数: persecutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foreclose', '[fɔːr\'kloʊz]', 'v.取消抵押品的赎回权；排除', '1. The Bank foreclosed on the mortgage. 银行取消了该抵押品的赎回权。 2. The building society will be forced to foreclose on this mortgage because regular payments have not been made. 住宅互助协会被迫取消这项抵押的赎取权，因为没有交纳定期的付款。 3. They tried to foreclose the possibility of his meeting with the chairman. 他们设法排除他与董事长会面的可能性。', '形容词: foreclosable 过去式: foreclosed 过去分词: foreclosed 现在分词: foreclosing 第三人称单数: forecloses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peel', '[piːl]', 'n.果皮 vt.剥落；削皮 vi.脱皮；脱衣服', '1. She threw the banana peel into the trash can. 她将香蕉皮扔进垃圾筒。 2. It is said that the apple peel contains a lot of vitamins. 据说苹果皮富含维生素。 3. The paper was beginning to peel off the walls. 墙上的纸渐渐脱落了. 4. He likes to peel an apple before he eats it . 吃苹果前，他喜欢削皮。 5. He got sunburn and his skin began to peel. 他被日光灼伤后,皮肤开始脱落。', '过去式: peeled 过去分词: peeled 现在分词: peeling 第三人称单数: peels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brace', '[breɪs]', 'v.防备；支撑；绷紧；振作 n.支柱；支架；牙箍；一对；（复）吊带裤；大括号', '1. It is urgent that we brace against hurricanes. 我们必须做好防飓风的准备。 2. The struts are firmly braced. 那些支柱上得很牢固。 3. She braced herself against the wall. 她靠在墙上。 4. He faced the angry crowd, his arms folded, his legs braced. 面对着愤怒的人群,他抱紧双臂,绷紧双腿。 5. The odor of souls is a brace to the walls. 灵魂的气息是这些砖墙的支柱。', '过去式: braced 过去分词: braced 现在分词: bracing 第三人称单数: braces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obsession', '[əb\'seʃn]', 'n.困扰；沉迷；着魔；妄想', '1. Winning is no longer just a goal;it becomes an obsession. 打赢官司不再仅仅是一个目标，更成为一种无法摆脱的困扰。 2. I was suffering from obsession that my career would be ended. 那时的我陷入了我的事业有可能就此终止的困扰当中。 3. Her obsession with mah-jongg began three months ago. 她对麻将的沉迷是三个月前开始的。 4. \"This isn\'t just a whim of mine, it\'s a magnificent obsession! 跑步并不是我的一时冲动,而是一种疯狂的着迷！', '形容词: obsessional 副词: obsessionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dissonant', '[\'dɪsənənt]', 'adj.不一致的；刺耳的；不和谐的', '1. It will only grow louder and more dissonant. 这样的声音只会更大和更加刺耳。 2. His voice is drowned by the dissonant scream of a siren outside. 她的声音被外面杂乱刺耳的警报声吞没了。 3. Their dissonant harmonies were amazing, too. 他们的不和谐和声演奏也令人惊叹。 4. Death and decay is the result of an inherently dissonant biology. 死亡与腐烂是内在生物体不和谐的结果。', '副词: dissonantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gabble', '[\'ɡæbl]', 'v.急促而不清楚地说；喋喋不休地讲 n.急促讲出而叫人听不清说的话', '1. Don\'t gabble, Lucy, I can\'t understand when you run your words together. 不要说得那么急，露西，你说话象连珠炮似的，我听不懂。 2. She was nervous and started to gabble. 她紧张得话都说不清了。 3. In the end, I couldn\'t bear her gabble any more. 最后，我终于受不了她的罗嗦了。 4. Who is speaking at such a gabble ? 谁在说话说得那么急，叫人听不清楚?', '名词: gabbler 过去式: gabbled 过去分词: gabbled 现在分词: gabbling 第三人称单数: gabbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discord', '[\'dɪskɔːrd]', 'n.不调和；不一致；[音]不谐和 vi.不一致；不协调', '1. What has brought discord into the family? 什么事使得这个家庭不和？ 2. He\'s been a source of discord and worry. 他成为不和和烦恼的根源。 3. Various discords have arisen over this question. 人们在这个问题上发生了不少争执。 4. The discord of his music was hard on the ear. 他演奏的不和谐音很刺耳。 5. The speaker\'s opinion discords with the principles of this society. 演讲者的意见与本会的原则不符。', '过去式: discorded 过去分词: discorded 现在分词: discording 第三人称单数: discords');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('herd', '[hɜːrd]', 'n.兽群；牧人；群 vt.放牧；群集；使 ... 成群，把…赶到一起 vi.聚在一起', '1. A large herd could wreck a train. 庞大的兽群将会使火车失事。 2. The report of the gun will scare the herd. 枪声会惊吓兽群。 3. The herdsman looks after a herd of animals. 牧人放牧着一群牲畜。 4. The Goatherd scolded them for their ingratitude in leaving him, when during the storm he had taken more care of them than of his own herd. 牧人骂他们忘恩负义说他曾经在风雪中对他们照顾得比自己的羊还好。 5. Dogs are often trained to herd sheep. 狗常被训练来放羊。 6. You should not herd with the man as him. 你不应和他那样的人来往。', '过去式: herded 过去分词: herded 现在分词: herding 第三人称单数: herds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lumen', '[\'luːmen]', 'n.内腔；流明(光流的强度单位)', '1. The innermost region of cotton is called lumen. 棉纤维的最内层组织叫内腔。 2. A former luminance unit equals to one lumen per square foot. 旧制光的亮度单位等于每平方英尺流明。', '形容词: lumena 名词复数: lumens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commute', '[kə\'mjuːt]', 'v.通勤；折换；减刑；改变；交换 n.乘车上下班', '1. Mary used to commute five miles from her home in the suburb. 玛丽过去每天从郊区的家里走五英里来上班。 2. They chose to commute equity into license agreements. 他们选择了将股权转换成许可协议。 3. Regular train travellers may commute a single monthly payment for daily tickets. 经常坐火车的人可以按每天的票价折换购买月票。 4. He seemed at times to be asking God to commute these penalties. 有时他好象还恳求上帝减轻惩罚。 5. Her commute to work will be easy. 她上下班交通会很方便。', '过去式: commuted 过去分词: commuted 现在分词: commuting 第三人称单数: commutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gawky', '[\'ɡɔːki]', 'adj.笨拙的 n.笨拙的人', '1. Of a scrawny build;spindly or gawky. 骨瘦如柴的；瘦长的或笨拙的 2. Of a scrawny build; spindly or gawky. 骨瘦如柴的；瘦长的或笨拙的 3. You\'re a naught, gawky, foolish Cinderella. 相反，我讨厌你，你是一个淘气、迟钝而愚蠢的灰姑娘。 4. Mark Cuban\'s best player is still a tall gawky German guy. 马克库班的最好的球员依然是那个迟钝的德国大个儿。', '副词: gawkily 比较级: gawkier 最高级: gawkiest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parturition', '[ˌpɑːrtjʊ\'rɪʃn]', 'n.生产；分娩', '1. She is a well-known parturition hastening midwife. 她是这一带有名的催生婆。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accentuate', '[ək\'sentʃueɪt]', 'v.重读；强调；突出', '1. Accentuate the word “accent”on the first syllable. 在“accent”一词的第一个音节上加重音符号。 2. Mrs Obama\'s speeches rarely accentuate the positive. 奥巴马夫人的演讲很少强调美国积极的一面。 3. The tight jumper only accentuated his fat stomach. 那件紧身套头毛衣反更突出了他那肥胖的肚子。 4. She has beautiful eyes, so we should accentuate them in the makeup. 她眼睛很美丽，我们在化妆时应该突出她的眼睛。', '名词: accentuation 过去式: accentuated 过去分词: accentuated 现在分词: accentuating 第三人称单数: accentuates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('duckling', '[\'dʌklɪŋ]', 'n.小鸭子', '1. The ducklings plumped into the water. 小鸭们突然跳进水中。 2. We\'re going to feed the duckling. 我们去喂小鸭子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('humility', '[hjuː\'mɪləti]', 'n.谦逊；谦虚；谦卑', '1. Humility is the beginning of wisdom. 智慧源于谦逊。 2. Without humility there can be no humanity. 没有谦逊就没有仁爱。 3. Forgiveness is a virtue of humility. 宽恕是一种谦虚的美德。 4. Trading requires practice, humility, and perseverance. 交易需要实践，谦虚，和恒心。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sanctimonious', '[ˌsæŋktɪ\'moʊniəs]', 'adj.伪装虔诚的；道貌岸然的', '1. It\'s that sanctimonious air that people can\'t stand. 人们所不能容忍的就是那副假正经的样子。 2. You do not have to be so sanctimonious to prove that you are devout. 您不必如此伪善 3. Please, spare me any sanctimonious injunctions about her chosen way of life. 请不要故作虚伪的指责她所选择的生活方式。', '副词: sanctimoniously 名词: sanctimoniousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scrub', '[skrʌb]', 'n.用力擦洗；矮树；渺小之物 v.用力擦洗', '1. Give that floor a good hard scrub. 使劲擦洗一下那地板。 2. The country is covered in scrub. 这一地区为矮灌木丛覆盖。 3. We found the animal on a scrub hill. 我们在一个灌木丛生的丘陵上找到这动物。 4. Although she scrubbed the old pot thoroughly, she could not make it look completely clean. 虽然她彻底地用力擦洗那只旧壶，但她无法把它完全洗干净。', '形容词: scrubbable 过去式: scrubbed 过去分词: scrubbed 现在分词: scrubbing 第三人称单数: scrubs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amalgam', '[ə\'mælɡəm]', 'n.汞合金；混合物', '1. The dentist used amalgam to fill my teeth. 牙医用汞合金给我补牙。 2. Silver amalgam is used as a dental filling. 银汞合金被用作牙的填料。 3. Her character is an amalgam of many different traits. 她的个性是许多不同特性的融合。 4. The new religion is an amalgam of supersitious beliefs and modern science. 这种新宗教是迷信和现代科学的混合物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exhaust', '[ɪɡ\'zɔːst]', 'v.使筋疲力尽；耗尽；详尽论述 n.排气装置；废气', '1. Caring for young children can exhaust you physically and mentally. 照顾小孩子会使你身心疲惫。 2. The expedition was forced to turn back when it exhausted its food supply. 没有了食物,这个探险队不得不返航。 3. He failed to exhaust this subject. 他没能对这个题作详尽无遗的论述。 4. The car needs a new exhaust. 这辆车需要换一个新的排气管。', '形容词: exhaustible 副词: exhaustedly 名词: exhauster 过去式: exhausted 过去分词: exhausted 现在分词: exhausting 第三人称单数: exhausts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('opine', '[oʊ\'paɪn]', 'v.认为；想', '1. I opine that it will rain before night. 我想天黑以前要下雨的。 2. I felt my chin drop, my mouth opin in astonishment. 我觉得我的下巴下降，我的惊讶嘴里奥平。 3. In my opine ,it is a shame to deceive your Friends . 我认为，这是一个耻辱，来欺骗你的朋友。 4. Some people opine that Rani Ketki in fact the first Urdu short story. 某些人民opine那Rani Ketki实际上第一Urdu短篇小说。', '过去式: opined 过去分词: opined 现在分词: opining 第三人称单数: opines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('draggy', '[\'drægɪ]', 'adj.拖沓的(呆滞的；无生气的)', '1. When I get depressed I feel really down and draggy. 当我觉得心情郁闷的时候，我真的是感到沮丧。 2. She is forgetful, draggy in doing everything. 她这人就是爱忘事，做什么事情总是拖拖拉拉的. 3. She has a bad memory, everything is done in a draggy way by her. 她这人就是爱忘事，做什么事情总是拖拖拉拉的 4. She always forget things and draggy in doing whatever. 她这人就是爱忘事，做什么事情总是拖拖拉拉的', '比较级: draggier 最高级: draggiest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fetus', '[\'fiːtəs]', 'n.胎；胎儿', '1. The fetus of the diabetic gravida may also have disproportionately large shoulders and body size compared with the head. 糖尿病孕妇的胎儿也可能有与胎头不相称的肩宽或躯体过大。 2. Previously reported cases are briefly reviewed and the differences between teratoma and fetus in fetu are discussed. 于此简略回顾过去的文献，并论述畸胎瘤与胎内胎之区别要点。 3. This is a second trimester fetus and uterus. 图示中期妊娠的胎儿及子宫。 4. Therefore, an unborn fetus is alive, just like us. 因此，胎儿的生命，是和我们一样的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ineffaceable', '[ˌɪnə\'feɪsəbəl]', 'adj.抹不掉的；不能消除的', '1. This is the ineffaceable track of the greatest single avalanche in recorded history. 这是在有文字记载的历史上最大的一次崩落所留下的难以消除的痕迹。', '副词: ineffaceably 名词: ineffaceability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('serviceable', '[\'sɜːrvɪsəbl]', 'adj.可用的；易于服务的；有用的；耐用的', '1. No man can become a serviceable servant solely by obedience to written edicts. 没有人单靠遵守成文的法令，就能成为一个有用的仆人。 2. The coat is made of a serviceable fabric. 这件外套是用一种耐用的织物做的。 3. If it chipped like flint, he could make a serviceable knife out of it. 只要它的质地接近打火石，卡森就有足够的信心将它磨成一把耐用的小刀。', '副词: serviceably 名词: serviceability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('principle', '[\'prɪnsəpl]', 'n.原理；原则；主义；信念', '1. A bicycle and a motorcycle are built on the same principle. 自行车和摩托车是根据同样的原理制造的。 2. Archimedes ,a great physicist ,discovered the principle of floating bodies . 阿基米德，一位伟大的物理学家，发现了浮体原理。 3. We adhere to the principle that everyone should be treated fairly. 我们坚持人人都应该被平等对待这一原则。 4. It is easier to fight for one\'s principle than to live up to them. 为自己的主义斗争，要比他们施诸实践更容易。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intestine', '[ɪn\'testɪn]', 'n.肠 adj.国内的；内部的', '1. The tapeworm is an inhabitant of the intestine. 绦虫是栖居肠内的寄生虫。 2. Vitamin K is not absorbed from the upper intestine. 维生素K不是从肠的上部吸收的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('purblind', '[\'pɜːˌblaɪnd]', 'adj.半盲的；视力不佳的；愚钝的', '1. Sadly, I expect the football authorities will be as purblind. 可叹的是，我估计足球当局也会和我们的大使馆一样愚钝和半盲。 2. Even his most purblind supporters knows this is nonsense. 即使贝卢斯科尼最愚蠢的支持者也知道这是无稽之谈。 3. If an administrator has no access to information,it\'s as if he was purblind and hard of hearing and had a stuffed nose. 做管理工作的人没有信息，就是鼻子不通，耳目不灵。 4. But, at last I began, in a purblind groping way, to read, write, and cipher, on the very smallest scale. 我犹如笨鸟，瞎摸着前进，终于慢慢地读啊，写啊，算啊，掌握了一点小门道。', '副词: purblindly 名词: purblindness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dual', '[\'duːəl]', 'adj.双重的；成双的 n.双数', '1. She has dual nationality. 她有双重国籍。 2. His dual role as a composer and a conductor made him very busy. 他作曲家和指挥家的双重身份使他非常繁忙。 3. The car has dual exhaust pipes. 这车有双排气管。', '副词: dually');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pavid', '[\'pævɪd]', 'adj.害怕的；胆小的', '1. That\'s proved us we are a human being, a generous but also jealous, a brave but also pavid... 而对于pessimist而言，好像any tiny barrier 都是一种challenge. 2. A. pavid L. 红花七叶树 3. Students\'Pavid Psychology in Exercises on Apparatus Lessons and Its Curing Methods 浅析学生在器械体操教学中的害怕心理及防治方法 4. Discussion of resolving the student\'s pavid psychology problem in speed skating teaching 对速度滑冰教学中消除学生畏惧心理问题的探讨', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consummate', '[\'kɑːnsəmeɪt]', 'adj.圆满的；完美的；完全的 vt.完成；使达到极点；圆房', '1. Her happiness was consummate when her father took her to Paris. 她父亲带她去巴黎，她的幸福达至极点。 2. She is a consummate artist. 她是个技艺高超的艺术家。 3. She dealt with the problem with consummate skill. 她以巧妙的手腕处理了这个问题。 4. He won the race with consummate ease. 他不费吹灰之力就赢了赛跑。 5. His ambition was consummated when he received his doctor\'s degree from Cambridge. 当他从剑桥大学获得了博士学位时，他的抱负实现了。', '形容词: consummative 副词: consummately 名词: consummator 过去式: consummated 过去分词: consummated 现在分词: consummating 第三人称单数: consummates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('original', '[ə\'rɪdʒənl]', 'adj.原始的；最初的；有独创性的；原版的 n.原版；真品；怪人；有独创性的人 n.起源', '1. Our original plan was to go to Spain, but it was too expensive. 我们的原始计划是去西班牙,但是去那里太贵了。 2. I prefer your original plan to these. 我认为你最初的计划比这些都要好。 3. His designs are highly original. 他的设计独树一帜。 4. This is the original painting, and the others are copies. 这画是原作,其他的是复制品。 5. The Greek translation is faithful to the Hebrew original. 希腊语翻译很忠实于希伯来原文。 6. Fujian Province is the original and major production region of jasmine tea. 福建省是茉莉花茶的起源地和主产区。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hedonism', '[\'hiːdənɪzəm]', 'n.快乐论；快乐主义；享乐主义', '1. But his eudemonism was not epicurean hedonism, because eudemonia was an activity. 但他的幸福观不是享乐主义的快乐论,因为幸福是“实现活动”。 2. There was room, it was felt, for both idealism and hedonism. 他们感到人要有点理想主义和乐天主义。 3. Hedonism is the theory that pleasure is the only thing intrinsically good, pain the only thing intrinsically bad. 享乐主义认为快乐是唯一的本质上的好事，而痛苦则是唯一的本质上的坏事。 4. I am not hedonism, but I have liked the life which enjoys. 我不是享乐主义，可我喜欢过享受的生活。', '形容词: hedonistic 副词: hedonistically 名词: hedonist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('explicate', '[\'eksplɪkeɪt]', 'v.详细解说；阐述', '1. How can we best explicate \'King Lear\' and understand it? 我们怎样才能最详尽地分析并理解《李尔王》呢? 2. Please explicate more on the questions, as they are important. 请阐述更多的问题，因为他们是很重要的。', '名词: explication 过去式: explicated 过去分词: explicated 现在分词: explicating 第三人称单数: explicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('denigrate', '[\'denɪɡreɪt]', 'v.诋毁；贬低；诬蔑', '1. We must be fair competitors and must never denigrate other firms. 我们必须公平竞争 2. I didn\'t intend to denigrate her achievements. 我不是想贬低她的成绩。', '名词: denigration 过去式: denigrated 过去分词: denigrated 现在分词: denigrating 第三人称单数: denigrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overlook', '[ˌoʊvər\'lʊk]', 'v.俯瞰；远眺；没注意到；忽视 n.忽视；远眺', '1. My room overlooked the garden. 我的房间俯瞰花园。 2. We overlook the church from our house. 我们可从家中俯瞰教堂。 3. My room overlooks the sea. 从我的房间可眺望大海。 4. He overlooked a spelling error on the first page. 他没有看出第一页中有个拼写错误。 5. It was a slight overlook on my part. 这是我的小疏忽。', '过去式: overlooked 过去分词: overlooked 现在分词: overlooking 第三人称单数: overlooks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plagiarism', '[\'pleɪdʒərɪzəm]', 'n.剽窃；剽窃物', '1. Evidence of plagiarism has been found in his latest book. 他最近的一本书中被查出有剽窃的痕迹。 2. Punishments for plagiarism differ in schools. 每个学校剽窃的惩罚是不同的。 3. The content of his book is no more than plagiarism. 他这本书的内容完全是抄袭他人的观点。 4. Plagiarism is a form of intellectual dishonesty. 抄袭是智力欺诈的一种形式。', '形容词: plagiaristic 名词: plagiarist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('troll', '[troʊl]', 'v.反复；轮唱(歌曲)；用曳绳钓；搜索；滚动 n.钓绳；钓饵 n.巨人；巨怪', '1. The game engine will evaluate the script and link this behavior to the cowardly troll. 游戏引擎将会计算这个脚本并把这个行为和胆怯的巨人相关联。 2. With the key, you can free the imprisoned troll, who will then free the passageway for you as a reward. 用这把钥匙可以释放被囚禁的巨人们，它们作为回报会帮你清除通道。 3. These were evidently a different type of troll than the mountain variety, since they seemed considerably more intelligent and less smelly. 这些巨怪和山怪有明显的不同，因为他们似乎更聪明而且没有那么浓的臭味。', '名词: troller 过去式: trolled 过去分词: trolled 现在分词: trolling 第三人称单数: trolls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gutless', '[\'ɡʌtləs]', 'adj.没有勇气的；懦怯的；不重要的', '1. Little Girl： Hah! You\'re just a gutless fatso! 小女孩：哈，你只是个没有胆子的胖子！ 2. Are You Too Busy? Or Just Gutless? 你太忙?亦或只是没有勇气? 3. Twenty-seven gutless years, your highness. 虚度二十七载，殿下。 4. Kate: Isn\'t that kind of gutless. 凯特：你真没勇气。', '名词: gutlessness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sapphire', '[\'sæfaɪər]', 'n.蓝宝石；深蓝色 adj.蓝宝石的；深蓝色的', '1. She had the sapphire set in a gold ring. 她把那枚蓝宝石镶在金戒指上了。 2. A first time brooder, a Sapphire Gold xback. 第一次生产的蓝宝石紫蓝底过背。 3. The sapphire is next in hardness to the diamond. 蓝宝石的硬度仅次于钻石。 4. Conclusion Alkali elements have the positive effect on the crystal of sapphire. 结论碱金属元素对山东蓝宝石的结晶有积极的推动作用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swindle', '[\'swɪndl]', 'v.诈骗；骗取 n.诈取；骗局', '1. He tried to swindle the insurance company. 他企图诈骗保险公司。 2. Honest merchants do not swindle their customers. 诚实的商人不欺骗他们的顾客。 3. The gang swindle the bank out of $1.5m. 该团伙骗走银行150万美元。 4. I got bitten in a mail order swindle. 我在一次邮购诈欺中受骗了。', '名词: swindler 过去式: swindled 过去分词: swindled 现在分词: swindling 第三人称单数: swindles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('latch', '[lætʃ]', 'n.门闩；碰锁；弹簧锁 v.上闩；缠着；明白', '1. Please leave the door latch shut. 请把门闩上。 2. The sound of the latch roused him. 门闩的声音惊醒了他。 3. Position the latch on the hood inner panel. 把锁闩定位在引擎罩内板上。 4. This door won\'t latch properly. 这门闩不牢。', '过去式: latched 过去分词: latched 现在分词: latching 第三人称单数: latches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('naysayer', '[\'neɪˌseɪə]', 'n.否定者；怀疑主义者', '1. Because it\'s so easy to be branded a naysayer, Ms. 乐观主义者认为用很少的资源也可以成就大事； 2. Don\'t take counsel of your fears or naysayer. 勿向恐惧与反对者低头。 3. FAST PAYER! GREAT EBAYER! NOT A NAYSAYER! WOULD VOTE FOR IF RUNNING FOR MAYOR! 信用指数经双方同意撤回：买卖双方皆同意撤回此次交易的信用评价。进一步了解。2007-11-25 4. They will naysay any policy that includes the use of nuclear weapons. 他们将反对任何涉及到使用核武器的政策', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('achromatic', '[ˌækrə\'mætɪk]', 'adj.无色的；[生]非染色质的；[音]自然音阶的', '1. To rid of color; render achromatic. 使无色；使成非彩色 2. Who said achromatic colour autumn and winter.... 首页>>风景名胜>>谁说秋冬无色。。。。。 3. Design of Three-in-one Composite Achromatic Compensator[J]. 引用该论文 许言强;宋连科;郑春红. 4. Achromatic analysis of the two-in-one composite 1/4 wave-plate[J]. 引用该论文 薛冬;李国华;郝殿中;王伟.', '副词: achromatically 名词: achromatism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perspective', '[pər\'spektɪv]', 'n.远景；看法；透视 adj.透视的', '1. A fine perspective opened out before us. 一幅美丽的远景展开在我们眼前。 2. Do you agree with this perspective? 你同意这个看法吗? 3. The painting provides us with one of the earliest examples of the use of perspective. 那幅画给我们提供了采用透视画法的最早的范例。 4. The first row of each perspective shows its name. 每个透视的第一行都显示该透视的名称。', '形容词: perspectival 副词: perspectively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inter', '[ɪn\'tɜːr]', 'vt.埋葬', '1. They interred their dear comrade in the arms. 他们埋葬了他们亲爱的战友。 2. The man who died in that accident has been interred. 在那次事故中死的那个人已经被埋葬了。', '过去式: interred 过去分词: interred 现在分词: interring 第三人称单数: inters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pacify', '[\'pæsɪfaɪ]', 'v.使 ... 平静；抚慰；安慰', '1. She knew that he had become delirious, and tried to pacify him. 她知道他已经神志昏迷起来了，极力想使他镇静下来。 2. He tried to pacify the protesters with promise of reform. 他试图以改革的承诺安抚抗议者。 3. I bought an ice cream to pacify my crying daughter. 我买了个冰淇淋来抚慰哭泣的女儿。', '形容词: pacifiable 过去式: pacified 过去分词: pacified 现在分词: pacifying 第三人称单数: pacifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beguile', '[bɪ\'ɡaɪl]', 'v.诱骗；使陶醉；哄；消磨', '1. The travelers were beguiled by the beauty of the landscapes. 游客们被景色的美丽所陶醉。 2. He beguiled me into lending him my bicycle. 他骗我把自行车借给了他。', '副词: beguilingly 名词: beguilement 过去式: beguiled 过去分词: beguiled 现在分词: beguiling 第三人称单数: beguiles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fruition', '[fru\'ɪʃn]', 'n.取得成果；成就；实现；完成', '1. Our efforts have come to fruition. 我们的努力有了成果。 2. Success is the fruition of his years of work. 成功是他多年工作的成果。 3. His extravagant ideas were never brought to fruition. 他不切实际的想法永远没有实现。 4. The plan should come to fruition in another year. 该计划再过一年便可完成。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frequent', '[\'friːkwənt]', 'adj.频繁的；经常的 vt.常到；常去', '1. My girlfriend writes frequent letters to me. 我的女朋友频繁地给我写信。 2. Traffic accidents are alarmingly frequent of late. 近来交通事故频繁得吓人。 3. He is a frequent visitor to our house. 他是我们家的常客。 4. He suffers from frequent bouts of depression. 他患多发性抑郁症。 5. He used to frequent the town\'s bars and night-clubs. 他从前常去镇上的酒吧和夜总会。', '名词: frequentation 过去式: frequented 过去分词: frequented 现在分词: frequenting 第三人称单数: frequents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('justifiable', '[\'dʒʌstɪfaɪəbl]', 'adj.可辩解的；可证明为正当的；有理的', '1. That is not a justifiable act of war. 这是不能够辩解的战争行为。 2. Whether mercy killing is justifiable is still an open question. 安乐死是否正当仍然是一个有争论的问题。 3. What he has done is hardly justifiable. 他的所作所为说不过去。', '副词: justifiably 名词: justifiability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mock', '[mɑːk]', 'v.嘲弄；嘲笑；模仿 n.嘲笑；模仿；戏弄 adj.假的；伪装的；模拟的', '1. He went to church only to mock. 他到教堂去只是为了嘲弄宗教。 2. We should not mock at other people\'s religious beliefs. 我们不应该嘲笑别人的宗教信仰。 3. I have a pet monkey which attempts to mock all my actions. 我养了一只猴子当宠物，它试图模仿我所有的动作。 4. His bully make a mock of all the fine thing he say about kindness to others. 他那恃强欺弱的行为对于他所说的待人友善的漂亮言词是一个嘲弄。 5. She handed him the envelope with mock solemnity. 她装出一副郑重其事的样子，把信封交给他。', '副词: mockingly 名词: mocker 过去式: mocked 过去分词: mocked 现在分词: mocking 第三人称单数: mocks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('audacious', '[ɔː\'deɪʃəs]', 'adj.无畏的；放肆的；大胆创新的', '1. I admire those audacious warriors from childhood. 我从小敬慕那些无畏的战士。', '副词: audaciously 名词: audaciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('circular', '[\'sɜːrkjələr]', 'adj.圆形的；循环的 n.传单；通报', '1. We can compute the circular area with radius. 我们能用半径计算出圆的面积。 2. The full moon has a circular form. 满月呈圆形。 3. Why the wedding ring is circular? 为什么结婚戒指是圆形的? 4. As long as no key is pressed, the scanning goes around in a circular manner. 只要没有按下键，扫描就循环地进行。 5. Have you seen that circular from the new furniture centre? 你见到那家本地新开的家俱总汇的广告了吗？', '副词: circularly 名词: circularity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('partisan', '[\'pɑːrtəzn]', 'adj.偏袒的；党派性的 n.强烈支持者；党羽；游击队员', '1. You must listen to both points of view and try not to be partisan. 你必须兼听双方观点 2. The other obstacle is partisan bickering. 另一个障碍是党派间的纷争。 3. He is a staunch partisan of the Republican Party. 他是共和党的坚定支持者。 4. Partisan politics is often an obstruction to good government. 党羽的政治阴谋常是良好政府的阻碍。', '名词: partisanship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abrade', '[ə\'breɪd]', 'v.擦伤；磨损', '1. The cook is trying to abrade carrote into threads. 厨师正在把胡萝卜磨成细丝。', '过去式: abraded 过去分词: abraded 现在分词: abrading 第三人称单数: abrades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shield', '[ʃiːld]', 'n.盾；盾状物；防卫物 vt.保护；庇护', '1. The shield protected him from the blows of his enemy. 这盾牌保护他免受敌人的打击。 2. There is a shield in the badge of PLA men. 解放军的徽章上有着盾状物。 3. He must pile more sand on top as a shield. 他必须在顶上多加些沙土作为防御物。 4. Motorcyclists must wear helmets to shield them from injury. 摩托车手必须戴头盔保护自己免受伤害。', '名词: shielder 过去式: shielded 过去分词: shielded 现在分词: shielding 第三人称单数: shields');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('placid', '[\'plæsɪd]', 'adj.平静的；宁静的；温和的', '1. For the next two months, life in the village went its placid way. 接下来的两个月，村中的生活一如既往的平静。 2. Her idea of love was more that of placid affection, serving the loved one softly in an atmosphere, flower-scented and dim-lighted, of ethereal calm. 她把爱情看得更像是平静的温情，在一个花香馥郁、光影迷离、虚无缥缈、万籁俱寂的氛围里，被拿来温柔地献给心爱的人。 3. I enjoy the placid pace of village life. 我喜欢宁静的乡村生活。 4. The heavens were placid, but still luminous with the light at the retreating sun. 天空一片宁静，夕阳染得天际色彩斑斓。', '副词: placidly 名词: placidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('landfill', '[\'lændfɪl]', 'n.垃圾填埋地；垃圾填埋法 vt.在垃圾填埋地上处理', '1. The settlement of MSW landfill is a principal Geotechnical Engineering problem of sanitary landfilling. 生活垃圾卫生填埋场的沉降是目前卫生填埋法所涉及的主要的岩土工程问题之一。', '过去式: landfilled 过去分词: landfilled 现在分词: landfilling 第三人称单数: landfills');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('provincial', '[prə\'vɪnʃl]', 'adj.省的；地方的；偏狭的 n.乡下人；地方人民', '1. His articles are published on the provincial newspaper. 他的文章在省报上发表了。 2. claim membership 3. The man displayed provincial attitudes towards the theatre. 这个人显示出对戏剧界的守旧态度。 4. Whenever I go to London I feel like a provincial. 我一去伦敦，就总是觉得自己像个乡巴佬。', '副词: provincially 名词: provincialism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arrogate', '[\'ærəɡeɪt]', 'v.冒称；霸占；擅自', '1. Don\'t arrogate wrong intentions to your colleagues. 不要硬说你同事们动机不良。 2. Do not arrogate wrong intentions to your friends. 不要硬说你的朋友存心不良。 3. Don\'t arrogate evil motives to me. 不要栽脏给我。 4. Don\'t easily arrogate evil motives to others. 别轻易地认为他人存心不良。', '形容词: arrogative 名词: arrogation 过去式: arrogated 过去分词: arrogated 现在分词: arrogating 第三人称单数: arrogates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stutter', '[\'stʌtər]', 'v.口吃；结巴着说话 n.口吃；说话结巴', '1. Those who stutter often receive speech therapy. 那些口吃者经常接受语言治疗。 2. I always stutter on my words when I get nervous. 当我感到紧张时，我说话总是结巴。 3. He speaks with a slight stutter. 他说话有点口吃。 4. The moment he relaxes his concentration,he will lapse into a stutter. 他思想一不集中，就结结巴巴起来。', '副词: stutteringly 名词: stutterer 过去式: stuttered 过去分词: stuttered 现在分词: stuttering 第三人称单数: stutters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('industrious', '[ɪn\'dʌstriəs]', 'adj.勤劳的；勤奋的', '1. I knew that he was an industrious man. 我知道他是一个勤劳的人。 2. The Chinese are industrious people. 中国人民是一个勤劳的民族。 3. The Chinese are an industrious people. 中国人是个勤奋的民族。 4. And others of them have said that he was an industrious plodder rather than an original thinker. 还有人说斯宾塞是个勤奋的实干家而不是独创性的思想家。', '副词: industriously 名词: industriousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scalding', '[\'skɔːldɪŋ]', 'adj.滚烫的；尖刻的；严厉的 动词scald的现在分词形式.', '1. Scalding tears poured down her face. 滚烫的泪水从她脸上扑簌簌地流下来。 2. Scalding molten steel is in the crude iron ladle. 钢包里是滚烫的钢水。', '副词: scaldingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('genial', '[\'dʒiːniəl]', 'adj.友好的；(气候)温暖的', '1. Her genial smile made every guest feel at home. 她亲切的笑容使每个人都感觉宾至如归。 2. The man was so genial that I was drawn to him at once. 他这么和蔼，我立刻为他着迷。 3. The Nankun Mountain with a genial climate is an ideal holiday resort. 气候宜人的南昆山是一处度假胜地。 4. The genial warmth of the sun around the door appeared somewhat human. 门周围温暖柔和的阳光仿佛人一样温情脉脉。', '副词: genially 名词: geniality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cavity', '[\'kævəti]', 'n.洞；空穴；腔；蛀洞', '1. I have a toothache because there is a cavity in one of my teeth. 我牙疼，因为我的一颗牙齿上有个洞。 2. He jammed the material in until the cavity was full. 他用力把材料塞进去，直到空穴完全填满。 3. The peritoneal cavity is a closed sac. 腹膜腔是一个封闭的囊腔。 4. The tumor growing in the enteric cavity blocked excretion of food. 肿瘤在肠腔里生长阻碍了食物排泄。', '名词复数: cavities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loophole', '[\'luːphoʊl]', 'n.枪眼；小窗；换气孔；漏洞 vt.钻空子；开孔', '1. Another had been shot at a loophole in the very act of firing into the house, and now lay in agony, the pistol still smoking in his hand. 另一个海盗企图在枪眼向屋里射击时，自己中弹倒在了地上，此刻正痛苦地躺在那里，手中的枪还在冒烟。 2. If the mutineers succeeded in crossing the stockade, he argued, they would take possession of any unprotected loophole, and shoot us down like rats in our own stronghold. 他说，如果叛乱分子越过了栅栏，他们会占据任何无人守卫的枪眼，然后像打耗子一样将我们全都射死在我们自己的堡垒里。 3. A good lawyer can always find a loophole. 精明的律师总能找到漏洞。 4. The tax-free gift to the spouse is a perfectly legal loophole. 赠与配偶的礼物是免税的，这是一个天衣无缝的法律漏洞。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('filial', '[\'fɪliəl]', 'adj.子女的；孝顺的', '1. She had done her filial respect to her mother. 她已经对母亲尽了孝心。 2. What Confucius says parents cares most is filial health. 孔子说父母最关心的是子女的健康。 3. The law cannot legislate filial responsibility any more than it can legislate love. 法律不能立法爱，更不能立法子女的义务。 4. She is extremely filial towards her parents . 她对父母十分孝顺。', '副词: filially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solvent', '[\'sɑːlvənt]', 'n.溶剂；解决者 adj.有偿付能力的；有溶解力的', '1. Water is a very good solvent for ionic species. 水对各种离子是非常好的溶剂。 2. Smoke is almost as great a solvent as divorce. 吸烟和离婚已变成两大消溶剂。 3. A bankrupt company is not solvent. 一个破产的公司是没有偿还债务的能力的。 4. They need the money to stay solvent. 他们需要这笔钱来保持偿付能力。', '名词: solvency');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('opulent', '[\'ɑːpjələnt]', 'adj.富裕的；充足的', '1. An opulent priest is a contradiction. 教士养尊处优，就是离经叛道。 2. David was easy, and even opulent in his circumstances. 戴维的家境不差，甚至相当富裕。 3. The opulent clothing is decorated with jewelry over her body. 她衣着华丽 4. She is depicted in a room within an opulent palace. 她被描绘成住在一座豪华宫殿的房间中。', '副词: opulently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('otter', '[\'ɑːtər]', 'n.水獭；水獭皮', '1. Otter is a fur-covered, fish-eating aquatic animal. 水獭是全身长毛、以鱼为食的水生动物。 2. My jacket is made of otter skins. 我的皮夹克是用水獭皮做的。', '名词复数: otter');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('menthol', '[\'menθɔːl]', 'n.薄荷脑', '1. The sodium alginate and gelatin were used as shell-material and menthol as core-material. 研究了凝聚法制备薄荷脑微胶囊的工艺过程和方法。 2. The cigarette range includes the Magnum, Supreme, Classic, Mild, Lights, Magnum Lights, Slims, Ultra lights, Menthol, Menthol Lights, One and Gold. 卷烟范围包括玛格南，最高法院，经典，温和，灯光，玛格南灯，细长，超灯，薄荷醇，薄荷脑灯，一个和黄金。', '形容词: mentholated');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bludgeon', '[\'blʌdʒən]', 'v.用大头棒打；强迫 n.大头棒；棍棒', '1. He had been bludgeoned to death. 他被大头短棒连击致死。 2. They tried to bludgeon me into telling them,but I refused. 他们尽力迫使我告诉他们', '名词: bludgeoner 过去式: bludgeoned 过去分词: bludgeoned 现在分词: bludgeoning 第三人称单数: bludgeons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monocle', '[\'mɑːnəkl]', 'n.单片眼镜', '1. The old lady could not read clearly without her monocle. 这位婆婆若不戴上她的单片眼镜，便无法阅读。', '形容词: monocled');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frivolous', '[\'frɪvələs]', 'adj.轻佻的；妄动的；琐碎的；无足轻重的', '1. She had a reputation of being a frivolous coquette. 大家都说她是一个轻佻的荡妇。 2. Some of Mr Obama\'s friends spook business.Whereas Mr McCain supports curbs on frivolous lawsuits, trial lawyers back Mr Obama with open wallets. 奥巴马的朋友们在起诉公司，而麦凯恩却支持限制琐碎的诉讼，而诉讼律师们敞开了口袋支持奥巴马。 3. Don\'t waste your time on frivolous matters. 别把时间浪费在无足轻重的事情上。', '副词: frivolously 名词: frivolousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sullen', '[\'sʌlən]', 'adj.愠怒的；闷闷不乐的；阴沉的', '1. The sullen child refused to answer my questions. 那愠怒的孩子拒绝回答我的问题。 2. She had not come to him today with this feeling of sullen antagonism. 她今天并没有带着这种愠怒的抵触情绪到他这儿来。 3. A sullen look shaded his face. 闷闷不乐的表情使他的脸蒙上阴影。 4. This sullen weather disagrees with me. 遇上这种阴沉的天气我就感到不舒服。', '副词: sullenly 比较级: sullener 最高级: sullenest 名词: sullenness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('outfox', '[ˌaʊt\'fɑːks]', 'vt.以机智胜过', '1. He always outfoxes his opponents at chess. 他下国际象棋总是胜人一筹。', '过去式: outfoxed 过去分词: outfoxed 现在分词: outfoxing 第三人称单数: outfoxes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('declaim', '[dɪ\'kleɪm]', 'v.高谈阔论；雄辩；大声说', '1. A preacher stood declaiming in the town centre. 传教士站在市镇中心慷慨陈词。 2. It is not a sign of humility to declaim against pride. 用慷慨激昂的言语攻击傲慢并不是谦逊的标志。 3. She wrote a book declaiming against our corrupt society. 她写了一本书抨击我们这腐败的社会。', '名词: declaimer 过去式: declaimed 过去分词: declaimed 现在分词: declaiming 第三人称单数: declaims');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anhydrous', '[æn\'haɪdrəs]', 'adj.无水的', '1. Anhydrous nitric acid is dissociated. 无水硝酸是电离的。 2. Pengshan Anhydrous Sodium Sulfate Plant. 安徽全力集团有限公司彭山元明粉厂。 3. Citric acid anhydrous powdered p. A. 无水柠檬酸。 4. Spec:Dihydrate and anhydrous standards. 规格：二水和无水两个品种。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insularity', '[ˌɪnsju\'lærəti]', 'n.岛国性质；（思想观念的）偏狭', '1. It was a typical case of British chauvinism and insularity. 这是典型的英国沙文主义和偏狭心理的事例。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hardihood', '[\'hɑːdɪˌhʊd]', 'n.大胆；鲁莽', '1. Jack have the hardihood to deny what he have do. 杰克厚颜地否认了自己所干的事。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('responsiveness', '[rɪ\'spɒnsɪvnəs]', 'n.响应性；反应性', '1. Lock coarsening may entail a trade-off between performance and responsiveness. 锁粗化可能要在性能和响应性之间进行平衡。 2. He constantly sought to maintain control over the company to ensure its flexibility and responsiveness. 他一直在想保持对这个公司的控制，以保持弹性和快速响应性。 3. It is suggested that exposure to cotton dust may increase airway responsiveness in new workers. 结论棉尘职业暴露可引起新工人气道反应性的增高。 4. Reduced antiplatelet drug responsiveness, including resistance to currently used oral antiplatelet agents, has been suggested to play a role in these worse outcomes. 降低抗血小板药物反应性已被认为在这些更糟的结果的出现中起到了推波助澜的作用，其中就包括对目前常用口服抗血小板剂的抵制。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agony', '[\'æɡəni]', 'n.极度的痛苦；挣扎', '1. It was great agony to watch him passing away. 看着他死去是极大的痛苦。 2. The agony of that moment was terrific. 那一刹那的痛苦是可怕的。 3. He was in an agony of remorse. 他处于悔恨的海洋中。 4. Rescue the jobber girl who struggles in agony. 救救痛苦中挣扎的打工妹。', '名词复数: agonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aquatic', '[ə\'kwætɪk]', 'adj.水生的；水中的；水上的 n.水生动物；水草', '1. Many land animals evolved from aquatic creatures. 许多陆地动物是从水生生物演化而来的。 2. Aquatic food chains are different from terrestrial ones. 水生食物链不同于陆地食物链。 3. The oil leakage from the cargo ship caused severe aquatic pollution. 货船的漏油造成严重的海域污染。 4. Swimming and water skiing are both aquatic sports. 游泳和滑水都是两项水上运动。 5. Everybody knew that the aquarium is the raising aquatic animal\'s place. 大家知道水族馆是饲养水生动物的地方。', '副词: aquatically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('epicurean', '[ˌepɪkjʊ\'riːən]', 'adj.好享乐的；享乐主义的 n.美食主义者；享乐主义者', '1. I\'m not an epicurean, but I do enjoy gourmet meals. 我不是美食主义者，但我确实喜欢美食大餐。 2. I used to be simply an epicurean squandering life under the eyes of Death. 我不过是一个生活在死亡面前的享乐主义者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dilapidated', '[dɪ\'læpɪdeɪtɪd]', 'adj.破旧的；荒废的；快要倒塌的 动词dilapidate的过去式和过去分词.', '1. The house is very dilapidated but it has possibilities. 这房子已破旧不堪，但还有可利用的价值。 2. A dilapidated house stands disconsolately amid the rubbles. 一栋破旧的房子凄凉地耸立在断垣残壁中。 3. The dilapidated barn detracts charm from the landscape. 荒废失修的谷仓有损景色的美。 4. The building wore a dilapidated look. 这建筑看起来要倒塌了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scads', '[skædz]', 'n.大量；巨额 名词scad的复数形式.', '1. Over the years, your brain has scored up scads of patterns, information that tells you that if one thing happens, something else is likely to follow. 多年以来，你的大脑已经获得了大量模式，信息，告诉你如果发生了某件事情，接下来就会发生什么。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tauten', '[\'tɔːtn]', 'v.拉紧', '1. When I grin, the stitches tauten. 当我咧嘴而笑，针脚便会绷紧。 2. She had cosmetic surgery to tauten her drooping breasts. 她动美容外科手术，使下垂的乳房坚挺起来。 3. A type of lacquer formerly used to protect,waterproof,and tauten the cloth surfaces of airplane wings. 漆涂料从前用来保护飞机翼布防水并使其绷紧的涂料 4. A type of lacquer formerly used to protect, waterproof, and tauten the cloth surfaces of airplane wings. 漆涂料从前用来保护飞机翼布防水并使其绷紧的涂料', '过去式: tautened 过去分词: tautened 现在分词: tautening 第三人称单数: tautens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pinch', '[pɪntʃ]', 'n.捏；少量；一撮；困苦；<俚>偷窃 v.掐；夹痛；使困苦；<俚>偷窃；逮捕', '1. She gave him a painful pinch. 她捏得他很痛。 2. He put a pinch of salt on his food. 他在自己的食物上撒了一撮盐。 3. Even the town council is now feeling the pinch. 连市政府目前都感到经费困难。 4. He decided to pinch back the buds on the plant. 他决定将植物上的芽掐掉。', '过去式: pinched 过去分词: pinched 现在分词: pinching 第三人称单数: pinches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pancreas', '[\'pæŋkriəs]', 'n.胰脏', '1. I didn\'t even know what a pancreas was. 我当时甚至不知道胰脏究竟是什么。 2. Metastasis of renal cell carcinoma to the pancreas is uncommon. 摘要肾细胞癌很少转移到胰脏。', '形容词: pancreatic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incompatible', '[ˌɪnkəm\'pætəbl]', 'adj.不相容的；不能并存的；矛盾的', '1. Those two blood groups are incompatible. 那两种血型是不相容的。 2. Therefore, Kant\'s philosophy is incompatible with ecofeminism. 因此，康德哲学与生态女性主义是不相容的。 3. These people think that communism and the Three People\'s Principles are incompatible. 他们以为共产主义和三民主义是不能并存的。 4. That is not incompatible with humility. 而这与谦卑是不矛盾的。', '副词: incompatibly 名词: incompatibleness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imbecile', '[\'ɪmbəsl]', 'n.心智能力极低的人 adj.愚蠢的；傻的', '1. Forrest Gump is an IQ of only 75 imbecile. 阿甘是个智商只有75的低能儿。 2. He was an imbecile to sign a contract with them. 他跟他们签合同,真是愚不可及。 3. If I was once to sit down under it, I should become imbecile. 我要是忍受这事，不成为一个傻瓜才怪呢！ 4. Did you ever see anything so imbecile as her mother? 像她母亲那样无用的人,你说少见不少见?', '副词: imbecilely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jibe', '[dʒaɪb]', 'v.嘲笑；嘲弄；<口>符合；相一致；（使）改变方向；（使）从一舷转至另一舷', '1. She jibed his folly. 她嘲笑他的愚行。 2. Your statement doesn\'t jibe with the facts. 你的说法与事实不符。 3. Her story didn\'t jibe with the witnesses\' account. 她的说法和证人的描述有出入。 4. His words do not jibe with his actions 他说的和做的不一致(言行不一)。', '过去式: jibed 过去分词: jibed 现在分词: jibing 第三人称单数: jibes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('palate', '[\'pælət]', 'n.上颚；味觉；口味', '1. There is something wrong with my palate. 我的上颚有些不适。 2. I have a good palate for fine wine. 我善于品尝好酒。 3. The fat meat soon disgusted the palate. 大肥肉很快让人吃腻。 4. Spicy food suits my palate best. 辛辣的食物最合我的口味了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irreconcilable', '[ɪ\'rekənsaɪləbl]', 'adj.不能和解的；不能协调的；矛盾的', '1. The separated couple was irreconcilable. 那对分居的夫妻不可能和解。 2. This is an irreconcilable conflict. 这是一个不可调和的矛盾。 3. We can never agree our views are irreconcilable. 我们永远不能一致--彼此的看法无法调和。 4. Good and evil are irreconcilable. 善与恶不可调和。', '副词: irreconcilably 名词: irreconcilability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pest', '[pest]', 'n.害虫；讨厌的人', '1. Stores of grain are frequently attacked by pests. 储存的谷物经常受到害虫的破坏。 2. It won\'t be long before we can be rid of the pest altogether. 不要太久，我们就能把这种害虫消除干净。 3. That child is being a real pest. 那个孩子真讨厌。 4. My little brother is a pest when he spoils my games. 我的小弟弟破坏我的各种游戏真讨厌。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prim', '[prɪm]', 'adj.规规矩矩的；古板的；拘谨的；庄重的 v.（使）一本正经；使整洁', '1. He is prim and precise in manner. 他的态度一本正经而严谨。 2. She\'s too prim to enjoy rude jokes! 她太古板,不喜欢听粗野的笑话！ 3. You can\'t tell her that joke---she\'s much too prim and proper. 你可别跟她讲那个笑话；她这个人古板正经得要命。 4. Even Mr. Fleagle stopped two or three times to hold back a small prim smile. 就连弗利格尔先生也停顿了两三次好抑制他那一丝拘谨的微笑。', '副词: primly 比较级: primmer 最高级: primmest 名词: primness 过去式: primmed 过去分词: primmed 现在分词: primming 第三人称单数: prims');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bather', '[\'beɪðər]', 'n.入浴者；浴疗者', '1. The beach was swarming with bathers. 海滩上挤满了游泳的人。 2. A bather stood under a hot waterfall at a medicinal bathing complex in Greece Monday. 周一，一名游泳者站在希腊一个温泉疗养地的温泉瀑布下。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('modulate', '[\'mɑːdʒəleɪt]', 'v.调整；调节（声音）；变调', '1. The speaker had a really noble voice which he could modulate with great skill. 这位演说者有副相当好的嗓子，他能很技巧地调整它。 2. He knows when to move upstage,when to modulate his voice,and when to throw away a line. 他懂得什么时候该移向舞台后方，什么时候该调整声调，以及什么时候该轻轻带过一句台词。 3. Please modulate the sound on the TV. 请调节一下电视机的音量。 4. Moreover, it has been shown to induce steatosis, modulate apoptosis, and increase cellular oncogenic potential. 更且，它会引起脂肪变性，调节细胞凋亡，增加细胞的致癌性。', '形容词: modulative 名词: modulability 过去式: modulated 过去分词: modulated 现在分词: modulating 第三人称单数: modulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('displace', '[dɪs\'pleɪs]', 'v.取代；移置；替换', '1. Weeds tend to displace other plants. 杂草越来越多，有取代其他植物之势。 2. Moderates have displaced the extremists on the committee. 在委员会中，稳健派人士取代了激进派人士。 3. Please don\'t displace my dictionaries. 请别动我的词典。 4. The indigenous population was soon displaced by the settlers. 没过多久，外来移民就把当地人赶出了家园。', '形容词: displaceable 名词: displacer 过去式: displaced 过去分词: displaced 现在分词: displacing 第三人称单数: displaces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pop', '[pɑːp]', 'v.发出(砰的响声)；取出；突然行动；突然出现；爆开；睁大；开枪 n.流行音乐，流行艺术；爆裂声；<美口>爸爸 adj.通俗的；流行的；热门的', '1. The champagne cork popped when he pulled it out. 他拔香槟酒的瓶塞时它砰的一声开了。 2. I must pop round to baker\'s for a loaf of bread. 我得到面包店去买一个面包来。 3. The rabbits popped out as soon as we opened the hutch. 我们一打开兔箱，兔子就突然跑出来了。 4. He seem to pop up in the most unlikely place. 在他似乎绝不可能到的地方,他往往就在那里出现。 5. He likes pop; he doesn\'t care for classic music. 他喜欢流行歌曲，不喜欢古典音乐。 6. We\'ve got many students study pop psychology in our school. 我们学校有很多学生学习通俗心理学。', '过去式: popped 过去分词: popped 现在分词: popping 第三人称单数: pops');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mania', '[\'meɪniə]', 'n. 狂热； 癖好； [医]躁狂 suf. ... 狂； 对 ... 有过分的热情', '1. Strictly,mania is a kind of madness which makes people violent. 严格地说，狂热是一种使人极端性的精神病。 2. French potholer, Berger, is a mania for cave exploration. 法国洞穴探险家伯杰是一位洞穴探险的狂热爱好者。 3. Mania is a habit we develop for a long time. 癖好是长时间形成的一种习惯。 4. Collecting small items can easily become a mania. 收藏零星物品往往容易变成一种癖好。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('palter', '[\'pɔːltə]', 'vi.含糊其词；马虎处理；讨价还价；敷衍了事', '1. Palter with sth. 马马虎虎地对付某事 2. Please answer my questions quickly and properly, not palter with them. 请马上准备回答我的问题，不要含糊其辞。', '名词: palterer 过去式: paltered 过去分词: paltered 现在分词: paltering 第三人称单数: palters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boor', '[bʊr]', 'n.粗野的人；不懂礼貌的人；农民；乡下人', '1. I\'m a bit of a boor, so I hope you won\'t mind if I speak bluntly. 我是一个粗人,说话直来直去,你可别见怪。 2. \"Oh, the man\'s impossible--an ill-bred boor,\" said Scarlett. \"唔，刚才这个人太差劲----是个没教养的东西，\"思嘉说。 3. If he fears the intellectual, he despises the boor. 他对知识分子有戒心，但是更瞧不起乡下人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defoliate', '[ˌdiː\'foʊlieɪt]', 'v.(使)落叶；除叶', '1. Infestations of these caterpillars may defoliate oaks and other hardwood trees but usually do no permanent damage. 横行的毛虫使得橡树落叶和其他硬木树但是通常不会有持久的损害。', '名词: defoliation 过去式: defoliated 过去分词: defoliated 现在分词: defoliating 第三人称单数: defoliates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gully', '[\'ɡʌli]', 'n.小峡谷；排水沟 v.在…上开沟；形成冲沟 =gulley.', '1. It\'s unlikely that this gully was produced by nature. 这个溪谷不大可能是自然出现的。 2. A few days afterwards a heavy wagon passed through the gully. 几天后一辆大篷车经过了这个小峡谷。 3. The torrent scoured a gully down the hillside. 那激流顺山坡而下冲出一条水沟。', '名词复数: gullies 过去式: gullied 过去分词: gullied 现在分词: gullying 第三人称单数: gullies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('calibre', '[\'kælɪbər]', 'n.(枪等)口径；(人或事)品质；才能', '1. A small bore frifle means that the weapon is in the 0.22 to 0.38 calibre range. 小口径步枪是指枪的口径为0. 2. Calibre from the words. It is difficult to identify and understanding. 口径不一，各言其是，很难明辨是非和统一认识。 3. His work is of the highest calibre. 他的工作质量最高。 4. This work\'s of a very high calibre. 这部作品是高质量的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('induct', '[ɪn\'dʌkt]', 'vt.使就职；使入伍；使入门；引导，带领；【电】感应', '1. Induct To admit as a member; receive. 吸收为会员吸收为成员;接纳。 2. Induct and train users on system applications. 为新用户进行培训。 3. Induct, utilize and manage various resources. 合理引入、利用和管理各种资源。 4. To induct into office by a formal ceremony. 就职通过正式的就职典礼而就任职位', '过去式: inducted 过去分词: inducted 现在分词: inducting 第三人称单数: inducts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cylinder', '[\'sɪlɪndər]', 'n.圆筒；汽缸；圆柱体', '1. The cylinder is a crucial part of the washing machine. 滚筒是洗衣机必不可少的部分。 2. She handed over a small metal cylinder. 她递过来一个小的金属圆筒。 3. The engine is misfiring badly on one cylinder. 发动机有一个汽缸严重失灵。 4. The accident didn\'t do much damage to the cylinder. 在意外事故中，汽缸没有受到重大损坏。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('neonate', '[\'niːoʊneɪt]', 'n.初生婴儿', '1. In a neonate following in utero exposure. 例新生儿子宫内暴露引起的中毒。 2. Postnatal appearance of the neonate. 新生儿的产后表现。 3. Hemolytic icterus occurs in the neonate of the horse and swine. 溶血性黄疸发生于马和猪的初生幼畜。 4. Clinical use of healthy neonate umbilical cord orbital implant. 健康新生儿脐带义眼座的临床应用', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hoe', '[hoʊ]', 'n.锄头 v.锄地；铲除', '1. The gardener used a hoe to remove weeds. 这园丁用锄头锄草。 2. Many small gardens are cultivated with the spade and hoe. 一些小花园用铁锹和锄头耕种。', '名词: hoer 过去式: hoed 过去分词: hoed 现在分词: hoeing 第三人称单数: hoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dignity', '[\'dɪɡnəti]', 'n.尊严；高贵；端庄', '1. He would do nothing beneath his dignity. 他决不愿意干任何有损自身尊严的事。 2. The real dignity of a man lies in what he is, not in what he has. 一个人的真正尊严在于他的品格，而非他的财富。 3. A man\'s dignity depends not upon his wealth but upon his character. 人高尚与否不取决於他的财富,而取决於他的品格。 4. She bears herself with dignity. 她举止庄重大方。', '名词复数: dignities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('latent', '[\'leɪtnt]', 'adj.潜伏的；潜在的', '1. He was infected with a latent infection. 他被感染了一种潜伏性的传染病。 2. We must take measures to control the latent disease germs. 我们必须采取措施控制潜伏的病菌。 3. Within everyone there was a latent volcano of unhappiness and discontent. 在每个人心中都有一座潜伏着不幸福与不满的火山。 4. The latent cause of crime is often avarice. 贫婪常是犯罪的潜在诱因。', '副词: latently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sow', '[saʊ]', 'v.播种；散布 n.母猪', '1. These seeds should be sown in April. 这些种子应在四月播种。 2. His words had sowed the seeds of suspicion in their minds. 他的话已在他们心中播下怀疑的种子。 3. The enemy tried to sow discontent among our men . 敌人企图在我们的士兵中间散布不满情绪。', '名词: sower 过去式: sowed 过去分词: sown/sowed 现在分词: sowing 第三人称单数: sows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mischievous', '[\'mɪstʃɪvəs]', 'adj.调皮的；恶作剧的；有害的', '1. The little boy is as mischievous as a monkey. 这个小男孩像猴子一样调皮。 2. She yelled out at her mischievous child. 她对她淘气的孩子大喊大叫。 3. The thought sent a mischievous little smile to her lips. 一想到这个念头，她的嘴角浮现一丝恶作剧般的微笑。 4. Not only is it a mistaken belief, it is a mischievous one. 它不仅是一个错误的观点，而且也是一个有害的观点。', '副词: mischievously 名词: mischievousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ruse', '[ruːz]', 'n.策略；谋略；诈术', '1. Their first ruse having failed, then tried another. 他们一计不成, 又施一计。 2. Ruse culture shows diversity posture in the expression in market economy. 谋略文化在市场经济中的表现呈多元化态势。 3. The criminal adopted ruse to escape detection. 这罪犯采取诈术来逃避侦破。 4. To feign frankness is a ruse of war. 装作坦白，是为了作战的目的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hawser', '[\'hɔːzər]', 'n.大缆；系船索；曳船索', '1. The fingers were pinched under a hawser. 手指被夹在大缆绳下面。 2. On the other side of the hawser was a hostile knot of young dockers. 在钢缆的那一边，是一伙满怀敌意的码头工人。 3. There\'s a new hawser faked down there. 有条新铁索盘卷在那。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('presumption', '[prɪ\'zʌmpʃn]', 'n.推测；可能性；冒昧；放肆；[法律]推定', '1. I don\'t think that\'s a false presumption. 我认为那并不是错误的推测。 2. On this presumption, she stopped at noon at a neat farm-house, to rest herself. 在这种推测下，到了正午时分，她便在一间整洁的农舍前停下来歇一歇脚。 3. It is not presumption on my part. 在我这方面不算冒昧。 4. Please pardon my presumption in writing to you. 请原谅我很冒昧地写信给你。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trajectory', '[trə\'dʒektəri]', 'n.轨道；弹道；轨迹', '1. The missile deflected from its trajectory. 导弹已偏离轨道。 2. My career seemed to be on a downward trajectory. 我的事业似乎在走下坡路。 3. From then on it must coast in a trajectory, or flight path, to its target. 从那时起，它就得沿着弹道，即沿着飞行航线滑向其目标。 4. It is not difficult to sketch the subsequent trajectory. 很容易描绘出它们后来的轨迹。', '名词复数: trajectories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ravish', '[\'rævɪʃ]', 'v.强奸；使 ... 狂喜；抢夺', '1. I was ravished by her beauty. 我被她的美貌迷住了。', '名词: ravisher 过去式: ravished 过去分词: ravished 现在分词: ravishing 第三人称单数: ravishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rapids', '[\'ræpɪdz]', 'n.急流；湍流', '1. They fell into the seething waters of the rapids. 他们跌进了汹涌的急流中。 2. His canoe was there, on the river below the rapids. 他的独木舟在河里的急流中。 3. The Rhosili is a turbulent, swift-flowing river, full of dangerous rapids and currents. 罗西里是一条汹涌的迅速滚滚的河，充满着危险的险滩和湍流。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wince', '[wɪns]', 'n.畏缩；（因痛苦或苦恼等)面部肌肉抽搐 v.畏缩；战栗；退避', '1. Mention branding and a wince passes around the table. 一提及品牌推广，畏缩情绪就传遍了整张桌子。 2. His smile soon modified to a wince. 他的微笑很快就成了脸部肌肉的抽搐。 3. That statistic must surely make them wince. 这样的统计数据必定会让他们退缩。 4. As soon as he touched her she seemed to wince and stiffen. 只消他碰到她，她便一阵畏缩，全身僵硬。', '名词: wincer 过去式: winced 过去分词: winced 现在分词: wincing 第三人称单数: winces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alms', '[ɑːmz]', 'n.<古>救济金；救济品 名词alm的复数形式', '1. My unemployment alms was expiration. 我的失业救济金满期了。 2. A person may also give as much as he or she pleases as voluntary alms or charity. 一个人可以尽其所能地义务捐献救济金或慈善捐款。 3. He gave alms to beggars in the street. 他给街上的乞丐一些施舍。 4. He thinks it\'s a shame to beg others for alms. 他认为向他人乞求救济是耻辱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('magnitude', '[\'mæɡnɪtuːd]', 'n.大小；重要；光度；（地震）级数；（星星）等级', '1. I want to know the magnitude of this equipment. 我想知道这个设备的大小。 2. The magnitude of the epidemic was frightening. 这种流行病传播范围之广令人惶惶不安。 3. I had not realized the magnitude of the problem. 我没意识到这个问题的重要性。 4. The main quake was estimated at magnitude 6.6. 据估计主震区的震级有6.', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thump', '[θʌmp]', 'v.重击；怦怦跳；猛击；用拳头打 n.重击声；重打', '1. He was thumping the keys of the piano. 他重重地敲击钢琴琴键。 2. My heart was thumping with happiness. 我的心兴奋得咚咚直跳。 3. I feel pain in my head for it\'s thumping all the time. 我感到头疼，脑袋一直在不断的敲击。 4. The two boys began to thump one another 那两个男孩开始动起拳头相互对打。 5. He sat down with a thump. 他砰的一声坐下。', '名词: thumper 过去式: thumped 过去分词: thumped 现在分词: thumping 第三人称单数: thumps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dissent', '[dɪ\'sent]', 'n.异议 v.持异议', '1. They expressed their dissent from official policy. 他们对官方的政策表示出异议。 2. It is too late to make any dissent. 现在提出异议太晚了。 3. The right to dissent is part of our political system. 有持异议的权利是我们政治体制的组成部分。 4. If enough members dissent, the new bill won\'t be approved. 假如持异议的会员够多，新法案就不会被核准。', '副词: dissentingly 过去式: dissented 过去分词: dissented 现在分词: dissenting 第三人称单数: dissents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prorogue', '[proʊ\'roʊg]', 'v.休会；延期；必会', '1. Parliament is prorogue for the summer recess. 因暑假议会休会。 2. Parliament be prorogue for the summer recess . 因暑假议会休会。 3. The legislature moved to prorogue the present session. 立法机关提议停止目前的会议。 4. Adjourn, postpone The legislature moved to prorogue the present session. 立法机关提议停止目前的会议。', '名词: prorogation 过去式: prorogued 过去分词: prorogued 现在分词: proroguing 第三人称单数: prorogues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mercurial', '[mɜːr\'kjʊriəl]', 'adj.善变的；活泼的；水银的；[天文]水星的 n.水银剂', '1. Our desires and aversions are mercurial rulers. 我们的欲望与嫌恶是变化无常的统治者。 2. He was of a mercurial temperament and therefore unpredictable. 他是个反复无常的人,因此对他的行为无法预言。 3. She has a mercurial turn of conversation. 她谈话善转话锋。 4. A mercurial barometer has a glass tube a little more than 30 inches long. 水银气压表有一长30英寸多一点的玻璃管。', '副词: mercurially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pleat', '[pliːt]', 'n.褶；褶状物 v.打褶', '1. Press the pleats flat. 把褶子熨平。 2. I would like to have pleat in the front. 我想要前面有褶。 3. Now we\'re going to pleat the backside. 现在我们将要开始制作背后的褶。 4. You can pleat palm fronds to make huts, umbrellas and baskets. 人们可以把棕榈叶折叠起来盖棚屋，制伞，编篮子。', '名词: pleater 过去式: pleated 过去分词: pleated 现在分词: pleating 第三人称单数: pleats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gene', '[dʒiːn]', 'n.基因', '1. The position that a given gene occupies on a chromosome. 基因座在一条染色体上某种给定基因所占的位置 2. The degree to which an expressed gene produces its effects in an organism. 基因的表现度描述一个组织中的一个基因产生作用的程度 3. In addition to gene, intelligence also depends on an adequate diet, a good education and a decent home environment. 除了遗传基因外，智力的高低还取决于良好的营养，良好的教育和良好的家庭环境。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('throwback', '[\'θroʊbæk]', 'n.返回；返祖现象', '1. The car\'s design is a throwback to the 1960s. 这种汽车的设计回到了20世纪60年代。 2. His sentiment is a throwback to the old colonial day. 他的观点还是从前殖民时代的那种观点。 3. Being a sort of throwback to the Victorian age, she won\'t go against her old dad\'s wishes. 她有点像维多利亚时代的女性,不肯违背自己老父的意愿。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fealty', '[\'fiːəlti]', 'n.效忠；忠诚；忠实', '1. He swore fealty to his motherland. 他宣誓效忠祖国。 2. He took an oath of fealty to the king. 他宣誓对国王效忠。 3. There is no doubt with his fealty. 他的忠诚无可置疑。 4. The ties of family seem stronger than the oaths of fealty. 家族之绊似乎胜过忠诚之誓。', '名词复数: fealties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('genealogy', '[ˌdʒiːni\'ælədʒi]', 'n.家系；宗谱', '1. The noble took pride in his genealogy. 该位贵族以自己的血统为傲. 2. This view of kinship helps explain why Mormons are so interested in genealogy. 这种有关血缘的观点可以帮助我们解释为什么摩门教徒对家系这么感兴趣。 3. Many libraries specialize in genealogy. 许多图书馆专门收藏氏族家谱。 4. The genealogy of his family was reduced to ashes in the fire. 他家的谱牒已在一次大火中化为灰烬。', '形容词: genealogical 副词: genealogically 名词: genealogist 名词复数: genealogies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confound', '[kən\'faʊnd]', 'vt.使困惑；混淆；挫败；诅咒', '1. Don\'t confound the means with the ends. 不要把手段和目的混淆起来。 2. To confound two things means not to be able to tell them apart. 混淆两件事物的意思是说没能把它们区分开来。', '名词: confounder 过去式: confounded 过去分词: confounded 现在分词: confounding 第三人称单数: confounds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('downpour', '[\'daʊnpɔːr]', 'n.倾盆大雨', '1. She was drenched by the sudden downpour. 她被那场突然下的倾盆大雨淋得湿透。 2. The clouds broke after the heavy downpour. 乌云在倾盆大雨过后驱散了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nonsensical', '[nɑːn\'sensɪkl]', 'adj.没有意义的；荒谬的', '1. These objections are nonsensical 这些反对的理由是无稽之谈。 2. These objections are nonsensical. 这些反对的理由是无稽之谈。 3. He said several nonsensical things 他说了许多荒谬的话。 4. He said several nonsensical things. 他说了许多荒谬的话。', '副词: nonsensically 名词: nonsensicality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ransom', '[\'rænsəm]', 'n.赎金；赎身；赎回 vt.赎回', '1. You are our prisoner now and we won\'t release you until a ransom is paid. 你现已遭我们禁锢,要到交出赎金以后,才能放你走。 2. They have to pay a large ransom. 他们不得不付一大笔赎金。 3. They held the travellers for ransom. 他们将旅客当作人质索取赎金。 4. A king\'s ransom would hardly have procured all that my daughters asked for. 即使是一个国王的赎身钱，也买不起我的女儿们所要的东西。 5. They ransomed the kidnapped child with 10,000 dollars. 他们用一万元赎回了被绑架的孩子。', '名词: ransomer 过去式: ransomed 过去分词: ransomed 现在分词: ransoming 第三人称单数: ransoms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('annex', '[ə\'neks]', 'vt.并吞；附加；获得 n.附件；附属物；附属建筑物', '1. Japan annexed Korea in 1910. 日本在1910年吞并了朝鲜。 2. In the years immediately preceding the outbreak of war in1939, Hitler succeeded in annexing various parts of Europe to Germany without firing a shot. 在1939年大战爆发的前几年，希特勒没开一抢而成功地把欧洲许多地区并吞为德国领土。 3. Happiness is not always annexed to wealth. 财富并不一定会带来幸福。 4. A new wing has been annexed to the hospital. 医院已经增建了一个新侧楼。 5. Any annex is the integral part of this contract. 本合同一切附件均为本合同的有效组成部分。', '形容词: annexational 名词: annexation 过去式: annexed 过去分词: annexed 现在分词: annexing 第三人称单数: annexes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('timid', '[\'tɪmɪd]', 'adj.胆怯的；害羞的', '1. They taunted him for being timid. 他们讥笑他胆小。 2. He is as timid as a sheep. 他像绵羊一样怯懦。 3. The least noise would startle the timid child. 最小的响声也会吓着这个胆小的孩子的。 4. He is a timid boy; it\'s impossible for him to brawl with anyone. 他是一个胆小的男孩，他不可能和任何人吵架。', '副词: timidly 比较级: timider 最高级: timidest 名词: timidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delectation', '[ˌdiːlek\'teɪʃn]', 'n.享受；愉快', '1. Combine to wish you reside to stop the delectation! 并祝您居停愉快！ 2. And now for your further delectation, we present a selection of popular melodies. 为使你们更加愉快，我们奉献给你们一组精选的流行歌曲。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irrepressible', '[ˌɪrɪ\'presəbl]', 'adj.抑制不住的；难以征服的', '1. He registered irrepressible joy. 他流露出压抑不住的喜悦。', '副词: irrepressibly 名词: irrepressibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preview', '[\'priːvjuː]', 'n.预审；试映；预习；预告 vt.事先查看；预习', '1. They sent the recording for our preview. 他们把那录音送来给我们预先审查。 2. After a sneak preview of the film they decided to shelve it. 该影片在试映后，他们决定把它搁置起来。 3. Please do the preview and review work. 请做好预习和复习工作。 4. And some Japanese who saw the preview were pleasantly surprised. 一些日本人在看过电影预告后大表惊艳。 5. You may also preview and buy my work here. 你也可以在这里查看与购买我的作品。', '过去式: previewed/prevued 过去分词: previewed/prevued 现在分词: previewing/prevuing 第三人称单数: previews/prevues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comply', '[kəm\'plaɪ]', 'vi.顺从；遵照；答应', '1. She was told to pay the fine, but refused to comply. 通知她交纳罚款，但她拒不服从。 2. He was willing to comply with my proposal. 他愿意顺从我的建议。 3. Everyone should comply with the law. 每个人都应该遵守法律。 4. Is it our duty to comply with his requests? 我们有义务满足他的要求吗?', '过去式: complied 过去分词: complied 现在分词: complying 第三人称单数: complies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('know-how', '[noʊ haʊ]', 'n. <口> 实践知识； 技术秘诀； 诀窍', '1. If you\'re in the pool, you must know the ropes. 如果你想要赌钱就得懂诀窍。 2. I gave her a tip on how to concoct a new kind of soup. 我教她配制一种新汤的诀窍。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hiatus', '[haɪ\'eɪtəs]', 'n.裂缝；分裂；间断；停顿', '1. My marriage is not ending. It\'s just on hiatus. 我的婚姻还没完，只是有点裂缝。 2. We renewed our friendship after a hiatus of twenty years. 我们在分裂二十多年后又新生了友谊。 3. After a five-month hiatus, the talks resumed. 谈判在中断了五个月之后又开始了。 4. The travel show was on hiatus during coverage of Wimbledon. 该旅游节目因为转播温布顿网球赛而暂停播出。', '形容词: hiatal 名词复数: hiatuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deception', '[dɪ\'sepʃn]', 'n.骗局；诡计；欺诈', '1. It\'s a deception, as far as I can discover. 就我所知，这是一个骗局。 2. The whole episode had been a cruel deception. 整个经历都是残酷的骗局。 3. He obtained our trust by deception. 他靠欺骗获取了我们的信任。 4. Deception was foreign to his nature. 欺骗和他的本性格格不入。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('requisite', '[\'rekwɪzɪt]', 'adj.必要的；需要的 n.必需品', '1. The state provided the requisite capital for this farm. 国家为这个农场提供了必要的资金。 2. They are accompanied by the requisite shipping documnts in order. 它们必须随付必要的，正确无误的装船单据。 3. The requisite conditions may seldom have concurred. 此等恰恰需要的条件，常难能凑合。 4. In return, the EPA provides the company the information and technical support it needs to install the requisite lighting. 作为回报，美国环境保护署应为企业提供它所需要的信息和技术支持来安装这些照明设备。 5. Food and air are requisite for life. 食物和空气是生命的必需品。', '副词: requisitely 名词: requisiteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contact', '[\'kɑːntækt]', 'n.接触；联系；熟人 v.(与)联系；(与)接触 adj.接触的', '1. The rich secluded themselves from contact with the poor. 富人不肯同穷人接触。 2. I finally made contact with her in Paris. 我终于在巴黎同她取得了联系。 3. She has a contact in the software industry. 她在软件行业有个熟人。 4. Contact the police at once! 立刻与警方联系！ 5. She suffers from a contact skin rash. 她患上了一种接触传染性皮疹。', '形容词: contactual 副词: contactually 过去式: contacted 过去分词: contacted 现在分词: contacting 第三人称单数: contacts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amalgamate', '[ə\'mælɡəmeɪt]', 'v.合并；混合', '1. Our local brewery has amalgamated with another firm. 我们本地的酿酒厂与另一个公司合并了。 2. There are plans to amalgamate the village school with a larger one nearby. 有计划让乡村学校和附近一所规模较大的学校合并。', '形容词: amalgamative 名词: amalgamator 过去式: amalgamated 过去分词: amalgamated 现在分词: amalgamating 第三人称单数: amalgamates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eulogy', '[\'juːlədʒi]', 'n.颂词；颂扬；悼词', '1. He pronounced a eulogy upon the hero. 他向英雄致颂词。 2. Joe will deliver the eulogy and then we can leave. 乔会发表一篇悼词，然后我们就可以离开了。', '形容词: eulogistic 副词: eulogistically 名词复数: eulogies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('layover', '[\'leɪoʊvər]', 'n.短暂停留；逗留；津贴', '1. You have a layover in Chicago. 你要在芝加哥作短暂停留。 2. We had a two-hour layover in Denver yesterday. 我们昨天在丹佛市逗留了两个小时。 3. I have a layover in Los Angeles for four hours before boarding my plane to Shanghai. 在登上飞往上海的航班前，我会在洛杉矶逗留四个小时。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('septic', '[\'septɪk]', 'adj.腐败的；败血的', '1. I put him in the septic tank. 我把他丢进了化粪池里。 2. The leading cause of death was septic shock. 其主要死因为败血性休克。', '名词: septicity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ceremonious', '[ˌserə\'moʊniəs]', 'adj.拘礼的；礼节性的；正式的', '1. Putting on a hat can be a ceremonious act, an elegant gesture in the ritual of dressing. 戴帽子被看作一种礼节性的举动，是着装仪式上一个优雅的举动。', '副词: ceremoniously 名词: ceremoniousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reap', '[riːp]', 'vt.收割；收获；获得 vi.收割', '1. The peasants are reaping a field of barley. 农民们正在收割大麦。 2. He that soweth virtue shall reap fame. 播下美德，收获名望。 3. If you plant pride, you will reap destruction. 如果你种下骄傲，你就会收获毁灭。 4. It is a season that peasants reap the corn from what they planted in spring. 农民们春季播种玉米，现在是他们收获的季节。 5. They that sow in tears shall reap in joy. 流泪撒种的必欢呼收割。', '过去式: reaped 过去分词: reaped 现在分词: reaping 第三人称单数: reaps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sack', '[sæk]', 'n.袋子；解雇 vt.解雇；把 ... 装入袋子；劫掠', '1. There is a sack of potatoes in the corner of the room. 屋子一角有一袋马铃薯。 2. He tumbled his clothes and books into a big sack. 他把他的衣服和书胡乱装进一只大口袋。 3. The poor guy got the sack yesterday. 那个可怜的家伙昨天给辞退了。 4. If you are late again, the boss will sack you. 如果你再迟到,老板就会解雇你。', '过去式: sacked 过去分词: sacked 现在分词: sacking 第三人称单数: sacks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tremulous', '[\'tremjələs]', 'adj.颤抖的；胆小的；害怕的', '1. She answered the king\'s question with a tremulous voice. 她用颤抖的声音回答国王的问题。 2. She stood there with a tremulous look. 她怯生生地站在那儿。', '副词: tremulously 名词: tremulousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ravine', '[rə\'viːn]', 'n.峡谷；溪谷；沟壑', '1. The soldiers shot down into the ravine. 士兵们向下往深谷里开枪。 2. The river had worn a ravine between the hills. 那条河在两山之间已造成一个深谷。 3. A car swerved to avoid a bus and plunged into a ravine. 一辆小车为避开一辆公共汽车急转方向，却一头坠入了峡谷之中。 4. He could only watch helplessly as the car plunged into the ravine. 他只能眼睁睁地看着汽车冲入溪谷。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infinity', '[ɪn\'fɪnəti]', 'n.无限；无穷；[数]无穷大', '1. Theoretically, a line can extend into infinity. 从理论上来说直线可以无限地延伸。 2. Numbers go on forever to infinity. 数字可以永远地数下去，直到无穷。 3. Its valid values range from 0.0 To infinity. 其有效值范围为0.', '名词复数: infinities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('caterpillar', '[\'kætərpɪlər]', 'n.毛虫 Caterpillar. n.卡特彼勒(财富500强公司之一；总部所在地美国；主要经营工业农业设备)', '1. A caterpillar is the larva of a butterfly. 毛虫是蝴蝶的幼体。 2. The ugly caterpillar will change into a beautiful butterfly. 丑陋的毛虫会变成美丽的蝴蝶。 3. A caterpillar must pass through the cocoon stage to become a butterfly. 毛毛虫必须经过茧的阶段才能变成蝴蝶。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('syringe', '[sɪ\'rɪndʒ]', 'n.注射器 vt.（用液体注射器）冲洗', '1. Syringe used to be an ordinary appliance in medical treatment. 注射器最初只是一件普通的医疗器具。 2. The child started to wail when the nurse come over with a syringe. 当护士拿著针筒走过来时，孩子便嚎啕大哭起来。 3. He boiled his syringe and fired his knife to sterilize them. 他把注射器放到水中煮，把刀子放在火上烧来进行消毒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pontifical', '[pɑːn\'tɪfɪkl]', 'adj.自以为是的；武断的；教皇的；大祭司的 n.主教于祭典所用的书；主教的祭服', '1. One of a college of12 ecclesiastics charged with the registry of important pontifical proceedings. 君士坦丁堡的秘书长负责管理重要主教礼典程序的12个教士组成的教士团中的一员 2. Doctorate in Sacred Theology (S.Th.D.), Moral Theology, Pontifical Gregorian University. 以及其他多位辅仁大学神学院教授担任本培育课程讲师。 3. To provide for the incorporation of the Procurator in Hong Kong of the Pontifical Foreign Missions Institute. 本条例旨在为宗座外方传教会香港总务长成立为法团而订定条文。 4. One of a college of12ecclesiastics charged with the registry of important pontifical proceedings. 他们的婚事在结婚登记处外宣布了。', '副词: pontifically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amiable', '[\'eɪmiəbl]', 'adj.和蔼的；亲切的', '1. The amiable countenance of Mr. Pickwick was fast recovering its customary expression. 匹克威克先生的和蔼的脸孔在很快地恢复着平常的表情。 2. The hostess received her friends with an amiable smile. 女主人带着亲切的微笑迎接朋友们的到来。 3. You can sort out any differences you have in an amiable manner. 你可以以温柔亲切的主式澄清所有的误会。', '副词: amiably 名词: amiability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('betray', '[bɪ\'treɪ]', 'vt.背叛；出卖；泄露；显露', '1. He betrayed his country. 他背叛了他的国家。 2. He promised never to betray the organization. 他发誓永不背叛组织。 3. He was seduced to betray his friend. 他受唆使而出卖朋友。 4. As long as you don\'t betray me, I\'ll do whatever you ask me to. 只要你不出卖我,要我做什么我都愿意。', '名词: betrayal 过去式: betrayed 过去分词: betrayed 现在分词: betraying 第三人称单数: betrays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elephantine', '[ˌelɪ\'fæntiːn]', 'adj.象的；巨大的；粗笨的', '1. Their daughter is quite plump but their son is positively elephantine. 他们的女儿很胖; 可是儿子呢，简直像大象。 2. These elephantine oddities seem to carry a message. Each artist has an idiosyncratic eye. 这些笨拙的古怪作品好象在传达着一个信息，即每个艺术家都有着个性化的眼睛。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sinecure', '[\'saɪnɪkjʊr]', 'n.挂名职务；闲差事；<古> 领干薪的牧师职位', '1. This is hardly a [not a, no] sinecure. 这哪里是 [不是] 闲差事((很忙))。 2. He even had a job, a sinecure, more highly-paid than his old job had been. 他甚至还有一个工作，一个挂名差使，比他原来的工作的待遇要好多了。 3. Sinecure---A job or position requiring little work but usually providing some income. N. 工作清闲而报酬丰厚的职位。 4. His stable services were merely a sinecure, and consisted simply in a daily care and inspection. 他在马厩里的工作是个轻闲差使，每天只要去照料照料巡视一番。', '名词: sinecurism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('besmirch', '[bɪ\'smɜːrtʃ]', 'vt.弄污；污渍', '1. This eradicator can wash hard besmirch. 这种去污剂能去除难洗的污渍。 2. This eradicator could clean hard besmirch. 这种去污剂能去除难洗的污渍。 3. This eradicator can wipe off difficult besmirch. 这种去污剂能去除难洗的污渍。 4. This eradicator can wipe off the hard besmirch. 这种去污剂能去除难洗的污渍。', '名词: besmircher 过去式: besmirched 过去分词: besmirched 现在分词: besmirching 第三人称单数: besmirches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rarefaction', '[ˌrerə\'fækʃən]', 'n.稀薄；稀薄化', '1. Simulation results show that rarefaction effect plays an important role in gas damping, which decreases as Kn Number increases. 数值模拟结果表明，稀薄效应对气体阻尼的影响较大，随着克努森数的不断增大，气体阻尼逐渐减小。 2. Several applications require consideration of rarefaction, which motivates the present thesis to focus on simulation of driven cavity flows in this region. 因此本文的动机是模拟空穴流场在稀薄区域上的应用。', '形容词: rarefactive');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spectrum', '[\'spektrəm]', 'n.系列；幅度；范围；光谱；[科]频谱', '1. There\'s a wide spectrum of opinions on this problem. 对这个问题的说法众说纷纭，莫衷一是。 2. There are tense competition in the whole spectrum of the industry. 整个工业领域竞争很激烈。 3. The press has published a wide spectrum of books. 这个出版社出版了一系列范围广泛的书籍。 4. In the spectrum, distinct colours shade into each other. 在光谱中，截然不同的颜色相互融合起来。', '名词复数: spectra');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('denude', '[dɪ\'nuːd]', 'vt.剥光；剥蚀', '1. The elevation of crust can make rock gold deposit weather and denude and the level of the denudation depends on the scale of the elevation. 地壳上升会使岩金矿床风化剥蚀，而剥蚀程度取决于地壳上升幅度。', '名词: denudation 过去式: denuded 过去分词: denuded 现在分词: denuding 第三人称单数: denudes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frowzy', '[\'fraʊzɪ]', 'adj.不整洁的；臭的 =frowsy.', '1. Frowzy clothes; a frowzy professor. 脏衣服; 邋遢的教授 2. At London I am pent up in frowzy lodgings, where there is not room enough to swing a cat. 在伦敦，我守在肮脏的住所里面，那地方狭窄得无法转身。', '名词: frowziness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('screw', '[skruː]', 'n.螺钉；螺丝；螺状物；螺旋桨；螺旋；吝啬鬼；监狱看守人；<粗>性交；<英俚>工资；薪水 v.拧紧；拧；压榨；<粗>性交', '1. Turn the screw to the right to tighten it. 将螺钉向右旋紧。 2. One of the screws is loose. 一只螺丝松了。 3. The screw did its work, and Ressel was pleased. 由于螺旋桨起了作用，所以莱塞尔感到高兴。 4. He used all of his efforts to loosen the screw. 他用尽全力来拧开这个螺旋装置。 5. The table legs are screwed to the floor. 这张桌子的腿是用螺丝固定在地板上的。', '形容词: screwable 名词: screwer 过去式: screwed 过去分词: screwed 现在分词: screwing 第三人称单数: screws');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('morose', '[mə\'roʊs]', 'adj.郁闷的；抑郁的；难相处的', '1. He lost his morose depressed attitude and began to open his heart to others. 他那消沉的情绪为之一扫而光，开始与人热情交往。 2. The next time you\'re feeling cranky or morose, check in with your body. 下一次你感觉心情烦躁或者郁闷、审视一下你的身体。 3. He became insular, emotionally dead, passionless and morose. 他变得孤僻,心灰意冷,郁郁寡欢。 4. He became at times listless and morose. 有时候他就愈加无精打彩，脾气乖张。', '副词: morosely 名词: moroseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('attrition', '[ə\'trɪʃn]', 'n.摩擦；消耗；人员耗损', '1. Lube can ease attrition, and extend the using time of machines. 润滑剂能减少摩擦，延长机器寿命。 2. We should learn to respect others so as to avoid attrition and confliction. 我们应该学会尊重对方，避免摩擦和冲突。 3. But the objective of strategic attrition may also be achieved by campaigns of attrition. 但达到战略消耗目的的，还有战役的消耗战。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('engrave', '[ɪn\'ɡreɪv]', 'v.雕刻；刻上；铭记', '1. It is difficult to engrave in marble. 在大理石上雕刻是困难的。 2. His memorial was engraved on the stone. 纪念他的碑文刻在石碑上。 3. The jeweller will engrave the inside of the ring with her name. 珠宝匠将在戒指的内表面上刻上她的名字。 4. The terrible scene was engraved on his memory. 那可怕的情景铭记在他的记忆里。', '名词: engraver 过去式: engraved 过去分词: engraved 现在分词: engraving 第三人称单数: engraves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fracas', '[\'freɪkəs]', 'n.喧噪；吵闹；纷扰', '1. Five others were hurt in the fracas. 骚乱中另有五人受伤。 2. The police were called in to stop the fracas. 警察奉命去制止骚乱。 3. The new wages policy caused a terrible fracas at the meeting yesterday. 新的工资政策在昨天的会上引起了激烈的吵闹。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conspectus', '[kən\'spektəs]', 'n.概要；大纲', '1. What a Design Conspectus should be? 什么是设计概论该有的样子? 2. A conspectus of Hubei woody plants in the Harvard University Herbaria, U.S.A. 哈佛大学植物标本馆中的湖北木本植物标本志要. 3. LI Si-guang. 1973. Conspectus of Geomechanics [M]. Science Press, Beijing. 24 (in Chinese). 李四光.;1973 4. The teaching of Mao Zedong Thought Conspectus is an alternant process between teachers and students. 毛泽东思想概论”课教学过程是教师与学生交互作用的过程。', '名词复数: conspectuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('privy', '[\'prɪvi]', 'adj.私下知情的；私人的；秘密的 n.有利害关系的人；厕所', '1. The lawyer was privy to government secrets. 律师对政府秘密私下知情。 2. Very few of them were privy to the details of the conspiracy. 他们之中很少人知道密谋的详情。 3. They were accused of being privy to the plot against the king. 他们被控欺君谋反、 知情不举。 4. The privy took proceedings against the company. 当事人对这家公司提起诉讼。', '名词复数: privies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('calamity', '[kə\'læməti]', 'n.灾难；不幸事件', '1. The recent flooding in the south was a calamity. 最近南方的洪水是一场灾难。 2. She is always on the alert for some new calamity. 她总是保持警觉以防某种新的灾难。', '名词复数: calamities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('doting', '[\'doʊtɪŋ]', 'adj.百依百顺的；溺爱的 动词dote的现在分词形式.', '1. Irene asked her doting husband if he would build her a handloom. 艾琳要她的百依百顺的丈夫为她制作一架手摇织布机。 2. A doting mother alienates her husband by lavishing too much love on their child. 一个溺爱孩子的母亲给予太多的爱在孩子身上,而疏远了丈夫。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('atrocity', '[ə\'trɑːsəti]', 'n.暴行；残暴', '1. People were annoyed by his atrocity. 他的暴行激怒了人们。 2. This atrocity shocked the world opinion. 这暴行使全世界舆论感到震惊。 3. I am shocked by the atrocity of this man\'s crimes. 这个人行凶手段残忍狠毒使我震惊。', '名词复数: atrocities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transience', '[\'trænziəns]', 'n.短暂，片刻，稍纵即逝', '1. The result is a culture of transience and disposability. 结果就是一种稍纵即逝的文化，一种随意弃置的文化。', '异体字: transiency');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hamstring', '[\'hæmstrɪŋ]', 'n.腿筋 v.切断腿筋使成跛腿；减弱活动能力；使无效', '1. I had a little hamstring problem, so I\'ve been laying low. 我腿筋有点毛病，所以我被放着躺低。 2. He felt his hamstring in the match against Everton and was forced off at half time. 在对埃弗顿的比赛中他感到腿部不适，中场休息的时候被替换下场。 3. You shall hamstring their horses and burn their chariots with fire. 你要砍断他们马的蹄筋，用火焚烧他们的战车。 4. The state prosecutors and police organizations wereadamantly opposed, believing that videotaping would be expensiveand cumbersome, and would hamstring their ability to close cases. 州检察官和警方机构坚决地反对，认为录像会增加花费和使工作不便，并且会削弱他们结案的能力。', '过去式: hamstrung 过去分词: hamstrung 现在分词: hamstringing 第三人称单数: hamstrings');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decant', '[dɪ\'kænt]', 'v.轻轻倒出；移入其他容器', '1. She always used to decant the milk into a jug. 她曾经总是把牛奶慢慢倒入水壶中。 2. You should decant it now to allow it to breathe. 你应该慢慢倒，好让香味散发出来。', '名词: decantation 过去式: decanted 过去分词: decanted 现在分词: decanting 第三人称单数: decants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comic', '[\'kɑːmɪk]', 'n.连环图画；喜剧演员 adj.滑稽的；有趣的；喜剧的', '1. Children like to read comics. 孩子们喜欢看连环漫画。 2. He is looking for his comic book. 他在找他的连环画。 3. He is a popular TV comic. 他是观众喜爱的电视喜剧演员。 4. The comic scenes in the play were overdone. 这剧的滑稽场面太夸张了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maleficent', '[mə\'lefəsənt]', 'adj.有害的；做坏事的；犯罪的', '1. Fairy Fauna： Why, it\'s Maleficent! 佛那：啊！是马雷菲森！ 2. Maleficent： Stand back, you fools! 马雷菲森：走开，你们这群蠢货！ 3. Maleficent： Why no, your majesty. 马雷菲森：当然没有，王后陛下。 4. On Maleficent\'s forbidden mountain. 在梅尔菲森的禁山上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('taxonomist', '[tæk\'sɑːnəmɪst]', 'n.分类学者', '1. A-Fan wants to be a taxonomist of plants. 阿帆想成为一位植物分类学者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ballast', '[\'bæləst]', 'n. 压载物； 压舱物； （铺铁路路基时所用的）石块； 镇流器； 稳定力量 vt. 给 ... 装压舱物（压载物）； 使稳定', '1. If not ventilated properly, their ballast circuitry can get fried enough to fail. 如果通风不畅，压载物的线路板会如同被煎过似的坏掉。 2. The ship was furnished with ballast. 船上装了压舱物。 3. So are the motions of a little vessel without ballast tossed about on a stormy sea. 在惊涛骇浪的大海上，一只没有压舱物的小船就是这样颠颠簸簸。 4. The starting time is the time the ballast needs to light and stabilise the lamp. 镇流器使灯启动并使其稳定工作所需的时间。', '过去式: ballasted 过去分词: ballasted 现在分词: ballasting 第三人称单数: ballasts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('feral', '[\'ferəl]', 'adj.野生的；凶猛的', '1. Never try to grab a feral cat if he/she is escaping. 不要试着抓取一只野生的猫如果他/她正在逃脱。 2. No one is dare to get close to the dog as it is too feral. 他们的狗太凶猛了，所以没有敢靠近它。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sill', '[sɪl]', 'n.基石(岩床底面)', '1. She neatly aligned the flower pots on the window sill. 她把花盆整齐地排成一行在窗台上。 2. The cat quickly jumped on to the window sill and ran away. 猫迅速跳到窗台上跑了。 3. Credit is the sill of not only commercial economy but also social morals. 信用既是商业经济的基石,又是社会道德的基石。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('precise', '[prɪ\'saɪs]', 'adj.精确的；恰好的；准确的；严格的', '1. With the new technique, measurement was claimed to be much more precise. 有了这种技术,人们断言测量的结果会精确得多。 2. At the precise moment that I put my foot on the step, the bus started. 恰恰就在我登上公共汽车踏板的时候，车子开动了。 3. I am not clear about the precise bearing of the word in this passage. 我说不准这个字在这段文章里的确切意义是什么。 4. Precise employees are highly appreciated in our company. 我们公司十分欣赏工作态度严谨的员工。', '名词: preciseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drip', '[drɪp]', 'n.滴；点滴；乏味的人 v.滴下；漏出', '1. A drip of water fell from the tap. 从龙头滴下一滴水。 2. The patient is on a drip. 病人正在输液。 3. The patient is put on a drip after her operation. 那个病人动过手术后就打点滴。 4. Don\'t be such a drip! Come and join in the fun. 别呆在那里了! 过来一起玩儿吧。 5. As water continues to drip, the icicle grows. 随着水不断下滴，冰柱的体积也慢慢增大。', '过去式: dripped 过去分词: dripped 现在分词: dripping 第三人称单数: drips');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('royalty', '[\'rɔɪəlti]', 'n.皇家；皇族 n.版税', '1. She claims to be descended from royalty. 她声称她是皇室后裔。 2. Salt was an important item on the table of royalty. 盐在皇家餐桌上占有重要的位置。 3. This palace was home to French royalty. 这座宫殿是法国皇族的住宅。 4. His income is mainly from royalty. 他的收入主要来自版税。', '名词复数: royalties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mendacious', '[men\'deɪʃəs]', 'adj.〈文〉虚假的；撒谎的', '1. The mendacious beggar told a different tale of woe at every house. 这个撒谎的乞丐对每一家都编了一个不同的悲伤的故事。', '副词: mendaciously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intuition', '[ˌɪntu\'ɪʃn]', 'n.直觉；直觉的知识', '1. He takes his ground on intuition. 他的意见是凭直觉。 2. She sensed what was wrong by intuition. 她凭直觉意识到什么地方出毛病了。 3. It was said in a flash of intuition. 这话是凭一刹那的直觉说出的。 4. She had an intuition that her friend was ill. 她有一种直觉:她的朋友病了。', '形容词: intuitional 副词: intuitionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meteorology', '[ˌmiːtiə\'rɑːlədʒi]', 'n.气象学；气象状态', '1. When it comes to meteorology,I\'m just a layman. 谈到气象学，我只是个门外汉。', '形容词: meteorological 副词: meteorologically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chase', '[tʃeɪs]', 'vt.追捕；追求；镂刻，雕刻；试图赢得 vi.奔跑；追赶 n.追捕；争取；狩猎', '1. Chase the cow out of the garden. 把牛逐出花园。 2. He chased (after) the burglar but couldn\'t catch him. 他追赶窃贼却未捉住。 3. Why do modern people chase material possessions? 为什么现在的人们追求物质财富？ 4. The criminal was caught after a car chase. 开着汽车追来追去才把罪犯捉住。', '过去式: chased 过去分词: chased 现在分词: chasing 第三人称单数: chases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intact', '[ɪn\'tækt]', 'adj.完好无缺的；原封不动的；未经触碰的', '1. Despite his misfortunes, his faith and optimism remained intact. 虽然他遭到一连串的不幸，他的信心和乐观丝毫未减。 2. You may have your money back on this woolen sweater if it is kept clean and intact. 如果羊毛衫保持清洁、完好无缺，您可以退款。 3. The money was returned intact by its finder. 钱原封未动地被捡拾者送还。 4. This stretch of wetlands has remained intact. 这块湿地一直保持着自然的面貌。', '副词: intactly 名词: intactness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dowdy', '[\'daʊdi]', 'adj.过时的；邋遢的；寒酸的；懒散的', '1. She looked very plain and dowdy. 她长得非常普通,衣着也过时。 2. The dowdy fellow is quite unlike the general run of my wife\'s guests. 这个邋里邋遢的家伙完全不象我妻子的其他客人。 3. I get so sick of women in dowdy old clothes and perpetual crepe. 我对那些穿得又丑又旧和永远带着黑纱的女人腻烦透了。 4. She made the other women look dowdy. 跟她相比其他妇女显得太懒散。', '形容词: dowdyish 副词: dowdily 比较级: dowdier 最高级: dowdiest 名词: dowdiness 名词复数: dowdies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distain', '[dɪ\'steɪn]', 'vt. <古>使变色； 弄脏； 伤害名誉', '1. Real Programmers distain structured programming. 真正的程序员鄙视结构化编程。 2. Distain each regulation of Yu Taobao later, decide housekeep then. 后来鄙视于淘宝的各项规则，于是决定自立门户。” 3. How to accomplish to the thing of disinclination distain? 怎么样对不感兴趣的事做到不屑？ 4. This makes the excuse of those people that distain to Ma Yun. 比如，他承认到现在为止阿里巴巴对雅虎中国的整合仍然不算成功，“收购雅虎中国，我们得到的最宝贵的东西，不是搜索技术，而是并购经验。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('curriculum', '[kə\'rɪkjələm]', 'n.全部课程；课程', '1. Our curriculum comprises Politics, Chinese, English and History. 我们的课程共有四门：政治、汉语、英语、历史。 2. Our mathematics curriculum is much more complicated now. 我们的数学课现在复杂得多了。', '形容词: curricular 名词复数: curricula');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trait', '[treɪt]', 'n.特征；特点；少许；一笔', '1. They suddenly exhibit a striking new trait. 它们突然呈现出一种新的显著特征。 2. One of his less attractive traits is criticizing his wife in public. 他有个不大讨人喜欢的特点，就是爱当众责备妻子。 3. Our CEO talks and behaves without a trait of authority. 我们公司的首席执行官言行举止没有一点官气。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lunatic', '[\'luːnətɪk]', 'n.疯子 adj.疯狂的；极蠢的', '1. People in this town know him as a lunatic. 这个镇上的人们称他为疯子。 2. You\'re driving on the wrong side of the road, you lunatic! 你现在是逆行开车，你这个蠢材！ 3. I really don\'t know what kind of man he really is; on one occasion, he is normal, and on another, he acts like a lunatic. 我真不了解他到底是怎样的人; 一会儿正常，一会儿又像个疯子。 4. The man\'s lunatic behavior is a menace to society. 那个人的疯狂行为构成对社会的威胁。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heave', '[hiːv]', 'v.用力举起；抛出；扔；恶心；（费力地）发出（叹息等） n.举；抛；起伏', '1. They heave at the heavy box, but can not lift it. 他们想搬动那只很重的箱子，但抬不起来。 2. He hove a chair through the window. 他把椅子从窗户中抛出。 3. Heave the rocks into the ravine. 把这些石头扔进深谷里。 4. It\'s a very bad thing to heave things around. 把东西到处乱扔是很不好的习惯。 5. With one more heave, we got the box onto the shelf. 我们再使把劲,就把箱子抬到架子上了。', '名词: heaver 过去式: heaved 过去分词: heaved 现在分词: heaving 第三人称单数: heaves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gourmand', '[gʊr\'mɑnd]', 'n.饕餮者；美食家；贪食者', '1. He was long famed as a gourmand and heavy smoker and drinker. 长期以来，他一直以嗜好美食和烟酒闻名。 2. If you are gourmand, come to our restaurant. 如果您是个美食家', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demonstrative', '[dɪ\'mɑːnstrətɪv]', 'adj.易流露感情的；论证的；[语法]指示的', '1. He greeted us in a demonstrative manner. 他热情地和我们打招呼。 2. He was neither impulsive nor demonstrative. 他既不感情用事,又不将喜怒哀乐形之于色。 3. Some people are more demonstrative than others. 有些人较爱流露感情. 4. These figures are demonstrative of our progress. 这些数字表明了我们的进步。', '副词: demonstratively 名词: demonstrativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aggravate', '[\'æɡrəveɪt]', 'vt.恶化；严重', '1. Scratching can aggravate the rash. 搔痒会使疹子发炎。 2. The Europeans\' appeasement policy towards irrational regimes would only aggravate the hidden dangers. 欧洲国家对非理性政权的绥靖政策,只会让潜在危机恶化。 3. This will aggravate the current scarcity of natural resources caused by environmental degradation. 这将会加剧由环境恶化而导致的自然资源匮乏的情况。 4. The lack of rain aggravated the already serious shortage of food. 干旱少雨使原本就很严重的粮食短缺问题更加严重。', '形容词: aggravative 副词: aggravatingly 名词: aggravator 过去式: aggravated 过去分词: aggravated 现在分词: aggravating 第三人称单数: aggravates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entreaty', '[ɪn\'triːti]', 'n.恳求；哀求', '1. Her gaze clung to him in entreaty. 她的眼光带着恳求的神色停留在他身上。 2. He knelt in front of the emperor with a look of entreaty. 他面带恳求的神态跪在皇帝面前。 3. She\'s so mean that all entreaty in the world will not get any money out of her. 她小气得要命，无论怎样恳求她，她都不会拿出钱来。 4. Mrs. Quilp dared only make a gesture of entreaty. 奎尔普太太仅能大着胆子做出一种哀求的姿势。', '名词复数: entreaties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('axle', '[\'æksl]', 'n.轮轴；车轴', '1. Clean axle shaft tubes and oil channels in housing. 清洁驱动桥轮轴底盘和壳内油路。 2. The bike chain drives a sun gear on the rear axle, which transmits power to planetary gears situated around it. 自行车的链条会驱动后轮轮轴上的太阳齿轮，将动力传送到四周的行星齿轮。 3. They weld the pieces of a broken axle. 他们焊接断了的车轴。 4. Remove the upper suspension arm nut and bolt at the axle bracket. 从车轴支架上拆去上端悬吊臂螺帽和螺栓。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('teeter', '[\'tiːtər]', 'v.摇摆；摇摇欲坠；犹豫不决；上下往复的运动 n.翘翘板', '1. She was teetering around in very high-heeled shoes. 她穿著高跟鞋摇摇晃晃地四处走。 2. The drunken man teetered on the edge of the pavement. 那醉汉在人行道边上东倒西歪的。 3. While watching a goat teeter on a tree limb, he said he had leukaemia. 他将目光投向一只踩在大树枝上摇摇欲坠的山羊，说，他患了白血病。 4. The children often teeter in the park. 孩子们常在公园玩跷跷板。 5. The performance of teeter board was very wonderful, and drew rounds of applause. 晃板的演出很精彩,引来人们阵阵的鼓掌。', '过去式: teetered 过去分词: teetered 现在分词: teetering 第三人称单数: teeters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stuffy', '[\'stʌfi]', 'adj.(房间等)不通气的；(人或事物)沉闷乏味的；自负的', '1. Lacking fresh air; stuffy. 不通风的缺乏新鲜空气的; 闷气的 2. The office was so stuffy that, knowing the Chief was away, the Secretary stripped to the shirt. 办公室里十分闷热，由于知道主任出去了，这个秘书脱得剩衬衫。 3. The atmosphere is very stuffy in here can we open a window? 这的空气很闷--咱们能把窗户打开吗? 4. Our office is really stuffy. 我们的办公室很闷。', '副词: stuffily 比较级: stuffier 最高级: stuffiest 名词: stuffiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bombastic', '[bɒm\'bæstɪk]', 'adj.夸大的', '1. The orator spoke in a bombastic manner. 这位演说家的讲话言过其实。 2. The candidate spoke in a bombastic way of all that he would do if elected. 候选人大肆吹嘘,一旦他当选将要如何如何。 3. The chairperson of this commission criticised that the police had adoped bombast gestures. 该委员会的主度批评了警方采取的高调姿态。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('electorate', '[ɪ\'lektərət]', 'n.(全体)选民', '1. The electorate is growing tired of his posturings. 选民对他的口是心非逐渐生厌。 2. Unemployment was the electorate\'s main concern. 失业是选民们最关切的问题。 3. A successful politician is one who keeps his finger on the pulse of the electorate. 一位成功的政治家是一个对选民有深刻了解的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accuracy', '[\'ækjərəsi]', 'n.准确(性)；精确度', '1. He\'s a man of accuracy and strict method. 他是个精细而严谨的人。 2. Accuracy is more important than speed in his new job. 对他的新工作，准确比速度更重要。 3. I can predict something with great accuracy. 我能很准确地预测某事。 4. It is impossible to say with any accuracy how many are affected. 无论如何也说不准受影响的有多少。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('witness', '[\'wɪtnəs]', 'n.目击者；证人 vt.目击；经历；见证；出席；观察 vi.证明；为(宗教信仰)做见证', '1. The witness was telling about the whole accident. 目击者正在讲述整个事故的过程。 2. The lawyer examined the witness. 律师讯问了证人。 3. A material witness failed to appear in court. 一名重要的证人没有出庭。 4. Did anyone witness the traffic accident? 有谁目击了这场交通事故？ 5. The empty cupboard was a witness of his poverty. 空的食橱就是他贫穷的证明。', '名词: witnesser 过去式: witnessed 过去分词: witnessed 现在分词: witnessing 第三人称单数: witnesses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evaporate', '[ɪ\'væpəreɪt]', 'v.蒸发；失去水分；消失', '1. If you heat the water,it will evaporate. 你要是把水加热，水会蒸发的。 2. He was afraid his savings would evaporate overnight. 他担心他的储蓄隔夜就蒸发了。 3. Once you have seen fear and depression evaporate in the hot, intense beacon of awareness, you want to repeat the process. 但你发现在热烈的，强度的觉知下，恐惧与压抑消失了，你会想去重复这个过程。 4. Nechyba and Vigdor also show that the peer effects evaporate once they consider the quality of teaching. 内希巴和维格多还表示，一旦他们将教育质量因素纳入考虑范围，同伴效应就消失了。', '形容词: evaporative 副词: evaporatively 名词: evaporation 过去式: evaporated 过去分词: evaporated 现在分词: evaporating 第三人称单数: evaporates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inferno', '[ɪn\'fɜːrnoʊ]', 'n.火海；地狱般的场所', '1. The oil wells turned into a raging inferno. 油井化为熊熊的火海。 2. People caught in that inferno were wailing and crying. 埋身火海的人在大声哭叫。 3. The inferno has killed 64 people in just five days. 大火仅在短短五天内就夺去了64人的生命。 4. The burning building became an inferno. 燃烧着的大楼成了地狱般的地方。', '名词复数: infernos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('affluent', '[\'æfluənt]', 'adj.富裕的 n.支流', '1. We live in an affluent society . 我们生活在一个富裕的社会中。 2. He was born to an affluent family. 他生在富裕人家。 3. A car and a house are considered as necessities in an affluent society. 在一个富裕的社会里,汽车和洋房都被当作是必需品。', '副词: affluently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mettlesome', '[\'metəlsəm]', 'adj.精神抖擞的', '1. The actor was considered a mettlesome dramatic performer. 这个演员被认为是个勇敢的戏剧演员。 2. The mettlesome horses prompted her to realize life rightly. 勇敢的马儿提示她如何正确对待生命。 3. The mettlesome actress resumed her career after recovering from a stroke. 从中风恢复过来后，坚强的女演员又重新开始了她的演艺生涯。 4. In the chilly autumn wind, the soldiers set out with a mettlesome and handsome bearing. 秋风飒飒中，战士们英姿勃发地出发了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imposing', '[ɪm\'poʊzɪŋ]', 'adj.令人难忘的；壮丽的 动词impose的现在分词.', '1. He was an imposing figure on stage. 他在舞台上的表演令人难忘。 2. The main hall of the temple is so imposing! 这个佛寺的大殿建造得真气派！ 3. She\'d never think of imposing herself. 她决不想勉强别人接纳自己。 4. You are always imposing on their generosity. 你总是在利用别人的慷慨而占便宜', '副词: imposingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resentment', '[rɪ\'zentmənt]', 'n.怨恨；愤恨', '1. A feeling of resentment urged him to abandon them. 一种怨恨的心情促使他离开了她们。 2. He shows no resentment towards anyone. 他对任何人都无怨恨。 3. There was hysteria in her cry of resentment. 她愤恨的喊声中带有歇斯底里。 4. To his Surprise Hitler showed no resentment or anger. 使他感到意外的是，希特勒竟未表示愤恨，也没有发脾气。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('labored', '[\'leɪbəd]', 'adj.(动作、呼吸等)困难的；吃力的 动词labor的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. An old woman labored up. 老妇人吃力地爬上。 2. The historic strike gave an enormous impetus to the whole American labor movement. 这次历史性的罢工对整个美国的劳工运动起了很大的推动作用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sprain', '[spreɪn]', 'v.扭伤 n.扭伤', '1. His odds are very poor after he sprained his wrist. 他扭伤了手腕，获胜的可能性极小。 2. The doctor ordered the man who had sprained his ankle to keep quiet a few days. 医生命令那扭伤足踝的人静养几天。 3. He got a foot sprain in his ankle. 他脚踝受了严重的扭伤。 4. Sprain and strain is caused by overstretching. 扭伤和拉伤都是由过度伸展导致。', '过去式: sprained 过去分词: sprained 现在分词: spraining 第三人称单数: sprains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repent', '[rɪ\'pent]', 'v.后悔；悔悟；忏悔', '1. He is kind and gracious to all sinners who repent. 他对忏悔的罪人一概慈悲为怀。 2. Bitterly did we repent our decision. 我们非常后悔做此决定。 3. Marry in haste, repent at leisure. [谚]结婚太急，后悔莫及; 草率结婚必后悔。 4. Have you nothing to repent of? 你没有可懊悔的事吗？', '名词: repenter 过去式: repented 过去分词: repented 现在分词: repenting 第三人称单数: repents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prerequisite', '[ˌpriː\'rekwəzɪt]', 'n.先决条件；前提 adj.作为前提的；必备的', '1. Careful study of the market is a prerequisite for success. 仔细研究市场情况是取得成功的先决条件。 2. Good muscles are one of the prerequisites of physical fitness. 肌肉发达是身体健康的一个必备条件。 3. Stability is a prerequisite for reform and development. 稳定是改革和发展的前提。 4. A sense of humour is prerequisite to understanding her work. 要理解她的作品就必须具有幽默感。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adequate', '[\'ædɪkwət]', 'adj.足够的；适当的；能胜任的', '1. We had adequate food for a week\'s journey. 我们有足够的食物可以做一星期的旅行。 2. He sought for an adequate solution to the problem. 他寻求解决这个问题的适当办法。 3. I hope he will be adequate to the job. 我希望他将胜任这一工作。', '副词: adequately 名词: adequacy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pastiche', '[pæ\'stiːʃ]', 'n.混成曲；模仿作品', '1. This particular kind of pastiche actually contributed to the failures in Iraq. 这种古怪的大杂烩其实导致了在伊拉克的失败。” 2. He has a gift for pastiche. 他有模仿他人作品的天赋。 3. This elaborate pastiche was too much for me. 画这样精致的一幅模仿作品是我力所不能及的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extinguish', '[ɪk\'stɪŋɡwɪʃ]', 'vt.熄灭；扑灭；消灭；使破灭；偿清', '1. Smoking is forbidden. Please extinguish your cigarettes. 吸烟是禁止的，请你把烟熄掉。 2. They tried to extinguish the flames. 他们竭力要把火焰扑灭。 3. The dictator wanted to extinguish all of his opposition in one go. 这位独裁者想一口气消灭所有对手。 4. Nothing could extinguish his faith in human nature. 没有什么能使他丧失对人性的信心。', '形容词: extinguishable 名词: extinguishment 过去式: extinguished 过去分词: extinguished 现在分词: extinguishing 第三人称单数: extinguishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('upfront', '[ˌʌp\'frʌnt]', 'adj.在前面的；预付的；直率的 adv 在前面； 在最前面.', '1. But on balance, the incentive to innovate is greater where access is granted more freely, because upfront profits are more valuable. 但是总的来说，当公司能够更自由地获得许可时，创新的诱惑力更大，因为预付的利益更有价值。 2. Another possible counter-action to sides playing the Direct Ball to targetmen upfront is to get your defenders to Man-mark the intended attacking targets out of the game. 应对采用直传球到最前面的进攻核心的球队的另一个可能的方法是，让你的后卫去盯住预期的进攻核心，让他们脱离比赛。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grasping', '[\'ɡræspɪŋ]', 'adj.贪心的；贪婪的 动词grasp的现在分词形式.', '1. Don\'t let those grasping taxi-drivers charge you too much. 不要让那些贪婪的出租汽车司机向你漫天要价。 2. It makes a woman grasping to see her children want for things. 一个女人看到她的孩子们缺这少那,就会变得贪婪。', '副词: graspingly 名词: graspingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desertion', '[dɪ\'zɜːʃn]', 'n.开小差；遗弃；潜逃', '1. The soldier was shot for desertion. 那个士兵因逃跑而被枪决了。 2. Desertion is a ground for divorce. 被配偶遗弃是离婚的充分理由。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('predisposition', '[ˌpriːdɪspə\'zɪʃn]', 'n.倾向；癖性；（易患病的）体质', '1. She has a predisposition to Huntington\'s disease. 她有患亨延顿氏症的倾向。 2. This prosperity has bought a sedentary lifestyle and a sugary diet, which may have triggered a genetic predisposition to diabetes among Arabs. 繁荣带来了凝滞不动的生活习惯和嗜糖的饮食结构，在阿拉伯人中这容易诱发高血糖的遗传倾向。 3. She has a predisposition to criticize others. 她有喜欢挑人毛病的癖性。 4. It creates and controls our genetic emotional profile as well as our predisposition to certain emotional conditions. 它创造和控制我们的遗传情感模式和对某一个情感状况容易得病的体质。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ferret', '[\'ferɪt]', 'n.白鼬；雪貂 v.用雪貂打猎；搜出', '1. Whatever plans they had for the ferret and himself had now been abandoned. 但他打算让白鼬做的事以及他自己的计划全都泡汤了。 2. Ferret and cats both like to chase furry stuff. 雪貂的个性和猫一样喜欢追逐毛茸茸的东西。 3. The detective ferret out the criminal. 那位侦探把犯人搜出来了。 4. See if you can ferret out any information about his past that we can use to discredit him. 看看你能否查获我们可以用来使他名誉扫地的历史记录。', '形容词: ferrety 名词: ferreter 过去式: ferreted 过去分词: ferreted 现在分词: ferreting 第三人称单数: ferrets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('callus', '[\'kæləs]', 'n.老茧 v.结硬皮', '1. I walked to him and took his outstretched hand which was rough with callus. 我走向他，握起他那长满老茧的手。 2. We have tried treatment, but the position of the callus revealed by the scan needed surgery. 我们尝试过药物治疗，但扫描显示，老茧的位置需要进行手术。 3. Heavy work callused his hands. 繁重的劳动使他的双手生出茧子来。', '名词复数: calluses 过去式: callused 过去分词: callused 现在分词: callusing 第三人称单数: calluses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proofread', '[\'pruːfriːd]', 'vt.校对', '1. It\'s a part of your duties to proofread. 校对是你的份内之事。 2. Proofread them for content and spelling. 就内容和拼写进行校对。', '名词: proofreader 过去式: proofread 过去分词: proofread 现在分词: proofreading 第三人称单数: proofreads');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rally', '[\'ræli]', 'n.集会；（价值等）回升；回合 vi.重整旗鼓；恢复精神；(人)集合起来 vt.嘲弄；重新召集；激励', '1. They will hold a peace rally. 他们要举行一个拥护和平的大会。 2. Countless people joined the rally at the square. 不计其数的人参加了广场上的集会。 3. After a brief rally share fall back to a new low. 股票经过一次短暂回升后回落到一个新的低点。 4. His sudden rally surprised the doctor. 他的突然复元使医生大为惊奇。 5. The team was thrown onto the defensive as their opponents rallied. 该队在对手重整旗鼓后,被迫采取守势。 6. The commander was able to rally the fleeing troops. 指挥官能够重整其溃散的部队。', '名词复数: rallies 过去式: rallied 过去分词: rallied 现在分词: rallying 第三人称单数: rallies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impresario', '[ˌɪmprə\'sɑːrioʊ]', 'n.制作人；经理人；主办者', '1. He is the London\'s leading theatrical impresario. 他是伦敦头号剧场的经理人。', '名词复数: impresarios');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vagrant', '[\'veɪɡrənt]', 'n.流浪汉；漂泊者；无赖 adj.流浪的；漂泊的；游荡的', '1. The vagrant had to beg for money. 那个流浪汉不得不乞求钱财。 2. You shall be a vagrant and a wanderer on earth. 你终会沦为一个流浪汉,到处漂泊。 3. We met a band of vagrant beggars there. 我们在那里遇到了一伙流浪的乞丐。 4. After leading a vagrant life, he was too glad to get back to his home town. 经过一段漂泊的生活,他巴不得回到家乡。', '副词: vagrantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('helmet', '[\'helmɪt]', 'n.头盔；安全帽', '1. The sword bit the knight\'s helmet. 剑刺穿了武士的头盔。 2. A miner\'s lamp is fixed onto his helmet. 矿灯固定在矿工的头盔上。 3. The safety helmet is held on by an elastic strap. 安全帽用一根松紧带系住。 4. All visitors to the site must wear safety helmet. 到工地的所有参观者必须带上安全帽。', '形容词: helmeted 过去式: helmeted 过去分词: helmeted 现在分词: helmeting 第三人称单数: helmets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contrived', '[kən\'traɪvd]', 'adj.人为的；做作的；不自然的 动词contrive的过去式和过去分词.', '1. In application of material, we can\'t totally cast away the contrived things. 在物质的运用上，我们也已经深陷其中，完完全全的脱离不掉人为的参与了。 2. If you read between the lines, you can detect his contrived explanation. 在字里行间，你可以看出他牵强的解释。 3. The book\'s happy ending seemed contrived. 这部书大团圆的结局读来让人感到不真实。 4. The humour of the play is self-conscious and contrived. 这部剧的幽默是刻意而为的，而且牵强做作。', '副词: contrivedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emergency', '[i\'mɜːrdʒənsi]', 'n.突发事件；紧急状态 adj.应急的；紧急的；备用的', '1. She has the ability to keep calm in an emergency. 她有处变不惊的本事。 2. We took the emergency in our stride. 我们泰然地处理了紧急情况。 3. Ring the bell in an emergency. 情况紧急时请按铃。 4. The rioting grew worse and the government declared a state of emergency. 骚乱恶化，政府只得宣布进入紧急状态。 5. He has made every arrangement to meet any emergency. 他已作好了应急的一切准备。', '名词复数: emergencies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('braggadocio', '[ˌbræɡə\'doʊtʃioʊ]', 'n.自夸；吹牛大王', '1. He was disliked because his manner was always full of braggadocio. 人们讨厌他,因为他老是吹牛。 2. Great Leap Forward period braggadocio atlas, ha-ha!!! 首页>>军事历史>>大跃进时期的吹牛图集,哈哈!!! 3. American frontiersman and folk hero known for his marksmanship, fighting skills, and braggadocio. 芬克，麦克1770?－1822以枪法、斗技和吹牛而出名的美国拓荒者和民间英雄人物 4. I must confess there is an element of braggadocio: a marathon is something that will be accomplished only by a small subset of society. 我还必须承认有自夸的因素，因为跑马拉松只有极少数人能完成。', '名词复数: braggadocios');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('magnanimous', '[mæɡ\'nænɪməs]', 'adj.度量大的；宽大的；有雅量的；高尚的', '1. He is a magnanimous person. 他是个宽宏大量的人。 2. He is a leader who is magnanimous in victory. 他是个在胜利时宽宏大度的领袖。 3. He was magnanimous in defeat and praised his opponent\'s skill. 他对失败表现得很洒脱，并且赞扬了对手的才能。', '副词: magnanimously 名词: magnanimousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('libretto', '[lɪ\'bretoʊ]', 'n.歌词集；歌剧剧本', '1. The printed libretto was handsomely got up. 这本印刷的歌剧剧本装帧得很美观。', '名词复数: librettos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compelling', '[kəm\'pelɪŋ]', 'adj.引人注目的；紧迫的；令人信服的', '1. Her latest book makes compelling reading. 她新出的书读起来扣人心弦。 2. She was really a strange, eager, compelling young woman. 她真是个奇特，热切而令人难以抗拒的年轻女人。 3. Leaves grown very lush, flowers are opening in full swing, very compelling. 树叶长得很茂盛，花也开得如火如荼，非常引人注目。 4. I have no compelling reasons to refuse. 我没有驱使我拒绝的理由。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loft', '[lɔːft]', 'n.阁楼', '1. We need the steps to get into the loft. 我们上阁楼要用摺梯. 2. The farmer piled straw in the loft. 农民把稻草堆在阁楼上。 3. He\'s living in a converted loft in lower Manhattan. 他住在下曼哈顿的一间改建的阁楼里。', '过去式: lofted 过去分词: lofted 现在分词: lofting 第三人称单数: lofts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rapscallion', '[ræp\'skæljən]', 'n.流氓；恶棍', '1. Any old ravening rapscallion can rattle on and rave about things he doesn’t like. 也许是七音符，也许是天才宝贝，也许是宝马王子的初恋，看多了张根锡，于是梦里梦外，总有些与他的牵连。 2. Strong Practicalism and high view of beauty in Greek mythology agreed with his “half rapscallion”. 希腊神话强烈的现世主义精神，对于生的热烈追求，迎合了他“半流氓”的思想特点；', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disgorge', '[dɪs\'ɡɔːrdʒ]', 'v.吐出；流出；涌出；被迫交出；下客', '1. She was trying hard to disgorge a fish bone. 她拚命想把鱼刺吐出来。 2. The Avon disgorges into the Severn. 埃文河流入塞文河。 3. Crowds disgorged from the theatre into the dark street. 人流从戏院涌出，进入了黑洞洞的街道。 4. They persuaded him to disgorge the missing documents. 他们劝他交出不见的文件。', '名词: disgorgement 过去式: disgorged 过去分词: disgorged 现在分词: disgorging 第三人称单数: disgorges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('guise', '[ɡaɪz]', 'n.装束；外观；伪装；借口', '1. They spoke to me under the guise of friendship. 他们伪装成友善的样子对我说话。 2. But tyranny also appeared in another guise. 但是暴政总是伪装成另一种形式。 3. Some will be based on misjudgments, and others will simply be pretextual - justifying aggression under the guise of pre-emption. 一些情况可能是建立在判断错误的基础上，其他情况只是借口，即在预防的伪装下试图证明进攻的正当性。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cripple', '[\'krɪpl]', 'n.跛者；残废 v.削弱；使...瘫痪', '1. They helped the cripple up to the bank. 他们把那跛脚的人扶上岸。 2. It is impolite to make fun of a cripple. 取笑一个跛足是不礼貌的。 3. A long delay might cripple me in a way. 长期拖下去可能在某些方面把我拖垮了。 4. His first task was to cripple the enemy at sea. 他的首要任务是使海上的敌人失去战斗力。', '名词: crippler 过去式: crippled 过去分词: crippled 现在分词: crippling 第三人称单数: cripples');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desperado', '[ˌdespə\'rɑːdoʊ]', 'n.恶汉；亡命徒', '1. The desperado cowboy has caught all of the bank robbers. 那个孤胆英雄式的牛仔抓住了抢劫银行的所有歹徒。', '名词复数: desperadoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nonchalance', '[\'nɒnʃələns]', 'n.不关心；无动于衷；冷淡', '1. Some journalists criticize her nonchalance and indifference. 一些记者批评她的冷淡与漠不关心。 2. One year later, I came back to Guangzhou, and the unusual nonchalance between us was sensed by our sensitive friends, who set a trap for us.We met again at a karaoke hall. 一年后我回到广州，我们之间的异常冷淡让敏感的朋友察觉，他们精心设下了布局。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arachnid', '[ə\'ræknɪd]', 'n.蛛形纲动物', '1. Look no further than the Medical Arachnid. “医疗蜘蛛”正是你不二的选择。 2. An arachnid of the order Acarina, which includes the mites and ticks. 螨，蜱，壁虱蛛形目动物，包括螨和蜱 3. A pincerlike claw of a crustacean or an arachnid,such as a lobster,crab,or scorpion. 螯如龙、虾、蟹或蝎等甲壳纲动物蜘蛛纲动物的钳样爪 4. Their lower bodies are supported by six spindly arachnid limbs and their heavily bandaged torsos are human in form. 由六条细长的节肢类的腿支撑着低矮的身体，类人躯干缠绕着大量绷带。', '形容词: arachnidan');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cocoon', '[kə\'kuːn]', 'n.茧；茧状物 v.包围；包裹', '1. Silkworms make cocoons. 蚕做茧。 2. A cocoon is a kind of silk covering made by an insect. 蚕茧是由昆虫制造的一种由丝组成的外包层。 3. The children tore the cocoon open to see if there was a pupa. 孩子们撕开蚕茧看看里面有没有蛹。 4. Families cocoon around the TV set most evenings. 好多家庭大部分晚上都围在电视机前看电视。', '过去式: cocooned 过去分词: cocooned 现在分词: cocooning 第三人称单数: cocoons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ephemeral', '[ɪ\'femərəl]', 'adj.短暂的；朝生暮死的 n.生存极短时间的事物', '1. Most newspapers are of ephemeral interest. 多数报纸只能引起读者短暂的注意。 2. Slang words are often ephemeral. 俚语往往只流行于一时。 3. Such novels came forward to enjoy ephemeral popularity only. 这样的小说只是昙花一现的东西而已。', '副词: ephemerally 名词: ephemerality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('metropolitan', '[ˌmetrə\'pɑːlɪtən]', 'adj.大都市的；大主教区的 n.大都市的居民；大主教', '1. Metropolitan residents are used to fast rhythm. 大都市的居民习惯于快节奏。 2. He can not adjust himself to the pace of metropolitan life. 他适应不了都市生活的节奏。 3. She left the small island and became famous in metropolitan France. 她离开小岛而在法国的大都市中成名。 4. Metropolitan residents are used to fast rhythm. 大都市的居民习惯于快节奏。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gratify', '[\'ɡrætɪfaɪ]', 'v.使满足；使高兴', '1. Now that she has a job in France she can gratify her desire to see Europe. 既然现在她在法国工作，那就可以满足她游览欧洲的愿望了。 2. I was gratified to see how much my birthday present was appreciated. 看到我的生日礼物受到极大的赞赏，我感到高兴。', '形容词: gratifying 副词: gratifyingly 名词: gratifier 过去式: gratified 过去分词: gratified 现在分词: gratifying 第三人称单数: gratifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('xerophyte', '[\'zɪrəˌfaɪt]', 'n.旱生植物', '1. A xerophyte is a plant which is able to survive in an ecosystem with little available water or moisture. 旱生植物可以在水分极少或湿度极小的生态环境中生存。', '形容词: xerophytic 副词: xerophytically 名词: xerophytism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('garble', '[\'gɑːbəl]', 'vt.断章取义；曲解；混淆 n.断章取义；混淆', '1. Don\'t garble out of my statement. 别断章取义地引用我的话。 2. They \"gobble\", and Gore\'s gobbling soon turnssintos\"garble\". 它们咯咯叫，但戈尔的咯咯叫声(gobble)很快就变成了“garble”，意思是“表达不清，说糊涂话”。 3. The injured man is still groggy and can only give a garble account of the accident. 受伤的男子仍不很清醒，只能含糊地说出事故的情形。 4. Then it puts its packet on the wire and simultaneously listens to see if any other device sent something at the same time, which would cause a collision and garble both packets. 然后把该包放到网上，同时听一听看看在同一时刻是否有其它的设备也在发送信息，因为它会引起碰撞，并弄坏两个包。', '名词: garbler 过去式: garbled 过去分词: garbled 现在分词: garbling 第三人称单数: garbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rejoice', '[rɪ\'dʒɔɪs]', 'v.（使）高兴；（使）欢喜', '1. I always rejoice in my comrades\' achievements. 我总是为同志们的成就感到高兴。 2. We rejoiced at the good news. 我们为这个好消息而高兴。 3. They all rejoiced to hear the happy news. 他们都很乐于听到这个令人高兴的消息。 4. It rejoices my heart to hear that my son is still alive. 听到儿子仍活着，我心很高兴。', '名词: rejoicer 过去式: rejoiced 过去分词: rejoiced 现在分词: rejoicing 第三人称单数: rejoices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arboreal', '[ɑːr\'bɔːriəl]', 'adj.树木的；栖于树木的，生活在树上的；像树的', '1. Human vision like that of other primates has evolved in an arboreal environment. 人类的视觉，和其它灵长目动物的一样，是在丛林环境中进化出来的。 2. Man was evolved from an ancestor that was probably arboreal. 人大概是从住在树上的祖先进化而来的。 3. Squirrels are arboreal creatures. 松鼠是栖於树上的动物。', '副词: arboreally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impermeability', '[ɪmpɜːmjəbɪ\'lɪtɪ]', 'n.不能渗透的性质或状态；不渗透性；不透过性', '1. Beautiful color prints, high impermeability to gas and moisture-proof. 优质彩色印刷，高气体阻隔性及防潮性。 2. In this paper, the anlysis is presented to study the impermeability and crack resistance of basement concrete wall. 本文尝试聚丙烯纤维砼应用于地下室砼墙抗裂防水。 3. It is superior to sodium silicate cement in impermeability, resistance to dilute acid and cohesive strength. 钾水玻璃胶泥的抗渗透性、耐稀酸性和粘结强度高于钠水玻璃胶泥。 4. The detecting results show that concrete has no cracks and has excellent impermeability. 现场检测表明，混凝土未出现裂纹，且抗渗性良好，达到了预期效果。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('capricious', '[kə\'prɪʃəs]', 'adj.变化无常的；任性的', '1. He judged her to be capricious, and easily weary of the pleasure of the moment. 他认为她是任性的，很容易对一时的快乐产生厌倦。', '副词: capriciously 名词: capriciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cadge', '[kædʒ]', 'v.乞讨；（无缘故地）索要', '1. Homeless people forced to cadge in subway stations. 无家可归的人们被迫在地铁站里乞讨。 2. May I cadge a cigarette from you? 我可以向你要支香烟吗? 3. Could I cadge a lift with you? 我能顺便坐你的汽车吗? 4. He\'s always cadging meals from his friends. 他总吃朋友的便宜饭。', '名词: cadger 过去式: cadged 过去分词: cadged 现在分词: cadging 第三人称单数: cadges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comatose', '[\'koʊmətoʊs]', 'adj.昏睡状态的；昏迷的', '1. I always feel a bit comatose after dinner. 我在晚饭后总觉得有点昏昏欲睡。 2. There are two kinds of distractions of mind, they are comatose and unsteady minds. 人心的散乱有两种：一是昏沉，一是浮动。 3. He was comatose and had a severe fever and tachycardia. 他处于昏迷状态，伴高热和心动过速。 4. The patient\'s condition is very critical and he is in a comatose state. 病人的情况非常危急，他已经处于昏迷状态。', '副词: comatosely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trinket', '[\'trɪŋkɪt]', 'n.廉价的小装饰品；不值钱的珠宝', '1. A small, exquisitely wrought trinket. 珠宝，首饰小巧精致的装饰物 2. A small mass-produced article, such as a toy or trinket. 新奇的小物件创新大量生产的小物件，如玩具或小装饰品 3. He buy her trinket and take her to the theater. 他给她购买小装饰品并带她去看戏。 4. He bought her some trinket. 他给她买了些不值钱的珠宝。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('afflict', '[ə\'flɪkt]', 'vt.使苦恼；折磨', '1. I don\'t want to afflict you with my troubles. 我不想使你为我的困难而苦恼。 2. He was afflicted with cancer. 他患了癌症。 3. AIDS and cancer are maladies that afflict humanity. 爱滋病和癌症是折磨人类的疾病. 4. He will not afflict us beyond our power of endurance. 不会折磨得我们超过了承受能力的。', '形容词: afflictive 副词: afflictively 名词: afflicter 过去式: afflicted 过去分词: afflicted 现在分词: afflicting 第三人称单数: afflicts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ocular', '[\'ɑːkjələr]', 'adj.眼睛的；视觉的；目击的 n.目镜', '1. The ocular defects made him lose the chance for the job. 视力缺陷让他失去了这个工作的机会。 2. It was the ocular proof that the criminal could not deny. 这是罪犯不能否认的目击证据。 3. The Huygens ocular, which dates back over 250 years is still in wide use today. 二百五十多年前的惠更斯目镜今天还在广泛使用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thread', '[θred]', 'n.线；思路；螺纹；线索；细丝；帖子 vt.穿过；穿线于；遍布 vi.滴下成丝状；小心地通过；蜿蜒前进', '1. How many spools of thread did you use? 你用了几轴线? 2. The thread seems to match the cloth. 这线和这布似乎很相称。 3. I need one more spool of thread before finishing the embroidery. 再来一轴线我就可以完成这幅刺绣了。 4. He passed me a coil of thread. 他递给我一卷线。', '名词: threader 过去式: threaded 过去分词: threaded 现在分词: threading 第三人称单数: threads');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expatriate', '[ˌeks\'peɪtriət]', 'n.移居外国者', '1. Many people, Chinese and expatriate, did just that. 无论是中国人还是外国人,许多人都在这么做。 2. He is content to remain an expatriate the rest of his life. 他满足于馀生流亡于国外。 3. She worked harder than most of my wealthy expatriate students. 她学习用功，比我教的大部分有钱的侨民子弟都要用功。', '名词: expatriation 过去式: expatriated 过去分词: expatriated 现在分词: expatriating 第三人称单数: expatriates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('respondent', '[rɪ\'spɑːndənt]', 'n.应答者；被告 adj.回答的；应答的；感应的', '1. Only 62 percent of respondents said they were satisfied. 只有百分之六十二的回答者表示他们满意。 2. The respondent was not acting bona fide. 被告的行为不真诚。 3. He stated that he had never seen the respondent. 他说他从未见过被告。 4. The police must first order the respondent to stop the nuisance. 警察必须首先命令被告停止伤害行为。', '名词: respondence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('centrifugal', '[ˌsentrɪ\'fjuːɡl]', 'adj.离心的', '1. Harmful gases must be drawn out by centrifugal ventilator. 有害气体必须通过离心式通风装置排出。 2. The handdriven generator is equipped with a centrifugal governor. 手摇直流发电机装有离心调速装置。', '副词: centrifugally 名词: centrifugalism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mammoth', '[\'mæməθ]', 'adj.巨大的；庞大的 n.长毛象；猛犸', '1. Building the new railroad will be a mammoth job. 修建那条新铁路将是一项巨大工程。 2. The mammoth buffalo roamed the plains. 庞大的野牛群出没在这些平原上。 3. By comparison, the Great Wall in China is a mammoth presence. 相比之下，中国的长城真是个庞然大物。 4. The woolly mammoth was a month old when she died. 这只长毛象刚满月就不幸身亡。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('phenomena', '[fə\'nɒmɪnə]', 'n.现象 名词phenomenon的复数形式.', '1. He finally found out the method for applying his theory to phenomena. 他最终发现了把他的理论应用到现象中的方法。 2. He strongly believes that there must be a physical explanation for these strange phenomena. 他坚信这些奇怪的现象一定可以根据自然规律作出解释。 3. We should dare to combat unhealthy phenomena. 我们要敢于同不良现象作斗争。 4. We cannot relate these two phenomena. 我们无法说明这两种现象之间的关系。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('constitute', '[\'kɑːnstətuːt]', 'vt.构成；组成；任命；建立；制定', '1. Twelve months constitute one year. 十二个月构成一年。 2. Correct grammar and sentence structure do not in themselves constitute good writing. 正确的语法和句子结构本身并不能构成一篇好文章。 3. The committee is constituted of members of all three parties. 委员会由所有三个政党的成员组成。 4. He was constituted representative of the party. 他被任命为该党的代表。', '名词: constituter 过去式: constituted 过去分词: constituted 现在分词: constituting 第三人称单数: constitutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('falsify', '[\'fɔːlsɪfaɪ]', 'vt.伪造，篡改；歪曲；改变公认的规则；证明…是假的', '1. They have to falsify account to get balance. 他们必须做假帐才能平衡帐目。 2. All those who try to falsify history are bound to end up at criminals in history. 一切伪造历史的人必然会成历史的罪人。 3. Her speech in Parliament was falsified by the newspapers. 她在议会里的发言被报纸歪曲了。', '名词: falsification 过去式: falsified 过去分词: falsified 现在分词: falsifying 第三人称单数: falsifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('descry', '[dɪ\'skraɪ]', 'v.远远看到；发现；察看', '1. I descry a sail on the horizon. 我看见在天水交接处的轮船。 2. Our host descried a gentleman of unusual appearance standing at the far end of the hall. 我们的男主人远远看到有个外表不俗的绅士站在大厅的尽头。', '名词: descrier 过去式: descried 过去分词: descried 现在分词: descrying 第三人称单数: descries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('soothe', '[suːð]', 'v.缓和；使安静；安慰', '1. He smeared some balm on his hand to soothe the pain. 他在手上涂了些药膏来止痛。 2. He tried to soothe the crying child. 他试着去哄那个在哭的孩子。 3. The soft texture of the blanket can soothe her. 这条毯子柔软的触感可以让她安静下来。 4. A nice cup of tea will soothe your nerves. 一杯好茶可以使你的心绪平静下来。', '名词: soother 过去式: soothed 过去分词: soothed 现在分词: soothing 第三人称单数: soothes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quota', '[\'kwoʊtə]', 'n.限额；配额；定额；最低票数', '1. Why is my Daily Resultb Quota so sall? 为什么我的每日工作限额那么小？ 2. Calculate the total Sentence Quota of the summary. 计算出摘要应包含的句子的限额。 3. The committee reversed its decision on import quota. 委员会取消了对进口货物的配额的决定。 4. The quota on import cars has been lifted. 对汽车的进口配额已被取消。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('congenial', '[kən\'dʒiːniəl]', 'adj.同性质的；适意的；趣味相同的；友善的', '1. No fuss was made in my day if a new writer took from an old one whatever material he found congenial. 在我那个时代，如果一个新作家从一个老作家的作品中摘取了他能用的合适材料，并不受到反对。 2. In the next year he obtained, through the good offices of an old friend, a post with a publishing firm which, though not highly paid, he found more congenial. 第二年，通过一个老朋友帮忙，他在一家出版公司谋到一个职位，薪水虽不高，却更令他感到惬意。 3. They are of congenial temper. 他们的性情相投。 4. I found him very congenial. 我发现他跟人很合得来。', '副词: congenially 名词: congeniality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ceramic', '[sə\'ræmɪk]', 'adj.陶器的 n.陶器；陶瓷学', '1. These ceramic tiles are the ultimate in modern kitchen design. 这种瓷砖是现代厨房装修中的极品。 2. There is a ceramic shop in the Arcade. 商店街中有一家陶器店。 3. I know a retired electrical engineer who has become a highly-paid ceramic artist. 我还认识一个退休的电力工程师，退休之后他成为了一名身价颇高的陶器艺术家。 4. There is a ceramic shop in the Arcade. 商店街中有一家陶器店。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gospel', '[\'ɡɑːspl]', 'n.新约圣经四福书之一；福音；真理', '1. The man was preaching the Gospel. 此人在传布福音。 2. Today there is another gospel being preached. 当今世代，所传讲的福音已是另一个福音。 3. We took the teacher\'s words as gospel. 我们把老师的话当作真理。 4. Then Paul re-iterates the great facts of the Gospel once more. 最后，保罗再次重申福音的伟大真理。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amortize', '[\'æmərtaɪz]', 'v.分期偿还；摊还 =amortise(英).', '1. He refused to amortize the debt. 他拒绝分期偿还债务。 2. I intend to amortize the total cost of the car over three years. 我打算用三年时间分期偿还汽车的所有费用。 3. He wanted to amortize his fixed rental cost by stretching the operating hours. 他想用延长营业时间来分摊固定的租金。 4. But for other long-term expenses, you have to amortize them over the useful life . 但是对于其他的长期待摊费用，你必须根据使用年限进行摊销。', '形容词: amortizable 过去式: amortized 过去分词: amortized 现在分词: amortizing 第三人称单数: amortizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dismay', '[dɪs\'meɪ]', 'n.沮丧；绝望 vt.使 ... 沮丧；使 ... 惊愕', '1. The enemy retreated in perfect dismay. 敌人沮丧地退去。 2. To my dismay, he made the same mistakes. 让我感到沮丧的是，他又犯了同样的错误。 3. He watched the burning bouse with dismay. 他绝望地看着着火的房子。 4. The teacher was dismayed at the students\' lack of response. 老师对学生的毫无反应感到沮丧。', '副词: dismayingly 过去式: dismayed 过去分词: dismayed 现在分词: dismaying 第三人称单数: dismays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scenario', '[sə\'nærioʊ]', 'n.剧本；情节梗概', '1. The scenario was remade 12 times. 剧本总共修改了12次。 2. A detailed script or scenario consulted to avoid discrepancies from shot to shot in a film. 一个好的电影剧本是制作一部好影片的重要因素。 3. It looked ominously like we were about to repeat the earlier scenario. 而且看上去很不妙，好象我们又得重复上次那一幕了。 4. Take a glaring scenario closer home. 我们周围地区便有些很明显的例子。', '名词复数: scenarios');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exploit', '[ɪk\'splɔɪt]', 'vt.剥削；利用；开发；开拓 n.功绩；英勇行为', '1. The capitalists exploit the workers in order to maximize profits. 资本家剥削工人是为了使利润最大化。 2. You must exploit all your spare time to learn English. 你必须利用一切空闲时间来学习英语。 3. People should read the related regulations before they exploit natural resources. 在开发自然资源前，人们应该先了解相关的规定。 4. We should look for blank parts in the market and exploit new market continuously. 我们应找准市场空白,不断开拓新市场。 5. Great men are remembered for their notable exploits. 伟人们因其丰功伟绩而被世人铭记。', '形容词: exploitable 副词: exploitatively 名词: exploitability 过去式: exploited 过去分词: exploited 现在分词: exploiting 第三人称单数: exploits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solder', '[\'sɑːdər]', 'n.焊接剂；接合物 v.焊接', '1. Generally the same fluxes will work for lead-free solder. 一般来说,相同的焊剂用于无铅焊料是有效的。 2. An ideal connection that puts any solder to shame. 这种理想的连结方式，让其它各类接合方式瞠乎其后。 3. He soldered the wire back on. 他把金属丝重新焊上去了。 4. Surface to solder are gold and clean. 待焊接的表面是清洁的金面。', '名词: solderer 过去式: soldered 过去分词: soldered 现在分词: soldering 第三人称单数: solders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impervious', '[ɪm\'pɜːrviəs]', 'adj.不能渗透的；不为所动的', '1. This material is impervious to rainwater. 这种材料防雨。 2. Rubber boots are impervious to water. 橡胶鞋是防水的。 3. He is impervious to criticism. 他对批评我行我素。', '副词: imperviously 名词: imperviousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('effigy', '[\'efɪdʒi]', 'n.肖像；雕像；模拟像', '1. In Maryland, protesters hung a junior congressman in effigy. 在马里兰州，抗议者们举着一位资深国会议员的肖像表示不满。 2. There the effigy stands, and stares from age to age across the changing ocean. 雕像依然耸立在那儿，千秋万载地凝视着那变幻无常的大海。 3. There is an effigy of Einstein around the corner. 在拐角处有爱因斯坦的模拟像。', '名词复数: effigies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('madcap', '[\'mædkæp]', 'adj.鲁莽的；狂妄的 n.鲁莽的人；狂妄', '1. A madcap four minutes shortly after the interval seemingly ended the game as a contest. 下半场开始疯狂的4分钟看起来要让比赛进入垃圾时间了。 2. That last is Berowne, the merry madcap. 最后的一个就是俾隆，他是个快活鲁莽的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bullyrag', '[\'bʊliːˌræg]', 'vt.威吓；恐吓', '1. If you are unwilling to or can\'t help, you should speak of it directly and don\'t nonsense to bullyrag him. 不愿意或力有不及则明言之，不要说些不着边际的话，吃别人豆腐。 2. and here they can\'t come and pick at a feller and bullyrag him so. 而且这儿也没谁来欺负你。” 3. i don t ever get enough to eat , gen ally - and here they can t come and pick at a feller and bullyrag him so . 就这么生活，我觉得再好也不过了。平常我连顿饱饭也没吃过而且这儿也没谁来欺负你。” 4. Synonyms bludgeon, bluster, ', NULL);
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acquiesce', '[ˌækwi\'es]', 'vi.默许；勉强同意', '1. She wants to marry a poor primary-school teacher but her parents will never acquiesce. 她想嫁一位贫穷小学教师，但她的父母永不会默许。 2. Even if the rest of the world is willing to acquiesce in the consolidation of copyright power in the entertainment industries, we should not be. 即使世界上的其他国家默许娱乐业的著作霸权，我们也不应该这样做。', '过去式: acquiesced 过去分词: acquiesced 现在分词: acquiescing 第三人称单数: acquiesces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('liken', '[\'laɪkən]', 'v.比作；比拟；使像', '1. Someone likens his voice to the croak of a bull-frog. 有人把他的声音比作牛蛙的叫声。 2. Life can be likened to a journey with an unknown destination. 生命可以被比作一次不知目的地的旅行。 3. We often liken the heart to a pump. 我们常把心脏比拟为水泵。', '过去式: likened 过去分词: likened 现在分词: likening 第三人称单数: likens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cathedral', '[kə\'θiːdrəl]', 'n.大教堂', '1. Photography is strictly forbidden in the cathedral. 教堂内严禁摄影。 2. This street offers a fine vista of the cathedral. 这条街的尽头是个大教堂，远远望去非常好看。 3. The dome of St. Paul Cathedral is well known in the world. 圣保罗教堂的圆顶闻名于世。 4. This cathedral was regarded as a miracle in architectural history. 这座大教堂被认为是建筑史上的奇迹。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hardheaded', '[\'hɑːd\'hedɪd]', 'adj.顽固的；现实的；冷静的；脚踏实地的', '1. Hardheaded solve a few problems. 脚踏实地解决一些问题。 2. If you weren\'t so hardheaded, maybe I could teach you something. 假如你不是那么顽固,也许我可以教你点儿什么。 3. Have you ever been described as stubborn or hardheaded? By whom? 你被人说过固执吗？是谁说的？ 4. A word that Wang Shutong likes most is: Dreamy Gao Yuan, hardheaded. 王树彤最喜欢的一句话是：梦想高远，脚踏实地。', '副词: hardheadedly 名词: hardheadedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stentorian', '[sten\'tɔːriən]', 'adj.极洪亮的；非常响亮的', '1. The stentorian tones of the auctioneer, calling out to clear the way, now announced that the sale was about to commence. 拍卖人用洪亮的声音招呼大家闪开一点，然后宣布拍卖即将开始。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sleigh', '[sleɪ]', 'n.雪橇 vi.坐雪橇', '1. Sleigh bells tinkled in the distance. 从远处传来串串的雪橇铃响。 2. The dogs are harnessed to a sleigh. 这些狗被套在一辆雪橇上。', '名词: sleigher 过去式: sleighed 过去分词: sleighed 现在分词: sleighing 第三人称单数: sleighs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('supplement', '[\'sʌplɪmənt]', 'n.增刊；补充物 vt.增补；补充', '1. It comes out each week and it has a magazine supplement. 每周出版一期，还附有杂志增刊。 2. The upset supplement supplier went up with the puppet to the upper room for supper. 心烦意乱的增刊供给者与傀儡一起到上面的房间吃晚餐。 3. The money I got was a useful supplement to my ordinary income. 我得到的那笔钱是很管用的外快。 4. Man\'s work is rather the needful supplement to himself than the outcome of it. 一个人的工作更多地是他自身的必要补充,而非这种补充的结果。 5. She gives private lessons to supplement her income. 她给私人授课以贴补收入。', '形容词: supplementary 名词: supplementarity 过去式: supplemented 过去分词: supplemented 现在分词: supplementing 第三人称单数: supplements');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sampler', '[\'sæmplər]', 'n.刺绣样本；集锦；采样员；取样器', '1. This sampler can be used only in streams shallow enough to be waded. 这种取样器只能用在能涉渡的浅水河流上。 2. The simplest type of rain sampler is essentially a funnel and bottle. 最简单的雨水采样器，实质上是一个漏斗和瓶子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pharmacology', '[ˌfɑːrmə\'kɑːlədʒədʒi]', 'n.药理学；药物学', '1. She took up a post as research assistant in the Department of Pharmacology. 她在药物学系做研究助理。', '形容词: pharmacologic 副词: pharmacologically 名词: pharmacologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('onset', '[\'ɑːnset]', 'n.攻击；进攻；开始', '1. The fierce onset of the enemy broke the ranks of the army. 敌人的猛烈攻击致使全军大乱。 2. Our troops withstood the onset of the enemy. 我们的部队抵挡住了敌人的进攻。 3. The onset of the enemy took us by surprise. 敌人的进攻出乎我们意外。 4. He went to see a doctor at the onset of a fever. 他开始发烧时便去看医生了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('multifarious', '[ˌmʌltɪ\'feriəs]', 'adj.多种的；各式各样的', '1. The contents are multifarious and disorderly. 内容庞杂。 2. It has a multifarious and bright prospect. 其发展前景是多样化而光明的。 3. They cannot afford the multifarious expenses. 他们无力承担这些五花八门的开支。 4. All of us have multifarious attitudes, which results in our pain. 我们所有的人都有各种各样的态度，这是我们的痛苦。', '副词: multifariously 名词: multifariousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crucial', '[\'kruːʃl]', 'adj.决定性的；关键的', '1. Her work has been crucial to the project\'s success. 她的工作对项目的成功至关重要。 2. It is crucial that we get this right. 我们把这个问题弄明白是极其重要的。 3. Trust is crucial for successful friendship. 相互信任是维系友谊的关键。 4. The battle had reached a crucial stage. 战斗已到了关键阶段。', '副词: crucially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dike', '[daɪk]', 'n.堤坝；排水沟；女同性恋者 v.开沟排水；构筑防护 =dyke(英）.', '1. Fortunately, the flood did not break the dike. 还好，这场大水没有把堤坝冲坏。 2. We must take effective measures to prevent the dike from going out. 我们必须采取有效措施防止堤坝倒坍。 3. They dug a dike along walls of the school. 他们沿校墙挖沟。 4. They want to dike the land to protect it from water. 他们想筑堤保护田地以防止洪水。', '名词: diker 过去式: diked/dyked 过去分词: diked/dyked 现在分词: diking/dyking 第三人称单数: dikes/dykes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crutch', '[krʌtʃ]', 'n.拐杖；支柱 v.支撑', '1. He is lame in one leg and walks with the help of a crutch. 他的一条腿跛了，走路借助于拐杖。 2. Religion was her crutch in times of sorrow. 宗教是她忧伤时依赖的支柱。 3. The book was simply a crutch to my memory. 那本书是我的记忆的支柱。 4. How closely women crutch the very chains that bind them! 你看女人们把那根捆住她们的锁链抓得多紧！', '过去式: crutched 过去分词: crutched 现在分词: crutching 第三人称单数: crutches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contradictory', '[ˌkɑːntrə\'dɪktəri]', 'adj.矛盾的 n.矛盾', '1. I was bewildered by the contradictory statements. 我被互相矛盾的陈述搞得莫衷一是。 2. People found this sort of contradictory reality hard to accept. 人们都觉得这矛盾的现实难以接受。 3. His remark was contradictory to the truth. 他的叙述与事实矛盾。 4. We had to face up to a number of seemingly contradictory concerns. 我们不得不正视若干看起来相互矛盾的问题。', '副词: contradictorily 名词: contradictoriness 名词复数: contradictories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carcinogen', '[kɑːr\'sɪnədʒən]', 'n.致癌物', '1. Inorganic arsenic has been documented as a human carcinogen of the skin and lung. 砷已被公认为人类之皮肤和肺的致癌物。', '形容词: carcinogenic 名词: carcinogenesis');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('haunt', '[hɔːnt]', 'n.常到的地方 vt.缠住；常到；出没(像鬼魂一样) vi.徘徊；出没(像鬼魂一样)', '1. The college library is a favorite haunt. 大学图书馆是人们喜欢的地方。 2. His youthful escapades came back to haunt him. 年轻时的胡作非为时常令他感到苦恼。 3. The memory in later times returned to haunt him. 那回忆后来经常浮现在他脑海。 4. Her wishful face haunt my dream like the rai at ight. 她的热切的脸，如夜雨似的，搅扰着我的梦魂。 5. The area was a haunt of criminals. 这个地区是罪犯经常出没的地方。', '名词: haunter 过去式: haunted 过去分词: haunted 现在分词: haunting 第三人称单数: haunts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('paramount', '[\'pærəmaʊnt]', 'adj.极为重要的；至高无上的 n.最高统治者 Paramount. n.派拉蒙(美电影公司)', '1. This matter is of paramount importance. 此事至关重要。 2. The reduction of unemployment should be paramount. 降低失业率应是头等大事。 3. These constitutions are paramount. 这些宪法至高无上。 4. This duty is paramount to all the others. 没有比这更重要的义务了。 5. MGM, Paramount, and Columbia are all majors in film industry. 米高梅、派拉蒙和哥伦比亚都是电影业的大公司。', '副词: paramountly 名词: paramountcy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frenzy', '[\'frenzi]', 'n.狂乱；狂暴；狂怒', '1. In a frenzy of hate he killed his enemy. 在一阵痛恨的狂乱中，他杀死了敌人。 2. They were singing in a frenzy of joy. 他们欣喜若狂地高声歌唱。 3. His frenzy of the previous day had all calmed down. 他前一天的慌乱都平静下来了。 4. The speaker worked the crowd up into a frenzy. 演讲者煽动起群众疯狂的情绪。', '名词复数: frenzies 过去式: frenzied 过去分词: frenzied 现在分词: frenzying 第三人称单数: frenzies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('constitution', '[ˌkɒnstə\'tjuːʃən]', 'n.宪法；组织；体质；构成，组成，构造', '1. The President swore to uphold the constitution. 总统宣誓维护宪法。 2. The country\'s constitution embodies the ideals of freedom and equality. 这个国家的宪法体现了自由和平等的理想。 3. The constitution of a primitive society is not necessarily simple. 原始社会的结构并不一定就是简单的。 4. Hunger and disease had weakened his constitution. 他饥饿与疾病交加，体质已削弱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vulpine', '[\'vʌlpaɪn]', 'adj.狐狸的；狡猾的', '1. This is what I call human intelligence, as distinguished from mere vulpine（狡诈） or animal intelligence. 鄙人想起在大学时，校园里有一位叱咤风云的哲学博士，名叫张鸣久。 2. Vulpine eyeball turns, say fawningly: \"The monkey says rightly, you are so great, who can see your mistake? 狐狸眼珠转了一转，讨好地说：“猴子说得对，您那么伟大，有谁能够看出您的错误呢？” 3. Sometimes one came near to my window， attracted by my light， barked a vulpine curse at me， and then retreated. 途中经过鹅湖，那里是麝鼠居处之地，它们的住宅矗立在冰上，但我经过时没有看到过一只麝鼠在外。 4. They use the method of snowball after, raise vulpine amount year after year to increase. 以后他们用滚雪球的办法,养狐狸数量逐年增加。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('other-directed', '[\'ʌðədə\'rektɪd]', 'adj.受人支配的；缺少自主性的', '1. Contract189199- book Weihai or other direct steamer. 合同189,199号预约威海号装运，或其他直船只也可。 2. Contract 189199- book Weihai or other direct steamer. 合同189，199号预约威海号装运，或其他直船只也可。 3. Don\'t err too far in the other direction,either. 但也不要走另一极端。 4. We can try to take the road in the other direction. 我们可以反方向走这条路试试。', '名词: otherdirectedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drawn', '[drɔːn]', 'adj.憔悴的 动词draw的过去分词形式.', '1. She was thinner, her face quite drawn and colourless, her eyes larger by contrast. 她已经瘦了许多，面上憔悴无血色，眼眶子已经深深的陷入。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carpenter', '[\'kɑːrpəntər]', 'n.木匠 v.做木工活', '1. The carpenter was busy sawing the logs into planks. 这位木匠正忙着把圆木锯成厚板。 2. The carpenter flung aside all his tools in a rage. 木匠怒气冲冲地将工具扔在一边。 3. The carpenter told me how to use a bevel. 木匠告诉我怎样用斜角规。 4. My uncle carpentered a table and a few stools for his needy neighbor. 我叔父给他穷困的邻居做了一张桌子和几只凳子。', '名词: carpentry 过去式: carpentered 过去分词: carpentered 现在分词: carpentering 第三人称单数: carpenters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('multiple', '[\'mʌltɪpl]', 'adj.多种多样的；许多的 n.倍数；并联', '1. He is the person with multiple injuries. 他就是那个多处受伤的人。 2. A multiple crash can often be seen on that motorway. 那条公路上的联环撞车事故很多。 3. Words can have multiple meanings. 词汇可以有许多释义。 4. 10 is a multiple of 5. 10是5的倍数。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plunder', '[\'plʌndər]', 'v.掠夺；抢劫 n.抢夺；掠夺品；赃物；战利品', '1. The imperialists plunder and exploit the people of the colonial countries. 帝国主义者掠夺和剥削殖民地国家的人民。 2. The invaders plundered food and valuables from coastal towns and villages. 侵略者在沿海城乡抢劫食物和贵重物品。 3. They plundered a palace of its treasures. 他们劫掠了宫殿的财宝。 4. she didn\'t accept the goods obtained by plunder. 她拒绝了抢夺来的财物。', '形容词: plunderable 名词: plunderer 过去式: plundered 过去分词: plundered 现在分词: plundering 第三人称单数: plunders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('denizen', '[\'denɪzn]', 'n.居住者；外籍居民；外来动植物；老主顾 v.使归化；使入籍', '1. His greatest danger now lies in the unknown denizen of the water. 现在他最大的危险是未知的水中居住者。 2. In this country children of denizen go to school free. 在这个国家外籍居民的孩子免费上学。 3. Because of the company business she has become a denizen of Tokyo. 由于公司业务她成了东京的常客。', '名词: denizenation 过去式: denizened 过去分词: denizened 现在分词: denizening 第三人称单数: denizens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revulsion', '[rɪ\'vʌlʃn]', 'n.剧变；非常的厌恶；剧烈的反应', '1. This is the period of revulsion. 这是剧变的一段时期。 2. She stared at the snake in revulsion. 她盯着那条蛇,感到很厌恶。 3. He had a revulsion against his neighbor. 他对邻居非常反感。 4. My feeling for him undergo a revulsion when I discover his cruelty. 当我发现他的残忍时,对他的感情起了剧变。', '形容词: revulsive');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swathe', '[sweɪð]', 'n.一长片；绷带；包布；束带 vt.缠裹；紧绑 =swath.', '1. The flood cut a wide swath in this area. 洪水席卷了这一地区，满目一片疮痍。 2. The earthquake devastated a huge swath of Sichuan. 地震摧毁了四川的一大片带状区域。 3. His head was swathed in bandages. 他的头用绷带缠着。 4. She sat in the sofa, swathed in a blanket. 她坐在沙发上，身上裹着一条毛毯。', '名词: swather 过去式: swathed 过去分词: swathed 现在分词: swathing 第三人称单数: swathes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intermediary', '[ˌɪntər\'miːdieri]', 'n.仲裁者；调解者；中介 adj.中间的；媒介的 [计算机] 媒介.', '1. Explained by Gautama Buddha, he also stated that there is no intermediary between mankind and the divine; distant gods and God are subjected to karma themselves in decaying heavens. 佛陀解释，他也声称人与神之间并没有仲裁者；遥远的众神和神本身在腐朽的天堂上会受到因果报应。 2. He refused to act as an intermediary between the two director. 他拒绝充当这两个董事之间的调解人。 3. I found a part-time job through a intermediary. 我通过中介找到了一份兼职。 4. For Descartes, the imagination is a important intermediary between the thinking and the extension. 想象是思维转向物体性广延的重要中介。 5. Now, a living language has been found that can play the same intermediary role more successfully. 最近，已找到了一种现存的语言，它能更有效地起到中间媒介的作用。', '名词复数: intermediaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('utopia', '[juː\'toʊpiə]', 'n.理想国；乌托邦', '1. In the cycle of destruction and creation, people find themselves farther and farther away from Utopia. 在毁灭与创生的轮回中，人们离理想国越来越远。 2. He intended to establish a holy bourgeois utopia by concluding equal social contracts. 他企图通过缔结平等的社会契约来建立神圣的资产阶级理想国。 3. When Vida came in to tea Carol sketched her Utopia. 维达来喝茶的时候，卡萝尔就情不自禁把她的乌托邦扼要地说了一下。 4. The concrete Utopia is never contented. 具体的乌托邦永不满足。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hospitable', '[hɑː\'spɪtəbl]', 'adj.好客的；殷勤的；易于接受的；宜人的', '1. It does not take much to be a hospitable host. 做一个好客的主人不需要很高的条件。 2. Americans have the reputation of being very hospitable people. 美国人有非常好客的美誉。', '副词: hospitably');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vilify', '[\'vɪlɪfaɪ]', 'v.诽谤；中伤', '1. She was vilified by the press for her controversial views. 因她持有异议，新闻界对她横加挞伐。 2. The politicians in Washington can get more votes by holding televised hearings where they vilify the oil companies. 华盛顿的政客们却要举行电视听证会,在会上中伤石油公司,以获得更多的选票。', '名词: vilification 过去式: vilified 过去分词: vilified 现在分词: vilifying 第三人称单数: vilifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('visionary', '[\'vɪʒəneri]', 'adj.幻想的；有远见卓识的 n.空想家；梦想者', '1. What he thought is visionary. 他所想的是不切实际的。 2. I have believed that it\'s a visionary tale. 我已相信这是虚无的传说。 3. Former Prime Minister is a recognized visionary statesman. 前任首相是一位公认的有远见的政治家。 4. Their visionary ideas are often misunderstood by their own generation. 他们有远见的理想往往招致同时代人的误解。 5. The ideas of a visionary may seem impractical to us. 在我们看来,空想家的观念好像不切实际。', '名词: visionariness 名词复数: visionaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imprudent', '[ɪm\'pruːdnt]', 'adj.轻率的；不谨慎的', '1. It would be imprudent to resign from your present job before you are offered another. 还没有得到新的工作就辞去现有的工作太轻率了. 2. It is imprudent of you to lend money to a stranger. 你把钱借给陌生人,未免太不谨慎了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('underwrite', '[ˌʌndər\'raɪt]', 'v.承保；写在……下面；给……保险', '1. The shares were underwritten by the Bank of England. 这些股票由英格兰银行包销。 2. The government underwrotethe initial costs of the operation. 政府为该项活动提供了开办时所需的费用。 3. Please underwrite the withdrawal slip. 请您在取款单上签字。 4. Grant foreign banks the right to underwrite bond on the same terms as local banks. 准许外国银行有权按本土银行同样的条件从事债券保险业务。', '过去式: underwrote 过去分词: underwritten 现在分词: underwriting 第三人称单数: underwrites');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flout', '[flaʊt]', 'v.藐视；轻视；嘲笑 n.嘲弄；轻视', '1. No one can flout the law with impunity. 任何人都不能不受惩罚地藐视法律。 2. They flouted all our offers of help and friendship. 他们对我们愿意提供的所有帮助和友谊表示藐视。 3. The foolish boy flout his mother\'s advice. 这个愚蠢的孩子轻视他母亲的劝告。', '副词: floutingly 名词: flouter 过去式: flouted 过去分词: flouted 现在分词: flouting 第三人称单数: flouts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exasperate', '[ɪɡ\'zæspəreɪt]', 'v.使 ... 恼怒；激怒；使恶化 adj.被激怒的；表面粗糙的', '1. That child exasperates me. 那孩子真让我生气。 2. She was exasperated at his stupidity. 她因为他的愚笨而发怒。 3. He shouted in an exasperate voice. 他以愤怒的声音嚷着。', '副词: exasperatedly 名词: exasperater 过去式: exasperated 过去分词: exasperated 现在分词: exasperating 第三人称单数: exasperates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embroider', '[ɪm\'brɔɪdər]', 'v.刺绣；镶边；装饰', '1. She embroidered the cushion with flowers. 她把垫子绣上了花。 2. She embroiders very well. 她很会刺绣。 3. He is likely to embroider the truth a bit. 他往往会修饰一下事实。 4. He used a little poetic licence to embroider a good story. 他用了一些创新的词语，使动人的故事锦上添花。', '名词: embroiderer 过去式: embroidered 过去分词: embroidered 现在分词: embroidering 第三人称单数: embroiders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desperate', '[\'despərət]', 'adj.绝望的；不顾一切的；极其想要的', '1. The situation is desperate. 情况令人感到绝。 2. I had no money left and was desperate. 我一点钱都没有了,简直绝望了。 3. They made a desperate plea for help. 他们不顾一切地恳求帮助。 4. His failure made him desperate. 他因失败而铤而走险。', '副词: desperately 名词: desperateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('portend', '[pɔːr\'tend]', 'vt. 成为 ... 的前兆； 预知； 预警', '1. Black clouds portend a storm. 乌云是暴风雨的前兆。 2. It portends we are in danger. 这预示我们陷入危险。 3. His silence portends trouble. 他沉默不语不是好兆头。', '过去式: portended 过去分词: portended 现在分词: portending 第三人称单数: portends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cachet', '[kæ\'ʃeɪ]', 'n.(证明品质的)优良标志；威望；声望', '1. Rembrandt\'s paintings show the cachet of genius. 伦勃朗的绘画是天才的象徵。 2. Federal courts have a certain cachet which state courts lack. 联邦法院有某种州法院所缺乏的特别的东西。 3. Her presence lends a certain cachet to the company. 他的出席给予了公司一定的威望。 4. Her success in business had earned her a certain cachet in society. 她事业有成，赢得了一定的社会声望。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stash', '[stæʃ]', 'vt.隐藏；储藏 n.隐藏地点；隐藏物', '1. Select the option to stash the password to a file. 选择将密码隐藏在在文件中的选项。 2. And you will have your personal garage to stash your rides. 你将拥有自己的个人修车场以隐藏你的赛车。', '过去式: stashed 过去分词: stashed 现在分词: stashing 第三人称单数: stashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rhyme', '[raɪm]', 'n.韵；押韵；韵文 v.押韵；用韵诗表达', '1. Do you understand the rhyme of this poem? 你理解这首诗的韵吗? 2. Poetry often follows special patterns of rhyme. 诗歌常常遵循专门的节奏和押韵格式。 3. Shakespeare sometimes wrote in rhyme. 莎士比亚有时用韵文写作。 4. You can\'t rhyme “sleep”with “feet”. 你不能用“sleep”和“feet”押韵。', '过去式: rhymed/rimed 过去分词: rhymed/rimed 现在分词: rhyming/riming 第三人称单数: rhymes/rimes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gratitude', '[\'ɡrætɪtuːd]', 'n.感激；感谢；感恩', '1. His heart overflowed with gratitude. 他的心里充满了感激之情。 2. She showed me her gratitude by inviting me to dinner. 她邀请我吃饭以表示她的感激。 3. We welcome the opportunity to express our gratitude. 我们能有机会表示谢意十分高兴。 4. We owe you a debt of gratitude for you help. 承蒙帮助，感恩不尽。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sapling', '[\'sæplɪŋ]', 'n.树苗；小树；年轻人', '1. She cut down the sapling with one chop. 她一斧子就把树苗砍倒了。 2. The sapling that bears our mark of love has grown into a big tree, 承载着我们爱的见证的小树已长成一棵大树，', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gregariousness', '[ɡrɪ\'ɡeriəsnəs]', '群集性,合群性,群居本能,群集度', '1. The well-established correlations between gregariousness and relative brain size in various mammalian groups are also consistent with the idea. 在各种不同的哺乳类支系中，社群的紧密程度与相对脑量有正相关，是确立的事实，而这个事实也可以与我们的理论互相发明。 2. Within these structures, the market offers the opportunities to attain status, while the monopoly of power and the geometric gregariousness are the obstacles for high stat... 在这种结构下,市场给予了人们获得地位的机遇,然而权力垄断、地缘集聚则成为获得地位的障碍,个人素质则是克服障碍的重要条件。 3. Talk about dog\'s behavior from the point of gregariousness 从群居性谈犬的行为 4. The American has dwindled intoan Odd Fellow -- one who may be known by the development of hisorgan of gregariousness, and a manifest lack of intellect andcheerful self-reliance; 我不禁觉得好笑，我 在沈思时，他们却煞有介事地锁起牢门，全然不知我的思绪就跟在他们身后出了牢房，丝毫不受任何阻碍，而他们自己才真正是危险的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mnemonics', '[niː\'mɒnɪks]', 'n.记忆术', '1. Mnemonics is important in learning English. 记忆术对学英语很重要。 2. According to mnemonics, people often forget unless they review from time to time. 依照记忆术,人只有经过一次次的复习才不容易忘记。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stipple', '[\'stɪpl]', 'v.点画；点描 n.点画', '1. Stipple with Density at 85, Threshold at 20, Dot Size at 3. 画点画密度为85，阈值为20，斑点大小为3。 2. This is called a ruling and with very fine lines it gives the same appearance as a stipple. 这称作网线。如采用极精细的网线,便可产生与网点相同的效果。 3. Stipple acts as a black grain that represents darks of an image with circular dots of different sizes and densities. 画点画充当黑深色衣物粮食，代表一个图像圆形点不同规模和密度。 4. Catch gender and be addicted to more alkalescent stipple cell all grow in quantity. 多染性和嗜碱性点彩细胞均增多。', '名词: stippler 过去式: stippled 过去分词: stippled 现在分词: stippling 第三人称单数: stipples');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parley', '[\'pɑːrli]', 'n.会谈；谈判 v.会谈；谈判', '1. They held a parley with the enemy. 他们和敌军进行商议。 2. He arranged a parley with us. 他安排和我们讲和。 3. Then he began to parley with me. 然后他开始跟我谈判。 4. The governor was forced to parley with the rebels. 州长被迫与反叛者谈判。', '名词复数: parleys 过去式: parleyed 过去分词: parleyed 现在分词: parleying 第三人称单数: parleys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pistol', '[\'pɪstl]', 'n.手枪', '1. A pistol shot rang out. 响起了手枪的声音。 2. It sounded like a small pistol going off. 那声音听起来像一支小手枪响。 3. He pushed forward the safety catch of his pistol. 他把他手枪的安全锁扣向前推了推。 4. The general came in, hipping a pistol. 将军走了进来,他的胯部佩带着一柄手枪。', '过去式: pistoled 过去分词: pistoled 现在分词: pistoling 第三人称单数: pistols');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gallows', '[\'ɡæloʊz]', 'n.绞刑架', '1. The murderer was sentenced to the gallows. 杀人犯被判处绞刑。 2. They did not send an innocent man to the gallows. 被他们送上绞架的并不是一个无辜的人。 3. Only our brand of gallows humor saves us from utter despair. 只有我们招牌式的黑色幽默把我们从完全的绝望中拯救出来。', '名词复数: gallows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verisimilar', '[ˌverə\'sɪmələ]', 'adj.似真的(可能的)', '1. The fixed special weekly English activities by foreign teachers supply the students with entirely verisimilar environment for their English study. 每周固定的外教授课特色英语活动，为学生提供全真的英语学习环境。 2. The result of experiment shows that it is easy in use,and the generated graph is verisimilar,so the thought is of reference value. 实验结果表明，该方法简单易行，生成图形逼真，此思想具有借鉴意义。 3. Twenty-five Swedish textile experts learn the techniques of \"Shen embroidery\" (or \"verisimilar embroidery\" ) at Shen Shou Art Museum in Nantong, east China\'s Jiangsu Province, Nov. 5, 2007. 当日，来自瑞典的25位纺织专家来到南通沈寿艺术馆学习刺绣。 4. if i could smile more verisimilar, my happiness will become verisimilitude? 要是我的微笑可以再像真多一点,我的快乐应当会再逼真一点吧?', '副词: verisimilarly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unrequited', '[ˌʌnrɪ\'kwaɪtɪd]', 'adj.无报答的；得不到回应的', '1. Clark\'s unrequited love for Lois and her crush on Superman are the soul of the story. 克拉克对路易斯不求回报的爱以及她对超人的迷恋是故事的灵魂所在。 2. The unrequited love festered in her mind. 单恋使她苦恼。 3. She fell in an unrequited love with the artist. 她单恋那位艺术家。', '副词: unrequitedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unprincipled', '[ʌn\'prɪnsəpld]', 'adj.不道德的；无原则的；放荡不羁的', '1. He is totally unprincipled in money matters; you can\'t trust him. 他在金钱方面根本不讲道德，你不能相信他。 2. Unprincipled accommodation will do harm to him. 无原则的迁就对他有害。 3. In a few years his unprincipled wife warped the probity of a lifetime . 在以后的几年里,他那放荡不羁的老婆把他的生活搅了个一塌糊涂。', '名词: unprincipledness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('addendum', '[ə\'dendəm]', 'n.补遗；附录', '1. The part brachiopod genera and species are described as addendum in this paper. 文中补遗描述部分腕足类属种。 2. This is an addendum to the book. 这是本书的附录。 3. Six parts and one addendum are separated in the paper. 论文由六章和一个附录组成。', '名词复数: addenda');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quaff', '[kwæf]', 'v.〈旧或修辞〉一口气喝干；大口地喝 n.一饮而尽；痛饮', '1. He is quaffing his beer by the pint. 他论品脱地大喝啤酒。 2. We quaffed wine last night. 我们昨晚畅饮了一次酒。', '名词: quaffer 过去式: quaffed 过去分词: quaffed 现在分词: quaffing 第三人称单数: quaffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chaste', '[tʃeɪst]', 'adj.贞洁的；纯洁的；朴素的', '1. A wife loyal to her husband is chaste. 一个忠于丈夫的妻子是贞洁的。 2. These girls are told by the nuns to be chaste. 修女们教这些女孩子要贞洁。 3. She gave him a chaste kiss on the cheek. 她在他的脸颊上留下了纯洁的一吻。 4. She wore a chaste gold chain around her neck. 她戴着一条造型简洁的金项链。', '副词: chastely 比较级: chaster 最高级: chastest 名词: chasteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tickler', '[\'tɪkələ]', 'n.备忘录；记事本', '1. You can also use a tickler file to supplement this. 你也可以使用一个备忘录文件作为增补。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whisper', '[\'wɪspər]', 'n.低语；窃窃私语；飒飒的声音 vi.低声说；窃窃私语；飒飒地响 vt.耳语；私语', '1. There is no word, no whisper, no cry. 这里没有消息，没有低语，没有呼唤。 2. She said it in a whisper, so I didn\'t hear. 她是悄声说的，所以我没有听见。 3. I heard the whisper of wind in the pines. 我听见风吹过松林间飒飒作响。 4. The children were whispering in the corner. 孩子们正在角落里低声耳语。 5. Fatso leaned over to whisper in her ear. 胖子欠身对她耳语几句。', '形容词: whispery 名词: whisperer 过去式: whispered 过去分词: whispered 现在分词: whispering 第三人称单数: whispers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marred', '[mɑːr]', 'vt.破坏；毁坏 n.污点；瑕疵 abbr.海上的（=maritime） Mar. abbr.三月（March）', '1. This will mar the beauty of your hair. 这会影响你头发的美观。 2. Nothing had occurred to mar this trip. 没有什么事破坏这次旅行的圆满成功。 3. Nothing happened to mar the old man\'s happiness. 那老人的幸福没有受到任何事情的破坏. 4. His handling of the crisis can make or mar his career. 他对这一危机的处理可能决定他事业的成败。', '过去式: marred 过去分词: marred 现在分词: marring 第三人称单数: mars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recondite', '[\'rekəndaɪt]', 'adj.深奥的；难解的；隐藏的', '1. Gene research is a recondite area of learning. 基因研究是一个奥博的学术领域。 2. The recondite treatise is hard to understand. 这篇深奥的论文很费解。', '副词: reconditely 名词: reconditeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('granite', '[\'ɡrænɪt]', 'n.花岗石', '1. The valley ended in a perpendicular rim of granite. 那山谷的尽头是花岗石的断崖。 2. He has a heart of granite. 他有一副铁石心肠。 3. He is pointing down a block of granite. 他正在用锐利的工具修整一块花岗石。 4. The old man\'s grave is made of granite. 那老人的墓是用花岗石造的。', '形容词: granitic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('iconoclastic', '[ˌkɑːnə\'klæstɪk]', 'adj.打破旧习的；破除因袭的', '1. The iconoclastic idea construed by the canvas is striking. 画布上打破旧习的新观念让人震惊。 2. Tom is an irreverent, iconoclastic figure who refuses to conform. 汤姆是个傲慢的、反传统的、拒绝遵奉的人。 3. The iconoclastic commissioner concludes that it is good for students. 这位打破常规的委员认为，这对学生是有好处的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glitter', '[\'ɡlɪtər]', 'n.灿烂；闪烁；辉耀；亮片 v.闪烁', '1. Wealth\'s glitter never washed a foul life clean. 财富的光辉永远洗不净肮脏的生涯。 2. In these cities what remains of the old China is hidden by the glitter. 在这些城市里，旧中国所遗留下来的东西都被闪烁的灯光掩埋了。 3. He stared at me with a cruel glitter in his eyes. 他眼露凶光地瞪着我。 4. She felt the glitter of the visions mounting to her brain. 这个梦幻世界放射出的华丽光辉逐渐侵入了她的脑海。 5. The diamond ring on her finger glittered in the light. 她手指上的钻石戒指在灯光下闪闪发光。', '形容词: glittery 副词: glitteringly 过去式: glittered 过去分词: glittered 现在分词: glittering 第三人称单数: glitters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('olfaction', '[ɒl\'fækʃən]', 'n.嗅觉', '1. The difficulties of active olfaction are pointed, out at the end. 最后，指出了当前主动嗅觉研究的主要难点。 2. Through Jia Bao-Yu\'s olfaction and gustation, his spiritual love and facultative desire was emphasized. 通过贾宝玉的嗅觉与味觉，进入他的深层意识与美感触觉，突显他的精神恋爱与官能欲望。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extol', '[ɪk\'stoʊl]', 'v.颂扬；称赞', '1. The general was extolled as the man who had led the country to victory. 这位将军被誉为领导全国赢得胜利的人。 2. He keeps extolling her goodness. 他对她的善良赞不绝口。 3. They extol the virtues of the peaceful life. 对于农村宁静生活的美处，他们称赞不已。', '名词: extoller');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diver', '[\'daɪvər]', 'n.跳水者；潜水员', '1. The diver first drew a deep breath. 跳水员先深深地吸了一口气。 2. The diver poised on the edge of the high board. 跳水运动员在高台边上站稳。 3. The young diver is working under the water with a diving suit. 潜水员穿着潜水衣正在水下工作。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mourn', '[mɔːrn]', 'v.哀悼；忧伤；服丧', '1. People wore crapes to mourn our leader. 人们戴着黑纱哀悼我们的领导。 2. We mourn for our fallen soldiers. 我们哀悼阵亡的兵士。 3. The old woman still mourns for her son. 这位老太太还在为儿子的死伤心。 4. We mourn in black. 我们穿黑色衣服服丧。', '副词: mourningly 名词: mourner 过去式: mourned 过去分词: mourned 现在分词: mourning 第三人称单数: mourns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stonewall', '[\'stoʊn\'wɔːl]', 'v.阻碍议事；妨碍；[体]打防守球', '1. I want you to stonewall it, let them plead the Fifth Amendment. 我要你抵制它，让他们请求第五次修改。', '名词: stonewaller 过去式: stonewalled 过去分词: stonewalled 现在分词: stonewalling 第三人称单数: stonewalls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impregnable', '[ɪm\'preɡnəbl]', 'adj.坚不可摧的；不可战胜的', '1. They will establish impregnable fortresses. 他们将建造坚不可摧的城堡。 2. The lofty walls of the castle seemed impregnable. 这座城堡的高墙似乎坚不可摧。 3. The lawyer won his case with an impregnable argument. 律师以无可辩驳的论据打赢了那场官司。 4. Only in this way can you be in an impregnable position for good. 也只有这样，你才能永远立于不败之地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perpetual', '[pər\'petʃuəl]', 'adj.永久的；永恒的；一再往复的', '1. He was perpetual president of the country. 他是该国的终身总统。 2. He has run his course and takes his perpetual rest. 他已走完他的行程而长眠了。 3. She lives in perpetual fear of being discovered. 她永远生活在怕被发现的恐惧中。 4. It is the secret of perpetual youth. 它是青春永驻的秘诀。', '副词: perpetually');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('migratory', '[\'maɪɡrətɔːri]', 'adj.迁移的；流浪的', '1. Migratory beekeeping is nothing new. 迁移的养蜂人不是初见的。 2. These living beings are migratory birds . 这些生物就是候鸟。 3. Migratory workers migrate to cities in search of work. 流动工人移往城市找寻工作。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cartoon', '[kɑːr\'tuːn]', 'n.卡通；漫画；草图 vt.为 ... 画漫画', '1. The kids glued their eyes to the TV set, watching a cartoon. 孩子们目不转睛地盯着电视机看卡通片。 2. The man looks like a cartoon character with a plaster on his temple. 那人太阳穴上贴了一块膏药，看上去像个卡通人物。 3. This movie theater often shows the latest cartoon films. 这家电影院经常放映一些最新的卡通电影. 4. A newspaper cartoon is an amusing drawing, usually about some event in the news. 报纸上的漫画是一种风趣的图画，通常是针对某一件时事的。 5. The pen should draw cartoon using a pencil? 画漫画的笔应该可以使用铅笔吧？', '形容词: cartoonish 名词: cartoonist 过去式: cartooned 过去分词: cartooned 现在分词: cartooning 第三人称单数: cartoons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dunce', '[dʌns]', 'n.在学习上愚笨的或迟钝的人（尤指学生）', '1. A stupid person; a dunce. 笨蛋愚蠢的人; 迟钝的学习者 2. It is very impolite to call others a dunce. 叫别人蠢材是不礼貌的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ruminant', '[\'ruːmɪnənt]', 'n.反刍动物 adj.反刍的；沉思的', '1. Cows and sheep are both ruminants. 牛和羊都是反刍动物。 2. That was denuded by these ruminant pests. 全被那些反刍的害人虫给毁了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disillusion', '[ˌdɪsɪ\'luːʒn]', 'n.觉醒；幻灭 v.给…泼冷水；使幻想破灭', '1. I knew it all, the whole drab compass of marital disillusion. 我清楚地知道婚姻幻灭的单调乏味的境界。 2. Don\'t say anything to disillusion them. 别给他们泼冷水。 3. I hate to disillusion you, but your chances of winning are nil. 我并不愿意使你的想法破灭，但你没有取胜的机会。 4. She still believes in Santa Claus and it would be cruel to disillusion her. 她仍然相信有圣诞老人，要是使她这一幻想破灭就於心不忍了。', '形容词: disillusive 名词: disillusionment 过去式: disillusioned 过去分词: disillusioned 现在分词: disillusioning 第三人称单数: disillusions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desecrate', '[\'desɪkreɪt]', 'v.亵渎；玷污', '1. The enemy desecrate the church by using it as a stable. 敌人亵渎这所教堂, 把它当做马厩。 2. I won`t be the one who betrays my dead king and lets you desecrate his tomb. 我不会像他们一样背叛死去的国王，任凭你亵渎他的坟墓的。 3. It\'s a crime to desecrate the country\'s flag. 玷污国旗是犯罪。', '名词: desecrater 过去式: desecrated 过去分词: desecrated 现在分词: desecrating 第三人称单数: desecrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debase', '[dɪ\'beɪs]', 'v.降低质量、地位或价值；贬低', '1. Sport is being debased by commercialism. 体育运动的价值受商业化的影响而逐渐下降。 2. There exists an incentive to debase the currency. 存在货币贬值的动机。 3. I think we can debase the price to get more market share. 我认为我们可以通过降低价格来夺得更大的市场份额。 4. You debase yourself by telling such lies. 你说这些谎话就降低了身份。', '名词: debasement 过去式: debased 过去分词: debased 现在分词: debasing 第三人称单数: debases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rescue', '[\'reskjuː]', 'vt.营救；援救 n.营救；救援', '1. He dived from the bridge to rescue the drowning child. 他从桥上跳入水中去抢救那溺水儿童。 2. Had Jim not dived in to rescue him, the boy would have drowned. 如果不是吉姆跳下水去救，那小孩早就淹死了。 3. The government has rescued the firm from bankruptcy by giving them a grant. 政府拨款给这家公司使其免于破产。 4. The rescue attempt was impeded by bad weather. 营救工作受到恶劣天气的妨碍。', '形容词: rescuable 名词: rescuer 过去式: rescued 过去分词: rescued 现在分词: rescuing 第三人称单数: rescues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('squint', '[skwɪnt]', 'vi.眯眼看；斜视；窥视；偏移 vt.使斜眼；眯眼看 n.斜视；斜孔小窗；一瞥 adj.斜视的；斜的', '1. He squinted in the bright sunlight. 他在很亮的阳光下眯起了眼睛。 2. He squinted through the peephole. 他眯起眼睛靠近窥视孔看了看。 3. A squint can sometimes be corrected by an eyepatch. 斜视有时候可以通过戴眼罩来纠正。 4. If I squint with all my strength I may see it. 如果我斜视与我所有的力量我可以看到它。 5. He has a bad squint. 他患有严重的斜视。', '形容词: squinty 名词: squinter 过去式: squinted 过去分词: squinted 现在分词: squinting 第三人称单数: squints');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mutineer', '[ˌmjuːtə\'nɪr]', 'n.反叛者；叛变者', '1. the mutineer, indeed, died under the doctor\'s knife, and Hunter, do what we could, never recovered consciousness in this world. 那个海盗最终死于医生的刀下。尽管我们已经竭尽全力，亨特还是没能苏醒过来。 2. \"So you snatched a pistol from a mutineer,\" came Fan Po-wen\'s sarcastic voice, \"and had to shoot a few peasants before you could make your way out of the town; eh? Whew! What a hero!\" “那么，你是从变兵手里夺了手枪； 又打死了几个乡下人，这才逃出来的? 嘿！ 你倒真是了不得 3. Mutin 穆廷', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('moron', '[\'mɔːrɑːn]', 'n.笨人', '1. He\'s an absolute moron! 他纯粹是个傻子！ 2. They\'re a load of morons. 他们是一群笨蛋。', '形容词: moronic 副词: moronically 名词: moronism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('municipality', '[mjuːˌnɪsɪ\'pæləti]', 'n.自治市；市当局', '1. An official who receives the rents and fees of a municipality; a treasurer. 财务管理人收取市政租金和费用的官员; 司库', '名词复数: municipalities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crestfallen', '[\'krestfɔːlən]', 'adj.垂头丧气的；气馁的', '1. The youth looked exceedingly crestfallen. 那青年看上去垂头丧气极了。 2. He looked a little crestfallen (or depressed). 他看起来有点灰溜溜的样子。 3. What happened? You look so crestfallen like it\'s the end of the world! 怎麽了？你看起来垂头丧气的，好像世界末日一样。', '副词: crestfallenly 名词: crestfallenness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forswear', '[fɔːr\'swer]', 'vt.发誓放弃；发誓否认 vi.作伪证', '1. You must tell the truth to the judge,because if you forswear yourself you could go to prison. 你必须向法官说老实话，因为你如果作伪证就可能坐牢。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('savant', '[sæ\'vɑːnt]', 'n.学者；专家', '1. The hypothesis can explain various characters going with idiot savant. 这个假说能对白痴学者所表现的种种特征加以解析说明。 2. I need to be taught by savant who was focus on EV and FCV. 我需要向电动汽车和燃料电池汽车方面的专家学习。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mumble', '[\'mʌmbl]', 'v.喃喃而语；咕哝 n.喃喃而语；咕哝', '1. Uh, you really shouldn\'t mumble, because I can\'t understand a word you\'re saying. 喔，你不应该咕咕哝哝地说，因为你说的我一句话也听不懂。 2. The only time most women give their orating husbands undivided attention is when the old boys mumble in their sleep. 大多数女人对丈夫的说话最专心倾听的，就是老公在睡梦中咕哝的话。 3. Uh, you really shouldn\'t mumble, because I can\'t understand a word you\'re saying. 喔，你不应该咕咕哝哝地说，因为你说的我一句话也听不懂。 4. The only time most women give their orating husbands undivided attention is when the old boys mumble in their sleep. 大多数女人对丈夫的说话最专心倾听的，就是老公在睡梦中咕哝的话。', '形容词: mumbly 名词: mumbler 过去式: mumbled 过去分词: mumbled 现在分词: mumbling 第三人称单数: mumbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barge', '[bɑːrdʒ]', 'n.驳船 vi.猛撞；冲；闯 vt.以驳船载运', '1. They sank the barge by making a hole in the bottom. 他们在驳船底部打个洞把它弄沉了。 2. People on the barge looked rather happy. 游船上的人们看上去很高兴。 3. He barged past me in the queue. 我在排队时他在我面前硬挤过去了。 4. How rude of you to barge into the conversation! 你打断人家的谈话，多没礼貌啊！', '过去式: barged 过去分词: barged 现在分词: barging 第三人称单数: barges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abduct', '[æb\'dʌkt]', 'vt.诱拐；绑走', '1. He had attempted to abduct the two children. 他曾企图诱拐这两名儿童。 2. I can say you abduct a high school student. 我可以告你诱拐中学生。', '名词: abduction 过去式: abducted 过去分词: abducted 现在分词: abducting 第三人称单数: abducts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('regress', '[rɪ\'ɡres]', 'v.倒退；回归；退化 n.退回；回归；逆向思维', '1. Some children may regress to an earlier stage of development. 有些孩子的状态会倒退到更小的年龄段。 2. Many men, when very angry, regress to their childhood and show their bad temper by shouting and stamping their feet. 很多人，盛怒之下又退回到孩提时代，边大喊大叫边跺脚地发脾气。 3. This is because the rates of return on most systems tend to regress to the mean. 这是由于大多数系统的回报率会回归到这个水平。 4. The attempt leads to an infinite regress. 这种作法会导致无穷倒退。', '名词: regressor 过去式: regressed 过去分词: regressed 现在分词: regressing 第三人称单数: regresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tipple', '[\'tɪpl]', 'v.常喝；不断喝酒 n.酒；烈酒', '1. He started tippling when his wife left him. 他自妻子离去之後便开始酗酒。 2. Daily tipple aids older women\'s minds. 每日小酒有益年长女性心智。 3. His favourite tipple is whisky. 他爱喝的烈酒是威士忌。', '名词: tippler 过去式: tippled 过去分词: tippled 现在分词: tippling 第三人称单数: tipples');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compassion', '[kəm\'pæʃn]', 'n.怜悯；同情', '1. I had compassion for him. 我怜悯他。 2. He teaches us to have compassion on the poor. 他教导我们对穷人应有怜悯心。 3. Compassion is a sign of weakness. 怜悯是弱者的标志。 4. I should not have compassion for those lofty birds. 我不会怜悯这些高贵的鸟。', '形容词: compassionless');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pellucid', '[pə\'luːsɪd]', 'adj.清澈透明的；易懂的', '1. The butterfly alights on my pellucid fingertip. 蝴蝶栖落在我透明的指尖。 2. Characterized by transparent clearness;pellucid. 有清澈特征的；透明的 3. Characterized by transparent cLearner\'ss; pellucid. 有清澈特征的；透明的 4. Characterized by transparent clearness; pellucid. 有清澈特征的；透明的', '副词: pellucidly 名词: pellucidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confide', '[kən\'faɪd]', 'v.吐露；委托；信赖', '1. She confided to me the secret. 她向我吐露了那个秘密。 2. Nowadays girls seldom confide in their mothers. 现在的女孩很少对母亲吐露心事。 3. Can I confide my children to your care? 托你照顾一下我的孩子好吗? 4. Don\'t confide in him. 不要信赖他。', '名词: confider 过去式: confided 过去分词: confided 现在分词: confiding 第三人称单数: confides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pictorial', '[pɪk\'tɔːriəl]', 'adj.绘画的；用图片的 n.画报', '1. We have quite a variety of pictorial story books. 我们有许多连环画图书。 2. They have insist on a full pictorial coverage of the event. 他们坚持要用图片来报导这些事件。 3. The pretty girl on the cover of the pictorial is just a sales gimmick. 画报的封面上印上美女不过是吸引顾客的一种生意眼。 4. If that is not a pictorial, then it is a magazine. 那不是画报就是杂志。', '副词: pictorially 名词: pictoriality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wile', '[waɪl]', 'n.诡计；阴谋；欺骗 v.欺骗；诱惑；消遣', '1. The fox\'s wiles will never enter the lion\'s head. 狐狸的诡计永远进不了狮子的头脑。 2. The little boy has many wiles. 这个小孩有很多诡计。 3. All her wiles were not enough to persuade them to sell the villa. 她花言巧语也未能打动他们卖掉别墅。 4. I am tricked by the salesman\'s wile into buying worthless goods. 我上了推销员的当，买了毫无价值的东西。 5. The teahouse is a great place to wile away an evening. 茶馆是消磨夜晚的好去处。', '过去式: wiled 过去分词: wiled 现在分词: wiling 第三人称单数: wiles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bore', '[bɔːr]', 'v.使厌烦；开凿；钻孔；挖掘；盯着看 n.讨厌的人；麻烦事；(管道、枪炮等的)孔；涌潮；(找水或石油的)钻孔 动词bear的过去式.', '1. He bored us all by talking for hours about his new house. 他连续几个小时大谈他的新房子，使我们大家都厌烦透了。 2. They are going to bore a tunnel through this mountain. 他们打算开凿一条穿越此山的隧道。 3. This drill can bore through rock. 这台钻机能钻透岩石。 4. Worms have bored into the wood. 虫子已经蛀穿了木料。 5. He was making a bore of himself. 他快要使自己变成一个惹人讨厌的人物了。', '过去式: bored 过去分词: bored 现在分词: boring 第三人称单数: bores');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chuckle', '[\'tʃʌkl]', 'v.轻声笑；咯咯笑；暗自笑 n.轻声笑；咯咯笑', '1. Cynics chuckle, and even Mr Paul sounds unenthusiastic about the Paulville project, in which he had no hand. 好挖苦的人轻声笑了，甚至保罗对这个保罗村项目听起来也不热心，因为他不参与这个项目。 2. Cynics chuckle, and even Mr Paul sounds unenthusiastic about the Paulville project, in which he had no hand. 好挖苦的人轻声笑了，甚至保罗对这个保罗村项目听起来也不热心，因为他不参与这个项目。', '形容词: chucklesome 副词: chucklingly 名词: chuckler 过去式: chuckled 过去分词: chuckled 现在分词: chuckling 第三人称单数: chuckles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sublime', '[sə\'blaɪm]', 'adj.高尚的；壮观的；非凡的；极其的 vt.变高尚；升华；气化 n.顶峰；高尚', '1. You may also imbibe it slowly in small sips to appreciate the subtle allure of tea-drinking, until your spirits soar up and up into a sublime aesthetic realm. 在百忙之中泡上一壶浓茶，择雅静之处，自斟自饮，可以消除疲劳、涤烦益思、振奋精神，也可以细啜慢饮，达到美的享受，使精神世界升华到高尚的艺术境界。 2. I like sublime mountain scenery. 我喜爱壮丽的山景。 3. In the matter of profanity he was sublime. 他破口乱骂的本领，也是卓越非凡的。 4. The food was absolutely sublime. 这吃的东西棒极了. 5. He has the power to turn the ordinary into the sublime. 爱人会化平凡为高尚，使生活得到升华。 6. Art is about creativity, transmuting the humblest subjects into the sublime. 艺术是一种创造力，能够把最卑贱的事物变得崇高庄严。', '副词: sublimely 名词: sublimeness 过去式: sublimed 过去分词: sublimed 现在分词: subliming 第三人称单数: sublimes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enduring', '[ɪn\'dʊrɪŋ]', 'adj.持久的；忍耐的', '1. People all want an enduring peace. 人们都想要有持久的和平。 2. And the benefits are enduring, rather than one-off. 而且这种利润是持久的，而不是一次性的。', '副词: enduringly 名词: enduringness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deforest', '[ˌdiː\'fɔːrɪst]', 'v.采伐森林；清除树林', '1. I intend that humans cease to deforest and reforest those regions that have been deforested. 我希望人类停止滥砍伐,并对那些已经过度砍伐的森林重新造林。 2. There was no option but to deforest the area. 惟一的选择就是砍掉树林。', '名词: deforestation 过去式: deforested 过去分词: deforested 现在分词: deforesting 第三人称单数: deforests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reactant', '[ri\'æktənt]', 'n.[化]反应物', '1. Oxygen is often used as reactant in chemical processes. 在化学过程中，氧气经常充当为反应物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oblivious', '[ə\'blɪviəs]', 'adj.没注意到；健忘的', '1. I was oblivious of my surroundings. 我没有注意到周围的事物。 2. He sat there reading the book, oblivious of the people nearby. 他坐在那里看书,没注意到附近的人们。 3. I am oblivious to what was happening. 我对发生的事情没有记忆了。 4. He was oblivious of his promise. 他忘记了他的诺言。', '副词: obliviously 名词: obliviousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nudge', '[nʌdʒ]', 'vt.轻推；轻触；推进 vi.轻推 n.轻推', '1. I nudged her and pointed to the man across the street. 我用肘碰了她一下并指了指街对面的那个男的。 2. She nudged him with her elbow. 她用肘轻触了他一下。 3. The horse nudged my pocket with its nose. 马用鼻子轻轻地拱我的衣袋。 4. We tried to nudge them towards a practical solution. 我们试图促成他们达成一个可行的解决办法。 5. The ship is nudging through the ice. 船在冰中推进。 6. She gave me a nudge in the ribs. 她以肘轻触我肋部一下。', '名词: nudger 过去式: nudged 过去分词: nudged 现在分词: nudging 第三人称单数: nudges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mortar', '[\'mɔːrtər]', 'n.臼；研钵；[军]迫击炮 n.灰泥；灰浆 v.用灰泥涂抹；用灰泥结合', '1. The farmers pound rice in a mortar. 农民们在臼中舂米。 2. He ground the rock candy with a mortar and pestle. 他自己动手用研钵和杵把冰糖研成粉。 3. The army was fired by mortars. 军队被迫击炮攻击。 4. Mortar is used to knit bricks together. 灰泥是用来黏合砖的。 5. Stones are bedded in mortar or concrete. 用灰泥或水泥砌石块。', '过去式: mortared 过去分词: mortared 现在分词: mortaring 第三人称单数: mortars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('austere', '[ɔː\'stɪr]', 'adj.简朴的；严厉的；苦行的；紧缩的', '1. The room was furnished in austere style. 这间屋子陈设得简单朴素。 2. Father was an austere man, very strict with his children. 父亲是个严厉的人,对子女十分严格。 3. Monks are leading simple, austere lives. 僧侣们过着清苦的生活。 4. We led an austere life in the mountains. 我们在山区过着艰苦的生活。', '副词: austerely 比较级: austerer 最高级: austerest 名词: austereness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('averse', '[ə\'vɜːrs]', 'adj.厌恶的；反对的', '1. We are averse to taking action. 我们反对采取行动。 2. He is averse to hard work. 他不愿意努力工作。', '副词: aversely 名词: averseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rivalry', '[\'raɪvlri]', 'n.敌对；竞争；对抗', '1. He was incited to achievement by rivalry. 竞争激励他努力取得成就。 2. Sibling rivalry is part of the original sin. 兄弟间的敌对相争，是最原始的一种罪。 3. There is great rivalry between the two brothers. 这两兄弟间有一场激烈的竞争。 4. There is cut-throat rivalry among the supermarkets. 这些超级市场之间的竞争可谓你死我活。', '名词复数: rivalries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('umbrage', '[\'ʌmbrɪdʒ]', 'n.阴影；不快；怀疑；怨恨', '1. They sheltered in the umbrage of a rain forest. 他们躲蔽在雨林树荫下。 2. She took umbrage at my remarks about her hair. 我对她头发的评论使她很不高兴。 3. He took umbrage at my remarks and left . 他觉得我的话伤了他的感情 4. The pope himself had taken great umbrage at the book. 教皇本人对这本书曾极为生气。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('squall', '[skwɔːl]', 'n.狂风；暴风雪；尖叫；哇哇器声 v.狂风吹袭；哇哇地叫嚷', '1. The squall speedily blew over. 风暴很快平息下来了。 2. It is said that the squall will come tomorrow. 据说暴风雪明天就要来了。 3. Have you heard the child\'s squall? 你听到那个孩子的尖叫声了吗？', '名词: squaller 过去式: squalled 过去分词: squalled 现在分词: squalling 第三人称单数: squalls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perfervid', '[pɜː\'fɜːvɪd]', 'adj.极端或过分热情的', '1. Thank you!But i perfervid my way. 谢谢。但是我喜欢这么说。 2. The perfervid woman was by this time half in love with a vision. 走路的人说的每一句话，她都能听见。他们并没有谈什么秘密。 3. To court their own discomfiture by love is a common instinct with certain perfervid women. 有些性情热烈的女人，平常总是为了爱情而自寻苦恼。 4. And expression is very earnest, but, osculatory time grew, what can experience him however is kind, and speak with fervor and assurance, perfervid. 而且表情非常严肃,但是,接触的时间长了,却能感受到他的和蔼,并且侃侃而谈,非常热心。', '副词: perfervidly 名词: perfervidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('circulation', '[ˌsɜːrkjə\'leɪʃn]', 'n.流通；循环；发行量；消息传播', '1. The old coins have been withdrawn from circulation. 旧硬币已经收回不再流通了。 2. The coins were taken out of circulation. 这种硬币已停止流通。 3. Harvey discovered the circulation of the blood. 哈唯发现了血液循环。 4. The newspaper\'s circulation has trebled since last year. 去年以来该报的发行量已增加到原来的三倍。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imbroglio', '[ɪm\'broʊlioʊ]', 'n.纷乱；纠葛', '1. Lu Xu and Qian Xuantong went their own way because they had different thoughts and were trapped in the imbroglio of personal connections. 而鲁迅与钱玄同的分道扬镳，则是由于他们后期思想的差异和人脉关系的纠葛所造成。', '名词复数: imbroglios');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('constant', '[\'kɑːnstənt]', 'adj.不变的；经常的 n.常数；恒量', '1. In our world nothing seems constant. 在我们这个世界上似乎没有东西是永恒不变的。 2. The birth rate in this city is almost constant. 这城市的出生率几乎是不变的。 3. The machinery requires constant maintenance. 这些机器需要经常保养维修。 4. The constant friction between the young couple finally caused divorce. 小夫妻俩之间经常的冲突终于导致了离婚。 5. The speed of light is an important constant. 光速是一个重要的常数。', '副词: constantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('moor', '[mʊr]', 'n.荒野；旷野 Moor: 摩尔人. v.系住；停泊', '1. It was a far fetch from Jane\'s house to the moor. 简的家离那片荒野地有相当长一段距离。 2. A track was gradually worn across the moor. 一条横越荒野的小径渐渐被踩出来了。 3. He used to go for long walks on the moors. 他过去时常在荒野上长时间地散步。 4. The following day, she is like the rose of moor, blossomming proud pistil. 以后的日子,她一如旷野的玫瑰,绽放着骄傲的蕊。 5. They moored their laden boats near my trees. 他们把满载的船只拴在我的树上。', '过去式: moored 过去分词: moored 现在分词: mooring 第三人称单数: moors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('totter', '[\'tɑːtər]', 'v.蹒跚；摇摇欲坠', '1. She managed to totter back to her seat. 她东倒西歪地好不容易回到了座位上。 2. Babies and very old people totter as they walk. 小孩与老年人走路蹒跚。 3. The piles of books tottered and then fell. 这堆书晃了几下，然后就倒了。 4. With that overturned,the clan authority and the authority of the husband all begin to totter. 它既被打翻，族权和夫权便一概跟着动摇起来。', '形容词: tottery 名词: totterer 过去式: tottered 过去分词: tottered 现在分词: tottering 第三人称单数: totters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incidence', '[\'ɪnsɪdəns]', 'n.发生(率)；入射', '1. Each incidence of truancy will impact the citizenship credit. 每次发生玩忽职守事件都会影响公民的信用。 2. Basically, can effectively control the incidence of bird strike. 基本上可以有效控制鸟击事件的发生。 3. Then I have to think deeply what benefit there is behind the incidence. 那时候我就必须深思发生的事情背后有什么益处。 4. he measured the angle of incidence of the reflected light. 他仔细测量了光的入射的角度。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disclose', '[dɪs\'kloʊz]', 'vt.揭露；使某物显露；公开', '1. I have no intention of disclosing their names. 我无意泄露他们的姓名。 2. The Government disclosed that another diplomat has been arrested for spying. 政府透露 3. The violets disclose their petals. 紫罗兰绽开花瓣。 4. Science can disclose the mysteries of nature. 科学能解开自然界的奥秘。', '形容词: disclosable 名词: discloser 过去式: disclosed 过去分词: disclosed 现在分词: disclosing 第三人称单数: discloses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tarpaulin', '[tɑːr\'pɔːlɪn]', 'n.涂焦帆布；防水衣；防水帽', '1. We put a tarpaulin across the window to block out the sun-light. 我们将涂焦帆布横挂在窗子上遮住阳光。 2. The tarpaulin is too leaky to be of much use. 防水衣是漏的，不能再用了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scroll', '[skroʊl]', 'n.卷轴；画卷；名册；卷形物 v.卷动', '1. At the ceremony he was presented with a scroll commemorating his achievement. 在典礼上，他被授予表彰他成就的卷轴。 2. As I opened the scroll,a panorama of the Yellow River unfolded. 我打开卷轴时,黄河的景象展现在眼前。 3. That scroll of Chinese painting is theirs . 那幅中国画卷是他们的。 4. Scroll down to see the entire text. 翻滚一下使能看到整个文本。', '过去式: scrolled 过去分词: scrolled 现在分词: scrolling 第三人称单数: scrolls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('empirical', '[ɪm\'pɪrɪkl]', 'adj.经验主义的；以观察或实验为根据的', '1. His science was generally empirical and often bad. 他的科学一般来自经验。 2. Inquiry into the nature of things based on logical reasoning rather than empirical methods. 自然科学基于逻辑推理而不是凭经验得来的方法来探究事物的本质。 3. Unboundedness has a greater empirical credibility. 无界性有更大的经验可信性。 4. The Sprint phase is an empirical process. 冲刺阶段是一个完全根据经验的过程。', '副词: empirically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entry', '[\'entri]', 'n.进入；进入权；入口；条目', '1. He pretended not to observe our entry. 他装作没有看见我们进来。 2. The people without a ticket are denied entry. 没有票的人不许入内。 3. He has applied for an entry visa. 他已申请入境签证。 4. You can leave your umbrella in the entry. 雨伞可放在入口处。', '名词复数: entries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detest', '[dɪ\'test]', 'v.厌恶；痛恨', '1. I detest all affectation. 我厌恶一切矫揉造作的行为。 2. She detests having to talk to people at parties. 她讨厌在宴会上为应酬而和人交谈。 3. I detest people who tell lies. 我痛恨撒谎的人。 4. I detest violence with my whole being. 我毕生谴责暴力行为。', '名词: detester 过去式: detested 过去分词: detested 现在分词: detesting 第三人称单数: detests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('legend', '[\'ledʒənd]', 'n.传说；传奇；图例', '1. According to the old legend, Romulus was the founder of Rome. 按照古老的传说，罗穆卢斯是古罗马的建国者。 2. This oriental legend is fascinating. 这个东方传说很吸引人。 3. The little girl is very interested in the old legend of immortal creatures. 小女孩对有关永生的精灵的古老传奇非常感兴趣。 4. He is a legend in his lifetime for his scientific discoveries. 他的科学发现使他一生成为传奇人物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pagan', '[\'peɪɡən]', 'n.异教徒；无宗教信仰者 adj.异教的；异教徒的；无宗教信仰的', '1. Dymphna was a virgin daughter of a pagan king. 邓娜是一位异教徒国王的女儿，并且还是处子之身。 2. Christmas is an adaptation of the Pagan feast of Yule. 圣诞节是按照非异教徒犹太人的盛宴改换过来的。 3. He had a weak personality - always under the influence of his pagan wife, Jezebel. 他有一个软弱的人格，常常受他异教的妻子耶洗别的影响。 4. Instead of the pagan god Lupercus, the Church looked for a suitable patron saint2 of love to take his place. 教会要寻找一位合适的爱情守护神来代替异教的畜牧神。', '形容词: paganish 名词: pagandom');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ingratiate', '[ɪn\'ɡreɪʃieɪt]', 'v.取悦；迎合；讨好', '1. She quickly sought to ingratiate herself with the new administration. 她很快就试图使她自己获得新政府的欢心。 2. She tried to ingratiate herself with the director in the hope of getting promotion. 她竭力迎合主任希望得到提升。 3. He never ingratiate himself with his boss. 他从不去讨好上司。 4. I used to be upset by these attempts to ingratiate. 我以前常常对这样的讨好感到厌烦。', '形容词: ingratiatory 名词: ingratiation 过去式: ingratiated 过去分词: ingratiated 现在分词: ingratiating 第三人称单数: ingratiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shipwright', '[\'ʃɪpˌraɪt]', 'n.造船者；修船者', '1. Who build stronger than mason , a shipwright , or a carpenter? [谁的建筑比泥水匠,修船者,木匠更坚固? 2. Shipwright allows the construction of ships to be undertaken in earnest. 船坞可以大为提高船舶建造效率。 3. When a shipwright builds a vessel, does he build it to keep it upon the stocks? 一个造船匠造船的目的，是不是为了要把船搁在船架上呢？ 4. Shipwright has the slipway, wood seasoning stores and manpower needed to build ships for a strong fleet. 船坞拥有建造大型船舶所必需的船台、木料仓库和足够人力。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pariah', '[pə\'raɪə]', 'n.南印度的最下级民；贱民；被社会遗弃者', '1. The emancipation process of pariah began in the period of colony. 贱民解放的过程起始于殖民地时期。 2. A small country with many foes cannot afford to become a pariah. 有着众多敌人的小国承担不起变成被遗弃贱民的代价。 3. She has been pilloried and turned into a pariah. 公众嘲笑她，她变成了弃儿。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mince', '[mɪns]', 'n.切碎物；粉碎；肉馅 v.切碎；矫揉做作地说，委婉地说；小步走路', '1. She had a hot mince pie for him. 她给他做了热碎肉馅饼。 2. Wash cattlefish, wipe dry and mince then in a meat grinder. 墨鱼肉洗净，抹乾水切碎，放入碎肉机内搅烂。 3. They hunt bats with a net or long poles, and then roast the beasts over charcoal fires or mince them up into a traditional Thai dish. 村民用网和长竹竿捉蝙蝠，然后放在木炭上烘烤，或将它们切碎放入传统泰国菜中。', '名词: mincer 过去式: minced 过去分词: minced 现在分词: mincing 第三人称单数: minces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('composure', '[kəm\'poʊʒər]', 'n.镇静；沉着', '1. Keep calm; don\'t lose your composure. 保持镇静，不要惊慌失措。 2. She recovered her composure and smiled. 她恢复了镇静，笑了笑。 3. He could see that she was struggling to preserve her composure. 他看出她是竭力故作镇定。 4. He showed great composure in difficult situations. 他在困难环境中表现得极沉着。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sextant', '[\'sekstənt]', 'n.六分仪(航海定向仪器)', '1. Before he died,the unfortunate man handed you his sextant. 在那个不幸的人临死之前，他给了你他的六分仪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('squirrel', '[\'skwɜːrəl]', 'n.松鼠；松鼠皮毛 vt.储存', '1. The squirrel is a lovely small animal. 松鼠是一种可爱的小动物。 2. The squirrel ran up a tree and got out of my reach. 松鼠跑到树上去了，我逮不着。 3. The squirrel hoards up nuts for the winter. 松鼠储藏坚果以防冬天。 4. Nervous householders continue to squirrel more money away in the banks. 不安的居民持续不断地把更多钱存入银行里。', '过去式: squirreled/squirrelled 过去分词: squirreled/squirrelled 现在分词: squirreling/squirrelling 第三人称单数: squirrels/squirrels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('far-reaching', '[fɑːr \'riːtʃɪŋ]', 'adj.深远的；伸至远处的；广大的', '1. Some of the propositions reach far. 这些立论中有些影响是很深远的。 2. If this observation is accurate, as I believe it is, the implications are far- reaching. 如果这个见解正如我所自信的那样是正确的话，其意义是深远的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sequacious', '[sɪ\'kweɪʃəs]', 'adj.盲从的；前后一贯的', '1. I want something sequacious now and robust. 我现在想要前后一贯和健全的东西。 2. The Chinese modern literature before the new period became break the ranks cause the mortification literature policy and yarnsmith\'s sequacious craze. 摘要新时期以前的中国当代文学，在禁欲文化政策与作家狂热盲从的双重夹击下，成了世界文学的掉队者。 3. Teenagers are very sequacious and they often emulate the behavior of their idols who are sometimes negative role models. 青少年非常盲从，经常模仿他们偶像的行为，而有些偶像却是负面榜样。 4. Teenagers are so immature, ignorant and sequacious that they can hardly distinguish right from wrong and easily go astray. 青少年不成熟、无知和盲从，他们很难辩明是非，很容易误入歧途。', '副词: sequaciously 名词: sequacity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('excerpt', '[\'eksɜːrpt]', 'n.摘录 vt.摘录；引用', '1. This is an excerpt from a novel. 这是一部小说的摘录。 2. I\'ve seen a short excerpt from the film on television. 我在电视上看过这部影片的片段。 3. You can excerpt passages from a book. 你可以从一本书中摘录几段。 4. Can you excerpt something from the newspaper? 你能从报纸上选录些东西吗?', '过去式: excerpted 过去分词: excerpted 现在分词: excerpting 第三人称单数: excerpts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plummet', '[\'plʌmɪt]', 'n.铅锤；铅垂线 vi.垂直落下；暴跌', '1. Just watch your electricity bills plummet! 您的电费帐单将直线下降! 2. Share price plummet or plunge on the news of the devaluation. 一有贬值的消息，股票价格就暴跌了。 3. House prices have plummeted in this area. 此地房价大跌。 4. Our economy would plummet into the abyss of national economic ruin. 我们的经济将会陷入全面崩溃的深渊。', '过去式: plummeted 过去分词: plummeted 现在分词: plummeting 第三人称单数: plummets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reprimand', '[\'reprɪmænd]', 'n.训斥；谴责 v.训斥；谴责', '1. His boss gave him a reprimand for being late. 他的老板因他迟到而训了他一顿。 2. He received a severe reprimand for his behaviour. 他的行为受到了谴责。 3. His negligence passed without reprimand. 他玩忽职守并未受到斥责。 4. She was severely reprimanded for accepting the money. 她因为接受了那笔钱而受到严厉训斥。', '过去式: reprimanded 过去分词: reprimanded 现在分词: reprimanding 第三人称单数: reprimands');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hypnotic', '[hɪp\'nɑːtɪk]', 'adj.催眠的；催眠术的；易于催眠的 n.催眠药；安眠药；催眠状态的人', '1. The rhythmic music can be hypnotic. 有节奏的音乐有催眠作用。 2. Chloral hydrate is a rapidly effective hypnotic 水合氯醛为一种作用迅速的催眠药。 3. Did you take hypnotic last night? 你昨天晚上吃了安眠药吗?', '副词: hypnotically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reprehensible', '[ˌreprɪ\'hensəbl]', 'adj.应受谴责的', '1. It was reprehensible of him to be so disloyal. 他如此不忠，应受谴责。 2. His conduct was thoroughly reprehensible. 他的行为完全应该受到谴责。', '副词: reprehensibly 名词: reprehensibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bouncing', '[\'baʊnsɪŋ]', 'adj.跳跃的；精神饱满的；健壮的；巨大的 动词bounce的现在分词形式.', '1. A giant wave rolled over the bouncing boat. 一个巨浪卷过这条颠簸的小船。 2. The water in the cup danced with the bouncing of the car. 杯中的水随着汽车的颠簸而跳荡。 3. A bonny, bouncing baby, Freddie was her heart\'s desire and joy. 弗雷迪是一个健康活泼的婴儿，是她的心肝宝贝和欢乐所在。', '副词: bouncingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infatuate', '[ɪn\'fætʃʊˌeɪt]', 'v. 使 ... 冲昏头脑； 使 ... 糊涂 vt. 使 ... 冲昏头脑； 使 ... 糊涂 adj.被冲昏头脑的', '1. Those are the toys that infatuate children. 这是些使孩子们愚蠢的玩具。 2. Why I am so infatuate to network game. 为什么我对网络游戏这么着迷。 3. Yu Su is a TV worker, and also an art infatuate. 俞苏是一位专业电视工作者，也是一位艺术爱好者。 4. I am so infatuate, as a result is unwary beside true good friend. 我是那么着迷，以致疏忽了身边真实的好友。', '过去式: infatuated 过去分词: infatuated 现在分词: infatuating 第三人称单数: infatuates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evict', '[ɪ\'vɪkt]', 'v.驱逐；依法收回', '1. The landlord can evict a tenant who doesn\'t pay the rent. 房东能够驱逐出不付租金的房客。 2. Don\'t fall behind with the rent, or you\'ll be evicted. 不要逾期不缴房租，否则会被逐出。', '名词: evictee 过去式: evicted 过去分词: evicted 现在分词: evicting 第三人称单数: evicts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infest', '[ɪn\'fest]', 'v.侵扰；猖獗；寄生于', '1. There is a warehouse infested by rats. 那有一个大批老鼠出没的仓库。 2. It\'s a garden infested with weeds. 这是杂草丛生的花园。', '名词: infestation 过去式: infested 过去分词: infested 现在分词: infesting 第三人称单数: infests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compost', '[\'kɑːmpoʊst]', 'n.混合肥料；堆肥 v.使成堆肥', '1. The compost is specially formulated for pot plants. 此混合肥料专门用于盆栽植物。 2. But remember not to leave meat and dairy products in the compost. 但是,记住不要在混合肥料中加上肉和日常生活垃圾。 3. I spade compost into the flower beds. 我用铁锹把堆肥撒到花坛中。 4. We were assigned the work of digging in compost in the fields. 分配给我们的任务是在田里翻埋堆肥。 5. They collect vegetable waste and compost it. 他们收集不要的蔬菜,把它们制成堆肥。', '过去式: composted 过去分词: composted 现在分词: composting 第三人称单数: composts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ceremony', '[\'serəmoʊni]', 'n.仪式；礼节；典礼', '1. The marriage ceremony took place in the church. 婚礼在教堂举行。 2. They hold a mystic religious ceremony. 他们举行了一个神秘的宗教仪式。 3. There\'s no need for ceremony between friends. 朋友之间不必拘礼. 4. What the old headmaster said at the graduation ceremony dwells in my mind. 老校长在毕业典礼上讲的话一直留在我的脑海里。', '名词复数: ceremonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anarchist', '[\'ænərkɪst]', 'n.无政府主义者', '1. This work is about the life of an anarchist. 这部作品介绍了一个无政府主义者的生活。 2. I did my best to comfort them and assure them I was not an anarchist. 我尽量安抚他们并让它们明白我并不是一个无政府主义者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sheen', '[ʃiːn]', 'n.光辉；光彩；光泽', '1. Her face glowed with a healthy red sheen. 她的脸上闪着健康的红光。 2. The swallows swooped past with a steel-blue sheen on their swift little bodies. 燕子掠空而过，迅速的小身体闪出发青的光彩。 3. Her hair has a beautiful golden sheen. 她的头发有美丽的金色的光泽。 4. The pearly sheen absorbed many people. 珍珠的光泽吸引了很多人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('condone', '[kən\'doʊn]', 'vt.宽恕', '1. People cannot condone the use of fierce violence. 人们不能宽恕使用凶残的暴力。 2. No faith or culture should condone the outrages against them. 任何信仰或文化都不能宽恕对妇幼施加的暴行。', '名词: condoner 过去式: condoned 过去分词: condoned 现在分词: condoning 第三人称单数: condones');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abominate', '[ə\'bɑːmɪneɪt]', 'vt.痛恨；憎恶', '1. All the teachers abominate cheating in examinations. 所有教师都憎恶考试作弊。', '名词: abominator 过去式: abominated 过去分词: abominated 现在分词: abominating 第三人称单数: abominates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wan', '[wɑn]', 'adj.苍白的；病态的；暗淡的 vi.变苍白；呈病态 abbr.广域网（=wide area network)', '1. Her face wan after her long illness. 她久病后脸色变得苍白。 2. The child looked pale and wan. 这孩子看上去脸色不好，一副有病的样子。', '副词: wanly 比较级: wanner 最高级: wannest 名词: wanness 过去式: wanned 过去分词: wanned 现在分词: wanning 第三人称单数: wans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('weld', '[weld]', 'v.焊接；使结合 n.焊接；焊缝', '1. Weld abandoned tools onto the wheel. 把废弃的工具焊接上车轮。 2. His job is to weld parts together. 他的工作是焊接零件。 3. They weld the pieces of a broken axle. 他们焊接断了的车轴。 4. His job is to weld parts together. 他的工作是焊接零件。', '名词: welder 过去式: welded 过去分词: welded 现在分词: welding 第三人称单数: welds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contend', '[kən\'tend]', 'v.竞争；争斗；争辩；坚决主张', '1. Three armed groups were contending for power. 三个武装集团在争夺权力。 2. John has to contend with great difficulties. 约翰得与那些艰难困苦作斗争。 3. They have to contend against drought every year. 他们每年都得与干旱做斗争。 4. But the potential is simply too significant, the experts contend. 但是专家们主张，潜力是非常重要的。', '名词: contender 过去式: contended 过去分词: contended 现在分词: contending 第三人称单数: contends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subsidiary', '[səb\'sɪdieri]', 'n.子公司；附属机构 adj.辅助的；补贴的；附属的', '1. be disguised by(with) sth 2. A lack of corporate interest has made the subsidiary an orphan. 因缺乏共同利益,这家附属机构无人管理。 3. I plan to study journalism as a subsidiary course. 我打算辅修新闻学。 4. Public transportation plays a subsidiary role. 公共交通起辅助的作用。', '副词: subsidiarily 名词复数: subsidiaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('epidermis', '[ˌepɪ\'dɜːrmɪs]', 'n.表皮；上皮', '1. That part of the epidermis on his hand is damaged. 他手上那块表皮受到损伤。 2. We may say that the epidermis protects the dermis. 我们可以说是表皮保护了真皮。 3. All debris and detached epidermis must be removed. 一切碎屑和分离的老皮必须清除。', '形容词: epidermal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contemptuous', '[kən\'temptʃʊəs]', 'adj.轻视的；轻蔑的；瞧不起的', '1. You should not be contemptuous of underprivileged people. 你不应该看不起无权无势的人。 2. He gave a contemptuous laugh. 他轻蔑地笑了笑。 3. My girl friend is contemptuous of my humble home. 我的女朋友瞧不起我的简陋的家。 4. Snobs are usually contemptuous of people they feel to be beneath them. 势利者通常瞧不起他们认为地位在他们之下的人。', '副词: contemptuously 名词: contemptuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conviviality', '[kənˌvɪvi\'æləti]', 'n.欢乐；高兴；欢宴', '1. Sumptuous food and patriotic music created an atmosphere of elegant conviviality. 佳肴盛馔和爱国乐曲，使气氛十分优雅而欢乐。 2. Your task is to make up a guest list with the maximal conviviality rating of the guests. 你的任务是设计一份参加聚会者的名单，使总的欢乐度最高。 3. Gatherings of friends bring joy with conviviality and celebration. 朋友的聚合带来欢宴和庆祝的喜悦。 4. Distance muted the gorging and tippling at the table to an elfin conviviality. 由于距离远，所以餐桌上的大吃大喝变成了无声的精灵欢宴。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('down', '[daʊn]', 'adv.向下 prep.沿着 ... 而下 adj.向下的；消沉的；无礼的 n.绒毛；汗毛 v.击倒；打败；吞下；被抑制', '1. Please sit down. 请坐下。 2. He is walking down the seaside. 他正沿海边走去。 3. I\'ve been feeling down since I lost my job. 自从失去工作後,我的情绪一直处於低潮。 4. She\'s terribly down on people who don\'t do things her way. 她对不按她的要求做事的人十分不满。 5. A quilt stuffed with the down of the eider duck. 这条被子是用绒鸭毛做芯子的。 6. Antiaircraft guns downed three bombers. 高射炮击落了三架轰炸机。', '过去式: downed 过去分词: downed 现在分词: downing 第三人称单数: downs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prosecution', '[ˌprɑːsɪ\'kjuːʃn]', 'n.起诉；原告；实行', '1. Tony has brought a prosecution against them. 汤尼已对他们提出起诉。 2. No one should be immune from prosecution. 任何人都不应免于被起诉。 3. Failure to pay your taxes will make you liable to prosecution. 不缴纳税款就可能被起诉。 4. Mr Smith acted as counsel for the prosecution. 史密斯先生担任原告的律师。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('freak', '[friːk]', 'n.怪人；狂热爱好者；怪事；反复无常 adj.奇异的；不正常的 vt.使强烈反应(震惊；畏惧) vi.在药物影响下变得异乎寻常', '1. People think she\'s a freak just because she\'s religious. 就因为她信教,人们就把她当成怪人。 2. H is an acid freak. 他是个迷幻药瘾的人。 3. By some freak I was overpaid this month. 真稀奇 4. Or is he inclined to be a fibber, to fits of rage, to be a control freak, to be envious of you, to be secretive? 还是他倾向于一个撒小谎者，容易动怒，性格反复无常的，嫉妒你的，偷偷摸摸的人。 5. He was really confused by the freak result. 这个异乎寻常的结果让他非常困惑。 6. Listening to a good stereo system always freaks me out. 我一听到好的立体声音乐就乐不可支。 7. John\'s party was really wild and everyone freaked out(on drugs). 约翰搞得聚会真够疯狂在,大家都（吸食毒品)神魂颠倒了。', '过去式: freaked 过去分词: freaked 现在分词: freaking 第三人称单数: freaks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ambivalence', '[æm\'bɪvələns]', 'n.矛盾情绪；矛盾心理', '1. She felt a certain ambivalence towards him. 她对他的态度有些矛盾。 2. But lately ambivalence is turning into out-and-out royalism. 但是近来，这种矛盾的情绪逐渐转变成彻底的君权思想。 3. He understood the public\'s ambivalence, shown by every poll. 他了解每次民意测验反映出来的公众的矛盾心理。 4. Their ambivalence gave us a chance to play for time and recoup. 他们的矛盾心理使我们有机会拖延时间争取复原。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('probe', '[proʊb]', 'n.调查；查究；探针；探测器 v.用探针测；探测；详细调查', '1. They launched a probe into the disappearance of government funds. 他们发起了对政府资金流失一事的调查. 2. Pressure on the industry was building even before the latest probe. 事实上,在最近的调查之前,压力就已经在这个行业聚集。 3. The image sent back by the probe is very clear. 探针传回的图像非常清晰。 4. The brain surgeon asked the nurse to pass him a probe. 脑外科医生要护士将探针递给他。 5. The doctor will probe your stomach with a camera. 医生会用带摄像头的胃镜检查你的胃。', '副词: probingly 名词: prober 过去式: probed 过去分词: probed 现在分词: probing 第三人称单数: probes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cunning', '[\'kʌnɪŋ]', 'adj.狡猾的；有眼光的；精巧的；可爱的 n.【C】狡诈；灵巧', '1. Many politicians are cunning sophists. 许多政客都是狡猾的诡辩家。 2. The fox is known for its cleverness and cunning. 狐狸的机敏和狡猾是人所共知的。 3. She showed her cunning in the way she avoided answering the question. 她对问题避而不答，显示出她很狡猾。 4. He devised a very cunning scheme to help her. 他想出一个帮助她的很好的办法。 5. The fox is believed to have a great deal of cunning. 人们相信狐狸十分狡猾。', '副词: cunningly 名词: cunningness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('panic', '[\'pænɪk]', 'n.惊慌；恐慌 v.使…惊慌；感到恐慌 adj.恐慌的；惊慌的', '1. There was a panic when the building caught fire. 大楼起火时, 人们一片惊慌。 2. Rumours of an imminent earthquake startled a panic. 谣传即将发生地震引起了一阵恐慌。 3. The thunder panicked the horse. 雷声使马受惊了。 4. The idea might panic the investors. 这个想法可能会使投资者惶恐不安。 5. The financial crisis caused panic selling of securities. 金融危机引发了恐慌之下的债权抛售。', '形容词: panicky 过去式: panicked 过去分词: panicked 现在分词: panicking 第三人称单数: panics');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('guile', '[ɡaɪl]', 'n.狡猾；狡诈', '1. They used their craft and guile to close the deal. 他们用他们的精明狡猾完成了这笔交易。 2. Anon is not known for guile or intricate schemes. 阿农从不耍阴谋诡计。', '过去式: guiled 过去分词: guiled 现在分词: guiling 第三人称单数: guiles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flavoring', '[\'fleɪvrɪŋ]', 'n.调味料 动词flavor的现在分词形式. =flavouring.', '1. But Eastern cooks have been using glutamate-rich seaweed as flavoring for more than 1000 years. 但一千多年来，东方的厨师一直用富含谷氨酸盐的海藻当调味料。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loom', '[luːm]', 'n.织布机 n.若隐若现 vi.隐约可见；迫近', '1. I don\'t know how to use a hand loom. 我不知道怎样使用手工织布机。 2. The fabric was weaving at her loom. 她的织布机正编织着这些织物。 3. The shuttle flies back and forth on the loom. 织布机上梭子来回飞动。 4. The children are so excited to watch for the first loom of the land. 孩子们兴奋地注视着陆地的初现。 5. The mountainous island loomed on the horizon. 那座巨大的岛屿隐隐约约浮现在地平线上。', '过去式: loomed 过去分词: loomed 现在分词: looming 第三人称单数: looms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exhaustive', '[ɪɡ\'zɔːstɪv]', 'adj.彻底的；详尽的；消耗的', '1. He has made an exhaustive study of the problem. 他对这个问题进行了彻底的研究。 2. After an exhaustive search the missing document was found. 经过彻底搜寻丢失的文件被找到了。 3. An exhaustive investigation of the facts proves the contrary. 彻底地调查事实后发现情况正好相反。 4. To compile an exhaustive dictionary is an exhausting task. 编写一本详尽的字典是一件吃力的工作。', '副词: exhaustively 名词: exhaustiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spike', '[spaɪk]', 'n.长钉；尖状物；钉鞋；峰值；穗；穗状花；【排球】扣球 v.以大钉钉牢；使 ... 失效；用尖物刺伤；【排球】扣球', '1. There are many sharp spikes on the railings in the park. 公园的栏杆上有很多尖头。 2. In that case, the price spike would be something like a dead-cat bounce. 在那种情况下，股价峰值可能会像死猫诈尸一样反弹。 3. Here is effective rice spike number. 这是水稻有效稻穗数。 4. They\'ll do anything to spike the guns of the opposition. 他们会使出各种手段来挫败对手。', '形容词: spiked 过去式: spiked 过去分词: spiked 现在分词: spiking 第三人称单数: spikes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('despoil', '[dɪ\'spɔɪl]', 'v.夺取；掠夺', '1. A region despoiled of its scenic beauty by unchecked development. 由于不加限制的发展而使这个地区丧失了其美丽景色 2. Museums have despoiled India of many priceless treasures. 博物馆里有许多从印度掠夺来的无价之宝。', '名词: despoiler 过去式: despoiled 过去分词: despoiled 现在分词: despoiling 第三人称单数: despoils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enormity', '[ɪ\'nɔːrməti]', 'n.暴行；极恶；巨大', '1. Such enormities would not be tolerated today. 这种严重罪行今日是不能容忍的。 2. The enormity of the crime has shocked even experienced policemen. 这件罪行极端凶残，连经历丰富的警察都感震惊。 3. He talked for some time with Bundy, and his questions reflected the enormity of his doubts. 他同邦迪谈了一会儿，他提出的问题反映出他有很大的怀疑。', '名词复数: enormities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remorse', '[rɪ\'mɔːrs]', 'n.懊悔；悔恨', '1. He seemed to feel no remorse at all. 他当时似乎一点也不感到懊悔。 2. He was filled with remorse for not believing her. 他因为没有相信她而懊悔不已。 3. He was filled with remorse after hitting the child. 他打过孩子后感到悔恨不已。 4. Her anger gave place to remorse. 她不再感到愤怒，而是感到悔恨。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compulsion', '[kəm\'pʌlʃn]', 'n.强迫；强制；难以抗拒的冲动；（不能克制的）欲望', '1. I will pay nothing under compulsion. 在强迫之下我分文也不愿付。 2. Compulsion will never result in convincing them. 强迫永远不会使他们信服。 3. John will take his medicine only by compulsion. 只有对他用强制手段约翰才会服药。 4. She felt a sudden compulsion to hit him. 她突然感到一种难以抗拒的冲动,想要揍他。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inequity', '[ɪn\'ekwəti]', 'n.不公平；不公正', '1. It is right to fight to overcome Inequity. 反抗不平等是正当的。 2. Reducing inequity is the highest human achievement. 减少不平等才是人类的最大成就。 3. An inequity in salaries is an obvious drawback in the industry. 在产业薪酬管理方面的不足表现得尤为明显。', '名词复数: inequities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peregrination', '[ˌperəɡrɪ\'neɪʃn]', 'n. <正式>游历； 旅行', '1. Peregrin:Well,that isn\'t so bad. 皮平：噢，那还不错。 2. Peregrin:I didn\'t think it would end this way. 皮平：没想到会这样结束。 3. Peregrin:What,Gandalf? See what? 皮平：什么，甘道夫？看到什么？ 4. Gandalf: Knock your head against these doors, Peregrin Took! 甘道夫：用你的头把大门撞开。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('columnist', '[\'kɑːləmnɪst]', 'n.专栏作家', '1. She\'s a columnist for USA Today. 她是《今日美国报》的专栏作家。 2. The host was interviewing a local columnist. 节目主持人正在同一位当地的专栏作家交谈。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spartan', '[\'spɑːrtn]', 'n.斯巴达人；刚勇之人 adj.斯巴达的；斯巴达人的；斯巴达式的；斯巴达文化的；纪律性强的', '1. Only one among us keeps his Spartan reserve. 我们之中只有一人仍保持着斯巴达人的缄默。 2. Enjolras, who was grave, dominated it, in the attitude of a young Spartan sacrificing his naked sword to the sombre genius, Epidotas. 安灼拉严肃地坐镇街垒，他的姿势正如一个年轻的斯巴达人，他立誓要把光秃秃的剑奉献给忧郁的天才埃比陀达斯。 3. Go tell the Spartans, passerby, that here, by Spartan law, we lie! 走，去告诉斯巴达人们，过路人，斯巴达的法律，我们躺在这儿！ 4. Spartan women with property enjoyed good social states, because Spartan law forbade dividing the land originally allotted to a family. 拥有地产的女性拥有较高的社会地位，因为斯巴达的法律禁止分割原属于家庭的土地。', '副词: Spartanly 名词: Spartanism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lot', '[lɑːt]', 'n.许多；大量；抽签；签；命运；一块地；拍卖品；一类或一些(人或物)；批；套；份儿 adv.很；非常 v.划分；分配', '1. It takes a lot of labor to build a railway. 修筑一条铁路要花费许多劳动力。 2. She had a lot of problems to contend with. 她有许多问题要解决。 3. The flood did a lot of damage to the crops. 洪水毁坏了大量农作物。 4. This firm prints a lot of musical and sports books. 这家公司出版了大量的音乐和体育书籍。 5. I\'m feeling a lot better today. 我今天身体好多了.', '过去式: lotted 过去分词: lotted 现在分词: lotting 第三人称单数: lots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mettle', '[\'metl]', 'n.勇气；气质；性格', '1. As to whether MoUs recover, that depends on their mettle. 至于宇宙主宰者能否复原，这取决于他们的勇气。 2. This is the first assault on the new world we seek, the first test of our mettle. 这是对我们所寻求的新世界的第一次攻击，也是对我们勇气的第一次挑战。 3. These were spirited men, men of character and mettle. 这些都是有骨气的人，有特殊性格和气质的人。 4. These were spirited men, men of character and mettle. 这些都是有骨气的人，有特殊性格和气质的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('penance', '[\'penəns]', 'n.自我惩罚；忏悔；赎罪 v.使忏悔', '1. He had done penance for his sins, we should forgive him. 他已经为赎罪自我惩罚了，我们应该原谅他。 2. She regards living in New York as a penance; she hates big cities. 她把住在纽约视为一件苦事,她讨厌大都市。 3. There is no absolution without penance. 没有忏悔就谈不上宽恕。 4. She knelt at her mother\'s feet in penance. 她忏悔地跪在母亲脚下。', '过去式: penanced 过去分词: penanced 现在分词: penancing 第三人称单数: penances');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malaise', '[mə\'leɪz]', 'n.莫名的不安；身体不适', '1. The country is laden with economic and political malaise. 该国充满经济和政治上的隐忧。 2. You can see signs of malaise in our office. 在我们办公室里可以看到有某种不安迹象。 3. One year after the crash, the markets remain mired in a deep malaise. 股市崩盘一年后，市场仍是萎靡不振。 4. He coughed with sputum and feeling of malaise. 他咳嗽有浓痰，而且觉得很虚弱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tango', '[\'tæŋɡoʊ]', 'n.探戈舞；探戈舞曲 v.跳探戈舞', '1. But the slow street tango had begun. 可是那慢步探戈舞已经开始了。 2. This piece of music is suitable for tango. 这支曲子适合跳探戈舞。 3. Sorry, I promised someone else in this tango. 对不起，我已经答应和别人跳这支探戈舞了。 4. When he grabbed me and started to tango I relaxed again. 当他拉我去跳探戈的时候，我才松了一口气。', '形容词: tangolike 名词复数: tangos 过去式: tangoed 过去分词: tangoed 现在分词: tangoing 第三人称单数: tangos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recast', '[ˌriː\'kæst]', 'v.改动；改变演员阵容；重铸；重作 n.重铸；改变角色', '1. She recast her lecture as a radio talk. 她把讲义改动后用作电台的讲话. 2. I\'ve been recast as Brutus. 我改演布鲁特斯一角。 3. They tried their best to recast a bell. 他们尽了自己最大努力重铸了一口钟。', '过去式: recast 过去分词: recast 现在分词: recasting 第三人称单数: recasts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('berserk', '[bər\'zɜːrk]', 'adj.狂暴的；狂怒的', '1. The dog went berserk when a wasp stung him. 狗被黄蜂咬了,变得非常狂暴。 2. He suddenly went berserk with rage. 他突然狂怒起来。 3. My husband will go berserk if he finds you here. 要是我丈夫发觉你在这里，他会气疯的。', '副词: berserkly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nonesuch', '[\'nʌnˌsʌtʃ]', 'n.无以匹敌的人；无双的事物 adj.无双的；无与伦比的', '1. The Nonesuch could be considered the oldest actively expelling oil source bed. 农萨奇页岩可能是最古老的还在排油的烃源岩。 2. Nonesuch, beautiful, fair, lovely, pretty, comely, angelic, glamorous, beauteous, beautiful; voluptuous, etc. 绝品,美丽,美丽,可爱美丽动人,天使,富有魔力,美妙的,美丽,漂亮,;色情,等等。 3. Xiangyu butterfly museum, collect the nonesuch butterfly and shrink the natural fairy in one place. 翔宇蝴蝶博物馆， 浓世界精品蝴蝶于一处，缩自然精灵成一馆。 4. We will supply a top-ranking international freight agency service, and create the future logistic nonesuch. 我们为您提供一流的国际货运代理服务，更创造未来物流价值的典范！', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exact', '[ɪɡ\'zækt]', 'adj.精密严谨的；确切的', '1. She\'s a very exact person. 她是个一丝不苟的人。 2. We need exact instruments. 我们需要精密仪器。 3. What is the exact size of the room? 这个房间的确切面积是多少？ 4. It was difficult to tell her exact age. 很难说出她的确切年龄。', '形容词: exactable 名词: exactness 过去式: exacted 过去分词: exacted 现在分词: exacting 第三人称单数: exacts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('militia', '[mə\'lɪʃə]', 'n.民兵组织；义勇军；国民军', '1. The militia captured the castle. 民兵占领了这座城堡。 2. People gathered to form a militia to protect their town. 人们聚集起来，组成国民自卫队来保卫他们的城镇。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scramble', '[\'skræmbl]', 'n.混乱；攀爬；争夺 v.攀爬；混杂；争抢；紧急起飞；杂乱地生长', '1. A table was pushed over in the scramble. 在混乱中一张桌子被推翻了。 2. It\'s quite a scramble to get to the top of the hill! 要往上爬很长一段路才能到达山顶呢！ 3. He broke his leg in his scramble down the wall. 他爬墙摔断了腿。 4. There was a scramble for the best seats. 大家都在抢最好的座位。 5. How can you scramble up such a steep hillside? 你怎么能爬上这么陡峭的山坡?', '过去式: scrambled 过去分词: scrambled 现在分词: scrambling 第三人称单数: scrambles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('environ', '[ɪn\'vaɪrən]', 'vt.包围；环绕', '1. Trees environ the yard. 树木环绕着那个院子。', '过去式: environed 过去分词: environed 现在分词: environing 第三人称单数: environs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('leakage', '[\'liːkɪdʒ]', 'n.泄漏，泄漏物', '1. Leakage at the point where pipes are connected. 管道连接处的泄漏。 2. Deep packing glands eliminate leakage. 深厚的填料密封垫避免泄漏。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conciliatory', '[kən\'sɪliətɔːri]', 'adj.调和的；安抚的', '1. Her expression was not conciliatory. 她的脸色显得毫不调和。 2. His letter was couched in conciliatory terms. 他那封信里使用了表示和解的言辞。 3. A more conciliatory approach is more productive. 更加柔和的手段总是更有成效。 4. The politician struck a conciliatory tone with his former adversaries. 那个政客用安抚的口吻跟以前的对手说话。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('announce', '[ə\'naʊns]', 'vt.宣布；宣告；预示；播报 vi.作播音员；宣布竞选', '1. I hope to announce the winner shortly. 我希望马上宣布胜利者的名字。 2. The president will announce a momentous decision. 主席将宣布重要决定。 3. We can go out to people and announce Good News. 我们能够走向人们，宣告天国的好消息。 4. I will always announce my goals to the world. 我要常常向世人宣告我的目标。 5. Cindy announces four programs a week. 辛迪一星期担任四个节目的播音员。', '过去式: announced 过去分词: announced 现在分词: announcing 第三人称单数: announces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amendment', '[ə\'mendmənt]', 'n.修正；修正案；改进', '1. The amendment is an appendage of that contract. 这个修改案是那个合同的附件。 2. The amendment will become effective next year. 修正案将于明年生效。 3. That representative brought forth an amendment to the press law. 那位代表提出了一项对新闻法的修正案。 4. He seemed to have resolved on amendment. 他似乎已决心痛改前非。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sizzler', '[\'sɪzlə]', 'n.极烫的东西；大热天', '1. Whew! What a sizzler! 唷! 多热的天哪！', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beat', '[biːt]', 'v.打；打败；跳动；敲打；战胜 n.拍子；敲打；心跳声 adj.精疲力尽的', '1. His father beat the disobedient boy. 他的父亲打那个不听话的男孩。 2. If we don\'t prepare for the speech contest, they will beat us. 如果这场演讲比赛我们不做好准备的话,他们就会打败我们。 3. He\'s alive；his heart is still beating. 他还活著－－心脏还在跳。 4. They beat drums to cheer up the players. 他们擂鼓给运动员加油。 5. Every member of the band must follow the beat. 乐队的每个成员都必须跟着拍子演奏。 6. I am completely beat. 我累极了。', '过去式: beat 过去分词: beaten/beat 现在分词: beating 第三人称单数: beats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concomitant', '[kən\'kɒmətənt]', 'adj.相伴的；附随的；共存的 n.附随物', '1. The concomitant season of spring is summer. 紧接着春天而来的就是夏天。 2. Tsunamis are concomitant with off shore earthquakes. 海啸是随海上地震而产生的。 3. Deafness is a frequent concomitant of old age. 耳聋是老年伴随而来的现象。', '副词: concomitantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obituary', '[oʊ\'bɪtʃueri]', 'n.讣告 adj.死亡的', '1. Martin was very shocked to see his best friend\'s obituary in the news paper. 马丁在报上看见好友的讣告，感到非常震惊。 2. Five days after the letter came, he found Andersen\'s obituary in the morning paper. 收到那封信五天后，他在早报上发现了安德森的讣告。 3. The obituary records the whole life of the deceased. 讣文记述了这位死者的生平。 4. I never want to see anybody die, but there are a few obituary notices I have read with pleasure. 我从未想过看到人家死，但有几段讣闻，我是欣然拜读过了。', '名词复数: obituaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inconstancy', '[ɪn\'kɒnstənsi]', 'n.易变；不定性；不忠实', '1. Constancy is therefore inconstancy held in check and confined to the same object. 因此恒定不变就是将易变控制与局限在同一个对象上。 2. Constancy in love is perpetual inconstancy, inasmuch as the heart is drawn to one quality after another in the beloved, now preferring this, now that. 爱所恒定不变的是它永恒的易变，因为心被心爱人一个接着一个的特质所吸引，一会儿更喜欢这个，一会儿又更喜欢那个。', '名词复数: inconstancies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hinterland', '[\'hɪntərlænd]', 'n.内陆地区；内地；腹地', '1. A century ago, eastern Germany was an agricultural hinterland. 一个世纪前, 德国东部是个农业的内陆地区。 2. Circuses in the hinterland were hilarious. 内地的马戏团非常热闹。 3. Her shows in border areas and the hinterland had a big influence. 她在边疆和内地演出颇具影响。 4. However, Dunhuang is located in the hinterland of the great desert. 然而，敦煌处在大漠的腹地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maunder', '[\'mɔːndər]', 'v.絮叨；闲逛；徘徊', '1. The drunk sat there maundering about his troubles. 那醉鬼坐在那里唠叨着自己的烦恼事。 2. Don\'t just maunder about,do some work. 别光闲荡了，做点正经事吧。', '过去式: maundered 过去分词: maundered 现在分词: maundering 第三人称单数: maunders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('finable', '[\'faɪnəbəl]', 'adj.应罚款的', '1. Stress can be the undoing of so many fine players. 紧张可能是这许多优秀选手失败的原因。 2. The portrait shows fine effects of light and shade. 这幅肖像画的浓淡色调表现得很好。 3. That was a fine meal if ever there was one! 那确实是一顿丰盛的饭。 4. Let\'s cash in on the fine weather and go out. 我们趁天气好出去玩玩吧。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conjugal', '[\'kɒndʒəgəl]', 'adj.婚姻的；夫妻间的', '1. Then these are just conjugal visits. 然后这些仅仅是婚姻调查。 2. A couple\'s conjugal fate is prearranged. 婚姻是缘分。', '副词: conjugally 名词: conjugality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nifty', '[\'nɪfti]', 'adj.小巧的；漂亮的；熟练的；极好的 n.俏皮话；漂亮东西', '1. a nifty little gadget for peeling potatoes 削土豆皮的小巧的工具 2. My key chain has several nifty tools on it. 我的钥匙链有些极小巧的工具在上面。 3. That is a nifty suit. 那是很漂亮的一身衣服。 4. Learn some nifty pen-flicking tricks. 学习一些漂亮的玩笔技巧。', '副词: niftily 比较级: niftier 最高级: niftiest 名词: niftiness 名词复数: nifties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scission', '[\'sɪʒən]', 'n.切断；分离；分裂', '1. The reaction of chain scission is first-order reaction. 白油的断链为一级反应。 2. This derivation is only valid if no chain scission accompanies crosslinking. 这一关系式仅适用于交联时不伴有断链发生的情况。 3. This derivation is only valid if no chain scission accompanies cross linking. 这一关系式仅适用于交联时不伴有断链发生的情况。 4. The results show that chain scission and oxidation occurr in the whole reaction. 研究表明,白油在热氧老化过程中主要发生断链和氧化反应。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('restiveness', '[\'restɪvnəs]', 'n.倔强；难以驾御', '1. He is restiveness just like donkey. 他像驴子一样倔强。 2. Seeing a faint restiveness in Lincoln\'s eye, he changed the subject. 他觉察到林肯眼神略带烦躁，便改了话题。 3. This is also the side of my caprice and restiveness , and still will consist this spirit . 这也是我的一种任性和倔强吧，以后还是会坚持这种自由精神。 4. Popular restiveness against national leaders, even if it is not allowed to show itself in Toyako, puts the G8’s goals in even greater question. 公众对国家领导人的难以驾驭，即使这次在东京不允许被展示，使得G8的目标陷入了更多的困境。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diminution', '[ˌdɪmɪ\'nuːʃn]', 'n.减少；缩小；减少量；缩小量', '1. The government tried to prevent the diminution of resources. 政府试图阻止资源的减少。 2. They are hoping for a small diminution in taxes. 他们希望税捐略微减少。', '形容词: diminutional');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tumid', '[\'tjuːmɪd]', 'adj.浮夸的；肿胀的', '1. Schoolboy how pouch of purify black, tumid? 男生怎样去除黑色、肿胀的眼袋？ 2. So high as heaved the tumid hills, so low Down sunk a hollow bottom broad and deep, Capacious bed of waters. 高耸的山峰升得这高,低洼的湖底沉得这低 3. Her eyes are so red and tumid , and I knew that she said “ Nothing “, she was dreaded that solicitous about her . 通红的眼睛，任谁都看得出来，这句“没什么”只是为了不让别人替她担心。 4. My eyelid has been tumid since yesterday. This morning it became worse. So painful! 从昨天起，左下眼皮就肿了。今早更为严重，发炎了。疼死！', '副词: tumidly 名词: tumidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tattle', '[\'tætl]', 'v.闲谈；泄密 n.闲谈；饶舌', '1. Who\'s been tattling? 谁在说闲话呢？', '副词: tattlingly 过去式: tattled 过去分词: tattled 现在分词: tattling 第三人称单数: tattles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rapport', '[ræ\'pɔːr]', 'n.关系；亲善；一致', '1. He is in rapport with his pupils. 他与学生关系很好。 2. Father and son have a great rapport. 父子情深。 3. The actor developed a close rapport with his audience. 该演员与观众建立了密切的关系。 4. She has an excellent rapport with her staff. 她跟她职员的关系非常融洽。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brat', '[bræt]', 'n.乳臭未干的小孩；顽童', '1. That spoiled brat is used to having his own way. 那位被宠坏的小孩习惯于我行我素。 2. Love is a brat who always wants what he or she can\'t have. 爱情就是一个不懂事的小孩，永远想要自己无法拥有的东西。 3. The brat sicked his dog on the passer-by. 那个顽童纵狗去咬过路人。 4. That brat was known to devil all of his classmates. 那个淘气孩子让所有同学都很头疼。', '形容词: brattish 名词: brattishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('painstaking', '[\'peɪnzteɪkɪŋ]', 'adj.辛苦的；勤勉的；十分小心的 n.辛苦；苦心；工夫', '1. Planned or executed with painstaking attention to numerous parts or details. 精心制作的对众多部分或细节给予精心注意的计划或制作的', '副词: painstakingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('necessitous', '[nə\'sesətəs]', 'adj.贫困的；急需的', '1. A young man negligent, an old man necessitous. 少壮不努力,老大徒伤悲。 2. The bishop planned to visit necessitous areas of the city. 主教打算走访城市里的贫困地区。 3. We must reserve the necessitous of life and the supplies of earthquake relief. 我们必须储备生活必需品和抗震救灾物资。 4. The time which was left to him from the afflicted,the sick,and the necessitous,he devoted to work. 在痛苦和贫病的人之后留下的时间，他用在劳动上。', '副词: necessitously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('armada', '[ɑːr\'mɑːdə]', 'n.舰队；机群；（车辆）编队', '1. Spain used to be famous for its strong armada. 西班牙曾以其强大的舰队而著称。 2. The Spanish Armada sailed to England in1588. 西班牙无敌舰队在一五八八年派遣到英格兰。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sedition', '[sɪ\'dɪʃn]', 'n.煽动骚乱的言语或行为', '1. They were charged with sedition. 他们被指控煽动叛乱。 2. He was brought to trial on charges of sedition. 他以煽动闹事罪被送法院审理。 3. His denial of sedition was a denial of violence. 他对煽动叛乱的否定又是对暴力的否定。', '名词: seditionist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fixate', '[\'fɪkseɪt]', 'v.早期停止性的成熟；注视；固定', '1. An infant with normal vision will fixate on a light held before him. 一个有正常视力的婴儿会注视他面前的光亮。', '过去式: fixated 过去分词: fixated 现在分词: fixating 第三人称单数: fixates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conclusive', '[kən\'kluːsɪv]', 'adj.决定性的；确实的；结论性的', '1. It was not a war that promised a conclusive end. 那并不是一场指望有决定性结果的战争。 2. They produced some fairly conclusive evidence. 他们提供了一些相当确凿的证据。 3. Her fingerprints on the gun were conclusive proof of her guilt. 她在枪上留下的指纹就是她犯罪的确凿证据。 4. These arguments, particularly the last one, were conclusive. 这些理由,特别是最后一个,是毫无争论余地的。', '副词: conclusively 名词: conclusiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compliant', '[kəm\'plaɪənt]', 'adj.适用的；顺从的', '1. Future versions will be fully compliant with the industry standard. 今后的版本将完全符合工业标准的要求。 2. For years I had tried to be a compliant and dutiful wife. 几年来,我努力做一名顺从和尽职尽职的妻子。', '副词: compliantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defuse', '[ˌdiː\'fjuːz]', 'vt.拆除(炸弹等)的雷管；消除危险；缓和', '1. The bomb blew up as experts tried to defuse it. 专家们试图拆除引信时炸弹爆炸了。 2. He was killed while trying to defuse a roadside bomb. 他试图拆除道路旁的炸弹引信时，不幸遇难。 3. This may defuse some of their anger. 这也许能够消除他们的怒气。 4. Give up resentment can defuse cancer. 丢弃怨恨甚至能够化解癌症。', '过去式: defused 过去分词: defused 现在分词: defusing 第三人称单数: defuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cantankerous', '[kæn\'tæŋkərəs]', 'adj.脾气坏的；好争吵的；难相处的', '1. The cantankerous bus driver rouse on the childrenfor singing. 那个坏脾气的公共汽车司机因为孩子们唱歌而骂他们。 2. He\'s a cantankerous, nasty man who hates students with a passion. 他是一个脾气很坏，令人讨厌的人，他的爱好就是与学生作对。 3. David\'s first wife was cantankerous. 大卫的第一任妻子是一个很任性的人。', '副词: cantankerously 名词: cantankerousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('core', '[kɔːr]', 'n.核心；果心；要点 vt.挖去果核', '1. The core of our appeal is freedom of speech. 我们的要求的核心是言论自由。 2. He is American to the core. 他是个地地道道的美国人。 3. He ate the plum, and threw the core away. 他吃掉了李子，并扔掉了果核。 4. Let\'s get to the core of the argument. 咱们进入实质性的辩论吧。', '过去式: cored 过去分词: cored 现在分词: coring 第三人称单数: cores');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('herbicide', '[\'ɜːrbɪsaɪd]', 'n.除草剂', '1. This herbicide degrades in moist soil. 这种除草剂在潮湿的土壤中分解。', '形容词: herbicidal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vaccine', '[væk\'siːn]', 'n.疫苗', '1. The vaccine was used to protect the whole population against infection. 这种疫苗用以为全体居民预防传染病。 2. The smallpox vaccine has saved many lives. 天花疫苗挽救了许多人的生命。 3. The search for a new vaccine took priority over all other medical research. 在各种医药研究中，应首先解决寻找新疫苗的问题。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impressed', '[ɪm\'pres]', 'n.印记；印象；特征 v.使 ... 有印象；影响；印刻；传送', '1. Their honesty and hospitality leave an indelible impress on her life. 他们的诚实与好客给她一生留下了难以磨灭的印象。 2. I had a chance to impress her with my efficiency and I muffed it up. 我本来有机会使她对我的办事效率有印象,但是我错过了这个机会。 3. She impressed me as a scholar. 她给我留下了学者的印象。 4. What impress you most when you go to IKEA? 您去宜家时以下哪一项对您影响最深刻？', '过去式: impressed 过去分词: impressed 现在分词: impressing 第三人称单数: impresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('haughty', '[\'hɔːti]', 'adj.傲慢的；自大的；骄傲的', '1. It is hard for a haughty man to swallow his words. 要一个傲慢的人认错是很困难的。 2. The nobles treated the common people with haughty contempt. 王公贵族以不屑一顾的傲慢态度对待平民百姓。', '副词: haughtily 比较级: haughtier 最高级: haughtiest 名词: haughtiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chimera', '[kaɪ\'mɪrə]', 'n.神话怪物；妄想；嵌合体 Chimera. [希神]奇美拉（喷火女怪）.', '1. But it is a chimera, and a dangerous one at that. 但这只是一个妄想,而且是一个很危险的妄想。 2. Different species can also form a chimera. 不同的物种也可以形成嵌合体。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nicety', '[\'naɪsəti]', 'n.准确；精确；细微的区别；优美的东西', '1. The job calls for nicety of judgment. 这一工作要求判断准确。 2. This is a point of great nicety. 这是非常细微的一点。 3. Having a bosom friend is one of the niceties of life. 得一知己乃人生一大乐事。', '名词复数: niceties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('orthodox', '[\'ɔːrθədɑːks]', 'adj.正统的；传统的；东正教的', '1. He is very orthodox in his views. 他的观点十分正统。 2. The young generation today don\'t like orthodox teaching. 当今的年轻一代不喜欢正统的说教。 3. Orthodox Christian churches often have elaborate steeples. 传统的基督教堂都有精致的尖塔。 4. The restaurant offers the orthodox Christmas dinner of turkey. 这个餐馆供应传统的圣诞火鸡餐。', '副词: orthodoxly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('macabre', '[mə\'kɑːbrə]', 'adj.恐怖的；令人毛骨悚然的；以死亡为主题的', '1. Even a successful electrocution is macabre. 就算是一次成功的电刑，它也是很恐怖的。 2. If that doesn’t give you a macabre thrill, nothing will. 如果没有给带来阵阵寒颤，那么你会什么事都不惧怕了。', '副词: macabrely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('purgative', '[\'pɜːrɡətɪv]', 'n.泻药 adj.催泻的', '1. Take some purgative and it will help you purge your bowels of bad matter. 吃点泻药有助于你将肠胃中的有害物质除去。 2. This oil has a purgative effect. 这种油有催泻作用.', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('onslaught', '[\'ɑːnslɔːt]', 'n.猛攻；攻击；抨击', '1. Our army tried to withstand the enemy onslaught. 我们的军队奋力抵挡敌人的猛攻。 2. The army took the fort on the first onslaught. 那支军队第一次突击就夺取了要塞。 3. The town survives the onslaught of tourists every summer. 每年夏天，这座小城都要熬过一段旅游者蜂拥而至的苦日子。 4. The central nervous systems survived the onslaught from the virus. 中央神经系统 承受了病毒的猛烈攻击', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anticlimax', '[ˌænti\'klaɪmæks]', 'n.突降；急转而下；虎头蛇尾', '1. Before the listener knows where he is, the mounting tension is lifted in a pianissimo anticlimax. 在听众不知不觉之间，紧张气氛在最弱音的突减中被提升了。 2. The anticlimax of a brilliant career is quite disappointing. 辉煌事业的急转而下很令人失望。 3. It was an anticlimax when they abandoned the game. 他们放弃比赛,真是扫兴。 4. The holiday itself was rather an anticlimax after all the excitement of planning it. 尽管计划度假时兴致勃勃，而到头来假日本身却颇为扫兴。', '形容词: anticlimactic 副词: anticlimactically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hieroglyph', '[\'haɪərəɡlɪf]', 'n.象形文字；图画文字；秘密文字', '1. As a hieroglyph this symbol represents the unification of Upper and Lower Egypt. 如一个象形文字那样，这个符号表现了上埃及和下埃及的统一。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grating', '[\'ɡreɪtɪŋ]', 'n.格子；格栅；[物]光栅 adj.磨擦的；刺耳的 动词grate的现在分词.', '1. From the cellar grating floated up the flabby gush of porter. 隔着地窖的格子窗飘出走了气的黑啤酒味儿。 2. A face leered at him through a grating in a door. 有一张脸从门上的格栅里恶狠狠地瞪着他。 3. The grating are made of rods or wire. 光栅由金属或丝制造。 4. As he spoke there was the sharp sound of horses\' hoofs and grating wheels against the cub, followed by a sharp pull at the bell. 就在他说话的时候,响起了一阵清脆的马蹄声和马车轮子摩擦路边镶边石的轧轧声,接着有人猛烈地拉着门铃。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embolden', '[ɪm\'boʊldən]', 'vt. 给 ... 壮胆； 鼓励', '1. If we fail to make that case effectively, we will weaken already tenuous democratic forces and embolden those in Iraq who seek to foment chaos and instability. 如果我们不能有效地做到这点，我们将削弱本来就已软弱的民主力量，并给那些企图制造混乱和动荡的伊拉克人壮胆。 2. People behind the scenes are rooting for you, even though they may not outwardly reveal their support of you just yet - let that knowledge embolden you. 人们会在幕后支持你，虽然他们表面上或许还未显露出他们对你的支持，让那个认知帮你壮壮胆吧。 3. However, they acknowledged that such a forum could embolden supporters of political reform within the Communist party. 不过，它们承认，有这样一个论坛，可能鼓励共产党内支持政治改革的人士。', '过去式: emboldened 过去分词: emboldened 现在分词: emboldening 第三人称单数: emboldens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pod', '[pɑːd]', 'n.豆荚；分离舱 n.(海豹或鲸等的)一群 v.剥掉(豆荚)', '1. The pod of this plant, containing a sweet edible pulp and seeds that yield a gum used as a stabilizer in food products. 角豆荚角豆植物的豆荚，内含味甜可食的肉质部分以及种子，它们产生出一种胶，可用于食品中做稳定剂 2. A pod, such as that of a pea or bean, that splits into two valves with the seeds attached to one edge of the valves. 豆荚豆荚，如豌豆或蚕豆之类的，分成两个裂片，其果实附着在其中一片裂片之上 3. He is podding peas. 他正在剥豌豆。 4. This kind of pea has a long pod. 这种豌豆长着长豆荚。', '过去式: podded 过去分词: podded 现在分词: podding 第三人称单数: pods');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parallel', '[\'pærəlel]', 'adj.平行的；相同的；类似的；并联的 n.对比；平行线(面)；双杠；相似物 vt.相比；相应；与 ... 平行', '1. In the parallel world, there might be an answer for everything. 在平行世界里,似乎有一切的答案。 2. Parallel processing is the most important peculiarity in this design. 其中,并行化的设计理念是该设计的最大特点。 3. The railway lines run parallel to the road. 铁路线和那条道路平行。 4. My experience in this matter is parallel to yours. 在这件事情上，我的经验和你的类似。 5. It is inappropriate to draw such a parallel. 这种比拟是不恰当的。 6. No one can parallel him in Math. 在数学方面无人能与他匹敌。', '过去式: paralleled/parallelled 过去分词: paralleled/parallelled 现在分词: paralleling/parallelling 第三人称单数: parallels/parallels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impecunious', '[ˌɪmpɪ\'kjuːniəs]', 'adj.没有钱的；身无分文的；贫穷的', '1. But it may the easiest way to let you impecunious. 但它也可能是让你变得身无分文最容易的办法. 2. He is impecunious, does not know anyone who can lend mony. 他身无分文 3. The impecunious mother recalls voidly her past youth. 这个贫穷的母亲怅惘地回忆她已经逝去的青春。', '副词: impecuniously 名词: impecuniousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extenuate', '[ɪk\'stenjʊˌeɪt]', 'vt. <古>减轻； 使人原谅； 使变瘦', '1. Because of extenuating circumstances, the court acquitted him of the crime. 因考虑到情有可原，法庭判他无罪。 2. Nothing can extenuate such appalling behavior. 这种骇人听闻的行径罪不可恕。', '形容词: extenuative 名词: extenuator 过去式: extenuated 过去分词: extenuated 现在分词: extenuating 第三人称单数: extenuates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('positiveness', '[\'pɒzətɪvnɪs]', 'n.肯定；信心；积极性', '1. The words undoubtedly give the air of positiveness. 毫无疑问,这些话增添了肯定的气氛。 2. She nodded her head with some positiveness. 她带著几分自信地点了点头。 3. Although his words were harsh, there was positiveness in them. 虽然他的话很苛刻,但有建设性。 4. If she needs salvation, she will posit a savior. 如果她需要救助，她就会设想一个救助者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embed', '[ɪm\'bed]', 'v.(使)插入；(使)嵌入；深留脑中', '1. The harpoon struck but did not embed. 鱼叉击中了但并没有插入。 2. You can embed URLs in your comment lines. 可以将URL嵌入注释行。 3. The scene was embedded in his memory. 那一幕情景深深地留在他的记忆。 4. The idea bacame embedded in his mind. 这想法在他头脑中根深蒂固了。', '异体字: imbed 名词: embedment 过去式: embedded 过去分词: embedded 现在分词: embedding 第三人称单数: embeds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stingy', '[\'stɪndʒi]', 'adj.吝啬的；小气的', '1. After the death of his stingy wife,Edward loosened up a great deal. 爱德华在吝啬的妻子死后，用钱广大方得多了。 2. There was once a very poor person who was also very stingy. 有一个很穷又很吝啬的人向上帝祷告。 3. Since when have you been so stingy? 你是什么时候变得这样小气的？ 4. Although I don\'t like wasting money,I either cannot accept the strict budgeting and stingy man. 虽然我不爱乱花钱，但也接受不了精打细算，小气的男人。', '副词: stingily 比较级: stingier 最高级: stingiest 名词: stinginess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('truculent', '[\'trʌkjələnt]', 'adj.野蛮的；好斗的；残酷的', '1. He was seen as truculent, temperamental , too unwilling to tolerate others. 他们认为他为人蛮横无理，性情暴躁，不大能容人。 2. It was his usual aspect, and a truculent one. 这是他惯常的模样，是一种好斗的表情。 3. He was in no truculent state of mind now. 这会儿他心肠一点也不狠毒了。', '副词: truculently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('locomotion', '[ˌloʊkə\'moʊʃn]', 'n.运动；移动；转位', '1. By land, air or sea, birds are masters of locomotion. 无论是通过陆地,飞越空中还是穿过海洋,鸟应算是运动能手了。 2. The simplest behavior of a robot is locomotion. 机器人最简单的行为是移动。 3. Food sources also elicit oriented locomotion and recognition behavior patterns in most insects. 食物源也引诱大多数昆虫定向迁移和识别行为。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suspend', '[sə\'spend]', 'v.暂停；悬浮；中止；勒令停职', '1. As the workers went on strike, the company was obliged to suspend its operations. 由于工人罢工,该公司被迫暂停营运。 2. Such fine particles suspend readily in water. 这种微粒极易悬浮在水中。 3. They decided to suspend trade with that country. 他们决定中断和那个国家的贸易。 4. The policeman was suspended while the complaint was investigated. 因该警察遭投诉，在调查期间已令其暂停职务。', '过去式: suspended 过去分词: suspended 现在分词: suspending 第三人称单数: suspends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('humidity', '[hjuː\'mɪdəti]', 'n.湿度；湿气', '1. My laundry will not dry because of the humidity. 由于湿度关系，我的衣物无法晾干。 2. Humidity is a measure of moisture in the atmosphere. 湿度是空气内含水分多少的量度。 3. It\'s said by forecast that the humidity in the air today is 60%. 据预报说今天的空气湿度是百分之六十。 4. Humidity caused me another fit of rheumatism. 湿气使我的风湿病又发作了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('voluminous', '[və\'luːmɪnəs]', 'adj.卷数多的；大部头的；大量的；著书多的', '1. This is the creation of Tolstoy\'s first volume rank voluminous novel. 这是托尔斯泰创作的第一部卷秩浩繁的长篇小说。 2. It was inhabited by an old gentleman who wrote voluminous books. 上面住着一位老先生,他在写作大部头的书。 3. The importance of the subject is suggested by a voluminous literature. 很多文献提到了这个问题的重要性。', '副词: voluminously 名词: voluminosity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('duet', '[du\'et]', 'n.二重奏；二重唱 vi.演奏二重奏或二重唱', '1. There is a piano duet by two Italians. 有意大利人的钢琴二重奏。 2. The duet reached a climax in a string of tense beats, which, moments later, met with thunderous applauses which resonated in the huge hall for minutes. 二重奏在一连串紧密的敲打中达到了顶峰，不久之后，在大厅中持续响起了雷鸣般的掌声。 3. They also won the duet for another Beijing spot. 他们还赢得了二重唱另一场北京。 4. John sang in with Joan in a duet last night. 昨晚约翰和琼唱了二重唱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tenacity', '[tə\'næsəti]', 'n.坚韧；固执；不屈不挠；顽固', '1. Her stubbornness led to tenacity and determination. 她的固执使她成为坚韧和果断。 2. The athletes displayed great tenacity throughout the contest. 运动员在比赛中表现出坚韧的斗志。 3. Her stubbornness led to tenacity and determination. 她的固执使她成为坚韧和果断。 4. The same tenacity that served me so well in ski racing helped me survive my second bout with cancer. 同样的固执很大程度的帮助我在滑雪比赛上做出突出表现也在我同癌症的第二回合的比赛中拯救了我。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('midget', '[\'mɪdʒɪt]', 'n.侏儒；极小者 adj.极小的', '1. I was in love with a midget\'s mother. 我爱上了侏儒的母亲。 2. One once put me against a wall in the gym and shouted, \"You\'re a midget.\" 有一次一个男孩把我推到体育馆的墙上，大声喊道，“你是一个小矮人。” 3. \"Why do we need another midget guard?\" “为什么我们当时要选一个迷你后卫呢？”', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('numismatic', '[ˌnjuːmɪz\'mætɪk]', 'adj.钱币学的；货币的', '1. The Smithsonian houses the National Numismatic Collection of the United States. 史密森收藏学会是美国的国家钱币收藏馆。 2. Coinage dating from the 8th Century B.C. to the17th Century A.D. Numismatic evidence of the advances made by smelting technology in ancient India. 造币的技术可以回溯到公元前八世纪到公元七世纪。钱币的证据表明了古印度有了熔炼的技术。 3. Description: Portret van Pertinax op een sestertie. Foto met toestemming van Classical Numismatic Group, Inc. (CNG). 它在文件描述页上的描述于下面显示。 4. Our host was Mr.Zhou Xiang, who is head of the numismatic department of the museum. 接待我们的是周祥先生，周先生是博物馆钱币部门的负责人。', '副词: numismatically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('primp', '[prɪmp]', 'v.刻意打扮', '1. To dress or groom(oneself)with elaborate care;primp. 精心打扮精心地打扮或修饰(自己);过分地打扮 2. To dress or groom oneself with elaborate care or vanity; primp. 精心地或卖弄地打扮或修饰自己；细心打扮。 3. To dress or groom(oneself) with elaborate care; primp. 精心打扮精心地打扮或修饰（自己）；过分地打扮 4. Too much time is spent in primp uping, too little at work. 在打扮上用时太多,在工作上用时太少。', '过去式: primped 过去分词: primped 现在分词: primping 第三人称单数: primps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indicate', '[\'ɪndɪkeɪt]', 'v.指示；象征；显示；暗示，预示 v.表明；指明', '1. This is used to indicate the temperature of the enclosure. 这个用来指示壳体的温度。 2. Sword indicates the bearer to a just and generous pursuit of honor and virtue in warlike deeds. 长剑象征剑的佩有者在格斗中具备公正、宽恕的美德。 3. My car\'s gas gauge indicated that there was little gas left. 我车上的汽油表显示剩下的油不多了。 4. His hesitation indicates unwillingness. 他的犹豫表明不愿意。', '形容词: indicatory 过去式: indicated 过去分词: indicated 现在分词: indicating 第三人称单数: indicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('palaver', '[pə\'lɑːvər]', 'v.空谈；奉承 n.谈判；空谈；奉承', '1. The boy tried to palaver his mother into letting him stay up later. 男孩想要跟他的母亲罗哩八嗦，让他熬夜得较晚。 2. I know that he want to palaver on me,but i am not believe this. 我知道他想要拍我马屁，但我才不吃那一套。 3. You should keep calm so you can evolve in palaver. 假使你想在谈判中取得一些进展，我劝你还是保持冷静为好。 4. No matter it is business palaver or vacation, we ll provide you the best service. 无论是商务洽谈还是休闲度假,这里都将为您提供最完善的服务。', '过去式: palavered 过去分词: palavered 现在分词: palavering 第三人称单数: palavers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diligence', '[\'dɪlɪdʒəns]', 'n.勤奋', '1. Patience combined with diligence is necessary to success. 耐心结合勤奋是成功所必需的。 2. Diligence is often the door to success. 勤奋常会引向成功。 3. Her diligence must have something to do with his success. 她的勤勉和她的成功一定有某些关系。 4. Her diligence has set an example to the others. 她的勤奋为其他人树立了榜样。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('valor', '[\'vælə]', 'n.英勇；勇猛', '1. His valor in the war was seen by everybody. 他在战争中的英勇人所共见。 2. The king knighted the soldier for his valor. 国王因那位军人英勇而封他为爵士。 3. They owed their lives to the valor of the firemen. 他们将其生命归功于消防员的英勇。 4. Fortitude is distinct from valor. 刚毅与勇猛不同。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grin', '[ɡrɪn]', 'v.露齿而笑；(以咧嘴笑来)表示 n.露齿笑；咧嘴笑', '1. They grinned with pleasure when I gave them the sweets. 当我给他们糖果时，他们高兴地咧开嘴笑了。 2. He grin at me, as if sharing a secret joke. 他朝我龇牙一笑，好像彼此会心领略一个笑话。 3. When the rain returns, I will grin even more? 天再下雨时，我会咧嘴笑得更多? 4. He grin at me, as if sharing a secret joke. 他朝我龇牙一笑，好像彼此会心领略一个笑话。 5. He twisted his face into a grin. 他扭歪着脸露齿而笑。', '副词: grinningly 名词: grinner 过去式: grinned 过去分词: grinned 现在分词: grinning 第三人称单数: grins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adjust', '[ə\'dʒʌst]', 'v.调整；校准；调节；使适应', '1. Could you teach me how to adjust the iris of the camera? 你能教我怎么调照相机的光圈吗？ 2. This kind of desk can be adjusted to the height you need. 这种书桌的高低可以按照你的需要调节。 3. He can\'t adjust himself to the whirl of modern life in this big city. 他无法适应这个大都市的现代生活的忙碌。 4. Over the years, we all learned to adjust, to become more comfortable with each other, and to adapt to our new family arrangement. 年复一年，我们都学会了调整自己，学会了彼此宽容，学会了适应我们新的家庭规则。', '形容词: adjustable 副词: adjustably 名词: adjuster 过去式: adjusted 过去分词: adjusted 现在分词: adjusting 第三人称单数: adjusts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gabby', '[\'ɡæbi]', 'adj.饶舌的；爱说话的', '1. She was kept from her housework by gabby neighbors. 话多的邻居妨碍她做家务。 2. Ted observed that her friends were a bunch of gabby four-flushers. 特德注意到她的朋友是一群多嘴多舌的牛皮大王。 3. A patient, any patient, is entitled to have confidence respected, to be protected against a gabby doctor. 病人，任何病人，都有权要求医生尊重他的隐情，有权不吃一个多嘴饶舌的医生的亏。', '比较级: gabbier 最高级: gabbiest 名词: gabbiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shoplift', '[\'ʃɒplɪft]', 'v.从商店中偷商品', '1. I accept that he was caught shoplifting but there\'s no need to keep rubbing his nose in it. 我承认他在冒充顾客进商店行窃时被抓住过，但也没必要老是提起他的过失行为。', '名词: shoplifter 过去式: shoplifted 过去分词: shoplifted 现在分词: shoplifting 第三人称单数: shoplifts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slipshod', '[\'slɪpʃɑːd]', 'adj.穿塌跟鞋的；粗枝大叶的；不整洁的', '1. You\' re too slipshod about your presentation. 你表达得太不认真. 2. He is sometimes slipshod in handling his sources. 他在处理资料来源时有时有点潦草。 3. Slipshod girls cleaning the windows of the little shops broke the monotony of the street. 衣衫不整的女孩子在揩抹小店铺的橱窗,这打破了街头的单调。', '名词: slipshoddiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dowse', '[daʊz]', 'v.浸湿；熄灭；吸收；松弛；脱；探寻（水源等） n.<英>击打；湿透 =douse', '1. Dow Jones agrees to be bought by News Corporation. 道琼斯统一被新闻集团收购。 2. You mean the Dow Brand Handi-wrap? 是陶氏保鲜膜吗 3. The Dow Jones index fell 15 points this morning. 道琼斯指数今天上午下跌了15点。 4. The Dow advanced 2.3% for the year. 道琼整个年度只涨了2.;3%25，', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mire', '[\'maɪər]', 'n.泥沼；泥泞；困境 v.(使)陷于泥泞；(使)陷入困境', '1. The mist arose in the remote mire. 遥远的泥沼上方升起了薄雾。 2. He has run away and landed in the mire. 他逃开,却开到泥坑里去了。 3. He tried to increase his income by gambling only to plunge more deeply into the mire. 他企图借赌博增加收入,却陷入了更深的困境。 4. Don\' t mire the wheels of a cart. 不要让车轮陷于泥坑。', '过去式: mired 过去分词: mired 现在分词: miring 第三人称单数: mires');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boo', '[buː]', 'int.(表示不满、轻蔑等)嘘；呸 n.嘘声（pl v.发出嘘声', '1. Even if you don\'t like one of the players you should not boo and hiss at them. 即使是你不喜欢其中的一个球员，你不应该对他们发出嘘声。', '名词复数: boos 过去式: booed 过去分词: booed 现在分词: booing 第三人称单数: boos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('familiarity', '[fəˌmɪli\'ærəti]', 'n.亲密；熟悉；精通；不拘礼节', '1. It partly has to do with familiarity. 它部分必须用亲密做。 2. Hurstwood naturally abandoned his show of fine manners with her and modified his attitude to one of easy familiarity. 赫斯渥对她的态度自然不再是彬彬有礼，而是一种随便的亲密态度。 3. Familiarity with food and beverage cost controls. 熟悉食品和饮料的成本控制。 4. Too much familiarity breeds contempt. 过分熟悉会使人互不服气。', '名词复数: familiarities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inhabitant', '[ɪn\'hæbɪtənt]', 'n.居民', '1. Every inhabitant here has an obligation to pay taxes. 这里的每一位居民都有纳税的义务。 2. The inhabitant can see the Church House and the Death House， but never the exterior of the Court House. 居民也能看到教会安置和死囚刑前的住房，但从未见过法院的外貌。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('throes', '[θroʊz]', 'n.剧痛；挣扎 名词throe的复数形式.', '1. His heart beat with strange throes of pain. 他的心带着奇怪的剧痛跳动着。 2. The nation is in the throes of the fastest urban growth in human history. 中国正处于人类历史上最快速的城市增长的剧痛之中。 3. He sees banking in the throes of profound change. 他知道银行业正因巨变而痛苦挣扎。 4. That doesn\'t mean China wants to risk more money on a Ponzi scheme in its last throes. 不过，这并不意味着中国打算拿更多的钱在这个庞兹骗局中冒险，作最后的挣扎。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unwarranted', '[ʌn\'wɔːrəntɪd]', 'adj.无根据的；不必要的；未经授权的；无保证的', '1. Your assumption that I would agree was unwarranted. 你认为我会同意，这种假设是毫无根据的。 2. I strongly resent such unwarranted aspersions. 我对这种莫须有的诽谤深恶痛绝. 3. Their concern seems to be unwarranted. 他们的担心似乎是没有必要的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unravel', '[ʌn\'rævl]', 'v.解开；阐明；解释；破坏(计划、安排等)', '1. My knitting has unravelled. 我编织的东西散开了。 2. The baby unraveled its mother\'s knitting. 那婴儿将母亲的编织物拆散了。 3. One wrong move and the reef could unravel in a day. 一个措施不对，这块珊瑚礁就可能在一天之内分崩离析。 4. There is still a good deal to unravel. 还有不少问题要澄清。', '过去式: unraveled/unravelled 过去分词: unraveled/unravelled 现在分词: unraveling/unravelling 第三人称单数: unravels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('creep', '[kriːp]', 'vi.蹑手蹑脚地走；爬；渐渐出现；蔓延；毛骨悚然 n.卑鄙小人；爬；徐行；蠕动', '1. We take off our shoes and creep cautiously along the passage. 我们脱掉了鞋，在走廊中蹑手蹑脚地往前走。 2. The spider learns to creep on the wall. 蜘蛛学爬壁。 3. As the doctors became more tired, errors began to creep into their work. 由于越来越疲劳，医生的工作开始出现差错。 4. Old age creeps up on you before you realize it. 人不知不觉就变老了。 5. You slimy little creep! 你这个卑鄙无耻的奴才！', '过去式: crept 过去分词: crept 现在分词: creeping 第三人称单数: creeps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ewe', '[juː]', 'n.母羊；埃维人（住在加纳、多哥境内和贝宁边境地区的农民）；埃维语', '1. One ewe has produced twins. 一只母羊一胎生了两只小羊。 2. The farmer has 20 ewes on his farm. 这个农场主的农场里有20只母羊。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parlance', '[\'pɑːrləns]', 'n.说法；用语；语调；辩论', '1. In naval parlance,the left side of a ship is the port side. 用海军的说法来说，船的左边称为左舷。 2. The phrase is common diplomatic parlance for spying. 这个短语是适用于间谍的一般外交用语。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ripen', '[\'raɪpən]', 'v.(使)成熟', '1. The sun ripens the corn. 阳光使农作物成熟。 2. Time had ripened his life and mellowed its fruits. 时间使他的生命成熟，结出硕果。 3. We are waiting for the first crops to ripen. 我们正等待着第一次农作物的成熟。', '名词: ripener 过去式: ripened 过去分词: ripened 现在分词: ripening 第三人称单数: ripens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rucksack', '[\'rʌksæk]', 'n.帆布背包', '1. He was weighted down with a heavy rucksack. 他背着很重的背包。 2. She shouldered her rucksack and set off along the road. 她背起帆布背包就上路了。 3. In their view anybody with a rucksack and long hair is a hippy. 在他们看来，肩背帆布包、留长发的人都是嬉皮士。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deteriorate', '[dɪ\'tɪriəreɪt]', 'v.恶化；变质；衰退', '1. We cannot allow the situation to deteriorate. 我们不容许情况恶化。 2. Relation between the two countries have deteriorated sharply in recent week. 最近几周那两个国家间的关系严重恶化了。 3. Food is apt to deteriorate in summer. 食物在夏天容易变质。 4. The discussion deteriorated into a bitter quarrel. 这场讨论演变成了激烈的争吵。', '形容词: deteriorative 名词: deterioration 过去式: deteriorated 过去分词: deteriorated 现在分词: deteriorating 第三人称单数: deteriorates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bough', '[baʊ]', 'n.大树枝', '1. The window of her car was broken by a bough during last night\'s storm. 在昨晚的风暴中她的车窗被一根大树枝打破了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spur', '[spɜːr]', 'n.支脉；刺激；马刺；鞭策 vt.刺激；鞭策；促进', '1. She went to London on the spur of the moment. 她一时兴起就到伦敦去了。 2. International competition was a spur to modernization. 国际竞争是实现现代化的动力。 3. A good heart horse often needs a good spur. 好马常需好靴刺。 4. The thought of the prize was the spur for the team. 夺取锦标的想法是该队的动力。 5. What spurred her to do that? 是什么促使她那么干的？', '过去式: spurred 过去分词: spurred 现在分词: spurring 第三人称单数: spurs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spontaneity', '[ˌspɑːntə\'neɪəti]', 'n.自然性', '1. The romantic spontaneity and courage are gone. 浪漫的自然感和勇气均荡然无存。 2. But the very essence of creativity is spontaneity. 但是创造力的精髓在于自发性。', '名词复数: spontaneities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boon', '[buːn]', 'n.恩惠；所感激的事 adj.合得来的', '1. This baby is a great boon to the Smith family. 这个宝宝是老天赐给史密斯家的宝贝。 2. Remember the hurt that we give to others, forget the boon. 记住自己对别人的伤害，忘掉自己对别人的恩惠。 3. A priest accompanying your regiment into the fray is indeed a boon. 对于你的师团来说，有一名牧师与你的部队一同冲杀敌阵，着实是一种恩惠。 4. Park is a great boon to people in big city. 在大城市里，公园是人们的好去处。 5. He has a couple of boon companions. 他有几个爱吃喝交际的朋友。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('friable', '[\'fraɪəbl]', 'adj.易碎的；松散的', '1. Colonoscopic views of less severe UC are seen below, with friable, erythematous mucosa with reduced haustral folds. 可见到并不严重的溃疡性结肠炎的结肠镜检图，易碎的红斑粘膜，伴结肠带减少。 2. This patient had severe ulcerative, friable atheromatous plaques and had undergone angiography, which increases the risk for such emboli. 该病人有严重的溃疡形成，易碎的粥样斑块，同时也做了会增加血栓形成危险的血管造影术。', '名词: friability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pious', '[\'paɪəs]', 'adj.虔诚的；伪善的；不太可能实现的', '1. He is a pious Christian. 他是一名虔诚的基督教徒。 2. He is a pious person to his belief. 他是一个对其信仰虔诚的人。 3. Honest doubt is better than in a pious fraud. 诚实的怀疑胜过伪善的信任。 4. Congress did no more than set out some pious hopes. 国会除了提出一些不可能实现的希望之外别无所为。', '副词: piously 名词: piousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unleash', '[ʌn\'liːʃ]', 'v.解开 ... 的皮带；解除 ... 的束缚；释放', '1. Go at once,or I will unleash my dog on you! 立刻走，要不我就放我的狗咬你！ 2. He could unleash the mobs in the Arab world against us. 他本来可以发动阿拉伯世界的下层群众反对我们。 3. May you unleash a storm of affection on your loved ones. 愿你将狂风暴雨般的情感倾注到你所爱的人身上。 4. He would have no qualms about using missiles to unleash a nuclear war. 他会毫无顾忌地利用火箭发动一场核战争。', '过去式: unleashed 过去分词: unleashed 现在分词: unleashing 第三人称单数: unleashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('geyser', '[\'ɡaɪzər]', 'n.间歇泉；天然热喷泉；<英>热水器', '1. The tourists marveled at the geyser, which spurted water to a height of ten meters. 间歇泉喷出数十米高的水柱,这景观让游客很惊讶。 2. When we got close, we could see rainbows reflected in the steam from the geyser. 我们走近间歇泉,可以看到映照在间歇泉蒸汽中的彩虹。 3. The butler was almost invisible in the stream of an antiquated geyser. 在这座古老的热水锅炉产生的水蒸汽中隐隐约约可以看到那个男仆的影子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ineluctable', '[ˌɪnɪ\'lʌktəbl]', 'adj.难免的；不能逃避的', '1. The onward march of globalisation is, of course, not ineluctable. 当然，全球化进程并不是不可阻挡的。 2. In the process of learning good English, meeting the difficulty is ineluctable. 在学好英语的过程中，遇到困难是不可避免的。', '副词: ineluctably 名词: ineluctability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scathe', '[skeɪð]', 'n.危害；损伤；损害 vt.损伤；伤害', '1. This study put forward a systemic secure technic for domestic long distance natrual gas pipelines to reduce the scathe and influence farthest. 本选题的研究，将为国内天然气长输管道的安全运行提出一套比较系统的保障技术，将天然气长输管道事故的危害及影响降至最低。 2. Objective:To study the clinical effect and side effect of Aescine Sodium Liniment and Mei De Xi Cream on sofe tissue scathe. 目的:比较研究七叶皂甙钠搽剂和美得喜乳膏治疗软组织损伤的临床疗效和安全性。 3. \"Though not without scathe. “尽管不是没有伤害。 4. Waxes for Electron Wafer Binding: Waxes for Electron Wafer Binding,mainly used in precision process of micro electron wafer (U piece,S piece or SMD piece),excellent strong adhesive ability,no scathe to element ,cleanup easily after process. 电子晶片粘接蜡系列：主要用于微电子硅片或石英晶片（U片、S片或SMD片）的精密加工，具有极强的附着力，对元件无任何损伤，使用后易去除。', '过去式: scathed 过去分词: scathed 现在分词: scathing 第三人称单数: scathes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foyer', '[\'fɔɪər]', 'n.门厅；休息室', '1. Late arrivals must wait in the foyer. 来晚的人要在门厅等候。 2. I flung open the foyer doors and went out into the street. 我推开了门厅的大门，冲到了街上。 3. Let\'s meet in the foyer of the Bijou Theater. 让我们在珠宝戏院的休息室会面。 4. We sat side by side, then went to the foyer. 我们肩并肩地坐着，然后去了休息室。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tresses', '[\'tresɪz]', 'n.女人的长发 名词tress的复数形式.', '1. All her beautiful tresses have been sheared/shorn off. 她那长长的秀发都给剪掉了。 2. She is combing her dark tresses. 她正在梳理她那黑发。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monochromatic', '[ˌmɒnəkrə\'mætɪk]', 'adj.单色的、一色的', '1. Thanks to that, they do not look so monochromatic. 得益于此,他们看起来不才不至于那么单调。 2. My sister selected a monochromatic color-scheme for her new apartment. 我妹妹为自己的新居选择了单一色调的设计。 3. By far the most nearly monochromatic source available at present is the laser. 目前可用的最接近单色光的光源是激光器。', '副词: monochromatically 名词: monochromaticity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plentitude', '[\'plentətuːd]', 'n.充分；充足', '1. It presents balanced and with a big sensation of plentitude. 它平衡，协调，圆润，沁人心脾。 2. The relationship between continuity and discontinuity is antinomy and untie.Discontinuity is the plentitude condition to continuity.Continuity will not exist with discontinuity. 连续性与间断性两者是对立统一的关系：间断性是连续性的充分条件，没有间断性就没有连续性，不存在没有间断性的连续性。 3. The four chain club differs in design and style, but all planned for professional arrangement, plentitude exercises area and highest standard equipment. 力美健的四个俱乐部环境设计各不相同,但在空间设计的共同考虑是专业的布局,充裕的面积和高标准的配置。 4. For the sake of enhancing the efficiency of gas inlet and outlet, the mathematical model that takes the plentitude coefficient as the target function may be established. 为获得高的进排气效率，可建立以丰满系数为目标函数的数学模型；', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('restive', '[\'restɪv]', 'adj.不愿向前走的；倔强的；难驾驭的；不耐烦的', '1. His face was quite stolid,but he looked at her with restive eyes. 他脸上没有表情，眼睛却倔强地看着她。 2. If Kosovo remains unresolved and restive, the EU will not admit Serbia as a member. 如果科索沃问题悬而未决且难以控制，欧盟不会承认塞尔维亚为一个成员国。 3. When the singer was late, the audience grew restive. 歌手迟迟不出场,听众变得不耐烦了。', '副词: restively 名词: restiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('guru', '[\'ɡʊruː]', 'n.古鲁(指印度教等宗教的宗师或领袖)；领袖；专家', '1. The inner earth peoples have also manifest guru patterns. 地心人类也显化了古鲁的模式。 2. This is how the dance of the guru and devotee emerged in the human expression. 这就是暴露在人类语法中的古鲁和信徒之舞。 3. Become a trader,bounty hunter, rebel, stock market guru or a deadly space pirate. 成为一个商人，津贴猎人，叛乱者，股票市场领袖或者一名极度的空间盗版者。 4. The book had added to her reputation as a kind of guru of the movement to tame the college admissions frenzy. 这本书使为她增添了名气，使她成为所谓缓解大学招生压力运动的领袖人物。', '名词复数: gurus');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intercept', '[ˌɪntər\'sept]', 'n.截取；妨碍；截距 vt.拦截；阻止', '1. You are a warrior without intercept in that scenario. 此时你就是一个没有拦截的战士了。 2. I don\'t,and I don\'t think you will either after you hear this next intercept. 如果听了以下的截获内容，我相信你不会在怀疑了。 3. Now, no.6 is running up to intercept. 现在6号正要上前去拦截。 4. It is illegal to intercept a letter or parcel before it is delivered. 在送达之前，中途拦截信件或包裹是非法的。', '形容词: interceptive 过去式: intercepted 过去分词: intercepted 现在分词: intercepting 第三人称单数: intercepts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overweening', '[ˌoʊvər\'wiːnɪŋ]', 'adj.自负的；过分的', '1. The overweening enemy will soon learn this to his cost. 关于这一点，傲视一切敌人不久就要得到惨痛的教训。 2. He was overweening and displayed his slight skill before an expert on a public occasion. 他目中无人，在大庭广众之下班门弄斧。 3. Throughout her life she has hidden her insecurities behind a facade of, at times, overweening self-confidence. 在她一生中，她常常靠摆出泰然自若的样子，来掩饰内心的犹豫不定。', '副词: overweeningly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('misgiving', '[ˌmɪs\'ɡɪvɪŋ]', 'n.疑虑；怀疑 动词misgive的现在分词.', '1. All their misgivings were driven out by the arrival of the good news. 一听到这个好消息，他们一切疑虑都烟消云散了。 2. I have many misgivings about taking the job. 我对是否接受那项工作顾虑重重。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vitreous', '[\'vɪtriəs]', 'adj.玻璃的；似玻璃的', '1. When core board is glass, it is vitreous door. 门芯板为玻璃时，则为玻璃门。 2. Inside lesser room, vitreous tea table can reduce a room embrace. 在较小的房间内，玻璃茶几可以减少房间的拥堵。 3. Vitreous rocks are hard and shiny. 玻璃状的岩石坚硬而晶莹闪光。 4. Jade showed vitreous luster, translucent or transparent. 翡翠呈现玻璃光泽，半透明或透明。', '名词: vitreosity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('atrophy', '[\'ætrəfi]', 'n.萎缩；衰退；虚脱；萎缩症 v.萎缩；衰退；虚脱', '1. More exercises can avoid atrophy of cartilage. 多加锻炼可以避免软骨萎缩。 2. The cultural life of the country will sink into atrophy unless more writers and artists emerge. 除非能多涌现出一些作家和艺术家 3. Muscles that are not used will atrophy. 肌肉经常不用就会萎缩。 4. Their political power gradually atrophied. 他们的政治力量逐渐衰退了。', '形容词: atrophic 名词复数: atrophies 过去式: atrophied 过去分词: atrophied 现在分词: atrophying 第三人称单数: atrophies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('outrage', '[\'aʊtreɪdʒ]', 'n.暴行；愤怒；义愤 vt.凌辱；激怒', '1. The Government has been dilatory in condemning the outrage. 政府迟迟才谴责是次暴行。 2. We should never forget the outrage committed by the Japanese invaders. 我们永远都不应该忘记日本侵略者犯下的暴行。 3. All right-minded people will be surely shocked by this outrage. 凡是有正义感的人都一定会对这种暴行感到震惊。 4. Her answer was greeted with cries of outrage. 她的回答引起了一片愤怒的吼叫。 5. He was outraged by their behavior. 他们的行为使他感到愤慨。', '过去式: outraged 过去分词: outraged 现在分词: outraging 第三人称单数: outrages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sneaking', '[\'sniːkɪŋ]', 'adj.秘密的；不公开的 动词sneak的现在分词.', '1. Darkness was sneaking up on the explorers. They decided to stop for a night. 夜幕悄悄地笼罩控险者，他们决定停下来过夜。 2. James love sneaking up on his sister to frighten her. 詹姆斯喜欢溜到妹妹身后吓她一大跳。', '副词: sneakingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('humid', '[\'hjuːmɪd]', 'adj.潮湿的', '1. The humid climate didn\'t agree with him. 那潮湿的气候对他不合适。 2. She thought of her humid, stuffy darkroom. 她想起了自己那间闷热潮湿的暗室。', '副词: humidly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gratification', '[ˌɡrætɪfɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.满足；喜悦', '1. He had the gratification of knowing that he had done his best. 他了解自己已尽了最大努力而感到满足。 2. Many also equate instant gratification with happiness. 许多人还等同即刻满足与幸福。 3. Again Hist experienced the profound gratification when he heard the language of praise spoken by those we love. 听了心爱的人说出这番赞扬的话，希斯特又一次感到由衷的喜悦。 4. Rhett never presumed on these conversations but stood by, exuding fatherly pride and gratification at the notice taken of his daughter. 瑞德从来不打搅这种谈话，只悄悄地站在一旁，流露出作父亲的骄傲和对人们这样夸奖他女儿的喜悦之情。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incision', '[ɪn\'sɪʒn]', 'n.切口；切割', '1. An incision was made into his leg. 他腿上切开了一个口子。 2. An incision was made into his hand to take out the splinter. 他手上切开了一个口子以便取出那根刺。 3. Result shows both high quality of incision and good efficiency. 结果表明,这种方案不仅切割品质好,而且效率可以大大提高。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harbor', '[\'hɑːbə]', 'n.海港；避难所 vt.庇护；心怀；窝藏 vi.生存；进入避祸所', '1. The ship steamed into the harbor. 船驶入了港湾。 2. The bombers made a sudden strike on the harbor. 轰炸机对这港口进行了一次突然袭击。 3. They also harbor exotic life-forms, far below the reach of sunlight. 他们也是外来的生物避难所，远远低于阳光的到达。 4. They harbored refugees in times of war. 他们在战争期间收留难民。 5. The Earth is the only world known so far to harbor life. 据我们所知,地球是唯一维持生物生存的世界。', '名词: harborer 过去式: harbored 过去分词: harbored 现在分词: harboring 第三人称单数: harbors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('substantiate', '[səb\'stænʃieɪt]', 'vt.证实；实体化', '1. The eyewitness can substantiate all the testimony. 目击证人能够证实所有的证词。 2. Despite this, more research is needed to substantiate this association. 尽管如此，这种联系还有赖更多研究来佐证。 3. Field experience did not usually substantiate the claims. 实际经验通常都不能使这些看法具体化。 4. This paper makes good use of modem technology to substantiate the idea. 这篇论文充分利用现代相关技术对这种设计思想加以具体化。', '名词: substantiation 过去式: substantiated 过去分词: substantiated 现在分词: substantiating 第三人称单数: substantiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('odometer', '[oʊ\'dɑːmɪtər]', 'n.里程表', '1. The odometer shows now 140 miles per hour. 里程表显示现在的时速为140英里。', '名词: odometry');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irreducible', '[ˌɪrɪ\'duːsəbl]', 'adj.不能复归的；不能削减的；不可约的', '1. It is the irreducible seat of strength. 这是不可逆的力量的席位。 2. Expenditure on road repair has been cut to an irreducible minimum. 修路费已削减到不能再减的最低限度了。 3. An \"irreducible\" element is one that can not be quantified. “不可折算的”因素是一种不能数量化的因素。', '副词: irreducibly 名词: irreducibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bellicose', '[\'belɪkoʊs]', 'adj.好战的；好斗的', '1. The result of being bellicose is that all your previous efforts become wasted. 恋战的后果就是前功尽弃。 2. His bellicose disposition alienated his friend. 他生性好斗，他的朋友们都疏远了他。 3. Bellicose workers are problems of the factory. 好争吵的工人是这工厂的问题所在。', '副词: bellicosely 名词: bellicosity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stricture', '[\'strɪktʃər]', 'n.苛评；非难；限制；[医]狭窄', '1. If stricture develops, bouginage will be needed. 若狭窄发生，则需用探条扩张术。 2. If countercurrent is long-standing, esophagus will form scar and stricture finally. 若反流长期存在，食管最终将会形成瘢痕和狭窄。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desuetude', '[\'deswɪˌtjuːd]', 'n.废止；不用', '1. These words have fallen into desuetude. 这些词如今已经不用了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('underlying', '[ˌʌndər\'laɪɪŋ]', 'adj.潜在的；隐含的；在下面的；基本的；<经>优先的 动词underlie的现在分词', '1. This word has its underlying meaning. 这个单词有它潜在的含义。 2. The underlying assumption is that the amount of money available is limited. 隐含的假定是可用的资金有限。 3. We dug down to the underlying rock. 我们往下挖直到碰到了下面的石块。 4. The underlying idea is an appealing one. 基础的概念是一种吸引人的概念。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('littoral', '[\'lɪtərəl]', 'adj.海岸的；沿海的 n.沿海地区', '1. But Jiangsu Province did not produce littoral advantage well. 但江苏却没有把海滨的优势很好地发挥出来。 2. The littoral zone of a sea is the part of the sea between high and low tide marks. 海的沿岸地带是高潮的测标和低潮的测标之间的海域。 3. Space forces should support the air force in the \"space littoral\". 空间部队应该在\"空间前沿\"支援空军作战。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('furtive', '[\'fɜːrtɪv]', 'adj.偷偷的', '1. He cast a furtive glance at her. 他偷偷瞥了她一眼。 2. They are making a furtive movement. 他们正做一项诡秘的行动。 3. That person was furtive and did not want to be noticed. 那人鬼鬼祟祟的并不想让人注意。', '副词: furtively 名词: furtiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hippopotamus', '[ˌhɪpə\'pɑːtəməs]', 'n.河马', '1. The children enjoyed watching the hippopotamus wallowing in the mud. 孩子们喜欢看河马在泥中打滚。 2. My favorite animal is the hippopotamus. 我最喜欢的动物是河马。', '名词复数: hippopotamuses/hippopotami');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ruminate', '[\'ruːmɪneɪt]', 'v.深思；沉思；反刍', '1. The discovery provides pabulum for the scientific community to ruminate on for decades to come. 这项发现为科学界对未来十年的深思提供了精神食粮。 2. The cow began to ruminate after eating up grass. 牛吃完草后开始反刍。', '形容词: ruminative 副词: ruminatively 名词: ruminator 过去式: ruminated 过去分词: ruminated 现在分词: ruminating 第三人称单数: ruminates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('willful', '[\'wɪlfəl]', 'adj.任性的；故意的；有意的', '1. Yes, I\'ve often been the willful child. 因为我常常表现得和那个任性的孩子一样。 2. A willful beast must go his own way. 任性的野兽一定会坚持走自已的路。', '副词: willfully 名词: willfulness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cheeky', '[\'tʃiːki]', 'adj.厚脸皮的；莽撞的、放肆的', '1. Her cheeky remarks really get up my nose! 她那些不要脸的话真惹我生气！ 2. He boxed the boy\'s ears for being cheeky. 他打了这男孩儿耳光以教训其不懂羞耻。 3. You cheeky young cub! 你这莽撞的毛头小伙子！ 4. She gave him a clip round the ear for being cheeky. 她因他放肆给了他一记耳光。', '副词: cheekily 比较级: cheekier 最高级: cheekiest 名词: cheekiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accompany', '[ə\'kʌmpəni]', 'vt.陪伴；伴随...发生；补充；给 ... 伴奏 vi.伴奏', '1. She asked me to accompany her to the airport. 她要求我陪她到机场去。 2. Lightning usually accompanies thunder. 闪电通常伴有雷声。 3. The text is accompanied by illustration. 正文附有插图。 4. The singer was accompanied on the piano by her sister. 女歌手由她姐姐钢琴伴奏。 5. In the singer\'s eyes,she accompanied magnificently. 在那名歌手的眼里,她伴奏得精彩极了。', '过去式: accompanied 过去分词: accompanied 现在分词: accompanying 第三人称单数: accompanies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bleachers', '[\'bliːtʃərz]', 'n.(运动场内票价低廉的)露天座位；漂白工人 名词bleacher的复数形式.', '1. The bleachers were full to overflowing. 看台上人满为患。 2. Is there still a ticket on the outfield bleachers? 还有外野席的票么? 3. Why Are Flour Bleacher Not Ceased to Use? 面粉增白剂风波何时休? 4. It is bleacher, it is strong oxidant. 它是漂白剂，又是强氧化剂。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brocade', '[brə\'keɪd]', 'n.织锦', '1. This kind of brocade looks very beautiful. 这种织锦看上去很漂亮。 2. The sofa was covered with expensive brocade. 沙发上铺上了华贵的织锦。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('employ', '[ɪm\'plɔɪ]', 'v.雇佣；使用', '1. They employ casual labor to pick the fruit 他们雇佣临时工摘水果。 2. You must employ someone to oversee the project. 你得雇个人监督这一工程。 3. Why do you think we should employ you? 你认为我们为何要雇佣你? 4. Different artists employ different painting techniques. 不同的画家会使用不同的绘画技巧。', '形容词: employable 名词: employability 过去式: employed 过去分词: employed 现在分词: employing 第三人称单数: employs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mulct', '[mʌlkt]', 'n.罚金 vt.处以罚金；诈取', '1. John was mulcted in￡500 by the court. 约翰被法庭罚款500英镑。', '过去式: mulcted 过去分词: mulcted 现在分词: mulcting 第三人称单数: mulcts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('massive', '[\'mæsɪv]', 'adj.巨大的；大量的；大规模的；大范围的；严重的', '1. A massive boulder blocked the entrance of the cave. 一块巨大的圆石堵住了山洞的入口。 2. We have seen massive changes in recent years. 这几年我们经历了巨大的变化。 3. The soldier suffered a massive haemorrhage and died soon after. 那个战士经受了大量出血的痛苦，不久便去世了。 4. We must make massive efforts to improve things. 我们必须作出极大的努力去改善一切。', '副词: massively 名词: massiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meddle', '[\'medl]', 'v.干涉', '1. Don\'t meddle in my affairs. 别干预我的事情。 2. Do not meddle with the tools. 不要乱动工具。 3. He is inclined to meddle in other people\'s affairs. 他总喜欢干涉别人的事。', '名词: meddler 过去式: meddled 过去分词: meddled 现在分词: meddling 第三人称单数: meddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preposition', '[ˌprepə\'zɪʃn]', 'n.介词', '1. Preposition is abbreviated as \"prep\" in this dictionary. 介词在词典中略作 “prep”。 2. Avoid ending a sentence with a preposition. 避免用介词结束一个句子。 3. You should cancel this preposition in the sentence. 你应该删去句子中的这个介系词。 4. The verb\"abide\"is construed with the preposition\"by\". 动词abide与介词by连用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amphibian', '[æm\'fɪbiən]', 'adj.两栖类的；水陆两用的 n.两栖动物；水陆两用飞机；水陆两用车', '1. It is being actively pursued by amphibian specialists, for example. 举个例，许多两栖类生物研究专家正积极的从事这项工作。 2. Unfortunately for the Chinese Giant Salamander, which is the largest amphibian in the world, it is a delicacy in China and the target of illegal hunting. 不幸的是中国大鲵，这种动物世界里最大的两栖类，在中国成为了一种美味被非法捕杀。 3. The living space of the amphibian is much larger than that of others. 两栖动物的生活空间要比单栖动物大得多。 4. The frog is an amphibian, which means it can live on land and in water. 青蛙属于两栖动物，也就是说它既能生活在陆地上也能生活在水里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blackball', '[\'blækbɔːl]', 'n.反对票 vt.投票反对；排斥', '1. The attempt to blackball it is neo-McCarthyism. 试图阻止它的是一股新麦卡锡主义。” 2. Don\'t blackball me, Mitch.Please. ', '别排斥我; 米奇.;求你了 3. But i do blackball anything refers to Japan! 这个句子.;我暗地里自愧不如 4. Have new edition of blackball of more than 1 million users. 有超过100万名用户投票反对新版。');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('protuberant', '[proʊ\'tuːbərənt]', 'adj.突出的；隆起的', '1. Characterized by convexity;protuberant. 突起的，凸状的有凸出的特征的;突出的，隆起的 2. Characterized by convexity; protuberant. 突起的，凸状的有凸出的特征的；突出的，隆起的 3. Of a bulging shape; protuberant. 隆起的凸出的，膨胀的 4. Projecting outward or upward from a line or surface; protuberant. 突起的从直线或平面向外或向上伸的；突出的', '副词: protuberantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rabies', '[\'reɪbiːz]', 'n.狂犬病', '1. He had a vaccination against rabies. 他做了疫苗注射以预防狂犬病。 2. Animals with rabies often froth at the mouth. 患狂犬病的动物常常口吐白沫。', '形容词: rabietic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carafe', '[kə\'ræf]', 'n.卡夫卡瓶；玻璃水瓶', '1. He ordered a half-carafe of house wine . 他要了半卡拉夫瓶的本店酒。 2. We want to have a carafe of ordinary water, please. 我们想要喝一卡拉夫瓶水。 3. I can\'t drink more than half a carafe. 我顶多能喝半瓶。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anvil', '[\'ænvɪl]', 'n.铁砧；[解]砧骨', '1. The man put the iron block on the anvil. 那人把铁块放在铁砧上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('degradation', '[ˌdeɡrə\'deɪʃn]', 'n.降格；堕落；退化', '1. Slow degradation of ground water quality may result from repeated use. 循环使用地下水可以导致缓慢的水质降低。 2. Being sent to prison was the final degradation. 堕落到最后地步就是被关进监狱。 3. Gambling is always coupled with degradation . 赌博总是与堕落相联系。 4. Environmental degradation is a global issue of common concern to the international community today. 环境恶化是当今国际社会普遍关注的全球性问题。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('belittle', '[bɪ\'lɪtl]', 'vt.轻视；贬低；使相形见小', '1. He will no longer belittle me or interfere with my research. 他不再将轻视我或干涉我的研究。 2. But this is not to belittle the importance of ritualistic worship. 但这并不是轻视了仪式功修的重要性。 3. The Whigs may attempt to belittle our candidates. 辉格党人可能会试图贬低我们的候选人。 4. Don\'t belittle what he has achieved. 不要贬低他所取得的。', '名词: belittlement 过去式: belittled 过去分词: belittled 现在分词: belittling 第三人称单数: belittles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flak', '[flæk]', 'n.高射炮；抨击；指责 =flack.', '1. Behind us are two self-propelled flaks as reserve. 在我们身后有两辆自行高射炮作为预备队。 2. The plan for the new tax has came in for a lot of flak. 新的税务计划遭到了猛烈抨击。 3. \"He took a lot of flak after that interview,\" the guard said. 门警说：“那次访问以后,他饱受抨击。” 4. He took a lot of flak for his stand against abortion. 他因坚持反对堕胎而饱受责难。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obsess', '[əb\'ses]', 'v.着迷；困扰', '1. Entrepreneurs must know their competition, but not obsess over it. 企业家必须了解他们所面临的竞争情况，但是也不必过分沉溺于其中。 2. The fear of death obsessed her throughout her old age. 她晚年一直受著死亡恐惧的困扰。 3. For many people, it\'s easy to obsess over minor issues. 很多人被细小的问题所困扰。', '名词: obsessor 过去式: obsessed 过去分词: obsessed 现在分词: obsessing 第三人称单数: obsesses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irascible', '[ɪ\'ræsəbl]', 'adj.易怒的；暴躁的', '1. He was an irascible man. 他是个脾气暴躁的人。 2. Laziness makes people irascible. 懒，能使人脾气大。 3. He has an irascible temperament. 他性情急躁。 4. His irascible reviews made him one of Germany\'s most familiar figures. 他暴躁的评论方式使他成为德国最家喻户晓的人物之一。', '副词: irascibly 名词: irascibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cumbersome', '[\'kʌmbərsəm]', 'adj.笨重的；不方便的', '1. The grizzly bear looked cumbersome and awkward. 灰熊看上去又笨拙又迟钝。 2. This arrangement is cumbersome to manage. 如此安排繁琐得难以管理。 3. They are cumbersome on land, but stealthy and sleek in the water. 它们在陆地上行动笨拙但在水里却敏捷灵活。 4. A tabulation of a function of two variables is cumbersome, but possible. 二元函数的列表法是不方便的，然而是可能的。', '副词: cumbersomely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('analgesic', '[ˌænəl\'dʒiːzɪk]', 'n.镇痛剂 adj.止痛的', '1. Aspirin is a mild analgesic. 阿司匹林是药性平和的止痛药。 2. The roots can be used medicinally as an analgesic. 根罐装可药用作为一种止痛药。 3. Propofol has no muscle relaxant or analgesic properties. 异丙酚没有肌松和镇痛作用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('causal', '[\'kɔːzl]', 'adj.原因的；关于因果的', '1. A causal agency, force, or quality. 起因诱因、原因性动力或特质 2. Don\'t overuse a causal connective like \'because\'. 不要过多地使用像 because 这样表示原因的连接词。 3. Because\' is a causal conjunction. because一词是表示原因的连接词. 4. The causal link between the subsidy and damage. 补贴与损害之间存在因果关系。', '副词: causally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('catalog', '[\'kætəlɔːg]', 'n.目录；大学概况手册；商品型录 vt.做目录；分类说明；名入列表 vi.(商品)在型录中明码标价', '1. You can look for the book in the library catalog. 你可以在图书馆的图书目录上查找这本书。 2. These names are to be listed in the catalog. 这些名字将列入目录。 3. Please show me a catalog of your books. 请拿一本图书目录给我看看。 4. Has the Harvard catalog come yet? 哈佛大学简介来了吗？ 5. Can you catalog all these books? 你能给所有这些书编目录吗？ 6. This stamp catalogues at two dollars. 这张邮票的目录价格为2美元。', '异体字: catalogue 名词: cataloger 过去式: cataloged/catalogued 过去分词: cataloged/catalogued 现在分词: cataloging/cataloguing 第三人称单数: catalogs/catalogues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('timeworn', '[\'taɪmˌwoʊrn]', 'adj.陈旧的；老朽的', '1. It is not some timeworn practice integral to the games. 这不是奥运会原始就具有的一部分。 2. It would be timeworn if I only use Chinese element and it would be involute if I only use Europe element. 完全使用中国的元素会很古板，完全使用欧式的元素会很繁复。 3. When I found it from school library, the back cover of this timeworn book was missing. The pages are frangible. 当我在校图书馆找到这本陈旧的书时，封底已经不见，泛黄的纸岌岌可危，似乎随时都会碎掉。 4. Dusted in winter white, a timeworn cypress looms over Long Lake, some 10,000 feet up in the Min Mountains. 在蒙上了一层白色的冬天，一棵老圬的柏树呈现在岷山中约10000英尺（3048米）高处的长海上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('larva', '[\'lɑːrvə]', 'n.幼虫；幼体', '1. The larva hatches out and lives in the soil. 幼虫孵化之后就在土壤里生活。 2. It shows the metamorphosis of a larva into a butterfly. 它展示了从幼虫变成蝴蝶的过程。 3. The tadpole is the larva of the frog. 蝌蚪是青蛙的幼体。 4. A caterpillar is the larva of a butterfly. 毛虫是蝴蝶的幼体。', '形容词: larval 名词复数: larvae');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('striate', '[\'straɪˌeɪt]', 'v.加条纹 adj.有条纹的', '1. Stem erect, branched above, striate. 茎直立，上面分枝，具条纹。 2. Stems striate or reduced to a caudex. 茎具条纹或者缩短成茎基。 3. Stems erect, subterete, striate, branched apically. 茎直立，近圆柱状，具条纹，顶部的分枝。 4. Stem erect, green striate, ribbed. 茎直立，绿色具条纹，棱。', '过去式: striated 过去分词: striated 现在分词: striating 第三人称单数: striates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avenge', '[ə\'vendʒ]', 'vt. 为 ... 报复； 报仇', '1. How was he to avenge the one without outraging the other? 怎样才能为这一个进行报复而不冒犯那一个呢？ 2. Avenge the slain forefather by vanquishing Major Duke. 报复杀害的祖先主要由击败杜克。 3. He swore by Jupiter to avenge his father\'s death. 他对天发誓，要给他爸爸报仇。 4. He will avenge the people on their oppressor. 他将为人民向压迫者报仇。', '副词: avengingly 名词: avenger 过去式: avenged 过去分词: avenged 现在分词: avenging 第三人称单数: avenges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('villainous', '[\'vɪlənəs]', 'adj.邪恶的；恶毒的；坏透的', '1. We expect our hero\'s rival to show his villainous side. 我们都期待着英雄在他的竞争中显现出他邪恶的一面。 2. After Goku mistakes Kami for the villainous Piccolo it is time for the young warrior to begin his grueling three year training for the next World Martial Arts Tournament. 在误把神仙当作邪恶的短笛大魔王之后，小悟空又即将开始他为期三年的严酷修炼，以准备参加下一届的天下第一比武大会。', '副词: villainously 名词: villainousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aloft', '[ə\'lɔːft]', 'adv.在高处；在空中；在桅杆上 prep.在 ... 上', '1. The balloon went aloft. 气球升向天空。 2. Currents of warm air keep the hang-gliders aloft. 悬挂式滑翔机借着暖气流在高空飞行。 3. The sailor climbed aloft to look for land. 那个水手爬上桅顶寻找陆地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('futile', '[\'fjuːtl]', 'adj.无效的；无用的', '1. Pace considers attempts at timing futile. 贝斯认为企图控制时间是无效的。 2. We are the Borg, Earth assimilation is inevitable, Resistant is futile! 我们是博格，地球将被同化，抵抗是无效的！ 3. It is futile to attempt to convince him that certain things are simply undoable. 使他相信某事情是完全不可为的是无用的尝试。 4. Any unrealistic objective is not worth pursuing sedulously since it is doomed to a futile project. 任何不现实的目标不值得去辛苦地追求因为它注定是无用的计划。', '副词: futilely 名词: futileness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('homely', '[\'hoʊmli]', 'adj.家常的；平凡的；相貌平庸的；简单且好的', '1. We had a homely meal of bread and cheese. 我们吃了一顿面包加乳酪的家常便餐。 2. That in those homely sayings was couched the collective wisdom of generations. 那些朴实的话语表达了一代又一代人的集体智慧。 3. I was very disappointed to see her sister; she was a homely girl. 我看到她的妹妹很失望,她是一个相貌平平的女孩。 4. This hotel is a homely and comfortable establishment. 这家旅馆亲切而舒适。', '比较级: homelier 最高级: homeliest 名词: homeliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gusher', '[\'ɡʌʃər]', 'n.自喷井；迸发出的东西', '1. The oil rushes up the tube and spouts up as a gusher. 石油会沿着钢管上涌，如同自喷井那样喷射出来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fiat', '[\'fiːæt]', 'n.命令；法令 n.（F~）菲亚特（意大利汽车公司名或其出产的轿车品牌名）', '1. The opening of a market stall is governed by municipal fiat. 开设市场摊位受市政法令管制。 2. His influence stretched beyond Fiat. 他的影响超出了菲亚特。 3. While talking, he changed freeway lanes, maneuvering the Fiat with one hand. 他一边讲话，一边用一只手开着菲亚特离开了高速干道。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delinquent', '[dɪ\'lɪŋkwənt]', 'adj.有过失的；怠忽的；失职的；拖欠的 n.行为不良的人；少年犯', '1. Most delinquent children have deprived backgrounds. 多数少年犯都有贫困且未受教育的背景。 2. You are a delinquent subordinate. 你是一个失职的部下。 3. The businessman was billed for delinquent taxes. 那商人因拖欠税金而被罚款。 4. A boy might live in a minus neighborhood but not be a delinquent. 一个男孩子可以生活在一个差劲的街坊而不沦为罪犯。', '副词: delinquently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('firebrand', '[\'faɪərbrænd]', 'n.火把；在燃烧的木柴；煽动者', '1. We kindled a firebrand in the cave. 我们在山洞里点燃火把。 2. He is represented by the media as a dangerous firebrand. 传播媒体报导他是个危险的煽动者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dandy', '[\'dændi]', 'adj.<口>极好的 n.花花公子；好打扮的人', '1. He\'s well-learned and full of dandy ideas. 他学习很好，并且有许多好主意。 2. If you folks want to come along, fine and dandy. 如果你们俩愿意和我一块去,那再好不过了。 3. However, in real life he is a dandy. 但在现实生活中，他却是个游戏人间的花花公子。 4. The dandy cares too much about the smartness of his clothes. 那个花花公子有些过份注意他的衣着。', '形容词: dandyish 副词: dandyishly 比较级: dandier 最高级: dandiest 名词: dandyism 名词复数: dandies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('termination', '[ˌtɜːrmɪ\'neɪʃn]', 'n.终止；结束；词尾；结果', '1. She chose to have an early termination. 她选择了早期终止妊娠。 2. I was discharged of all my obligations after my termination. 在我的合同终止时，我的义务也终止了。 3. How long is the termination period of your present position? 您现在的劳动合同什么时候结束? 4. This affair was brought to a happy termination. 这件事得到圆满的结果。', '形容词: terminational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('torment', '[\'tɔːrment]', 'n.苦痛；拷问；折磨；烦恼 vt.使苦恼；折磨', '1. He was in torment after the operation. 手术后他非常痛苦。 2. That child is a torment to his parents. 这孩子对他的父母是一种折磨。 3. He suffered a hideous torment when the enemy caught him. 敌人抓到他后，他受到可怕的折磨。 4. What a little torment that child is! 这孩子真烦人！ 5. She torments everyone with silly questions. 她用无聊的问题来烦扰大家。', '副词: tormentingly 过去式: tormented 过去分词: tormented 现在分词: tormenting 第三人称单数: torments');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pang', '[pæŋ]', 'n.（肉体上的）剧痛；（精神上的）悲痛；苦闷 v.使剧痛', '1. She felt an acute pang in her arm. 她感到手臂上一阵剧痛。 2. He told himself that it was with the pang which procedes recovery. 他告诫自己这种难受的感觉正好是全愈的先兆。 3. He experienced a pang of sadness. 他感到一阵悲痛。 4. He felt the pangs of remorse at the thought of that. 一提起那事，他就感到良心的谴责。', '过去式: panged 过去分词: panged 现在分词: panging 第三人称单数: pangs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pulpit', '[\'pʊlpɪt]', 'n.讲道坛', '1. There is a white-spindled staircase leading to the pulpit. 有一个白色纺锤形的阶梯通往讲道坛。 2. You don\'t need a choir, or a pulpit or anything else you can see. 你不需要一个唱诗班,或讲道坛或任何你能见的东西。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eclat', '[eɪ\'klaː]', 'n. 巨大成功； 喝彩； <古>坏名声', '1. Her latest novel was received with great eclat. 她最新的小说备受赞赏。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verdigris', '[\'vɜːrdɪɡriː]', 'n.铜绿；铜锈', '1. Verdigris has spread all over that abandoned copper pot. 那把已经废弃的铜壶上长满了铜锈。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jar', '[dʒɑːr]', 'n.广口瓶；坛子；刺耳声；震动 vi.发刺耳声；不协调；震荡；冲突 vt.扰乱；震动', '1. I can\'t get the lid off this jar. 我打不开这广口瓶的盖子。 2. The jar contains ten glasses of water. 这只大口瓶能装十杯水。 3. I need a jar to make the krauts. 我需要一个坛子做泡菜。 4. He fashioned the clay into a jar. 他用粘土做成一个陶土罐子。 5. The iron gate jarred when he opened it. 他开门时，铁门发出刺耳的嘎嘎声。 6. The children\'s screams jar my nerves. 孩子们的尖叫声使我神经不安。', '副词: jarringly 名词: jarful 过去式: jarred 过去分词: jarred 现在分词: jarring 第三人称单数: jars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('staccato', '[stə\'kɑːtoʊ]', 'adj.断音的；不连贯的 adv.断音地；不连贯地 n.不连贯的态度或声音', '1. The most popular approach is the staccato tremolo. 现在最流行的方法是断音练习。 2. Maybe I\'m a back number. I can never enjoy a play of staccato scenes. 也许我是个落伍的人了，我欣赏不了一出场面互不连贯的戏。 3. He shouted a series of staccato orders. 他一顿一顿地大声下了几道命令.', '名词复数: staccatos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trapeze', '[træ\'piːz]', 'n.<体> 吊杠（杂技演员和体操运动员用的）', '1. They have magic shows, flying trapeze arts, tightrope walking and even the clowns. 他们有魔术表演、空中飞人、走钢丝,甚至还有小丑。 2. By the time he was nine years old, he was already performing as a trapeze artist. 他年仅九岁时，便已经在表演空中飞人的特技。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jejune', '[dʒɪ\'dʒuːn]', 'adj.空洞的；不成熟的；缺乏营养的', '1. I detected a jejune air that had not inbed me before. 我感到一种沉闷的空气，这种感觉是以前从来没有的。 2. Then she was gone, leaving me in unexpectedly jejune loneliness. 于是她走了，置我于意想不到的空虚孤独之中。 3. I detected a jejune air that had not imbedded me before. 我感到一种沉闷的空气,这种感觉是以前从来没有的。 4. She seems a rather creepy, jejune and adolescent fantasy. 她是一个怪异，不成熟的青春幻想产物。', '副词: jejunely 名词: jejuneness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anthem', '[\'ænθəm]', 'n.圣歌；赞美诗', '1. But as she spoke some of her supporters broke into the Peronist party anthem. 但是，正当菲南德斯发表此言论之时，她的一些拥护者竟大声唱起了庇隆党的赞美诗。 2. The anthem that the organist played cemented Soapy to the iron fence. 风琴师弹奏的赞美诗音乐把苏贝胶在铁栏杆上了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('writ', '[rɪt]', 'n.令状', '1. The police showed him the writ of search before entering the house. 警察进屋前，给他出示了搜查令。 2. The company has been served with a writ for breach of contract. 这家公司因违约已接到法院令状。 3. Creditors could obtain a writ for the arrest of their debtors. 债权人可以获得逮捕债务人的令状。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yummy', '[\'jʌmi]', 'adj.美味的；好吃的；愉快的；吸引人的，悦人的', '1. This cake is really yummy. 蛋糕非常美味。 2. Chocolate cake for tea? How yummy! 有巧克力蛋糕当茶点? 多好吃啊！ 3. I could eat a whole pot of that hot, yummy carrot. 我可以吃一锅那样的又热又好吃的胡萝卜。', '比较级: yummier 最高级: yummiest 名词: yumminess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('summation', '[sʌ\'meɪʃn]', 'n.总结；加法；总和；有代表性的整体', '1. The defense attorney phrased his summation at last. 最后,辩护律师作了辩论总结。 2. What he said was a fair summation of the discussion. 他这番话对讨论作了恰当的总结。 3. After a dramatic pause, the lawyer finished her summation. 在戏剧性的沉默之后,这位律师作完了她的总述。 4. It is convenient to introduce here the summation operator. 应当在此介绍一下求和的算符。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ubiquitous', '[juː\'bɪkwɪtəs]', 'adj.到处存在的', '1. He could see the ubiquitous TV cameras. 他可以看到那些无处不在的电视摄像机。 2. The struggle between opposites is ubiquitous. 对立的争斗无所不在。 3. Happiness is ubiquitous, may fall short of demand. 幸福无处不在', '副词: ubiquitously 名词: ubiquitousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('damped', '[\'dæmpt]', '阻尼的,衰减的', '1. The motion at this time scale is clearly dominated by the lightly damped phugoid. 采用这种时间尺度时，运动显然由小阻尼的沉浮模态所决定。 2. Express the differences of displacement variation of a mass subjected by a free damped vibration and a forced vibration, separately. 分别叙述一质量受到无阻尼的振动与强制振动时位移变化的不同。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tangy', '[\'tæŋi]', 'adj.强烈的；扑鼻的；有刺激性的', '1. I love the tangy smell of the sea air when I go to the beach. 我去海边的时候很喜欢海风这种强烈的气息。 2. The tea goes with this tangy lemon tart perfectly. 这种茶配上这种香味扑鼻的柠檬塔非常完美。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('puffery', '[\'pʌfərɪ]', 'n.极力吹捧；夸大宣传', '1. Puffery: Flattering, often exaggerated praise and publicity, especially when used for promotional purposes. 吹捧:尤指用于促销的常是夸张的赞扬和宣传。 2. It\'s all puffery and nonsense that can constrain and damage the mind and a life. 谁如果说这样的生活会压抑和损伤脑力和生命力，那绝对是胡说八道。 3. Western courts tend to dismiss the claims of real estate agents as \"mere puffery\". 西方的法院倾向于驳回房地产商的申诉而仅仅因“夸大其词”。 4. The satirical magazine Spy threw darts at all the puffery of the era, and was especially fast to disdain the gaudy arrivistes in favor of dandruff-flecked Old Money. 一家叫《窥视》的讽刺杂志对那一时代的浮夸风大肆抨击，尤其鄙视那些爱炫耀的暴发户，认为那些老富翁更有品味，尽管他们的头发上有头屑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interdict', '[\'ɪntərdɪkt]', 'v.禁止；停止；阻断 n.[法]禁令', '1. The third-way reflects the flavonoid compound can interdict adsorption. 第三种给药方式反映一定浓度的药物可以阻断病毒对细胞的吸附作用。 2. The defendant did not obey the interdict. 被告人不遵守禁令。', '形容词: interdictive 副词: interdictively 名词: interdiction 过去式: interdicted 过去分词: interdicted 现在分词: interdicting 第三人称单数: interdicts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anomalous', '[ə\'nɑːmələs]', 'adj.反常的；不规则的', '1. The phenomenon is called anomalous propagation. 这种现象被称为异常传播。 2. He is in an anomalous position as the only part-time worker in the firm. 他与众不同，是公司里唯一的兼职人员。 3. The mechanism of this anomalous vascular response is unknown. 此种不规则的血管反应的机制尚不清楚。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foment', '[foʊ\'ment]', 'v.煽动；引发；激起；[医]热敷', '1. His word finally foment her hostility. 他的言词终于引发了她的敌意。', '名词: fomenter 过去式: fomented 过去分词: fomented 现在分词: fomenting 第三人称单数: foments');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('austerity', '[ɔː\'sterəti]', 'n.节俭；苦行；(经济的)紧缩；严厉', '1. Austerity, not market reform, was his message. 节俭，而不是改革，才是他传递的信息。 2. Austerity is the only path to attain liberation. 苦修是通向解脱的唯一的道路。 3. Wartime austerities included food rationing and shortage of fuel. 战时的艰苦包括食物配给和燃料短缺。 4. Children are afraid of the austerity of their schoolmaster. 孩子们都害怕校长的严厉。', '名词复数: austerities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exacerbate', '[ɪɡ\'zæsərbeɪt]', 'vt.加重(使 ... 恶化；激怒)', '1. Scratching exacerbates a skin rash. 皮疹搔後会恶化。 2. Her mother\'s interference exacerbated the difficulties in their marriage. 她母亲从中干预使他们的婚姻雪上加霜。 3. China\'s older air-traffic-control systems exacerbate the delays. 中国陈旧的空中交通控制系统更是雪上加霜。', '名词: exacerbation 过去式: exacerbated 过去分词: exacerbated 现在分词: exacerbating 第三人称单数: exacerbates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deciduous', '[dɪ\'sɪdʒuəs]', 'adj.每年落叶的；非永久性的；（牙齿或角等）定期脱落的；蚂蚁交合后脱落翅膀', '1. Very few plants in my garden are deciduous. 我公园里的落叶植物很少。 2. The climate is not suitable for deciduous vegetation. 这种气候不适合落叶植物的生长。', '副词: deciduously 名词: deciduousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('welter', '[\'weltər]', 'n.混乱；次重量级的摔跤手 v.翻滚；沉迷；混乱', '1. I have just cleared up a bewildering welter of data saved in my computer. 我刚整理了保存在我电脑里的很难处理的杂乱无章的数据。 2. The chiefs of all the villages were weltering in luxury and pleasure. 所有的村庄的头领都沉迷于骄奢淫逸之中。', '过去式: weltered 过去分词: weltered 现在分词: weltering 第三人称单数: welters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pacifist', '[\'pæsɪfɪst]', 'adj.非战主义的 n.和平主义者；反战；反对武力', '1. Pacifist movements gathered strength in Norway. 在挪威,和平主义的运动力量逐渐增强。 2. Ultimately he wants to revise the pacifist constitution. 他最终希望修改和平宪法。 3. I\'ve never met such an ardent pacifist as Terry. 我从未见过像特里这样热情的和平主义者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mystic', '[\'mɪstɪk]', 'adj.神秘的；神秘主义者的 n.神秘主义者', '1. They hold a mystic religious ceremony. 他们举行了一个神秘的宗教仪式。 2. I know some world\'s mystic religions. 我了解一些世界上的神秘宗教。 3. He believes in mystic philosophy. 他信奉的是神秘主义哲学。 4. The mystic describes himself as being transported to another world. 这个神秘主义者描述自己好像被送入了另一个世界。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('soil', '[sɔɪl]', 'n.土地；土壤；污物，粪便 v.弄污', '1. It\'s rich there because of the fertility of soil. 因为土地肥沃，那儿很富裕。 2. Fertile soil yields good crops. 肥沃的土地能种出好庄稼。 3. This kind of soil contains much alkali. 这种土壤含碱丰富。 4. He transplanted the seedlings into peaty soil. 他把幼苗移栽到含泥炭的土壤里。 5. Her slanderous words soiled his reputation. 她中伤性的话损害了他的名誉。', '过去式: soiled 过去分词: soiled 现在分词: soiling 第三人称单数: soils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dispense', '[dɪ\'spens]', 'vt.分发；分配；免除；配(药)', '1. The Red Cross dispensed food and clothing to the victims. 红十字会分发食品和衣物给受害者。 2. In data security, the right of users to dispense and revoke privileges for objects they own, e.g. access on programs and data sets. 在数据安全技术中，用户对其拥有的对象行使分配和取消特权的权利，例如对程序和数据集的访问权。 3. Let\'s dispense with the formalities. 让我们免去那些礼节吧。 4. She cannot dispense with a servant. 她不能没有佣人。', '过去式: dispensed 过去分词: dispensed 现在分词: dispensing 第三人称单数: dispenses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obeisance', '[oʊ\'biːsns]', 'n.鞠躬；敬礼；敬重', '1. He made obeisance to the king. 他向国王表示臣服。 2. He made a deep obeisance to the queen. 他向女王深深鞠了一躬。 3. They made obeisance to the sultan. 他们向那苏丹鞠躬致敬。 4. Every one is requested to pay obeisance to principles here. 要求这里的每个人都尊重原则 。', '形容词: obeisant');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sceptical', '[\'skeptɪkl]', 'adj.怀疑的', '1. He listened to me with a sceptical expression. 他听我讲话的时候带着怀疑的表情。 2. A small smile came over Winifred\'s face, subtle and sceptical. 威妮弗莱德的脸上露出了一丝神秘，怀疑的微笑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('understudy', '[\'ʌndərstʌdi]', 'v.充当（某角色的）候补演员 n.候补演员', '1. The understudy was substituted when the leading actor fell ill. 主角演员患病，由替角代替演出。 2. When the star became sick,his understudy stepped into his part. 当这位电影明星生病时，由他的候补演员担任他的角色。 3. She got the part and I was her understudy. 她得到了这个角色，我只能作为替补的临时演员。', '名词复数: understudies 过去式: understudied 过去分词: understudied 现在分词: understudying 第三人称单数: understudies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bewitching', '[bɪ\'wɪtʃɪŋ]', 'adj.迷人的；使人着迷的 动词bewitch的现在分词形式.', '1. She gave him a bewitching smile. 她给他迷人的一笑。 2. He kept the book open at the bewitching portrait. 他把书翻在这迷人的肖像一页上。 3. I might never have heard that entrancing sound, or smelt that bewitching smell! 永远听不到那种叫人醉心的声响，闻不到那股叫人着迷的气味了！', '副词: bewitchingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thrive', '[θraɪv]', 'vi.兴旺；繁荣；茁壮成长', '1. A business cannot thrive without good management. 没有良好的经营管理，事业就不会兴旺发达。 2. But will they survive and thrive? 但是，他们会生存下来并兴旺繁殖吗? 3. May our country prosper and thrive forever! 希望我们的国家繁荣兴旺，长盛不衰。 4. A business can not thrive without investment. 没有投资任何生意都无法繁荣。', '名词: thriver 过去式: thrived/throve 过去分词: thrived/thriven 现在分词: thriving 第三人称单数: thrives');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yacht', '[jɑːt]', 'n.游艇；快艇 vi.驾快艇', '1. Huge waves drove the yacht onto the rocks. 巨浪把游艇卷到岩石上。 2. The yacht hit a rock and damaged her bows. 游艇碰上了礁石，撞坏了船头。 3. Our little dinghy was dwarfed by the big yacht. 我们的小船跟大游艇一比显得很小。 4. They were able to position the yacht by means of radar. 他们能够用雷达测定快艇的方位。', '过去式: yachted 过去分词: yachted 现在分词: yachting 第三人称单数: yachts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('superfluous', '[suː\'pɜːrfluəs]', 'adj.多余的；过剩的；不必要的', '1. Repack all the superfluous cups in the box. 把多余的杯子都重新装入箱中。 2. He has already been told, so our comments are superfluous. 早就有人同他说过，所以我们的意见是多余的。 3. The market is already superfluous. 市场已经过剩了。 4. She crossed out all the superfluous words and phrases in the draft. 她把草稿中不必要的词句都杠掉了。', '副词: superfluously 名词: superfluousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brute', '[bruːt]', 'n.畜生；残忍的人 adj.残忍的；无理性的；粗暴的', '1. Eichmann is not a low police brute. 艾克曼不是一个低三下四的警察畜生。 2. That\'s your fault for foisting the brute on us. 你真不该把那个畜生带到咱们这个圈子里来！ 3. We all wait to punish the brute. 我们都想惩罚那个残忍的人。 4. Brute force was used to put down the revolt. 使用残忍的武力平息反叛。', '名词: brutism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imputation', '[ˌɪmpju\'teɪʃn]', 'n.归罪；责难', '1. I\'m quite willing to accept the imputation. 我完全接受你的指责。 2. I could not rest under the imputation. 我受到诋毁,无法平静。 3. But the imputation shall not discourage me. 然而，这种指责不会使我泄气。 4. I cannot rest under an imputation. 我不能甘受诬陷。', '形容词: imputative 副词: imputatively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rebuttal', '[rɪ\'bʌtl]', 'n.反驳；反证', '1. The accusations met with a firm rebuttal. 这些指控受到了坚决的驳斥。 2. They made a clause-by-clause rebuttal of the letter. 他们对这封信逐句作了反驳。 3. If your dad shoots off his mouth at your party, you can make a calm rebuttal. 如果你爸爸在你的晚会上高谈别人的秘密，你可以很冷静地制止他。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fraternal', '[frə\'tɜːrnl]', 'adj.兄弟的；兄弟般的；[生]异卵双生的', '1. We\'ll do all we can to step up our aid to our fraternal countries. 我们将尽力加强对兄弟国家的援助。 2. The party sent its fraternal greetings to the trade union meeting. 党向工会大会致以亲切的问候。 3. In other words, their senses of what was fair were similar.No such correlations were seen in the behaviour of fraternal twins. 换句话说，他们的公平感是很相似的，而在异卵双生的双胞胎中就没有发现这样的关系。', '副词: fraternally 名词: fraternalism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('squabble', '[\'skwɑːbl]', 'v.（为琐事）争论；口角 n.争论；口角', '1. No man will squabble over a nickel. 没有人会为了五分钱而吵架。 2. I hate to squabble with my wife about [over] money. 我厌恶为钱的事与太太争吵。 3. The silly family\'s squabble became a joke in the neighborhood. 这场无聊的家庭纠纷已经成为街坊邻居的笑柄。 4. A judge may have to sort out the immediate squabble. 法官可能不得不解决当前的争吵。', '名词: squabbler 过去式: squabbled 过去分词: squabbled 现在分词: squabbling 第三人称单数: squabbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crinkle', '[\'krɪŋkl]', 'v.变皱；沙沙作响 n.皱纹；波状；沙沙声；[植]绉叶病', '1. She crinkled up her nose in distaste. 她厌恶地皱起鼻子。 2. There were crinkles at the corner of her eyes when she smiled. 当她笑的时候，眼角处有一些皱纹。', '形容词: crinkly 过去式: crinkled 过去分词: crinkled 现在分词: crinkling 第三人称单数: crinkles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peccadillo', '[ˌpekə\'dɪloʊ]', 'n.轻罪；小过失', '1. For this peccadillo he was demoted and sent back to pound the beat. 由于这次过失，他被降了级，又被打发去干徒步巡警了。 2. He is such a fury! He just flied into rage at such a peccadillo! 对于这样一个小过错就罚款5000英镑简直是太过分了。 3. The shoe that wear crosses peccadillo to tighten, can have generated great pressure to the foot, this makes the person feels not only uncomfortable and still can make the foot is formed a few.. 穿的鞋过小过紧，会对脚产生过大压力，这不仅使人感到不舒适而且还会使脚形成一些... 4. theatricalized little space this is a force because of color and common peccadillo method becomes rich the example of artistic quality. 戏剧化的小空间这是一个因颜色的力量而将一个普通的小过道变得富有艺术性的例子。', '名词复数: peccadilloes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('terrestrial', '[tə\'restriəl]', 'adj.陆地的；陆生的；地球的 n.地球生物', '1. Men live on the terrestrial parts of the earth. 人们住在地球上的陆地部分。 2. Aquatic food chains are different from terrestrial ones. 水生食物链不同于陆地食物链。 3. Although they can swim, the polar bears are terrestrial animals. 北极熊虽然会游泳，但也是陆栖动物。 4. A terrestrial globe is one that represents the earth. 地球仪是表现地球的器具。', '副词: terrestrially 名词: terrestrialness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spoke', '[spoʊk]', 'n.轮辐 v.为…装轮辐 动词speak的过去式.', '1. He spoke with disapproval of your proposal. 他对你的建议很不以为然。 2. He spoke scarcely a word of English. 他几乎连一个英文单词都不会说。 3. He spoke for too long, as is his wont. 他讲话时间太长了，这正是他向来的习惯。 4. He spoke with assertion. 他坚定地说。', '过去式: spoked 过去分词: spoked 现在分词: spoking 第三人称单数: spokes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skeleton', '[\'skelɪtn]', 'n.骨架；纲要；骨骼；骨瘦如柴的人或动物；家丑 adj.骨骼的', '1. The block is still just a skeleton of girders. 这片建筑还只是仅有主梁的骨架。 2. The director set out the plan in skeleton form. 主任提纲挈领地说明了这一计划。 3. I\'ve written the skeleton of my report, but I have to fill in the details. 我已写出报告的梗概，但我必须补充细节。 4. The shell of a snail is its skeleton. 蜗牛的壳是它的骨骼。 5. As a part of the whole skeleton, oral maxillofacial bone loss has some association with systemic osteoporosis. 做为全身骨骼的一部分，颌骨的骨丢失一直被认为与全身骨质疏松存在关联性。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impostor', '[ɪm\'pɑːstər]', 'n.冒充者；骗子', '1. The man turned out to be an impostor. 那个人结果却是一名冒充者。 2. He said he was a doctor, but it subsequently emerged that he was an impostor. 他说他是位医生，但后来却发现他是个骗子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spool', '[spuːl]', 'n.线轴；缠线用的卷盘 v.缠绕；卷在线轴上', '1. The film fly off the spool and wind itself round the projector. 电影胶片从卷轴滑出缠绕在放映机上了。 2. An object,such as a spool or barrel,around which material is wound. 电影胶片从卷轴滑出缠绕在放映机上了。', '过去式: spooled 过去分词: spooled 现在分词: spooling 第三人称单数: spools');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compromise', '[\'kɑːmprəmaɪz]', 'n.妥协；折衷；折衷案；和解 vt.妥协处理；危害 vi.妥协，和解；让步', '1. He did it without compromise of his dignity. 他做这事而不损及他的尊严。 2. The agreement is a compromise, not a sell-out. 这个协议是双方妥协的产物而不是一方让步。 3. After some discussion we arrive at a compromise. 经过一番讨论之后，我们达成一项折衷方案。 4. Or are we ready to compromise our faith? 或者，我们准备好了在信仰上折衷吗？ 5. With this increased awareness, attackers are finding it more difficult to compromise systems at the network level. 由于对这些认识得越来越清楚，攻击者发现在网络级上危害系统更加困难。 6. They found it wiser to compromise with her. 他们觉得与她妥协更明智。', '名词: compromiser 过去式: compromised 过去分词: compromised 现在分词: compromising 第三人称单数: compromises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meddlesome', '[\'medlsəm]', 'adj.爱管闲事的', '1. By this means the meddlesome woman cast in a bone between the wife and the husband. 这爱管闲事的女人就用这种手段挑起他们夫妻这间的不和。 2. Get rid of that meddlesome fool! 让那个爱管闲事的家伙走开。', '副词: meddlesomely 名词: meddlesomeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('equivocation', '[ɪˌkwɪvə\'keɪʃn]', 'n.模糊话；含糊其辞', '1. There is an element of equivocation in some of his statements. 他的很多话中存在着模棱两可的内容。 2. He answered openly and honestly without hesitation or equivocation. 他回答问题坦荡、真诚，没有丝毫犹豫和含糊。 3. Equivocation is first cousin to a lie. 含糊其词是谎话的近亲。 4. These actions must be condemned without equivocation. 对这些行为必须毫不含糊地予以谴责。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('toupee', '[tuː\'peɪ]', 'n.假发；顶髻', '1. When he grew bald,he bought a toupee. 他头发日渐稀少，于是买了假发。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('countrified', '[\'kʌntrifaɪd]', 'adj.土气的；粗俗的；带有乡村风味的', '1. Besides, many of them always retained their countrified simplicity. 土气的衣服；土头土脑的笨拙。 2. \"Your town tastes would find them far too countrified. 尤苔莎醒了过来。那哗啦声原是楼下女仆开百叶窗的声响。 3. At this meeting Olga\'s bookish and countrified sister, Tatiana (Tanya), falls in love with Onegin. 聚会中，奥佳那位书生气十足且满身土气的姐姐塔替雅娜爱上了奥涅金。 4. Content\'s from highness go to lowliness in turn is countrified fry, clear fry, wheat bran fry, generate article. 薯蓣皂苷元之含量由高至低依次为土炒、清炒、麸炒、生品。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apiary', '[\'eɪpieri]', 'n.养蜂场；蜂房', '1. My sister was put in charge of the apiary. 我姐姐被派去负责养蜂场。 2. Apiary Inspector Peter Kaczynski came out of retirement to put together this rapid response unit for the State of Victoria. 已经退休的养蜂场的督察员彼德，立刻在维多利亚成立回应单位。 3. These requirements rule for all apiary sites, including migration sites. 这些规定是蜂房所在地必须满足的条件，迁移地也是一样。', '名词复数: apiaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('susceptibility', '[səˌseptə\'bɪləti]', 'n.敏感性；感受性；磁化率 (复数）susceptibilities:感情.', '1. Asthmatics have an increased susceptibility to viral illnesses. 气喘病人对病毒性病变的敏感性增加了。 2. Susceptibility to heat damage is influenced by genetically controlled factors. 对热害的敏感性则受遗传所控制的因素的影响。 3. In addition, some suggestion of improving susceptibility of low temperature flow improvers for diesel fuel are presented. 另外，对提高柴油低温流动改进剂的感受性提出了几点建议。 4. Pauli paramagnetism of an weakly interacting Fermi gas is studied.The expression of susceptibility is derived analytically. 摘要研究弱相互作用费米体系的泡利顺磁性，导出磁化率的解析表达式。', '名词复数: susceptibilities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cataclysm', '[\'kætəklɪzəm]', 'n.大洪水；地震；(社会政治的)大变动', '1. The cataclysm flooded the entire valley. 洪水淹没了整个山谷。 2. A cataclysm caused by the dam breaking. 一场因水坝破裂所造成的大洪水。 3. No cataclysm has desolated the whole world. 没有任何激变曾使整个世界变成荒芜。 4. World War II was a cataclysm for all of Europe. 第二次世界大战对整个欧洲是一大剧变。', '形容词: cataclysmic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('calculated', '[\'kælkjuleɪtɪd]', 'adj.有计划的；经计算的；可能的 动词calculate的过去式与过去分词.', '1. His political opponents made a calculated attack on him. 他的政敌们对他进行了包藏祸心的攻击。 2. The calculated result conforms to the ground ejection test well. 计算结果成功地用于地面试验中。 3. There is a calculated risk in anesthetizing this patient. 麻醉这个病人预计有一定危险。', '副词: calculatedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alert', '[ə\'lɜːrt]', 'adj.警觉的；灵敏的 vt.使意识到；警惕 n.警戒；警报', '1. The alert leopard went up to a deer quietly. 警觉的豹子静悄悄地走近一只鹿。 2. Although he\'s over eighty his mind is still remarkably alert. 他虽已年过八十，但头脑仍然十分机敏。 3. I must alert him to the need to solve the problem. 我必须使他认识到解决这问题的必要性。 4. But we must remain on the alert. 但是我们现在仍然要保持警惕。 5. Troops are on the alert against any possible aggression. 军队戒备着可能的来犯。', '过去式: alerted 过去分词: alerted 现在分词: alerting 第三人称单数: alerts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('churl', '[tʃɜːrl]', 'n.粗鄙之人；中世纪的农民', '1. Of, like, or befitting a churl; boorish or vulgar. 粗鲁的象或适合粗鲁人的；粗鲁的或庸俗的 2. Poison, I see, hath been his timeless end: O churl! 我知道了，一定是毒药结果了他的生命。 3. And, tender churl, makest waste in niggarding. 温柔的怪物呵，用吝啬浪费了全部， 4. And tender churl,makest waste in niggarding. 娇弱的悭吝人啊，越是算计，则浪费越多。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('curfew', '[\'kɜːrfjuː]', 'n.宵禁', '1. A yellow-coded curfew is now in effect. 现在开始黄色戒备等级宵禁。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('facile', '[\'fæsl]', 'adj.易做到的；轻易完成的；麻利的', '1. The facile answer is a multimethod approach. 最方便的答案是多种方法的普查。 2. That is only a facile answer. 那只是一个很肤浅的回答。 3. What he said is a facile remark. 他说的话全是信口开河。 4. She is a facile speaker. 她是个能说会道的人。', '副词: facilely 名词: facileness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('improvise', '[\'ɪmprəvaɪz]', 'v.即兴创作；即兴表演；临时准备', '1. Akel says this style of acting required the crew to improvise as well. 称这种演出方式要求剧组人员都要即兴创作。 2. It is much easier to improvise a song than it is to improvise a symphony. 即兴创作一支歌曲比即兴创作一部交响曲要简单得多。', '名词: improviser 过去式: improvised 过去分词: improvised 现在分词: improvising 第三人称单数: improvises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blackmail', '[\'blækmeɪl]', 'n.勒索；敲诈 vt.勒索；讹诈', '1. She was sent to prison for blackmail. 因犯敲诈勒索罪她被送进监牢。 2. It\'s a clear case of blackmail! 这显然是敲诈！ 3. He can be ruthless in getting what he wants, but I believe he would stop short of blackmail. 他这个人为达到目的是心黑手辣的,但我认为他还不至于使用敲诈手段。 4. Someone was trying to blackmail him with pictures of him and his mistress. 有人想用他和情人的照片来敲诈勒索他。', '名词: blackmailer');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('leak', '[liːk]', 'v.渗；漏；泄露 n.漏洞；泄露', '1. Water had started to leak into the cellar. 水已开始渗入地下室。 2. The kitchen roof is apt to leak when it rains. 厨房的屋顶下雨时容易漏雨。 3. The details were supposed to be secret but somehow leaked out. 这些细节原属秘密，可是不知怎么给泄露出去了。 4. There is a leak in the roof. 屋顶有一个漏洞。', '名词: leaker 过去式: leaked 过去分词: leaked 现在分词: leaking 第三人称单数: leaks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('excursive', '[ek\'skɜːsɪv]', 'adj.游览的；离题的；散漫的', '1. For this excursive you will need someone\'s help. 这个练习你需要别人的协助。 2. Method: Adopt intestines push movement and excursive intestines flesh experimentation to determine motor function. 方法:采用肠推进运动及离体肠肌实验法测定消化道运动功能。 3. Most things I handled in my first year in ASE are excursive events happened in production line. 在我在日月光的第一年，大部份时间都是处理生产线发生的异常。 4. After being trained by these excursive drivers, your driving skills would advance by leaps and bounds. 拉拉杂杂说这麽多，其实还是一样，人生是我的，要为自己努力认真的活著。', '副词: excursively 名词: excursiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spurious', '[\'spjʊriəs]', 'adj.假的；伪造的', '1. That link, reckon the authors, is not spurious. 文章作者关于这一关系的估计不是伪造的。 2. Mr Denard could look gentlemanly, smart in grey suits or his spurious colonel\'s uniform. 德纳尔先生穿着那灰色的军服或伪造的上校制服看起来就很雅致，而且酷毙了！', '副词: spuriously 名词: spuriousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('halfhearted', '[\'hɑːf\'hɑːtɪd]', 'adj.半心半意的；不热心的；兴趣不大的', '1. A halfhearted attempt at writing a novel. 并不热心的试图写一部小说', '副词: halfheartedly 名词: halfheartedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('legion', '[\'liːdʒən]', 'n.军团；众多的人 adj.很多的', '1. Bush spoke to the nation\'s largest veterans\' group, The American Legion. 布什总统已经对美国最大的退伍军人团体美国军团发表了讲话。 2. Each legion contained between 3000 and 6000 soldiers. 每个军团有三千至六千名步兵。 3. The varieties of policies are legion. 政策的种类是繁多的。 4. As for the homeless, their name is legion. 至于无家可归的人，那就为数众多了。 5. The filmstar has a legion of admires. 那个影星有一大群崇拜者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('burlesque', '[bɜːr\'lesk]', 'n.滑稽模仿；滑稽娱乐(常伴有脱衣舞)；嘲讽性作品 adj.滑稽模仿的；讽刺性作品的；滑稽表演的 v.(以滑稽或夸张手法)模仿嘲弄', '1. By taking bribes the judge made a burlesque of his high office. 那位法官受了贿赂,嘲弄了自己的高位。 2. He just is a second banana in that burlesque. 他只不过是那场滑稽戏里的配角。 3. The book read like a black comic burlesque. 这本书读起来像一个黑色幽默的讽刺作品。 4. The burlesque element weakens the serious portions of the book. 书里的戏谑成分使严肃部分受到损害。 5. He shouldn\'t burlesque the elder. 他不应模仿那长者。', '副词: burlesquely 名词: burlesquer 过去式: burlesqued 过去分词: burlesqued 现在分词: burlesquing 第三人称单数: burlesques');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delegate', '[\'delɪɡeɪt]', 'n.代表 v.派 ... 为代表；委派；授权；委托', '1. Babbitt was an official delegate. 巴比特是一名正式代表。 2. He was elected as a delegate to the annual conference. 他被选为年会代表。 3. He can\'t delegate command. 他不能委派代表来指挥。 4. You can\'t do all the jobs yourself---you can delegate a task to your subordinate. 你不能包揽所有的工作---你可以把任务委派给下属。', '名词: delegator 过去式: delegated 过去分词: delegated 现在分词: delegating 第三人称单数: delegates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intellect', '[\'ɪntəlekt]', 'n.智力；理智；才智非凡的人；知识份子', '1. You estimate his intellect too highly. 你把他的智力评估得太高。 2. The problem challenges us to use our intellect. 这个问题需要我们运用智力。 3. She is short on intellect,but long on shape. 她短于理智而长于姿态。 4. By theory, my behavior is not intellect. 理论上来说，这是不理智的行为。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cognate', '[\'kɑːɡneɪt]', 'n.同源词 adj.同源的；相关的', '1. Haus and house are cognates. Haus与house为同源词。 2. German and Dutch are cognate languages. 德语和荷兰语为同源语言。 3. Physics and astronomy are cognate sciences. 物理学和天文学是相关联的科学。', '名词: cognation');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tuber', '[\'tuːbər]', 'n.块茎；球根；[解]结节；隆起；肿胀', '1. The potato is a tuber plant. 马铃薯是块茎植物。 2. Along with the rise of temperature, both tuber weight and bulk increased rapidly. 随着温度的升高，块茎重量和体积迅速增长。 3. A small tuber was detected in her armpit. 发现她腋下有个小结节。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('galley', '[\'ɡæli]', 'n.单层甲板大帆船；（船或飞机的）厨房；[印]活版盘', '1. This must be the chest of the galley\'s carpenter. 这一定是船上的木匠的箱子。 2. The boy was caughtand sold to be a galley slave. 这个男孩被抓住,并被卖到战舰上做奴隶。 3. The stewardess will get you some water from the galley. 空中小姐会从厨房给你拿些水来。', '名词复数: galleys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('languor', '[\'læŋɡər]', 'n.怠惰；疲倦；无气力', '1. The idea of being misled suffused her with languor. 被人引入邪路的想法使她变得懒洋洋的。 2. \"It was hot, yet with a sweet languor about it\" (Theodore Dreiser) “天气是炎热的，然而却有一种惬意的懒洋洋的感觉”(西奥多·德莱塞) 3. There was no languor in her now. 这时候她身上的烦恼已经无影无踪。 4. Languor is upon your heart and the slumber is still on your eyes. 乏倦压在你的心上，你眼中尚有睡意。', '形容词: languorous 副词: languorously 名词: languorousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dock', '[dɑːk]', 'n.码头；船坞；船埠 v.进(港、码头)', '1. The ship\'s hull scraped along the side of the dock. 船行时船身擦着码头的边。 2. The cruise ship is strikebound in the dock. 巡洋舰因罢工而停泊在码头上。 3. The liner is in dock for a refit. 班轮正在船坞修理。 4. The yacht is lying up in the dock. 那条游艇正停在船坞里。 5. He rowed up the canal looking for a place to dock the boat. 他在运河里划船，寻找一个码头泊船。', '过去式: docked 过去分词: docked 现在分词: docking 第三人称单数: docks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('predestine', '[priː\'destɪn]', 'vt.预定；注定', '1. They both felt that they were predestined to spend their lives together. 他们俩都觉得他们注定了要在一起生活一辈子。 2. She was obviously predestined to succeed. 她显然注定了能成功。 3. It seemed that his failure was predestined. 他的失败似乎是命中注定的。', '过去式: predestined 过去分词: predestined 现在分词: predestining 第三人称单数: predestines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flit', '[flɪt]', 'v.轻快地飞；掠过；搬家(尤指为躲债) n.掠过；搬家', '1. Bees were flitting from flower to flower. 蜜蜂在花丛间飞来飞去。 2. Fancies flitted through my mind. 我的脑中掠过各种幻想。 3. I had to change schools every time my parents flitted. 每次我的父母搬家，我都不得不转学。 4. He did a moonlight flit last night. 他昨晚半夜秘密搬家了。', '名词: flitter 过去式: flitted 过去分词: flitted 现在分词: flitting 第三人称单数: flits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insincerity', '[ˌɪnsɪn\'serəti]', 'n.不诚实；无诚意；伪善', '1. False teeth may symbolize insincerity. 假牙代表伪善，不真诚。 2. The great enemy of clear language is insincerity. 伪善是清晰语言主要的敌人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('breezeway', '[\'briːzweɪ]', 'n.有屋顶的通路', '1. Children at play on the stone benches in the breezeway of the Dr. 图1：为小朋友在国父纪念馆走廊的石凳玩。 2. Also an enclosed breezeway with hot tub included leads to workshop and garage. 另外一个封闭的热水浴，包括通往工厂和车库。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('freckle', '[\'frekl]', 'n.雀斑；斑点 v.长雀斑', '1. Ann\'s face and back are covered with freckles. 安的脸上和背上长满了雀斑。 2. There is a big black freckle on his face. 他的脸上有一个很大的黑痣。 3. When she lies in the sun, her face gets covered with freckles. 当她躺在阳光下时，她的脸上就布满了斑点。 4. Do you freckle easily? 你容易长雀斑吗?', '形容词: freckly 过去式: freckled 过去分词: freckled 现在分词: freckling 第三人称单数: freckles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arsenal', '[\'ɑːrsənl]', 'n.兵工厂；军械库；储藏 Arsenal. n.阿森纳(英格兰一足球队名)', '1. Even the workers at the arsenal have got a secret organization. 兵工厂工人暗中也有组织。 2. The cannon on the Arsenal crest bears great similarity with those on the crest of the Royal Arsenal Gatehouse in Woolwich. 阿森纳徽章上的大炮和伍里奇市皇家兵工厂大门上的徽章极为相似。 3. Cade has a small arsenal of weapons, including a collection of antique blasters liberated on various missions. 凯德拥有一个小型军械库，收集了在任务中缴获来的各种老式爆能枪。 4. I was shocked to discover that it was an arsenal containing an array of antiquated armor and armament. 我愕然发现这竟是个军械库，里面存放着全系列的古老盔甲和武器。 5. Arsenal scored in the final minute of the game. 阿森纳队在比赛的最后一分钟进了一球。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('propitiate', '[prə\'pɪʃieɪt]', 'v.慰抚；劝解；取悦', '1. They offered sacrifices to propitiate the gods. 他们供奉祭品以求神息怒。', '形容词: propitiable 副词: propitiatingly 名词: propitiator 过去式: propitiated 过去分词: propitiated 现在分词: propitiating 第三人称单数: propitiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peckish', '[\'pekɪʃ]', 'adj.饿的；易怒的', '1. I\'m dying for a cup of tea and I\'m also a bit peckish. 我很想喝杯茶，肚子也有点饿了。 2. Looks may not kill, but they can leave you feeling peckish. 长相也许不会要你的命，但可能会让你挨饿。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('miscreant', '[\'mɪskriənt]', 'n.歹徒；恶棍；异端 adj.极恶的；邪道的；异端的', '1. We need tougher penalties to discourage miscreants. 我们需要更加严厉的惩罚措施来磨灭歹徒的威风。 2. The days of a judge telling a miscreant to join the army or go to jail are over. 由法官判一名恶棍不当兵就坐牢的日子过去了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('labyrinth', '[\'læbərɪnθ]', 'n.迷宫；难解的事件', '1. The old building was a labyrinth of dark corridors. 那古老建筑是一座长廊纵横光线昏暗的迷宫。 2. The Labyrinth sport no longer exists. 迷宫运动不再存在。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swarm', '[swɔːrm]', 'n.群；蜂群 v.云集；充满', '1. I saw a swarm of bees attacking the poor monkey. 我看到一群蜜蜂正在攻击可怜的猴子。 2. He has received a swarm of letters. 他已经收到了一大批信件。 3. The locust swarm has destroyed all the crops and vegetables. 蝗虫群毁坏了所有的庄稼和蔬菜。 4. Like bees in a swarm, these stars move on ever changing orbits. 好比蜂群内的蜜蜂那般，球状星团内的恒星运行在不断变化的轨道之上。 5. Many students swarm into the canteen after class. 放学后,很多学生拥进食堂。', '名词: swarmer 过去式: swarmed 过去分词: swarmed 现在分词: swarming 第三人称单数: swarms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assail', '[ə\'seɪl]', 'v.使苦恼，纠缠；猛烈攻击；言语抨击', '1. The thought came to assail me. 这个想法使我困扰。 2. Then doubts and fears did assail the very strongest . 疑惑和恐惧的确困扰过意志最坚强的人。 3. The enemy may assail our defense positions tomorrow. 敌人可能明天就攻击我们的防守据点。 4. This book is not meant to assail Christianity. 这本书的本意不是抨击基督教的。', '形容词: assailable 名词: assailableness 过去式: assailed 过去分词: assailed 现在分词: assailing 第三人称单数: assails');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('truism', '[\'truːɪzəm]', 'n.自明之理；老生常谈', '1. This observation is nearly a truism. 这个观察接近于真理。 2. It is a truism that we never really know the value of something until we lose it. 直到失去才会懂得珍惜，这是条永恒的真理。 3. He seems to have no unique opinion, and his speech full of truism. 他似乎没有什么独到的见解，他的讲话充满了陈词滥调。 4. It\'s a truism but worth repeating: Most middle-class household budgets can be cut. 这是一个老生常谈但值得重复的问题：大多数中产阶级家庭预算都能削减。', '形容词: truistic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('venial', '[\'viːniəl]', 'adj.可原谅的；(错误等)轻微的', '1. The venial sins are relatively minor and more easily forgiven. 可宽恕的罪都是比较微小且易被原谅的。 2. Her poverty had been a venial fault for two gallant gentlemen. 她的贫穷对那两位殷勤的绅士而言，只是一个微不足道的缺点。', '副词: venially 名词: veniality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meretricious', '[ˌmerə\'trɪʃəs]', 'adj.华而不实的；俗艳的；似是而非的', '1. the books on her father s shelves , the paintings on the walls , the music on the piano - all was just so much meretricious display. 她父亲架上的书墙上的画和钢琴上的乐曲至多也不过是些平庸的装饰。', '副词: meretriciously 名词: meretriciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hankering', '[\'hæŋkərɪŋ]', 'n.渴望', '1. Thus we experience the most severe hankering for You. 这样，我们感受到最剧烈地渴望祢。 2. Because there was a new book this summer that renewed our hankering for Hogwarts. 因为今夏的新书让我们对霍格沃茨的渴望再次复活。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('constraint', '[kən\'streɪnt]', 'n.约束；强制；约束条件；对感情的压抑；虚情假意 [计算机] 限制.', '1. There have been financial and political constraints on development. 发展过程中会遇到财政和政治的约束。 2. The country decides to reduce constraints on imports. 这个国家决定减少对进口物品的限制。 3. There are no constraints on your choice of subject for the essay. 文章内容不拘。 4. I was aware of a certain constraint on their part when they were in my presence. 我觉察到我在时他们有些拘束。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('signatory', '[\'sɪɡnətɔːri]', 'n.签署者；签约国', '1. An electronic signatory shall properly keep the data made by electronic signature. 电子签名人应当妥善保管电子签名制作数据。 2. China is a signatory to the 1958 New York Convention. 中国是1958年纽约公约的签署国。 3. Brazil becomes a signatory to the Buenos Aires copyright treaty. 巴西成为布宜诺斯艾利斯版权公约的签约国。', '名词复数: signatories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dillydally', '[\'dɪlɪˌdælɪ]', 'vi.磨蹭', '1. The eye looked at others to finish the job livelily, and I still am over there dillydally. 眼看着别人欢快地完成了任务，而我还在那里磨蹭。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('implement', '[\'ɪmplɪmənt]', 'n.工具；器具；当工具的物品 vt.实施；执行；向 ... 提供工具(或手段)', '1. What implements are needed for gardening? 园艺需要些什么工具？ 2. That implement is useful for many purposes in the kitchen. 那种工具在厨房里有许多用途。 3. The system can preferably implement automatic text categorization for Chinese pages, and has a higher quality. 该系统可以很好地实现一个中文网页的自动分类，且系统中的分类器具有较高的分类质量。 4. Her designs will be put on ice until money is available to implement them. 她的设计将暂时搁起来，等有了钱再去实施。', '名词: implementation 过去式: implemented 过去分词: implemented 现在分词: implementing 第三人称单数: implements');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acerbic', '[ə\'sɜːrbɪk]', 'adj.酸的；尖酸的', '1. The letter was written in her usual acerbic style. 这封信是用她惯常的尖刻语调写的。 2. One acerbic blogger calls her \"Obama\'s bitter half\". 有一位尖刻的博客将她称为“让奥巴马痛苦的另一半”。 3. Mr. Foster goes through this with acerbic thoroughness. 福氏在记述这部分内容时，叙述详尽，用语尖刻。', '副词: acerbically 异体字: acerb');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('knack', '[næk]', 'n.技巧；诀窍', '1. There is a knack in tying ropes together. 把绳子绑在一起有点技巧。 2. He has a knack of teaching mathematics. 他教数学有点技巧。 3. There\'s a knack in/to locking this door which takes a while to master. 锁这门要有窍门，得用些时间才能学会。 4. She has a knack of making friends. 她有一套交朋友的诀窍。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fringe', '[frɪndʒ]', 'n.流苏；边缘；次要；额外补贴 vt.用流苏修饰；镶边', '1. The girl wore her hair in a fringe. 那个女孩子额前梳着刘海。 2. The edge of the carpet was frayed into a fringe. 地毯的边缘被散编成一绺绺流苏。 3. They put up tent on the fringe of the woods. 他们在树林边缘搭起帐篷。 4. A fringe of trees stood round the pool. 池塘四周耸立着一圈树木。 5. Coconut palms fringe the shoreline. 岸边点缀着椰子树。', '形容词: fringy 过去式: fringed 过去分词: fringed 现在分词: fringing 第三人称单数: fringes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('definite', '[\'defɪnət]', 'adj.明确的；一定的；有把握的', '1. His vague ideas crystallized into a definite plan. 他那些模糊的想法变成了一个明确的计划。 2. The workers demand a definite answer. 工人们要求一个明确的答复。 3. You have our definite support. 我们绝对支持您。 4. It\'s definite that he will win. 他肯定会赢。', '副词: definitely 名词: definiteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('neologism', '[ni\'ɑːlədʒɪzəm]', 'n.新字；新语；新语症', '1. I don\'t think these neologisms worth passing on to beginners. 我认为这些新词不值得教给初学者。 2. She caught up a popular neologism from the newspapers. 她急忙采用了报刊上流行的一种新词语。', '形容词: neologistic 名词: neologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coronation', '[ˌkɔːrə\'neɪʃn]', 'n.加冕礼', '1. That\'s a beautiful coronation coach. 那是一架漂亮的加冕马车。 2. She is portrayed wearing her coronation robes. 给她画的是她穿着加冕礼服的像。 3. The Pope was present at the coronation of Queen Elizabeth II. 教皇参加了伊丽莎白二世的加冕礼。 4. Fifty heads of state attended the Queen\'s coronation to do her honour. 五十位国家元首参加了女王的加冕典礼，向女王表示敬意。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flamboyant', '[flæm\'bɔɪənt]', 'adj.艳丽的；炫耀的；火焰似的 n.凤凰木', '1. Versace is famous for his flamboyant designs. 凡赛斯因为它们艳丽的设计而闻名。 2. Using colorful and bright hue, the artist expresses the affecting beauty of the flowers and the flamboyant bursting. 作者用艳丽，明快的色彩表现了花动人的美丽和艳丽的绽放。 3. Pictorialism lent character to the flamboyant baron\'s photographs while their light came from Whistler\'s painting. 写实主义赋予了爱炫耀的男爵的相片以特色，而他们的灵感来自于惠斯勒的绘画。', '副词: flamboyantly 名词: flamboyance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gild', '[ɡɪld]', 'v.镀金；虚饰 n.协会；行会（=guild)', '1. The setting sun gilds the sky. 落日把天空染成金色。 2. Her beauty gilds her vice. 她的美貌掩盖了她的邪恶。 3. For such a beautiful girl, to use make-up would be to gild the lily. 对一个这样漂亮的女孩来说，化妆有些画蛇添足。', '名词: gilder 过去式: gilded/gilt 过去分词: gilded/gilt 现在分词: gilding 第三人称单数: gilds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yen', '[jen]', 'n.日元 n.上瘾 vi.对 ... 上瘾', '1. I gave the beggar as much as 1,000 yen. 我给了这乞丐整整一千日元。 2. Please exchange twenty thousand yen into dollars. 请将两万日元换成美金。 3. She\'s developed a yen for detective stories. 她看侦探小说看上瘾了。', '名词复数: yen 过去式: yenned 过去分词: yenned 现在分词: yenning 第三人称单数: yens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shrewd', '[ʃruːd]', 'adj.精明的；敏锐的；狡猾的', '1. Her brother is a shrewd businessman. 她兄弟是个精明的生意人。 2. It was a shrewd assessment and probably pretty close to the truth. 这个评估很有道理，可能相当正确。 3. He\'s an artist, a scientist and a shrewd businessman (all) rolled into one. 他既是艺术家，又是科学家，同时还是个精明的生意人。 4. His skill in negotiating earned him a reputation as a shrewd tactician. 他的谈判技巧使他赢得了精明战略家的名声。', '副词: shrewdly 比较级: shrewder 最高级: shrewdest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('erupt', '[ɪ\'rʌpt]', 'v.爆发；喷发；发疹', '1. Violence has erupted on the streets. 大街上突然发生了暴乱。 2. The demonstration erupted into violence. 示威游行中突然出现了武斗。 3. An active volcano may erupt at any time. 活火山随时可能喷发。 4. It\'s many years since Mount Vesuvius last erupted. 维苏威火山上一次喷发至今已有很多年了。', '形容词: eruptive 副词: eruptively 过去式: erupted 过去分词: erupted 现在分词: erupting 第三人称单数: erupts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('curator', '[kjʊ\'reɪtər]', 'n.(博物馆、展览馆等的)馆长；管理者', '1. Curator conducted the visitors round the museum. 馆长领着游客们在博物馆中参观。 2. The curator has mentored a lot of college students. 这位馆长教导了很多大学生。 3. As the curator of the island, this is the largest compromise I can make. 作为岛的管理者,这是我能够做到的最大让步了。', '形容词: curatorial 名词: curatorship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hide', '[haɪd]', 'v.藏；隐瞒；遮避 vt.鞭打 n.兽皮', '1. I hid the broken plate behind the table. 我把打碎的盘子藏在餐桌后面了。 2. I hide the message in a cleave in the rock. 我把情报藏在石块的裂缝里。 3. She tried to hide her feelings. 她设法不表露自己的感情。 4. The future is hidden from us. 未来是我们难以预卜的。 5. The boots are made of buffalo hide. 这双靴子是由水牛皮制成的。', '过去式: hid 过去分词: hidden/hid 现在分词: hiding 第三人称单数: hides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subject', '[\'sʌbdʒɪkt]', 'n.话题；科目；主题；题材；主观；[语]主语 n.实验对象；(君主国)国民 adj.易患的；服从的 vt.使服从；使隶属；使遭遇', '1. She dare not mention the subject again. 她不敢重提那个话题。 2. Mathematics is her favorite subject. 数学是她喜欢的科目。 3. He is said to be writing a paper on this subject. 据说他正在写一篇关于这个主题的论文。 4. Hawthorne concedes that normal life can be a subject for art. 霍桑承认日常生活可以作为艺术的题材。 5. We need some male subjects for a psychology experiment. 我们需要几个男子作心理学实验对象。 6. Mary is very subject to colds. 玛丽很容易患感冒。 7. Ancient Rome subjected most of Europe 古罗马帝国征服了欧洲大部分。', '名词: subjection 过去式: subjected 过去分词: subjected 现在分词: subjecting 第三人称单数: subjects');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grimace', '[ɡrɪ\'meɪs]', 'n.面部的歪扭；鬼脸；痛苦的表情 vi.扮鬼脸；作苦相', '1. Thomas made a grimace after he had tasted the wine. 汤玛斯尝了那葡萄酒後做了个鬼脸。 2. I fought back the grimace that would give her lie away. 我对抗似的朝她做了个鬼脸，揭穿她的谎言。 3. An odd grimace crosses her mouth and vanishes. 她的嘴角掠过一丝奇怪的表情，转眼就消失了。 4. He acknowledged his mistake with a wry grimace. 他做了个怪怪的表情，算是认了错。 5. The latter made a grimace at the two women and gleefully hurried out behind Tu Wei-yueh. 李麻子朝阿珍她们扮鬼脸，笑了一笑，也就赶快跟了出去。', '名词: grimacer 过去式: grimaced 过去分词: grimaced 现在分词: grimacing 第三人称单数: grimaces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stomach', '[\'stʌmək]', 'n.胃；胃口；腹部 vt.忍受；吃得下', '1. He had had too much to eat and his stomach started to kick up. 他吃得太多了,胃不舒服。 2. Anxiety may disorder the stomach. 忧虑可能会引起胃部不适。 3. The stomach revolts at such food. 这样的食物倒胃囗。 4. The film about eye operations turned my stomach. 这部眼科手术的影片看得我恶心极了。 5. I can\'t stomach your constant nagging. 我再也忍受不了你不停的唠叨了。', '过去式: stomached 过去分词: stomached 现在分词: stomaching 第三人称单数: stomachs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gourmet', '[\'ɡʊrmeɪ]', 'n.美食家', '1. A gourmet like him always eats in expensive restaurants. 像他这样的美食家总是到豪华的餐馆用餐。 2. Raffaele is also a gourmet and loves good food. 拉斐尔也是一个美食家，喜欢各种好吃的食物。 3. A gourmet is a person who is experienced and knowledgeable in fine food and drink. 美食家实在美食家娘方面见多识广的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('measured', '[\'meʒərd]', 'adj.量过的；慎重的；缓慢有节奏的；有韵律的 动词measure的过去式和过去分词.', '1. Econometrics deals with measurable and measured quantities in economics. 计量经济学的对象是经济学中可测量和已测出的量。 2. Her actions were a measured response to his provocations. 她的行动是对他的挑衅慎重而有节制的反应。 3. For a more measured analysis, Ms Roy should perhaps turn to the finance ministry\'s recently published Economic Survey. 罗伊女士可能应该关注一下财政部最近发布的经济调查之后再做一个更加慎重的分析。 4. His reply was given in measured phrases. 他的回答是经过字斟句酌的。', '副词: measuredly 名词: measuredness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scrutinize', '[\'skruːtənaɪz]', 'v.仔细检查；细看', '1. We must scrutinize and evaluate. 我们必须细细察看并做出评价。 2. She leaned forward to scrutinize their faces. 她探身向前，端详他们的面容。 3. The boss came to scrutinize how things were going on for himself. 老板亲自详察工作进展情况。 4. All parts of the aircraft are closely scrutinized for signs of wear or damage. 飞机的所有部件都被仔细查看以防磨损和损坏。', '副词: scrutinizingly 名词: scrutinizer 过去式: scrutinized 过去分词: scrutinized 现在分词: scrutinizing 第三人称单数: scrutinizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('noisome', '[\'nɔɪsəm]', 'adj.〈正式或文〉令人不快的；令人作呕的；有害的', '1. I destroy all noisome and rank weeds, I keep down all pestilent vapours. 我摧毁了一切丛生的毒草，控制一切有害的烟雾。', '副词: noisomely 名词: noisomeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dyslexia', '[dɪs\'leksiə]', 'n.阅读障碍', '1. Dyslexia can also affect a person emotionally. 阅读困难症还会影响一个人的心情。 2. Dyslexia most commonly affects reading, spelling and writing. 阅读障碍症最普遍影响阅读、拼写和写作。 3. What causes dyslexia is not clear. 阅读苦难的病因还不清楚。', '名词: dyslectic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trenchant', '[\'trentʃənt]', 'adj.清晰的；锐利的；尖刻的；(论据等)有力的', '1. The directions are trenchant and easy to follow. 那些说明清晰易懂。 2. Trenchant essays can criticize contemporary abuses. 杂文言辞犀利，可以针砭世弊。 3. Some of their comments were quite trenchant. 他们的有些批评十分尖锐。 4. The trenchant and inspiring comments of the scholars impressed the audience greatly. 学者们的理性思考和精彩阐释，引起了到会听众的兴趣与好评。', '副词: trenchantly 名词: trenchancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lunar', '[\'luːnər]', 'adj.月亮的；阴历的；银的', '1. The astronauts piloted their craft down to the lunar surface. 宇航员驾驶宇宙飞船在月球表面降落。 2. Lunar eclipse occur when the earth\'s shadow fall on the moon. 地球的影子落在月球上时,就发生月蚀。 3. It was reported that there would be a lunar eclipse tomorrow evening. 据报道说，明天晚上有月食。 4. All traditional Chinese festivals are lunar calendar festivals. 中国的传统节日都是按照太阴历计算的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prerogative', '[prɪ\'rɑːɡətɪv]', 'n.特权；显著的优点', '1. A ruler may use his prerogative of mercy towards a criminal. 统治者可行使赦免罪犯的特权。 2. No single molecule has the sole prerogative of growth regulation. 没有一种单个的分子具有调节生长的唯一特权。', '形容词: prerogatived');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('addle', '[\'ædl]', 'v.使腐坏；使昏乱 adj.腐烂的；昏乱的', '1. My brain feels addled. 我感到昏头昏脑的。', '过去式: addled 过去分词: addled 现在分词: addling 第三人称单数: addles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spark', '[spɑːrk]', 'vi.闪烁；冒火花；热情回应 vt.激发；引起；向...求爱 n.火星；朝气；情人；俗丽的年轻人', '1. A tiny star can spark in the darkness. 小星星也会在黑暗中发光。 2. Druce lit the cigar, which began to spark and crackle. 德鲁斯点着一支雪茄，这支雪茄发出火花，噼噼啪啪地响起来。 3. He sparked to her plan. 他欣然同意了她的计划。 4. You can spark the spirit of enterprise. 你们可以激发事业上的进取心。 5. A cigarette spark started the fire. 香烟的火星引起这场火灾。', '名词: sparker 过去式: sparked 过去分词: sparked 现在分词: sparking 第三人称单数: sparks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ludicrous', '[\'luːdɪkrəs]', 'adj.荒谬的；可笑的；滑稽的', '1. It is ludicrous to argue that this would be an insupportable burden. 认为这种负担不可承受的说法是荒谬的。 2. He made many ludicrous mistakes in his speech. 他的演讲中有许多可笑的错误。 3. In normal times, this would be a ludicrous question. 在正常时期，这会是个可笑的问题。 4. The ludicrous performance of the clown fascinated the children. 小丑那滑稽的表演吸引着孩子。', '副词: ludicrously 名词: ludicrousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('campaign', '[kæm\'peɪn]', 'n.运动；战役；活动；竞选运动 v.参加竞选；从事运动', '1. The campaign was a blockbuster. 这次竞选运动声势浩大。 2. They are planning a new campaign against corruption. 他们正在策划一个新的反贪污运动。 3. The campaign to seize the city was a failure. 攻占这个城市的战役失败了。 4. We were outmanoeuvred and outfought throughout the winter campaign. 我们在整个冬季战役中始终不如对手。 5. He announced that he would campaign for the senate. 他宣布他将参加议员竞选。', '名词: campaigner 过去式: campaigned 过去分词: campaigned 现在分词: campaigning 第三人称单数: campaigns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tenant', '[\'tenənt]', 'n.房客；佃户；承租人；<律>占用者 vt.租赁；租借', '1. The tenant has not yet paid his rent. 房客还没有交付租金。 2. The desk was left by the previous tenant. 这张桌子是前面房客留下的。 3. He\'s a tenant farmer. 他是佃农. 4. There is a clause in the contract forbidding tenant to sublet. 合同中列有条款，禁止承租人转租。 5. I will tenant my building out during the summer vocation. 我会在暑假期间把房子租出去。', '过去式: tenanted 过去分词: tenanted 现在分词: tenanting 第三人称单数: tenants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chancellor', '[\'tʃænsələr]', 'n.大臣；总理；名誉校长；大法官', '1. He was England\'s worst Chancellor of the Exchequer. 他是英国最糟糕的财政大臣。 2. The knives are out for the chancellor. 要对这位大臣兴师问罪了。 3. The Chancellor will present his budget to Parliament tomorrow. 总理明天将在会议上提出他的预算案。 4. The move welcomed by German Chancellor Angela Merkel. 此举受到德国总理默克尔欢迎。', '名词: chancellorship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pernicious', '[pər\'nɪʃəs]', 'adj.有害的；恶性的', '1. This event had a pernicious influence on society. 这件事情对社会造成了有害的影响。 2. Pollution of the water supply reached a level pernicious to the health of the population. 水源污染已经达到危及居民健康的程度。 3. Lack of intrinsic factor can result in pernicious anemia. 缺乏内源因素可导致恶性贫血。', '副词: perniciously 名词: perniciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nomad', '[\'noʊmæd]', 'n.游牧部落一员；流浪者', '1. The nomads have no habitation. 游牧者没有定居处。 2. Most of the nomads live in grassland and have no fixed home. 游牧部落的大多人都生活在草原上并且居无定所。 3. He was indeed a nomad of no nationality. 他的确是个无国籍的游民。', '形容词: nomadic 副词: nomadically 名词: nomadism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dicker', '[\'dɪkər]', 'n.十个；十张；做小生意；讨价还价 v.还价', '1. I do not work for anybody now and I do bit of dicker. 我现在不为任何人工作，我自己做点小生意。 2. My grandmother dickered with the pedlar over the price of apples. 我祖母为苹果的价格与小贩讨价还价。 3. We hate having to dicker with the boss when trying to arrange a trade. 我们讨厌在跟老板交易时讨价还价。', '过去式: dickered 过去分词: dickered 现在分词: dickering 第三人称单数: dickers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whimsical', '[\'wɪmzɪkl]', 'adj.异想天开的；古怪的；反复无常的', '1. He has a whimsical sense of humor. 他有着离奇的幽默感。 2. It\'s only a whimsical story for children. 这不过是一个希奇古怪的儿童故事。', '副词: whimsically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('polarize', '[\'poʊləraɪz]', 'vt. 使极化； 使 ... 偏振化； 使 ... 两极分化 vi. 形成极化', '1. Public opinion has polarized on this issue. 在这个问题上公众的意见已两极分化。', '形容词: polarizable 名词: polarizer 过去式: polarized 过去分词: polarized 现在分词: polarizing 第三人称单数: polarizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('locomotive', '[ˌloʊkə\'moʊtɪv]', 'n.火车头；机车 adj.运动的；火车头的；旅行的', '1. He is a locomotive engineer. 他是一名火车司机。 2. They detached the locomotive from the train. 他们使火车头与列车脱离了。 3. The locomotive was dashed to pieces. 机车撞得粉碎。 4. The locomotive pulled a long line of freight cars. 那台机车拖了一长列货车。 5. Hands and feet are locomotive organs. 手和脚是运动器官。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grudge', '[ɡrʌdʒ]', 'n.怨恨；恶意 vt.不愿；吝惜；嫉妒', '1. He harbors a secret grudge against his father. 他对父亲暗怀不满。 2. I was willing to settle my grudge with Harrison. 我原意解决我和哈里森的怨恨。 3. I always feel he has a grudge against me, although I don\'t know why. 我总觉得他讨厌我，但我不知道为什么。 4. He has a grudge against me. 他对我有恶意. 5. I grudge paying so much for such inferior goods. 我不愿花这么多钱买次品。', '副词: grudgingly 名词: grudger 过去式: grudged 过去分词: grudged 现在分词: grudging 第三人称单数: grudges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dipsomania', '[ˌdɪpsə\'meɪnɪə]', 'n.嗜酒狂', '1. Let us discuss, first, five of the most common manias: kleptomania, pyromania, dipsomania, megalomania, and monomania . 首先让我们讨论五种最常见的狂热症：盗窃狂症，纵火狂症，耽酒狂症，妄想自大狂症，偏执狂症。 2. Let us discuss, first, five of the most common manias: kleptomania, pyromania, dipsomania, megalomania, and monomania 首先让我们讨论五种最常见的狂热症:盗窃狂症，纵火狂症，耽酒狂症，妄想自大狂症，偏执狂症。', '形容词: dipsomaniac');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('collapse', '[kə\'læps]', 'v.（使）倒塌；（使）崩溃；（使）瓦解；折叠 n.倒塌；崩溃；暴跌', '1. The roof collapsed under the weight of snow. 房顶在雪的重压下突然坍塌下来。 2. If you work too hard,your health may collapse. 如果你工作太累的话，你可能病倒。 3. The enterprise collapsed through lack of support. 该企业因无力支持而倒闭。 4. He collapsed the wheelchair and put it on the boat. 他将轮椅折叠起来放在船上。 5. A flood caused the collapse of the bridge. 洪水使桥倒塌了。', '形容词: collapsible 名词: collapsibility 过去式: collapsed 过去分词: collapsed 现在分词: collapsing 第三人称单数: collapses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('welsh', '[welʃ]', 'v.<俚>不付赌金而溜掉；逃避责任 Welsh: n.威尔士人 adj.威尔士人的；威尔士语的', '1. He welshed on his debts. 他赖帐不还。', '异体字: welch 名词: welsher 过去式: welshed/welched 过去分词: welshed/welched 现在分词: welshing/welching 第三人称单数: welshes/welches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ecumenical', '[ˌiːkjuː\'menɪkl]', 'adj.促进基督教不同教派大联合的；世界范围的；普遍的', '1. The First Ecumenical Council in 325 A. 但是第一次神圣普世大公会议又没有指出主日不可下跪是否可以有例外。 2. First ecumenical movement since the Reformation. 宗教改革之后第一次合一运动。 3. A doctrinal or disciplinary actof an ecumenical council. 教令全基督教会议的教义或纪律法令。 4. A doctrinal or disciplinary act of an ecumenical council. 教令全基督教会议的教义或纪律法令', '副词: ecumenically 异体字: ecumenic 名词: ecumenicalism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fondle', '[\'fɑːndl]', 'v.爱；爱抚；溺爱；抚弄', '1. Today I shall fondle my children while they are young. 今天我要趁孩子还小的时候，多加爱护. 2. Mothers and fathers must have a chance to fondle their new babies. 父母一定有机会来爱抚他们的新生儿。 3. The birds sing songs and the cool breeze fondle the green grass . 鸟儿唱歌和凉风抚弄着绿草。 4. The beautiful thing on the world often makes one fondle admiringly. 世上美的东西往往令人爱不释手。', '名词: fondler 过去式: fondled 过去分词: fondled 现在分词: fondling 第三人称单数: fondles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hie', '[haɪ]', 'v.快走；赶紧；催促', '1. Hie yourself to home. 快回家吧。 2. I will hie to the market. 我要赶快去市场。 3. You go to the exhibition centre, I must hie myself to tell the new matters. 你去展览中心吧，我得赶紧汇报一下这个新情况。', '过去式: hied 过去分词: hied 现在分词: hieing/hying 第三人称单数: hies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remiss', '[rɪ\'mɪs]', 'adj.疏忽的；怠慢的；不留心的', '1. It is remiss of her to forget to pay the bill. 她忘了付帐，真粗心大意。 2. I have been very remiss in writing to you. 我不曾写信给你，实在疏忽之至。 3. I\'d be remiss if I didn\'t mention it. 如果我不提到它那就是不负责任。” 4. You have been very remiss in fulfilling your obligations. 你一向太不负责了。', '副词: remissly 名词: remissness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('underplay', '[ˌʌndər\'pleɪ]', 'v.轻描淡写；表演不充分 n.不充分的表演；暗中的活动', '1. To understate(a role)intentionally;underplay. 表演有克制有意识轻描淡写（一角色）；含蓄克制地扮演 2. To understate(a role) intentionally; underplay. 表演有克制有意识轻描淡写（一角色）；含蓄克制地扮演 3. Opinion polls underplay Mr Le Pen\'s support; almost half of respondents say they are undecided. 民意测验不能充分说明勒庞的支持度；几乎一半的受调查者声称他们尚未决定。 4. Such optimism may underplay the potential channels through which the subprime mess can infect other countries. 这些乐观主义者忽视了次级危机传染到其它国家通道的重要性。', '过去式: underplayed 过去分词: underplayed 现在分词: underplaying 第三人称单数: underplays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('encyclopedia', '[ɪnˌsaɪklə\'piːdiə]', 'n.百科全书', '1. We bought a multimedia encyclopedia. 我们买了一套多媒体百科全书。 2. This encyclopedia is truly a compendium of knowledge. 这部百科全书真正是知识宝库。 3. A dictionary explains words and an encyclopedia explains facts. 词典解释词义，百科全书解释事物。 4. The new encyclopedia runs to several thousand pages. 这部新的百料全书总共有数千页。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pivot', '[\'pɪvət]', 'n.枢；中心；旋转 adj.在枢轴上转动的；关键的 vt.装枢轴于；以 ... 为中心 vi.在枢轴上转动', '1. A grasping device consisting of two arms joined at one end by a pivot or hingelike scissors. 钳，火钳一种用来抓取的工具，由通过枢轴或枢状剪结合于一端的两臂组成 2. Their daughter was the pivot of their lives. 女儿是他们生活的中心。 3. West Africa was the pivot of the cocoa trade. 西非是可可豆贸易的中心。 4. Because her job had been the pivot of her life, retirement was very difficult. 因为她的工作一向是她生命的支柱，所以退休后日子很不好过。 5. The technicians mounted the arms onto the pivot shafts. 技工将雨刷臂安装在枢轴上。 6. The whole discussion pivots on this one point. 整个讨论内容均以此为中心。 7. The technicians mounted the arms onto the pivot shafts. 技工将雨刷臂安装在枢轴上。', '形容词: pivotable 过去式: pivoted 过去分词: pivoted 现在分词: pivoting 第三人称单数: pivots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hubbub', '[\'hʌbʌb]', 'n.嘈杂；喧哗', '1. The hubbub of voices drowned out the host\'s voice. 嘈杂的声音淹没了主人的声音。 2. It was difficult to hear what he was saying over the hubbub. 声音太嘈杂，难以听清楚他的讲话。 3. At lunchtime, a pleasant hubbub of voices fills the museum\'s cafeteria. 午餐时间,博物馆的餐厅里洋溢着一片愉快的嘈杂声。 4. There arose a hubbub among them. 他们发出了一阵喧哗。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exacting', '[ɪɡ\'zæktɪŋ]', 'adj.严格的；吃力的 动词exact的现在分词形式.', '1. If the government goes on exacting so much from the taxpayer, it will not last long. 如果该政府继续如此征税的话，它将不会持续多久。 2. I have so trained myself in secretarial work that only exacting problems are interesting to me. 毫不夸张的说，我在文秘方面受过严密的训练，越是难度大的工作越能激起我的工作热情。 3. His work was so exacting that by the end of the day he was worn out. 他的工作十分吃力,到一天过完的时候他已经精疲力竭了。', '副词: exactingly 名词: exactingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('metaphysics', '[ˌmetə\'fɪzɪks]', 'n.形而上学；玄学', '1. There is an alliance between logic and metaphysics. 逻辑与形而上学之间有类似之处。 2. Metaphysics is part and parcel of the idealist world outlook. 形而上学是唯心主义世界观的组成部分。 3. They tried to quit themselves of the shackles of metaphysics. 他们尽力设法摆脱形而上学的枷锁。 4. Metaphysics goes against materialism. 玄学和唯物论是相违背的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shrine', '[ʃraɪn]', 'n. 圣地； 神龛； 庙 v. 将 ... 置于神龛内； 把 ... 奉为神圣', '1. Many pilgrims worship at the shrine. 许多朝圣者参拜圣地。 2. Mark Twain\'s birth place is visited as a shrine. 马克吐温的诞生地被参观者视作圣地。 3. They bowed down before the shrine. 他们在神龛前鞠躬示敬。 4. He put the promise in the shrine beside the tablet of O-Tei. 他将这句誓言放在神龛内阿真的牌位旁。', '过去式: shrined 过去分词: shrined 现在分词: shrining 第三人称单数: shrines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sprawling', '[\'sprɔːlɪŋ]', 'adj.不规则伸展的；摊开手脚的；字迹潦草的；庞大的 动词sprawl的现在分词.', '1. He was sprawling on the sofa. 他手脚张开地躺在沙发上。 2. His fist sent the robber sprawling on the ground. 他一拳把那抢劫犯打得四脚朝天。 3. He was sprawling in an armchair in front of the TV. 他伸开手脚坐在电视机前的单座沙发上。 4. He was sprawling in the sofa in front of the TV. 他伸开手脚坐在电视机前的沙发上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('germ', '[dʒɜːrm]', 'n.细菌；微生物；胚芽', '1. Germs may invade the organism. 细菌会侵入有机体。 2. Germs are invisible to the naked eye. 细菌用肉眼看不见。 3. Disinfectant kills germs. 消毒剂灭杀细菌。 4. This is a ubiquitous germ that lives in nature and can be found in the soil or water. 这是一种在自然界普遍存在的微生物，甚至在土壤和水源中都可以存在。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glimpse', '[ɡlɪmps]', 'n.一瞥；一闪；略微；隐约感觉 v.瞥见', '1. He caught a glimpse of me when I passed by. 当我走过时，他瞥了我一眼。 2. A glimpse of her face will tell you that she is innocent. 你只要一看见她的脸就会明白，她是无辜的。 3. I only caught a glimpse of him sitting in the car, so I can\'t tell exactly what he looked like. 我只瞥见他坐在车里，所以我无法确切说出他长得什么样。 4. He caught a glimpse of her before she banished into the crowd. 他看见她一闪就在人群中消失了。 5. I glimpsed at her among the crowd before she disappeared from sight. 就在她即将消失在人群里之前，我瞥见了她。', '名词: glimpser 过去式: glimpsed 过去分词: glimpsed 现在分词: glimpsing 第三人称单数: glimpses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impinge', '[ɪm\'pɪndʒ]', 'vi.撞击；侵犯；对...有影响 vt.撞击，打击', '1. Sound waves impinge on the eardrum. 声波撞击着耳膜。 2. Furthermore, the treaty should not impinge on the freedom of access to information. 另外,条约不应影响获取信息的自由。 3. He never allowed his work to impinge on his private life. 他从不让他的工作妨碍私生活。 4. Your political opinions will necessarily impinge on your public life. 你的政治观点必然会影响你的社会生活。', '名词: impingement 过去式: impinged 过去分词: impinged 现在分词: impinging 第三人称单数: impinges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('donor', '[\'doʊnər]', 'n.捐赠人；施主；供者', '1. The donor\'s identity is a close secret. 捐赠人的身分是一个严加保守的秘密。 2. The donor prefers to remain anonymous. 捐赠者希望不披露姓名。 3. His body rejected the liver of the donor. 他的身体排斥捐赠者的肝。 4. It was also counting on getting food aid from South Korea, its biggest donor. 朝鲜当局当时还指望从其最大施主韩国获得粮食援助。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('neolithic', '[ˌniːə\'lɪθɪk]', 'adj.新石器时代的', '1. Cattle were first domesticated in Neolithic times. 新石器时代有人开始驯养牛。 2. By 10,000 BC, most of mankind was at the Neolithic level. 到公元前 10000年，大部分人类已经处于新石器时代的水平。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tycoon', '[taɪ\'kuːn]', 'n.企业界的大亨；（日本幕府的）将军', '1. The self-made tycoon was bragging about the secret of his success. 那位靠自我奋斗发了财的大亨正在夸耀他成功的秘诀。 2. Disgraced media tycoon Conrad Black will appeal against his convictions for fraud, his lawyer has said. 令人蒙羞的媒体企业界的大亨康拉德黑色将为诈欺不服他的定罪而上诉，他的律师已经说。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snappy', '[\'snæpi]', 'adj.干脆的；精力充沛的；敏捷的；严寒的；时髦的', '1. The days just prior to marriage are like a snappy introduction to a tedious book. 婚前的日子相对于婚姻来说就像是一本冗长乏味的书的一段短小精悍的序言。 2. She\' s always snappy early in the morning. 她总是一大早就嚷嚷。 3. Pack your bags and make it snappy; we leave in five minutes. 赶快把东西装进你们的包里，5分钟后我们就走。 4. She was wearing a snappy little red number. 她身著一款时髦的红色连衣裙。', '副词: snappily 比较级: snappier 最高级: snappiest 名词: snappiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imprint', '[ɪm\'prɪnt]', 'vt.刻上记号；加特征；盖印；铭记 n.印记；痕迹；特征；印象', '1. Bette Davis will imprint her unique personality on any role she plays. 蓓蒂·戴维斯不论扮演什么角色都体现出她自己独特的性格。 2. He imprints a paper with a seal. 他在文件上盖章。 3. He tried to imprint the number on his memory. 他试图把那个号码牢牢记住 4. Only very little could escape life\'s imprint. 能逃脱生命印记的只是极少数。', '过去式: imprinted 过去分词: imprinted 现在分词: imprinting 第三人称单数: imprints');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sopping', '[\'sɑːpɪŋ]', 'adj.浑身湿透的 动词sop的现在分词形式.', '1. Your clothes are sopping. 你的衣服湿透了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infinitesimal', '[ˌɪnfɪnɪ\'tesɪml]', 'adj.极微的；无限小的 n.极微量', '1. The body\'s annual intake of metallic iron is infinitesimal. 人体对金属铁的年摄入量是微不足道的。 2. The probability of encountering them again was infinitesimal. 重新碰到它们的可能性微乎其微。 3. An entire ecosystem is contained in one infinitesimal speck. 这样小的细菌也包含有一个完整的生态系统.', '副词: infinitesimally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inclusive', '[ɪn\'kluːsɪv]', 'adj.包含 ... 在内的；包罗广泛的；包括端点的 [计算机] 包括的', '1. The monthly rent is $20 inclusive of everything. 月房租总共二十美元,包括一切费用在内。 2. His concept of history is modern and inclusive. 她的历史观现代又富包容性。 3. The party must adopt more inclusive strategies and a broader vision. 这个党必须采取更广泛的策略和更远大的视野。 4. I\'ll be away from the 20th to the 31st of May inclusive. 我从五月二十号到三十一号（包括这两天）,都不会在。', '副词: inclusively 名词: inclusiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plaintiff', '[\'pleɪntɪf]', 'n.原告', '1. The plaintiff accused the defendant of fraud. 原告指控被告欺诈。 2. Plaintiff is an antonym of defendant. 原告是被告的反义字。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impale', '[ɪm\'peɪl]', 'v.刺穿；钉住；使陷入困境', '1. In former times, prisoners\' heads were impaled on pointed stakes. 从前的人把监犯的头钉在尖桩上。', '异体字: empale 名词: impalement 过去式: impaled 过去分词: impaled 现在分词: impaling 第三人称单数: impales');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chromatic', '[krə\'mætɪk]', 'adj.彩色的；着色的；【生】 易染的；染色质的；【音】半音的，半音阶的；变音的；变音体系的', '1. Why does somebody like to wear chromatic briefs? 为什么有人喜欢穿彩色内裤？ 2. These chromatic stone carvings are all made from a whole piece of stone. 这些彩色石雕作品均为一块完整的石材雕刻而成。 3. The removal of the chromatic aberration is then of primary importance. 这时消除色差具有头等重要性。', '副词: chromatically 名词: chromaticism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gravel', '[\'ɡrævl]', 'n.碎石 v.铺碎石；使困惑', '1. The water is infiltrating the gravel bed. 水正渗透进碎石底层。 2. A lonely fisherman stood on a tuft of gravel. 一个孤单的渔夫站在碎石丛中。 3. Depressions are usually caused by heavy trucks passing over the gravel. 路面下沉通常是由路过铺碎石的重型卡车引起的。', '过去式: graveled/gravelled 过去分词: graveled/gravelled 现在分词: graveling/gravelling 第三人称单数: gravels/gravels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harness', '[\'hɑːrnɪs]', 'n.马具；安全带；甲胄；系在身上的绳子 vt.束以马具；披上甲胄；利用；管理；控制', '1. Stirrup is an important part of harness. 马镫是马具的一个重要的部分。 2. You can not judge of the horse by the harness. 凭马具难断马优劣。 3. Safety harness is quite necessary in terms of the accidents. 考虑到意外事故,安全带是必要的。 4. The parachutist was buckled into his harness. 跳伞者扣上了背带。 5. I harness the horse to the cart. 我把马套在车上。', '名词: harnesser 过去式: harnessed 过去分词: harnessed 现在分词: harnessing 第三人称单数: harnesses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pastry', '[\'peɪstri]', 'n.面粉糕饼；馅饼皮', '1. Before cooking,she pressed pastry flat and thin. 制做前她把馅饼皮压得薄又平。 2. Roll out the pastry and cut into small triangles.The exact size is up to you. 擀好馅饼皮后，将其切成小的三角形状，具体的大小取决于个人。', '名词复数: pastries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boom', '[buːm]', 'n.繁荣；兴旺；激增；低沉声 n.帆杠；吊杆；支臂；尾桁；水栅 vi.急速增长；发出低沉声 vt.使兴旺；促进', '1. It\'s a boom year this year. 今年是繁荣昌盛的一年。 2. He made his pile during the property boom. 在房地产生意兴隆期间他发了大财。 3. The oil market is enjoying a boom. 石油市场欣欣向荣。 4. City growth far outran the general population boom. 城市的发展大大超过总的人口激增。 5. The boom swung over the deck. 帆杠在甲板上转动。 6. Business is booming. 商业正日趋繁荣。 7. Foreign investments boomed the city. 国外投资使这个城市迅速繁荣起来。', '过去式: boomed 过去分词: boomed 现在分词: booming 第三人称单数: booms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('garrulity', '[gæ\'ruːlətɪ]', 'n.饶舌；多嘴', '1. The morning is waning fast amidst my garrulity. 我这么一唠叨不要紧，上午的时间快要过去了。 2. She said nothing when met you, changing the former days garrulity. 见了面她一改往日的喋喋不休，望着你不说话。 3. The old Major, with eager garrulity and mischievous relish, told his nephew wonderful particulars regarding the lives of these heroines, and diverted the young man with a thousand scandals. 老少校絮絮叨叨、津津有味地大谈阔论，把这些女界俊杰的有趣经历，她们的无数风流韵事，讲给侄儿听。 4. The morning is waning fast amidst my garrulity 我这么一唠叨不要紧，上午的时间快要过去了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reproof', '[rɪ\'pruːf]', 'n.斥责；责备', '1. Impatient of reproof, he left his parents and went away. 忍受不了责难，他离开父母出走了。 2. The warmth of her smile belied the reproof. 她亲切的笑容表明她的斥责并非真的。 3. The child was abashed by his mother\'s reproof. 孩子因母亲的责备而惶惶不安; 4. His words were a mixture of pity and reproof. 他的话里既有同情也有责备。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ruthlessness', '[\'ruːθləsnəs]', 'n.无情；残忍；冷酷', '1. Others speak of utter devotion to work, combined with a degree of ruthlessness. 有的则认为是由于全身心地投入工作以至于对自己近乎残忍的科度。 2. Oh, yes, he had a streak of ruthlessness that rivaled Peter\'s, but he had the decency to be appalled by his own brutality. 哦，是的，他有着可与彼得抗争的冷酷无情的气息，但是他正派得会为自己的残忍而骇怕。 3. Ruthlessness is the kindness of the wise. 冷酷是智者的仁慈。 4. She doesn\'t have the ruthlessness required to succeed in business. 要在生意场上干出一番名堂，她缺乏必要的冷酷心肠。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flutter', '[\'flʌtər]', 'n.摆动；振翼；烦扰 vi.摆动；振翼；烦扰 vt.使心烦；使焦虑', '1. There was a flutter of wings among the trees. 树林里响起一阵飞鸟的拍翅声。 2. He immediately fell into a great flutter. 他立刻变得心慌意乱。 3. The news caused a flutter among the teaching staff. 这个消息在全体教师中引起了不安。 4. Banners fluttered in the breeze. 旗帜在微风中飘扬。', '形容词: fluttery 名词: flutterer 过去式: fluttered 过去分词: fluttered 现在分词: fluttering 第三人称单数: flutters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barrier', '[\'bæriər]', 'n.栅栏；障碍物；屏障', '1. The ice skater rammed into the barrier. 溜冰者撞到护栏上了。 2. Heavy duties on imports and exports are a barrier to international trade. 进出口的高关税是国际贸易的障碍。 3. The Sahara Desert is a natural barrier between north and central Africa. 撒哈拉沙漠是北非与中非之间的天然屏障。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tenable', '[\'tenəbl]', 'adj.站得住脚的；无懈可击的', '1. None of these arguments are tenable. 这些论点没有一个是站得住脚的。 2. The lectureship is tenable for a period of three years. 讲师这一职位任期三年。 3. In a word, our theory is tenable. 综上所述，我们的理论成立。', '副词: tenably 名词: tenability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('catholic', '[\'kæθlɪk]', 'adj.天主教的；(catholic)普遍的；广泛的 n.天主教徒', '1. Anselm\'s theology is not Catholic faith. 安塞姆的神学并不是天主教的信念。 2. The atom bomb is of catholic concern. 原子弹受到普遍的关注。 3. As a young person he had more catholic tastes than he does now. 他在年轻时兴趣比现在广泛得多。 4. Leonardo da Vinci was a catholic genius who excelled in almost everything he did. 达文西是一个广泛的天才,他做的很多事也得到成功。 5. He was a Catholic but didn\'t practise his religion. 他那时是天主教徒，但并不实践信仰。', '副词: catholically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('implicit', '[ɪm\'plɪsɪt]', 'adj.含蓄的；绝对的；无疑问的；固有的；无保留的；暗示的', '1. Her attitude was implicit in the answer she gave us. 她在给我们的答复中态度是含蓄的。 2. The system of rules implicit in a language, viewed as a mechanism for generating all sentences possible in that language. 语法规则隐含在一种语言中的规则体系，被看作在该语言中生成所有可能的语句的机制 3. The crew had implicit faith in the captain\'s judgment. 全体船员都绝对相信船长的判断。 4. The oak is implicit in the acorn. 橡实是橡树固有的。', '副词: implicitly 名词: implicitness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('panache', '[pə\'næʃ]', 'n.羽饰；炫耀；假威风', '1. They displayed none of the panache, drive, imagination or willingness to take risks which this operation demanded. 他们没有什么炫耀，驱使，想象或者自发地去冒险。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('balm', '[bɑːm]', 'n.香油；药膏', '1. Balm of a rose can rival a variety of other balm. 一滴玫瑰香油可以媲美多种其它香油。 2. Attar is the rarest balm, price is even more expensive than gold. 玫瑰油是最名贵的香油，价钱比黄金还要贵。 3. He smeared some balm on his hand to soothe the pain. 他在手上涂了些药膏来止痛。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incumbent', '[ɪn\'kʌmbənt]', 'adj.负有义务的；凭依的 n.在职者；领圣职的俸禄的牧师', '1. It is incumbent on me to reclaim him. 劝他改过是我义不容辞的义务。 2. I think it\'s incumbent upon us to support him. 我变为支持他是我们义不容辞的责任。 3. It is incumbent upon justice to give some warnings of their doubt about a case. 法官有责任提醒人们有关他们对案件的疑问。 4. He, as the incumbent, is vulnerable on this. 作为在职者,他在这个问题上易受攻击。', '副词: incumbently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pillage', '[\'pɪlɪdʒ]', 'n.掠夺；抢劫；掠夺物 v.掠夺；抢劫', '1. The pillage was not contained to just the enlisted men. 参与财宝掠夺的，不仅仅是那些应征入伍的大兵们。 2. They brought back horrific accounts of murder and pillage. 他们带回了残杀掳掠的可怕消息。 3. The town was pillaged by the invading army. 入侵的军队将该城镇掠夺一空。 4. Her handbag was pillaged on her way home. 在回家的路上，她的手提包被抢劫了。', '名词: pillager 过去式: pillaged 过去分词: pillaged 现在分词: pillaging 第三人称单数: pillages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flax', '[flæks]', 'n.亚麻；麻布；亚麻织品', '1. Wash them in water, and you will have flax. 放到水里洗一洗，就成了亚麻。 2. There is more wool and flax in the fields. 田野里有着更多的羊毛和更多的亚麻。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rig', '[rɪɡ]', 'n.装备；帆具；服装；钻井架；钻塔 v.装配；装扮；临时赶造；操纵', '1. Judging by its rig, I\'d say it was a fishing boat. 从船具装备来看，我认为这是一艘渔船。 2. Our camping rig includes cooking pots and sleeping bags. 我们的野营装备包括锅子和睡袋。 3. Most modern yachts have a fore and aft rig, but the old galleons were squared-rigged. 大多数现代化游艇配备的都是前后帆，而老式大帆船装的却是横帆。 4. On Halloween the children rig themselves up in funny clothes. 万圣节前夕孩子们穿上各种滑稽的服装。 5. I will have our people rig them with explosives. 我将会用炸药让我们的民族装配他们。', '过去式: rigged 过去分词: rigged 现在分词: rigging 第三人称单数: rigs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indecisive', '[ˌɪndɪ\'saɪsɪv]', 'adj.犹豫不决的；非决定性的', '1. He\'s too indecisive to make a good leader. 他优柔寡断，当不了好领导。 2. This is also one of Central authorities indecisive reasons. 这也是中央政府犹豫不决的原因之一。 3. We asked him a lot about this matter, but he only gave us an indecisive answer. 关于此事我们向他提出了许多问题,但他只给了我们一个无决定性的答案。', '副词: indecisively 名词: indecisiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('urgent', '[\'ɜːrdʒənt]', 'adj.紧急的；急迫的；坚持要求的', '1. They\'ve made an urgent request for international aid. 他们紧急请求国际援助。 2. I was prevented from going by urgent business. 我因急事不能去。 3. Jean spoke, her voice low and urgent. 吉恩说话的时候声音压得很低,感觉很急迫。 4. Seeing that no one takes actions, he spoke to me in an urgent whisper. 没看到一个人采取行动,他忍不住向我低声催促。', '副词: urgently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('renovate', '[\'renəveɪt]', 'vt.修理；翻新；革新；刷新', '1. They are going to renovate the old furniture. 他们准备将旧家具整修一番。 2. I\'ve decided to renovate the garden next year. 我准备明年把这座庭园修葺一下。 3. We purchase your technology chiefly in order to renovate our old equipment. 我们购买你们的技术，主要是为了改造我们的旧设备。 4. It cost much to renovate old college buildings at the University of Chang Jiang. 翻新长江大学的旧校舍花费很大。', '名词: renovation 过去式: renovated 过去分词: renovated 现在分词: renovating 第三人称单数: renovates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pester', '[\'pestər]', 'v.纠缠；使苦恼', '1. Don\'t pester me with your trivial matters. 别拿你那些鸡毛蒜皮的事同我纠缠。', '名词: pesterer 过去式: pestered 过去分词: pestered 现在分词: pestering 第三人称单数: pesters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ambience', '[\'æmbiəns]', 'n.气氛', '1. I can feel the tense ambience of the room. 我可以感觉到房间里的紧张气氛。 2. We\'ve tried to createthe ambience of a French bistro. 我们想尽量创造出法国小餐馆的气氛。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loll', '[lɑːl]', 'v.懒洋洋地呆着、坐或站着(常指倚着某物)；懒散地闲逛；伸出舌头', '1. My head lolled against his shoulder. 我把头懒懒地靠在他的肩上。 2. She was lolling on a sofa, with nothing to do. 她懒洋洋地躺在沙发上,无事可做。 3. Do stand up straight, don\'t loll about like that! 站直，别那样歪七竖八的！ 4. Don\'t loll about in the street after school. 放学后不要在街上到处闲逛。', '副词: lollingly 名词: loller 过去式: lolled 过去分词: lolled 现在分词: lolling 第三人称单数: lolls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stickler', '[\'stɪklər]', 'n.坚持……的人；难题', '1. She\'s a stickler for the truth. 她是个坚持实事求是的人。 2. My high school coach is a stickler for discipline. 我的中学教练是个严格强调纪律的人。 3. You will find Mrs.Carboy a stickler about trifles. 您会发现卡博太太是个拘泥小节的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deferential', '[ˌdefə\'renʃl]', 'adj.恭敬的；顺从的', '1. He is deferential to his superiors. 他对他的长官是恭敬的。 2. She is always extremely deferential to anyone in authority. 她对任何权威人士总是必恭必敬。', '副词: deferentially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('upsurge', '[\'ʌpsɜːrdʒ]', 'n.高潮；(突然的)增长 v.增长；高涨', '1. A new upsurge of revolution has come. 革命的新高潮来了。 2. A new upsurge in construction is in the making. 一个建设的新高潮正在兴起。 3. There has been a recent upsurge of violence in the area. 近日该地区暴力事件急增。 4. There is now an increased upsurge of book-publishing in society. 现在社会上出书的热潮一浪高过一浪。 5. After the Sino-Japanese War of 1894-1895, ethnicism began to upsurge inside Chinese society. 甲午战争后民族主义开始在中国社会内部初步兴起。', '过去式: upsurged 过去分词: upsurged 现在分词: upsurging 第三人称单数: upsurges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('connive', '[kə\'naɪv]', 'v.共谋；默许；纵容', '1. We want to let to benefit the customer and connive development. 我们就是要做到让利于客户 2. The student tried to connive with her friend to cheat in the examination. 那个学生企图和她的朋友串谋考试作弊。 3. Some government officials connive at graft. 有些政府官员对贪污受贿视而不见。 4. The prisoners paid the guards to connive at their escape. 囚犯们贿赂看守，使看守默许他们越狱。', '名词: conniver 过去式: connived 过去分词: connived 现在分词: conniving 第三人称单数: connives');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eternal', '[ɪ\'tɜːrnl]', 'adj.永久的；永恒的 n.永恒的事', '1. The price of liberty is eternal vigilance. 自由的代价是永久提高警惕。 2. The bad man will suffer eternal damnation. 坏人将会受到永远的惩罚。 3. He is, as it were, an eternal boy. 他好像是个永远年轻的小伙子。 4. She felt eternal gratitude to him for saving her life. 她终生感激他的救命之恩。 5. The eternal motion of the stars fascinated him. 星体永恒的运行使他著迷。', '副词: eternally 名词: eternality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('presentation', '[ˌpriːzen\'teɪʃn]', 'n.介绍；陈述；赠送物；报告；[美]讲课', '1. Amy did her presentation on her cat. 艾米做的介绍是关于她的猫的。 2. I was asked to give a short presentation on the aims of the plan. 他们要求我就这计划的目的作一个简短的陈述。 3. We want to make her a presentation to celebrate her jubilee. 我们想送她一件礼物以庆贺她的纪念日。 4. I have to make a big presentation in the meeting. 我必须在会议中作重要报告。', '形容词: presentational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jolt', '[dʒoʊlt]', 'n.震摇；摇动；震惊；少量 vt.颠簸；敲击；动摇；震动 vi.颠簸而行', '1. The car stopped with a jolt. 汽车停止时震动了一下。 2. The sudden jolt plunged her forward. 突然颠了一下，她向前打了个趔趄。 3. With a tremendous jolt the car started. 汽车狠狠摇晃一下才起动了。 4. The news came as a jolt. 消息传来,引起震惊。 5. The horse jolted me terribly when he jumped. 马跳跃时,我被颠得很厉害。 6. The cart jolted along over the country road. 二轮货车在农村道路上颠簸着前进。', '形容词: jolty 副词: joltily 名词: jolter 过去式: jolted 过去分词: jolted 现在分词: jolting 第三人称单数: jolts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quell', '[kwel]', 'vt.压制；平息；消除；减轻', '1. Soldiers were sent in to quell the riots. 已派士兵去镇压动乱。 2. The armed force had to be called out to quell violence. 不得不出动军队来镇压暴力行动。 3. His actio have done little to quell the eculation. 他的行动无助平息传言。 4. The police have been called in to quell a minor disturbance. 警察奉命出动以平息一场小规模的骚乱。', '过去式: quelled 过去分词: quelled 现在分词: quelling 第三人称单数: quells');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cloy', '[klɔɪ]', 'v.(吃甜食)生腻；吃腻', '1. The pleasures of idleness soon cloy. 无所事事的享乐很快就使人厌烦了。 2. She has cloyed with rich food. 她已经吃腻美食。 3. Chocolates start to cloy if you eat too many. 巧克力糖吃太多就会腻。', '副词: cloyingly 名词: cloyingness 过去式: cloyed 过去分词: cloyed 现在分词: cloying 第三人称单数: cloys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malignant', '[mə\'lɪɡnənt]', 'adj.有恶意的；恶性的；有害的', '1. This is a kind of very malignant tumor. 这是一种很恶性的肿瘤。 2. Malignant gliomas are more aggressive in older people. 恶性的神经胶质瘤在老人身上更具有攻击性。 3. Indeed, not all viruses are malignant. 事实上，并非所有的病毒都是有害的。 4. At any rate, magical practices seem to have assumed a more malignant form in Nevis than in some of the other islands. 无论如何，在奈利斯岛上，魔法的习俗比在一些其他岛屿上似乎采取了一种更为有害的方式。', '副词: malignantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('iconoclast', '[aɪ\'kɑːnəklæst]', 'n.毁坏宗教神像的人；提倡打破旧习的人', '1. The beliefs, practices, or doctrine of an iconoclast. 反对传统、毁坏偶像的思想、行为或主义', '形容词: iconoclastic 副词: iconoclastically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('menace', '[\'menəs]', 'n.威胁；恐吓；<口>讨厌的人（物） v.威吓；威胁', '1. These weapons are a menace to world peace. 这些武器是对世界和平的威胁。 2. The man\'s lunatic behavior is a menace to society. 那个人的疯狂行为构成对社会的威胁。 3. That film creates an atmosphere of menace. 那部影片营造出吓人的气氛。 4. Your vicious dog is menacing my cat! 你那条恶狗对我家的猫太凶了！', '副词: menacingly 名词: menacer 过去式: menaced 过去分词: menaced 现在分词: menacing 第三人称单数: menaces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jubilation', '[ˌdʒuːbɪ\'leɪʃn]', 'n.欢腾；喜悦；庆祝', '1. The whole city was a scene of jubilation. 全市一片欢腾。 2. In traditional Chinese culture red symbolizes celebration and jubilation. 在中国传统文化力，红色代表喜庆。 3. In traditional Chinese culture, red symbolizes celebration and jubilation. 在中国传统文化力，红色代表喜庆。 4. It is a day that the whole world joins in the jubilation. 这是一个普天同庆的日子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confidential', '[ˌkɑːnfɪ\'denʃl]', 'adj.秘密的；机密的；表示信任的；获信赖的', '1. He has been on confidential missions to Berlin. 他前往柏林执行秘密任务。 2. He told me the confidential information. 他向我透露了这个秘密的信息。 3. He was an author whose works were so little known as to be almost confidential. 他这位作家的著作是如此不为人所知，以致几乎等于机密文件。 4. Don\'t be too confidential with strangers. 不要过份相信陌生人。', '副词: confidentially 名词: confidentiality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('freight', '[freɪt]', 'n.（货运）运费；货运；货物 vt.装货于；运送', '1. At an auction, the buyer pays the freight. 在拍卖会上，买家支付运费。 2. The freight must be added to the cost of the goods. 运费必须打入货的成本。 3. We can send it by air/sea freight. 我们可以空运[海运]。 4. Eight thousand tons of freight were being landed each day. 每天卸货8000吨上岸。 5. They freighted the boat with bananas. 他们把香蕉装上船。', '过去式: freighted 过去分词: freighted 现在分词: freighting 第三人称单数: freights');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('curt', '[kɜːrt]', 'adj.(言语)简短失礼的；简短的； 草率的', '1. He rapped out a series of curt commands. 他大声发出了一连串简短的命令。 2. `No!\' was his curt rejoinder. 他草率地回答了一声｀不!＇ 3. He rapped out a series of curt commands. 他大声发出了一连串简短的命令。', '副词: curtly 比较级: curter 最高级: curtest 名词: curtness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('optional', '[\'ɑːpʃənl]', 'adj.任选的', '1. The insurance cover is optional. 保险范围可以随意选择。 2. It is optional with you. 那是你的自由。 3. The goods are optional, but only one. 这些物品是可以任选的, 但只能选一个。 4. A 4-speed automatic transmission is optional. 四段自动变速器是可自由选择的。', '副词: optionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('construct', '[kən\'strʌkt]', 'vt.建造；构筑；造(句) n.构想', '1. This factory was constructed by our company. 这家工厂是由我们公司建设的。 2. They are planning to construct a new supermarket. 他们正在计划建造一个新的超级市场。 3. You must learn how to construct a logical argument. 你必须学会怎样确立合乎逻辑的论点。 4. He taught us how to construct sentences. 他教我们怎样造句。 5. There is a contrast between lived reality and the construct held in the mind. 现实生活与头脑所持概念之间有明显差别。', '形容词: constructible 名词: constructor 过去式: constructed 过去分词: constructed 现在分词: constructing 第三人称单数: constructs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elbow', '[\'elboʊ]', 'n.手肘；扶手；急弯 v.用手肘推开；推挤', '1. He barked his elbow on the wall. 他碰到墙上，肘部擦破了皮。 2. You jogged my elbow and spoiled what I was drawing. 你撞到了我的手肘，弄坏了我正在画的图画。 3. He tried to elbow me off the line in the lunchroom. 他想用肘把我挤出餐厅的候餐行列。 4. He elbowed his way through the crowd. 他在人群中挤出一条路。', '过去式: elbowed 过去分词: elbowed 现在分词: elbowing 第三人称单数: elbows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('uproarious', '[ʌp\'rɔːriəs]', 'adj.喧嚣的；令人捧腹大笑的；滑稽的', '1. Never was a gathering more varied and more uproarious. 像这样各色人等混杂，环境喧闹不堪的集会倒是从未见过。 2. This utterance of his was greeted with bursts of uproarious laughter. 他的这番话引起阵阵哄笑。', '副词: uproariously 名词: uproariousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fortuitous', '[fɔːr\'tuːɪtəs]', 'adj.偶然的；幸运的', '1. The occurrence of such things is by no means fortuitous. 出现这种问题绝不是偶然的。 2. We knew each other by a fortuitous meeting. 我们在一次偶然的邂逅中认识。 3. A series of fortuitous circumstances advanced her career. 一系列的幸运事使她的事业一帆风顺。', '副词: fortuitously 名词: fortuitousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seminary', '[\'semɪneri]', 'n.神学院；学院；发源地', '1. The Fuller Theological Seminary opened in 1947. 福乐神学院创立于1947年。', '名词复数: seminaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bamboozle', '[bæm\'buːzl]', 'v.欺骗；隐瞒；迷惑', '1. He bamboozled me into believing that he\'d lost all his money. 他欺骗我让我相信他把钱全丢光了。 2. You\'ve completely bamboozled me. 你完全把我搞糊涂了。', '名词: bamboozlement 过去式: bamboozled 过去分词: bamboozled 现在分词: bamboozling 第三人称单数: bamboozles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flag', '[flæɡ]', 'n.旗；旗帜；信号旗 vt.(以旗子)标出 v.无力地下垂；减退；枯萎', '1. Flags are fluttering in the breeze. 旗子在风中飘扬。 2. The flag was flown at half-staff. 那旗帜降了半旗。 3. The flag was aflutter in the air. 旗帜在空中飘扬。 4. The signal flag is fully in our sight from this position. 我从这个位置完全可以看到信号旗。 5. Halfway through the race he began to flag. 赛跑到一半他开始有点跑不动了。', '名词: flagger 过去式: flagged 过去分词: flagged 现在分词: flagging 第三人称单数: flags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accurate', '[\'ækjərət]', 'adj.准确的；精确的', '1. Hearsay definitely can\'t be regarded as accurate information. 道听途说的决然不能算作很准确的消息。 2. The manager impressed on his office staff the importance of keeping accurate records. 经理让办公室职员认识到做精确记录的重要性。', '副词: accurately 名词: accurateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spoof', '[spuːf]', 'n.滑稽模仿；诳骗；愚弄 v.滑稽地模仿；发送仿真电邮；愚弄', '1. It\'s a spoof on horror movies. 这是对恐怖片的滑稽模仿。 2. Once again, thank you for alerting us to the spoof email you received. 再一次，感谢您提醒我们您所收到的欺骗信件。 3. It is a movie that spoofs other movies. 这是一部夸张地模仿其他电影的影片。 4. Someone has been spoofing my address. 有人一直在冒用我的电邮地址发送电邮。', '过去式: spoofed 过去分词: spoofed 现在分词: spoofing 第三人称单数: spoofs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swell', '[swel]', 'v.（使）膨胀；（使）鼓起；（使）增长 n.增大；膨胀；肿胀；汹涌 adj.<口>很棒的；时髦的；一流的', '1. The hills swell gradually up from the plain. 山丘逐渐由平原膨胀起来。 2. Tom had a fall and his under lip began to swell up. 汤姆跌了一跤，下唇开始肿起。 3. The budget deficit could swell further over the next few years. 未来几年内财政赤字可能会有更多增长。 4. The groups change more swiftly, swell with new arrivals, dissolve and form in the same breath. 人群的变化越来越快，忽而随着新来的客人而增大，忽而分散后又立即重新组合。', '比较级: sweller 最高级: swellest 过去式: swelled 过去分词: swelled/swollen 现在分词: swelling 第三人称单数: swells');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gaffe', '[ɡæf]', 'n.过失；失态；出丑；失言', '1. I had no idea of the gaffe which I was committing. 我不清楚我犯了什么错误。 2. He didn\'t realize what a gaffe he\'d made. 他没意识到自己已出乖露丑。 3. Don\'t make gaffe here, we can discuss about this question at home. 别在这里出丑,这问题我们回家再谈。 4. She resigned not long after that gaffe. 她在那次失言后不久便主动请辞。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('procrastinate', '[proʊ\'kræstɪneɪt]', 'v.延迟；拖延；耽搁', '1. He procrastinated until it was too late to do anything at all. 他因循坐误，一事无成。 2. Do not procrastinate what you ought to do. 不要拖延你应该作的事。 3. People often use several well-known excuses to procrastinate. 人们经常用一些人所共知的借口去拖延时间。 4. When you receive a new project or task, don\'t procrastinate. Attend to it right away. 当你接受了一个新项目或者新任务，不要耽搁时间，立即去做。', '名词: procrastination 过去式: procrastinated 过去分词: procrastinated 现在分词: procrastinating 第三人称单数: procrastinates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loam', '[loʊm]', 'n.壤土；沃土 v.用壤土填', '1. The ship was completely buried in the soft loam of the sea bottom. 这条船被完全埋到海底松软的肥土里。', '形容词: loamy 过去式: loamed 过去分词: loamed 现在分词: loaming 第三人称单数: loams');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('microscope', '[\'maɪkrəskoʊp]', 'n.显微镜', '1. He focuses the lens of a microscope. 他调整显微镜的透镜以定焦点。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abate', '[ə\'beɪt]', 'v.缓和；减弱；消除', '1. Nothing could abate his rage. 什么都不能平息他的愤怒。 2. She is trying to abate the tension between her parents. 她试着缓和她父母的紧张关系。 3. The ship sailed when the storm abated. 这船在暴风雨减弱时起航。 4. Nothing can abate the force of that argument. 什么也不能减弱那场辩论的影响力。', '过去式: abated 过去分词: abated 现在分词: abating 第三人称单数: abates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arable', '[\'ærəbl]', 'adj.可耕的；适合种植的 n.<英>可耕地', '1. Now in India, 63 percent of land is arable. 现在的印度，63%25的土地是可耕地。 2. Second,we have a large population but not enough arable land. 第二条是人口多，耕地少。 3. He farmed 200 acres of prime arable land. 他耕种了200英亩良田。 4. The soil proved too infertile to sustain real pasture or arable crops. 这土壤被证明太贫瘠,不能真正用作放牧或种植作物。', '名词: arability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('regiment', '[\'redʒɪmənt]', 'n.（军队）团；大量（人或物） v.组编成团；组织；严格管制', '1. Our regiment suffered heavy casualties. 我团伤亡惨重。 2. He became a trooper in the Royal Tank Regiment. 他当上了皇家坦克团的装甲兵。', '形容词: regimental 副词: regimentally 名词: regimentation 过去式: regimented 过去分词: regimented 现在分词: regimenting 第三人称单数: regiments');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unscented', '[ʌn\'sentɪd]', 'adj.无气味的 无香味的.', '1. There is also a clear, unscented version for consumers who just want extra control for their hair. 也有一个明确的，无气味的版本为消费者谁只是想额外控制他们的头发。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expiation', '[ˌekspi\'eɪʃn]', 'n.赎罪；补偿', '1. And he shall put his hand upon the head of the victim, and it shall be acceptable, and help to its expiation. 先按手在全燔祭牲的头上，使祭牲蒙受悦纳，代自己赎罪。 2. However, currently the expiation mode of e-co-protection and construction in our country is unimproved. 但是，目前我国的生态保护与建设的补偿措施并不完善。 3. Conclusion Interspace expanding of environmental profit and loss can promote environmental expiation and regional sustainable development. 结论通过深化区域之间环境损益空间关系研究，促进区域生态补偿和可持续发展。', '形容词: expiatory');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resonant', '[\'rezənənt]', 'adj.共鸣的；回响的；洪亮的', '1. The amplified strings require less energy to produce a rich resonant sound. 声音被放大了，在琴弦上反需用很小的力量，就能产生丰满的、共鸣音响。 2. The air was resonant with bells. 空中回荡着钟声。 3. He has a resonant voice. or His voice carries well. 他嗓音洪亮。 4. He has a resonant voice. 他嗓音洪亮。', '副词: resonantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tusk', '[tʌsk]', 'n.长牙；獠牙；尖形物 v.以牙刺戳；以牙掘', '1. A huge tusk decorated the wall of his study. 他书房的墙上装饰着一支巨大的象牙。 2. The second blind grasped one of the elephant\'s tusks and felt it. 第二个瞎子抓住了一个象牙，摸了摸它。 3. The wild boar had its tusk sunk deeply into a tree and howled desperately. 野猪的獠牙陷在了树里，绝望地嗥叫着。', '形容词: tusked 过去式: tusked 过去分词: tusked 现在分词: tusking 第三人称单数: tusks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('excursion', '[ɪk\'skɜːrʒn]', 'n.远足；短途旅行；【物】偏移，漂移，偏离；偏差，偏振', '1. The excursion was the high spot of our holiday. 我们那个假日的最大乐趣是远足。 2. We are planning an excursion to the blue mountain. 我们正在计划去蓝山远足。 3. I was roped in for this excursion before I knew it. 我不知不觉被拉来参加了这次远足旅行。 4. We shall make an excursion to Hangzhou this weekend. 这个周末我们将去杭州旅行。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blush', '[blʌʃ]', 'n.脸红；羞愧 vi.泛红；羞愧', '1. Her blush witnessed her agitation. 她脸红表示了她的激动。 2. She turn away to hide her blush. 她扭过脸，怕人见她脸红。 3. That story might raise a blush on a young girl\'s cheeks . 那个故事可能使少女听了脸红。 4. I have to blush to admit that thing. 我不得不羞愧地承认了那件事。 5. She would blush at the drop of a hat. 她动不动就脸红。', '形容词: blushful 副词: blushingly 过去式: blushed 过去分词: blushed 现在分词: blushing 第三人称单数: blushes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dab', '[dæb]', 'v.轻触；轻涂 n.轻拍；少量；熟手；比目鱼', '1. Dab the coffee off with your handkerchief. 用你的手帕把咖啡擦掉。 2. You can dab at the stain on your coat with a wet towel. 你可以用湿毛巾在衣服的污迹处轻轻地擦几下。 3. Dab the solution on your scar to relieve the pain. 将药液涂在伤口上以缓解疼痛。 4. Again, try not to use too much water. Just dab the paint on. 这次也不要用太多的水。只涂上少量的颜料就可以了。 5. She gave me a dab with her umbrella. 她用雨伞轻轻拍了我一下。', '过去式: dabbed 过去分词: dabbed 现在分词: dabbing 第三人称单数: dabs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mimic', '[\'mɪmɪk]', 'vt.模仿；模拟 n.模仿者；仿制品 adj.模仿的；假的', '1. He mimicked his uncle\'s voice and gestures perfectly. 他把叔叔的声音和姿态模仿得惟妙惟肖。 2. He could mimic all the teachers\' accents. 他能够模仿每位老师的口音。 3. You would like to mimic this plan on your test environment. 您需要在测试环境中模拟该计划。 4. One of my brothers is a wonderful mimic. 我的一个兄弟很善于模仿。 5. At the international level sport is frankly mimic warfare. 国际级比赛简直就是一场模拟战争。', '名词: mimicker 过去式: mimicked 过去分词: mimicked 现在分词: mimicking 第三人称单数: mimics');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drudgery', '[\'drʌdʒəri]', 'n.苦差事；苦工', '1. This sentiment still survives, and it has piled up mountains of useless drudgery. 这种心理如今依然存在，而且它堆起了无用苦工的大山。 2. This flexibility has the added benefit of breaking up any sense of endless routine or day in day out drudgery. 这种灵活性具有打破任何没有尽头的例行公事或日复一日苦工感觉的额外好处。', '名词复数: drudgeries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clout', '[klaʊt]', 'n.猛击；影响力 [英]破布. v.猛击', '1. He has a lot of clout with the board of directors. 他对董事会有很大的影响力。 2. They gained considerable political clout. 他们赢得了可观的政治影响力。', '过去式: clouted 过去分词: clouted 现在分词: clouting 第三人称单数: clouts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('traipse', '[treɪps]', 'v.闲逛；游荡 n.闲荡；无精打采者', '1. We spent the afternoon traipsing from one shop to another. 我们用了一下午的时间逛了一家又一家商店。 2. We traipsed all the way to New York to see the tall ships. 我们一路游荡到纽约看高桅横帆船。', '过去式: traipsed 过去分词: traipsed 现在分词: traipsing 第三人称单数: traipses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retain', '[rɪ\'teɪn]', 'vt.保持；保留；记住；聘请', '1. His speech could not retain the interest of his audience. 他的讲话不能保持住听众的兴趣。 2. I will retain my right. 我将保留我的权力。 3. Does it retain the key elements of the original story? 它是否保留了原作的关键要素? 4. She has a good memory and finds it easy to retain matters. 她记忆力好,很容易记住事情。', '形容词: retainable 名词: retainability 过去式: retained 过去分词: retained 现在分词: retaining 第三人称单数: retains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('estrange', '[ə\'streɪndʒ]', 'vt.使疏远', '1. His behaviour estrange him from his brother. 他的行为使他与哥哥疏远了。 2. They are estranged. 他们疏远了。 3. He is estranged from his wife. 他和妻子分居了。', '名词: estrangement 过去式: estranged 过去分词: estranged 现在分词: estranging 第三人称单数: estranges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gargoyle', '[\'ɡɑːrɡɔɪl]', 'n.滴水嘴；奇形怪状的人', '1. His face was the gargoyle of the devil, it was not human, it was not sane. 他的脸简直就像魔鬼模样的屋檐滴水嘴。 2. As an example, suppose you\'re carving a gargoyle up in the corner of this building. 举个例子，假设你在雕刻建筑高处的某一角上的滴水嘴怪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pecan', '[pɪ\'kɑːn]', 'n.美洲山核桃（树）', '1. It tastes like real butter pecan. 吃起来很像真的奶油山核桃。 2. We can have some pecan or apple pie. 我们可以来点核桃或苹果派。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unsettling', '[ʌn\'setlɪŋ]', 'adj.使人不安的 动词unsettle的现在分词形式.', '1. The news was very unsettling. 这则新闻实在扰乱人心。 2. This is a very good and unsettling article. 这是一篇很好但同时又使人不安的文章。 3. Changes are unsettling but sometimes imperative. 变动使人心烦，可是有时又别无选择。 4. After an unsettling but promising period, you\'re craving stability. 经过不安但充满希望的时期，你渴望稳定。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anonymous', '[ə\'nɑːnɪməs]', 'adj.匿名的；无名的；没特色的', '1. It is unpleasant to receive anonymous letters. 接到匿名信是一件令人不快的事。 2. The man was arrested after an anonymous tip-off. 有人匿名举报后，那个人被抓了起来。 3. The author chooses to remain anonymous. 作者愿不署名。 4. An anonymous author wrote this book. 这本书出自无名氏之手。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dilapidation', '[dɪˌlæpɪ\'deɪʃn]', 'n.荒废；破损；崩塌', '1. Pavement dilapidation data is the most important data of pavement maintenance management. 路面破损数据是路面养护管理中重要的数据之一。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brazen', '[\'breɪzn]', 'adj.厚颜无耻的；明目张胆的；响而刺耳的；黄铜(制)的 v.厚着脸皮做；使变得无耻；无耻地对待', '1. It was brazen of him to say so. 他这样说真是无耻。 2. Her toleration of his brazen attitude is enough to show her great tolerance. 她容忍了他厚颜无耻的态度,足以显示她的宽容。 3. They showed a brazen disregard for her privacy. 他们明目张胆地无视她的隐私权。 4. The case of the pesticide plant reflects brazen discrimination. 杀虫剂厂的案例反映了一种明目张胆的歧视态度。 5. Some people prefer to brazen a thing out rather than admit defeat. 有的人不愿承认失败，而是宁肯厚着脸皮干下去。', '副词: brazenly 名词: brazenness 过去式: brazened 过去分词: brazened 现在分词: brazening 第三人称单数: brazens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abeyance', '[ə\'beɪəns]', 'n.暂时中止；（指问题等）缓议；暂时无效或停用', '1. The decision was held in abeyance during the war. 在战争期间，这项决定暂时搁下了。 2. The question is in abeyance until we know more about it. 问题暂时搁置，直到我们了解更多有关情况再行研究。 3. The decision is in abeyance until he returns from holiday. 那项决议在他度假回来之前一直搁置着。 4. The rule has been in abeyance since 1966. 这项规则从1966年起就已失效。', '形容词: abeyant');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yawn', '[jɔːn]', 'v.打呵欠；张开 n.呵欠；<口>乏味的人（事）', '1. His long boring story made me yawn. 他的冗长的故事听得我直打呵欠。 2. He closed the book, yawned, and went to bed. 他合起书, 打了个呵欠, 然后上床睡觉了。 3. The deep crevasse yawned at their feet. 他们脚下的冰川有一道深深的裂缝。 4. I gave a loud yawn, but he just kept on talking. 我大声打了个呵欠，可他还是不停地讲下去。', '名词: yawner 过去式: yawned 过去分词: yawned 现在分词: yawning 第三人称单数: yawns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recluse', '[\'rekluːs]', 'n.隐士', '1. This recluse shunned all company. 这位隐士不与任何人来往。 2. All these years, Eric had lived as a recluse. 这些年来，埃里克都是过着隐士生活。 3. She can\'t just be written off as an eccentric recluse. 不能仅仅把她当成一个古怪的隐居者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('moment', '[\'moʊmənt]', 'n.片刻；瞬间；力矩；非常重要的时机；准确时刻', '1. I\'ll be back in a moment. 我一会儿就回来。 2. Would you take a seat for a moment? 请你稍坐片刻好吗? 3. He thought for a moment and then spoke. 他想了片刻，然後说。 4. Love is a moment that lasts forever. 爱的瞬间就是永恒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transgression', '[træns\'ɡreʃn]', 'n.违反；犯罪；逸出', '1. This would be a serious transgression of the law. 不论哪一种情形都是严重的违反律法。 2. What they did is transgression! 他们所做的是犯罪！ 3. The hothead usually cause much transgression. 暴怒的人通常犯罪多。 4. The ways that I could think of are involved transgression of the law. 我所想出的办法都是超越法律的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snipe', '[snaɪp]', 'n.沙锥；鹬；卑鄙的人 v.伏击；狙击；抨击', '1. The snipe has a very long thin beak. 鹬长着非常细长的鸟嘴。 2. In the south a snipe hunt is practically a rite of passage. 在南方，猎取鹬类实际上是一种成人仪式。 3. The rebels have started sniping at civilians. 反抗者开始伏击平民。 4. He was ordered to snipe at anyone moving about the camp. 他奉令狙击任何在营地附近走动的人。', '过去式: sniped 过去分词: sniped 现在分词: sniping 第三人称单数: snipes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inflame', '[ɪn\'fleɪm]', 'v.激怒；加剧；发炎', '1. Her question seemed to inflame him all the more. 她的问题似乎更加激怒了他。 2. Our lack of response seemed to inflame the colonel. 由于我们没有反应，好象惹恼了那个上校。 3. Insults only served to inflame the feud. 侮辱只是起了加剧长期不和的作用。 4. A misinterpreted or misattributed attack could inflame tensions. 一次误解或错误归因的攻击可能加剧紧张局势。', '名词: inflamer 过去式: inflamed 过去分词: inflamed 现在分词: inflaming 第三人称单数: inflames');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obverse', '[\'ɑːbvɜːrs]', 'n.（货币或奖章的）正面；较明显的一面；对应面 adj.正面的；对应面的', '1. The head of the Queen appears on the obverse of British coins. 英国硬币的正面有女王的头像。 2. The obverse shows the Temple of Heaven in Beijing. 正面以北京天坛作主题。 3. The obverse of love is hate. 与爱相对的是恨。 4. We should see the reverse as well as the obverse of things. 我们不但应该看到事物的正面,也要看到事物的反面。 5. Smooth language communication depends on obverse words expression. 语言信息交流的通畅依赖于话语的正向表达。', '副词: obversely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ramify', '[\'ræməˌfaɪ]', 'v.分枝；(使)分枝；(使)分叉', '1. The optimal control is an important ramify of auto-control theory, the optimal control problem of Singular bilinear systems is studied in this paper firstly. 摘要最优控制是自动控制理论的重要研究分支，本文首次对广义双线性系统的最优控制问题进行研究。 2. Ramify vi., vt. 分支； 3. ramify into a labyrinth 分枝成迷宫状 4. to ramify into a labyrinth 分枝成迷宫状', '过去式: ramified 过去分词: ramified 现在分词: ramifying 第三人称单数: ramifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appraise', '[ə\'preɪz]', 'vt.评价；估价；鉴定', '1. They tried to appraise the poet-ry of John Milton. 他们试图评价弥尔顿的诗。 2. It is very high that people appraise to his thesis. 人们对他的论文评价很高。 3. It would be unwise to buy the house before having it appraised. 买房子不事先估价是不明智的。 4. The teacher is appraising the students\' work. 老师正在评定学生的作业。', '形容词: appraisable 名词: appraisement 过去式: appraised 过去分词: appraised 现在分词: appraising 第三人称单数: appraises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('docile', '[\'dɑːsl]', 'adj.容易控制的；温顺的', '1. In every sense she is docile and obedient to him. 她对他可谓百依百顺。 2. He trembled lest he himself should lose a docile pupil. 他担心自己会失去一个听话的学生。 3. The house faces a docile body of water. 这幢房子面朝一泓平静的湖水。 4. Giant pandas have very docile temperaments. 大熊猫的性情很温顺。', '副词: docilely 名词: docility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delta', '[\'deltə]', 'n.(河流的)三角洲；希腊语第四个字母（Δ、δ）', '1. There are fertile fields in the Nile Delta. 尼罗河三角洲土地肥沃。 2. They were the terror of the Ganges delta. 他们已成为恒河三角洲的令人胆寒的力量。', '形容词: deltaic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ascetic', '[ə\'setɪk]', 'adj.禁欲的 n.苦行者', '1. This is achieved by strict celibacy and ascetic practices. 这要通过严厉的独身生活和禁欲修行而达到。 2. Rabia went into the desert to pray and became an ascetic. 随后拉比尔走进沙漠祈祷，从此成为苦行者。', '副词: ascetically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bequest', '[bɪ\'kwest]', 'n.遗产；遗赠物', '1. He left a bequest to each of his grandchildren. 他给他的孙子孙女每人留下一笔遗产。 2. We must note to protect our national bequest. 我们必须注意保护自己的民族遗产。 3. The picture was acquired by bequest in 1921. 这幅画是在1921年通过遗赠获得的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defalcate', '[dɪ\'fælˌkeɪt]', 'vi. 挪用公款 vt. <古>扣除； 缩减', '1. The accountant has been put into jail due to defalcate much money from company. 这个会计由于公司挪用巨额款项而进了监狱。 2. As we have learned, this is Yunnan province is big defalcate case since founding a state. 据了解，这是建国以来云南省大的一起挪用公款案。 3. Lately, some large brand real estate agency corporations defalcate clients funds and break out fund sandal. 近来,大型品牌房地产中介公司频频挪用客户资金,爆发\"资金门\"丑闻,引发了房地产中介行业的信任危机。 4. Benefit carries out secret of country of financial bilk, theft, corruption, defalcate, filch or other crime with the computer. 利用计算机实施金融诈骗、盗窃、贪污、挪用公款、窃取国家秘密或其他犯罪。', '名词: defalcation 过去式: defalcated 过去分词: defalcated 现在分词: defalcating 第三人称单数: defalcates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forger', '[\'fɔːrdʒər]', 'n.伪造者；铁匠；膺造者', '1. Accordingly, the forger was put to death. 因此伪造者被处死。 2. The forger swindled the merchants of this city out of large sums of money. 那个伪造者骗走了这个城市商人们的一大笔钱。 3. I am a forger of swords, sir, not a speculator on dwarven motives for falsehood. 我是一位铸剑师，先生，不是琢磨矮人撒谎动机的研究家。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diagnose', '[ˌdaɪəɡ\'noʊs]', 'v.判断；诊断(疾病)', '1. Geological investigations must correctly diagnose a specific soil-like condition. 地质调查必须正确地判断出明确的土状条件。 2. What more will you want to know to diagnose this problem? 要弄清这个问题，你还需要知道些什么? 3. The book diagnoses our present economic ills. 这本书切中了我们现在经济的时弊。 4. The test is used to diagnose a variety of diseases. 此项化验可用于诊断多种疾病。', '形容词: diagnosable 过去式: diagnosed 过去分词: diagnosed 现在分词: diagnosing 第三人称单数: diagnoses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('haggle', '[\'hæɡl]', 'vi.争论；讨价还价 vt.乱砍 n.讨价还价；争论', '1. It\'s not worth haggling over a few pence. 为几便士争论不休实在不值得。 2. He preferred to be overcharged than to haggle. 他宁愿被”宰”也不愿讨价还价。 3. You can haggle with the best of them. 能和最厉害的人讨价还价。 4. In many countries you have to haggle before you buy anything. 在许多国家里买东西之前都得讨价还价。', '名词: haggler 过去式: haggled 过去分词: haggled 现在分词: haggling 第三人称单数: haggles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antihistamine', '[ˌænti\'hɪstəmiːn]', 'n.抗组胺剂', '1. Taking an antihistamine isn\'t the only way to battle seasonal allergies. 采用抗组胺剂并不是唯一防止季节性过敏的方法。', '形容词: antihistaminic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dwarf', '[dwɔːrf]', 'n.矮子；侏儒 vt.使矮小 vi.变小', '1. You are a giant of words and dwarf of action. 你是言词的巨人,行动的矮子。 2. There is a dwarf apple tree in our garden. 在我们的花园里有一棵矮苹果树。 3. The kind dwarf asked the little princess to have dinner with him. 善良的小矮人邀请小公主和他一起吃晚饭。 4. A dwarf on a giant\'s shoulders sees further of the two. 侏儒站在巨人肩上要比两个人看得远。 5. Each innovation destined to dwarf the extensive accomplishment of the Greeks-Euclidean geometry. 每一个创新都注定希腊人的巨大成就--欧几里德几何相形见绌。 6. They act out their dramas in a setting whose wilderness immensity both dwarf and ennobles whatever they achieve 他们在荒原上奠定了他们的事业，而广阔无际的天地既使他们的成就显得渺小，也显得崇高。', '形容词: dwarfish 名词: dwarfishness 名词复数: dwarfs 过去式: dwarfed 过去分词: dwarfed 现在分词: dwarfing 第三人称单数: dwarfs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compatible', '[kəm\'pætəbl]', 'adj.一致的；兼容的；适合的 n.兼容', '1. The proposed new regulation is not compatible with the existing policy. 提出的新规定与现有的政策不符。 2. We should remain the compatible family relationships. 我们应该维持和谐的家庭关系。 3. He and his wife are not compatible 他跟他的妻子合不来。 4. It may not be compatible with your version of Mac OS X. 它可能与您的Mac OS X版本不兼容。 5. He drove a car at a speed compatible with safety. 他以安全速度行车。', '副词: compatibly 名词: compatibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('orient', '[\'ɔːriənt]', 'n.东方；亚洲 adj.东方的 vt.使适应；使…朝向；定 ... 的方位', '1. They love paintings from the Orient. 他们喜欢来自东方的绘画。 2. China is the biggest country in the orient. 中国是东方最大的国家。 3. The idea of cantilever construction is ancient in the Orient. 在亚洲古代就已实行过悬臂施工。 4. The vase seems to have an orient origin. 这花瓶好像来自东方。 5. I need some time to orient my thinking. 我需要一些时间来使我的思想适应。', '过去式: oriented 过去分词: oriented 现在分词: orienting 第三人称单数: orients');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('riddle', '[\'rɪdl]', 'n.谜；谜语 vt.解谜；出谜题；充满；打洞；筛选 vi.出谜题', '1. That painting is still a riddle to us. 那幅画对我们仍然是个谜。 2. He could not solve the riddle. 他猜不出这个谜。 3. He got the answer to the riddle as quick as a flash. 他一下子就猜中了谜底。 4. The riddle was at last unriddled. 这个谜语终于得到了解答。 5. She loved to riddle out the solution to problems. 她喜欢解答问题。', '名词: riddler 过去式: riddled 过去分词: riddled 现在分词: riddling 第三人称单数: riddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foliage', '[\'foʊliɪdʒ]', 'n.叶子(总称)；簇叶', '1. Pollution has stripped the trees of their foliage. 污染剥光了这些树的叶子。 2. In summer the house next door is hidden luxuriant foliage. 夏天时，隔壁房子被繁茂的叶子所掩盖。', '形容词: foliaged');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intensify', '[ɪn\'tensɪfaɪ]', 'vt.增强；强化；加剧', '1. You must intensify your sense of responsibility. 你必须加强责任感。 2. We need to intensify our effort to fight corruption and to prevent and eliminate its root causes. 加大治本力度，从源头上预防和治理腐败。 3. Her anger intensified. 她更加生气了。', '名词: intensification 过去式: intensified 过去分词: intensified 现在分词: intensifying 第三人称单数: intensifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('microscopic', '[ˌmaɪkrə\'skɑːpɪk]', 'adj.显微镜的；极小的；微观的', '1. The vacuolar localization of the last class of excretion products, isoprenoids, is based on electron microscopic observations. 在液泡中最后一类分泌物是一类异戎二稀，是根据电子显微镜的观察定位的。 2. It\'s impossible to read his microscopic handwriting. 不可能看清他那极小的书写字迹。 3. The researchers intend to use the standard lithographic techniques employed in chipmaking to coat a semiconductor with microscopic magnets. 研究人员拟应用芯片制作中所用的标准平版印刷技术，将许多极小的磁铁包被到一块半导体上。 4. On the other hand, the microscopic principle of surface plasma resonance is explicated. 并且进一步从微观的角度解释了表面等离子体波共振现象。', '副词: microscopically 异体字: microscopical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mortgage', '[\'mɔːrɡɪdʒ]', 'n.按揭；抵押；抵押贷款 vt.抵押', '1. Mortgage Insurance vs Term Life Insurance. 按揭人寿保险。 2. Mortgage is a security interest in real property. 按揭是不动产的一种物权担保。 3. The bank foreclosed a mortgage on the property. 银行取消了抵押人的财产赎回权。 4. We\'re having difficulty keeping up our mortgage payments. 我们难以继续支付分期偿还的抵押贷款。 5. He will have to mortgage his land for a loan. 他不得不将土地抵押来申请贷款。', '过去式: mortgaged 过去分词: mortgaged 现在分词: mortgaging 第三人称单数: mortgages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('escalate', '[\'eskəleɪt]', 'vt.升级 vi.升高；逐步升级', '1. Shouting may seem necessary, but it tends to escalate conflicts. 大喊大叫也许比较容易，但是它容易导致使冲突升级。 2. The government is deliberately escalating the war for political reasons. 政府出于政治目的蓄意使战争逐步升级。 3. House prices have escalated rapidly. 房价已急速上涨。 4. Even a limited confrontation can escalate into a major war. 即使是局部的对抗也可能扩大成一场大战。', '形容词: escalatory 名词: escalation 过去式: escalated 过去分词: escalated 现在分词: escalating 第三人称单数: escalates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agility', '[ə\'dʒɪləti]', 'n.敏捷；灵活；轻快', '1. The boy came upstairs with agility. 那男孩敏捷地走上楼来。 2. Each point of Agility now adds 1 Attack Power. 现在每一点敏捷将增加猫形态下的一点攻击强度。 3. The spiderman moves with feline agility. 蜘蛛人的动作像猫一们灵活。 4. It takes good agility to become a ballet dancer. 成为芭蕾舞者需要相当的灵活度。', 'none');
