INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dispensable', '[dɪ\'spensəbl]', 'adj.不是必要的；可有可无的', '1. A garage is useful but dispensable. 汽车房虽然有用 2. He repents having compensated the dispensable pesion for fear of penalty. 他后悔因害怕处罚而补偿了不必要的养老金。 3. They looked on music and art lessons as dispensable. 他们认为音乐课和美术课是可有可无的。 4. Otherwise Miller would become a dispensable figurehead. 否则米勒就会变成可有可无的傀儡。', '名词: dispensability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heretical', '[hə\'retɪkl]', 'adj.异教的；异端的', '1. It thus gave Judaism a religious dimension whose mystical approaches to God were viewed by some as dangerously pantheistic and heretical. 它就这样赋予了犹太教一个宗教的尺度，神秘接近上帝是靠一些人危险的泛神论和异教的观察。 2. In the old days he had hidden a heretical mind beneath an appearance of conformity. 在过去，他在服从的外表下面隐藏着异端的思想。', '副词: heretically 名词: hereticalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chorus', '[\'kɔːrəs]', 'n.合唱队；歌舞队；齐声说道；副歌部分 vt.合唱', '1. The audience chimed in on the chorus. 听众开始跟合唱队一起唱起来。 2. The chorus is dressed as fairies. 歌舞队的人都装扮成仙子。 3. When I asked questions, they answered up in chorus. 我提问题时,他们迅速齐声回答。 4. The chorus is very catchy to say the least. 副歌部分很容易上口。 5. The papers all chorused the praises of the President. 各报都异口同声地对总统表示赞扬。', '名词复数: choruses 过去式: chorused/chorussed 过去分词: chorused/chorussed 现在分词: chorusing/chorussing 第三人称单数: choruses/chorusses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bicker', '[\'bɪkər]', 'v.斗嘴；闪烁；发出潺潺声 n.口角；潺潺流水声', '1. They always bicker when they meet at school. 在学校见面时他们总是争吵。 2. The two children used to bicker about who should do the washing-up. 这两个小孩子过去常为该由谁洗餐具一事而争吵。 3. This sort of discussion seemed only to cause bicker. 这一类讨论似乎只会导致口角。', '名词: bickerer 过去式: bickered 过去分词: bickered 现在分词: bickering 第三人称单数: bickers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corrupt', '[kə\'rʌpt]', 'adj.腐败的；堕落的；讹误的 vt.贿赂；使恶化；使腐烂 vi.腐败；腐烂', '1. She wrote a book declaiming against our corrupt society. 她写了一本书抨击我们这腐败的社会。 2. The corrupt judge dismissed the case without a hearing. 腐败的法官没有听审就驳回了这个案子。 3. The official led a corrupt life. 这个官员过着堕落的生活。 4. The manuscript is so corrupt that parts of it make no sense at all. 这稿子由于讹误太多，以致有的部分意义不明。 5. He was sent to prison for trying to corrupt a policeman with money. 他因为试图用钱贿赂一名警察而被送入监狱。 6. Complete power corrupts completely. 绝对的权力造成绝对的腐败。', '形容词: corruptive 副词: corruptly 名词: corrupter 过去式: corrupted 过去分词: corrupted 现在分词: corrupting 第三人称单数: corrupts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pilfer', '[\'pɪlfər]', 'v.盗；偷；窃', '1. They may pilfer other animals\' food. 它们可能会偷吃其它动物的食品。 2. As we predicted from the results of the first experiments, knowers rushed to pilfer the human-made cache if they were paired with another knower. 结果，知情渡鸦要是与另一只也知情的渡鸦在一起，就会急著去偷取人藏起的物事，符合我们根据先前的实验结果所做的预测。', '名词: pilferage 过去式: pilfered 过去分词: pilfered 现在分词: pilfering 第三人称单数: pilfers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unnoticed', '[ˌʌn\'noʊtɪst]', 'adj.不被注意的；被忽视的', '1. He slipped in unnoticed. 他溜了进来，没有人注意到他。 2. Your hard work will not go unnoticed. 你的辛勤工作是不会不被注意的。 3. My wife\'s complaints went unnoticed. 我妻子的抱怨无人理会。 4. I can\'t let this act of kindness go unnoticed. 我不能让这种好人好事湮没无闻。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disembodied', '[ˌdɪsɪm\'bɑːdid]', 'adj.无实体的；空洞的 动词disembody的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. Disembodied voices could be heard in the darkness. 在黑暗中听见了人声，却看不见人影。 2. His death disembodied his spirits. 他的死亡使其灵魂脱离了躯体。 3. The troops were disembodied after the war. 战后军队被遣散。 4. Announces a disembodied female voice. 一个空洞的女声播报着，', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bit', '[bɪt]', 'n.少量；小块；片刻；马嚼子；（烟头等的）咬嘴；钻头；钥匙齿；<美口>一角二分半钱；[计]比特 v.给（马等）上嚼口；约束 动词bite的过去式和过去分词', '1. He only put a bit on his plate to make fashion. 他只是拨了一点食物到盘子里做做样子。 2. He assembled the model aircraft bit by bit. 他一块一块地装配飞机模型。 3. Let the broth simmer down a bit more. 让肉汤炖得再久一些吧。 4. The horse was champing the bit . 这匹马格格地咬着马嚼子。', '过去式: bitted 过去分词: bitted 现在分词: bitting 第三人称单数: bits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stricken', '[\'strɪkən]', 'adj.受伤或患病的；受灾的；受挫的；被击中的；与容器口齐平的 suf.表示“深受…之苦的” 动词strike的过去分词.', '1. She was stricken in years when I met her. 我见她时，她已年老体衰。 2. Medical supplies are being dropped to the stricken area. 目前医药用品正空投到灾区。 3. She raised her stricken face and begged for help. 她仰起苦闷的脸，乞求帮助。 4. The stricken tanker began to break up on the rocks. 油轮被击中后撞上礁石,毁了。 5. The two heroic little sisters quickly headed off the panic-stricken sheep. 两个英雄小姐妹赶忙上前拦住受惊的羊群。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trickle', '[\'trɪkl]', 'vi.滴流；慢慢移动 n.细流；徐徐地流', '1. A river that flowed out of the lake was reduced to a trickle. 一条曾经从该湖流出的小河，现在已经变成了一条滴流。 2. Only a trickle of water came out of the pipe. 管子里淌出来的只是小小的细流。 3. No water to trickle down into the cabinets below. 没有水，以涓滴细流下来到机柜下面。', '过去式: trickled 过去分词: trickled 现在分词: trickling 第三人称单数: trickles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shed', '[ʃed]', 'vt.除掉；使脱落；使流出；使清晰 n.小屋；车棚', '1. This method can help students shed inhibitions. 这一方法能帮助学生去除顾虑。 2. Most trees shed their leaves in autumn. 大多数树在秋天落叶。 3. It\'s too late to change your mind now and there is no point in shedding tears. 你现在改变主意已经太迟了,而且为此伤心落泪是毫无用处的。 4. Can you shed any light on the situation? 你能说明一下这个情形吗？ 5. The snow has banked up against the shed. 雪在小屋旁聚积起来。', '过去式: shed 过去分词: shed 现在分词: shedding 第三人称单数: sheds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('croak', '[kroʊk]', 'v.嗄嗄叫；发牢骚；<俚>死 n.呱呱声；哇哇声', '1. A bullfrog was croaking in the distance. 一只牛蛙在远处呱呱地叫。 2. Frogs began to croak with the rainfall. 一下雨青蛙就开始呱呱地叫起来。 3. Everyone seemed rather out of sorts and inclined to croak. 每个人似乎都有点不对劲，想发发牢骚。 4. He sat on the playground listening to the distant croak. 他坐在操场上，聆听远处的蛙鸣。', '形容词: croaky 副词: croakily 过去式: croaked 过去分词: croaked 现在分词: croaking 第三人称单数: croaks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clarion', '[\'klærɪən]', 'n.尖音小号；号角声 adj.嘹亮的', '1. To all the people present, his speech is a clarion call. 对所有在场的人而言，他的演讲都是动人的号召。 2. Our clarion call reverberates the earth, even the deaf shall hear. 金声掷地振群聋。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('putrid', '[\'pjuːtrɪd]', 'adj.腐臭的；腐败的；令人厌恶的', '1. A putrid smell drove us from the room. 一股腐臭的气味迫使我们离开这房间。 2. On the third floor, a window had just been opened, releasing a putrid brown cloud. 在三楼上，一扇窗户已经被仅仅打开，释放腐败的褐色云。 3. Soon there will be a real dearth of customers as the cheater’s putrid reputation becomes known. 很快这个欺骗者的臭名远播，便没有顾客了。', '副词: putridly 名词: putridity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infuse', '[ɪn\'fjuːz]', 'vt.注入；使获得；鼓舞；泡制；倾注（液体）', '1. We must infuse new blood into the Party. 我们必须给党注入新鲜血液。 2. They infuse the young people with patriotism. 他们向年轻人灌输爱国主义精神。 3. The news infused the workers with new life. 那条消息使工人获得新的活力。 4. Don\'t drink the tea until it has finished infusing. 等茶泡好后再喝。', '名词: infuser 过去式: infused 过去分词: infused 现在分词: infusing 第三人称单数: infuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chic', '[ʃiːk]', 'adj.别致的；时髦的 n.别致；时尚', '1. I like your chic hat. 我喜欢你样式别致的帽子。 2. The Ballerina didn\'t even have a chic Russian name to her credit. 这位芭蕾舞演员甚至没有一个很别致的俄罗斯名字来给她增光。 3. She is always so chic, so elegant. 她总是那么时髦，那么优雅。 4. She wears her clothes with chic. 她穿的衣服很雅致。', '副词: chicly 比较级: chicer 最高级: chicest 名词: chicness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('justification', '[ˌdʒʌstɪfɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.辩护；正当的理由', '1. I suppose that, in justification, he could always claim he had a family to support. 我想他反正会以养家为理由来进行辩解。 2. This is not a justification for his actions. 这不是对他行为的辩护。 3. What can be said in justification of his behavior? 能说些什么来为他的行为辩解呢? 4. I can see no justification for dividing the company into smaller units. 我认为没有理由把公司划分为小单位。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('turquoise', '[\'tɜːrkwɔɪz]', 'n.绿松石；青绿色 adj.青绿色的', '1. Blue turquoise is valued as a gemstone. 蓝色的绿松石被视为宝石。 2. The women made baskets and pottery;the men wove textiles and crafted turquoise jewelry. 妇女制造篮子和陶器，男子织布，并用绿松石制做饰品。 3. Turquoise as a cultural carrier offers a great amount of information on disseminating the Central Plain culture all around. 绿松石作为一种文化载体，它承载了中原文化向四周传播的诸多信息。 4. Using colors such as blue, green, turquoise, and silver can create a calm effect. 使用蓝色、绿色、青绿色和银白色，能给人一种平静的氛围。 5. They said it was a very pretty light green or turquoise color. 他们说它是相当淡的绿色或青绿色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forebear', '[\'fɔːrber]', 'n.祖先；祖宗 =forbear.', '1. Our forebear might even teach us a few old tricks that could be used to help the living. 祖先甚至可以教我们一些有助于生活的古老窍门。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recipe', '[\'resəpi]', 'n.秘诀；食谱；药方', '1. What\'s your recipe for success? 你取得成功有什么窍门？ 2. He knows the recipe for this dish. 他知道这道菜的烹饪方法。 3. This recipe will be enough for four servings. 本食谱为四人食用分量。 4. In fact, could I ask you for the recipe? 事实上,我能向你要这道菜的食谱吗?', '名词复数: recipes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('helve', '[helv]', 'n.柄', '1. Do not throw the helve after hatchet. 莫赔了夫人又折兵。 2. The axe goes to the wood where it borrows its helve. 斧头伐木不畏缩，尽管斧柄木头做。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transcendent', '[træn\'sendənt]', 'adj.卓越的；超然的', '1. Nostalgia implies beauty of sorrow and beauty of the transcendent world. 怀旧的审美心理指向是感伤之美和彼岸之美。 2. But in the Zoroastrian faith, Ahura Mazda is abstract and transcendent. 但在琐罗亚斯德教的信仰里面，阿胡玛兹达是抽象和超然的。 3. Therefore, education is essentially transcendent and its real value lies in transcending. 所以，教育本质上具有超越性，教育的真正价值在于超越。', '副词: transcendently 名词: transcendence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fuss', '[fʌs]', 'n.大惊小怪；小题大作；强烈不满或争吵 vi.无事自扰；焦急；对小事激动 vt.扰乱；使焦躁', '1. Stop all this fuss and get on with your work. 别大惊小怪的闹了，继续干你的活儿去吧。 2. I do not want to make a fuss over such a trifle. 我不想为这种小事大惊小怪。 3. That\'s why we\'re making such a fuss over her. 所以我们才为她这么小题大作。 4. There is sure to be a fuss when my parents find the window is broken. 我父母发现窗子被打破后，一定会有一番斥责。 5. Stop fussing and eat your food! 别大惊小怪的，吃你的东西吧！ 6. Don\'t fuss me while I\'m driving. 我开车时别打搅我.', '名词: fusser 过去式: fussed 过去分词: fussed 现在分词: fussing 第三人称单数: fusses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unsound', '[ˌʌn\'saʊnd]', 'adj.腐烂变质的；谬误的；无根据的；靠不住的', '1. In theory as well as in practice, the idea is unsound. 这个主意在理论上和实践上都站不住脚。 2. Do not listen to unsound advice. 别去听无根据的劝告。 3. I am afraid that it is an unsound investment. 我担心这项投资靠不住。', '副词: unsoundly 比较级: unsounder 最高级: unsoundest 名词: unsoundness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('guy', '[ɡaɪ]', 'n.家伙；(男)人 n.拉索；牵索 vt.嘲笑', '1. This ordinary quiet guy just freaked out and shot ten people. 这个平时温和的家伙简直发疯了，开枪打死了十个人。 2. I made a harmless remark to some guy at the bar and he swung at me. 在酒吧里我向某个家伙说了句无恶意的话，他就向我打了一拳。 3. He\'s a nice guy. 他是个好人。 4. Sean is really a very sweet guy and loaded with talent. 西恩真是一个讨人喜欢的小伙，而且多才多艺。 5. Gather all your friends and laugh to tears when the poor guy starts farting. 召集你的朋友一起嘲笑那个被整的放屁朋友。', '过去式: guyed 过去分词: guyed 现在分词: guying 第三人称单数: guys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hyperbole', '[haɪ\'pɜːrbəli]', 'n.夸张法', '1. American humor is founded largely on hyperbole. 美国式的幽默主要以夸张为基础。 2. The phrase is of course a hyperbole. 这句话当然有些夸张。 3. The film is being promoted with all the usual hyperbole. 这部电影正以所有惯用的夸张手法大力宣传。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retinue', '[\'retənuː]', 'n.侍从；随员', '1. The Queen was flanked by a retinue of bodyguards and policemen. 女王左右有保镖和警察护卫着。 2. The king arrived first, and his retinue came next. 国王先到，随后是他的侍从们。 3. She is a retinue of doctor. 她是医生的助手。 4. He strode past with his retinue of aides. 他与他的随员们大步走了过去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('materialize', '[mə\'tɪriəlaɪz]', 'v.成为现实；成有形；实现；具体化；出现', '1. The threatened strike never materialized. 扬言要举行罢工，却从未付诸行动。 2. Our plans did not materialize. 我们的计画未能实现。 3. He claimed that he could make ghosts materialize. 他声称他可以使鬼魂现身。 4. He failed to materialize yesterday. 昨天他并没有出现。', '名词: materialization 过去式: materialized 过去分词: materialized 现在分词: materializing 第三人称单数: materializes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('depredation', '[ˌdeprə\'deɪʃn]', 'n.掠夺；破坏、蹂躏', '1. Most southern towns have suffered from the reckless depredation of the armed gang. 大多数南方城镇都遭受过这帮武装匪徒的鲁蛮掠夺。 2. Even so, they might not be so vulnerable to human depredation if they did not, like humans, reproduce so slowly. 尽管如此，如果它们不像人类一样繁殖如此缓慢，它们对人类的掠夺也不会如此无能为力。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fallible', '[\'fæləbl]', 'adj.易犯错误的；可能不正确的', '1. Human beings are only fallible. 人类本身易犯错误 2. Attention, please, this is the most fallible course. 这是比较容易出问题的环节。 3. Everybody is fallible. 人人都难免有错。 4. Memory is selective and fallible. 记忆有选择性而且会出错。', '副词: fallibly 名词: fallibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expound', '[ɪk\'spaʊnd]', 'v.详细说明；阐述；解释', '1. Laws are a dead letter without courts to expound and define their true meaning and operation. 法律如果没有法院来详细说明和解释其真正意义和作用，就是一纸空文。 2. He has an hour to expound his views to the public. 他有一小时可以向大众阐述他的观点。 3. Secondly, I expound the trend and reason for the administration legislates. 其次，阐述了行政立法的发展趋势及成因。 4. Laws are a dead letter without courts to expound and define their true meaning and operation. 法律如果没有法院来详细说明和解释其真正意义和作用，就是一纸空文。', '名词: expounder 过去式: expounded 过去分词: expounded 现在分词: expounding 第三人称单数: expounds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clairvoyance', '[kler\'vɔɪəns]', 'n.千里眼；超人的洞察力', '1. Precognition is a form of clairvoyance. 预知是超视力的一种形式。 2. Thus, telepathy is actually a specific form of clairvoyance. 心灵感应实际上是超视力的一种特殊形式。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revere', '[rɪ\'vɪr]', 'n.（R~）里维尔（美国马萨诸塞州城市避暑胜地）； v.尊敬；敬畏；崇敬', '1. Students revere the old professor. 学生尊敬这位老教授。 2. I revere him greatly. 我很尊敬他。 3. I will teach you to revere and worshipfully fear the Lord. 我要教导你们敬畏耶和华。 4. People came to the memorial to revere the memory of the great leader. 人们来到纪念馆崇敬地纪念这位伟大的领袖。', '过去式: revered 过去分词: revered 现在分词: revering 第三人称单数: reveres');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('husk', '[hʌsk]', 'n.外壳；皮；无用之物；支架 v.剥壳；削皮', '1. The husk of this coconut is particularly strong. 椰子的外壳很明显非常坚固。 2. How can we remove the husk of the grains? 我们怎样去掉谷物的外皮？', '名词: husker 过去式: husked 过去分词: husked 现在分词: husking 第三人称单数: husks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('converge', '[kən\'vɜːrdʒ]', 'vi.聚合；集中；会聚 vt.使集合', '1. The roads converge just before the station. 四面八方的道路会聚在火车站前。 2. These lines converge at a certain point. 这些线集中于某一点。 3. If you look at the end of your nose, your eyes converge. 如果你看着你的鼻尖，你的两眼就向一点集中。 4. In this case the rays obviously do not converge. 此时，光线显然不会聚。', '过去式: converged 过去分词: converged 现在分词: converging 第三人称单数: converges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wallow', '[\'wɑːloʊ]', 'v.打滚；沉溺于；(船等)颠簸 n.打滚；打滚的地方；堕落', '1. He threw himself upon his back and wallow at my feet. 他四脚朝天地倒下去，在我脚边打滚。 2. The children enjoyed watching the hippopotamus wallowing in the mud. 孩子们喜欢看河马在泥中打滚。 3. He seemed to be wallowing in luxury. 他似乎沉溺于豪华的享乐中。 4. We should not wallow in the valley of despair. 我们不应该陷在绝望中不能自拔。 5. His parents are partly responsible for his wallow. 他的父母对他的堕落负有部分责任。', '名词: wallower 过去式: wallowed 过去分词: wallowed 现在分词: wallowing 第三人称单数: wallows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('annals', '[\'ænlz]', 'n.纪年表；年鉴；年报', '1. His name will go down in the annals. 他的名字将载入编年史。 2. The tournament added a brilliant page to the annals of world table-tennis. 这次比赛给世界乒乓球史增添了光辉的一页。 3. The research is published in the current issue of the Annals of Internal Medicine. 该研究发表在最近一期内科学年鉴上。 4. The annals of the society have been published. 社会年刊已经出版了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rambunctious', '[ræm\'bʌŋkʃəs]', 'adj.粗暴的；喧闹的；放纵的', '1. Their rambunctious son always got into trouble. 他们那个不受管束的儿子老是惹麻烦。 2. Joey: Oh, like you\'ve never gotten a little rambunctious with Ross. 你和罗斯就不会有小动作? 3. It\'s not the chirping,rambunctious play that they did when they first arrived. 他们现在已经不像刚开始见面那会儿，总是冲着对方乱叫，或者在玩耍时动作粗暴。 4. Joey: Oh, like you‘ve never gotten a little rambunctious with Ross. 粗暴的，骚乱的，难控制的。重音在第二个元音上。', '副词: rambunctiously 名词: rambunctiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cavalcade', '[ˌkævl\'keɪd]', 'n.(车或马的)队列；系列；连续', '1. A cavalcade processed through town. 马车队列队从城里经过。 2. Welcome to join the cavalcade of block city! 欢迎加入围城游戏行列！ 3. He was watching the road with its long cavalcade of fleeing city-people. 他正看着路上连绵不尽的逃难的城里人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tautological', '[ˌtɔːtə\'lɒdʒɪkl]', 'adj.重复的；赘述的', '1. We say that the truth-conditions are tautological. 我们称该真值条件是重言式的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compliance', '[kəm\'plaɪəns]', 'n.顺从；服从；遵守；屈服；柔度；灵活性', '1. In compliance with your wishes, we have withdrawn our suggestion. 遵照你的要求我们已将建议撤销。 2. It is important to drive in compliance with the traffic laws. 行驶时遵守交通规则是很重要的。 3. Compliance is expected of all members. 要求全体人员都遵守. 4. He was terrified into compliance. 他被吓唬得屈服了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('integrate', '[\'ɪntɪɡreɪt]', 'v.整合；结合；取消隔离；求积分 adj.完整的；组合的', '1. The Message Board tool is an easy tool to integrate into daily school life. 留言板是一种非常方便的工具,可以将其整合到日常学校生活中。 2. Only 20% of teachers report feeling very well prepared to integrate education technology into classroom instruction. 仅有20%25的教师认为他们感觉能够将技术与课堂教学进行整合。 3. I learn quickly. I integrate disparate concepts with relative ease. 我学习速度很快,我能将完全不同的概念毫不费力地结合在一起。 4. We must carry out the Party\'s education policy that education should serve socialist modernization and the people and integrate itself with productive labor and social practice. 全面贯彻党的教育方针 5. Science is not an independent knowledge system, it has to integrate from various perspectives in order to reach a full understanding. 但是科学并非独立的知识系统，必须从不同的角度作综合性研究，方能对它有较完整的认识。', '形容词: integrative 过去式: integrated 过去分词: integrated 现在分词: integrating 第三人称单数: integrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('provenance', '[\'prɑːvənəns]', 'n.出处；起源', '1. The provenance of this poem not clear. 这首诗出处不详。 2. This plant\'s provenance is Asia. 这种植物原产于亚洲。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corny', '[\'kɔːrni]', 'adj.谷类的；平淡无奇的；乡巴佬的；陈词滥调；长鸡眼的', '1. Fred\'s jokes are always so corny. 弗雷德的笑话总是如此毫无新意。 2. He has an endless supply of corny jokes. 他有说不完的老掉牙的笑话。 3. The movie was just so corny that I had to leave before it finished. 这部电影太老土了我不得不在电影没放完之前离开。 4. The boss gets too corny when he talk to the worker. 老板每次跟员工说话都是陈腔滥调。', '副词: cornily 比较级: cornier 最高级: corniest 名词: corniness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abrupt', '[ə\'brʌpt]', 'adj.突然的；唐突的；意外的；陡峭的', '1. The river takes an abrupt bend to the west. 这河突然向西转弯。 2. His speech comes to an abrupt stop. 他的演讲突然停止了。 3. That young man has an abrupt manner. 那个年轻人态度很无礼。 4. His manner of speaking was quite abrupt. 他的说话方式很唐突。', '副词: abruptly 名词: abruptness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('civil', '[\'sɪvl]', 'adj.公民的；文明的；国内的；民用的；民事的；【建】土木的', '1. The law shall strictly protect civil rights. 法律应严格保护公民的权利。 2. The presence of the army should act as a check on civil unrest. 军队的存在应能制止民间的动乱。 3. The boy was so cold and even didn\'t return a civil greeting. 那个男孩是那么的冷淡,他甚至都没有回敬一个礼貌的问候。 4. The America Civil War broke out during the presidency of Lincoln. 在林肯就职其间,美国爆发了内战。', '副词: civilly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('implication', '[ˌɪmplɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.牵连；含意；暗示；卷入', '1. His implication in the crime was obvious to all. 大家都清楚他和这一罪行有牵连。 2. The trial resulted in the implication of several major figures in the organization. 审讯结果表明这个组织中几个主要人物都牵连在案。 3. He has not actually realized the full implication. 他还没有真正认识到全部含意。 4. The new report has far-reaching implications for the future of broadcasting. 这一新报告对广播业的前途有些意味深长的暗示。', '形容词: implicative 副词: implicatively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('improvised', '[ɪmprə\'vaɪzd]', 'adj.即席而作的；临时的 动词improvise的过去式和过去分词.', '1. A type of music that originated in the West Indies,notably in Trinidad,and is characterized by improvised lyrics on topical or broadly humorous subjects. 卡力骚曲，一种起源于西印度的音乐，在特立尼达有影响，主要特征是根据主题或广泛的幽默体裁即席而作的音律。 2. We shook down a straw mattress as an improvised bed. 我们在地上摊开一条草垫作为临时床铺。 3. On her right hand she had what looked like an improvised glove . 她右手戴着一只看来象是临时凑合着用的手套。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('responsive', '[rɪ\'spɑːnsɪv]', 'adj.回答的；应答的；易感应的', '1. Mentally responsive and perceptive; quick. 思维敏捷的思维反应迅速且感觉灵敏的; 快速敏捷的 2. Not responsive, as to treatment or stimuli. 无感应的对治疗或刺激没有反应的 3. Highly aware of and responsive to what is fashionable and up-to-date. 赶时髦的，新潮的对于流行的和时新的东西很敏感的并且积极响应的', '副词: responsively 名词: responsiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boggle', '[\'bɑːɡl]', 'v.犹豫；吃惊；困惑', '1. He boggled at the thought of swimming in winter. 他想到要在冬天游泳就有些犹豫。 2. Don\'t boggle, the good chance will be lost. 别犹豫不决，否则会错失良机。 3. My neighbour wears his dressing-gown to work. The mind boggles! 我的邻居穿着晨衣去上班。真不可思议！ 4. And of course, the cultural references are likely to boggle your mind. 当然，里面的文化内容可能会让你摸不着头脑。', '名词: boggler 过去式: boggled 过去分词: boggled 现在分词: boggling 第三人称单数: boggles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('upswing', '[\'ʌpswɪŋ]', 'n.上升；增长；改进；回升时期 v.向上摆动；提高；回升', '1. This policy led to an upswing in the party\'s popularity. 这一政策使该党深得人心。 2. Many analysts are predicting an upswing in the economy. 许多分析家预测经济将会增长。 3. It\'s a tremendous upswing in technological progress. 这是技术发展上的巨大进步。 4. The economy seems to be on the upswing. 经济好像处在回升时期。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('totem', '[\'toʊtəm]', 'n.图腾；图腾形象', '1. He also hits pretty hard with his totem. 同时他也能够运用他的图腾柱使出强力的打击。 2. A social system is based on affiliations to totems. 基于图腾的紧密联系之上的一种社会制度。', '形容词: totemic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trivia', '[\'trɪviə]', 'n.琐事；不重要的事情', '1. She never immersed herself in that sort of trivia. 她从来不沉湎于往日琐事。 2. Their quarrels about the trivia are always interminable. 他们对琐事的争吵总是没完没了。 3. Much of our research is wasted on trivia. 我们的许多研究都浪费在一些无足轻重的琐事上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('refresh', '[rɪ\'freʃ]', 'v.（使）恢复精神；提神；提醒', '1. A cool drink refreshed me after my long walk. 走了很长的一段路之后，一杯冷饮使我恢复了精神。 2. He has drunk one cup of coffee to refresh oneself. 他喝了一杯咖啡提神。 3. I refreshed myself with a cup of coffee. 我喝了一杯咖啡给自己提提神。 4. Let me refresh your memory with some fact. 我来提几件事帮你恢复记忆吧。', '过去式: refreshed 过去分词: refreshed 现在分词: refreshing 第三人称单数: refreshes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('panoramic', '[ˌpænə\'ræmɪk]', 'adj.全景的', '1. Most rooms enjoy panoramic views of the sea. 大多数房间都能看到海的全景。 2. The new machine design also supports this excellent panoramic view. 新机器的整体设计提供了最佳的全景视野。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agile', '[\'ædʒl]', 'adj.（动作）敏捷的；灵活的；（头脑）机灵的', '1. He was quick and agile and he didn\'t mind losing. 他敏捷，灵活，输了不在乎。 2. You might sometimes need an agile negotiator. 你有时会需要一个灵活的谈判代表。 3. The problem that he answers newsman is very agile. 他回答新闻记者的问题很灵活。 4. One need an agile mind to solve puzzles. 解谜必须有机灵的头脑。', '副词: agilely 名词: agileness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wispy', '[\'wɪspi]', 'adj.小束的；细微的；模糊的', '1. A wisp of hair had escaped from under her hat. 一绺头发从她的帽下露出来。 2. A wisp of hair straggled across her ear. 一束头发散落在她耳朵上。 3. A small wisp or tuft,as of wool or cotton. 一束或一簇，如羊毛或棉花 4. A small wisp or tuft, as of wool or cotton. 一束或一簇，如羊毛或棉花', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tantalize', '[\'tæntəlaɪz]', 'v.（以可望而不可即之物）逗引或招惹（人或动物）；使着急', '1. Give the dog the bone don\'t tantalize him. 把那块骨头给那条狗吧--别让它乾著急了。 2. He was tantalized by visions of power and wealth. 他追求不到可望而不可即的权力和财富，受尽了折磨。', '副词: tantalizingly 名词: tantalization 过去式: tantalized 过去分词: tantalized 现在分词: tantalizing 第三人称单数: tantalizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preside', '[prɪ\'zaɪd]', 'v.主持；任主席；统辖', '1. Mr Smith will preside over the next meeting. 史密斯先生将主持下一次会议。 2. The old professor had presided over a seminar for theoretical physicists. 老教授主持了一次理论物理学家的研讨会。 3. He will preside at the election of school officers. 他是校际选举大会的主席。 4. When the Assembly holds its meeting, the chairman shall preside over the Assembly. 会员大会召开会议时，理事长担任会议主席。', '名词: presider 过去式: presided 过去分词: presided 现在分词: presiding 第三人称单数: presides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quote', '[kwoʊt]', 'v.引述；报价；举证 n.引用', '1. She asked the reporter not to quote her remarks. 她要求记者不要引述她的话。 2. Please quote your price in terms of pound. 请您报盘时用英镑报价。 3. Can you quote me a recent instance? 你能给我举一个最近的例子吗？ 4. A direct quote was taken from his speech. 直接引用他的演讲。', '名词: quoter 过去式: quoted 过去分词: quoted 现在分词: quoting 第三人称单数: quotes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enlightening', '[ɪn\'laɪtnɪŋ]', 'adj.有启迪的；使人感悟的 动词enlighten的现在分词.', '1. She was anxious to enlighten me about the events that led up to the dispute. 她急着要使我明白引起这场争执的那些事情。 2. The act or a means of enlightening. 启迪启迪的行为或方式', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pastor', '[\'pæstər]', 'n.牧师 v.作...牧师', '1. He was the son of a poor pastor. 他是一个穷牧师的儿子。 2. The villagers all loved the kind pastor. 村民们都爱戴这个好心的牧师。 3. We have no pastor at present: the church is run by five deacons. 我们目前没有牧师:教会的事是由五位执事管理的。 4. He was the son of a poor pastor. 他是一个穷牧师的儿子。', '名词: pastorship 过去式: pastored 过去分词: pastored 现在分词: pastoring 第三人称单数: pastors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appetizing', '[\'æpɪtaɪzɪŋ]', 'adj.开胃的；促进食欲的 =appetising.', '1. The roast beef is very appetizing. 烤牛肉让人胃口大开。 2. The list of ingredients sounds very appetizing. 这张单子上列的配料听起来使人馋涎欲滴.', '副词: appetizingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sequestrate', '[\'siːkwəstreɪt]', 'vt.扣押；查封；没收', '1. No onecan sequestrate his estates. 任何人都不能没收他的资产。 2. No one can sequestrate his estates. 他就是一国之君，既自给，又自立。 3. Scientists at Cornell University, led by Lehmann, are working on ways to sequestrate carbon in biochar-enriched soil. 在莱曼的带领下，康奈尔大学的科学家们正在研究如何将碳从富含生物炭的土壤中分离出来。 4. Otherwise, we will break the units, sequestrate your 20% deposit.At the same time, we will recourse the rest expense by law. 否则,我司将立刻拆机,没收其20%25定金,同时,将通过法律途径向其追索其他损失!!!!!', '过去式: sequestrated 过去分词: sequestrated 现在分词: sequestrating 第三人称单数: sequestrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enact', '[ɪ\'nækt]', 'vt.制定法律；扮演', '1. Several bills were enacted at the end of this session of Parliament. 这届国会结束时，好几个议案制定成为法律。 2. Our government has to enact better safety regulations in factories. 我们的政府应该要制定较好的工厂安全法规。 3. Americans are called to enact this promise in our lives and in our laws. 美国人民肩负着一种使命，那就是要竭力将这个诺言变成生活中和法律上的现实。 4. And then we enact one of my cunning rescue operations. 随后我们就会上演我那巧妙的营救行动了。', '形容词: enactable 名词: enactor 过去式: enacted 过去分词: enacted 现在分词: enacting 第三人称单数: enacts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disengage', '[ˌdɪsɪn\'ɡeɪdʒ]', 'v.解除；解开；使脱离', '1. He managed to disengage himself from the contract. 他成功地为自己解除了契约义务。 2. Disengage the clutch and let\'s see what happens. 松手，让我们看看出了什么事。 3. She tried to disengage herself from his grip. 她企图挣脱他牢牢抓住的手。 4. I want to disengage myself from his influence. 我想从他的影响中摆脱出来。', '名词: disengagement 过去式: disengaged 过去分词: disengaged 现在分词: disengaging 第三人称单数: disengages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assemble', '[ə\'sembl]', 'v.集合；收集；装配', '1. The students assembled in the school garden. 学生们在校园集合。 2. If the fire-alarm goes, staff should assemble outside the building. 火警警报响时全体人员应到楼外集合。 3. Assemble your papers and put them in the file . 把你们的论文收集起来归档。 4. The processing and assemble business is a component part of our foreign trade. 加工和装配贸易是我国对外贸易的一个组成部分。', '过去式: assembled 过去分词: assembled 现在分词: assembling 第三人称单数: assembles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emit', '[i\'mɪt]', 'vt.发出，发射；放射；吐露', '1. The cheese was emitting a strong smell. 干酪散发出强烈的气味。 2. A volcano emits smoke and ashes. 火山散发着烟和灰。 3. He was so pale that he seemed to emit a pearly glow. 他白得似乎发出像一样珍珠的微光。 4. Fireflies emit light but not heat. 萤火虫发光但不放出热。', '名词: emitter 过去式: emitted 过去分词: emitted 现在分词: emitting 第三人称单数: emits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vessel', '[\'vesl]', 'n.容器；器皿；船；舰；脉管，血管', '1. The simplest calorimeter is a metal vessel used with a thermometer. 最简单的量热计是一个带温度计的金属容器。 2. A pot is a vessel for holding food. 锅是盛食物的器皿。 3. They plotted the new position of each vessel. 他们标明每艘船的新位置。 4. There are some fishing vessels in the harbor. 港湾里有许多渔船。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('theoretical', '[ˌθiːə\'retɪkl]', 'adj.理论上的', '1. These findings have both theoretical and practical applications. 这些发现具有理论和实际的应用。 2. Theoretical study must be closely integrated with practice. 理论学习要紧密结合实际。 3. It\'s a theoretical possibility, but I don\'t suppose it will happen. 这是一种理论上的可能性，但我认为这种情况不会发生。', '副词: theoretically 异体字: theoretic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flair', '[fler]', 'n.天赋；才华；鉴别力', '1. Cordellia has a flair for languages. 很有语言天赋。 2. The flair system will be tweaked to allow for it be detached from league success. 该天赋系统将被调整，以便它从联赛的成功分离。 3. She performs the songs with style and flair. 她演唱歌曲既有风度又有才华。 4. He shows little flair for this subject. 他在这个科目上没有什么才华。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('align', '[ə\'laɪn]', 'vt.使结盟；使一致；使成一行；调整；排列 vi.成一条线', '1. Our company should align ourselves with theirs. 我们的公司必须与他们的公司合作。 2. The iron flings align themselves in the direction of the magnetic field. 铁屑按磁场的方向排列。 3. Could you align this table with those? 你能把这张桌子同那些桌子排成一行吗？ 4. How can I align these bricks with the rest of the wall? 我怎么才能将这些砖与其余的墙对齐(排成直线)?', '名词: aligner');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ragtime', '[\'ræɡtaɪm]', 'n.拉格泰姆音乐；繁音拍子 adj.滑稽的；不严肃的', '1. Ragtime music was popular in the early 20th century. 20世纪初期拉格泰姆音乐很流行。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tourniquet', '[\'tɜːrnəkət]', 'n.止血带；压脉器', '1. A tourniquet should never be used. 决不要使用止血带。 2. The tourniquet should occlude venous and lymphatic return. 止血带应阻断静脉及淋巴回流。 3. I made a tourniquet and was able to stop her wrists from bleeding. 我弄了条止血带，能让她的手停止流血。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pulley', '[\'pʊli]', 'n.滑车；滑轮；皮带轮', '1. There is no bucket and pulley to this well. 那口井没有吊桶和滑车。 2. This allowed the oil in the nose drive to leak out around the pulley. 这允许油在要在滑车周遭渗漏的鼻子运动里。 3. The lifting device is a system of rope and pulley. 这种起重装置是由缆索和滑轮组成的。 4. Pulley bearings are frictionless. 滑轮轴承是无摩擦的。', '名词复数: pulleys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prognosticate', '[prɒg\'nɒstɪˌkeɪt]', 'vt.预知；预言；预测', '1. Then they prognosticate on whether what happened in Argentina is a good sign for the senator from New York. 然后他们会预言，在阿根廷发生的事，对于这位来自纽约的参议员而言，是否是个好兆头。 2. It is the most important matter to influence the stability and prognosticate of surgery. 术后角膜愈合反应是影响手术稳定性及预测性的重要原因之一。 3. In order to prognosticate the prospecting targets using geochemical data from mine districts, correspondence cluster analysis is applied. 摘要为利用矿区地球化学数据进行找矿靶区预测，采用了对应聚类分析方法。', '形容词: prognosticative 名词: prognostication 过去式: prognosticated 过去分词: prognosticated 现在分词: prognosticating 第三人称单数: prognosticates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insubordinate', '[ˌɪnsə\'bɔːdɪnət]', 'adj.不顺从的；反抗的', '1. Many teachers dislike insubordinate children. 很多教师不喜欢不顺从的儿童。 2. That\'s an insubordinate response. 这种回答是目无领导的。 3. To be insubordinate is to invite dismissal from a corporation. 不服从将会被公司解雇。 4. The professor cited several instances of insubordinate behavior. 教授引用数个反抗行为的例证。', '副词: insubordinately 名词: insubordination');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swift', '[swɪft]', 'adj.快的；迅速的；敏捷的 n.雨燕；线轴 Swift. n.斯威夫特（人名）', '1. His landing is both swift and sure. 他的落地既快又稳。 2. He made a remarkably swift recovery. 他康复得相当快。 3. They\'ve been very swift to deny these rumors. 他们在辟谣方面反应迅速。 4. With the failure of the peace talks, all hopes of a swift end to the war have flown out of the window. 和谈失败后,迅速结束战争的希望都已化为乌有。 5. feel a strong antagonism for sb 6. The Augustan age of English literature includes the writers Dryden, Swift and Pope. 在英国文学的全盛时期 有德莱顿，斯威夫特和蒲柏等文豪。', '副词: swiftly 比较级: swifter 最高级: swiftest 名词: swiftness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lash', '[læʃ]', 'n.鞭子；鞭打；睫毛；讽刺 v.鞭打；摆动；抨击', '1. By rod and lash, the boy was punished. 木棍和鞭子用来惩罚这个男孩。 2. The pirate captain beat his crew with a lash. 海盗船长用鞭子抽打他的船员。 3. With a lash of its tail the tiger leaped at her. 老虎把尾巴一甩朝她扑过来。 4. Does the Lash Extender come in other colors apart from black ? 睫毛增长液除黑色外，还有什么其它颜色？ 5. He began to lash Luke unmercifully across buttocks and thighs. 他开始无情地鞭打卢克的屁股和大腿。', '过去式: lashed 过去分词: lashed 现在分词: lashing 第三人称单数: lashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('explosive', '[ɪk\'sploʊsɪv]', 'adj.爆炸(性)的；引发争论的；大声的 n.炸药', '1. Hydrogen is highly explosive. 氢极易爆炸。 2. The most impressive volcanic phenomena are explosive eruptions. 最令人难忘的火山现象是爆炸喷发。 3. The question of race today is an explosive one. 种族问题在今天是一个会引起激烈争论的问题。 4. He bent double with explosive laughter. 他大笑得直不起腰来。 5. We carefully moved the explosive to another place. 我们谨慎地把炸药转移到了另一个地方。', '副词: explosively 名词: explosiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dyspeptic', '[dɪs\'peptɪk]', 'adj.消化不良的；胃弱的；脾气暴躁的 n.患消化不良的人', '1. Child coating on the tongue is hoar, be dyspeptic? 孩子舌苔发白,是消化不良吗? 2. See the pictures, read the pictures until you get dyspeptic. 看图、读图，直到看得你消化不良。 3. Some of the best material here is Beckett\'s dyspeptic book talk. 此卷最好看的地方是贝克特对某些书的恶评。 4. Knowing when to give endoscopy to a primary dyspeptic patient is a difficult decision for any gastroenterologist. 摘要判定消化不良患者，何者须施行内视镜检查，一直困扰著胃肠科医师；', '副词: dyspeptically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scare', '[sker]', 'v.受惊吓；恐吓；吓走 n.惊吓；惊恐', '1. You scare them to death with your mouth. 你一开口就能把人吓死。 2. We\'ll scare her out of telling the police. 我们要把她吓得不敢报警。 3. His threats scared them out of carrying out the plan. 他的威胁迫使他们不敢实行该计划。 4. The dog scared the thief away. 狗把小偷吓走了。 5. You did give me a scare. 你真吓了我一跳。', '名词: scarer 过去式: scared 过去分词: scared 现在分词: scaring 第三人称单数: scares');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blemish', '[\'blemɪʃ]', 'n.瑕疵；污点；缺点 v.玷污；损害', '1. These wine glasses were sold at half price because of blemishes in the jade. 这些酒杯半价出售，因为玉上有瑕疵。 2. There is a blemish in the swimming suit. 这件游泳衣上有个污点。 3. That mole is a blemish on his face. 那个黑痣是他脸上的缺点。 4. His reputation was blemished by a newspaper article alleging he had taken bribes. 报纸上一篇文章说他受贿，他的声誉因此受到玷污。', '名词: blemisher 过去式: blemished 过去分词: blemished 现在分词: blemishing 第三人称单数: blemishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brattish', '[b\'rætɪʃ]', 'adj.(小孩)讨厌的；不礼貌的；不听话的；宠坏的', '1. The brat sicked his dog on the passer-by. 那个顽童纵狗去咬过路人。 2. That spoiled brat is used to having his own way. 那位被宠坏的小孩习惯于我行我素。 3. Deep down, Kobe is still the spoiled brat. 更深一层说，科比还是一个被宠怀的毛孩子。 4. \"Who said it wasn\'t, brat?\" Madam sounded angry. 大娘很生气的说：“毛丫头，谁说值得?', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('charter', '[\'tʃɑːrtər]', 'n.宪章；特许；(船、机、车等的)租赁 vt.包租；特许；发给 ... 执照 adj.特许的', '1. You should read the Charter of the United Nations. 你应该阅读一下联合国宪章。 2. The rights of our citizens are governed by charter. 我们公民的权利是由宪章规定的。 3. The company was granted a charter trade in the occupied territory. 这家公司被授予特权，可以在被占领地区进行贸易活动。 4. The holiday-makers chartered a boat to go fishing. 渡假者租了一艘船去钓鱼。', '名词: charterer 过去式: chartered 过去分词: chartered 现在分词: chartering 第三人称单数: charters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('destitute', '[\'destɪtuːt]', 'adj.穷困的；赤贫的；缺乏的', '1. When he died, his family was left completely destitute. 他死时家里一贫如洗。 2. The hurricane left thousands of people destitute. 这场飓风造成的几千人失去了一切。 3. Here is an asylum for the care of mentally ill or destitute people. 这儿是一家照顾精神病患者和赤贫人员的收容所。 4. They are destitute of common sense. 他们缺乏常识。', '名词: destituteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incriminate', '[ɪn\'krɪmɪneɪt]', 'v.牵连；控告；使负罪', '1. She refused to make a statement to the police in case she incriminated herself. 她拒绝向警方作陈述以免受连累。 2. No one can be forced to incriminate himself. 没有人有义务证明自己有罪。 3. He is accused of perjury with the intention of incriminate his employer. 他被控告犯有意图加罪于其雇主的伪证罪。', '形容词: incriminatory 名词: incrimination 过去式: incriminated 过去分词: incriminated 现在分词: incriminating 第三人称单数: incriminates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('animation', '[ˌænɪ\'meɪʃn]', 'n.活泼；生气；兴奋；动画片；动画片制作', '1. They talked of their holiday plans with great animation. 他们非常起劲地谈着度假计划。 2. He was full of colour and animation. 他充满魅力,生机勃勃。 3. We felt an animation about the ambitious plan. 我们对此宏伟规划感到兴奋。 4. The animation is awesome and gets better and better every year. 动画片尤其精采，而且一年比一年好看。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rankle', '[\'ræŋkl]', 'v.化脓；发炎；惹怒；使痛苦', '1. The insult still rankled in his mind. 他对那次受辱仍耿耿於怀。 2. The insult still rankles in his mind. 他对那次受辱仍然耿耿于怀。', '过去式: rankled 过去分词: rankled 现在分词: rankling 第三人称单数: rankles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tease', '[tiːz]', 'n.揶揄者；戏弄 v.欺负；嘲弄', '1. He is a terrible tease. 他特别爱戏弄人。 2. It\'s too bad of you to tease the child like that. 你那样逗弄小孩真不好。 3. You must never tease a child because he stutters . 你切不可因为一个孩子口吃而去取笑他。 4. Don\'t take it seriously. He\'s only teasing. 别把它当真，他只不过是在开玩笑。', '副词: teasingly 过去式: teased 过去分词: teased 现在分词: teasing 第三人称单数: teases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('staunch', '[stɔːntʃ]', 'adj.坚定的；坚固的；忠实可信的；不漏水的 vt.止住；止血 =stanch.', '1. He\'s a staunch supporter of the monarchy. 他是君主制的坚定拥护者。 2. They are staunch soldiers. 他们是忠诚的战士。 3. And the fingers trying to staunch the bloody wound at his neck. 和试图止住脖子上正在流血的伤口的手指时会有什么感觉。 4. Messy rescues of Citigroup and Bank of America have failed to staunch their losses. 对花旗和美洲银行棘手的营救并没有止住他们的亏损。', '副词: staunchly 异体字: stanch 比较级: stauncher/stancher 最高级: staunchest/stanchest 名词: staunchness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inspiration', '[ˌɪnspə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.灵感；鼓舞人心(的东西)；吸气', '1. Many poets and artists have drawn their inspiration from nature. 许多诗人和艺术家从大自然中获得他们的灵感。 2. Her speeches have ever been a fount of inspiration to her audiences. 她的演说对于听众来说永远是灵感之源。 3. His wife was a constant inspiration to him. 他的妻子经常鼓励他。 4. Let\'s give mutual support and inspiration to each other. 让我们互相支持，互相鼓励。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('humiliate', '[hjuː\'mɪlieɪt]', 'vt.使 ... 蒙羞；使丢脸', '1. She was humiliated because her children behaved so badly. 她为她的孩子表现不好而感到羞辱。 2. Though I aim to defeat you, should I succeed, I will not humiliate you. 虽然我的目标是战胜你,但就算我胜利了,那并不会让你蒙羞。 3. The boy humiliate his parents by behaving badly in front of the guests. 那男孩在客人面前表现不好,使父母丢面子。 4. I didn\'t want to humiliate her in front of her colleagues. 我不想当着她同事们的面令她难堪。', '过去式: humiliated 过去分词: humiliated 现在分词: humiliating 第三人称单数: humiliates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sorcery', '[\'sɔːrsəri]', 'n.巫术；魔法', '1. At that time most people believe in sorcery and witchcraft . 那时候大多数人相信巫术和魔法 2. The house was disappeared by sorcery. 这座房子被魔法变没了。', '形容词: sorcerous 副词: sorcerously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pore', '[pɔːr]', 'n.毛孔；小孔 v.熟读；钻研；沉思', '1. He was sweating through every pore. 他每个毛孔都在冒汗。 2. Sweat exudes through the pores. 汗从毛孔中渗出。 3. Water seeped into the pores of the rock. 水迅速被岩石的空隙吸收。 4. He had spent several hours in the library poring over those musty documents. 他一连好几个小时呆在图书馆里仔细翻阅那些发霉味的文献资料。', '过去式: pored 过去分词: pored 现在分词: poring 第三人称单数: pores');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preservative', '[prɪ\'zɜːrvətɪv]', 'n.防腐剂；预防法；预防药 adj.保存的；有保存力的；防腐的', '1. Salt is a common food preservative. 盐是一种常用的食物防腐剂。 2. It is used as a preservative in certain acid food products. 在某些酸性食物制品中它被使用作为防腐剂。 3. For the first, the best preservative to keep the mind in health, is the faithful admonition of a friend. 说到第一种，最能保人心神之健康的预防药就是朋友的忠言规谏。 4. The fact is that ascorbic acid is only the preservative part of naturally occurring vitamin C. 事实上，抗坏血酸只是天然维生素C的能够保存的部分。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('husky', '[\'hʌski]', 'adj.声音沙哑的；强壮的 n.哈士奇；爱斯基摩狗；强壮的人', '1. The teacher speaks with a husky voice. 老师以嘶哑的声音说话。 2. I\'m still a bit husky after the recent cold. 我最近患过感冒，声音还有些沙哑。 3. A husky sergeant opened the car door. 一个大个子警长把车门拉开。 4. Husky seems to be a little silly,but quite cute. 哈士奇看起来有点傻乎乎，但却挺可爱。', '副词: huskily 比较级: huskier 最高级: huskiest 名词复数: huskies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('serendipity', '[ˌserən\'dɪpəti]', 'n.善于发掘新奇事物的天赋；易遇奇缘的运气', '1. When destiny has a sense of humor, it is called serendipity. 当命运富有幽默感时,即被称之为缘分。 2. Even your own life is filled with examples of serendipity. 甚至你的生活中也充满了意外收获的例子。', '形容词: serendipitous 副词: serendipitously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rattle', '[\'rætl]', 'vi.嘎嘎作响；喋喋不休 vt.使惊惶失措；使恼火；使作响；急促地谈讲 n.嘎嘎声；嘎嘎响的东西；拔浪鼓', '1. When the window blows,all the doors rattle. 只要风一吹,所有的门都吱吱嘎嘎作响。 2. The boy put some stones in a tin box and made them rattle. 男孩把一些石子放在铁盒子里，然后摇得哗啦哗啦地响。 3. The child rattled away merrily. 那孩子快活地喋喋不休地说着。 4. He rattled on about his job, not noticing how bored she was. 他只顾喋喋不休地说自己工作上的事，没注意到她有多麽腻烦。 5. It may, however, rattle the people you\'re meeting. 但是，它会使你要会见的人心慌意乱。 6. The rattle of the engine was very loud. 发动机的嘎嘎声很大。', '过去式: rattled 过去分词: rattled 现在分词: rattling 第三人称单数: rattles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('veneer', '[və\'nɪr]', 'n.薄片镶饰；虚饰或虚伪的外表 vt.加薄片镶饰', '1. The furniture is made of plywood covered in teak veneer. 这家具是用贴柚木薄片的合板做成的。 2. Much modern furniture is not solid but using a sandwich of wood veneer on plywood. 许多现代家俱用的并非实心木料，而是在胶合板上镶上一层木板饰面而已。 3. The panel had a veneer of gold and ivory. 这木板上面镶饰了一层金和象牙。 4. He has a veneer of friendliness. 他有友好的外表。 5. He decided to veneer the pine desk with mahogany. 他决定用桃花心木薄板镶在那张松木桌上。', '名词: veneerer 过去式: veneered 过去分词: veneered 现在分词: veneering 第三人称单数: veneers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('traverse', '[trə\'vɜːrs]', 'n.横贯；横木 v.横贯；穿越；详细讨论；阻止；否认；【计】遍历', '1. The railway traverses hundreds of miles of desert. 这条铁路贯穿数百英里的沙漠。 2. The traverse across the country will be long and arduous. 穿越这个国家将是漫长而又艰苦的旅程。 3. The traverse in the room was easily seen from the doorway. 从门口看过去，很容易看见房间门窗的横档。 4. The railway traverses hundreds of miles of desert. 这条铁路贯穿数百英里的沙漠。', '形容词: traversable 名词: traversal 过去式: traversed 过去分词: traversed 现在分词: traversing 第三人称单数: traverses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('originality', '[əˌrɪdʒə\'næləti]', 'n.独创性；创造力；新颖', '1. The clay figure is a work of great originality. 这尊泥人是颇具独创性的作品。 2. Einstein was distinguished for his originality. 爱因斯坦以其独创性称著。 3. He gives free play to his originality. 他尽情发挥自己的创造力。 4. Creativity and originality are more important than technical skill. 创造力和独创性比专门技术更为重要。', '名词复数: originalities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oatmeal', '[\'oʊtmiːl]', 'n.燕麦片；燕麦粥；浅棕色', '1. The oatmeal is burning. 麦片粥烧焦了。 2. I often eat oatmeal as breakfast. 我经常吃燕麦粥当早饭。 3. The oatmeal lumps if you don\'t stir it well. 如果你不好好搅拌，麦片粥会结块。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('asphyxia', '[æs\'fɪksiə]', 'n.窒息', '1. Oxygen levels below 19.5% may cause asphyxia. 空气中氧含量低于19.', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fang', '[fæŋ]', 'n.尖牙', '1. Some snakes have poisonous fangs. 有些蛇长有毒牙。 2. The dog growled and showed its fangs. 那狗叫个不停，露出了尖牙。', '形容词: fanged');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corrugate', '[\'kɒrəˌgeɪt]', 'v.（使）起波浪形；起皱纹', '1. His brow corrugated with the effort of thinking. 他皱着眉头用心地思考。', '形容词: corrugated 过去式: corrugated 过去分词: corrugated 现在分词: corrugating 第三人称单数: corrugates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detach', '[dɪ\'tætʃ]', 'vt.使分离；拆卸；派遣 [计算机] 脱离.', '1. He detached a link from a chain. 他从链子上拆下一个链环。 2. I tried to detach myself from the reality of these terrible events. 我尽力使自己从这些可怕事件的现实中摆脱出来。 3. We should detach good apples from bad. 我们必须把好的苹果与坏的分开. 4. He detached a link from a chain. 他从链子上拆下一个链环。', '形容词: detachable 副词: detachably 名词: detachability 过去式: detached 过去分词: detached 现在分词: detaching 第三人称单数: detaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('excruciate', '[ɪk\'skruːʃɪˌeɪt]', 'vt.使苦恼；折磨；拷问', '1. heart excruciate 内心拷问 2. excruciate vt. 施酷刑； 3. excruciate / iks5kru:Fieit/ vt. 使受酷刑,折磨;', '名词: excruciation 过去式: excruciated 过去分词: excruciated 现在分词: excruciating 第三人称单数: excruciates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hectic', '[\'hektɪk]', 'adj.忙乱的；兴奋的；[医]发热的；发红的', '1. I had a hectic day in the office. 我在办公室里忙乱了一天。 2. It can be a hectic life on a 24-hour news channel. 24小时新闻频道的生活可能非常忙乱。 3. The journalist leads a hectic life. 新闻记者过着紧张兴奋的生活。 4. Hectic phobophobia can be cured. 赤面恐怖症是可以治疗的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('musket', '[\'mʌskɪt]', 'n.滑膛枪', '1. I hunted with a musket two years ago. 两年前我用滑膛枪打猎。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fusion', '[\'fjuːʒn]', 'n.融合；结合；熔合；核聚变', '1. There is now a worrying fusion of information and entertainment. 现在信息和娱乐已经出现令人忧虑的相互融合。 2. She was a fusion of the dreamer and doer. 她是空想者和实干者的结合。 3. The movie displayed a perfect fusion of image and sound. 这部电影展示了音响与影像的完美结合。 4. Brass is formed by the fusion of copper and zinc. 黄铜是由铜和锌熔合制成的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shrink', '[ʃrɪŋk]', 'vi.收缩；退缩；萎缩；畏惧，害怕 vt.使收缩 n.收缩；萎缩 n.精神科医生', '1. Will this woolen sweater shrink when washed? 这件羊毛衫洗后会缩水吗？ 2. The company\'s profit margins shrank from 32.5% to 17%. 该公司的边际利润率从32.5%降到了17%。 3. We will never shrink from difficulties. 我们在困难面前决不退缩。 4. The economy is shrinking instead of growing. 经济正在萎缩而不是在增长中。 5. The hot water shrank my pullover. 我的套头毛衣遇热水后收缩了。 6. You can expect some shrink when the jeans are washed. 这种牛仔裤洗后要缩些水。 7. My aunt saw this shrink after her divorce. 我阿姨在离婚后去见过这位心理医生。', '形容词: shrinkable 名词: shrinker 过去式: shrank/shrunk 过去分词: shrunk/shrunken 现在分词: shrinking 第三人称单数: shrinks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('upbraid', '[ʌp\'breɪd]', 'vt.斥责；责骂', '1. The old man upbraided him with ingratitude. 那位老人斥责他忘恩负义。', '副词: upbraidingly 名词: upbraider 过去式: upbraided 过去分词: upbraided 现在分词: upbraiding 第三人称单数: upbraids');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('religion', '[rɪ\'lɪdʒən]', 'n.宗教；宗教信仰', '1. He is a disciple of religion. 他是宗教信徒。 2. Jesus was the founder of the Christian religion. 耶稣是基督教的创始人。 3. Politics and religion are daily topics of conversation. 政治和宗教是人们平常交谈的主要话题。 4. There are many religions in the world. 世界上有许多种宗教信仰。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mushroom', '[\'mʌʃrʊm]', 'n.蘑菇；菌菇状物；暴发户 vi.采蘑菇；雨后春笋般涌现；迅速增加', '1. Some mushrooms are poisonous. 有些蘑菇有毒。 2. I gathered many mushrooms after rain. 雨后我采了很多蘑菇。 3. The mushroom cloud of the A-bomb hung over the desert again. 原子弹爆炸的蘑菇云再度笼罩在沙漠的上空。 4. Mushroom clouds appear after nuclear explosions. 核弹爆炸后会产生蘑菇云。 5. Let\'s go mushrooming. 我们采蘑菇去吧。', '过去式: mushroomed 过去分词: mushroomed 现在分词: mushrooming 第三人称单数: mushrooms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('superficiality', '[ˌsjuːpəˌfɪʃi\'æləti]', 'n.表面性的事物；肤浅；浅薄', '1. Superficiality is the terrible enemy of an article. 肤浅是文章的大敌。 2. His rapidity in establishing inter-personal relations tends to be matched by the superficiality of such relations. 他建立个人之间关系的迅速，往往同这种关系的肤浅相一致。 3. I\'ve got an idea they\'ll seem to get the very superficiality in a few years. 我认为几年后他们就会变得非常浅薄。 4. With the rapid development of our society,our circumstances and life are faced with more dangers of fickleness and superficiality. 在人类社会飞速发展的今天，我们的环境和生活面临着更为浮躁和浅薄的危险。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aspiration', '[ˌæspə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.抱负；热望；志向；渴望 n.吸引术；抽吸；吸气；发送气音', '1. His true aspiration is to become the President of the United States. 他真正的抱负是想成为美国总统。 2. He nursed an aspiration to be a poet. 他心怀当诗人的愿望。 3. The generalship was his aspiration. 将官之职位是他梦寐以求的目标。 4. These are not just my goals, but our common aspiration. 这些不仅仅是我的目标,而且是我们的共同志向。 5. Aspiration cytologic examination reealed a fibrocystic change. 抽吸细胞学检查为纤维囊性变。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expunge', '[ɪk\'spʌndʒ]', 'vt.擦掉；删掉；除去', '1. She expunged the sound of his voice from the tape recording. 她从录音带上抹去了他的说话声。 2. The editor expunged a passage from the book. 该编辑删去了书中的一段。 3. Nothing can expunge the shame of what he did. 他行为的可耻是无法抹去的。 4. Her name was expunged from the list. 她的名字已从名册上除掉。', '名词: expunger 过去式: expunged 过去分词: expunged 现在分词: expunging 第三人称单数: expunges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trowel', '[\'traʊəl]', 'n.泥刀；小铲子 v.用泥刀抹开；抹平', '1. Some of the grid sections will accumulate immediately in the trowel areas. 有些板栅碎块可能立即堆积在刮刀的地方。 2. Common tools include the trowel, penknife, and brush. 常用的工具包括铲子、小刀以及刷子。', '名词: troweler 过去式: troweled/trowelled 过去分词: troweled/trowelled 现在分词: troweling/trowelling 第三人称单数: trowels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('salutary', '[\'sæljəteri]', 'adj.有益的；有用的；有益健康的', '1. The punishment had a salutary effect on the boy. 这项处罚对那个男孩产生了有利的影响。 2. The accident is a salutary reminder of the danger of climbing. 这一事故有益的一面是提醒了我们攀登活动是有许多危险的。', '副词: salutarily 名词: salutariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oppose', '[ə\'poʊz]', 'v.反对；对抗；使对立', '1. It was courageous of him to oppose his chief. 他敢反对他的上司，真是勇敢。 2. The rabbles met on the square to oppose their new mayor. 平民们在广场上集会反对他们的新市长。 3. They opposed the government\'s new policies. 他们反对政府的新政策。 4. We\'re firmly opposed to the practice of powerpolitics between nations. 我们强烈反对在国与国之间实行强权政治。', '名词: opposer 过去式: opposed 过去分词: opposed 现在分词: opposing 第三人称单数: opposes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eloquence', '[\'eləkwəns]', 'n.雄辩；口才', '1. His eloquence did not avail against the facts. 他的雄辩在事实面前不起什么作用。 2. Eloquence and ignorance sometimes go together. 滔滔不绝的雄辩有时候是伴随着无知的。 3. She was charmed by his eloquence. 她被他的口才所倾倒。 4. He inherited his eloquence from his father, a Christian preacher. 他继承了他那个当基督教传教士的父亲的口才。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('permissive', '[pər\'mɪsɪv]', 'adj.放任的；纵容的；许可的；获准的', '1. Should parents be strict or permissive? 父母应该严格还是放任? 2. He claims that society has been far too permissive towards drug taking. 他认为社会对吸毒太纵容了。 3. First, democracy is basically a permissive system. 第一，民主，本质上，是一个许可体制。', '副词: permissively 名词: permissiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('martial', '[\'mɑːrʃl]', 'adj.军事的；战争的；好战的', '1. He faced a court martial for disobeying orders. 他因不服从命令受到军法审判。 2. The city remains firmly under martial law. 这个城市仍实施严格的军事管制。 3. The president also harked back to ancient Sinhalese martial heroes. 总统又提及古代僧伽罗战争英雄。 4. We should always remember that Japan is a martial nation. 我们应该始终牢记日本是一个好战的国家。', '副词: martially 名词: martialism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wig', '[wɪɡ]', 'n.假发；呵斥 vt.严斥；责骂', '1. Judges wear wigs in court. 法官开庭时戴假发。 2. The actress wore a black wig over her blond hair. 女演员的金发上戴着黑色的假发。 3. She has a wig on, but we soon penetrate her disguise. 她戴了一顶假发，但是我们很快就识穿了她的伪装。 4. The teacher wigged him for absent-mindedness. 教师呵斥他心不在焉。', '过去式: wigged 过去分词: wigged 现在分词: wigging 第三人称单数: wigs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('credible', '[\'kredəbl]', 'adj.可信的；可靠的', '1. It is hardly credible. 这是难以置信的。 2. These denials are simply not credible. 这些否认是不可信的。 3. So far, there is only one credible proposal. 到目前为止，只有一个可靠的建议。 4. But I believe real things are more credible. 但是我认为还是现实的东西比较可靠。', '副词: credibly 名词: credibleness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('supremacy', '[suː\'preməsi]', 'n.至高；主权；最高权力或地位', '1. After seizing air and naval supremacy, Chinese troops would force their way across the Strait of Taiwan and storm ashore. 在夺取空军和海军的至高权后,中国军队将穿过台湾海峡猛攻上岸。 2. The indirect democracy, the representative government, is based on the principle of popular supremacy. 人民主权原则作为代议制民主建立的主要理论根据，成为现代国家政治统治合法性的前提和基础。 3. The supremacy of the pope was rejected, but in his place the monarch was enthroned as the head of the church. 教皇的主权固然被拒绝了，但皇帝竟登上了教会元首的地位。', '名词复数: supremacies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coherent', '[koʊ\'hɪrənt]', 'adj.连贯的；有条理的；一致的；粘着的', '1. He welded their stories into a single coherent account. 他把他们的故事连在一起写成一个连贯的报导。 2. The subjects of the curriculum form a coherent whole. 课程中的科目构成了一个连贯的整体。 3. She only became coherent again two hours after the attack. 她发病两小时之后才恢复了清楚地说话的能力。 4. She had felt there was something wrong, but couldn\'t give coherent reasons. 她感到有些不对头，但是讲不清楚理由。', '副词: coherently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arcane', '[ɑːr\'keɪn]', 'adj.神秘的；不可思议的', '1. The technique at one time was arcane in the minds of most chemists. 这种技术在大多数化学家心目中一度是神秘的。 2. What is arcane to them is lucid to me. 对他们来说深奥难解的东西对我却一清二楚。 3. He wanders through a mysterious world of arcane theology. 他在奇妙的神学领域的神秘世界之中穿梭。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frothy', '[\'frɔːθi]', 'adj.起泡的；多泡的；空洞的', '1. Beat the eggs up to a frothy consistency. 把鸡蛋打成黏稠泡沫状。 2. She pauses to sip a frothy iced coffee from a plastic tumbler. 她停下来呷了一口塑料杯里浮满泡沫的冰镇咖啡。', '副词: frothily 比较级: frothier 最高级: frothiest 名词: frothiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chip', '[tʃɪp]', 'n.缺口；碎屑；油炸土豆条；薄片；筹码；芯片；（足球）高球；（高尔夫球）近穴球 v.形成（缺口）；切下；凿下；凑份子；打高球；近穴击球；将（土豆等）切条', '1. It was difficult finding two cups without some kind of chip on them. 很难找到两个一点没有缺口的杯子。 2. A small chip of ice flew into the air. 一小块碎冰飞溅到了空中。 3. She had a hamburger and a portion of chip. 她吃了一个汉堡包和一份炸薯条。 4. I\'ve got chocolate chip for you. 我给你们买了巧克力薄片。 5. Be careful with these plates they chip very easily. 小心这些盘子--边缘容易破损。', '过去式: chipped 过去分词: chipped 现在分词: chipping 第三人称单数: chips');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('astronomical', '[ˌæstrə\'nɑːmɪkl]', 'adj.天文学的；巨大的', '1. He is engaged in astronomical research. 他致力于天文学的研究。 2. He was too poor to buy an astronomical telescope. 他太穷了，买不起天文望远镜。 3. The costs of land for building are astronomical. 买地建房的花费很庞大。 4. Astronomical sums of money will be needed for this river tunnel plan. 这条过江隧道的计划需要极大的一笔钱。', '副词: astronomically 异体字: astronomic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emollient', '[i\'mɑːliənt]', 'adj.使柔软的；润肤的；缓和的 n.润肤剂；润滑剂；软化剂；缓和剂', '1. The northerners\' initial response has been emollient. 北方人的最初反应便是尽量缓和时局。 2. Use an emollient for dry skin. 干燥的皮肤要使用润肤剂。 3. Glycerine is the preferred emollient. 甘油是首选的润滑剂。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crag', '[kræɡ]', 'n.峭壁；危岩', '1. They surmount one crag after another. 他们登上一块又一块的峭壁。 2. The fugitive lived in a cave in the mountain crag for several years. 这个逃犯在一个山上峭壁的岩洞里住了几年。 3. The despairing man jumped off the crag. 那个绝望的人跳下了悬崖。 4. The prison on the crag was not so dominant as of yore. 悬崖顶上的监狱不像以前那么威风凛凛了。', '形容词: cragged');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('notable', '[\'noʊtəbl]', 'adj.显著的；著名的 n.名人', '1. The difference contrast is notable. 差别对比是显著的。 2. This book had a notable impact on literature and art. 这本书对文学艺术产生显著的影响。 3. Tsim Sha Tsui is a notable tourist destination. 尖沙咀是著名的游客区。 4. You can also take in some of the notable architectural monuments. 你也可以将一些著名的纪念性建筑包括在参观的项目中。 5. He is the most notable son of Manchester. 他是曼切斯特最显赫的名人。', '副词: notably 名词: notableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('charisma', '[kə\'rɪzmə]', 'n.非凡的领导力；魅力', '1. The President has great personal charisma. 总统具有超凡的个人魅力。 2. Most movie stars have a lot of charisma. 大部分电影明星很有魅力。', '名词复数: charismata');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('straiten', '[\'streɪtn]', 'vt.使为难；使穷困；限制', '1. Let them become as dust before the wind : and let the angel of the Lord straiten them. 我寻求了上主，他听了我的祈求：由我受的一切惊惶中，将我救出。 2. Therefore, first I asked him if his circumstances admitted him to spare so much money at that time, and if it would not straiten him. 于是我首先问他,以他目前的情况,能不能拿出这么多的钱,拿出来会不会使他手头拮据。 3. When I’m lonely be my friend, when I’m sad be my joy, when I’m hurt be my mender and my fixer, when I’m wrong straiten me out and be my righteousness. 主啊！请做我孤独时的朋友，悲伤时的喜乐；受伤害时的修复者，将我从错误中拯救出来，成为我的公义。 4. to straiten the number of people entering into the stadium 限制进入体育场的人数', '过去式: straitened 过去分词: straitened 现在分词: straitening 第三人称单数: straitens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fabricate', '[\'fæbrɪkeɪt]', 'v.编造；虚构；制造', '1. The defense accused police of fabricating evidence. 被告指责警察编造证据。 2. The story was fabricated and completely untrue. 这故事是捏造的，一点不真实。 3. It is not easy to fabricate DNA evidence. 要假造染色体为证是不容易的。 4. The finest crafts people fabricated this golden ring. 这枚金戒指是由最优秀的工匠制作的。', '名词: fabrication 过去式: fabricated 过去分词: fabricated 现在分词: fabricating 第三人称单数: fabricates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avert', '[ə\'vɜːrt]', 'vt.转开；避免；防止', '1. It was Scott\'s turn to avert his gaze. 这下轮到斯科特移开他注视的目光了。 2. The government has failed to avert a national strike. 政府没有能够避免这场全国性的罢工。 3. He managed to avert suspicion. 他设法避嫌。 4. The lake will be dyked to avert floods. 将为此湖筑堤以防洪水。', '形容词: avertible 过去式: averted 过去分词: averted 现在分词: averting 第三人称单数: averts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shack', '[ʃæk]', 'n.棚房；窝棚；小室 vt.居住', '1. All we could afford was this shack, which we built ourselves, with our own hands and without any help from anyone. 我们所能承担的只有这个棚房，在没有其他人帮助下用手自己建造的。 2. The shack seemed almost ready to collapse. 那小屋子好像是快要倒塌了。 3. The boy makes a shack out of the old board in the backyard. 男孩们在后院用旧木板盖起一间小木屋。 4. She was going to shack up in a hotel for a couple of days. 她准备去旅馆暂住几天。', '过去式: shacked 过去分词: shacked 现在分词: shacking 第三人称单数: shacks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hazard', '[\'hæzərd]', 'n.危险；冒险；危害 vt.冒险；赌运气 阿扎尔（英超切尔西队球员）', '1. The car had its hazard warning lights on. 这辆汽车亮起了危险信号灯。 2. He had put his own life in hazard. 他是在拿自己的生命来冒险。 3. There are many serious health hazards associated with smoking. 许多危害健康的情况都与吸烟有关。 4. He hazarded all his money in the attempt to save the business. 他为挽救这家企业，不惜冒险投入他的全部金钱。', '过去式: hazarded 过去分词: hazarded 现在分词: hazarding 第三人称单数: hazards');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inchoate', '[ɪn\'koʊət]', 'adj.刚开始的；早期的；不成熟的', '1. Who knows the main symptom of inchoate lung cancer? 有谁知道早期肺癌的主要症状吗？ 2. How much is the cure rate of inchoate esophagus cancer? 早期食道癌的治愈率是多少？ 3. Her early works are an inchoate idea, nothing but full of lush rhetoric. 她的早期作品都不太成熟,除了华丽的词藻外就没什么内容了。', '副词: inchoately 名词: inchoateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('opprobrious', '[ə\'prəʊbriəs]', 'adj.嘴不干净的；辱骂的；臭名昭著的', '1. It is now freely applied as an adjective of an opprobrious kind. 目前它被任意用作一种骂人的形容词。 2. He ransacked his extensive vocabulary in order to find opprobrious names to call her. 他从他的丰富词汇中挑出所有难听的话来骂她。 3. He ransacked an extensive vocabulary in order to find opprobrious names to call her. 他从他的丰富词汇中挑出所有难听的话来骂她。 4. A court is not bound to credit bald assertions, unsupportable conclusions, and opprobrious epithets woven into the fabric of the complaint. 法庭不必采信由枯燥的断言，没有根据的结论和无理的绰号所编织的诉求。', '副词: opprobriously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('laxative', '[\'læksətɪv]', 'n.泻药 adj.通便的；不简洁的', '1. I’m constipated. I need some laxative. 我便秘了。给我点泻药。 2. A stool softener or laxative may be ordered. 可能要医嘱开大便软化剂或泻药。 3. Excessive consumption may produce a laxative effect. 超量使用或会导致腹泻。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('implausible', '[ɪm\'plɔːzəbl]', 'adj.难信的；似乎不合情理的；不像真实的', '1. His excuses were totally implausible. 他的借口完全不可相信。 2. Her explanation is not implausible. 她的解释并非没有道理。 3. This is a blatantly implausible claim. 这明显是无理的要求。', '副词: implausibly 名词: implausibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ail', '[eɪl]', 'v.使 ... 苦恼；苦恼；生病 n.小病', '1. It may provide answers to some of the problems that ail America. 这一点可能解答困扰美国的某些问题。 2. If you eat all that junk food now , you will ail tomorrow. 如果你现在吃太多的垃圾食品，将来你会因此而苦恼。 3. That child is ailing. 小孩生病了。', '过去式: ailed 过去分词: ailed 现在分词: ailing 第三人称单数: ails');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('survive', '[sər\'vaɪv]', 'vt.幸免于难；存活；艰难度过；比 ... 活得长 vi.活着；继续存在', '1. She was the only one to survive the crash. 她是这次飞机失事的唯一幸存者。 2. These birds are able to survive the perils of the Arctic winter. 这些鸟能在北极寒冷的冬天里生存。 3. I don\'t know how I ever survived high school. 我都不知道我是怎样熬过高中那段岁月的。 4. Santos is survived by his wife of 49 years. 桑托斯的妻子比他多活了49年。 5. You need to be tough to survive in the jungle. 要在丛林中活下来就要有坚忍不拔的意志。', '名词: survivor 过去式: survived 过去分词: survived 现在分词: surviving 第三人称单数: survives');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skyscraper', '[\'skaɪskreɪpər]', 'n.摩天大楼', '1. A new skyscraper has been put up downtown. 市中心又建起了一座摩天大厦。 2. The skyscraper towers into the sky. 该摩天大楼高耸入云。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reinforce', '[ˌriːɪn\'fɔːrs]', 'vt.加固；加强；增强；使更具说服力 vi.得到加强', '1. We will use metal strap to reinforce the outside. 我们会在纸箱外用金属带加固。 2. Any good speaker should be able to reinforce his argument with facts. 一个好的演讲者会用事实来加强他论点。 3. Public reaction will reinforce it. 社会反响会进一步增强它的作用。 4. This evidence reinforces my view that he is a spy. 这个证据证实了我认为他是间谍的这一看法。', '形容词: reinforceable');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chandelier', '[ˌʃændə\'lɪr]', 'n.枝形吊灯(烛台)', '1. A large chandelier glorifies the whole room. 枝形大吊灯使整个房间光亮夺目。 2. There was a crystal chandelier above their heads. 他们头顶上方有一个水晶枝形吊灯。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fritter', '[\'frɪtər]', 'n.油炸馅饼 v.浪费', '1. Guests love to eat fritter containing sliced apple. 客人喜欢吃夹有苹果片的油炸馅饼。 2. He has frittered away every chance he ever got. 他把到手的每个机会都糟塌掉了。 3. And some are going to fritter away the years quarreling about staff cuts. 但另一些却是为裁员问题争执不休而浪费时间。', '过去式: frittered 过去分词: frittered 现在分词: frittering 第三人称单数: fritters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('configuration', '[kənˌfɪɡjə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.结构；布局；形态；格式塔心理完形 [计算机] 配置.', '1. It is something resembling this structure in configuration or pattern. 这是一种在外形或结构上类似这种构造的东西。 2. The configuration of this plant is complex. 这个工厂的布局很复杂。 3. This is the configuration of the earth\'s surface. 这就是地球表面的形状。 4. Where do I put my configuration files? 我把配置文件放在哪里了?', '形容词: configurative 副词: configurationally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pettish', '[\'petɪʃ]', 'adj.易怒的；使性子的', '1. Dear, I can\'t act in pettish to you any further, wanting you do this did that. 亲爱的，我再也不能对你撒娇，要你做这做那了。 2. For caress with cry up, children with smile with act in pettish to take in to requite, for make fun of and ignore, the children take in to respond with self-will by get mad. 对于抚爱和夸奖，孩子们以微笑和撒娇加以回报，对于嘲弄和漠视，孩子们以发怒和任性加以回应。 3. But, I the most dear, why you can\'t come to a stop again to embrace my term I act in pettish term I commited tomfoolery? 可是，我最亲爱的，为什么你不能再停下来抱着我任我撒娇任我胡闹了呢？ 4. Just we finally dare not not to wish unwilling, show so before person weak, come to in public act in pettish of suspicion. 只是我们终究是不敢不愿不甘心，在人前就这么示弱，落得当众撒娇之嫌。', '副词: pettishly 名词: pettishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('largesse', '[lɑːr\'dʒes]', 'n.慷慨援助；施舍', '1. Mr. King liked the lordliness of giving largess. 金先生喜欢慷慨赠予的贵族气派。 2. The economy of Greenland remains dependent on Danish largesse. 格陵兰依然要依靠丹麦经济上的援助。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diagonal', '[daɪ\'æɡənl]', 'adj.对角线的；斜的；斜纹的 n.对角线；斜线；斜列', '1. When 2 or 4 or 6 players, the diagonal play is your enemy. 2人、4人或6人游戏时与互为对角线的一方对抗， 2. Of course! My outlet is diagonal. 当然咯，我的插座是斜的。 3. The wood surface of the furniture is full of diagonal stripes. 这件家具的木头表面上布满了斜纹。 4. Each stitch covers a diagonal of one cell of the grid. 每条缝线覆盖格子的对角线。', '副词: diagonally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flexible', '[\'fleksəbl]', 'adj.柔韧的；灵活的；易弯曲的；可变通的', '1. This tube is flexible but tough. 这管子柔软但很坚固。 2. We need a foreign policy that is more flexible. 我们需要一个更为灵活的外交政策。 3. People use Java because it is flexible and runs on multiple platforms. 人们使用Java是因为它的灵活性及在多种平台上可以运行。 4. Leather and rubber are flexible, glass and iron are not. 皮革和橡胶都是易弯曲的，玻璃和铁则不然。', '副词: flexibly 名词: flexibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mosque', '[mɑːsk]', 'n.清真寺', '1. They go to the mosque to pray once a week. 他们每周一次到清真寺去祈祷。 2. He is Imam of Mosque in Siping City, Jili Province. 现任吉林省四平市清真寺教长。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bumptious', '[\'bʌmpʃəs]', 'adj.自吹自擂的；傲慢的', '1. His classmates called him a show-off because of his bumptious airs. 由于他老是装出一副自以为是的架势,所以同学们就叫他“自大的夜郎”。', '副词: bumptiously 名词: bumptiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wroth', '[rɔːθ]', 'adj.(大海等)汹涌的；暴怒的', '1. He was wroth to see the damage to his home. 他看到家里遭到的毁坏愤怒极了。 2. The king went wroth. 国王勃然大怒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('authentic', '[ɔː\'θentɪk]', 'adj.真正的；真实的；可信的；可靠的', '1. This is an authentic medieval sword. 这是一把真正的中世纪剑。 2. He found out the most authentic restaurants. 他找到了最正宗的餐馆。 3. The details of the costume were totally authentic. 这件古装的每个小地方都完全真实。 4. He\'s got an authentic letter by Shakespeare. 他弄到了一封莎士比亚的亲笔信。', '副词: authentically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incarnate', '[ɪn\'kɑːrnət]', 'v.体现；使 ... 具体化 adj.化身的；人体化的', '1. He incarnates all the qualities of a successful manager. 他表现出了事业有成的经理人员所具有的一切品质。 2. The guards are sadistic beasts and their leader is the devil incarnate. 那些警卫都是残暴的野兽，他们的首领是个魔鬼的化身。 3. The guards were sadistic beasts and their leader was the devil incarnate. 那些警卫都是残暴的野兽，他们的首领是个魔鬼的化身。', '名词: incarnator 过去式: incarnated 过去分词: incarnated 现在分词: incarnating 第三人称单数: incarnates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unjustified', '[ʌn\'dʒʌstɪfaɪd]', 'adj.不合理的；不正当的；未被证明其正确的', '1. The action of the strikers was unjustified. 罢工者的行为是不合理的。 2. We reject these allegations as wholly unjustified. 我们拒绝接受这些完全不合理的主张。 3. The criticism was wholly unjustified. 这样的批评完全是不公平的。 4. You have made several unjustified presuppositions. 你作了一些毫无根据的假设。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('euphonious', '[juː\'foʊniəs]', 'adj.悦耳的', '1. He was enchanted with the euphonious music. 他陶醉在那悦耳的音乐中。 2. The euphonious sound of Carrie\'s cello playing always puts me at ease. 嘉莉悦耳的大提琴演奏总让我心旷神怡。', '副词: euphoniously 名词: euphoniousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('provisional', '[prə\'vɪʒənl]', 'adj.暂时的 n.临时性；临时人员', '1. We are now in a position to attempt a provisional synthesis. 我们现在可以探讨一下暂时的综合。 2. The Palestinians would then get a provisional state with temporary borders. 巴勒斯坦人将建立一个拥有暂时边界的临时国家。 3. Any physical theory is always provisional, in the sense that it is only a hypothesis: you can never prove it. 任何物理理论都是暂时的，因为它只是一种假设：人们永远不可能也证明它。 4. We shouldn\'t forget that the resolution is provisional. 我们不要忘了这个决议的临时性。', '副词: provisionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('etch', '[etʃ]', 'v.蚀刻；铭刻；鲜明地描述；流露出', '1. The artist must have spent hours etching the image on the glass. 这位美术家一定花了好几小时把这画像蚀刻在玻璃上。 2. This terrible event is etched forever in my mind. 这一可怕事件永远深深地铭刻在我心中。 3. The trees were etched against the winter sky. 在冬日天空的衬托下，树木的轮廓很清晰。 4. Tiredness was etched on his face. 他的脸上流露出了疲惫。', '名词: etcher 过去式: etched 过去分词: etched 现在分词: etching 第三人称单数: etches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monologue', '[\'mɑːnəlɔːɡ]', 'n.独白；独角戏；长篇大论；自言自语', '1. He writes dialogue by cut monologue in two. 他把独白切成两截来写对白。 2. The movie starts with a long monologue. 这部电影以一个很长的独白开始。 3. The Boss\'s monologue is interrupted by the sound of a fire alarm. 老板的长篇大论被一阵火警声打断。 4. He went into a long monologue about life in America. 他开始滔滔不绝地谈起美国的生活。', '形容词: monologic 名词: monologuist 过去式: monologued/monologged 过去分词: monologued/monologged 现在分词: monologuing/monologging 第三人称单数: monologues/monologs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('schematic', '[skiː\'mætɪk]', 'adj.图解的；扼要的', '1. Provide circuit lists and schematic wiring diagram. 提供电路清单和线路图解。 2. We reproduced a same working schematic diagram. 我们复制了一份同样的施工简图。 3. The play has a very schematic plot. 这出戏的剧情非常严谨。', '副词: schematically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('occupation', '[ˌɑːkju\'peɪʃn]', 'n.职业；占有；消遣；居住', '1. I haven\'t entered your name and occupation yet. 我尚未记下你的名字和职业。 2. Please state your name, age and occupation. 请说明姓名、年龄和职业。 3. He is a merchant in occupation. 他的职业是经商。 4. He returned from Paris and found his office was under someone else\'s occupation. 他从巴黎回来，发现他的办公室被别人占了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nemesis', '[\'neməsɪs]', 'n.不可避免的报应 Nemesis. n.[希神]复仇女神', '1. To follow the proposed course of action is to invite nemesis. 按照别人建议的行动步骤而行动就是自找报应。 2. You can\'t do as you want relying on power, or you may invite a nemesis. 你们不能怙恃权势就为所欲为，小心遭报应。', '名词复数: nemeses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parity', '[\'pærəti]', 'n.相等；势均力敌；等值', '1. Eventually, as the technology matu res we are likely to see penetration levels approach parity across all groups. 最终，在技术成熟的时候，我们有可能看到差距水平在所有的群体中趋向相等。 2. Of all the regions of the non-Western world, only East Asia has the potential to achieve parity with the West. 在所有非西方的地区中，只有东亚才有这个潜能和西方平起平坐。 3. The two sides soon achieved parity. 双方很快就达到了平局。 4. The hardware detected a parity error. 硬件检测到奇偶校验错误。', '名词复数: parities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('void', '[vɔɪd]', 'adj.空的；无效的；缺乏的 n.真空；空白；空虚 vt.使无效；排泄；使空出 vi.排泄', '1. Void function may not return a value 空函数不可返回一个值。 2. The court ruled that the claim was null and void. 法庭裁决此项要求无效。 3. His suggestions are totally void of common sense. 他的建议完全缺乏常识。 4. That part of the town is completely void of interest for visitors. 城镇的那部分对游客完全没有吸引力。 5. In the next weeks, government floated as in a void. 以后的几个星期,政府宛如漂浮于真空之中。 6. We will void the existing and issue a new one. 我们将把现有的作废，然后再出一张新的。', '名词: voider 过去式: voided 过去分词: voided 现在分词: voiding 第三人称单数: voids');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verboten', '[fɛr\'boʊtən]', 'adj.被禁止的', '1. Tattoos are strictly verboten. 纹身是被严格禁止的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sally', '[\'sæli]', 'n.俏皮话；突围 v.冲出；突围；出发旅行', '1. Everyone waited for his next sally. 大家都在等着听他还有什么俏皮话。 2. She gibed at him, but he returned with a witty sally. 她用话刺他，他却回了她一句聪明的俏皮话。 3. The soldiers made a successful sally. 士兵们进行了一次成功的突围。', '名词复数: sallies 过去式: sallied 过去分词: sallied 现在分词: sallying 第三人称单数: sallies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('milk', '[mɪlk]', 'n.奶；牛奶；乳汁 v.挤乳；产乳；榨取', '1. A baby vomits milk from repletion. 婴儿吃饱会吐奶。 2. She dribbled some milk onto the cereal. 她把一些奶滴在燕麦片上。 3. The cat lapped up the milk. 猫舔食牛奶。 4. I am boiling the milk. 我正在煮牛奶。 5. The farmer whistled as he milked. 农夫一边挤奶一边吹口哨。', '名词: milker 过去式: milked 过去分词: milked 现在分词: milking 第三人称单数: milks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unwonted', '[ʌn\'woʊntɪd]', 'adj.异常的；不习惯的', '1. The gardens had an unwonted trimness. 这些花园异常整洁。 2. He spoke with unwonted enthusiasm. 他讲话显得出人意料的热心。 3. Grace lapsed into unwonted sedateness. 格雷丝变得异常严肃起来。 4. This betrayed unwonted agitation. 这说明当时他那种从未有过的惊慌。', '副词: unwontedly 名词: unwontedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gait', '[ɡeɪt]', 'n.步态；步法', '1. He is awkward in his gait. 他的步态不雅观。 2. His easy gait shows self-confidence. 他从容的步态显示出自信。 3. The man walked along with an unsteady gait. 那人脚步不稳地向前走去。 4. The fastest gait of a horse is the gallop. 马最快的步法是奔驰。', '过去式: gaited 过去分词: gaited 现在分词: gaiting 第三人称单数: gaits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scurvy', '[\'skɜːrvi]', 'n.坏血病 adj.下流的；卑鄙的', '1. The crew remained free from scurvy. 那些船员仍然没有患坏血病之虞。 2. Vitamin C, found in citrus fruits, prevents scurvy. 柑桔类水果中含有维生素C，可防治坏血病。 3. He\'s a scurvy wretch. 他是个卑鄙的家伙。 4. That was a scurvy trick to play on an old lady. 用那样的花招欺负一个老太太，可真卑鄙。', '副词: scurvily 比较级: scurvier 最高级: scurviest 名词: scurviness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hub', '[hʌb]', 'n.中心；轮毂；轮轴', '1. Chicago is a hub of airline traffic. 芝加哥是航运中心。 2. The playground is the hub of parental supervision. 游乐场是家长监督的中心。 3. That restaurant has served as a hub of the community for decades. 几十年来，这个饭店一直是社区居民交流的中心。 4. Hong Kong is the regional hub for thousands of international companies. 香港是国际公司在亚太区的营商中心。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desalinize', '[diː\'seɪlɪˌnaɪz]', 'v.除去盐份', '1. I know, time can desalinize everything, cure all pain of injury, but I know how often does it need also either, I could put you in the corner of memory , no longer touch. 我知道，时间可以淡化一切，医治一切的伤痛，但是我也不知道还需要多久的时间，我才能把你给放在记忆的角落里，不再碰触。 2. The government should desalinize the function of distribution and play the leading and guiding function in the reform of distribution system. 政府应该淡化其分配职能,在分配制度改革中发挥着主导和引导作用。 3. I know, time can desalinize eerything, cure all pain of injury, but I know how often does it need also either, I could put you in the corner of memory , no longer touch. 我知道，时间可以淡化一切，医治一切的伤痛，但是我也不知道还需要多久的时间，我才能把你给放在记忆的角落里，不再碰触。 4. In the political aspect, it is necessary to treat class properties scientifically and desalinize officer\'s standard consciousness, and practically analyze the intellectuals\' political roles. 在政治方面，要科学对待阶级属性和淡化官本位意识，实事求是地分析知识分子的政治角色；', '名词: desalinization 过去式: desalinized 过去分词: desalinized 现在分词: desalinizing 第三人称单数: desalinizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('screed', '[skriːd]', 'n.冗长的文章；（泥水匠用的）匀泥尺；磨光面', '1. Screed four series of nearly 60 standard models. 上海市高新技术企业; 2. To the renting object belong a cellar and a screed compartment. 不过意思就这样啦。。 3. The enraged Screed had to admit defeat, and moved on. 恼羞成怒的斯克里德不得不承认失败，拂袖而去。 4. The pro-whaling screed was approved by a much thinner margin: 33 votes to 32. 上一次关于捕鲸的冗长决议是以33票对32票的微弱差数通过的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('raid', '[reɪd]', 'n.突然袭击；突击搜捕；劫掠；集体抛售 v.劫掠；攫取；突击搜捕；袭击', '1. We launched a bombing raid on enemy bases. 我们对敌方基地实施了突然袭击。 2. The raid was purely retaliatory. 这次袭击完全是报复性的。 3. Police made a lightning raid on the house. 警方突然查抄了那座房子。 4. They were arrested during a dawn raid. 在一次清晨的突击搜查中，他们都被捕了。 5. They promise they will never raid tourist. 他们保证再也不抢劫游客。', '名词: raider 过去式: raided 过去分词: raided 现在分词: raiding 第三人称单数: raids');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sock', '[sɑːk]', 'n.短袜', '1. There is a hole in my sock. 我的袜子上有个洞。 2. He selected a pair of socks to match his suit. 他挑选了一双与他衣服相配的短袜。', '过去式: socked 过去分词: socked 现在分词: socking 第三人称单数: socks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petulant', '[\'petʃələnt]', 'adj.暴躁的；任性的；难以取悦的', '1. They were incredulous and petulant. 他们不肯轻信，脾气暴躁。 2. He behaved like a petulant child and refused to cooperate. 他像个任性的孩子，拒不合作。', '副词: petulantly 名词: petulance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sticky', '[\'stɪki]', 'adj.粘的；闷热的；困难的；令人不满意的', '1. I am uncomfortable because my body is sticky . 我身上粘粘的，很不舒服。 2. Yuanxiao is a kind of sticky round dumplings. 元宵是一种粘粘的圆的面团。 3. A hot, sticky day makes a person listless. 天气闷热使人觉得身上有气无力。 4. They put me in a sticky position. 他们将我置于一个困难的境地。', '副词: stickily 比较级: stickier 最高级: stickiest 名词: stickiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blurb', '[blɜːrb]', 'n.大肆宣传；吹捧性广告；简介；短评 v.大做广告', '1. I am fed up with the blurb that finance agency keeps sending me. 我对那家财务代理公司不断寄来的宣传广告感到极为厌烦。 2. In the blurb I couldn\'t see anything about thinking at all. 在这本书的简介中，我根本找不到任何有关思想的东西。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cleft', '[kleft]', 'adj.裂开的；分离的 n.裂缝；开裂 动词cleave的过去式和过去分词.', '1. It provides free operations to children from underprivileged backgrounds with cleft pallets. 这家医院为贫困家庭的唇腭裂患儿提供免费手术。 2. The climber fell down a cleft in the rocks. 爬山者跌入岩石的裂缝里。 3. The man cleft a block of wood in two with an axe. 那人用斧头把一块木头劈成两半。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('granulate', '[\'grænjəˌleɪt]', 'v.(使)成颗粒', '1. To cause to form hard particles; granulate. 使粒化:使形成硬的微粒;使粒化。 2. To cause to form hard particles;granulate. 使粒化使形成硬的微粒;使粒化 3. Wounds and ulcers can granulate. 伤口和溃疡的地方会长出肉芽。 4. Seeds numerous, curved (cochleate), small, densely granulate. 种子多数，弄弯(螺卷)，小，密被颗粒状。', '形容词: granulative 名词: granulator 过去式: granulated 过去分词: granulated 现在分词: granulating 第三人称单数: granulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inanimate', '[ɪn\'ænɪmət]', 'adj.无生命的', '1. Rocks and stones are inanimate. 岩石是无生命的。 2. Animals are living beings, not inanimate objects. 动物是生灵，不是没有生命的物体。', '副词: inanimately 名词: inanimateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fructify', '[\'frʌktəˌfaɪ]', 'v.结果实；使结果多；使多产', '1. Luck fructifies in the prepared mind. 幸运总是降临在有准备的人身上。', '过去式: fructified 过去分词: fructified 现在分词: fructifying 第三人称单数: fructifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('misnomer', '[ˌmɪs\'noʊmər]', 'n.误称；用词不当', '1. Indeed, the word \"constant\" may be a misnomer. 当然，“常数”这个词或许是个误称。 2. Luckily, that property is a bit of a misnomer. 幸运的是,这个属性名只是有点用词不当。', '形容词: misnomered');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embarrass', '[ɪm\'bærəs]', 'vt.使窘迫；使尴尬；使为难 vi.窘迫', '1. She dragged up that incident just to embarrass me. 她又扯起那件事故意想使我难堪。 2. He was embarrassed by many debts. 他被很多债务弄得焦灼不安。 3. She may embarrass you with her uncouth behavior. 她的粗野行为可能会让你尴尬。 4. You didn\'t embarrass me in the slightest. 你一点也没让我为难。 5. Eye contact may convey sincerity and attentiveness in Western cultures but too much eye contact may embarrass people in some Oriental cultures. 在西方文化，目光接触能传递真诚和关注，但太多的目光接触在某些东方文化中则令人窘迫。', '副词: embarrassedly 过去式: embarrassed 过去分词: embarrassed 现在分词: embarrassing 第三人称单数: embarrasses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('respite', '[\'respɪt]', 'n.暂缓；缓刑 vt.延迟；推延', '1. His Divine Mother would allow him no respite till he had left behind the entire realm of duality with its visions, experiences, and ecstatic dreams. 他的神圣母亲并没有允许他暂缓，直到他已经离开拥有各种异像，体验和入迷的梦的整个二元领域为止。', '过去式: respited 过去分词: respited 现在分词: respiting 第三人称单数: respites');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anodyne', '[\'ænədaɪn]', 'n.止痛药；安慰物 adj.止痛的；减轻忧愁的', '1. What anodyne is acetanilide better? 什么止痛药止痛比较好？ 2. He took some anodyne to relieve the pain. 他吃了些止痛药来缓解疼痛。 3. She had an acute pain in her wounded leg, so she had to take an anodyne. 她受伤的那条腿疼的厉害，她只好吃了一片止疼药。 4. Friendship is not only the condiment but also the anodyne of life. 友谊是人生的调味品,也是人生的止痛药。 5. This is daytime television at its most anodyne. 现在正是日间电视最不痛不痒的节目时间。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stanch', '[stɔːntʃ]', 'vt. 止住； 止血 vt. <古>减轻 adj. 坚固的 =staunch', '1. Cuttlebone can be used as a medicine to stanch bleeding. 海螵蛸可以入药，用来止血。', '异体字: staunch 名词: stancher 过去式: stanched/staunched 过去分词: stanched/staunched 现在分词: stanching/staunching 第三人称单数: stanches/staunches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conjure', '[\'kʌndʒə]', 'v.变戏法；恳求；唤起；以咒文召唤', '1. Jean can conjure up a good meal in half an hour. 琼能在半小时内变戏法似的做出一顿美味的饭菜。 2. Be on your guard, I conjure you. 千万要警惕呀，我恳求你。', '过去式: conjured 过去分词: conjured 现在分词: conjuring 第三人称单数: conjures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('superfluity', '[ˌsjuːpə\'fluːəti]', 'n.多余；过剩；奢侈品', '1. This book has a superfluity of introduction. 此本书中有多余的介绍。 2. The teacher pruned the student\'s article of its superfluities. 老师删去这个学生文章中的多余内容。 3. There is also a superfluity of stop signals. 此外，停止符的数量也有冗余。', '名词复数: superfluities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('charade', '[ʃə\'reɪd]', 'n.看手势猜字谜游戏；易识破的伪装', '1. Did you ever play charade before. 你有玩过看手势猜字谜游戏吗? 2. His poems, despite their dignity and felicity, have an air of charade. 他的诗篇虽然庄严巧妙，却有猜迷之嫌。 3. The interviews were just charade. 面试不过是个幌子。 4. The whole scene was as unreal as a charade. 整个场面就像手势字谜游戏那样矫饰做作。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consequence', '[\'kɑːnsəkwens]', 'n.结果；后果；重要性；影响', '1. It terrified me to contemplate the consequence of your action. 一想到你行动的后果,我就感到害怕。 2. He studied hard, and in consequence he passed the exam. 他努力学习，因此通过了考试。 3. Happiness is not a reward it is a consequence. 幸福不是报偿，而是结果。 4. In consequence of his bad conduct he was dismissed. 由于行为不良，他被开除了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('underling', '[\'ʌndərlɪŋ]', 'n.部下；下属', '1. He\'s an underling of a gang leader. 他是匪首的爪牙。 2. He seemed to be master, not underling now. 他现在显得象是个主人，不是个下属了。 3. God rules the universe and Satan is an underling in the scheme of things. 神长官整个宇宙，撒但只是一个下僚。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rampart', '[\'ræmpɑːrt]', 'n.垒；壁垒；城墙；防御', '1. They had been the great rampart of the colony on the North. 他们一向是北部殖民地的坚强保垒。 2. The rampart was destroyed totally. 壁垒被彻底摧毁了。 3. Perhaps the tower is part of the rampart of the city. 这城楼或许就是城墙的一部分。', '过去式: ramparted 过去分词: ramparted 现在分词: ramparting 第三人称单数: ramparts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disparity', '[dɪ\'spærəti]', 'n.不一致', '1. The disparity of age made it even grotesque. 年龄的悬殊甚至使它显得可笑。 2. We are still seeing a disparity between the rates of pay for men and women. 我们仍然能看到男女薪酬的不一致。 3. The great disparity between the teams did not make for an entertaining game. 两队实力悬殊，所以比赛并不精彩。', '名词复数: disparities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vitalize', '[\'vaɪtəˌlaɪz]', 'vt. 给与 ... 生命力； 激发； 使有活力', '1. Having separate time and interests will help vitalize the marriage. 拥有各自的私人空间将会激发你们婚姻的活力。', '名词: vitalization 过去式: vitalized 过去分词: vitalized 现在分词: vitalizing 第三人称单数: vitalizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lark', '[lɑːrk]', 'n.云雀；百灵鸟；嬉戏；玩笑 v.嬉戏', '1. A lark was singing high up in the sky. 一只云雀在高空中歌唱。 2. He is so proud of her, and always compares her to a lark. 他为她而感到骄傲，总是把她比作云雀。 3. The twitter of the lark is very pleasant. 百灵鸟的叫声很动听。 4. The merry lark warbles in the forest. 那只快乐的百灵鸟在树林里鸣叫。 5. Stop larking about and get on with your work. 别到处胡闹了，干活儿去吧。', '形容词: larkish 名词: larker 过去式: larked 过去分词: larked 现在分词: larking 第三人称单数: larks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crumple', '[\'krʌmpl]', 'v.（使)起皱；(使)崩溃；压垮 n.压痕；皱痕', '1. He put on a crumpled suit. 他穿上一件皱巴巴的西装。 2. Silk dresses are easy to crumple up if not carefully handled. 真丝衣服若不能正确处理，很容易起皱。 3. The wall was likely to crumple up at any time. 墙随时可以坍掉。 4. Her resistance to the proposal has crumpled. 她对这个建议的抵触情绪已化为乌有了。', '形容词: crumply 过去式: crumpled 过去分词: crumpled 现在分词: crumpling 第三人称单数: crumples');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('negate', '[nɪ\'ɡeɪt]', 'vt.否定；否认；使无效', '1. How can you negate God? 你怎么能否定上帝的存在? 2. These facts negate your theory. 这些事实否定了你的理论。 3. This power is always conceived in relation to men; it is not the power to do but the power to attract. It is a power that negates itself. (cf. Beauty, Susan Sontag) 这种力量也常常被认为和男性有关；这不是一种行动力而是一种吸引力。这是一种否定自身的力量。 4. The story negated the trade supported by the government. 该项报道否认了此项贸易受到政府的支持。', '名词: negator 过去式: negated 过去分词: negated 现在分词: negating 第三人称单数: negates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reiterate', '[ri\'ɪtəreɪt]', 'vt.重申', '1. The captain reiterated the command to us. 上尉对我们重申了那项命令。 2. We reiterate our determination to combat terrorism. 我们重申打击恐怖主义的决心。 3. I must reiterate that our position on this issue is very clear. 我必须重申我们对这一项议题的立场很清楚。', '形容词: reiterative 副词: reiteratively 名词: reiteration 过去式: reiterated 过去分词: reiterated 现在分词: reiterating 第三人称单数: reiterates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invade', '[ɪn\'veɪd]', 'v.侵略；拥入；侵害；侵扰', '1. When did the Romans invade Britain? 古罗马人是何时侵略英国的? 2. The town was invaded by reporters. 这个城市涌进了大批记者。 3. In the summer tourists invade the mountain village. 夏天游客成群结队地到这个山村来。 4. Germs may invade the organism. 细菌会侵入有机体。', '名词: invader 过去式: invaded 过去分词: invaded 现在分词: invading 第三人称单数: invades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barbarian', '[bɑːr\'beriən]', 'n.野蛮人 adj.野蛮的', '1. The barbarians conquered Rome. 野蛮人征服了罗马。 2. To the barbarian of the lower stage, a slave was valueless . 对于低级阶段的野蛮人来说，奴隶是没有价值的。 3. The barbarian defiled the church by use it as stable. 蛮夷人把教堂当作畜牲圈，使其受到玷污。 4. Rome went down before the barbarian invaders. 罗马被野蛮的侵略者所征服。', '名词: barbarianism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blowhard', '[\'bloʊhɑːrd]', 'n.自吹自擂者', '1. I don\'t want to sit next to that old blowhard. 我不想坐在那个爱自吹自擂的老人旁边。 2. The worst kind of interviewer is the blowhard. 爱吹牛的人是最差劲的面试官。 3. I don\'twant to sit next to that old blowhard. 我不想坐在那个爱自吹自擂的老人旁边。 4. I can sound like a bit of a blowhard, actually. 事实上，我给人感觉起来好像是个吹牛的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extravagance', '[ɪk\'strævəɡəns]', 'n.铺张浪费；奢侈品；富丽堂皇', '1. His extravagance kept him always in debt. 他的挥霍无度使他常常负债。 2. Extravagance has eaten up his inheritance. 他挥霍无度，耗尽了他所继承的财产。 3. My father rather gave me snuff about my extravagance, but I was prepared for that. 我父亲对我的铺张浪费大加谴责，不过我早就有了思想准备。 4. Going to the theatre is our only extravagance. 去剧院看戏是我们唯一的奢侈享受。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flunk', '[flʌŋk]', 'v.（使）失败；（使） 考试不及格 n.失败；不及格', '1. If you flunk finals you don\'t get the chance to do them again. 若你最后考试失败，你没有再做一次的机会了。 2. Several students have been flunked out. 有几名学生因考试不及格而被迫退学。 3. No less than ten students flunked the exam. 整整有十位学生在这次考试中不及格。 4. If you don\'t get on the ball and start studying harder, you\'re going to flunk. 如果你不积极进取，更加努力学习，你就会考不及格的。 5. If you flunk finals you don\'t get the chance to do them again. 若你最后考试失败，你没有再做一次的机会了。', '名词: flunker 过去式: flunked 过去分词: flunked 现在分词: flunking 第三人称单数: flunks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rumple', '[\'rʌmpl]', 'n.皱纹；皱褶 v.弄皱；弄乱', '1. You mustn\'t play in your new skirt, you\'ll rumple it. 你千万不要穿着新裙子去玩耍，你会把它弄皱的。', '形容词: rumply 过去式: rumpled 过去分词: rumpled 现在分词: rumpling 第三人称单数: rumples');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delimit', '[di\'lɪmɪt]', 'vt.定界限；划界', '1. The first chapter delimits her area of research. 第一章阐明了她的研究领域。 2. It is necessary to delimit the anomaly clearly. 清楚地圈定异常是必要的。 3. The group which they delimit are called natural groups. 由此划分出的类群称为自然类群。 4. The first chapter delimits her area of research. 第一章阐明了她的研究领域。', '形容词: delimitative 异体字: delimitate 名词: delimitation 过去式: delimited/delimitated 过去分词: delimited/delimitated 现在分词: delimiting/delimitating 第三人称单数: delimits/delimitates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('igneous', '[\'ɪɡniəs]', 'adj.(指岩石)火成的；火的；似火的', '1. Igneous rocks do not contain fossils. 火成岩不含化石。 2. The rocks here are igneous and do not fracture along predictable lines. 这儿的石头都是火成岩，石头的裂缝极不规则。 3. Igneous fusion is fusion by heat alone. 火熔解是指靠热度所完成的熔解。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cavern', '[\'kævərn]', 'n.大洞穴 v.置于洞穴中；挖空', '1. The girl lost her way in the cavern. 女孩在大洞穴中迷了路。 2. They explored the large cavern at the base of this cliff. 他们勘探了这个悬崖底部的大洞穴。', '过去式: caverned 过去分词: caverned 现在分词: caverning 第三人称单数: caverns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demoralize', '[dɪ\'mɔːrəlaɪz]', 'v.使士气低落；使失去斗志', '1. The troops were thoroughly demoralized by this set-back. 这一挫败使部队士气丧失殆尽。 2. Each attack is designed to demoralize our people and divide us from one another. 每一起袭击事件都妄想摧毁我们的士气，在我们中间制造隔阂。 3. Constant criticism is enough to demoralize anybody. 频繁的批评足以使任何人意志消沉。', '名词: demoralization 过去式: demoralized 过去分词: demoralized 现在分词: demoralizing 第三人称单数: demoralizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('outlandish', '[aʊt\'lændɪʃ]', 'adj.奇异的；异国风格的', '1. An outlandish glow came from the UFO. 从不明飞行物上发出奇特的光。 2. Her views on children are rather outlandish. 她对儿童的看法很奇怪. 3. The girl wore an outlandish dress. 那女孩穿着异国风格的衣服。 4. The outlandish costume screamed with clashing colors. 这件异国风味的服装由于颜色不协调而显得刺眼', '副词: outlandishly 名词: outlandishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pygmy', '[\'pɪɡmi]', 'n.矮人；侏儒', '1. The children stare at the silent Pygmy boy for a long time and he stares at them. 那个小男孩眼睛盯着那个安静的小矮人不放一段时间后他打量着他们两人。 2. He\'s a pygmy when compared with great musicians. 他和伟大的音乐家相比就成了侏儒。 3. Rare newborn albino Pygmy Marmoset monkeys perched on a zookeeper\'s fingers. 稀有的新出生白子侏儒狨猴栖息在一位动物园管理员的手指上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('omnipresent', '[ˌɑːmnɪ\'preznt]', 'adj.无处不在的', '1. Network is omnipresent nowadays. 现在的社会网络无处不在。 2. To these gutty inventor, good luck is omnipresent. 对于这些有勇气的发明家,机遇无所不在。', '名词: omnipresence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shrivel', '[\'ʃrɪvl]', 'v.（使）枯萎；（使）干枯；（使）皱缩', '1. Under the direct sunlight young plants will shrivel up. 在阳光的直射下，小苗会枯萎的。 2. The dry air shrivels the leather. 因空气干燥皮子都皱了。', '过去式: shriveled/shrivelled 过去分词: shriveled/shrivelled 现在分词: shriveling/shrivelling 第三人称单数: shrivels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dissemble', '[dɪ\'sembl]', 'v.掩饰；假装', '1. She tried to dissemble her anger with a smile on her face. 她试图用她脸上的微笑来掩饰她的愤怒。 2. I tried to dissemble an interest I didn\'t feel. 我设法假装感兴趣。', '副词: dissemblingly 名词: dissemblance 过去式: dissembled 过去分词: dissembled 现在分词: dissembling 第三人称单数: dissembles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mauve', '[moʊv]', 'n.淡紫色 adj.淡紫色的', '1. If you shut it in glass, it would turn the glass mauve or violet . 如果你把它装在玻璃容器里，它会把玻璃变成紫红色或淡紫色。 2. I\'m not sure black is your colour, Capitain. You could try mauve. 我觉得你穿黑色不好看，上校，你该试试淡紫色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('winning', '[\'wɪnɪŋ]', 'n.胜利；获得；成功 adj.获胜的；迷人的；使人成功的 动词win的现在分词.', '1. He anchored the winning team. 他担任胜了那一队的最后一棒。 2. Her winning time was 0.05 outside the would mark of Wilma. 她的获胜时间同威尔玛的世界记录只差0. 3. The usual rule in primaries is that voters flock to the winning candidate. 初选通常的规律是选民们纷纷涌向获胜的候选人。 4. Cowperwood returned his most winning beam. 柯帕乌报以最得意的微笑。', '副词: winningly 名词: winningness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ladle', '[\'leɪdl]', 'n.杓子；长柄杓 v.以杓舀取', '1. She dipped up soup from the pot with a ladle. 她用勺从锅里舀汤。 2. I use a soup ladle. 我用了一柄长柄汤杓。 3. She dipped out the soup with a ladle. 她用长柄杓舀汤。 4. There was a wood ladle chained to the deck. 甲板上拴著一个木长柄杓。 5. She ladled cream over her pudding. 她在布丁上浇了一勺奶油。', '名词: ladler 过去式: ladled 过去分词: ladled 现在分词: ladling 第三人称单数: ladles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disinfect', '[ˌdɪsɪn\'fekt]', 'v.消毒；杀菌', '1. Disinfect the wound before you bandage it up. 伤口包扎之前应先消毒。 2. Two health workers disinfect each car goes through the village. 两个防疫人员给每一辆进出村子的车子消毒。 3. Caregivers should be trained in ways to clean, sanitize and disinfect. 护理人员应该接受打扫、清洁和消毒方面的训练。', '名词: disinfection 过去式: disinfected 过去分词: disinfected 现在分词: disinfecting 第三人称单数: disinfects');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('typo', '[\'taɪpoʊ]', 'n.打字排版错误', '1. So a lie, or a mistake, or a typo, can be amplified and streamlined and then beamed into every home in a matter of seconds, all thanks to the wonderful power of the Interweb. 真要感谢功能强大的互联网，它使得一个谎言，一条误传，甚至一个排版错误都可能被放大，并瞬间传遍全世界。', '名词复数: typos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cerebral', '[sə\'riːbrəl]', 'adj.大脑的；理智的', '1. This bibliography provides references to studies that attempt to correlate cerebral functions to cerebral structures in individuals with abnormalities. 在研究变态个体时企图使大脑皮层官能与大脑的结构相关提供参考。 2. His style is far more cerebral than confrontational. 他的执教风格是理智的，而不是过激的。 3. Bryant still puts up the numbers, but he is a more cerebral player now. 科比还是能打出不错的数据，但他现在更是一个更理智的球员。', '副词: cerebrally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hut', '[hʌt]', 'n.小屋；棚屋 v.在棚屋中隐蔽', '1. They tore down that old hut. 他们把那间旧草屋拆掉了。 2. The hut was made out of pieces of wood. 这小屋是用木板建造的。 3. The hut was made of poles covered with grass mats. 茅屋用木杆搭成，上面以草席覆盖。 4. We heard the rain spattering down on the roof of the hut. 我们听到雨滴滴答答打在小屋的顶上。 5. We can hut on the mountain tonight. 今晚我们可以住在山上的棚屋里。', '过去式: hutted 过去分词: hutted 现在分词: hutting 第三人称单数: huts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('traitor', '[\'treɪtər]', 'n.叛徒；卖国贼；出卖朋友者', '1. The infamous traitor was sentenced to death. 那个罪大恶极的叛徒被判处死刑。 2. He struck a knife into the traitor\'s heart. 他将刀戳入卖国贼的心脏。 3. The traitor sold our important military secrets to the enemy. 这卖国贼把我方重要的军事秘密卖给敌人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plod', '[plɑːd]', 'v.沉重地走；辛勤工作；孜孜从事 n.沉重的步伐；辛勤工作', '1. They had to plod wearily on up the hill. 他们不得不迈著疲倦的步子登上山。 2. We plodded on through the rain for several hours. 我们在雨中跋涉了几个小时。 3. Do you plod through the day at the office? 你是否在办公室里埋头苦干了一整天呢？ 4. I could recognize his plod anywhere. 我能在任何地方辨认出他的沉重脚步声。', '副词: ploddingly 名词: plodder 过去式: plodded 过去分词: plodded 现在分词: plodding 第三人称单数: plods');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pastoral', '[\'pæstərəl]', 'adj.田园的；宁静的；牧人的；牧师的 n.田园诗；牧歌；牧函', '1. Trace an analogy between pastoral poetry and landscape painting. 找出田园诗和风景画之间的相似之处。 2. This idyllic pastoral scene is only part of the picure. 但这种田园诗般的乡村风光只汪是一个侧面而已。 3. The first part, mainly discuss Chinese ncient pastoral eclogue the origins and the spirit substance of the literature. 第一部分，主要论述中国古代田园牧歌文学的起源及精神实质对于迟子建的影响。 4. And poetic quality shows warm interest about pastoral and distant aesthetic interest. 而诗性则表现为温厚的牧歌情调和淡远的审美情趣。', '副词: pastorally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jettison', '[\'dʒetɪsn]', 'v.抛弃；丢弃；投弃 n.投弃；投弃的货物', '1. The first-stage vehicle is used to launch the rocket and is then jettisoned in the upper atmosphere. 第一级运载火箭是用来发射火箭的,进入高层大气后即抛掉。 2. We jettison an unworkable plan . 我们放弃难实行的计划。 3. We\'re going to jettison the cargo. 我们正准备投弃货物。 4. No jettison of cargo shall be allowed as general average, unless such cargo is carried in accordance with the recognised custom of the trade. 被抛弃的货物，除非按照公认的海运习惯运送，不得作为共同海损受到补偿。', '过去式: jettisoned 过去分词: jettisoned 现在分词: jettisoning 第三人称单数: jettisons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('riffle', '[\'rɪfl]', 'n.急流；涟漪；洗牌；浅滩；槽沟 v.洗牌；翻查；使湍急', '1. Army regulations prescribe how a riffle must be carried. 军规中对持枪方式有明文规定。 2. Don\'t continually riffle the ends or over shuffle the deck. 9. 十、不要拨牌直到底牌或者把牌洗过头（感觉翻的怪怪的）。 3. A participant drops in a bookmark as you riffle the pages. 参加者在书签投下作为你浅滩页。 4. Once riffle and tank was the main weapons of the battle field. 步枪和坦克曾经是战场上的主要武器。', '过去式: riffled 过去分词: riffled 现在分词: riffling 第三人称单数: riffles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flight', '[flaɪt]', 'n.飞行；航班；镖尾；逃走，逃离，溃逃', '1. She photographed the birds in flight. 她拍摄鸟儿飞行的照片。 2. I\'ll book a direct flight to London for you. 我将为你预订直飞伦敦的航班。', '过去式: flighted 过去分词: flighted 现在分词: flighting 第三人称单数: flights');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ornate', '[ɔːr\'neɪt]', 'adj.华丽的；装饰的', '1. The style is ornate and highly decorative. 这种风格很华丽，而且装饰效果很好。 2. That style of architecture is too ornate for my taste. 那种建筑风格太华丽了，不对我的口味。 3. The parks of this city are famous for their ornate fountains. 这个城市的公园以其华丽的喷泉而著名。', '副词: ornately 名词: ornateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alluring', '[ə\'lʊrɪŋ]', 'adj.迷人的；诱惑的 动词allure的现在分词形式.', '1. Yeah, the singer with the grey hair is so alluring. 嗯，那个银发歌手非常迷人！ 2. The scent is really soft and alluring. 这香味真是柔和诱人。 3. Lisette\'s large red mouth broke into a most alluring smile. 莉莎特的鲜红大嘴露出一副极为诱人的微笑。 4. Never have I seen her lips so alluring. 我从来没有看见她的嘴唇是那么诱惑人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mottled', '[\'mɑːtld]', 'adj.有杂色的；斑驳的 动词mottle的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. Mottled pink and brown areas are a combination of the cosmic dust and reddish emission from ionized hydrogen gas. 斑驳的粉红色和褐色区域是宇宙尘埃和电离氢气放射出的红光相结合的产物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hail', '[heɪl]', 'n.冰雹 vi.下冰雹 vt.招呼；喝彩；宣称；来自 n.欢呼', '1. For three hours, the hail rattles on the roof. 一连三个小时，冰雹在屋顶上哗啦哗啦地下着。 2. The hail beat a loud tattoo on the windowpane. 冰雹在窗玻璃上嘈杂地连续敲打。 3. It\'s hailing outside. 外面在下冰雹。 4. An old friend hailed me from the other side of the street. 一个老朋友从街的对面喊我。 5. The youngsters greeted their idol with a hail. 那群年轻人向他们的偶像欢呼致敬。', '过去式: hailed 过去分词: hailed 现在分词: hailing 第三人称单数: hails');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retention', '[rɪ\'tenʃn]', 'n.保留物；保存；保持(力)；记忆力', '1. The retention is withheld only for bonus situation. 滞留金只是为了发奖金。 2. Did you specify a reasonable retention age? 是否指定了合理的保持期? 3. Plan a retention policy for e-mail messages and log entries. 为电子邮件和日志项计划一个保持策略。 4. His retention of energy at this hour is really surprising. 人们惊叹他在这个时候还能保持如此旺盛的精力。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eminent', '[\'emɪnənt]', 'adj.著名的；卓越的', '1. Was an eminent landscape poet in ancient China. 是中国古代著名的山水诗作家。 2. Eminent physicists from all over the world came to the United States to celebrate the centennial of Einstein\'s birth. 全世界著名的物理学家来到美国庆祝爱因斯坦诞生一百周年。 3. Churchill was one of the world\'s most eminent statesmen. 邱吉尔是世界上最卓越的政治家之一。 4. Throughout the ages this eminent masterpiece has always held a special place in the hearts of Irish people. 各个时代，这一卓越的杰作都始终在爱尔兰民众的心中占据着一个特殊的位置。', '副词: eminently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crafty', '[\'kræfti]', 'adj.狡猾的；熟练的；巧妙的', '1. They are crafty politicians. 他们是群老奸巨滑的政客。 2. He\'s a crafty old fox. 他是一只狡猾的老狐狸。 3. This crafty man is nothing but a crook. 那个狡猾的人纯粹是个骗子。 4. This fellow is very crafty; we had better be on our guard. 这个家伙诡计多端， 我们可得小心点儿。', '副词: craftily 比较级: craftier 最高级: craftiest 名词: craftiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deflect', '[dɪ\'flekt]', 'v.使偏斜；转向；改变原计划', '1. The missile deflected from its trajectory. 导弹已偏离轨道。 2. The bullet hit a wall and was deflected from its course. 子弹击中墙壁而改变了方向。 3. Don\'t try to deflect me from my intention! 别想改变我的意图。', '形容词: deflectable 名词: deflector 过去式: deflected 过去分词: deflected 现在分词: deflecting 第三人称单数: deflects');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bulge', '[bʌldʒ]', 'n.膨胀；暴增 v.膨胀；充满', '1. The apple made a bulge in his pocket. 苹果把他口袋塞得鼓了起来。 2. The gun caused a bulge in his jacket. 藏在衣服内的枪使他的上衣鼓出一块。 3. The baby boom created a bulge in school enrollment. 生育高峰造成学校入学人数的暴涨 4. After the war there was a bulge in the birth rate. 战后出生率激增。 5. My pockets were bulging with apples. 我的口袋因装着苹果而鼓起来了。', '形容词: bulgy 名词: bulginess 过去式: bulged 过去分词: bulged 现在分词: bulging 第三人称单数: bulges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rag', '[ræɡ]', 'n.破布；碎布；破衣服；（低劣的）报纸', '1. She twisted a rag round my hand. 她用一块破布包住我的手。 2. He plugged the hole in the pipe with an old rag. 他用一块旧破布把管子上的那个洞塞住了。 3. He wrapped a clean rag around his ankle. 他把一小块乾净的布缠住脚腕。 4. It\'s just an old rag I had in the closet. 这只不过是我挂在壁橱里的旧衣服罢了。', '过去式: ragged 过去分词: ragged 现在分词: ragging 第三人称单数: rags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monarch', '[\'mɑːnərk]', 'n.帝王；统治者；君主 n.君王斑点蝶', '1. They attempted to overthrow the monarch. 他们企图推翻国王。 2. The national band played for the visiting monarch. 国家乐团演奏给来访的帝王听。 3. I think myself happier now than the greatest monarch upon earth. 我觉得这个时候比世界上什么帝王都快乐。 4. They also crowned Dath\'Remar as their first monarch. 他们拥护达斯雷玛成为他们的第一任皇权统治者。 5. I saw the monarch butterfly by accident. 我偶尔看见了君王斑点蝶。', '形容词: monarchal 副词: monarchally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discombobulate', '[ˌdɪskəm\'bɒbjəˌleɪt]', 'vt.使混乱；使困惑', '1. The term comes from \"discombobulate\" which means to confuse or frustrate, and \"Google\". “Discomgooglation”一词是“discombobulate”（混乱、丧气）和Google（搜索引擎“谷歌”）两个词的合成。', '名词: discombobulation 过去式: discombobulated 过去分词: discombobulated 现在分词: discombobulating 第三人称单数: discombobulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fainthearted', '[\'feɪnth\'ɑːtɪd]', 'adj.懦弱的；无精神的；胆小的', '1. Fortune is not on the side of the fainthearted. 命运之神不支持懦夫。 2. Fortune is not on side of the fainthearted. 命运之神不支持懦夫。 3. Even a sip is not for the fainthearted. 即便是小啜一口也不是懦夫所能承受的。 4. This cemetery is not for the fainthearted. 当我去参观的时候，我并没有跟团去我毫无目的的在一个方形的砖制的墓地闲逛，发现很多墓地已经被破坏了，很多遗体都稀稀拉拉的存在着，胆小的人是不敢来这个墓地的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mobility', '[moʊ\'bɪləti]', 'n.流动性；机动性；情感不定', '1. Housing is a far bigger drag on American job mobility. 住房严重拖累了美国就业的流动性。 2. Recent years have witnessed a growing social mobility. 近年来人们的社会流动性越来越大。 3. Mobility is very important in guerrilla warfare. 机动性在游击战中至关重要。 4. A private car gives a much greater degree of comfort and mobility. 私人小汽车能给人很大的舒服和机动性。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ford', '[fɔːrd]', 'v.涉过；涉水 n.浅滩 Ford. n.福特汽车；福特（人名）', '1. The stream was so deep that we could not ford it. 河水太深了,以致于我们无法涉水而过。 2. She forded the river in a hurry. 她匆匆忙忙涉水过了河。 3. The soldier rode out of the ford with the scouts in advance. 侦察兵先涉过浅滩，战士们跟着安然渡过。 4. This shallow ford made it possible for us to cross the river. 我们有可能从这片浅滩过河。 5. This company has exclusive rights for the sale of Ford cars in the city. 这家公司享有福特汽车在本市的独家经销权。', '形容词: fordable 过去式: forded 过去分词: forded 现在分词: fording 第三人称单数: fords');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('backhanded', '[ˌbæk\'hændɪd]', 'adj.间接的；讽刺的；反手拍击的 动词backhand的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. He reached his goal with a backhanded and dishonest way. 他以间接的、不诚实的方法达到目标。 2. That\'s rather a backhanded compliment. 那倒是一则挖苦的恭维话。 3. Brown took his usual backhanded jabs at his club yesterday. 布朗昨天在他的酒吧习惯性的在背后说别人的坏话。', '副词: backhandedly 名词: backhandedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illegitimate', '[ˌɪlə\'dʒɪtəmət]', 'adj.非法的；私生的；不合规则的', '1. The agency made illegitimate use of public funds. 这个机构非法动用公款。 2. Perhaps she was an illegitimate daughter. 也许她是个私生女。 3. He was discarded as an illegitimate child. 他被当作私生子抛弃了。 4. In this sentence the writer uses an illegitimate construction. 作者在这个句子中用了不符合语法的结构。', '副词: illegitimately');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flagrant', '[\'fleɪɡrənt]', 'adj.恶名昭著的；明目张胆的', '1. Telling the story was a flagrant breach of trust. 说谎是一种可耻的破坏信誉的行为。 2. The most flagrant scofflaw of them all is the red-light runner. 最明目张胆的藐视法律行径要算闯红灯了。 3. My manager was fired for a flagrant abuse of company funds. 我的经理因明目张胆地滥用公司的资金而被解雇。', '副词: flagrantly 名词: flagrancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rebellious', '[rɪ\'beljəs]', 'adj.叛逆的；难以控制的', '1. This child is obstinate and rebellious. 这个孩子倔强，难以管束。 2. Those rebellious teenagers are hard to control. 那些反叛的青少年很难管教。 3. The rebellious student was sent home. 这个叛逆的学生被送回家去了。 4. I know I shouldn\'t have been so rebellious. 我知道我本来不该这么叛逆。', '副词: rebelliously 名词: rebelliousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incorrigible', '[ɪn\'kɔːrɪdʒəbl]', 'adj.无药可救的；积习难改的；固执的 n.不可救药的人', '1. Eye myopia is sometimes incorrigible. 有时候眼睛近视真的无药可救了。 2. Most of them are incorrigible, and hated by others. 他们多数是不可救药的,而且憎恨他人。 3. Her husband is an incorrigible flirt. 她的丈夫是个积习难改的调情老手。 4. The new dealers were incorrigible philosophizers. 新政人物都是一些固执的空谈阔论者。', '副词: incorrigibly 名词: incorrigibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scrappy', '[\'skræpi]', 'adj.零碎的；好斗的；斗志旺盛的；零乱的', '1. The concert was rather a scrappy affair. 这场音乐会真可说是一个七拼八凑的大杂烩。 2. The note was written on a scrappy bit of paper. 便条写在一片破纸上。 3. I have only a scrappy knowledge of the latest scientific achievements. 对于科学的最新成就我只是星星点点知道一些。 4. \"It was a scrappy game,\" he told Sky Sports. “这是一场竞争激烈的球队，\"他接受天空体育采访说道。', '副词: scrappily 比较级: scrappier 最高级: scrappiest 名词: scrappiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vim', '[vɪm]', 'n.精力；生气；精神', '1. He is a person who is full of vim. 他是一个精力充沛的人。 2. He set to his task with renewed vim and vigour. 他再度打起精神,着手完成自己的工作。 3. This young chap works with vim and vigour. 这小伙子干活有股子猛劲儿。 4. The global housing boom has lost a lot of its vim. 全球房市发展势头已大大减弱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('privilege', '[\'prɪvəlɪdʒ]', 'n.特权；荣幸；特别恩典；基本人权 vt.给特权；免除', '1. I had the privilege of meeting the queen. 我有会见王后的特权。 2. It is a great privilege to know you. 认识你是一件难得的事。 3. It was a privilege to work with him. 和他在一起工作是一项殊荣。 4. Kings cannot privilege what God forbade. 国王不能原谅上帝不允许做的事。', '过去式: privileged 过去分词: privileged 现在分词: privileging 第三人称单数: privileges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('passive', '[\'pæsɪv]', 'adj.被动的；消极的 n.被动性', '1. He played a passive role in the marriage. 他在婚姻中扮演了一个被动的角色。 2. You are passive when you allow things to happen, but do nothing. 当你让这些事发生,而不做任何事来阻止它,你是消极的。 3. Good is the passive that obeys reason. 善是服从理智的被动性。 4. Passive tear suctioning force can be demonstrated by a Venturi tube model. 被动性泪液吸引之力量，可藉由文氏管模型来解释。', '副词: passively 名词: passiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cringe', '[krɪndʒ]', 'vi.畏缩；觉得尴尬不安或难为情；阿谀，奉承 n.畏缩；阿谀，奉承', '1. People often cringe when they hear the word \"fat\". 人们常常听到“脂肪”这个词后会畏缩。 2. But just the thought of mentioning it to her made him cringe. 可是一想到要向她表明这一想法，他就会犹豫、退缩。 3. It may be difficult to believe, but some people actually cringe when an opportunity presents itself. 令人难以置信的是，有些人竟在机遇来临时畏缩。 4. His way of sleeping makes me cringe. 他睡觉的方式令我生厌。', '过去式: cringed 过去分词: cringed 现在分词: cringing 第三人称单数: cringes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clique', '[kliːk]', 'n.派系；小集团', '1. I always hang out and eat lunch with my clique. 我总是和我那群朋友出去和一起去吃午餐。 2. On this point they are entirely at one with the capitulationist clique. 在这一点上，他们和投降派毫无二致。 3. But I have a clear conscience, partly because I have never tried to form a clique. 但是我问心无愧,其中一点就是我从来不搞小圈子。 4. The reactionary ruling clique is torn by internal strife. 反动统治集团内部勾心斗角，四分五裂。', '形容词: cliquey 副词: cliquishly 名词: cliquishness 过去式: cliqued 过去分词: cliqued 现在分词: cliquing 第三人称单数: cliques');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contrite', '[kən\'traɪt]', 'adj.悔悟了的；后悔的；痛悔的', '1. He was to be contrite and wish to be reconciled. 他必须感到悔悟，并且希望得到赦免。 2. He made a contrite apology. 他深表懊悔地致歉。 3. The look she gave Anna was guilty and contrite. 她给安娜的脸色是内疚和愧悔的。 4. She was contrite the whole morning after her angry outburst. 她发了一通脾气之后整个早上都追悔莫及。', '副词: contritely 名词: contriteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('catalyst', '[\'kætəlɪst]', 'n.催化剂；刺激因素', '1. War is a catalyst to help them to choose. 战争是一副催化剂来帮助他们选择。 2. Debate is the best catalyst of thought. 争论是思想最好的催化剂。 3. This tragedy will be a catalyst for good. 这场悲剧会是美好的催化剂。 4. The results were then used to make better car catalyst. 这一研究的成果可随后用于生产出效果更好的汽车催化剂。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stagy', '[\'steɪdʒi]', 'adj.做作的；演戏一般的 =stagey.', '1. The room was decorated with stagy opulence. 那房间装饰得富丽堂皇，像戏台似的。', '副词: stagily 名词: staginess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('characterization', '[ˌkærəktəraɪ\'zeɪʃn]', 'n.特性描述；人物性格塑造', '1. It\'s a list of places of interest with brief characterizations of each. 这是一张带有每个地方简短的特点描述的名胜古迹表。 2. Dickens\'s novels are full of vivid characterization. 狄更斯的小说中充满了栩栩如生的人物形象。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('espouse', '[ɪ\'spaʊz]', 'vt.支持；赞成；嫁娶', '1. Today, astronomers espouse the theory that comets spawn the swarms. 如今，天文学家们支持彗星产生了流星团的说法。 2. But not all Talons espouse the humans\' extermination. 但是不是所有的魔爪都支持杀光人类。', '名词: espouser 过去式: espoused 过去分词: espoused 现在分词: espousing 第三人称单数: espouses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delirium', '[dɪ\'lɪriəm]', 'n.精神错乱；说胡话；狂喜', '1. He was exhausted by the fever and delirium. 他发烧精神错乱说胡话，因而疲惫不堪。 2. Sports fans were in delirium after their team\'s victory. 球迷在他们所支持的球队胜利后极度兴奋。', '形容词: deliriant 名词复数: deliriums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('warp', '[wɔːrp]', 'vt.使翘起；弄歪；歪曲 vi.变歪；扭曲 n.弯曲；歪曲；乖僻；经纱；绞船索', '1. The heat has warped the boards. 热使木板弯翘了。 2. His judgement was warped by self-interest. 他受私心影响判断不确。 3. Histories are often warped by biases. 历史常为偏见所曲解。 4. The window frames had begun to warp. 窗框已经开始变形。 5. There is a warp in the board. 这块木板有点弯曲。', '名词: warper 过去式: warped 过去分词: warped 现在分词: warping 第三人称单数: warps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recapitulate', '[ˌriːkə\'pɪtʃuleɪt]', 'v.扼要重述', '1. It will be helpful to recapitulate them. 在这里将其简要重述一下也是有帮助的。 2. Let me just recapitulate (on) what we\'ve agreed so far. 让我仅扼要重述一下到目前为止我们已取得的一致意见。', '形容词: recapitulative 过去式: recapitulated 过去分词: recapitulated 现在分词: recapitulating 第三人称单数: recapitulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('divers', '[\'daɪvərz]', 'adj.不同的；种种的 pron.若干个 n.跳水者，潜水员（名词diver的复数形式）', '1. Divers persons were present, of all stations in life. 不同身份的、形形色色的人都出席了。 2. The vigorous man is engaged in divers activities. 那个精力旺盛的男人从事各种不同的活动。 3. He chose divers of them, who were asked to accompany him. 他选择他们当中的几个人，要他们和他作伴。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('belligerence', '[bə\'lɪdʒərəns]', 'n.交战；好战性；斗争性', '1. What poses a threat here is not belligerence but inertia. 在这里，真正造成威胁的并不是交战状态，而是经济的呆滞。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suitcase', '[\'suːtkeɪs]', 'n.手提箱', '1. My wife compacted my clothes in a suitcase. 妻子把我的衣服紧塞在手提箱里。 2. We\'ve got a spare suitcase but it\'s not very get-at-able. 我们有个多余的手提箱，但是不太容易拿出来。 3. He stuffed the suitcase with his clothes. 他把衣服塞满手提箱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subjugate', '[\'sʌbdʒuɡeɪt]', 'v.征服；制服；克制；抑制', '1. Imperialism has not been able to subjugate China. 帝国主义不能征服中国。 2. It\'s not our aim to subjugate our foe. 我们的目的不是要制服敌人。 3. The city residents have to oppress and subjugate their loves towards water. 城市人不得不压抑克制自己身上的亲水本能。', '名词: subjugation 过去式: subjugated 过去分词: subjugated 现在分词: subjugating 第三人称单数: subjugates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pique', '[piːk]', 'n.生气；愤怒 v.伤害 ... 自尊心；激怒；产生', '1. Out of pique they refused to accept the compromise offered. 他们气得拒不接受对方提出的妥协建议。 2. Tom finished the sentence with an air of pique. 汤姆有些生气地说完这句话。 3. When he realized nobody was listening to him, he left the room in a fit of pique. 他发觉谁也没有听他讲话，一气之下就走了。 4. He was piqued to discover that he hadn\'t been invited. 他发现自己未被邀请,感到伤了自尊。', '过去式: piqued 过去分词: piqued 现在分词: piquing 第三人称单数: piques');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perk', '[pɜːrk]', 'v.（使）振作；打扮；竖起 vi.滤煮 n.额外津贴；特权；利益', '1. No one can help him perk after his wife was died. 他的妻子死后，没有人可以使他振作起来。 2. A cup of coffee will soon perk you up. 你喝一杯咖啡马上精神会振作起来。 3. He had perked himself up for the occasion. 他为此事打扮了一番。 4. The horse perked up its head when I shouted. 我吆喝时那马扬起了头。 5. His perks include a car provided by the firm. 他的额外津贴包括公司提供的一辆汽车。', '过去式: perked 过去分词: perked 现在分词: perking 第三人称单数: perks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accomplish', '[ə\'kɑːmplɪʃ]', 'vt.完成；实现', '1. I have accomplished a great deal in the last few months. 在过去几个月里，我完成了相当多的工作。 2. The prediction was literally accomplished. 这个预言确实实现了。 3. The role of a judge is to accomplish fairness. 法官的职责是实现公平。', '形容词: accomplishable 名词: accomplisher 过去式: accomplished 过去分词: accomplished 现在分词: accomplishing 第三人称单数: accomplishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('purvey', '[pər\'veɪ]', 'v.供给；供应', '1. They purvey food for the army. 他们供应食品给军队。', '名词: purveyance 过去式: purveyed 过去分词: purveyed 现在分词: purveying 第三人称单数: purveys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scatter', '[\'skætər]', 'vt.散播；撒；驱散 vi.分散；消散 n.散布；零星少量', '1. She wanted us to scatter her ashes to the winds. 她希望我们把她的骨灰散播到风中。 2. The farmers were scattering seed on the fields. 农夫把种子撒在田里。 3. Let\'s try not to scatter food or drink on the table. 别把饭或汤撒到桌上。 4. The police scattered the crowd. 警察驱散了人群。 5. Small villages scatter at the foot of the mountain. 村庄零零落落地散布在山脚下。 6. She gave the soup a quick scatter of herbs. 她把香料快速撒在汤上。', '名词: scatterer 过去式: scattered 过去分词: scattered 现在分词: scattering 第三人称单数: scatters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heinous', '[\'heɪnəs]', 'adj.可憎的；十恶不赦的', '1. His brother is a heinous boy. 他弟弟是个讨厌的孩子。 2. They admitted to the most heinous crimes. 他们承认了极其恶劣的罪行。 3. I do not want to meet that heinous person. 我不想见那个十恶不赦的人。', '副词: heinously 名词: heinousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fictitious', '[fɪk\'tɪʃəs]', 'adj.假想的；虚假的；虚伪的', '1. Hamlet was a fictitious character. 哈姆莱特是一个虚构的人物。 2. The characters in this story are all fictitious. 这个故事里的人物都是假想的。 3. The account he gives of his childhood is quite fictitious. 他把童年往事说得很假。 4. He greeted me with a fictitious enthusiasm. 他用虚伪的热情跟我打招呼。', '副词: fictitiously 名词: fictitiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('needle', '[\'niːdl]', 'n.针 vt.用针缝；激怒；嘲弄 vi.缝纫', '1. The needle pierced her finger. 针刺进了她的手指。 2. She pricked herself on a needle. 她被针扎了一下。 3. The road looks beautiful covered by golden pine needles. 这条路上铺满了金黄色的松针，看上去美极了。 4. My mother is needling my coat. 我妈妈在给我缝外套。 5. The girl is good at needling. 这个女孩擅长做缝纫活。', '名词: needler 过去式: needled 过去分词: needled 现在分词: needling 第三人称单数: needles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('offstage', '[ˌɔːf\'steɪdʒ]', 'adj.不在舞台上的；戏外的 adv.不在舞台上地；戏外', '1. Kabuki employs two musical ensembles, one onstage and the other offstage. 歌舞伎有两个音乐剧团，一是在舞台上，一是舞台内部。 2. The stars were having an offstage relationship. 这些明星在现实生活中有着亲昵关系。 3. It was the tank was brought on for the first trick and then taken offstage. 水箱是为第一个魔术准备的,后来被搬到台下了。 4. While Cash told it like it is in his songs, he lied and cheated offstage. 虽然卡什在歌声中是真诚的，但他在舞台之下却撒谎骗人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seemly', '[\'siːmli]', 'adj.适当的；合宜的；得体的 adv.适当地', '1. Friendly relations should keep a seemly distance . 适当的距离是人际交往中最需要把握的尺寸。 2. We will call at a more seemly time. 我们会在更适合的时候来拜访的。 3. Chewing gum on a train is not seemly in a lady. 淑女在火车上嚼囗香糖不太合适。', '比较级: seemlier 最高级: seemliest 名词: seemliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cavil', '[\'kævl]', 'v.挑毛病；吹毛求疵 n.无端指摘；挑毛病', '1. Even he could find nothing to cavil about. 连他都挑不出什么毛病来。 2. He cavilled at being asked to cook his own breakfast. 他嗔怪让他自己做早饭。', '名词: caviler 过去式: caviled/cavilled 过去分词: caviled/cavilled 现在分词: caviling/cavilling 第三人称单数: cavils/cavils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marrow', '[\'mæroʊ]', 'n.骨髓；精华；活力 n.西葫芦', '1. Bone marrow is full of stem cells. 骨髓中含有丰富的干细胞。 2. How is application marrow donated? 怎样申请骨髓捐赠？ 3. I wanted to live deep and suck out all the marrow of life! 我希望活的深刻，吸取生命中所有的精华，把非生命的一切都击溃。 4. Fear took the marrow out of him. 恐惧使他失去了活力。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chrysanthemum', '[krɪ\'sænθəməm]', 'n.菊花', '1. It was a special tea which tasted of chrysanthemum. 它是一种有菊花味的特别茶叶。 2. There are many species of chrysanthemum. 菊花品种很多。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kin', '[kɪn]', 'n.家族；亲属 adj.亲属关系的；同类的 suf.(接名词后)小的', '1. The conversion will be a tendency for kin enterprise in China. 中国的家族企业进行转型将成为一种趋势。 2. However, the Mesozoic is best known as the age of reptiles, when dinosaurs and their kin dominated the continents. 但中生代还是以爬行动物时代而著名，在这个时期，恐龙以及它们的家族统治了整个大陆。 3. All our kin came to the family reunion. 我们的亲属全都参加了这次家庭团聚会。 4. Her next of kin have been informed. 已通知她最近的亲属了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prolific', '[prə\'lɪfɪk]', 'adj.多产的；作品丰富的', '1. Shakespeare was a prolific writer. 莎士比亚是一个多产的作家。 2. Trollope\'s strict work routine enabled him to keep his day job as a civil servant while being such a prolific writer. 特罗洛普严格的工作常规使他成为一名如此多产的作家同时仍能让他白天做好公务员这份差使。', '副词: prolifically 名词: prolificacy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retribution', '[ˌretrɪ\'bjuːʃn]', 'n.报应；惩罚；报复；报偿', '1. Restitution is more important than retribution. 赔偿比惩罚重要。 2. His right hand suddenly ordered divine retribution to stand by. 他的右手突然命令上天的惩罚做好准备。 3. Then it\'s like Orr wearing a face shield while dishing out retribution. 然后它就像奥尔身穿面罩而抛出报复。 4. The French were in a state of postwar shock and clamoring for fearful retribution. 法国人处于一种战后惊恐状态，叫嚷要进行可怕的报复。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('justify', '[\'dʒʌstɪfaɪ]', 'vt.替 ... 辩护；证明 ... 正当；调整版面', '1. He had to justify himself for his conduct. 他不得不为自己的行为辩白。 2. Don\'t try to justify your mistakes. 不要为自己的缺点辩护。 3. Nothing can justify your cheating on an exam. 任何事情都不能成为你考试作弊的理由。 4. Such action can be justified on the grounds of greater efficiency. 以提高功效为依据可以证明采取这种措施是正确的。', '过去式: justified 过去分词: justified 现在分词: justifying 第三人称单数: justifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accretion', '[ə\'kriːʃn]', 'n.生长；增加；连生；积累而成的东西；添加物；【地】冲积层', '1. The fund was increased by the accretion of new shareholders. 随着新股民的增加，基金上涨了。 2. The chimney was blocked by an accretion of soot. 烟囱被聚积的煤烟子堵塞了。 3. The mythical story has been overlaid by literary accretions. 这个虚构的故事是由一些文学添加而成的。', '形容词: accretionary');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('attribute', '[\'ætrɪbjuːt]', 'vt.把 ... 归于 n.属性；标志；象征；特征', '1. Most historians attribute such declines to wars and conquests. 大多数的历史学家把这样的衰亡归于战争和征服。 2. Many people\'s success can be attributed to hard work and a bit of luck. 很多人的成功都可以归于勤奋加上一点儿运气。 3. Public perception can also create a legal right for an attribute of a product. 公众的认知也能为产品的某个属性创造法律权利。 4. The attribute that indicates that the same copy of a routine cannot be used by another task. 一种属性，表示某一例行程序的同一副本不能被另一个任务使用。', '形容词: attributable 名词: attributer 过去式: attributed 过去分词: attributed 现在分词: attributing 第三人称单数: attributes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decentralize', '[ˌdiː\'sentrəlaɪz]', 'v.(使)权力下放；(使工业、人口等)分散 =decentralise(美).', '1. The city government is looking for ways to decentralize. 市政府正在寻求分权的方法。 2. If we decentralize, the provinces will have more autonomy. 我们把权力下放，各省就有更多的自主权。 3. The chief measures to consolidate democracy are to decentralize, to develop political culture and to establish civil society. 民主巩固的主要措施是下放权力,培养民主政治文化,形成文明社会。 4. This ability to decentralize solar energy is something that fossil fuel burning cannot match. 这个分散太阳能的能力是传统的燃料燃烧所比不上的。', '名词: decentralization 过去式: decentralized 过去分词: decentralized 现在分词: decentralizing 第三人称单数: decentralizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spurn', '[spɜːrn]', 'v.轻蔑地拒绝；摒弃 n.摒弃', '1. I spurn your offer. 我拒绝你的提议。 2. Carl had been from his childhood a ball of fortune to spurn at. 自从童年时起卡尔就一直是一个被命运跑踢来踢去的球，饱经沧桑。', '名词: spurner 过去式: spurned 过去分词: spurned 现在分词: spurning 第三人称单数: spurns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('omniscient', '[ɑːm\'nɪsiənt]', 'adj.全知的；无所不知的', '1. The novel has an omniscient narrator. 这部小说有一个全知的叙述者。 2. Because He is omniscient, God sees everything. 上帝明察秋毫，因为祂是全知的上帝。 3. Christians believe that God is omniscient. 基督教徒相信上帝是无所不知的。 4. He\'s nervous when trying to potray himself as omniscient. 当他试图把自己描绘得无所不知时,内心其实很紧张。', '副词: omnisciently 名词: omniscience');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('uncooperative', '[ˌʌnkoʊ\'ɑːpərətɪv]', 'adj.不合作的；不配合的', '1. It won\'t work with that uncooperative attitude. 对于不合作的人,这是无效的。 2. It would not facilitate matters if you were uncooperative. 如果你不合作, 事情就不好办了。 3. The witness was extremely uncooperative. 这个证人极不配合。 4. She is also uncooperative with the nurses, and always upsets her roommates. 她与护士们也不配合，还总是骚扰室友。', '副词: uncooperatively 名词: uncooperativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vocalist', '[\'voʊkəlɪst]', 'n.声乐家；歌手', '1. Mr.Steffen is an excellent vocalist. 斯蒂芬先生是位优秀的声乐家。 2. In appreciation of the enthusiastic applause,the vocalist sang an encore. 为了答谢热情的掌声，那个声乐家再唱一曲。', '形容词: vocalistic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agglomerate', '[ə\'ɡlɑːməreɪt]', 'v.使结块；使成团或凝结；集结 n.〈地质〉集块岩；〈化学〉附聚物；团块；集结 adj.凝聚的；成团的；结块的', '1. The system determines the size and distribution of the agglomerate. 这个系统确定凝聚的大小和分布。', '形容词: agglomerative 名词: agglomerator 过去式: agglomerated 过去分词: agglomerated 现在分词: agglomerating 第三人称单数: agglomerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('academic', '[ˌækə\'demɪk]', 'adj.学院的；学术的；理论的 n.大学教师，大学生；学者，学究', '1. Sir Lawrence Alma-Tadema was an English painter in the academic tradition. 阿尔玛·台德玛是学院派的英国画家。 2. With my strong academic background, I am competent. 依我良好的学术背景,我能胜任。 3. Applicant must possess good conduct and obtain satisfactory academic results. 申请者必须拥有良好品性,并考获令人满意的成绩; 4. During the past four years I have had a good deal of academic experience in communications technology. 四年来,我掌握了丰富的通信技术上的理论知识。', '副词: academically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gratis', '[\'ɡrætɪs]', 'adj.免费的 adv.免费地', '1. Entrance is gratis. 免费入场。 2. Wine is gratis. 酒水免费。 3. We provide gratis service. 我们提供免费服务。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vertical', '[\'vɜːrtɪkl]', 'adj.垂直的；纵向的；顶点的 n.垂直物；垂直的位置', '1. The northern face of the mountain is almost vertical. 这座山向北的一面几乎是垂直的。 2. The vertical line meets the horizontal one here. 垂直线与水平线在此相交。 3. Wire saws can cut in any orientation, vertical or horizontal. 钢丝锯能够切割任何方向,纵向或横向。 4. The angles refer to the polar view angle, i.e. the angle measured from the vertical. 角涉及到极面观的角，例如垂直物上测量的角。', '副词: vertically 名词: verticality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unbosom', '[ʌn\'bʊzəm]', 'v.吐露心事；剖明心迹', '1. You\'ll feel better if you unbosom your sorrows to me. 如果你把你的痛苦对我倾诉出来，你会感觉更好一些。 2. But whenever you want to unbosom,I\'ll be right here! 在对的时候遇到对的人是很难得的一件事;所以你们要珍惜. 3. At last she decided to unbosom herself to her mother,and shared her secret sorrow. 她最终决定把自己心里的悲伤告诉她母亲。 4. At last she decided to unbosom herself to her mother, and shared her secret sorrow. 她最终决定把自己心里的悲伤告诉她母亲。', '名词: unbosomer 过去式: unbosomed 过去分词: unbosomed 现在分词: unbosoming 第三人称单数: unbosoms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('riot', '[\'raɪət]', 'n.暴乱；骚乱；喧闹；（色彩）丰富；<俚>有趣的人 v.闹事；骚乱', '1. The military were called in to deal with the riot. 已将军队调来镇压暴乱。 2. The outbreak of riot caused many people to die. 暴乱的发生使很多人丧生。 3. The police stopped several riots on election night. 警方在竞选之夜制止了几处骚乱。 4. Football hooligans ran riot through the town. 闹事的足球迷在城里胡作非为。 5. He fermented prejudiced crowds to riot. 他煽动有偏见的群众起来闹事。', '名词: rioter 过去式: rioted 过去分词: rioted 现在分词: rioting 第三人称单数: riots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('initiate', '[ɪ\'nɪʃieɪt]', 'vt.开始；创始；启蒙；介绍加入 n.创始人 adj.新加入的；启蒙的', '1. This term we will initiate a new teaching plan. 这学期我们将开始实行一个新的教学计划。 2. The company initiated a management training program for small businesses. 该公司发起了针对小企业的管理培训方案。 3. I shall initiate you into our business methods. 我将把我们的营业方法介绍给你。 4. My father wanted to initiate me into fishing. 我爸爸想教我钓鱼。', '名词: initiator 过去式: initiated 过去分词: initiated 现在分词: initiating 第三人称单数: initiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subsequent', '[\'sʌbsɪkwənt]', 'adj.随后的；后来的', '1. Subsequent events proved me wrong. 後来发生的事证明我错了。 2. He confessed to other crimes subsequent to the bank robbery. 他供认抢劫银行案後，又坦白了其他罪行。 3. Subsequent to its success as a play, it was made into a film. 该剧在舞台上获得成功之後，又摄制成了电影。 4. Subsequent events confirmed our doubts. 后来发生的事证实了我们的怀疑。', '副词: subsequently 名词: subsequence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('platonic', '[plə\'tɑːnɪk]', 'adj.柏拉图哲学的；柏拉图主义的；理想的；不切实际的', '1. The Platonic notion is that mathematics is the imperturbable structure that underlies the very architecture of the universe. 柏拉图主义认为，数学所表现出的泰然自若之境界乃宇宙之根本。 2. Butritualremainsthat we must do as eries of platonic actions before we can haveintercourse. 但是还有典礼，我们必须在我们可以交往之前，参加一系列不切实际的活动。', '副词: Platonically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flagging', '[\'flægɪŋ]', 'adj.衰弱的；萎靡的 n.石板路 动词flag的现在分词形式.', '1. Is China\'s flagging economy as strong as an ox? 衰退中的中国经济依旧气壮如牛?', '副词: flaggingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('libelous', '[\'laɪbələs]', 'adj.诽谤的；损害名誉的 =libellous.', '1. A plaintiff\'s interpretation in a libel suit of allegedly libelous or slanderous material. 对被告诽谤言辞的解释在诽谤案件中，原告对所称的诽谤的或谣言的材料的解释', '副词: libelously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exemplify', '[ɪɡ\'zemplɪfaɪ]', 'vt.例证；示范', '1. I will exemplify my point with a story. 我会用一个故事举例说明我的观点。 2. To exemplify this theory,let us examine some species of insect. 为举例说明这种理论，我们来检查一些种类的昆虫。 3. The plays of Wilds exemplify the comedy of manners. 王尔德的戏剧是风尚喜剧的典范。 4. The recent oil price rises exemplify the difficulties which the motor industry is now facing. 最近的石油涨价是汽车工业正面临的困难的一个例子。', '形容词: exemplifiable 名词: exemplifier 过去式: exemplified 过去分词: exemplified 现在分词: exemplifying 第三人称单数: exemplifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saboteur', '[ˌsæbə\'tɜːr]', 'n.从事破坏活动者', '1. The torch has been closed since it was damaged by a saboteur\'s bomb in 1916. 女神手举的火炬，自从1916遭到破坏者破坏后就一直是关闭的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pressing', '[\'presɪŋ]', 'adj.紧迫的；紧急的 press的现在分词.', '1. The third pressing issue is the economy. 第三个紧迫的问题是经济。 2. I have more pressing things to attend to. 我有更紧迫的事情要做。 3. I\'m afraid some pressing business has come up. 也许有些紧急的事要办。 4. Pressing business kept him in Leeds, so he sent his deputy on to represent him in Edinburgh. 紧急的事务使他留在里兹，所以他派代理人代表他先赶到爱丁堡去。', '副词: pressingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intrepid', '[ɪn\'trepɪd]', 'adj.无畏的；刚毅的', '1. He is not really satisfied with his intrepid action. 他没有真正满意他的无畏行动。 2. Some intrepid individuals were still prepared to make the journey. 某些无畏的人仍然准备作此旅行。 3. He has an intrepid disposition, and great strength. 他生性悍勇,力大过人。 4. Lately, though, an intrepid band of researchers has been trying to remedy that. 而近来一些坚韧不拔的研究者一直试图在修正那种探索。', '副词: intrepidly 名词: intrepidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sulky', '[\'sʌlki]', 'adj.生气的；阴沉的', '1. He was very sulky about it indeed. 他对这事确实很生气。 2. The boss was as sulky as a bear that day. 老板那天怒气冲冲。 3. I should have been sulky and mean. 我应该阴沉而自卑。 4. I see that Basil is in one of his sulky moods. 我觉得贝西尔现在情绪很低沉。', '副词: sulkily 比较级: sulkier 最高级: sulkiest 名词: sulkiness 名词复数: sulkies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lurch', '[lɜːrtʃ]', 'v.突然倾斜；蹒跚地走；(突然感到恐怖或激动时心或胃)猛地一跳(或动) n.举步蹒跚；突然倾斜', '1. Suddenly the horse lurched to one side and the child fell off. 马突然歪向一边，小孩就摔了下来。 2. Their relationship seems to lurch from one crisis to the next. 他们的关系好像坎坷不平，危机不断。 3. The man lurched drunkenly out of the pub. 那男人醉醺醺地踉跄着走出了酒吧。 4. The ship gave a lurch to starboard. 船突然向右侧倾斜。', '副词: lurchingly 过去式: lurched 过去分词: lurched 现在分词: lurching 第三人称单数: lurches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mate', '[meɪt]', 'n.配偶；伙伴；同事 vt.使 ... 配对；使 ... 一致 vi.交配', '1. I thought she was an ideal mate. 我认为她是我的理想配偶。 2. The eagle mourned for his dead mate. 那只鹰为它死去的配偶伤心。 3. He is my soul mate. 他和我性情相投。 4. Who is your best mate at Liverpool? 谁是你在利物浦最好的伙伴? 5. It\'s high time to mate the doves. 现在正是鸽子配对的好时候。 6. Many animals mate in the spring. 许多动物在春天交配。', '过去式: mated 过去分词: mated 现在分词: mating 第三人称单数: mates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aegis', '[\'iːdʒɪs]', 'n.保护；庇护；资助；宙斯盾', '1. A child whose welfare is now under the aegis of the courts. 儿童福利现在处于法庭的保护之下 2. Medical supplies are flied in under the aegis of the red cross. 在红十字会的保护下，正在空运进医药用品。 3. A concert was held under the aegis of the parents\' association. 在父母协会的赞助下举行了音乐会。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cognomen', '[kɒg\'noʊmən]', 'n.姓；（古罗马）第三个名字；别名；绰号', '1. Abbiamo lo stesso nome e lo stesso cognomen. 我们同名同姓。 2. An additional cognomen given to a Roman citizen, often in honor of military victories. 附加名为表彰夺取军事胜利而授予罗马人的附加名 3. An additional cognomen given to a Roman citizen,often in honor of military victories. 附加名为表彰夺取军事胜利而授予罗马人的附加名。 4. Legio IV Scythica was a Roman legion levied by Mark Antony around 42 BC, for his campaign against the Parthian Empire, hence her other cognomen, Parthica. 第四\"西徐卡\"军团，是由马克-安东尼组建于公元前42年，前去参加他进攻帕提亚帝国的战役。因此该军团也获得了\"帕提卡\"的称号。', '形容词: cognominal 名词复数: cognomens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('somber', '[\'sɒmbə]', 'adj.微暗的；阴暗的；忧郁的；严肃的；严峻的', '1. She looked up staring at the somber December sky. 她抬起头来，凝望着十二月份阴沉沉的天空。 2. His eyes were somber, resentful and yet nervous. 他的眼睛显得阴沉、愤懑，然而又惶惶不安。 3. A funeral is a somber occasion. 葬礼是个忧郁的场合。 4. Herzog\'s somber face brightened. 赫索格严肃的脸上露出了笑容。', '副词: somberly 名词: somberness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('curd', '[kɜːrd]', 'n.凝乳', '1. Milk can be made into curds. 牛奶可制成凝乳。 2. She prefers fresh curd cheese. 她爱吃新鲜凝乳制的奶酪。', '形容词: curdy 过去式: curded 过去分词: curded 现在分词: curding 第三人称单数: curds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pastel', '[pæ\'stel]', 'n.彩色粉笔；粉蜡；蜡笔画；彩色粉笔画 adj.清淡柔和的', '1. She works in (ie uses) pastels. 她用彩色粉笔作画。 2. It is pastel, and not oil, on panel. 画家没有用油彩，而是用色粉笔画在画板上。 3. Pastel colours are restful to the eye. 清淡柔和的颜色可以养目。', '名词: pastelist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preen', '[priːn]', 'v.整理羽毛；精心打扮；沾沾自喜', '1. Juvenile king penguins preen on the shore. 年轻的企鹅首领在岸边用嘴整理羽毛。 2. The girl is preening oneself in front of the mirror. 那女孩正对着镜子梳妆打扮. 3. She preened herself upon her beauty. 她为自已的美貌感到自满。 4. He\'s always preening himself on his success. 他总是对自己的成功沾沾自喜。', '名词: preener 过去式: preened 过去分词: preened 现在分词: preening 第三人称单数: preens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('specifics', '[spə\'sɪfɪks]', 'n.细微问题；细节 名词specific的复数形式.', '1. Do not disclose the specifics of the project. 不要给他们透露项目的细节。 2. Neither Larijani nor Solana provided specifics. 拉里贾尼和索拉纳都没有提供细节。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concrete', '[\'kɑːŋkriːt]', 'adj.具体的；实质性的；混凝土的 n.水泥；混凝土；具体物 v.凝结；结合', '1. I can\'t tell you anything concrete. 这具体的我也说不上来。 2. He had nothing concrete to fasten it upon. 他抓不到什么具体的证据。 3. The statue rests on a bed of concrete. 这座雕像立在混凝土的基座上。 4. Between these are fixed precast concrete external cladding panels. 在它们之间填上预制混凝土的外层空心板。 5. Tom tumbled over and hit his head on the concrete. 汤姆摔倒，头撞到水泥地。 6. The government concreted the road over. 政府用混凝土铺路。', '副词: concretely 名词: concreteness 过去式: concreted 过去分词: concreted 现在分词: concreting 第三人称单数: concretes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fresco', '[\'freskoʊ]', 'n.壁画', '1. This is a masterpiece in fresco. 这是一幅壁画法的杰作。 2. The frescos in the Sistine Chapel are world-famous. 西斯廷教堂的壁画举世闻名。', '名词: frescoer 名词复数: frescoes 过去式: frescoed 过去分词: frescoed 现在分词: frescoing 第三人称单数: frescoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suffice', '[sə\'faɪs]', 'vi.足够；使满足 vt.使 ... 足够', '1. The rations will suffice until next week. 这些口粮足够吃到下星期。 2. An hour should suffice for the journey. 这点路程一小时足够了。 3. The rules will suffice for all ordinary needs. 这些规定将能满足所有一般场合的需要。 4. Two meals a day suffice an old man. 老人一天二餐就足够了。', '名词: sufficer 过去式: sufficed 过去分词: sufficed 现在分词: sufficing 第三人称单数: suffices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bohemian', '[boʊ\'hiːmiən]', 'n.波希米亚人；波希米亚语；放浪者 adj.波希米亚人的；放浪的；波希米亚语的', '1. Mr King was highly educated, but was a Bohemian down to his boots. 金先生受过很好的教育，但他是一个极其脱俗不拘小节的人。 2. That famous film star leads a bohemian life. 那位著名的电影明星过着放荡不羁的生活。 3. After a very proper upbringing he chose to lead the Bohemian life of an artist. 他受过正统的教育，却立意过著艺术家我行我素的生活。', '名词: bohemianism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('miserly', '[\'maɪzərli]', 'adj.吝啬的；少量的', '1. He is miserly with both his time and his money. 他对于自己的时间和金钱都是吝啬的。 2. Their miserly offer is unlikely to be accepted. 他们极少的出价不大可能会被接受。', '名词: miserliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('soigne', '[swɑː\'njeɪ]', '整齐的, 整洁的', '1. Seafood is living, let people eat the rest assured that tastes good.Le service d \'ici est soigne. 这样的地方最好的卖点就是环境、服务，菜品比较清淡，不多深色。 2. Le service d’ici est soigne. 这儿的服务很周到。 3. soigne, nurse, foster, cultivate, maintain, tend, service 照顾。护理。照料。保养。抚养。收养。医学护理。 4. ...Soigne Soigne International Aquamoisture Mask ... 一项评论对该产品所给予的 .', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('liquefy', '[\'lɪkwɪfaɪ]', 'v.液化；溶解', '1. Then the clump would liquefy and start to drip and run off our hands. 然后,这团混合物会液化,并开始从手中滴落出来。', '名词: liquefier');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nonchalant', '[ˌnɑːnʃə\'lɑːnt]', 'adj.若无其事的；不关心的；冷淡的', '1. \"It\'ll be fine,\" she replied, with a nonchalant shrug. 她若无其事地耸耸肩说：“会好的。” 2. He immediately remarked with the most nonchalant air. 他接着就装出十分冷静的模样说了话。 3. She defeated all her rivals for the job with nonchalant ease. 她从容不迫地击败求职的所有竞争者。 4. His nonchalant attitude irritated me. 他那漠不关心的态度使我恼火。', '副词: nonchalantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coagulant', '[koʊ\'ægjələnt]', 'n.凝结剂', '1. Coagulation of such systems requires rather drastic treatment with massive doses of coagulant salts. 凝聚这种体系时需要用大量凝结剂盐类进行相当激烈的处理。 2. Polyelectrolytes as coagulant aids lower the required dosages of alum and auxiliary chemicals. 高分子电解质作为凝结剂援助更低白矾和辅助化学制品必需的剂量。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pinnacle', '[\'pɪnəkl]', 'n.小尖塔；尖峰；高峰 vt.造小尖塔；放置高处', '1. I can see the small pinnacle from here. 我能从这儿看到那个小尖塔。', '过去式: pinnacled 过去分词: pinnacled 现在分词: pinnacling 第三人称单数: pinnacles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mash', '[mæʃ]', 'n. 麦芽浆； 糊状物； 土豆泥 v. 把 ... 捣成糊状 v. 挑逗； 调情', '1. Single malt Scotch whiskies are distilled entirely from a fermented mash of malted barley. 苏格兰纯麦威士忌完全从发酵的大麦芽浆中蒸馏获得。 2. Top quality barley malt and cereal grains are crushed and then mixed with pre-conditioned water to form mash. 经过严格控制，将谷物渣由麦芽浆分隔出来，然后提取清澈金黄的麦芽汁，再将槐花加入麦牙汁中煮滚。 3. Pouring water over the sago pulp causes the plant starch to drain from the mash, and the starch will be dried into flour. 在西谷椰子的果肉上浇水能使它凝结成淀粉状从而从杂质中分离出来，而这些糊状物会被晒成面粉状的西米。 4. Please mash the potatoes for tomorrow\'s dinner. 请做土豆泥，明天要吃。', '过去式: mashed 过去分词: mashed 现在分词: mashing 第三人称单数: mashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anagram', '[\'ænəɡræm]', 'n.变位词；(变换或颠倒字母顺序而成另一词的)回文构词法', '1. An anagram is a word or phrase spelled by rearranging the letters of another word or phrase. 变位词是通过重新排列单词或短语的字母而得到的单词或短语。', '形容词: anagrammatic 副词: anagrammatically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disarm', '[dɪs\'ɑːrm]', 'v.放下武器；裁军；解除武装；缓和', '1. It is difficult to persuade them to disarm. 要说服他们放下武器是很难的。 2. The superpowers are unlikely to disarm completely. 超级大国不太可能彻底裁军。 3. The police disarmed the criminal. 警察缴下了罪犯的枪械。 4. The world has waited 12 years for Iraq to disarm. 全世界等待伊拉克解除武装已有12年之久。', '名词: disarmer 过去式: disarmed 过去分词: disarmed 现在分词: disarming 第三人称单数: disarms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('genome', '[\'dʒiːnoʊm]', 'n.基因组；染色体组', '1. Scientists have decoded the dog genome. 科学家已经译解了狗的基因组。 2. The Human Genome Project has several objectives. 人类基因组计划有若干目标。', '形容词: genomic 异体字: genom');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('howler', '[\'haʊlər]', 'n.嚎叫的人或动物；大错误；滑稽可笑的错误', '1. Male howler monkeys use their loud voices to fight for food, mates, or territory. 雄性吼猴利用牠们的大嗓门去争夺食物，求偶，或宣示领土。 2. The car came a howler on the road. 车在途中出了事故。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detrimental', '[ˌdetrɪ\'mentl]', 'adj.有害的 n.有害的人或事', '1. Lack of sleep is detrimental to one\'s health. 缺乏睡眠有害健康。 2. Smoking is detrimental to health. 吸烟封健康是有害的。 3. He works long hours to the detriment of his health. 他长时间的工作，有损健康。', '副词: detrimentally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mantle', '[\'mæntl]', 'n.斗篷；覆盖物；墙的外皮；（汽灯的）纱罩；[地]地幔 v.覆盖；笼罩；脸红', '1. The light loose mantle was thrown over his tunic. 一件轻质宽大的斗蓬披在上衣外面。 2. The earth had donned her mantle of brightest green. 大地披上了苍翠欲滴的绿色斗篷。 3. The mountain was covered with a mantle of snow. 山上覆盖着一层雪。 4. The earth has a core and a mantle around it. 地球的中心是地核，地核的周围是地幔。 5. Snow mantled the hills. 雪覆盖着丘陵。', '过去式: mantled 过去分词: mantled 现在分词: mantling 第三人称单数: mantles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('precocious', '[prɪ\'koʊʃəs]', 'adj.早熟的', '1. That child is far too precocious. 孩子过于老成。 2. His son is a precocious child who could play the piano at the age of three. 他的儿子是一个三岁就能弹奏钢琴的早慧儿童。', '副词: precociously 名词: precocity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scamp', '[skæmp]', 'n.无赖；调皮家伙 v.草率地做', '1. His mother tell him not to talk to the scamp on the street. 他母亲叫他不要跟街上的流氓说话。 2. That little scamp Jimmy has hidden my slippers again! 这个调皮的小吉米又把我的拖鞋藏起来了！ 3. Don\'t scamp your work because you are pressed for time. 不要因为时间紧而敷衍了事。 4. If you do not like the assignment, just do not do them, but do not scamp them. 如果你不喜欢分配给你的任务，干脆不要做，而不要草率从事。', '名词: scamper 过去式: scamped 过去分词: scamped 现在分词: scamping 第三人称单数: scamps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hirsute', '[\'hɜːrsuːt]', 'adj.多毛的', '1. Stems long hirsute with appressed, deflexed hairs. 茎具长硬毛具贴伏，外折的毛。 2. Berries trigonous ovoid, densely hirsute. 浆果三棱的卵形体，密被长硬毛。 3. Filament tube ca. 4 mm, sparsely hirsute. 花丝筒约4毫米，疏生长硬毛。 4. Branchlets stiffly brownish yellow hirsute. 小枝带硬的褐色黄多毛。', '名词: hirsuteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('request', '[rɪ\'kwest]', 'n.请求；要求 vt.请求；要求', '1. I will oblige any sincere request. 我会答应任何诚意的请求。 2. His answer to my request was a negative. 我的请求遭到了他的拒绝。 3. Your request will be dealt with in due course. 你的要求将在适当时机予以处理。 4. I bought it at your request. 我应你的要求买下来。 5. We request you to deduct our commission from the invoice. 我们请求你方从发票中扣除我们的佣金。', '名词: requester 过去式: requested 过去分词: requested 现在分词: requesting 第三人称单数: requests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('savage', '[\'sævɪdʒ]', 'adj.野性的；凶猛的；粗鲁的；荒野的；原始的 n.野蛮人；粗人；凶恶的人 vt.激烈抨击；猛烈攻击', '1. Most of the time elephants are tame but they can be very savage. 大多数时候大象很温顺,但他们也会大发野性。 2. He was wild and savage, and no man could mount him, or do anything at all with him. 它既野又凶，谁都驾驭不了它，谁也对它没办法。 3. He smarted from the savage attacks on his film. 他因自己的影片受到猛烈攻击而感到痛心。 4. She was irritated by his savage behavior. 他的不文明行为激怒了她。 5. These civilizations flourished while Europeans were still savages living in caves. 当欧洲人还是居住在洞穴中的野蛮人时，这些地方的文化早已十分繁荣昌盛。 6. Smith\'s play was savaged by the critics. 史密斯的剧本遭到评论家的猛烈抨击。', '副词: savagely 名词: savageness 过去式: savaged 过去分词: savaged 现在分词: savaging 第三人称单数: savages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nostalgia', '[nə\'stældʒə]', 'n.乡愁；向往过去；怀旧之情', '1. The soldiers were filled with nostalgia. 士兵们心中充满了乡愁。 2. The familiar and echoing sound of pianos from Gulangyu is his nostalgia. 那回荡着的熟悉的鼓浪屿钢琴声就是他的乡愁。 3. The sight inspired him with nostalgia. 这景象激起了他的怀旧之情。 4. Her work is pervaded by nostalgia for a past age. 她的作品充满了怀旧之情。', '形容词: nostalgic 副词: nostalgically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('awe-inspiring', '[ɔː ɪn\'spaɪərɪŋ]', 'adj.令人敬畏的；令人惊叹的', '1. It was at its most glorious and awe inspiring when facing the Undead. 当面对亡灵才是它最辉煌最让人敬畏的时刻。 2. The grandeur of life\'s complexity elicits awe regardless of what creative processes were employed. 不管创造过程用哪种方式，生命复杂度之壮观同样令人敬畏。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sidle', '[\'saɪdl]', 'v.(偷偷地)侧身而行；侧身挨近 n.侧身移动；侧身行进', '1. The hole is so narrow that we sidle inside . 洞口太窄了，我们只能侧着身子走进去。 2. If you sit at the back you can sidle out without anyone seeing you leave. 假如你坐在后面你可以溜出去而没人看见。 3. A man sidled up to me and asked if I wanted a ticket for the match. 一男子偷偷走到我跟前,问我要不要比赛票子。', '副词: sidlingly 过去式: sidled 过去分词: sidled 现在分词: sidling 第三人称单数: sidles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('relentless', '[rɪ\'lentləs]', 'adj.冷酷无情的；不间断的', '1. He was relentless in demanding repayment of the debt. 他冷酷无情地要求偿还那笔债。 2. However, in Antarctica, the elements are relentless. 然而，在南极洲，自然环境是冷酷无情的。 3. I\'m relentless in the pursuit of my goals. 我持续不断地追求我的目标。 4. The traffic noise is relentless. 车辆的噪音一刻也不停止。', '副词: relentlessly 名词: relentlessness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('substance', '[\'sʌbstəns]', 'n.实质；物质；财产；内容；重要性', '1. The Substance and Prospect of \"East China Sea\" Dispute between China and Japan 中日\"东海问题\"的实质及展望 2. The emery is a hard metallic substance. 金刚砂是非常坚硬的金属物质。 3. Beware of what you do with this dangerous substance. 你处理这些危险品时，可要当心。 4. Later he became a man of substance. 后来，他成为颇具资产的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ornithologist', '[ˌɔːrnɪ\'θɑːlədʒɪst]', 'n.鸟类学家', '1. The islands are an ornithologist\'s paradise and a vacationer\'s delight. 群岛是鸟类学家的天堂，度假者的乐园。 2. The ornithologist will take you ashore and help you identify different species of birds. 鸟类学家将带您登陆，帮您识别不同的鸟类品种。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adjudicate', '[ə\'dʒuːdɪkeɪt]', 'v.判决；裁定；充当裁判', '1. The court will adjudicate on(upon)the case next Monday. 法庭将于下周一宣判此案。 2. The minister could not adjudicate in such an issue. 部长不能在这样一个问题上作出裁定。', '形容词: adjudicative 名词: adjudication 过去式: adjudicated 过去分词: adjudicated 现在分词: adjudicating 第三人称单数: adjudicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('idyll', '[\'aɪdl]', 'n.田园生活；田园诗 =idyl.', '1. Here they had been trying to create a weekend idyll for the urban middle classes. 他们曾试图让城市中产阶级在周末来这里享受农家乐。 2. I\'ve composed only one idyll. 我只作了一首田园诗。', '副词: idyllically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defect', '[\'diːfekt]', 'n.缺点；缺陷 vi.背叛', '1. If it were not for this defect, I shall hire him at once. 如果不是因为这个缺点，我会马上雇用他。 2. The new car had to be withdrawn from the market because of a mechanical defect. 那种新汽车因有机械缺陷只好撤出市场。 3. We thought that his troops might defect. 我们认为他的部队会叛变。', '名词: defection 过去式: defected 过去分词: defected 现在分词: defecting 第三人称单数: defects');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('germane', '[dʒɜːr\'meɪn]', 'adj.有密切关系的；恰当的', '1. The fact is not germane to this issue. 此事实与此问题无密切关系。 2. He asks questions that are germane and central to the issue. 他问了一些与论点有密切关系的重要问题。', '副词: germanely 名词: germaneness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compass', '[\'kʌmpəs]', 'n.圆规；指南针；范围 vt.达到；围绕；图谋', '1. Now we begin to draw a circle with compasses. 现在我们开始用圆规画一个圆。 2. I need a compass to draw a circle. 我需要一支圆规画圆。 3. A compass needle points to the north. 罗盘的指针永远指向北方。 4. The compass was invented by the Chinese, as is well known. 众所周知,指南针是中国人发明的。 5. In order to compass our object we must work hard. 为了达到我们的目标，我们必须努力工作。', '形容词: compassable 过去式: compassed 过去分词: compassed 现在分词: compassing 第三人称单数: compasses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glaze', '[ɡleɪz]', 'v.装以玻璃；上釉；变得光滑；变呆滞 n.釉；覆罩的一层', '1. There was raw glaze on the pots that sat again on the drying rack. 在干燥架上又摆上了才上釉的陶罐。 2. Tang three-color glaze horses are famous for their perfect design and realism. 唐三彩上釉马以其造型精美和形态生动而著名。 3. The glaze of the table was scratched. 桌子的釉面被刮坏了。 4. Tang three-color glaze horses are famous for their perfect design and realism. 唐三彩上釉马以其造型精美和形态生动而著名。', '名词: glazer 过去式: glazed 过去分词: glazed 现在分词: glazing 第三人称单数: glazes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insipid', '[ɪn\'sɪpɪd]', 'adj.没有味道的；枯燥乏味的', '1. The food was rather insipid and needed gingering up. 这食物缺少味道，需要加点作料。', '副词: insipidly 名词: insipidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('xenophobia', '[ˌzenə\'foʊbiə]', 'n.仇外；排外', '1. Excessive patriotism can lead to xenophobia. 爱国主义过了头即可导致仇视一切外国人。 2. Xenophobia hindered the country\'s development. 排外阻碍了这个国家的发展。 3. They are nationalist to the point of xenophobia. 他们的民族主义情绪达到了恐外症的程度。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contagious', '[kən\'teɪdʒəs]', 'adj.传染性的；感染性的', '1. Scarlet fever is highly contagious. 猩红热传染性很强。 2. Have you ever had any contagious disease? 你是否有或曾经有过传染疾病? 3. The incidence of various contagious diseases has markedly dropped. 各种传染病的发病率大幅度下降。 4. He has contagious laughter. 他有着容易感染人的笑声。', '副词: contagiously 名词: contagiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('affected', '[ə\'fektɪd]', 'adj.受影响的；受感动的；受疾病侵袭的 adj.做作的；假装的 动词affect的过去式和过去分词.', '1. It is said that the rhythm of tides is affected by the moon. 据说潮汐的涨落受月亮的影响。 2. He was much affected by the sad news. 这个悲惨的消息使他非常难过。 3. His affected manners are painful to endure. 他做作的举止让人不堪忍受。 4. The girl was neither affected nor pretentious. 这位姑娘既不虚伪也不做作。', '副词: affectedly 名词: affectedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reportorial', '[ˌrepə\'tɒrɪəl]', 'adj.报告者的；采访记者的', '1. I was frantic to finish the report on schedule. 我十万火急地要按预定时间完成报告。 2. He claimed that the newspaper report was a libel. 他声称报纸上的报导是一种诽谤。 3. How can I worm out of giving that report? 我怎么逃脱不做那个报告呢？ 4. He is reading a report of the state of the roads. 他正在看一篇关于道路状况的报告。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immunity', '[ɪ\'mjuːnəti]', 'n.免疫；免疫性；免除；豁免', '1. Children who have gotten the chickenpox build an immunity to it so that they do not get it a second time. 已经得过水痘的小孩会对它免疫,所以不会再得第二次。 2. This vaccine will give you immunity for two years. 接种这种疫苗可有两年免疫力。 3. Nobody will be given immunity from taxation. 没有人可以免除被征税。 4. He has diplomatic immunity. 他有外交豁免权。', '名词复数: immunities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impermanent', '[ɪm\'pɜːrmənənt]', 'adj.暂时的；非永久的', '1. The world is in continuous flux and is impermanent. 世界变迁不已，并非是常久不变的。', '名词: impermanence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('servitude', '[\'sɜːrvətuːd]', 'n.奴役；束缚；徒刑；〈法〉役劝', '1. They spent their lives in servitude. 他们在奴役下生活。 2. Such ill-paid farm work is a form of servitude. 这种农活儿工资低得可怜，简直是苦役。 3. Yet what could she offer them except a life of poverty, servitude and despair? 可是除了贫穷、不自由和绝望的生活,她能给予孩子们什么呢? 4. The criminal was sentenced to five years\' servitude. 这犯人被判处五年劳役。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('periphery', '[pə\'rɪfəri]', 'n.周边；边缘；外围', '1. The US cordons China\'s periphery. 美国在中国周边都画上了警戒线。 2. You can take a look at the periphery of the Yandi Ling. 你可以到周边的炎帝陵看看。 3. He was on the periphery of Kenya\'s liberation struggles, but he was still imprisoned briefly during repressive times. 他身处肯尼亚解放斗争的边缘，但仍在镇压时期遭到短时间的囚禁。 4. The condition makes it difficult for patients to see objects at the periphery of their vision. 这种病症使患者难于看见视觉边缘的物体。', '名词复数: peripheries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wit', '[wɪt]', 'n.智力；才智；机智；风趣 v.<古>知道；即', '1. Wit is the lowest form of humor. 智力是幽默的最低形式。 2. His character is a combination of wit and kindness. 他的性格是智慧与善良的结合。 3. Sloth tarnishes the edge of wit. 懒散能磨去才智的锋芒。 4. He gave me a taste of his acid wit. 他让我尝到了他敏锐尖刻之机智的滋味。 5. He will leave at the end of term, to wit 30 July. 他要在期末离开，也就是7月30日。', '过去式: wist 过去分词: wist 现在分词: witting 第三人称单数: wot');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fop', '[fɑːp]', 'n.(喜好精致服装的)花花公子', '1. A young fop came up to George and introduced himself. 一个花花公子走到乔治面前并作了自我介绍。 2. He is a fop,he never been serious about any girls but twiddle with them. 他是一个花花公子。他到处玩弄感情，从没对哪个女孩子认真过。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('onus', '[\'oʊnəs]', 'n.负担；义务；耻辱', '1. The demographic bonus became a demographic onus. 人口统计上的奖励变成了负担。 2. Never has technology or our relationship to it had such an onus. 技术以及我们与技术的关系从来不像现在这样成了一项重担。 3. The onus of proof lies with you. 你有责任提供证据。 4. The onus is on you to complete this report. 完成这篇报告的责任落在你身上了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pullulate', '[\'pʌljʊleɪt]', 'vi.繁殖；剧增', '1. The tea plant pullulate very good in the fertile soil. 茶树在这片肥沃的山地上长得很好。 2. Will exceed your expectation by all means, pullulate with you and creat resplendence together with you! 我们深信,深祥科技定可不断超越您的期望,与您一起成长,共创辉煌! 3. Ton or fait aussi des petits. Race of Abel, love, pullulate! Even your gold has progeny. 恋爱,繁殖!连你们的黄金也生出了小黄金。 4. As the going says: ‘Seed always take root, pullulate, and blossom out, and result everywhere. 有句话“是种子在那儿都能生根，发牙，开花，结果。”', '形容词: pullulative 名词: pullulation 过去式: pullulated 过去分词: pullulated 现在分词: pullulating 第三人称单数: pullulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interlard', '[ˌɪntə\'lɑːd]', 'v.混杂；混入', '1. Foreign words interlard his speech. 他的演讲中穿插着众多的外国的词儿。 2. Moreover,folk law and country law have ever interacted,and therefore have sucked and conceded each other to some degree,＂I am in you＂,＂you are in mine＂,intercross and interlard. 外来因素只可能是现代化的一个推动力．但不能视为现代性的象征。国家法在相当程度上是移植国外制度特别是欧美和日本的制度构建的。 3. Moreover, folk law and country law have ever interacted, and therefore have sucked and conceded each other to some degree, \"I am in you\", \"you are in mine\", intercross and interlard. 而且，国家法与民间法从来都是相互影响并由此在一定程度上相互转化和承认，“你中有我”，“我中有你”，交错混杂。 4. to interlard a lecture with quotations 在讲话中夹杂着许多引语', '过去式: interlarded 过去分词: interlarded 现在分词: interlarding 第三人称单数: interlards');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debut', '[deɪ\'bjuː]', 'n.首次露面；初次登场 v.初次登场；首次推出', '1. His debut marks him out for future success. 他的首次亮相预示了将来的成功。 2. He will make his debut for the first team this week. 本周他将在第一支出场的队伍中首次亮相。 3. She made a successful debut. 她初次登台获得成功。 4. The young actress made her debut in the new comedy. 这位年轻的女演员在新上演的喜剧里首次登台演出。 5. A new product will debut next week. 一种新产品将在下周面世。', '过去式: debuted 过去分词: debuted 现在分词: debuting 第三人称单数: debuts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recession', '[rɪ\'seʃn]', 'n.后退；（经济）不景气', '1. A few days later, there was a gradual recession of flood waters. 几天之后,洪水逐渐消退。 2. The recession has caused thousands of bankruptcy. 经济不景气造成数千万的破产。 3. There is no sign that the recession has bottomed out yet. 没有迹象表明萧条已经到了极点。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abstain', '[əb\'steɪn]', 'v.戒绝；弃权；节制', '1. He swore to abstain from smoking. 他发誓要戒烟。 2. A high percentage of women said they had abstained from alcohol during pregnancy. 很大比例的妇女称他们在怀孕期间戒了酒。 3. I abstained from voting. 我弃权不投票。 4. Six countries voted for the change, five voted against, and two abstained. 六个国家投票赞成改变，五个反对，还有两个弃权。', '名词: abstainer 过去式: abstained 过去分词: abstained 现在分词: abstaining 第三人称单数: abstains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inaugural', '[ɪ\'nɔːɡjərəl]', 'adj.就职典礼的；开幕的；首次的 n.就职演说；就职典礼', '1. His inaugural speech was very inspiring. 他的就职演说很鼓动人心。 2. The inaugural session closed at17:10local. 开幕式在当地时间下午5点10分结束。 3. Only 13 nations took part in the inaugural tournament, with a majority of nine coming from South America. 只有13个国家参加了首次世界杯联赛，其中大部分来自南美。 4. Bill Clinton heralded at his Second Inaugural Address that the journey of our America must go on. 比尔克林顿在其第二任就职演说中宣告说，美国之路必须走下去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hepatitis', '[ˌhepə\'taɪtɪs]', 'n.肝炎', '1. He is experimenting with drugs to cure hepatitis. 他正在试验治疗肝炎的药。 2. The tests for hepatitis were negative. 肝炎检查结果是阴性。', '名词复数: hepatitides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pugilist', '[\'pjuːdʒɪlɪst]', 'n.职业拳击手', '1. The pugilist blocked his opponent\'s blows and then put in a sudden right to the jaw. 拳击手挡住了对方的袭击，接着用右手向他的颌部突然一击。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monomania', '[\'mɑːnə\'meɪniə]', 'n.对一事的狂热；[医]偏执狂', '1. Jiang Ruxiang:why will none but monomania survive? 姜汝祥:为什么只有偏执狂才能生存? 2. The western world was indeed black with homicidal monomania. 西方世界的确被杀人狂抹黑了。 3. The western world was indeed black with homicidal monomania . 西方世界的确被杀人狂抹黑了。 4. Audley, and do you select me as the victim of your monomania? 难道你选定我作你那躁狂症的牺牲品吗？', '形容词: monomaniacal 副词: monomaniacally 名词: monomaniac');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chivalrous', '[\'ʃɪvəlrəs]', 'adj.骑士的；有骑士风度的；侠义的', '1. I will be neither chivalrous nor sporting. 我既没有骑士精神也没有运动精神。 2. Men are so little chivalrous now. 现在的男人几乎没有什么骑士风度了。 3. One doesn\'t get much more chivalrous than you. 没有人能够比你更具有骑士风度了。 4. He is a chivalrous old gentleman. 他是个彬彬有礼的老绅士。', '副词: chivalrously 名词: chivalrousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('broker', '[\'broʊkər]', 'n.经纪人 vt.安排；协商', '1. I am an insurance broker. 我是一名保险经纪人。 2. I do not regard a broker as a member of the human race. 我不把经纪人当作是人类的一个成员。 3. The broker buys and sells shares for others. 经纪人替他人买卖股票。 4. Fighting between the two rival sides continued despite attempts by the neighboring country to broker a ceasefire. 敌对双方的战斗仍在继续,尽管邻国努力调停以实现停火。', '过去式: brokered 过去分词: brokered 现在分词: brokering 第三人称单数: brokers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crumble', '[\'krʌmbl]', 'v.崩溃；弄碎；破灭', '1. The masonry of the old building began to crumble. 旧楼房的砖石结构开始崩落。 2. The earthquake made the wall sink and start to crumble. 这次地震把这堵墙震得下陷并开始崩塌。 3. He crumbled the bread in his fingers. 他用手指把面包捏碎了。 4. Even these hard parts may crumble to dust. 甚至这些坚硬的部分也会破碎成粉末。', '过去式: crumbled 过去分词: crumbled 现在分词: crumbling 第三人称单数: crumbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('epistolary', '[ɪ\'pɪstəleri]', 'adj.书信的；用书信的；书信体的', '1. All postal operators recognise, however, that the epistolary habit has taken a hit from the internet. 然而所有邮政运营商均意识到，书信传统已经受到互联网的冲击。 2. The novel itself is an epistolary, written entirely in letters by its cast of characters, though Dracula himself is revealed only through the impressions of others. 这部小说本身是由主演以书信的形式记录的，虽然吸血鬼本身只能通过其他人想象才能显示出来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skim', '[skɪm]', 'vt.撇去；略读；掠过；滑过 vi.掠过；表面凝结；<俚>瞒报 n.浮沫；略读；脱脂物', '1. It took me an hour to skim the book. 我花了一小时把这本书浏览了一遍。 2. A seagull skims the water. 海鸥掠过水面。 3. The hovercraft is able to skim over the water. 气垫船能掠过水面飞速行驶。 4. During the cold night, the puddles skimmed over. 夜间寒冷，水洼面上结了冰。 5. I notice you have two quarts of skim milk. 我看到你拿了两夸托脱脂牛奶。', '过去式: skimmed 过去分词: skimmed 现在分词: skimming 第三人称单数: skims');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('denim', '[\'denɪm]', 'n.粗斜纹布 (复数)denims:工作服； 牛仔裤.', '1. We required stock of denim jeans only form pakistan. 巴基斯坦求购牛仔裤库存。 2. She doesn\'t wear glasses and at the moment she\'s wearing a white sweater with blue denim jeans. 她不戴眼镜，身穿白色毛衣和蓝色斜纹粗棉布牛仔裤。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exceptionable', '[ɪk\'sepʃənəbəl]', 'adj.可反对的；可提出异议的', '1. There\'s nothing exceptionable in it. 那没有可非难之处。 2. There are no exceptionable scenes in the play. 这出剧中没有能引起争议的情节。', '副词: exceptionably 名词: exceptionability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('natty', '[\'næti]', 'adj.整洁的；整洁时髦的；机敏的', '1. Keep the depot clear and natty, and make sure that the product settle orderly. 勤打扫，勤整理，确保仓库的整洁和货物的摆放有序。 2. He is a natty dresser. 他是个穿衣整洁时髦的潮人。 3. His suitings are natty to a degree. 他的衣料极其漂亮。', '副词: nattily 比较级: nattier 最高级: nattiest 名词: nattiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elucidate', '[i\'luːsɪdeɪt]', 'v.阐明；说明', '1. There is no need for him to elucidate. 他没有必要去详细阐明。 2. I will try to elucidate what I think the problems are. 我将尽力阐明我认为问题的所在。 3. Please elucidate the reasons for your action. 请说明你采取行动的理由。 4. This is the aspect that China does not explain or elucidate in public forums. 在公开场合，中国并没有对后面的观点作出解释说明。', '形容词: elucidative 名词: elucidation 过去式: elucidated 过去分词: elucidated 现在分词: elucidating 第三人称单数: elucidates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revise', '[rɪ\'vaɪz]', 'n.校订；修正；再校稿 v.校订；修正；校正', '1. A method to revise the radius of switch probes is also put forward. 此外还提出了一种修正开关式球测头半径的计量学方法。 2. The market turmoil has spurred economists to revise their forecasts. 当前的市场动荡已促使经济学家们重新修正自己的预测数据。 3. A method to revise the radius of switch probes is also put forward. 此外还提出了一种修正开关式球测头半径的计量学方法。 4. The market turmoil has spurred economists to revise their forecasts. 当前的市场动荡已促使经济学家们重新修正自己的预测数据。', '形容词: revisable 名词: reviser 过去式: revised 过去分词: revised 现在分词: revising 第三人称单数: revises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('edify', '[\'edɪfaɪ]', 'vt. <古>建立； 训导； 教导； 启发； 薰陶', '1. A sermon, especially one intended to edify a congregation on a practical matter and not intended to be a theological discourse. 布道一次讲道，尤其是旨在于实际问题上启发会众，而不在于成为神学讲演 2. This is an edifying book. 这是一本陶冶情操的书。 3. Travel is an edifying experience, especially for young people. 旅游可以使人增长见闻，尤其对年轻人。', '名词: edifier 过去式: edified 过去分词: edified 现在分词: edifying 第三人称单数: edifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dire', '[\'daɪər]', 'adj.可怕的；悲惨的；极其的', '1. You\'ll be in dire trouble if you don\'t watch out. 你若不小心，就会有可怕的麻烦。 2. Some in their beds shall toss and groan in dire dreams. 有些人将在床上辗转反侧，在可怕的梦中呻吟。 3. The backward economy and the cruel exploitation by the serf-owners kept the people in dire poverty and misery. 经济的落后和农奴主的残酷剥削，使人民群众处于极端贫穷和悲惨的生活境地。 4. On the way to this present greatness and security the American people passed through one phase of dire conflict. 美国人民在走向现在强大和安全的道路上却曾经历了一段悲惨的冲突。', '副词: direly 比较级: direr 最高级: direst 名词: direness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nip', '[nɪp]', 'v.夹；咬；捏；剪断；冻伤；阻止；偷；<俚>快速行动 v.小饮 n.捏；夹；咬；寒冷 n.少量；小口（尤指烈酒）', '1. I nipped my finger in the door. 我的手指被门夹了一下。 2. The dog nipped the postman on the leg. 那只狗咬了邮递员的腿。 3. Don\'t nip any stalks off the plant. 别掐断植物茎。 4. The icy breeze nipped the young blooms. 寒风摧残了初绽的花朵。 5. The dog gave me a nasty nip on the leg. 那狗在我腿上狠咬了一口。', '过去式: nipped 过去分词: nipped 现在分词: niping 第三人称单数: nips');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crack', '[kræk]', 'v.破裂；砸开；发出爆裂声；撞击；破解；变嘶哑；崩溃；制裁；<非正式>开玩笑 n.裂缝；裂痕；爆裂声；猛击；尝试；俏皮话 adj.训练有素的', '1. The glass will crack if you pour boiled water into it . 一倒进去滚开水，这个玻璃杯就会破裂。 2. You may crack these nuts with a hammer. 你可以用锤子把这些坚果敲开。 3. I cracked two eggs into the frying pan. 我往平底锅里打了两个鸡蛋。 4. Thunder cracked overhead. 雷在头顶上炸响了。 5. There is a crack in this window. 这扇窗户上有个裂纹。 6. She is a crack shot with a rifle. 她是步枪神枪手。', '过去式: cracked 过去分词: cracked 现在分词: cracking 第三人称单数: cracks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unrepentant', '[ˌʌnrɪ\'pentənt]', 'adj.不后悔的；不思悔改的；顽固不化的', '1. Ali was mouthy, gutsy, and unrepentant. 阿里是伶牙俐齿的，坚定无畏的，从不懊悔的。 2. He was preaching down on the unrepentant sinners. 他正谴责那些没有悔意的罪人们。 3. I remain an unrepentant rationalist. 我仍是一位执迷不悟的理性主义者。 4. The country that stands out as unrepentant is Greece. 明显顽固不化的国家的是希腊。', '副词: unrepentantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entrust', '[ɪn\'trʌst]', 'vt.信赖；信托；交托', '1. I hope we can entrust each other. 我希望我们能彼此相互信任。 2. I know I can entrust you with my secret. 我知道我能把我的秘密告诉你。 3. I wouldn\'t advise you to entrust anything of value to him. 我劝你不要把任何贵重的东西托付给他看管。 4. You are a magistrate, and the only person I can entrust this matter to. 你是法官，这件事我只信托你一个人。', '异体字: intrust 过去式: entrusted 过去分词: entrusted 现在分词: entrusting 第三人称单数: entrusts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('redolent', '[\'redələnt]', 'adj.有 ... 香味的；令人想起 ... 的', '1. Their own yard is redolent with lilacs. 他们家自己的院子里散发着丁香花的芬芳。 2. The kitchen was redolent of onions. 厨房里满是洋葱味。 3. The castle is redolent of the past. 那城堡使人怀古。 4. His image is redolent of the smell of old leather,old money and class. 他的形象使人联想起旧皮革的气味、旧钞票和等级。', '副词: redolently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vomit', '[\'vɑːmɪt]', 'v.吐出；呕吐；喷出 n.呕吐；呕吐物', '1. He vomited up all he had eaten. 他把吃下的东西全吐了出来。 2. The mixture of drinks made me vomit. 我喝了混合饮料后吐了起来。 3. She was stricken by pain and began to vomit. 她感到一阵疼痛, 开始呕吐起来。 4. Tall chimneys vomit forth black smoke. 高高的烟囱喷吐出黑烟。 5. He had no recollection of the feast and his vomit afterwards. 他对酒席以及后来的呕吐完全没印象了。', '名词: vomiter 过去式: vomited 过去分词: vomited 现在分词: vomiting 第三人称单数: vomits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('threat', '[θret]', 'n.威胁；恐吓；凶兆', '1. His presence is a threat to our success. 他的出现对我们的成功是一个威胁。 2. The threat of an economic depression hangs over the world. 经济衰退的威胁笼罩着世界。 3. Pollution poses a threat to the continued existence of this species. 污染对这一物种的继续生存造成了威胁。 4. He took not notice of his father\'s threat. 他不理会他父亲的恐吓。', '过去式: threated 过去分词: threated 现在分词: threating 第三人称单数: threats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('befoul', '[bɪ\'faʊl]', 'vt.弄脏；玷辱', '1. How dare you)befoul my lucky number! 如何挑战你)弄脏我的幸运数目! 2. The lowest rank of the undead, zombies befoul much of the wilderness of the Western Kingdoms, as well as the tombs and crypts of the whole of Sanctuary. 僵尸是最低阶的不死生物，在西方国家的荒野及教堂寺庙的墓地和地窖处常有大批出没著。 3. Certain people used to befoul its banks every day.Others who came there in the morning to bathe would abuse the offenders loudly. 每天都有某些人习惯性地把湖岸弄脏，另一些早上来到湖边淋浴的人会大声地辱骂冒犯者。 4. Toxic corrosion:befoul a sacrificial vehicle, causing it to leak vile toxic that foes had best avoid. Can not ues it on a enemy units. 铁幕:使目标无敌22秒;3分钟冷却.;有效目标为建筑物;车辆和水面的船', '过去式: befouled 过去分词: befouled 现在分词: befouling 第三人称单数: befouls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('complicate', '[\'kɑːmplɪkeɪt]', 'v.使复杂化；使起纠纷 adj.复杂的', '1. There is no need to complicate matters. 没有必要使问题复杂化。 2. He always likes to complicate simple matters. 他总喜欢把简单的事情复杂化。 3. This text is more complicate than we can imagine. 这篇课文比我们想象的还要复杂。 4. My brother can understand the most complicate circuit diagrams. 再复杂的线路图哥哥都能看懂。', '过去式: complicated 过去分词: complicated 现在分词: complicating 第三人称单数: complicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('publicize', '[\'pʌblɪsaɪz]', 'v.宣传；公布；广告', '1. We should publicize the census well. 我们要做好这次人口普查的宣传工作。 2. We are trying to publicize our products by advertisement on buses. 我们正试图在公共汽车上做广告来宣传我们的产品。 3. No other entity or individual may publicize any major animal epidemic emergency. 其他任何单位和个人不得公布重大动物疫情。 4. To satisfy employees, a firm is likely to publicize bravely its adherence to this policy. 为了稳住职工，公司可能会公布要坚持执行这个政策。', '过去式: publicized 过去分词: publicized 现在分词: publicizing 第三人称单数: publicizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ditty', '[\'dɪti]', 'n.小调；小曲', '1. He quavered forth a quaint old ditty. 他用颤抖的嗓音哼了一首稀奇古怪的古老小调。 2. We all like her ditty. 我们都喜欢她的小曲。 3. The beggar sits on the side of the road singing ditty for money . 那个乞丐坐在路边唱着小曲讨钱。', '名词复数: ditties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vintner', '[\'vɪntnər]', 'n.酒商；酿酒者', '1. The vintner worked the wine in big oak vats. 酒商在大橡木桶中酿酒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slaughter', '[\'slɔːtər]', 'n.残杀；屠杀；大量杀戮 v.残杀；屠杀', '1. He had no strong feelings about human slaughter. 他对人类残杀没有强烈的感情。 2. I am really terrified to witness the slaughter. 我亲眼目睹这场屠杀，真是吓坏了。 3. Wholesale slaughter was carried out in the name of progress. 大规模的屠杀在维护进步的名义下进行。 4. He waded through slaughter to the throne. 他行杀戮而得王位。 5. Hundreds of innocent civilians were cruelly slaughtered. 数百名无辜平民遭残杀。', '形容词: slaughterous 名词: slaughterer 过去式: slaughtered 过去分词: slaughtered 现在分词: slaughtering 第三人称单数: slaughters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emulate', '[\'emjuleɪt]', 'vt.效法；尽力赶上 [计算机] 仿真.', '1. You should emulate his good example. 你应该效法他的好榜样。 2. The proverb tells us to emulate the industry of the ant. 这格言告诉我们要效法蚂蚁的勤勉。 3. I wish he\'d stop holding the elder brother as an example to emulate. 我希望他不再把哥哥作为自己的学习榜样。 4. You must work hard to emulate your sister. 你必须努力工作, 赶上你姐姐。 5. If one computer system or program emulates another, it behaves in the same way. 如果一台计算机系统或者程序模拟另外一台电脑,它表现在以同样的方式运行。', '形容词: emulative 副词: emulatively 名词: emulator 过去式: emulated 过去分词: emulated 现在分词: emulating 第三人称单数: emulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('miasma', '[mi\'æzmə]', 'n.瘴气；烟雾弥漫的空气；不良气氛', '1. A miasma rose from the marsh. 沼泽地里冒出了瘴气。 2. Changing water levels now at times unleash a miasma of disease from exposed sewage. 如今，大坝不时地改变水位，从暴露的污水释放出了疾病瘴气。 3. A miasma of stale alcohol hung around him. 他身上老有股难闻的酒精味。 4. When he\'d opened his eyes again the miasma was gone and he was neither alone nor among sahuagin. 当他再次睁开眼睛的时候，窒息毒液已经消失，他既不孤单也不身处沙华鱼人中。', '形容词: miasmal 名词复数: miasmas');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('variegation', '[ˌverɪ\'geɪʃən]', 'n.上色；彩色；杂色；斑驳', '1. We supply various metal& plastics nameplates, and we have processing of etch,laser ,polish &brush,oxidation,variegation,epoxy dripping,back adhesive to fulfit your unique demand. 我们还提供各种金属，塑料铭牌，并有蚀刻，激光雕刻，批花，氧化，上色，滴胶，背胶等生产工艺，以满足您个性化的需要。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tactile', '[\'tæktl]', 'adj.触觉的；有触觉的；能触知的', '1. That kind of tactile feedback might seem like a minor feature. 这种有触觉的反馈还是次要特性。 2. I live in the realm of the tactile which could be the last stronghold of the analog world. 我生活在触觉的国度中，这也许是模拟世界的最后一个根据地。 3. That kind of tactile feedback might seem like a minor feature. 这种有触觉的反馈还是次要特性。', '副词: tactilely 名词: tactility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frail', '[freɪl]', 'adj.脆弱的；虚弱的', '1. I will not torment the emotionally frail. 我再也不折磨情感脆弱的人了。 2. Jail life made the frail retailer avail every snail in the pail. 监狱生命使脆弱的零售商在桶里有益于每只蜗牛。 3. His frail hands could hardly hold a cup. 他虚弱的手连杯子也拿不住。 4. This frail child did not survive. 这个身体虚弱的孩子没能活下来。', '副词: frailly 比较级: frailer 最高级: frailest 名词: frailness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stake', '[steɪk]', 'n.桩；赌注；利害关系 v.用桩支撑；下注', '1. He drove a stake into the ground. 他向地里打了一根桩子。 2. This decision puts our lives at stake. 这么一决定,我们的生命就吉凶难卜了。 3. Most parents feel that they have a stake in their children\'s future,and so will use every effort to help them. 大多数家长认为，孩子们的前途和他们有利害关系，所以尽一切努力帮助他们。 4. He put up a stake to support the newly planted tree. 他竖了一根桩支撑新种的树。', '过去式: staked 过去分词: staked 现在分词: staking 第三人称单数: stakes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('uncommitted', '[ˌʌnkə\'mɪtɪd]', 'adj.不受约束的；未承诺的；自由的；不承担责任的；未被监禁的', '1. Our professional ethic enjoins us to stay uncommitted and report the facts. 我们的职业道德要求我们要保持中立，报道事实真相。 2. I am still uncommitted to undertaking the work. 我还没有说定要接受这份工作。 3. She will join the club later, but at the moment wants to remain uncommitted. 她迟些将加入俱乐部，但目前仍想保持自由。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gormandize', '[\'gɔːməndˌaɪz]', 'v.拼命吃；贪吃', '1. He\'s a famous gormand in Beijing. 他是北京城有名的吃主儿。 2. I am full, I want to drink my fill! to gormandize! to sleep! to do nothing! 好天主！不用再捉弄人吧，永生的天父！我要吃个够，喝个痛快！塞饱，睡足，什么事也不做！ 3. gormand n. 美食者', '名词: gormandizer 过去式: gormandized 过去分词: gormandized 现在分词: gormandizing 第三人称单数: gormandizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amass', '[ə\'mæs]', 'v.积聚；收集', '1. A speculator may try to amass great wealth. 投机商会想方设法积聚钱财。 2. Mr. Smith\'s business was very successful, and he was able to amass a fortune. 史密斯先生的事业极为成功，所以他积聚了一大笔财富。 3. She continues to amass a staggering amount of material on the history and technology relating to current-day mind control and other forms of abuse. 她继续收集在历史和技术上涉及到当今的精神控制和其他的孽待形式的令人惊愕的材料。 4. So, as you begin to amass this knowledge and these abilities, there will be others attracted to you for their own reasons because of what they can access through you. 所以，如同你们开始收集这知识和这些能力，将会有吸引他们自己的动机，因为他们能够通过你们访问。', '形容词: amassable 名词: amasser 过去式: amassed 过去分词: amassed 现在分词: amassing 第三人称单数: amasses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nonpareil', '[ˌnɑːnpə\'rel]', 'adj.无法匹敌的 n.全善全美的人；粘有糖粒的扁圆巧克力', '1. We may have to agree that the noble Lord is not precisely a nonpareil as a departmental minister. 我们也许只能一致认定：这位高贵的勋爵作为一位大臣不一定算得全善全美。 2. Studies on the micropropagation of5cultivars of almond,Bulgaria1,Nonpareil,Fritz,Prize and Neplus,was conducted with node explants. 对5个引进的美国扁桃品种Bulgaria1、Nonpareil、Fritz、Prize和Neplus的微繁殖进行了研究。 3. Keane may be a nonpareil in that regard but Neville will never be found wanting if a team-mate needs someone by his side. 基恩也许得到了无比的尊敬，但如果队友需要帮助的话内维尔总会出现在你的面前。 4. Can McGrady, entering his 11th NBA season, at long last live up to his nonpareil reputation and deliver a blue-collar, crunch-time effort in the post-season? 麦迪即将进入第11个赛季，他能在季后赛的关键时刻咬紧牙关，像那些专干脏活的蓝领队员杀出一条血路，以对得上无上名气吗?', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plutocracy', '[pluː\'tɑːkrəsi]', 'n.富豪或财阀统治；富豪或财阀统治的国家；富豪阶级', '1. Newspapers are the organs of plutocracy. 报纸是富人的喉舌。 2. The most prolific of the debunkers of the plutocracy was Gustavus Myers. 揭发富豪统治集团的作家中，最多产的是古斯塔夫斯·迈尔斯。 3. Further, it will hasten the demise of China\'s remaining state-owned industries and the creation of a plutocracy. 再者，该法将催促中国剩余的国有资产缩水，催生财阀阶层。 4. Where by design or accident, Britain has chosen to be the service center for the global plutocracy. 不知是出于精心策划还是纯属偶然，英国已经成为了全球财阀们的服务中心。', '形容词: plutocratic 副词: plutocratically 名词: plutocrat 名词复数: plutocracies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('smut', '[smʌt]', 'n.污物；淫秽内容；黑穗病 v.污染；（使）生黑穗病', '1. Its main Chinese competitor, Baidu, is just as good at finding smut. 它的中国主要竞争对手，百度，也同样发现淫秽内容。 2. Comparison of control efficacy against corn head smut between 40% Vitavax 200FF and 15% triadimefon WP was made in 1998. 比较了卫福和粉锈宁拌种防治玉米丝黑穗病的效果。 3. Comparison of control efficacy against corn head smut between 40% Vitavax 200FF and 15% triadimefon WP was made in 1998. 比较了卫福和粉锈宁拌种防治玉米丝黑穗病的效果。', '形容词: smutty 副词: smuttily 名词: smuttiness 过去式: smutted 过去分词: smutted 现在分词: smutting 第三人称单数: smuts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hanker', '[\'hæŋkər]', 'v.向往；渴望；期望', '1. If you hanker for the great outdoors, it would be hard to beat Switzerland. 如果你对户外的极致景色心驰神往，那么瑞士就是最佳之选。 2. I hankered for a good cup of coffee. 我真想喝一大杯咖啡。 3. So try to understand why you hanker for compromise. 所以，要试著去了解，为什麽你会渴望妥协。 4. One should not hanker after pomp and extravagance in a wedding. 结婚不要讲排场。', '名词: hankerer 过去式: hankered 过去分词: hankered 现在分词: hankering 第三人称单数: hankers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('breed', '[briːd]', 'v.繁殖；养育；引起，产生；教养 n.品种；血统', '1. Wild animals don\'t breed well in captivity. 野生动物圈养时不好繁殖。 2. How often do lions breed? 狮子多长时间产一次仔? 3. I breed some chicks for pets. 我养了一些小鸡当宠物。 4. Spartan youths were bred as warriors. 斯巴达青年被培养成战士. 5. Spaniel is a breed of dog with large ears. 西班牙猎狗是一种长着大耳朵的猎狗。', '过去式: bred 过去分词: bred 现在分词: breeding 第三人称单数: breeds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gradation', '[ɡrə\'deɪʃn]', 'n.渐变；阶段；等级；刻度；元音交替', '1. I have noticed the subtle gradation in colour in this painting. 我已经注意到这幅画中色彩的渐变。 2. A good actor can express every gradation of feeling from joy to grief. 一名好演员能够表现出由快乐至痛苦的每一阶段的感情变化。 3. It was hard to understand all the minute gradations of their bureaucracy. 很难弄清楚他们那套官僚体制全部细微的层次分别。', '形容词: gradational 副词: gradationally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('polarity', '[pə\'lærəti]', 'n.极性；磁性引力；两极', '1. Polarity is inherent in a magnet. 极性是磁铁的固有性质。 2. Note the polarity of the voltage drop across R. 注意R上电压降的极性。 3. The hydrophobicity is related to molecular volume and polarity. 分子的疏水性跟分子的体积和极性有关。 4. The field is strongest at the poles, diminishes at the equator, and differs in polarity from the Northern to the Southern Hemisphere. 南北两极的磁场最强，赤道上磁场较为微弱，而各地的磁性也会因纬度而改变。', '名词复数: polarities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('buggy', '[\'bʌɡi]', 'adj.多虫的 n.轻型马车；婴儿车', '1. Amasai spent all the morning washing the buggy. 阿马萨花了整整一上午刷洗那辆轻便马车。 2. We drove in a buggy past the Dorset house. 我们驾了一辆轻型小马车经过道塞特家的住宅。 3. She put her little daughter in the buggy. 她把小女儿放在婴儿车里。', '比较级: buggier 最高级: buggiest 名词: bugginess 名词复数: buggies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('motile', '[\'moʊtɪl]', 'adj.[生]能动的；有自动力的 n.[心]运动表象型', '1. For instance, motile aerobic bacteria are positively aerotactic, whereas motile obigate anaerobic bacteria are negatively aerotactic. 例如能动的需氧细菌表现出正的趋氧性，然而能动的厌氧细菌则表现出负的趋氧性。', '名词: motility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bauxite', '[\'bɔːksaɪt]', 'n.铝土岩(产铝的矿土、石)', '1. Aluminum is made from bauxite. 铝是从铝土矿中提炼出的。', '形容词: bauxitic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sonata', '[sə\'nɑːtə]', 'n.奏鸣曲', '1. She led off her recital with a Haydn sonata. 她在独奏会上首先演出的是海顿的奏鸣曲。 2. The pianist executed the sonata perfectly. 这钢琴家把这首奏鸣曲演奏得非常完美。 3. He heard someone playing his sonata in F. 他听见某人正用F调在弹他的奏鸣曲。 4. She\'s going to play the opening bar of the sonata. 她准备演奏这支奏鸣曲的开始数小节。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('simulate', '[\'sɪmjuleɪt]', 'vt.假装；模拟；模仿', '1. These insects can simulate dead leaves . 这些昆虫可以伪装成枯叶。 2. I tried to simulate surprise at the news. 听到这个消息后，我竭力装出一副吃惊的样子。 3. He shook a sheet of metal to simulate the noise of thunder. 他摇动一块金属薄片来模拟雷声。 4. You can simulate different browser types for tests. 您可以为测试模拟不同类型的浏览器。', '形容词: simulative 过去式: simulated 过去分词: simulated 现在分词: simulating 第三人称单数: simulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flatten', '[\'flætn]', 'vt.使变平；打倒 vi.变平', '1. She used a rolling pin to flatten the pie dough . 她用擀面棍来擀平做馅饼的面团。 2. The boxer was flattened with one punch. 那个拳击手被一拳击倒了。 3. He was totally flattened by her sarcasm. 她说的挖苦话使他无地自容。 4. The land flattens out near the coast. 海岸附近地势变得很平坦。', '名词: flattener 过去式: flattened 过去分词: flattened 现在分词: flattening 第三人称单数: flattens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('omnivorous', '[ɑːm\'nɪvərəs]', 'adj.杂食的；涉猎广泛的', '1. But the omnivorous beast is rampant still. 但是这只杂食动物依然毫无节制. 2. He is omnivorous of books. 他什麽书都读。 3. She has always been an omnivorous reader. 她一向阅读兴趣广泛。', '副词: omnivorously 名词: omnivorousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blandishment', '[\'blændɪʃmənt]', 'n.奉承', '1. She resisted his blandishments. 她把他的甜言蜜语顶了回去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immure', '[ɪ\'mjʊr]', 'vt.监禁；禁闭', '1. Immure a shrine. 把神龛嵌于墙内', '名词: immurement 过去式: immured 过去分词: immured 现在分词: immuring 第三人称单数: immures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pantomime', '[\'pæntəmaɪm]', 'n.哑剧；童话剧；哑剧演员；手势 v.打手势；演哑剧', '1. The actor is skilled in pantomime. 这个演员擅长表演哑剧。 2. The audience roared with laughter at the pantomime. 观众被这哑剧逗得哈哈大笑。 3. The children were very excited by the pantomime. 孩子们看了童话剧非常兴奋。 4. Some tourists make themselves understood abroad by pantomime. 一些游客在国外通常用手势来让别人明白自己的意思。 5. Apes are routinely beaten into submission and forced to pantomime human behaviors that are foreign and confusing. 猿类被屈打得顺从，被迫模仿对于它们来说是莫名其妙，难以理解的人类行为举止。', '形容词: pantomimic 名词: pantomimist 过去式: pantomimed 过去分词: pantomimed 现在分词: pantomiming 第三人称单数: pantomimes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stanza', '[\'stænzə]', 'n.诗节', '1. He\'s reading the second stanza. 他正在读诗的第二节。 2. I don\'t think this stanza detracts from the integrity of the poem. 我认为这一节并没有损害全诗的统一性。', '形容词: stanzaic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('envisage', '[ɪn\'vɪzɪdʒ]', 'vt.面对；想像', '1. Nobody can envisage the consequences of total nuclear war. 没有人能想像出全面核子战争的后果。 2. I don\'t envisage working with him again. 我想像不出再与他一起工作的可能。 3. Nobody can envisage the consequences of total nuclear war. 没有人能想像出全面核子战争的后果。 4. I can\'t envisage the plan(\'s)working. 我无法设想计划能否行得通.', '过去式: envisaged 过去分词: envisaged 现在分词: envisaging 第三人称单数: envisages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cluster', '[\'klʌstər]', 'n.群；簇；丛；串 v.群集；丛生；使成群', '1. A cluster of tourists are waiting for their tour guide. 一群游客正在等他们的导游。 2. You can see stars in clusters in the night sky. 你可以看到夜空中的星群。 3. You can see clusters of berries in the garden. 花园里能见到一簇簇浆果。 4. You can see ivy growing in thick clusters anywhere. 到哪儿都能看见成丛生长的常春藤。 5. The men clustered together round the fire and sang songs. 人们聚集在篝火周围唱歌。', '过去式: clustered 过去分词: clustered 现在分词: clustering 第三人称单数: clusters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rabid', '[\'ræbɪd]', 'adj.患狂犬病的；疯狂的；极端的；激进的', '1. The customs agents destroyed the dog that was found to be rabid. 海关消灭了被发现患有狂犬病的狗。 2. He is absolutely a rabid football fan. 他完全是一个狂热的足球迷。 3. The attack is believed to have been carried out by a group of rabid anti-semites. 这次袭击被认为是由一群极端的反犹份子发动的。', '副词: rabidly 名词: rabidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whelp', '[welp]', 'n.幼兽；小孩；可鄙的人；扣齿链 v.下崽；产仔', '1. The female dog bore five whelps. 母狗生了五只小狗。 2. A bull, finding a lion\'s whelp asleep, gore him to death with his horn. 一只公牛发现一只狮子的幼兽在睡觉，便用角把它抵死了。 3. The dog stays home to whelp and raises her puppy. 这条狗待在家里生了小狗并把它们养大。 4. It looked as if the dog was about to whelp. 看来这条狗要下崽了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scan', '[skæn]', 'vt.扫描；浏览；审视；细看 vi.合韵律；划分音步 n.扫描；浏览；细看', '1. Could you teach me how to scan an image? 你可以教我如何扫描一个影像吗? 2. I scanned the newspaper when I was waiting for the bus. 等公共汽车的时候，我匆匆浏览了一下报纸。 3. She scanned his face, looking for signs of what he was thinking. 她审视他的脸,试图探寻他在思考什么。 4. I scanned my pocket for change. 我仔细查看囗袋找零钱。 5. The verses scan well. 这些诗句符合韵律。 6. The doctors gave him an ultrasonic brain scan. 医生给他做了脑部超声波扫描检查。', '形容词: scannable 名词: scanner 过去式: scanned 过去分词: scanned 现在分词: scanning 第三人称单数: scans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('receipt', '[rɪ\'siːt]', 'n.收据；收条；收到 v.出收据', '1. May I have a receipt? 我可以要一张收据吗？ 2. Please send me a receipt for the money. 请寄给我一张收到此款的收据。 3. We only take goods back if customers can produce the receipt. 顾客如能出示收据，我们才能予以退货。 4. Please give the receipt to the bearer. 收条请交来人带回。 5. His main work is to receipt for each lot of goods. 他的主要工作是给每一批货物开收据。', '过去式: receipted 过去分词: receipted 现在分词: receipting 第三人称单数: receipts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bleach', '[bliːtʃ]', 'n.漂白剂；漂白 v.变白；漂白', '1. I\'d like to buy a strong household bleach. 我想买强力家用漂白剂。 2. She scrubbed the counters down with bleach. 她用漂白剂把柜台擦洗干净。 3. I wonder if bleach will get that black spot out of my white jeans. 我在想漂白水能不能够将我白色牛仔裤上的班块清除。 4. How can the skin just bleach a bit ah? 皮肤怎么才能变白一点啊?', '过去式: bleached 过去分词: bleached 现在分词: bleaching 第三人称单数: bleaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mitten', '[\'mɪtn]', 'n.【C】连指手套 n.求婚拒绝', '1. In winter she wears mittens. 冬天时她戴连指手套。 2. I have a pair of leather mittens. 我有一副皮连指手套。 3. She said that she had been given the mitten. 她说她的求婚被拒绝了 4. She had given her ex-boyfriend the mitten and married an old man. 她拒绝她以前的男朋友而嫁给了一个老头子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sap', '[sæp]', 'n.树液；汁液；精力；<俚>易上当的人；地道 v.挖地道；削弱；逐渐耗竭', '1. These bugs drink much sap every day. 这些虫子每天吸食许多树液。 2. Maple sugar is made from the sap of maple trees. 枫糖是由枫树的树液制成的。 3. The sap flowed out when he broke the stem of the flower. 他把花茎折断，汁液就流了出来。 4. It was the beginning of the spring and the sap was rising in the boys. 正当初春季节，勃勃的生气在小伙子们身上奔涌。 5. The criticism sapped his determination. 批评削弱了他的决心。', '过去式: sapped 过去分词: sapped 现在分词: sapping 第三人称单数: saps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('facetious', '[fə\'siːʃəs]', 'adj.（常为不当地）引人发笑的；诙谐的', '1. He is so facetious that he turns everything into a joke. 他好开玩笑，把一切都变成戏谑。 2. I became angry with the little boy at his facetious remarks. 我对那小男孩的玩笑话感到生气。 3. Facetious remarks are part of his stock-in-trade. 讲俏皮话是他的拿手好戏。', '副词: facetiously 名词: facetiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('herpetologist', '[hɜːpə\'tɒlədʒɪst]', 'n.爬虫学家', '1. Felix became a herpetologist instead. 费利克斯而是成为了一位爬虫学家。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stain', '[steɪn]', 'n.污点；瑕疵；着色剂；染料 v.弄脏；玷污；着色', '1. The stain on his shirt is difficult to clean off. 他衬衣上的污点很难去除掉。 2. It will remain an indelible stain on his memory. 这将成为他记忆中一个不可磨灭的污点。 3. Such a man is a stain to humanity. 这种人是人类的耻辱。 4. There isn\'t a stain on her reputation. 她的名誉没有半点瑕疵。 5. These carpets won\'t stain easily. 这些地毯不易弄脏。', '形容词: stainable 名词: stainer 过去式: stained 过去分词: stained 现在分词: staining 第三人称单数: stains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jagged', '[\'dʒæɡɪd]', 'adj.参差不齐的 动词jag的过去式和过去分词.', '1. Jagged rocks stuck up through the grass. 锯齿状的岩石从杂草中突了出来。 2. On all sides, skyscrapers rose like jagged teeth. 四周耸起的摩天大楼参差不齐。 3. Why then are lightning bolts so jagged and irregular? 为什么闪电会以参差不齐的形态出现呢？', '副词: jaggedly 名词: jaggedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muffler', '[\'mʌflər]', 'n.围巾；头巾；厚手套；消声器', '1. They took off his coat and cap and muffler. 大家给他脱去大衣、帽子、围巾。 2. The colors of your coat,hat and muffler shall harmonize. 你外套、帽子和围巾的色彩应该协调。 3. Thus, a successful muffler design method is developed. 探索了一种消声器的设计和模拟分析方法。 4. We provide just about everything except muffler inspections. 我们几乎提供一切，除了检查排气消声器。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clannish', '[\'klænɪʃ]', 'adj.排他的；门户之见的', '1. Even by clannish Japan\'s standards, the island seems a friendly, close-knit place. 即便存在日本的排他标准,这个岛看上去是个友善,待人亲密的地方。 2. Clannish person does not separate oneself and another person. 氏族人不分自己和他人。', '副词: clannishly 名词: clannishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('halcyon', '[\'hælsiən]', 'adj.宁静的；平稳的 n.翡翠鸟；传说中的太平鸟', '1. He yearned for the halcyon daysof his childhood. 他怀念儿时宁静幸福的日子。 2. The Christmas season always made Bonnie yean for those halcyon days of her youth. 圣诞节长使波尼怀念她年轻时平静、愉快的日子。 3. Through those halcyon weeks Julia darted and shone. 经过几个平稳幸福的星期，朱莉娅崭露头角，光彩照人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prudish', '[\'pruːdɪʃ]', 'adj.过分拘谨的；装规矩的；过份规矩的', '1. American culture is in many ways still fairly prudish. 美国文化在许多方面还是相当拘谨的。 2. I don\'t consider myself prudish but I do think the sex scenes in the film were a bit excessive. 我不认为自己是过分规矩的，但是我确实认为电影里的性爱场面有点过火了。', '副词: prudishly 名词: prudishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hilarious', '[hɪ\'leriəs]', 'adj.欢闹的；愉快的', '1. The party get quite hilarious after they bring more wine. 当他们拿来更多葡萄酒後聚会变得十分热闹起来。 2. Jimmy Durante\'s buffoonery was hilarious. 吉米·杜兰特的滑稽表演令人捧腹。 3. He does a hilarious imitation of Tony Blair. 他模仿托尼布莱尔的滑稽表演令观众捧腹。 4. A former model wrote a hilarious novel based on pillow talk with her many male friends. 一位前模特儿以她同许多男友的枕头谈话为基础写出了一本有趣的小说。', '副词: hilariously 名词: hilariousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('easel', '[\'iːzl]', 'n.画架', '1. He paused in the middle of folding up his easel. 他画架收到一半，却停了下来。 2. This is a well designed easel which folds up quickly and neatly. 这个画架设计得很好, 可以迅速而整齐地折叠起来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('random', '[\'rændəm]', 'adj.任意的；随机的；随意的 n.随意；任意 adv.随机地', '1. Men are exposed to more acts of random physical violence. 男人受到更多的任意的身体强烈活动。 2. Most people know that the outcome of a coin toss is random. 大部分人都知道掷硬币的结果是随机的。 3. The computer will generate apparently random numbers. 电脑似乎将随机产生号码。 4. This random approach is not as dubious as one might expect. 这种随意的途径并不象人们所预期的那样无把握。 5. Soiled dishes were piled at random. 脏碟子胡乱地堆放着。 6. Complex organs made up of separate but necessary subsystems cannot be the result of random chance. 复杂的器官是由独立的，必要的子系统组成，而且不能随机地形成。', '副词: randomly 名词: randomness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('daguerreotype', '[də\'ɡerətaɪp]', 'n.(早期)银板照相；银版照片 v.用银版法拍摄', '1. French artist and inventor of the daguerreotype process for obtaining positive photographic prints. 达盖尔，路易斯·雅克·曼德1789－1851法国艺术家和发明家，发明了银版摄影术，能洗出照片的正画 2. Daguerre:French artist and inventor of the daguerreotype process for obtaining positive photographic prints. \"达盖尔:法国艺术家和发明家;发明了银版摄影术;能洗出照片的正画.;\" 3. To make a daguerreotype of. 用达尔银版法拍摄 4. In 1840 he developed the calotype;an early photographic process that improved on the daguerreotype, it involved the use of a photographic negative, from which multiple prints could be made. 1840年他开发卡罗式照相法，这是一种改良达盖尔式照相法的早期照相方法，它使用一种摄影负像，由此可以复印多份照片。', '名词: daguerreotyper 过去式: daguerreotyped 过去分词: daguerreotyped 现在分词: daguerreotyping 第三人称单数: daguerreotypes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aluminium', '[ˌæljə\'mɪniəm]', 'n.铝 =aluminum（美）', '1. I hardly ever know that aluminium alloy could be as strong as steel. 我几乎从来不知道铝合金竟会和钢强度一样大。 2. Aluminium was slowly wedging its way in the metal market. 当时铝正在慢慢地挤入金属市场。 3. By mixing aluminium with other metals, scientists have been able to produce a variety of alloys, some of which have the strength of steel but weigh only one third as much. 把铝和其他金属混合，科学家们能够制造出各种合金，其中一些具有钢一样的强度，但其重量只是钢的三分之一。 4. Wrapping aluminium foil round a joint allows the meat to cook in its own juice/juices. 用铝箔把肉包住使之在原汁中烹制。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defer', '[dɪ\'fɜːr]', 'v.推迟；延期；使延期入伍 v.顺从；把…委托给他人', '1. They cannot defer their departure any longer. 他们再不能推迟动身了。 2. We wish to defer our decision until next week. 我们希望推迟到下星期再作出决定。 3. I will defer going till I have more money. 我要延期到我有更多钱时才去。 4. The company agree to defer payment for three month. 公司同意延期三个月后付款。 5. We should defer to our parents\' wishes. 我们应当顺从父母的意愿。', '形容词: deferrable 名词: deferrer 过去式: deferred 过去分词: deferred 现在分词: deferring 第三人称单数: defers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gaggle', '[\'ɡæɡl]', 'n.鹅群；一群(喧哗的人) v.嘎嘎地叫；咯咯地说出', '1. They all burst out laughing, sounding like a gaggle of geese. 她们全都放声大笑,像一群鹅一样嘎嘎地叫着。 2. A gaggle of schoolgirls followed the tennis star to his car. 一群叽哩呱啦的女学生跟著网球明星到他的车子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hearken', '[\'hɑːrkən]', 'vt.倾听(给予注意)', '1. Will you hearken to my calling, as I call from far away? 你可会倾听我的召唤，我那来自远方的召唤？', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sporadic', '[spə\'rædɪk]', 'adj.不定时发生的；零星的', '1. Primary hepatic leiomyosarcoma is very rare with only sporadic cases reported. 摘要原发性肝脏平滑肌肉瘤非常少见，因此只有一些零星的病例报告。 2. Her only income came from sporadic leasing deals, forcing her to dip repeatedly into retirement savings. 她仅有的收入来自于零星的租赁交易，这令她不得不经常动用退休储蓄。', '副词: sporadically 异体字: sporadical 名词: sporadicalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commodious', '[kə\'moʊdiəs]', 'adj.宽敞的', '1. It is a commodious house. 这是一间宽敞的房屋。 2. The students\' cupboards are very commodious. 学生们的橱柜非常宽敞。', '副词: commodiously 名词: commodiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lout', '[laʊt]', 'n.笨人', '1. He had no training, no skills, just a big, bungling and useless lout! 他什么也不行，什么也不会，只是个傻大黑粗的废物！', '过去式: louted 过去分词: louted 现在分词: louting 第三人称单数: louts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jazz', '[dʒæz]', 'n.爵士乐；<俚>空话；各种杂物 vt.使有生气；以爵士风格演奏 vi.跳爵士舞；奏爵士乐；游荡', '1. She\'s potty about jazz. 她迷上了爵士音乐。 2. I don\'t dig modern jazz. 我不喜欢现代爵士乐。 3. Does jazz hold any appeal for you? 你对爵士乐有兴趣吗？ 4. Jazz has never really turned me on. 我从未对爵士乐真正产生过兴趣。 5. We need to jazz this room up a bit. 我们需要把这间屋子装饰一下使之更有生气。 6. I don\'t like to jazz up the classics. 我不喜欢用爵士乐的形式来演奏古典乐曲。', '形容词: jazzish 名词: jazzer 过去式: jazzed 过去分词: jazzed 现在分词: jazzing 第三人称单数: jazzes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('polemical', '[pə\'lemɪkl]', 'adj.辩论的；争论的；争议的 =polemic.', '1. The letter was probably written for polemical impact. 这封信可能是为了造成争论性影响而写的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dislocate', '[\'dɪsloʊkeɪt]', 'v.使脱臼；使混乱', '1. How did she dislocate her shoulder 4 times? 她怎么使她的肩膀四次脱臼? 2. Flights have been dislocated by the fog. 大雾将飞机的班次搅乱了。 3. Only an exceptionally heavy snowfall might temporarily dislocate railway service. 只有罕见的暴雪才会暂时打乱铁路的运行。', '过去式: dislocated 过去分词: dislocated 现在分词: dislocating 第三人称单数: dislocates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('backwater', '[\'bækwɔːtər]', 'n.回水；回水河汊；穷乡僻壤', '1. Some were playing water-polo in the backwater. 有些人在回水河汊玩水球。 2. There aren\'t any good shops in this village, it\'s a real backwater. 在这村庄没有任何一间好的商店，真的是闭塞落后的地方。 3. I find this town too much of a backwater. 我觉得这个城镇太闭塞。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('graphite', '[\'ɡræfaɪt]', 'n.石墨；黑铅；铅笔粉', '1. Graphite is a soft black substance. 石墨是一种软而黑的物质。 2. Graphite is used in making lead pencils. 石墨常被用来做成铅笔。', '形容词: graphitic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fluorescent', '[ˌflɔː\'resnt]', 'n.日光灯 adj.萤光的', '1. There are two fluorescent lights on the ceiling. 天花板上挂了两盏日光灯。 2. I hate this cheap fluorescent lighting. 我讨厌这些廉价的日光灯。 3. Antibodies are conjugated with a fluorescent dye. 抗体接合上萤光染料。 4. Fluorescent bird droppings may help shed light on contested predictions in ecology. 鸟类排遗上的萤光或许能解释生态学上的一些争议。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nonconformist', '[ˌnɑːnkən\'fɔːrmɪst]', 'adj.不墨守成规的 n.不墨守成规的人 Nonconformist. adj.不信奉英国国教的 n.不信奉英国国教的人', '1. An eccentric or nonconformist person, especially a member of a counterculture. 离经叛道之人反常或不符合常规之人，尤指反主流文化的成员 2. A Nonconformist chapel, especially a Baptist or Methodist one. 非英国国教的礼拜堂基督新教徒的教堂，尤指浸信会或卫理公会教徒 3. Angel Clare had sadly disappointed his father, first by nonconformist views and then by sincere scruples against taking orders. 安吉尔·克莱使他的父亲十分失望，先是他不信奉国教的观点，后来又顾虑重重，不愿意当牧师。', '名词: Nonconformism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concession', '[kən\'seʃn]', 'n.让步；特许权；租界；妥协', '1. I hope you can make some concession. 我希望你能做些让步。 2. I must make a concession to him. 我必须对他让步。 3. They interpreted her silence as concession. 他们把她的沈默解释为让步。 4. He has an ice-cream concession in the subway station. 他在地铁站拥有一家冰淇淋分店。', '形容词: concessional');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impetuous', '[ɪm\'petʃuəs]', 'adj.冲动的；猛烈的；轻率的', '1. He is an impetuous young man. 他是个易冲动的年轻人。 2. She regretted her impetuous decision. 她后悔自己做了冲动的决定。 3. It was impetuous of her to do that. 她竟做那种事,真是鲁莽。 4. Youngsters are usually more impetuous than old people. 年轻人常比老年人急躁。', '副词: impetuously 名词: impetuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('declination', '[ˌdeklə\'neɪʃən]', 'n.倾斜；衰微；磁偏差；谢绝', '1. The paper analyzed the cause of the declination in a raise boring. 这文章分析了天井钻进偏斜的原因。 2. The declination course started in the left ventricle prior to the rightventaide. 心室舒张功能的减退左室先于右室。 3. Average outside diameter allowed declination of drawing brass and brass alloy tube. 拉制铜及铜合金管平均外径允许偏差。 4. Moral obligation prohibits declination of the call. 义不容辞', '形容词: declinational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dissociation', '[dɪˌsəʊsi\'eɪʃn]', 'n.分解；分离；游离', '1. Generally ionic salts with a large anion should have a high dissociation constant. 一般情况下，包含大的阴离子的盐具有高的分解常数。 2. Defining feature is dissociation of certain aspects of personality. 确定特征是人格的某些样子的分离。 3. The dissociation has been forgetting the color sky. 游离在遗忘了颜色的天空。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('minion', '[\'mɪniən]', 'n.下属；奴才；宠臣', '1. Can you send one of your minions to collect this file? 你能不能派个助手来取这份档案？ 2. While I was waiting to see him, a minion brought me some tea. 我在等着见他时，他手下的人给我倒了杯茶。 3. They are the dictator and his minions. 他们就是那个独裁者和他的奴仆。 4. All offered up sacrifices to the minion of fortune. 所有的人都情愿为这个命运的宠儿作出牺牲。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demur', '[dɪ\'mɜːr]', 'v.提出异议；反对；<古>拖延 n.异议；反对', '1. He demurred to my statement. 他对我的陈述提出异议。 2. Lawyer demured what the attestor said. 律师对证人的话的真实性提出了怀疑。 3. Workers demurred at working on Sundays. 工人们反对在星期天工作。 4. I suggested putting the matter to a vote, but the chairman demurred to it. 我建议对此事投票表决，但主席表示反对。 5. He accepted the criticism without demur. 他毫无异议地接受了批评。', '形容词: demurrable 过去式: demurred 过去分词: demurred 现在分词: demurring 第三人称单数: demurs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obstruct', '[əb\'strʌkt]', 'v.阻隔；妨碍；阻塞', '1. They do not obstruct most individuals who use patented products. 他们不会妨碍个人使用专利产品。 2. Five colors bewilder our eyes and obstruct our insights. 五种变化多端的颜色，迷惑我们的眼睛，妨碍我们的洞察力。 3. Such masses may also focally obstruct the biliary tract and lead to an elevated alkaline phosphatase. 肿物也可阻塞胆管，导致碱性磷酸酶升高。 4. But wherever Zhao went he would cause traffic jams and obstruct pavements as stunned crowds gathered to gawp. 但赵良所到之处，都会因惊讶的人们围观而造成塞车和道路阻塞。', '形容词: obstructive 副词: obstructively 名词: obstructer 过去式: obstructed 过去分词: obstructed 现在分词: obstructing 第三人称单数: obstructs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sideshow', '[\'saɪdʃoʊ]', 'n.穿插表演；枝节的问题；余兴', '1. The sideshows will fetch in the people as well. 幕间穿插的表演同样可以招徕看客。 2. If we didn\'t, Whitewater would soon look like the sideshow it was. 如果我们不能解决这个麻烦，白水事件马上会显得好似芝麻绿豆大的小事一般。 3. Everything else about Sony is a sideshow. 索尼的其他事情都只是余兴节目。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preeminent', '[priː\'emɪnənt]', 'adj.卓越的；优秀的；超群的', '1. His preeminent services had entitled him to the first place in his country\'s love. 他卓越的功绩，使得他最为全国人民所爱戴。 2. This country has always been preeminent in the field of medical research. 这个国家在医学研究领域上一直是卓越超群的。', '副词: preeminently 异体字: pre-eminent 名词: preeminence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sovereignty', '[\'sɑːvrənti]', 'n.主权；独立国', '1. The sovereignty of these islands is in dispute. 这些岛屿的主权有争执。 2. China\'s sovereignty and territorial integrity brook no division. 中国的主权和领土完整不容分割。 3. The issue of sovereignty is a red line that cannot be crossed. 主权问题是一条不能跨越的红线。 4. The declaration proclaimed the full sovereignty of the republic. 这份宣言宣告这个共和国完全独立自主。', '名词复数: sovereignties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corral', '[kə\'ræl]', 'n.畜栏 v.把…赶入围栏；聚集', '1. They drove the ponies into a corral. 他们把矮种马赶进了畜栏。 2. The kids were kept in the small corral. 羊羔圈养在小畜栏里。 3. After we corral the horses we\'ll have lunch. 把马关进围栏后,我们就吃中饭。 4. But email is too widely distributed to corral into any kind of structure now. 但是电子邮件的使用分布非常广泛，目前不可能统一为任何一种结构。', '过去式: corralled 过去分词: corralled 现在分词: corralling 第三人称单数: corrals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nausea', '[\'nɔːziə]', 'n.恶心；反胃；作呕；极端的厌恶', '1. Waves of nausea washed over him. 他突然感到阵阵恶心。 2. Early pregnancy is often accompanied by nausea. 怀孕初期常伴有恶心。 3. My stomach feels bloated and I have nausea. 我胃胀胀,而且反胃。 4. I\'m not sure,Billy. I have a nausea. 我不确定,比利, 我感觉作呕。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crook', '[krʊk]', 'n.钩；曲柄杖；弯曲；<口>骗子 vi.弯曲；诈骗 vt.使成钩状；使弯曲', '1. By the crook, the cook looked through a cookbook before making hooked cookies. 在溪边，厨子在做钩形饼干之前查阅了一本食谱。 2. He had shepherd\'s crook tipped with iron. 他有一根牧羊人用的带铁头的棍杖。 3. He carried the package in the crook of his arm. 他臂弯里挎着一个包裹。 4. As the developmt of the hypocotyl continues, the characteristic crook in the upper portion becomes apparent. 由于下胚轴继续发音，上部特有的弯曲变得明显。 5. She crooked her little finger as she drank her tea. 她喝茶时弯起小指头。', '过去式: crooked 过去分词: crooked 现在分词: crooking 第三人称单数: crooks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('regime', '[reɪ\'ʒiːm]', 'n.政体；政权；制度 n.养生法(=regimen)', '1. The people are held down by a vicious and repressive military regime. 人民受着凶恶而专制的军事政权的压迫。 2. The old capitalist regime is on its last legs. 旧的资本主义制度即将灭亡。 3. The regime has been propped up by foreign aid. 该政权是靠外国援助维持着的。 4. The overthrow of the regime was followed by a period of anarchy. 那政权被推翻以後，有一段时期是无政府状态。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glee', '[ɡliː]', 'n.欢乐；高兴', '1. Unfortunately, glee is very confined. 但不幸的是，快活很有限。 2. The newcomer rubbed his hands with glee. 那个新来的人快快活活地搓着双手。 3. With difficulty she restrained a smile of glee. 她好不容易才克制住自己将要露出的喜悦笑容来。 4. She clapped her hands in childish glee. 她孩子气地高兴地拍着手。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indent', '[ɪn\'dent]', 'n.订货单 n.凹痕 v.切割成锯齿状；缩排；定货', '1. On the adjoining page we hand you an indent for various line, which please ship at once. 我们已将委托购买的各种商品在附页列明，请立即发运。 2. A firm order is often called an indent. 确定的订单常称作订货单。 3. The fallen tree limb left a big indent on his car. 掉下来的树枝在他的车上留下了一个大凹口。 4. The mountains indent the horizon. 山峦使地平线成锯齿状。', '过去式: indented 过去分词: indented 现在分词: indenting 第三人称单数: indents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thatch', '[θætʃ]', 'n.茅草；茅草屋顶 v.用茅草等盖(屋顶)', '1. The family lived in a thatched cottage before liberation. 解放前，他们一家住在茅屋里。 2. Apart from a new mosque, its buildings are made of mud, stone and thatch. 除了一座新的清真寺，这里的建筑都是泥、石和茅草所成。 3. They topped off the hut with a straw thatch. 他们给小屋盖上茅草屋顶。 4. They are sheltering under the thatch. 他们在茅草屋顶下避雨。 5. The village hut was thatched with palm leaves. 乡村小屋用棕榈叶作顶。', '形容词: thatchy 名词: thatcher 过去式: thatched 过去分词: thatched 现在分词: thatching 第三人称单数: thatches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reptilian', '[rep\'tɪliən]', 'adj.爬虫类的；卑鄙的 n.爬行类动物', '1. The reptilian brain is much like a baby\'s brain. 爬行动物的脑袋很像婴儿的大脑。 2. He turned a cold and reptilian gaze on me. 他给了我一个冷酷的，卑劣的凝视。 3. Their skulls, pelvises, and hind feet are reptilian. 它们的头骨、骨盆和后腿都类似爬行动物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('poster', '[\'poʊstər]', 'n.海报；装饰画；急行旅人', '1. The lettering on the poster is very eye-catching. 海报上的字体非常醒目。 2. The poster only stayed up a few hours before it was stolen. 那张海报贴上去没几个小时就让人给偷走了。 3. He put up a poster advertising the circus. 他贴了一张宣传马戏团的海报。 4. The poster wouldn\'t stick even though I drenched it with glue. 我涂了大量胶水，可那张海报就是贴不住。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ventilate', '[\'ventɪleɪt]', 'vt. 使 ... 空气流通； 通风', '1. We ventilate a room by opening windows. 我们开窗以使室内空气流通。 2. They should ventilate the galleries of a coal-mine. 他们应该使煤矿坑道通风。 3. Ventilate the spillage area thoroughly. 完全使漏地区通风。', '名词: ventilation 过去式: ventilated 过去分词: ventilated 现在分词: ventilating 第三人称单数: ventilates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gravity', '[\'ɡrævəti]', 'n.重力；庄重；严重；严肃', '1. He discoursed impressively on Newton\'s theory of gravity. 他讲述了牛顿的引力定律，给人以深刻的印象。 2. The stone rolled down the hill by gravity. 石头在重力作用下向山下滚去。 3. The force of gravity pulls things towards the earth\'s centre. 地心吸力把物体吸向地心。 4. The lunar gravity is about one-sixth that on earth. 月亮的引力大约为地球的六分之一。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barren', '[\'bærən]', 'adj.贫瘠的；无效的；不育的 n.荒地', '1. No one could raise crops on this barren land. 没人能够在这么贫瘠的土地上种庄稼。 2. Life is a barren field frozen with snow. 生命就像是被雪覆盖的荒芜土地。 3. We shall turn this piece of barren land into wheat fields. 我们要把这块不毛之地变为麦田。 4. He was engaged in a barren argument with Paul. 他在同保罗作无用的争论。', '副词: barrenly 名词: barrenness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pier', '[pɪr]', 'n.码头；桥墩；桥柱；[建]窗间壁；支柱', '1. The ship lies at the pier. 船在码头停着。 2. Takings at the pier have dropped off this season. 这个季节，码头上的收入下降了。 3. She parted with her friend on the pier yesterday. 她昨天在码头和朋友分别。 4. The truck stove in the pier of the road bridge. 卡车撞坏了公路桥的桥墩。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indigenous', '[ɪn\'dɪdʒənəs]', 'adj.土生土长的；本地的；天生的', '1. Indians were the indigenous inhabitants of America. 印第安人是美洲的土著居民。 2. Shinto is the natural indigenous religion of Japan. 日本之神道教是日本本土的自然教。 3. The indigenous population was soon displaced by the settlers. 没过多久，外来移民就把当地人赶出了家园。 4. Love and hate are emotions indigenous to all humanity. 爱兴恨是人类固有的感情。', '副词: indigenously 名词: indigenousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mutter', '[\'mʌtər]', 'v.咕哝；抱怨；低语 n.嘟哝；抱怨；低语', '1. Mutter Sarah was muttering away to herself as she did the washing-up. 萨拉一边洗碗碟一边独自咕哝个没完。 2. Some members of the government are beginning to mutter about the prime minister. 一些政府官员开始咕咕哝哝地抱怨首相。 3. Some members of the government are beginning to mutter about the prime minister. 一些政府官员开始咕咕哝哝地抱怨首相。 4. Don\'t mutter when they are studying. 当他们学习时不要轻声低语。 5. Some members of the government are beginning to mutter about the prime minister. 一些政府官员开始咕咕哝哝地抱怨首相。', '名词: mutterer 过去式: muttered 过去分词: muttered 现在分词: muttering 第三人称单数: mutters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lexical', '[\'leksɪkl]', 'adj.词汇的；词典的', '1. What are your ways to lexical learning? 您的英语词汇学习方法？ 2. Word recognition plays an important role in English lexical learning. 单词识别在英语词汇学习中起着举足轻重的作用。 3. It provides a brief definition of each lexical concept in the model. 它提供模型中每个词汇概念的简短定义。', '副词: lexically 名词: lexicality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sycophant', '[\'sɪkəfænt]', 'n.马屁精', '1. An obsequious follower or dependent; a sycophant. 奴才，马屁精一个奴颜卑膝的献媚者；溜须拍马者 2. Carol: Dad, you\'re being a sycophant. 卡罗尔：你这是在献媚。 3. An obsequious follower or dependent;a sycophant. 奴才，马屁精一个奴颜卑膝的献媚者；溜须拍马者 4. One who lives off and flatters the rich; a sycophant. 奉承逗乐的食客以奉承富人为生的人；趋炎附势者', '形容词: sycophantic 副词: sycophantically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cutlery', '[\'kʌtləri]', 'n.【U】刀具；刀具业', '1. The top drawer is the one with the cutlery in. 最上面的抽屉是放刀叉的。 2. Knife and fork is a main cutlery for European people. 刀叉是欧洲人主要餐具。 3. It\'s bad manners to fidget about with the cutlery at the table. 用餐时摆弄刀叉玩儿是不雅的。 4. Shef-field is famous for its cutlery. 谢菲尔德以餐具闻名。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('twig', '[twɪɡ]', 'n.小枝；嫩枝 v.理解；领悟', '1. Elaine plucked a twig from the offending japonica and set about its systematic defoliation with savage concentration. 埃莱恩从难看的山茶上折了个嫩枝，开始猛烈的收集系统的落叶。', '过去式: twigged 过去分词: twigged 现在分词: twigging 第三人称单数: twigs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('singe', '[sɪndʒ]', 'v.(轻微)烧焦；烫焦；损伤 n.烧焦', '1. The rug singed because it was too near the fire. 地毯太靠近壁炉已烤焦了。 2. The iron\'s too hot, you\'ll singe the dress. 熨斗太热了，你会把衣服烫焦的。 3. The last time we agree to help that company out of its difficulty, we singe our wing quite badly. 上次我们答应帮助那家公司摆脱困境时我们自己遭受了很大的损失。', '过去式: singed 过去分词: singed 现在分词: singeing 第三人称单数: singes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('specious', '[\'spiːʃəs]', 'adj.似是而非的；华而不实的', '1. Such talk is actually specious and groundless. 这些话实际上毫无根据, 似是而非的。 2. This specious statement sidesteps the real issue. 这是避重就轻、似是而非的一种说法。 3. There are some specious concepts in analysis on status of building energy efficiency. 在对建筑节能现状的分析中有一些模糊概念。', '副词: speciously 名词: speciosity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exceed', '[ɪk\'siːd]', 'vt.超过；超出 vi.领先', '1. His knowledge of history exceeds mine. 他的历史知识超过我。 2. Demand began to exceed supply. 开始供不应求。 3. The fine shall not exceed $300. 罚款不超过三百美元。', '过去式: exceeded 过去分词: exceeded 现在分词: exceeding 第三人称单数: exceeds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ration', '[\'ræʃn]', 'n.定额；定量；配给 vt.限量供应；配给', '1. Ration is widely used in manufacturing industry. 定额是制造业中广泛使用的一个概念。 2. Have you used your ration of petrol for this week? 你用了这星期给你定量的汽油了吗? 3. The country cut the bread ration last year. 那个国家去年削减面包配给量。 4. They had to ration petrol during the war. 战时他们不得不限量供给汽油。', '过去式: rationed 过去分词: rationed 现在分词: rationing 第三人称单数: rations');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ebullience', '[ɪ\'bʊliəns]', 'n.沸腾；热情；热情洋溢', '1. She burst into the room with her usual ebullience, and immediately started talking to everyone. 她像往常一样兴高采烈地冲进了房间，立刻跟大家攀谈起来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('serrated', '[sə\'reɪtɪd]', 'adj.锯齿状的；有锯齿的 动词serrate的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. The cells have an irregular shape with a slightly serrated border. 细胞的形状不规则，边缘呈锯齿状。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barbecue', '[\'bɑːrbɪkjuː]', 'n.烤肉；烧烤；烤架 v.烤炙', '1. The sunshine bodes well for our barbecue. 明媚的阳光对我们的烤肉野餐是个吉兆。 2. The rain loused up the barbecue. 下雨弄砸了烤肉野餐。 3. If you\'re not busy Sunday, we\'d love to have you both over for a barbecue. 如果你周日有空，我们想请你们俩来吃烧烤。 4. We can\'t calculate on having good weather for the barbecue. 我们不能指望着有好天气才去烧烤。 5. Now and then we like to barbecue chicken in the back yard. 我们偶而会在后院子里烤鸡吃。', '过去式: barbecued 过去分词: barbecued 现在分词: barbecuing 第三人称单数: barbecues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('feeble', '[\'fiːbl]', 'adj.虚弱的；无力的', '1. The bishop said it with a feeble voice as he woke. 主教醒过来，用虚弱的声音说出。 2. Feeble and uncertain securities were thrown upon the market. 虚弱的或者没有把握的证券都向市场抛售了。 3. Tighter credit conditions are sapping already feeble demand. 紧缩的信贷让本就无力的需求更加乏力。 4. He bleated out a feeble excuse. 他以微弱的声音作无力的辩解。', '副词: feebly 比较级: feebler 最高级: feeblest 名词: feebleness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sloppy', '[\'slɑːpi]', 'adj.肥大的；潦草的；草率的；稀薄的；庸俗感伤的', '1. At home I tend to wear big sloppy jumpers and jeans. 在家里我喜欢穿宽大的套衫和牛仔裤。 2. I can\'t decipher his sloppy handwriting. 我无法辨认他那潦草的字迹。 3. She lectured him on his sloppy demeanor. 她谴责他那种草率的态度。 4. I hate sloppy romantic films. 我讨厌那些庸俗伤感的爱情片。', '副词: sloppily 比较级: sloppier 最高级: sloppiest 名词: sloppiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gruff', '[ɡrʌf]', 'adj.粗鲁的；生硬的；粗糙的；粗哑的', '1. His gruff manner made me angry. 他粗暴的态度让我生气。 2. Her answer was gruff, but her eyes twinkled. 她的回答很粗鲁，但她眨了眨眼睛。 3. His gruff hoarse voice struck my ears. 他那粗重嘶哑的嗓音传入了我的耳中。 4. He could only roar in a gruff voice. 他仅能以沙哑的声音吼叫着。', '副词: gruffly 比较级: gruffer 最高级: gruffest 名词: gruffness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glossary', '[\'ɡlɑːsəri]', 'n.词汇表；术语汇编', '1. There is a glossary at the end of the textbook. 这本教科书后面有词汇表。 2. The text is supplemented by an adequate glossary. 正文附有一个详细的词汇表。 3. He put a tick beside each word in the glossary that he had learned by heart. 他在词表中每一个已熟记的生词旁做了个记号。 4. There is a definition of infants in the glossary. 在术语表中有对婴幼儿的定义。', '形容词: glossarial 名词: glossarist 名词复数: glossaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('huddle', '[\'hʌdl]', 'n.杂乱一团；混乱；拥挤 v.推挤；乱堆；草率了事', '1. He shouted into the cavernous arena as if he were shouting into a huddle. 他对着球场吼叫，似乎他面对的是混乱的人群。 2. James insisted the Cavs needed to go bigger and broke from the huddle shaking his head in disagreement. 詹姆斯不住地摇头表示反对，他坚持认为骑士应该换上大个球员，打破场上的混乱局面。 3. The track led them to a huddle of barns and outbuildings. 那条路把他们带到了一片杂乱拥挤的谷仓和库房。 4. At the BeiBei plant, women huddle over a conveyor belt in frigid temperatures, gluing rubber sneakers together. 在贝贝公司，妇女拥挤在寒冷的传送带周围粘橡胶旅游鞋。', '名词: huddler 过去式: huddled 过去分词: huddled 现在分词: huddling 第三人称单数: huddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amplify', '[\'æmplɪfaɪ]', 'v.扩大；详述；增强', '1. We must amplify our effort by working a lot harder. 我们必须更努力地工作来扩大成果。 2. The new manager wants to amplify the company. 新经理想要扩大公司。 3. A manufacturer can amplify the demand of a product by advertising widely. 厂商能用大做广告的方法来扩大人们对产品的需求。 4. Please amplify your remarks by giving us some examples. 请举例详述你的话。', '过去式: amplified 过去分词: amplified 现在分词: amplifying 第三人称单数: amplifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apprehensive', '[ˌæprɪ\'hensɪv]', 'adj.忧虑的；善于领会的；知晓的', '1. He is always apprehensive for his son\'s safety. 他经常担心儿子的安全。 2. I am apprehensive about the results of the exams. 我为考试成绩担忧。 3. She is an apprehensive girl. 她是个善解人意的女孩。 4. Judgement is implied in every apprehensive act. 每一种理解的行为都说明是运用了判断。', '副词: apprehensively 名词: apprehensiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sparing', '[\'sperɪŋ]', 'adj.节约的；不足的；慎用', '1. He is very sparing with his money. 他用钱很省。 2. You should be more sparing of your money. 你应该更节省用钱。 3. The professor was sparing in his praise. 那位教授不轻易表扬人。 4. This guide to the museum is sparing of information. 这本博物馆指南内容不丰富。', '副词: sparingly 名词: sparingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resigned', '[rɪ\'zaɪnd]', 'adj.认命的；顺从的；听任的 动词resign的过去式和过去分词.', '1. I\'m resigned to my fate. 我听天由命。 2. Her look was skeptical and resigned. 她的表情是将信将疑而又无可奈何。', '副词: resignedly 名词: resignedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('latitude', '[\'lætɪtuːd]', 'n.纬度；自由', '1. The latitude of the island is 30 degrees north. 这个岛的纬度是北纬三十度。 2. Latitude reaches a maximum of 90°at the poles. 两极纬度的最大值为90°。 3. You have a wide latitude to act as you think best. 你拥有自己认为最好的、广泛的行动上的自由。 4. We allow considerable latitude at these hearings. 我们在这种听证会上允许相当大的自由。', '形容词: latitudinal 副词: latitudinally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('metropolis', '[mə\'trɑːpəlɪs]', 'n.大都市；重要中心；首府', '1. New York is the metropolis of North America. 纽约是北美的大都市。 2. This was a great, pleasing metropolis after all. 这毕竟是个令人振奋的大都市。 3. The former appealed to Corcyra, which was the metropolis of Epidamnus. 民主者向伊庇丹努的首府科西拉求助。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('penetrate', '[\'penətreɪt]', 'v.渗透；看穿；穿透；了解；（情报人员的）渗透', '1. The mist penetrated into the room. 雾气渗进了室内。 2. The University Chinese training should penetrate the humanity consciousness 大学语文教育应渗透人文精神 3. Honda\'s success in penetrating Western motorcycle markets. 本田公司的成功渗透西方摩托车的市场。 4. Not many people managed to penetrate my disguise. 没有几个人识破我的伪装。', '名词: penetrator 过去式: penetrated 过去分词: penetrated 现在分词: penetrating 第三人称单数: penetrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('virtual', '[\'vɜːrtʃuəl]', 'adj.实质的；【计】虚拟的', '1. Our deputy manager is the virtual head of the business. 我们的副经理是公司的实际负责人。 2. A virtual state of war exists between the two countries. 这两国间实际上处于战争状态。 3. For　example, in a Virtual space, Students can \"dissect\" a human body, \"visit\" ancient battlefields, or \"talk\" with Shakespeare, ... 比如,在虚拟的空间中,学生们可以与莎士比亚“对话”。', '名词: virtuality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heady', '[\'hedi]', 'adj.强烈作用于感官的；兴奋的；陶醉的；头晕的；冲动的', '1. The heady years were, of course, followed by some grimmer ones. 在令人兴奋的岁月之后，自然是比较黯淡的时期。 2. The air was heady with the perfume from roses. 空气中玫瑰花的香味令人陶醉。 3. She felt heady with success. 成功使她得意忘形。', '副词: headily 比较级: headier 最高级: headiest 名词: headiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mannered', '[\'mænərd]', 'adj.装模作样的；矫揉造作的；墨守成规的，中规中矩的', '1. I think taught responsibilities are too formal, too mannered. 我认为教人责任太过于形式,太装模作样。 2. Her prose is far too mannered and self-conscious. 她的散文过于矫揉造作。 3. His performance as Hamlet was criticized for being very mannered. 他扮演的哈姆雷特被指太墨守成规了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oblige', '[ə\'blaɪdʒ]', 'vt.迫使；责成；使感激；施恩于；帮 ... 的忙；使…成为必要 vi.帮忙', '1. The law oblige parents to send their children to school. 法律上要求父母送子女入学。 2. The Convention contains innovative measures that oblige countries to return stolen assets to their rightful owners. 公约载有一些责成各国将被盗资产返还其合法所有人的创新措施。 3. I\'m much obliged to you. 我非常感谢你。 4. I am obliged to you for your gracious hospitality. 我很感谢你的热情好客。 5. I\'ll do any thing within reason to oblige. 凡能做到的我都愿效劳。', '名词: obliger 过去式: obliged 过去分词: obliged 现在分词: obliging 第三人称单数: obliges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sensitivity', '[ˌsensə\'tɪvəti]', 'n.敏感；多愁善感；感受性；灵敏度', '1. Strength and sensitivity do not often go together. 力量和敏感并非常常能兼而有之。 2. His remarks convicted him of a lack of sensitivity. 他的言辞显示了他缺乏敏感性。 3. How can ability change my sensitivity? 怎样才可以改变我的多愁善感？ 4. Can the person of sensitivity get depressed disease? 多愁善感的人会不会得抑郁症？', '名词复数: sensitivities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ribald', '[\'rɪbld]', 'adj.说话猥亵的；下流的 n.说话猥亵的人', '1. The answer was lost in a shout of ribald laughter. 回答被一阵下流的狂笑声掩盖了。 2. He loves entertaining his friends with ribald stories. 他喜欢用下流故事来逗他的朋友们开心。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rotate', '[\'roʊteɪt]', 'v.轮流；(使)旋转 adj.车轮状的', '1. The post of chairman rotates among members of the committee. 主席一职由委员会的成员轮流担任。 2. Interns have to rotate for a few months. 实习医生轮流工作了几个月。 3. He rotates the handle gently. 他轻轻地转动手柄。 4. Does the earth rotate on an axis? 地球是绕轴旋转的吗？', '形容词: rotatable 过去式: rotated 过去分词: rotated 现在分词: rotating 第三人称单数: rotates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enunciate', '[ɪ\'nʌnsieɪt]', 'v.清晰地发音；(清楚地)表达；阐述，宣布', '1. She enunciated each word slowly for her students. 她把每个字都给学生慢慢念清楚。 2. That actor enunciates very well. 那演员发音很清晰。 3. He is always willing to enunciate his opinions on the subject of politics. 他总是愿意对政治问题发表意见。', '形容词: enunciable 副词: enunciatively 名词: enunciation 过去式: enunciated 过去分词: enunciated 现在分词: enunciating 第三人称单数: enunciates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perspicuous', '[pə\'spɪkjʊəs]', 'adj.明晰的；易懂的', '1. A.L.R. These are the symbols (or Verses) of the perspicuous Book. 艾列弗，俩目，拉仪。这些是明确的天经的节文。 2. The most perspicuous physical characteristic of the porosity of a soil or rock matrix is its continuity. 岩土格架的孔隙率的最清晰的物理特性是它的连续性。 3. The analysis of concepts is a matter of finding more perspicuous and complexity-revealing words. 对概念进行分析是一项有关寻找更加明白易懂和能揭示复杂性的词汇的问题。 4. Such solutions were more manageable, more perspicuous, and more readily used for calculation. 这样的解，在计算中是更易于掌握的，更明白的，并且是更易于使用的。', '副词: perspicuously 名词: perspicuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('esoteric', '[ˌesə\'terɪk]', 'adj.秘传的；神秘的；难懂的', '1. I asked, but he said he couldn\'t tell me the recipe because it was esoteric. 我问了，但是他说他不能告诉我那药方，因为那是秘传的。 2. Certain kinds of armor are made according to arcane and esoteric methods that involve weaving magic into the substance of the armor. 有一些护甲在制造的过程中用秘传的方法和神秘的技艺将魔法编织在护甲之上。 3. Like many esoteric pursuits, this has been facilitated by the internet. 像好多神秘的追求嗜好一样，互联网也已经为此提供了便利。 4. There are no esoteric formulas or secret states of mind that produce good designs effortlessly. 没有任何奥妙的公式或神秘的心境可毫不费力地提出好的设计方案。', '副词: esoterically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detached', '[dɪ\'tætʃt]', 'adj.超然的；分离的；独立的', '1. Our persuasion did not alter his detached opinion. 我们的劝说没有改变他超然的意见。 2. He took a detached attitude to the matter. 他对那件事持超然的态度。 3. Is the name of the database to be detached. 要分离的数据库的名称。 4. It is also possible that the nidus of the osteochondral loose body was a completely detached portion of calcified ligamentum flavum. 骨软骨游离体的病灶很可能是一段完全分离的黄韧带。', '副词: detachedly 名词: detachedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debrief', '[ˌdiː\'briːf]', 'v.向……询问情况；汇报情况', '1. When they debrief you, that’s the story you’ll tell. 当他们向你询问情况时,那就是你要讲述的故事。 2. Clinton is due to debrief the National Security Council and Obama on his trip. 按照预期，克林顿应向国家安全委员会和奥巴马汇报这次任务的情况。', '过去式: debriefed 过去分词: debriefed 现在分词: debriefing 第三人称单数: debriefs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preternatural', '[ˌpriːtər\'nætʃrəl]', 'adj.异常的；超自然的；不可思议的', '1. Below his preternatural affability there is some acid and steel. 在他异常和蔼可亲的表情之下，有着尖刻和钢铁般的坚毅。 2. The land around them was perfectly still, glowing with a kind of preternatural light that allowed him to see and sense everything around him. 四周的大地是如此完美的寂静，被一种超自然的光芒照耀着，这光芒让他能看见和感觉到周围的一切。 3. There is a kind of scenery that is the most preternatural and magnificent. 实在亦有一种奇绝壮绝的景致。 4. The suddenness of storms in that climate is something almost preternatural 在那地带，突起的风暴几乎是件不可思议的事。', '副词: preternaturally 名词: preternaturalism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sate', '[seɪt]', 'vt.使心满意足；过份地给与', '1. Nothing could sate the careerist\'s greed for power. 什么也满足不了这个野心家的权力欲。 2. She sated with sleep. 她睡腻了。', '过去式: sated 过去分词: sated 现在分词: sating 第三人称单数: sates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unpalatable', '[ʌn\'pælətəbl]', 'adj.不可口的；不好吃的；让人不快的', '1. The fish was particularly unpalatable. 这鱼特别难吃。 2. His views on capital punishment are unpalatable to many. 他对死刑存废的见解许多人都不以为然。', '副词: unpalatably 名词: unpalatability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impulsive', '[ɪm\'pʌlsɪv]', 'adj.冲动的；任性的 n.(引起冲动的)原因', '1. Her impulsive passion was a positive defect. 她的冲动的激情则完完全全是个缺点。 2. A jagged equity curve tends to be a sign of impulsive trading. 锯齿状曲线多半代表冲动的交易。', '副词: impulsively 名词: impulsiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discourse', '[\'dɪskɔːrs]', 'n.谈话，讨论；（一系列的）演讲，文章 vi.讲述；谈话 vt.叙述；讨论', '1. The judges had solemn discourse together. 法官们在一起严肃地交谈。 2. They listened to his discourse on human relations. 他们听他作关于人际关系的演讲。 3. He discoursed impressively on Newton\'s theory of gravity. 他讲述了牛顿的引力定律，给人以深刻的印象。 4. The teacher is discoursing with him. 老师正在和他谈话。 5. The old man discoursed his experiences when he was a child. 这位老人叙述了他孩子时的经历。', '名词: discourser 过去式: discoursed 过去分词: discoursed 现在分词: discoursing 第三人称单数: discourses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lathe', '[leɪð]', 'n.车床 vt.用车床加工', '1. This is a heavy duty turret lathe. 这是一台重型转台车床。 2. Get lathe No.9 set to turn the new piston. 把九号车床调好来车这个新活塞。', '过去式: lathed 过去分词: lathed 现在分词: lathing 第三人称单数: lathes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subside', '[səb\'saɪd]', 'vi.沉没；平息；下陷', '1. The hematoma will usually subside in time. 血肿通常随时间消逝。 2. The storm began to subside. 风暴渐渐平息了。 3. He waited until the applause had subsided. 他一直等到掌声平息后才继续下去。 4. Weak foundations caused the house to subside. 由于地基不牢，这所房子已下陷。', '名词: subsidence 过去式: subsided 过去分词: subsided 现在分词: subsiding 第三人称单数: subsides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dim', '[dɪm]', 'adj.暗淡的；模糊的；笨的 v.使暗淡；使失去光泽 n.车头近光灯；停车灯', '1. Most comets are so dim that they can not be seen by the naked eye. 彗星很暗淡,肉眼看不见。 2. He spoke with firmness, but his face was very sad and his eyes at times were dim. 他讲话时预期坚定，但面带愁容，时而眼神暗淡。 3. I made out two dim shapes in the gloom. 我在朦胧中看出有两个模糊的影子。 4. She is rather dim about the importance of keeping records. 她不明白作记录的重要性。 5. Old age hasn\'t dimmed her memory. 她虽然年事已高，但记忆并未模糊。', '副词: dimly 比较级: dimmer 最高级: dimmest 名词: dimness 过去式: dimmed 过去分词: dimmed 现在分词: dimming 第三人称单数: dims');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rage', '[reɪdʒ]', 'n.狂怒；大怒；狂暴；肆虐；风行 v.大怒；怒斥；激烈进行；肆虐', '1. He was mad with rage. 他快要气疯了。 2. I was gnashing my teeth with rage. 我咬牙切齿愤怒已极。 3. He flew into a rage at the news. 他听到这个消息勃然大怒。 4. The storm showed elemental rage in its violence. 这场风暴显示了大自然的狂暴力量。 5. You are not yourself when you rage like that. 你那样大发雷霆有点失常。', '过去式: raged 过去分词: raged 现在分词: raging 第三人称单数: rages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disheveled', '[dɪ\'ʃevəld]', 'adj.凌乱的；不整洁的 =dishevelled.', '1. A disheveled pile of books on the library table. 图书馆的桌子上摆着一堆凌乱不整的书 2. A disheveled mass, as of hair. 被弄乱的一大团，如头发 3. His disheveled hair was dirty. 他散乱的头发很脏。 4. Her disheveled coat was waving in the wind. 她蓬散的衣服在风中飘荡。', '异体字: dishevelled');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tadpole', '[\'tædpoʊl]', 'n.蝌蚪', '1. A tadpole has a tail. 蝌蚪有尾巴。 2. The tadpole hatches from the egg. 蝌蚪从卵中孵化出来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infatuated', '[ɪn\'fætʃueɪtɪd]', 'adj.昏头昏脑的；入迷的', '1. The infatuated fan stalked the celebrity. 那位着了迷的崇拜者追踪这位名人。 2. It\'s no use talking to him: he\'s completely infatuated. 跟他谈也没用，他已完全堕入情网。', '副词: infatuatedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fallacy', '[\'fæləsi]', 'n.谬论；谬误的推理', '1. He had no difficulty in disposing of the fallacy. 他毫无困难地驳倒了这个谬论。 2. The fallacy has been exposed in its naked absurdity. 这谬论的荒诞性已被充分揭露。 3. This is a statement based on fallacy. 这是一项基于谬误推理之声明。 4. Division of mankind into workingman and capitalists suffers from the fallacy of simplism. 硬把人类分成工人阶级和资本阶级就犯了过分简单化的错误。', '名词复数: fallacies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('misrepresent', '[ˌmɪsˌreprɪ\'zent]', 'v.误称；歪曲；不合适地代表', '1. If you misrepresent what\'s in the plan, we will call you out. 如果有人再恶意解读健保改革计划，我们会直接批评你。 2. Something intended to misrepresent the true nature of an activity. 意欲歪曲一个行动真实性质的东西。 3. Astrologers do not misrepresent their sources of information, and make every effort to verify their accuracy. 占星家不歪曲他们的信息来源，并尽一切努力，以核实其准确性。', '形容词: misrepresentative 名词: misrepresentation 过去式: misrepresented 过去分词: misrepresented 现在分词: misrepresenting 第三人称单数: misrepresents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malice', '[\'mælɪs]', 'n.恶意；怨恨；蓄意 [律]预谋.', '1. I know you bear no malice towards me. 我知道你对我毫无恶意。 2. There was a spice of malice in his words. 他的话中带有几分恶意。 3. It seems so absurd to bear malice after all that. 经过这一切之后还抱有怨恨情绪是很荒谬的。 4. His expression changed from kindness to malice. 他的表情从和蔼可亲变成满腔怨恨。 5. She did not trip Rose up accidentally, it was done with malice aforethought. 她并不是无意中把罗斯绊倒的，她这样做是有预谋的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monarchy', '[\'mɑːnərki]', 'n.君主政体；君主国；君主政治', '1. Let\'s not make a sacred cow of the monarchy. 咱们别把君主政体奉若神明。 2. For the great experiment of the Sumerians was civilization, a culture transformed by the practical effects of urbanization, writing, and monarchy. 苏美人最大的证实便是他们的文明，文化被转化为了对都市化，书写文字，喝君主政体的现实的影响。 3. Morocco is a sovereign independent monarchy. 摩洛哥是个有主权而独立的君主国。 4. The monstrous monarch monopolized monarchy. 可怕的君主垄断了君主国。', '形容词: monarchial 名词复数: monarchies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hunker', '[\'hʌŋkər]', 'vi.蹲；蹲坐', '1. He felt his backache and didn\'t hunker down. 他感到背很痛，而且蹲不下身。 2. I have to hunker down to finish my algebra this evening. 我今晚要专专心心地把代数作业做完。 3. I perform best when I can hunker down and do some undisturbed work. 我发现当自己盘腿而坐，并在没有干扰的环境下任务完成的特别好。 4. Work hard, hunker down, tighten your belt, and make a better life. 努力工作、盘腿坐下、勒紧腰带、和改善生活。', '过去式: hunkered 过去分词: hunkered 现在分词: hunkering 第三人称单数: hunkers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('masquerade', '[ˌmæskə\'reɪd]', 'n.化妆舞会；伪装 v.伪装', '1. We want to join in the masquerade. 我们想去参加化装舞会。 2. They were all dressed up to attend the masquerade. 他们都盛装去参加那个化装舞会。 3. Her sorrow is just a masquerade. 她难过的样子纯粹是假装的。 4. He might try to masquerade as a policeman. 他也许会设法化装成警察。', '名词: masquerader 过去式: masqueraded 过去分词: masqueraded 现在分词: masquerading 第三人称单数: masquerades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alleviate', '[ə\'liːvieɪt]', 'vt.减轻；使 ... 缓和', '1. They alleviated the boredom of waiting by singing songs. 他们以唱歌来减轻等候的厌烦。 2. The doctor gave her an injection to alleviate the pain. 医生给她注射以减轻疼痛。 3. This medicine will alleviate your sore throat. 这种药会减轻你的嗓子痛。 4. He could only alleviate the sorrow by drinking. 他只能借酒浇愁。', '名词: alleviation 过去式: alleviated 过去分词: alleviated 现在分词: alleviating 第三人称单数: alleviates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rebate', '[\'riːbeɪt]', 'n.回扣 vt.减少；变钝 vi.减少', '1. He get a tax rebate at the end of the year. 他在年底得到了一笔退回的税款。 2. Buyers are offered a cash rebate. 购买者享受现金回扣。 3. Could you grant me a premium rebate? 你能给我保险费折扣吗? 4. How can you rebate your tax on your summer job? 你怎样才能减纳你夏季劳动所得税呢? 5. It goes against our principle to give rebate to our clients. 给客户回扣有悖于我方原则。', '名词: rebater 过去式: rebated 过去分词: rebated 现在分词: rebating 第三人称单数: rebates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skinflint', '[\'skɪnflɪnt]', 'n.吝啬鬼', '1. He is a real skinflint. 他真的是一个吝啬鬼。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antediluvian', '[ˌæntidɪ\'luːviən]', 'adj.大洪水前的；上古的；古风的；古老的 n.大洪水以前的人；很老的人；老古董', '1. His ideas are positively antediluvian! 他的思想是纯粹的老古董！ 2. For love? What antediluvian notions you have! Can one talk of love in these days? 爱？多么古老的字眼！现在还有人谈论爱情吗？ 3. She was more than old-fashioned, she was an antediluvian. 她不只是守旧', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gastronomy', '[ɡæ\'strɑːnəmi]', 'n.美食法；美食学', '1. Pre-hispanc Food in Mexican Gastronomy. 西班牙殖民前的墨西哥食谱中的食品。 2. Gastronomy: Enjoy with light seafood and fish. 配食: 适宜与清淡海鲜及鱼肉一起食用。 3. Followed by nature attractions, panoramic viewpoints and gastronomy. 根据自然吸引、全景的观点和美食法跟随。 4. In Chinese gastronomy three senses must be satisfied: smell, sight and taste. 中国的烹饪技术要满足三种感觉：香，形，味。', '名词复数: gastronomies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('covenant', '[\'kʌvənənt]', 'n.盟约；契约 v.立书保证', '1. China has acceded to the international human rights covenant. 中国已经加入了国际人权公约 2. The covenant of the League of Nations bound all signatory states not to go to war. 国际联盟盟约规定，所有签字国都不得诉诸战争。 3. The money was given to us by deed of covenant. 这笔钱是根据契约书付给我们的。 4. I made a covenant with my eyes not to look lustfully at a girl. 我与眼睛立约,怎能恋恋瞻望处女呢? 5. They covenanted with us for establishing a joint venture. 他们就建立合资公司的事和我们签了合约。', '形容词: covenantal 副词: covenantally 过去式: covenanted 过去分词: covenanted 现在分词: covenanting 第三人称单数: covenants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blanch', '[blæntʃ]', 'v.漂白；（使）变白；烫洗', '1. He blanched with shock. 他吓得脸都白了。 2. He blanched (with fear) at the sight of the snake. 他看见蛇(吓得)脸色煞白。 3. You blanch almonds to remove their skins. 你把杏仁焯一下，烫去表皮。', '异体字: blench 名词: blancher 过去式: blanched/blenched 过去分词: blanched/blenched 现在分词: blanching/blenching 第三人称单数: blanches/blenches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('untutored', '[ˌʌn\'tuːtərd]', 'adj.未受教导的；未经训练的', '1. He had only untutored strength like a bull in a china shop. 他只有一身的蛮力，干事笨手笨脚的。 2. As the untutored crowds learn to read, they are likely to reach for a newspaper. 当众多文盲学习识字时，他们很可能成为未来的报纸读者。 3. To my untutored ear, your voice sounds almost professional. 照我这外行人听来，你的嗓音差不多够专业水平了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sidestep', '[\'saɪdstep]', 'v.向旁侧避让；回避', '1. He cleverly sidestepped the tackle. 他巧妙地一晃，绕过阻截队员。 2. Try your best to sidestep for sensitive issues like this. 你应尽可能地回避像这类敏感的问题。 3. This attempt to sidestep the question of what intelligence is was very ingenious. 这种回避了什么是智能的问题的尝试是非常巧妙的。', '名词: sidestepper 过去式: sidestepped 过去分词: sidestepped 现在分词: sidestepping 第三人称单数: sidesteps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('momentous', '[moʊ\'mentəs]', 'adj.重要的；重大的', '1. I have some momentous news to tell you. 我有重要的消息要告诉你。 2. I am deeply honoured to be invited to this momentous occasion. 能应邀出席如此重要的场合，我深感荣幸。 3. This is a momentous, hard-won achievement. 这是一个非常重大和来之不易的成就。 4. History bears evidence that each momentous political change is usually followed by an economic revival. 历史证明，在每次重大的政治变革之后随之而来的往往是经济上的复兴。', '副词: momentously 名词: momentousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('craven', '[\'kreɪvn]', 'adj.懦弱的；畏缩的 n.懦夫', '1. No man wants to be thought a craven person. 没有人愿意被认为是懦弱的人。 2. He is a craven deserter. 他是个胆小的逃兵。 3. A hero risks his life to help others; a craven runs from the scene. 英雄冒着生命危险去帮助别人；而懦夫却临阵脱逃。', '副词: cravenly 名词: cravenness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prescription', '[prɪ\'skrɪpʃn]', 'n.处方；药方；对策', '1. The doctor is writing a prescription. 医生正在开处方。 2. The doctor dispensed a prescription to his patient. 医生开处方给病人配药。 3. The prescription of drugs is a doctor\'s responsibility. 开药方是医生的职责。 4. His prescription for economic recovery was not well received. 他为经济复苏提出的对策反应不佳。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mode', '[moʊd]', 'n.方式；模式；样式；风格', '1. The country girl was not used to their lavish mode of living. 这个乡下姑娘不习惯他们奢侈的生活方式。 2. The spacecraft was in its recovery mode. 这艘飞船处于返回状态。 3. Her new dress is the latest mode in this season. 她的新连衣裙是这一季最新的款式。 4. He has no intention of changing his mode of attire. 他没有意愿去改变自己穿着的风格。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perpetuate', '[pər\'petʃueɪt]', 'vt.使永存；使不朽', '1. These measures will perpetuate the hostility between the two groups. 采取这些措施势必使那两集团永远对立。 2. They decided to perpetuate the memory of their leader by erecting a statue. 他们为永远纪念那位领袖决定建一座雕像。', '名词: perpetuance 过去式: perpetuated 过去分词: perpetuated 现在分词: perpetuating 第三人称单数: perpetuates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incongruity', '[ˌɪnkɒn\'ɡruːəti]', 'n.不调和；不一致；不配合', '1. She was struck by the incongruity of the situation. 这一局面煞是怪异，让她惊愕不已。 2. It was a night when sorrow may come to the brightest without causing any great sense of incongruity. 这是一个可由哀愁变为狂喜而又不引起任何严重不协调感的夜晚。 3. The incongruity of the word \"spirit\" in his mouth struck him so sharply. 从他嘴里说出不相称的“血气”这两个字,真是强烈地感动了他。', '名词复数: incongruities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barbarous', '[\'bɑːrbərəs]', 'adj.野蛮的；粗俗的', '1. It is a barbarous way to extend territory by arms. 以武力扩张领土是一种野蛮的方式。 2. It\'s likely to be the most barbarous war that we have ever known. 这将会是一场我们所知道的最残忍的战争。 3. It is barbarous to call at 5 a.m. 清晨五点给人打电话是缺乏教养的行为。', '副词: barbarously 名词: barbarousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imperil', '[ɪm\'perəl]', 'v.使陷于危险中；危及', '1. I will not imperil my soul. I will uphold the justice of the Church. 我不愿使我的灵魂受到玷污，我要维护教会法律的公正。 2. The security of the country had been imperilled. 国家安全处於危险之中。 3. A victory for Allende would imperil our interests in the Western Hemisphere. 阿连德一旦获胜，就将危及我们在西半球的利益。', '名词: imperilment 过去式: imperiled/imperilled 过去分词: imperiled/imperilled 现在分词: imperiling/imperilling 第三人称单数: imperils/imperils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('morass', '[mə\'ræs]', 'n.沼泽；陷阱；困境', '1. There is no simple way out of this morass. 要走出这个沼泽没有简单的办法。 2. I tried to drag myself out of the morass of despair. 我设法让自己从绝望的困境中脱离出来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('highbrow', '[\'haɪbraʊ]', 'adj.文化修养高的；自诩文化修养高的 n.高知识分子；自以为文化修养很高的人', '1. We had a highbrow discussion on classical music. 我们就古典音乐来了一次高水准的讨论。 2. The guest speaker was a highbrow Professor from the local college. 演讲嘉宾是当地大学里一位学识渊博的教授。 3. What appeals to me in the highbrow papers are the books and film reviews. 针对高级知识分子的报纸中,对我颇有吸引力的是书刊评论和影评。', '名词: highbrowism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retreat', '[rɪ\'triːt]', 'n.撤退；改变；隐居处 v.撤退；改变；退避；缩回象棋的棋子', '1. The troop made good their retreat from the occupied city. 部队从沦陷的城市安全撤出。 2. He immediately sounded a retreat. 他立刻下令撤退。 3. The minister made an undignified retreat from his earlier position. 那部长很不光彩地背离了他原先的立场。 4. The Senator made an embarrassing retreat from his earlier position. 这位参议员很尴尬地改变了他早先的立场。 5. After several reverses the enemy was forced to retreat. 几经失败之后，敌军被迫后撤。', '名词: retreater 过去式: retreated 过去分词: retreated 现在分词: retreating 第三人称单数: retreats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kaleidoscopic', '[kəˌlaɪdə\'skɒpɪk]', 'adj.万花筒似的；千变万化的', '1. London is a kaleidoscopic world. 伦敦是个天花筒般的世界。 2. Thoughts appear as kaleidoscopic patterns of light and sound. 思想显现为光和声的万花筒般的图案。 3. Its serial, kaleidoscopic exposures force us to follow its lead. 它那系列的、多变的画面引着我们跟着它走。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('straggle', '[\'stræɡl]', 'v.分散；蔓延；散乱分布；掉队 n.散乱的一群', '1. Vines are straggling over the fences. 藤蔓在篱笆上爬着。　 2. The villages straggle in the mountains. 村庄散布在山林之中。 3. A few young children are straggling along behind their parents. 几个孩子跟不上父母的步子，落在后面。', '名词: straggler 过去式: straggled 过去分词: straggled 现在分词: straggling 第三人称单数: straggles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dilute', '[daɪ\'luːt]', 'vt.稀释；冲淡 adj.冲淡的；稀释的', '1. Dilute the bleach in a gallon of water. 用一加仑水稀释漂白粉。 2. The fragrances are highly diluted. 芳香剂被高度稀释了。 3. The nurse diluted the drug with saline water. 护士用生理盐水把药加以稀释。 4. He thought Rear Admiral Henry\'s presence might dilute the tension of the dinner. 他认为亨利少将的参加也许可以冲淡这顿晚餐的紧张气氛。 5. Readers feel dilute after reading Wei Yingwu\'s poetry, in reality, the poet concealed his solitude under this kind dilute style. 韦应物诗歌给人以冲淡的感觉，其实在这种冲淡的风格下隐含着诗人性格的孤独因素。', '形容词: dilutive 名词: diluter 过去式: diluted 过去分词: diluted 现在分词: diluting 第三人称单数: dilutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('artifice', '[\'ɑːrtɪfɪs]', 'n.诡计；欺骗；技巧', '1. The child cheated them with an artifice. 那个孩子用巧办法骗了他们。 2. Pretending to faint was merely an artifice. 假装昏迷只不过是个诡计。 3. There was no room in him for sham or artifice. 他无论如何也得老实。 4. He display a great deal of artifice in decorate his new house. 他在布置新房子中表现出富有技巧。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('moat', '[moʊt]', 'n.壕沟；护城河 v.将…围以壕沟', '1. When the moat is deep a ladder can be used. 城壕深了架梯子；问题总有解决的办法。 2. A moat separates the animals in the zoo from the spectators. 一条深沟把动物园里的动物和观众隔开。 3. The medieval town is fortified with a high wall and a deep moat. 这座中世纪的城市用高墙深沟来加强防御。 4. There is a moat round the castle. 城堡外环绕着一条护城河。', '过去式: moated 过去分词: moated 现在分词: moating 第三人称单数: moats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('occlude', '[ə\'kluːd]', 'v.使闭塞；封闭；(牙齿)咬合', '1. So we have a greater tendency to make thrombi that can occlude the coronary vessels. 所以我们有制造血凝块的倾向，这个血凝块会封闭冠状血管。 2. As the dentures occlude, then the manner in which the teeth come together will also have the potential to either help or hinder retention and stability. 当义齿咬合时，上下颌牙齿接近的方式也将增强或妨碍固位和稳定。', '形容词: occludent 过去式: occluded 过去分词: occluded 现在分词: occluding 第三人称单数: occludes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('equanimity', '[ˌekwə\'nɪməti]', 'n.平静；镇定', '1. He received the bad news with surprising equanimity. 听到这个坏消息时,他平静得令人吃惊。 2. She was sure his equanimity was fictitious. 她确信他的镇定是佯装的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fatal', '[\'feɪtl]', 'adj.致命的；毁灭性的；决定性的', '1. We gave the enemy a fatal blow. 我们给敌人以致命的打击。 2. There is a fatal flaw in the plan. 计划中有一个致命的缺陷。 3. A possibly fatal crisis may be at hand. 毁灭性的危机可能近在咫尺。 4. The fatal day of the election finally arrived. 大选决定命运的一天终于来到了。', '副词: fatally 名词: fatality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rustic', '[\'rʌstɪk]', 'adj.乡村的；纯朴的；手工粗糙的；土气的 n.乡下人；村夫；农民', '1. His rage was soon calmed down by the rustic peace. 乡村的宁静很快就使他的怒气平静下来。 2. Visitors from cosmopolitan cities were held spellbound by the rustic scenery. 来自大都会的游客被乡村景色迷住了。 3. The village has a certain rustic charm. 这个村子有某一种质朴的魅力。 4. But little Pearl was not clad in rustic weeds. 当然，小珠儿穿的并不是破衣烂衫。 5. The fellow is as handsome a rustic as need be seen. 这个家伙作为一个乡下人是够漂亮的。', '副词: rustically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('underdog', '[\'ʌndərdɔːɡ]', 'n.处于劣势的一方；牺牲者；受害者；输家', '1. The underdog team scored two surprise goals. 处于劣势的一队出人意料地进了两球。 2. The underdogs were beginning to organize their protests. 那一群受迫害的人开始组织抗议。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pallid', '[\'pælɪd]', 'adj.苍白的；暗淡的；无生气的', '1. You look a bit pallid,do you feel all right? 你脸色有点苍白，你没事儿吧? 2. His pallid skin was sensitive to the glaring sun. 他苍白的皮肤对耀眼的阳光很敏感。 3. This is a pallid production of what should be a great ballet. 对于一个伟大的芭蕾舞剧应该是什么来说，这是一个毫无生气的成果。', '副词: pallidly 名词: pallidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vertex', '[\'vɜːrteks]', 'n.[几何]顶点；最高点；头顶', '1. A triangle has three vertices. 三角形有三个顶点。 2. A triangular prism has 6 vertices. 一个三棱柱有六个顶点。 3. My heart jumped to my throat when the roller coaster arrived the vertex . 过山车到达最高点的时候，我的心都提到嗓子眼儿了。', '名词复数: vertexes/vertices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pilgrim', '[\'pɪlɡrɪm]', 'n.朝圣者 Pilgrim. n.(1620年移居美洲的)英国清教徒', '1. We met many pilgrims on their way to Mecca. 我们遇到许多去麦加朝圣的人。 2. At length the pilgrim could shake the dust off his feet at Heidelberg. 那个朝圣者终于可以在海德堡停下来了。 3. I edged closer like a pilgrim approaching a shrine. 我像一位走近庙宇的朝圣者一样再往近走。 4. Their family goes back to the time of the Pilgrim Fathers. 他们家族的渊源可追溯到清教徒前辈移民时代。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cartographer', '[kɑːr\'tɑːɡrəfər]', 'n.地图制作者；制图师', '1. A river is an edge, for one thing, and not simply in the cartographer\'s sense that it divides one piece of ground from another. 首先，一条河是一个边界，并且不是简单的在地图制作者的意识里那样它把一片土地从另一片上分开。 2. Map of Taiwan and part of the mainland coast, put together by a French cartographer. 本图由法国皇家水陆制图师根据耶稣会士的纪录绘成，范围包括台湾岛及大陆沿海的一部分。 3. He told me he would never have found a way out of the thicket if he didn\'t stumble upon a cartographer\'s hut. 他告诉我要不是他偶然发现了一个制图师小屋，他永远也找不到离开灌木丛的路。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forecast', '[\'fɔːrkæst]', 'n.预测；预报 v.预测', '1. Share prices plunged as a result of the gloomy economic forecast. 关于经济前景暗淡的预测导致股票价格大跌。 2. The Treasury\'s forecast assumes that inflation will remain below 3%. 财政部的预测称,通货膨胀率将保持在3%25以下。 3. The weather forecast says it will be sunny tomorrow. 天气预报说明天是晴天。 4. Despite the good weather forecast, the next morning was as wet as ever. 尽管预报称天气很好，但次日上午仍阴雨绵绵。 5. They tried to forecast the result of the football match. 他们试图预测这场足球比赛的结果。', '形容词: forecastable 名词: forecaster 过去式: forecast/forecasted 过去分词: forecast/forecasted 现在分词: forecasting 第三人称单数: forecasts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discipline', '[\'dɪsəplɪn]', 'n.纪律；训练；学科 vt.训练；惩罚', '1. She is strict in the matter of discipline. 她对纪律的要求是严格的。 2. It takes years of discipline to become a pianist. 要成为钢琴家需经多年训练。 3. Applied linguistics is a new and independent discipline. 应用语言学是一门新兴的独立学科。 4. It showed that they had been well disciplined. 这表明他们受过良好的训练。', '形容词: disciplinal 名词: discipliner 过去式: disciplined 过去分词: disciplined 现在分词: disciplining 第三人称单数: disciplines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dogmatism', '[\'dɔːɡmətɪzəm]', 'n.武断；教条主义；独断论', '1. Dogmatism is puppyish coming to its full growth. 教条主义是盲目自高自大的全副面目。 2. Both dogmatism and revisionism run counter to Marxism. 教条主义和修正主义都是违反马克思主义的。 3. His dogmatism is doomed to put him into isolation. 他的独断专行注定使他陷入孤立。 4. Dogmatism is a malady in the academic research nowadays. 摘要“独断论”是当今学术研究的弊病。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('iridescence', '[ˌɪrɪ\'desns]', 'n.彩虹色；灿烂的光辉', '1. Iridescence was considered as a special color on meat and meat products. 摘要彩虹色斑点是近年来发现存在于肉及肉制品中的一种非正常颜色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('principal', '[\'prɪnsəpl]', 'adj.主要的；首要的 n.本金；资本；校长；主角；委托人；主犯', '1. Our principal problem is lack of time. 我们的主要问题就是缺少时间。 2. My wages are the principal source of my income. 薪金是我收入的主要来源。 3. My principal concern is my family\'s welfare. 我至为关心的是我一家的幸福。 4. How much interest will there be on a principal of $5000? 5000美元本金的利息是多少？', '副词: principally 名词: principalship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('empathy', '[\'empəθi]', 'n.移情作用；共鸣；[心]神入', '1. I must have a certain gift for empathy. 我一定有移情的天赋。 2. There is a strange empathy between the old lady and her grandson. 老妇人和她孙子间有种莫名其妙的心灵相通的感觉。 3. Empathy helps us to understand how others feel. 设身处地让我们了解他人的感觉。 4. For Kohut, empathy is simply what allows an individual to know another\'s experience without losing one\'s objectivity. 对科胡特来说，神入仅仅是允许一个个体了解另一个个体的体验而不失其客观性。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foothold', '[\'fʊthoʊld]', 'n.立足处；据点；根据地', '1. The idea has gained foothold. 这种思想已经扎了根。 2. It is not easy to get a foothold as an anchorman. 一个电视节目主持人要站住脚可不容易。 3. It may be many years before the new company can gain a secure foothold in the market. 也许要经过若干年这家新公司才能在市场上取得稳固的立足点。 4. It isn\'t easy to get a foothold as an actor. 演员要得到巩固的地位不容易。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impending', '[ɪm\'pendɪŋ]', 'adj.即将发生的；迫在眉睫的 动词impend的现在分词.', '1. The dark clouds suggest an impending storm. 乌云表明暴风雨即将来临。 2. He was inadequately prepared for the impending examinations. 他对即将举行的考试准备不足。 3. She was keyed up over her impending operation. 她为了即将进行的手术而心中忐忑不安。 4. We are not in denial of impending, dreadful possibilities. 我们并不否认有随时发生可怕情况的可能性。 5. Hurricane is impending. 台风就要来了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verbiage', '[\'vɜːbiɪdʒ]', 'n.废话；冗长；措辞', '1. His report was page after page of empty verbiage, and nobody would like to hear it. 他作的报告空话连篇,根本没人听。 2. His style is characterised by verbiage. 他写文章的特点就是冗长。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('august', '[\'ɔːɡəst]', 'adj.（a~）威严的；尊贵的 n.八月', '1. There\'s an august group of statesmen in the auditorium. 大礼堂里坐着一群德高望重的政治家。 2. The august presence of the queen impressed me. 皇后尊贵的出场给我留下了深刻印象。 3. Tourism is at its peak in August. 旅游业在八月份达到高峰。 4. His summer vacation will end in the late August. 他的暑假将于八月底结束。', '副词: augustly 名词: augustness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('previous', '[\'priːviəs]', 'adj.以前的；先于；在 ... 之前', '1. His previous attempts had been unsuccessful. 他以前的尝试没有成功。 2. It happened previous to his arrival there. 事件发生于他到那儿以前。 3. You must collect enough materials previous to your writing. 你在写作之前必须收集好足够的材料。', '副词: previously 名词: previousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('craving', '[\'kreɪvɪŋ]', 'n.渴望；热望 动词crave的现在分词.', '1. The miserable girl had a craving for sympathy. 那个可怜的女孩渴望得到同情。 2. They are driven by a craving for personal glory. 对个人荣誉的渴望驱动着他们。 3. I had a craving for something sweet. 我馋甜的东西。 4. There is no limit to their craving and vanity. 她们的欲望和空虚是无止尽的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malodor', '[mæl\'oʊdə]', 'n.恶臭', '1. Relatively high criteria for quality assurance of malodor sampling were also required. 针对现有国标方法中的恶臭采样技术进行了更为全面的叙述。 2. As the odor pollution becomes more and more serious, the degradation of malodor gas is an urgent task in waste gas treatment. 随着恶臭污染越来越严重，恶臭气体的处理逐渐成为废气治理中的热点问题。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reward', '[rɪ\'wɔːrd]', 'n.报答；赏金；报酬 vt.奖赏；给 ... 报酬', '1. An act of kindness deserves a reward. 做好事,当然要有报答。 2. By rights, half the reward should be mine. 按理说，有一半奖赏应该是我的。 3. You have received a just reward. 你已得到了应有的报酬。 4. They rewarded the winners with gifts of fruits and flowers. 他们奖给优胜者一些水果和鲜花。', '形容词: rewardable 名词: rewarder 过去式: rewarded 过去分词: rewarded 现在分词: rewarding 第三人称单数: rewards');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('edgy', '[\'edʒi]', 'adj.急躁的；尖利的；刀口锐利的', '1. He has an edgy temper. 他性情急躁。 2. He was edgy and irritable. It was conceivable that he could blow up. 他急躁易怒，可以想到他是会发火的。 3. The parents have been a bit edgy lately, waiting for their children\'s examination results. 父母们近来一直有点儿紧张，等待孩子们的考试成绩。 4. The edgy stick may be dangerous to play with. 玩这种尖利的棍子有危险。', '副词: edgily 比较级: edgier 最高级: edgiest 名词: edginess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solidarity', '[ˌsɑːlɪ\'dærəti]', 'n.团结', '1. Their sense of solidarity is very low. 他们的团结观念非常薄弱。 2. The strike fostered a sense of solidarity among the workers. 罢工促进了工人之间的团结。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fibrous', '[\'faɪbrəs]', 'adj.纤维的；纤维性的', '1. Pily fibrous price is 1,200 dollar per ton. 棉花纤维的价格是1200美元/吨。 2. Cellophane is made of long, fibrous molecules. 玻璃纸系由长形纤维分子组成。 3. The bones are joined to one another by heavy, fibrous ligaments. 这些骨通过粗壮的纤维韧带彼此连接。', '副词: fibrously 名词: fibrousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swig', '[swɪɡ]', 'n.大喝；吞咽 v.豪饮；大口地喝', '1. He took a deep swig from the bottle. 他从瓶子里喝了一大口。 2. John kept swigging at the bottle of brandy. 约翰对着那瓶白兰地酒大口地喝个不停。', '名词: swigger 过去式: swigged 过去分词: swigged 现在分词: swigging 第三人称单数: swigs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drizzly', '[\'drɪzli]', 'adj.毛毛雨的', '1. Toward evening, there came a drizzly rain. 傍晚那会儿下了一阵小雨。 2. It was a drizzly day with gentle breeze at an autumn afternoon . 这是一个秋天的下午,细雨淅沥,秋风瑟瑟。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flick', '[flɪk]', 'n.快速的轻打；抖动 n.电影 vt.轻弹；抖动；忽然摇动；按开开关 vi.轻击；快速翻阅', '1. He gave it a flick with his finger. 他用手指轻叩它。 2. He hit the ball with just a flick of the wrist. 他只用手腕轻轻一抖，打出了那个球。 3. By a flick of his whip,he drove the fly from the horse\'s head. 他用鞭子轻抽了一下，将马头上的苍蝇驱走。 4. He turned the pancake over with a strong flick of his wrist. 他一抖腕子就把饼翻过来了。 5. The flick has copped four awards. 这部电影获得了四项大奖。 6. Please don\'t flick ash on the carpet! 请勿把烟灰弹在地毯上！ 7. He gave it a flick with his finger or he felt the flick of a whip. 陀螺在鞭子的轻击下转动。', '形容词: flickable 过去式: flicked 过去分词: flicked 现在分词: flicking 第三人称单数: flicks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cygnet', '[\'sɪɡnət]', 'n.小天鹅', '1. I felt like a cross between a Tchaikovsky cygnet and a lipizzaner. 我感觉就像是夹在柴可夫斯基的小天鹅和利比扎马中间。 2. The iQ\'s roof and door panels, and even the headlights and side mirrors, are carried over for the Cygnet. 智商的屋顶和门板，甚至头灯和侧后视镜，结转的小天鹅。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('minnow', '[\'mɪnoʊ]', 'n.鲦鱼；小淡水鱼；无足轻重的小公司；不起眼的小型运动队', '1. The minnow had grown and had become a full-fledged fish. 这条鲦鱼已经长大，成为一条发育健全的鱼。 2. These two companies are both minnows in the international market. 在国际市场上，这两家公司都是微不足道的。', '名词复数: minnow');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enthralling', '[ɪn\'θrɔːlɪŋ]', 'adj.迷人的；吸引人的 动词enthrall的现在分词形式.', '1. Music is the maximum enthralling phenomenon in the globle. 音乐是全地球上最迷人的一种事物。 2. It was claimed Bellamy, who scored twice in the game, struck a spectator who had come onto the pitch as Manchester United recorded an enthralling victory. 翻译成中文的意思就是，正当曼联队庆祝这个迷人的胜利之时，有传闻生成这场比赛攻入两球的贝拉米攻击了一冲入场内的观众。 3. For nearly an hour of this enthralling Premiership clash, Wigan looked likely to become the first team to beat Arsenal at Emirates Stadium. 这场吸引人的英超比赛里，维甘领先了近一个小时并似乎可以成为第一支在酋长球场打败阿森纳的球队。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disaffect', '[ˌdɪsə\'fekt]', 'v.使疏远；使不满', '1. The politician tried to disaffect every major voting bloc. 该政客企图煽起每个主要的选举集团的不满。 2. However, you must not let this disaster disaffect you. 但是你不可以因为这种灾难而产生不满情绪。', '名词: disaffection 过去式: disaffected 过去分词: disaffected 现在分词: disaffecting 第三人称单数: disaffects');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vocation', '[voʊ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.职业；行业；使命', '1. She chose nursing as her vocation. 她选择护士为职业。 2. He was equipped with knowledge for the vocation. 他具有这项职业的学识。 3. She struggled for years to find her true vocation. 她多年来苦苦寻找真正适合自己的职业。 4. The industry is facing vocation conformity in China. 在中国,这种工业面临行业整合。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disjunctive', '[dɪs\'dʒʌŋktɪv]', 'adj.可分的；分离的；分隔的', '1. Should Dilemma Observe the Rules of Disjunctive Syllogism? 二难推理需要遵守选言推理的规则吗? 2. Partition is for disjunctive space and of generation. 隔断是为了分隔空间而产生的。 3. Categoricalness implies another property which he called it disjunctive. 范畴性还隐含着另外一条性质，他把它叫做析取性。 4. The disjunctive proposition is a compound proposition of non-truth value. 尽举选言命题是非纯真值复合命题,其真值不是肢命题的真值的真值函数。', '副词: disjunctively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sacrament', '[\'sækrəmənt]', 'n.圣礼；圣事；圣餐', '1. The sacrament of Baptism is but once to be administered unto any person. 任何人都只能受洗一次。 2. Vacuumation is the medical sacrament corresponding to baptism. 种痘是相当于洗礼的医学上的圣礼。 3. Jesus waits for us in this sacrament of love. 耶稣在这爱的圣事之中等待著我们。 4. She received the sacrament. 她领了圣餐。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barricade', '[ˌbærɪ\'keɪd]', 'n.【C】路障；街垒；障碍物；栅栏 n.(常用复数形式)barricades:有激烈争论的领域或议题 vt.设路障挡住；阻拦；封锁', '1. Please step behind the police barricade. 请站在警戒线之后。 2. The soldiers make a barricade across the road. 士兵在路上设路障。 3. The soldiers stormed the barricades erected by the rioting crowd. 士兵们向暴乱分子设置的街垒发起了猛攻。 4. Everyone should be guarded by legal barricades. 人人都应受法律保障。 5. Residents were ready to go to the barricades to fight the school closure. 居民关于反对学校关闭一事准备展开争论。 6. They barricaded the main road with fallen trees. 他们用倒下的树堵住了主要道路。', '名词: barricader 过去式: barricaded 过去分词: barricaded 现在分词: barricading 第三人称单数: barricades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shattered', '[\'ʃætərd]', 'adj.疲惫不堪的；垮掉的；砸碎的 动词shatter的过去式和过去分词.', '1. We were totally shattered after the long journey. 我们经过长途旅行都已精疲力竭。 2. The vase shattered into a thousand pieces. 花瓶已经粉碎了。 3. Music is an appeasement to shattered nerves. 音乐可抚慰受重创的神经。 4. The heavy rain shattered on the roof. 大雨哗啦啦打在屋顶上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fallibility', '[ˌfælə\'bɪləti]', 'n.易错；易误；不可靠', '1. But more than that, it involves an encounter with your fallibility. 产品或服务失去市场；公司赢利状况不佳；过分沉湎于某一嗜好。 2. Does it suggest a fallibility in Cleanthes’s position? 它是否暗示克里安堤斯的声明有错？ 3. What he could not permit to slip by was my implication of their fallibility. 不过他断难放过我暗指他们犯了错误的话。 4. The recognition of fallibility is simply an acknowledgment of our humanity. 承认人皆有错不过是正视人性而已。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amplitude', '[\'æmplɪtuːd]', 'n.广阔；充足；丰富；[物]振幅', '1. The foreground for the cooperation between China and UAE in the energy field is amplitude. 中阿能源领域合作势头好，前景广阔。 2. By their comprehensiveness and amplitude these picture fille the imagination. 这些照片以其综合性和丰富而充满了想像力。 3. Sound waves are measured by their amplitude. 声波是根据其振幅来测量的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adaptable', '[ə\'dæptəbl]', 'adj.能适应的；适应性强的；可改编的', '1. Any coupling device must be adaptable to obtain reasonable performance in all expected situations. 所有联结设备在所有期望的情况一定是能适应的得到合理的表现。 2. The adaptable Indian rhino is intermediate in size. 适应性强的印度犀牛是中等体型的。 3. This multi-skilling approach will provide the organization with an adaptable workforce. 多功能技术的办法，给组织提供了一个适应性强的劳动力。', '名词: adaptability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('waive', '[weɪv]', 'vt.放弃；不坚持；推迟；搁置', '1. He waived his claim to the estate. 他放弃了对遗产的要求权。 2. We cannot waive this rule except in case of illness. 我们不能放弃这项规定，除非因病例外。 3. He waived his claim to all the land west of the river. 他不再坚持对河西岸全部土地的要求。 4. They waived that problem aside last week. 他们上周就把那个问题撇开不管了。', '过去式: waived 过去分词: waived 现在分词: waiving 第三人称单数: waives');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('astound', '[ə\'staʊnd]', 'v.使惊骇；使大吃一惊', '1. Her elopement astounded her parents. 她的私奔使她的父母大为震惊。 2. The figures revealed by the report are astounding. 这份报告透露的数字使人震惊。 3. The figures in that report astounded everyone. 那份报告中的数字让每个人大吃一惊。 4. We were astounded to read your letter. 我们看了你的信大吃一惊。', '副词: astoundingly 过去式: astounded 过去分词: astounded 现在分词: astounding 第三人称单数: astounds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fickle', '[\'fɪkl]', 'adj.变幻无常的；易变的', '1. The weather\'s so fickle in summer. 夏日的天气如此多变。 2. It\'s the third time that he changed his mind; he\'s so fickle! 他改变主意已经是第三回了,他这人太反复无常了！ 3. The television world was a notoriously fickle one. 电视圈是出了名的变化无常。 4. He turned out to be fickle - he has left me. 他原来是个善变的人 - 他离开我了。', '副词: fickly 名词: fickleness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('staple', '[\'steɪpl]', 'n.U形(订书)钉；主要产物(要素)；原料(地) adj.主要的；重要的 vt.用订书机装订', '1. He used a pair of scissors to take the staple out of the document. 他用剪刀将订书钉从文件上取了出来。 2. Coffee is the staple of this district. 咖啡是这个地区的主要产品。 3. Bread, potato and other staple continue to rise in price. 面包、土豆及其他主食的价格继续上涨。 4. For example, rice is a staple crop in much of Asia. 例如，在亚洲大米是原料农作物。 5. Short stories are her staple reading. 短篇小说是她经常看的读物。 6. He stapled the paper together. 他把文件钉在一起。', '过去式: stapled 过去分词: stapled 现在分词: stapling 第三人称单数: staples');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('egoism', '[\'eɡoʊɪzəm]', 'n.自我主义；利己主义', '1. The egoism of an artist sometimes seem natural. 艺术家的自负有时看起来是自然的。 2. We cannot help the egoism of our senses. 我们禁不住要陷入感官司的自我主义之中。 3. He was looked down upon because of his egoism. 他因自私而受人冷落。 4. They seemed to love the land and the people with a sort of fierce egoism. 他们似乎是带著强烈的利己主义来爱这里的人和土地的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decent', '[\'diːsnt]', 'adj.相当好的；体面的；适当的；正派的', '1. Are there any decent restaurants around here? 这附近有没有好的餐厅？ 2. He dreamed of living in decent conditions. 他梦想着过体面的生活。 3. The lack of decent public transport is a great disadvantage. 没有适当的公共交通工具是很不方便的。 4. John and his wife Leah are very decent people. 约翰是他的妻子丽亚都是非常正派的人。', '副词: decently 名词: decentness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eccentric', '[ɪk\'sentrɪk]', 'adj.古怪的；反常的；不同圆心的 n.怪人；[物]偏心轮', '1. The old lady is a bit of an eccentric. 这位老太是个有点古怪的人。 2. She put him down as an eccentric person. 她认为他是个行为古怪的人。 3. His actions since that morning have been eccentric and unpredictable. 自从那天早晨,他的行动一直是反常而不可捉摸。 4. The motors and drive units on these two types of polisher\'s oscillate in an eccentric circular motion. 发动机和转速单位在这两种抛光机上的振蒎是一个偏圆心的运动。 5. He had the name of an eccentric. 他有怪人之称。', '副词: eccentrically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suffuse', '[sə\'fjuːz]', 'v.遍布 ...；弥漫；充满', '1. The evening sky was suffused with crimson. 黄昏时分天空红霞灿灿。 2. A blush suffused his cheeks. 他瞬间满脸通红。 3. They want to move everyone with their behaviors and suffuse the world with love. 她们表示要用自己的行为去感染世界上的每一个人，让爱心充满全世界。', '形容词: suffusive 名词: suffusion 过去式: suffused 过去分词: suffused 现在分词: suffusing 第三人称单数: suffuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whistle', '[\'wɪsl]', 'n.口哨；汽笛；警笛 v.吹口哨；鸣汽笛；呼啸；吹口哨召唤', '1. The whistle goes at the end of the match. 比赛结束时哨声响了。 2. He gave a loud whistle of gladness. 他吹了一声响亮的口号表示高兴。 3. The whistle went and the man knocked off for lunch. 汽笛响了，工人们停工午餐。 4. The horse shied at the shrill whistle. 那匹马听到刺耳的汽笛声，惊得往后倒退。 5. The little boy rounded his lips to whistle. 那个小男孩把双唇收圆好吹口哨。', '过去式: whistled 过去分词: whistled 现在分词: whistling 第三人称单数: whistles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('patriot', '[\'peɪtriət]', 'n.爱国者', '1. The patriot sticks to his moral principles. 那个爱国者固守他自已的道德信念。 2. He regards himself as a patriot. 他自认为是个爱国者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quotidian', '[kwoʊ\'tɪdiən]', 'adj.每日的；平凡的 n.每日疟', '1. Intrigue against each other is quotidian in every company. 勾心斗角在每个单位都司空见惯。 2. The texts mainly deal with the vivid quotidian communication. 课文以日常交际为主，生动活泼。 3. Gaze detection can endow quotidian machines with seemingly magical behavior. 这种视线侦测系统可以让日常用品做出看似神奇的行为。 4. There\'s nothing quite like a real train conductor to add color to a quotidian commute. 没有什么能象一位现实中的火车售票员那样为日常的上下班交通线增加些色彩。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unfasten', '[ʌn\'fæsn]', 'v.解开；松开', '1. He unfastened the buckles and took off the coat. 他解开扣子，把上衣脱掉。 2. You may unfasten your seat belt now. 现在可以松开您的安全带了。', '过去式: unfastened 过去分词: unfastened 现在分词: unfastening 第三人称单数: unfastens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bluff', '[blʌf]', 'v.虚张声势 n.虚张声势；吓唬；绝壁 adj.直率的', '1. He could bluff his way through any difficulty. 他可以招摇撞骗闯过任何难关。 2. John is a deep card; no one can bluff him easily. 约翰是个机灵鬼，谁也不容易欺骗他。 3. The man is trying to bluff his way out of the whole thing. 这人想装做无辜来摆脱此事。 4. They were bluffed into believing we were not ready for the attack. 他们上了当，以为我们还没有作好进攻准备。 5. The company\'s threat to sack anyone who went on strike was just (a) bluff. 公司威胁说谁罢工就解雇谁，那只不过是虚张声势罢了。 6. He was bluff, strong, friendly, and outgoing. 他性格坦率，倔强，和蔼，开朗。', '形容词: bluffable 副词: bluffly 比较级: bluffer 最高级: bluffest 名词: bluffer 过去式: bluffed 过去分词: bluffed 现在分词: bluffing 第三人称单数: bluffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subdued', '[səb\'duːd]', 'adj.屈服的；柔和的；减弱的；被抑制的 动词subdue的过去式和过去分词.', '1. The subdued moonlit glare helps to bring out more of the lunar landscape. 柔和的月光会帮助我们更多更好的勾勒出月球的景象。 2. calm drivers get wound up by subdued, low-key voices that don\'t vary in pitch. 熟练的驾驶者对那种柔和的毫无变化的语调感到厌烦. 3. There is a subdued atmosphere in the school at exam time. 在考试期间，学校里有一种压抑的氛围。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ailment', '[\'eɪlmənt]', 'n.小病；疾病', '1. M.Forestier suffered from a bronchial ailment. 弗赖斯节先生患有支气管疾病。 2. Finding the right herb to cure a particular ailment requires a little research. 还需要做些研究才能找到合适的草药来治疗某种疾病。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dulcet', '[\'dʌlsɪt]', 'adj.优美的；美妙的；美味的', '1. The dulcet sound of the stream ravishes me. 溪水发出的优美声音让我陶醉。 2. Dulcet feelings disappeared in a wink. 美妙的感觉稍瞬即逝。 3. The meandering and stretching Olympus looks inscrutably lush and dulcet. 奥林匹斯山峰峦起伏、绵延伸展,郁郁葱葱中掩映着深不可测的美妙。', '副词: dulcetly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('miscellany', '[\'mɪsəleɪni]', 'n.杂集；文集；混合物', '1. The show was a miscellany of song and dance. 那场演出是又有歌曲又有舞蹈的混合表演。 2. There is a miscellany of objects in the room. 屋里一堆乱七八糟的东西。', '名词复数: miscellanies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clown', '[klaʊn]', 'n.小丑；粗鲁愚蠢的人 v.扮小丑；胡闹', '1. It\'s a picture depicting him as a clown. 这是一幅把他画成小丑的画。 2. I just curled up when I saw her dressed as a clown. 我见她打扮得像个小丑，把我笑得直不起腰来。 3. I wish he would stop being such a clown. 我希望他能够不再像个粗俗的小丑。 4. Start climbing up the charts, so sick, but they tried to clown. 开始向美好奋斗', '形容词: clownish 副词: clownishly 名词: clownishness 过去式: clowned 过去分词: clowned 现在分词: clowning 第三人称单数: clowns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disclaimer', '[dɪs\'kleɪmər]', 'n.放弃；弃权；免责声明', '1. That was a few days ahead of the German disclaimer. 那是在德国人放弃前几天。 2. This disclaimer is to be regarded as part of the internet publication which you were referred from. 此免责声明被认为是互联网上涉及到著作的一部分。 3. Now, Ms.Fanizzi Krystoff is much more specific -- to the point of spelling out details in the style of a disclaimer. 现在，克里斯多夫的着装规定变得非常明确，用免责声明般的风格指出着装细节。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tint', '[tɪnt]', 'n. 色彩； 浅色； 染发剂 vt. 给 ... 染色', '1. Tint leaves the footage colors but wipes out darks. 著色使得画面的色彩，但清除掉深色衣物。 2. Today salt-loving bacteria thrive in brine pools on the dry lake bed, lending a blood-red tint in this aerial view. 如今，喜爱盐分的宅细菌在干涸湖床上的咸水池里繁茂生长，使得这幅空拍画面带着血红的色彩。 3. She gave me instructions on how to apply the tint. 她告诉我如何使用染发剂。', '名词: tinter 过去式: tinted 过去分词: tinted 现在分词: tinting 第三人称单数: tints');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plumb', '[plʌm]', 'v.（用铅垂）测量；探测 n.铅锤；垂直 adj.垂直的；<口>完全的 adv.恰恰；<口>彻底地', '1. We need to plumb the line. 我们需要用铅垂测量这条线。 2. We begin to plumb the mysteries of the universe. 我们开始探索宇宙的奥秘。 3. It was unprofitable to plumb that sort of thing. 这种事弄个水落石出没有什么好处。 4. Bricklayers and carpenters often use plumb lines . 瓦工和木工经常使用铅垂线。 5. Is this wall plumb? 这墙是垂直的吗？ 6. The bullet hit him plumb between the eyes. 子弹正好打在他的双眼之间。', '形容词: plumbable 过去式: plumbed 过去分词: plumbed 现在分词: plumbing 第三人称单数: plumbs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vagrancy', '[\'veɪɡrənsi]', 'n.流浪罪；漂泊；神思恍惚', '1. He was convicted of drunkenness and vagrancy. 他因醉酒和流浪罪被判刑。', '名词复数: vagrancies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sangfroid', '[sɑːŋ\'frwɑː]', 'n.镇静；泰然；沉着', '1. She had the strength and sangfroid of a woman in the prime of life. 她具有正值青春的少妇的力量和沉着。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immerse', '[ɪ\'mɜːrs]', 'vt.浸；陷入', '1. I immerse my clothes in the water. 我把衣服浸在水里。 2. Please immerse the plant in water for a few minutes. 把那棵植物在水里浸泡几分钟。 3. He immersed himself totally in his work. 他埋头于工作。 4. I immerse myself into reciting English vocabulary. 我专心于背英语词汇。', '过去式: immersed 过去分词: immersed 现在分词: immersing 第三人称单数: immerses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hubris', '[\'hjuːbrɪs]', 'n.傲慢；骄傲', '1. If that is the case,China might be able to avoid the pitfall of hubris. 如果事实如此，中国也许能避免高傲自大的缺点。', '形容词: hubristic 副词: hubristically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('zigzag', '[\'zɪɡzæɡ]', 'n.曲折；之字形 adj.曲折的；锯齿形的 adv.曲折地；成锯齿形地 vt.使曲折 vi.曲折前行', '1. As long as the insect remains in the odor stream, fairly direct or weakly zigzag flight paths are maintained until it overshoots the odor source. 只要昆虫与气味一接触时，它们沿着几乎是直接的或稍有曲折的飞行路线，直到越过气味源。 2. The same effect causes student drivers to zigzag down the road, as each late large correction of the steering wheel overreacts to the last late overcorrection. 这就跟新手开车总是开出之字形道理一样，因为每次转动方向盘，总是会矫枉过正，超过上次校正所偏离的部分。 3. As long as the insect remains in the odor stream, fairly direct or weakly zigzag flight paths are maintained until it overshoots the odor source. 只要昆虫与气味一接触时，它们沿着几乎是直接的或稍有曲折的飞行路线，直到越过气味源。', '过去式: zigzagged 过去分词: zigzagged 现在分词: zigzagging 第三人称单数: zigzags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slanderous', '[\'slɑːndərəs]', 'adj.诽谤的；中伤的', '1. He made slanderous statement about the Prime Minister on television. 他在电视上讲话诽谤首相。 2. Her slanderous words soiled his reputation. 她中伤性的话损害了他的名誉。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stratagem', '[\'strætədʒəm]', 'n.战略；计谋', '1. They have worked out the stratagem to attack the enemy. 他们已经想出了攻击敌人的策略。 2. I was merely a pawn in his cunning stratagem. 我只不过是他那狡猾计谋中的一件工具。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('equivalent', '[ɪ\'kwɪvələnt]', 'adj.等价的 相等的 n.相等物', '1. Is there a French word that is the exact equivalent of the English word `home\'? 法语中有没有和英语home完全一样的对应词?', '副词: equivalently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('institutionalized', '[ˌɪnstɪ\'tuːʃənəlaɪzd]', 'adj.使成惯例的 动词institutionalize的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. More and more of our savings are institutionalized rather than individualized. 我们的储蓄越来越多地由个人手里转入各种组织的控制中。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aroma', '[ə\'roʊmə]', 'n.浓香；香气', '1. The aroma of coffee always cheers me up. 咖啡的浓香总能给我一份好心情。 2. Their attributes are a golden colour, a fruity aroma and a smooth flavour. 他们的归属是一个金制的颜色，水果的浓香和一个平滑的滋味。 3. Its delicate aroma is sweet and appealing. 其微妙的香气是甜的吸引力。 4. The green coffee beans have no flavor or aroma. 生咖啡豆既没有味道也没有香气。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('robe', '[roʊb]', 'n.长袍 v.(使)穿上长袍', '1. Many Arabs wear long flowing robes. 许多阿拉伯人身穿松垂的长袍. 2. She was simply dressed in a plain white robe. 她只穿了一件朴素的白色长袍。 3. In the early morning, he robed and drove abroad. 他一早就穿好衣服开车出门了。 4. He robes himself in moonlight. 他沐浴在月光下。', '过去式: robed 过去分词: robed 现在分词: robing 第三人称单数: robes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fluvial', '[\'fluːviəl]', 'adj.河流的；生于河中的；河流冲刷作用形成的', '1. Most other Dutch soil types are fluvial. 荷兰大多数其它土壤类型是沼生的。 2. The unconformity marks the change from fluvial to marginal marine deposition. 不整合面标志着河相至边缘海相沉积的相变。 3. Understand the distribution of worldwide fluvial hydrocarbon production. 理解全球河成油气开采的分布。 4. Introduced is a method for predicting sedimental sand body with fluvial facies. 介绍一种河流相沉积砂体预测方法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('methodical', '[mə\'θɑːdɪkl]', 'adj.有条不紊的；井然的', '1. A scientist is usually a methodical person. 科学家通常是办事有条不紊的人。 2. This book is about systematic and methodical training. 这本书是关于有系统和有规律的训练。', '副词: methodically 异体字: methodic 名词: methodicalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repulsion', '[rɪ\'pʌlʃn]', 'n.厌恶；反感；[物]排斥；斥力', '1. I have repulsion for snakes. 我很讨厌蛇。 2. I felt a mixture of amazement and repulsion. 我感到惊愕并混杂着反感。 3. Coulomb repulsion imposes the need for high temperature. 库仑斥力增添了对高温的需求。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tatter', '[\'tætə]', 'v.使破烂；变得破烂 n.破布；碎纸', '1. The flag was tattered by a gale. 旗子被大风刮成了碎布条。 2. The beggar\'s shirt was in tatters. 这乞丐的衣服已成了碎片。 3. She replies to my point so convincingly that my argument is soon in tatter. 她很有说服力,很快就将我的论点驳倒。', '过去式: tattered 过去分词: tattered 现在分词: tattering 第三人称单数: tatters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parable', '[\'pærəbl]', 'n.寓言；比喻', '1. This parable tells us not to trust strangers. 寓言告诫我们不要相信陌生人。 2. She was very inspired by the parable. 她从这则寓言中得到了启示。 3. In the eleventh parable in Luke Jesus uses a lamp. 耶稣用灯做为第十一个比喻。 4. This parable explained an interest relationship with knowledge. 这个比喻说明了兴趣与知识的关系。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ruddy', '[\'rʌdi]', 'adj.红的；红润的', '1. Their fur tends toward ruddy brown. 他们的毛往往是红褐色。 2. The fire cast a ruddy glow over the city. 这场火把城市上空映得一片通红。 3. He looked at the children\'s ruddy cheeks and smiled. 他看着孩子们红润的脸颊，笑了。 4. After the vacation，children are all in ruddy health. 孩子们度假后个个红光满面.', '副词: ruddily 比较级: ruddier 最高级: ruddiest 名词: ruddiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pylon', '[\'paɪlən]', 'n.高压电线架；桥塔；塔门；路标塔', '1. The helicopter lifted up the steel pylon, transported it to the site, and dropped it gently into place. 直升飞机把高压电缆铁塔吊起，运至工地，然后轻轻放下使之就位。 2. The cables intersect the tower or pylon at different heights. 钢索在桥塔或塔柱的不同高度上相交。 3. Entry to the Pylon is from the pedestrian walkway on the Harbour Bridge. 桥塔的入口处就设在港湾大桥的行人道上。 4. The pylon cell units were hoisted to the deck by the transfer derrick. 塔室块件由传递用的转臂吊机吊放在桥面上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impersonate', '[ɪm\'pɜːrsəneɪt]', 'v.模仿；扮演；假冒', '1. I use character quotes from movies and impersonate people we know. 我会利用电影中的角色来扮演或模仿我们生活中熟悉的人。 2. I use character quotes from movies and impersonate people we know. 我会利用电影中的角色来扮演或模仿我们生活中熟悉的人。 3. After creating the root object and making changes to the properties of any object accessed through it, your code should not impersonate a different user. 创建一个根对象并改变一些配置属性后，你的代码不能扮演不同的用户。', '名词: impersonation 过去式: impersonated 过去分词: impersonated 现在分词: impersonating 第三人称单数: impersonates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prance', '[præns]', 'v.腾跃；欢跃；昂首阔步 n.(马)后足立地腾跃；昂首阔步', '1. The children were prancing about with delight. 孩子们高兴得蹦蹦跳跳。 2. Aunt Jennifer\'s tigers prance across a screen. 珍妮弗阿姨的老虎们腾跃屏风。 3. The little girl pranced about the room in her new clothes. 小女孩穿著新衣在屋里雀跃。 4. That cheeky new secretary just pranced up to me and asked if I worked here! 那个冒失的新秘书兴冲冲地蹦跳到我跟前，问我是否在这里工作。', '副词: prancingly 名词: prancer 过去式: pranced 过去分词: pranced 现在分词: prancing 第三人称单数: prances');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bandage', '[\'bændɪdʒ]', 'n.绷带 vt.用绷带包扎', '1. The nurse eased away the bandage from the wound. 护士小心翼翼地解开伤口处的绷带。 2. I twisted the bandage round her knee. 我用带缠住了她的膝盖。 3. The waitress put a bandage round his hand. 女服务员用绷带将他的手包扎起来。 4. The surgeon bandaged up his injured head. 外科医生把他受伤的头部包扎起来。', '名词: bandager 过去式: bandaged 过去分词: bandaged 现在分词: bandaging 第三人称单数: bandages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proprietary', '[prə\'praɪəteri]', 'adj.专利的；所有权的 n.所有权；所有人', '1. We have some proprietary specific medicine . 我们有些专卖特效药。 2. For grease marks, try a proprietary dry cleaner. 若要去除油污,可以试试一种专利干洗剂。 3. The company has a proprietary right to the property. 公司拥有这笔财产的所有权。 4. Proprietary right is the foundation of jus rerem. 所有权是物权法之根基。', '副词: proprietarily 名词复数: proprietaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reactionary', '[ri\'ækʃəneri]', 'adj.反动的；反动主义的；反对改革的 n.反对政府或社会变革者；反动分子', '1. The reactionary classes never give up power voluntarily. 反动阶级从来不会自动放弃政权。 2. This was a victory over reactionary forces. 这是对反动势力的一个胜利。 3. All efforts made by reactionary forces against socialism will only end in failure. 反动势力阻止社会主义事业的一切企图只能以失败而告终。 4. No explanation or excuse could get over the fact that the man is a reactionary. 任何解释和辩解都回避不了这样一个事实：这个人是反动分子。', '名词复数: reactionaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tag', '[tæɡ]', 'n.标签；附属物；捉人游戏；谚语；名称 vt.连接；附以签条；尾随；添饰；指责 vi.紧随；尾随', '1. She peered at the tag to read the price. 她细看标签以看清价格。 2. The kids are playing tag over there. 小孩子正在那儿玩捉人游戏。 3. He would make a shot at a Latin tag. 他要尝试一下拉丁文短语。 4. A tag is another name for a media information attribute. 标记是媒体信息属性的另一个名称。 5. Will you tag these two together? 你把这两个连接在一起好吗? 6. If you\'re going to the cinema, do you mind if I tag along ? 你要是去看电影, 我也一起去行吗?', '过去式: tagged 过去分词: tagged 现在分词: tagging 第三人称单数: tags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('variance', '[\'veriəns]', 'n.不一致；变化；[数]方差', '1. We are at variance about our lodger. 我们在对待房客的问题上意见不一。 2. Variance between transeunt request and self judgement. 外在的要求常和自己的判断不一致。 3. Carl\'s actions were always at variance with his promises. 卡尔的言行不一致。 4. This theory is at variance with the known facts. 这种理论与已知事实不符。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gouge', '[ɡaʊdʒ]', 'v.用圆凿子挖；挖出；<非>欺骗 n.圆凿；凿；凿孔；<非>欺诈', '1. A maniac had gouged several holes in the priceless painting. 有个狂徒在那幅价值连城的画上乱凿了几个洞。 2. To make a Halloween lantern, you first have to gouge out the inside of the pumpkin. 要做一个万圣节灯笼, 你先得挖空这个南瓜。', '名词: gouger 过去式: gouged 过去分词: gouged 现在分词: gouging 第三人称单数: gouges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lure', '[lʊr]', 'vt.诱惑；吸引 n.诱惑；吸引力；饵', '1. The travel brochure lured me into taking a Caribbean vacation. 这本旅游小册子诱使我去加勒比地区度假。 2. The enticement of the big city lure her away from her home. 大城市的种种诱惑吸引了她离家出走。 3. It\'s very difficult to lure talent away from Silicon Valley. 很难将硅谷的人才吸引走。 4. Do not lure her away from her duty . 不要引诱她离开职守。 5. He left home because of the lures of the life in the city. 由于受到城市生活的诱惑,他离开了家。', '副词: luringly 名词: lurer 过去式: lured 过去分词: lured 现在分词: luring 第三人称单数: lures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bluster', '[\'blʌstər]', 'v.咆哮；(风)狂吹；夸口 n.狂风声；咆哮；大话', '1. He blustered his way through the crowd. 他吆喝着挤过人群。 2. They blustered about how they would beat us all up. 他们威胁说他们要如何痛打我们大家。 3. The gale blustered all night. 大风刮了一夜。 4. The storm is blustering northeastward across the open Atlantic. 风暴正向东北方向移动，吹向广袤的大西洋。 5. We could hear the bluster of the wind and rain. 我们能听到狂风暴雨的吹打声。', '形容词: blustery 名词: blusterer 过去式: blustered 过去分词: blustered 现在分词: blustering 第三人称单数: blusters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cordial', '[\'kɔːrdʒəl]', 'n.兴奋剂；补品 adj.热忱的；诚恳的；兴奋的', '1. By means of a few drops of strong cordial, the doctor revived the besotted corpse for a few minutes. 博士滴了几滴强烈的兴奋剂，使这个没有知觉的身躯复活了几分钟。 2. It was a cordial affair in which Pancalli expressed his appreciation for the work carried out by Juventus in recent months. 这是一次热忱的会晤，潘卡利感谢了近几个月来尤文所做的工作。 3. Please accept my cordial and humblest apologies. 请接受我诚恳的道歉。', '副词: cordially 名词: cordiality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('feisty', '[\'faɪsti]', 'adj.易怒的；活跃的', '1. A feisty old lady had to call the electric company for a repairman. 一位火爆脾气的老太太给供电公司打电话要个检修工。 2. He was a strong and a feisty old man, considering that life is so hard. 他是一个这么强壮和活跃的老人，生活却是如此之艰难。', '比较级: feistier 最高级: feistiest 名词: feistiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('symphony', '[\'sɪmfəni]', 'n.交响乐', '1. The first movement of the symphony is beautiful. 这部交响乐的第一乐章是很优美的。 2. I like listening to the symphony. 我喜欢听交响乐。', '名词复数: symphonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enlighten', '[ɪn\'laɪtn]', 'v.启发；开导；教导', '1. This book will enlighten the reader. 这本书将会启发读者。 2. Enlighten me with your thoughts on this matter. 你们在如下事件上的思想启发了我。 3. Can you enlighten me--I don\'t understand this proposal. 我不明白这条建议，你能不能启发我一下。 4. Can you enlighten me on this subject? 关于这个问题，你能指点我一下吗？', '名词: enlightener 过去式: enlightened 过去分词: enlightened 现在分词: enlightening 第三人称单数: enlightens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gag', '[ɡæɡ]', 'n.箝口物；箝制言论(的命令)；笑话；恶作剧 v.塞住口部；遏制言论；使呕吐；十分想要(做某事)', '1. The robbers rammed the gag in her mouth. 强盗用力将堵嘴物塞进她口中。 2. The burglars bound him hand and foot and placed a gag in his mouth. 夜盗们捆住了他的手脚，并用东西塞住他的嘴。 3. Gag orders at this stage in the proceedings are rare, though not unprecedented. 虽说并非史无前例，但进展到这阶段下达禁令实属罕见。 4. There is always a standing gag in his company. 他的连队里一直流传着一句老笑话。 5. The thieves left the night-watchman tied up and gagged. 窃贼把夜班守卫员捆住，把他的嘴也堵住了。', '过去式: gagged 过去分词: gagged 现在分词: gagging 第三人称单数: gags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cosmopolitan', '[ˌkɑːzmə\'pɑːlɪtən]', 'adj.世界性的；久经世故的；遍生于世界的；四海一家的 n.世界主义者', '1. New York is a highly cosmopolitan city. 纽约是一个高度世界性的城市。 2. Alexander envisioned a cosmopolitan culture in his new empire. 亚历山大打算让他的新帝国具有世界性的文化。 3. The rose is a cosmopolitan plant. 玫瑰是遍生于世界各地的植物。 4. She has a very cosmopolitan outlook on life. 她有四海一家的人生观。', '名词: cosmopolitanism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('staid', '[steɪd]', 'adj.固定的；（指人﹑ 外表﹑ 行为﹑ 爱好等）古板的；保守的；一本正经的', '1. He does this by transmitting not a staid image but a simulacra. 他不是通过传输固定的图像而是传输某种拟像而做到了这一点。 2. The museum is trying to get rid of its staid image. 博物馆力图改变自己古板的形象。 3. I always thought of him as a rather staid old gentleman. 我一直以为他是个相当古板的绅士。 4. The locals were a very staid lot. 当地居民非常保守。', '副词: staidly 名词: staidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subpoena', '[sə\'piːnə]', 'n.（传唤出庭的）传票 v.用（传票）传唤', '1. The couple may get a subpoena to appear. 这对夫妇可能会接到传票出庭。 2. They got a subpoena to examine our books. 他们拿到了传票，要来检查我们的书。 3. Subpoena shall be issued for coercive summons. 拘传应当发拘传票。 4. The witness are subpoenaed to attend the trial. 用传票传唤证人参加审判。', '过去式: subpoenaed 过去分词: subpoenaed 现在分词: subpoenaing 第三人称单数: subpoenas');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('collude', '[kə\'luːd]', 'v.串通；共谋', '1. With collude of packaging group dark ground. 与装潢队暗地勾结。 2. They two are people of the same ilk, who collude with one another. 他们俩臭味相投，相互勾结。 3. We need human rights because corporation and official collude. 我们要人权。那些只为人民币服务的官员，百般阻挠、胁民工的投诉。 4. We need survivorship because corporation and gangdom collude and slay worker. 我们要生存。万恶的企业、工头和黑社会势力勾结，砍死砍伤要工资的农民工不计其数。', '名词: colluder 过去式: colluded 过去分词: colluded 现在分词: colluding 第三人称单数: colludes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anticipatory', '[ænˌtɪsɪ\'peɪtəri]', 'adj.预期的；提早发生的', '1. During that time I was diagnosed with anticipatory anxiety disorder. 就在那个时候，我被诊断出患有预想性焦虑失调症。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tirade', '[\'taɪreɪd]', 'n.长篇的攻击性演说', '1. His writings are one long tirade against ignorance. 他的著作称得上反对无知的长篇演说。 2. After the chairman delivered his opening speech, Mr Smith launched into a brilliant tirade. 主席致开幕词后，史密斯先生作了精彩的长篇演说。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('numinous', '[\'nuːmɪnəs]', 'adj.精神上的；神圣的；神秘的', '1. This garment was beautifully numinous after being touched and blessed by so many loving hands. 在经过如此多充满爱的手触碰和祝福后，这件衣服是神圣美好的。 2. They led me to a numinous place that day. 那天他们领着我去了一个神秘的地方。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('millennium', '[mɪ\'leniəm]', 'n.一千年；太平盛世', '1. The current hypothesis is that the Vedic form of Sanskrit survived until the middle of the first millennium BC. 当前的假说就是梵语形式的吠陀经保存了下来，直到公元前一千年中叶为止。 2. Each of these Pyramid inches represents one millennium, or 1000 years, showing that Zoroaster was the middle Manifestation. 每一个这些棱椎的每一英寸都代表一个千禧年，或一千年，表明琐罗亚斯德是中间的表现。 3. I do not expect the millennium to come during my lifetime. 我并不指望我这一生中能碰上太平盛世。', '形容词: millennial 副词: millennially 名词: millennialism 名词复数: millenniums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('placate', '[\'pleɪkeɪt]', 'v.抚慰；平息；和解', '1. His intent is clearly not to placate his critics. 他的目的显然不是要安抚批评他的人。 2. The concessions did little to placate the students. 让步根本未能平息学生的愤怒。', '形容词: placatory 名词: placater 过去式: placated 过去分词: placated 现在分词: placating 第三人称单数: placates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pat', '[pæt]', 'n.轻拍；轻打；小块 v.轻拍；抚摸；拍打', '1. He gave her a reassuring pat on the shoulder. 他轻拍了一下她的肩膀让她放心。 2. He gave me a light pat on the shoulder. 他在我肩上轻轻一拍。 3. It was a basket with fresh eggs, a newly-baked loaf of bread, a pat of butter. 这个篮子里有新鲜鸡蛋，一条新出炉的面包和一小块黄油。 4. The children wanted to pat the bunny . 孩子们想轻拍这只兔子。', '副词: patly 名词: patness 过去式: patted 过去分词: patted 现在分词: patting 第三人称单数: pats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insane', '[ɪn\'seɪn]', 'adj.疯狂的；精神错乱的；荒唐的', '1. Are you insane? 你疯了吗？ 2. I have an insane desire to finish that thing. 我疯狂地渴望去完成那件事。 3. That person is insane. 那人精神错乱。 4. The insane man was committed to an asylum. 那个精神失常的人被送进了精神病院。', '副词: insanely 名词: insaneness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bowdlerize', '[\'baʊdləraɪz]', 'v.删改 =bowdlerise(英).', '1. There is no need to bowdlerize your speech when dealing with anyone from a legal standpoint. 从法律角度说，你不需要再跟任何人修订你的演讲稿了。', '名词: bowdlerism 过去式: bowdlerized 过去分词: bowdlerized 现在分词: bowdlerizing 第三人称单数: bowdlerizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discriminatory', '[dɪ\'skrɪmɪnətɔːri]', 'adj.歧视的；差别待遇的', '1. Protection for domestic industry is admittedly discriminatory. 保护本国工业是种名正言顺的歧视。 2. The new legislation is highly discriminatory. 新的法案，有许多地方厚此薄彼。 3. The operation of such discriminatory policies is known as regional policy. 这种实行区别对待的政策被称为地区政策。', '副词: discriminatorily');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('procure', '[prə\'kjʊr]', 'v.获得；采办；拉皮条', '1. Can you procure that rare old book ? 你能获得那本珍本古书吗? 2. The book is out of print and difficult to procure . 那种书已绝版，难于获得。 3. I will try to procure you the best terms I can. 我要尽量使你获得好的条件。 4. He was responsible for procuring supplies for the army. 他的职责是为部队采办军需品。', '形容词: procurable 名词: procurance 过去式: procured 过去分词: procured 现在分词: procuring 第三人称单数: procures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('restorative', '[rɪ\'stɔːrətɪv]', 'adj.恢复健康和体力的；恢复的 n.使恢复的东西；恢复药', '1. Nature has an exhilarative and restorative effect. 大自然具有使人畅快并恢复体力的效果。 2. The brandy acted as a restorative. 喝白兰地酒消除了疲劳。', '副词: restoratively 名词: restorativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decency', '[\'diːsnsi]', 'n.得体；礼貌；体面 (复)decencies：礼仪；行为规范.', '1. Such conduct outrages our normal sense of decency. 这种行为伤害了我们正常的得体感。 2. His essential decency makes it impossible to dislike him. 他十分正派，使人不能不喜欢他。 3. You should have the decency to apologize for what you did. 你应该讲点礼貌，为你所做的事道歉。 4. All people with a sense of decency will look down upon such conduct as that. 注重尊严的人都会轻视那种行为。', '名词复数: decencies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('poach', '[poʊtʃ]', 'vt.(侵入他人地界)偷猎(或捕鱼)；水煮；侵占；挖走', '1. They cannot poach for herring form our waters. 他们不可以在我国海域捕捞鲱鱼。 2. Fred was caught poaching hares. 弗雷德因偷猎野兔被捉. 3. When the water boils, drop the asparagus to poach. 水开后,投入芦笋煮熟。 4. Rival salesmen were poaching on his territory. 这些推销员是竞争对手，却跑到他的地盘来兜生意。', '形容词: poachable 过去式: poached 过去分词: poached 现在分词: poaching 第三人称单数: poaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disintegrate', '[dɪs\'ɪntɪɡreɪt]', 'vi.瓦解；崩溃 vt.使粉碎；使碎裂', '1. The alliance will soon disintegrate unless something is done to pull it together. 这个联盟会很快瓦解，除非采取措施加强它的团结。 2. Their marriage rapidly disintegrated. 他们的婚姻迅速破裂了。 3. The family is starting to disintegrate. 这个家庭要破裂了。 4. The plane flew into a mountain and disintegrated on impact. 飞机冲向一座山，撞得粉碎。', '形容词: disintegrative 名词: disintegrator 过去式: disintegrated 过去分词: disintegrated 现在分词: disintegrating 第三人称单数: disintegrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maintenance', '[\'meɪntənəns]', 'n.维修；维护；保持；生活费用；抚养费', '1. He\'s taking classes in car maintenance. 他正在上汽车维修课。 2. The machinery requires constant maintenance. 这些机器需要经常保养维修。 3. The roof of the ancient temple caved in because of bad maintenance. 那座古老的宙宇由于维护不好屋顶塌了下来。 4. Our policy is maintenance of friendly relations with all countries. 我们的政策是与所有国家保持友好关系。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('valve', '[vælv]', 'n.瓣膜；真空管；阀门；电子管', '1. The valve of the heart allows the blood to pass in one direction only. 心脏的瓣膜使血液只能朝一个方向流动 2. We need a valve detector. 我们需要个真空管检波器。 3. The pump sucks air out (of the vessel) through this valve. 这台泵通过这个阀门把(容器中的)空气抽出。 4. We need an eye bolt to fit this valve. 我们需要一个有眼螺栓来固定这个阀门。', '形容词: valveless 过去式: valved 过去分词: valved 现在分词: valving 第三人称单数: valves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stupor', '[\'stuːpər]', 'n.昏迷；麻木；不省人事', '1. The noise of someone banging at the door roused her from her stupor. 梆梆的敲门声把她从昏迷中唤醒了。 2. Kunta lay numbly, in a kind of stupor. 昆塔麻木地躺在那里，陷于一种痴呆的状态。 3. He lay on the bed in a drunken stupor. 他躺在床上醉的不省人事.', '形容词: stuporous');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crate', '[kreɪt]', 'n.板条箱；篓子；旧汽车 v.装进纸条箱', '1. Someone has sticked a label on the crate. 有人在板条箱上贴了标签。 2. They have sold up ten crates of mineral water in the afternoon. 他们这个下午卖掉了十箱矿泉水。 3. Use an empty crate as a makeshift for a table. 用空板条箱权充桌子。 4. He bought a crate of oranges for his children. 他给孩子买了一箱柳橙。 5. Please crate the paintings before shipping them to the museum. 在海运到博物馆之前把这些油画装入箱中。', '过去式: crated 过去分词: crated 现在分词: crating 第三人称单数: crates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('residue', '[\'rezɪduː]', 'n.残渣；剩余物；[律]剩余财产', '1. The insoluble lead oxide is remained in the residue. 不溶性氧化物相留存在残渣中。 2. This is a kind of brandy distilled from grape or apple residue. 这是种渣酿白兰地酒，由葡萄或苹果残渣酿成的白兰地。 3. The flies leave a sticky residue on crops. 苍蝇在庄稼上留下黏糊糊的东西。 4. The residue of estate belongs to his son. 剩余财产属于他的儿子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('variegate', '[\'verɪˌgeɪt]', 'vt. 使 ... 多样化； 弄成杂色', '1. To diversify(something)in color, shading, or character;variegate. 呈多样化使（某物）在色彩、明暗或性质上多样化；使不同 2. To diversify(something)in color,shading,or character;variegate. 呈多样化使(某物)在色彩、明暗或性质上多样化;使不同 3. To diversify(something) in color, shading, or character; variegate. 呈多样化使（某物）在色彩、明暗或性质上多样化；使不同 4. To diversify(something) in color, shading, or character;variegate. 呈多样化使（某物）在色彩、明暗或性质上多样化；', '名词: variegator 过去式: variegated 过去分词: variegated 现在分词: variegating 第三人称单数: variegates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ingenuous', '[ɪn\'dʒenjuəs]', 'adj.天真的；单纯的；率直的；坦白的', '1. She looked at him with an ingenuous smile. 她带着天真的微笑望着他。 2. He is too ingenuous in believing what people say. 他太天真，轻信别人的话。 3. She\'s an ingenuous country girl. 她是个单纯的乡村姑娘。 4. It was his ingenuous smile that won Deborah\'s heart. 是他率直的微笑赢得了黛博拉的芳心。', '副词: ingenuously 名词: ingenuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exalt', '[ɪɡ\'zɔːlt]', 'v.赞扬；提升；加强', '1. All the people of whom you and I are the rag-tag and bobtail, all the camp followers of western civilization, we have taken it for granted that even if we did not live up to those exalted ethical standards, we did a great deal better than anyone else. 我们所有的人，包括你和我这样的下层平民，以及所有西方文明的依附者都认为，即使我们尚未达到那些崇高的道德标准，我们也还是是比别的任何人都干得好得多。 2. He was exalted to the position of general manager. 他被提升到总经理的职位。', '名词: exalter 过去式: exalted 过去分词: exalted 现在分词: exalting 第三人称单数: exalts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plausible', '[\'plɔːzəbl]', 'adj.似真实合理的；动听的；看起来有道理的，貌似可信的', '1. Such a theory seems very plausible. 这一理论貌似十分有理。 2. He can not find a plausible reason for his absence. 翻译他找不到缺席的合理理由。 3. Though controversial, it is plausible. 虽有争议，却似乎行得通。 4. He trotted out a most plausible story, but most of us were inclined to doubt the truth of it. 他提出了一个听起来很有道理的说法，但我们大多数人对此都持怀疑态度。', '副词: plausibly 名词: plausibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('improvident', '[ɪm\'prɑːvɪdənt]', 'adj.不顾将来的；无远见的；不节约的；不经济的', '1. You will pay for your improvident and undisciplined behavior. 你会为自己轻率任性的行为付出代价的。 2. Her improvident speech at the meeting has set a stone rolling. 她在会上的发言缺乏远见，已产生严重后果。 3. He must bear the consequences of his improvident action. 他必须对自己挥霍浪费所造成的后果负责。 4. Mining likewise was carried on in the most superficial and improvident fashion and consequently the maximum of labor yielded but a minimum of result. 矿业也是在最肤浅而不经济的方式下进行，因此在极大的劳力中获取微小的成果。', '副词: improvidently 名词: improvidence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('breach', '[briːtʃ]', 'n.破坏；违背；决裂；裂口；（浪的）冲击 v.违反；突破；在 ... 上打开缺口', '1. Union officials denounced the action as a breach of the agreement. 工会负责人谴责这一行动破坏了协议。 2. You are in breach of your contract. 你违反了你签的合同。 3. It caused a lifelong breach with his father. 这使得他们父子终身失和。 4. The huge waves made a breach in the sea wall. 大浪在堤上冲出一个缺口。 5. He never do the things breach the benefits of group. 他不做任何违背集体利益的事。', '过去式: breached 过去分词: breached 现在分词: breaching 第三人称单数: breaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vulgar', '[\'vʌlɡər]', 'adj.通俗的；粗俗的；乡土的 n.平民，百姓', '1. Life is a vulgar flare amid the cool radiance. 生命只是惨淡的星光里的平凡的一闪. 2. The vice premier led a vulgar life in his hometown after he resigned. 那位副总理辞职后在故乡过着平民生活。 3. Her taste in clothing is rather vulgar. 她穿着相当俗气。 4. Putting food into one\'s mouth with a knife is considered vulgar in England. 在英国，用刀把食物送进嘴里被认为是粗鲁的行为。', '副词: vulgarly 名词: vulgarness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prolix', '[\'proʊlɪks]', 'adj.罗嗦的；冗长的', '1. Too much speaking makes it a little prolix . 说了那么多，有些罗嗦了。 2. It is too prolix to separate the standard into two parts, because many contents are the same in the two parts. 将标准分为两部分,重复部分过多,显得过于冗长。', '副词: prolixly 名词: prolixity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('summon', '[\'sʌmən]', 'vt.召唤；召集；振奋', '1. I\'ve heard the residents of the Infernos will summon a Diety of Fire to honor any hero who brings them the Grail. 我听说地狱的居民会召唤烈火守护神来纪念为他们带来圣杯的英雄。 2. \"A man brags that he can summon the dead. 一个人炫耀说可以召唤死者灵魂。 3. The shareholders were summoned to a general meeting. 那些股东被召集去叁加股东大会。 4. They had to summon a second conference and change the previous decision. 他们不得不召集第二次会议，改变以前的决定。', '名词: summoner 过去式: summoned 过去分词: summoned 现在分词: summoning 第三人称单数: summons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('medicate', '[\'medɪkeɪt]', 'vt.用药治疗；加药于', '1. A small, flat absorbent pad used to medicate, drain, or protect a wound or sore. 小拭子，小垫子用于加药物、排干或保护伤口或痛处的吸收性的小扁块 2. Be you allergic to any medicate? 你有药物过敏反应吗？', '形容词: medicative 过去式: medicated 过去分词: medicated 现在分词: medicating 第三人称单数: medicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('potentiate', '[pə\'tenʃɪˌeɪt]', 'vt.赋与力量；加强', '1. Drugs potentiate the effect of alcohol. 药物有加强酒精效果的作用。 2. In particular, we consider thrombotic complications, which constitute a major concern when agents that potentiate hemostasis are administered. 尤其是着重注意了血栓性并发症，这一使用止血药物加强凝血功能时最常关心的问题。', '名词: potentiation 过去式: potentiated 过去分词: potentiated 现在分词: potentiating 第三人称单数: potentiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embroil', '[ɪm\'brɔɪl]', 'v.使卷入；使陷入；牵连', '1. I was reluctant to embroil myself in his problems. 我不愿意卷入到他的问题中去。 2. John and Peter were quarreling, but Mary refused to get embroiled in it. 约翰和彼特在争吵，但玛丽不愿卷入他们的纠纷中。', '名词: embroilment 过去式: embroiled 过去分词: embroiled 现在分词: embroiling 第三人称单数: embroils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stint', '[stɪnt]', 'v.节省；限制；<古>停止 n.节约；限制；定额的工作；滨鹬', '1. Don\'t stint on the cream! 不要舍不得放奶油！ 2. We hope that you will not stint your criticism. 请不吝指教。 3. She stinted herself of food in order to let the children have enough. 她自己省着吃，好让孩子们吃饱。 4. Don\'t stint yourself; take all you want. 别拘束,要什么就拿什么。 5. He lavished money on his children without stint. 他在孩子们身上花钱毫不吝惜。', '副词: stintingly 名词: stinter 过去式: stinted 过去分词: stinted 现在分词: stinting 第三人称单数: stints');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shingle', '[\'ʃɪŋɡl]', 'n.小圆石；砂砾；木瓦；屋顶板；<口>小招牌；女子短发式样 v.盖以木瓦；挤压；锻铁', '1. On this beach there\'s too much shingle and not enough sand. 在这个海滩上,圆卵石太多,沙太少。 2. I prefer a sandy beach to a shingle one. 我喜欢沙滩，不喜欢遍布小石子的海滩。 3. The roof of our house is covered by shingles. 我家的屋顶是用木瓦铺的。 4. They lapped one shingle over another in laying a roof. 他们在铺房顶时，使瓦互相搭接起来。', '形容词: shingly 名词: shingler 过去式: shingled 过去分词: shingled 现在分词: shingling 第三人称单数: shingles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('margin', '[\'mɑːrdʒən]', 'n.边缘；余地；幅度；利润；差额；页边空白；定金；【商】原价和卖价之差 vt.加边于；为…付保证金', '1. We came to the margin of the wood. 我们来到树林的边缘。 2. We allowed a margin of 20 minutes in catching the train. 我们有20分钟的余地赶火车。 3. There is no margin for error in our plan. 我们的计划中不留有误差幅度。 4. Our pricing policy aims at producing a 35% gross margin. 我们的定价政策目的在于赢得35%的毛利润。 5. The shore was margined with foam. 岸边都是泡沫。', '形容词: margined 过去式: margined 过去分词: margined 现在分词: margining 第三人称单数: margins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deaden', '[\'dedn]', 'vt.使(感觉、痛苦等)减弱；使隔音 vi 死去；失去活力或光泽；不快乐.', '1. Her feet were deaden with cold. 她的脚都冻得麻木了。 2. Unhappiness had deadened her to the lives of others. 她遭遇不幸,因而对别人的生活也无动于衷。', '名词: deadener 过去式: deadened 过去分词: deadened 现在分词: deadening 第三人称单数: deadens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flock', '[flɑːk]', 'n.一群；兽群；大堆；群众；羊群 v.聚集；成群而行', '1. There are many flocks of tourists in the palace. 宫殿里有好几群游客。 2. A flock of sheep poured through the gate. 一群羊从羊圈口涌了出来。 3. People came in flocks to see the royal procession. 人们蜂拥而至瞻望皇室人员外出时的仪仗队。 4. A few sheep have been lost from the flock. 羊群里少了几只羊。 5. Huge numbers of birds have flocked together by the lake. 成群的鸟聚集在湖畔。', '过去式: flocked 过去分词: flocked 现在分词: flocking 第三人称单数: flocks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cleave', '[kliːv]', 'v.裂开；分开（尤指沿天然纹理）；使分开；穿过；依恋或忠实；粘着', '1. This wood cleaves easily. 这种木材容易劈开。 2. He cleaved an apple with a knife. 他用一把刀子将苹果切开。 3. A strong blow will cleave a plank in two. 强烈打击将使木板裂成两块。 4. They cleaved a path through the wilderness. 他们在荒原中开辟出一条路。', '形容词: cleavable 过去式: cleft/cleaved/clove 过去分词: cleft/cleaved/cloven 现在分词: cleaving 第三人称单数: cleaves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chagrin', '[ʃə\'ɡrɪn]', 'n.懊恼 v.使 ... 懊恼', '1. Much to his chagrin, he do not win the race. 他没能赢那场比赛，大为懊丧。 2. He noted with chagrin how little hair clung to his head. 他苦恼地发现原来他头上的毛发是那么的稀疏。', '过去式: chagrined 过去分词: chagrined 现在分词: chagrining 第三人称单数: chagrins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bale', '[beɪl]', 'n.包；捆；灾祸；不幸 v.将 ... 打包', '1. The cloth was packed in bales. 布已经打成包。 2. I sat on a bale of straw near the fire. 我坐在炉火边的一捆稻草上。 3. The bale will be coming. 不幸就要降临了。', '名词: baler 过去式: baled 过去分词: baled 现在分词: baling 第三人称单数: bales');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shuttle', '[\'ʃʌtl]', 'n.梭子；穿梭；往返移动之物；航天飞机 v.往返运送；穿梭移动', '1. The shuttle flies back and forth on the loom. 织布机上梭子来回飞动。 2. He refined the whole art of shuttle diplomacy. 他把穿梭外交艺术提高到炉火纯青的地步。 3. There is a shuttle service between the city center and the air station. 在市中心和飞机场之间有往返的穿梭运行班车。 4. The U.S. made the first space shuttle in the world. 美国制造了世界上第一架航天飞机。 5. We shuttled the passengers to the city center by helicopter. 我们来来回回地用直升机把旅客运送到市中心。', '名词: shuttler 过去式: shuttled 过去分词: shuttled 现在分词: shuttling 第三人称单数: shuttles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('caveat', '[\'kæviæt]', 'n.防止误解的说明；警告', '1. I would offer a caveat for those who want to join me in the dual calling. 为防止发生误解，我想对那些想要步我后尘的人提出警告。 2. I recommend the deal, but with certain caveats. 我介绍这笔交易，但有几项要提请注意。 3. Is there a caveat in all this bustle? 所有这些急剧的变化有什么警示吗? 4. This last recommendation comes with a caveat: drinking no alcohol is clearly better than drinking too much. 最后这项建议附有一条警告：不喝酒比饮酒过多要好得多。', '过去式: caveated/caveatted 过去分词: caveated/caveatted 现在分词: caveating/caveatting 第三人称单数: caveats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('badger', '[\'bædʒər]', 'n.獾；獾皮(毛) Badger:獾州人(对威斯康星州人的昵称). v.纠缠；一再烦扰；吵着要', '1. The Badger strode heavily into the room. 獾大步流星地跨进房间。 2. A badger jumped out of a small tunnel. 一只獾从一个小地洞里跳了出来。 3. You can\'t badger me into going to the party. 你不能纠缠我去参加聚会。 4. Reporters constantly badger her about her private life. 记者经常纠缠着打听她的私生活。', '过去式: badgered 过去分词: badgered 现在分词: badgering 第三人称单数: badgers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('affiliation', '[əˌfɪli\'eɪʃn]', 'n.加入；入会；联系；附属机构，分公司，分部；结交，交往', '1. You need the affiliation of investor. 你需要投资者的加入。 2. The society has many affiliations throughout the country. 这个社团在全国有很多关系. 3. Risk is always having affiliation with its impact on practice. 风险总是和效用联系在一起的。 4. Participation in social groups in the community is independent of religious affiliation, and one\'s circle of friends will include people of a variety of denominations. 社会上的社交团体是不管哪个教派的人都可以参加的，而一个人的社交范围包括各种教派的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('craft', '[kræft]', 'n.工艺；手艺；狡诈；船舶；航空器；行会成员 vt.手工制作；精心制作', '1. He graduated from a school of crafts and arts. 他毕业于一所工艺美术学校。 2. He learned his craft from an old master. 他从一位老匠人那儿学得他的手艺。 3. By crafts the gambler tricked them out of all their money. 那个赌徒用诡计赢去了他们所有的钱。 4. Hundreds of small craft accompany the liner into harbour. 数百只小艇随同这艘班轮驶入港湾。 5. He told us a carefully crafted story. 他给我们讲了一个精心编织的故事。', '名词: crafter 过去式: crafted 过去分词: crafted 现在分词: crafting 第三人称单数: crafts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('soluble', '[\'sɑːljəbl]', 'adj.可溶解的；可解决的', '1. Soluble metallic hydroxides are bases that are alkalies. 可溶解的金属氢氧化合物都是碱。 2. A subsequent wet depithing serves to remove soluble and strongly adhering pith. 后续的除髓工序可以继续除去可溶解的和粘附牢固的蔗髓。', '副词: solubly 名词: solubleness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rakish', '[\'reɪkɪʃ]', 'adj.放荡的；轻快的；潇洒的；(船)外形灵巧的', '1. She wore her hat at a rakish angle. 她把帽子戴得吊儿郎当的。 2. He plays the novel\'s rakish hero. 他扮演小说中放荡的主人公。 3. He looked as if he had glued the rakish beard on to his solemn face. 他看上去就象是把流云般的胡须贴在他庄重的脸上一样。 4. The rakish actor was known for dating models. 那位风流倜傥的演员爱跟模特儿交往是出了名的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drawl', '[drɔːl]', 'v.拖长声调说话 n.慢吞吞拉长调子的说话方式', '1. He drawled a greeting to her. 他慢吞吞地对她说声问候。 2. She drawled in that slow, lazy style of hers. 她以她那种缓慢的、懒洋洋的方式拖长声调地说话。 3. She speaks with a Southern drawl. 她讲话带着美国南方人慢吞吞的拉长调子的语气。 4. He had a bit of a Southern drawl. 他说话有点南方人慢吞吞拖长音调的口音。', '名词: drawler 过去式: drawled 过去分词: drawled 现在分词: drawling 第三人称单数: drawls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anthropologist', '[ˌænθrə\'pɑːlədʒɪst]', 'n.人类学家', '1. The anthropologist contrasted two cultures in his lecture. 这位人类学家在讲座中将两种文化进行对比。 2. To my surprise, the anthropologist was accused of murder. 令我大吃一惊的是，那位人类学家竟然被控谋杀。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alias', '[\'eɪliəs]', 'n.别名；化名 adv.又被称为；另外地', '1. The name is not an official host name or alias. 该名称不是正式的主机名或别名。 2. It is not permitted for an alias to refer to another alias. 不允许一个别名参考另一个别名。 3. He checked into the hotel under an alias. 他用化名登记住进旅馆。 4. The thief\'s real name was John Smith, alias Edward Ball. 这小偷的真名是约翰史密斯，化名叫爱德华鲍尔。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ungainly', '[ʌn\'ɡeɪnli]', 'adj.笨拙的；难看的；不雅的', '1. He walked in long ungainly strides. 他迈着笨拙的大步子行走。 2. I thought him terribly ungainly when he danced. 我觉得他跳舞极其难看。', '比较级: ungainlier 最高级: ungainliest 名词: ungainliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prick', '[prɪk]', 'v.刺；扎；竖起；受责备 n.扎；刺；刺痛；<俚>蠢人', '1. The thorns of roses prick rather badly. 玫瑰刺刺得很痛。 2. I am afraid I have to prick your finger and take a drop of blood. 我恐怕不得不刺破你的手指，取一滴血。 3. She pricked herself on a needle. 她被针扎了一下。 4. The rabbit stopped suddenly, pricking up its ears. 兔子突然停下来，竖起自己的耳朵。 5. The needle left a prick in the tailor\'s finger. 裁缝的手指上有个针扎的孔。', '过去式: pricked 过去分词: pricked 现在分词: pricking 第三人称单数: pricks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stroll', '[stroʊl]', 'n.闲逛；漫步 v.闲逛；漫步', '1. She decided to take a stroll in the garden. 她决定在花园散步。 2. A stroll round the garden hardly qualifies as exercise! 在花园转转算不上锻炼！ 3. My father sometimes goes out for a stroll with a stick in his hand. 父亲有时候带着手杖出去散步。 4. A casual stroll through a lunatic asylum shows that faith does not prove anything. 疯人院的一次闲庭漫步说明信念并不能证明一切。 5. We stroll through a meadow full of tall grass. 我们漫步走过长满高草的牧场。', '过去式: strolled 过去分词: strolled 现在分词: strolling 第三人称单数: strolls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bawdy', '[\'bɔːdi]', 'adj.淫猥的；下流的', '1. After a few drinks, they were all singing bawdy songs at the top of their voices. 喝了几杯酒之后，他们就扯着嗓门唱一些下流歌曲。', '副词: bawdily 比较级: bawdier 最高级: bawdiest 名词: bawdiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sensual', '[\'senʃuəl]', 'adj.肉欲的；色情的；世俗的；感官的；感觉论的', '1. He lived a life devoted entirely to sensual pleasure. 他一生耽于肉欲。 2. The first wife is in fact our soul, often neglected in our pursuit of material, wealth and sensual pleasure. 第一个其实在我们的灵魂深处，在我们追求物质，财富，色情的时候经常忽略她。 3. A glutton derives sensual pleasures from eating. 暴食者可从吃中得到感官上的愉悦。', '副词: sensually 名词: sensualness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('multitude', '[\'mʌltɪtuːd]', 'n.大量；多数；群众', '1. A multitude of heroic figures emerge. 大量英雄人物出现了。 2. An angry multitude collected in the street. 街道上聚集了一大群愤怒的人。 3. There are a multitude of reasons against it. 有许多反对理由。 4. The multitude may laugh at his music, but we know better. 一般人也许会嘲笑他的音乐，但我们更了解它。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fractional', '[\'frækʃənl]', 'adj.微不足道的；断片的；分数的；小数的', '1. The difference between bus and rail fares is fractional. 公共汽车费与火车费相差无几。 2. In this case the fractional part is discarded. 在此情况下小数部分被丢掉了。', '副词: fractionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distinct', '[dɪ\'stɪŋkt]', 'adj.明显的；清晰的；不同的；独特的', '1. There is a distinct possibility that she\'ll be your teacher next term. 她下学期当你们的老师的可能性非常大。 2. On the contrary, he was looking at Harry with distinct pride. 相反,他望着哈利的目光中带着明显的自豪。 3. There\'s a distinct smell of cigarettes every time he comes into the room. 他每次进房间,都带着一股浓重的烟味。 4. Two people may both dream of the other,and find that their dreams had a distinct connection. 两个人可能互相梦见对方,而且发现他们的梦有着清晰的联系。', '副词: distinctly 名词: distinctness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pirouette', '[ˌpɪru\'et]', 'n.(舞蹈)脚尖立地的旋转 vi.用脚尖旋转', '1. She turned a pirouette on the ice. 她在冰上做了个单足旋转动作。 2. The skater executed a triple pirouette. 这位滑冰者完成了一次三周单腿旋转。 3. You mean you can pirouette and all that sort of thing? 你的意思是你能“单脚着地旋转”和做诸如此类的动作？', '过去式: pirouetted 过去分词: pirouetted 现在分词: pirouetting 第三人称单数: pirouettes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('self-abasement', '[ˌselfə\'beɪsmənt]', 'n.自卑；自谦', '1. Each confession brought her into an attitude of abasement. 每次忏悔都让她感到自卑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('asterisk', '[\'æstərɪsk]', 'n.星号(*)', '1. The asterisked questions may be omitted. 带星号的问题可以略去。', '过去式: asterisked 过去分词: asterisked 现在分词: asterisking 第三人称单数: asterisks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('separate', '[\'sepərət]', 'adj.分开的；不同的；单独的；各自的 v.分开；隔开；区分；分居；脱离 n.分开；抽印本', '1. Can these two definitions be conflated, or must they be kept separate? 这两个定义可以合成一个呢，还是必须分开? 2. I advocate separate classes for students to learn Chinese in different ways. 我建议我们分班授课，让不同的学生以不同的方式学习华文。 3. We don\'t have a separate dining room—the living area is all one. 我们没有单独的饭厅——活动空间都在一处。 4. The house is divided into two living units or residences, usually having separate entrances. 房屋分为两个居住部分,一般具有各自的出口。 5. We\'d better separate the good ones from the bad ones. 我们最好把好的和坏的分开。 6. Nothing can separate them from each other now. 现在什么也不能把他们彼此分开了。', '副词: separately 名词: separateness 过去式: separated 过去分词: separated 现在分词: separating 第三人称单数: separates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fragment', '[\'fræɡmənt]', 'n.碎片；片段 v.使破碎；分裂', '1. She dropped the vase on the floor and it broke into fragments. 她把花瓶掉在地上，摔成了碎片。 2. There\'s a fragment of glass in the wound. 伤口内有玻璃碎片。 3. Her hand was cut by a fragment of glass. 她的手被一块玻璃碎片划破了。 4. I overheard a fragment of their conversation. 我无意中听到他们谈话的片段。 5. These bullets fragment on impact. 这些子弹射中物体时爆炸成碎片。', '过去式: fragmented 过去分词: fragmented 现在分词: fragmenting 第三人称单数: fragments');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('goodwill', '[ˌɡʊd\'wɪl]', 'n.善意；亲切；友好；商誉；信誉', '1. Letters provide a means of promoting goodwill. 信件意味着一种善意。 2. She gave repeated assurances of your goodwill. 关于你的善意,她一而再地作出保证。 3. This is a good time to create goodwill and trust between yourself and others. 今天适宜在你自己和他人之间建立亲切与信任。 4. He attended the meeting as a goodwill messenger. 他作为友好使者出席了会议。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('existential', '[ˌeɡzɪ\'stenʃəl]', 'adj.有关存在的；存在判断的', '1. Existential literature is a literature of life and philosophy. 存在文学是一种人生文学、哲学文学。 2. Also at work is our existential anxiety, the fear of death and the unknown. 存在的焦虑，以及对死亡和未知事物的恐惧，也在发挥作用。 3. Linguistics have been arguing about some ideas in English existential sentence. 关于英语存在句的某些观点,语言学家们一直争论不休。 4. Formal logicians are not concerned with existential matters. 真正的逻辑学家不关心与存在判断有关的问题。', '副词: existentially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coarse', '[kɔːrs]', 'adj.粗糙的；粗俗的；非精制的', '1. The medicine powder is too coarse, keep grinding it. 药面太粗了，再磨细点。 2. His coarse manners shocked everyone. 他的粗鲁的举止使每个人震惊。', '副词: coarsely 比较级: coarser 最高级: coarsest 名词: coarseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abrasion', '[ə\'breɪʒn]', 'n.擦伤；磨损；磨损处', '1. She was treated for cuts and abrasions. 她的割伤和擦伤得到了治疗。 2. Diamonds have extreme resistance to abrasion. 钻石极抗磨损。 3. The rivet heads on the bucket are in good condition and without severe abrasion. 扣件铆钉钉头状况良好，并无严重磨损。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contaminate', '[kən\'tæməˌneɪt]', 'vt.弄脏；污染', '1. Contaminate your bed, and you will one night suffocate in your own waste. 如果你弄脏了自己的环境，总有一天会窒息在你所丢弃的垃圾之中。 2. All over the world, oil spills regularly contaminate coasts. 在世界各地，油溢出物经常污染着海岸。 3. They are contaminating the minds of our young people with these subversive ideas. 他们这些颠覆性的思想是对我们年轻人的精神污染。', '形容词: contaminative 名词: contaminator 过去式: contaminated 过去分词: contaminated 现在分词: contaminating 第三人称单数: contaminates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skyrocket', '[\'skaɪrɑːkɪt]', 'n. 冲天火箭（烟火） vt. 使 ... 上升； 发射 vi. 陡升； 猛涨', '1. Through the first week in June, as cases began to skyrocket in Australia, WHO continued to put off the final call. 虽然六月第一周里澳大利亚的病例显著上升，但世卫组织依然推迟最后的升级。 2. In the end, the quality of video and audio will skyrocket without undue stress on the network. 最后，由于在网上没有了过度的压力，视频和声频的质量将猛涨。', '过去式: skyrocketed 过去分词: skyrocketed 现在分词: skyrocketing 第三人称单数: skyrockets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dodge', '[dɑːdʒ]', 'v.避开；躲避 n.躲避；诡计', '1. He dodged past me. 他躲躲闪闪地从我旁边走过。 2. He dodged the falling rock and escaped unhurt. 他闪身躲过了滚落的岩石，安然脱险了。 3. She was sharp-witted enough to dodge her attacker. 她才思敏捷足以避开别人的攻击。 4. The man jumped aside to dodge the speeding truck. 这人跳到旁边以躲避疾驶的卡车。 5. Do you like to go playing dodge ball with us? 要不要和我们一起去打躲避球?', '过去式: dodged 过去分词: dodged 现在分词: dodging 第三人称单数: dodges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sordid', '[\'sɔːrdɪd]', 'adj.卑鄙的；不诚实的；肮脏的；破烂的', '1. He has sordid motives on us. 他对我们有卑鄙的动机。 2. I want no part of this sordid business. 我决不卷入这一卑鄙勾当。 3. I didn\'t want to hear the sordid details of their relationship. 我不想听他们之间的那些龌龊细节。 4. The slum area was sordid and filthy beyond belief. 该贫民区之污秽肮脏简直令人难以置信。', '副词: sordidly 名词: sordidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('etymology', '[ˌetɪ\'mɑːlədʒi]', 'n.语源；词源学', '1. This dictionary does not give etymologies. 这部词典不介绍词源。 2. The hippies\' etymology is contentious. 关于嬉皮士的语源是有争议的。 3. As we learn about interesting words we will look at their etymology. 随着我们不断学习到新的有趣词汇，我们将进一步学习词源。 4. From the etymology speaking, anthropology is the study of science. 从语源学上讲，人类学是研究人的科学。', '名词复数: etymologies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bid', '[bɪd]', 'v.（买方）出价；投标；吩咐；叫牌 n.出价；努力；叫牌', '1. She bid 500 for the painting. 她喊价500买这幅画。 2. Several firms have bid for the contract to build the new concert hall. 有几家公司投标，争取建造新音乐厅的合同。 3. Several companies are bidding for the contract to build the bridge. 有几家公司在投标争取承包建桥工程。 4. Do as you are bidden. 按照吩咐你的去做。 5. He made a bid of 50 for a painting. 他为一幅画出价50英镑。', '名词: bidder 过去式: bade/bid 过去分词: bidden/bid 现在分词: bidding 第三人称单数: bids');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hypertension', '[ˌhaɪpər\'tenʃn]', 'n.高血压；过度紧张', '1. They claim that hypertension has numerous causes. 他们认为高血压有许多原因。 2. Hypertension is not an unusual occurrence in the PACU. 麻醉后监护室患者经常出现高血压。', '形容词: hypertensive');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coat', '[koʊt]', 'n.外套；上衣；层；表皮 vt.涂上；覆盖；包上', '1. You may hang your coat on the hook. 你可以把外套挂在钩子上。 2. She was wearing a woolen coat, with a cotton blouse underneath. 她外面穿了一件毛外套，里面穿一件棉布衬衫。 3. Jane bought a fur coat yesterday. 简昨天买了一件裘皮大衣。 4. One of the buttons has come off my coat. 我上衣上的一颗扣子掉了。 5. The bookshelves were coated with red paint. 书架上涂了一层红色的油漆。', '形容词: coated 过去式: coated 过去分词: coated 现在分词: coating 第三人称单数: coats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unworldly', '[ʌn\'wɜːrldli]', 'adj.超凡的；超脱世俗的；天真的', '1. The landscape had a stark, unworldly beauty. 那景色有一种简朴、超凡的美。 2. I am just a weltfremd, unworldly, young man. 我只是个与世无争的年轻人。 3. I grew up in an unworldly blue-collar environment. 我在一个并不世俗的蓝领家庭环境长大。', '比较级: unworldlier 最高级: unworldliest 名词: unworldliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blunder', '[\'blʌndər]', 'n.大错 v.失策；绊倒；弄糟', '1. He made a blunder in front of his girlfriend. 他在女朋友面前犯了大错。 2. I saw that I had been guilty of a careless blunder. 我意识到自己因疏忽而酿成大错。 3. I made a terrible blunder in introducing her to my husband. 我把她介绍给我的丈夫是犯了一个极大的错误。 4. I hope you will not blunder again . 我希望你不要再犯大错。', '副词: blunderingly 名词: blunderer 过去式: blundered 过去分词: blundered 现在分词: blundering 第三人称单数: blunders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('feint', '[feɪnt]', 'n.伪装；佯装攻击 v.佯攻；佯击 adj.（纸等）印有隐格线的', '1. He made a feint of working hard. 他装作努力工作。 2. Softness and consideration is probably a temporary feint. 温柔体贴可能只是一时的假象。 3. The feint on the army\'s left flank was followed by a frontal attack. 先佯攻军队的左翼，紧接的是一个正面攻击。 4. The fighter feinted with his right hand and struck with his left. 拳击手用右手虚幌一下而用左手打出去。', '过去式: feinted 过去分词: feinted 现在分词: feinting 第三人称单数: feints');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('attest', '[ə\'test]', 'v.证明；作证', '1. Several witnesses can attest to her good character. 好几位证人证实她品行端正。 2. The child\'s good health attests to his mother\'s care. 孩子的健康证实他母亲的悉心照料。 3. No one can attest to the absolute truth of his statement. 没有人可以证明他的话是绝对正确的。 4. I can attest to the truth of his words. 我可以证实他的话是真的。', '名词: attestant 过去式: attested 过去分词: attested 现在分词: attesting 第三人称单数: attests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confidant', '[ˌkɒnfɪ\'dænt]', 'n.心腹朋友；知己', '1. The artless woman had made a confidant of the boy. 这个心地单纯的女人把孩子当作心腹朋友。 2. She unbosomed her secret to her confidant. 她向知己吐露自己的秘密。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incubus', '[\'ɪŋkjʊbəs]', 'n.恶梦；负担；梦淫妖(据说会趁女人熟睡而与其交配的恶鬼)', '1. Joyce regarded his US citizenship as a moral and political incubus. 乔伊斯把他的美国公民身份当做是一个道德和政治上的负担。', '名词复数: incubuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crayon', '[\'kreɪən]', 'n.蜡笔；蜡笔画 v.以蜡笔作画', '1. The baby daubed up the wall with his crayon. 小孩用蜡笔把墙上画得斑斑点点。 2. The boy wants to draw in crayon. 这个男孩想用蜡笔画画。', '名词: crayonist 过去式: crayoned 过去分词: crayoned 现在分词: crayoning 第三人称单数: crayons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wigwag', '[\'wɪgˌwæg]', 'v.摇摆；挥；摇 n.旗子信号；手光信号', '1. Yet I know and you know people who blunder through life trying to wigwag other people into becoming interested in them. 然而，你我都知道，有人终身的错误，就是只想别人关心他，对他发生兴趣。 2. You should wigwag the rubber hammer not more than 40cm otherwise you would damage the tile. 其余部分敲击力量适当控制。 3. Watched the pendulum wigwag. 观察钟摆的摆动 4. to wigwag the flags 晃动旗子', '名词: wigwagger 过去式: wigwagged 过去分词: wigwagged 现在分词: wigwagging 第三人称单数: wigwags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flail', '[fleɪl]', 'v.挥动；用连迦打；敲打 n.连迦', '1. The baby\'s legs flailed under the quilt. 小孩的两条小腿在被子下面乱动。 2. The flail is often not used today, but in the past it was indispensable for grinding crops. 连耞虽然平时不常使用, 但在打碾庄稼的时节, 谁家也离不开它。', '过去式: flailed 过去分词: flailed 现在分词: flailing 第三人称单数: flails');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discretion', '[dɪ\'skreʃn]', 'n.谨慎；慎重；自行决定', '1. We reposed great trust in his tact and discretion. 我们极为信任他的机智和谨慎。 2. You must choose you friends with discretion. 你一定要慎重地择友。 3. I won\'t tell you what time to leave, you\'re old enough to use your own discretion. 我不告诉你什么时候离开，你已经长大了，该自己作出决定。 4. The hours of the meetings will be fixed at the monitor\'s discretion. 开会时间将由班长自行决定。', '形容词: discretional 副词: discretionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('piquant', '[\'piːkənt]', 'adj.辛辣的；开胃的；刺激的；令人兴奋的', '1. Bland vegetables are often served with a piquant sauce. 清淡的蔬菜常以辛辣的沙司调味。 2. He heard of a piquant bit of news. 他听到了一则令人兴奋的消息。', '副词: piquantly 名词: piquancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('outgoing', '[\'aʊtɡoʊɪŋ]', 'adj.外向的；即将离职的；出发的', '1. He is an outgoing and lively person. 他是个性格开朗而又活泼的人。 2. My twin brother is more outgoing than me. 我的双胞胎兄弟比我更外向。 3. I was totally affected by this outgoing girl. 我被这个性格外向的女孩子深深感染了。 4. He is the outgoing chairperson. 他就是那位即将离职的主席。', '名词: outgoingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bemused', '[bɪ\'mjuːzd]', 'adj.困惑的；发呆的 动词bemuse的过去式和过去分词.', '1. He was looking at them with a bemused expression. 他困惑地瞪着他们。 2. He is totally bemused by the traffic system in the city. 这城市里的交通制度把他完全弄糊涂了。 3. He greeted me with a bemused look. 他欢迎我时,满脸呆若木鸡的表情。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vituperative', '[vɪ\'tjuːpərətɪv]', 'adj.辱骂的；责骂的', '1. Internet chatrooms are full of vituperative anti-foreign sentiment. 互联网聊天室里充斥着谩骂式的反外情绪。 2. I was really taken aback by their vituperative animosity toward the Soviet Union. 他们对苏联如此深恶痛绝，着实令我吃惊。 3. China changed its mind after vituperative outbursts online by nationalists. 民族主义者在网上责骂之后，中国政府改变了想法。', '副词: vituperatively 名词: vituperativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swarthy', '[\'swɔːrði]', 'adj.黑黝黝的', '1. She has a swarthy complexion. 她的肤色黝黑。', '副词: swarthily 比较级: swarthier 最高级: swarthiest 名词: swarthiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('treacherous', '[\'tretʃərəs]', 'adj.背信弃义的；背叛的；不可靠的；危险的', '1. You treacherous cur! 你这个背信弃义的家伙！ 2. He is treacherous to his friends. 他对他的朋友不忠。 3. My memory is treacherous. 我的记忆靠不住。 4. The road becomes treacherous when it is iced up. 道路结冰以后就很危险了。', '副词: treacherously 名词: treacherousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('analgesia', '[ˌænəl\'dʒiːʒə]', 'n.痛觉缺失', '1. Promethazine 5mg and Nacl 50ml jo int analgesia. B组患儿采用氯丙嗪5mg+异丙嗪5mg+生理盐水50ml。 2. Labor Analgesia: Is There an Ideal Technique? 有一种理想的分娩镇痛技术吗？ 3. ObjectiveTo study the mechanism of analgesia o f bru cine. 目的研究马钱子碱镇痛作用的机制。 4. Conclusion: Intranasal sufentanil for analgesia is safe and useful. 结论：经鼻滴入舒芬太尼镇痛安全有效。', '形容词: analgetic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bromide', '[\'broʊmaɪd]', 'n.[化]溴化物；陈词滥调；令人讨厌的人；平庸的人', '1. Experimental work indicates that about 14%of the bromide in sea water precipitates with the halite as sea water evaporates. 实验工作证明', '形容词: bromidic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comprehend', '[ˌkɑːmprɪ\'hend]', 'vt.充分理解；领悟；包括', '1. I cannot comprehend this phrase. 我无法理解这个片语。 2. If you can use a word correctly and effectively you comprehend it. 你如果可以正确有效地使用一个词，你就是了解它了。 3. The child couldn\'t comprehend the text. 这孩子不懂该课文的含义。 4. The park comprehends all the land on the other side of the river. 这个公园包括河对岸的所有地方。', '形容词: comprehendible 副词: comprehendingly 过去式: comprehended 过去分词: comprehended 现在分词: comprehending 第三人称单数: comprehends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obdurate', '[\'ɑːbdərət]', 'adj.固执的；顽固的；冷酷的', '1. He is obdurate in his convictions. 他执着于自己所坚信的事。 2. He remained obdurate, refusing to alter his decision. 他依然固执己见 3. The child\'s misery would move even the most obdurate heart. 这个孩子所受的苦难会打动世界上最冷酷的心。', '副词: obdurately 名词: obdurateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('renege', '[rɪ\'niːɡ]', 'v.背信；违约', '1. Any more colourful candidate could renege on a deal. 任何不同政见的候选人都可能就此交易而报复。 2. You will almost surely have to renege on some of these promises. 你却几乎必然将违背你的一些诺言。 3. It says firmly that the EU must not renege on its promise. 报告非常坚定地声称欧盟一定不会食言。 4. But there is also a temptation to renege to gain sales, much as one prisoner might end up ratting on another. 但违背约定，降低价格来赢得销售也很诱人，正如其中一个囚徒会出卖同伴，先说出供词。', '名词: reneger 过去式: reneged 过去分词: reneged 现在分词: reneging 第三人称单数: reneges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trilogy', '[\'trɪlədʒi]', 'n.三部曲', '1. He is best know for his trilogy on working life. 他以描写工人阶级生活的三部曲而著名。 2. As the second part of this trilogy it compares with the second act in a play. 作为这个三部曲中的第二部，它就象一出戏剧中的第二幕。', '名词复数: trilogies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('culmination', '[ˌkʌlmɪ\'neɪʃn]', 'n.顶点；最高潮', '1. The show marked the culmination of months of hard work. 这场演出标志着几个月艰辛工作的最终成果。 2. The space race reached its culmination in the first moon walk. 太空竞争以第一次在月球行走而达到顶峰。 3. It may truly be regarded as the culmination of classical Greek geometry. 这确实可以看成是古典希腊几何的登峰造级之作。 4. The culmination of love is blindness. 爱情的最高潮就是愚昧。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sediment', '[\'sedɪmənt]', 'n.沉淀物', '1. He emptied out the water barrel to clear it of sediment. 他把水桶倒空以清掉桶底的沉淀物。 2. If you are replacing the bottom element, remove the accumulated sediment on the bottom of the tank. 如果是拆卸下部加热元件，需要清除累积在内胆底部的沉淀物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('importune', '[ˌɪmpɔːr\'tuːn]', 'v.强求；硬要；胡搅蛮缠 adj.胡搅蛮缠的', '1. It is not cost-efficient that sometimes we make ourselves exhausted just to importune something. 有时候为了强求一样东西而令自己的身心都疲惫不堪，是很不划算的。', '副词: importunely 名词: importuner 过去式: importuned 过去分词: importuned 现在分词: importuning 第三人称单数: importunes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('archer', '[\'ɑːrtʃər]', 'n.射箭运动员；弓箭手 Archer. n.射手座；阿切尔(姓氏)', '1. How does the archer aims at the target? 箭手是如何瞄准的? 2. The archer who won the game is very young. 获得冠军的那个弓箭手很年轻。 3. I am the best archer in our college. 我是我们学校最好的射手。 4. A good archer is not known by his arrows but his aim. 神箭手因其射中靶子而非因其箭而闻名。 5. Sagittarius, the Archer, is the ninth astrological sign in Zodiac. 人马座', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stationary', '[\'steɪʃəneri]', 'adj.静止的，不动的；稳定的 n.驻军', '1. He crashed into a stationary bus. 他撞了一辆停着不动的公共汽车。 2. A stationary object is easy to be aimed at. 一个静止不动的物体是容易瞄准的。 3. An astronaut will attempt to leave the stationary spaceship and then return to it. 一名宇航员试着离开静止不动的宇宙飞船，然后再返回。', '名词: stationariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swamp', '[swɑːmp]', 'n.沼泽；湿地；困境 v.淹没；使陷于困境；使忙于应付', '1. In the swamp we were beset by mosquitoes. 我们在沼泽地受到蚊子的围攻。 2. The heavy rain has turned the small garden into a swamp. 大雨使这小花园变成了一块沼泽地。 3. Walk through the swamp and we can see the hunter\'s cabin. 走过这片湿地就能看到猎人的小屋了。 4. Their company is in a financial swamp. 他们的公司陷入了财政困境。 5. In summer visitors swamp the island. 夏天，这个岛上熙熙攘攘，人满为患。', '形容词: swampy 名词: swampiness 过去式: swamped 过去分词: swamped 现在分词: swamping 第三人称单数: swamps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chaff', '[tʃæf]', 'n.谷壳；糠；揶揄 v.开玩笑；戏弄', '1. The girl is winnowing the chaff from the corn. 那个女孩正在簸去谷壳。 2. An old bird is not to be caught with chaff. 谷壳捉不到老鸟。 3. They are sorting out the wheat from the chaff. 他们正在把小麦从糠皮中拣出来。 4. We often chaff him for his fear of his wife. 我们常常拿他的怕老婆开玩笑。', '形容词: chaffy 过去式: chaffed 过去分词: chaffed 现在分词: chaffing 第三人称单数: chaffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sinister', '[\'sɪnɪstər]', 'adj.邪恶的；不祥的；灾难性的；左边的', '1. He showed his sinister motive at last. 他终于露出了他那邪恶的用心。 2. The author\'s laconic prose manages to be both dexterous and sinister. 这位作者简洁的文字做到既洗练又有邪恶的暗示。 3. Maston was oppressed by sinister forebodings. 梅斯顿感到自己被一种不祥的预感紧紧地抓住了。 4. Events began to take on a more sinister aspect. 事情开始呈现较为不祥的征兆。', '副词: sinisterly 名词: sinisterness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ranger', '[\'reɪndʒər]', 'n.守林人；骑警；突击队员；漫游者', '1. He was the head ranger of the national park. 他曾是国家公园的首席看守员。 2. Ranger must be ready to deal with emergencies of all kinds. 国家公园管理员必须随时准备好处理各种紧急情况。 3. Davidson says he\'s the lowest man on the Ranger totem pole. 大卫森说他是骑警阶层最低的。 4. I\'m a retired U.S. Army Ranger and a combat veteran. 我是美国突击队的退役队员 还是个经验丰富的老兵', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verify', '[\'verɪfaɪ]', 'vt.核实；证明', '1. He tried in every way to verify this theory. 他想一切办法来验证这个理论。 2. Men were sent out to verify whether it was true. 几个人被派去查清事实。 3. The truth verified the allegations. 事实证明了这些说法。 4. The reader should verify this calculation. 此式可由读者自行证明。', '名词: verifier 过去式: verified 过去分词: verified 现在分词: verifying 第三人称单数: verifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gravitate', '[\'ɡrævɪteɪt]', 'v.受吸引；下沉；重力吸引，受重力作用；移动，移向', '1. When this beautiful girl arrived, all the men in the room gravitated towards her. 这美貌的姑娘一到，全屋的男人都让她吸引住了。 2. In summer people gravitate to the seaside. 夏天的海边吸引人们。 3. The planets gravitate to (towards) the sun. 行星绕着太阳运行。', '名词: gravitater 过去式: gravitated 过去分词: gravitated 现在分词: gravitating 第三人称单数: gravitates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overstate', '[ˌoʊvər\'steɪt]', 'v.夸大的叙述；夸张', '1. It is hard to overstate what is at stake. 现实情形之紧急，再怎么夸张也不为过。', '名词: overstatement 过去式: overstated 过去分词: overstated 现在分词: overstating 第三人称单数: overstates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accessory', '[ək\'sesəri]', 'n.附件；配件；同谋 adj.辅助的；附属的；同谋的', '1. He asked me to buy him some accessories for a car. 他让我给他买些汽车附件。 2. Every item shall include a standard complement of accessories and special tools to ensure the normal operation. 为保证设备的正常运转，每个品目都应包括一套标准定额的附件和专用工具。 3. This silk scarf is the perfect accessory for stylish summer evenings. 这条丝绸围巾对于这个时髦的夏日夜晚,是再合适不过的配件了。 4. He is Tom\'s accessory. 他是汤姆的帮凶。 5. He was using his accessory muscles of respiration. 他在用呼吸辅助肌进行呼吸。', '形容词: accessorial 副词: accessorily 名词: accessoriness 名词复数: accessories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fume', '[fjuːm]', 'n.烟；汽；愤怒 v.冒烟；愤怒', '1. The fireman was suffocated by the fumes. 那个消防队员让浓烟憋死了。 2. The fume caused by coalburning is one of the main air pollutants in China. 燃煤烟尘是我国最主要的大气污染物之一。 3. The ground was hidden by a white fume. 地面上笼罩着一层白色的水汽。 4. Mother was in a fume this morning. 今天早上妈妈很生气。 5. The burnt heaps of wood were still fuming. 燃烧的木堆仍在冒着烟。', '过去式: fumed 过去分词: fumed 现在分词: fuming 第三人称单数: fumes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glare', '[ɡler]', 'n.闪耀光；刺眼 v.发眩光；瞪视', '1. I like turning a corner from the shade of a house into the full torrid glare of an open space. 我喜欢将来自房子的色度的一个角落变成开着空间的完整晒焦的闪耀光。 2. These sunglasses are designed to reduce glare. 这些太阳镜是为减少刺眼的强光而设计的。 3. The glare of the oncoming headlights temporarily blinded me. 迎面车灯刺眼的光照得我瞬间什么也看不见。 4. Eyelashes defend the eye by shading it from glare. 眼睫毛通过遮掩眼睛而使眼睛避免受眩光刺激。', '过去式: glared 过去分词: glared 现在分词: glaring 第三人称单数: glares');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('uncanny', '[ʌn\'kæni]', 'adj.神秘的；不可思议的', '1. The silence was uncanny. 静得出奇。 2. I had an uncanny feeling of being watched. 我有一种奇怪的感觉，好像有人监视我。 3. His powers of observation were uncanny. 他的观察能力非常惊人。 4. The similarity between the two is uncanny. 这两者之间有着不可思议的相似性。', '副词: uncannily 比较级: uncannier 最高级: uncanniest 名词: uncanniness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quagmire', '[\'kwæɡmaɪər]', 'n.沼泽；绝境', '1. The heavy rain had turned the pitch into a quagmire. 大雨滂沱 2. I hope we can quickly get out of the quagmire. 我希望我们能够快点走出这个困境。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fake', '[feɪk]', 'adj.假的 n.骗子；假货；欺骗 vt.伪造；伪装 vi.假造', '1. Cops arrest 8 men who manufacture and sale fake collage notice . 警察在本月初逮捕了8名伪造和贩卖假大学录取通知书的人. 2. I can\'t believe he sold me a lousy fake watch! 我真不敢相信,他居然卖给我一块糟糕的假表! 3. He looked like a postman but he was really a fake. 他看上去像个邮递员，但实际上是假冒的。 4. On closer examination the painting was proved to be a fake. 再经仔细观察，证实那幅画是膺品。 5. He faked his father\'s signature. 他伪造父亲的签字。 6. Every politician has to fake a little. 每个政治家都是有点矫揉造作。', '过去式: faked 过去分词: faked 现在分词: faking 第三人称单数: fakes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stupendous', '[stuː\'pendəs]', 'adj.惊人的；巨大的', '1. The opera was quite stupendous. 这部歌剧很精彩。 2. The dam is a stupendous engineering feat. 这水坝乃是一项惊人的工程上的壮举。 3. He made a stupendous mistake. 他犯了一个极大的错误。 4. We are caught in a mysterious and stupendous historical process. 我们陷进了一个神秘的、巨大的历史进程里。', '副词: stupendously 名词: stupendousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('track', '[træk]', 'n.轨道；跑道；踪迹；小路；乐曲 v.追踪；跟踪', '1. The tram is being switched on to another track . 电车正被移至另外一条轨道上。 2. The cyclist went at full sail along the track. 自行车手沿着跑道全速前进。 3. I quickly lose her track in the crowd. 我在人群中失去了她的踪迹。 4. A track runs across the field to his house. 一条小路穿过原野通到他的家。 5. It\'s difficult to track an animal right after rain. 刚下完雨后要追踪猎物是很困难的。', '形容词: trackable 名词: tracker 过去式: tracked 过去分词: tracked 现在分词: tracking 第三人称单数: tracks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('auricular', '[ɒ\'rɪkjələ]', 'adj.耳的；听觉的；耳语的；耳状的', '1. Auricular ossification is a rare clinical entity. 临床上,耳壳骨化是罕见的临床症状。 2. Of, relating to, or located near the ear;auricular. 耳的耳的、与耳有关的或位于近耳处的； 3. Of, relating to, or located near the ear; auricular. 耳的耳的、与耳有关的或位于近耳处的；近耳的 4. My apprehension of words is auricular; I must hear what I read. 我对词汇的理解是通过听力来完成的；我必须听到我所阅读的内容。', '副词: auricularly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conversant', '[kən\'vɜːrsnt]', 'adj.熟悉的；亲近的', '1. She is conversant with English. 她精通英语。 2. I am thoroughly conversant with all the rules. 我对所有的规则了如指掌。 3. We become the most conversant strangers in the world. 我们变成了世界上最熟悉的陌生人。', '副词: conversantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('propitious', '[prə\'pɪʃəs]', 'adj.有利的；适合的；吉利的', '1. The circumstances were not propitious for further expansion of the company. 这些情况不利于公司的进一步发展。 2. It was not a propitious time to start a new business. 这个时候开张不吉利。 3. People like to hear propitious sentences. 人们都喜欢听吉利的话。', '副词: propitiously 名词: propitiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('puckish', '[\'pʌkɪʃ]', 'adj.爱恶作剧的；精灵似的；淘气的；顽皮的', '1. There are also more puckish signs of a zeitgeist shift. 也有一些时代思想转变的恶作剧。 2. With her sharp and puckish look, she dared anyone to contradict her. 她犀利而恶作剧般的神色，不惧怕任何反对者。', '副词: puckishly 名词: puckishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rudimentary', '[ˌruːdɪ\'mentri]', 'adj.基本的；初步的；未充分发展的', '1. They were given only rudimentary training in the job. 他们仅仅受到过基本的职业训练。 2. E-mail filters are still rudimentary cures and pretty ineffective in curtailing the deluge of unwanted messages. 电子邮件过滤软体仍旧是基本的补救方法，但对于如洪水般涌来的垃圾讯息，筛减效力实在不彰。 3. I have only a rudimentary grasp of physics. 我对物理学仅有初步的了解。 4. The robot now has several of its sensory organs attached and a rudimentary nervous system working. 机器人现在已经接上了好几个感测器，而且初步的神经系统也可以运作了。', '副词: rudimentarily 名词: rudimentariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('innovative', '[\'ɪnəveɪtɪv]', 'adj.创新的；革新的', '1. Its glass carving is beautiful and innovative. 玻璃雕刻创意新颖。 2. These designs are full of innovative ideas. 这些设计富有创新的理念。 3. She was an imaginative and innovative manager. 她是个有想象力和革新精神的经理。 4. This is an innovative approach to language teaching. 这是语言教学中一种革新的方法。', '名词: innovativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alchemy', '[\'ælkəmi]', 'n.炼金术；魔力', '1. One of the supreme quests of alchemy is to transmute lead into gold. 炼金术的终极目的之一是将铅转化为金。', '形容词: alchemical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sedate', '[sɪ\'deɪt]', 'adj.安静的；镇静的 vt.使安静；使镇静', '1. A sedate color scheme calls for an obvious place for the eye to rest. 一个安静的配色方案需要为眼睛提供一个显著的休息的地方。', '副词: sedately 名词: sedateness 过去式: sedated 过去分词: sedated 现在分词: sedating 第三人称单数: sedates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('raillery', '[\'reɪləri]', 'n.善意的嘲弄；逗趣', '1. She asked, with a touch of raillery. 她开玩笑地问道。 2. He was gifted, on occasion, with a gentle raillery, which almost always concealed a serious meaning. 他一有机会，总爱说一些温和的讥诮言词，但几乎每次都含着严正的意义。 3. These two sharp wits never met in former times but a perfect war of raillery was kept up between them. 过去这两个机灵嘴快的人每一次见面都要展开一场彼此挖苦讥笑的地地道道的舌战。 4. He was gifted,on occasion,with a gentle raillery,which almost always concealed a serious meaning. 他一有机会，总爱说一些温和的讥诮言词，但几乎每次都含着严正的意义。', '名词复数: railleries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slouch', '[slaʊtʃ]', 'n.没精打采的样子；耷拉；笨人 v.没精打采地站', '1. There had something of a slouch and a sneer in his bearing. 他的脸上带着一副心灰意懒而又不屑一顾的神情。 2. He is good at chess and no slouch at bridge, either. 他擅长棋类，桥牌也非弱项。 3. Don\'t slouch! Stand up straight! 别没精打采的! 起来站直了！', '形容词: slouchy 副词: slouchily 名词: slouchiness 过去式: slouched 过去分词: slouched 现在分词: slouching 第三人称单数: slouches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('knit', '[nɪt]', 'v.编织；密接；结合；皱眉 n.编织', '1. She often knits while watching TV. 她常常一边看电视一边织毛衣。 2. She preferred to sew rather than to knit. 她喜欢缝纫而不喜欢编织。 3. The doctor knit the two broken bones in his arm. 医生把他臂上的两块折骨接好了。 4. The treaty knit the economies of the two nations together. 该条约把两国的经济紧密地结合在一起。 5. The son begins to knit a big fishnet. 儿子就开始编织大网了。', '名词: knitter 过去式: knit/knitted 过去分词: knit/knitted 现在分词: knitting 第三人称单数: knits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('associate', '[ə\'soʊʃieɪt]', 'vt.联想；联合 n.伙伴；同事；同伴 adj.副的；共事的；有联系的 n.准学士学位获得者 vi.交往', '1. I always associate her with roses. 我总是把她与玫瑰花联想在一起。 2. We should associate ourselves with this large firm. 我们应该和这家大公司联合。 3. Mr. Miller is a business associate of our company. 米勒先生是我们公司的生意伙伴。 4. I got a new job and a new group of work associates. 我有了新工作和一班新同事。 5. He is an associate editor of the newspaper. 他是报纸的副主编。 6. You are wooing troubles if you associate with him. 你和他交往会招来麻烦。', '过去式: associated 过去分词: associated 现在分词: associating 第三人称单数: associates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fragile', '[\'frædʒl]', 'adj.易碎的；脆的；精细的；虚弱的', '1. Glasses are fragile and must be handled with great care. 玻璃制品易碎，必须小心轻放。 2. This glass plate is very fragile. 这个玻璃盘子很容易碎。 3. The fragile boxes arrived intact. 这些易碎的箱子完整无损地运到了。 4. Happiness is made of glass, it shines the brightest where it is most fragile. 幸福是玻璃做成的,它最脆弱的地方最闪亮!', '副词: fragilely 名词: fragility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('serried', '[\'serid]', 'adj.密集的；林立的；拥挤的 动词serry的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. Above the bush the trees stood in serried ranks. 荆棘之上耸立着密密麻麻的大树。 2. We flew over the city with its serried ranks of identical grey houses. 我们飞过城市上空，看到林立的统一灰色调的房子。', '副词: serriedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tantrum', '[\'tæntrəm]', 'n.发脾气；发怒', '1. She regularly throws tantrums. 她经常大发脾气。 2. He always flies into a tantrum when he\'s contradicted. 每当不如意时他就会大发脾气。 3. She was always in a tantrum if interrupted. 要是有人打扰她，她总是要发一通脾气。 4. This child has a tantrum whenever she doesn\'t get her own way. 一旦不能为所欲为，这个孩子就会发怒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saga', '[\'sɑːɡə]', 'n.世家；英雄事迹；冒险故事', '1. This new novel is an absorbing family saga. 这部新小说是一部引人入胜的家世小说。 2. The novelist had issued many saga novels. 那个小说家已经发表了很多长篇小说。 3. His saga inspires young people\'s patriotism. 他的英雄事迹激发起年轻人的爱国主义精神。 4. He is only beginning to realize the role he is destined to play in the great saga. 他刚开始认识到他在这伟大的冒险故事里所扮演的角色是命中注定的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whine', '[waɪn]', 'n.闹声；抱怨；牢骚 v.哭诉；发牢骚', '1. The whine of the motors jangled her nerves. 马达的闹声使她的神经受不了。 2. There were a few whines and whimpers about policy changes. 关于政策的变动有一些抱怨和不满。 3. They do not sweat and whine about their condition. 它们并不对它们的处境牢骚烦恼。 4. I can no longer abide the young people of our country who live off their parents and the fat of the land and then they find nothing better to do than whine and complain. 我再也无法忍受我们国家那些年轻人，离开他们的双亲和肥沃的土地，然后他们发现什么也做不了，只有满腹的牢骚和怨气。 5. You whine, complain and act like a child. 你就像个小孩一样吵闹抱怨个不停。', '形容词: whiny 副词: whiningly 名词: whiner 过去式: whined 过去分词: whined 现在分词: whining 第三人称单数: whines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gleam', '[ɡliːm]', 'v.闪烁；隐约地闪现 n.微光；闪光；闪现', '1. The lighthouse of the island gleamed in the distance. 远处岛上的灯塔在闪耀着。 2. His face gleamed with pleasure. 他的脸上闪现出欢快的神色。 3. I could see the faint gleam of light in the distance. 我能看见远处微弱的灯光。 4. I saw the gleam of the knife as it flashed through the air. 我看见了刀在空中划过时的闪光。', '名词: gleamer 过去式: gleamed 过去分词: gleamed 现在分词: gleaming 第三人称单数: gleams');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ingenuity', '[ˌɪndʒə\'nuːəti]', 'n.心灵手巧；独创性；精巧', '1. The writer showed ingenuity in creating a surprising ending. 作者别具匠心地设计了一个出人意料的结尾。 2. She had the ingenuity to succeed where everyone else had failed. 她真是心灵手巧,别人办不到的事她却做成了。 3. It took some ingenuity to squeeze all the furniture into the little room. 把全部家具都塞进那个小房间是很费了一番心思的。 4. This movie is of great ingenuity. 这部影片很有独创性。', '名词复数: ingenuities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('satiny', '[\'sætni]', 'adj.光滑的；柔细的', '1. White frost and silver storm powder crystallise the leaves on this beautiful object, topped with a satiny pink gold lid. 白色冰霜和银色暴风雪尘在烛体上勾勒出精巧的常春藤叶，最后冠之一枚光滑的金粉色盖。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('feat', '[fiːt]', 'n.技艺；功绩；技艺表演', '1. It was quite a feat to move that piano by yourself. 你真有能耐，一个人挪动那架钢琴。 2. I was amazed to see his dangerous feat. 他的危险技艺让我感到惊讶。 3. The skyscraper is a feat of engineering. 那座摩天大楼是一项工程的壮举。 4. The first flight into space was a brilliant feat. 第一次太空飞行是项光辉的伟绩。', '副词: featly 比较级: feater 最高级: featest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lever', '[\'levər]', 'n.杠杆；控制杆；手段 v.撬开；使用杠杆', '1. He employed his knife as a lever. 他把刀子当杠杆用。 2. This lever must serve some ulterior purpose. 这撬棒准是用于不可告人的目的的。 3. Push hard and the lever will go down. 用力推就能把控制杆按下去。 4. Move this lever to change gear. 换档时扳动这根操纵杆。 5. They managed to lever the door open. 他们设法撬开了门。', '过去式: levered 过去分词: levered 现在分词: levering 第三人称单数: levers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hush', '[hʌʃ]', 'n.肃静；安静；沉默 vi.安静下来；掩饰 vt.使肃静或安静；缄默', '1. There was a sudden hush. 突然肃静下来。 2. A hush fell over the meeting-room. 会议室里一下子安静了下来。 3. I am in the morning hush, of Stranglethorn\'s jungle, green and lush. 我是清幽安静的晨,弥漫在绿色茂盛的荆棘谷。 4. There was an odd hush that caught Scarlett\'s heart. 这时周围突然是一片古怪的安静，它把思嘉的心一下子揪住了。 5. Here she comes! Everyone hush up! 她来了！请大家安静！ 6. She hushed the baby to sleep. 她使婴儿安静入睡。', '过去式: hushed 过去分词: hushed 现在分词: hushing 第三人称单数: hushes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deviation', '[ˌdiːvi\'eɪʃn]', 'n.偏离；出轨；背弃 n.[数]偏差', '1. Deviation from this rule are very rare. 很少有违反这条规则的。 2. There was little deviation from his usual routine. 他没有什么反常的举动。 3. She was so hopelessly kind-hearted that she even forgave her husband\'s second deviation. 她是如此的善良,也是如此的软弱,居然原谅了丈夫的第二次出轨。 4. Party ideologists accused her of deviation from communist doctrines. 党内理论家谴责她背弃了共产党的信条。 5. The deviation is reduced to one millimetre. 偏差减为一毫米。', '形容词: deviationist 名词: deviationism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('streak', '[striːk]', 'n.一系列；条痕；斑纹；倾向；少许；痕迹 v.加条纹；夹杂着；快速移动；闪现', '1. It is time to start a new winning streak. 是开始新一轮地连胜的时候了。 2. She has had a long streak of bad luck. 她遭遇了一连串的不幸。 3. There was a streak of blood on his face. 他脸上有一道血痕。 4. The fox tabby cat has clearly, the obvious streak. 狸花猫有非常清楚、明显的斑纹。 5. The Indians used to streak their faces with paint. 印第安人过去常用颜料在脸上涂条纹。', '名词: streaker 过去式: streaked 过去分词: streaked 现在分词: streaking 第三人称单数: streaks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lull', '[lʌl]', 'v.使安静；使入睡；哄骗；平息 n.暂停；间歇', '1. The mother lulled the baby to sleep. 母亲哄着孩子入睡了。 2. They lulled me into a false sense of security. 他们哄骗我，让我产生了一种虚假的安全感。 3. During the night the wind lulled. 夜里，风停了。 4. This is just the lull before the storm. 这只是暴风雨前的暂时平静。', '过去式: lulled 过去分词: lulled 现在分词: lulling 第三人称单数: lulls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('morale', '[mə\'ræl]', 'n.士气；斗志；道德准则', '1. They bolstered their morale by singing. 他们以唱歌来鼓舞士气。 2. They sang songs to keep their morale up. 他们唱　歌以保持高昂的士气。 3. We\'ll soon attack the enemy together. Keep up your morale, soldier! 我们就要会剿敌军了，同志们要保持斗志啊。 4. A sincere compliment boosts one\'s morale. 由衷的称赞可鼓舞一个人的精神。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pithiness', '[\'pɪθɪnɪs]', 'n.有力；简洁', '1. Our company believes that enhancing the training of the employees is the pithiness guarantee to providing knight service and reducing cost. 我公司始终认为加强对员工的培训是为客户提供供优质服务和降低成本的有力保障。 2. Her work is known for pithiness of style. 她的作品以简洁著称。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('treason', '[\'triːzn]', 'n.叛逆 通敌 背叛 叛国罪', '1. He was executed for treason. 他因叛国罪已处死。 2. He was beheaded for high treason. 他因叛国罪被斩首。 3. English politician and historian who was falsely accused of treason and banished(1667). While in France he wrote his major work, The History of the Rebellion and Civil Wars in England(1702-1704). 克拉伦登英国政治家和历史学家，被错判叛国罪并流放(1667年)。在法国写出他的重要著作英国叛乱和内战史(1702－1704年) 4. They have committed treason against the state. 他们已犯了叛国罪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decode', '[ˌdiː\'koʊd]', 'v.解码；译解；译码', '1. Method is used to decode the array of bytes. 方法用来解码字节数组。 2. The Lab Activity will help students decode a waveform. 实验活动将帮助学生解码一道波形。', '名词: decoder 过去式: decoded 过去分词: decoded 现在分词: decoding 第三人称单数: decodes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appease', '[ə\'piːz]', 'v.安抚；缓和；平息；姑息', '1. Chamberlain tried to appease Hitler at Munich. 张伯伦在慕尼黑尽量安抚希特勒。 2. His attempts to appease her only added fuel to the fire. 他试着安抚她，结果却造成火上加油的局面。 3. State governments are left scrabbling to appease ruraldisgruntlement rather than investing in efforts to lift theproductivity of land and labour. 政府花钱努力来提高农民和工人的生产力还不如想办法缓和农民的不满。 4. Many in the New Republic began to turn against the Jedi in an effort to appease the Yuuzhan Vong and blunt their destructive incursions. 新共和国的许多人开始反对绝地，他们对遇战疯人实施绥靖政策，试图以此缓和遇战疯人毁灭性的入侵行动。', '形容词: appeasable 副词: appeasably 名词: appeaser 过去式: appeased 过去分词: appeased 现在分词: appeasing 第三人称单数: appeases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rotund', '[roʊ\'tʌnd]', 'adj.(指人)圆胖的；(声音)洪亮的', '1. He was a large rotund man with a very jovial nature and a compassionate disposition. 他是一个又高又胖的男人，天性快乐并富有同情心。 2. These rotund amphibians can grow to 8 inches (20 centimeters) in length and would cover a good-size tea saucer. 这种洪亮的两栖动物可以长到20厘米长，可以盖住一个大尺寸的茶托。', '副词: rotundly 名词: rotundity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resort', '[rɪ\'zɔːrt]', 'n.(度假)胜地；手段；凭借 vi.诉诸；常去', '1. The island is a favorite summer resort for tourists. 这座岛是旅游者的避暑胜地。 2. Its unique natural scenery makes it an ideal holiday resort. 独具特色的自然景观,使这里成为度假休闲的理想胜地。 3. A carriage was the only resort. 乘马车是唯一的办法。 4. The resort to force is forbidden in this school. 该学校禁止动武。 5. If other means fail，we shall resort to force. 如果其他手段均失败,我们就将诉诸武力。', '过去式: resorted 过去分词: resorted 现在分词: resorting 第三人称单数: resorts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nomadic', '[nəʊ\'mædɪk]', 'adj.游牧的；游牧民族的；流浪的', '1. His tribe was unusual for its sedentarism.Plains tribes were commonly nomadic. 他的部落过着与众不同的隐居生活，而平原上的部落一般都是游牧的。 2. The Ming adopted a new strategy to keep the nomadic Mongols out by constructing walls along the northern border of China. 明朝采取了一个新的策略通过沿中国北方边界建造长城来阻挡游牧的蒙古。 3. I don\'t have known nomadic blood in the family. 据我所知，我身上并没有游牧民族的血液。 4. The Yuma Indians, such as this tribesman, were generally nomadic. 照片中的部落男人就是尤马族的印第安人，他们通常都是游牧民族。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perilous', '[\'perələs]', 'adj.危险的；冒险的', '1. The snow and the blackout combined to make motoring perilous. 大雪加上灯火管制使得车辆行驶成了危险的事。 2. Whoever bars others from revolution will find himself in a very perilous position. 凡是不准人家革命，那是很危险的。', '副词: perilously 名词: perilousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('equation', '[ɪ\'kweɪʒn]', 'n.相等；均衡；方程式；等式', '1. The equation of wealth with happiness can be dangerous. 把财富与幸福等同起来是很危险的 2. I can\'t make this equation come out. 我不会解这个方程式。 3. What does x represent in this equation? 这个方程式中的x代表什么? 4. The professor wrote an equation on the blackboard. 教授在黑板上写了一个等式。', '形容词: equational 副词: equationally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peevish', '[\'piːvɪʃ]', 'adj.易怒的；暴躁的；撒娇的', '1. He becomes peevish and refuses to eat. 他变得易怒了，而且还不吃东西。 2. A peevish child is unhappy and makes others unhappy. 一个脾气暴躁的孩子自己不高兴也使别人不高兴。 3. He has grown peevish and fallen off from what he used to be. 他变得性情乖张，脾气暴躁，不似以前那么随和。 4. The child is never peevish unless sick. 这孩子只有在生病时才会闹别扭。', '副词: peevishly 名词: peevishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('talisman', '[\'tælɪzmən]', 'n.避邪物；护身符', '1. The talisman consists of two circles with triangles drawn on them. 这种护身符由两个圆圈组成，圆圈上画有三角。 2. Aventurine has been used as a lucky talisman and is a popular gem for gamblers. 沙金石常用作幸运护身符，赌徒们特别喜欢这种宝石。', '名词复数: talismans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fade', '[feɪd]', 'v.逐渐消失；褪色；凋谢 n.淡入；淡出', '1. Hopes of a peaceful settlement are now fading. 和平解决的希望正在消失。 2. The closing music fades out when the hero rides off into the sunset. 当男主角策马向夕阳驰去时，尾声音乐逐渐消失。 3. As evening came the coastline faded into darkness. 夜晚来临，海岸线融入茫茫夜色中。 4. These sunproof curtains will not fade . 这些耐晒的窗帘不褪色。 5. They\'ll fade in to an outdoor scene. 他们将淡入至户外的一个场景。', '过去式: faded 过去分词: faded 现在分词: fading 第三人称单数: fades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('speculate', '[\'spekjuleɪt]', 'vt.推测 vi.投机；深思', '1. The doctors speculate that he died of cancer. 医生推测他死于癌症。 2. Can you speculate how such damage might arise? 你能否想出这种伤害是怎样引起的? 3. He likes to speculate on the stock market. 他喜欢炒股。 4. It\'s dangerous to speculate. 做投机买卖是很危险的。', '过去式: speculated 过去分词: speculated 现在分词: speculating 第三人称单数: speculates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unmitigated', '[ʌn\'mɪtɪɡeɪtɪd]', 'adj.未缓和的；十足的；绝对的', '1. The costs of unmitigated climate change are potentially enormous. 未减缓的气候变化所造成的经济损失将是巨大的。 2. He is an unmitigated liar! 他是个十足的撒谎精！ 3. Your unmitigated greed led directly to the destruction of your tainted gold. 十足的贪婪直接导致了你们那些肮脏金钱的毁灭。 4. The evening was an unmitigated disaster. 这一晚完全是一场灾难。', '副词: unmitigatedly 名词: unmitigatedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('potpourri', '[ˌpoʊpʊ\'riː]', 'n.混杂物；文集；（干的）百花香', '1. B: It smells like a potpourri bag. 闻起来像是百味袋。 2. A potpourri of bug decorates the sill. 圈框外点缀着爬虫的尸体。 3. The robust fragrance of potpourri filled the room. 大烩饭的浓香充满了整间屋子。 4. Chm-VC essence Potpourri Collection lot of skills. 详细说明： VC精华文摘合集大量技巧.', '名词复数: potpourris');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plait', '[plæt]', 'n.辫子；皱褶 v.编辫子；编制；打褶', '1. She wore her hair in plaits. 她把头发编成辫子。 2. Her mother helped her to plait her hair. 她的母亲帮她编辫子。', '名词: plaiter 过去式: plaited 过去分词: plaited 现在分词: plaiting 第三人称单数: plaits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('betoken', '[bɪ\'toʊkən]', 'v.预示；是 ... 的预兆；表示', '1. Those black clouds betoken rain. 那些乌云预示即将下雨。 2. That would only betoken for us seven years of plenty and seven years of scarcity. 那只是预示我们将有七年丰收和七年饥荒。', '过去式: betokened 过去分词: betokened 现在分词: betokening 第三人称单数: betokens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('excess', '[ɪk\'ses]', 'n.超过；过量；过剩 adj.过量的；额外的', '1. Our school has a student number in excess of 800. 我们学校的学生数超过八百人。 2. His excesses at parties are well known. 尽人皆知他在聚会上十分放肆。 3. An excess of fat in one\'s diet can lead to heart disease. 食物中脂肪过多会导致心脏病。 4. This wave of excess density is sound. 这种过剩密度的波就是声波。 5. The fat boy went on a diet to get rid of his excess weight. 这个胖男孩节制饮食以减轻过量的体重。', '过去式: excessed 过去分词: excessed 现在分词: excessing 第三人称单数: excesses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elongate', '[ɪ\'lɔːŋɡeɪt]', 'v.延长；伸长 adj.延长了的；细长的', '1. We plan to elongate the cooperation with that company in Australia. 我们打算延长与澳洲那家公司的合作关系。 2. Lines will elongate when height is increased. 线可随着深度的增加而拉长。 3. These elongate sand bodies are attached to a bulge of the mainland. 这些长条形砂体连接于主陆的突出部位。', '过去式: elongated 过去分词: elongated 现在分词: elongating 第三人称单数: elongates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oracular', '[ə\'rækjələr]', 'adj.神谕的；玄妙的；明哲的', '1. To us this oracular remark seemed to herald Hitler. 这番玄妙深奥的话在我们看来仿佛预示着希特勒的来临。', '副词: oracularly 名词: oracularity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pejorative', '[pɪ\'dʒɔːrətɪv]', 'n.轻蔑语 adj.贬低的；轻蔑的', '1. The word has a pejorative overtone. 这个单词有点贬义。 2. I\'m using the word \'academic\' here in a pejorative sense. 我这里使用的“学术”一词是贬义的。', '副词: pejoratively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('engulf', '[ɪn\'ɡʌlf]', 'vt.吞没；席卷；吞噬', '1. The waves engulfed the boat. 大浪吞没了小舟。 2. The stormy sea engulfed the small motor sailboat. 汹涌的大海吞没了那艘小机帆船。 3. The country was engulfed in civil war. 该国陷入内战。 4. A wave of grief engulfed them. 一阵悲伤吞噬了他们。', '名词: engulfment 过去式: engulfed 过去分词: engulfed 现在分词: engulfing 第三人称单数: engulfs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('excise', '[\'eksaɪz]', 'n.货物税；消费税 vt.征税 vt.切除；删除', '1. He has suggested imposing an oil import fee and raising excise taxes on liquor and cigarette. 他建议增加石油进口税与提高烟酒货物税。 2. Excise started being levied last August. 消费税起征于去年的8月份。 3. The surgeon excised the lump from her breast. 外科医生切除了她乳房的肿块。 4. The censor insisted on excising the passage from the film. 电影审查员坚持剪去影片的这一段。', '名词: excision 过去式: excised 过去分词: excised 现在分词: excising 第三人称单数: excises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surveyor', '[sər\'veɪər]', 'n.测量员；勘测员；房产鉴定员；检查员', '1. The surveyor made a survey of the land. 测量员对土地进行了测量。 2. The surveyor integrated the area of all the farms into a total acreage of the township. 勘测员把所有农田面积加进了小镇的总面积。 3. The surveyor went over the house thoroughly and advised us not to buy it. 房屋鉴定人彻底察看了房子以后,劝我们不要买。 4. I had been a quality surveyor , construction member and principal of item. 先后做过质量检查员、施工员及项目负责人，', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intangible', '[ɪn\'tændʒəbl]', 'adj.难以明了的；无形的 n.无形的东西', '1. We felt an intangible presence in the room. 我们感到房子里有一种难以捉摸的东西。 2. The island was intangible, inviolate. 我们这个岛令人莫测高深，是不可侵犯的。 3. Sound is intangible and the same is true of light. 声音是无形的,而光也同样如此。 4. Stocks and bonds are intangible property. 股票和证券是无形财产。 5. The intangible value of love lies in the mutual trust. 爱情中最无形的价值在于双方互相信任。', '副词: intangibly 名词: intangibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cohesion', '[koʊ\'hiːʒn]', 'n.凝聚力；团结；内聚力', '1. These high levels of inequality erode social cohesion in the region. 这些严重的不平等侵蚀了该地区的社会凝聚力。 2. The most important thing is more cohesion within the party to win the next general election. 要想赢得下届大选的胜利,最重要的是我们党内要更加团结。 3. I had to bring some cohesion and unity into the company. 我得使整个公司恢复内聚力和统一。', '形容词: cohesive 副词: cohesively 名词: cohesiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unreserved', '[ˌʌnrɪ\'zɜːrvd]', 'adj.坦率的；无保留的；没有被预订的', '1. Frank and unreserved in speech. 直言不讳的在言语上坦率且无保留地 2. An unreserved seat. 无人占据的座位', '副词: unreservedly 名词: unreservedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gimmick', '[\'ɡɪmɪk]', 'n.暗机关；小发明；花招；噱头 vt.用暗机关改变或影响', '1. But this is surely no more than a populist gimmick. 但这无疑只是一个民粹主义者的小花招罢了。 2. The advertisement is just a gimmick to make consumers buy their products. 宣传只是一种使消费者买他们产品的花招。', '形容词: gimmicky 过去式: gimmicked 过去分词: gimmicked 现在分词: gimmicking 第三人称单数: gimmicks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('singularity', '[ˌsɪŋɡju\'lærəti]', 'n.单独；奇异', '1. They are convinced of the singularity of their good taste. 他们确信自己的品味高雅非凡。 2. He was surprised at the singularity of the stranger\'s appearance. 他对那个陌生人古怪的外貌感到惊讶。', '名词复数: singularities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('endearing', '[ɪn\'dɪrɪŋ]', 'adj.惹人喜爱的；可爱的 动词endear的现在分词形式.', '1. He never speaks an endearing word to his wife. 他从未封妻子说句亲密的话。 2. The endearing sweetness of her manners so charmed Bertram. 她那甜蜜可爱的姿态叫勃特拉姆为之倾倒。', '副词: endearingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compensatory', '[ˌkɒmpen\'seɪtəri]', 'adj.赔偿的；补偿的', '1. He received a compensatory payment of $20000. 他获得了2万元的赔偿金。 2. They are discussing the compensatory policy. 他们正在讨论补偿的政策。 3. He also suggested that this is one of the compensatory mechanisms. 他也提出,这是一种补偿的机制。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oar', '[ɔːr]', 'n.桨；橹；划手 v.划行', '1. In dragon boat rowing each person has one oar. 划龙舟时每个人都拿着一枝桨。 2. Sometimes an oar is used to steer a boat. 有时桨用以操纵小舟。 3. A rowing or paddling stroke in which the oar or paddle is pushed forward,used to check a boat\'s forward motion or move it backward. 倒浆，把橹或桨向前推以阻止船向前运动或向后移动的一种划船或摇桨方式。', '形容词: oared 过去式: oared 过去分词: oared 现在分词: oaring 第三人称单数: oars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insomnia', '[ɪn\'sɑːmniə]', 'n.失眠；失眠症', '1. Lately he has been moaning about his insomnia and headache. 他近来一直诉说自己患了失眠和头痛症。 2. Too much stress on the job could cause insomnia. 工作压力太大可能会导致失眠。 3. The medicine works like magic on insomnia. 这药治疗失眠有奇效。 4. She sufferd from insomnia recently. 她最近患了失眠症。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('poll', '[poʊl]', 'n.民意测验；投票；票数 v.做民意测验；获得 ... 票', '1. We are going to conduct a public opinion poll. 我们将进行民意测验。 2. The president has a favourable rating in the opinion poll. 民意测验对总统评价很好。 3. They organized a poll to elect a president. 他们组织了一次投票选举总统。 4. The final result of the poll will be known tomorrow. 投票结果将于明天公布。 5. We can poll using a questionnaire. 我们可以用调查问卷进行民意测验。', '名词: poller 过去式: polled 过去分词: polled 现在分词: polling 第三人称单数: polls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enamel', '[ɪ\'næml]', 'n.搪瓷；珐琅；瓷釉 v.涂以瓷釉', '1. The pots are made with blue enamel. 这些锅上有蓝色的搪瓷。 2. Some of the enamel on this pan is chipped off. 这平底锅上的搪瓷有些已脱落。 3. Rust has already bitten into the enamel. 铁锈已经烂进搪瓷里去了。 4. The enamel of her teeth is very white. 她牙齿的珐琅质很白。', '名词: enameler 过去式: enameled/enamelled 过去分词: enameled/enamelled 现在分词: enameling/enamelling 第三人称单数: enamels/enamels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('substitute', '[\'sʌbstɪtuːt]', 'n.代用品；代替者；替补队员 vt.代替；用 ... 代替；代以', '1. Water is not a proper substitute for wine. 水不是酒的适当代用品。 2. Is saccharin a good substitute for sugar? 糖精是糖的良好替代品吗? 3. We recommend this brand as a good substitute. 我们推荐的新品种可以完全替代原来的产品。 4. His friend Humboldt was his substitute. 他的朋友洪堡接替了他。 5. Only art can substitute for nature. 唯有艺术能代替自然。', '形容词: substitutable 名词: substitutability 过去式: substituted 过去分词: substituted 现在分词: substituting 第三人称单数: substitutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loosen', '[\'luːsn]', 'vt.松开；放松；放宽 vi.变松；松弛', '1. I loosened my tie, but I didn\'t take it off. 我松开了领带，但是没有把它解下来。 2. Can you loosen the lid of this jar? 你能把这个瓶盖松开吗? 3. A emperor should never loosen the grasp of power. 君主应永不放松对权力的掌控。 4. The government has loosened restrictions on the sale of liquor. 政府已经放宽了对销售烈酒的限制。 5. The government\'s control over the newspapers has loosened in recent years. 近年来政府对报纸的控制已经变松了。', '过去式: loosened 过去分词: loosened 现在分词: loosening 第三人称单数: loosens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('caulk', '[kɔːk]', 'vt.填塞(隙缝)使不渗水；填嵌 n.堵 =calk.', '1. Shipbuilders caulk wooden boats with oakum and tar. 造船工匠用麻丝和沥青填塞木船缝隙，使之不渗水。 2. To clean,caulk,or repair(a ship in this position). 将（船倾侧后）进行清扫、堵缝或修理 3. Caulk or grouting needed in tub area. 需要为汽缸做灌浆或防漏。 4. To clean, caulk, or repair(a ship in this position). 将(船倾侧后)进行清扫、堵缝或。', '名词: caulker');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('undermine', '[ˌʌndər\'maɪn]', 'vt.逐渐削弱；暗中损害；在...下挖；从根基处损害', '1. They will do anything to undermine their adversary\'s reputation. 他们会不择手段地去损害对手的名誉。 2. The President\'s enemies are spreading rumours to undermine his authority. 总统的敌人在散布谣言以逐渐破坏他的威信。 3. Badgers had undermined the foundations of the church. 獾在这座教堂的地基处打了洞。 4. A mole can undermine the strongest rampart. 一只田鼠能毁坏最坚固的堡垒。', '过去式: undermined 过去分词: undermined 现在分词: undermining 第三人称单数: undermines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('raspy', '[\'ræspi]', 'adj.刺耳的；粗糙的；易怒的', '1. They can be noisy birds with their calls sounding harsh and raspy. 他们可能是有他们的呼叫吵杂的鸟发声的粗糙和刺耳的。 2. She gave her character a very recognizable high-pitched yet raspy voice. 她以高调刺耳的声音让人们一下子记住了蓝妹妹。', '比较级: raspier 最高级: raspiest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bovine', '[\'boʊvaɪn]', 'adj.(似)牛的；迟钝的 n.牛科动物', '1. A cow is a kind of domestic bovine animals. 母牛是家养牛属动物的一种。 2. He showed a rather bovine expression when he heard the news. 当听到这个消息时，他显出一脸迟钝。 3. The most widely used animal serum is fetal bovine serum (FBS). 目前应用最广泛的动物血清是胎牛血清（FBS）。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boast', '[boʊst]', 'v.自夸；吹牛；以...为荣 n.自夸；引以为荣的事物', '1. Don\'t boast and don\'t be modest. 不要自夸,也不要太谦虚。 2. That\'s nothing to boast about. 那没有什麽值得自吹的。 3. Nobody should boast of his learning. 谁也不应当夸耀自己的学识。 4. He never boasted of his cleverness. 他未曾夸耀过自己的聪明。 5. That brother of yours is full of boasts. 你那个宝贝兄弟满口大话。', '形容词: boastful 副词: boastfully 名词: boaster 过去式: boasted 过去分词: boasted 现在分词: boasting 第三人称单数: boasts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illusive', '[ɪ\'luːsɪv]', 'adj.幻影的；错觉的；迷惑人的', '1. He was fond of calling his detractor illiterate, denouncing his scientific theories as illegitimate and illusive. 他喜欢把他的恶意批评者称作文盲，公然抨击他的科学理论是非法的，迷惑人的。', '副词: illusively 名词: illusiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fret', '[fret]', 'v.(使)烦恼；(使)焦急；(使)磨损；侵蚀 n.烦躁；磨损；焦急 n.[音]音品；音柱', '1. You always get yourself into a fret over nothing. 你总为了莫须有的事，把自己弄得烦恼不已。 2. Don\'t fret over these small details. 不要为这些小事烦恼。 3. But Canadians are grumpy.They worry about government ethics, but they fret even more about things like the state of their health-care system. 但是加拿大人是乖戾的，他们担心政府的道德问题，但他们更为诸如医疗保健体制状况之类的问题焦急。 4. As she spoke we could see that she was in a fret. 她讲话时，我们看得出她很烦躁。', '过去式: fretted 过去分词: fretted 现在分词: fretting 第三人称单数: frets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invoice', '[\'ɪnvɔɪs]', 'n.发货单；发票；货物 vt.开票；寄发票；开清单', '1. The goods or services itemized in an invoice. 清单项目清单上逐条列出的货物或服务。 2. They sent me the goods,together with an invoice. 他们把货寄给了我，并附上了发票。 3. We received the invoice, but the item has not arrived yet. 我们收到了发票，但货物还没有到。 4. We need to check it against our order and the invoice when it comes in. 当货物到达时，我们必须用它来核对我们的定货单和发票。 5. We will invoice at ruling price. 我们将按现价开具发票。', '过去式: invoiced 过去分词: invoiced 现在分词: invoicing 第三人称单数: invoices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('circulate', '[\'sɜːrkjəleɪt]', 'vi.流通；循环；传播 vt.使流通，使环流', '1. Please open a window to allow the air to circulate. 打开窗子让空气流通。 2. Foreign money is not allowed to circulate in China. 外币不允许在中国流通。 3. Money shall circulate freely within the common market. 货币应在共同市场内自由流通。 4. Blood circulates through the body. 血液在体内循环。', '形容词: circulative 名词: circulator 过去式: circulated 过去分词: circulated 现在分词: circulating 第三人称单数: circulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decompose', '[ˌdiːkəm\'poʊz]', 'v.分解，拆分，拆解；腐烂', '1. A prism decomposes light. 棱镜可以分解光线。 2. These then decompose to give malonaldehyde. 然后分解生成丙醛酸 3. You can apply heat to decompose organic compounds. 你可以加热来分解有机化合物。 4. There is a decomposing corpse of a deer. 那儿有一具鹿的腐尸。', '形容词: decomposable 名词: decomposability 过去式: decomposed 过去分词: decomposed 现在分词: decomposing 第三人称单数: decomposes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plane', '[pleɪn]', 'n.飞机；水平；平面 n.刨子 n.悬铃木 adj.平的；飞机的 vt.磨平；刨 vi.（鸟、飞机）滑翔', '1. The plane flew high above. 飞机高高地在上空飞。 2. The plane circled the airport before landing. 飞机在着陆之前在机场上空盘旋。 3. Keep your work on a high plane. 使你的工作保持在高水平上。 4. Let\'s keep the conversation on a friendly plane. 让我们友好地谈话。 5. The carpenter evened a board with a plane. 那位木工用刨刨平一块木板。 6. The bark of plane trees peels off regularly. 悬铃木的树皮到时候就脱落。 7. The dense fog delayed the plane\'s start. 浓雾延误了飞机的起飞。 8. He has planed the plank smooth. 他已把木板刨平。 9. Seagulls planed over the cliffs. 海鸥在翱翔,飞过了悬崖。', '名词: planeness 过去式: planed 过去分词: planed 现在分词: planing 第三人称单数: planes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apparatus', '[ˌæpə\'rætəs]', 'n.器官；装置；机构；组织；仪器', '1. The bird has specialized vocal apparatus. 这只鸟有特殊的发音器官。 2. The demonstrators set up apparatus for the experiment. 示范者安装好了实验装置。 3. The whole apparatus operates under high vacuum. 整个装置在高真空下运转。 4. The city\'s security apparatus needs reforming. 这个城市的治安机构需要改良。', '名词复数: apparatus');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('epic', '[\'epɪk]', 'n.史诗；叙事诗 adj.史诗的；叙事诗的；宏大的；壮丽的', '1. That movie was an epic about the Roman Empire. 那电影是一部有关罗马帝国的史诗般的作品。 2. The Odyssey is an epic of ancient Greece. 《奥德塞》是古希腊的一首史诗。 3. It is still the beginning of the home epic. 它依然是一篇家庭叙事诗的开端。 4. It is perhaps the best of epic fantasies. 这也许是史诗奇幻小说中最好的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bewildering', '[bɪ\'wɪldərɪŋ]', 'adj.令人困惑的；使人混乱的 动词bewilder的现在分词形式.', '1. One of the important and bewildering promotional tools of modern marketing management is advertising. 广告是现代营销管理中重要且令人困惑的促销工具之一。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hedonic', '[hiː\'dɒnɪk]', 'adj.享乐的', '1. This is what psychologists have called \'hedonic adaptation\'. 这就是心理学家所说的“享乐性适应”。 2. Here cultural hedonic deep, ancient Chaoshan culture edify here growth us. 这儿文化底蕴深厚，古老的潮汕文化陶冶着在这里生长的我们。 3. Keywords: online airline ticket, price dispersion, Hedonic price model. 关键字：线上机票、价格差异、特性价格模式。 4. Hotel.\'s.Home the old carpet.Handmade blankets.Pure blanket.To Hedonic Price. 饭店.;公司', '副词: hedonically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proximate', '[\'prɑːksɪmət]', 'adj.最接近的；直接的', '1. The proximate reason is that the latter matter far less than they used to. 近似的解释是，高收入经济体的重要性已大不如前。 2. Indeed, one proximate cause of the crisis was a tapering-off of export growth. 事实上，危机爆发的一个最直接的原因是这些国家的出口逐渐减少。', '副词: proximately 名词: proximateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sermon', '[\'sɜːrmən]', 'n.布道；说教', '1. The minister preached a sermon on humility. 牧师就谦恭的问题布道。 2. Father gave me a sermon on table manners. 父亲就餐桌礼仪问题对我作了一番说教。 3. It is easier than the practice to deliver a sermon. 说教比实践更容易。', '形容词: sermonic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sanguine', '[\'sæŋɡwɪn]', 'adj.乐天的；自信的；红润的 n.血红色', '1. I was born in high summer and own a sanguine character. 出生于盛夏的我，拥有乐天性格。 2. His private expectations were not so sanguine. 他私下的期望并不是那么乐观。 3. We are sanguine that we shall be succeeding. 我们自信会成功。 4. His hair was very fair, his face naturally sanguine. 他的头发很淡，脸色天生红润。', '副词: sanguinely 名词: sanguineness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repudiate', '[rɪ\'pjuːdieɪt]', 'v.拒绝；拒付；断绝；否认', '1. The new government repudiated the treaty signed by the former government. 新政府拒绝履行前任政府签订的条约。 2. He repudiated the court\'s decision to offer bail. 他不接受法庭的保释裁决。 3. He would repudiate all debts incurred by his son. 他拒绝偿还他儿子的一切债务。 4. She repudiated her only daughter. 她与她的独生女儿断绝了母女关系。', '形容词: repudiative 名词: repudiator 过去式: repudiated 过去分词: repudiated 现在分词: repudiating 第三人称单数: repudiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stunning', '[\'stʌnɪŋ]', 'adj.令人震惊的；<口>极好的；极漂亮的', '1. The newspapers had fallen into a stunning silence. 报界陷入令人吃惊的沉默。 2. The President\'s final decision came with stunning suddenness. 总统之最后决定的突然性令人吃惊。 3. She was a stunning girl. I couldn\'t take my eyes off her. 她是一个极漂亮的姑娘，我无法把目光从她身上移开。 4. Eva wore a stunning gown to the ball. 伊娃穿了件很漂亮的晚礼服参加舞会。', '副词: stunningly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('laud', '[lɔːd]', 'v.赞美 n.颂歌；赞美', '1. He was lauded for his courage. 他的勇敢受到了人们的称赞。 2. My mother lauded me yesterday. 我妈妈昨天表扬了我。 3. I will laud my enemies and they will become our friends. 我赞美敌人', '名词: lauder 过去式: lauded 过去分词: lauded 现在分词: lauding 第三人称单数: lauds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assuage', '[ə\'sweɪdʒ]', 'v.缓和；减轻；镇定', '1. Nothing can assuage the widow\'s grief. 什么也不能缓和这寡妇的哀伤。 2. His reply did little to assuage my suspicions. 他的答覆一点也没有减少我的怀疑。', '名词: assuagement 过去式: assuaged 过去分词: assuaged 现在分词: assuaging 第三人称单数: assuages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sermonize', '[\'sɜːrmənaɪz]', 'v.说教；讲道 =sermonise(英).', '1. The boy got a sermon from his father. 这男孩受到他父亲的训斥。 2. He preaches the same sermon every Christmas. 他每逢圣诞节都宣讲同一教旨。 3. The half- baked sermon cause spiritual indigestion. 半生不熟的说教会引起精神上的消化不良。 4. Sometimes the rector came up and preached a sermon. 有时候教区牧师来布道。', '名词: sermonizer 过去式: sermonized 过去分词: sermonized 现在分词: sermonizing 第三人称单数: sermonizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indicative', '[ɪn\'dɪkətɪv]', 'adj.指示的；暗示的；【语】陈述的 n.陈述语气', '1. Use the indicative mood to make a sentence. 请用陈述语气造句。 2. There are three moods, indicative, imperative and subjunctive in English. 英语中有三种语气，即陈述语气，祈使语气和虚拟语气。', '副词: indicatively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reimburse', '[ˌriːɪm\'bɜːrs]', 'vt.偿还；报销', '1. I was reimbursed in full. 我已得到全部补偿。 2. We will reimburse the customer for any loss or damage. 我们将赔偿顾客所受到的一切损失和损害。 3. The company will reimburse you for travel expenses. 公司会为你报销差旅费。 4. All expenses will be reimbursed to you. 一切费用都能给你报销。', '形容词: reimbursable 名词: reimbursement 过去式: reimbursed 过去分词: reimbursed 现在分词: reimbursing 第三人称单数: reimburses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('err', '[er]', 'v.犯错；做错', '1. Instead, the policy maker may decide to err on the side of safety. 相反，为了公众安全决策者会作出决策，而不惜犯错。 2. They know to err oneself, alarmed, you see me, I see you, how is knowing good. 他们自知犯错，一阵惊慌，你看我，我看你，不知如何是好。 3. She would not err in any way, if she could help it. 只要有可能的话，她要避免做错任何动作。', '过去式: erred 过去分词: erred 现在分词: erring 第三人称单数: errs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immunize', '[\'ɪmjunaɪz]', 'vt.使免疫；赋予免疫性', '1. Have you been immunized (against smallpox) yet? 你接种过(抗天花)疫苗没有?', '名词: immunization 过去式: immunized 过去分词: immunized 现在分词: immunizing 第三人称单数: immunizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('willowy', '[\'wɪloʊi]', 'adj.柳树茂密的；柳树般的；苗条的', '1. Some guys go for tall, willowy girls. 有些男人喜欢又高又瘦的女人。 2. She was transformed from a lanky adolescent into a willowy young woman. 她从一个瘦削的少女变成一位苗条的少妇。', '比较级: willowier 最高级: willowiest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conglomerate', '[kən\'ɡlɑːmərət]', 'n.联合企业；密集体；城郊混合区；[地]砾岩 adj.聚成一团的；成簇的 vt.使聚集；使结成；结合', '1. An American conglomerate holds a major share in the company. 一家美国的大联合企业持有该公司的大部分股份。 2. The firm has been taken over by an American conglomerate. 该公司已被美国一企业集团接管。 3. The house was a conglomerate of architectural styles. 这幢房子是多种建筑风格的综合。 4. Sandstone and conglomerate are the consolidated equivalent of sand and gravel. 砂岩和砾岩分别是砂和砾石固结的产物。 5. A large number of people conglomerated round her. 在她周围聚集了一大群人。', '形容词: conglomeratic 名词: conglomerator 过去式: conglomerated 过去分词: conglomerated 现在分词: conglomerating 第三人称单数: conglomerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reprove', '[rɪ\'pruːv]', 'v.责备；责骂；非难', '1. I stand corrected and reprove myself. 我承认有错并予自责。 2. She reproved him for telling lies. 她骂他说谎。 3. She again found herself unable to reprove him. 她又一次发现自己难以开口责备他。 4. I have to reprove you for repeating the same mistakes over and over again. 你屡屡重犯同样的错误，我不得不严厉地批评你。', '形容词: reprovable 副词: reprovingly 名词: reprover 过去式: reproved 过去分词: reproved 现在分词: reproving 第三人称单数: reproves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('precipitant', '[prɪ\'sɪpətənt]', 'adj.倾斜下落的；倒栽葱的；突如其来的 n.沉淀剂', '1. With calcium chloride precipitant to eliminate the interference of PO43-, total nitrogen in compound fertilizer is determined by formol method. 用氯化钙作沉淀剂，消除磷酸根离子的干扰，用甲醛法测定复合肥中的总氮。', '副词: precipitantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pantheon', '[\'pænθiɑːn]', 'n.万神殿；众神；名流；伟人', '1. The amazing Pantheon has stopped me in my tracks . 神奇的万神殿当场让我驻足。 2. She has won her place in the pantheon of popular culture. 她在大众文化名流中获得了一席之地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('piddling', '[\'pɪdlɪŋ]', 'adj.无用的；琐屑的', '1. I don\'t want to hear all the piddling little details! 我不想听那些琐碎的事！', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compartment', '[kəm\'pɑːrtmənt]', 'n.间隔；个别室；卧车包房 vt.划分', '1. This is a case with separate compartments for shoes, jewelry, etc. 这是一个分格存放鞋、珠宝等的箱子。 2. and the rats move into the front compartment. 老鼠就会移入前间隔间。 3. Since there was no one else in the compartment I was able to spread myself. 车厢间隔里没有别人，我正好能伸胳膊伸腿舒坦一下。 4. The first-class compartments are in the front of the train. 头等车室在列车的前面。 5. Life today is compartmented into work and leisure. 现今生活分成工作和闲暇两部分。', '形容词: compartmental 过去式: compartmented 过去分词: compartmented 现在分词: compartmenting 第三人称单数: compartments');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('curb', '[kɜːrb]', 'n.路边；克制；勒马绳 vt.抑制；勒住；牵(狗)到合适地方大小便', '1. He parked his car along the curb. 他把汽车停靠在路边。 2. I stood at the curb trying to breathe. 我站在人行道沿上想缓口气。 3. You must try to put a curb on your bad temper. 你必须学着克制自己暴躁的脾气。 4. High interest rates put a curb on spending. 高利率抑制了消费 5. I could be able to curb my desires. 我能够抑制住自己的欲望。', '过去式: curbed 过去分词: curbed 现在分词: curbing 第三人称单数: curbs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abbreviate', '[ə\'briːvieɪt]', 'vt.缩写；缩短；使简略', '1. In writing, the title `Doctor\' is abbreviated to `Dr\'. 在书写时，Doctor头衔的缩写是Dr. 2. It is seldom acceptable to abbreviate words in formal writing. 在正式的书面语中使用缩写语通常是不能接受的。 3. The teacher asked me to abbreviate my report to one page . 老师让我把报告缩短为一页。 4. The United States of america is commonly abbreviated to U.S.a.. 美利坚合众国常被缩略为 U.', '名词: abbreviator 过去式: abbreviated 过去分词: abbreviated 现在分词: abbreviating 第三人称单数: abbreviates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('provident', '[\'prɑːvɪdənt]', 'adj.有先见之明的；节俭的', '1. Some of the farmers had been provident in the good years but others were ruined by the bad harvests. 有些农民在丰年节衣缩食有备无患，但也有些农民由於歉收而陷入绝境。 2. Provident men lay aside money for their families. 深谋远虑的人为家庭贮蓄钱财。 3. She has been provident since she was young, so she is thrifty in shopping. 她从小节省惯了，买东西的时候很节俭。', '副词: providently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vampire', '[\'væmpaɪər]', 'n.吸血鬼；吸血蝠', '1. I want to dress up as a vampire. 我想要装扮成吸血鬼。 2. Vampire is fond of extracting blood from others. 吸血鬼喜欢吸别人的血。', '形容词: vampiric');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('daunt', '[dɔːnt]', 'vt.使 ... 胆怯；恐吓', '1. Danger didn\'t daunt the hero. 危险并没有吓住那英雄。 2. I was rather daunted by the thought of addressing such an audience. 我一想到要对这样的听众讲话，就有些胆小。 3. No difficulties in the world can daunt us. 世界上任何困难都吓不倒我们。 4. Even a greater natural calamity cannot daunt us. 再大的自然灾害也压不垮我们。', '副词: dauntingly 名词: daunter 过去式: daunted 过去分词: daunted 现在分词: daunting 第三人称单数: daunts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foil', '[fɔɪl]', 'n.钝头剑；箔；陪衬物；（击剑运动用的）花剑 vt.挫败；击退；阻挠', '1. The foil is a thrusting weapon with no cutting edge. 花剑，没有劈杀用的剑刀，是刺戳用兵器。 2. Our foil packets seal the flavour in. 我们用锡纸包装以保持原味。 3. Aluminum foil can be used for wrapping food. 铝箔用于包装食物。 4. This box of chocolate was wrapped round with foil. 这盒巧克力用箔纸包着。 5. Only confident, people will never foil. 只要有信心，人永远不会挫败。', '过去式: foiled 过去分词: foiled 现在分词: foiling 第三人称单数: foils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('badge', '[bædʒ]', 'n.象征；标记；徽章；证章 vt.授给 ... 徽章', '1. Chains are a badge of slavery. 锁链是奴役的标志。 2. The olive leaf is a badge of peace. 橄榄叶是和平的象征。 3. What is that badge on your lapel? 你翻领上的是什么徽章? 4. He was awarded a merit badge for his bravery in the battle. 他因为在战斗中的勇猛被授予一枚奖章。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pilot', '[\'paɪlət]', 'n.飞行员；领航员；试播节目；<美>排障器；[机]导向器 v.驾驶；领航；向导；试点 adj.试验性的；引导的', '1. A pilot must be awake to the changes in the weather. 飞行员必须警觉天气的变化。 2. Mark used to be a pilot on the Mississippi River. 马克曾在密西西比河上当过领航员。 3. JULES I think her biggest deal was she starred in a pilot. 朱尔斯：我想她最重要的演出是在一个试片里担任主角。 4. When did you learn to pilot an airplane? 你什么时候学会驾驶飞机的? 5. We are doing a pilot study to see if the new product will sell well. 我们正在为这种新产品做试销调查，看它的销路好不好。', '过去式: piloted 过去分词: piloted 现在分词: piloting 第三人称单数: pilots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dummy', '[\'dʌmi]', 'n.傀儡；假人；仿制品；笨蛋；哑巴 adj.假的；仿造的 vt.保密', '1. I have no ideas of my own. I am just a dummy doll. 我没有自己的想法,我只是一个傀儡娃娃。 2. Students are practicing thrusts at the straw filled dummy. 现在让学生们在填充稻草的假人靶上练刀。 3. The life-size dummy is used to display clothes. 和人大小相似的假人可以用来陈列衣服。 4. The bottles of whisky on display are all dummies. 所陈列的威士忌酒都是假的。 5. David carried a dummy duck to the dock. 大卫带着一只假鸭到港口。 6. She dummied up the books that are to be published. 她对即将出版的书保密。', '名词复数: dummies 过去式: dummied 过去分词: dummied 现在分词: dummying 第三人称单数: dummies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('potentate', '[\'poʊtnteɪt]', 'n.有权的人；统治者；君主', '1. People rose up against the despotic rule of their potentate. 人们起来反抗君主的专制统治。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pungent', '[\'pʌndʒənt]', 'adj.刺鼻的；辛辣的；尖锐的；刻薄的', '1. With less fat to balance out the pungent flavors, you can really taste the natural piquancy of lush spring fields. 以少量的脂肪来平衡辛辣的香草味，你能真正品尝到春天郁郁葱葱的野外所特有的自然辛辣味。 2. The president was shocked because he received an anonymous letter which contained some pungent problems. 总统收到了一封匿名信，里面有一些很尖锐的问题，这让他感到很震惊。 3. Yet it breeds antipathies of the most pungent character between those who lay the emphasis differently. 然而，由于个人的着重点不同，彼此之间就产生了许多非常尖锐的嫌恶感。', '副词: pungently 名词: pungency');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('companion', '[kəm\'pæniən]', 'n.同伴；志趣相投的人；成对物品之一；参考书 v.陪伴', '1. He is a good companion on the journey. 他是个好旅伴。 2. He had always considered her an ideal companion for his son. 他一直以为她是他儿子的理想伴侣。 3. The dog has been her constant companion these past ten years. 过去十年来,这只狗一直与她形影不离。 4. His brother is not much of a companion for him. 他兄弟与他情趣不甚相投。 5. I worked as a companion to an old princess. 我当过一位老公爵夫人的陪伴人。', '过去式: companioned 过去分词: companioned 现在分词: companioning 第三人称单数: companions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chord', '[kɔːrd]', 'n.弦；和弦；情绪', '1. He is replacing the broken chord of his violin. 他正在更换小提琴上那根断了的弦。 2. Love is a chord in life, not a solo alone. 爱是人生的和弦，不是孤独的独奏曲。 3. There are two naturals in this chord. 这一和弦中有两个本位音。 4. Her speech struck a deep chord in my heart. 她的话深深地拨动了我的心弦。', '过去式: chorded 过去分词: chorded 现在分词: chording 第三人称单数: chords');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('henpecked', '[\'henpekt]', 'adj.顺从妻子的；惧内的', '1. He is a man rude but henpecked. 他是一个粗暴而惧内的男人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scribble', '[\'skrɪbl]', 'v.潦草地书写；乱写 n.潦草的写法', '1. The speaker spoke so fast that he could only scribble down several broken words. 演讲者讲得太快了，他只能匆匆记下几个支离破碎的字。 2. Do not scribble on the wall! 不要在墙上乱涂！ 3. The students are told not to scribble on the desk. 学生们被要求不在桌子上乱写。 4. I can make nothing of all this scribble. 这样潦草的笔迹我一点也看不懂。', '形容词: scribbly 过去式: scribbled 过去分词: scribbled 现在分词: scribbling 第三人称单数: scribbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wizen', '[\'wɪzən]', 'v.干涸；使干枯 adj.凋谢的；枯萎的', '1. Hard wind and bitter cold wizen his face. 强风与酷寒使他的脸孔皱缩了。 2. There would be a day when our faces would be wrinkled and wizen . 总有一天，我们的脸会布满皱纹而且变得皱缩的。 3. Don\'t sigh for wizen flowers,because no wizen flowers no fruits! 不要为凋谢的花惋惜，花不谢，是结不出果实的。 4. You raise Super Mega Pet through each of the Seven Stages of Life, from Egg to Wizen. Super Mega Pet: Digital Life Form 你从蛋举起上等的百万宠爱穿过每个七个阶段的生命使，起皱。', '过去式: wizened 过去分词: wizened 现在分词: wizening 第三人称单数: wizens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vanity', '[\'vænəti]', 'n.自负；虚荣心；无价值的东西；浮华', '1. Vanity is his Achilles\' heel. 虚荣自负是他的致命伤。 2. He has many faults, but vanity is not one of them. 他有很多缺点，但并没有虚荣心。 3. His vanity brought his downfall. 他因虚荣心太重而垮台。 4. She married the rich man out of vanity. 她出于虚荣心而嫁给了那个富人。', '名词复数: vanities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foster', '[\'fɔːstər]', 'vt.领养；培养；促进；鼓励；抱有（希望等） adj.收养的', '1. People who cannot have a baby of their own sometimes foster (a child). 不能生育的人有时领养别人的(孩子). 2. It is very important to foster an interest. 培养一种兴趣是十分重要的。 3. The mother tried to foster her son\'s interest in music. 母亲设法培养儿子对音乐的兴趣。 4. Ignorance fosters superstition. 无知助长迷信。 5. The foster children also deserve love and care. 收养的孩子也应该得到关爱。', '过去式: fostered 过去分词: fostered 现在分词: fostering 第三人称单数: fosters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disparate', '[\'dɪspərət]', 'adj.不同的；异类的', '1. The five experiments gave quite disparate results. 这五次试验所获得的结果迥然不同。 2. Chalk and cheese are disparate substances. 粉笔和乳酪是完全不同的东西。 3. With such disparate political groups, the country is in real mess. 有着这么多根本不相同的政治集团，这个国家是真正陷入了困境。', '副词: disparately 名词: disparateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decree', '[dɪ\'kriː]', 'n.法令；判决 v.颁布；裁定；注定', '1. This decree obliges unions to delay strikes . 这项法令使协会不得不推迟罢工。 2. The decree imposed strict censorship of the media. 这个法令强制实行严格的媒体审查制度。 3. The final decree dissolved their marriage. 最后的判决解除了他们的婚姻关系。 4. This decree has the force of law behind it. 这一裁决有法律的力量作后盾。 5. The dictator decreed that his birthday would be a public holiday. 该独裁者发布命令，将其生日定为公众假期。', '形容词: decreeable 名词: decreer 过去式: decreed 过去分词: decreed 现在分词: decreeing 第三人称单数: decrees');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demolish', '[dɪ\'mɑːlɪʃ]', 'v.拆毁；破坏；驳倒；<口>吃光', '1. They have demolished the slum district. 贫民区已被拆除。 2. They\'re going to demolish that old building. 他们将拆毁那座旧建筑物。 3. It was an experience that completely demolished her confidence. 这个经历彻底摧毁了她的信心。 4. Her article brilliantly demolishes his argument. 她的文章精辟地批驳了他的论点。', '过去式: demolished 过去分词: demolished 现在分词: demolishing 第三人称单数: demolishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quartet', '[kwɔːr\'tet]', 'n.四重奏', '1. They danced to the music of a string quartet. 他们随着弦乐四重奏乐曲跳舞。 2. The concert started with a Mozart Quartet. 音乐会以莫札特的一曲四重奏开始。 3. This quartet represents a major new trend in modern music. 这首四重奏的曲子反映了现代音乐中一种主要的新趋向。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apostate', '[ə\'pɑːsteɪt]', 'n.背教者；变节者；脱党者 adj.背教的；变节的；脱党的', '1. He is an apostate from Christianity. 他是一个基督教的背信者。 2. The most furious anarchist become the most barefaced apostate. 最激烈的无政府主义者，居然成了最露骨的变节者。 3. The Jerusalem Post denounced him as an apostate. 耶路撒冷邮报也批评他变节。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('waylay', '[weɪ\'leɪ]', 'v.伏击；拦住；拦路抢劫', '1. She linger outside the theater to waylay him after the show. 她在戏院外面徘徊想在演出之后拦住他说话。 2. He waylaid me with a request for a loan. 他等我经过时拦住我向我借钱。 3. The patrol was waylaid by bandits. 巡逻队遭到土匪伏击。', '名词: waylayer 过去式: waylaid 过去分词: waylaid 现在分词: waylaying 第三人称单数: waylays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agnostic', '[æɡ\'nɑːstɪk]', 'n.不可知论者 adj.不可知论的；不可知论者的', '1. Catholics are agnostic to the Protestant creeds. 天主教徒对于新教教义来说，是不可知论者。 2. It was all new to me because, like my father, I was an agnostic and had not heard of fundamentalism. 这对我来说是新鲜的，因为我以前跟父亲一样，都是不可知论者，我并无接触过基要派。 3. Catholics are agnostic to the Protestant creeds. 天主教徒对于新教教义来说，是不可知论者。 4. It was all new to me because, like my father, I was an agnostic and had not heard of fundamentalism. 这对我来说是新鲜的，因为我以前跟父亲一样，都是不可知论者，我并无接触过基要派。', '副词: agnostically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('periscope', '[\'perɪskoʊp]', 'n.潜望镜', '1. A simple periscope uses mirrors. 简单的潜望镜使用平面镜。 2. Three kinds of periscope series are now produced in Thales Optronics. 泰利斯光电子公司目前生产三种系列的潜望镜。', '形容词: periscopic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anachronistic', '[əˌnækrə\'nɪstɪk]', 'adj.时代错误的；落伍的，过时的，不合时宜的', '1. In remembering historic events, the mistake you tend to make is anachronistic. 在记历史事件时,你容易犯的错误是时代错误。 2. For one thing, JVs themselves are a tad anachronistic. 首先，合资企业本身多少就是一个时代错误。 3. English public schools are anachronistic. 英国的公立学校已经落伍过时了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pasteurize', '[\'pæstʃəraɪz]', 'vt.用（巴氏消毒法）高热杀菌；消毒', '1. Additionally, donor milk banks pasteurize all milk prior to distribution and check it for bacterial content. 另外，母乳银行在分发母乳之前会对所有母乳进行巴氏消毒，检查细菌情况。', '名词: pasteurizer 过去式: pasteurized 过去分词: pasteurized 现在分词: pasteurizing 第三人称单数: pasteurizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hoary', '[\'hɔːri]', 'adj.灰白的；古老的', '1. His hoary hair showed his age. 他的花白的头发显示出了他的年龄。 2. The hoary peasant mused over his past sufferings. 这位白发的农民默想着他过去所受的苦难。 3. He told us a hoary old joke that we\'d all heard many times before. 他给我们讲了一个我们都听了很多次的老掉牙的笑话。 4. They discussed the hoary old problem. 他们讨论老问题。', '副词: hoarily 比较级: hoarier 最高级: hoariest 名词: hoariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invigorating', '[ɪn\'vɪɡəreɪtɪŋ]', 'adj.精神充沛的 动词invigorate的现在分词形式.', '1. An invigorating, refreshing, or restorative agent or influence. 增强物增加活力、精神或帮助恢复的物品或影响 2. A brisk walk in cool weather is invigorating. 在凉爽的天气里轻松地散步令人心旷神怡。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ode', '[oʊd]', 'n.颂诗；赋', '1. I am reading \'Ode to Autumn\' written by Keats. 我在读济慈的“秋颂”。 2. It is an ode to friendship along the ancient Silk Road. 这是一曲古丝绸之路上的友谊之歌。 3. As a young child, she often recites lines from the ancient ode. 小时候她经常背诵古赋里的辞句。', '形容词: odic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('armistice', '[\'ɑːrmɪstɪs]', 'n.休战；休战书；停战条约', '1. After the armistice he had spent a month in Paris. 停战以后他在巴黎呆了一个月。 2. The Sultan asked for an armistice in January 1878. 1878年1月苏丹要求停火。 3. The two nations signed an armistice. 两国签署了停火协议。 4. The armistice did not spare France a pang. 停战协定并未使法国免遭剧烈的创伤。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('luxurious', '[lʌɡ\'ʒʊriəs]', 'adj.奢侈的；豪华的', '1. She has been honing for a luxurious life. 她一直渴望过豪华奢侈的生活。 2. He lived in luxurious surroundings. 他生活在奢侈的环境中。 3. The lady appeared with a luxurious fur coat. 那位夫人穿着华贵的毛皮外套来了。 4. The millionaire leads a luxurious life. 那个百万富翁过着豪华的生活。', '副词: luxuriously 名词: luxuriousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hygiene', '[\'haɪdʒiːn]', 'n.卫生；卫生学', '1. People should wash regularly to ensure personal hygiene. 人们应经常洗澡以保证个人卫生。 2. Many diseases proceed from negligence of hygiene. 许多疾病源于不讲卫生。 3. He\'s going to give us a lecture on public hygiene. 他要给我们作关于公共卫生方面的报告。 4. Hygiene has evolved into preventive medicine. 卫生学已逐步发展成为预防医学。', '名词: hygienist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demean', '[dɪ\'miːn]', 'v.贬低；降低', '1. I\'ll never demean myself by doing something dishonorable. 我决不会做什么不名誉的事来辱没自己。 2. You will demean yourself if you agree to the terms of the contract. 要是你同意契约的条款，就等于瞧不起自己。 3. He felt he would demean himself if he replied to the scurrilous letter. 他觉得如果他回复那封充满辱骂的信，会自贬身份。 4. I wouldn\'t demean myself by asking for charity. 我决不低三下四地乞求施舍。', '副词: demeaningly 过去式: demeaned 过去分词: demeaned 现在分词: demeaning 第三人称单数: demeans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('circumference', '[sər\'kʌmfərəns]', 'n.圆周；周围；周长', '1. That point falls on the circumference of the circle. 那一个点落在这圆的圆周线上。 2. He went jogging around the circumference of the reservoir every morning. 他每天早晨绕着水库周围慢跑。 3. This tree has a circumference of 6 feet. 这棵树周长六英尺。 4. The circumference of the earth is almost 25,000 miles. 地球的圆周长约为两万五千英里。', '形容词: circumferential');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sterilize', '[\'sterəlaɪz]', 'vt.使不育；杀菌 使贫瘠', '1. After her fourth child she decided to have herself sterilized. 她生了第四个孩子后决定做绝育手术。', '名词: sterilizer 过去式: sterilized 过去分词: sterilized 现在分词: sterilizing 第三人称单数: sterilizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('definition', '[ˌdefɪ\'nɪʃn]', 'n.定义；阐释；清晰度', '1. To give a definition of a word is more difficult than to give an illustration of its use. 给一个词下定义要比举例说明它的用法困难。 2. My duties require clearer definition. 我的职责需要更清楚的说明。 3. The photo lacks definition. 这张照片不够清晰。', '形容词: definitional');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gosling', '[\'ɡɑːzlɪŋ]', 'n.小鹅；年轻无知的人', '1. This report is about diagnosis and control of gosling pest. 这份报告是关于小鹅瘟的诊断与防制的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deadlock', '[\'dedlɑːk]', 'n.僵局；停顿；(比赛等的)分数不分上下 v.停顿；相持不下', '1. The negotiations have reached a deadlock. 谈判陷入僵局。 2. Without upheaval, deadlock would be entrenched. 不经过巨变，僵局将很难打破。 3. We can only make minor concessions, but it might break the deadlock. 我们只能做些较小的让步，但这就可能打破僵局。 4. A potential deadlock condition has been detected. 检测出潜在的死锁状态。 5. The employer and strikers have been deadlocked for almost a week. 雇主与罢工工人已僵持了近一个星期。', '过去式: deadlocked 过去分词: deadlocked 现在分词: deadlocking 第三人称单数: deadlocks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shamble', '[\'ʃæmbl]', 'n.蹒跚；摇晃的脚步 v.蹒跚地走；摇摇晃晃地走；摇晃不稳', '1. Wait, please; you betray too much vigor, too much decision; you want more of a shamble. 您先别忙；这可显着太有精神，太有决断了；还得再带点儿磨磨蹭蹭的样子才成。 2. Shuffle and shamble indicate moving without lifting the feet completely off the ground. shuffle 和shamble 均指行走时脚不完全离开地面. 3. They shamble, unused to walking on two legs, and find the human\'s mild sensory depravation unnerving. 他们摇摇晃晃,不习惯用两条腿走路,并且觉得人类温和的感观会使他们失常堕落。 4. Wait, please; you betray too much vigor, too much decision; you want more of a shamble . 您先别忙；这可显着太有精神，太有决断了；还得再带点儿磨磨蹭蹭的样子才成。', '过去式: shambled 过去分词: shambled 现在分词: shambling 第三人称单数: shambles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defunct', '[dɪ\'fʌŋkt]', 'adj.死的；不能使用的；非现存的；失效的 n.死者', '1. A family name becomes defunct when the only heir dies without any son. 当唯一的继承人死去了之后没儿子，那这个姓就要绝迹了。 2. It is a defunct political organization. 这是一个解散了的政治组织。 3. Most of the time of the defunct had been passed in helping himself. 死者生前大部分时间都是用来造福自己。', '形容词: defunctive 名词: defunctness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glitch', '[ɡlɪtʃ]', 'n.小故障；小失误', '1. There is a glitch in the computer program somewhere. 这个计算机程序中的某个部分有点小问题。 2. It could just be a random glitch that can be solved by restarting the machine. 可能只是一个小故障，重新启动主机就能解决了。', '形容词: glitchy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assessment', '[ə\'sesmənt]', 'n.评价；评估；评定', '1. His assessment of the situation was spot-on. 他对形势判断得很正确。 2. Your assessment is substantially correct. 你的估计基本正确。 3. It was a shrewd assessment and probably pretty close to the truth. 这个评估很有道理，可能相当正确。 4. Continuous assessment is made of all students\' work. 对全体学生的功课作出连贯性的评定。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('semblance', '[\'sembləns]', 'n.假象；类似；外观；假装；外表', '1. By now any semblance of normality had disappeared. 到了现在，任何常态的假象都消失了。 2. Your mother bears the semblance of yourself. 你的母亲有你的相似之处。 3. Those clouds have the semblance of a large head. 那些云的形状像一个巨大的人头。 4. He escaped under the semblance of a university student. 他装成一个大学生逃跑了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obvious', '[\'ɑːbviəs]', 'adj.明显的；显然的', '1. It is obvious that she is very clever. 很明显，她挺聪明。 2. The embassy is an obvious target for terrorist attacks. 大使馆是恐怖分子攻击的明显目标。 3. The merits of the scheme are quite obvious. 该计画的可取之处是相当明显的。 4. All great truths are obvious truths. But no all obvious truths are great truths. 所有伟大的真理都是显而易见的事实,但并非所有显而易见的事实都是伟大的真理。', '副词: obviously 名词: obviousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pedestal', '[\'pedɪstl]', 'n.基架；底座；受人尊敬的地位 vt.搁在台上；颂扬', '1. The workers put the statue on its pedestal. 工人们把雕像放到基座上。 2. The two images stand on a pedestal facing the west. 两个肖像都座落在面向西面的基架。 3. Before it could be transported to the United States, a site had to be found for it and a pedestal had to be built. 在雕像可以运往美国之前，必须给它选个场地，还要建造一个雕像底座。 4. He put his wife on a pedestal and so was all the more hurt when he found she was capable of deceiving him. 他把妻子当作偶像崇拜，因此当他知道她是在欺骗他时，他受到的打击实在太大了。 5. He desired not to be pedestalled, but to sink into the crowd. 他不愿高高在上, 而愿深入到民众当中去。', '过去式: pedestaled/pedestalled 过去分词: pedestaled/pedestalled 现在分词: pedestaling/pedestalling 第三人称单数: pedestals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embodiment', '[ɪm\'bɑːdimənt]', 'n.化身；体现', '1. She\'s the embodiment of kindness. 她是慈祥的化身。 2. The new factory is the embodiment of the very latest ideas. 这座新工厂是那些最新设想的体现。 3. If there is a French exception, Mr Chirac is its embodiment. 如果说，存在一个法国例外，希拉克就是其体现。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retort', '[rɪ\'tɔːrt]', 'v.反驳；回嘴；反击 n.反驳；顶嘴', '1. He retorted that it was my fault as much as his. 他反驳说我的错误并不比他的小。 2. The analysts could retort only that the geometric proofs were clumsy and inelegant. 分析学家只能回嘴说几何的证明是笨拙而不优美的。 3. \'Don\'t be ridiculous!\' Pat retorted angrily. “别荒唐了！”帕特生气地回答道。 4. Her roommate\'s retort made her angry. 她同屋的反驳使她生气。', '名词: retorter 过去式: retorted 过去分词: retorted 现在分词: retorting 第三人称单数: retorts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flatulence', '[\'flætʃələns]', 'n.肠胃气胀；浮夸；空虚', '1. One symptom of chronic gastritis is flatulence. 慢性胃炎的症状之一就是气胀。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('narcissism', '[\'nɑːrsɪsɪzəm]', 'n.自我陶醉；自恋', '1. He indulged himself in narcissism when he read his own work. 看见自己的作品，他自我陶醉起来。 2. This is a form of self-admiration, narcissism. 这是一种自爱、自恋的表现。 3. Current technology fuels the increase in narcissism. 当代科技刺激了自恋的增长。', '形容词: narcissistic 副词: narcissistically 异体字: narcism 名词: narcissist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('feign', '[feɪn]', 'vt.假装；捏造 vi.假装；装作', '1. People may feign incapability to fraudulently claim the benefits, thus depriving the really needy. 人可能假装无能欺诈索赔的好处，从而剥夺了真正有需要的。 2. People may feign incapability to fraudulently claim the benefits, thus depriving the really needy. 人可能假装无能欺诈索赔的好处，从而剥夺了真正有需要的。 3. To feign frankness is a ruse of war. 装作坦白，是为了作战的目的。', '过去式: feigned 过去分词: feigned 现在分词: feigning 第三人称单数: feigns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slab', '[slæb]', 'n.平板；厚板；厚片 v.切成厚板；以平板盖上', '1. The top of the table was formed by a stone slab. 桌面是一块石板。 2. A slab of stone laid flat over a grave. 平放在墓上的纪念碑石 3. The top of the table was a polished slab of marble. 桌面是一块磨光的大理石板。 4. A man was eating a huge slab of pizza. 一个人正在吃巨大的厚厚的批萨。', '过去式: slabbed 过去分词: slabbed 现在分词: slabbing 第三人称单数: slabs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muffled', '[\'mʌfld]', 'adj.(指声音)听不清的；低沉的 动词muffle的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. Her voice sounded muffled up. 她的声音听起来像是很压抑。 2. He speaks in a muffled voice which is not clear. 他说话闷声闷气的，让人听不清楚。 3. The noises of the street were muffled considerably. 街上的噪音减轻了许多。 4. There was a muffled explosion somewhere on their right. 在他们的右面什么地方有一声沉闷的爆炸声。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intractable', '[ɪn\'træktəbl]', 'adj.难驾驭的；倔强的；难加工的；难治疗的', '1. We are facing an intractable problem. 我们面临着一个难以解决的问题。 2. I\'m an intractable person and I will untiringly do what I want to do. 我是一个倔强的人，我想做的事情我一定会坚持不懈努力到底的。 3. You\'d better not use the intractable materials. 你最好不要用这些不易加工的材料。 4. The doctor told him that it was intractable pain. 医生告诉他这是难治疗的疼痛。', '副词: intractably 名词: intractability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lucid', '[\'luːsɪd]', 'adj.明白易懂的；清晰的；神智清醒的', '1. He had great powers of lucid exposition. 他具有清晰的表述能力。', '副词: lucidly 名词: lucidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wilt', '[wɪlt]', 'v.（使)枯萎；（使)萎靡 n.枯萎；憔悴', '1. The flowers are wilting for lack of water. 这些花因缺水而渐渐枯萎。 2. Several sleepless nights made him wilt. 数个不眠之夜使他憔悴。 3. We are the flowers in the wind, blooming for its wilt. 我们是风中飘落的花朵,为了枯萎而盛开。', '过去式: wilted 过去分词: wilted 现在分词: wilting 第三人称单数: wilts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obsessed', '[əb\'sest]', 'adj.着迷的', '1. The life of western Hunan obsessed him and applied him with many writing materials. 湘西生活有令他推崇和着迷的巨大魅力，也为他的写作提供大量的素材。 2. The whole, obsessed as it is with maximizing power and sex, must be questioned as to its emptiness. 整体上，被着迷的是当它在力量和性最大值的时候，一定会因为它的空虚被询问。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vile', '[vaɪl]', 'adj.恶劣的；简陋的；低廉的', '1. He\'s a vile dog! 他是个无耻之徒！ 2. Murder is a vile and loathsome crime. 谋杀是邪恶而令人发指的罪行。 3. Dad: So the goblins worked night and day in their vile workshops, and they built a golden army. 父亲：所以妖精们在他们简陋的作坊里日以继夜的工作，建造了黄金军团。 4. Do you expect me to drink this vile concoction? 你难道想让我喝这种乌七八糟的东西?', '副词: vilely 比较级: viler 最高级: vilest 名词: vileness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('epitomize', '[ɪ\'pɪtəmaɪz]', 'v. 摘要； 概括； 成为 ... 的缩影； 作为典范', '1. For a practice that has come to epitomize unethical business behavior, insider trading has received surprisingly little ethical analysis. 现实中，内幕交易已经成为不道德商业行为的缩影，但奇怪的是，几乎没人对其进行过伦理分析。 2. The Summer Season could be said to epitomize all that is traditionally English about England. 英格兰夏日是传统英格兰的缩影，要想定义它，的确是件难事。', '过去式: epitomized 过去分词: epitomized 现在分词: epitomizing 第三人称单数: epitomizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('collar', '[\'kɑːlər]', 'n.衣领；项圈；[机]轴环 vt.抓住；为 ... 戴上项圈；为 ... 上领子', '1. He grabbed my collar and pulled me towards him. 他抓住我的领子把我拉倒他面前。 2. He turned up his coat collar against the chill wind. 他竖起大衣领抵御寒风。 3. Where are the dog\'s collar and lead? 狗的颈圈和皮带哪去了？ 4. He seized the pickpocket by the collar. 他抓住那个扒手的衣领。', '形容词: collared 过去式: collared 过去分词: collared 现在分词: collaring 第三人称单数: collars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assorted', '[ə\'sɔːrtəd]', 'adj.各种各样的；各色俱备的；配合的；适合的 动词assort的过去式和过去分词.', '1. Demonstrators attacked the police, using sticks and assorted missiles. 示威者用棍棒和各种投掷物攻击警察。 2. Men and woman of assorted ages and degrees of prosperity rub shoulders and exchange opinions. 各种不同年龄和各种不同家境的男女互相接触并交换意见。 3. The jumper comes in assorted colours. 各种颜色的针织套衫一应俱全。 4. We have very nice braised assorted vegetables. 我们这里的素什锦非常好。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pathology', '[pə\'θɑːlədʒi]', 'n.病理学', '1. Pathology is the study of disease. 病理学是研究疾病的科学。 2. All cases were confirmed as RMAL by postoperative pathology. 所有手术病例，术后病理学诊断均为肾错构瘤。', '名词: pathologist 名词复数: pathologies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dastard', '[\'dæstəd]', 'n.懦夫；卑鄙的人 adj.怯懦的；卑劣的', '1. \"Yes, you pitiful dastard,\" retorted the lovely damsel. “是的，你这个卑鄙的胆小鬼，”那位美丽的少女反唇相讥。 2. \"Yes, you pitiful dastard,\" retorted the lovely damsel “是的，你这个卑鄙的胆小鬼，”那位美丽的少女反唇相讥。 3. \"yes. you pitiful dastard,\" retorted the lovely damsel “是的，你这个卑鄙的胆小鬼，”那位美丽的少女反唇相讥。 4. dastard n. 懦夫 [dastardly 懦弱的;', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hostile', '[\'hɑːstl]', 'adj.敌对的；怀敌意的', '1. Let\'s hope they will refrain from hostile actions. 希望他们不采取敌对行动。 2. I don\'t like her manner -- she\'s very hostile. 我不喜欢她的态度--待人如仇敌。 3. I don\'t know why she is hostile to me. 我不知道她为什么对我抱有敌意。 4. The new government was hostile to them. 新政府对他们怀有敌意。', '副词: hostilely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('manifold', '[\'mænɪfoʊld]', 'n.多种；复印本；多支管 adj.多种的；多方面的 v.复写；繁殖；增多', '1. The uses of this machine are manifold. 这台机器有多种用途。 2. Taoyuan Coal Mine is the threatened mine by manifold groundwater. 桃园煤矿是一个受多种地下水害威胁的矿井。 3. Interconnecting flow passages travel through the manifold from the valve cavities. 互相连接流程通道旅行过来自活瓣洞的复印本。 4. observant fairly', '副词: manifoldly 名词: manifoldness 过去式: manifolded 过去分词: manifolded 现在分词: manifolding 第三人称单数: manifolds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recede', '[rɪ\'siːd]', 'vi.后退；减弱 vt.撤回', '1. His hair is beginning to recede from his forehead. 他的头发开始从前额往后秃了。 2. As the tide receded we were able to look for shells. 潮水退去，我们就能寻找贝壳了。 3. The prospect of bankruptcy has now receded. 破产的危险已经减少了。 4. Eventually the danger began to recede. 这种危险终于开始减轻。 5. The company decided to recede from a bargain. 公司决定撤销买卖合同。', '过去式: receded 过去分词: receded 现在分词: receding 第三人称单数: recedes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clot', '[klɑːt]', 'n.凝块；一群；<非正式>笨蛋 v.凝结；阻塞', '1. Ruby,convicted murdered of Oswald,died on January 3,1967 from a blood clot that lodged in his lungs. Ruby，曾经被指控谋杀Oswald，由于血液凝块进入肺部，死于1967年1月3日。 2. The pipe under the bathroom sink was jammed by a huge clot of hair. 浴室洗手台下的水管被一大团头发堵塞了。 3. A haemophiliac\'s blood will not clot properly. 血友病患者的血液凝固不良。 4. Researchers say the water dilutes the blood, making it less likely to clot. 研究人员说，水可以稀释血液，使之不易发生凝结。', '过去式: clotted 过去分词: clotted 现在分词: clotting 第三人称单数: clots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hitherto', '[ˌhɪðər\'tuː]', 'adv.到目前为止；迄今', '1. Hitherto, this is the advanced method. 到目前为止，这是先进的方法。 2. Hitherto he had experienced no great success in his attempt. 到目前为止，他的这种尝试还没有取得任何重大的成功。 3. For hitherto though I have lost all my time. 迄今我虽然失去了全部的时日。 4. I had hitherto continued to board with Godfrey. 迄今我仍在戈费雷处用膳。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ensign', '[\'ensən]', 'n.国旗；军旗；海军少尉；徽章', '1. The ensign of the United States is Stars and Stripes. 美国国旗是星条旗。 2. At that moment, from behind the short bushes, there appeared the artillery ensign. 此时从矮小的丛林后面出现了炮兵部队的军旗。 3. Her elder brother was an ensign before his discharge. 她哥哥退伍前是海军少尉。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('opacity', '[oʊ\'pæsəti]', 'n.不透明；晦涩难懂；迟钝；暧昧', '1. Opacity is due to crazes in the resin. 不透明是因树脂中产生裂纹。', '名词复数: opacities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confidence', '[\'kɑːnfɪdəns]', 'n.信任；把握；信心；知心话 adj.骗得信任的', '1. The servant enjoyed his master\'s confidence. 这仆人深得主人的信赖。 2. We have full confidence that we shall succeed. 我们完全有把握取得成功。 3. The worst barrier to your success is not lack of money, but lack of confidence. 你成功最大的障碍不是缺钱,而是缺乏信心。 4. The two girls told each other confidences about their boyfriends. 这两个姑娘相互谈了关于各自男友的悄悄话。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carbohydrate', '[ˌkɑːrboʊ\'haɪdreɪt]', 'n.碳水化合物；糖类', '1. Carbohydrates provide our bodies with heat and energy. 碳水化合物给我们的身体提供热量和能量。 2. Athletes usually eat a high carbohydrate diet. 运动员通常吃高碳水化合物食物。 3. The receptor for hemagglutinin may be a carbohydrate. 其血凝素受体为糖类。 4. Of excessive adipose or carbohydrate food can bring about fatty liver. 过量的脂肪或糖类食物可导致脂肪肝。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ridge', '[rɪdʒ]', 'n.脊；山脊；山脉；隆起部 v.（使）成山脊', '1. Recurvature follows after it traverses the ridge axis. 预料尼伯特将于横过副高脊线后开始转向。 2. Riding on the ridge of the bridge, the proud bride shouts loudly to the cloud. 骄傲的新娘骑在桥脊上对着云大声喊。 3. He walked along the mountain ridge. 他顺着山脊走。 4. The evening before the battle, Wellington took up a defensive position along, and to the rear of, a long ridge. 那场战斗的前夜，威灵顿沿一条长长的山脊背后占据了一个防守阵地。 5. The floor of the Atlantic ridges in the middle from north to south. 大西洋洋底在中部形成由北向南的海脊。', '过去式: ridged 过去分词: ridged 现在分词: ridging 第三人称单数: ridges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consolidate', '[kən\'sɒləˌdeɪt]', 'v.合并；统一；巩固', '1. The two companies consolidated last year. 这两个公司去年合并了。 2. We will consolidate and deliver together then. 我们届时将提前统一运输。 3. He bribes his leader to consolidate his position. 他贿赂他的领导来巩固他的地位。 4. We\'ve made a good start, now it\'s time to consolidate. 我们有了一个良好的开端, 现在应该加以巩固。', '名词: consolidator 过去式: consolidated 过去分词: consolidated 现在分词: consolidating 第三人称单数: consolidates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('palpable', '[\'pælpəbl]', 'adj.易觉察的；可摸到的；明显的', '1. The tension in the room was almost palpable. 屋子里的紧张气氛几乎能感觉到。 2. None of the vessels and nerves of the hand is visible or palpable. 手的血管和神经不能看到或摸到。 3. There is a palpable difference in their ages. 他们的年龄有着明显的差别。 4. A sense of urgency was palpable in Bali. 紧迫意识在巴厘岛会议中十分明显。', '副词: palpably 名词: palpability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unfounded', '[ʌn\'faʊndɪd]', 'adj.无事实根据的；无基础的；尚未建立的', '1. We hold that their proposal is unfounded. 我们认为他们的建议是无事实根据的。 2. The claims are, I repeat, totally unfounded. 我再说一遍，这些说法是毫无根据的。 3. In the end, such fears proved largely unfounded. 最终，事实证明这种担忧是多余的。 4. This saying is completely unfounded. 这种说法完全是无稽之谈。', '副词: unfoundedly 名词: unfoundedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wiretap', '[\'waɪətæp]', 'n.窃听或偷录；窃听装置 v.窃听', '1. The house is wiretapped. 那一家的电话被窃听。', '名词: wiretapper 过去式: wiretapped 过去分词: wiretapped 现在分词: wiretapping 第三人称单数: wiretaps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wizened', '[\'wɪznd]', 'adj.皱缩的；枯萎的；消瘦的 动词wizen的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. The hand looked chapped and wizened. 那手看上去粗糙干瘪。 2. She complained of headache, and she looked old and wizened. 她说她头痛，看上去显得又衰老又干巴。 3. Perched sedately on the kerbside, wizened women sell textiles and ethnic handicrafts. 消瘦的妇女们安静的坐在路边出售纺织品和民族手工艺品。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mope', '[moʊp]', 'v.抑郁不乐；闲逛；无精打采 n.闷闷不乐的人', '1. Stop moping! 别那麽垂头丧气的！ 2. He\'s been moping around (the house) all day. 他整天都在(房子)周围瞎转悠。 3. Don\'t mope round the house like that. Go for a walk. 别在家里那样闷闷不乐地闲荡，去散散步。 4. He is no mope, only thoughtful and quiet. 他不是那种忧郁的人,只是好思考,不多说话。', '形容词: mopish 副词: mopishly 名词: moper 过去式: moped 过去分词: moped 现在分词: moping 第三人称单数: mopes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('orchid', '[\'ɔːrkɪd]', 'n.兰花；淡紫色', '1. The smell of the orchid is pleasant. 兰花的香味很宜人。 2. Many kinds of wild orchid are becoming rare. 很多种野生兰越来越罕见了。 3. She wore a single orchid on her evening dress. 她在晚礼服上缀着一朵兰花。 4. The wallpaper in our bedroom has a pattern of orchids. 我们卧室的壁纸是兰花图案的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('norm', '[nɔːrm]', 'n.规范；标准', '1. Criminal behaviour seem to be the norm in this neighbourhood. 犯罪行为似乎是这一带的正常现象。 2. Law is a social norm reflecting the will of a state. 法是具有国家意志的社会规范。 3. You must adapt to the norms of the society you live in. 在社会中生活就要遵循社会行为准则。 4. There\'s a production norm below which each worker must not fall. 每个工人的产量都不得低于生产指标。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avow', '[ə\'vaʊ]', 'vt.承认；公开宣称声明', '1. He avowed that he would never return. 他声明他决不回来了。 2. He avowed openly that he was divorced. 他坦白承认自己离了婚。', '形容词: avowable 副词: avowably 名词: avower 过去式: avowed 过去分词: avowed 现在分词: avowing 第三人称单数: avows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('euphemism', '[\'juːfəmɪzəm]', 'n.委婉语', '1. \"Pass away\" is a euphemism for \"die\". \"过世\"是\"死\"的委婉语。 2. Euphemism is a very common and complicated linguistic phenomenon. 委婉语是一种十分常见而又非常复杂的语言现象。', '形容词: euphemistic 副词: euphemistically 名词: euphemist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revitalize', '[ˌriː\'vaɪtəlaɪz]', 'vt.使复兴；使振兴；使复活；使恢复', '1. I think we have to revitalize our society. 我觉得我们的社会需要新生。 2. The Chinese light industry was revitalized in the 1980\'s. 中国轻工业在20世纪80年代重新振兴起来。 3. The shakeup gave Clinton a chance to revitalize his weary team. 此次内阁改组给克林顿以机会使其疲惫的内阁恢复活力。', '名词: revitalization 过去式: revitalized 过去分词: revitalized 现在分词: revitalizing 第三人称单数: revitalizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exchequer', '[ɪks\'tʃekər]', 'n.国库 Exchequer. n.英国财政部；英国的税务法庭', '1. There\'s nothing left in the exchequer this month. 本月份本人国库空虚。 2. This resulted in a considerable loss to the exchequer. 这使国库遭受了重大损失。 3. The Chancellor of the Exchequer is the minister in charge of finance in Britain. 英国财政大臣是负责财政的大臣。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wretched', '[\'retʃɪd]', 'adj.可怜的；不幸的；悲惨的；质量差的；恶劣的；卑鄙的', '1. She looked wretched and forlorn, despairing of the arrival of a friend who had promised to meet her. 她看上去又可怜又孤独，对于答应来看她的朋友的到来已不抱希望。 2. The wretched man lost all his money. 这个不幸的男人丢了所有的钱。 3. She lamented to us about her wretched lot. 她向我们哀叹自己悲惨的遭遇。 4. I cannot picture myself in more wretched condition. 我想像不出一个比这更悲惨的境地了。', '副词: wretchedly 比较级: wretcheder 最高级: wretchedest 名词: wretchedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exquisite', '[ɪk\'skwɪzɪt]', 'adj.精挑细选的；精致的；细腻的；强烈的 n.过分在意外表着装的人', '1. The hostess had exquisite taste in clothes. 女主人对衣著十分讲究。 2. The girl came up with a set of exquisite stamps. 那姑娘拿出一套精美的邮票。 3. Her skirt has very exquisite lace. 她的裙子有非常精致的花边。 4. The bracelet was made with exquisite workmanship. 这只手镯做得巧夺天工。', '副词: exquisitely 名词: exquisiteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('philatelist', '[fɪ\'lætəlɪst]', 'n.集邮家', '1. He is a philatelist; part of his collection is rare sets of postage stamps of the Qing Dynasty. 他是一位集邮家。他藏品的一部分是罕见的套头的大清国邮票。 2. Respected Primier ministre Dr.Helmut Kohl, I am a Chinese retired employee as well as a philatelist for many years. 如果从发信的时间排序，德国总理科尔是我的第一位对外国首脑的求签的对象，从明信片背面的信文中，你可以看出是相当粗糙。 3. The program provides a wide range of features making it useful to the expert philatelist and novice alike. 由网友上传分享:StampPro is a Windows based United States stamp inventory and tracking program and much more. 4. James was also an avid flag collector and member of NAVA, and a longtime philatelist. 注册以获得一个免费帐号，或登入（如果你已经是会员）。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petroleum', '[pə\'troʊliəm]', 'n.石油', '1. Indonesia is abundant in petroleum deposits. 印尼的石油蕴藏量丰富。 2. Petroleum can be used to produce various chemical products. 石油可用于生产多种化学产品。 3. Any new source of energy will be welcome, as there is a shortage of petroleum. 由于石油短缺，任何一种新能源都会受欢迎。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prose', '[proʊz]', 'adj.散文的 n.散文', '1. This is a verbal translation of the prose. 这是那篇散文的逐字直译。 2. He has lately set forth a book on prose. 他最近出版一本论散文的著作。 3. His prose is written in elegant language. 他的散文写得十分优雅。 4. I want to glance over one time this piece of prose. 我想浏览一下这篇散文。', '过去式: prosed 过去分词: prosed 现在分词: prosing 第三人称单数: proses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('celerity', '[sə\'lerətɪ]', 'n.敏捷；快速', '1. Hanson jumped out of bed with more celerity than he usually displayed and looked at the note. 汉生以从未有过的敏捷从床上一跃而起，来看那张纸条。 2. Shallow Seismic Refraction Survey is one kind of celerity,effective and economic means in engineering exploration. 浅层折射波法是工程勘探中常用的一种经济并且快速有效的方法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loathe', '[loʊð]', 'v.厌恶；憎恶', '1. You know how I loathe typing and shorthand. 你知道我多么讨厌打字和速记。 2. I loathe people who spread malicious gossip. 我讨厌那些散布充满恶意的流言蜚语的人。 3. I value copyright. I loathe its abuse. 我重视版权，我憎恶版权被滥用。', '名词: loather 过去式: loathed 过去分词: loathed 现在分词: loathing 第三人称单数: loathes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extort', '[ɪk\'stɔːrt]', 'v.勒索；敲诈；强要', '1. Weep over is the behavior which threaten to extort. 哭泣是恐吓勒索的行为。 2. The blackmailer tried to extort a large sum of money from him. 勒索者企图向他敲诈一大笔钱。 3. The police used torture to extort a confession from him. 警方对他严刑逼供。', '形容词: extortive 名词: extorter 过去式: extorted 过去分词: extorted 现在分词: extorting 第三人称单数: extorts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('capacious', '[kə\'peɪʃəs]', 'adj.容量大的；广阔的；宽敞的', '1. He has a capacious memory. 他有丰富的记忆力。 2. It is also equipped with capacious dustbin. 它还配有大容量的垃圾箱。 3. People is chickenshit, heart is capacious. 人是渺小的，心灵是广阔的。 4. Gradually his capacious chin encroached upon the borders of the white cravat. 他的广阔的下巴逐渐侵占了白领带的边界。', '副词: capaciously 名词: capaciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chafe', '[tʃeɪf]', 'v.擦痛；激怒；摩擦 n.擦伤；气恼', '1. A stiff collar may chafe your neck. 硬的衣领会擦伤你的脖子。 2. Her shoes chafed the skin on her feet. 鞋子擦破了她脚上的皮肤。 3. The loud noise chafed him. 吵闹声使他烦躁。 4. Why didn\'t he chafe and become restless? 为什么他没有气急败坏，坐立不安呢?', '过去式: chafed 过去分词: chafed 现在分词: chafing 第三人称单数: chafes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trumpet', '[\'trʌmpɪt]', 'n.喇叭；喇叭声；喇叭手 vt.宣扬；鼓吹；吹嘘 vi.吹喇叭；发出喇叭似的声音', '1. The trumpet sounded. 喇叭吹响了。 2. He plays the violin, but I play the trumpet. 他拉提琴，我吹喇叭。 3. Now the dog is singing with the trumpet. 现在这只狗正在合着喇叭唱歌。 4. A blast of the trumpet gave her a start. 突然发出的喇叭声吓了她一跳。 5. He likes to trumpet his own opinions. 他喜欢宣扬自己的意见。 6. The boy is trumpeting. 这个小男孩正在吹喇叭。', '过去式: trumpeted 过去分词: trumpeted 现在分词: trumpeting 第三人称单数: trumpets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quash', '[kwɔːʃ]', 'v.镇压；撤销；平息', '1. The army was called in to quash the revolt. 军队被调来镇压叛乱。 2. The applicant sought judicial review to quash the order. 申请人寻求司法复审以撤消命令。 3. The appeal court quashed the care order made by the juvenile court. 上诉法院撤销了少年法院发出的照看令。 4. I was about to learn how to quash hunger. 我要面对的就是如何驱走饥饿。', '过去式: quashed 过去分词: quashed 现在分词: quashing 第三人称单数: quashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mesh', '[meʃ]', 'n.网孔；网状物；罗网；[机]啮合 vt.使匹配；以网捕捉；使啮合 vi.被网缠住；互相协调；啮合', '1. The fish tangled in the mesh of the net has died. 那条卡在网眼上的鱼已经死了。 2. He is mending the wire mesh in front of the chicken coop. 他正在鸡笼前面修理铁丝网。 3. The gears are in mesh. 齿轮相互啮合。 4. Our ways of looking at these problems don\'t mesh. 我们观察这些问题的方法并不一致。', '形容词: meshy 过去式: meshed 过去分词: meshed 现在分词: meshing 第三人称单数: meshes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('safe', '[seɪf]', 'adj.安全的；安然无恙的；可靠的；谨慎的 n.保险箱', '1. There is no safe landing on that coast. 那一带海岸没有安全的登陆处。 2. It is not safe to drive like that, you must slow down. 那样开车是不安全的,你必须减速。 3. The rescuers brought the climbers back safe and sound. 救援人员把登山的人都安然无恙地救了回来。 4. The train is a safe means of transportation. 火车是一种安全可靠的交通工具。 5. All valuables should be kept in the safe. 所有贵重物品应存放在保险箱。', '副词: safely 比较级: safer 最高级: safest 名词: safeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elated', '[i\'leɪtɪd]', 'adj.兴高采烈的 动词elate的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. He was elated at the news. 这个消息使他很兴奋。 2. The crowds in the square were elated by the news. 这消息使广场上的人群欢欣鼓舞。', '副词: elatedly 名词: elatedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wax', '[wæks]', 'n.蜡；蜂蜡 vt.(用蜡)涂 vi.变圆', '1. Blobs of wax covered the candlestick. 烛台上全是一团团的蜡。 2. He is modeling a unicorn in wax . 他在用蜡制作独角兽。 3. They bought wax and honey up by the great. 他们大量购进蜜蜡和蜂蜜。 4. Why did she have to wax the floors herself? 她干什么非要自己动手给地板打腊? 5. The moon is waxing. 月亮越来越圆。', '过去式: waxed 过去分词: waxed 现在分词: waxing 第三人称单数: waxes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ramp', '[ræmp]', 'n.坡道；斜坡；移动舷梯 vi.加速；横冲直撞；敲诈', '1. He is able to push the wheelchair down a ramp. 他能把轮椅推下坡道。 2. As she looked ahead down the long ramp leading to the guard\'s gate,her heart sank. 低头看着前面通往安检门的坡道，她的心沉了下去。 3. That driver drove the car up the ramp. 那司机将车开上了斜坡。 4. After the ramp, the road veered to the right abruptly. 下了坡之后，路突然转向右边。 5. We\'ve had to ramp up production to meet demand. 我们得增加生产量以满足需求。', '过去式: ramped 过去分词: ramped 现在分词: ramping 第三人称单数: ramps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gerontocracy', '[ˌdʒerən\'tɑːkrəsi]', 'n.老人政治；老人政府', '1. The Regent found the idea odd-as he had the puzzling gerontocracy the Robotech Masters had favored. 瑞金特觉得这是个奇怪的想法，正如机器人统治者的老人政府让他产生的迷惑。', '形容词: gerontocratic 名词: gerontocrat 名词复数: gerontocracies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('veracity', '[və\'ræsəti]', 'n.真实性；诚实', '1. I don\'t doubt the veracity of your report. 我毫不怀疑你报告中的真实性。 2. The chairman disallowed the veracity of his report. 主席不承认他的报道的真实性。 3. There is no question of his veracity. 他的诚实是毫无疑问的。 4. I can testify to this man\'s veracity and good character. 我可以作证,此人诚实可靠,品德良好。', '名词复数: veracities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snivel', '[\'snɪvl]', 'vi.啼哭；抽泣；流鼻涕 n.啜泣', '1. I got a bad headache and snivel. 我头痛得厉害，还流鼻涕。', '名词: sniveler 过去式: sniveled/snivelled 过去分词: sniveled/snivelled 现在分词: sniveling/snivelling 第三人称单数: snivels/snivels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enzyme', '[\'enzaɪm]', 'n.酶', '1. Nitrate reductase is a short-lived enzyme. 硝酸还原酶是短寿酶。 2. Thermodynamics of transient enzyme kinetics. 瞬时酶动态热力学。', '形容词: enzymatic 副词: enzymatically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ciliate', '[\'sɪlɪɪt]', 'n.[动植]纤毛虫adj', '1. Ovary ovoid, furfuraceous ciliate, apex 4-lobed. 子房卵球形，软鳞片状的缘毛，先端4裂。 2. Leaf apex usually acute; calyx lobe margin ciliate. 叶先端通常锐尖；萼裂片边缘具缘毛。 3. Calyx ciliate; corolla yellow to greenish yellow. 花萼具缘毛；花冠黄到黄绿色。 4. Style filiform;stigma funnelform, margin ciliate. 花柱丝状漏斗状的柱头，边缘具缘毛。', '副词: ciliately 名词: ciliation');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shavings', '[\'ʃeɪvɪŋz]', 'n.削皮；刨；刮 名词shaving的复数形式.', '1. A structural material made of wood fragments, such as chips or shavings, that are mechanically pressed into sheet form and bonded together with resin. 碎料板由碎木，如木屑或创花制成的一种结构材料，用合成树脂粘合在一起并用机器压成板状 2. Slender, curved wood shavings used especially for packing. 细刨花尤用于包装的细长而弯曲的薄木屑', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hatch', '[hætʃ]', 'n.孵化；舱口，舱口盖 v.孵；孵出；策划', '1. The hatch date for tit eggs appears to be determined about a month earlier, when the eggs are laid. 白颊山雀孵化的时间，似乎在孵化前一个月，也就是下蛋时便已决定。 2. Both men quickly disappeared down the hatch. 两个人很快从舱口下去不见了。 3. We heard the noise of a hatch being closed. 我们听到关舱口的声音。 4. An incubator is used to hatch chicken. 孵卵器用来孵小鸡。', '名词: hatcher 过去式: hatched 过去分词: hatched 现在分词: hatching 第三人称单数: hatches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cardiologist', '[ˌkɑːrdi\'ɑːlədʒɪst]', 'n.心脏病学家', '1. A cardiologist generally performs the angioplasty. 血管成形术一般由心脏病专家来完成。 2. The cardiologist paused, smiled and leaned over. 那位心脏病专家顿了顿，微微一笑，斜靠了过去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('liquid', '[\'lɪkwɪd]', 'adj.液体的；液态的；清澈的；清脆的；已转化成现款的（财） n.液体', '1. The doctor recommended that the patient be fed liquid food. 医生建议病人应吃流质食物。 2. Air whether in the gaseous or liquid state is a fluid. 空气，无论是气态的还是液态的，都是一种流体。 3. The earth is believed to have a liquid core. 人们相信地球有一个液态核。 4. Kate is a pretty girl with large liquid eyes. 凯特是一个有一双水汪汪大眼睛的漂亮姑娘。 5. Plasma is clear yellow liquid. 血浆是种透明淡黄的液体。', '副词: liquidly 名词: liquidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fosse', '[fɔːs]', 'n.护城河；壕沟 =foss.', '1. The whole army began to clamour for the fosse to be filled up. 全军都开始叫嚷着要将壕堑填平。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shelter', '[\'ʃeltər]', 'n.避难所；庇护；庇护所 v.保护；隐匿；庇护', '1. The refugees\' main requirements are food and shelter. 难民的主要必需品是食物和住所。 2. In the storm I took shelter under the tree. 暴风雨时，我正在树下躲避。 3. The spectators scuttled for shelter when it began to rain. 一下起雨来，观众就纷纷找地方躲避。 4. People were scrambling madly for shelter. 人们疯了似的抢着往隐蔽处跑。 5. These plants must be sheltered from direct sunlight. 这种植物必须遮起来，免受阳光直射。', '形容词: shelterless 名词: shelterer 过去式: sheltered 过去分词: sheltered 现在分词: sheltering 第三人称单数: shelters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('issue', '[\'ɪʃuː]', 'n.议题；问题；期刊号；一次发行额；发行；<律>子女 v.发表；公布；正式发给；发行；流出', '1. You\'re just avoiding the issue. 你只不过是在回避问题。 2. The union plans to raise the issue of overtime. 工会打算提出加班的问题。 3. Parliament will debate the nationalization issue next week. 议会将在下周辩论国有化议题。 4. They make an issue of this with UEFA. 他们就此向欧足联提出上诉。 5. Xinhua News Agency is authorized to issue the following statement. 新华社受权发表如下声明。', '形容词: issueless 名词: issuer 过去式: issued 过去分词: issued 现在分词: issuing 第三人称单数: issues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delirious', '[dɪ\'lɪriəs]', 'adj.神志昏迷的；精神错乱的；发狂的；非常激动的；极度兴奋的', '1. During the fever he became delirious and said some strange things. 发高烧时他神志昏迷,说了些稀奇古怪的事。 2. He\'s so delirious and he doesn\'t know where he is. 他精神错乱，竟不知自己身在何处。 3. The children were delirious as they opened the parcels. 孩子们打开包裹时欣喜若狂.', '副词: deliriously 名词: deliriousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snug', '[snʌɡ]', 'adj.温暖舒适的；合身的；安全的 v.使整洁干净；舒适地依靠；紧贴 n.<英>酒吧里的私房', '1. He sat in a snug little room. 他坐在一个舒适的小房间里。 2. They lead a happy and snug life. 他们的小日子过得挺舒坦。 3. The sweater felt too snug when he tried it on. 这件毛衣他试穿时感到太紧身了。 4. Mary helped her old parents to snug their house for winter. 玛丽帮助年迈的父母把房子弄妥当准备过冬。', '副词: snugly 比较级: snugger 最高级: snuggest 名词: snugness 过去式: snugged 过去分词: snugged 现在分词: snugging 第三人称单数: snugs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hardy', '[\'hɑːrdi]', 'adj.强壮的；勇敢的；能吃苦耐劳的；耐寒的', '1. A few hardy people swam in the icy water. 一些强壮的人在冰冷的水中游泳。 2. Only a hardy man should enter the auto race. 只有胆大的人才能参加摩托赛。 3. Camels are tough and hardy creatures. 骆驼是能吃苦耐劳的动物。 4. Their children are remarkably hardy. 他们的孩子非常能吃苦耐劳。', '副词: hardily 比较级: hardier 最高级: hardiest 名词: hardiness 名词复数: hardies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('limbo', '[\'lɪmboʊ]', 'n.林波舞(西印度群岛的一种舞蹈)；中间或不定的状态；拘禁', '1. Israel is in political limbo today. 以色列今天陷入政治僵局。 2. I\'m in limbo, waiting to know if I\'ve got the job or not. 我心神不定，等着知道是否已得到了那份工作。 3. Management kept her promotion in limbo for months. 有好几个月领导将她的升迁之事放置一边。 4. Some other way of entering limbo must be thought of. 要进监狱，还得另打主意。', '名词复数: limbos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indemnify', '[ɪn\'demnɪfaɪ]', 'v.赔偿；补偿；保护；保障', '1. They offered to indemnify us for our losses. 他们提出要赔偿我们的损失。 2. The loss does not fall on the owner of the destroyed capital, since the destroyer has agreed to indemnify him for it. 损失不会落到甲的身上，因为挥霍者已经同意给予赔偿。 3. The insurance company will indemnify you for the cost of living elsewhere while the fire damage is repaired. 火灾善后修复期间你在别处居住的费用将由保险公司补偿。 4. We agree to indemnify WACA and its members for any loss or damages resulted from the publication of our material submitted. 我等同意确保世华建协及其会员在出版我等参选数据后对所有损失及补偿不需要负责。', '名词: indemnifier 过去式: indemnified 过去分词: indemnified 现在分词: indemnifying 第三人称单数: indemnifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scrutable', '[\'skruːtəbəl]', 'adj.（通过细看和细查）可以理解的', '1. The Air France A330 last words released by the media “Power failure, cabin pressure loss”, has a lot of scrutable information hidden therein. 媒体披露的法航A330最后遗言“电力中断、机舱失压”，隐藏着很多可以解读的信息。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ligature', '[\'lɪɡətʃər]', 'n.绳索；结扎线；连音；连字 v.捆；缚；结扎', '1. Ligatures are used in surgery to stop the flow of a bleeding artery. 结扎线被用于外科手术中阻止动脉流血。', '过去式: ligatured 过去分词: ligatured 现在分词: ligaturing 第三人称单数: ligatures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('toady', '[\'toʊdi]', 'n.谄媚者；拍马屁的人 v.谄媚；拍马屁', '1. He toadied to his boss for promotion. 他为升职向老板献殷勤。 2. The former servant made his way into power by toadying to the king. 这位当年的仆人通过向国王谄媚而掌上了权。', '名词复数: toadies 过去式: toadied 过去分词: toadied 现在分词: toadying 第三人称单数: toadies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('asthma', '[\'æzmə]', 'n.哮喘', '1. Her son developed asthma when he was two. 她的儿子两岁时患了哮喘。 2. Obesity is also associated with asthma. 肥胖症也易导致哮喘的发生。 3. Moving to the country cured her of asthma. 搬到乡下她的哮喘就好了。', '形容词: asthmatic 副词: asthmatically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tinder', '[\'tɪndər]', 'n.火绒；火种', '1. The plants are as dry as tinder after this long drought. 植物经过长期干旱之后干枯得如同火绒一般。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tussle', '[\'tʌsl]', 'n.扭打；斗争；论争 v.扭打；打斗', '1. I had a tussle to get the knife off him. 我与他扭打一阵才把刀子夺下。 2. We have a tussle every year about where to go on holiday. 我们每年都要为前往何处度假而争论一番. 3. They began to tussle with each other for the coin. 他们为争夺硬币扭打起来。 4. The children were tussling with one another for the ball. 孩子们在你抢我夺地争球。', '过去式: tussled 过去分词: tussled 现在分词: tussling 第三人称单数: tussles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saintly', '[\'seɪntli]', 'adj.圣洁的；像圣徒一样的', '1. This picture gives us a saintly feeling. 这幅图片给我们一种圣洁的感觉。 2. A saintly man was living outside a town. 在一个城镇附近，住着一位圣人。 3. Mother Teresa is famous for all of her saintly deeds. 特蕾莎修女因为她的高尚的德行而闻名于世。', '比较级: saintlier 最高级: saintliest 名词: saintliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slant', '[slænt]', 'n.倾斜；斜面；个人的观点或见解；倾向性；偏见 vt.使倾斜；歪曲 vi.倾斜', '1. The wooden floor has a noticeable slant. 这木地板可以看得出有些倾斜。 2. Has your roof a sharp slant? 你的屋顶是否有一个陡峭的斜面？ 3. She put a new slant on the play. 她对那出戏提出了一种新的见解。 4. The editorial had an antiunion slant. 这篇社论有一种反工会的倾向。 5. When drawing, shearing means to slant an image. 绘制时,修剪意味着使图像倾斜。 6. Most handwriting slants to the right. 大多数手写体都向右斜。', '副词: slantingly 过去式: slanted 过去分词: slanted 现在分词: slanting 第三人称单数: slants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('graze', '[ɡreɪz]', 'v.放牧；（牛、羊等）吃草 v.轻擦；擦伤 n.放牧 n.擦伤', '1. We are grazing the sheep in the next field. 我们在旁边的地里放羊。 2. The sheep usually graze in the grass land. 羊通常在草地吃草。 3. Cattle are not allowed to graze in the plots. 禁止牛在田里吃草。 4. The bullet grazed my shoulder. 子弹擦过我的肩膀。 5. Cows are left to graze in the pasture. 奶牛都是留给放牧在牧场。 6. His knee stung from the graze. 他的膝盖擦伤后十分疼痛。', '形容词: grazeable 名词: grazer 过去式: grazed 过去分词: grazed 现在分词: grazing 第三人称单数: grazes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('percussion', '[pər\'kʌʃn]', 'n.碰撞；打击乐器；[医]叩诊', '1. In an orchestra, people who play percussion instruments sit at the back. 在管弦乐队中，演奏打击乐器的人会坐在后面。 2. The next day, the woodwind, brass, and percussion of the orchestra joined us. 次日，管弦乐队的木管乐器、铜管乐器和打击乐器与我们合练。 3. For example, it makes percussion instruments out of general household items like pots, pans, and plastic hoses. 举例来说，他们将盆子、锅子及塑胶水管等一般家庭用品当成打击乐器。 4. The emphasis on percussion and Cuban rhythms make the style quite danceable and accessible. 它对于打击乐器和古巴旋律的偏重,使得这一音乐形式相当适合于跳舞,且易于理解。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flaggy', '[\'flægɪ]', 'adj.多扁石的；多菖蒲的', '1. Typically the rock is massive, but commonly it is flaggy or schistose. 这类岩石典型地呈块状，但常呈薄板状或片理化。 2. The gold metallogeny is characterized by auriferous pyrite and occurred in the alternating layer of heavy-layer metasandstone,flaggy metasandstone and graphitization schist. 金矿化以含金黄铁矿为特征,产出于盖县组变质砂岩段厚层状变质砂岩、薄层状变质砂岩和石墨化片岩的互层带中,矿体产状与地层一致; 3. third is low-density turbidity sequence composed of flaggy sandstone and mudstone; 三为由薄层状砂岩与泥岩呈韵律状互层构成的浊流远端低密度流序列；', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impermeable', '[ɪm\'pɜːrmiəbl]', 'adj.不能渗透的；不渗透性的', '1. Water cannot easily flow in these impermeable rocks. 水不容易流进那些不透水的岩石。 2. Thin layers of other impermeable materials are found in nature, too. 在自然界中也发现有其他非渗透性薄层物质。', '副词: impermeably 名词: impermeability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('colony', '[\'kɑːləni]', 'n.殖民地；侨居地；侨民；聚居(地)；群体；菌落', '1. This country used to be a British colony in Asia. 这个国家曾是英国在亚洲的殖民地。 2. Britain was mandated to govern the former colony of German East Africa. 英国授权代管德国在东非的前殖民地。 3. That first winter in America was very hard for the new colony. 对于新侨民来说,在美国的第一个冬天是非常难熬的。 4. They live in an artists\' colony. 他们住在艺术家聚居区。', '名词复数: colonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perpendicular', '[ˌpɜːrpən\'dɪkjələr]', 'adj.垂直的；直立的；陡峭的 n.垂直线', '1. The wall is usually perpendicular. 墙通常是垂直的。 2. There are many perpendicular marble columns in Greek temples. 希腊庙宇有很多垂直的大理石柱。 3. He\'d drunk so much that he found it hard to remain perpendicular. 他喝酒太多，简直站都站不直了。 4. The wall is a little out of the perpendicular. 那墙有点斜。 5. The pillar had been restored to the perpendicular. 这柱子恢复垂直。', '副词: perpendicularly 名词: perpendicularity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('symmetry', '[\'sɪmətri]', 'n.对称(性)；匀称；整齐', '1. These values constitute the symmetry waveform. 有这些数据来构成对称波形。 2. Many stems and roots show radial symmetry. 很多的茎和根都是辐射对称的。 3. His teeth spoiled the symmetry of his face. 他的牙齿破坏了他的面部匀称。 4. This addition may interfere with the symmetry of the layout. 这么一加，会破坏整个布局的匀称。', '名词复数: symmetries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flinch', '[flɪntʃ]', 'v.畏缩；退缩；畏首畏尾 n.退缩；逃避', '1. Jane didn\'t flinch once when the doctor cleaned the cut in her arm. 医生为琼清洗手臂上的伤口时，她毫不畏缩。 2. Rex gently placed his armored hand on her shoulder, making her flinch from the cold hardness. 雷克斯将他戴着装甲的手轻轻地放在她的肩上，那种坚硬冰冷的感觉让她畏缩了一下。 3. You mustn\'t flinch from a difficulty. 你不应从困难面前退缩。 4. He willed himself not to move, not to even flinch. 他强迫自己不动，也不退缩。 5. You mustn\'t flinch from a difficulty. 你不应从困难面前退缩。', '副词: flinchingly 名词: flincher 过去式: flinched 过去分词: flinched 现在分词: flinching 第三人称单数: flinches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consistency', '[kən\'sɪstənsɪ]', 'n.连贯；一致性；强度；硬度；浓稠度', '1. We are certainly lacking consistency. 我们确实缺少连贯。 2. These accounts show no consistency. 这些报道前后不一。 3. She has played with great consistency all season. 她整个赛季表现相当稳定。 4. His action lacks consistency. 他的行为缺乏一致性。', '名词复数: consistencies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shilly-shally', '[\'ʃɪliʃæli]', '犹豫不决', '1. If you keep shilly-shallying like this we\'ll be late. 要是你老这样举棋不定，我们就来不及了。', '名词: shilly-shallier 名词复数: shilly-shallies 过去式: shilly-shallied 过去分词: shilly-shallied 现在分词: shilly-shallying 第三人称单数: shilly-shallies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jarring', '[\'dʒɑːɪŋ]', 'adj.辗轧的；刺耳的；不调和的；震惊的 n.辗轧声；震动；冲突 动词jar的现在分词形式.', '1. One of the most jarring tragedies of the disaster was the school collapse in a suburb of Dujiangyan. 灾难中最令人震惊的惨剧之一是都江堰郊区一个学校的坍塌。 2. The annular clamped diaphragm is extensively insensitive to jarring or vibration. 环形固定的膜片对振动或震动有抵抗性。 3. It also reduces impact, meaning no jarring or pounding on joints and bones. 水也能减缓冲击力，意即不会对筋骨造成强大撞击或剧烈震动。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nurture', '[\'nɜːrtʃər]', 'vt.养育；培育；照顾；扶持 n.养育；培育；环境因素', '1. She nurtured the child as if he had been her own. 她把那个孩子当作自己的孩子来教育。 2. Most vegetables we buy in winter are nurtured in the greenhouse. 我们冬天买的大多数蔬菜都是在温室里培育的。 3. We have to care for and nurture the plant first. 我们必须先要照顾灌溉树木。 4. They are best friends and nurture each other. 他们是最好的朋友，并且相互扶持。 5. The child got his nurture from his loving parents. 这个孩子的教育来自他慈爱的双亲。', '名词: nurturer 过去式: nurtured 过去分词: nurtured 现在分词: nurturing 第三人称单数: nurtures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stark', '[stɑːrk]', 'adj.严酷的；荒凉的；光秃秃的；鲜明的 adv.完全；实在；简直', '1. He now faces the stark reality of life in prison. 他现在要面对狱中生活的严酷现实了。 2. Those afflicted with the stark problem of how to keep on living. 受维持生计的严酷问题困扰的那些人们。 3. The landscape was grey and stark. 景色灰暗荒凉。 4. The tree has only stark branches. 这棵树只剩下光秃秃的树枝。 5. The fool is talking stark nonsense. 这傻瓜完全是在胡扯。', '副词: starkly 比较级: starker 最高级: starkest 名词: starkness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('paunchy', '[\'pɔːntʃiːˌ \'pɑːn-]', 'adj.大腹便便的', '1. The door was flung open and there rushed in a paunchy middle-aged man, with inch-long hair cut close to his head. 大门猛然推开，一名只留有一寸长短发、腹大便便的中年男子冲了进来。', '比较级: paunchier 最高级: paunchiest 名词: paunchiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interchangeable', '[ˌɪntər\'tʃeɪndʒəbl]', 'adj.可互换的', '1. The two words are interchangeable. 这两个单词是可互换的。 2. The parts of that car\'s engine are interchangeable with those of this one. 那辆车的引擎零件，可与这辆车的互换。', '副词: interchangeably 名词: interchangeability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('designate', '[\'dezɪɡneɪt]', 'vt.指定；标明；把...定名为；选派 adj.指定的', '1. She was designated sportswoman of the year. 她被指定为本年度的体坛明星。 2. The chairman has designated that boy as his successor. 主席已经指定那个男孩作他的继承人。 3. Black lines designate boundaries on this map. 在这幅地图上黑线标示疆界。 4. The ruler of a kingdom is designated a king. 王国的统治者称作国王。 5. The ambassador designate is going to meet honored foreign guests. 大使指定人选将要迎接外国贵客。', '形容词: designative 名词: designator 过去式: designated 过去分词: designated 现在分词: designating 第三人称单数: designates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perjure', '[\'pɜːrdʒər]', 'vt.发伪誓；作伪证', '1. Several witnesses at the trial were clearly prepared to perjure themselves in order to protect the accused. 在审判时几个证人显然已准备好为袒护被告而作伪证。', '名词: perjurer 过去式: perjured 过去分词: perjured 现在分词: perjuring 第三人称单数: perjures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suspect', '[sə\'spekt]', 'v.怀疑；猜想 n.嫌疑犯 adj.可疑的；不可信的', '1. They suspected an ambush. 他们怀疑有埋伏。 2. I suspect he was lying by the boy\'s abnormal behaviour. 从那个男孩的反常举动中,我怀疑他在撒谎。 3. Just at that time, I began to suspect whether to tell her that matter. 只是在那个时候,我开始怀疑我是否应该告诉她那件事。 4. She has more intelligence than we suspected her to possess. 她的智慧比我们猜想的要高。 5. He\'s a prime suspect in the murder case. 他是这次谋杀案的主要怀疑对象 6. His motives are highly suspect. 他的动机是高度令人生疑的。', '过去式: suspected 过去分词: suspected 现在分词: suspecting 第三人称单数: suspects');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('twaddle', '[\'twɑːdl]', 'n.废话；拙劣的文字 v.讲废话', '1. I\'ve never heard such utter twaddle! 我还从来没听过这么愚蠢透顶的话！ 2. This is all hopeless twaddle that I am saying about her. 我这样说她，那是全无希望的拙劣废话。 3. The novel is sentimental twaddle. 这部小说纯粹是无病呻吟。 4. \"Lily, don\'t twaddle otherwise I\'ll let your brother know it.\" Mary has to threaten her. “莉莉，别胡说！小心我告诉你哥哥。” 玛丽威胁说。', '名词: twaddler 过去式: twaddled 过去分词: twaddled 现在分词: twaddling 第三人称单数: twaddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pudgy', '[\'pʌdʒi]', 'adj.矮胖的', '1. The wizard clapped a pudgy hand to his vast forehead. 巫师用胖乎乎的手拍了一下宽大的前额。 2. He was a massive black giant and I was a pudgy little redhead. 他是个大黑块头，而我是个红头发的小矮胖子。', '比较级: pudgier 最高级: pudgiest 名词: pudginess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illusion', '[ɪ\'luːʒn]', 'n.错觉；幻觉；错误的信仰(或观念)', '1. Mirrors in a room often give an illusion of space. 房间里的镜子常给人一种空间增大的错觉。 2. A mirage is an optical illusion. 海市蜃楼是一种视错觉。 3. I thought I saw a ghost but it was just an optical illusion. 我以为我看见鬼了，其实只是一种幻觉。 4. This creates an illusion of variety. 这造成了一种多样化的幻觉。', '形容词: illusional');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avid', '[\'ævɪd]', 'adj.渴望的；贪婪的；热心的', '1. Avid fans of the show attribute the loss of ratings to a misjudgement on the part of FOX Network for airing the second season on Friday evenings instead of Tuesday evenings. 渴望的影迷把低收视率归咎于富克斯网络的判断不公，把放映时间从星期二改为星期五晚。 2. She was also an avid photographer. 亚非还是个热心的摄影家。 3. I cajoled the avid entrepreneur into doing the business for me. 我引诱那个热心的企业家为我做生意。', '副词: avidly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('informed', '[ɪn\'fɔːrmd]', 'adj.见多识广的；消息灵通的；有学问的 v.通知，告诉（动词inform的过去式和过去分词）', '1. Reading is an excellent way to learn new things and stay informed. 阅读是学习新事物和使人见多识广的最佳方法。 2. Informed sources said it was likely that the President would make a televised statement. 消息灵通人士透露总统可能发表电视声明。 3. Plato was one of the most informed men of his day. 柏拉图是那时代最多有学问的人。 4. The secretary informed me of his arrival. 秘书通知我他来了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tout', '[taʊt]', 'v.兜售；高价卖；刺探；吹捧 n.贩子', '1. We should tout our wares on television. 我们应该在电视上兜售商品。 2. Toyota Motor Corp., Nissan Motor Co. and Honda Motor Co. will tout their latest models at the Beijing car show tomorrow. 日本丰田、本田和日产汽车公司在昨日开幕的北京国际车展上极力推介自己的新产品。 3. The politician was touted as a friend of people. 这个政客被吹捧为人民之友。', '名词: touter 过去式: touted 过去分词: touted 现在分词: touting 第三人称单数: touts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ointment', '[\'ɔɪntmənt]', 'n.药膏；油膏；软膏', '1. You\'d better apply some ointment to the cut. 你最好在伤口上擦些药膏。 2. She dabbed the ointment on the rash. 她将药膏轻抹在疹子上。 3. This ointment will subdue the inflammation. 这油膏可以消此炎症。 4. Administer the ointment once every day. 每天一次搽用这油膏。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conviction', '[kən\'vɪkʃn]', 'n.坚信；定罪；信服', '1. I have the conviction that he is right. 我深信他是对的。 2. She holds deep religious convictions. 她有深刻的宗教信仰。 3. This was his third conviction. 这是他第三次被判罪。 4. They have no previous convictions. 他们没有前科。', '形容词: convictional');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loutish', '[\'laʊtɪʃ]', 'adj.粗野的；无礼的', '1. Tom suddenly changed from a well-behaved child into a loutish adolescent. 汤姆突然从一个有礼貌的小孩变成一个粗野的少年。', '副词: loutishly 名词: loutishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vestigial', '[ve\'stɪdʒiəl]', 'adj.痕迹的；遗迹的；退化的', '1. The wings of the chicken have become vestigial; it can no longer fly. 鸡的翅膀逐渐退化，不会在空中飞行了。', '副词: vestigially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scraggly', '[\'skræɡli]', 'adj.散乱的；锯齿状的；凸凹不平的', '1. But replanted bamboo comes out scraggly. 但重新种植的竹子依然参差不齐。 2. There were some scraggly bushes, but that was all. 那里只有有蓬乱的灌木。 3. There were some scraggly bushes,but that was all. 哪里只有有蓬乱的灌木。 4. Each winter also shorten long stems that have grown too scraggly. 每年冬天;也缩短长叶子变得太scraggly.', '比较级: scragglier 最高级: scraggliest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reconstitute', '[ˌriː\'kɑːnstətuːt]', 'v.重组；使恢复原状', '1. The board of directors of the firm has been reconstituted recently. 公司的董事会最近进行了重组。 2. We decided to reconstitute the committee under a new chairman. 我们决定在新主席领导之下重组一个委员会。 3. Use warm water to reconstitute dried milk powder. 用温水冲奶粉。 4. Every day she reconstitutes the frozen orange juice by adding water. 她每天通过加水把冰冻的橘子汁恢复原状。', '过去式: reconstituted 过去分词: reconstituted 现在分词: reconstituting 第三人称单数: reconstitutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kindle', '[\'kɪndl]', 'v.燃烧；使 ... 着火；激起；发亮', '1. The wood was wet and wouldn\'t kindle easily. 这木柴太湿，不易燃烧。 2. The sparks kindled the dry grass. 有些火星把干草给引着了。 3. The speaker tried to kindle the crowd\'s interest with a lively speech. 演讲者试图以生动活泼的讲话来激起听众的兴趣。 4. Her eyes kindled with excitement. 她的眼睛里闪耀出激动的神色。', '名词: kindler 过去式: kindled 过去分词: kindled 现在分词: kindling 第三人称单数: kindles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bungle', '[\'bʌŋɡl]', 'v.拙劣地工作；粗率地做；搞坏；贻误 n.粗制滥造；搞糟的工作', '1. Don\'t let him mend your bike. He\'s sure to bungle the job. 别让他修理你的自行车. 2. Otherwise, it will bungle deepens reform, block up economy grows. 否则,它将会贻误深化改革,阻碍经济发展。 3. The whole job was a gigantic bungle. 整件工作都糟透了。', '副词: bunglingly 名词: bungler 过去式: bungled 过去分词: bungled 现在分词: bungling 第三人称单数: bungles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lap', '[læp]', 'n.膝部；（衣服的）下摆；控制范围 n.重叠部分；(跑道的)一圈 n.舐；（波浪）拍打声 v.包围；（使）重叠；领先一圈 v.舔食；轻拍', '1. The child sat on its mother\'s lap. 小孩坐在妈妈的膝上。 2. For quite some time, everything fell into his lap. 好长一段时间他事事称心如意。 3. The leading car crashed midway through the tenth lap. 领先的那辆赛车在第十圈的中途撞毁了。 4. The cat lapped up the milk. 猫舔食牛奶。 5. The two pictures are made to lap over each other. 那两张画被重叠在一起。 6. The waves gently lap against the shore. 海浪轻轻地拍打着海岸。', '名词: lapful 过去式: lapped 过去分词: lapped 现在分词: lapping 第三人称单数: laps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('behoove', '[bɪ\'huːv]', 'v.理应；有必要', '1. The post-Cold War new world order is still taking shape.It would behoove Taiwanese leaders to play close attention and make necessary adjustments in policy. 后冷战时代的新世界秩序，其实仍然在形成当中，身在台湾的领导者是有必要做密切的观察与应变。', '过去式: behooved 过去分词: behooved 现在分词: behooving 第三人称单数: behooves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('circumscribe', '[\'sɜːrkəmskraɪb]', 'v.限制；划一条线包围；确定...的范围；画（几何图形的）外接圆', '1. Do not circumscribe your study only in classes. 不要把自己的学习只局限于课堂。 2. A man should not circumscribe his activity by any inflexible fence of rigid rules. 人不应该将自己的行为限制在由僵化的条文构成的不可变通的范围之内。 3. Please circumscribe the words which are wrongly spelled. 请将拼错的词圈出来。 4. First, it is always possible to circumscribe a sphere in a camera-aligned quad. 首先，它总能保证和一个与摄像机对齐的矩形相切。', '形容词: circumscribable 名词: circumscriber 过去式: circumscribed 过去分词: circumscribed 现在分词: circumscribing 第三人称单数: circumscribes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('burrow', '[\'bɜːroʊ]', 'n.(兔子等)所掘的地洞 vt.挖掘(洞穴)；钻进 vi.翻寻；挖洞', '1. The ideal riverbank is crumbly enough for the birds to excavate a nesting burrow with their beaks. 理想的河岸边土壤很松软，这些鸟可以很轻松的用自己喙去凿出适合做窝的地洞。 2. You burrow and rankle in his heart! 你挖掘并折磨他的心灵！ 3. Burrow beneath laudatory headlines on business and political leaders, and it becomes clear that the strategy works. 挖掘赞誉标题背后的商政要人，这个策略已变得有效。 4. Nobody comes to visit me, although a mouse did burrow into my cabin once. 没有人来拜访我，不过确实有一只耗子曾挖洞来过我的小木屋。', '名词: burrower 过去式: burrowed 过去分词: burrowed 现在分词: burrowing 第三人称单数: burrows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('supplicant', '[\'sʌplɪkənt]', 'n.恳求者 adj.恳求的', '1. Where would a Supplicant find him? 那些要求变异的人是在哪里找到他的呢？ 2. The supplicant is Sun Xing Zhe, because in the famous novel he represented the mind that is unsettled as a monkey. 此提请者是孙行者，因为在该有名的小说中，他是代表像猴子般无法定下来的心。 3. Goddess, I beseech you, I pray as a supplicant that by your majesty you grant this to me. 母亲，我乞求汝，我祈请，以汝之权威将我所祈者赋予给我。 4. Be prompt in your response, be courteous and treat me as a potential colleague, not as a supplicant. 反应迅速，彬彬有礼，把我当作一个潜在的同事，而不是一个哀求者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('litter', '[\'lɪtər]', 'n.垃圾；杂乱；一窝(幼仔)；褥草；轿子 v.乱丢垃圾；弄乱；产(幼仔)；用草等给动物铺窝', '1. There was litter strewn all over the pavement. 人行道上到处都是扔的垃圾。 2. The desk was covered with a litter of documents. 书桌上满满地放着一堆杂乱的文件。 3. His litter strewn room really needed to be cleaned. 他杂乱的房间该好好收拾一下了。 4. His dog hasn\'t had a litter of puppies. 他的狗还没有生过一窝小狗。', '名词: litterer 过去式: littered 过去分词: littered 现在分词: littering 第三人称单数: litters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muted', '[mjuːt]', 'n.哑子；弱音器；默音字母 adj.哑的；沉默的；无声的 vt.减音；减弱 vi.(鸟)排泄', '1. He\'s a deaf mute and cannot tell anyone secret. 他是个聋哑人，不会把他们的秘密告诉任何人。 2. He has been passing himself off as a deaf - mute . 他一直装聋作哑。 3. You need get a mute on your guitar to make the tune soft. 你得给吉他安个弱音器好让音柔和一点。 4. The letter \"e\" in \"mouse\" is mute. “mouse”中的字母“e”不发音。 5. He tried to speak but he was still mute. 他尽力想说，却仍然哑口无声。 6. Please mute a music instrument. 请减低乐器的声音。', '副词: mutely 比较级: muter 最高级: mutest 名词: muteness 过去式: muted 过去分词: muted 现在分词: muting 第三人称单数: mutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('juxtapose', '[ˌdʒʌkstə\'poʊz]', 'v.并置；并列', '1. Elements of Indian culture juxtapose newer designs. 印度文化元素与新型设计并行。 2. We tried to juxtapose the sculptures to give the best effect. 我们把雕刻品加以并排以得到最好的效果。 3. Juxtapose the use of override with new. What is shadowing? 什么时候使用override?什么时候使用new? 什么叫shadowing? 4. Juxtapose the HTTP verbs GET and POST. What is HEAD? 对比http动词GET和POST? 什么是HEAD?', '过去式: juxtaposed 过去分词: juxtaposed 现在分词: juxtaposing 第三人称单数: juxtaposes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contentious', '[kən\'tenʃəs]', 'adj.好辩的；好争吵的；有争议的', '1. There is a contentious clause in the treaty. 这条约中有一条有争议的条款。', '副词: contentiously 名词: contentiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('befuddlement', '[bɪ\'fʌdlmənt]', 'n.迷惘；昏迷；烂醉', '1. To add to the befuddlement, the expansion of the universe now seems to be accelerating, a process with truly mind-stretching consequences. 更教人迷糊的是，现今宇宙的膨胀似乎正在加速之中，这真是让人连脑子也一起跟著膨胀。 2. To add to the befuddlement , the expansion of the universe now seems to be accelerating, a process with truly mind-stretching consequences. 更教人迷糊的是，现今宇宙的膨胀似乎正在加速之中，这真是让人连脑子也一起跟著膨胀。 3. Befuddlement and Embarrassment of Love--A Perspective on Russian Literature in 19th Century 爱的迷惘与无奈--19世纪俄罗斯文学管窥 4. befuddlement n. 迷惑不解；', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prehistoric', '[ˌpriːhɪ\'stɔːrɪk]', 'adj.史前的；陈腐的 =prehistorical.', '1. Some prehistoric people lived in caves. 有些史前时期的人住在洞穴里。 2. They have found prehistoric remains. 他们发现了史前遗迹。 3. His ideas on morals are really prehistoric. 他的道德观念真是太陈腐了。', '副词: prehistorically 异体字: prehistorical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blizzard', '[\'blɪzərd]', 'n.暴风雪；大量 n.暴雪（美国游戏软件制作公司）', '1. It was sheer madness to attempt the drive during a blizzard. 试图在暴风雨中驾车绝对是极度愚蠢的 2. The blizzard blotted out the sky and the land. 暴风雪铺天盖地而来。 3. We were marooned by the blizzard. 我们为暴风雪所困。 4. The blizzard was still raging outside. 外面暴风雪仍在肆虐。 5. The QA program Blizzard uses does have a small draw back. 暴雪的质量保证体系使用一种小回溯的方法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('temp', '[temp]', 'n.临时雇员 v.临时做工 abbr.暂时的(=temporary) 温度(=temperature).', '1. He\'s been temping for over a year now and wants a permanent job. 他做临时工作已一年多了，想找个固定的工作。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('erasure', '[ɪ\'reɪʒər]', 'n.擦除；抹掉', '1. How can I specify erasure patterns when erasing disk blocks? 擦除磁盘块时如何指定擦除模式？ 2. The past was erased, the erasure was forgotten, the lie became truth. 过去给人擦拭个干净，擦拭的行为又忘了个干净，于是，谎言就变成了真理。 3. The bomb spelled erasure of the whole village. 那颗炸弹把整个村子夷为平地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('affix', '[ə\'fɪks]', 'v.使附于；署名；粘贴 n.附加物；词缀', '1. Please affix some lables on your handle-luggage. 请把这些标签系在您的手提行李上。 2. Please affix your name to my homework. 请在我的作业本上签个名。 3. Please affix your company\'s stamp here. 请在这里盖上你们公司的章。 4. Please affix a stamp. 请贴上邮票。 5. In word-formation, morphemes are labeled root, stem, base and affix. 在构词法中', '形容词: affixable 名词: affixer 过去式: affixed 过去分词: affixed 现在分词: affixing 第三人称单数: affixes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exempt', '[ɪɡ\'zempt]', 'adj.免除的 vt.免除 n.免税者；被免除义务者', '1. He is exempt from military service. 他免服兵役。 2. These houses are exempt from paying rates. 这些房子是免付捐税的。 3. Poor eyesight will exempt you from military service. 视力不佳将使你免服兵役。 4. We hope you will exempt us from taxes. 希望贵方能给予我们免征关税待遇。', '形容词: exemptible 过去式: exempted 过去分词: exempted 现在分词: exempting 第三人称单数: exempts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sensitive', '[\'sensətɪv]', 'adj.灵敏的；敏感的；感光的；易受伤害的；善解人意的 n.敏感的人', '1. She\'s got very sensitive hearing, skin, etc. 她的听觉、 触觉等很灵敏。 2. Don\'t be so sensitive and I was not criticizing you. 别那么敏感,我不是在批评你。 3. What food and fruit are sensitive? 哪些食物和水果是感光的？ 4. The film is coated with light sensitive chemicals, which are change by the different shades and colors of light. 胶卷上涂了一层感光的化学物质，这些物质因光的不同色度与颜色而改变。', '副词: sensitively 名词: sensitiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hinder', '[\'hɪndər]', 'v.阻碍；打扰 adj.后面的', '1. The crowd hindered him from leaving. 人群使他无法脱身。 2. Heavy snow hindered the construction work. 大雪妨碍了这项建筑工程的进行。 3. Don\'t let me hinder you from going. 别让我妨碍了你走。 4. Don\'t hinder me. 不要妨碍我。 5. The hinder leg of this horse was broken. 这匹马的后腿断了。', '名词: hinderer 过去式: hindered 过去分词: hindered 现在分词: hindering 第三人称单数: hinders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pierce', '[pɪrs]', 'v.刺穿；穿透；洞悉 Pierce. n.皮尔斯（人名）', '1. The needle pierced her finger. 针刺进了她的手指。 2. This new type of bullet can pierce armor. 这种新型子弹头能够穿甲。 3. Her shrieks pierced the air. 她尖锐的叫声直刺云天。 4. The regiment pierced through the enemy\'s lines. 这个团突破了敌军防线。', '形容词: piercing 副词: piercingly 名词: piercer 过去式: pierced 过去分词: pierced 现在分词: piercing 第三人称单数: pierces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solicitude', '[sə\'lɪsɪtuːd]', 'n.关心；挂念；焦虑', '1. His future is my greatest solicitude. 他的前途是我最关心的问题。 2. The solicitude shown for him by his neighbours after robbery touched him deeply. 他被抢劫后邻居对他的关切使他十分感动。 3. Her letter showed deep solicitude for your welfare. 她的来信表示对您的安康甚为挂念。 4. Her mother and sisters were spared much solicitude on her account. 她的母亲和妹妹们也免得为她焦虑了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gastric', '[\'ɡæstrɪk]', 'adj.胃的', '1. Gastric juices help us digest our food. 胃液能帮助消化。 2. He got a gastric ulcer 他得了胃溃疡。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('paraphrase', '[\'pærəfreɪz]', 'n.释义；解述；改写 v.改写；解述', '1. The teacher amplified the sense by a paraphrase. 老师用转述释义的方法详述了它的意义。 2. She gave us a paraphrase of that film. 她向我们复述了那部电影。 3. The paraphrase of the sonnet is easy to understand. 该十四行诗的意译易于理解。 4. Paraphrase this article in 250 words or less. 用不到 250 个字意译出这篇文章。', '形容词: paraphrasable 名词: paraphraser 过去式: paraphrased 过去分词: paraphrased 现在分词: paraphrasing 第三人称单数: paraphrases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blur', '[blɜːr]', 'v.弄脏；使 ... 模糊 n.污点；模糊', '1. The damp paper caused the ink to blur. 潮纸因墨水弄上污渍。 2. Don\'t blur the distinctions between things. 不要模糊事物之间的差别。 3. Do drunkards blur reality, or come closer to it? 酒醉之后是使现实模糊不清，还是更加接近现实了呢? 4. But we see it only as a hazy blur. 但我们看到的只是模糊的斑点。', '形容词: blurry 名词: blurriness 过去式: blurred 过去分词: blurred 现在分词: blurring 第三人称单数: blurs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comma', '[\'kɑːmə]', 'n.逗号；停顿；间歇；银纹多角蛱蝶', '1. The clause should be set off by a comma. 这个从句应该用逗号隔开。 2. People often use a comma instead of a full stop. 人们常常用逗号，而不是句号。 3. In the 19th century the population of comma butterflies crashed. 19世纪，黄钩蛱蝶的数量锐减。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avoid', '[ə\'vɔɪd]', 'vt.避免；逃避；[律]使无效；撤销', '1. You should avoid unnecessary repetition. 你应避免不必要的重复。 2. They all avoided mentioning that name. 他们都避免提及那名字。 3. He\'ll grab at any excuse to avoid doing the dishes. 他会随便找个借口来逃避洗碗。 4. No one can avoid his own responsibility. 没有人能够逃避自己的责任。', '形容词: avoidable 副词: avoidably 名词: avoider 过去式: avoided 过去分词: avoided 现在分词: avoiding 第三人称单数: avoids');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('install', '[ɪn\'stɔːl]', 'vt.安装；安置；使 ... 就职', '1. She installed her air-conditioner without help by herself. 她自己安装了空调。 2. The workers are installing a heating system. 工人们正在安装供暖系统。 3. It is necessary that you install a burglar alarm. 你有必要装防盗警报器。 4. The children are comfortably installed in a new home. 孩子们在新居舒适地安顿下来。', '名词: installer');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('injection', '[ɪn\'dʒekʃn]', 'n.注射；注射物；数学函数', '1. The morphine was administered by injection. 那吗啡是注射进去的。 2. The doctor gave her an injection to alleviate the pain. 医生给她注射以减轻疼痛。 3. An injection is better than a pill. 注射比服用药片见效快。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decamp', '[dɪ\'kæmp]', 'v.(士兵)离营；匆忙秘密地离开', '1. The soldiers decamped at dawn. 士兵在黎明时撤离了营地。 2. She has decamped with all our money. 她携带我们所有的钱潜逃了。 3. The lodger has decamped with paying nothing at all. 房客根本没付房租就溜走了。 4. The young man decamped with his neighbor\'s daughter. 那个青年与他邻居的女儿一起私奔了。', '名词: decampment 过去式: decamped 过去分词: decamped 现在分词: decamping 第三人称单数: decamps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inventory', '[\'ɪnvəntɔːri]', 'n.详细目录；存货(清单) vt.编制(详细目录)', '1. The job of compiling the inventory took several hours. 编辑详细目录的工作花了好几个小时。 2. The inventory showed that the store was overstocked. 清单显示商店存货过多。 3. All of the inventory has been tagged and referenced. 所有存货清单都被贴上了标签，以备参考。 4. Is the shop inventory verified before the commencement of a sales promotion? 有否在减价开始前按公司清单核实存货? 5. He inventories the minor losses and submitted it to the management. 他将那些较小的损失编进目录，上交给管理层。', '形容词: inventorial 副词: inventorially 名词复数: inventories 过去式: inventoried 过去分词: inventoried 现在分词: inventorying 第三人称单数: inventories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('filings', '[\'faɪlɪŋz]', 'n.（金属的）锉屑；末 名词filing的复数形式.', '1. When the current stops, the iron filings drop off 当电流停止时，这些铁屑就掉了下来。 2. your hair has many scalp filings. 你的头发有很多头皮屑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('splendor', '[\'splendə]', 'n.光辉；壮丽；显赫；辉煌', '1. There below lay Paris in all its splendor. 那下面就是光彩夺目的巴黎。 2. Never in his life had he gazed on such splendor. 他生平从没有见过如此壮丽的场面。 3. We admired the splendor of the mountain scenery. 我们赞赏着壮丽的山景。 4. Then the doors of the hall flew open, and showed the whole splendor of a court. 大厅的门一打开,显赫壮观的宫廷景象展现出来了。', '形容词: splendorous');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hypothesis', '[haɪ\'pɑːθəsɪs]', 'n.假说；假设；前提；猜测', '1. The hypothesis promptly attracted some interest. 这个假说很快引起了注意。 2. The validity of the hypothesis can be tested. 这种假说的可靠性是经得起考验的。 3. His hypothesis turned out to be correct. 事实证明他的假设是正确的。 4. The survey result consisted with our hypothesis. 调查结果和我们的假设相一致。', '名词复数: hypotheses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('canorous', '[kə\'nɒrəs]', 'adj.音乐般地；音调优美的；响亮的', '1. The first, establish a canorous brand easily. 第一,易于树立起响亮的品牌。 2. Later, new rural area has very canorous name \" rebuild home \" . 图王、拒绝游泳的鱼和郭吉军。 3. Colour is decorated indoors in very important, it is human vision in most canorous language symbol. 色彩在室内装饰中十分重要，它是人类视觉中最响亮的语言符号。 4. At the beginning of this century, swede puts forward catchword of a canorous: \"Make commodity more beautiful! 本世纪初，瑞典人提出一个响亮的口号：“把日用品做得更美！”', '副词: canorously 名词: canorousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irritable', '[\'ɪrɪtəbl]', 'adj.易怒的；急躁的', '1. The old man is an irritable person. 那个老人是个易怒的人。 2. We were both workaholics who got more irritable when we were exhausted. 我们都是工作狂，疲惫不堪的时候脾气越发暴躁。 3. Our teacher is an irritable old lady. She gets angry easily. 我们的老师是位脾气急躁的老太太。她很容易生气。', '副词: irritably 名词: irritableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carouse', '[kə\'raʊz]', 'v.痛饮；畅饮；狂欢 n.狂饮作乐', '1. Joy of the plenteous dinner, strong carouse and drinking? 你瞭解那快乐是丰足的饮宴者，纵情狂欢的饮乐吗？ 2. His followers did not rape or carouse, like the troops of many warlord armies. 他的部下也不象许多军阀的军队那样强奸民女，大吃大喝。 3. My anticipated “calm retreat” in San Sebastian turned into a wild carouse! 在珊西笆鸶靪，我所期待的静谧休閒地，竟变成热热闹闹的盛会。 4. No wonder they drink ,smoke ,fright ,carouse and otherwise engage in inappropriate social behavior. 难怪他们喝酒、抽烟、打架、狂欢作乐或者做出不当的社会举动。', '名词: carouser 过去式: caroused 过去分词: caroused 现在分词: carousing 第三人称单数: carouses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skillet', '[\'skɪlɪt]', 'n.煎锅', '1. Melt a small amount of butter in a pan or skillet on the medium heat. 煎锅用中小火加热，入黄油化开。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debar', '[dɪ\'bɑːr]', 'v.排除在外；阻止(行使权力等)', '1. So far, we can\'t debar the seismal possibility. 到目前为止 2. Convicted criminals are debarred from voting in elections. 已判刑的罪犯均被剥夺选举投票权。 3. The railroad gates debar people from crossing the tracks. 铁道的栅栏阻止行人跨越轨道。', '名词: debarment 过去式: debarred 过去分词: debarred 现在分词: debarring 第三人称单数: debars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sanctify', '[\'sæŋktɪfaɪ]', 'v.使神圣；使圣洁；认可；批准', '1. God blessed the seventh day and sanctified it. 上帝祝福第七天并且使它成为神圣的日子。 2. This is sanctified ground, and we may not tread upon it. 这是圣地，我们不可践踏。', '名词: sanctification 过去式: sanctified 过去分词: sanctified 现在分词: sanctifying 第三人称单数: sanctifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saccharine', '[\'sækəriːn]', 'adj.糖质的；含糖的；奉承的；娇媚的', '1. We used saccharine tablets in lieu of sugar. 我们用糖精片代替糖。 2. We used saccharine tablets in lieu of sugar. 我们用糖精片代替糖。 3. She smiled with saccharine sweetness. 她的笑里只有虚情假意的甜蜜。 4. When he talks to his boss, he puts on a saccharine smile. 他跟老板说话的时候', '副词: saccharinely 名词: saccharinity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('locale', '[loʊ\'kæl]', 'n.现场；场所', '1. Premier Wen Jiabao commands the earthquake locale in person. 温家宝总理在地震现场亲自指挥。 2. Maybe, the first and the second shot, is not at the same locale. 或许，前后两次枪击并不是在同一个现场击发的。 3. Marseilles is the locale of the novel. 马赛是这部小说的背景地点。 4. The director is looking for a suitable locale for his new film. 导演在为新片物色合适的拍摄场地。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comestible', '[kə\'mestɪbl]', 'adj.可以吃的 (复)comestibles：n.；食物', '1. And the LORD said unto Satan, Whence comest thou? 耶和华问撒但说，你从那里来。 2. And the LORD said unto Satan， Whence comest thou? 耶和华问撒但说，你曾用心察看我的仆人约伯没有。 3. And the LORD said unto Satan, From whence comest thou? 耶和华问撒但说，你从那里来。 4. A way of separating some comestible red pigment from the red turnip is studied by this paper. 本文以胭脂萝卜为原料进行食用红色素的提取研究。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('throttle', '[\'θrɑːtl]', 'n.节流阀；油门；喉咙 v.扼喉咙；使窒息', '1. He moved the throttle to the firewall. 他把节流阀移动到了防火墙。 2. He drove his motorbike up and down the drive at full throttle. 他骑着摩托车，开足油门，在车道上来回奔驰。 3. To do this you will need to learn how to trail brake while keeping some throttle on. 要做到这一点，你需要学习在逐渐放开刹车的同时保持一点油门。 4. He wanted to seize the baby and throttle it. 他真想把孩子抓过来卡死。', '名词: throttler 过去式: throttled 过去分词: throttled 现在分词: throttling 第三人称单数: throttles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entrepreneur', '[ˌɑːntrəprə\'nɜːr]', 'n.企业家；承包商；主办者', '1. He is a shipping entrepreneur. 他是个航运企业家。 2. The entrepreneur has become a news figure. 这位企业家变成了新闻人物。', '形容词: entrepreneurial 名词: entrepreneurialism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deluxe', '[dɪ\'lʌks]', 'adj.豪华的；高级的', '1. The deluxe suite also comes with a very nice bar. 豪华套房另外还有一个非常别致的小酒吧。 2. I suppose your deluxe suite is a little bigger. 我希望这个豪华套房能更大些。 3. Would you like a standard,superior,deluxe,or presidential suite? 您想订标准套房、高级套房、豪华套房还是总统套房? 4. It will be published in an deluxe edition in autumn. 它将在秋季出版精装本。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pervert', '[pər\'vɜːrt]', 'vt.误用；歪曲；曲解；败坏 n.变态；色狼', '1. Scientific knowledge was perverted to help cause destruction and war. 科学知识被滥用于破坏和战争。 2. To pervert what a person has said is to give a wrong meaning to it. 歪曲一个人所说的就是对其所说给予错误的理解。 3. He made an attempt to pervert the meaning of an innocent story. 他试图曲解了一个无辜故事的意义。 4. The corrupt man takes bribes to pervert the course of justice. 那个腐败的男人收受贿赂颠倒正义。 5. Cinema is the ultimate pervert art. 电影是终极的变态艺术。', '形容词: pervertible 名词: perverter 过去式: perverted 过去分词: perverted 现在分词: perverting 第三人称单数: perverts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('menial', '[\'miːniəl]', 'adj.适合仆人做的；卑微的 n.佣人；家仆；卑贱的人', '1. he performed the menial chore of shining shoes. 他像仆人一样做些擦鞋的家务活。 2. There are no menial jobs, only menial attitudes. 没有卑贱的工作,只有卑贱的态度。 3. There is a positive attitude here, from the boss down to the lowliest menial. 在这里上至老板下至最低微的下人，都有很积极的态度。', '副词: menially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flatter', '[\'flætər]', 'v.奉承；恭维；取悦；显得好看', '1. My boss likes it when we flatter him. 我的老板喜欢我们奉承他。 2. Friends who flatter you to your face are not true friends. 凡是当面奉承你的朋友不是真朋友。 3. He flattered her about her cooking. 他恭维她的烹调手艺。 4. It\'s impossible for you to ask a girl to teach you how to flatter another. 你不可能让一个女孩教你如何取悦另一个女孩。', '副词: flatteringly 名词: flatterer 过去式: flattered 过去分词: flattered 现在分词: flattering 第三人称单数: flatters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acolyte', '[\'ækəlaɪt]', 'n.（教士的）助手；侍僧', '1. A Shade is created by sacrificing an Acolyte with the Sacrificial Pit. 阴影是侍僧在牺牲祭坛牺牲后变成的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('permanent', '[\'pɜːrmənənt]', 'adj.永久的；持久的 n.<口> 烫发', '1. The incident left permanent traces on his mind. 那件事在他头脑里留下了永久的印象。 2. I am looking for a permanent position. 我在找一个永久性的职业。 3. These factors usually have a longer and more permanent impact on share prices. 这项因素通常会对股价产生更加长远和持久的影响。', '副词: permanently 名词: permanentness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cravat', '[krə\'væt]', 'n.饰带；围巾；三角绷带', '1. I have never seen a man wearing cravat. 我从来没有见过有人戴领巾。 2. You\'re never fully dressed without a cravat. 不打领结，就不算正装。 3. I have just bought myself an expensive cravat. 我给自己买了一条昂贵的领带。 4. She wrapped round her a long red woolen cravat, and open the door. 她围好一条红色的长呢围脖,然后打开房门。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('veteran', '[\'vetərən]', 'adj.老练的 n.老手；老兵', '1. A good idea soaked into that veteran worker. 那位老工人的头脑里有了一个好主意。 2. This veteran cadre is looked up to by everybody. 这位老干部受到众人的尊敬。 3. The baseball veteran loved to coach young players. 这位棒球老手喜欢指导年轻选手。 4. That comrade writing these poems is a veteran. 写这些诗的那个同志是个老兵。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drool', '[druːl]', 'v.流口水；垂涎；胡说 n.口水；胡话', '1. The male may drool and vocalize with a lip-smacking sound or a hiss. 雄龟会流出口水，并击打嘴唇发出声音，或是发出嘶嘶声。 2. I was testing my keyboard for drool resistance. 我在测试键盘的‘防口水’性能。', '过去式: drooled 过去分词: drooled 现在分词: drooling 第三人称单数: drools');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pulsation', '[pʌl\'seɪʃn]', 'n.脉博；悸动；震动', '1. The pulsation of the dorsal artery of your foot is a bit weak. 足背动脉波动稍弱。 2. Usually, at this point, a pulsation may be felt at the end of the spine. 这时通常会在脊椎尾部感到一种搏动。 3. It offers the true pulsation of natural growth. 它提供了自然成长的真正跳动。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adhere', '[əd\'hɪr]', 'vi.遵守；坚持；粘附', '1. They failed to adhere to our original agreement. 他们未能遵守我们原定的协议。 2. We should adhere to our opinions. 我们应当坚持我们的意见。 3. We adhere to the principle stand of marxism. 我们坚持马克思主义思想原则。 4. The new paint won\'t adhere to the walls so I\'ll have to strip it all off and start from scratch. 新涂的油漆粘不住墙壁,因此我得把它全部刮掉,重新刷过。', '过去式: adhered 过去分词: adhered 现在分词: adhering 第三人称单数: adheres');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('knave', '[neɪv]', 'n.无赖；纸牌中的J；<古>男仆；出身卑微的人', '1. He is a knave in grain. 他是一个坏透了的人。 2. Knave is usually a person who brings trouble. 一个无赖往往意味着他是一个带来麻烦的人。 3. He hid a knave of hearts in his pocket. 他把一张红桃J 藏在口袋里。', '形容词: knavish 副词: knavishly 名词: knavishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('homogeneous', '[ˌhoʊmə\'dʒiːniəs]', 'adj.同质的；同种的；相似的', '1. Life in the United States is no longer if it ever was culturally homogeneous. 美国的生活已经不再是，如果它曾经是，同源文化。 2. Japan has a largely homogeneous population. 日本的人口基本上同属一 个种族。 3. More of the hitherto homogeneous societies are becoming plural ones. 越来越多的单一种族社会逐渐变得多元化。', '副词: homogeneously 名词: homogeneousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abrogate', '[\'æbrəɡeɪt]', 'v.废除；取消', '1. The government cannot just abrogate contracts. 政府不能单纯的撤销合同。 2. I want to report the loss of credit card and abrogate it. 我要办理信用卡挂失并取消那张卡。', '名词: abrogation 过去式: abrogated 过去分词: abrogated 现在分词: abrogating 第三人称单数: abrogates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emasculate', '[i\'mæskjuleɪt]', 'v.阉割；使柔弱；削弱 adj.去势的；柔弱的', '1. He felt emasculated by her dominance. 他感到她的支配地位使自己变的柔弱。 2. The company tried to emasculate the unions. 公司企图削弱工会力量。', '形容词: emasculative 名词: emasculation 过去式: emasculated 过去分词: emasculated 现在分词: emasculating 第三人称单数: emasculates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('regressive', '[rɪ\'ɡresɪv]', 'adj.退步的；退化的；递减的(税率)；回归的', '1. This is both regressive and likely to aggravate the deficit. 这既是一种退步，又可能使财政赤字加速增长。 2. The policy has been condemned as a regressive step. 这项政策被认为是一种倒退而受到谴责。 3. A sum of useful data and regressive equation were obtained. 获得大量的分析数据及回归方程。', '副词: regressively 名词: regressiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('self-assertion', '[ˌselfə\'sɜːʃən]', 'n.坚持己见；自信', '1. Self trust is the essence of heroism. 自信乃英雄主义的精髓。 2. This takes a serious toll on our self esteem and confidence. 这对我们的自尊和自信造成了严重而不佳的影响。', '形容词: self-assertive 副词: self-assertively 名词: self-assertiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('puddle', '[\'pʌdl]', 'n.水坑；地上积水；胶泥 v.搅浊；在泥污中打滚；排尿', '1. The puddle evaporated rapidly in the sun. 水坑在阳光下迅速蒸发。 2. I have rarely seen such a huge puddle of milk. 我几乎没看过这么大的奶水坑。', '形容词: puddly 过去式: puddled 过去分词: puddled 现在分词: puddling 第三人称单数: puddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pitiless', '[\'pɪtiləs]', 'adj.无情的；冷酷的；无怜悯心的', '1. The fact stood out cut in steel on the pitiless daylight. 在无情的光天化日下,这个事实是确凿无疑的。 2. This ruler is a pitiless tyrant. 这个统治者是一个冷酷的暴君。 3. The pitiless north wind blew for weeks. 凛冽的北风一连刮了几个星期。 4. The pitiless woman refused to help the poor sick girl. 这铁石心肠的妇人拒绝帮助这个生病的可怜女孩。', '副词: pitilessly 名词: pitilessness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pander', '[\'pændər]', 'v.迎合；拉皮条 n.拉皮条者', '1. Since she was an only child, her parents pandered to her every whim. 由于她是独女，父母对她总是百依百顺。 2. The newspapers there pander to people\'s interest in crime and violence. 那儿的报纸迎合读者对犯罪和暴力的兴趣。', '过去式: pandered 过去分词: pandered 现在分词: pandering 第三人称单数: panders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surmise', '[sər\'maɪz]', 'n.推测 vt.推测；臆测', '1. It turned out that my surmise was correct. 结果表明我的推测没有错。 2. I surmise that he will take the job. 我推测他会接受这份工作。 3. They surmise that inflation in services is being underestimated, causing real growth to be overstated. 他们推测是因为低估了服务领域的通胀，因此实际增长才会被高估。', '过去式: surmised 过去分词: surmised 现在分词: surmising 第三人称单数: surmises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('husbandry', '[\'hʌzbəndri]', 'n.农事；耕作；农牧业；节约（资源）', '1. The development of agriculture and animal husbandry has been given top priority in the Tibetan economy. 发展农牧业在西藏的经济生活中处于最重要的地位。 2. Over years, Jieqi has played an important role in China\'s agricultural and animal husbandry production. 长期以来，二十四节气在中国的农牧业生产中一直起着重要的作用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concerto', '[kən\'tʃɜːrtoʊ]', 'n.[音]协奏曲', '1. The piano concerto was wonderfully rendered. 这首钢琴协奏曲演奏得很好。 2. The concert ended with a Mozart violin concerto. 音乐会在莫扎特的小提琴协奏曲中结束。 3. She played the difficult piano concerto to perfection. 她将这首难度大的钢琴协奏曲弹奏得完美无缺。', '名词复数: concertos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recessive', '[rɪ\'sesɪv]', 'adj.后退的；逆行的；隐性遗传的 n.[遗传学]隐性基因；隐性性状', '1. Brown eyes are dominant and blue eyes are recessive. 棕色眼睛是显性的，蓝色眼睛是隐性的。 2. Genes are described as DOMINANT or RECESSIVE. 基因分为显性基因和隐性基因。', '副词: recessively 名词: recessiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spunk', '[spʌŋk]', 'n.精神；勇气；怒气；火绒 v.<方言>鼓励', '1. She might be small, but she\'s got a lot of spunk. 她或许是小了点，但她很有精神。 2. He had a cold shower to renew the spunk and then kept on working. 他冲了个冷水浴清醒一下头脑，然后又继续回去工作。 3. He got his spunk up and told the truth. 他鼓起勇气，说出了真相。 4. I admire your spunk and independence. 我欣赏你的勇气和自立。 5. Spunk up, everything will be all right. 别恢心，一切都会好起来的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discompose', '[ˌdɪskəm\'poʊz]', 'vt.使不安；使烦乱；使烦恼', '1. The grin of his friend discompose jack when he tried to make his speech. 杰克想要讲演时，他的朋友裂着嘴笑，使他心里很慌乱。', '副词: discomposedly 过去式: discomposed 过去分词: discomposed 现在分词: discomposing 第三人称单数: discomposes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expand', '[ɪk\'spænd]', 'v.使 ... 膨胀；详述；扩张；增加；张开', '1. Metals expand when they are heated. 金属遇热则膨胀。 2. Would you expand upon the matter a little further? 请你再进一步谈谈这件事好吗? 3. They conferred on the best way to expand business. 他们商议扩展业务的最好方法。 4. Our foreign trade has expanded during recent years. 近年来我们的对外贸易有所增加。', '形容词: expandable 名词: expander 过去式: expanded 过去分词: expanded 现在分词: expanding 第三人称单数: expands');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assume', '[ə\'suːm]', 'vt.假定；设想；承担；(想当然的)认为；假装', '1. Let\'s assume it to be true. 让我们假定这是真的。 2. We assume his guilt. 我们假定他是有罪的。 3. They assumed their operational positions. 他们设想了自己在实施中的作用。 4. I am not afraid to assume the responsibility. 我不怕承担责任.', '形容词: assumable 副词: assumably 名词: assumer 过去式: assumed 过去分词: assumed 现在分词: assuming 第三人称单数: assumes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accessible', '[ək\'sesəbl]', 'adj.可得到的；易接近的；可进入的；易受影响的；易理解的', '1. Such information is not really accessible. 这种信息不是很容易得到的。 2. A manager should be accessible to his staff. 一个管理人员应该让职员感到平易近人。 3. This database is only accessible by the authorized manager. 只有授权的管理员才可以访问此数据库。 4. He is not accessible to pity. 他不大有同情心。', '副词: accessibly 名词: accessibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('violate', '[\'vaɪəleɪt]', 'v.侵犯；违反；扰乱；亵渎；强奸', '1. Don\'t violate other people\'s copyright. 不要侵犯他人版权。 2. I\'m committed not to violate the rules. 我有义务不违反规定。 3. The country violated the international agreement. 这个国家违反了国际协议。 4. The sound of guns violated the peace of the countryside. 炮声扰乱了乡村的宁静。', '形容词: violative 名词: violator 过去式: violated 过去分词: violated 现在分词: violating 第三人称单数: violates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('largess', '[\'lɑːdʒɪs]', 'n.慷慨的赠与；赏赐', '1. Our financial institutions are overleveraged and dependent on government largess for their survival. 金融机构可超额利用杠杆作用，还可依赖政府的赠与生存下去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fulcrum', '[\'fʊlkrəm]', 'n.（杠杆的）支点；支柱；最重要的部分', '1. Give me a fulcrum on which to rest, and I will move the earth. 给我一个支承的支点，我就会转动地球。 2. Many people see marriage as the fulcrum of their lives. 许多人视婚姻为生命最重要的部分。 3. For broadcasting management, a brand is just such a fulcrum. 对于广播经营来说，品牌就是它的一个支点。', '名词复数: fulcrums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inexplicable', '[ˌɪnɪk\'splɪkəbl]', 'adj.无法说明的；无法解释的；费解的', '1. His inexplicable debts were a byword in his circle. 他那些来历不明的借款成为那圈子里人议论的话题。 2. Her inexplicable absence worried me. 她的缺席无法解释, 令我担忧。 3. The most inexplicable things will brew in any mind. 任何大脑都会酝酿出令人费解的观念。', '副词: inexplicably 名词: inexplicability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apprise', '[ə\'praɪz]', 'vt.通知；报告', '1. I\'m glad to apprise you that you are the winner. 我很高兴地通知您，您获奖了。', '过去式: apprised 过去分词: apprised 现在分词: apprising 第三人称单数: apprises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entwine', '[ɪn\'twaɪn]', 'v.(使) 缠绕；纠缠', '1. The plant will entwine round the stick as it grows. 这种植物会缠绕着竿子生长。 2. They walked along with (their) arms entwined. 他们挽著胳膊走去。', '异体字: intwine 名词: entwinement 过去式: entwined 过去分词: entwined 现在分词: entwining 第三人称单数: entwines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fasten', '[\'fæsn]', 'vt.拴紧；使固定；系；强加于 vi.固定；系紧；抓紧', '1. Do not fasten all the windows up while you sleep. 睡觉时不要将所有的窗户都关紧。 2. For your own safety,please fasten your seat belts. 安全起见，请系紧安全带。 3. I fastened the pages together with a paperclip. 我用一个纸夹把那几页纸夹在一起。 4. The little boy has learnt to fasten shoelaces. 这小男孩已学会系鞋带了。 5. What can I use to fasten on this clip? 我用什么才能将这个夹子固定好?', '名词: fastener 过去式: fastened 过去分词: fastened 现在分词: fastening 第三人称单数: fastens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gladiator', '[\'ɡlædieɪtər]', 'n.角斗士；与野兽搏斗者', '1. He was a handsome man, and built like a gladiator. 他这人仪表堂堂，体格魁梧得像一位斗士。 2. Isabel looked a moment at the vanquished gladiator. 伊莎贝尔望了一眼那个打败的角斗士。 3. It was intended for gladiator shows and wild beast hunts. 那是用来做角斗表演和猎捕野兽的。', '形容词: gladiatorial');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scruple', '[\'skruːpl]', 'n.顾忌；迟疑 v.顾虑', '1. He has absolutely no scruples; he\'ll do anything to get what he wants. 他没有一点点顾忌，为了得到自己想要的东西，他什么事都做得出来。 2. She will tell lies without scruple. 她会肆无忌惮地说谎。 3. Jane did it at once, and made no scruple about it. 简毫不犹豫，立刻就办了。 4. Don\'t scruple to ask for anything you want. 你要什么请尽量讲。', '过去式: scrupled 过去分词: scrupled 现在分词: scrupling 第三人称单数: scruples');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inveterate', '[ɪn\'vetərət]', 'adj.根深蒂固的；成瘾的', '1. It seems that your inveterate prejudice utterly affected your judgement. 看来你根深蒂固的偏见已经完全影响了你的判断力。 2. He is a politician known as an inveterate kisser of babies. 他是一个吻婴儿成癖的政客。 3. It is hard for an inveterate smoker to give up tobacco. 老烟鬼很难戒烟。', '副词: inveterately 名词: inveteracy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skirmish', '[\'skɜːrmɪʃ]', 'n.前哨战；小争斗；小冲突 v.参与小争斗', '1. The skirmish grew into a major battle. 小冲突扩大形成大战斗。 2. This area is peaceful except for a few skirmishes in the distance. 除了远处的零星的小冲突之外，这个地区是和平的。', '名词: skirmisher 过去式: skirmished 过去分词: skirmished 现在分词: skirmishing 第三人称单数: skirmishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indenture', '[ɪn\'dentʃər]', 'n.契约；合同；锯齿状的边缘；凹的部分 （复数）indentures:师徒契约； 定期服务合同. vt.以契约束缚', '1. Soon thereafter, private agents scoured the ports taverns, and countryside to sign on workers for indenture. 此后不久，私人机构迅速搜查港口的小客栈和乡下地区，来招募契约仆役。 2. The indenture contract was a device that enabled people to pay for their passage to America by selling their labor to someone in the New World for a specified period of time. 契约是使人们以向新大陆的某个雇主在一段时间里出卖劳动力的方式来支付其赴美旅费的手段。', '过去式: indentured 过去分词: indentured 现在分词: indenturing 第三人称单数: indentures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stratum', '[\'streɪtəm]', 'n.地层；阶层', '1. They represent each society stratum. 他们代表各个社会阶层。 2. Such inequalities are found in every stratum. 这类不公平的现象存在于社会的每一个阶层。', '形容词: stratal 名词复数: strata');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hackneyed', '[\'hæknid]', 'adj.（指词语﹑ 言辞等）陈腐的；老生常谈的 动词hackney的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. Yes, it\'s a hackneyed phrase, but politics is the art of the possible. 没错，这是一条陈腐的词语，但政治的确是一种可能事件的艺术。 2. The hackneyed phrase came unintended to his lips. 他顺口说了这句老掉牙的套话。 3. \"Last but not least\" is regarded as a hackneyed expression. “最后的但并非最不重要的一点“这个词组被认为是陈词烂调了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ancestry', '[\'ænsestri]', 'n.祖先；家世；门第；血统', '1. Many of the early settlers in America had English ancestry. 许多早期美国移民的祖先都是英国人。 2. He cames of a good ancestry. 他家世很好。 3. He is an American of French ancestry. 他是法国血统的美国人。', '名词复数: ancestries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aboveboard', '[ə\'bʌv\'boʊrd]', 'adv.光明正大地；率直地 adj.光明正大的；率直的', '1. If you are worried about his price or quality, you can still be open and aboveboard and just go visit other sellers to compare prices and quality. 如果你害怕他价钱收得太贵或者品质不好，可以光明正大地去别的贩卖者那里参看价钱和品质。 2. Everything we do is aboveboard and never furtive. 做任何事，我们都是光明正大的，从不偷偷摸摸。 3. His business dealings were aboveboard. 他的生意来往是光明正大的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reversion', '[rɪ\'vɜːrʒn]', 'n.返回；逆转；恢复；反向', '1. I\'m trying to prevent the reversion of my garden to nature. 我正在试图防止我的花园返回一片荒芜的自然状态。 2. The reversion frequency is increased by the addition of mutagents. 逆转的频率靠加入诱发变因素而增加。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jumpy', '[\'dʒʌmpi]', 'adj.跳跃的；跳动的；神经质的；紧张不安的', '1. The jumpy mother is always cross with her children. 这个神经质的母亲老是对孩子发脾气。 2. It was beginning to make him very jumpy. 这使他开始感到心神不安。', '比较级: jumpier 最高级: jumpiest 名词: jumpiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('haphazard', '[hæp\'hæzərd]', 'adj.偶然的；随意的；杂乱无章的 adv.杂乱地；任意地 n.偶然', '1. Meetings occurred in a somewhat haphazard fashion. 会见是以多少有点偶然的方式进行的。 2. I don\'t like the haphazard way he does things. 我不喜欢他随意的办事方式。 3. Why did you put the volumes of the encyclopedia in haphazard order? 你为何把这套百科全书放得杂乱无章? 4. It is just a thing done at haphazard. 这只是件偶然为之的事情。', '副词: haphazardly 名词: haphazardness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loiter', '[\'lɔɪtər]', 'v.闲荡；虚度；徘徊', '1. There are several young boys loitering around the building. 这栋房子周围有几个小男孩在晃荡。 2. The high school students like to loiter in the Central Square; 高中学生喜欢在中心广场闲荡； 3. Don\'t loiter your time away. 不要虚度时光。 4. Please do not loiter in the street after school. 放学后，请不要在街头徘徊。', '名词: loiterer 过去式: loitered 过去分词: loitered 现在分词: loitering 第三人称单数: loiters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('auspices', '[\'ɔːspɪsɪz]', 'n.赞助；前兆 名词auspice的复数形式.', '1. The association is under the auspices of Word Bank. 这个组织是在世界银行的赞助下办的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mangy', '[\'meɪndʒi]', 'adj.患疥癣的；褴褛的；污秽的；卑鄙的', '1. You scared me to death,you mangy thing! 你把我吓死了，你这臭东西！ 2. A bird is known by its note, and a mangy his talk. 闻其歌知其鸟，听其言知其人。 3. I work for him, not for some mangy crow! 我为他工作，而不是为脏污的乌鸦！ 4. How mangy students do your class have? 你班有多少学生？', '副词: mangily 比较级: mangier 最高级: mangiest 名词: manginess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lineaments', '[\'lɪniəmənts]', '轮廓', '1. His face shows the lineaments of the Hapsburgs. 他的脸具有哈布斯堡王室的外貌特徵。 2. We found the lineaments of the situation. 我们找到了情况的关键因素。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('animadvert', '[ˌænəmæd\'vɜːt]', 'vi.苛责；非难', '1. Try to avoid the too frequent use of such Latin words as juxtaposition, animadvert, salutation, recapitulate. 尽量不要经常使用这些拉丁词语，比如juxtaposition， animadvert， salutation， recapitulate。 2. There is hardly a subject that you can mention that will not make him animadvert upon some aspect of human nature. 你所能提出的问题，几乎没有不会使他在人性方面予以评论的。 3. In 1950s the glass curtain walls were bricked as a animadvert on capitalist aesthetic. 1950年代将玻璃幕墙用砖砌上以示对资本主义审美的批判； 4. Animadvert on the tow consciousnesses;we will try to discuss the prospect of feminism literature. 并且,借助于对这种现象的批判,本论文将试图继续探讨女性写作在“自恋”与“自虐”之后将向何处去的重大课题。', '过去式: animadverted 过去分词: animadverted 现在分词: animadverting 第三人称单数: animadverts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preponderate', '[prɪ\'pɒndəˌreɪt]', 'v.以重量胜过；占优势；胜过', '1. Christians preponderate in the population of that part of the country. 基督教徒在该国那一地区的人口中居多。', '副词: preponderately 名词: preponderation 过去式: preponderated 过去分词: preponderated 现在分词: preponderating 第三人称单数: preponderates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('icicle', '[\'aɪsɪkl]', 'n.冰柱；冰垂', '1. As water continues to drip, the icicle grows. 随着水不断下滴，冰柱的体积也慢慢增大。 2. The spectacle of the icicle in the cave is amazing. 石花洞的冰凌奇观让人叹为观止。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('iota', '[aɪ\'oʊtə]', 'n.极微小；希腊文的第九个字母', '1. There is not an iota of truth in his remarks. 他说的那番话一点儿真实性也没有。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unfeigned', '[ʌn\'feɪnd]', 'adj.真实的；真诚的', '1. Unfeigned, fervent love through the Spirit should be the chief token of a true conversion. 藉由圣灵产生对弟兄真诚的爱，是真实悔改的最佳表徵。', '副词: unfeignedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cynosure', '[\'sɪnəʃʊr]', 'n.注意的焦点；指引物 Cynosure. n.北极星', '1. Her mind delighted itself with scenes of luxury and refinement, situations in which she was the cynosure of all eyes, the arbiter of all fates. 她又自得其乐地想象各种豪华风雅的场面，在这些场面里她是人们目光的焦点，主宰命运的女神。', '形容词: cynosural');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sledgehammer', '[\'sledʒhæmər]', 'n.长柄大锤 v.用大锤敲打 adj.重击的；无情的', '1. She hit the nail with a sledgehammer. 她用大锤钉钉子。 2. She picked up the sledgehammer and began banging away with enthusiasm. 她拿起大锤便用力敲打起来。 3. I was holding a large crowbar, and my co-worker was holding a sledgehammer. 我拿着一根很大的撬棍，我的同事拿着一把大锤。 4. Printing business cards on a thirty-inch press is using a sledgehammer to crack a nut. 在30英寸印刷机上印刷名片简直是大材小用，得不偿失。 5. They were free to use sledgehammer prosecutorial tactics. 他们大可用一些无情的原告人策略。', '过去式: sledgehammered 过去分词: sledgehammered 现在分词: sledgehammering 第三人称单数: sledgehammers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ken', '[ken]', 'n.视野；眼界；知识范围 v.知道；了解 Ken. n.肯恩(男子名)', '1. His ideas are quite beyond my ken. 我很不理解他的想法。 2. I can\'t repair a car engine; it\'s quite beyond my ken. 我不会修理汽车引擎，这超出了我的知识范围。', '过去式: kenned/kent 过去分词: kenned/kent 现在分词: kenning 第三人称单数: kens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('controversial', '[ˌkɑːntrə\'vɜːrʃl]', 'adj.有争议的；引起争论的', '1. We tried to stay away from controversial topics at the dinner party. 晚宴上我们尽力避免一些有争议的话题。 2. This is a controversial question. 这是个引起争论的问题。', '副词: controversially 名词: controversialist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compassionate', '[kəm\'pæʃənət]', 'adj.有同情心的 vt.同情', '1. The plight of the refugees arouses the compassionate old man. 难民的困苦唤醒了那位有同情心的老人。 2. We provide free broadband services, the spread of sophisticated Chinese cooking, including Guangdong and Sichuan cooking, and compassionate customer service. 我们提供自由宽频服务，中国烹调精妙的传播包括四川和广东烹调，并且有同情心的顾客服务。 3. The Ministry released him on compassionate grounds. 内阁因同情而将他释放。 4. Compassionate forgiveness allows for compassion in action to be born in the dance of life. 富于同情的原谅，允许行动中的同情在生命之舞中得以诞生。', '副词: compassionately 名词: compassionateness 过去式: compassionated 过去分词: compassionated 现在分词: compassionating 第三人称单数: compassionates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bend', '[bend]', 'v.弯曲；使弯曲；屈服；屈从；集中于 n.弯曲；弯道', '1. The branches bent in the wind. 树枝被风吹弯了。 2. The branch bent but didn\'t break when the boy climbed along it. 那男孩爬上树枝时，树枝弯曲了，但是没有折断。 3. They refused to bend to the hijackers\' demands. 他们拒绝屈从于劫机者的要求。 4. She can\'t bend him to her will. 她无法使他服从自己的意志。 5. The stream takes a sudden bend to the east. 小溪突然转向东流。', '过去式: bent 过去分词: bent 现在分词: bending 第三人称单数: bends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seminal', '[\'semɪnl]', 'adj.精液的；种子的；生殖的；创新的；影响深远的', '1. Furthermore, sugar from crude honey can be easily absorbed and useful to the formation of seminal fluid. 另外，天然蜂蜜中的糖极易被人体吸收，对精液的形成十分有益。 2. The atypia is degeneratie and not obsered in the seminal esicles of young men. 这种非典型现象属于自然退化性表现，在青年男性的精囊是看不到的。 3. We know of the greatest strength is not elephant, Hercules, mechanical on the world, however seminal force. 我们知道世界上最大力气的不是大象、大力士、机械，而是种子的力量。 4. His seminal research in genetics revolutionized the treatment of cancer. 他在基因学上的重要研究改革了癌症的疗法。', '副词: seminally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slack', '[slæk]', 'adj.松弛的；懈怠的；萧条的 n.松弛的部分；松散；淡季 vt.使缓慢；疏忽 vi.变松弛；逃避工作', '1. A rope is slack if it hasn\'t been pulled tight. 如果一根绳子没有拉紧,那它是松的。 2. She was shocked at the slack discipline in the school. 对于学校松弛的纪律她感到震惊。 3. He is slack in answering letters. 他疏于回信。 4. After intense work in the summer, we are slack off now. 夏季紧张的工作过後，我们现在放松了。 5. There is too much slack in the rope. 这条绳子太松了。 6. The driver slacked up before reaching the crossroads. 司机在驶近十字路口时减慢了速度。 7. You should slack the rope before trying to untie the knot. 解结之前你应该先将绳索放松。', '副词: slackly 比较级: slacker 最高级: slackest 名词: slackness 过去式: slacked 过去分词: slacked 现在分词: slacking 第三人称单数: slacks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('versant', '[\'vɜːsənt]', 'n.山的斜坡；倾斜地带 adj.熟练的；通晓的；专心从事的', '1. Thank you for completing Versant for English. 这时您可以挂断电话,测试完成。 2. Thank you for completing the Versant for English test. 时,整个考试结束,你就可以挂上电话了。 3. Track advances in database technologies, standards, operating systems and use these to improve Versant products. 于是，性能开始下降，磁盘使用也有所增加。 4. Critical Job Elements -The ideal candidate will be versant in virtually all details of ITE and telecom product s...... ... 公司名称：锐德世系统设备商贸（上海）有限公司工作地点：其他发布时间：2009-6-12', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subterfuge', '[\'sʌbtərfjuːdʒ]', 'n.遁词；借口；托辞', '1. It was no subterfuge on her part. She just lied in her throat and we all realized toe grossness of her false utterance. 她所说的不是什么遁词。她简直是在撒弥天大谎。对她说假话之无耻程度，我们都是了解的。 2. This subterfuge went on for weeks. 这个借口持续了几个星期。 3. The Independents tried hard to swallow the wretched subterfuge. 独立党的党员们硬着头皮想把这一拙劣的托词信以为真。 4. Her claim to be a journalist was simply a subterfuge to get into the theatre without paying. 她自称是记者，这只是个看戏不买票的花招而已。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pushy', '[\'pʊʃi]', 'adj.<口>固执己见的；莽撞的；强求的', '1. He made himself unpopular by being so pushy. 他特别喜欢出风头，所以人缘不好。', '副词: pushily 比较级: pushier 最高级: pushiest 名词: pushiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('broil', '[brɔɪl]', 'vt.烤；使卷入 vi.烤；吵架 n.被烤过的食物；喧闹', '1. Some people like to broil prawns, but I prefer to boil them. 有些人喜欢烤明虾，可是我喜欢用煮的。 2. But just as we do not burn down our houses to broil our daily chops, there is no reason why the admirer of Marx should go through his historic circuitous detours and redundancies. 但是，就像我们不会烧毁我们的房子来烤我们每天的排骨，马克思的支持者没有理由要遵循他的历史迂回绕弯和冗余。 3. Some people like to broil prawns, but I prefer to boil them. 有些人喜欢烤明虾，可是我喜欢用煮的。 4. But just as we do not burn down our houses to broil our daily chops, there is no reason why the admirer of Marx should go through his historic circuitous detours and redundancies. 但是，就像我们不会烧毁我们的房子来烤我们每天的排骨，马克思的支持者没有理由要遵循他的历史迂回绕弯和冗余。', '过去式: broiled 过去分词: broiled 现在分词: broiling 第三人称单数: broils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insert', '[ɪn\'sɜːrt]', 'v.插入；嵌入 n.插入物', '1. She inserted the key into the lock. 她把钥匙插入锁中。 2. You can insert additional pages into that book. 你可以把附加的散页插入那本书里。 3. The next procedure is to insert the battery. 接下来的步骤是装进电池。 4. He tried to insert an advertisement in a newspaper. 他设法将广告刊登在报纸上。 5. She found an insert in the book. 她在那本书中找到了一个插入物。', '名词: inserter 过去式: inserted 过去分词: inserted 现在分词: inserting 第三人称单数: inserts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flannel', '[\'flænl]', 'n.法兰绒；法兰绒男裤；毛巾；花言巧语 v.说或写兜圈子的话', '1. The girl looked happy in her new flannel. 女孩穿着新的法兰绒衣服，看上去很高兴。 2. He bought a pair of cricket flannels yesterday. 昨天他买了一条法兰绒男裤。 3. You should dry your hands by a face flannel. 你应该用条毛巾擦干你的手。 4. He gave me a lot of flannel but I still don\'t know the answer to my question. 他说了很多恭维话,我仍然不知道怎样解决我的问题。 5. Stop flannelling and give a straight answer! 别再兜圈子了，直截了当地回答！', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prowess', '[\'praʊəs]', 'n.英勇；非凡的能力', '1. The soldiers sang a song of victory, describing their prowess in battle. 战士们唱起了歌颂他们英勇战斗的凯歌。 2. Your dedication and prowess serve as an example for all Blood Knights. 你的贡献和英勇可以作为一个所有血骑士的例子。 3. He shows great prowess at acting. 他显示了非凡的演技。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('metallurgy', '[\'metlɜːrdʒi]', 'n.冶金学；冶金术', '1. I graduated in metallurgy from Birmingham in 1985. 我于1985年在伯明翰大学修读完冶金学学位。 2. They are mainly used in metallurgy and conveyor systems. 它们主要应用在冶金和输送设备领域。', '形容词: metallurgic 副词: metallurgically 名词: metallurgist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fascinate', '[\'fæsɪneɪt]', 'vt.使 ... 入迷；吸引住 vi.有吸引力', '1. Anything to do with old myths and legends fascinates me. 任何与上古神话传说有关的东西都会使我着迷。 2. The place continues to fascinate visitors, cloaked in its mystery. 这个地方笼罩在神秘气氛下，继续使游览者着迷。 3. The students were fascinated by his ideas. 学生们都被他的思想吸引住了。 4. I watched her, fascianted. 我瞧着她,完全被她吸引住了。 5. It seems that the private lives of movie stars never fail to fascinate. 电影明星的私生活似乎总是使人津津乐道。', '过去式: fascinated 过去分词: fascinated 现在分词: fascinating 第三人称单数: fascinates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('percolate', '[\'pɜːrkəleɪt]', 'v.过滤；渗透；浸透', '1. I\'ll percolate some coffee for you. 我给你滤煮一些咖啡。 2. The rain will percolate through the soil. 雨水渗入土中。 3. The rumour percolated through the firm. 那谣言在公司里慢慢流传开来。 4. The resolution of type mappings will percolate up the chain until a match is found. 类型映射的解析将贯穿链直到找到一个匹配的。', '名词: percolation 过去式: percolated 过去分词: percolated 现在分词: percolating 第三人称单数: percolates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('opus', '[\'oʊpəs]', 'n.作品(尤指编号的乐曲)；艺术作品(尤指巨著)', '1. The violinist played his own opus No.16. 这位提琴家演奏他自己的第十六号乐曲。 2. His latest offering is a magnum opus on philosophy. 他的最新作品是一部关于哲学的巨著。', '名词复数: opera');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('declamation', '[ˌdeklə\'meɪʃn]', 'n.朗诵；雄辩', '1. Declamation is a traditional Chinese teaching method. 诵读教学是我国传统的语文教学方法。 2. His ecstatic declamation of the sonorous rhythm was enough for me. 他朗诵时的那种洪亮的节奏，那种心醉神迷，对我已足够了。 3. I see that I have lapsed into parable and ecstatic declamation. 我知道我在比喻和狂喜的辩论中造成了遗误。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slake', '[sleɪk]', 'vt.消除；满足；(石灰）熟化', '1. We had to slake ourselves with rainwater in the desert. 在沙漠中我们不得不用雨水解渴。 2. A menu will not satisfy your hunger, a formula will not slake your thirst. 菜单不可能填饱你的肚子，一套准则也不可能消除你的饥渴。 3. We returned to the barn and slake our thirst with tea 我们回到谷仓,饮茶解渴 4. I shall not seek a well to slake the burning thirst of my heart, 我不会找一口井来消除内心强烈的渴望，', '过去式: slaked 过去分词: slaked 现在分词: slaking 第三人称单数: slakes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cramp', '[kræmp]', 'n.抽筋；痉挛；夹钳 (复)cramps: 绞痛. v.束缚；使痉挛；用夹钳夹紧', '1. The swimmer got cramp in his legs and had to be helped out of the water. 游泳者两腿抽筋，不得不由他人救助出水。 2. I got a cramp while swimming and almost drowned. 我游泳时痉挛，差点溺水。 3. He held the pieces together with a cramp while the glue was drying. 他用夹子把这些碎片夹在一起，等着胶水变干。 4. Tighter trade restrictions might cramp economic growth. 较严格的贸易限制会妨碍经济的增长。', '过去式: cramped 过去分词: cramped 现在分词: cramping 第三人称单数: cramps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wheeze', '[wiːz]', 'v.喘息；呼哧呼哧地响 n.喘息声', '1. The old man managed to wheeze out a few words. 老人勉强地喘息着说出了几句话。 2. This old instrument can only wheeze out a tune now. 这只旧乐器现在只能呼哧呼哧地奏出一个曲调。 3. That truck was older than he was.It would wheeze and rattle down the road. 那卡车比他还要老，会发出呼哧呼哧的响然后沿路开下去。 4. He has a slight wheeze in his chest. 他呼吸时胸部发出轻微的响声。', '副词: wheezingly 名词: wheezer 过去式: wheezed 过去分词: wheezed 现在分词: wheezing 第三人称单数: wheezes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monstrous', '[\'mɑːnstrəs]', 'adj.怪异的；畸形的；巨大的', '1. It is a thing of monstrous beauty. 这东西真是体现了畸形美。 2. This is often seen in monstrous plants. 这在畸形的植物中是常常看到的。 3. The tree planted by the magician quickly grew to a monstrous height. 魔术师种下的树很快就长得极其高大。', '副词: monstrously 名词: monstrousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bereave', '[bɪ\'riːv]', 'vt.剥夺；使丧失', '1. The accident bereaved him of his wife and child. 车祸夺去了他的妻子和儿子的生命。 2. Indignation bereft him of speech. 他气愤得说不出话来。', '名词: bereavement 过去式: bereaved/bereft 过去分词: bereaved/bereft 现在分词: bereaving 第三人称单数: bereaves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('altruistic', '[ˌæltru\'ɪstɪk]', 'adj.利他主义的；无私的', '1. Mr Pickens\'s interest is not solely altruistic. 皮肯斯先生的盎然兴味并不单单是利他主义。 2. The company tried to project an altruistic image. 那个公司试图树立一种利他的形象。 3. Altruistic spirit should be cultivated by us vigorously. 利他的精神是我们应该努力培养的。 4. Happy people are more generous and altruistic. 快乐的人会更无私，更为别人着想。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('espionage', '[\'espiənɑːʒ]', 'n.间谍活动', '1. The man was charged with industrial espionage. 此人被控告从事工业间谍活动。 2. Bureau that runs espionage operations. 此人被控告从事工业间谍活动。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('available', '[ə\'veɪləbl]', 'adj.可利用的；可得到的；有空的；有效的；<贬>【政】有资格的，适合的', '1. Do you have a room available? 你们有空房间吗？ 2. The swimming pool is available only in summer. 这个游泳池只在夏天开放。 3. All sorts of lamps are available in that shop. 在那家商店可买到各式各样的灯具。 4. The Prime Minister was not available for comment. 首相无暇作出评论。', '副词: availably 名词: availability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mangle', '[\'mæŋɡl]', 'v.碾压；损坏；糟蹋；乱切 n.碾压机', '1. New shoes don\'t cut, blister, or mangle his feet. 新鞋子不会硌脚，起泡，或让脚受伤。 2. The symphony was dreadfully mangled. 那首交响乐曲给糟蹋得不成样子。 3. The plane is late; it is going to mangle your schedule for the day. 航班延误了，而它将影响你一整天的行程。', '名词: mangler 过去式: mangled 过去分词: mangled 现在分词: mangling 第三人称单数: mangles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('propeller', '[prə\'pelər]', 'n.螺旋桨；推进器 =propellor.', '1. A piece of string has twisted round the propeller. 一根绳子缠在螺旋桨上了。 2. The propeller doesn\'t work well. 推进器运转不灵。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brunt', '[brʌnt]', 'n.正面的冲击；主要的压力', '1. I seriously doubt their contentions will bear the brunt of close scrutiny. 我非常怀疑他们的观点能经受住仔细审查的冲击。 2. But other cities such as Beer Sheva and Ashdod have taken the brunt today. 对其他城市来说,如比尔谢瓦和阿什多德,今天就已首当其冲了。 3. She had to bear the brunt of the criticisms. 她不得不承受批评的压力。 4. These exhausted men carried the brunt of the war. 这些疲倦的士兵承受了战场上的主要压力。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resurgence', '[rɪ\'sɜːrdʒəns]', 'n.再起；复活；再现', '1. A resurgence of his grief swept over Nim. 悲痛又涌上了尼姆的心头。 2. Mr McCain\'s resurgence is extraordinary. 麦凯恩先生的东山再起令人惊叹。 3. Another was a resurgence of inflation. 另外一个是通胀再次抬头。 4. For investors, the dollar\'s resurgence is proving a tricky puzzle. 对投资者而言，美元反弹给他们出了一道颇费思量的谜题。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remonstrate', '[rɪ\'mɑːnstreɪt]', 'v.表示异议；抗议；劝诫', '1. He went to the manager to remonstrate. 他去向经理提出异议。 2. She opend her mouth as if to remonstrate. 她张了张嘴，仿佛是想劝两句。 3. Miss Temple seemed to remonstrate. 谭波尔小姐似乎在抗议。 4. A district official went to remonstrate with the landowners. 区里派了一个干部去对地主进行劝诫。', '形容词: remonstrative 副词: remonstratively 名词: remonstration 过去式: remonstrated 过去分词: remonstrated 现在分词: remonstrating 第三人称单数: remonstrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quay', '[kiː]', 'n.码头', '1. We put off from the quay. 我们驶离了码头。 2. We moored alongside the quay. 我们靠码头停泊。 3. A crowd was waiting on the quay. 有一群人在码头上等着。 4. The quay is big enough for 100 ships. 这个码头大得足以停靠100艘船。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deserted', '[dɪ\'zɜːrtɪd]', 'adj.废弃的；荒芜的；被遗弃的 动词desert的过去式和过去分词.', '1. A mysterious light came from the deserted house. 废弃的房屋里亮起了神秘的灯光。 2. On another occasion, he landed in a deserted car park. 还有一次，他在一个废弃的停车场着陆。 3. They walked across a deserted land. 他们穿过一片荒芜的土地。 4. With a sinking heart, I realized that I was on a deserted island. 带著一颗深沈的心，我明白自己是在个荒芜的岛上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evocative', '[ɪ\'vɑːkətɪv]', 'adj.引起回忆或唤起感情的', '1. That smell is evocative of school. 这种气味使人回想起学校来。 2. His talk was evocative of the bygone days. 他的谈话令人回忆起往昔的时日。', '副词: evocatively 名词: evocativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agenda', '[ə\'dʒendə]', 'n.议事日程', '1. This agenda will form the basis of our next meeting. 本议程将成为下次会议的中心议题。 2. Let\'s go on to the next item on the agenda. 我们讨论议程表上的下一项吧。 3. Let\'s thrash the matter over before putting it on the agenda. 我们先把这件事仔细研究一下，再把它列入议事日程。', '名词复数: agendas');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conflict', '[\'kɑːnflɪkt]', 'n.冲突；战斗；矛盾；斗争 vi.冲突；抵触；争执', '1. Both sides suffered heavy casualties in the border armed conflict. 在这次边界武装冲突中双方都遭到了重大伤亡。 2. He was wounded in the conflict. 他在战斗中负伤。 3. This is an irreconcilable conflict. 这是一个不可调和的矛盾。 4. He\'s got involved in a political conflict he can\'t extricate himself from. 他陷在一场政治斗争中不能脱身。 5. Your interests conflict with mine. 你的利益和我的冲突。', '形容词: conflictive 名词: confliction 过去式: conflicted 过去分词: conflicted 现在分词: conflicting 第三人称单数: conflicts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('summary', '[\'sʌməri]', 'n.摘要；总结 adj.简略的；概要的；即决的', '1. Please write me a summary of this report. 请替我写一份这份报告的摘要。 2. Your summary will need fleshing out before you present it. 你的总结需要增加一些具体材料再交出。 3. I went through by a summary method. 我成功运用了一个简易的方法。 4. He gave a summary report of the day\'s events. 他对一天的事件作了简要的报告。', '副词: summarily 名词: summariness 名词复数: summaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('giggle', '[\'ɡɪɡl]', 'v.咯咯地笑 n.咯咯笑；趣事', '1. Stop giggling, children; this is a serious matter. 孩子们，别傻笑了，这是严肃的事情。 2. The children couldn\'t stop giggling at the teacher\'s high-pitched voice. 教师的嗓音很高，孩子们都不禁咯咯地笑起来。 3. There was a giggle from the back of the class. 从教室后面传来咯咯的笑声。 4. What a giggle! 多有意思的玩意儿！', '形容词: giggly 副词: gigglingly 名词: giggler 过去式: giggled 过去分词: giggled 现在分词: giggling 第三人称单数: giggles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fluctuate', '[\'flʌktʃueɪt]', 'vi.波动；动摇；起伏 vt.使动摇', '1. Fruit prices fluctuate with the seasons. 水果价格随着季节波动。 2. Some investors panic when stock prices fluctuate wildly. 当股票价格大幅波动时,一些投资者便开始恐慌起来。 3. While the psychological unbalance may fluctuate the individual\'s original philosophy and regular act tendency which make conditions for the naissance of aberrance. 而心理的失衡极大地动摇了个体原有的人生观和行为定势 ,为越轨行为的产生创造了条件。 4. Both the light and radio outputs fluctuate markedly. 光和无线电的输出都引人注目地起伏变化。', '形容词: fluctuant 名词: fluctuation 过去式: fluctuated 过去分词: fluctuated 现在分词: fluctuating 第三人称单数: fluctuates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('critique', '[krɪ\'tiːk]', 'n.批评；批评法；评论', '1. He plays down Mr. Brown\'s idea in his critique. 他在自己的评论中大肆批评布朗先生的想法。 2. The book presents a critique of the Government\'s policies. 该书对政府的政策作出了批评性的分析. 3. Most of this critique is familiar enough. 许多此类的批评已经相当为大家熟悉。 4. They all joined in a very spirited critique upon the party. 她们凑在一起对那伙人发表了一通痛快淋漓的批评。', '过去式: critiqued 过去分词: critiqued 现在分词: critiquing 第三人称单数: critiques');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clasp', '[klæsp]', 'n.扣子；钩；紧握；握手 v.扣紧；紧握；密切合作', '1. The button won\'t clasp. 扣子扣不上。', '过去式: clasped 过去分词: clasped 现在分词: clasping 第三人称单数: clasps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bounteous', '[\'baʊntiəs]', 'adj.慷慨的；宽大的；宽裕的', '1. God\'s bounteous blessings. 上帝的慷慨赐福。 2. We are grateful to you for your bounteous gifts. 对您给予的丰厚礼物，我们不胜感激。', '副词: bounteously 名词: bounteousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bestial', '[\'bestʃəl]', 'adj.残忍的；野蛮的；缺乏智慧的', '1. The Roman gladiatorial contests were bestial amusements. 罗马角斗是野蛮的娱乐', '副词: bestially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('queer', '[kwɪr]', 'adj.古怪的；奇怪的；可疑的；<俚>同性恋的 n.<俚>同性恋者 vt.把...弄糟；使陷入不利', '1. There is something queer about him. 他有些古怪。 2. Her queer way of dressing attracted the attention of the passerby. 她古怪的着装方式引起了过路人的注意。 3. I have a queer dream last night. 我昨晚做了一个奇怪的梦。 4. I heard some very queer noises in the garden. 我听到花园里有些可疑的声音。 5. His blunder would certainly queer his chances of promotion. 他犯的大错肯定会毁了他晋升的机会。', '形容词: queerish 副词: queerly 比较级: queerer 最高级: queerest 名词: queerness 过去式: queered 过去分词: queered 现在分词: queering 第三人称单数: queers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revelation', '[ˌrevə\'leɪʃn]', 'n.揭露；泄露；发觉；启示', '1. The revelation of his past lead to his resignation. 对他过去的揭露导致了他的辞职。 2. Have you read the ex-minister\'s amazing revelations in the newspaper? 你看了前任部长在报上揭露的那些惊人的事实没有？ 3. The revelation of the plot of the traitors caused their capture. 反叛者阴谋的泄露使他们被捕。 4. Her true nature was a revelation to me. 她的真实性格对我是一个新发现。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scandal', '[\'skændl]', 'n.丑闻；反感；耻辱；中伤', '1. The scandal caused tempests in the newspaper. 那件丑闻在报纸上引起阵阵风波。 2. The villagers knew about the scandal. 村子里的居民知道这件丑事。 3. This scandal may topple the government. 这桩丑闻有可能使政府垮台。 4. The President is at the center of a recent scandal over revelation about his financial interests. 总统因近来被揭露涉嫌金融权益问题而成为丑闻的主角。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contumely', '[\'kɒntjʊməlɪ]', 'n.无礼；傲慢；侮辱', '1. It were better to have no opinion of God at all, than such an opinion, as is unworthy of him: for the one is unbelief, the other is contumely and certainly superstition is the reproach of the deity. 本性经常被隐藏，有时候它可以被战胜，但绝不会泯灭。若我们强压本性，结果只能是我们变得暴戾；若是我们尊重社会规则和舆论，本性则会变得不那么举重若轻了； 2. Th\'oppressor\'s wrong, the proud man\'s contumely, 压迫者的凌虐，狂傲者的侮慢， 3. The oppressor\'s wrong, the proud man\'s contumely, 忍受压迫者虐待、傲慢者凌辱， 4. Of an impulsive and passionate nature, she had fortified herself to encounter the stings and venomous stabs of public contumely, wreaking itself in every variety of insult; 她本是一个充满热情、容易冲动的人，此时她已使自己坚强起来，以面对用形形色色的侮辱来发泄的公愤的毒刺和利刃；', '形容词: contumelious 副词: contumeliously 名词复数: contumelies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('auxiliary', '[ɔːɡ\'zɪliəri]', 'n.助动词；辅助物；帮助者 adj.辅助的；附加的', '1. In Chinese, the classification of the auxiliary verb and the adverb always have dispute. 摘要汉语中助动词和副词的分类一直有争议。 2. We have an auxiliary generator in case of power cuts. 我们有一台万一断电时使用的备用发电机。 3. She is an auxiliary nurse. 她是一名助理护士。', '名词复数: auxiliaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('allocate', '[\'æləkeɪt]', 'vt.分派；分配；分配额', '1. The system was unable to allocate a new data object. 系统无法分派新的数据对象。 2. Allocate rations for a week - long campingtrip. 分配一星期外出野营的定额。 3. You must allocate the money carefully. 你们必须谨慎地分配钱。', '形容词: allocable 名词: allocation 过去式: allocated 过去分词: allocated 现在分词: allocating 第三人称单数: allocates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transmute', '[trænz\'mjuːt]', 'v.使 ... 变形', '1. It is possible to transmute one form of energy into another. 把某种形态的能量改变成另一形态的能量是可能的。 2. In former times it was thought that ordinary metal could be transmuted into gold. 古时认为一般金属能变成黄金。', '形容词: transmutable 副词: transmutably 名词: transmutability 过去式: transmuted 过去分词: transmuted 现在分词: transmuting 第三人称单数: transmutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coercion', '[koʊ\'ɜːrʒn]', 'n.强迫；威压；高压政治', '1. The superpowers got what they wanted by coercion. 超级大国靠强迫手段得到了他们想要的东西。 2. In its work a residents committee shall adopt a democratic approach and shall not resort to coercion or commandism. 居民委员会进行工作，应当采取民主的方法，不得强迫命令。 3. The surprisingly big vote for the Maoists probably owed something to coercion and intimidation. 毛派最终能凭多票当选，也许与他们的高压政治与胁迫力量有某些关系。', '形容词: coercionary');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fustian', '[\'fʌstʃən]', 'adj.浮夸的；麻纱布制的 n.空洞的话；无意义的高调；麻纱布织物', '1. They flounder about between fustian in expression, and bathos in sentiment(William Hazlitt. 他们陷入在口头上夸夸其谈，在感情上矫柔造作的泥潭之中（威廉 哈兹里特）。 2. \"They flounder about between fustian in expression, and bathos in sentiment\" (William Hazlitt). “他们陷入在口头上夸夸其谈，在感情上矫柔造作的泥潭之中” （威廉·哈兹里特）。 3. They flounder about between fustian in expression,and bathos in sentiment(William Hazlitt. 他们陷入在口头上夸夸其谈，在感情上矫柔造作的泥潭之中（威廉·哈兹里特）。 4. A waistcoat of broadcloth or of fustian is alike to an aching heart, and we laugh no merrier on velvet cushions than we did on wooden chairs. 对伤心之人来说，无论是黑色绸料还是棉布做的马甲都别无二致。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('synthesis', '[\'sɪnθəsɪs]', 'n.合成；综合；综合分析', '1. The ribosome is the site of protein synthesis. 核糖体是合成蛋白质的地方。 2. His work is a synthesis of several ideas. 他的作品是由几种构想综合而成的。 3. Our beliefs are a synthesis of Eastern and Western religions. 我们的信仰是东西方宗教的综合体。 4. We made a synthesis of their studies. 我们综合分析了他们的研究报告。', '名词: synthesist 名词复数: syntheses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('volatile', '[\'vɑːlətl]', 'adj.不稳定的；反复无常的；易挥发的 n.挥发物', '1. The political situation is becoming more volatile. 政局变得更加动荡不定。 2. Food and fuel prices are very volatile in a war situation. 在战争环境下,食物和燃料的价格都很不稳定。 3. He has a highly volatile personality. 他有着反复无常的个性。 4. He had a rather volatile temper and can\'t have been easy to live with. 他脾气暴躁,很难相处。', '名词: volatility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unremitting', '[ˌʌnrɪ\'mɪtɪŋ]', 'adj.不懈的；不间断的；坚忍的', '1. Her love for Chinese dance led to her unremitting efforts. 这爱促使她在创作中不懈地追求中国舞蹈的神韵， 2. Success is attainable through unremitting hard work. 经过不间断的努力工作，成功是可达成的。 3. He represented a people who had prevailed by unremitting tenacity. 他代表一个以坚韧不拔的意志取胜的民族。', '副词: unremittingly 名词: unremittingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pedal', '[\'pedl]', 'n.踏板；乐器的脚踏键 v.用脚踏动；踩踏板', '1. The pedal of a cycle is attached to a crank. 自行车的踏板与曲柄相连。 2. He pushed hard on the brake pedal to avoid a collision. 他使劲踩下煞车踏板以避免撞车。 3. He had to pedal hard to get up the hill. 他得用力踩动，以便上山。 4. I saw him pedal to school every morning. 我看到他每天早晨骑自行车上学。', '过去式: pedaled/pedalled 过去分词: pedaled/pedalled 现在分词: pedaling/pedalling 第三人称单数: pedals/pedals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deportation', '[ˌdiːpɔː\'teɪʃn]', 'n.驱逐；驱逐出境；放逐', '1. The government issued a deportation order against the four men. 政府发出了对那4名男子的驱逐令。 2. Years ago convicted criminals in England could face deportation to Australia. 很多年以前，英国已定罪的犯人可能被驱逐到澳大利亚。 3. The man was sentenced to deportation for robbery. 这个男人因犯盗窃罪被驱逐出境。 4. Deportation of criminals from England to Australia was once common. 把犯人从英国放逐到澳大利亚的作法在过去曾一度盛行。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vagabond', '[\'væɡəbɑːnd]', 'n.流浪汉；无业游民 adj.流浪的；居无定所的', '1. The vagabond began to regret his waste of time. 这个流浪汉开始后悔他虚度了光阴。 2. He leads a vagabond life. 他过着流浪生活。', '名词: vagabondage 过去式: vagabonded 过去分词: vagabonded 现在分词: vagabonding 第三人称单数: vagabonds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tendentious', '[ten\'denʃəs]', 'adj.有目的的；有倾向的；有偏见的 =tendencious.', '1. Such tendentious statements are likely to provoke strong opposition. 这种有倾向性的说法可能招致强烈的反对。 2. His statement was frankly tendentious. 他的发言是有倾向性的。 3. Yet these arguments are tendentious. 可这都是些片面的论调。', '副词: tendentiously 名词: tendentiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crown', '[kraʊn]', 'n.王冠；王权；花冠；顶点；齿冠；克朗（丹麦、瑞典、捷克等国的货币单位） vt.加冕；使 ... 成王；居 ... 之顶；镶齿冠；使圆满；<口>打…的头部', '1. The crown was enchased with gold and silver. 这顶王冠上镶嵌着金和银。 2. She refused the crown. 她拒不接受王位。 3. I know she promised him a lilac crown. 我知道,她曾允诺他一顶紫丁香的花冠。 4. He cracked his crown on a microphone during a performance. 他在一次表演中在麦克风上把齿冠打破了。 5. They wanted to crown Caesar king . 他们想立凯撒为王。', '过去式: crowned 过去分词: crowned 现在分词: crowning 第三人称单数: crowns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kernel', '[\'kɜːrnl]', 'n.核心；仁；中心；精髓', '1. We must get at the kernel of the problem. 我们必须抓住问题的核心。 2. Are kernels of apricots edible? 杏仁能吃吗？ 3. The monitoring center is the kernel part of a home-oriented telemonitoring system.Its performance has influence on the tele-monitoring system definitively. 本文开发的中心监护站软件是远程家庭多生理参数监护系统的重要组成部分，其性能直接关系到远程监护系统的总体性能。 4. Mathematical thought and method is the kernel of mathematical knowledge. 数学思想方法是数学知识的精髓。', '形容词: kerneled');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jest', '[dʒest]', 'n.说笑；玩笑 v.开玩笑', '1. They made a jest of his ignorance. 他们笑话他无知。 2. He spoke it in a kind of jest, but it was with such an awkward smile. 他用一种说笑的口吻说着，但是说时带着那么不自然的微笑。 3. I said in jest I would marry Jim. 我开玩笑说要嫁给吉姆。 4. It began as a jest and ended as a tragedy. 事情以玩笑开始，以悲剧告终。 5. He is not a man to jest with. 他是个不能开玩笑的人。', '副词: jestingly 过去式: jested 过去分词: jested 现在分词: jesting 第三人称单数: jests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mackintosh', '[\'mækɪntɑːʃ]', 'n.橡皮布；橡皮布防水衣；雨衣 同macintosh.', '1. It can prolong the useful time of mackintosh. 它可延长橡皮布的使用寿命。 2. Alexander took off his black mackintosh. 亚历山大脱下黑色的雨衣。 3. Your mackintosh looks better belted. 你的雨衣系上带子更好看。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('warehouse', '[\'werhaʊs]', 'n.仓库 vt.存入仓库', '1. They stored their goods in a warehouse. 他们把货物储存在一个仓库里。 2. They operate three factories and a huge warehouse. 他们经营三家工厂和一个大仓库。 3. If necessary, please warehouse the goods. 如有必要，请将该货存入仓库。', '名词: warehouser 过去式: warehoused 过去分词: warehoused 现在分词: warehousing 第三人称单数: warehouses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('depression', '[dɪ\'preʃn]', 'n.沮丧；萧条', '1. He suffers from acute depression. 他患有严重的抑郁症。 2. He committed suicide during a fit of depression. 他一时想不开，自杀了。 3. Many people were idle during the depression. 在那萧条时期，很多人都无事可做。 4. Roughly speaking, I think we are heading for the depression. 大体说来,我认为我们正走向萧条。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('raisin', '[\'reɪzn]', 'n.葡萄干', '1. I\'d like to buy some raisin cookies, please. 我要买些葡萄干夹心点心。 2. Michael Phelps can turn a grape into a raisin just by looking at it. 菲尔普斯只要盯着葡萄看一看就能把葡萄烘成葡萄干！', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('majestic', '[mə\'dʒestɪk]', 'adj.宏伟的；高贵的；壮丽的', '1. The majestic ring corridor of engraved posts is spectacular and eye-catching. 宏伟的雕柱环形走廊，凛然风范，蔚然壮观，今人瞩目。 2. Majestic trees owe a sizeable chunk of their sky-high stature to tiny birds. 宏伟的大树能够与天齐高，多亏了身材娇小的鸟儿们帮了大忙。 3. The church of Notre-Dame de Paris is still no doubt, a majestic and sublime edifice. 毫无疑问，巴黎圣母院至今仍然是雄伟壮丽的建筑。 4. Construction of the Great Wall has a long history of the majestic immensity of the world rare miracle. 施工长城具有悠久的历史和壮丽的巨大的世界罕见的奇迹。', '副词: majestically 异体字: majestical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tame', '[teɪm]', 'adj.驯服的；柔顺的；乏味的 vt.驯养；使驯服；压制 vi.变得驯服', '1. A boy was playing with a tame snake. 一个男孩在玩一条驯服了的蛇。 2. The animals we find in the zoo are quite tame. 我们在动物园看到的动物都很驯服。 3. It\'s incredible that the tame wolf is as mild as a lamb. 令人难以置信的是驯服的狼温和如羊。 4. She is too tame. 她太柔顺了。 5. The Asian elephant can be tamed and trained. 亚洲象可以被驯养和训练。 6. That tiger is impossible to tame. 那只老虎难以驯服。', '形容词: tamable 副词: tamely 比较级: tamer 最高级: tamest 名词: tameness 过去式: tamed 过去分词: tamed 现在分词: taming 第三人称单数: tames');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('want', '[wɑːnt]', 'v.要；想要；通缉 n.缺乏；贫穷；需求品', '1. I want large ones, not small ones. 我要大的, 不要小的。 2. He wants me to go with him. 他希望我同他一起去。 3. What they talked about is what we want to know. 他们谈论什么是我们所想要知道的事。 4. He is wanted by the police. 警察正通缉他。 5. The plants died from want of water. 这些植物因缺水而死。', '形容词: wantless 名词: wanter 过去式: wanted 过去分词: wanted 现在分词: wanting 第三人称单数: wants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rendering', '[\'rendərɪŋ]', 'n.翻译；艺术表现；透视图；抹灰底层 动词render的现在分词和动名词形式.', '1. Rendering poetry into other languages is difficult. 翻译诗歌是很困难的。 2. Have you heard his rendering of Beethoven? 你听过他演奏的贝多芬的曲子吗? 3. This type of industrial design rendering is more about the object than the art. 这种工业设计类的效果图更多的关注物体，而不是艺术。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('temerity', '[tə\'merəti]', 'n.鲁莽；大胆', '1. Instead the French president\'s language betrays temerity. 相反，这位法国总统的言语表露出他的鲁莽。 2. Conducting the premiere of a symphony without a rehearsal requires temerity. 不排练而直接指挥一部交响乐的首次公演是鲁莽的。 3. He had the temerity to call me a liar. 他竟胆敢说我撒谎。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anecdote', '[\'ænɪkdoʊt]', 'n.轶事；奇闻', '1. He departs from the text to tell an anecdote. 他没讲课文而讲了一段轶事。 2. He preceded his lecture with a humorous anecdote. 他以一个幽默的轶事开始他的演说 3. He told me some anecdotes about our English teacher. 他告诉我几个关于英语老师的掌故。 4. It had never been more than a family anecdote. 那不过是个家庭趣谈罢了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('salubrious', '[sə\'luːbriəs]', 'adj.有益健康的；宜人的', '1. They live in a very salubrious area. 他们住在一个非常有益健康的地区。 2. The surroundings were not very salubrious. 环境不很有益健康。 3. We had to move to a house in a less salubrious area. 我们不得不搬到一座周围环境较为逊色的房子。 4. Kennington is a not particularly salubrious part of London. 肯尼顿是伦敦一个不起眼的小地方。', '副词: salubriously 名词: salubriousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('terminus', '[\'tɜːrmɪnəs]', 'n.终点；终点站；界限；界标', '1. Casablanca was the terminus of a long, rickety railway line. 卡莎布兰卡是一长而软弱的铁路线的终点。 2. I get on at the terminus. 我从终点站上车。 3. What time does the train reach the terminus? 火车什么时间到达终点站? 4. The bus goes on and on and reaches the terminus. 汽车不断地行使,到达了终点站。', '名词复数: terminuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proposition', '[ˌprɑːpə\'zɪʃn]', 'n.提议；事业；命题 vt.向 ... 调情', '1. His proposition is good in theory but cannot be put into practice. 他的建议在理论上可以，但不能付诸实现。 2. This is the inverse of his earlier proposition. 这和他早些时候提的建议截然相反。 3. This is not money-making proposition. 这不是个赚钱的事业。 4. Tunnelling under the English Channel is a big proposition. 在英吉利海峡海底凿隧道是一个大问题。 5. She was propositioned several times in the course of the evening. 整个晚上有人几次向她提出非分要求。', '形容词: propositional 副词: propositionally 过去式: propositioned 过去分词: propositioned 现在分词: propositioning 第三人称单数: propositions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abut', '[ə\'bʌt]', 'v.邻接；毗连', '1. His land abuts on mine. 他的土地和我的土地相毗连。 2. Can\'t. I have to go and see a man abut a horse, Ask you mother to listen to you. 我不能，我有点事得出去，请你妈妈听你弹吧。', '名词: abutter 过去式: abutted 过去分词: abutted 现在分词: abutting 第三人称单数: abuts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('definitive', '[dɪ\'fɪnətɪv]', 'adj.权威性的；明确的；确定的；决定性的 n.限定词', '1. Her book is the definitive work on Milton. 她的书是论述米尔顿的权威著作. 2. She\'s written the definitive history of Vienna. 她写下了权威性的维也纳历史。 3. Clearer fossil may provide a definitive answer. 如果能发现更清晰的化石,那么可能提供明确的答案。 4. There is no definitive answer to this. 没有什么确定的答案。', '副词: definitively 名词: definitiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('narcissist', '[nɑː\'sɪsɪst]', 'n.自我陶醉者', '1. See, I told you. I\'m married to a narcissist. 知道了吧我早就告诉过你我嫁了个自恋狂。 2. Narcissist plus histrionic equals therapy time. 自恋狂+戏剧人格=“该吃药了！” 3. The narcissist will win the tug-of-war. 自恋者会赢得拔河。 4. It\'s highly likely you\'re dealing with a narcissist. 很有可能你在应对的是一位自恋者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pathetic', '[pə\'θetɪk]', 'adj.可怜的；不足的；感伤的；悲哀的', '1. We saw the pathetic sight of starving children. 我们看到挨饿的儿童悲惨可怜的样子。 2. She dances well, but as a singer, she is pathetic. 她跳舞跳得好，但唱歌就差劲了。 3. God! The freshmen are pathetic this year! 天啊！今年的大一新生什么也不懂！ 4. I never heard anything that sounded so pathetic. 我从未听说过如此悲伤的事了。', '副词: pathetically 异体字: pathetical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enormous', '[ɪ\'nɔːrməs]', 'adj.巨大的；庞大的', '1. Long ago enormous animals lived on the earth. 很久以前，地球上生活着巨大的动物。 2. She stood alone on the enormous stage. 她孤零零地站在巨大的舞台上。 3. They overlooked the enormous risks involved. 他们忽略了暗含的巨大危险。 4. The sight of such an enormous crowd astonished us. 看到如此庞大的人群我惊讶万分。', '副词: enormously 名词: enormousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disfranchise', '[ˌdɪs\'fræntʃaɪz]', 'vt. 剥夺 ... 权力(尤指选举权)', '1. But if she is really driven from pillar to post,we can\'t disfranchise people\'s right of life for moral. 但是如果她真的走投无路了，那我们也不能因为道德去剥夺别人生存的权利。 2. to disfranchise someone of a privilege 剥夺某人的特权 3. to disfranchise someone of the right to vote 剥夺某人选举权 4. disfranchise; disfranchisement; curtail sb. of his citizenship 褫夺公民权', '名词: disfranchisement 过去式: disfranchised 过去分词: disfranchised 现在分词: disfranchising 第三人称单数: disfranchises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heresy', '[\'herəsi]', 'n.异端；异教；反面观点', '1. The book has a tincture of heresy. 这本书稍有异端意味。 2. He was sentenced to be guilty of heresy. 他被判犯有异端罪。 3. At this defiant heresy, Mammy\'s brow lowered with indignation. 听了这番不伦不类的犟话，嬷嬷烦恼得皱紧了眉头。 4. Every truth has geological strata,and you can\'t have an orthodoxy without a heresy. 每个真理都是有层次的，这世界没有错就没有对。', '名词复数: heresies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inhibitor', '[ɪn\'hɪbɪtər]', 'n.抑制物；约束者', '1. Argatroban is a new direct thrombin inhibitor. 阿加曲班是一种新型的直接凝血酶抑制药。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cavalier', '[ˌkævə\'lɪr]', 'n.骑士；武士 adj.傲慢的；满不在乎的；无忧无虑的', '1. The cavalier defeated all the antagonists. 那位骑士打败了所有的敌手。 2. The cavaliers rushed into the palace to protect the king. 武士们冲进宫里保护国王。 3. People were often irritated by his cavalier attitude toward them. 人们常常被他目空一切的态度弄得恼火。 4. But generally the industry adopted a rather cavalier attitude to click fraud. 但通常业界对点击欺诈都采取了有点轻视的态度。', '副词: cavalierly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bullish', '[\'bʊlɪʃ]', 'adj.似牡牛的；看涨的；上扬的；乐观的', '1. There was a bullish trend in the market. 市场行情有上涨趋势。 2. They made hay over the bullish stock market . 利用股票牛市,他们赚了一笔。 3. He is very bullish about the prospects of his business. 他对自己企业的前景非常乐观。 4. Trichet sounded very bullish on euro-zone economy (sic). 特里谢听起来对欧元区经济信心满怀。', '副词: bullishly 名词: bullishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muddy', '[\'mʌdi]', 'adj.泥泞的；浑浊的；糊涂的 v.使沾上烂泥；使 ... 混浊；使迷惑', '1. It\'s muddy underfoot. 地上很泥泞。 2. The country roads were muddy and full of furrows left by farm carts. 乡间道路泥泞不堪，布满了牛车压出的车辙。 3. The police dredged up the parcel from the muddy river. 警方从浑浊的河水中捞出包裹。 4. There is a muddy expression in his face. 他脸上有一种糊涂的表情。 5. Don\'t muddy your new shoes. 别把泥巴沾到新鞋子上面去。', '副词: muddily 比较级: muddier 最高级: muddiest 名词: muddiness 过去式: muddied 过去分词: muddied 现在分词: muddying 第三人称单数: muddies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retouch', '[ˌriː\'tʌtʃ]', 'v.润饰；修整 n.润饰；修整', '1. The fact that fragrance marketers retouch the dip tube out of the bottle image in their advertising is a testament to the problem. 事实上，香水行销润饰倾角管出了瓶子的形象在他们的广告是一个证明问题。 2. The fact that fragrance marketers retouch the dip tube out of the bottle image in their advertising is a testament to the problem. 事实上，香水行销润饰倾角管出了瓶子的形象在他们的广告是一个证明问题。', '名词: retoucher 过去式: retouched 过去分词: retouched 现在分词: retouching 第三人称单数: retouches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('iridescent', '[ˌɪrɪ\'desnt]', 'adj.彩虹色的；闪光的', '1. The iridescent bubbles were beautiful. 这些闪着彩虹般颜色的大气泡很美。 2. Male peacocks display their iridescent feathers for prospective female mates. 雄性孔雀为了吸引雌性伴侣而展现了他们彩虹色的羽毛。', '副词: iridescently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('divert', '[daɪ\'vɜːrt]', 'v.转移；娱乐', '1. A loud noise diverted my attention. 一阵喧闹声转移了我们的注意力。 2. They diverted the river to supply water to the town. 他们使河流改道以便向城市供水。 3. She dished up the anti-pollution business to divert the attention of the public. 她把防止污染的事情说得十分重要,以便转移公众的注意。 4. I found a computer game to divert the children. 我发现了一种供孩子娱乐的电脑游戏。', '副词: divertingly 名词: diverter 过去式: diverted 过去分词: diverted 现在分词: diverting 第三人称单数: diverts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('literal', '[\'lɪtərəl]', 'adj.逐字的；字面上的；文字的 n.错误字体', '1. A literal translation is not always the closest to the original meaning. 逐字翻译不一定最接近原义。 2. He made a literal interpretation. 他逐字解释。 3. There had been a literal truth in his declaration. 从字面上看，他刚才说的话并不假。 4. We can get the answer by literal interpretation. 我们单从字面上就可以找到答案.', '名词: literalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sliver', '[\'slɪvər]', 'n.裂片；细长条；梳棉 v.(使)成小片；剖成长条', '1. A sliver of glass nicked my hand. 一片玻璃扎了我的手。 2. Cut me just a small sliver of cheese. 给我切一小片干酪吧。 3. The sliver must therefore be attenuated. 因此，必须要拉细条子。 4. Eight slivers are drawn together to produce the drawn sliver. 八根梳棉条并合在一起被牵伸成熟条。 5. The glass slivered when it fell. 玻璃杯掉在地上摔碎了。', '过去式: slivered 过去分词: slivered 现在分词: slivering 第三人称单数: slivers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jaunt', '[dʒɔːnt]', 'n.远足 vi.短程旅游', '1. They are off for a day\'s jaunt to the beach. 他们出去到海边玩一天。 2. They jaunt about quite a lot, especially during the summer. 他们常常到处闲逛，夏天更是如此。', '过去式: jaunted 过去分词: jaunted 现在分词: jaunting 第三人称单数: jaunts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impoverish', '[ɪm\'pɑːvərɪʃ]', 'vt.使贫困；使贫瘠；使枯竭', '1. America still has enough credibility to charter a more profitable path that would impoverish its creditors slowly. 美国尚有足够的信用来让其得以选择一条更加有利可图的路径使它的债权人们渐渐贫困枯竭。', '名词: impoverishment 过去式: impoverished 过去分词: impoverished 现在分词: impoverishing 第三人称单数: impoverishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('destructible', '[dɪ\'strʌktəbəl]', 'adj.可破坏的', '1. Support beams in the mines are now destructible. 矿场里的横梁可以损坏？ 2. Thought that I would self destruct. 你原以为没有你我会自毁。 3. Siege weapons and destructible buildings will be added to PvP-PVP. 里将增加攻城武器和大面积杀伤性建筑。 4. Mr Cheney is proving no more destructible than Lord Voldemort. 切尼证明自己和伏地魔一样难被打倒。', '名词: destructibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fusty', '[\'fʌsti]', 'adj.旧式的；陈腐的；发霉的', '1. Under Mr.Blair, fusty old Britain has become an international exemplar of openness. 在布莱尔先生领导下，古板陈腐的英国已经成为国际上对外开放的榜样。 2. This blanket smells a bit fusty. 这毯子有点儿发霉的味儿。', '副词: fustily 比较级: fustier 最高级: fustiest 名词: fustiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spank', '[spæŋk]', 'vt.掴（屁股） vi.轻快地移动 n.拍击', '1. Behave yourself, or I\'ll spank you. 放规矩点，否则我会揍你的。 2. Say one more word, and I will spank you. 再多说一个字,那么我就打你屁股。 3. If I was naughty, they would spank me. 我如果调皮捣蛋的话，他们就会打我屁股， 4. The ship is spanking along. 船在平稳前进。 5. The boy got a sound spanking. 那男孩的屁股着实挨了一顿巴掌。', '过去式: spanked 过去分词: spanked 现在分词: spanking 第三人称单数: spanks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('burnish', '[\'bɜːrnɪʃ]', 'v.磨光；使光亮 n.光泽；抛光', '1. He is burnishing the knife. 他正在磨刀。 2. The copper has been burnished. 铜已被抛光。 3. Such bipartisanship will do something to burnish his reputation as a reformer. 这样的两党合作将对凸显作为改革者的声誉有益。 4. Scagliola diaphaneity is bad, and without burnish. 人造大理石透明度不好，而且没有光泽。', '名词: burnisher 过去式: burnished 过去分词: burnished 现在分词: burnishing 第三人称单数: burnishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contented', '[kən\'tentɪd]', 'adj.满足的；心安的 动词content的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. A contented person does not create progress. 满足的人不能进步。 2. The lady looked at me with a contented smile. 那位夫人带着满意的微笑看着我。 3. By following the steps, mothers should be able to lead a fulfilling and contented life. 按照这些步骤去做,妈妈们一定会感到日子充实、心情惬意。', '副词: contentedly 名词: contentedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reticent', '[\'retɪsnt]', 'adj.寡言少语的；沉默的；谨慎的；讳莫如深的', '1. He is a reticent and modest man. 他是个寡言少语、谦虚谨慎的人。 2. No one could elicit any response out of the reticent little girl. 没有人能从那个沉默的小女孩身上套出任何回答。 3. He was reticent about his opinion. 他有保留意见。 4. He seems unduly reticent on the subject of his past. 他似乎对他过去的事情讳莫如深。', '副词: reticently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('piebald', '[\'paɪbɔːld]', 'adj.花斑的；杂色的；杂种的 n.花斑马', '1. \"Piebald\" doesn\'t rhyme with \"ribald\". piebald和ribald不押韵。 2. Patchy in color;splotched or piebald. 杂色的；有斑纹的，花斑的 3. A piebald animal,especially a horse. 花斑马有花斑的动物，尤指马 4. A piebald animal, especially a horse. 花斑马有花斑的动物，尤指马', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disposed', '[dɪ\'spoʊzd]', 'adj.愿意的；想干的；有 ... 倾向的 动词dispose的过去式和过去分词', '1. I am not disposed to help that lazy fellow . 我不愿意帮助那个懒惰的人。 2. He seemed disposed to enter into conversation with him. 他看起来似乎愿意和他交谈。 3. I don\'t feel disposed to help you. 我不想帮你的忙。 4. I\'m not disposed to argue with him. 我不想和他争论。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exonerate', '[ɪɡ\'zɑːnəreɪt]', 'vt.确定无罪；免除责任', '1. Nothing can exonerate her from that. 任何解释都难辞其咎。 2. CFTC study last year appeared to exonerate them. CFTC去年的一个研究报告赦免了他们。 3. It pioneered the use of DNA to pinpoint or to exonerate suspects. 在FBI在确证罪犯过程中最早使用了基因技术。 4. There is no reason to exonerate him from the ordinary duties of a citizen. 没有理由免除他做公民应尽的义务。', '形容词: exonerative 名词: exoneration 过去式: exonerated 过去分词: exonerated 现在分词: exonerating 第三人称单数: exonerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tether', '[\'teðər]', 'n.系绳；系链；界限；（能力、财力、忍耐等的）极限 v.练栓；拘束', '1. The astronauts walked in outer space without a tether. 宇航员在没有系绳的情况下进行太空行走。 2. This group is composed of men who had never associated themselves with rickshaws but were forced to take up the trade, because they have reached the end of their tether. 这一些是以前决没想到自己能与洋车发生关系，而到了生和死的界限已经不甚分明，才抄起车把来的。', '过去式: tethered 过去分词: tethered 现在分词: tethering 第三人称单数: tethers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('larder', '[\'lɑːrdər]', 'n.食品室；食物贮藏室', '1. The cat somehow insinuated itself into the larder. 那只猫悄悄地溜进食品室。 2. There was a kitchen, a parlour, a pantry, and a larder. 那里有一个厨房、一个客厅，一个食品储藏室和一个食物冷储室。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indefatigable', '[ˌɪndɪ\'fætɪɡəbl]', 'adj.不知疲倦的；不屈不挠的', '1. The indefatigable bell now sounded for the fourth time. 那不知疲倦的钟声如今敲第四遍了。 2. He was indefatigable in his lectures on the aesthetics of love. 在讲授关于爱情的美学时，他是不知疲倦的。 3. Encouraged by this discovery, Edmond determined to assist the indefatigable laborer. 在这个发现的鼓舞之下，爱德蒙决心要帮助那个不屈不挠的劳动者。', '副词: indefatigably 名词: indefatigability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('approach', '[ə\'proʊtʃ]', 'v.靠近；接近；接洽；要求；达到；动手处理 n.途径；方法；接近；接洽；要求；路径；进场着陆；相似的事物', '1. He still had not the courage to approach her. 他仍没有勇气靠近她。 2. Such people as are friendly are easy to approach. 亲切之人容易接近。 3. She approached the bank for a loan. 她向银行要求贷款。 4. There is no one who even approaches his talents. 目前还没有谁的能力能与他媲美。 5. Narration should become a basic approach to preschool education. 叙事应是幼儿教育的基本途径。', '过去式: approached 过去分词: approached 现在分词: approaching 第三人称单数: approaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eschew', '[ɪs\'tʃuː]', 'vt.避开；回避；戒绝', '1. Plenty of companies eschew such corporate programmes. 相当多的公司避开这种公司计划。 2. They must take the vow of absolute continence and eschew all thought of greed and lust. 他们必须发誓要绝对禁欲，避开所有贪婪和欲望的想法。 3. Even companies that eschew formal open-source licenses engage in open practices in order to attract outside developers and business partners. 为了吸引外部开发者和商业伙伴，甚至那些回避开源许可证的公司也参与开放实践。', '名词: eschewal 过去式: eschewed 过去分词: eschewed 现在分词: eschewing 第三人称单数: eschews');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('check', '[tʃɛk]', 'v.检查；阻止；核对；买单 n.检查；阻碍；支票；账单；方格图案；(国际象棋)将军', '1. Do look out for spelling mistakes when you check your homework. 你检查作业时要当心拼写错误。 2. We had to check this tendency for administrative reasons. 由于市政管理的原因，我们不得不阻止这种趋势。 3. Please check the date. 请核实一下日期。 4. We conduct regular check on the quality of our products. 我们对产品做例行质量检查。', '形容词: checkable 过去式: checked 过去分词: checked 现在分词: checking 第三人称单数: checks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aspen', '[\'æspən]', 'n.白杨 adj.白杨的', '1. This was the subject of a combative discussion this week at the Aspen Ideas Festival. 这个问题成了本周在科罗拉多州举行的白杨思想节中激烈讨论的主题。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conjecture', '[kən\'dʒektʃər]', 'n.推测；臆测 v.推测', '1. We could not conjecture the fact from what he said. 我们从他的话中还推测不出真实情况。 2. But Manski\'s model did not confirm this conjecture. 但曼斯基的模型并无法证实这个推测。 3. No conjecture can be offered on the subject. 关于这个问题不可臆测。 4. Chronology protection is still just a conjecture, so time travel remains a possibility. 时序保护还只是个臆测而已，所以时光旅行仍是可能的。 5. We could not conjecture the fact from what he said. 我们从他的话中还推测不出真实情况。', '形容词: conjecturable 副词: conjecturably 名词: conjecturer 过去式: conjectured 过去分词: conjectured 现在分词: conjecturing 第三人称单数: conjectures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coincide', '[ˌkoʊɪn\'saɪd]', 'vi.一致；同时发生；符合', '1. They didn\'t coincide in opinion. 他们的意见不统一。 2. Our opinions did not coincide on this case. 在这个案例上,我们的意见不一致。 3. My religious beliefs don\'t coincide with yours. 我的宗教信仰跟你的不一样。 4. Their stories coincided. 他们的叙述一致.', '过去式: coincided 过去分词: coincided 现在分词: coinciding 第三人称单数: coincides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('profound', '[prə\'faʊnd]', 'adj.深奥的；渊博的；极度的；意义深远的', '1. Beauty is but superficial while mind is profound. 美貌是肤浅的,而思想才是深邃的。 2. I was impressed by his devotion to his research but I didn\'t have the slightest interest in his profound theories. 给我留下了很深印象,但我对他那些深奥的理论丝毫不感兴趣。 3. Our professor is a man of profound learning. 我们的教授是一个学识渊博的人。 4. Reading makes a full man, meditation a profound man, discourse a clear man. 阅读培养学问丰富的人,思考培养见识深刻的人,演讲培养思路清晰的人。', '副词: profoundly 比较级: profounder 最高级: profoundest 名词: profoundness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dreary', '[\'drɪri]', 'adj.沉闷的；令人沮丧的；情绪低落的', '1. By day the monotonous hours wore on in the same heavy, hashed manner as on that first dreary afternoon. 在白天，那沉闷的时刻，就和第一个凄凉的下午一样，忧郁寂寞地度过。 2. Its yellow ambiguous stripes and dreary sky are homologous, which makes the world harmonious. 它背上灰黄斑驳的花纹，跟沉闷的天空遥遥相应，造成和谐的色调。 3. Hurstwood\'s dreary state made its beauty become more and more vivid. 赫斯渥那令人沮丧的处境使得这些情景更加美丽迷人。', '副词: drearily 比较级: drearier 最高级: dreariest 名词: dreariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appoint', '[ə\'pɔɪnt]', 'v.任命；委派；指定；约定', '1. The company decided to appoint a new treasurer. 公司决定任命一位新司库。 2. They appointed him chairman. 他们任命他为主席。 3. As a top manager, he should appoint none but people on their merit. 作为一位总经理，他应该任人为贤。 4. We must appoint a new teacher soon. 我们必须尽快委派一个新教师。', '过去式: appointed 过去分词: appointed 现在分词: appointing 第三人称单数: appoints');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ecstatic', '[ɪk\'stætɪk]', 'adj.狂喜的', '1. My daughter\'s birth was ecstatic. 我女儿的出生令人欣喜。 2. He was ecstatic at the news. 他获知消息后欣喜若狂。', '副词: ecstatically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arrant', '[\'ærənt]', 'adj.彻头彻尾的；极端的；臭名昭著的；声名狼藉的', '1. Most of his theories are arrant nonsense. 他的大多数理论都是胡说八道。 2. The most arrant nonsense about a product is never questioned. 而且从来没有人对最荒谬绝伦的产品提出过质疑。', '副词: arrantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('weather', '[\'weðər]', 'n.天气；气象；境遇 vt.使风化；经受住；使日晒雨淋 vi.风化；褪色；经受风雨 adj.上风的；天气预报的', '1. What is the weather like today? 今天天气情况怎样？ 2. The meteorologist drew a picture of the weather. 气象学者画了一张气象图。 3. The past years had known him in many weathers. 过去的岁月里,他起起落落。 4. The rocks on the mountain have to be weathered by wind and water. 山上的岩石得经受风化和水蚀。 5. The paint on the walls had weathered. 墙壁上的涂料已经风干了。 6. Fill in the form below about the weather report. 续下面关于天气预报的表格。', '过去式: weathered 过去分词: weathered 现在分词: weathering 第三人称单数: weathers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grove', '[ɡroʊv]', 'n.小树林；果树园', '1. I used to take a walk in the quiet grove. 过去我常在那安静的小树林里散步。 2. He thought that Romainville was a little grove near Paris, where young lovers go to pluck lilacs in the month of April. 他想起罗曼维尔是巴黎附近的一处小树林，每逢四月，青年情侣总到那里去采丁香。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ambiguous', '[æm\'bɪɡjuəs]', 'adj.模棱两可的；含糊不清的', '1. He gave us an ambiguous answer . 他给了我们一个模棱两可的答复。 2. In fact, your ambiguous words amount to a refusal. 实际上,你说的那些模棱两可的话等于是拒绝。 3. Her account was deliberately ambiguous. 她的陈述故意含混不清。 4. Why are you always so ambiguous about this problem? 为什么你总是对这个问题含糊不清？', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('truncate', '[\'trʌŋkeɪt]', 'vt.切去一端；缩短；截棱成平面 adj.切去了头；缩短了的；截形的', '1. truncate a news item to fit an available space 删减一条新闻以适应报纸的篇幅 2. Erosion has truncated the ridges of the mountains. 侵蚀削去了山脊。', '副词: truncately 名词: truncation 过去式: truncated 过去分词: truncated 现在分词: truncating 第三人称单数: truncates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('excitability', '[ɪkˌsaɪtə\'bɪləti]', 'n.兴奋性；激动性；可激发性', '1. The nerve excitability deteriorates. 神经兴奋性衰退。 2. Voltage-gated potassium channels regulate cell membrane potential and excitability in neurons. 电压门控性钾通道维持神经元静息膜电位，参与细胞兴奋性的改变。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('waft', '[wɑːft]', 'v.飘浮；飘荡 n.一股；一阵微风；风信旗', '1. The sound of their voices wafted across the lake to us. 他们的声音飘过湖面传到我们这里。 2. Delicious smells wafted up from the kitchen. 厨房里飘出了香味。 3. A waft of sweet-smelling fragrance blew over from the flower bush. 一阵芬芳的气息从花丛中吹过来。 4. There is a waft of fresh air through the window. 从窗子吹进了一股新鲜空气。', '名词: wafter 过去式: wafted 过去分词: wafted 现在分词: wafting 第三人称单数: wafts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monolithic', '[ˌmɒnə\'lɪθɪk]', 'adj.独石的；单体的；整体的', '1. A monolithic sculpture. 独块巨石雕塑 2. Monolithic structure ensures high reliability. 单晶体结构 3. At now and more attention wsa given to building monolithic movement technology. 目前建筑物整体平移技术得到了越来越广泛的关注。 4. Mathematics is not a single monolithic structure of absolute truth! 数学并不是绝对真理的单一整体结构。', '副词: monolithically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interaction', '[ˌɪntər\'ækʃn]', 'n.相互作用；相互影响；互动交流', '1. Price is determined through the interaction of demand and supply. 价格在供需的相互作用中形成。 2. Often the development groups have little in common and no interaction with one another. 通常情况下,开发团队的共性很少,相互之间也没有交互。 3. There should be a lot more interaction between the social services and local doctors. 社会公益服务机构和当地医生应该加强协作。 4. People get job satisfaction from different factors, such as social interaction with colleagues. 人们在从工作得到不同的方面工作满足,同事之间的相互交流。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glade', '[ɡleɪd]', 'n.林间空地', '1. The family had their lunch in the glade. 全家在林中的空地上吃了午饭。 2. A nice skinny dip in a quiet glade takes you back to nature. 在寂静的林间水潭进行惬意的裸泳，真是回到了大自然的怀抱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consign', '[kən\'saɪn]', 'vt.交付；放逐；委托', '1. The goods were consigned to you by railway. 货物已由铁路托运到你处。 2. We will consign the goods to him by express. 我们将以快递把货物寄给他。 3. The captured criminals were consigned to the dungeons. 抓到的罪犯被送进了地牢。 4. He consigned all the unpleasant thoughts to oblivion. 他把一切不愉快的思想置于脑后。', '形容词: consignable 名词: consignation 过去式: consigned 过去分词: consigned 现在分词: consigning 第三人称单数: consigns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invoke', '[ɪn\'voʊk]', 'vt.援引；引起；求助；请求；乞灵于 [计算机] 调用.', '1. The government has invoked the official secret act in having the book banned. 政府援引国家机密保密法以禁该书。 2. It invokes new problems. 它引起一些新的问题。 3. The speech invoked his memory of childhood. 演讲唤起了他童年的记忆。 4. They invoked help in the desperate situation. 他们在走投无路的情况下恳求援助。 5. This command can invoke the applications. 这条命令可以调用应用程序。', '名词: invoker 过去式: invoked 过去分词: invoked 现在分词: invoking 第三人称单数: invokes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parch', '[pɑːrtʃ]', 'v.烘；烤干；炙烤', '1. These grains may parch, but they will not pop. 这些谷类只能被烤干，却不可能爆开。 2. But you can parch the clothes with the gas in the kitchen. 你用煤气火烤干衣服吧。 3. The fierce sun parched the bare earth. 灼热的阳光炙烤着光秃秃的大地。', '过去式: parched 过去分词: parched 现在分词: parching 第三人称单数: parches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rant', '[rænt]', 'v.咆哮；大声地说；激昂地说；大声斥责 n.咆哮；夸夸其谈', '1. The old man ranted that nobody paid any attention to his opinion. 老人怒气冲冲地叫嚷说没人听他的意见。 2. You can rant and rave at the fine, but you\'ll still have to pay it. 你闹也好，骂也好，罚金还是得交。 3. This actor rants his lines. 这演员背台词拿腔拿调。 4. He ranted at me about my mistakes. 他大声数落我。 5. If they are ranting, allow them to rant. 如果他们咆哮就让他们咆哮。', '名词: ranter 过去式: ranted 过去分词: ranted 现在分词: ranting 第三人称单数: rants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('didactic', '[daɪ\'dæktɪk]', 'adj.教诲的；说教的', '1. This novel was intended to be neither didactic nor aggressive. 这部书的本意，既不想教训人，也不想攻击人。 2. Most of the articles in the magazine are of a didactic nature. 杂志上大部分文章的本质都是说教性的。 3. His speech to the new freshmen was painfully didactic. 他的演说对于新人来说是一种痛苦的说教。', '副词: didactically 异体字: didactical 名词: didacticism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glacial', '[\'ɡleɪʃl]', 'adj.冰川(期)的；非常冷的；缓慢的；(人)态度不友善的', '1. Recent glacial recession is alarming to scientists. 最近的冰川缩减令科学家震惊。 2. Newly installed seismometers will listen for glacial earthquakes. 新安装的地震仪将可监听冰河地震的声音。 3. It was a door even more glacial than that of winter which was ajar. 比起平时冬季的那扇半开的门,这扇门更冻人。 4. Work proceeded at a glacial pace. 工作以极缓慢的速度进行着。', '副词: glacially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('myopic', '[maɪ\'ɒpɪk]', 'adj.近视的；缺乏远见的', '1. What do myopic eye and normal eye differ? 近视的眼睛和正常的眼睛有什么不同？ 2. Is there really a kind of glasses that can reduce myopic degrees? 真的有一种眼镜能降低近视度数吗? 3. Her understanding of economic development is shaky and myopic. 她关于经济发展的观点是站不住脚的，是目光短浅的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emigrate', '[\'emɪɡreɪt]', 'v.移居；移民', '1. I\'ll emigrate to the western woods. 我要移居到西部的丛林里去。 2. He\'s decided to emigrate and start a new life in America. 他决定移居美国，开始新的生活。 3. Many people had to emigrate during the Nazi period. 在纳粹党期间许多人不得不移民。 4. I don\'t like your plan to emigrate to Canada. 我不赞成你移民加拿大的计划。', '名词: emigration 过去式: emigrated 过去分词: emigrated 现在分词: emigrating 第三人称单数: emigrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rout', '[raʊt]', 'n. 彻底溃败； 凑热闹的人； 大败 v. 使 ... 溃败； 使 ... 败逃', '1. It\'s an utter rout, and your broadcasts are criminal lies. 这是一场溃败，你广播的新闻都是可耻的谎言。 2. Markets across Europe were also in freefall, following yet another rout in Asia. 伴随着亚洲市场的节节溃败，整个欧洲市场同样直线下滑。', '过去式: routed 过去分词: routed 现在分词: routing 第三人称单数: routs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imponderable', '[ɪm\'pɑːndərəbl]', 'n.无法估量的事物 adj.无重量的；无法计算的；不可估价的', '1. We can\'t predict the outcome. There are too many imponderables. 我们无法预测结果。难以逆料的情况太多了。 2. The effect of his new method is imponderable. 他的新方法所起的作用是无法正确估计的。 3. Our resources in technical knowledge are imponderable. 我们的技术知识资源是无法估量的。 4. Our imponderable resources in knowledge are constantly growing and are inexhaustible. 我们无法估量的知识资源是不断发展永不枯竭的。', '副词: imponderably 名词: imponderability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jitters', '[\'dʒɪtərz]', 'n.紧张；怯场 名词jitter的复数形式.', '1. No one can escape the first date jitters. 没人能避免第一次约会的紧张。 2. I always get the jitters before I go on stage. 我登台之前总是感到紧张。 3. He performed very well without any jitters. 他表演的很好，没有任何怯场。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('notorious', '[noʊ\'tɔːriəs]', 'adj.臭名昭著的', '1. He is notorious for his goings-on. 他因行为不检点而声名狼藉。 2. The district is notorious for its fogs. 那地区以浓雾出名。 3. Hitler is a notorious dictator. 希特勒是一个臭名昭著的独裁者。 4. The notorious thief will be put up for trial next week. 那个臭名昭著的偷窃犯将于下周出庭受审。', '副词: notoriously 名词: notoriousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('festal', '[\'festəl]', 'adj.节日的；欢乐的', '1. The peoples are in a festal atmosphere. 各族人民都沉浸在节日的气氛之中。 2. I had wished festal activities should attract her, but it did work. 我希望节日的活动能吸引她，可还是无济于事。', '副词: festally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irrevocable', '[ɪ\'revəkəbl]', 'adj.不能挽回的；不能取消的；不能变更的', '1. The doom which I have passed upon her is irrevocable. 我对她下的判决是不能挽回的。 2. We ask you to use an irrevocable letter of credit. 我们要求您们开一张不可撤销的信用状。 3. The decision has been made and is irrevocable. 木已成舟已作出决定，无法反悔 4. His life was set on an irrevocable course. 他的生活道路不可改变。', '副词: irrevocably 名词: irrevocability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scrape', '[skreɪp]', 'v.刮掉；擦掉 n.擦伤；擦掉；刮擦声；<口>窘境', '1. I must have scraped some of the paint off when I was parking the car. 我准是停放汽车的时候刮掉了一些油漆。 2. He bent over to scrape some dirt off his shoes. 他弯腰刮掉鞋子上的尘土。 3. Scrape your shoes on the door mat before you come in. 进屋前先在门口擦鞋垫上擦一擦鞋子。 4. He suffered a few cuts and scrapes. 他割破和擦伤了几个地方。', '过去式: scraped 过去分词: scraped 现在分词: scraping 第三人称单数: scrapes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wick', '[wɪk]', 'n.蜡烛芯；灯芯', '1. It was empty, but a feeble tallow candle, with a broken back and a long, cauliflower-headed wick sputtered upon the table. 房间是空空洞洞的，只点了一支暗淡无光的牛脂蜡烛，背部开裂，蜡烛芯长长的，花椰菜头似的，蜡烛油溅泼在桌子上。 2. A wick connects it to a reservoir. 一灯芯绳把它与水槽相连。 3. The wick is the quintessence of the candle. 灯芯是蜡烛的精华。', '过去式: wicked 过去分词: wicked 现在分词: wicking 第三人称单数: wicks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pawn', '[pɔːn]', 'n. 典当； 抵押物； 人质； (国际象棋中)卒 vt. 典当； 以 ... 为担保', '1. He tried by every means to redeem the pawn. 他千方百计要赎回典当物。 2. He had nothing left that he could pawn. 他再也没有什么可以典当的东西了。 3. To make matters worse, Tien is used as a pawn in the battle. 更糟糕的是，天津饭也被抓来当作了人质。 4. This was sacrificing a pawn to save a rook. 这是丢卒保车。 5. He tried by every means to redeem the pawn. 他千方百计要赎回典当物。', '形容词: pawnable 名词: pawnage 过去式: pawned 过去分词: pawned 现在分词: pawning 第三人称单数: pawns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maul', '[mɔːl]', 'n.大槌 v.打伤；虐打；粗暴对待；猛烈抨击', '1. He died after being mauled by a tiger. 他被老虎咬死了。 2. Stop pulling my arm,you have no right to maul me about like this! 别拉我的胳膊，你没有权利这样粗暴地对待我！ 3. Her novel has been badly mauled by the critics. 她的小说横遭评论家抨击。', '名词: mauler 过去式: mauled/malled 过去分词: mauled/malled 现在分词: mauling/malling 第三人称单数: mauls/malls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harshly', '[hɑːʃli]', 'adv.粗糙地；粗暴地；刺耳地', '1. Sustained, harshly abusive language; invective. 骂人话尖刻的责骂性言词; 骂语 2. You should not criticize him so harshly in his face. 你不应该当面这么严厉地批评他。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distrait', '[dɪ\'streɪ]', 'adj.心不在焉的', '1. When she did not occupy her accustomed chair at the seminar, Freud felt uneasy and distrait(Times Literary Supplement) 在专家讲座会上当她不坐在经常坐的椅子上时，弗洛伊德就感到不安和心不在焉(时代文学增刊) 2. When she did not occupy her accustomed chair at the seminar, Freud felt uneasy and distrait(bTimes Literary Supplement) 在专家讲座会上当她不坐在经常坐的椅子上时，弗洛伊德就感到不安和心不在焉(b时代文学增刊) 3. \"When she did not occupy her accustomed chair at the seminar, Freud felt uneasy and distrait\" (Times Literary Supplement) “在专家讲座会上当她不坐在经常坐的椅子上时，弗洛伊德就感到不安和心不在焉”(时代文学增刊)', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('daft', '[dæft]', 'adj.愚蠢可笑的', '1. Don\'t be so daft! 别那麽傻了！ 2. You\'re right. I look daft with one shoe. 你说的对，我穿一只鞋是有点蠢。', '副词: daftly 比较级: dafter 最高级: daftest 名词: daftness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discography', '[dɪs\'kɑːɡrəfi]', 'n.唱片分类目录；音乐唱片分类学；音乐唱片分类法', '1. Discography of the Bayreuth Festival. [2006]. 放大图片 Wagner Im Festspielhaus. 2. And then there is his growing discography. 然后是他的日渐增长的唱片目录。 3. Some tracks are rare, or not included in her discography albums. 包括多首热门单曲，以及以往的专辑中不曾收录的歌曲。 4. Should Kobe\'s fans be satisfied with his current discography? 科比的球迷们是否满足于他现在的状态？', '形容词: discographical 名词: discographer 名词复数: discographies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deplete', '[dɪ\'pliːt]', 'vt.耗尽；使空竭', '1. Our stock of food is greatly depleted. 我们的食物储备已消耗殆尽。 2. Mankind must take care not to deplete the earth of its natural resources. 人类必须注意，切莫耗尽地球上的自然资源。 3. Wars in the region have depleted the country\'s food supplies. 这个地区的战争使国家的粮食供应空乏。 4. This expense has depleted our funds. 这笔花费已使我们的资金所剩无几。', '形容词: depletable 过去式: depleted 过去分词: depleted 现在分词: depleting 第三人称单数: depletes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dangle', '[\'dæŋɡl]', 'v.摇晃；悬垂；挂着；追求 n.摇摆；摇摆物', '1. The leaves dangled in the wind. 树叶随风摇摆。 2. He dangled the bone in front of the puppy. 他晃动着骨头逗小狗。 3. The children sat on the high wall, with their legs dangling. 小孩子们坐在高墙上，脚悬垂着。 4. Huge earrings dangled from her ears. 她的耳朵上吊着巨大的耳环。 5. Do not swing it backwards or let it dangle. 不要将腿向后摇摆或者悬吊空中。', '形容词: dangly 名词: dangler 过去式: dangled 过去分词: dangled 现在分词: dangling 第三人称单数: dangles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immensity', '[ɪ\'mensəti]', 'n.无限；巨大；无垠', '1. We have no intuitive grasp of the immensity of time. 我们对时间的无限没有什么直观的认识。 2. The business is conducted on a scale of unprecedented immensity. 这项业务是按前所未有的巨大规模来经营的。 3. I can\'t imagine the immensity of space. 我想象不出太空的浩瀚无际。', '名词复数: immensities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('famish', '[\'fæmɪʃ]', 'v.（使）挨饿；（使）饥饿', '1. When\'s lunch? I\'m famished! 什么时候吃午饭? 我都快饿死了！ 2. The long drought famished many people. 久旱使很多人陷入饥饿。', '名词: famishment 过去式: famished 过去分词: famished 现在分词: famishing 第三人称单数: famishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('colonize', '[\'kɑːlənaɪz]', 'v.开拓殖民地；移居于殖民地', '1. Britain colonized many parts of Africa. 英国在非洲开拓了许多殖民地。 2. Some Westerners came to colonize; others came to convert; most came to exploit. 有些西方人为了殖民而来，有些是为了宣传基督教义，但大多数是为了剥削。 3. Someday human beings will attempt to colonize outer space. 有朝一日人类会试图开拓外太空成殖民地。 4. The divers want to show it\'s possible for humans to colonize the seabed. 这几名潜水员想证明人类能够在海底生活。', '名词: colonizer 过去式: colonized 过去分词: colonized 现在分词: colonizing 第三人称单数: colonizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('statuary', '[\'stætʃueri]', 'n.雕像；雕塑艺术', '1. The home-made statuary gave an artistic air to the room. 这些自制的雕像给房间增添了艺术气息。 2. There will be a display of bronze statuary in this museum next week. 下星期这个博物馆将举办一个青铜雕塑作品展览。', '名词复数: statuaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('benefactor', '[\'benɪfæktər]', 'n.恩人；捐助者；赠送者', '1. He did, however, discover his anonymous benefactor. 不过,他终于找到了那个匿名的恩人。 2. We showed high respect to benefactors. 我们对捐助者表达了崇高的敬意。 3. The quiet benefactor gets the largest reward. 这位不声张的捐助者得到了最大的回报。 4. The chieftain of that country is disguised as a benefactor this time. 那个国家的首领这一次伪装出一副施恩者的姿态。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frustrate', '[\'frʌstreɪt]', 'vt.挫败；击败；使沮丧；使灰心 adj.无益的；挫败的；挫折的', '1. This is the place that we frustrate enemy. 这是我们挫败敌人的地方。 2. They made their preparations to frustrate the conspiracy. 他们作好准备挫败以这个阴谋。 3. The terrible weather frustrated our hopes of going out. 恶劣的天气使我们外出的愿望无法实现。 4. We have the confidence in frustrating our enemy. 我们有信心击败敌人。 5. The prisoner made a frustrate attempt to escape. 囚犯妄图逃跑。', '副词: frustratingly 名词: frustrater 过去式: frustrated 过去分词: frustrated 现在分词: frustrating 第三人称单数: frustrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hermetic', '[hɜːr\'metɪk]', 'adj.密封的；与外界隔绝的；深奥的；炼金术的', '1. The hermetic seal on the packet means that the food lasts longer. 封袋上的密封印表明食物能保存更长的时间。 2. It\'s the hermetic confines of an isolated life. 这是与世隔绝的不受外界干扰的区域。', '副词: hermetically 异体字: hermetical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('metaphor', '[\'metəfər]', 'n.象征；隐喻', '1. In poetry the rose is often a metaphor for love. 玫瑰在诗中通常作为爱的象征。 2. She has a striking originality in her use of metaphor. 她在运用隐喻方面有独创性。 3. This metaphor is beyond (above) all comprehension. 这个隐喻难以理解。 4. Then you only need to learn one metaphor. 然后你只需要学习一个隐喻。', '形容词: metaphoric 副词: metaphorically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unexceptional', '[ˌʌnɪk\'sepʃənl]', 'adj.非例外的；普通的；平凡的', '1. There is no unexceptional regulation. 没有无例外的规定。 2. Mr Radulovich was in most ways unexceptional. 拉杜洛维奇先生在很大程度上是一位普通人。', '副词: unexceptionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('colloquium', '[kə\'loʊkwiəm]', 'n.学术讨论会', '1. He was not willing to attend the colloquium. 他不愿参加这个学术讨论会。', '名词复数: colloquiums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oxidize', '[\'ɑːksɪdaɪz]', 'v.氧化；生锈', '1. The dye is allowed to oxidize before the next dip. 染料允许在下个垂度之前氧化。 2. In addition, argon plasma will not oxidize silver unlike an air or oxygen plasma. 此外，氩气等离子体不会像大气或氧气等离子体氧化银。', '形容词: oxidizable 名词: oxidization 过去式: oxidized 过去分词: oxidized 现在分词: oxidizing 第三人称单数: oxidizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('readily', '[\'redɪli]', 'adv.容易地；迅速地；乐意地；欣然', '1. These problems are not readily soluble. 这些问题不容易解决。 2. They can readily be brought anywhere. 它们易于携带。 3. She stood up readily. 她迅速地站了起来。 4. She readily accepted his proposal of marriage. 她乐意地接受了他的求婚。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monochrome', '[\'mɑːnəkroʊm]', 'n.单色；单色画法 adj.单色的；黑白的', '1. Textures change, but colors are monochrome. 纹理变化了，但色彩仍是单色。 2. That is a Czechslovakian, pre-war, monochrome, low-budget movie. 这是捷克，战前的，黑白，低成本电影。', '形容词: monochromic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sibilant', '[\'sɪbɪlənt]', 'adj.发咝咝声的 n.丝丝音', '1. I heard the sibilant sound of whispering. 我听到窃窃私语声。', '副词: sibilantly 名词: sibilance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ordinance', '[\'ɔːrdɪnəns]', 'n.法令；条例', '1. Everyone should obey the government ordinance. 每个人都必须遵守这条政府法令。 2. The French Foreign Legion was founded by a Royal Ordinance. 法国外籍兵团是按照皇家法令建立的。 3. The Town Planning Amendment Ordinance has come. 城市规划修订条例已经生效。 4. The ordinance applies equally to local and imported workers. 该条例适用于本地及外来工人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('validate', '[\'vælɪdeɪt]', 'vt.使生效；证实；确认；验证', '1. How will you validate your competency model? 如何使你的胜任素质模型真正有效? 2. The ticket has to be stamped by the airline to validate it. 须经航空公司盖章，该机票才能生效。 3. Do these results validate his theory? 这些结果可以证实他的理论吗? 4. How to validate the documents and information submitted by the customer? 如何去证实客户所提交的文件和信息?', '名词: validation 过去式: validated 过去分词: validated 现在分词: validating 第三人称单数: validates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conscience', '[\'kɑːnʃəns]', 'n.良心；是非之心；顾忌', '1. She was afflicted with conscience. 她受良心责备。 2. The thief\'s conscience smote him. 那个贼突然良心发现。 3. She gave him back the money she\'d stolen for the sake of her conscience. 为了不受良心的谴责，她把从他那偷来的钱还给他了。 4. This is a document that serves as the nation\'s conscience. 这是一份表明民族道德准则的文件。', '形容词: conscienceless');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acarpous', '[eɪ\'kɑːpəs]', 'adj.[植]不结果的；无果实的', '1. The abysmal academician\'s acarpous writing had accomplished little in achievements to date. 到目前为止，那位深不可测的院士的没有结果的著作仅仅完成了极少数部分。 2. In addition, the isozyme bands and enzyme activity of high yield female plant, low yield female plant and acarpous female plant were compared. 此外，还比较了高产、低产、不结果雌株之间同工酶的酶带和活性差别。 3. The only acarpous plant exhibited in the show won the acclaim of many vistors obsessed with its beauty and glamor.With accretion of praises andcompliments, it also wins many awards. 那棵唯一不结果子的在演出中展示的植物赢得了很多为她的美丽和魅力着迷的参观者的好评。不仅是赞扬和褒奖，她还赢得了很多奖项。 4. 31.The only acarpous plant exhibited in the show won the acclaim of many vistors obsessed with its beauty and glamor. 那棵唯一不结果子的在演出中展示的植物赢得了很多为她的美丽和魅力着迷的参观者的好评。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perfunctory', '[pər\'fʌŋktəri]', 'adj.敷衍的', '1. The little boy gave his face a perfunctory wash. 这个小男孩敷衍地洗了把脸。 2. He is never serious and works in a perfunctory manner. 他工作浮皮潦草，从不认真。 3. The operator answered the phone with a perfunctory greeting. 接线员接通电话,象征性的打了招呼。', '副词: perfunctorily 名词: perfunctoriness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('betroth', '[bɪ\'trɔːθ]', 'vt. 同 ... 订婚； 同意结婚', '1. Her father betrothed her to him at an early age. 她父亲在她年幼时已把她许配给他。 2. She betrothed herself to him. 她和他订婚了。', '过去式: betrothed 过去分词: betrothed 现在分词: betrothing 第三人称单数: betroths');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('academician', '[ˌækədə\'mɪʃn]', 'n.学者；院士；大学教师；大学生；知识分子；学会会员', '1. As an academician, I think Mathematics is an intriguing and absorbing science. 作为一名学者，我认为数学是一门既有趣又引人入胜的科学。 2. Our professor is an academician of the Science Academy. 我们的教授是科学院的院士。 3. Professor Wang was appointed academician of the Engineering Academy. 王教授被评为工程院院士。 4. I\'m the first academician in our family. 我是我们家第一个大学生。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bazaar', '[bə\'zɑːr]', 'n.市集；商场；义卖的地方', '1. To make the bazaar model work, it helps enormously if you have at least a little skill at charming people. 要使市集模式运行起来，你至少有一点点让人们喜欢你的本领是非常重要的。 2. I am going to go shopping in the bazaar in the morning. 我上半天打算去商场购物。 3. The high-grade mattress offered By this Bazaar assures you of a luxurious comfort. 本商场供应高级床垫，给您享受一次奢侈的舒适。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verge', '[vɜːrdʒ]', 'v.接近；濒于；下沉；趋于 v.处在...的边沿 n.边缘；界限；权杖', '1. The path verges on the edge of a precipice. 这条小径濒临断崖的边缘。 2. He is verging on a breakdown. 他正濒临精神崩溃。 3. The sun was verging towards the horizon. 太阳向地平线下降。 4. The economy verges toward inflation. 经济倾向于通货膨胀。 5. Her land verges on the neighboring township. 她的土地与邻镇相连。 6. The country\'s economy is on the verge of collapse. 这个国家的经济已到了崩溃的边缘。', '过去式: verged 过去分词: verged 现在分词: verging 第三人称单数: verges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pursue', '[pər\'suː]', 'v.追求；追捕；继续执行；从事', '1. Everyone has the freedom to pursue their dreams. 每个人都有追求各自梦想的自由。 2. The police are pursuing an escaped prisoner. 警方正在追捕一名越狱的逃犯。 3. Let\'s not pursue this argument. 让我们别再继续这个争论了。 4. She wishes to pursue a medical career. 她希望从事医学工作。', '形容词: pursuable 名词: pursuer 过去式: pursued 过去分词: pursued 现在分词: pursuing 第三人称单数: pursues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bassoon', '[bə\'suːn]', 'n.低音管；巴颂管', '1. His brother is an outstanding bassoon player. 他的哥哥是一名出色的大管演奏家。 2. He tucked the bassoon under an arm and stamped out. 他把巴松管夹在腋下,跺着脚走了出去。', '名词: bassoonist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inhumane', '[ˌɪnhjuː\'meɪn]', 'adj.无情的；残忍的；不人道的', '1. I don\'t think he\'s an inhumane man. 我认为他不是一个没有人性的人。 2. I wander about the dread nocturnal countryside of this inhuman season. 在这无情的季节里，在这可怕的夜间，我在乡野徘徊。 3. In their time those ideas decried working conditions that the West now considers to be simply inhumane. 在那个时代这些思想谴责的工作环境现在的西方也认为是残忍的。 4. They were guilty of the most barbarous and inhuman atrocities. 他们犯有最野蛮、最不人道的暴行。', '副词: inhumanely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bubble', '[\'bʌbl]', 'n.气泡；泡影 v.起泡；冒泡；充满...感情', '1. A bubble will burst at the slightest touch. 气泡稍微一碰就破。 2. As a stock market bubble is taking shape, the investors should take precautions against the risks. 股市泡沫正在形成,投资者应该防范风险。 3. His hope vanished like a bubble. 他的希望化作泡影。 4. He didn\'t want to burst the newcomer\'s bubble. 他不想打破这个新来者的不切实际的美梦。 5. The water in the pan was beginning to bubble. 锅里的水开始起泡。', '过去式: bubbled 过去分词: bubbled 现在分词: bubbling 第三人称单数: bubbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prohibitive', '[prə\'hɪbətɪv]', 'adj.禁止的；抑制的；（价格等）过高的', '1. On legislative science, prohibitive regulation expresses the aim of preventing national power from invading citizen rights better. 从立法学上来说，禁止性规则更能表达防范国家权力可能侵犯公民权利的目的。 2. The government has put a prohibitive tax on foreign goods. 政府对外国货征收抑制性税率。 3. The cost of travel to the far east is prohibitive. 到远东旅游的费用高的令人不敢问津。 4. The costs of relocating a business are often prohibitive. 迁移商店的成本通常是非常高的。', '副词: prohibitively 异体字: prohibitory 名词: prohibitiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('automation', '[ˌɔːtə\'meɪʃn]', 'n.自动化', '1. Automation has obsoleted many unskilled workers. 自动化使很多非技术工人受到淘汰。 2. So is the case with industrial automation. 在工业自动化方面，情况也一样。', '形容词: automative');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('guarantee', '[ˌɡærən\'tiː]', 'n.保证；保证书；担保；担保人；抵押品 vt.保证；担保', '1. A diploma is no guarantee of efficiency. 持有文凭不能保证工作效率一定高。 2. I guarantee that this will not happen again. 我保证此类事情不会再发生。 3. We guarantee the fastness of these dyes. 我们担保这些染料不褪色。 4. He put up his house as a guarantee. 他提供房子作为担保。 5. A diploma is no guarantee of efficiency. 持有文凭不能保证工作效率一定高。', '过去式: guaranteed 过去分词: guaranteed 现在分词: guaranteeing 第三人称单数: guarantees');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cognizance', '[\'kɑːɡnɪzəns]', 'n.认知；[法]审理；审判管辖权；标记', '1. Little cognizance is taken of these events. 这些事件未有引起注意。 2. Knowledge is a cognizance of basic impersonality. 知识是一种具有客观基础的认知。 3. The case still is in farther cognizance. 案件仍在进一步审理中。 4. The point does not fall under the cognizance or deliberations of this committee. 这问题不归这个委员会审理或审议。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overreach', '[ˌoʊvər\'riːtʃ]', 'v.做事过头；（靠狡诈）取胜；（伸得过长而）超出 v.做得过头；伸得过远；夸大；行骗 n.马后蹄踢前蹄', '1. Don\'t apply for that job: you\'re in danger of overreaching yourself. 不要申请那份工作，以免有不自量力之嫌。 2. Cleverness may overreach itself. 聪明反被聪明误。 3. He had to overreach in order to catch my hand. 为了抓住我的手，他不得不把手伸得过长。 4. But I also, I make music that suits the way I sing also, I try not to overreach. 但我也会创作适合我演唱风格的歌曲. 5. Already under fire for overreach, the Obama team is wary of anything that smacks of bigger government. 奥巴马政府早已备受做过头的攻击，他们对于给人以大政府印象的事情非常警惕。', '名词: overreacher 过去式: overreached 过去分词: overreached 现在分词: overreaching 第三人称单数: overreaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surreptitious', '[ˌsɜːrəp\'tɪʃəs]', 'adj.暗中进行的；鬼鬼祟祟的；保密的', '1. She carried out a surreptitious search of his belongings. 她暗地里搜查他的东西。 2. His surreptitious behaviour naturally aroused suspicion. 他那鬼鬼祟祟的行为自然引起了旁人的怀疑。 3. He was surreptitious in his movements. 他行踪诡秘。', '副词: surreptitiously 名词: surreptitiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overwhelm', '[ˌoʊvər\'welm]', 'vt.打击；压倒；使感动；淹没；打败', '1. No difficulty can overwhelm us. 困难压不倒我们。 2. If I cannot overwhelm with my quality, I will overwhelm with my quantity. 如果我不能以质量压倒，我就一定要以数量压倒。 3. Your kindness quite overwhelmed me. 你的好意使我感激难言。 4. The village was overwhelmed when the floods came. 这个村庄在洪水泛滥时被淹没了。', '过去式: overwhelmed 过去分词: overwhelmed 现在分词: overwhelming 第三人称单数: overwhelms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evoke', '[ɪ\'voʊk]', 'vt.唤起；引起', '1. Songs can evoke old memories. 歌曲可以唤起往日的回忆。 2. Pieces of fine art may evoke emotional or spiritual responses in us. 一件件精美的艺术品可以唤起我们情感和精神上的响应。 3. The photographs evoked strong memories of our holidays in France. 照片唤起了我们在法国度假的深深的记忆。 4. His case is unlikely to evoke public sympathy. 他的情况不大可能引起公众的同情。', '形容词: evocable 过去式: evoked 过去分词: evoked 现在分词: evoking 第三人称单数: evokes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revenue', '[\'revənuː]', 'n.税收；收入；税务局', '1. National tax revenue grew by a large margin every year. 国家税收连年大幅度增长。 2. The state does not collect enough revenue to cover its expenditure. 政府征收的税收不能满足支出。 3. Rent is one form of revenue. 房租是一种收入。 4. The document states that all revenue has to be declared to the tax office. 该文件规定必须向税务局申报所有收入。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('weasel', '[\'wiːzl]', 'n.鼬鼠；黄鼠狼；狡猾的人 v.逃避；推诿', '1. The weasel is a timid animal but will fight like a tiger in defence of its young. 鼬鼠是一种胆小的动物，但在保护其幼畜时也会凶猛地搏斗。 2. Weasel lives mainly on rats and rabbits. 黄鼠狼主要以老鼠和兔子为食。 3. Is she a role model for women in politics or just another lying weasel? 她究竟是女人从政的角色模范或者只是狡猾奸诈的鼬? 4. Their boss escaped to weasel out of his responsibility. 他们的老板为逃避责任溜走了。', '过去式: weaseled/weaselled 过去分词: weaseled/weaselled 现在分词: weaseling/weaselling 第三人称单数: weasels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discern', '[dɪ\'sɜːrn]', 'v.辨别；看出；察觉', '1. Sometimes it\'s not easy to discern between the true and the false. 有时辨别真伪并不容易。 2. He was just able to discern the road in the dark. 他在黑暗中勉强能辨出道路。 3. They can discern me in spite of the fog. 虽然有雾，但他们能认得出我。 4. I soon discerned that the man was lying. 我马上察觉出那人在撒谎。', '名词: discerner 过去式: discerned 过去分词: discerned 现在分词: discerning 第三人称单数: discerns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('misshapen', '[ˌmɪs\'ʃeɪpən]', 'adj.畸形的', '1. His knee is misshapen and unable to move. 他的膝盖有点畸形，不能动。 2. He held out a hand the size of a pie plate, in which lay a tiny, misshapen kitten. 他伸出他那象馅饼盘一样大的手掌，上面有一只小小的、长得奇形怪状的小猫。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drone', '[droʊn]', 'n.雄蜂；游手好闲者；无人驾驶飞机 n.嗡嗡声；单调的声音 vi.嗡嗡叫；混日子 vt.单调低沉地说', '1. Drones do not work. 雄蜂不工作。 2. I deploy the rax ASAP and make a burst drone and a few IW. 部署的獭兔，并尽快作出突发无人驾驶飞机和一些信息战。 3. We could hear the distant drone of the traffic. 我们可以听到远处传来的车辆往来的嗡嗡声。 4. Her sharp questions punctuated the speaker\'s drone. 她的敏锐的问题不时地打断演讲者的话。 5. An aeroplane droned overhead. 一架飞机在头上嗡嗡飞过。 6. The minister droned out the psalm. 牧师喃喃地念赞美诗。', '过去式: droned 过去分词: droned 现在分词: droning 第三人称单数: drones');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transition', '[træn\'zɪʃn]', 'n.转变；过渡', '1. Such a sudden transition must affect her. 这样的一个突然变化一定会影响她。 2. His attitude underwent an abrupt transition. 他的态度突然改变了。 3. We hope there will be a peaceful transition to the new system. 我们希望能够和平过渡到新的制度。', '形容词: transitional 副词: transitionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('connotation', '[\'kɒnə\'teɪʃən]', 'n.涵义；言外之意；[逻]内涵', '1. A possible connotation of \"home\" is a place of warmth, comfort and affection\". “家”的可能涵义是“一个温暖、舒适和爱的地方”。 2. Hollywood holds connotations of romance and glittering success. 好莱坞一词包含了浪漫与耀眼的成就的含意。 3. The concept of celibacy carries connotations of asceticism and religious fervor. 修道者的独身观念含有禁欲兴宗教热情之意。 4. Every community has its unique connotation. 每一个社区都有自己独特的内涵。', '形容词: connotative 副词: connotatively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('etching', '[\'etʃɪŋ]', 'n.蚀刻版画；铜版画；蚀刻术 动词etch的现在分词.', '1. That is a beautiful etching of a bird. 那是一只鸟的漂亮的蚀刻画。 2. Hanging on the wall was a fine etching of the church. 挂在墙上的是一幅精致的教堂蚀刻板画。 3. She soaked the etching in an acid bath. 她将铜版画浸入到酸性溶液中。 4. He was able to procure a Rembrandt etching from the art dealer. 他从艺术品商人那里收购到了一幅伦勃朗的作品。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unfold', '[ʌn\'foʊld]', 'v.展开；开放；显露', '1. The war seemed to unfold in the blink of an eye. 这场战争在眨眼间就展开了。 2. That\'s how life tends to unfold before us. 生活就是这样在我们前面展开。 3. She seemed to unfold like a strong white lily under this genial breath of admiration and homage. 她似乎在这赞赏和尊敬的真诚氛围之中象一朵白色的水仙那样猛烈地开放了。 4. A walk through town will unfold many interesting buildings. 一条穿越城镇的行道将显露很多有趣的建筑物。', '名词: unfoldment 过去式: unfolded 过去分词: unfolded 现在分词: unfolding 第三人称单数: unfolds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compunction', '[kəm\'pʌŋkʃn]', 'n.良心的责备；后悔；悔恨', '1. He had lied to her without compunction. 他向她撒了谎却毫无愧疚。 2. She kept me waiting without the slightest compunction. 她使我久候而丝毫没有歉意。 3. I felt some compunction at having kept her waiting. 我有点后悔要她等我。', '形容词: compunctious 副词: compunctiously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hardbitten', '[ˌhɑːrd\'bɪtn]', 'adj.强硬的', '1. So I learnt the business of conducting that way, through actually doing it and conducting jaded and hardbitten West End musicians. 我学到了以那样的指挥方式谋生，并为疲倦和刻薄的伦敦西区音乐家担任指挥。 2. hardbitten Michael finds consolation in drink and drugs; 麻木不仁的迈克尔。。。。； 3. a hardbitten war journalist 久经沙场的战地记者', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perky', '[\'pɜːrki]', 'adj.活泼的；得意洋洋的', '1. She hasn\'t been her usual perky self lately. 她最近不像平常那样有精神。 2. He\'s still in hospital, but he seems quite perky. 他虽然还住着院,可是看上去倒挺精神的。 3. I was moderately attractive and at times, perky and outgoing. 我长得算是迷人,有时还挺自信和外向的。', '副词: perkily 比较级: perkier 最高级: perkiest 名词: perkiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('precipitation', '[prɪˌsɪpɪ\'teɪʃn]', 'n.仓促；急躁；沉淀；降雨量；坠落；凝结；冰雹', '1. You always act with precipitation. 你总是仓促行事。 2. Are Picoplankton Responsible for Calcite Precipitation in Lakes? 微型浮游生物应为湖泊中的方解石沉淀负责吗? 3. The quantity of precipitation varies greatly from year to year in these regions. 在这些地区每年降雨量的变化很大。 4. The storm brought several inches of precipitation. 暴雨带来了几英寸的降雨。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irk', '[ɜːrk]', 'v.使厌倦；使苦恼 n.厌倦；苦恼', '1. It irks me to see money being wasted. 我看著浪费金钱就讨厌。 2. It irked him that she had thought of it first. 她竟先想到那件事，为此他很不痛快。 3. By midday the irk of his pack became too oppressive. 走到中午的时候，累赘的包袱压得他受不了。', '过去式: irked 过去分词: irked 现在分词: irking 第三人称单数: irks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('huffy', '[\'hʌfi]', 'adj.愤怒的；傲慢的；易被冒犯的', '1. OK, OK, forget about it. There\'s no need to get huffy. （好了，好了，没事了。没必要为这种事大动肝火哦。） 2. He is not an easy going person. He always gets huffy with others. 他可不好相处呢。他总是对别人动怒。 3. You shouldn\'t get the hump about it or get all huffy. 你应该明白，你是学传媒的，不应该对这些事耿耿于怀或小题大做啊。 4. Lets talk about it there before the admins go huffy puffy. BTW your topic has been moved to 附件讨论区.', '副词: huffily 比较级: huffier 最高级: huffiest 名词: huffiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sanitary', '[\'sænəteri]', 'adj.卫生的；清洁的', '1. There was a small and not very sanitary inn nearby. 附近有一家不那么卫生的小客栈。 2. It\'s not sanitary to let flies come near food. 让苍蝇接近食物是不卫生的。 3. The oral sanitary product containing the zedoary turmeric oil has the function of inhibiting various pathogenic bacteria and virus growth while guaranteeing the tooth sanitation. 所述的含莪术油的口腔卫生产品在用于保证牙齿清洁的同时，具有抑制口腔和上呼吸道内各种致病细菌和病毒生长的作用。', '副词: sanitarily');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proselytize', '[\'prɑːsələtaɪz]', 'v.使改宗；劝诱改宗', '1. A wise man will not proselytize you. 智者不会对你改宗劝诱。 2. It is not your task as members of the Family of Light to proselytize. 作为光家族的成员来劝导改宗它不是你们的任务。 3. The Taoism from the outset it to peom to proselytize, to expand social influence. 该教从创始之初便以词来传教，扩大社会影响力。 4. If you try to proselytize someone, or battle them over a hot topic like abortion, you may reach a point of no return. 如果你试图让对方改变信仰，或者在一些，如堕胎这样的敏感问题上说服对方，那你以后想要改变观点也不行了。', '名词: proselytization 过去式: proselytized 过去分词: proselytized 现在分词: proselytizing 第三人称单数: proselytizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('earplug', '[\'ɪrplʌɡ]', 'n.耳栓，耳塞', '1. Luckily we took earplug with us, as the traffic outside our room was very noisy. 真幸运，我们带有耳塞，因为房间外面的车辆噪音太大。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exclamation', '[ˌeksklə\'meɪʃn]', 'n.惊呼；惊叹词', '1. I wish the exclamation mark had not been painted out, it would have made the slogan more forceful. 我想那个惊叹号要是没有被涂掉就好了，它会使标语更加有力。 2. My sainted aunt! ie as an exclamation expressing surprise. 我的妈呀! (表示惊讶的用语). 3. \"Good heavens!\" is an exclamation of surprise. “天哪！”是一个表示惊讶的感叹语。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('floppy', '[\'flɑːpi]', 'adj.松软的；懒散的 n.软盘 (=floppy disk)', '1. She was wearing a big floppy hat. 她戴了顶松软的大帽子。 2. This material\'s too floppy for a jacket. 这种料子做夹克衫太软了。 3. He was confused in mind and floppy in life. 他思想上糊里糊涂，生活上懒懒散散。 4. If you have such a floppy available now, put it in the drive, and continue. 如果您有这样一个可用的软盘，将他放入软驱，然后继续。', '副词: floppily 比较级: floppier 最高级: floppiest 名词: floppiness 名词复数: floppies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clandestine', '[klæn\'destɪn]', 'adj.秘密的(常指违法的行为)', '1. They had a clandestine meeting in the park yesterday. 昨天他们在公园开了个黑会。', '副词: clandestinely 名词: clandestineness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('closet', '[\'klɑːzət]', 'n.壁橱；衣帽间；密室；厕所 adj.隐藏的；不公开的；空谈的 vt.把 ... 关在房间里', '1. Put the coats back into the closet. 请把大衣放回到壁橱里。 2. You may put these books in the closet. 你可以把这些书放在壁橱里。 3. The Prince\'s bedroom is large, but his closet is larger. 王子的卧室也很大,不过他的衣帽间则更大。 4. The loser closely enclosed himself in the closet. 那个失败者把自己严密地封闭在小室内。 5. We must guard against closet racists. 我们必须警惕隐蔽的种族主义者。 6. He used to closet himself with a book. 过去他常把自己关在小房间里读书。', '名词: closetful 过去式: closeted 过去分词: closeted 现在分词: closeting 第三人称单数: closets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solace', '[\'sɑːləs]', 'n.安慰；慰藉 v.使快乐；使安慰；使缓和', '1. The sick man found solace in music. 那男病人从音乐中获得了安慰。 2. I\'m afraid he took his solace in drink. 恐怕他是借酒浇愁。 3. His work has been a real solace to him. 他从工作中得到莫大的慰藉。 4. I usually solace myself with music. 我通常用音乐抚慰自己。', '名词: solacer 过去式: solaced 过去分词: solaced 现在分词: solacing 第三人称单数: solaces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ventriloquist', '[ven\'trɪləkwɪst]', 'n.作腹语者；口技表演者', '1. To practice your ventriloquist voice, keep your lips motionless. 要练习以腹语术发声,你得保持双唇不动。 2. Every ventriloquist carries a dummy of their own. 所有的口技表演者都随身带着人偶。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('facade', '[fə\'sɑːd]', 'n.建筑物的正面；外表(犹指虚伪的)', '1. That is the facade of the Palace. 那是宫殿的正面。 2. The figure belongs to one of the colossi of the facade. 该头像属于神殿正面的一尊巨像。 3. His fine clothes are a mere facade. 他漂亮的衣着只是虚有其表而已。 4. Squalor and poverty lay behind the city\'s glittering facade. 这城市表面繁华,背后却肮脏和贫困。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('memorial', '[mə\'mɔːriəl]', 'n.纪念碑；纪念物；纪念仪式 adj.纪念的；追悼的', '1. This memorial commemorates those who died in the war. 这座纪念碑是纪念战争中牺牲者的。 2. The site of the memorial is granted in perpetuity to Canada. 纪念馆址已选定在加拿大作为永久的纪念。 3. People came to the memorial to revere the memory of the great leader. 人们来到纪念馆崇敬地纪念这位伟大的领袖。 4. His memorial was engraved on the stone. 纪念他的碑文刻在石碑上。 5. He made an entry of the memorial events in his diary. 他将可纪念的大事记入日记中。', '副词: memorially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distribute', '[dɪ\'strɪbjuːt]', 'v.分配；散发；分布', '1. Please distribute books among the students. 把书发给学生。 2. Clothes and blankets have been distributed among the refugees. 向难民分发了衣服和毯子。 3. We distribute handbills on the street every weekend. 我们每周都要在街上散发传单。 4. Some types of plants are widely distributed. 有些植物分布得很广。', '过去式: distributed 过去分词: distributed 现在分词: distributing 第三人称单数: distributes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assert', '[ə\'sɜːrt]', 'vt.断言；主张，坚持；生效；维护', '1. She asserted that he was innocent. 她断言，他是无罪的。 2. Upon inspection, we assert that the systems development process is empirical 通过以上分析,我们断言系统开发过程是经验的 3. We encouraged him to assert his view of the matter. 我们鼓励他坚持自己对此事的看法。 4. The laws of historical development will assert themselves. 历史发展的规律是不可抗拒的。', '形容词: assertable 名词: asserter 过去式: asserted 过去分词: asserted 现在分词: asserting 第三人称单数: asserts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avaricious', '[ˌævə\'rɪʃəs]', 'adj.贪财的；贪婪的', '1. He is so avaricious that we call him a blood sucker. 他如此贪婪, 我们都叫他吸血鬼。 2. Midas is a legendary king of Phrygia who was insatiably avaricious. 迈达斯是传说中弗律癸亚国的国王，他是一个贪得无厌的人。', '副词: avariciously 名词: avariciousness');
