INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recruit', '[rɪ\'kruːt]', 'v.吸收(新成员)；征兵；招聘 n.新成员；新兵', '1. We are having difficulties in recruiting well-qualified staff. 我们难以招募到素质好的职员。 2. His job was to recruit for the army. 他的工作是为陆军募兵。 3. We lower the standards in order to recruit real talents. 我们降低标准是为了招纳真正的人才。 4. This job presents many difficulties to the new recruit. 这件工作对那个新手来说困难重重。', '名词: recruiter 过去式: recruited 过去分词: recruited 现在分词: recruiting 第三人称单数: recruits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harridan', '[\'hærɪdən]', 'n.脾气暴躁的老妇人；老泼妇', '1. She was a mean old harridan. 她是一个吝啬的，脾气暴躁的老妇人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('browse', '[braʊz]', 'v.浏览；随意观看；吃草 n.嫩叶；浏览', '1. He likes to browse through the books in the public library. 他喜欢在公立图书馆浏览各种书籍。 2. I spent hours browsing in the bookstore. 我花了几个小时在书店里浏览图书。 3. You are welcome to come in and browse. 欢迎您光临本店随便看看。 4. The deer mainly browse on wild vegetation not crops. 鹿主要吃野生植物，而不是吃庄稼。 5. I had a browse through the books on the shelf. 我浏览了一遍书架上的书。', '过去式: browsed 过去分词: browsed 现在分词: browsing 第三人称单数: browses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intelligible', '[ɪn\'telɪdʒəbl]', 'adj.可理解的；明白易懂的；清楚的', '1. His theory is not intelligible to us. 他的理论我们无法理解。 2. The book is intelligible to anyone. 这本书任何人都看得懂。 3. The answers must be intelligible, but they do not have to be in complete sentences. 答案必须要清楚明晰，不过不必是完整的句子。', '副词: intelligibly 名词: intelligibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('waggish', '[\'wæɡɪʃ]', 'adj.诙谐的；滑稽的', '1. Waggish behavior or spirit; drollery. 诙谐幽默的行为或气氛；玩笑 2. Waggish behavior or spirit;drollery. 诙谐幽默的行为或气氛;玩笑 3. \"Muskrat Castle, as the house had been facetiously named by some waggish officer\" (James Fenimore Cooper). “马斯克拉特城堡，是一些机智幽默的军官给这所房子所起的滑稽的名字” （詹姆斯·费尼莫尔·库珀）。 4. During this melancholy pause, the turnkey read his newspaper with a waggish look. 在这个忧郁的停歇期间，看守滑稽地阅读着报纸。', '副词: waggishly 名词: waggishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brood', '[bruːd]', 'n.一窝；一伙；一家孩子；一组事物 v.孵；沉思；笼罩', '1. The bird was trying to find food for its brood. 鸟儿在为它的一窝小鸟觅食。 2. She grew up amidst a lively brood of brothers and sisters. 她是在一群活泼的兄弟姐妹中间长大的。 3. A brood of modern paintings will be exhibited at the museum. 一批现代画将在博物馆展览。 4. The hen broods ten eggs this time. 这次母鸡孵十个蛋。', '副词: broodingly 过去式: brooded 过去分词: brooded 现在分词: brooding 第三人称单数: broods');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dedication', '[ˌdedɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.奉献；献词；献堂礼', '1. Her dedication to her work was admirable. 她对工作的奉献精神可钦可佩。 2. She wanted to buy his love with her dedication to him and his work. 她想通过自己对他及其工作的奉献来换取他的爱。 3. His talent and dedication will insure his success. 他的才气和执着将确保他成功。 4. The book\'s dedication reads \"To Mother\". 本书献词写道：“献给母亲”。', '形容词: dedicative');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recipient', '[rɪ\'sɪpiənt]', 'n.接受者；收信人', '1. China is now the world\'s sixth-largest trading partner and the second-largest recipient of foreign investment after the United States. 中国现在是世界第6大贸易国，仅次于美国的世界第二大外国投资接受国。 2. The recipients of prizes had their names printed in the paper. 获奖者名单登在报上。 3. The postman spent almost a whole day looking for the recipient of the letter. 邮递员几乎花了整整一天时间寻找该信的收信人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gloomy', '[\'ɡluːmi]', 'adj.阴暗的；忧闷的；前景黯淡的', '1. Being alone in that gloomy house gave me the willies. 我一个人在那所阴暗的房子心里就发毛。 2. A few faint gleams of sunshine lit up the gloomy afternoon. 有几束隐约的阳光使阴暗的下午有些明亮。 3. Her smile is a breath of fresh air in this gloomy office. 她的微笑给沉闷的办公室带来生气。 4. There is a gloomy, overcast expression on his face. 他愁眉苦脸。', '副词: gloomily 比较级: gloomier 最高级: gloomiest 名词: gloominess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('threadbare', '[\'θredber]', 'adj.磨破的；陈腐的', '1. The carpets had worn rather threadbare. 地毯已磨得相当破旧了。 2. He had thrummed upon this topic till it is threadbare. 他对这个问题一再发言已使它成为陈词滥调。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intermingle', '[ˌɪntər\'mɪŋɡl]', 'v.混合；搀和；交织', '1. Oil and water will not intermingle. 油和水不相融。 2. The neighbors do not intermingle with each other. 左邻右舍不互相来往。 3. This book intermingled fact with fiction. 这本书事实和虚构情节交织。', '过去式: intermingled 过去分词: intermingled 现在分词: intermingling 第三人称单数: intermingles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lackey', '[\'læki]', 'n.仆人；侍从；走狗；马屁精 v.服侍；侍候；奉承', '1. An accomplice or a lackey who aids in the commission of base or disreputable acts. 同谋，同伙共犯或帮凶，其帮助实施无耻或下流的行为 2. A person of slavish or unquestioning obedience; a lackey. 象奴隶般的人一个象奴隶一般顺从或无条件服从的人; 卑躬屈膝者', '名词复数: lackeys 过去式: lackeyed 过去分词: lackeyed 现在分词: lackeying 第三人称单数: lackeys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tarry', '[\'tæri]', 'v.耽搁；逗留 adj.用柏油覆盖的', '1. Then open the door, and flee, and tarry not. 说完了，就开门逃跑，不要迟延。 2. Why did he tarry so long on his way? 他为什么在途中耽搁了那么久? 3. He tarried for a few days in my house. 他在我家里小住了几天。 4. Tarry awhile at this charming country inn. 在这个可爱的乡村小酒馆里呆一会儿吧。 5. This road needs to be tarry so that it can last longer. 这条路需要用柏油覆盖才能用更长的时间。', '比较级: tarrier 最高级: tarriest 名词: tarrier 过去式: tarried 过去分词: tarried 现在分词: tarrying 第三人称单数: tarries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('egalitarian', '[iˌɡælɪ\'teriən]', 'adj.平等主义的 n.平等主义者', '1. I am lways in an egalitarian stance. 我总是站在平等主义的立场上。 2. Some economists have used these results as egalitarian debating points. 一些经济学家把这些结果当作平等主义的一大论据。', '名词: egalitarianism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('epigram', '[\'epɪɡræm]', 'n.警句；诙谐短诗；精辟的措辞', '1. He fashioned no stilted epigram. 他不追求夸张的警句。 2. Sunddly a image or epigram light up the whole mood. 一个突如其来的形象或警句突然把意境照亮。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('auspicious', '[ɔː\'spɪʃəs]', 'adj.吉利的；幸运的；有利的', '1. The publication of my first book was an auspicious beginning of my career. 我的第一本书的出版是我事业吉祥的开始。 2. The new boy had an auspicious first day in the elementary school. 这个新来的男孩在小学校里有幸运的第一天。 3. Among historians of science, that\'s what is known as a rollicking and auspicious start. 在科学历史学家中，这就是所谓的快乐而幸运的开始。 4. The project had an auspicious beginning. 这个计划有一个良好的开端。', '副词: auspiciously 名词: auspiciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skirt', '[skɜːrt]', 'n.裙子；下摆；边缘；郊区；挡板 v.装边于；位于(边缘)；绕开', '1. How many skirts do you have? 你有多少条裙子？ 2. She tore her skirt on the nail. 钉子勾破了她的裙子。 3. Her skirt has very exquisite lace. 她的裙子有非常精致的花边。 4. She smoothed down the skirt of her dress. 她把连衣裙的下摆弄平。 5. The road skirted the woods. 这条路环绕林子。', '过去式: skirted 过去分词: skirted 现在分词: skirting 第三人称单数: skirts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('motto', '[\'mɑːtoʊ]', 'n.座右铭；箴言', '1. Who is the subscriber of that motto? 谁是那条座右铭的签字者? 2. Humility is the motto in his life. 谦卑是他的人生座右铭. 3. \"Proud, not complacent,\" the motto has always accompanied me. “自豪，但不自满” 这句箴言总是陪伴我。', '名词复数: mottoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('artistry', '[\'ɑːrtɪstri]', 'n.艺术性；艺术才能', '1. She was praised for her beauty and artistry. 人们称赞她的美丽和艺术气质。 2. Second, Bunin also adopts artistry synthesis. 其次，布宁还采用了艺术综合性。 3. He played the piece with effortless artistry. 他游刃有余地演奏了这首乐曲。 4. It takes imagination and artistry to write even a short piece of music. 即使创作一支短乐曲也需要想象和艺术才能。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('urchin', '[\'ɜːrtʃɪn]', 'n.顽童；[动]海胆；<古>刺猬', '1. You should sheer off the urchin. 你应该躲避这顽童。 2. Her hands were small and brown, an urchin\'s hands. 她那双手很小，有点淡褐色，简直就是一双顽童的手。 3. An urchin who had frequently seen him before, stopped to gaze. 一个以前常在那里看见他的顽童，停下来观望着。 4. The photo shows the scene of harvesting sea urchin. 图为海胆收获的场景。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mural', '[\'mjʊrəl]', 'adj.墙壁的；挂在墙壁上的 n.壁画', '1. There is a large mural in the temple. 那个寺院里有一幅很大的壁画。 2. Now we\'re going to learn mural painting. 我们现在要学画壁画儿了。', '名词: muralist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('axiom', '[\'æksiəm]', 'n.公理；格言；自明之理', '1. It’s a very cliched and abused axiom. 这简直就是陈词滥调和滥用公理。 2. The concern about this axiom stemmed from the fact. 对于这个公理的考虑是基于这样的事实。 3. I\'ve never deviated from that axiom. 我从来没有违背过这项原则。 4. This was not the axiom he wanted. 他需要的可不是这种不言自明的道理。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indite', '[ɪn\'daɪt]', 'vt.著作、撰写（诗、文等）', '1. She will indite him to some supper. 她要拉他吃晚饭。 2. Drama\'s indite was also inescapability. 戏曲创作也不可避免地浸染了时代的色彩。 3. I\'m hopeless how to indite a waltz. 创作圆舞曲我是一窍不通。 4. This essay is written just for trying to indite article in English. 此散文仅仅是出于尝试用英文创作文章。', '名词: inditement 过去式: indited 过去分词: indited 现在分词: inditing 第三人称单数: indites');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extradite', '[\'ekstrədaɪt]', 'v.引渡回国；拿获归案', '1. France has applied to extradite her. 法国提出引渡她的申请。 2. The Spanish police have refused to extradite a man wanted for a bank robbery in France. 西班牙警方拒绝引渡一个在法国抢劫银行而被通缉的人。', '过去式: extradited 过去分词: extradited 现在分词: extraditing 第三人称单数: extradites');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forfeiture', '[\'fɔːrfətʃər]', 'n.(财产等）没收；（名誉等）丧失', '1. Non-payment is forbidden under penalty of forfeiture. 严禁不支付,违者处以没收 (财产等) 的处罚。 2. The vanishment of Forfeiture of Property is an inexorable historical trend. 没收财产刑走向消亡是历史的必然趋势。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cellar', '[\'selər]', 'n.地窖；地下室 vt.把 ... 藏入地窑', '1. This wine cellar stays at an even temperature all year round. 这个酒窖常年保持恒温。 2. The cellar floods whenever it rains heavily. 一下大雨地窖里就灌满了水。 3. The cheese molded in the damp cellar. 乳酪在潮湿的地下室中长了霉。 4. They were ensconced in the cellar. 他们躲在地下室里。 5. The wine has been cellared for ten years. 酒在地窖里存了十年。', '过去式: cellared 过去分词: cellared 现在分词: cellaring 第三人称单数: cellars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pelagic', '[pə\'lædʒɪk]', 'adj.远洋的', '1. The ship is engaged in pelagic fishery. 这艘船从事远洋渔业。 2. Pelagic sediment contains tiny grain of material. 远洋沉积物包含了微细物质颗粒。 3. The kittiwakes return from their pelagic winter wanderings. 三趾鸥从冬季远洋漫游中归来了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('behold', '[bɪ\'hoʊld]', 'vt.看到；注视；领悟 vi.看；看啊(多用于祈使句；引起人的注意)', '1. They beheld the great wall. 他们看到了雄伟的长城。 2. We got up early to behold the sunrise. 我们早起观看了日出。 3. We beheld a beautiful vista before us. 我们注视着前面美丽的风景 4. Behold! What a beautiful sight it is! 看呀!这风景多么美丽!', '名词: beholder 过去式: beheld 过去分词: beheld 现在分词: beholding 第三人称单数: beholds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('district', '[\'dɪstrɪkt]', 'n.地区；行政区 vt.把 ... 划分成区', '1. This district used to grow cotton on a large scale. 这个地区过去大量种棉花。 2. We wish to be your agent in our district if the commission rate is favorable. 如佣金率优惠,我们愿意做你方在我们地区的代理。 3. He was elected the district attorney. 他被选为地方检察官。 4. The expressway rounded about the urban district. 高速公路环绕着市区。 5. The officials related have districted the city into three electoral districts. 相关官员把该市划分成三个选区。', '副词: districtwide 过去式: districted 过去分词: districted 现在分词: districting 第三人称单数: districts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swerve', '[swɜːrv]', 'vi.突然转向；转弯；偏离方向 vt.使突然转向；使转弯 n.转向；偏离方向；偏离的程度', '1. Don\'t race or swerve or suddenly hit your brakes. 不要赛车或者忽然转向或者忽然刹车。 2. If a spell targets the same player or object multiple times, you can\'t target it with Swerve. 如果某咒语将同一位牌手或物件多次指定为目标，你便无法指定它为方向偏离的目标。', '过去式: swerved 过去分词: swerved 现在分词: swerving 第三人称单数: swerves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('terminology', '[ˌtɜːrmə\'nɑːlədʒi]', 'n.术语；术语学', '1. Don\'t punish our brain with technical terminology. 别用术语来让我们伤脑筋了。 2. The article uses rather specialized musical terminology. 这篇文章用了相当专业的音乐术语。 3. Terminology is a complex cross-disciplinary science. 术语学是一门综合性的应用学科。 4. All language professionals acknowledge the crucial role of terminology. 语言工作者均了解术语学的重要作用。', '形容词: terminological 副词: terminologically 名词: terminologist 名词复数: terminologies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dermatologist', '[ˌdɜːrmə\'tɑːlədʒɪst]', 'n.皮肤学者；皮肤科医生', '1. I think you should see a dermatologist first. 我认为您应当先看皮肤科大夫。 2. Lisa is going to see a dermatologist for her bad skin rash. 莉莎的皮肤起了严重的疹子，她要去看皮肤科医生。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flint', '[flɪnt]', 'n.打火石；极硬的东西', '1. It is possible to strike fire from flint. 火石可以打火。 2. This layer of rock contains a lot of flint. 这一岩层中有大量燧石。 3. He has a heart of flint. 他有一副铁石心肠。 4. She gave him a look as hard as flint. 她冷酷地瞪他一眼。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('centurion', '[sen\'tʃʊriən]', 'n.百人队队长（古罗马军团的百人队指挥官）', '1. When Jesus had entered Capernaum, a centurion came to him, asking for help. 耶稣进了迦百农,有一个百夫长前来求助。', '形容词: centurial');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hunk', '[hʌŋk]', 'n.大块；<俚>有魅力的健壮男子', '1. She tore off a large hunk of bread. 她撕下了一大块面包。 2. An old pal is bringing me a two-carat hunk of ice. 一位老朋友要带给我一颗两克拉重的钻石。 3. You\'re quite a hunk yourself, you know. 要知道，你也是一个迷人的小伙子。 4. Most girls wish they can meet a sensitive hunk, with brains. 大多数的女孩都希望能遇到一位细心、有脑筋又有魅力的健壮美男子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tyranny', '[\'tɪrəni]', 'n.暴政；苛政；专制', '1. They will fight tyranny to the death. 他们誓死反对暴政。 2. Revolution is a frequent outgrowth of tyranny. 革命是暴政促成的常有结果。 3. Tyranny is fiercer than a tiger. 苛政猛于虎。 4. The world suffers most from the disinterested tyranny of its well wisher. 世界在漠然的苛政中为善者承受极大的痛楚。', '名词复数: tyrannies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('libido', '[lɪ\'biːdoʊ]', 'n.欲望；性欲；生命力', '1. Testosterone is one of the hormones controlling libido in human beings. 睾丸素是人体中控制欲望的一种荷尔蒙。 2. It is essential to your libido and sexual arousal. 这对维持你的性欲和性唤起至关重要。', '形容词: libidinal 副词: libidinally 名词复数: libidos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pithy', '[\'pɪθi]', 'adj.简练的；有髓的', '1. This article is short and pithy. 这篇文章短小精悍。 2. His pithy comments knocked the bottom out of my argument. 他精辟的评论驳倒了我的论点。 3. I enjoy reading his essays because they are compact and pithy. 他的文章简洁而精辟, 我很喜欢读。', '副词: pithily 比较级: pithier 最高级: pithiest 名词: pithiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sociable', '[\'soʊʃəbl]', 'adj.好交际的；社交的', '1. Roger is a very sociable person. 罗杰是个非常好交际的人。 2. But they were a sociable family and liked their neighbors, especially the O\'Hara girls. 不过塔尔顿家是个好交际的家庭，喜欢和邻居尤其是奥哈拉家的姑娘拉来往。 3. As a whole they are friendly and sociable people. 作为一个整体，他们是友善而好社交的人。 4. Sociable people, those who like to be with others, like red. 喜欢社交的人，喜欢和他人在于起的人都喜欢红色。', '副词: sociably 名词: sociableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clinical', '[\'klɪnɪkl]', 'adj.临床的；冷静的', '1. The scientists plan to start human clinical trials in the coming months. 科学家们计划在几个月内开展人类临床试验。 2. Clinical trials of the anti-cancer drug have produced encouraging results. 抗癌药物的临床试验结果令人鼓舞。 3. He seemed to have a rather clinical view of the breakup of his marriage. 他似乎是相当冷静地看待自己的婚姻破裂。 4. He watched her suffering with clinical detachment. 他冷漠地看著她遭受的痛苦。', '副词: clinically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disinter', '[ˌdɪsɪn\'tɜːr]', 'v.挖出；掘出', '1. The court granted him permission to disinter the body. 法院批准他掘出尸体。', '名词: disinterment 过去式: disinterred 过去分词: disinterred 现在分词: disinterring 第三人称单数: disinters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carve', '[kɑːrv]', 'v.雕刻；切割', '1. The statue was carved out of marble. 这座雕像是用大理石雕刻的。 2. We will look for a pumpkin, to carve into a jack-o-lantern. 我们将要找一颗南瓜来雕刻成南瓜灯。 3. He carved me some very nice pieces of chicken. 他为我切了几块很好的鸡肉。 4. It\'s your turn to carve the meat. 该你来把肉切开了。', '名词: carver 过去式: carved 过去分词: carved 现在分词: carving 第三人称单数: carves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deify', '[\'deɪɪfaɪ]', 'vt. 神化； 把 ... 当作神来崇拜或敬畏； 崇拜', '1. Primitive peoples deified the sun. 原始部落将太阳奉为神。 2. She deifies her leader very much. 她非常崇拜她的领导。', '名词: deifier 过去式: deified 过去分词: deified 现在分词: deifying 第三人称单数: deifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mastermind', '[\'mæstərmaɪnd]', 'n.聪明人；智多星；策划者 v.(巧妙地)策划', '1. School has made him into a mastermind. 学校使他变成了一个足智多谋的人。 2. The mastermind behind the scheme is executed after a brief trial. 阴谋的幕后策划者经过简短审讯便被处决了。 3. The mastermind of the expedition was a Frenchman. 这次探险的策划者是一个法国人。 4. Wishes can become a reality if you mastermind a way to get what you want. 如果你手段高明并极力争取自己想要的,愿望很快就能变成现实。', '过去式: masterminded 过去分词: masterminded 现在分词: masterminding 第三人称单数: masterminds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boding', '[\'boʊdɪŋ]', 'n.凶兆；前兆；预兆 adj.凶兆的；预兆的 动词bode的现在分词形式.', '1. The bad trading figures do not bode well. 这些交易数额欠佳，预示公司前景不妙。 2. His careful habits bode well for his future. 他那认真的习惯预示著他会有好的前途。 3. If we bide our time the chance will come. 只要我们等待时机，总会有希望的。 4. His idle habits bode ill for his future. 他的懒惰习惯预示他将来不会有好的前途。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whelm', '[welm]', 'v. 用 ... 覆盖； 淹没', '1. We whelm with tears at this time. 我们在这个时刻不由得感动泪流。 2. If Elfarran be not my own, I will unsay Segoy\\\'s word, I will unmake the islands, the white waves will whelm all. 叶芙阮若非我所有，我将毁言兮果乙之字，我将毁灭岛屿，由白浪淹没万世。 3. Things have been improving since those darks days, but the comeback story is getting a little stale with investors, who are tired that the company always seems to under whelm and lower expectations. 这段黑暗时期过后，情况出现了好转，但这样的复苏故事已让投资者感到有些厌倦，他们已被该公司的平淡业绩和低下预期弄得疲惫不堪。 4. under whelm 很不起眼; 无足轻重', '过去式: whelmed 过去分词: whelmed 现在分词: whelming 第三人称单数: whelms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('engrossment', '[ɪn\'groʊsmənt]', 'n.用大字写；占去 ... 所有的时间；囤积居奇，大量收买；全神贯注', '1. John was reading with engrossment. 约翰正在全神贯注地阅读。 2. His paper would then engross his thoughts. 然后，他就会埋头看报了。 3. To write or print a final copy of;engross. 请将银行汇付底单复印件一份发往本校。 4. Engross yourself in the benefits of your new habit. 了解你能从新习惯里获取什么利益。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rampant', '[\'ræmpənt]', 'adj.猖獗的；蔓延的；猛烈的；[纹]跃立的', '1. Sickness was rampant in the country. 疾病在这个国家猖獗。 2. Malaria is still rampant in some swampy regions. 疟疾在一些沼泽地区仍很猖獗。 3. Anarchy was rampant after the dictator died. 独裁者死后政治混乱猖獗。 4. Dissension is rampant among the members of the committee. 意见分歧在委员会的成员中蔓延。', '副词: rampantly 名词: rampancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flimflam', '[\'flɪmflæm]', 'n.胡说；胡扯；荒唐 vt.骗；骗取', '1. I might do something flimflam for the pain of this weakness. 我因如此而感到痛苦而渐渐荒唐胡闹下去。', '名词: flimflammer 过去式: flimflammed 过去分词: flimflammed 现在分词: flimflamming 第三人称单数: flimflams');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('babble', '[\'bæbl]', 'v.含糊不清地说；喋喋不休；潺潺作声 n.含糊不清的声音；潺潺声', '1. The baby babbled for hours. 那婴孩呀呀学语了好几个小时。 2. Don\'t babble the secret (out) to them. 别多嘴把秘密泄露给他们。 3. Pockets of silence are better than padding an interview with random babble. 片刻间歇的沈默比用胡言乱语填充面试要更好。 4. The water will cling round your feet and babble its secret. 湖水将回绕在你的脚边，潺潺地说出它的秘密。 5. I heard the babble of many voices. 我听到许多乱哄哄的说话声。', '过去式: babbled 过去分词: babbled 现在分词: babbling 第三人称单数: babbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ponderable', '[\'pɒndərəbəl]', 'adj.可秤的；有重量的；有价值的', '1. You should pause and ponder now. 你现在应该停下来仔细考虑一下。 2. I wanted to ponder the next move quietly. 我想平静地考虑下一步该怎么办。 3. Brigit didn\'t ponder on things too long. The morning was too lovely for problems or gloom. 布丽奇特对这些事情没有进行过多考虑。如此可爱的早晨不宜思考问题或闷闷不乐。 4. But it still remain a ponderable problem. 今南京方言属北方方言的江淮官话。', '名词: ponderability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decline', '[dɪ\'klaɪn]', 'v.下降；减少；变弱；拒绝；倾斜 n.衰微；跌落；晚年', '1. I wish prices would decline. 但愿物价下降。 2. The price of 14 inches TV set declined from 400 to 320 yuan each. 14英寸的电视机每台从400元降到320元。 3. He spent his declining years in the country. 他在乡间度过晚年。 4. I must regretfully decline your kind invitation. 我很抱歉必须拒绝你的盛情邀请。 5. This decline in vigour with the passing of time is called ageing. 这种随着时间流逝的活力衰退就叫做衰老。', '形容词: declinable 名词: decliner 过去式: declined 过去分词: declined 现在分词: declining 第三人称单数: declines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aesthete', '[\'esθiːt]', 'n.审美家 =esthete.', '1. Nobody will deny that Wilde is an outstanding aesthete. 毫无疑问，王尔德是一位杰出的唯美主义者。 2. He is a paradoxical aesthete as well as a paradoxical moralist. 他是一个矛盾的唯美主义者,同时他更是一个矛盾的道德家。', '异体字: esthete');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('epidemic', '[ˌepɪ\'demɪk]', 'n.流行病；传染病 adj.流行的；传染性的', '1. A flu epidemic raged through the school for weeks. 流感在这所学校里蔓延了几个星期。 2. The small town was suddenly struck by an epidemic. 小镇突然遭到传染病的袭击。 3. Violence is reaching epidemic levels. 暴力达到了流行的程度。 4. The corruption has become epidemic in the society. 这种腐化已成为社会上的一种歪风。', '副词: epidemically 异体字: epidemical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('awe', '[ɔː]', 'n.敬畏；恐惧 vt.使敬畏；使惊惧', '1. The children stared at the teacher with awe. 孩子很敬畏地凝视着老师。 2. We all listened to the venerable scholar with awe. 我们都怀着敬畏之心倾听着这位德高望重的学者的讲话。 3. An unsought pathos came hand in hand with awe. 与恐惧相随而来的是一种意想不到的悲怆。 4. No difficulty could awe these young men. 任何困难都吓不倒这些年轻人。', '过去式: awed 过去分词: awed 现在分词: awing 第三人称单数: awes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('osmosis', '[ɑːz\'moʊsɪs]', 'n.渗透；渗透性；潜移默化', '1. My mother taught me about the science of osmosis. 妈妈教我渗透的科学原理。 2. Blood can be cleaned by osmosis if the kidney has failed. 若肾功能衰退，可通过渗透作用使血液净化。 3. Children seem to learn about computers by osmosis. 孩子们似乎不知不觉地就了解了计算机. 4. He learned French by osmosis while residing in Paris for 15 years. 居住在巴黎的十五年中他已经潜移默化地学习了法语。', '形容词: osmotic 副词: osmotically 名词复数: osmoses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inquiry', '[ɪn\'kwaɪrɪ]', 'n.调查；询问；打听；查问 =enquiry(英).', '1. We made an application to the court for an inquiry. 我们曾请求法院调查。 2. They\'ve promised a thorough inquiry into the plane crash. 他们答应对这次飞机失事进行彻底的调查。 3. I\'m not able to help you with your inquiry. 我对你的咨询无能为力。 4. He is fishing for information by a letter of inquiry. 他写信询问，希望打听一下消息。', '异体字: enquiry 名词复数: inquiries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('salmon', '[\'sæmən]', 'n.鲑；大马哈鱼；橙红色的', '1. He planed to go fishing for salmon on Sunday. 他计划星期天去钓鲑鱼。 2. Do you have any fresh salmon in at the moment? 现在有新鲜大马哈鱼卖吗？', '名词复数: salmon');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lope', '[loʊp]', 'v.(使)大步慢跑 n.大步慢跑', '1. The tiger loped off into the jungle. 那老虎跑进丛林中去了。', '名词: loper 过去式: loped 过去分词: loped 现在分词: loping 第三人称单数: lopes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sift', '[sɪft]', 'v.筛下；筛分；详察', '1. Sift the flour before making the cake. 做蛋糕前先把面粉筛一下。 2. Snow sifted through the crack in the roof into the room. 雪从屋顶上的裂缝飘进屋里。 3. Sift out the wheat from the chaff. 把小麦的壳筛出来。 4. She had to sift ashes from the cinders. 她只好把煤渣中的灰筛出去。', '名词: sifter 过去式: sifted 过去分词: sifted 现在分词: sifting 第三人称单数: sifts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('archipelago', '[ˌɑːrkɪ\'peləɡoʊ]', 'n.群岛；多岛海', '1. Indonesia is the largest archipelago in the world. 印尼是世界上最大的群岛。 2. The archipelago continues for another 500 miles. 这个群岛又绵延了500英里。', '形容词: archipelagic 名词复数: archipelagoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plaza', '[\'plæzə]', 'n.广场；市场；购物中心', '1. The plaza in festival is a carpet of flowers. 节日的广场繁花似锦。 2. The plaza is bulging with people. 广场上满是人。 3. There\'s a grand fountain in the plaza. 广场上有一个壮丽的喷泉。 4. He gave me a ride to the plaza. 他让我搭车去市场。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eddy', '[\'edi]', 'n.漩涡；涡流 v.起漩涡；旋转', '1. The little paper boat was caught in an eddy and spun round and round in the water. 小纸船卷进了漩涡中，在水中直打转。 2. The motor car disappeared in eddy of dust. 汽车在一片扬尘的涡流中不见了。 3. The mist eddied round the old castle. 薄雾在那座古老的城堡的周围打转转。', '名词复数: eddies 过去式: eddied 过去分词: eddied 现在分词: eddying 第三人称单数: eddies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reprehend', '[ˌreprɪ\'hend]', 'vt.指责；责难', '1. Could Dell reprehend consumers who ordered products in low price? 戴尔是否可以指责每个消费向戴尔发出的低价订单？', '过去式: reprehended 过去分词: reprehended 现在分词: reprehending 第三人称单数: reprehends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jabber', '[\'dʒæbər]', 'v.快而不清楚地说话 n.含糊不清的话', '1. What is he jabbering about now? 他在叽里咕噜地说什么呢? 2. I would jabber on like a monkey in a tree. 我像树上的猴子一样一直说。 3. Don\'t jabber away when you can say it in a few words. 两句话能说完的事就别犯碎嘴子了。 4. Listen to the jabber of those monkeys. 听那些猴子在吱吱喳喳地叫。', '名词: jabberer 过去式: jabbered 过去分词: jabbered 现在分词: jabbering 第三人称单数: jabbers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('testify', '[\'testɪfaɪ]', 'v.作证；证明；声明', '1. He testified that he had not seen the accident. 他作证说他没有看见那次事故。 2. He agreed to testify on behalf of the accused man. 他同意为被告作证。 3. Her actions testify to her good character. 她的行为证明了她的人品是好的。 4. All kinds of human experience testify to the close link between love and fear. 人类的种种经验都证明了爱与怕之间的紧密联系。', '名词: testification 过去式: testified 过去分词: testified 现在分词: testifying 第三人称单数: testifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dumbfound', '[dʌm\'faʊnd]', 'vt. 使 ... 惊呆； 使 ... 发愣 =dumfound', '1. We were completely dumbfounded by her rudeness. 她粗鲁无礼，把我们吓呆了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blustering', '[\'blʌstərɪŋ]', 'adj.汹涌的；狂风大作的；狂暴的', '1. He always tries to bluster his way out of difficult situations. 他总是自吹自擂以摆脱困境。 2. I wasn\'t frightened by what he said it was just bluster. 他说的话吓不倒我－－不过是雷声大，雨点小。 3. He blustered his way through the crowd. 他吆喝着挤过人群。 4. The gale blustered all night. 大风刮了一夜。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slurp', '[slɜːrp]', 'v.饮食出声 n.吃喝的声音', '1. Stop slurping! 吃喝时别发出这麽大的声音！ 2. He was slurping (down) his soup. 他喝汤时发出啧啧的声音。 3. It is impolite to slurp your soup. 喝汤发出声音是不礼貌的。', '过去式: slurped 过去分词: slurped 现在分词: slurping 第三人称单数: slurps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forthright', '[\'fɔːrθraɪt]', 'adj.直截的；直率的；坦白的', '1. She gave him a forthright answer. 她给了他一个坦率的答覆。 2. His forthright behavior offends some people. 他那直率的行为冒犯了某些人。 3. His forthright behaviour shows that he\'s honest, but he seems rude to some people. 他的直率行为说明他是个诚实的人，可是有些人却认为他粗鲁。 4. His frank and forthright action deserves praise. 他光明磊落的行为值得称赞。', '副词: forthrightly 名词: forthrightness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('porous', '[\'pɔːrəs]', 'adj.可渗透的；多孔的', '1. We need to watch our plants so we become attuned to their needs, but small pots dry out faster than big ones and porous clay pots dry out faster than plastic ones. 我们必须经常观察我们的植物，这样才能了解它们的需要，但要注意小罐子比大罐子干透的时间更快，可渗透的粘土罐也比塑料罐子干透的时间更快。 2. Most soils and rocks are porous. 大部分土壤和岩石都是多孔的。 3. Oxford is a rather soft and porous cotton fabric. 牛浸布是一种颇为柔软，多孔的棉织物。', '副词: porously 名词: porousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('applicant', '[\'æplɪkənt]', 'n.申请人', '1. He gave every new applicant the once-over. 他匆匆地看一下每一个新来的申请人。 2. As the wage of the job was low, there were few applicants for it. 因为工资低,没有什么人申请这份工作。 3. The enterprise is an applicant of this credit. 这家企业是信用证的申请者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('podiatrist', '[pə\'daɪətrɪst]', 'n.脚病医生', '1. If none of these suggestions works and a podiatrist is not available, you might ask a friend or family member for help or get a professional pedicure at a beauty shop. 如果上面的建议对你而言都不可行，而且你也找不到脚病医生，你或许可以请你的朋友或者家人帮忙或者在美容店找个专业的修脚师。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('effervesce', '[ˌefə\'ves]', 'v.起泡沫；沸腾；兴奋', '1. The soda water is stale and doesn’t effervesce. 这苏打水没有气了，没有泡沫。这苏打水没有气了，没有泡沫。 2. Objective: To prepare Qingkailing effervesce granules. 目的:研制清开灵泡腾颗粒。 3. Made by rubber, effervesce layer to reduce the fatigue of the foot and legs. 采用橡胶制成，底部为发泡层，从而可减少脚步及腿部疲劳。 4. Result: The quality was stable by this technology to prepare Qingkailing effervesce granules. 结果:利用该工艺制备的清开灵泡腾颗粒,质量稳定。', '形容词: effervescent 副词: effervescently 名词: effervescence 过去式: effervesced 过去分词: effervesced 现在分词: effervescing 第三人称单数: effervesces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reparation', '[ˌrepə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.补偿；赔偿', '1. You must make reparation for the sorrow you have caused. 你必须对所造成的伤害予以补偿。 2. Offenders should be forced to make reparation to the community. 应该强迫违法犯罪分子对社会作出补偿。 3. I must demand reparation for the injury. 我必须要求损害的赔偿。 4. He had to make reparation from his own property. 他必须用其财产进行赔偿。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jettison', '[\'dʒetɪsn]', 'v.抛弃；丢弃；投弃 n.投弃；投弃的货物', '1. The first-stage vehicle is used to launch the rocket and is then jettisoned in the upper atmosphere. 第一级运载火箭是用来发射火箭的,进入高层大气后即抛掉。 2. We jettison an unworkable plan . 我们放弃难实行的计划。 3. We\'re going to jettison the cargo. 我们正准备投弃货物。 4. No jettison of cargo shall be allowed as general average, unless such cargo is carried in accordance with the recognised custom of the trade. 被抛弃的货物，除非按照公认的海运习惯运送，不得作为共同海损受到补偿。', '过去式: jettisoned 过去分词: jettisoned 现在分词: jettisoning 第三人称单数: jettisons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unpremeditated', '[ˌʌnpriː\'medɪteɪtɪd]', 'adj.无预谋的；非故意的；偶然的', '1. In profuse strains of unpremeditated art. 不事雕琢的艺术，倾吐你的衷心。 2. Slight unpremeditated Words are borne . 不加思索的轻率话语，. 3. The subjective behaviors show obviously their purposes and unpremeditated. 行为的主观方面表现为故意或过失; 4. There was fire in her and throughout her: she seemed the unpremeditated offshoot of a passionate moment. 她浑身上下有一团火，向四下发散着，像是在激情时刻不期而孕的一个子嗣。', '副词: unpremeditatedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('functional', '[\'fʌŋkʃənl]', 'adj.功能的；实用的；起作用的 n.【数】泛函', '1. What are the functional benefits of the brand? 你的品牌的功能方面的益处是什么? 2. This is a fully functional automaton. 这是一个有全自动功能的机器人。 3. The computer looks compact and functional. 这个计算机看起来小巧而实用. 4. Bathrooms don\'t have to be purely functional. 浴室不必完全只为了实用。', '副词: functionally 名词: functionality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intern', '[\'ɪntɜːrn]', 'n.实习生；拘留犯 vt.扣留 vi.作实习生', '1. The new intern is a little frisky. 这个新来的实习生有一点爱戏闹。 2. I was an administrative intern with the B. S. E. last summer. 我去年夏季在蓝星电子公司任管理实习生。 3. Susan may give you a instant position of Intern reporter. 苏珊可能会让你做一个临时的记者实习生。 4. He was just an intern. 他只不过是名拘留犯。 5. During the second world war,Japanese were interned in camps in the West. 第二次世界大战期间,日本士兵被扣留在西方国家的阵营里。 6. The young doctor is interning at the Medical Center this year. 今年这位年轻的医生要到医疗中心作实习生。', '名词: internship 过去式: interned 过去分词: interned 现在分词: interning 第三人称单数: interns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vogue', '[voʊɡ]', 'n.时尚；流行', '1. Hoop skirts were once the vogue. 圈环裙一度曾是时尚。 2. Now Vogue has delivered the same for men\'s wear. 如今,时尚已同样进入男装。 3. Decorate become a war, a gamble, a vogue is performed. 装修成为一场战争，一场赌博，一场时尚表演。 4. Short hair came back into vogue. 短发又开始流行起来了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('choice', '[tʃɔɪs]', 'n.选择；挑选；抉择 adj.上等的；精选的', '1. I believe that he can make a judicious choice. 我相信他能作出明智的选择。 2. The choice rests entirely with you. 这完全由你来选择。 3. We have no choice except to trust ourselves. 我们必须依靠自己,没有其他选择。 4. He is cautious in his choice of words. 他措辞很谨慎。 5. We select only the choicest apples for our pies. 我们精选最好的苹果制作馅饼。', '副词: choicely 比较级: choicer 最高级: choicest 名词: choiceness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('superiority', '[suːˌpɪri\'ɔːrəti]', 'n.优越性；优势', '1. This is the only way to demonstrate the superiority of socialism. 只有这样，才能表明社会主义的优越性。 2. Socialist democracy enjoys strong vitality and superiority. 社会主义民主政治具有强大的生命力和优越性。 3. Your army has numerical superiority over theirs. 与他们相比你们的军队占有人数优势。 4. He won the bout by great superiority. 他以绝对优势赢了这场比赛。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('constrain', '[kən\'streɪn]', 'vt.强迫；限制', '1. I felt constrained to do what he told me. 做他叫我做的事,我心里很不舒服。 2. She tried to constrain herself from a cough in class. 上课时她竭力忍住不咳嗽。 3. Cold weather constrains the plant\'s growth. 寒冷的天气抑制了植物的生长。 4. Don\'t constrain yourself only to class study. 不要把自己的学习只局限于课堂。', '形容词: constrainable 副词: constrainedly 名词: constrainer 过去式: constrained 过去分词: constrained 现在分词: constraining 第三人称单数: constrains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('turpitude', '[\'tɜːrpətuːd]', 'n. <正式>奸恶； 卑鄙； 背德', '1. Music is the only language which can not express turpitude and irony. 音乐是唯一不能用及表达卑鄙的或讽刺的事物的语言。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('truss', '[trʌs]', 'v.束紧；用桁架支撑 n.(干草的)一捆；一束；构架', '1. Truss the chicken before you roast it. 烤鸡前先将鸡贴身扎紧。 2. He was bearing a truss of trifles at his back. 他在背上背了一捆没有价值的杂物。 3. How to set up the operation truss suitable for China\'s private banks? 如何建立适合中国特点的私人银行业务构架?', '过去式: trussed 过去分词: trussed 现在分词: trussing 第三人称单数: trusses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irritation', '[ˌɪrɪ\'teɪʃn]', 'n.刺激；烦恼；刺激物', '1. Discontinue use if irritation or rash appear. 如果发生刺激或丘疹请停止使用。 2. May cause respiratory tract irritation. 五月引起呼吸器官的广阔地面刺激。 3. Aspirated material may also produce inflammation from chemical irritation, as with gastric contents. 吸入物如同胃内容物一样由于化学刺激物的作用可引起炎症。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compendium', '[kəm\'pendiəm]', 'n.简要；概略；提纲；手册', '1. The book is a compendium of their poetry, religion and philosophy. 这本书是他们诗歌、宗教和哲学的概略。 2. Instructions for using the tool can be found in the compendium. 在手册中可以找到这个工具的使用说明。', '名词复数: compendiums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('virtuosity', '[ˌvɜːrtʃu\'ɑːsəti]', 'n.精湛技巧；对艺术品的欣赏或爱好；艺术爱好者', '1. The violinist\'s virtuosity has amazed audiences all over the world. 小提琴家的精湛技艺使全世界的观众惊诧不已。', '名词复数: virtuosities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('puny', '[\'pjuːni]', 'adj.微小的；瘦弱的；微不足道的', '1. They laughed at my puny efforts at rock-climbing. 他们取笑我在攀岩活动中的那可怜劲儿。 2. Puny though he looked, he was as brave as a lion. 他看上去虽然瘦弱，但人很勇敢。 3. They laughed at my puny efforts. 他们嘲笑我微不足道的努力。 4. Some doctors are pretty puny characters. 医生中也不乏庸庸碌碌之辈。', '副词: punily 比较级: punier 最高级: puniest 名词: puniness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pun', '[pʌn]', 'n.双关语 vt.说双关语', '1. May my last breath is draw through a pipe and exhale in a pun. 希望我的最后一口气能够通过烟斗吸进来，然后呵成双关语。 2. This is a humorous pun, or play on words for hilarious effect. 这是一个幽默的双关语或是俏皮话来达到欢愉的效果。', '副词: punningly 过去式: punned 过去分词: punned 现在分词: punning 第三人称单数: puns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('treachery', '[\'tretʃəri]', 'n.叛变；背叛', '1. The stench of treachery hung in the air. 到处都是可耻的叛变的气息。 2. Treachery seems to have replaced loyalty. 叛变似乎已代替了忠诚。 3. Such treachery should be repaid in specie. 对这种奸诈应以同样的方式加以回报。 4. The officer was disgraced for his treachery. 那军官因背叛而被撤职。', '名词复数: treacheries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('status', '[\'steɪtəs]', 'n.地位；情形；状况，状态；身份', '1. Women\'s social status has changed much over the years. 这些年来妇女的社会地位有了很大改变。 2. I\'ll keep you posted on the status. 我会随时告诉你进展的情形。 3. We ask the bank to report on his financial status. 我们请银行报告他的财政状况。 4. There are many fine shadings of status through the social hierarchy. 在各个社会等级之间有许多细微的身分区别。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('valetudinarian', '[\'væləˌtjuːdən\'erɪən]', 'adj.有病的；虚弱的；过分担心健康的 n.病弱的人；过分担心健康的人', '1. He got sick easily since he was young, what a valetudinarian! 他从小就容易生病,是个药罐子。 2. Objective Check the ash of valetudinarian for plague before 50 years ,if exist plague in the soil near the ash. 目的检测死于50年前的鼠疫病人尸骨及尸骨周围土壤是否存在鼠疫菌。 3. At three and twenty he thought himself a valetudinarian, and passed his life in inspecting his tongue in the mirror. 二十三岁，他便以病夫自居，日日夜夜对着镜子看自己的舌头。 4. His method proved successful in his case,he was a valetudinarian,most people would need something more vigorous. 他的办法对他来说是成功的，但他是个体弱多病的人，而多数人需要的是精力充沛。', '名词: valetudinarianism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overt', '[oʊ\'vɜːrt]', 'adj.公开的；明显的；公然的', '1. In many emerging economies corruption is egregious and overt. 许多新兴经济体中的腐败是异乎寻常的和公开的。 2. Supreme People\'s Court promulgated the regulations on overt enforcement. 最高人民法院颁布执行公开的规定。 3. It was full of overt propaganda and the props were primitive. 节目充满了明显的宣传，一点也不精致，道具都是简单。 4. Spotting them can be tricky, since many animals display few overt symptoms. 确诊蓝舌病本身已经很难，因为很多染病动物并无明显的临床症状。', '副词: overtly 名词: overtness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('medley', '[\'medli]', 'n.混杂；[音]混成曲 adj.混杂的', '1. This always provokes a medley of cheers and boos. 这总是激起一阵欢呼声和讥笑声。 2. The menu described the dessert as \"a medley of exotic fruits\". 菜单上将这道甜点描述成“异国水果的大杂烩”。 3. He played a medley of Beatles songs. 他演奏一首披头士的混成曲。 4. A medley of songs brought the concert to a close. 演奏会以一段名曲集锦作为结束。 5. Today\'s sports meeting doesn\'t seem to include medley relay swimming. 现在的运动会好象还没有混合接力泳这个比赛项目。', '名词复数: medleys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bland', '[blænd]', 'adj.温和的；不油腻的；引不起兴趣的；平淡无奇的', '1. He said this with his face expanding in a bland smile. 他这样说着，脸上绽开了温和的笑容。 2. The sight of that bland,impregnably righteous face has been enough to make their blood run cold. 看见那张温和的而又非常正直的脸足够使他们冷静下来。 3. As a result news coverage tends to be bland. 结果新闻报道往往是平淡无奇的。 4. This will tend to produce either bland, have-a-nice-day standardisation of, more usually, various idiolects-private versions of the language---that work only in specific contexts. 这也许会带来平淡无奇的标准化语言，但更多的则是适用于特定环境的充满个人色彩的语汇。', '副词: blandly 比较级: blander 最高级: blandest 名词: blandness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('domesticate', '[də\'mestɪkeɪt]', 'vt.驯养；使专注于家务；教化 n.家禽；(家养)植物', '1. If you domesticate this raccoon,it will have trouble living in the wild. 如果你驯养这只浣熊，它生活在野外将会有困难。 2. Crusoe learns to plant crops, domesticate goats for milk, and even train a parrot for a pet. 鲁滨逊学会了种植粮食作物，驯养野羊，获取牛奶，甚至还训练出一只鹦鹉作宠物。', '名词: domestication 过去式: domesticated 过去分词: domesticated 现在分词: domesticating 第三人称单数: domesticates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chant', '[tʃænt]', 'n.圣歌；赞美诗；旋律；喊叫 v.吟唱；诵扬；叫喊', '1. Surviving books which contain complete written repertories of the chant with music do not appear before the tenth century, and are well established in the eleventh. 一些保存下来的古书中完整记载着十世纪音乐还没出现前的圣歌和在十一实际已经很好的配上音乐的圣歌。 2. What we call Gregorian chant today first appears distinctly in the Roman repertory of the fifth and sixth centuries. 我们现在说的格立高圣歌最早清楚的出现在5和6世纪的罗马剧目中。 3. The chant of the crowd was \"Work for all\". 群众反复有节奏地呼喊的是\"给大家工作\"。 4. The angels chant the chorus all day long. 天使们整天唱着圣歌，', '副词: chantingly 过去式: chanted 过去分词: chanted 现在分词: chanting 第三人称单数: chants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('derelict', '[\'derəlɪkt]', 'adj.抛弃的；玩忽职守的 n.被遗弃的人或物；玩忽职守者', '1. On the shore children still play, and fishermen drop anchor nearby, but the hulks of derelict hotels stand vacant. 海滨，孩子们依然在玩，而渔民已经在附近抛下了锚，但是被抛弃的旅馆的废壳空空的矗立在那儿。 2. The burying-ground is merely a huge waste of hummocky earth, like a derelict building-lot. 整个坟墓就是个巨大的半圆形的土丘，像一个被抛弃的建筑地基一样。 3. I\'m detached and moving toward the derelict spacecraft. 我准备脱离并前往被遗弃的太空船。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plaque', '[plæk]', 'n.匾；饰板；名牌；徽章；[医]齿菌斑', '1. A bronze plaque marks the house where the poet was born. 一块铜匾标示出诗人诞生的那所房子。 2. Cinderella\'s dress on the cutout plaque changes from white to gray to red and blue. 灰姑娘的礼服在保险开关匾改变从白色到灰色到红色和蓝色。 3. A plaque commemorates the battle. 有一块饰板用来纪念那次战役。 4. According to browse famous cases of plaque, study of ancient rubbings, explore the ancient stone tablets from each other, since the innovation environment, into a single cell. 宗照遍览名牌牌匾，研究古代拓片，探讨历代金石碑刻，取长补短，自创新境，独成一格。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cantata', '[kæn\'tɑːtə]', 'n.[音]康塔塔；清唱剧', '1. The cantata has a difficult vocal score. 这个康塔塔有个难度很大的声乐总谱。 2. The music of the song has been rearranged for the cantata. 这支歌已改编成大合唱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remainder', '[rɪ\'meɪndər]', 'n.剩余物；其余的人；[数]余数 vt.廉价出售', '1. The remainder must be paid by the end of June. 剩余部分的金额必须在月底前付清。 2. He spent the remainder of his life in the country. 他在乡村度过余生。 3. Nine people came in and the remainder stayed outside. 9个人进来，余下的人留在外面。 4. Take 4 from 9 and the remainder is 5. 9除以4余数为5。', '过去式: remaindered 过去分词: remaindered 现在分词: remaindering 第三人称单数: remainders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('characteristic', '[ˌkærəktə\'rɪstɪk]', 'n.特点；特性；特色 adj.典型的；特有的', '1. Ambition is a characteristic of all successful businessmen. 雄心勃勃是所有成功生意人的共同特点。 2. Kindness is one of his characteristics. 和善是他的特性之一。 3. A characteristic of the camel is its ability to live for a long time without water. 骆驼的特点是不喝水也能活很长时间。 4. They have been affected by trends in Italy too much to keep their own characteristics. 他们受意大利潮流的影响太大了,以致无法保持自己的特色。 5. It is the characteristic attitude of people towards life in those post-war years. 这是战后人们典型的处世态度。', '副词: characteristically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conception', '[kən\'sepʃn]', 'n.概念；观念；构想；怀孕', '1. I have no conception of what you mean. 我想不出你的意思是什么。 2. His conception of human nature is skewed. 他对人性的看法带有偏见。 3. That the earth is flat is an erroneous concept. 认为地球是平的观念是错的。 4. He\'s got a pretty strange conception of friendship. 他对友谊有一种非常独特的见解。', '形容词: conceptional 副词: conceptively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infiltrate', '[\'ɪnfɪltreɪt]', 'v.（使）渗透；（使）渗入；潜入', '1. The thick fog seemed to have infiltrated through the very walls into the room. 浓雾好像透过墙壁进到房间里。 2. The teacher tried to infiltrate her ideas into the children\'s minds. 老师设法把她的思想渗透到孩子们的心中。 3. Beware of the fifth column. They often infiltrate into key positions and seek to undermine the body politic from within. 要提防隐蔽的敌人，他们经常渗透到关键岗位企图从内部破坏国家政体。 4. The enemy infiltrated our land. 敌人混入我国领土。', '名词: infiltrator 过去式: infiltrated 过去分词: infiltrated 现在分词: infiltrating 第三人称单数: infiltrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('purify', '[\'pjʊrɪfaɪ]', 'v.(使）净化；（使）精炼；涤罪', '1. The endless lea will purify your thought. 一望无际的草原会净化你的思想。 2. Let\'s purify air with a negative ion generator. 我们用负离子发生器净化一下空气吧。 3. We have forgotten that Water can cleanse,and Fire purify,and that the Earth is mother to us all. 我们已经忘了，水可以洗濯洁净，火可以精炼提纯，大地是每个人的母亲。 4. Hindus purify themselves by bathing in the river Ganges. 印度教徒在恒河中浸泡借以涤罪。', '形容词: purificatory 名词: purifier 过去式: purified 过去分词: purified 现在分词: purifying 第三人称单数: purifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('priority', '[praɪ\'ɔːrəti]', 'n.优先权；优先；优先顺序', '1. This is the key and should be given top priority. 这是关键，要放在第一位。 2. Efficiency does not always have priority. 效率不一定总是优先。 3. Improving the plight of teachers is indeed a priority item. 改善教师的困难处境的确是优先处理的一件事情。', '名词复数: priorities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deficit', '[\'defɪsɪt]', 'n.赤字；逆差；亏损；亏空；不足', '1. The current trade deficit indicates a serious imbalance between our import and export trade. 当前的贸易赤字表明我们的进出口贸易严重失调。 2. That would still leave a substantial trade deficit. 这样仍然会出现巨额贸易逆差。 3. We have a great deficit this year. 我们今年有很大亏损。 4. The company had a deficit of 5000 dollars. 公司亏空了五千美元。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plush', '[plʌʃ]', 'adj.豪华的；优裕的；长毛绒的 n.长毛绒', '1. Its plush restaurants and cafes were the capital\'s political salon, awash with intelligence agents hoping to snoop on conversations. 其豪华的饭店和咖啡馆是重要的政治聚会场所，在那里随处是窥探情报的谍报人员。 2. Schroeder and Russian President Vladimir Putin exploited the photographers\' fixation on the goings-on on the terrace of the plush Hotel Royal to wander onto the lawn. 趁着记者们在豪华的皇家饭店的阳台上围着布什和希拉克，无暇顾及自己的空当，德国总理施罗德和俄罗斯总统普京溜到外面草坪上散步去了。 3. The little girl likes that plush toy bear the most. 小姑娘最喜欢的就是那个长毛绒的玩具小熊。 4. This material is a mixture fabric of pure wool and plush. 这种料子是纯羊毛与长毛绒的混纺织品。 5. This plush pug-dog is a new product. 这只长毛绒狮子狗是新产品。', '副词: plushly 比较级: plusher 最高级: plushest 名词: plushness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('animate', '[\'ænɪmeɪt]', 'v.使有生气；赋予生命；鼓励 adj.有生命的；有活力的', '1. A smile animated her face. 一丝笑容使她脸上平添了生气。 2. Jim\'s arrival served to animate the whole party. 吉姆的到来使聚会的整个气氛活跃了起来。 3. Animated by fresh hope, he started again. 他在新希望的激励之下，又从头做起。 4. His excitement animated us all. 他的激昂情绪振奋了我们大家。 5. The dog lay so still it scarcely seemed animate. 那条狗卧着一动也不动,简直不像活的。', '过去式: animated 过去分词: animated 现在分词: animating 第三人称单数: animates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cleavage', '[\'kliːvɪdʒ]', 'n.分裂；劈开；乳沟；[矿]解理；[生]卵裂', '1. This cleavage persisted during the whole civilized period. 这种分裂继续存在于整个文明期。 2. There was indeed a cleavage between them. 他们之间确有分岐。 3. He had made a great cleavage in his life. 他已在自己的生活里劈出了一条鸿沟。 4. That new gown shows a large amount of her cleavage! 那件新的女长服袒露出她大部分乳沟！', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('philistine', '[\'fɪlɪstiːn]', 'adj.市侩的 n.非利士人；平庸的人', '1. Time curbed the artist\'s pride and the philistine\'s vulgarity. 时间限制了艺术家的骄傲和市侩的鄙俗。 2. After that you will go to Gibeah of God, where there is a Philistine outpost. 此后你到神的山，在那里有非利士人的防兵。 3. At that time David was in the stronghold, and the Philistine garrison was at Bethlehem. 那时大卫在山寨，非利士人的防营在伯利恒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('smarmy', '[\'smɑːrmi]', 'adj.令人厌烦的；爱说奉承话的', '1. The waiters\' manners are always so smarmy. 那些服务员总是点头哈腰的. 2. I don\'t think being smarmy is going to work either. 我觉得奉承也不会有用。 3. Smarmy might work better, though it is difficult to bring off. 奉承也许会更有用，不过很难奏效。 4. Venue locations and the people that manage them can be smarmy. 建国以来难得一见的奇书，本书提供了两张地图---一张中国美食地图，以及基于“秀色可餐”的原理制作的中国美色地图。', '比较级: smarmier 最高级: smarmiest 名词: smarminess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grumpy', '[\'ɡrʌmpi]', 'adj.性情乖戾的；脾气暴躁的', '1. China has been a grumpy taker in this process. 在这过程中中国是个暴躁的攫取者。 2. If you find that your grumpy mood is becoming a habit, try expressive writing. 如果你觉得暴躁的情绪将成为一种习惯时，那么就试试写作吧。', '副词: grumpily 比较级: grumpier 最高级: grumpiest 名词: grumpiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lissome', '[\'lɪsəm]', 'adj.柔软的(敏捷的；轻快的)', '1. The lissome birchbark canoe seemed to be a fish, so easily did it cut through the rolling black waves and ranks of ice. 轻盈的桦皮舟像一条大鱼，在滚滚的黑色波涛和冰排中间飞一般地前进。 2. It seems Toto has his second kiss from a lissome banker\'s daughter, a rainstorm buss worthy of Anna Magnani. 似乎托托的二吻给了一个灵巧的银行家的女儿，安娜马格娜妮暴风雨般的吻。 3. Easy and flexible: The outside has non-slip, lissome and artistic, operate easily and can carry it in the pocket. 灵活方便:外表面深度防滑处理，轻盈美观，可放在衣袋中携带，操作简单方便。 4. He was charmed by the pale face, the lissome figure, draped in pearl grey, with a coiled string of pearls at the throat. 她令他着迷--苍白的脸色，婀娜的身影，珠灰色的衣裙，颈子上挂着的珍珠项链。', '副词: lissomely 名词: lissomeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('falsehood', '[\'fɔːlshʊd]', 'n.谎言；虚假', '1. Falsehood is the jockey of misfortune. 谎言是灾祸的骑师。 2. One falsehood spoils a thousand truths. 一个谎言毁坏千条真理。 3. I am greased with falsehood and treachery. 我全身都涂满了虚假和不忠实的润滑油。 4. It is sometimes difficult to disentangle truth from falsehood. 从虚假中解开事实有时是困难的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('earthshaking', '[\'ɜːθʃeɪkɪŋ]', 'adj.震撼全球的；极为重大的', '1. Is not each youth all has an earthshaking ending. 不是每一场青春都以幸福的泪水和撕心裂肺的痛苦而结束. 2. Such an earthshaking change must have far-reaching effects. 像这样翻天覆地的变化一定会产生深远的影响。 3. Wherever it went, there would be an earthshaking storm. “年”所到之处，地面上刮起狂风，下起暴雨； 4. Earthshaking changes have taken place from ancient times to the present. 自古至今，世界发生了翻天覆地的变化。', '副词: earthshakingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('condense', '[kən\'dens]', 'v.浓缩；凝结；缩短', '1. He condense his speech to half its original length. 他把演讲的长度浓缩了一半。 2. You can condense milk by boiling away much of the water in it. 煮去牛奶中大部分的水分可使它浓缩。 3. Steam condenses into water when cooling down. 蒸汽冷却时凝结成水。 4. Water vapors can condense to form clouds. 水蒸汽能凝结成云。', '形容词: condensable 名词: condensability 过去式: condensed 过去分词: condensed 现在分词: condensing 第三人称单数: condenses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ripple', '[\'rɪpl]', 'n.涟漪；波纹；潺潺声；粗钢梳 v.使起涟漪；使起波纹；使发出潺潺声；起伏；轻轻荡漾', '1. The small ripple split upon the beach . 小小的涟漪卷来，碎在沙滩上。 2. The pebble made a ripple on the surface of the lake. 石子在湖面上激起一个涟漪。 3. The air was so still that there was hardly a ripple on the pond\'s surface. 空气静止不动，池塘的水面上几乎看不到波纹。 4. She lay on the bank, listening to the ripple of the stream. 她躺在河岸上，听着小河的潺潺流水声。 5. The breeze rippled the quiet water. 微风吹皱了平静的水面。', '副词: ripplingly 名词: rippler 过去式: rippled 过去分词: rippled 现在分词: rippling 第三人称单数: ripples');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elude', '[i\'luːd]', 'vt.逃避；躲避；理解不了；记不起来', '1. The fox eluded the hunters by turning back quickly. 狐狸急转身逃脱了猎人的追逐。 2. The suspect continues to elude the police. 嫌疑犯继续躲避着警察。 3. The revolutionist eluded capture for weeks by hiding underground. 那位革命者为避免被捕在地下躲藏了几个星期。 4. The meaning eludes me. 我摸不透这意思。', '过去式: eluded 过去分词: eluded 现在分词: eluding 第三人称单数: eludes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stride', '[straɪd]', 'n.大步走；一大步；步伐；进步 vt.跨；跨骑 vi.迈大步走；跨过；分腿站立', '1. In a few strides he crossed the room. 他几大步就穿过了房间。 2. I was three strides from the door. 我距离那门有三大步远。 3. In a big stride he came out of the room. 他一个箭步出了房间。 4. The boy walked with a confident manly stride. 这男孩以自信的男人步伐行走。 5. The boy is too young to stride the ditch. 孩子太小跨不过这条沟。 6. China is striding ahead in her economic construction. 中国正在经济建设方面大步前进。', '名词: strider 过去式: strode 过去分词: stridden 现在分词: striding 第三人称单数: strides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('linear', '[\'lɪniər]', 'adj.直线的；长度的；线性的', '1. Students do not always progress in a linear fashion. 学生不会总是顺着一条直线进步。 2. The flow is linear, with some iterations in the planning phase. 过程流程是直线的，在计划阶段会有一些迭代。 3. He\'s making linear measurements. 他正在进行长度测量。 4. Not all types of motions are linear in character. 并非所有类型的运动在性质上都是线性的。', '副词: linearly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('graft', '[ɡræft]', 'n.嫁接；移植；<美>贪污；<英>努力 v.嫁接；移植；<美>贪污；<英>努力', '1. It is the graft of the pointed upon the round arch. 这是尖拱式样嫁接于开阔穹窿的一种风格。 2. He had a skin graft on the burnt leg. 他烧伤的腿上做了皮肤移植。 3. The gardener could graft as many as twenty cuttings an hour on to briar stems. 这位园丁每小时可以嫁接多达20根枝条到石南茎上去。 4. No one has been able to graft together trees belonging to quite distant families. 没人可以把种族差别很远的两种树嫁接到一起去。', '过去式: grafted 过去分词: grafted 现在分词: grafting 第三人称单数: grafts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('domain', '[doʊ\'meɪn]', 'n.领地；领域；范围', '1. Each of her cousins had charge of his own domain. 她的每一个亲属主管着自己的领地。 2. The kitchen is my wife\'s domain, and she doesn\'t like me going into it. 厨房是我妻子的领地,她不愿让我进去。 3. As soon as you create an account for the user, the user can participate in a secure domain. 一旦您为用户创建了一个帐号，用户就可以进入安全域中。 4. The doctor works in the domain of public health. 医生在公众健康范围内工作。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('satiated', '[\'seɪʃɪeɪtɪd]', 'adj. 充分满足的； 对 ... 厌倦的； 生腻的 动词satiate的过去式和过去分词形式', '1. She was so satiated with bananas that she would not even look at one. 她已吃腻了香蕉，她甚至连看都不想看一眼。 2. He was satiated with pleasure. 他厌倦了享乐。 3. She pushed her chair back from the table, satiated. 她把椅子从餐桌向后挪了挪，再也吃不下了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('category', '[\'kætəɡɔːri]', 'n.种类；类别；范畴', '1. There are different categories of books in a library. 图书馆里有各种不同种类的书籍。 2. They fall into different categories. 他们属于不同的类别。 3. They misplaced this book under another category. 他们把它错放到另一个类别去了。 4. How can a scientific category have its derivatives? 科学范畴何以能衍生?', '名词复数: categories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stowaway', '[\'stoʊəweɪ]', 'n.逃票乘客；收藏处', '1. The crew discovered the stowaway about two days into their voyage. 船员发现这个逃票者已经呆了两天的航程。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diatribe', '[\'daɪətraɪb]', 'n.长篇抨击；长时间谩骂', '1. He launched a diatribe against the younger generation. 他对年轻一代发起了长篇抨击。 2. The book is a diatribe against the academic left. 这本书对学术左派进行了长时间的谩骂。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retaliate', '[rɪ\'tælieɪt]', 'v.报复；回敬', '1. He sought every opportunity to retaliate on his persecutors. 他寻求每一个机会向迫害他的人们复仇。 2. He was waiting for an opportunity to retaliate. 他在伺机报复。 3. He slapped his sister, who retaliated by kicking him. 他打了妹妹一巴掌，他妹妹回敬他一脚。', '形容词: retaliative 名词: retaliation 过去式: retaliated 过去分词: retaliated 现在分词: retaliating 第三人称单数: retaliates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('macerate', '[\'mæsəreɪt]', 'v.浸软；消瘦', '1. Dried mushrooms macerate goes the foot wipes water. 冬菇浸软去脚擦干水。 2. Make law use: Dried macerate drop does water. 制法用法：虾米浸软沥干水。 3. Macerate fresh herb for topical use. 全草外用适量，鲜品捣烂敷患处。 4. Facing particieboard: A.Particieboard of macerate paper facing;B. 饰面刨花板：a.;浸渍纸饰面刨花板；', '名词: maceration 过去式: macerated 过去分词: macerated 现在分词: macerating 第三人称单数: macerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('redeem', '[rɪ\'diːm]', 'vt.赎回；弥补；履行；兑现；偿还；解救', '1. She redeemed her reputation with a powerful speech to the party convention. 她由于向党代表大会做了有力的演说而挽回了自己的声誉。 2. I redeemed my watch from the pawnshop. 我从当铺赎回了手表。 3. The sole redeeming feature of this job is the salary. 这份工作唯其薪水尚可弥补一切之不足。 4. Jones redeemed his earlier poor performance by scoring two goals. 琼斯射入两球方弥补其初时表现之不足。', '形容词: redeemable 过去式: redeemed 过去分词: redeemed 现在分词: redeeming 第三人称单数: redeems');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nexus', '[\'neksəs]', 'n.连系；联络；关系；网络；节；段；连杆；连接', '1. One is the employment-housing nexus. 其一是就业与住房的关系。 2. Furthermore,we think about how to introduce the research on the law?finance nexus to China\'s economic reality. 本文还探讨了如何将法与金融关系的研究引入到我国的经济现实中来。', '名词复数: nexus');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adolescent', '[ˌædə\'lesnt]', 'adj.青春期的；青少年的 n.青少年', '1. It is not unusual for grown adults to act in an adolescent way. 成人表现出青春期的样子很正常。 2. She says that risk-taking is normal adolescent behaviour. 她说冒险是青春期的正常表现。 3. I still remember my adolescent life. 我仍然记得我青少年时期的生活。 4. The adolescent period is one\'s best time. 青少年时期是一个人最美好的一段时光。 5. Overgrowth is common in adolescents. 青少年成长过快是普遍现象。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sheath', '[ʃiːθ]', 'n.鞘；护套 n.女式紧身衣服', '1. Put the dagger back in its sheath. 把短剑插回鞘内。 2. As he stepped forward, it dropped out of its sheath. 约押前行，刀从鞘内掉出来。 3. The continuous filament polyester sheath is braided over a continuous nylon fiber core. 连续细丝聚酯护套被编织物包上连续的尼龙纤维核心上方。 4. The polyester sheath provides added protection for ultraviolet light and from chemicals that are harmful to nylon. 聚酯护套提供增加的保护紫外线和从化学制品对尼龙伤害。', '名词复数: sheaths 过去式: sheathed 过去分词: sheathed 现在分词: sheathing 第三人称单数: sheaths');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rural', '[\'rʊrəl]', 'adj.农村的，乡村的，田园的', '1. The disease occurs most frequently in rural areas. 那疾病多见於农村地区。 2. Rural areas have been worst hit by the strike. 受罢工影响最严重的是乡村地区。 3. The rural scenery was so beautiful that he decided to stay one more week. 乡村风光太美了，以致于他决定再多呆一星期。 4. Nine tenths of the population in rural areas live from hand to mouth. 农村地区90%25的人仅够糊口。', '副词: rurally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intoxicate', '[ɪn\'tɒksɪkeɪt]', 'vt. 下毒； 使 ... 陶醉', '1. Cherishing a rose means to intoxicate yourself on her beauty more than pull her throns out. 喜欢玫瑰意思是要我们陶醉它的美丽，而不是去除它的刺。', '形容词: intoxicative 副词: intoxicatingly 名词: intoxication 过去式: intoxicated 过去分词: intoxicated 现在分词: intoxicating 第三人称单数: intoxicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obsolescent', '[ˌɒbsə\'lesnt]', 'adj.即将过时的；废退的', '1. This type of computer is obsolescent. 这类计算机是快要过时的。 2. Electronic equipment quickly becomes obsolescent. 电子设备淘汰得很快.', '副词: obsolescently 名词: obsolescence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bacchanal', '[\'bækənəl]', 'n.(行为放纵的)狂欢会；酒神节参与者 adj.酒神崇拜的', '1. How answers each bold Bacchanal ! 无聊的酒神个个雀跃！ 2. His eye was alight, his color coppery, his air swagger, devil-may-care, bacchanal. 他的眼睛发亮，面发铜色，态度傲慢，不顾一切地发着酒疯。 3. The tragedy is developed form the bacchanal doxology as one part of the fete ceremony of Dionysus. 悲剧作为狄俄尼索斯祭祀仪式的一部分，是由酒神颂歌发展而来的。 4. Cleaning up the wreckage left by our 250-year industrial bacchanal will require fundamental changes in a society hooked on its fossil fuels. 但是要清除250年来，工业肆虐留下的残骸需要对这个依赖矿物燃料发展的社会进行根本性变革。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ventral', '[\'ventrəl]', 'adj.腹部的', '1. The liver is somewhat ventral in position. 肝脏的位置在腹侧。 2. Its sucking mouth was in a terminal rather than a ventral position. 它的吸嘴位于末端，而不在腹部。', '副词: ventrally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delectable', '[dɪ\'lektəbl]', 'adj.快乐的；可喜的；愉快的；美味的', '1. For us, it was a delectable news. 但在我们听来，这无疑是个可喜的消息。 2. I felt a delectable sense of freedom. 我有一种愉快的自由感。', '副词: delectably 名词: delectability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('zany', '[\'zeɪni]', 'n.小丑；笨人 adj.滑稽的；荒唐的', '1. I thought morning deejays were supposed to be zany. 我想早间音乐主持人是很愚蠢的。 2. She made us all laugh with her zany tricks. 她那些滑稽的恶作剧逗得我们都大笑起来。 3. They threw their King Kong together with an unthinking haste that accounts for its zany illogic. 他们在一片未思索的匆忙中，匆匆把金刚凑在一起，而必须为电影的荒唐不合逻辑负责。', '副词: zanily 比较级: zanier 最高级: zaniest 名词: zaniness 名词复数: zanies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shell', '[ʃel]', 'n.壳；炮弹；[计]外壳程序 v.脱落；去壳；拾贝壳；炮轰', '1. There is an ornament made of shells on the wall. 墙上有一个贝壳做成的装饰品。 2. All that remained of the building after the fire was an empty shell. 一场大火过后，这座建筑剩下的只是一个空壳。 3. The snail retreated into its shell. 蜗牛缩进壳里去了。 4. Shells were bursting all around. 炮弹在四处爆炸。 5. The wheat will shell after a few days. 麦子已熟透，再过几天就会脱落了。', '名词: sheller 过去式: shelled 过去分词: shelled 现在分词: shelling 第三人称单数: shells');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commentary', '[\'kɑːmənteri]', 'n.实况报道；现场解说；评论；注释', '1. His running commentary on the football match was excellent. 他对这次足球赛所作的实况报道十分精彩。 2. Tours have live English commentary. 旅游配有现场英语解说。 3. We\'d better not make any commentary on others. 我们最好不要评论他人。 4. I think his commentary on this issue is not correct. 我认为他对这个问题的评论是不正确的。', '形容词: commentarial 名词复数: commentaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bust', '[bʌst]', 'n.半身像；胸部；搜查；失败 v.打碎；搜捕；降级；终止 adj.破产的；打碎的', '1. I worked up a lump of clay into a bust of my mother. 我把一块粘土制作成我母亲的半身像。 2. What is your bust size, madam? 小姐, 您胸围的尺寸是多少? 3. The police was engaged in a bust of the drug dealer. 警方正在搜捕那个毒贩子。 4. The movie was a total bust. 这部电影非常失败。 5. I busted my leg playing basketball. 我打篮球的时候弄伤了腿。 6. His company went bust. 他的公司破产了。', '过去式: busted 过去分词: busted 现在分词: busting 第三人称单数: busts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adjourn', '[ə\'dʒɜːrn]', 'v.(使)延期；中止；换地方', '1. The meeting adjourned till five o\'clock. 会议延至五点召开。 2. The chairman adjourn the meeting for a week. 主席把会议延期一周。 3. The motion to adjourn was carried. 休会的提议通过了。 4. The meeting will adjourn sine die. 这个会议将会无限期休会。', '名词: adjournment 过去式: adjourned 过去分词: adjourned 现在分词: adjourning 第三人称单数: adjourns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('complaisance', '[kəm\'pleɪzəns]', 'n.彬彬有礼；殷勤，奉承', '1. She speaks with complaisance. 她说话彬彬有礼。 2. His complaisance leaves a good impression on her. 他的彬彬有礼给她留下了深刻的印象。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pout', '[paʊt]', 'n.噘嘴 （复数）pouts:生气. n.大头鱼类（如鲶鱼、鳕等) v.噘嘴；绷脸；生气；伸出', '1. She looked at her lover with a pretentious pout. 她看着恋人，故作不悦地撅着嘴。 2. She pouted to show off her new lipstick. 她撅嘴炫耀她的新口红。 3. Tell that child to stop pouting. 叫那孩子别撅嘴撒娇。', '形容词: pouty 名词复数: pout 过去式: pouted 过去分词: pouted 现在分词: pouting 第三人称单数: pouts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('advocate', '[\'ædvəkeɪt]', 'v.提倡；主张 n.拥护者；提倡者；律师；辩护者', '1. Many educators advocate a liberal education. 很多教育家提倡通才教育。 2. We don\'t advocate learning by rote. 死记硬背的学习方法，我们是不提倡的。 3. Many people advocate building more hospitals. 许多人主张增设医院。 4. We advocate higher salaries for teachers. 我们主张涨老师的工资。 5. She is a passionate advocate of education reform. 她是一名教育改革的热情拥护者。', '形容词: advocatory 名词: advocator 过去式: advocated 过去分词: advocated 现在分词: advocating 第三人称单数: advocates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dismantle', '[dɪs\'mæntl]', 'vt.拆除；拆开；去除；废除', '1. This toy machine gun dismantles easily. 这种玩具机关枪很容易拆卸。 2. He began to dismantle segregation within the armed forces. 他着手拆除军队中的隔离。 3. We dismantled the house before knocking it down. 我们在拆房前搬空家具。 4. We should dismantle our inefficient tax system. 我们这个效益很差的税收制度应该废除.', '名词: dismantlement 过去式: dismantled 过去分词: dismantled 现在分词: dismantling 第三人称单数: dismantles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amorphous', '[ə\'mɔːrfəs]', 'adj.无定形的；杂乱的；非结晶的', '1. It is an amorphous colorless or white powder. 它是一种无定形的无色或白色粉末。 2. I really can\'t understand his amorphous ideas. 我真的弄不懂他那些乱七八糟的想法。 3. Microscopically the ores are medium grained to amorphous. 显微镜下，矿石为中粒至非晶质。', '副词: amorphously 名词: amorphousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ethos', '[\'iːθɑːs]', 'n.民族精神；道德风貌；气质', '1. We must develop an ethos of cost consciousness. 我们必须提高人们在成本意识方面的精神素质。 2. The day could not be far distant when naturalism would dominate the ethos of American literature. 自然主义将支配美国文学风气的时日，已经为期不远。 3. They cultivated a subversive alternative ethos. 他们培育了一种破坏性的交替的民族气质。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('engaged', '[ɪn\'ɡeɪdʒd]', 'adj.忙碌的；使用中的；订婚了的', '1. The professor is engaged in advanced studies. 该教授正进行高深的学术研究。 2. I couldn\'t get him as the line was engaged. 因电话占线，我没能挂通他的电话。 3. Jack and Anne are engaged. 杰克和安妮订婚了。 4. There were six engaged couples at the party. 宴会席上有六对订婚夫妇。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('effulgent', '[ɪ\'fʌldʒənt]', 'adj.光辉的；灿烂的', '1. Chenguan World----more effulgent due to you! 晨光世界,因为有你更精彩! 2. Why is baroque right for one age and too effulgent for another? 为什么巴洛克艺术风格适合某一时期，而另一时期却显得过于炫目辉煌？ 3. The letter turned out to be the most effulgent thing he ever produced. 结果这篇伪作成了他一生中最打动人的文字。 4. \"The crocus, the snowdrop, and the effulgent daffodil are considered bright harbingers of spring\" (John Gould). “藏红花、雪花莲和明亮的水仙花被看作是春天的光明预兆” （约翰·高尔德）。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clamp', '[klæmp]', 'n.夹子；螺丝钳 vt.夹住；强加；压制', '1. The wood is held in position by a clamp. 木头用钳夹固定住了。 2. He used a clamp to hold the arm on the chair until the glue dried. 他用夹子将扶手夹在椅子上, 直到胶水干后再取下。 3. Try to clamp these two blocks of wood together. 试着把这两块木头夹在一起。 4. The wood is held in position by a clamp. 木头用钳夹固定住了。', '过去式: clamped 过去分词: clamped 现在分词: clamping 第三人称单数: clamps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('understated', '[ˌʌndər\'steɪtɪd]', 'adj.不夸张的；朴素的；简朴的 动词understate的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. I expressed my opinion in understated words. 我以十分有节制的措辞表达了自己的观点。 2. He often speaks in the most understated manner possible. 他说话尽可能保持低调。 3. Understated elegance and nuance are the key features of his poems. 淡雅与细腻是他诗作的关键特征。 4. On such occasions, she always dressed herself with understated elegance. 在这样的场合，她总是衣着朴素而又大方。', '副词: understatedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incisive', '[ɪn\'saɪsɪv]', 'adj.一针见血的；敏锐的', '1. He gave a clear and incisive presentation of the matter. 他对整件事作出了一个清楚而又深刻的描述。 2. Many Chinese experts and scholars have an incisive exposition. 中国许多专家学者对此有精辟的论述。 3. He had an incisive and agile mind. 他的思路犀利敏捷。', '副词: incisively 名词: incisiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ultimate', '[\'ʌltɪmət]', 'adj.根本的；极限的；最后的；终极的 n.终极；极品；根本', '1. Hard work is the ultimate source of success. 努力工作是成功之本。 2. This had been an ultimate issue. 这个问题是个原则性的问题。 3. GUPTA And the Ironman is the ultimate competition. 甘普塔铁人是一个极限的竞争。 4. I believe that I will bring my ultimate competitiveness in the advanced business management into full play with the guidance of professional teachers. 我认为在精英的师资力量的指导下我将在高级商业管理方面发挥我极限的竞争力。 5. Such behavior is the ultimate in idiocy. 这样的行为愚蠢透顶。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cameo', '[\'kæmioʊ]', 'n.刻有浮雕的宝石或贝壳；（文艺或戏剧）小品；小品文', '1. That little girl is wearing a cameo brooch. 那小女孩戴着一枚浮雕宝石胸针。 2. But she has not been lighting up cinemas in the last 12 months, taking a series of supporting roles and cameo performances. 然而在过去的一年里，她并没有惊人之作，只是出演了一系列配角和小品。', '名词复数: cameos 过去式: cameoed 过去分词: cameoed 现在分词: cameoing 第三人称单数: cameos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fermentation', '[ˌfɜːmen\'teɪʃn]', 'n.发酵；骚动', '1. Fermentation is a biogenic process. 发酵是一种生物化学反应过程。 2. Sparkling wine needs to undergo a second alcoholic fermentation. 发泡葡萄酒需要二次发酵作用。 3. He shared the 1929 Nobel Prize for research on the fermentation of sugars. 他因在糖发酵上的研究和别人同获1929年的诺贝尔奖。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seethe', '[siːð]', 'v.沸腾；大怒；起泡 n.拥挤；激动；骚动', '1. Resentment and rage seethe within him. 怨恨与愤怒在他的内心翻腾。 2. She was seething with rage at his remarks. 他的评论把她气得火冒三丈。', '过去式: seethed 过去分词: seethed 现在分词: seething 第三人称单数: seethes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('baleful', '[\'beɪlfl]', 'adj.有害的；恶意的', '1. He now thinks this influence was baleful. 他现在认为这种影响是有害的。 2. The robber gave me a baleful look. 那强盗用威胁的眼光看着我。 3. But, the most darkling change still is the origin problem of baleful software. 但是,最令人害怕的变化还是恶意软件的来源问题。', '副词: balefully 名词: balefulness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('timidity', '[tɪ\'mɪdəti]', 'n.胆小；胆怯；羞怯', '1. His failure is largely due to timidity. 他的失败主要是由于胆小。 2. Extreme timidity or shyness are serious faults. 过度胆小或羞怯属于严重缺陷。 3. He had a terrible time in overcoming his timidity. 他费了很大的劲才克服了他的胆怯。 4. Self-effacement did not lead to timidity. 谦逊并不会导致胆怯。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pottery', '[\'pɑːtəri]', 'n.陶器', '1. Modern pottery is usually ornamental. 现代陶器通常用作装饰品。 2. Cup and dish belong to pottery Lei. 杯子和碟属于陶器类。', '名词复数: potteries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parabola', '[pə\'ræbələ]', 'n.[数]抛物线', '1. The plane should follow the parabola. 飞机须沿抛物线运动。 2. A parabola interpolation is used to reduce the measurement error. 采用抛物线插值计算互相关函数峰值,减少测量误差。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antibiotic', '[ˌæntibaɪ\'ɑːtɪk]', 'adj.抗菌的 n.抗生素', '1. Kimchi has antibiotic functions as lactic acid bacteria produced in the process of fermentation suppresses growth of harmful bacteria. 由于在发酵过程中产生的乳酸菌抑制了有害菌的生长，所以泡菜有抗生素作用。 2. When rhinosinusitis patients were not responsive to empiric antibiotic treatment in the Outpatient Clinic, specimens were taken from the middle meatus with cotton-tipped sticks. 在门诊中，当鼻腔鼻窦炎病患对抗生素治疗无效时，我们利用棉签从中鼻道取标本做嗜氧菌及厌氧菌的培养来决定正确的抗生素。 3. A new potent antibiotic will shortly be available. 一种新的高效抗生素不久将在市面销售。 4. She was injected with an antibiotic. 给她注射了抗生素。', '副词: antibiotically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delinquency', '[dɪ\'lɪŋkwənsi]', 'n.（少年）犯罪；失职', '1. Juvenile delinquency is a broad subject. 少年犯罪是一个广泛的问题。 2. Community service can help prevent juvenile delinquency. 社区服务有助于预防青少年犯罪。 3. We should curb juvenile delinquency by education. 我们应该通过教育抑制少年犯罪。 4. They are holding a forum on juvenile delinquency. 他们正举行一个有关青少年犯罪的讨论会。', '名词复数: delinquencies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shackle', '[\'ʃækl]', 'n.手铐；脚镣；镣铐；束缚物 v.给...戴上镣铐；束缚', '1. The prisoner was fastened by a shackle. 那个犯人被手铐铐着。 2. Shackle were placed on the prisoner\'s hands and feet. 囚犯的手脚都上了镣铐。 3. The prisoner broke the shackle with a hammer and escaped away. 囚犯用锤子打碎镣铐逃跑了。 4. Nowadays, people have shaken off the shackles of some conventions. 今天，人们已经摆脱了一些习俗的束缚。 5. He is too young to shackle himself with the responsibilities of a family. 他还太年轻，不能用家庭责任来束缚自己。', '名词: shackler 过去式: shackled 过去分词: shackled 现在分词: shackling 第三人称单数: shackles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incendiary', '[ɪn\'sendieri]', 'adj.放火的；煽动的；教唆的 n.纵火犯人；煽动者；燃烧弹', '1. They had it that the fire was incendiary. 他们认为这是有人纵火。 2. The soldiers were trained to deal with incendiary attacks. 士兵们受过对付火攻的训练。 3. But his image never entirely lost its incendiary appeal. 但他的音容笑貌留下了不可磨灭的印象。 4. At the beginning of your upkeep, you may put a fuse counter on Incendiary. 在你的维持开始时，你可以在纵火上面放置一个导线指示物。', '名词: incendiarism 名词复数: incendiaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oracle', '[\'ɔːrəkl]', 'n.神谕；神谕处；传达神谕的人；能提供可靠意见的人', '1. In times of difficulty, she prayed for an oracle to guide her. 在困难的时候,她祈祷神谕来指引她。 2. The earth is the great parent of all, the stones are her bones; these we may cast behind us; this, I think, the oracle means. 大地是万物之母，石头就是她的尸骨。我们可以往身后扔石头，我想神谕说的就是这个意思。 3. This oracle was still flourishing in 332 B.C. 这个神示殿在公元前332年依然很兴旺。 4. They consulted the oracle at Delphi. 他们在德尔斐神示所向神请示。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dapper', '[\'dæpər]', 'adj.衣冠楚楚的；短小精悍的；干净的', '1. You will look very dapper in a silk leisure suit. 真丝休闲西服，令您风姿翩翩。 2. What a dapper little man! 好一个短小精悍的人！', '副词: dapperly 名词: dapperness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tantamount', '[\'tæntəmaʊnt]', 'adj.同等的；相等的；相当于', '1. Her statement is tantamount to a confession of guilt. 她的供述等于认罪。 2. The excuse was tantamount to a refusal. 那种托辞形同拒绝。 3. The King\'s request was tantamount to a command. 国王的要求就相当於命令。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lambaste', '[læm\'beɪst]', 'vt.痛打；痛骂 =lambast.', '1. Everyone suddenly realize the sort lambaste. 大家恍然大悟般大骂起来。 2. Haven\'t you heard Tae lambast me on Thirsty Thursdays about that? 你没有听太渴了周四就揍对我吗？ 3. Get up.Result:Too early, lambaste dishonest trader to cheat sleeping pills. 起床。结果：起得太早，大骂奸商做假安眠药。 4. Only months ago,the idea that Mr Bush would publicly lambast America\'s corporate bosses was laughable. 可是就在几个月前，布什公开抨击美国大公司老板的想法却是荒谬可笑的。', '过去式: lambasted 过去分词: lambasted 现在分词: lambasting 第三人称单数: lambastes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('psyche', '[\'saɪki]', 'n.【C】精神；心灵；灵魂 Psyche：[希神]塞姬（爱神丘比特所爱的美女）.', '1. It was a false alarm at the psych ward. 在精神病房的是个错误警报。 2. In psychoanalysis, the division of the psyche that is conscious, most immediately controls thought and behavior, and is most in touch with external reality. 自我在精神分析学中指有意识的最直接地控制思想和行为，与外部世界联系也最多的那部分自我 3. The psyche was empty of its struggles and its pains. 心灵清空了它所有的挣扎和痛苦。 4. She spent her life plumbing the mysteries of the human psyche. 她毕生探索人类心灵的奥秘。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gull', '[ɡʌl]', 'n.鸥；易受骗之人 v.诈欺；骗', '1. Gull flies over the sea. 海鸥在大海上飞翔。 2. The wings of the sea gull were beating frantically. 海鸥的翅膀在疯狂地扑扇着。 3. Only Merlin would seek to gull me so, even though he should know better. 只有梅林会这样引我上当，他很明白这个道理。 4. It\'s wrong to gull a child. 欺骗孩子是不对的。', '过去式: gulled 过去分词: gulled 现在分词: gulling 第三人称单数: gulls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('con', '[kɑn]', 'n.骗局；反对；反对的理由 adv.反面地；反对地 vt.精读；记诵', '1. This so-called bargain is just a con! 这种所谓的大减价不过是个骗局! 2. The UN Security Council Voted with Three pros, one con and one abstention. 联合国安理会投票,三票赞成,一票反对,一票弃权。 3. We must be fair and consider the reason pro and con. 我们必须公平考虑赞成和反对的理由。 4. They debated the issue pro and con. 他们从正反两方面讨论这个问题。', '异体字: conn 过去式: conned 过去分词: conned 现在分词: conning 第三人称单数: cons/conns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nefarious', '[nɪ\'feriəs]', 'adj.违法的；邪恶的', '1. He guarded his nefarious doings from view. 他不让自己的罪恶行径给人看到。 2. He was universally feared because of his many nefarious deeds. 因为他干了许多罪恶的勾当, 所以人人都惧怕他。 3. The EU reckons that Intel\'s use of such rebates was nefarious. 欧盟认为，英特尔利用返点促销用意恶毒。', '副词: nefariously 名词: nefariousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inception', '[ɪn\'sepʃn]', 'n.开始；起初；取得学位', '1. The inception of the plan was due to him. 计划的开始取决于他。 2. He had been director of the project since its inception. 这项工作从一开始他就是负责人。 3. The programme has been successful since its inception. 这个方案自开始实施以来一直卓有成效。 4. The club has grown rapidly since its inception in 1990. 这个俱乐部自从1990年成立以来发展迅速。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hover', '[\'hʌvər]', 'v.盘旋；徘徊；靠近（某事物），维持在某种不确定的状态 n.盘旋', '1. The hawk is hovering overhead. 鹰在头顶上盘旋。 2. After the alien spacecraft had hovered over the park for a short time, it vanished. 那只外星来的宇宙飞船在公园上空盘旋了一会儿之后就不见了。 3. He hovered nervously in the doorway. 他在门口紧张地来回踱步。 4. The mercury hovered around 35 Celsius degree. 水银温度计停留在摄氏35度左右。 5. He felt creeping of fate, the circling of wolves, the hover of vultures. 他感到厄运已经来到，豺狼正在包围，秃鹰也在盘旋。', '副词: hoveringly 名词: hoverer 过去式: hovered 过去分词: hovered 现在分词: hovering 第三人称单数: hovers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crevice', '[\'krevɪs]', 'n.(岩石、墙等)裂缝', '1. Some grass grow in the crevice of the stone wall. 有些草从石墙的裂缝中长出来。 2. The earth heaved and surged, and instantly a large crevice split open. 地面一阵晃动，瞬即裂开一条大缝。', '形容词: creviced');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('complacent', '[kəm\'pleɪsnt]', 'adj.满足的；自满的；得意的', '1. To anyone who has actually witnessed these final stages, the complacent poeticizing of these adolescents must seem as exasperating as they are profoundly pathetic. 对目睹过晚期状态的人来说，这些年轻人自我满足的诗情必定会显得令人气恼又觉得可怜。 2. This lets Li Dapeng\'s complacent place just about. 这正是让李大鹏得意的地方。 3. By now he has dropped the complacent notion. 现在，他抛弃了一个得意的想法。', '副词: complacently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('umpire', '[\'ʌmpaɪər]', 'n.裁判员；仲裁人 vt.为 ... 裁决；为 ...仲裁 vi.裁判；仲裁', '1. The tennis umpire wore an eye-shade. 那网球裁判戴着遮光帽檐。 2. The umpire ousted the arguing player from the game. 裁判员将那位不服判决的运动员罚下场。 3. The umpire showed partiality for that team. 那个裁判偏向那个队。 4. The player accepted the umpire\'s decision. 那个运动员服从裁判员的裁决。 5. The umpire called the runner out. 裁判判定跑者出局。', '过去式: umpired 过去分词: umpired 现在分词: umpiring 第三人称单数: umpires');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('portentous', '[pɔːr\'tentəs]', 'adj.前兆的；不吉的；可怕的；煞有介事的；自命不凡的', '1. The present aspect of society is portentous of great change. 现在的社会预示着重大变革的发生。 2. I see a portentous thing to come. 我预感不祥的事情要来到了。 3. Such a portentous and mysterious monster roused all my curiosity. 这样一个可怕而神秘的怪物激起了我所有的猎奇心。 4. Keep it, in any case, familiar, facetious even, rather then pedantic and portentous. 无论如何，要使它显得很随便，甚至滑稽可笑，而不要显得很迂腐，夜郎自大。', '副词: portentously 名词: portentousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lounge', '[laʊndʒ]', 'n.休息室；候机室；起居室 v.闲荡；懒散地斜靠', '1. We watched television in the hotel lounge. 我们在旅馆休息室里看电视。 2. Please move forward to the passenger lounge . 请向前走到旅客休息室。 3. She is waiting for me in the departure lounge. 她在候机室等我。 4. The children have made an awful mess in the lounge. 孩子们把起居室弄得凌乱不堪。 5. I don\'t want to lounge about town. I have other things to do. 我不想在市区闲逛。我还有别的事要做。', '名词: lounger 过去式: lounged 过去分词: lounged 现在分词: lounging 第三人称单数: lounges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saliferous', '[sə\'lɪfərəs]', 'adj.含盐的；产盐的', '1. Maoxing block saliferous strata are mainly in 4th Member,Funing Formation,Eocene Series. 茅兴块段含盐系地层主要为始新统阜宁组四段。 2. The phase diagram of saliferous water-railway basis saltstone system was analysized. 对不同盐度洪水与铁路路基岩盐作用进行了相图分析。 3. Thin-walled cells of callow stirpe\"s cortex contain saliferous vacuoles, and pulpcells contain crystals. 幼茎皮层薄壁细胞中含有含盐液泡泡，髓细胞中含有晶体。 4. Palisade tissue is rich in saliferous vacuoles, while vascular bundle sheath is obvious. 栅栏组织富含含盐液泡泡，维管束鞘明显。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lubricant', '[\'luːbrɪkənt]', 'n.润滑剂', '1. Sweat is the lubricant of success. 汗水是成功的润滑剂。 2. Drain lubricant to the correct level. 将润滑剂排放到正确的高度。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insatiable', '[ɪn\'seɪʃəbl]', 'adj.不知足的；贪求无厌的', '1. His thirst for knowledge is insatiable. 他对知识的渴求不会满足。 2. He had an insatiable love for music. 他对音乐爱得入迷。 3. He has an insatiable appetite for money and power. 他对金钱和权力欲壑难填。 4. She ridiculed his insatiable greed. 她嘲笑他的贪得无厌。', '副词: insatiably 名词: insatiability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alkali', '[\'ælkəlaɪ]', 'n.碱', '1. This kind of soil contains much alkali. 这种土壤含碱丰富。 2. The key problem is to overcome alkali in the soil. 关键在于控制土壤里的碱分。 3. Acid and alkali are the basic concept of chemistry. 酸和碱是化学的基本概念。 4. Such detergents do not yellow the wool as alkali tends to do. 这种洗涤剂不会象碱那样使羊毛发黄。', '名词复数: alkalis');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diaphanous', '[daɪ\'æfənəs]', 'adj.透明的；模糊的', '1. She was wearing a dress of diaphanous silk. 她穿着一件薄如蝉翼的绸服。', '副词: diaphanously 名词: diaphaneity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spoilsport', '[\'spɔɪlspɔːrt]', 'n.损坏他人快乐的人；扫兴者', '1. You\'re such a spoilsport! 你真让人扫兴！ 2. This will be a fun trip. Don`t be a spoilsport. 这趟旅行会很好玩。别做扫兴鬼了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thaw', '[θɔː]', 'n.融雪 v.使融解；暖和', '1. This year the thaw will set in early. 今年融雪将提早。 2. The sky, swollen with the clouds that announce a thaw, hung as low as before a summer storm. 天上涨满了预告融雪的云，直压到人头顶上，像夏天里暴风雨之前一样。 3. Come up to the fire,and you will thaw out. 到火炉边来，你就会觉得暖和。 4. This warm weather should thaw the ice on the road very quickly. 这样暖和的天气可以使路上的冰很快地融化。', '过去式: thawed 过去分词: thawed 现在分词: thawing 第三人称单数: thaws');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('horn', '[hɔːrn]', 'n.喇叭；触角；角质；号 v.强行介入', '1. The driver tooted his horn as he approached the bend. 开车的人在快要转弯时按响了喇叭。 2. The driver hooted his horn (at us). 司机(冲著我们)鸣喇叭。 3. The rhinoceros has one horn on its nose. 犀牛鼻子上有一个角。 4. The lark\'s on the wing, the snail\'s on the horn. 云雀在空中飞翔，蜗牛伸出触角爬行。 5. Although he was not invited,Henry managed to horn in on Myra\'s wedding. 尽管亨利没有被邀请，他还是设法闯来参加迈拉的婚礼。', '名词: hornist 过去式: horned 过去分词: horned 现在分词: horning 第三人称单数: horns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('patrimony', '[\'pætrɪmoʊni]', 'n.祖传的财物；继承物；遗产；教会财产', '1. His grandfather left the patrimony to him. 他的祖父把祖传的财物留给了他. 2. This farm is part of my patrimony. 这个农场是我父亲遗产的一部分。', '形容词: patrimonial 副词: patrimonially 名词复数: patrimonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('behoove', '[bɪ\'huːv]', 'v.理应；有必要', '1. The post-Cold War new world order is still taking shape.It would behoove Taiwanese leaders to play close attention and make necessary adjustments in policy. 后冷战时代的新世界秩序，其实仍然在形成当中，身在台湾的领导者是有必要做密切的观察与应变。', '过去式: behooved 过去分词: behooved 现在分词: behooving 第三人称单数: behooves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conduit', '[\'kɒndʊɪt]', 'n.导管；水管；沟渠', '1. It\'s a conduit enclosing insulated electric wires. 这是包电线的导管。 2. There is a conduit underneath the new house. 这座新房子底下有个导水管。 3. Along either side of these conduits,lie the cultivated districts. 在这些沟渠的两边是耕耘区。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stretch', '[stretʃ]', 'v.伸展；延伸；张开；夸大 n.伸展；张开；弹性；一段时间；<俚>刑期 adj.可伸缩的', '1. Vast meadows stretch to the east. 辽阔的草场向东伸展。 2. She stretched across the table for the butter. 她探身去取放在餐桌对面的黄油。 3. The landscape seemed to stretch into infinity. 风景似乎延伸到了无穷远处。 4. Feeling intense fellowship with all human beings, she wished to throw herself into their arms, thinking that they would stretch them out to receive her. 她对所有的人怀着亲如手足的感情，她希望投身于他们的怀抱，以为他们会张开双臂接纳她。 5. I got out of the bed and had a good stretch. 我起床后舒服地伸了个懒腰。', '形容词: stretchable 名词: stretchability 过去式: stretched 过去分词: stretched 现在分词: stretching 第三人称单数: stretches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('longevity', '[lɔːn\'dʒevəti]', 'n.长寿；寿命', '1. His longevity vexed his heirs. 他的长寿令他的继承人们不快 2. Proper rest and enough sleep contribute to longevity. 适当的休息和足够的睡眠有益于长寿。 3. The worms have a longevity of about two years. 蠕虫的寿命大概是两年。', '形容词: longevous 名词复数: longevities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('viand', '[\'vaɪənd]', 'n.一件食品；珍馐美味；食物', '1. Let him be quick, the viand flits, 让他活着吧，美味已经消失，', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('velocity', '[və\'lɑːsəti]', 'n.速度；迅速；速率', '1. The car was moving at such a velocity! 那辆汽车的速度简直太快了！ 2. The velocity of sound in water is more than four times that in air. 声音在水中的速度是在空气中的速度的4倍多。 3. Gazelles can move with astonishing velocity. 羚羊跑起来速度惊人。 4. The velocity of light is about 186,000 miles per second. 光速大约是每秒十八万六千英里。', '名词复数: velocities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inexhaustible', '[ˌɪnɪɡ\'zɔːstəbl]', 'adj.用不完的；无穷的；不知疲倦的', '1. They are filled with inexhaustible drive. 他们浑身有使不完的干劲。 2. The rivers afford an inexhaustible supply of fish. 这几条河有取之不尽的鱼类资源。 3. The wisdom of the masses is inexhaustible. 群众的智慧是无穷的。 4. The potentialities of the human brain are inexhaustible. 人类头脑的潜力是无穷的。', '副词: inexhaustibly 名词: inexhaustibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('triumph', '[\'traɪʌmf]', 'n.凯旋；成就；胜利；欢欣 vi.战胜；庆祝胜利', '1. The winning team returned home in triumph. 球队凯旋而归。 2. The bridge is a triumph of modern engineering. 这座桥是现代工程的一大成就。 3. A smile of triumph lit up her face. 她的脸上闪露出胜利的微笑。 4. We finally won a diplomatic triumph. 我们终于赢得了外交的胜利。 5. Advancing culture is bound to triumph over declining culture. 先进的文化必然战胜没落的文化。', '过去式: triumphed 过去分词: triumphed 现在分词: triumphing 第三人称单数: triumphs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jolly', '[\'dʒɑːli]', 'adj.愉快的；快乐的 v.恭维；哄；开玩笑；戏虐 adv.非常；极为 n.（尤英）欢乐；欢庆 （复数jollies）娱乐，乐趣', '1. We had a jolly time during the winter holidays. 我们在寒假里过得很愉快。 2. They are making a jolly life of it. 他们生活得非常愉快。 3. Some indeed have a jolly life, others simply don\'t. 有些人的确有着欢乐的生活，但其他的人却没有。 4. They jollied the little girl into going with them. 他们哄得那女孩跟他们一起去。 5. He is a jolly good man. 他是一个大好人。 6. Some indeed have a jolly life, others simply don\'t. 有些人的确有着欢乐的生活，但其他的人却没有。', '副词: jollily 比较级: jollier 最高级: jolliest 名词: jolliness 名词复数: jollies 过去式: jollied 过去分词: jollied 现在分词: jollying 第三人称单数: jollies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slick', '[slɪk]', 'adj.光滑的；顺利地；（指人）圆滑的 v.使平滑 n.海面浮油', '1. I advised them to watch out for slick spots on the sidewalk. 我叫他们当心人行道上路滑的地方。 2. The slick floor brought me down in a heavy fall. 光滑的地板把我重重地摔了一跤。 3. The hurricane carried away the roof as slick as a whistle. 飓风把屋顶不费吹灰之力地刮掉了。 4. I don\'t trust those slick salesmen. 我不信任那些油嘴滑舌的推销员。 5. He used to slick his hair everyday before school. 他曾经每天在上学之前梳好头发。 6. There is a slick of oil on the water. 水面上有一片浮油。', '副词: slickly 比较级: slicker 最高级: slickest 名词: slickness 过去式: slicked 过去分词: slicked 现在分词: slicking 第三人称单数: slicks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blather', '[\'blæðər]', 'vi.胡说；喋喋不休地讲 n.废话；胡说 =blether.', '1. She blathers about goodness and beauty and her own genius. 她胡吹什么德行、美貌和自己的天才。', '异体字: blether 名词: blatherer 过去式: blathered 过去分词: blathered 现在分词: blathering 第三人称单数: blathers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('garret', '[\'ɡærət]', 'n.阁楼；顶楼', '1. They are the poor men living in a garret. 他们就是住在阁楼上的穷人。 2. She had moved from the wall of the garret, very near to the bench on which he sat. 那姑娘已离开阁楼的墙壁，走近了老人的长凳。 3. Joe was very busy in the garret. 裘正在顶楼上忙得不亦乐乎。 4. He would ask the foreman of the mill he watched for the privilege of sleeping in some out-of-the-way garret. 他们走后，他就想去问他守过更的那个工厂的监事借一间闲空的顶楼睡觉。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scotch', '[skɑːtʃ]', 'n.伤口；刻痕 v.粉碎；消灭；阻止', '1. The doctor scotched her false story. 医生戳穿了她的骗局。 2. Facts will eventually scotch these rumours. 这种谣言在事实面前将不攻自破。', '过去式: scotched 过去分词: scotched 现在分词: scotching 第三人称单数: scotches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('depreciate', '[dɪ\'priːʃieɪt]', 'v.贬值；降价；轻视', '1. If you neglect this property, it will depreciate. 如果你忽视这份资产，它无形中就贬值了。 2. New cars start to depreciate as soon as they are on the road. 新车一上路就开始贬值。', '名词: depreciator 过去式: depreciated 过去分词: depreciated 现在分词: depreciating 第三人称单数: depreciates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('catharsis', '[kə\'θɑːrsɪs]', 'n.洗涤；净化；精神发泄；导泻', '1. This kind thinks of enough to sweep the haze of catharsis day for you opportunely. 这种巧思足以为你一扫洗涤日的阴霾。 2. Controversy is being outweighed by catharsis as Cambodia faces up to its past. 随着柬埔寨直面自己的过去，由此得来的涤荡净化压倒了争议。 3. The need of a realm of another for catharsis and abandon is impending. 人们迫切需要一个宣泄减压的宽松环境。 4. Studies show, however, that the notion of anger catharsis is poppycock. 研究表明愤怒宣泄论是一派胡言。', '名词复数: catharses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('florescence', '[floʊ\'resəns]', 'n.开花；花期；全盛期', '1. Florescence wind accompanies the florescence. 花信风，随着花期而来的风。 2. However, it would not affect the floral bud differentiation and florescence. 补光后，植株健壮，但对花芽分化和花期影响不大。', '形容词: florescent');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fanatic', '[fə\'nætɪk]', 'n.狂热者；极端分子；盲信者 adj.狂热的；盲信的', '1. We call him a politics fanatic. 我们叫他政治狂。 2. My roommate is a fanatic of Michael Jordan. 我的室友是迈克尔·乔丹的狂热粉丝。 3. The religious fanatics flagellated themselves. 狂热的宗教信仰者鞭打自己。 4. She\'s fanatic about pop music. 她对流行音乐很狂热。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exponent', '[ɪk\'spoʊnənt]', 'n.【C】拥护者；说明者；楷模；指数', '1. Our senator is an exponent of free trade. 我们的参议员是一个自由贸易的拥护者 2. She\'s an exponent of the opinions of Freud. 她是弗洛伊德学说的鼓吹者。 3. Huxley was an exponent of Darwin\'s theory of evolution. 赫胥黎是达尔文进化论的解说者。 4. An exponent can be a person who pleads for a cause or an idea. 一位讲解者可以是为某种原因或者某种想法辩解的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transcendental', '[ˌtrænsen\'dentl]', 'adj.超凡的；超越经验的；形而上学的；先验的；[数学]超越的', '1. Someone says she is very ugly, transcendental and free from vulgarity ugly. 有人说她很丑，超凡脱俗的丑。 2. Gazing at that majestic painting was for me an almost transcendental experience. 我凝视着那幅气势磅礴的画,一种堪称超凡的感受油然而生。 3. The other group took a course in transcendental meditation. 另外一组参加了超越性的静思。 4. The remaining boundary condition leads to a transcendental equation. 剩下的一个边值条件导致一个超越方程。', '副词: transcendentally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('legislation', '[ˌledʒɪs\'leɪʃn]', 'n.法律；法规；立法', '1. The new legislation is highly discriminatory. 新的法案，有许多地方厚此薄彼。 2. We protect the interests of investors by the legislation in effect. 我们根据现行法律保护投资者的利益。 3. The legislation was made retrospective. 该项法规具有追溯效力。 4. The government will introduce legislation to restrict the sale of firearms. 政府将制定法规限制枪支出售。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sever', '[\'sevər]', 'v.切断；脱离；分开', '1. She had to sever all ties with her parents. 她不得不断绝与父母的一切联系。 2. This action will sever the object\'s link to its master. 该操作将切断此对象与其主控文档的链接。 3. His arm was severed from his body in the accident. 在那次意外中，他的手臂被切断了。 4. We must never sever the cultural vein of our nation. 我们不能割断民族的文化血脉。', '过去式: severed 过去分词: severed 现在分词: severing 第三人称单数: severs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eulogistic', '[ˌjuːlə\'dʒɪstɪk]', 'adj.颂扬的(歌颂的；称赞的)', '1. A formal eulogistic composition intended as a public compliment. 赞颂词正式的颂扬性文章，如公开称赞 2. The issue, it will be seen, is a perfectly sharp one, which no eulogistic terminology can smear over or wipe out. 你们将看到，这个问题非常突出，没有什么褒义术语能够掩饰或排除它。 3. His “Da Shou Bi” fame comes from his eulogistic and gravestone writings that are ordered by the king. 他的大手笔之文内容雅正，形式活泼，气势恢弘，在同类文章中别具一格，具有浓厚的文学色彩。 4. Show your corporation and products to the world ! Eulogistic transmission starts from here... 展示您的企业和产品给世界各地的消费者!传颂------从这里开始......', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glow', '[ɡloʊ]', 'n.光辉；热情；赤热 vi.发红光；红光焕发', '1. There is a glow of health in his face. 他的脸容光焕发。 2. There midnight\'s all a glimmer and noon (is) a purple glow. 那儿午夜浮光微摇，中午紫光争耀。 3. The sunset glow is very beautiful. 太阳的余辉非常美丽。 4. His face took on an affectionate glow. 他的脸上洋溢着热情的红光。 5. All fireflies glow with about the same brightness. 所有的萤火虫闪耀着差不多相同的光亮。', '过去式: glowed 过去分词: glowed 现在分词: glowing 第三人称单数: glows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shanty', '[\'ʃænti]', 'n.简陋小屋；(水手唱的)劳动号子 =chantey；chanty.', '1. His childhood was spent in a shanty. 他的童年是在一个简陋小屋里度过的。 2. It\'s one of my father\'s favourite shanties. 这是我父亲最喜爱的劳动号子之一。', '名词复数: shanties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brusque', '[brʌsk]', 'adj.唐突的；鲁莽的', '1. The doctor spoke in a brusque tone. 医生不客气地简单说了几个字。 2. She was businesslike and brusque, with no small talk. 她公事公办，不讲絮话，但有时话语唐突。 3. Her brusque manner concealed a caring nature. 她举止粗鲁但实际上很关心他人。 4. Some customers are rather brusque and don\'t seem to like conversation. 有些顾客相当粗鲁，也不愿多说话。', '副词: brusquely 名词: brusqueness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('applicable', '[ə\'plɪkəbl]', 'adj.合适的；适用的；可应用的', '1. Western notions of human rights are not necessarily applicable in other societies. 西方的人权观念不一定适合其他社会。 2. This section of the law is applicable only to corporations. 这部分法律只适用于公司。 3. This part of the form is not applicable to foreign students. 表格中的这一部分不适用於外国学生. 4. Above rate applicable until further notice. 除非另有通知，上述运费率适用。', '副词: applicably 名词: applicability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stultify', '[\'stʌltɪfaɪ]', 'vt. 使 ... 显得愚蠢； 使 ... 无效； 使 ... 厌烦', '1. Their unhelpfulness has stultified our efforts to improve things. 他们不管事，我们为改进工作的用心也就白费了。', '名词: stultification 过去式: stultified 过去分词: stultified 现在分词: stultifying 第三人称单数: stultifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enterprise', '[\'entərpraɪz]', 'n.企业；事业；进取心；谋划', '1. This enterprise is now on a firm footing and should soon get profits. 现在这家企业基础稳固，很快就会赢利。 2. They are involved in an exciting scientific enterprise. 他们投身于一项激动人心的科学事业。 3. We need a spirit of enterprise if we are to overcome our difficulties. 如果我们要克服困难，我们就要有进取精神。 4. His latest business enterprise has attracted a lot of attention. 他最新的企业规划引来了很多关注。', '名词: enterpriser');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lapidary', '[\'læpɪderi]', 'adj.优雅简洁的；宝石的 n.宝石工艺匠；宝石鉴定家', '1. In lapidary inscription a man is not upon oath. 在墓志铭中，人是并非经过发誓的。 2. It was the climax of the lapidary\'s skill. 这是宝石匠技术最高的表演。 3. Nay.It was the climax of the lapidary\'s skill. 这是宝石匠技术高超的表演。 4. Of or relating to the working of stone or gems; lapidary. 刻在石头上的石头或玉石雕刻的或与其有关的；玉石雕刻的', '名词复数: lapidaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arbiter', '[\'ɑːrbɪtər]', 'n.仲裁人；主宰者', '1. The arbiter will have the last say. 仲裁员的裁定是终局性的。 2. Experiment is the final arbiter in science. 实验是科学的最后仲裁者。 3. The only arbiter of good taste in wine is you. 只有你才是葡萄酒口味好与坏的决定者。 4. she was the final arbiter on all matters of fashion. 她是流行款式的最终主宰者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aquiline', '[\'ækwɪlaɪn]', 'adj.鹰的；似鹰的；钩状的', '1. He had a aquiline nose and deep-set brown eyes. 他拥有鹰钩鼻和深邃的棕色眼睛。', '名词: aquilinity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extinction', '[ɪk\'stɪŋkʃn]', 'n.消失；消减；废止', '1. Its extinction is just a question of time. 它的消失只是一个时间问题。 2. The World Dinosaur Valley brings back from extinction the most mammoth creatures our planet has ever known. 恐龙世界将呈现出世界上最多的已然消失的猛犸。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cloying', '[\'klɔɪɪŋ]', 'adj.因过量而厌烦的；甜得发腻的；过于感性的 动词cloy的现在分词形式.', '1. The pleasures of idleness soon cloy. 无所事事的享乐很快就使人厌烦了。 2. She has cloyed with rich food. 她已经吃腻美食。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insider', '[ɪn\'saɪdər]', 'n.局内人；知情人', '1. The situation was described by one insider as \"absolute chaos\". 据一名内部人士说，实情是乱作一团。 2. The insider trading undermined investors\'confidence in the stock market. 这起内线交易案动摇了投资人对股市的信心。 3. Gordon is an insider to what\'s happening on Wall Street. 戈登先生是华尔街所发生的事的内幕知情者。 4. They may rule we had insider knowledge which we should have reported. 他们可能判断出我们知道内情而没有报告。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('superannuated', '[ˌsuːpər\'ænjueɪtɪd]', 'adj.老朽的；退休的；陈旧过时的 动词superannuate的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. Are you still riding that superannuated old bike? 你还骑那辆老掉牙的自行车吗?', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ramshackle', '[\'ræmʃækl]', 'adj.要倒塌似的；摇摇欲坠的', '1. These ramshackle buildings have fallen down. 那几间危房倒坍了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indispensability', '[ɪndɪspensə\'bɪlətɪ]', 'n.不可缺少', '1. Prove your indispensability to customers. 向客户证明您的产品不可缺少。 2. The dream is one personal one part of indispensability. 梦想是一个人不可缺少的一部分。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('postscript', '[\'poʊstskrɪpt]', 'n.附笔', '1. As a postscript to his letter he added that he loved her. 他在信中加上附言，写上了他爱她。 2. He added a brief postscript to his speech, giving the latest figures. 他演讲完又补充说了一些最新数字。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debark', '[dɪ\'bɑːk]', 'vt.卸载 v.(使)下船；(使)登陆', '1. The mermaid in the deep sea, it is brilliant that no matter how lights on the bankare. Debark, what is done? Is a beautiful one interspersed , or a reticent onlooker ? 深海中的人鱼，无论岸上灯火如何辉煌．上岸，去做什么?一个美丽的点缀，还是一个沉默的旁观者？ 2. For the different part of Tripterygium wilfordii obtained in summer，the content range of triptolide in its given order was whole root,root bark,debark root,stem and leaves respectively. 夏季的雷公藤不同部位雷公藤内酯醇的含量高低，依次为全根、根皮、去皮根、茎、叶。 3. All troops will debark for ground assault 所有小队登陆时都会受到地面攻击 4. The debarking production line can be used for MDF and paper manufacturing industry of debark log and small diameter log. Its debarking clean rate is more than 90%. 剥皮备料工段成套生产线适用于造纸和中纤板行业的原木剥皮，主要是将原木、小径木等进行进行原木去皮，削片，其剥净率可达95%25以上。', '名词: debarkation 过去式: debarked 过去分词: debarked 现在分词: debarking 第三人称单数: debarks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deride', '[dɪ\'raɪd]', 'v.嘲笑；愚弄', '1. He derides her naive attitude. 他嘲弄她天真的态度。 2. They derided his efforts as childish. 他们嘲笑他的做法很幼稚。 3. No one has the right to deride the disadvantage of handicapped people. 任何人都没有权利嘲笑残疾人的不利条件。', '副词: deridingly 名词: derider 过去式: derided 过去分词: derided 现在分词: deriding 第三人称单数: derides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decadence', '[\'dekədəns]', 'n.衰落；颓废', '1. The decadence of morals is bad for nation. 道德的堕落对于国家是不利的。 2. But even your dreams will be but a pale shadow of my true decadence. 但你的梦不过是我真实衰落中一个苍白的影子罢了。 3. In time, the foul odor of Roman decadence would grow harder to disguise. 时日一到，罗马矫饰的颓废气味终将难以遮掩。 4. It embraced a decadence and an abandon that set it apart from the rest of Egypt. 这里拥抱着某种颓废和狂放，让它有别于埃及的其它地方。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('edifice', '[\'edɪfɪs]', 'n.大厦；大建筑物；大型支柱', '1. This edifice is used as a working place. 这栋大厦是工作用的。 2. There is a huge Victorian edifice in the area. 该地区有一幢维多利亚式的庞大建筑物。 3. The legislature is housed in an impressive granite edifice. 立法机构位于一幢引人注目的花岗岩大楼里。 4. The whole edifice of his hopes was destroyed . 他心中的希望整个都毁了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('utter', '[\'ʌtər]', 'adj.完全的；全然的；绝对的 v.说；发出；表达', '1. It\'s an utter mystery. 这完全是个谜。 2. What utter rubbish he talks! 他完全是胡说！ 3. A feeling of utter helplessness washed over him. 一种全然无助的感觉涌上他的心头。 4. He wanted to impress this man with his utter willingness to comply and obey. 他要这个人觉得他的绝对屈服与服从。 5. How can you utter such falsehoods? 你怎么能说出这种谎言？', '形容词: utterable 名词: utterer 过去式: uttered 过去分词: uttered 现在分词: uttering 第三人称单数: utters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('torture', '[\'tɔːrtʃər]', 'n.拷问；痛苦 vt.拷问；使痛苦；曲解', '1. The use of torture must disgust any civilized person. 施用酷刑必为文明社会的人所不齿。 2. Torture always dehumanizes both the torturer and his victim. 严刑拷打往往使施刑者和受刑者都丧失人性。 3. She suffered the torture of toothache. 她因牙痛而痛苦。 4. He tortured his prisoners. 他拷打犯人。', '名词: torturer 过去式: tortured 过去分词: tortured 现在分词: torturing 第三人称单数: tortures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('congest', '[kən\'dʒest]', 'vt.使充满；使拥塞；使充血 vi.充塞；充血', '1. The bus is much congested. 公共汽车非常拥挤。 2. He had a cold and was very congested. 他患了感冒，鼻子不通。', '形容词: congestive 名词: congestion 过去式: congested 过去分词: congested 现在分词: congesting 第三人称单数: congests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('refinery', '[rɪ\'faɪnəri]', 'n.精练厂', '1. The oil is carried to the oil refinery by pipelines. 石油通过输油管输送到炼油厂。 2. He has put in repeated requests for permission to help to build the big oil refinery. 他已经屡次提出申请，要求批准他参加建造那座大型炼油厂。 3. She works in a sugar refinery. 她在一家制糖厂工作。 4. He was dismissed from the oil refinery. 他被那家炼油厂解雇了。', '名词复数: refineries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parquet', '[pɑːr\'keɪ]', 'n.镶木地板；剧院正厅部分 v.用镶花地板装修', '1. The parquet floors shone like mirrors. 镶木地板亮得像镜子。 2. He slipped as he tried to waltz on the parquet floor. 他想在镶木地板上旋几个舞步时滑倒了。', '过去式: parqueted 过去分词: parqueted 现在分词: parqueting 第三人称单数: parquets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('underhanded', '[ˌʌndə\'hændɪd]', 'adj.不光明的；卑鄙的；人手不足的', '1. I don\'t believe in getting what you want by underhanded methods. 我认为以不光明的手法获取东西是不应该的。 2. A special news program exposed underhanded auto repair shops that are ripping off senior citizens. 一个特别新闻节目揭露了一家敲榨老年人的卑鄙的汽车维修店。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('withhold', '[wɪð\'hoʊld]', 'v.抑制；阻挡；扣留；保留', '1. The readers cannot withhold their admiration. 读者无法抑制自己的敬佩。 2. How shall I withhold from tears when we part? 我们离别时我如何忍得住眼泪呢？ 3. The dam is too weak to withhold the pressure of the rising water. 水坝不够牢固，抵挡不住水上涨的压力。 4. The board have decide to withhold part of their grant money from certain student. 委员会决定不发给某些学生的部分助学金。', '名词: withholder 过去式: withheld 过去分词: withheld 现在分词: withholding 第三人称单数: withholds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('goggle', '[\'ɡɑːɡl]', 'n.眼睛睁视；护目镜 vi.瞪视；瞪大眼睛看 adj.瞪大眼睛的；凝视的', '1. He goggled at her in surprise. 他惊奇地睁大眼睛看著她。', '形容词: goggly 过去式: goggled 过去分词: goggled 现在分词: goggling 第三人称单数: goggles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diurnal', '[daɪ\'ɜːrnl]', 'adj.每日的；白天的', '1. Over water the diurnal change in refraction is likely to be small. 在水面上，折光的周日变化可能是很小的。 2. A diurnal animal hunts its food during daylight. 白天活动的动物在白昼时猎食。 3. Unlike most other bats, this species is diurnal. 这种蝙蝠与大多数蝙蝠不同，是在日间活动的。', '副词: diurnally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peaky', '[\'piːki]', 'adj.多峰的；似峰的；憔悴的', '1. They tend to be looking a bit peaky and green about the gills. 他们看上去有点憔悴，被吓得脸色苍白。 2. For a while she was peaky and wouldn\'t eat. But she was coming around. 有一阵子她消瘦下去,不想吃什么,但她在恢复过来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verbose', '[vɜː\'bəʊs]', 'adj.罗嗦的；冗长的', '1. On Sunday, though, getting too verbose about your point of view could be awkward, especially when your opinion changes! 然而，礼拜日，你那些过于冗长的观点，可能会让你晕乎乎的，尤其在你想改变观点的时候！ 2. But the bulk calculating costs and the verbose results cause the difficulty of the dynamic analysis. 但是大量的运算成本且冗长的计算结果往往造成动态分析上的困难。', '副词: verbosely 名词: verboseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('licentious', '[laɪ\'senʃəs]', 'adj.放荡的；放肆的', '1. Higher infection was noted in licentious women. 有性乱史的女性支原体感染率较高。 2. This kind of freedom is licentious. 这样的自由是放肆的。 3. She felt uncomfortable for her licentious act. 她对她放肆的行为感到有点不舒服。', '副词: licentiously 名词: licentiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('occult', '[ə\'kʌlt]', 'adj.不可思议的；神秘的；超自然的 n.神秘学', '1. He and the black-leather fellow looked very occult. 他和那个象黑皮革似的家伙显得很神秘。 2. The occult rites of the organization were revealed only to its members. 这个组织的秘密礼仪只有其成员可以知道。 3. Astrology and alchemy are occult sciences. 占星学和炼丹术为神秘之学。 4. He\'s interested in witchcraft and the occult. 他对巫术魔法情有独钟。', '副词: occultly 名词: occultness 过去式: occulted 过去分词: occulted 现在分词: occulting 第三人称单数: occults');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('draftsmanship', '[\'drɑːftsmənˌʃɪp]', 'n.制图术', '1. Its founder made modern Chinese printing into a new era of the draftsmanship. 它的创办,将中国近代印刷带进了石印的新时代。 2. Ege[8] said, no one will challenge Calcar’s draftsmanship by created Versalius Fabrica. 视觉经验与艺术性是 数码插图最重要的一部分。 3. His draftsmanship and technique display an uncanny mechanical reproduction that generates an uncanny reality. 他用手工形成了一个比机械复制更加荒诞的现实。 4. His work demonstrates a mastery of design, colour, composition and draftsmanship. 塞尚的设计、色彩、布局和描绘都十分出色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('redress', '[rɪ\'dres]', 'n.赔偿；救济；矫正；缓解 v.纠正；补偿；革除；惩罚；<古>报答；恢复', '1. Any man deserves redress if he has been injured unfairly. 任何人若蒙受不公平的损害都应获得赔偿。 2. You must seek redress in the law courts for the damage to your car. 你的车子受到了损坏，你应当通过法律途径要求赔偿。 3. If the statute of limitations has run,the plaintiff is without redress. 如果过了法定诉讼时效，原告将无法得到救济。 4. A fault confessed is half redress. 认错改正一半错。 5. The team has more men than women so we must redress the balance. 这个队男的多女的少,所以我们得纠正平衡一下。', '名词: redresser 过去式: redressed 过去分词: redressed 现在分词: redressing 第三人称单数: redresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comparison', '[kəm\'pærɪsn]', 'n.比较；比喻', '1. In comparison with other students, Mike is more diligent. 和其他学生相比，麦克更加勤勉一些。 2. We can only tell good from bad by comparison. 我们可以通过比较来分辨好坏。 3. Reports of consecutive years should also be available for comparison. 网站应登载连续数年的报告,方便读者作比较。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('battalion', '[bə\'tæliən]', 'n.营（军队单位）；军队；大批', '1. This battalion is composed of 800 soldiers. 这个营是由八百个人组成的。 2. The battalion formed up by companies on the barrack square. 全营以连为单位在军营广场上列队。 3. Battalion headquarters has approved the retreat. 军队总部已同意撤退。 4. A whole battalion of soldiers surrounded us in a tight ring. 整个军队把我们紧紧地包围在包围圈中。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deplore', '[dɪ\'plɔːr]', 'vt. 悲叹； 谴责； 对 ... 深感遗憾', '1. Aren\'t Republicans supposed to deplore the politics of victimhood? 难道不该谴责共和党借政治受害者来炒作的行径吗？ 2. Jefferson helped consolidate the power of the national government even as he claimed to deplore and reject such power. 即使杰斐逊公开谴责并抵制国家政府的权力，但他还是帮助巩固了这种权力。', '过去式: deplored 过去分词: deplored 现在分词: deploring 第三人称单数: deplores');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('zest', '[zest]', 'n.热情；风味；(橙子、柠檬等的)皮', '1. He dived into his new job with great zest. 他充满热情地投入了新的工作。 2. The setback did not damp his zest. 挫折没有使他降低热情。 3. He entered into our plans with terrific zest. 他满腔热情的参加了我们的项目。 4. Humor gave zest to his speech. 幽默使他的演说妙趣横生。', '形容词: zestful 副词: zestfully 名词: zestfulness 过去式: zested 过去分词: zested 现在分词: zesting 第三人称单数: zests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mellifluous', '[me\'lɪfluəs]', 'adj.如蜜般的；流畅的；甜美的 =mellifluent.', '1. The sweet witty soul of Ovid lives in mellifluous and honey-tongued Shakespeare. 奥维德的风雅机智的灵魂活在语言甜美流畅的莎士比亚身上。', '副词: mellifluously 名词: mellifluousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marsupial', '[mɑːr\'suːpiəl]', 'n.有袋动物 adj.袋的；袋状的；有袋动物的', '1. Pouches are a peculiarity of marsupials. 腹袋是有袋动物的特色。 2. The koala, which is a marsupial, is like a kangaroo. 树熊，就像袋鼠一样是有袋科动物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maroon', '[mə\'ruːn]', 'adj.褐红色的 n.褐红色；鞭炮；被放逐到孤岛的人 v.使处于孤独无助之境；闲荡', '1. The sailors took command of the ship from the cruel captain and marooned him on a desert island. 水手们从残酷的船长手中夺过了指挥权，把他放逐到一个荒岛上。 2. Pirates used to maroon people on desert islands. 海盗过去惯常把人们遗弃在荒岛。', '过去式: marooned 过去分词: marooned 现在分词: marooning 第三人称单数: maroons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('porcupine', '[\'pɔːrkjupaɪn]', 'n.豪猪；箭猪', '1. A stormbound porcupine whimpered in a treetop. 一只被风雪困住的豪猪在树上悲啼。 2. A porcupine is covered with prickles. 箭猪身上长满了刺。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tangential', '[tæn\'dʒenʃl]', 'adj.离题的；肤浅的；切线的；相切的', '1. It is tangential to our main objective. 这与我们主要目的有偏离。 2. Too much time was spent discussing tangential issues. 太多时间花在讨论肤浅的问题上。', '副词: tangentially 异体字: tangental 名词: tangentiality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impassioned', '[ɪm\'pæʃnd]', 'adj.慷慨激昂的；热烈的 动词impassion的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. He made an impassioned speech in our school. 他在我们学校做了一次慷慨激昂的演讲。 2. He kept this impassioned doings a secret almost from himself 他把他这种感情热烈的行动保守得极秘密，几乎连对自己都不泄露。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vigilant', '[\'vɪdʒɪlənt]', 'adj.警戒的；警惕的', '1. We must keep an vigilant eye upon imperialism. 我们必须对帝国主义保持警戒。 2. A pilot must be vigilant at all times. 飞行员必须随时保持警惕。 3. The night shift has to be doubly vigilant. 值夜班要加倍警惕。 4. The British Prime Minister Gordon Brown has urged people to be vigilant against the potential terrorist attack. 英国首相戈登.', '副词: vigilantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acquittal', '[ə\'kwɪtl]', 'n.开释；宣告无罪', '1. The defence lawyer made an eloquent plea for his client\'s acquittal. 被告方的律师为委托人的无罪开释作了有说服力的辩护。 2. They were enraged at the acquittal of a policeman accused of murder. 大家都很愤怒一个被控谋杀警察的无罪开释。 3. Lack of evidence resulted in their acquittal. 因证据不足而宣判他们无罪。 4. There were three convictions and two acquittals in court today. 今日法庭宣判三人有罪，两人无罪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prickle', '[\'prɪkl]', 'n.(动物或植物上的)刺；棘；刺痛 v.(使）刺痛', '1. The scream sent a prickle down my spine. 尖叫声听得我像针由上到下刺我的脊骨。 2. My scalp began to prickle as I realized the horrible truth. 我了解到了那令人恐惧的事实，顿时感到不寒而栗。', '过去式: prickled 过去分词: prickled 现在分词: prickling 第三人称单数: prickles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carol', '[\'kærəl]', 'n.颂歌；欢乐的歌；卡罗尔（人名） v.欢唱', '1. The bells chimed a Christmas carol. 钟声奏出一曲圣诞颂歌。 2. She struck up the first carol on the grand piano. 她在那架大钢琴上演奏起第一支颂歌。 3. He used to carol cheerfully in the morning. 他以前常在早晨快乐地歌唱。', '名词: caroler 过去式: caroled/carolled 过去分词: caroled/carolled 现在分词: caroling/carolling 第三人称单数: carols/carols');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('moratorium', '[ˌmɔːrə\'tɔːriəm]', 'n.暂停；延期偿付；延期偿付期间', '1. The government has called for a moratorium on weapons testing. 政府已要求暂停武器试验。 2. The convention called for a two-year moratorium on commercial whaling. 会议呼吁两年内暂停商业捕鲸活动。 3. A moratorium or reparations payments emerged soon after the bank began operations 在银行开始营业后不久，就发生了赔款支付的延期偿付。 4. A moratorium or reparations payments emerged soon after the bank began operations. 在银行开始营业后不久，就发生了赔款支付的延期偿付。', '名词复数: moratoriums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anonymity', '[ˌænə\'nɪməti]', 'n.匿名；笔者不明', '1. Except there is that nagging question of anonymity. 而唯一留存的就是那个老生常谈的问题，匿名性。 2. This tradition of guaranteeing anonymity began to develop quickly. 这种担保匿名的传统便开始迅速扩展开来。', '名词复数: anonymities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unctuous', '[\'ʌŋktʃuəs]', 'adj.油腔滑调的；油的；虚情假意的', '1. He speaks in unctuous tones. 他说话油腔滑调。 2. He made an unctuous assurance. 他做了个虚请假意的承诺。', '副词: unctuously 名词: unctuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('synchronous', '[\'sɪŋkrənəs]', 'adj.同时的；同步的', '1. Rrecovery was synchronous with therapy. 恢复与治疗是同时的。 2. The communication between the two tiers is synchronous. 两个层次之间的通信是同步的。 3. A synchronous programming model is much simpler than an asynchronous one. 一个同步的程序模型比一个异步的要简单的多。', '副词: synchronously 名词: synchronousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vandalize', '[\'vændəlaɪz]', 'vt.肆意破坏', '1. The damage to the painting was the work of vandal. 毁坏这幅画的事是恣意破坏公物的人干的。 2. Do not go beyond or vandalize the obstruction sign. 切勿超越防撞牌或恣意破坏防撞牌。 3. Goblin Vandal deals no combat damage this turn. 莽撞鬼怪本回合不造成战斗伤害。 4. V is a Vandal, who likes to destroy. 是野蛮人，专门搞破坏。', '名词: vandalization 过去式: vandalized 过去分词: vandalized 现在分词: vandalizing 第三人称单数: vandalizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('weather', '[\'weðər]', 'n.天气；气象；境遇 vt.使风化；经受住；使日晒雨淋 vi.风化；褪色；经受风雨 adj.上风的；天气预报的', '1. What is the weather like today? 今天天气情况怎样？ 2. The meteorologist drew a picture of the weather. 气象学者画了一张气象图。 3. The past years had known him in many weathers. 过去的岁月里,他起起落落。 4. The rocks on the mountain have to be weathered by wind and water. 山上的岩石得经受风化和水蚀。 5. The paint on the walls had weathered. 墙壁上的涂料已经风干了。 6. Fill in the form below about the weather report. 续下面关于天气预报的表格。', '过去式: weathered 过去分词: weathered 现在分词: weathering 第三人称单数: weathers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chronic', '[\'krɑːnɪk]', 'adj.长期的；慢性的；惯常的', '1. There is a chronic unemployment problem in America. 在美国存在长期失业问题。 2. We finally won in this chronic war. 我们终于打赢了这场长期战争。 3. My brother has chronic bronchitis. 我的哥哥患有慢性支气管炎。 4. Have you got any chronic diseases in the past? 你过去有没有慢性病?', '副词: chronically 名词: chronicity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('manifesto', '[ˌmænɪ\'festoʊ]', 'n.宣言；声明 vi.发表宣言', '1. The Rosicrucian manifesto created quite a stir in European circles. 蔷薇十字会的宣言对欧洲造成相当大的震动。 2. The manifesto was crucial to the intellectual response to the war. 就知识界对战争的回应而言，宣言是至关重要的。 3. The party released its manifesto yesterday. 该党昨天发表了它的声明。 4. Do you have a mission statement or a manifesto?What can people expect to see there? 你的博客有关于使命任务一类的声明或者说明吗？', '名词复数: manifestoes 过去式: manifestoed 过去分词: manifestoed 现在分词: manifestoing 第三人称单数: manifestoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('teem', '[tiːm]', 'v.充满；富于；把……倒空；倾泻', '1. The river teems with all kinds of fish in summer. 夏天这条河里各种各样的鱼多得很。 2. The rain teemed down for hours. 大雨一直下了好几个小时。', '副词: teemingly 名词: teemer 过去式: teemed 过去分词: teemed 现在分词: teeming 第三人称单数: teems');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sheaf', '[ʃiːf]', 'n.束 v.捆；束', '1. He drew a sheaf of papers from his breast pocket. 他从上衣口袋里抽出一札文件。 2. The speaker had a sheaf of notes on the desk in front of him. 演讲者在他面前的桌子上放着一叠笔记。', '名词复数: sheaves 过去式: sheafed 过去分词: sheafed 现在分词: sheafing 第三人称单数: sheafs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pantry', '[\'pæntri]', 'n.食品储藏室；餐具室', '1. Tom was detected stealing cookies in the pantry. 汤姆在储藏室偷点心时被抓获。 2. No food was left in the pantry except some bread. 食品柜里除了一些面包其它什么也不剩。 3. He wanted to find some wine in the pantry. 他想在餐具室里找到一些酒。', '名词复数: pantries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subvention', '[səb\'venʃn]', 'n.补助金；津贴；援助', '1. Income from government subvention is recognised on an accruals basis. 政府补助金收入按应计制确认。 2. The association is funded by an annual subvention from the government. 协会的经费每年由政府拨款援助。', '形容词: subventionary');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rustle', '[\'rʌsl]', 'v.发出沙沙声；沙沙作响地移动；偷（牛马）；急速弄到 n.沙沙声；瑟瑟声；飒飒声', '1. A cold wind rustled the leaves. 寒风刮得树叶沙沙响。 2. Her silk dress rustled as she moved. 她走起路来丝绸衣裙沙沙作响。 3. He heard a mouse rustling among his papers. 他听见纸堆中有老鼠作响。 4. I\'ll try and rustle you up something to eat. 我设法给你弄点吃的。 5. The rustle of her pretty skirt was like music to him. 她的漂亮的裙子发出沙沙声，在他听来像音乐那样美妙。', '副词: rustlingly 名词: rustler 过去式: rustled 过去分词: rustled 现在分词: rustling 第三人称单数: rustles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('autobiography', '[ˌɔːtəbaɪ\'ɑːɡrəfi]', 'n.自传', '1. Iacocca\'s autobiography is a best- seller. 艾科卡的自传是一本畅销书。 2. He rounded out his quartet with an autobiography. 他以自传作为他的四部曲的结尾。', '形容词: autobiographic 副词: autobiographically 名词: autobiographer 名词复数: autobiographies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avowal', '[ə\'vaʊəl]', 'n.公开宣称；公开承认；坦白承认', '1. To make an earnest avowal or affirmation. 申明郑重地宣誓或肯定 2. The while flag of surrender is an avowal of defeat. 公开宣称;坦白承认。 3. The white flag of surrender is an avowal of defeat. 投降的白旗表示公开宣称战败。 4. Many a man thinks, what he is ashamed to avow. 坦率承认,公开地,大胆地,不害羞地承认;坦白', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inflamed', '[ɪn\'fleɪmd]', 'adj.发炎的；红肿的 动词inflame的过去式和过去分词.', '1. He is suffering from an inflamed throat. 他正承受着咽喉发炎之苦。 2. He addressed the others with extravagant gestures, blinking his inflamed eyelids. 他手舞足蹈地对大家讲着，眨着红肿眼皮。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apostasy', '[ə\'pɒstəsi]', 'n.背教；脱党；变节', '1. He was looked down upon for apostasy. 他因背教而受轻视。 2. Apostasy often has its roots in moral failure. 背教的人通常是先在道德方面一败涂地，', '名词复数: apostasies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demand', '[dɪ\'mænd]', 'n.要求；需求 v.要求；查问；需要', '1. Their demand is entirely justified. 他们的要求是完全正当的。 2. The demand for coal begins to slacken off in the spring. 煤的需求在春天开始减少。 3. He had the impertinence to demand a raise. 他竟冒失地要求增加工资。 4. The policeman demanded their names. 那个警察查问了他们的名字。', '形容词: demandable 名词: demander 过去式: demanded 过去分词: demanded 现在分词: demanding 第三人称单数: demands');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monetary', '[\'mʌnɪteri]', 'adj.货币的；金融的', '1. The monetary unit of the US is the dollar. 美国的货币单位是元。 2. He has changed his stance on monetary union. 他已经改变了对货币联盟的态度。 3. The monetary system of some countries used to be based on gold. 过去有些国家的货币制度是金本位制的。 4. The current monetary policy is strangling the economy. 现行金融政策抑制了经济的发展。', '副词: monetarily');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('designation', '[ˌdezɪɡ\'neɪʃn]', 'n.指示；指定；任命；命名', '1. The designation of Inshore Defense Strategy came from comrade Deng Xiaoping\"s instructions. 近海防御战略的名称来源于邓小平同志的指示。 2. Only a string can be given this designation. 只能对字符串做这种指定。 3. Does a professional who is licensed to practice need the designation? 被授权开业的专业人员需要指定吗? 4. The president is responsible for the designation of ambassadors. 总统负责对大使的任命。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consent', '[kən\'sent]', 'n.同意；赞成 v.同意；答应', '1. My father will never give his consent to our marriage. 我父亲决不会同意我们的婚姻的。 2. By the common consent of critics, Shakespeare is the prince of character delineators. 评论家一致公认莎士比亚是刻画人物的大师。 3. Her smile implied her consent to our proposal. 她的微笑暗示她赞成我们的提议。 4. On the other hand, it is not likely that the few landlords from the upper strata of the Miao nationality will consent to their demand. 但是这样的要求，可能苗族上层少数地主分子不赞成。 5. I\'m sure he wouldn\'t consent 我确信他不会同意。', '名词: consenter 过去式: consented 过去分词: consented 现在分词: consenting 第三人称单数: consents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cephalic', '[sɪ\'fælɪk]', 'adj.头的；头部的', '1. But the cephalic veins are sometimes difficult to isolate. 但部分患者分离头静脉存在困难。 2. One of the best areas for the cannula is the cephalic vein in the shoulder area. 肩部的头静脉是放置静脉导管最好的部位之一。', '副词: cephalically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('litigant', '[\'lɪtɪɡənt]', 'n.诉讼当事人 adj.诉讼的', '1. As to this case, I suggest that we should go to ask the litigant. 关于这个案子，我建议我们去问问当事人。 2. In civil proceedings, the litigants shall have equal litigant rights. 民事诉讼中,当事人有平等的诉讼权利。 3. The litigant participant and others shall abide by the rules of the court. 诉讼参与人和其他人应当遵守法庭规则。 4. The litigant procedure shall resume after the cause of the suspension is removed. 中止诉讼的原因消除后，恢复诉讼。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('charm', '[tʃɑːrm]', 'n.魅力；吸引力；迷人；美貌 v.（使）着迷；施魔法', '1. Her charm rests in her happy smile. 她的魅力在于她幸福的微笑。 2. The use of dialect lent great charm to the work . 方言的运用给这部作品增添了巨大的魅力。 3. The hotel is full of charm and character. 这家旅馆风格独特，极具吸引力。 4. Her charm prejudiced the judges in her favour. 她姿色迷人，因而评委都偏向她。 5. He guessed the idea would charm his publisher. 他认为这个主意能让他的出版商着迷。', '形容词: charmless 副词: charmingly 过去式: charmed 过去分词: charmed 现在分词: charming 第三人称单数: charms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('premeditated', '[ˌpriː\'medɪteɪtɪd]', 'adj.有预谋的 动词premeditate的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. The crime was premeditated. 犯罪是预谋好的。 2. He faced two counts of premeditated murder. 他被控犯有两宗有预谋的杀人案。', '副词: premeditatedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maple', '[\'meɪpl]', 'n.【C】枫树；槭树 n.【U】枫树干', '1. The maple leaf is the emblem of Canada. 枫叶是加拿大的象征。 2. The maple leaves are tinged with autumn red. 枫叶染上了秋天的红色。 3. The garden is flanked to the north with large maple trees. 花园的北侧是一些高大的枫树。 4. The weather is warm up and the sap is rising in the maple. 天气在转暖，槭树的树液在上升。 5. The maple is a good material for furniture. 枫树干是做家具的好材料。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snob', '[snɑːb]', 'n.势利小人；自命不凡的人', '1. Every one begrudged helping this snob. 每个人都不愿意帮助这势利小人。 2. He is a snob of the first water. 他是个头号势利小人。', '形容词: snobby');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impudent', '[\'ɪmpjədənt]', 'adj.无礼的；鲁莽的；卑鄙的', '1. He was impudent enough to call me a fool. 他无礼至极，竟然叫我傻瓜。 2. That impudent boy put his tongue out at me. 那个无礼的男孩冲著我吐舌头。 3. The teacher threatened to kick the impudent pupil out of the room. 老师威胁着要把这无礼的小学生撵出教室。 4. We mustn\'t give way to these impudent demands. 我们对这些蛮横的要求不能让步。', '副词: impudently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jade', '[dʒeɪd]', 'n.玉石；翡翠；翡翠色', '1. It\'s a collection of Chinese jade. 这是收藏的一批中国玉器。 2. These wine glasses were sold at half price because of blemishes in the jade. 这些酒杯半价出售，因为玉上有瑕疵。 3. This jade dragon is a genuine antique. 这件玉龙是真正的古玩。 4. I have a pair of jade bracelets. 我有一对翡翠手镯。', '过去式: jaded 过去分词: jaded 现在分词: jading 第三人称单数: jades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emote', '[ɪ\'moʊt]', 'vi.激动地表达感情', '1. Emote freely.Save celebratory gems for use outside. 你在上帝和众人面前愿意这样行吗？ 2. The dance emote got a ton of laughs. 舞蹈动作招来了一场大笑。 3. The /cower emote now has an animation. 奶牛这个表情将会加入动作。 4. That emote is hilarious. xD I hope they use it! 这面是热闹。我希望他们使用它！', '名词: emoter 过去式: emoted 过去分词: emoted 现在分词: emoting 第三人称单数: emotes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dissociate', '[dɪ\'soʊʃieɪt]', 'v.分离；使脱离关系；游离；分裂', '1. She tried to dissociate the two events in her mind. 她试图从思想上将这两件事分开。 2. I want to dissociate myself from my companions. 我想要与我的同伴断绝关系。 3. I wish to dissociate myself from what has just been said. 我要否认与刚刚说的话有关。', '形容词: dissociative 过去式: dissociated 过去分词: dissociated 现在分词: dissociating 第三人称单数: dissociates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apocrypha', '[ə\'pɑːkrɪfə]', 'n.伪经；伪书；可疑著作', '1. Why do you give me this tainted Apocrypha, this thousandth copy, this inept falsification? 为什么给我这本污损过的伪经，这第一千次的抄本，笨拙的伪造？', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('misperceive', '[ˌmɪspə\'siːv]', 'vt.看错；误解', '1. If we are ignorant of the facts of reality, or if we misperceive them, our mental construct cannot be correct. 如果我们忽略现实，或是对现实误察，我们的心理建构就不会正确。 2. When we misperceive microexpressions, we can make false assumptions about the people with whom we communicate. 如果我们错误的理解“微表情”的含义，我们会对交流对象形成错误的判断。 3. Since we aren\'t actually moving and the figure is static, we misperceive the straight lines as curved ones. 可是因为人们实际上并没有移动而画面也是静止的所以人们就错误地理解为直线弯曲了。 4. to misperceive the points of the compass 看错方位', '名词: misperception 过去式: misperceived 过去分词: misperceived 现在分词: misperceiving 第三人称单数: misperceives');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acquaint', '[ə\'kweɪnt]', 'vt.使了解；使熟知；告知', '1. We should first try to acquaint ourselves with the facts. 我们先要想法了解事实。 2. These books acquaint Chinese readers with the ancient cultures of these lands. 这些书帮助中国读者了解这些地区的古代文化。 3. You must acquaint yourself with your new duties. 你必须熟悉自己的新职务。 4. Please acquaint him with my arrival. 请通知他我到了。', '过去式: acquainted 过去分词: acquainted 现在分词: acquainting 第三人称单数: acquaints');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dissimulate', '[dɪ\'sɪmjuleɪt]', 'v.掩饰；假装；装糊涂', '1. Checked motifs dissimulate their patterns under a layer of black pigments. 格子基调在黑颜料层下掩饰了它们图形。', '形容词: dissimulative 名词: dissimulation 过去式: dissimulated 过去分词: dissimulated 现在分词: dissimulating 第三人称单数: dissimulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gist', '[dʒɪst]', 'n.要点；主旨', '1. He is quick in grasping the gist of a book. 他敏于了解书的要点。 2. He can not understand the gist of their argument. 他不明白他们争论的要点。 3. I cannot understand the gist of the article. 我不理解这篇文章的主旨。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chirp', '[tʃɜːrp]', 'v.吱喳而鸣；轻松愉快地说 n.喳喳声；唧唧声', '1. At night the crickets chirp in the woods. 夜里蟋蟀在林中唧唧地叫。 2. Birds had begun to chirp among the trees. 鸟儿们已经开始在树林里叽叽喳喳地叫了。 3. I was awakened by the chirps of the birds this morning. 今天早晨我被鸟叫声唤醒。 4. A cricket an inch long has a chirp that is audible for nearly a mile. 一英寸长的蟋蟀发出的唧唧声在将近一英里远的地方都能听见。', '过去式: chirped 过去分词: chirped 现在分词: chirping 第三人称单数: chirps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mull', '[mʌl]', 'v.思索；(充分)碾碎；混合 vt.加糖和香料并烫热 n.麦尔纱(一种涤绵织物) n.(苏格兰)海角；岬；乱糟糟', '1. I haven\'t decided yet; I\'m mulling it over in my mind. 我还没有决定，一直在仔细考虑。 2. He tried to mull things over in his mind. 他试图在他的脑海中思索事情。 3. Now we shall be able to mull some ale! 现在我们可以用它来调热甜酒了！ 4. I nearly made a mull of the business. 我几乎把生意弄得一团糟。', '过去式: mulled 过去分词: mulled 现在分词: mulling 第三人称单数: mulls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hallowed', '[\'hæloʊd]', 'adj.神圣的；受崇拜的 动词hallow的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. Until men united wield a hallowed sabre. 人们联合起来挥动那把神圣的军刀。 2. It\'s one of the theatre\'s most hallowed traditions. 这是戏院最受尊崇的传统之一。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('initiative', '[ɪ\'nɪʃətɪv]', 'adj.自发的 n.首创精神；主动权；第一步；倡议；项目', '1. She took an initiative part in the Wildlife Conservation Society. 她主动参加野生动物保护协会。 2. It is innovation plus initiative that has kept it thriving. 创新与进取精神使得它蓬勃发展。 3. In the economic trend of the new era, having the initiative is the key. 在新时期的经济大潮中，拥有主动权是关键。 4. Thus the initiative was lost at the very first move, and that is really the worst and most stupid way to fight. 开脚一步就丧失了主动权，真是最蠢最坏的打法。', '副词: initiatively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('climax', '[\'klaɪmæks]', 'n.高潮；极点；层进法；[生]顶极群落；巅峰，最高峰', '1. The music approached a climax. 乐曲接近高潮。 2. The climax of the celebration was a firework display. 庆祝会的高潮是燃放烟火。 3. The heat of summer has reached its climax. 已经是夏季最热的天气了。 4. The air war over Europe was reaching its climax. 欧洲的空战已近白热化。', '过去式: climaxed 过去分词: climaxed 现在分词: climaxing 第三人称单数: climaxes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thicket', '[\'θɪkɪt]', 'n.繁茂处；丛林；草丛', '1. We crawled into the thicket and hid. 我们爬进灌林丛,躲了起来。 2. A fox dart out of the midst of the thicket. 一只狐狸从灌木丛中窜了出来。 3. We were now at the margin of the thicket. 我们现在已经来到了丛林的边缘。 4. Suddenly he dashed into a bamboo thicket. 他忽然向竹丛里跑去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('char', '[tʃɑːr]', 'v.(使)烧成炭；(使)烧焦 v.<英>做杂役女佣 n.烧焦物；炭 n.杂役女工 n.茶', '1. They are charring wood in a kiln. 他们正在窑内将木头烧成木炭。 2. When she was eighteen, she went out as a char lady. 她18岁时外出当打杂女工。', '过去式: charred 过去分词: charred 现在分词: charring 第三人称单数: chars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agog', '[ə\'ɡɑːɡ]', 'adj.兴奋的；有强烈兴趣的', '1. The prospect of Christmas left the children agog. 对圣诞节的憧憬使得孩子们兴奋不已 2. The people are all agog to know the news about the World Cup. 人们都渴望得知世界杯足球赛的消息。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('granule', '[\'ɡrænjuːl]', 'n.小粒；微粒', '1. Produce of The New Plastic Granule. 生产新型塑料粒子项目。 2. Crushing and finishing granule of mass material. 团块物料的粉碎、整粒。 3. Sell Black salt (Lumps, Power, Granule. 出售黑盐(疙瘩、电力、冲剂). 4. Dispensing granule of Iristectorum Maxim. 川射干颗粒', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defoliator', '[diː\'foʊlɪˌeɪtə]', 'n.除叶剂；食叶之昆虫', '1. The key pests and rat include: nematodiasis of the pines and pine moth, forest rats, defoliator of the poplars, bristletail. 二是松毛虫、森林鼠害、杨树食叶害虫等常发性病虫害；三是小蠹虫、萧氏松茎象等钻蛀性害虫。 2. Apatura ilia is an important defoliator of Sslix matsudana and the paper stressfully describes its morphology. 柳紫闪蛱蝶是危害柳树的一种食叶性害虫,本文着重描述了该虫的外部形态特征。 3. Pineus armandicola Zhang is an important defoliator of armand pine( Pinus armandi ). 华山松球蚜 (PineusarmandicolaZhang)是华山松 (PinusarmandiFranch)的重要食叶性害虫。 4. Ivela ochropoda is one of the main defoliator pest occurred in Ulmus pumila, and is very serious in Wuqi County. 摘要榆毒蛾是榆树的食叶害虫之一，在吴起县发生严重。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cistern', '[\'sɪstərn]', 'n.蓄水池；水箱', '1. Water in the cistern is full. 贮水池的水是满的。 2. He managed to stop the overflow from the cistern. 他设法止住水溢出水箱外。', '形容词: cisternal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sprig', '[sprɪɡ]', 'n.小树枝；图钉 v.用小树枝装饰；用钉子钉上', '1. He wore a sprig of lilac in his button hole. 他在钮孔上面插了一小枝丁香。', '名词: sprigger 过去式: sprigged 过去分词: sprigged 现在分词: sprigging 第三人称单数: sprigs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insanity', '[ɪn\'sænəti]', 'n.疯狂；精神错乱；荒唐', '1. Genius is but one remove from insanity. 天才与疯狂之间只有毫厘之差。 2. Love: a temporary insanity curable by marriage. 爱情：可以由婚姻治愈的暂时的疯狂。 3. Love is a temporary insanity curable by marriage. 爱情是暂时性的癫狂,必须用婚姻来治愈。 4. In his defense he alleged temporary insanity. 在答辩中，他提出短暂的精神错乱为借口。', '名词复数: insanities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inch', '[ɪntʃ]', 'n.英寸；少量 v.慢慢移动 （复）inches: 身高.', '1. She shortened the shirt by an inch. 她把衬衫截短了一英寸。 2. The candle grew down until only an inch was left. 蜡烛越来越短,最后只剩下一英寸了。 3. There was an inch of snow on the ground. 地上积着一英寸厚的白雪。 4. They climbed the steep mountain inch by inch. 他们一点一点地攀上那座陡峭的山。 5. Prices are inching down. 物价在慢慢下降。 6. His legs are too long for his inches. 就他的身高而言，他的腿太长了。', '过去式: inched 过去分词: inched 现在分词: inching 第三人称单数: inches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fretwork', '[\'fretwɜːrk]', 'n.格子细工(在木头上雕出各种图案)', '1. a fretwork of sunlight and shadow 日光与树影交错而成的图案 2. Four-side fretwork square wine vessel, 藏品简介：釉下四方透雕方尊 3. the carved fretwork; an intricately carved door; stood as if carven from stone. 浮雕细工；刻划杂乱的门；像雕刻的石像一样站着。 4. the carved fretwork; an intricately carved door; stood as if carven from stone 浮雕细工；刻划杂乱的门；像雕刻的石像一样站着', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dupe', '[duːp]', 'n.受骗的人；上当者 vt.欺骗；愚弄', '1. Though much publicized to dupe the people,this pledge came to nothing. 此保证曾被大作宣传欺骗人民，但没有收到效果。 2. He held the blotter in his hand and contemplated it in stupid delight, almost ready to laugh at the hallucination of which he had been the dupe. 他拿着那吸墨纸，不断地看，呆头呆脑地感到幸运，几乎笑了出来，说自己竟会受到错觉的愚弄。', '形容词: dupable 名词: dupability 过去式: duped 过去分词: duped 现在分词: duping 第三人称单数: dupes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preoccupation', '[priˌɑːkju\'peɪʃn]', 'n.占据思想；全神贯注；心里总想着的事物', '1. She found his preoccupation with money irritating. 她发觉他心里只有钱，感到很生气。 2. A pension is not usually one of the preoccupations of an eighteen year-old! 一个十八岁的人通常是不会老惦记着养老金的！ 3. He always takes his preoccupation with the educational cause. 他总是一心想着教育事业。 4. She spoke slowly, in a state of preoccupation. 她说话慢吞吞的，显得心事重重。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dietetics', '[ˌdaɪə\'tetɪks]', 'n.营养学', '1. I heard that she was majoring in dietetics. 我听说她是学营养学的。 2. You have a bad diet habit and I don\'t think you know dietetics. 你的饮食习惯很差,我认为你对营养学一无所知。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gainsay', '[ˌɡeɪn\'seɪ]', 'v.否认；反驳', '1. She is a fine woman - that nobody can gainsay. 她是个好女人－无人能否认。 2. No one will gainsay his integrity. 没有人对他的正直有话可讲。 3. Beyond gainsay it is a genuine Rembrandt. 无可否认地，那是真的伦布兰特（的画）。 4. I will not gainsay love, called love forsooth. 我不想问：真有爱这回事吗？有就有吧--', '名词: gainsayer 过去式: gainsaid 过去分词: gainsaid 现在分词: gainsaying 第三人称单数: gainsays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pendent', '[\'pendənt]', 'adj.下垂的；悬而未决的 =pendant.', '1. When will the pendent problem be solved? 这个悬而未决的问题什么时候能解决呢？ 2. As coming to an agreement, we made a substantive progress in solving pendent trouble. 在达成共识后，我们在解决悬而未决的问题时取得了一个实质性进步。', '副词: pendently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('packed', '[pækt]', 'adj.塞满的；收拾好行李的；紧压的 动词pack的过去式和过去分词.', '1. The chaplain came and preached to a packed church. 牧师来给挤满教堂的人们讲道。 2. In a packed and silent courtroom the judge began to sum up. 在挤满人的肃静的法庭上，法官开始对诉讼案件加以扼要评述。 3. Yet he took time out from his packed schedule to receive us. 他非常繁忙，但仍挤出时间来接见我们。 4. I\'m all packed and ready to go. 我已打点好行装，等待出发了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ineptitude', '[ɪ\'neptɪtuːd]', 'n.不适当；愚笨；愚昧的言行', '1. History testifies to the ineptitude of coalitions in waging war. 历史昭示我们,多数国家联合作战,其进行甚为困难。 2. They joked about his ineptitude. 他们取笑他的笨拙。 3. TV cameras would follow you throughout, revealing your inexperience and ineptitude. 电视摄像机将对你全程追踪，把你缺乏经验和愚笨无能的模样都暴露在镜头下。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wary', '[\'weri]', 'adj.小心的；机警的', '1. He was wary of telling state secrets. 他小心翼翼以免泄漏国家机密。 2. Hood was wary but he grew to trust her. 胡德一开始将信将疑，但后来信任她了。 3. Lucy learned at school about being wary of strangers. 露西在学校里学会了要提防陌生人。 4. She was wary of strangers. 她对陌生人很警惕。', '副词: warily 比较级: warier 最高级: wariest 名词: wariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('encounter', '[ɪn\'kaʊntər]', 'n.意外的相见；邂逅；遭遇 v.遭遇；遇到；偶然碰到', '1. If both participate, it may be an actual encounter of bodiless consciousness. 如果是双向的，这会是一个真实的与灵魂的相见。 2. A fortunate encounter brought us together. 一次幸运的邂逅使我们相识。 3. It was a bloody encounter between the two armies. 这是那两军之间的一次激烈的遭遇战。 4. Don\'t be afraid to encounter risks. 不要害怕遭遇危险。', '过去式: encountered 过去分词: encountered 现在分词: encountering 第三人称单数: encounters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('superb', '[suː\'pɜːrb]', 'adj.极好的', '1. The sports facilities are superb in this city. 这个城市的运动设施是一流的。 2. The goalkeeper brought off a superb save. 守门员漂亮地救出了险球。 3. Ideas will come to you easily and some will prove to be superb. 你总很容易就能想到好计划，其中一些将得到极好的证实。', '副词: superbly 名词: superbness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('succinct', '[sək\'sɪŋkt]', 'adj.简洁的', '1. Milton summarizes the people\'s case in many such succinct passages. 弥尔顿在许多简洁的段落中概括了人民的处境。', '副词: succinctly 比较级: succincter 最高级: succinctest 名词: succinctness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inebriate', '[ɪn\'iːbrɪˌeɪt]', 'v.使醉 adj.喝醉的；陶醉的 n.酒徒', '1. Drinking tea can inebriate people in summer. 夏季饮茶不当也会让人有醉的感觉。 2. I closed my eyes, and inebriated in clear moonlight and faint fragrance . 我闭上眼睛，陶醉于清亮的月光与幽香中。', '名词: inebriation 过去式: inebriated 过去分词: inebriated 现在分词: inebriating 第三人称单数: inebriates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mentor', '[\'mentɔːr]', 'n.指导者 v.指导', '1. He fed on the great ideas of his mentor. 他以他导师的伟大思想为支撑。 2. The key to mastering any new job is finding the right mentor. 对新工作尽快上手的窍门，就是找对职业导师。 3. When they want to learn more, mentor. 如果这些年轻人想了解更多，那么就教导他们吧。', '过去式: mentored 过去分词: mentored 现在分词: mentoring 第三人称单数: mentors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('colloquy', '[\'kɑːləkwi]', 'n.谈话；会话；自由讨论', '1. They entered into eager colloquy with each other. 他们展开热切的相互交谈。 2. Miss Ophelia rose from this encouraging colloquy. 奥菲丽亚小姐觉得这段对话还比较满意，问完之后就站起身来。 3. Colloquy is a conversation which St. 交谈就是与天主对话。 4. The colloquy which followed was brief and to the point. 两人的对话既简短，又直截了当。', '名词复数: colloquies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brackish', '[\'brækɪʃ]', 'adj.（水）略咸的', '1. Are brackish with the salt of human tears! 人类眼泪的盐分已使得你咸涩难尝！ 2. Occasionally found in brackish waters. 偶然地发现于半咸淡水域. 3. He nods while he pours me a pint of brackish ale. 他一边点头一边给我倒了一杯啤酒。 4. The system can desalinate up to 600 liters of brackish water a day. 这个系统一天可以将高于600公升的盐水去盐。', '名词: brackishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('botany', '[\'bɑːtəni]', 'n.植物学；植物', '1. To what degree are you interested in botany? 你对植物学的兴趣达到什么程度？ 2. In learning botany, I understand much about nature. 学习植物学使我对大自然了解了许多。 3. Botany deals with the study of plants. 植物学论述植物的研究。 4. He taught Irene botany and natural history. 他教绮瑞娜认识植物和学习自然史。', '名词复数: botanies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('charity', '[\'tʃærəti]', 'n.慈善；宽厚；慈善机关(团体)；仁慈', '1. They did so under the mask of charity. 他们是打着慈善的幌子这么做的。 2. True charity doesn\'t consist in almsgiving. 真正的慈善不在于施舍。 3. She was always very generous in her charity. 她行善时总是很慷慨。 4. She regards his moral faults with charity. 她宽恕他的品行不端。', '名词复数: charities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('orchestra', '[\'ɔːrkɪstrə]', 'n.管弦乐队', '1. The orchestra tuned their instruments. 乐队在给乐器调音。 2. The orchestra has several concert engagements. 这管弦乐队已安排好几场音乐会。 3. This orchestra has been established under the patronage of the government. 这个交响乐团是在政府赞助下成立的。', '形容词: orchestral 副词: orchestrally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unsubstantiated', '[ˌʌnsəb\'stænʃieɪtɪd]', 'adj.无事实根据的', '1. His attack of the president was unsubstantiated. 说他袭击总统是没有事实根据的。 2. Many newspapers quoted figures that are unsubstantiated. 许多报纸采用了未经证实的数字。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dilatory', '[\'dɪlətɔːri]', 'adj.缓慢的；拖拉的；拖延的', '1. The dilatory limousine came rolling up the drive. 那辆姗姗来迟的大型轿车沿着汽车道开了上来。 2. The boss sacked a dilatory worker. 老板解雇了一个凡事爱拖拉的工人。 3. It is dilatory of you not to answer to me. 你真会拖，都没回我的信。 4. The Government has been dilatory in condemning the outrage. 政府迟迟才谴责是次暴行。', '副词: dilatorily 名词: dilatoriness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('convert', '[kən\'vɜːrt]', 'v.(使)转变；使…改变信仰；转化；兑换；换算 n.皈依者；改变信仰的人', '1. The solar cell can convert the energy of sunlight into electric energy. 太阳能电池能把阳光的能量转化为电能。 2. The old barn we bought to convert into flats was practically tumbling down. 那个旧谷仓我们买下想改建住房的，实际上已经快塌了。 3. My mother has converted to Catholicism. 我母亲已转而信仰天主教。 4. Coal can be converted to gas. 煤可以转化成煤气。 5. He is a recent convert to Christianity. 他最近改信基督教了。', '过去式: converted 过去分词: converted 现在分词: converting 第三人称单数: converts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('phenomenal', '[fə\'nɑːmɪnl]', 'adj.现象的；可感知的；非凡的', '1. Rather, our explanation will always require explanatorily primitive principles to bridge the gap from the physical to the phenomenal. 而是，我们的解释会一直必须一个基础解释原理来桥接物理和现象的鸿沟。 2. The phenomenal growth that has enabled Matsushita to rank so highly. 松下公司非凡的发展速度，使它名列前茅。', '副词: phenomenally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prosperity', '[prɑː\'sperəti]', 'n.繁荣；兴旺', '1. The new government ushered in a period of prosperity. 新政府的成立带来了一个繁荣的时期。 2. The empire was on the wane after its period of prosperity. 帝国经过全盛以后逐渐衰落。 3. We hope to have a life of happiness and prosperity. 我们希望拥有成功幸福的生活。 4. Prosperity destroys fools and endangers the wise. 繁荣兴旺既毁了蠢人，也使智者陷于险境。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('terminal', '[\'tɜːrmɪnl]', 'n.末端；终点站；终点；终端机；航站楼 adj.末端的；终点的；晚期的；（每）学期的', '1. That terminal is live. 那个接头有电。 2. A record message is played when the airport bus approaches the terminal. 当机场班车接近终点时，播放了注意事项录音。 3. I\'ll keep with you to the bus terminal. 我陪你到公共汽车终点站。 4. Please wait for me at the bus terminal. 请在公共汽车终点站等我。 5. Telomere locates on the terminal of DNA containing repeat DNA sequence. 端粒是位于染色体末端的串联重复核苷酸序列。', '副词: terminally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assent', '[ə\'sent]', 'n.同意；赞成 vi.赞成', '1. The government gave its assent to the new project. 政府同意了新的工程项目。 2. I can never assent to such a request. 我决不能同意这种要求。', '形容词: assentive 副词: assentingly 名词: assenter 过去式: assented 过去分词: assented 现在分词: assenting 第三人称单数: assents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rack', '[ræk]', 'n.行李架；（放衣物、碗碟等的）架子；拷问台；折磨；（比赛开始前固定球位置的）三角框 vt.使痛苦；把...放在架子上；累计取得', '1. He put his bag on the luggage rack. 他把包放在行李架上。 2. He put his shoes on the rack. 他把鞋放在架子上。 3. The famous ancient Chinese politician ShangYang was put on the rack. 中国古代著名的政治家商鞅被施以拉肢之刑。 4. We will all be on the rack until the exam results are published. 在考试结果公布之前,我们将一直焦虑不安。 5. I was racked with doubt and pain. 我满腹疑虑,痛苦万分。', '名词: racker 过去式: racked 过去分词: racked 现在分词: racking 第三人称单数: racks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wail', '[weɪl]', 'v.痛哭；发出似哭的尖声；悲叹 n.痛哭；尖叫声', '1. There\'s no use wailing about/over mistakes made in the past. 为过去的错误痛哭是没有用的。 2. The women gathered around and began to wail. 妇女们围拢在一起,开始嚎啕大哭。 3. The wind wailed in the forest all night. 风在林子里彻夜呼啸。 4. She was wailing for her lost child. 她为死去的孩子伤心悲痛. 5. Newborn babies begin their life with a wail. 新生儿痛哭一声便开始了他们的生命。', '副词: wailingly 名词: wailer 过去式: wailed 过去分词: wailed 现在分词: wailing 第三人称单数: wails');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whiff', '[wɪf]', 'n.一吹；一阵香气；香烟的一口 v.轻轻地吹；吹送；使被三阵出局', '1. I caught a whiff of perfume as she passed me. 她从我身边走过时，我闻到一股香水味。 2. Mr. Officer, I just baked cookies. Look, take a whiff of these. 大人先生，我只是在考小甜饼。看 3. A whiff of gas will quickly put you off. 你吸一口麻醉气体马上就会进入麻醉状态。', '名词: whiffer 过去式: whiffed 过去分词: whiffed 现在分词: whiffing 第三人称单数: whiffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('complacency', '[kəm\'pleɪsnsi]', 'n.自满；沾沾自喜', '1. This power is strong enough to shatter complacency. 这种力量足以打破自满情绪。 2. Many of us began maturing in complacency. 我们中许多人在自满情绪中成长。 3. With the state of affairs in the North so dangerous I see no reason for the government\'s complacency. 北方局势如此危险，我认为政府毫无理由沾沾自喜。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unaffected', '[ˌʌnə\'fektɪd]', 'adj.不受影响的；不矫揉造作的；自然的', '1. These rights are unaffected by the new laws. 这些权利不受新法规的影响。 2. The children seem unaffected emotionally by their parent\'s divorce. 孩子在情绪上似乎未受到父母离婚的影响。 3. The man looks natural and unaffected. 此人神情潇洒。 4. She felt her works are meaningful when she saw the unaffected delight of the children. 当她看到孩子们自然流露出的喜悦时，她感到自己的工作很有意义。', '副词: unaffectedly 名词: unaffectedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incredulity', '[ˌɪnkrə\'djuːləti]', 'n.不轻信', '1. There was a hint of incredulity in her voice. 她的声音中流露出一丝迟疑。 2. \"You persist in your incredulity, Edmond,\" continued Faria. “你仍然不肯相信，爱德蒙，”法利亚继续说道。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('empyrean', '[ˌempaɪ\'riːən]', 'n.天空；天神居处 adj.天堂的 =empyreal.', '1. Pulling moon on empyrean: music can clean our soul. 九天揽月:音乐可以净化我们的心灵。 2. Of or relating to the empyrean of ancient belief. 天堂的古人认为的天堂的或与其有关的 3. The Empyrean is a story that has no action in the physical world. 最高天是一个在现实世界中没有发生的故事。 4. Here are some thoughts I have about the story of The Empyrean. 这是我对最高天这个故事的一些想法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('regent', '[\'riːdʒənt]', 'n.摄政者；(大学等的)评议员 adj.摄政的', '1. The regent carried out an advanced system in his country. 摄政者在他的国家推行了一套先进的制度。 2. My lord Pharaoh! I propose the high priests offer tribute to their new regent. 敬爱的父王陛下！我认为最高祭司应该向新摄政王致上最高敬意！ 3. I enclose the letter which I have written to the Prince Regent under a flying seal. 我把写给摄政王的信装入开口信封。', '形容词: regental');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('minutes', '[\'mɪnɪts]', 'n.分钟；会议记录 名词minute的复数形式.', '1. The train was 10 minutes late. 火车晚点了10 分钟。 2. She dashed off two letters in thirty minutes. 她在30分钟内写好了两封信。 3. The period of exercise was geared down to ten minutes a day for men over 60. 60岁以上的人的锻炼时间减低到每日十分钟。 4. The minutes of the last meeting were approved. 上次会议记录已获得通过。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('buffer', '[\'bʌfər]', 'n.缓冲；(火车头尾或轨道末端的)缓冲器；[计算机]缓存区；老朽 v.缓冲；减轻；[计]缓存', '1. The world\'s natural ecosystems act as a buffer. 地球上的自然生态系统起着一种缓冲的作用。 2. Support from family and friends acts as a buffer against stress. 家庭和朋友的支持有助于减缓压力。 3. Computers record in action in the buffer. 计算机在缓冲器中记录信息。 4. He is a silly old buffer. 他是个老糊涂。', '过去式: buffered 过去分词: buffered 现在分词: buffering 第三人称单数: buffers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('constrict', '[kən\'strɪkt]', 'v.压缩；束紧；使收缩', '1. Doesn\'t that tight bracelet constrict your arm? 那个手镯那么紧不会压迫你的手臂吗? 2. Don\'t constrict your hair with tight hair bands and hats. 不要用紧绷绷的皮筋或帽子来固定头发。 3. Tight shoes constrict the feet. 鞋子太紧会挤脚。 4. Panic can constrict the blood vessels and impose an additional burden on the heart. 恐慌会使血管收缩，增加心脏负担。', '形容词: constrictive 副词: constrictively 过去式: constricted 过去分词: constricted 现在分词: constricting 第三人称单数: constricts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retail', '[\'riːteɪl]', 'n.零售 vt.零售；传述 adv.以零售形式', '1. They buy at wholesale and sell at retail. 他们大批地买进,再以零售方式卖出。 2. These biros retail at 70p. 这些圆珠笔零售价为70便士。 3. We should be able to retail most of these products to overseas customers. 我们应能够把这些产品的大部分卖给海外的顾客。 4. Who is responsible for retailing these rumors about him? 是谁散布这些有关他的流言蜚语的？', '名词: retailer 过去式: retailed 过去分词: retailed 现在分词: retailing 第三人称单数: retails');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('leer', '[lɪr]', 'n.（挑逗或恶意的）瞥视 v.用挑逗性的或含敌意的目光看', '1. He has a most unpleasant leer. 他目光猥亵，十分讨厌。 2. He looked at her with an evil leer. 他不怀好意地看着她。 3. Go away; I don\'t enjoy being leered at. 走开，我讨厌让人不怀好意地看著。', '副词: leeringly 过去式: leered 过去分词: leered 现在分词: leering 第三人称单数: leers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prank', '[præŋk]', 'n.开玩笑；恶作剧；戏谑 v.盛装；装饰；打扮', '1. Later on, we found out that it was one of our friends playing a prank on us. 后来我们才发现原来那是我们同去的一个朋友在和我们开玩笑呢。 2. Can you imagine Sir Alex Ferguson attempting a disruptive prank like this? 你能想象弗爵爷以这种打断采访的形式来和球员开玩笑么？ 3. He was the goat of their vicious prank. 他成为他们恶作剧的对象。 4. My older sister put me up to making a prank telephone call. 是我姐姐怂恿我打这个恶作剧电话的。', '过去式: pranked 过去分词: pranked 现在分词: pranking 第三人称单数: pranks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vie', '[vaɪ]', 'v.竞争', '1. But these encouraging trends must vie with the negatives. 但是这些令人鼓舞的潮流必须与其对立面进行激烈竞争。 2. Boys like to vie to become pack leader and play for laughs in class. 男孩喜欢竞争做群体领袖，在课堂上玩耍以博取笑声。', '过去式: vied 过去分词: vied 现在分词: vying 第三人称单数: vies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peck', '[pek]', 'v.啄；连续敲击；<口>轻吻 n.啄痕；啄食；<口>轻吻 n.配克；<口>大量', '1. That bird tried to peck me. 那只鸟想啄我。 2. The bird pecked at the bread crumbs. 鸟儿啄食面包屑。 3. She is pecking away at the keys of a typewriter. 她不停地敲打着打字机的键。 4. The boy started pecking at the keys of the piano. 男孩开始在钢琴上乱弹一气。 5. The parrot gave me a sharp peck on the finger. 鹦鹉把我的手指啄得很疼。', '过去式: pecked 过去分词: pecked 现在分词: pecking 第三人称单数: pecks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('idiom', '[\'ɪdiəm]', 'n.成语；惯用语；方言；风格；特色', '1. This idiom cannot be translated literally. 这个成语无法照字面翻译。 2. From that story comes the idiom \"Draw a snake and add feet to it\". “画蛇添足”这个成语就是从这个故事来的。 3. \"Let the cat out of the bag\" is an idiom meaning to tell a secret by mistake. “让猫从袋子里跑出来”是惯用语，意思是无意中泄露秘密。 4. He spoke in the idiom of the New England countryside. 他讲新英格兰乡下的方言。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hymn', '[hɪm]', 'n.赞美诗；圣歌 v.唱赞美歌', '1. The priests piously consecrated the robbery with a hymn. 教士们虔诚地唱了一首赞美诗，把这劫夺行为神圣化了。 2. He sang the verse of the hymn and we joined in the chorus. 他唱著赞美诗，而我们加入副歌里。 3. The hymn followed him faintly as he crossed the fields. 在他跨过田野时，圣歌还隐约地尾随着他。 4. They have no idea that the evil is on her way when they are singing a hymn in the church. 当他们正在教堂唱圣歌的时候，他们还不知道罪恶的事情就要到来。', '过去式: hymned 过去分词: hymned 现在分词: hymning 第三人称单数: hymns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('severe', '[sɪ\'vɪr]', 'adj.严厉的；严重的；剧烈的；严格的；严峻的', '1. The premier came under severe criticism. 这位总理遭到严厉的抨击。 2. He\'s suffering from severe mental disorder. 他患有严重的精神病。 3. A severe storm turned the small village down to ground. 一场剧烈的风暴把小村夷为平地。 4. The new product has stood a severe proof . 新产品经受了严格的考验。', '副词: severely 比较级: severer 最高级: severest 名词: severeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('greenhouse', '[\'ɡriːnhaʊs]', 'n.温室；暖房', '1. They had to smoke the plants in a greenhouse. 他们只好用烟熏温室里的植物。 2. Most vegetables we buy in winter are nurtured in the greenhouse. 我们冬天买的大多数蔬菜都是在温室里培育的。 3. Carbon dioxide is the largest contributor to the greenhouse effect. 二氧化碳太多是道致温室效应的最主要原因。 4. Behind the house is a greenhouse. 在那所房子後面是一个暖房。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chary', '[\'tʃeri]', 'adj.谨慎的；节俭的', '1. A cat is chary of wetting its paws. 猫尽量避免弄湿它的脚掌。 2. They are chary of investing such an amount of money in the risky business. 他们对于在那项风险很大的生意中投资态度很谨慎。 3. He is chary of praise. 他吝于称赞别人。 4. Oh sure. The boss is very chary about taking on more people at the moment. 喔，那是当然，老板目前非常不轻易增聘人手。', '副词: charily 比较级: charier 最高级: chariest 名词: chariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eerie', '[\'ɪri]', 'adj.怪诞的；可怕的；奇异的；害怕的', '1. The eerie glow filled the cabin as the pressure built around them. 当压力在他们周围建造的时候，怪诞的赤热装满了小屋。 2. The sky had an eerie yellow-orange hue, with the sun glowing behind a peculiar haze. 天空呈现出怪诞的橘黄色调，太阳隐在一层奇异的雾霭后透出昏黄的光晕。 3. Near an ear, a nearer ear, a nearly eerie ear. 靠近一只耳朵，一只近一些的耳朵，一只近乎可怕的耳朵。 4. So what\'s so eerie about this name? 但这名字有什麽可怕的呢？', '副词: eerily 异体字: eery 比较级: eerier 最高级: eeriest 名词: eeriness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oligarch', '[\'ɑːləɡɑːrk]', 'n.寡头政治执政者(支持者）', '1. Coke market is a typical double oligarch market. 可乐市场是一个典型的双寡头市场。 2. The oligarch, a bitter enemy of Putin, has denied any involvement. 与普京有很大分歧的该政治寡头则否认参与其中。 3. He was the most famous financial oligarch in American history. 他是当年美国最有名的财政寡头。 4. But there will always be another oligarch to take the place of the fallen. 当然一定会有另一个巨头来填补他的空位的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chromosome', '[\'kroʊməsoʊm]', 'n.染色体', '1. Chromosome studies on two species of Trifolium L. 两种车轴草的染色体研究。 2. Chromosome breaks may also lead to inversions and translocations. 染色体破裂也可能引起倒位与易位。', '形容词: chromosomal 副词: chromosomally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pessimism', '[\'pesɪmɪzəm]', 'n.悲观；悲观主义', '1. He has a tendency towards pessimism. 他有悲观的倾向。 2. There is the note of pessimism in his writings. 他的著作带有悲观色彩。 3. He never gave himself up to pessimism in spite of difficulties. 尽管遇到困难他从没有消极悲观过。 4. Pessimism is the hallmark of his major novels. 悲观主义是他的几部小说的主要特征。', '形容词: pessimistic 副词: pessimistically 名词: pessimist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('footle', '[\'fuːtəl]', 'vi.胡闹；浪费(时间) n.愚蠢；胡话', '1. I wish he would not footle about so much. 我希望他不要这样混日子。', '名词: footler 过去式: footled 过去分词: footled 现在分词: footling 第三人称单数: footles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('helot', '[\'helət]', 'n.希洛人；奴隶；受人轻视之人', '1. To manage the Tibet with helot system. 用农奴制度管理西藏。 2. The helot may simply run a key word search on CVs submitted electronically, freeing up a few minutes for a fag break. 这个没地位的人可能仅对电子版的简历进行一下关键词搜索，空出来几分钟时间抽支烟。 3. But his female viewpoint is closely linked up with Helot and is full of conflict and paradox. 但他的妇女观与农奴制息息相关，充满着矛盾与悖论。 4. Findings shows, before Tibetan peace is liberated, its society progress still is in the development phase of feudal Helot society. 新中国建立后,随着西藏的和平解放,以当时的中国科学院为主加上一些高等院校和有关单位的科学工作者开展了对西藏社会历史的大规模调查。调查结果显示,西藏和平解放前,其社会发展尚处于封建农奴社会的发展阶段。', '名词: helotry');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hidebound', '[\'haɪdbaʊnd]', 'adj.墨守成规的；死板的；（动物）皮包骨的；(树木)紧皮的', '1. Hidebound be to bring about liverish main reason? 营养不良是导致肝病的主要原因？ 2. Why does hidebound meeting feel giddy sometimes? 为什么营养不良会有时感到头晕？ 3. So, how should the old person judge him hidebound? 那么，老人应怎样判断自己是否营养不良了呢？ 4. You will never change their ideas.They are far too hidebound. 你无法改变他们的意思，因为他们太墨守成规。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('primate', '[\'praɪmeɪt]', 'n.灵长目动物 n.(常大写)首席主教', '1. Compared to body size, the primate brain is larger than that of other animals. 相对身躯而言，灵长目动物的大脑比其他动物的大脑都要大些。 2. This is the rarest primate species on earth, and the Endangered Primate Rescue Center had only one couple in captivity. 这是世界上最罕见的灵长目物种，援救濒临灭绝灵长目动物中心只囚禁了一对。', '形容词: primatial');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('medieval', '[ˌmedi\'iːvl]', 'adj.中世纪的', '1. Knighthood was an ideal in medieval Europe. 在中世纪的欧洲，成为骑士是理想。 2. The medieval town was fortified with a high wall and a deep moat. 这座中世纪的城市周围建有城墙和护城河。 3. This church is a classic example of medieval architecture. 这座教堂是中世纪建筑风格的典型实例。 4. The gallery is a treasure trove of medieval art. 这个画廊是中世纪艺术的宝库。', '副词: medievally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exhilaration', '[ɪɡˌzɪlə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.高兴；兴奋', '1. Her mood could swing rapidly from gloom to exhilaration. 她的情绪可能在转瞬之间从阴郁转向兴奋。 2. The growing child can thrill with the exhilaration of strenuous sports. 成长中的儿童会在剧烈运动中兴奋得发抖。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skew', '[skjuː]', 'adj.斜交的(不对称的；误解的) n.斜交(歪斜；歪轮；斜砌石) vt.歪斜；扭转 vi.歪斜；斜视', '1. The picture is a bit skew. 这幅画有点歪。 2. You\'ve got your hat on skew whiff. 你帽子戴歪了. 3. The delay difference between pairs is called delay skew. 在线对间的延迟差异被称为延迟歪斜. 4. His conception of human nature is skewed. 他对人性的看法带有偏见。 5. The boat skewed off course. 船偏离了航线。', '名词: skewness 过去式: skewed 过去分词: skewed 现在分词: skewing 第三人称单数: skews');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transfigure', '[træns\'fɪɡjər]', 'vt.使变形；使改观；美化', '1. Her face was transfigured by happiness. 她高兴得容光焕发。', '名词: transfigurement 过去式: transfigured 过去分词: transfigured 现在分词: transfiguring 第三人称单数: transfigures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pageant', '[\'pædʒənt]', 'n. 盛会； 游行； 壮丽的场面； <美>选美', '1. Secondly, the 2008 Olympics will be a red pageant. 其次，二零零八年的奥林匹克运动会将是一次红色的盛会。 2. Former Miss California USA Carrie Prejean is suing pageant officials for religious discrimination and libel. 前美国加州小姐嘉莉普雷让日前起诉盛会组织官员有宗教歧视和诽谤行为。 3. The coronation of the new king is a splendid pageant. 新国王的加冕典礼是一个非常壮丽的场面。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eradicate', '[ɪ\'rædɪkeɪt]', 'vt.根除；根绝；消灭', '1. He eradicated weeds in his garden. 他把花园中的杂草根除了。 2. They attempted to eradicate crime. 他们力图根除罪恶。 3. The disease has now been successfully eradicated from the world. 这种疾病已经成功地从世界上根除了。 4. Smallpox has almost been eradicated. 天花几乎已经被消灭了。', '形容词: eradicable 名词: eradication 过去式: eradicated 过去分词: eradicated 现在分词: eradicating 第三人称单数: eradicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maritime', '[\'mærɪtaɪm]', 'adj.海的；海上的；海事的', '1. England was a great maritime power. 英国曾是海上的强国。 2. This is a maritime form characterized by its low, branching habit and short, broad, densely bristly panicle. 这是一个以它的低，分枝体型和短，宽，密被刚毛的圆锥花序为特点的海上的形式。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interminable', '[ɪn\'tɜːrmɪnəbl]', 'adj.无止尽的；冗长的', '1. We are tired of the interminable waiting. 这种无止境的干等让我们厌倦。 2. I had interminable problems with my last car;it never worked well. 我上次的那辆车子没完没了地出故障，它从未好好地行驶过。 3. He made an interminable argument. 他无休止地争论。 4. The audience was bored by the president\'s interminable speech. 主席那冗长的讲话令听众们厌烦。', '副词: interminably 名词: interminability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('temper', '[\'tempər]', 'n.脾气；性情 vt.使缓和；调和；锻炼', '1. He slammed the door in a temper. 他生气地摔门。 2. You should learn to keep your temper under control. 你应该学会控制自己的脾气。 3. They are of congenial temper. 他们的性情相投。 4. If you temper criticism with reason,everyone can obey you. 如果以说理来缓和批评，谁都会服从你。', '形容词: temperable 名词: temperability 过去式: tempered 过去分词: tempered 现在分词: tempering 第三人称单数: tempers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('windy', '[\'wɪndi]', 'adj.有风的；多风的', '1. It\'s windy today. 今天有风。 2. Hold on to the hat on a windy day. 在有风的日子里请紧紧抓住帽子。 3. In spring, it\'s warm, sunny and windy. 春天是一个温暖、多日照和多风的季节。 4. The weather has turned cold and windy. 天气变得寒冷而多风.', '副词: windily 比较级: windier 最高级: windiest 名词: windiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grievous', '[\'ɡriːvəs]', 'adj.痛苦的；严重的；充满悲伤的', '1. We have before us an ordeal of the most grievous kind. 摆在我们面前的，是一场极为痛苦的严峻考验。 2. THE opposition in Zimbabwe suffered another grievous blow this week. 津巴布韦的反对派本周受到了痛苦的打击。 3. She has made a grievous mistake. 她犯了一个极严重的错误。 4. Maybe public pressure can force the Florida authorities to right a grievous wrong. 也许公众的压力可以迫使佛罗里达当局纠正这个严重的错误。', '副词: grievously 名词: grievousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('artillery', '[ɑːr\'tɪləri]', 'n.(军)火炮；大炮；炮兵(部队)', '1. The invaders would also have artillery. 进攻者还将配备火炮。 2. All Artillery Shells have been depleted. 火炮炮弹已经用尽。 3. Artillery and aircraft were involved in the action. 在这次战斗中，使用了大炮和飞机。 4. There is a continuing artillery barrage. 大炮持续不断的轰击伊军。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maelstrom', '[\'meɪlstrɑːm]', 'n.大漩涡；大动乱', '1. The maelstrom sucked in the canoe. 大漩涡吞没了独木舟。 2. The canoe was tossed about in the maelstrom. 独木舟在旋涡之中摇晃打转。 3. They were being sucked into the maelstrom of war. 他们就要被卷入战乱之中。 4. She was drawn into a maelstrom of revolutionary events. 她被卷入革命事件的洪流中。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rascal', '[\'ræskl]', 'n.淘气鬼；流氓；坏蛋', '1. The boy is nothing but a rascal. 这个男孩是个小淘气。 2. A militiaman happened to notice the rascal. 一位民兵偶然注意到了这个坏家伙。 3. If I ever catch the rascal I\'ll really wallop him! 我要是逮住这个流氓，非狠狠揍他一顿不可！ 4. The rascal lives on the credulity of the people. 那个流氓靠行骗为生。', '形容词: rascally');
