INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blueprint', '[\'bluːprɪnt]', 'n.蓝图；设计图；(周详的)计划 v.制成蓝图；计划', '1. There is a slight inaccuracy in this blueprint. 这张蓝图有点不准。 2. To receive this new blueprint, one must ask for it. 要去接收到这个新蓝图，你必须召唤它。 3. You have a perfect blueprint about your life. 人生计划已很完美。 4. Ascending human futures have a Divine Plan, a divine blueprint. 提升人类的未来有一个神性计划，一个神性蓝图。 5. You have a perfect blueprint about your life. 人生计划已很完美。', '过去式: blueprinted 过去分词: blueprinted 现在分词: blueprinting 第三人称单数: blueprints');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kennel', '[\'kenl]', 'n.狗舍；养狗场；排水道 v.置于狗舍；宿于狗舍', '1. Their dog Rover lives in a kennel in the back garden. 他们的小狗罗佛的窝在后花园。 2. Sporting dogs should be kept out of doors in a kennel. 猎狗应该养在户外的狗窝中。 3. We put the dog into a kennel when we go on holiday. 我们去度假时把狗送到养狗场寄养。 4. This Kennel Club took care of the pedigree of the Border Collie. 这个养狗俱乐部照顾纯种的边境牧羊犬。 5. The old dog have no energy to go out, but kennel all day. 这只老狗无精力出去，只好整天待在狗舍里。', '过去式: kenneled/kennelled 过去分词: kenneled/kennelled 现在分词: kenneling/kennelling 第三人称单数: kennels/kennels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grieve', '[ɡriːv]', 'vt.使伤心；使悲伤 vi.悲伤；伤心', '1. It grieves me to see him in such bad health. 看见他的健康状况如此不佳，我很伤心。 2. It grieves me to hear how disobedient you\'ve been. 听说你很不听话，使我感到非常难过。 3. She was grieving for the dead baby. 她为死去的孩子悲伤。 4. It\'s no use grieving about past errors. 为过去的错误懊悔不已是无济于事的。', '副词: grievingly 名词: griever 过去式: grieved 过去分词: grieved 现在分词: grieving 第三人称单数: grieves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tedious', '[\'tiːdiəs]', 'adj.单调乏味的；沉闷的', '1. The tedious job simply ate me up. 那单调乏味的工作简直把我烦死了。 2. He told me a tedious story. 他给我讲了一个冗长乏味的故事。 3. He is an exceedingly tedious fellow. 他是一个非常令人生厌的家伙。 4. How can he give us such a tedious lecture. 他怎么能做这么沉闷乏味的演讲。', '副词: tediously 名词: tediousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exponentially', '[ˌekspə\'nenʃəli]', 'adv.成倍地；幂地；指数地', '1. The density goes down exponentially with height. 分子密度随着高度的上升而指数衰减。 2. The dashpot displacement relaxes exponentially. 阻尼器位移按指数关系松弛。 3. Yes, exponentially, I am that lucky. 是的，从指数的角度来说，我很幸运。 4. The strategy worked, and Web content grew exponentially. 这种策略十分奏效,Web上的内容开始以指数级的速度增长。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('receptive', '[rɪ\'septɪv]', 'adj.易接受的；愿意接受的', '1. He grew eloquent under her receptive gaze. 遇到了她这种乐于接受的目光使他变得口若悬河起来。 2. He\'s not very receptive to my suggestions. 他不太愿意接纳我的建议。', '副词: receptively 名词: receptivity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cautionary', '[\'kɔːʃəneri]', 'adj.警戒的；警告的', '1. Her experiences provide a cautionary tale(= a warning)for us all. 她的经历成了我们大家的前车之鉴。 2. In her conclusion, the author sounds a cautionary note. 作者在结尾时敲响了警钟。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disprove', '[ˌdɪs\'pruːv]', 'v.证明 ... 是不对的；提出 ... 的反证', '1. In his latest book, he writes that the theory has been disproved. 他在最近写的书里说那种理论已证明不确。 2. The course of a river is almost always disproved of by the source. 河流的方向，几乎常被水源证明是不对的。 3. Their statement incorrect we disprove as follow. 他们的陈述不正确，现提反对意见如下。 4. I defy anyone to disprove the defendant\'s statements. 我倒要看看有没有人能对被告的陈述进行反驳。', '形容词: disprovable 名词: disproval 过去式: disproved 过去分词: disproved 现在分词: disproving 第三人称单数: disproves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inadvertently', '[ˌɪnəd\'vɜːrtəntli]', 'adv.不注意地；疏忽地；非故意地', '1. At present, if too many turtles are inadvertently caught in Hawaiian waters, the entire fishery is closed down. 现在，在夏威夷海域，如果海龟被不注意地捕捞过多，整个渔场就被关闭。 2. The interface design must assure that a user can never inadvertently fire the ejector seat when all he wants to do is make some minor adjustment to the program. 界面设计必须保证用户永远不会在非故意的情况下弹射座椅，特别是当他只是想对程序进行一些小的调整时。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('veer', '[vɪr]', 'vt.转向；改变 n.转向', '1. The wind has veered round to the north recently. 近日风向已转北了。 2. People whose thinking has become rigid tend to veer with the wind. 思想一僵化，随风倒的现象就多起来了。 3. The plane veered wildly. 那架飞机乱改航线。 4. She will not veer from her brave new intentions 她不会改变她的大胆的新计划。 5. In 20th century, the west philosophy and aesthetics had an important veer, which is language veer. 20世纪西方哲学与美学发生了一次重大的转向,那就是语言论的转向。', '过去式: veered 过去分词: veered 现在分词: veering 第三人称单数: veers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adore', '[ə\'dɔːr]', 'vt.爱慕；崇拜；很喜欢', '1. Men can only adore women who are adorable. 男人们只爱慕那些让人爱慕的女人。 2. The kids adore their father and confide in him. 孩子们崇拜并信赖他们的父亲。 3. The boys adore their mothers. 男孩们敬慕他们的母亲。 4. All the girls in our school adore the handsome mathematics teacher who happens to be a bachelor. 我们学校里所有女孩子都崇拜那个恰巧是单身汉的英俊数学老师。', '副词: adoringly 名词: adorer 过去式: adored 过去分词: adored 现在分词: adoring 第三人称单数: adores');
