INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shelve', '[ʃelv]', 'v.放在架子上；搁置；倾斜', '1. They had to shelve their holiday plans because their son was ill. 他们不得不把度假计划搁置，因为他们的儿子病了。 2. Those rare books are shelved in the East Library. 那些珍贵的书籍都放在图书馆东馆的架子上。', '名词: shelver 过去式: shelved 过去分词: shelved 现在分词: shelving 第三人称单数: shelves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jaundice', '[\'dʒɔːndɪs]', 'n.黄疸；偏见 v.使患黄疸病；使怀偏见', '1. He was suffering from a sharp attack of jaundice. 他患的是急性黄疸。 2. Yellowness of the eyes is one of the symptoms of jaundice. 眼睛发黄是黄疸病的症状之一。 3. I looked into the problem without jaundice of any kind. 我研讨这一问题，不怀任何偏见。 4. His social position jaundiced his view of things. 他的社会地位使他对事情的看法持有偏见。', '过去式: jaundiced 过去分词: jaundiced 现在分词: jaundicing 第三人称单数: jaundices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aerate', '[\'ereɪt]', 'vt.充气；使通气', '1. The potatoes were set outside to aerate. 马铃薯放到外面通风。 2. Each insect contributes something just as ants aerate the soil. 每一种昆虫都贡献了一些事情，就象蚂蚁松土给土壤增加空气一样。', '名词: aeration 过去式: aerated 过去分词: aerated 现在分词: aerating 第三人称单数: aerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transcribe', '[træn\'skraɪb]', 'v.抄写；用音标标出；改编(乐曲)；转录', '1. She jotted down a few notes, and later transcribed them into an exercise book. 她草草做了些笔记,然后誊写在练习本上。 2. He wanted to transcribe completely the conversation of the lowlifes. 他想要把那些下层社会份子的对话完全抄录下来。 3. This is a pianopiece transcribed for the guitar. 这是一首改编成用吉他演奏的钢琴曲。 4. I am able to get dictation in English and quickly transcribe into Chinese. 我会英语的口授笔记，同时能立即将其改写成中文。', '形容词: transcribable 名词: transcriber 过去式: transcribed 过去分词: transcribed 现在分词: transcribing 第三人称单数: transcribes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('microorganism', '[ˌmaɪkroʊ\'ɔːgənˌɪzəm]', 'n.微生物', '1. Bacteria belong to the microorganism. 细菌属于微生物。 2. This microorganism is a producer of disease. 该微生物是疾病制造者。 3. A microorganism is too small to see with the naked eye. 微生物太小,不能用肉眼看见。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lectern', '[\'lektərn]', 'n.诵经台；讲台', '1. The chauffeur walked to the lectern and delivered the speech. 而司机走上了讲台，作讲演。 2. An audience is dismayed to see a speaker peering down at a thick sheaf of papers on the lectern. 听众看到演讲人盯着放在讲台上厚厚的讲稿就会感到沮丧。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dowry', '[\'daʊri]', 'n.嫁妆；天资', '1. Her father gave her the two books he had written as her dowry. 作为她的嫁妆,她父亲将自己写的两本书给了她。 2. His family hoped that his bride would bring a large dowry. 他的家人希望新娘能带来丰厚的嫁妆。', '名词复数: dowries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drenched', '[drentʃd]', 'adj.湿透的 动词drench的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. It was a person under the eaves shaking out a drenched coat. 同样一个站在屋檐下避雨的人抖了抖已经湿透的衣服。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scorn', '[skɔːrn]', 'n.轻蔑；奚落；笑柄 v.轻蔑；鄙视；嘲弄；不屑', '1. He eyed me with a terrible scorn. 他极其轻蔑地打量着我。 2. He spat out the words with scorn. 他用轻蔑的口吻说了这番话。 3. He were to become a mark of public scorn. 他将成为公众奚落的典型。 4. The loser\'s scorn for the award is pure sour grape. 失败者对奖品的轻视纯粹是吃不到葡萄说葡萄酸。 5. You\'ve no right to scorn a poor girl. 你没有权利藐视一个穷女孩。', '形容词: scornful 副词: scornfully 名词: scorner 过去式: scorned 过去分词: scorned 现在分词: scorning 第三人称单数: scorns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('finite', '[\'faɪnaɪt]', 'adj.有限的', '1. The world\'s resources are finite. 世界的资源是有限的。 2. Fortunately, the casualties were finite. 幸运的是，人员伤亡有限。 3. It is quite possible that space and time are finite. 很有可能空间和时间是有限的。 4. Any battery has a finite life span no matter what device it powers. 任何电池都具有有限的寿命，无论它具有多大的能量。', '副词: finitely 名词: finiteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('killjoy', '[\'kɪldʒɔɪ]', 'n.扫兴的人；煞风景', '1. That killjoy ruined the fun by taking our beer away. 那个扫兴的家伙把啤酒拿走了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jot', '[dʒɑːt]', 'n.少量 v.草草记下；匆匆记下', '1. I don\'t care a jot for their feelings. 我一点都不理会他们的感受。 2. There\'s not a jot of truth in his story. 他一句实话也没有。 3. I\'ll just jot down their phone number before I forget it. 我得把电话号码记下来，以免待会儿忘记。 4. She jots down a few note,and later transcribes them into an exercise book. 她草草做了些笔记，然后誊写在练习本上。', '过去式: jotted 过去分词: jotted 现在分词: jotting 第三人称单数: jots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pedagogy', '[\'pedəɡɑːdʒi]', 'n.教育学；教授法；教育', '1. Paulo Freire is a representative of the Pedagogy of the Oppressed. 摘要弗莱雷是被压迫教育学的代表人物。 2. Narrative pedagogy is unending converging conversations. 叙述教育学是无穷尽的聚合交谈。 3. Phenomenological pedagogy calls for the rediscovery and return of human spirits in educational practice. 现象学教育学呼唤教育实践之人文精神的重新发现与回归。 4. After critical consideration on the anti-essentialism in pedagogy, we should seek certainty in the new era. 基于反本质主义教育学主张的批判性反思，我国教育学研究需要在具体的教育情境中追求确定性。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inquisitive', '[ɪn\'kwɪzətɪv]', 'adj.好奇的；爱打听的；求知欲强的', '1. He surveyed me with an inquisitive look. 他以好奇的眼光仔细地打量我。 2. Primates are alert, inquisitive animals. 灵长目动物是机灵、好奇的动物。 3. She was very inquisitive about other people\'s affairs. 她太爱打听别人的私事。 4. Don\'t be so inquisitive. 别那么爱管闲事。', '副词: inquisitively 名词: inquisitiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decomposition', '[ˌdiːkɒmpə\'zɪʃn]', 'n.分解；腐烂；变质', '1. This type of thermal decomposition is called pyrolysis. 这种类型的热分解反应称做热解。 2. The sewage has been activated to aid with decomposition. 为了帮助物质分解，污水已经用曝气处理法净化过了。 3. Warmer weather meant the decomposition of the corpse. 天气变暖会使尸体腐烂。 4. A plastic sheet was pegged down over the compost heap to hasten decomposition. 把塑料布铺盖在肥堆上，并用木桩固定好，以加速肥料腐烂。', '形容词: decompositional');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unbecoming', '[ˌʌnbɪ\'kʌmɪŋ]', 'adj.不合身的；不相称的；不适当的；不得体的', '1. She is wearing an unbecoming dress. 她穿着一条不合身的裙子。 2. He was drummed out of the service for conduct unbecoming of an officer. 他因行为与军官的身份不相称而被部队开除。 3. She felt that tears were unbecoming and foolish. 她觉得流泪是不适当的和愚蠢的。 4. It was thought to be unbecoming for young ladies to smoke. 年轻女子吸烟被认为是不得体的。', '副词: unbecomingly 名词: unbecomingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fanfare', '[\'fænfer]', 'n.仪式上用的短曲（通常用小号吹奏）；〈非正式〉炫耀', '1. A showy or ceremonious passage, such as a fanfare. 装饰乐句，花式吹奏一段炫耀或讲究仪式的音乐，例如小号曲 2. Despite all the fanfare by Federal regulators over recent bailouts of sick savings institutions, evidence is mounting that the deals are merely papering over the severe problems plaguing the industry. 不论联邦监管人员最近如何大张旗鼓挽救一蹶不振的储蓄行业，越来越多的证据显示：政府所做仅仅在掩饰困扰该待业的严重问题。 3. The royal visitor was saluted by a fanfare of trumpets. 皇室贵宾在嘹亮的铜管乐曲中受到热烈欢迎。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perception', '[pər\'sepʃn]', 'n.观念；洞察力；认识能力', '1. The public\'s perception of him is slowly changing. 公众对他的观念正在慢慢地发生变化。 2. His analysis of the problem showed great perception. 他对该问题的分析显示出敏锐的洞察力。 3. One of his goals is improving students\' power of perception in this matter. 他的目标之一是提高学生对该问题的认识能力。', '形容词: perceptional');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('askance', '[ə\'skæns]', 'adv.斜视地；怀疑地；不赞许地 =askant.', '1. The young man looked askance at the price. 那个年青人对那个价目侧目而视。 2. The older women in the town looked askance at what the young people were doing. 镇上上了年纪的女人用怀疑的目光看着年轻人所做的一切。 3. She looked at me rather askance. 她不悦地瞟了我一眼。', '异体字: askant');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fallow', '[\'fæloʊ]', 'adj.休耕的；不活跃的 n.休耕地；休耕 v.使休耕', '1. The field was lying fallow. 那田地正在休耕中。 2. The farmer kept his cows in a fallow field. 那农民把他的奶牛放在休闲地里。 3. They have their creative and their fallow times. 他们有他们的创作和沉潜期。 4. When John had finished his last book, he found that no new ideas would come; his brain seemed to be lying fallow. 约翰写完上一本书后，发现想不出什么新的构思；他的脑子似乎在休息。 5. Forest fallow is an intermediate class between forest and non-forest land uses. 休耕林是林地和非林地的中间阶段。 6. They take in fresh land in order to fallow the exhausted soil. 他们另行耕种新土地，使耗竭的土地得到休耕。', '名词: fallowness 过去式: fallowed 过去分词: fallowed 现在分词: fallowing 第三人称单数: fallows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nourish', '[\'nɜːrɪʃ]', 'v.滋养；给营养；培育；怀有', '1. They needed good food to nourish their bodies. 他们需要好食品滋养身体。 2. Milk is all we need to nourish a small baby. 我们供给婴儿营养只需喂奶就够了。 3. Most plants are nourished by water drawn up through their roots. 多数植物是靠着根吸收水分来维持生命的。 4. The school\'s goal is to nourish young musical talent. 这个学校的目标是培育年轻的音乐人才。', '名词: nourisher 过去式: nourished 过去分词: nourished 现在分词: nourishing 第三人称单数: nourishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('daubster', '[\'dɔːbstə]', 'n.拙劣的画家', '1. daubster n. 笨画匠 [(', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skein', '[skeɪn]', 'n.一束(线或纱)；混乱的一团；一群', '1. She passed me a skein of wool. 她递给我一绞毛线。 2. This skein of wool won\'t disentangle. 这束毛线解不开。 3. The twisted skein of fate smiles on us. 扭曲痛苦的命运向我们微笑了。 4. A skein of duck came across, gabbling softly to themselves 一群鸭子走过来，相互轻轻地低声而鸣。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proctor', '[\'prɑːktər]', 'n.代理人；学监', '1. As a gowned university proctor walked towards the stage, and the Chinese audience turned on the man, he threw a grey trainer. 正当着正装的校方学监走上讲台，中国听众转向那名男子时，他投掷了一只灰色运动软鞋。', '形容词: proctorial 名词: proctorship 过去式: proctored 过去分词: proctored 现在分词: proctoring 第三人称单数: proctors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('winnow', '[\'wɪnoʊ]', 'v.吹开糠皮；把挑出来；精选', '1. A device for winnowing grain. 簸谷器; 风选机去糠的设备 2. The girl is winnowing the chaff from the corn. 那个女孩正在簸去谷壳。', '名词: winnower 过去式: winnowed 过去分词: winnowed 现在分词: winnowing 第三人称单数: winnows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('default', '[dɪ\'fɔːlt]', 'n.缺席；默认(值)；不履行责任 v.拖欠；默认；不履行义务；缺席', '1. The team lost a game by default. 那个队因没有出席而输掉比赛。 2. If not specified, the default value is no password. 如果未指定，则默认值为没有密码。 3. In 1997, no default of travel agent requiring payment of compensation occurred. 在一九九七年，并没有因旅行代理商不履行责任而需要支付赔偿。 4. He said he had to default on that loan. 他说他必须拖欠那笔债务。', '名词: defaulter 过去式: defaulted 过去分词: defaulted 现在分词: defaulting 第三人称单数: defaults');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decipher', '[dɪ\'saɪfər]', 'vt.译解；辨认', '1. He could decipher military signals. 他能破译军事信号。 2. We can decipher the password intercepted by broadcasting station. 我们能破译电台截获的密码。 3. Can you decipher her scrawl? 你能辩认出她乱写的是什么吗? 4. I can\'t decipher what is inscribed on the pillar. 我认不出刻在柱子上的是什么。', '形容词: decipherable 名词: decipherer 过去式: deciphered 过去分词: deciphered 现在分词: deciphering 第三人称单数: deciphers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thrifty', '[\'θrɪfti]', 'adj.节俭的；兴旺的；茁壮的', '1. Her mother is a thrifty housewife. 她妈妈是一个节俭的主妇。 2. Only very thrifty children manage to fill up a money-box. 只有非常节俭的儿童才会设法填满一个储蓄罐。 3. Mr. Thompson is so thrifty that he is able to save more than half of his weekly salary. 汤普森先生是如此节俭,以致他能省下超过一半的周薪。', '副词: thriftily 比较级: triftier 最高级: triftiest 名词: thriftiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rescission', '[rɪ\'sɪʒn]', 'n.废除；取消', '1. The basis for rescission is that reality of consent is absent. 这种废除的理论基础就是缺乏真实的同意。 2. The regime of contract rescission is an important content in contract system. 合同解除制度是合同制度的重要内容。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kaleidoscope', '[kə\'laɪdəskoʊp]', 'n.万花筒；千变万化', '1. A kaleidoscope is an optical toy. 万花筒是一种光学玩具。 2. The child\'s wonder at the kaleidoscope never ended. 那孩子对万花筒惊讶不已。 3. At sunset the sky became a kaleidoscope of colors. 夕阳西下时，天空的颜色千变万化。 4. He swiftly dismissed the kaleidoscope of memory, oppressed by the urgent need of the present. 眼前有急于要办的事逼迫着他，他一下子打消了记忆中的那些千变万化的情景。', '形容词: kaleidoscopic 副词: kaleidoscopically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vitiate', '[\'vɪʃieɪt]', 'v.使败坏；损害；使失效', '1. This may vitiate a literal translation. 这就会损害直译的价值。 2. No such Variation shall vitiate this Contract. 任何该等变更都不会造成本合同失效。', '形容词: vitiable 名词: vitiation 过去式: vitiated 过去分词: vitiated 现在分词: vitiating 第三人称单数: vitiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('braid', '[breɪd]', 'n.辫子；穗带 v.编辫子；编织；镶缀', '1. She wears her hair in braids. 她把她的头发编成辫子。 2. The general\'s uniform was trimmed with gold braid. 将官的制服饰有金色的穗带。 3. She braids her hair every morning. 她每天早晨都梳辫子。 4. Ralph tried to braid a belt from strips of leather. 雷夫试着把一条条的皮革编织成一条皮带。', '名词: braider 过去式: braided 过去分词: braided 现在分词: braiding 第三人称单数: braids');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hike', '[haɪk]', 'n.徒步旅行；远足；涨价 vi.远足；提高', '1. He always bring a canteen with him on a hike. 他作徒步旅行时总是带着水壶。 2. The storm upset their plans for a hike. 暴风雨破坏了他们的远足计划。 3. The government announced a 300 per cent hike in bread prices. 政府宣布面包涨价三倍。 4. He wants to hike round the world. 他打算徒步旅行环游世界一周。', '名词: hiker 过去式: hiked 过去分词: hiked 现在分词: hiking 第三人称单数: hikes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('firefly', '[\'faɪərflaɪ]', 'n.萤火虫', '1. A firefly was shimmering on the wood doorpost. 一只萤火虫，贴在木头门框上，闪闪发亮。 2. The light of the firefly does not produce heat. 萤火虫的光不能产生热量，', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('athletics', '[æθ\'letɪks]', 'n.体育运动；田径', '1. She showed us the athletics awards she had won. 她给我们看她赢得的体育运动奖。 2. Athletics include all kinds of sports. 体育运动包括各种竞技。 3. I like all the athletics events. 我喜欢所有的田径项目。 4. Runners in an athletics stadium run in individual lanes. 在田径运动场上赛跑的人有各自的跑道。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beget', '[bɪ\'ɡet]', 'v.产生；引起；生(子女)', '1. Great love will beget great faith. 大的爱就产生大的信心。 2. Life on Earth alters Earth to beget more life. 地球上的生命改变着地球以产生更多的生命。 3. It may be that stable environments beget diversity because they allow rare species to persist. 可能是稳定的环境引起差异，因为他们允许稀有物种存留。 4. I were going to beget a child knowing that the child was going to be a homicidal maniac. 我明明知道自己的孩子将成为杀人疯子还要把孩子生出来。', '名词: begetter 过去式: begot 过去分词: begotten/begot 现在分词: begetting 第三人称单数: begets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sanction', '[\'sæŋkʃn]', 'n.批准；约束力；处罚 vt.批准；支持', '1. The minister can only act in this matter with the sanction of Parliament. 部长只有得到国会批准才能就此事采取行动。 2. The book was translated without the sanction of the author. 这本书未经作者许可就给翻译了。 3. Western nations imposed tough sanctions on the country. 西方各国对这个国家实行了严厉制裁。 4. The church would not sanction the king\'s second marriage. 教会不会批准国王第二次结婚。', '过去式: sanctioned 过去分词: sanctioned 现在分词: sanctioning 第三人称单数: sanctions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stiff', '[stɪf]', 'adj.硬的；僵直的；艰难的；生硬的；拘谨的；烈性的 adv.极其；僵硬地 n.死尸；流浪汉；过于拘谨的人；吝啬鬼；醉鬼', '1. Shoes are often stiff when they are new. 新鞋刚穿起来常常都是硬邦邦的。 2. She cleaned the sink with a stiff brush. 她用硬毛刷清洗水槽。 3. His legs felt stiff from having sat for so long. 由于坐得太久，他的双腿感到僵直。 4. He has to take a stiff test before he is qualified. 在取得资格之前,他必须通过一次艰难的考试。 5. The opera bored me stiff. 这个歌剧真把我腻烦透了。', '形容词: stiffish 副词: stiffly 比较级: stiffer 最高级: stiffest 名词: stiffness 过去式: stiffed 过去分词: stiffed 现在分词: stiffing 第三人称单数: stiffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('protuberance', '[proʊ\'tuːbərəns]', 'n.瘤；突起；结节', '1. A small protuberance or elevation, as from an organ, a tissue, or a structure. 隆起物，凸出物(器官，组织或结构上的)小隆起或凸出物 2. A rounded protuberance formed by the bones in a joint. (屈指时)指节膨出部关节中由骨头形成的圆形突出物 3. A knob, knot, protuberance, or swelling. 节，结，瘤球状物、结、节疤或肿瘤', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recompense', '[\'rekəmpens]', 'v.补偿；赔偿；报酬 n.报偿；回礼；赔偿', '1. He didn\'t try to recompense for our loss. 对我们的损失他无意补偿。 2. We had to recompense the peasants for the loss of their goats. 我们得赔偿农民损失的山羊。 3. The firm will recompense you for your traveling expenses. 公司将偿付你的旅费。 4. They gave him money in recompense for his trouble. 他们给他钱以酬劳他的辛苦。', '过去式: recompensed 过去分词: recompensed 现在分词: recompensing 第三人称单数: recompenses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tactic', '[\'tæktɪk]', 'n.战略；策略', '1. The new tactic was put into operation early in 1939. 这个新的战略是在1939年初开始运用的。 2. The team won the game thanks to Jeff\'s fabulous spot tactic. 多亏了杰夫当场制定的英明战略，他的球队赢了。 3. Reducing prices is a common sales tactic. 降价是常用的销售策略。 4. Confrontation is not always the best tactic. 对抗并非总是上策。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('criterion', '[kraɪ\'tɪriən]', 'n.标准；准则', '1. Practice is the sole criterion for testing truth. 实践是检验真理的唯一标准。 2. He thinks that the criterion of success is the ability to work joyfully. 他认为成功的检验标准是看能否愉快地生活。 3. We have a clear-cut criterion to go by. 我们有个可供遵循的明确标准。 4. The table shows the scoring for each criterion and criterion group. 上表显示每一准则和准则组别的评分。', '形容词: criterial 名词复数: criteria');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('porcine', '[\'pɔːrsaɪn]', 'adj.猪的；似猪的', '1. The scientific name is porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome. 学名是猪生殖和呼吸综合症。 2. The porcine Gamorreans tend to be heavy-set and stocky, standing about 1.8 meters tall and weighing in excess of 100 kilograms. 像猪的盖莫尔人通常体格壮硕矮胖，站起来约1.8公尺高、体重超过100公斤。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trammel', '[træml]', 'n.网；马梏；横木规；椭圆规；量规 （复）trammels: 束缚. v.束缚；妨害；用网捕', '1. No longer trammeled by his responsibility as chairman, he can say what he wish. 他不当董事长就不受职务约束了，想说什么就说什么。', '名词: trammeler 过去式: trammeled/trammelled 过去分词: trammeled/trammelled 现在分词: trammeling/trammelling 第三人称单数: trammels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slapdash', '[\'slæpdæʃ]', 'adj.草率的；马虎的 adv.鲁莽地；仓促地', '1. She has a very slapdash approach to keeping accounts. 她记账十分潦草马虎。 2. I think we in britain are very slapdash and don\'t care if we are right or wrong.\" 而我们英国人则很马虎,不在乎是对还是错。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mattress', '[\'mætrəs]', 'n.床垫', '1. He kept his life\'s savings under his mattress. 他将他一辈子的积蓄藏在床垫下。 2. We have just bought a new mattress. 我们买了一个新的床垫。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gust', '[ɡʌst]', 'n.突然一阵 n.风味 vi.猛吹', '1. A sudden gust of wind blew the door shut. 突然一阵大风把门吹得关上了。', '过去式: gusted 过去分词: gusted 现在分词: gusting 第三人称单数: gusts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blue', '[bluː]', 'adj.蓝色的；忧郁的；沮丧的；色情的 n.蓝色', '1. She wore a dark blue coat. 她穿着一件深蓝色的上衣。 2. The pots are made with blue enamel. 这些锅上有蓝色的搪瓷。 3. Someone has flown off with my blue bag. 有人把我那蓝色的包偷拿走了。 4. I\'m feeling blue today. 我今天的心情不好。 5. The color scheme of the room is blue and gold. 这个房间的色彩配置是蓝色和金黄色。', '副词: bluely 比较级: bluer 最高级: bluest 名词: blueness 过去式: blued 过去分词: blued 现在分词: bluing 第三人称单数: blues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wanderlust', '[\'wɑːndərlʌst]', 'n.漫游癖；旅游热', '1. There was a faraway hint of wanderlust in his expression. 在他的话语中恍惚地暗示他有旅行癖。 2. This phenomenon,sometimes called wanderlust, 这种现象，有时叫做流浪癖， 3. They nurtured my coming with wanderlust. 它们养育了我流浪的癖好。 4. Like many youngsters, he possessed a strong streak of wanderlust. 和许多年轻人一样，克利格也曾有过强烈的远行梦想。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('warmonger', '[\'wɔːrmʌŋɡər]', 'n.战争贩子；好战者；主战论者', '1. The Socialists were trying to smear Churchill as a warmonger. 工党企图诽谤邱吉尔先生是战争贩子。', '形容词: warmongering');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enjoin', '[ɪn\'dʒɔɪn]', 'v.命令；吩咐；禁止', '1. He enjoined obedience on the soldiers. 他命令士兵服从。 2. The judge enjoined him from selling alcohol. 法官禁止他卖酒。', '名词: enjoiner 过去式: enjoined 过去分词: enjoined 现在分词: enjoining 第三人称单数: enjoins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gash', '[ɡæʃ]', 'n.深的伤口(裂缝等） v.（使）负深伤', '1. He was bleeding from a gash on his head. 他头上的伤口在出血。 2. I was frightened when I saw the nasty gash in her arm. 她胳膊上又深又长的大伤口吓坏了我。 3. He gashed his foot on a piece of broken glass. 他的脚在一块碎玻璃上划了一个大口子。', '过去式: gashed 过去分词: gashed 现在分词: gashing 第三人称单数: gashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('moribund', '[\'mɔːrɪbʌnd]', 'adj.垂死的；即将结束的', '1. She watched the moribund patient and cried. 她看着这个垂死的病人，然后哭了。 2. The region\'s heavy industry is still inefficient and moribund. 这个地区的重工业仍然效率低下，行将消亡了。', '副词: moribundly 名词: moribundity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sly', '[slaɪ]', 'adj.狡猾的；会心的；淘气的；诡异的', '1. She\'s a sly puss. 她是个刁滑的姑娘。 2. The sly fox nimbly eluded the dogs. 那只狡猾的狐狸灵活地躲避开那群狗。 3. He cast a sly glance at his bridge partner. 他向桥牌搭档使了个会意的眼色。 4. The sly cat stole the meat while the cook\'s back was turned. 淘气的猫趁厨师转身之机偷吃了肉。', '副词: slyly 比较级: slier/slyer 最高级: sliest/slyest 名词: slyness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gibe', '[dʒaɪb]', 'v.嘲笑；讥笑 n.嘲笑；嘲讽话 =jibe.', '1. It\'s impolite to gibe at a foreign student\'s English. 嘲笑外国学生的英语是不礼貌的。 2. The gibe smarted in his brain. 人家的嘲笑令他脑子针扎似地作痛。 3. If we substitute the idea of respect for the audience, the gibe is turned against the player. 如果我们除去这个意思，放进尊重对象的意思去，那就只剩下讥笑弹琴者这个意思了。 4. It\'s impolite to gibe at a foreign student\'s English. 嘲笑外国学生的英语是不礼貌的。', '副词: gibingly 名词: giber');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aghast', '[ə\'ɡæst]', 'adj.惊骇的；吓呆的', '1. The robbers stood aghast at the sudden appearance of the policemen. 警察人员的突然出现，使那几个盗贼大惊失色。 2. Caderousse and his wife started and looked aghast at each other. 卡德鲁斯和他的妻子都吓了一跳，惊骇地互相望了一眼。 3. He stood aghast on hearing the news. 他听到这消息吓呆了。 4. She stood aghast at the black shadow in the drawing room. 她被客厅里的黑影吓呆了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seclude', '[sɪ\'kluːd]', 'vt.隔离；隔绝', '1. Moslems seclude their wives in the harem. 回教徒隔绝他们的妻子在闺房中。', '过去式: secluded 过去分词: secluded 现在分词: secluding 第三人称单数: secludes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stamp', '[stæmp]', 'n.邮票；图章；印；跺脚 v.跺脚；盖章', '1. My husband is a stamp collector. 我丈夫是个集邮者。 2. He is looking for his rubber stamp. 他正在找他的橡皮印章。 3. Please bring a photograph of yourself.We have to affix a stamp on the corner of it. 请带一张你的照片来,我们要在它的角上盖个印儿。 4. His face bears the stamp of suffering. 他的脸上有饱经苦难的烙印。 5. She stamped on the insect and killed it. 她踩死了一只虫子。', '过去式: stamped 过去分词: stamped 现在分词: stamping 第三人称单数: stamps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apostrophe', '[ə\'pɑːstrəfi]', 'n.撇号；单引号', '1. The number in this cell is formatted as text or preceded by an apostrophe. 此单元格中的数字为文本格式，或者其前面有撇号。 2. When you contract a word or two words you need to add an apostrophe. 当你要缩写一个或者两个词时，你需要加上撇号。', '形容词: apostrophic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('untrammeled', '[ʌn\'træmld]', 'adj.自由自在的；无阻碍的 =untrammelled.', '1. In short, and where the climate, and hot, untrammeled, publicity. 总之，和那里的气候一样，热辣、奔放、张扬。 2. In matters of conscience the soul must be left untrammeled. 在信仰问题上，心灵必须是不受任何约束的。 3. Add the apricot yellow will create the untrammeled winter youth. 银灰在质朴中显出厚重，使人恢复平和的心态。 4. You are attracted to those who are unbridled, untrammeled, and free. 你容易被那些逍遥不羁的人所吸引.', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gnome', '[noʊm]', 'n.土地神；土地神像；矮子；实力雄厚的国际银行家', '1. Susan bought a garden gnome to decorate her garden. 苏珊买了一个土地神像来装饰她的花园。 2. Thieves steal a gnome\'s magic lute. 窃贼盗取了一个侏儒的魔法鲁特琴。 3. The Chancellor of the Exchequer doesn\'t only have to convince the cabinet that his budget is sound, he has to convince the gnomes of Zurich. 财政大臣不但得要全体内阁确信他的预算是合理的，他还得使苏黎世的银行家们信服。', '形容词: gnomish');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nasal', '[\'neɪzl]', 'adj.鼻的；鼻声的；护鼻的 n.鼻音；鼻音字', '1. Background Bulbous nasal tips and lower dorsa are common facial features in Chinese people, and surgery to reshape these is frequently requested. 目的低鼻的同时伴有鼻尖扁平肥大圆钝的患者在临床工作中比较常见。 2. He talked to me with a nasal voice. 他带着鼻音和我说话。 3. A shrill, nasal tone strikes your listener like chalk screeching on a blackboard. 尖锐的鼻音会让你的听众感觉粉笔划过黑板一样刺耳。', '副词: nasally 名词: nasality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vain', '[veɪn]', 'adj.自负的；徒劳的；无效的；虚荣的', '1. She is vain and foolish, and yet people like her. 她自负而愚蠢，然而人们喜欢她。 2. She is vain of her voice. 她自以为她的声音了不起。 3. They endeavoured to make her happy but in vain. 他们尽量使她快乐，却徒劳无功。 4. All his father\'s exhortations were in vain. 他父亲的一切劝告都无效。', '副词: vainly 比较级: vainer 最高级: vainest 名词: vainness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recusant', '[rə\'kjuːzənt]', 'adj.不服从规章的 n.拒绝服从的人；拒不参加英国国教的天主教徒', '1. the recusant electors 叛逆的竞选者', '名词: recusancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('persiflage', '[\'pɜːrsɪflɑːʒ]', 'n.挖苦；嘲弄', '1. The persiflage is not appropriate when we have such serious problems to discuss. 当我们在讨论如此严肃的问题的时候,这种戏谑的言辞是不恰当的。 2. Even if such, I return clear feel there individual bring my warmth with love, after all is I am dreaming or live in the persiflage? 即便如此，我还分明的能感觉到那个人带给我的温暖和爱，到底是我在做梦还是生活在戏弄? 3. the jargon of intellectual persiflage 知识分子挖苦性的言论 4. deride mock ridicule scorn sneer quip flout hack jape persiflage taunt mordant spoof badinage banter等等。 中文同样是“嘲讽，嘲笑”，英文却有几十个单词：', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unique', '[ju\'niːk]', 'adj.独特的；独一无二的；稀罕的', '1. He occupies a unique place in English literature. 他在英国文学中占有独特的地位。 2. The elephant\'s trunk is a unique form of appendage. 象的鼻子是一种独特的附肢。 3. It\'s a unique work of art. 这是独一无二的艺术作品。 4. The custom is unique to the region. 这种风俗是这一地区特有的。', '副词: uniquely 名词: uniqueness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sobriety', '[sə\'braɪəti]', 'n.清醒；严肃；节制', '1. Her expression bespoke sobriety and saneness of soul. 她的表情证明她神志清醒正常。 2. You had to get to Henry in those moments of sobriety. 你必须在亨利清醒的时刻同他打交道。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('encipher', '[ɪn\'saɪfə]', 'vt.译成密码', '1. In SNA products, a key used to encipher operational keys that are to is used at a node. 在系统网络体系结构(sna)产品中,对将要在某个网点上使用的操作键标进行加密的一种键(也称键标,也就是密钥)。 2. A participant or privileged participant shall encipher any payment instruction it makes, and a payment instruction shall have effect once it is given. 参与者和特许参与者应按规定对其发起的支付指令进行加密，支付指令一经发出即具有支付效力。 3. The solutions include applying encipher technology, setting the standard of related protocol and trying to reduce the unsaf factors in electronic commerce transaction. 解决其安全的方法有:采用加密技术,制定相关协议标准,努力减少电子商务交易中的不安全因素。 4. Abstract: Fingerprint technology is an important part of computer software encipher, this paper presents the principles and methods to make and discriminate the laser hole fingerprint, the weak region fingerprint and the short sector fingerprint. 文摘:指纹技术是计算机加密技术的一个重要组成部分,文中详细论述了激光孔指纹、弱位法指纹及短扇区指纹的原理、制作与识别的方法。', '名词: encipherer 过去式: enciphered 过去分词: enciphered 现在分词: enciphering 第三人称单数: enciphers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('factitious', '[fæk\'tɪʃəs]', 'adj.人为的；不自然的；人工的', '1. Extensive advertising can cause a factitious demand for an article. 大规模的广告能引起对某一物品人为的需求。', '副词: factitiously 名词: factitiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perimeter', '[pə\'rɪmɪtər]', 'n.周长；周界；边缘', '1. Work out how long the perimeter of the playground. 请你算一算体育场的周长是多少米? 2. Guards patrolled the perimeter of the airfield. 卫兵沿机场四周巡逻。 3. A fence marked the perimeter of the field. 一道篱笆标明了那块田地的周界。 4. The barbed wire fence round the perimeter discouraged intruders. 周围有铁丝网阻止了外人闯入。', '形容词: perimetric 副词: perimetrically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('myriad', '[\'mɪriəd]', 'adj.无数的 n.极大数量', '1. There are myriad fish in the ocean. 海里有无数的鱼。 2. Myriad stars are twinkling in the night sky. 无数的星星在夜空中闪烁著。 3. Designs are available in a myriad of colours. 各种色彩的款式应有尽有。 4. I had three weeks to make a myriad of arrangements. 我花了3个星期做大量准备工作。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oversight', '[\'oʊvərsaɪt]', 'n.疏忽；失察；监管；看管', '1. The mistake was the result of an oversight. 这个错误是因疏忽而产生的。 2. This error is largely due to my oversight. 这个错误主要是由于我一时疏忽而造成的。 3. The central bank would work with a proposed Financial Services Oversight Council to decide which companies are too big to fail. 中央银行将与被提议的金融服务失察委员会一起决定哪个公司影响太大以至于不能让其失败。 4. The Court cured the constitutional defect in the legislation by reading in provisions providing for judicial oversight of such evictions. 透过在立法院通过阅读新条款，法院弥补了宪政缺陷解决对这种驱逐行动的失察判决。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petitioner', '[pə\'tɪʃənər]', 'n.请愿人；[法]上诉人；离婚案原告', '1. The competent petitioner thinks the perpetual impetus is petty. 有能力的请愿者认为永久的动力是可爱的。 2. The petitioner ask for a variation in her maintenance order. 上诉人要求对她生活费的命令的条件进行变更。 3. Both the petitioner and respondent provide for the upkeep of the children. 离婚案中的原告和被告都要提供孩子的赡养费。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('minutia', '[mɪ\'njuːʃɪə]', 'n.微枝末节；细节', '1. In this paper, we employ an improved minutia preserving smoothing algorithm based on solving a nonlinear diffusion equation. 但降噪算法常会因过度平滑引起图象细节特征的模糊，因此需要采用能保留细节的平滑处理算法。', '名词复数: minutiae');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('photosynthesis', '[ˌfoʊtoʊ\'sɪnθəsɪs]', 'n.光合作用', '1. Photosynthesis is an endergonic process. 光合作用是吸收能量的过程。 2. Our current research topic is photosynthesis. 我们现在研究的课题是光合作用。 3. Plants absorb solar energy during photosynthesis. 植物通过光合作用吸收太阳能。', '形容词: photosynthetic 副词: photosynthetically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contemptible', '[kən\'temptəbl]', 'adj.可鄙的；可轻视的', '1. His cowardice in face of the enemy was contemptible. 他在敌人面前胆小如鼠，真是可鄙。 2. It\'s a contemptible trick to play on a friend! 这种手段欺骗朋友，真是卑劣！ 3. The bold man glanced at the gangster with hatred and contempt. 那个大胆的男人用嫌恶轻视的眼神目瞄了那个帮派份子一眼。', '副词: contemptibly 名词: contemptibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('secretive', '[\'siːkrətɪv]', 'adj.秘密的；偷偷摸摸的', '1. I don\'t know why Fred is always secretive as regards his family. 我不知道为什么凡涉及到他的家，弗雷德总是保密。 2. Why was I always alone and secretive? 我为什么老是独自一个人偷偷摸摸的呢?', '副词: secretively 名词: secretiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('staunch', '[stɔːntʃ]', 'adj.坚定的；坚固的；忠实可信的；不漏水的 vt.止住；止血 =stanch.', '1. He\'s a staunch supporter of the monarchy. 他是君主制的坚定拥护者。 2. They are staunch soldiers. 他们是忠诚的战士。 3. And the fingers trying to staunch the bloody wound at his neck. 和试图止住脖子上正在流血的伤口的手指时会有什么感觉。 4. Messy rescues of Citigroup and Bank of America have failed to staunch their losses. 对花旗和美洲银行棘手的营救并没有止住他们的亏损。', '副词: staunchly 异体字: stanch 比较级: stauncher/stancher 最高级: staunchest/stanchest 名词: staunchness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enervate', '[\'enərveɪt]', 'adj.无力的；衰弱的 vt.使无力；使衰弱', '1. A hot climate enervate people who be not used to It . 热的气候使不习惯于热的人衰弱无力。 2. Soft living will enervate the leaders, and those under their command will be changed into beasts. 舒适的生命会弱化领导者，在他们命令之下的会变成了兽。 3. Enervate! - Revives someone after being knocked out, or being the recipient of the Stunning Spell (Stupefy! 让某个被麻醉的人苏醒,或者成为晕倒咒的被施咒者。(麻醉! 4. In the second, be a man, and shake off a miserable passion, which will enervate and destroy you. 如是后一种情况，那就振作起精神，设法摆脱那可怜的、必定会耗掉你全部精力的感情。', '形容词: enervative 名词: enervation 过去式: enervated 过去分词: enervated 现在分词: enervating 第三人称单数: enervates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nibble', '[\'nɪbl]', 'v.一点点地咬；轻咬；吹毛求疵；（审慎地）表示有意接受 n.轻咬；少量', '1. He didn\'t answer, but just continued to nibble at his food. 他没有回答，只是继续一点一点地吃东西。 2. The mice have nibbled a hole in the cheese. 老鼠在奶酪上啃出了一个洞。 3. Food and rent nibbled away at the money they had saved. 花在食物和房租上的钱把他们的积蓄一点一点耗掉了。 4. She nibbled his ears playfully. 她轻轻咬他的耳朵玩。 5. I feel a nibble on the end of my line. 我觉得有鱼轻轻地咬钩。', '过去式: nibbled 过去分词: nibbled 现在分词: nibbling 第三人称单数: nibbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vibrate', '[\'vaɪbreɪt]', 'vt.(使)振动；(使)摇摆 vi.回响；颤动', '1. They will cause the speaker diaphragm to vibrate. 它们将引起扬声器薄膜振动。 2. Vibrating air makes your ear drums vibrate. 振动着的空气使你的耳鼓振动。 3. Vibrate,as of a swing before it comes to a total rest. 像秋千在平衡前的摇摆。 4. He saw the wings of her butterfly hairpin vibrate subtly. 姑娘头上的蝴蝶发夹微微颤动了一下翅膀。', '过去式: vibrated 过去分词: vibrated 现在分词: vibrating 第三人称单数: vibrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('starchy', '[\'stɑːrtʃi]', 'adj.含淀粉的；古板的', '1. He eat too much starchy food. 他贪吃含淀粉多的食物。 2. Did you know that frying starchy foods can produce a cancer-causing substance? 你知道油炸富含淀粉的食物会释放致癌物吗？ 3. He\'s always been rather starchy. 他一向非常刻板.', '副词: starchily 比较级: starchier 最高级: starchiest 名词: starchiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gasification', '[ˌgæsəfə\'keɪʃən]', 'n.气化', '1. Gasification is really a simple process. 气化确实是一个简单的过程。 2. Coal gas is produced by the gasification of coal. 煤气是由煤的气化作用得到的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('baron', '[\'bærən]', 'n.【C】男爵(英国世袭的最低级的贵族爵位)；巨头(尤指商界)', '1. The Baron was in high good humour. 男爵情绪很好。 2. Then changed, I trow, was that bold Baron\'s brow. 我相信,那勇敢男爵的表情已有变化。 3. Her father is an oil baron. 她父亲是一位石油大王。 4. One of his friends is a steel baron. 他的一位朋友是钢铁大王。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subsist', '[səb\'sɪst]', 'v.供给食物；维持生活；生存；供养', '1. He subsisted mainly on vegetables and fruit. 他主要靠蔬菜和水果维持生命。 2. Don\'t worry about your children whom I can subsist. 别担心你的孩子们，我可以供养他们。 3. How do they manage to subsist on such a low wage? 他们这点工资怎么糊口？ 4. She has to get a casual work to subsist. 她不得不找一个临时工作维持生活。', '名词: subsister 过去式: subsisted 过去分词: subsisted 现在分词: subsisting 第三人称单数: subsists');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shunt', '[ʃʌnt]', 'v.使（火车头等）转轨；转移（方向等） n.分流器；转轨', '1. Can we shunt the talks onto a new topic? 我们谈话换个新话题好吧？ 2. She tried to shunt the blame onto Miss Williams. 她试图把责任推至威廉姆斯小姐身上。 3. The range can be increased by use of a shunt. 量程可以通过加上一个分流器来增大。 4. The shunt many be contained within the meter housing or connected externally. 这个分流器可以容置与仪表表壳中也可以外接。', '名词: shunter 过去式: shunted 过去分词: shunted 现在分词: shunting 第三人称单数: shunts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chicanery', '[ʃɪ\'keɪnəri]', 'n.欺诈；欺骗；强词夺理', '1. Judge players by what they do, when it comes to such chicanery and mini-mayhem. 法官球员他们做了什么，当这种欺骗和迷你混乱。', '名词复数: chicaneries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('posterior', '[pɑː\'stɪriər]', 'adj.(在时间；次序上)较后的 n.臀部', '1. A team of British academics has developed a mathematical formula to determine just how perfect your posterior is. 一个英国的学者小组发明一个能决定完美臀部的数学公式。', '副词: posteriorly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dislodge', '[dɪs\'lɑːdʒ]', 'v.逐出；用力移出；移走', '1. No one could dislodge them from their well-en-trenched positions. 没人能把他们从防守严密的地方逐出。 2. The wind dislodged some tiles. 风把瓦刮下来了。 3. They needed a bulldozer to dislodge the rock. 他们需要一台推土机来挖出岩石。 4. There is something between my teeth and I can\'t dislodge it. 我牙缝里塞了点东西，就是弄不出来。', '名词: dislodgement 过去式: dislodged 过去分词: dislodged 现在分词: dislodging 第三人称单数: dislodges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('application', '[ˌæplɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.应用；申请；专心；应用程序', '1. The application of new scientific discoveries to industrial production methods usually increases efficiency. 把新的科学发现运用到工业生产上,通常可以提高效率。 2. I didn\'t receive an acknowledgement of my application. 对我的申请,我还没有收到复信告知收悉。 3. The manager received twenty applications for the post. 经理收到了二十份求职申请书。 4. Patience and application will carry us through. 忍耐和专心会使我们度过难关。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reprise', '[rɪ\'priːz]', 'n.年金；再发生；[音]反复 v.重复；<古>赔偿', '1. I would not rent this flat if the reprise is higher than 300 yuan a mouth. 只要租金超过每个月三百元，我就不租这间公寓。 2. Battered investors may want to pray for a reprise of 2003. 遭受打击的投资者可能会祈祷2003年的情况再次出现。 3. Noted in two staves, the piano plays a reprise of its own opening theme. 钢琴在自己的展开主题中，演奏出一段贯穿在两行五线谱中的重奏。 4. He went on to reprise his role as a cop in both Die Hard sequels. 他又继续在2部《虎胆龙威》系列电影中饰演警察的角色。', '过去式: reprised 过去分词: reprised 现在分词: reprising 第三人称单数: reprises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tissue', '[\'tɪʃuː]', 'n.纸巾；薄绢；(生物的)组织；织物', '1. She gave us a box of tissues. 她递给我们一盒纸巾。 2. She wiped off the sweat from her face with a piece of facial tissue. 她用一张面巾纸擦掉脸上的汗水。 3. On her head was a tiny cap of silver tissue. 她头上戴着一顶银丝小帽。 4. Human tissue is made up of cells. 人体的组织是由细胞构成的。', '形容词: tissuey');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('needy', '[\'niːdi]', 'adj.贫穷的；缺乏的 n.贫穷的人', '1. There are many needy families in our village. 我们村子有很多贫困家庭。 2. He deems it his duty to help his needy friends. 他认为帮助穷朋友是他的义务。 3. The rich man gave much food to needy people. 那位富翁给了穷人很多食物。 4. The government has worked out a plan of succoring the needy. 政府已经制定出了救济贫民的计划。', '比较级: needier 最高级: neediest 名词: neediness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('posture', '[\'pɑːstʃər]', 'n.姿势；态度；情形 v.作 ... 姿势；摆架子', '1. Only humans have a natural upright posture. 只有人类才有自然直立的姿势。 2. The artist asked his model to take a reclining posture. 画家要求模特取斜倚着的姿势。 3. She has very good posture. 她举止很优雅。 4. The government adopted an uncompromising posture on the issue of independence. 政府在独立的问题上采取了毫不妥协的态度。 5. The war-monger would sometimes posture for peace 战争贩子有时也会装出主张和平的姿态。', '形容词: postural 名词: posturer 过去式: postured 过去分词: postured 现在分词: posturing 第三人称单数: postures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oafishness', '[oʊf]', 'n.蠢人；笨拙的人', '1. The oaf stumbled over the bucket, spilling all the water. 那个笨手笨脚的人绊到了木桶，把水全给泼了。 2. You clumsy oaf that\'s the second glass you\'ve broken today! 你这个笨家伙--这是你今天打碎的第二个玻璃杯！', '形容词: oafish 副词: oafishly 名词: oafishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pelf', '[pelf]', 'n.钱财', '1. After plundering enough pelf, he took a train bound for the border. 在抢得足够的钱财后，他乘上开往边境的火车。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quarry', '[\'kwɔːri]', 'n.采石场；猎获物；来源；被追逐的目标 v.挖出；苦心找出', '1. This mountain was the site for a quarry. 这座山曾经有一个采石场。 2. The horseman aimed his lance at his quarry. 骑手把长矛对准了他的猎物。 3. Each sentence seems a quarry of rich meditations. 每一句话似乎都给人以许多冥思默想。 4. It took the police several days to track down their quarry. 警方用了几天时间追查到案中目标。 5. We watched the workmen quarry out a huge block of marble . 我们看到劳工们挖出一大块大理石。', '名词: quarrier 名词复数: quarries 过去式: quarried 过去分词: quarried 现在分词: quarrying 第三人称单数: quarries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('terminate', '[\'tɜːmɪneɪt]', 'v.结束；终止；满期；达到终点', '1. Communist Party of China terminated the rule of feudal landlord class. 中国共产党结束了封建地主阶级的统治。 2. Your contract has been terminated. 你的合同已经被终止。 3. We have to terminate this contract. 我们不得不终止这个合同。 4. The contract will terminate soon. 契约快要期满了。', '过去式: terminated 过去分词: terminated 现在分词: terminating 第三人称单数: terminates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coloration', '[ˌkʌlə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.着色；染色；天然色；特色', '1. The absence of coloration in that drawing makes it dull. 那幅画因没有著色而显得晦暗。 2. This piece of cloth has bad coloration. 这块布料染的不好。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('garrulous', '[\'ɡærələs]', 'adj.喋喋不休的；饶舌的（尤指对琐事）', '1. As one grows old, one tends to be garrulous. 人老了，就爱唠叨。 2. He became positively garrulous after a few glasses of wine. 他几杯葡萄酒下肚之后便唠唠叨叨说个没完。 3. This man does not speak in a straightforward manner, he is garrulous. 这个男人说话做事太不洒脱了,婆婆妈妈的! 4. My garrulous neighbour had given away the secret. 我那爱唠叨的邻居已把秘密泄露了.', '副词: garrulously 名词: garrulousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('radius', '[\'reɪdiəs]', 'n.半径范围；半径；桡骨；辐射区', '1. Nobody is allowed to enter the operation radius. 不允许任何人进入工作半径范围以内。 2. What is the radius of this circle? 这个圆的半径有多长? 3. We can compute the circular area with radius. 我们能用半径计算出圆的面积。 4. The radius expands markedly at its lower end. 桡骨下端明显扩张。', '名词复数: radii');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bar', '[bɑːr]', 'n.酒吧；条；横木；栅 vt.禁止；阻挠；闩上；在 ... 设栅栏', '1. There are several bars in the hotel. 这家旅馆里有好几个酒吧。 2. A bar of chocolate is enough to stop his crying. 一条巧克力就可以让他不哭了。 3. There\'s a strong bar on the door. 门上有一个很坚固的闩。 4. There is a burning man hovering in the air over a grille in the Smoldering Corpse Bar. 有一个焚烧中的人，飘浮在冒烟尸体酒吧的铁栅上方。 5. After the bombing, the whole area was barred to the public. 轰炸后，整个地区禁止公众通行。', '过去式: barred 过去分词: barred 现在分词: barring 第三人称单数: bars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('missive', '[\'mɪsɪv]', 'n.公文；书信', '1. The missive remains unwritten and unsent. 这件公文未写也未发出去。 2. Today\'s missive is about supply constraints. 今天很大篇幅会讲到供应方面。 3. The subject line on this latest missive was Homepage. 这最新的信件的主题是“主页”。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corroborate', '[kə\'rɑːbəreɪt]', 'v.确证；证实', '1. There\'s nothing to corroborate your story. 无任何东西可以确证你的话。 2. Some observations do seem to corroborate the idea. 而某些观察所得似乎也佐证了这种想法。 3. Experiments have corroborated her predictions. 实验证实了她的预言。 4. His friend corroborated his guilt. 他的朋友证实了他的犯罪。', '形容词: corroborative 名词: corroboration 过去式: corroborated 过去分词: corroborated 现在分词: corroborating 第三人称单数: corroborates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('supplant', '[sə\'plænt]', 'v. 取代； 排挤 <古>根除', '1. The duke plotted to supplant the king. 公爵阴谋取代国王的地位。 2. She\'s been supplant in her aunt\'s affection by her brother. 她在她姑母心中的地位已被她兄弟取代了。 3. It is my view that the new historical disciplines complement rather than supplant traditional history. 我认为这些新的历史学科对传统历史学起到了补充而非排挤作用。', '过去式: supplanted 过去分词: supplanted 现在分词: supplanting 第三人称单数: supplants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harass', '[\'hærəs]', 'vt.使疲乏；骚扰', '1. The Mongols would harass the enemy from the sides until the latter were exhausted, then close in for the kill. 蒙古军会从四面八方不断侵扰敌人，直到敌人筋疲力尽，再包围并一举歼灭。 2. They received the order to harass the enemy\'s rear. 他们接到骚扰敌人后方的命令。 3. The guerrillas lay up by day, and by night sallied out to harass the enemy. 游击队员们白天隐藏起来，夜晚进行出击，骚扰敌人。', '名词: harasser 过去式: harassed 过去分词: harassed 现在分词: harassing 第三人称单数: harasses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lethal', '[\'liːθl]', 'adj.致命的；危险的；有效的', '1. Pot-holes can be lethal for the unwary cyclist. 路上的坑坑洼洼骑车的人一不小心就有致命危险。 2. In situation like this, she wish she have a gun or some lethal weapon. 在这种情况下，她真希望自己有一把枪或什么致命武器。 3. It was a potentially lethal mixture of drugs. 这种混合药物有很大的潜在危险。 4. This time it was covered in snow and ice and in a lethal condition. 这一次该山崖布满了雪和冰,条件实在不佳。', '副词: lethally 名词: lethality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reel', '[riːl]', 'v.卷；绕 v.眩晕；旋转；蹒跚 n.卷筒；线轴', '1. I put a new reel of film in my camera. 我一卷新胶卷装入照相机。 2. When you\'re sure that you have hooked the fish, reel in at once. 当你确信鱼儿已经上钩时，赶紧收卷钓线。 3. Help me to reel up this powerful fish. 帮我收绕钓线拉起这条大鱼。 4. He cast the line suddenly just like throw it into the water and then reel it back. 他把线突然抛出，就像扔进水中一样，然后把线绕回。 5. My head reeled with the facts and figures. 我的脑子被一堆事实和数据搞得一片混乱 6. The reel of film is not in the proper order. 电影胶片卷盘的顺序弄错了。', '形容词: reelable 名词: reeler 过去式: reeled 过去分词: reeled 现在分词: reeling 第三人称单数: reels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alabaster', '[\'æləbæstər]', 'n.雪花石膏；条纹大理石；石膏色 adj.雪白的；雪花石膏制的', '1. Her skin was white as alabaster. 她皮肤雪白光洁。 2. They admire her alabaster complexion. 他们羡慕她那白润光滑的肌肤。 3. That\'s an alabaster vase. 那是个雪花石膏做的花瓶。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crimp', '[krɪmp]', 'v.使起皱；使卷曲；抑制；妨碍 v.诱骗某人当兵（水兵） n.卷曲；卷发；褶皱；阻碍 n.强迫他人当兵（水兵）的人', '1. Bank balance sheet adjustment could crimp or bind credit. 银行资产负债表的调整可能抑制信贷的投放。 2. In a study of needled felts, crimp was found to be a very influential factor. 对针刺毛毡进行研究后发现卷曲是一项重要的影响因素。 3. His illness put a crimp in our plans. 他的生病妨碍了我们的计画。 4. The accident put a crimp in our vacation plans. 这意外事故阻碍了我们的假期计划。', '名词: crimper 过去式: crimped 过去分词: crimped 现在分词: crimping 第三人称单数: crimps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prostrate', '[\'prɑːstreɪt]', 'adj.卧倒的；拜倒的；瓦解的；无能为力的 v.拜倒；倒下；无能为力；筋疲力尽；虚脱', '1. The prisoners were forced to lie prostrate in front of their captors. 囚犯们被迫在逮捕他们的那些人面前卧倒。 2. The country,prostrate after years of war,began slowly to recover. 这个国家连年战争元气尽失后 3. The illness left her prostrate for several weeks. 这场病把她拖倒了几个星期。 4. The slaves prostrated themselves at their master\'s feet. 奴隶们拜倒在主子的脚下.', '名词: prostrator 过去式: prostrated 过去分词: prostrated 现在分词: prostrating 第三人称单数: prostrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('travesty', '[\'trævəsti]', 'n.滑稽模仿；歪曲；漫画 vt.使 ... 滑稽化；曲解', '1. His trial was a travesty of justice. 对他进行审判是对正义的歪曲。 2. His travesty satirize the key man in current political circles relentlessly. 他的漫画无情地讽刺了当今的政界要人。', '名词复数: travesties 过去式: travestied 过去分词: travestied 现在分词: travestying 第三人称单数: travesties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solo', '[\'soʊloʊ]', 'n.独奏；独唱 adj.单独的 adv.单独地 v.单独表演；[空]放单飞(飞行员一个人开飞机,无教练陪同)', '1. The first piece is a piano solo by Berio. 第一个节目是贝里奥的钢琴独奏。 2. The concert began with piano solo. 音乐会以一首钢琴独奏开始。 3. He has been asked to sing a solo at the concert. 他已被邀请在演奏会上表演独唱。 4. The student essayed his first solo flight. 该学员尝试作首次单独飞行。 5. His landing was awkward,but it was only the second time he\'d flown solo. 他的着陆技术很不熟练,但这只是他第二次单飞。', '名词复数: solos 过去式: soloed 过去分词: soloed 现在分词: soloing 第三人称单数: solos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nebulous', '[\'nebjələs]', 'adj.星云的；星云状的；朦胧的；模糊的', '1. Ideas of fairness in taxation are usually nebulous. 公平这一概念在税收领域一向是模糊不清的。 2. The companyhad a nebulous idea of the next model of car they would manufacture. 该公司对他们下次要制造的车型只有模糊的概念。', '副词: nebulously 名词: nebulousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repressed', '[rɪ\'prest]', 'adj.感情被压抑的；不能公开表达的 动词repress的过去式和过去分词.', '1. His childhood was repressed and solitary. 他的童年是压抑而孤独的。 2. Repressed rage turned his face scarlet. 压抑的愤怒使他的脸通红。 3. Their repressed emotions were ignited by her fiery speech. 她火爆的发言激起了他们压抑的情绪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('noxious', '[\'nɑːkʃəs]', 'adj.<正式>有害的；有毒的', '1. Noxious gases had built up in the sewer. 下水道 的有害气体越积越多。 2. Noxious chemicals are found in the river water. 河水里发现了有毒化学物品。 3. We must trace the source of these noxious gases. 我们必须查出毒气的来源。', '副词: noxiously 名词: noxiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scurry', '[\'skɜːri]', 'v.小步疾走；急赶 n.快跑声；疾走', '1. They scurried in out of the cold. 他们冻得很快跑进来了。 2. The rain sent everyone scurrying for shelter. 这阵雨把大家浇得纷纷找地方躲避。 3. I heard a scurry of footsteps. 我听到一阵匆忙奔跑的脚步声。 4. There was a great scurry for bargains. 大家急忙着去抢购特价品。', '名词复数: scurries 过去式: scurried 过去分词: scurried 现在分词: scurrying 第三人称单数: scurries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gallon', '[\'ɡælən]', 'n.加仑(容量单位)', '1. There are eight pints in a gallon. 一加仑有八品脱。 2. This type of car can run 25 miles a gallon. 这种汽车每加仑油料能行驶二十五英里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delicacy', '[\'delɪkəsi]', 'n.柔弱；精致；优雅；谨慎；佳肴', '1. The delicacy of his health alarmed us all. 他虚弱的身体使我们大家都很担忧。 2. The Chinese palace lanterns are famous for their delicacy. 中国的宫灯以精巧闻名。 3. Her act shows a complete want of delicacy. 她的行为显得极不优雅。 4. Religion is a subject that must be approached with great delicacy. 宗教是一个必须慎重处理的问题。', '名词复数: delicacies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('restrain', '[rɪ\'streɪn]', 'vt.抑制；阻止；束缚；剥夺', '1. He couldn\'t restrain his curiosity. 他抑制不住自己的好奇心。 2. She tried to restrain her sobs. 她设法抑制住自己的悲泣。 3. Shame may restrain what the law does not prohibit. 羞耻或许能阻止法律所不能禁止之事。 4. We must not restrain children of their liberty. 我们绝对不要限制孩子们的自由。', '形容词: restrainable 副词: restrainedly 名词: restrainer 过去式: restrained 过去分词: restrained 现在分词: restraining 第三人称单数: restrains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('opinionated', '[ə\'pɪnjəneɪtɪd]', 'adj.固执己见的 动词opinionate的过去式和过去分词.', '1. He is the most opinionated man I know. 他是我所认识的最固执己见的人。 2. One should never be presumptuous and opinionated. 切不可自以为是。', '副词: opinionatedly 名词: opinionatedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('celebrity', '[sə\'lebrəti]', 'n.名人；名誉；社会名流', '1. She became a celebrity overnight. 她一下变成名人了。 2. He was voted the worst dressed celebrity. 大家一致认为他是衣着最差的名人。 3. Celebrity, money and possessions are too often the touchstones for teenagers. 名誉、金钱和财产常常成为青少年们衡量事物的标准。 4. She achieved celebrity status overnight. 她一夜之间成为名流。', '名词: celebrityhood 名词复数: celebrities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obsolete', '[ˌɑːbsə\'liːt]', 'adj.已废弃的；过时的', '1. The army plans to phase out the equipment as it becomes obsolete. 军队计划淘汰这些设备，因为它们已经报废了。 2. This usage of the word is obsolete. 这个词的此类用法已经废弃了。 3. The obsolete regime is about to collapse. 那过时的政权即将崩溃。 4. You always depend on an obsolete viewpoint. 你老是信赖一个过时的观点。', '副词: obsoletely 名词: obsoleteness 过去式: obsoleted 过去分词: obsoleted 现在分词: obsoleting 第三人称单数: obsoletes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('neurology', '[nʊ\'rɑːlədʒi]', 'n.神经学；神经病学', '1. The study appears online in the journal Neurology. 研究发表于神经学期刊线上版。 2. What are the prospects of stem cell therapy for neurology? 干细胞治疗在神经病学的前景是什么？ 3. Freud\'s work stands at the crossroads between psychology and neurology. 弗洛伊德的理论站在心理学和精神病学的交叉点上。', '形容词: neurologic 副词: neurologically 名词: neurologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('schematize', '[\'skiːmətaɪz]', 'vt.以图表解释或图式化；计划', '1. In other words, users seem to end up with a top-down process and induces them to schematize what they have learned. 换句话说，这种由表及里的过程使用户更容易系统的组织他们所学过的东西。 2. This study aims to schematize the event structures expressed by adjectives in Chinese and thus provide the typology of event structure for this kind of word. 通过以上的分析本文试图为汉语中作谓语的形容词所能表达的事件结构进行图式的归纳,进而概括出该类形容词所能表达的事件结构模式。 3. But on other occasions Hardy abandoned a perilous, risky, and highly energizing impulse in favor of what was for him the fatally relaxing impulse to classify and schematize abstractly. 但在其它场合，哈代会抛弃一种充满风险的、冒险的、和极能赋予作品以生机活力的创造冲动，转而偏爱那种对他来说甚为致命的、松散的创作冲动，去抽明地进行分类和按先验图式表述。 4. o schemat do wykonania tego filtru... poprosilbym 为实施此过滤器的最佳方案...', '名词: schematization 过去式: schematized 过去分词: schematized 现在分词: schematizing 第三人称单数: schematizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gamble', '[\'ɡæmbl]', 'v.赌博；冒险；孤注一掷 n.赌博；冒险', '1. He spends all his time gambling in the casino. 他把时间都消磨在赌场的赌博上。 2. He gambled all his winnings on the last race. 他把赢得的钱全都压在最后一场赛马上了。 3. I wouldn\'t gamble on the weather being fine. 我可不指望天气能一直好下去。 4. Drive carefully and don\'t gamble with your life. 小心驾驶,别拿你的生命冒险。 5. The gamble paid off. 赌赢了。', '名词: gambler 过去式: gambled 过去分词: gambled 现在分词: gambling 第三人称单数: gambles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('outmaneuver', '[ˌaʊtmə\'nuːvə]', 'v.以策略制胜；以机动性胜过', '1. They outnumber the high elves and can outmaneuver most enemies. 他们的数量比高等精灵多，而且可以以策略制胜多数敌人。', '过去式: outmaneuvered 过去分词: outmaneuvered 现在分词: outmaneuvering 第三人称单数: outmaneuvers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solitary', '[\'sɑːləteri]', 'adj.孤独的；独立的；单个的；唯一的；荒凉的 n.隐士；单独禁闭', '1. His childhood was repressed and solitary. 他的童年是压抑而孤独的。 2. The trapper leads a solitary life in the mountains. 那个设陷阱捕猎的人孤独地生活在山里。 3. Solitary as their lives were, is there no one person who would serve my purpose? 尽管他们过的是遗世独立的生活，难道就没有一个能够对我的计划有帮助的人吗? 4. A solitary rider was seen in the distance. 远处有个孤零零的骑马的人。', '副词: solitarily 名词: solitariness 名词复数: solitaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rapt', '[ræpt]', 'adj.全神贯注的；入迷的；出神的', '1. We listened to her amazing story with rapt attention. 我们全神贯注地倾听她讲的惊人故事。 2. Mrs. Trenor fixed a rapt eye upon her. 特雷诺太太全神贯注地望着她。 3. There was a rapt look on his face whenever he looked at his sweetheart. 他看着他的恋人时，总是露出醉人的样子。 4. The two of them lay rapt and attentive. 他们两个趴着愣愣地凝神细听。', '副词: raptly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ire', '[\'aɪər]', 'n.愤怒', '1. The next day, the parents directed their ire at Mr.Jiang. 接下来的几天，这些家长将怒火转向了蒋先生。 2. I felt pain, and then I felt ire; and then I felt a determination to subdue her. 我感到痛苦，接着又感到愤怒，最后我下决心要征服她。 3. This after Imus\'s comment about the team raised the ire of civil rights leaders and Rutgers University. 在艾莫斯评论该队伍后,这激怒了人权组织领导人以及罗格斯大学。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recall', '[rɪ\'kɔːl]', 'n.回忆；取消；召回 vt.召回；恢复；回想起；唤起；与 ... 相似', '1. Do you have any recall of that meeting? 你还记得那次会见吗? 2. The new law is now established beyond recall. 新法律现已制定，不得撤销。 3. The experiment sample the raw test of novel Hero Borns to test for times , and it acquires an accuracy of 86.93% , while an recall rate of 91.83%. 实验对小说《英雄出世》的生文本进行了多次抽样测试 4. With the impulse of \"mercantile system\", the Occident adjust their policy one after the other, recall Jew in succession. 在“重商主义”政策的积极推动下,西欧各国相继调整对犹政策,纷纷召回犹太人。', '形容词: recallable 过去式: recalled 过去分词: recalled 现在分词: recalling 第三人称单数: recalls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chef', '[ʃef]', 'n.厨师；主厨', '1. The chef is not interested in Greek food. 厨师对希腊饭不感兴趣。 2. The chef sprinkle poppy seed on the cake. 厨师往蛋糕上撒罂粟籽。 3. I commended the chef on the excellent meal. I later wrote to commend him to his employer, the restaurant owner. 我称赞厨师做的菜味道好。随后我给雇用他的餐馆老板写了封信表扬他。 4. Dinner is in the hands of the chef. 晚餐由主厨负责。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unpretentious', '[ˌʌnprɪ\'tenʃəs]', 'adj.不炫耀的；含蓄的；谦虚的', '1. Simple and unpretentious in behavior. 朴素的，不做作的行为简便且不矫揉造作的 2. An unpretentious country church. 朴实无华的乡村教堂', '副词: unpretentiously 名词: unpretentiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('homeostasis', '[ˌhoʊmiə\'steɪsɪs]', 'n.自动平衡；体内平衡', '1. Homeostasis is the state of maintaining a constant composition of blood. 体内平衡是保持血液中成分稳定的状态。 2. The return of the disequilibrated organ systems of the body to steady states or dynamic stability is known as homeostasis. 人们身体里失调的器官系统恢复到稳定的或动态稳定状态的过程被称为体内平衡。', '形容词: homeostatic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('camouflage', '[\'kæməflɑːʒ]', 'n.伪装；掩饰；迷彩服 v.伪装；欺瞒', '1. They used branches of trees as camouflage. 他们用树枝做伪装。 2. The animal\'s markings provide effective camouflage. 这种动物身上的斑纹是很有效的伪装。 3. Interestingly, Jaguar has attempted to disguise the prototype as a BMW, even adopting the same psychedelic camouflage material as its German rival. 有趣的是，捷豹一直试图掩饰的原型作为一个宝马，即使采用同样的迷幻伪装材料作为其德国竞争对手。 4. Some of them even wore them with their camouflage combat smocks. 有些人还穿着迷彩服佩带勋章。 5. They used branches of trees as camouflage. 他们用树枝做伪装。', '名词: camouflager 过去式: camouflaged 过去分词: camouflaged 现在分词: camouflaging 第三人称单数: camouflages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wither', '[\'wɪðər]', 'vi.枯萎，干枯；凋谢 vt.以鄙视等态度慑服某人；使枯萎，使凋谢，使衰弱', '1. The grapes withered on the vine. 葡萄藤上的葡萄都干瘪了。 2. Either of the flowers will wither soon without water. 任何一朵花没有水都会很快枯萎。 3. My days are like the evening shadow; I wither away like grass. 我的年日，如日影偏斜。我也如草枯干。 4. The early morning rose would wither on the branch if it could feel envy. 清晨的玫瑰如果知道妒忌，都会在枝头枯萎。', '过去式: withered 过去分词: withered 现在分词: withering 第三人称单数: withers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('complexion', '[kəm\'plekʃn]', 'n.肤色；面色；体质；特性；局面', '1. That colour doesn\'t suit your complexion. 那颜色不适合你的肤色。 2. He has a dark complexion. 他肤色黝黑。 3. She has a pale complexion. 她面色苍白。 4. Her sparkling jewellery served as the perfect foil for her fine complexion. 她戴着闪闪生辉的首饰,更显得容貌姣好。', '形容词: complexional');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skunk', '[skʌŋk]', 'n.臭鼬；臭鼬皮；讨厌鬼 v.使惨败；欺骗', '1. A keen smell of skunk was left behind. 臭鼬留下刺鼻的味道。 2. He came home as drunk as a skunk again. 他回到家就醉得不省人世。 3. But on the contrary, she is really a selfish skunk. 可恰恰相反,她其实是个自私的讨厌鬼。', '过去式: skunked 过去分词: skunked 现在分词: skunking 第三人称单数: skunks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flighty', '[\'flaɪti]', 'adj.轻浮的；不负责任的；反复无常的', '1. He said I was too flighty to be a good supervisor. 他说我太轻浮不能成为一名好的管理员。 2. She is too flighty to take care of young children. 她太不负责任, 不能照顾小孩。', '副词: flightily 比较级: flightier 最高级: flightiest 名词: flightiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wrought', '[rɔːt]', 'adj.锤炼的；制成的；精心制作的；装饰的；激动的', '1. Some windows are provided with decorative shutters.Other details include decorative wrought iron balustrades and the windows are designed with traditional mullioned glazing. 带有百叶窗装饰的窗户，传统的竖框玻璃窗和带装饰图案的铁制阳台栏杆。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dynamic', '[daɪ\'næmɪk]', 'adj.动力的；动态的；有活力的；【音】力度变化的 n.动力；动力学', '1. This chapter is on the transformation of heat energy into dynamic energy. 这一章是关于热能转化成动力的。 2. The different varieties of the language are in a dynamic relationship with each other. 这种语言的不同变体间存在着动态的联系。 3. We are looking for dynamic persons to be salesmen. 我们正在寻找充满活力的销售人员。 4. A dynamic government is necessary to meet the demands of a changing society. 一个有活力的政府必须适应社会的改变。 5. They hoped it would act as a spiritual dynamic on all churches. 他们希望这对所有教堂来说都是一种精神动力。', '副词: dynamically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gorilla', '[ɡə\'rɪlə]', 'n.大猩猩；<口>残暴的人', '1. The gorilla had a massive forehead. 猩猩的前额很大。 2. Gorilla is bigger than chimpanzee. 大猩猩比黑猩猩大。 3. The mountain gorilla is on the verge of extinction. 居住在山区的大猩猩已濒临灭绝。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('affection', '[ə\'fekʃn]', 'n.影响；感情；喜爱；慈爱', '1. He\'s so susceptible that she easily gained his affection. 他易受感情影响，所以她很轻易就得到了他的爱。 2. You appear to me to allow nothing for the influence of friendship and affection. 我觉得你未免否定了友谊和感情对于一个人的影响。 3. Don\'t squander your affection on him, he\'ll never love you. 不要把感情浪费在他身上，他是永远不会爱你的。 4. He\'s so susceptible that she easily gained his affection. 他易受感情影响，所以她很轻易就得到了他的爱。', '形容词: affectional 副词: affectionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glean', '[ɡliːn]', 'v.拾落穗；收集', '1. What useful thing can you glean from that? 哪些有益的事情你能收集到的？ 2. He likes to glean the bamboo telegraph. 他喜欢收集小道消息。', '名词: gleaner 过去式: gleaned 过去分词: gleaned 现在分词: gleaning 第三人称单数: gleans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('promulgate', '[\'prɑːmlɡeɪt]', 'vt.发布；颁布；发表', '1. It is proved that the control system can satisfy the users\' requirement to promulgate test information. 实践证明，基于该方案设计的控制系统能够基本满足显示屏用户的文本发布需求。 2. Our group especially promulgate the most novel production with modern design elements for you in 2007. 我们的开发团队特为您发布2007年最高档新颖数码相框外壳前板。 3. The king promulgated a decree. 国王发布了一道命令。 4. The school shall erect regulations to implement gender equity education, and promulgate them. 学校应订定性别平等教育实施规定，并公告周知。', '名词: promulgation 过去式: promulgated 过去分词: promulgated 现在分词: promulgating 第三人称单数: promulgates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('group', '[ɡruːp]', 'n.群；组；团体；集团 v.聚合；成群、组；把 ... 聚集；把 ... 分类', '1. She has a very wide group of friends. 她有一大群朋友。 2. A group of boys dashed out of the classroom. 一群男孩子从教室里冲出来。 3. That group harmonizes well. 那一组用和声演唱得很出色。 4. He is a the most brisk young man in this group. 他是这个小组中最活跃的年轻人。 5. They encouraged the workers to group together. 他们鼓励工人们团结起来。', '过去式: grouped 过去分词: grouped 现在分词: grouping 第三人称单数: groups');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('idle', '[\'aɪdl]', 'adj.无目的；无聊的; 懒惰的；闲散的; 无根据的 vt.虚度; 使空闲 vi.不作事；闲逛; (机器)空转', '1. Being at an idle end,we often go to and look around the shops. 闲来无事，我们常去逛逛商店。 2. Idle folks have the least leisure. 懒惰的人最没空闲。 3. No matter how rich, one shall not live an idle life. 不管一个人多么富有,都不应该过着闲散的生活。 4. I never believe idle reports. 我从来不信捕风捉影的传闻。 5. The strike idled many workers. 罢工使许多工人没事干。 6. I hate you to idle about. 我不喜欢你游手好闲。', '副词: idly 比较级: idler 最高级: idlest 名词: idleness 过去式: idled 过去分词: idled 现在分词: idling 第三人称单数: idles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thrust', '[θrʌst]', 'v.刺；插入；推挤 n.刺；推力；要旨', '1. The mugger thrust at his victim with a knife. 抢劫者用刀子向受害人刺去。 2. The murderer killed her by thrusting a knife in her back. 凶手把刀刺进她的背部，杀害了她。 3. He thrust his hands into his pockets. 他把两手插入衣袋里。 4. We thrust our way through the crowd. 我们用力挤过人群。 5. The fencer parried his opponent\'s thrust. 击剑手挡开了对手的猛刺。', '形容词: thrustful 名词: thruster 过去式: thrust 过去分词: thrust 现在分词: thrusting 第三人称单数: thrusts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('culprit', '[\'kʌlprɪt]', 'n.罪犯；起因', '1. The hunt is on for the culprit. 正在搜捕该罪犯。 2. The police are now on the scent of the culprit. 警方已获得罪犯的线索。 3. The culprit will be whipped when he is found. 那个罪犯找到后就要挨鞭子抽打。 4. High production costs are the main culprit. 高生产成本是主要原因所在。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mete', '[miːt]', 'vt.量；测量；分配 n.边界；界石', '1. God mete out justice in his own good time. 羞恶自有报，只争迟与早。 2. Justice was meted out to the offenders. 犯人均已绳之以法。 3. The judge meted out severe penalties. 法官对犯人予以严惩。', '过去式: meted 过去分词: meted 现在分词: meting 第三人称单数: metes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('advisable', '[əd\'vaɪzəbl]', 'adj.明智的；可取的', '1. It is advisable to be forearmed. 预作准备是明智的。 2. This line of conduct seems advisable to me. 这一行动方针对我来说似乎是很可取的。 3. It is not advisable just to work away without making a timely summing-up of experience. 一味埋头干下去不做及时的经验总结是不可取的。', '副词: advisably 名词: advisability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maximize', '[\'mæksɪmaɪz]', 'v.使增加至最大限度；充分利用', '1. We must maximize profits. 我们必须尽量增加利润。 2. People are expected to act so as to maximize their well-being. 人们总是期望他们的行动能取得最大的利益。 3. Its aim is to maximize the difference between their value. 它的目标是最大限度地扩大它们之间价值的差距。 4. I\'ll maximize this opportunity to learn as much as I can and make as many Chinese friends as I can. 我要充分利用这次机会尽可能地多了解中国,对交一些中国朋友。', '名词: maximization 过去式: maximized 过去分词: maximized 现在分词: maximizing 第三人称单数: maximizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heal', '[hiːl]', 'vt.治愈；使恢复健康；使和解 vi.痊愈', '1. Time heals most pains. 时间会消除很多痛苦。 2. The medicine and rest will soon heal your wound. 药物治疗和休息会使你的伤口很快愈合。 3. The holy man healed them of their sickness. 那位神职人员治好了他们的疾病。 4. Nothing could heal the rupture between he and his father. 没有什么可以弥合他和父亲之间的裂痕。 5. The terrible wound took a long time to heal. 这重伤费了很长时间才痊愈。', '形容词: healable 过去式: healed 过去分词: healed 现在分词: healing 第三人称单数: heals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brim', '[brɪm]', 'n.边；边缘 v.（装）满；（使）溢出', '1. He drank at the fountain\'s brim. 他醉在喷泉边。 2. The heart-shaped brim and brown velvet ribbon around the hat add a lovel accent. 心形边和褐色丝绒带周围的帽子向勒沃尔口音。 3. Nevertheless, the brim part of design is not very ideal. 不外，图案的边缘部门不是很完美。 4. With a dim triumph, she trims the swimming-suit rim at the swimming-pool brim. 她带着暗淡的喜悦在泳池边整理泳装的边缘。 5. The tea cup was filled to the brim. 茶杯满到杯子边了。', '过去式: brimmed 过去分词: brimmed 现在分词: brimming 第三人称单数: brims');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compatriot', '[kəm\'peɪtiət]', 'n.同国人；同胞；同事 adj.同国的', '1. He believes that he and his compatriot student are the future leader. 他相信他和他同国的学生是未来的领袖。 2. My dear compatriot, it is time that we did something for our country. 亲爱的同胞们，为国效劳的时候到了。 3. I see the overseas compatriot in the extremely endeavor! 我看见国外的同胞在十分的努力！', '形容词: compatriotic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('victimize', '[\'vɪktɪmaɪz]', 'v.使牺牲；使受骗；使受害；欺负', '1. The fat boy was victimized by his classmates. 那个胖小子挨同学欺侮了。 2. Union leaders claimed that somemembers had been victimized (eg by being dismissed) for taking part in the strike. 工会领袖声称有些会员参加罢工竟遭资方惩处(如遭解雇).', '名词: victimization 过去式: victimized 过去分词: victimized 现在分词: victimizing 第三人称单数: victimizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petroglyph', '[\'petrəglɪf]', 'n.岩石雕刻', '1. Newspaper Rock Recreation Site offers a large petroglyph panel. 报纸岩娱乐区(Newspaper Rock Recreation Site)拥有一块巨大的岩石雕刻板。 2. A petroglyph emerges from the sands of the Sahara in Chad. 这是非洲乍得境内撒哈拉大沙漠里的一块岩石画。 3. It resembles a petroglyph of some sort more than it resembles the \"usual\" crop circle design. 与其说它像“普通的”麦田怪圈，不如说它有点像某种岩石雕刻。 4. Upon landing, he drew a petroglyph on Second Mesa, showing a maiden riding in a wingless, dome-shaped craft. 当他落地后，他在第二块岩石平顶绘一岩石雕刻，显示一位少女（具有传说的“蝴蝶”发型）骑在一没有翅膀的、圆形飞行器上。', '形容词: petroglyphic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expend', '[ɪk\'spend]', 'vt.花费；消耗', '1. He lived high and expended largely. 他生活讲究，花费很大。 2. He has expended much time and energy on that experiment. 他已经花费许多时间、金钱在那实验上。 3. The soldiers expended all their ammunition in that fight. 士兵在那场战斗中用尽了所有的弹药。 4. I had expended much time on the work but they told me it\'s useless. 我花了很多时间在这件工作上，他们却告诉我说这是无用的。', '过去式: expended 过去分词: expended 现在分词: expending 第三人称单数: expends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('equestrian', '[ɪ\'kwestriən]', 'n.骑马者；骑术家 adj.骑马的；骑术的', '1. The equestrian events will be held here. 马术比赛的赛事将在这里举行。 2. In all equestrian sports the horse must be considered paramount. 在所有的马术运动中，必须以马为最重要的考虑。', '名词: equestrianism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cytology', '[saɪ\'tɑːlədʒi]', 'n.细胞学', '1. How good is conventional sputum cytology? 传统痰细胞学检查有多好？', '形容词: cytologic 名词: cytologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('germicide', '[\'dʒɜːrmɪsaɪd]', 'n.杀菌物；杀菌剂 adj.有杀菌力的', '1. After all visible blood has been removed, disinfection is carried out under the conditions specified for the germicide. 当所有可见的血迹被除去后，在消毒剂的作用条件下进行消毒。 2. Ratified use of product: the 5 th classification as Germicide, Hygiene Disinfectant, Disinfectant. 核定使用商品（第5类）杀菌剂（真菌）；卫生消毒剂；消毒剂（商品截止） 3. Regular cleaning of the system is an effective supplement to germicide, dispersant and other resin control agent. 对系统进行定期清洗,是杀菌剂、分散剂及其他树酯控制剂的有效补充。 4. YOULUJIN (sodium Dichloroisocyanurate) is a kind of high effective and widely used germicide and disinfectant. 优氯净（二氯异氰尿酸钠）是一种广谱高效的杀菌、消毒剂，用途十分广泛。', '形容词: germicidal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stun', '[stʌn]', 'vt.使震惊；使目瞪口呆；使昏迷 n.震惊；晕眩', '1. This speech seemed to stun the king. 这话似乎使国王大吃一惊。 2. He was stunned by the sudden news. 他因听到这突然的消息而目瞪口呆。 3. She sat stunned for a while, until she recovered. 她一时昏迷，坐下呆了一会儿才醒过来。 4. The punch stunned me for a moment. 那一拳把我打得昏了一阵。 5. How do I set a laser printer to stun? 我怎么把一台激光打印机设置到震惊？', '过去式: stunned 过去分词: stunned 现在分词: stunning 第三人称单数: stuns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monumental', '[ˌmɑːnju\'mentl]', 'adj.纪念碑的；作为纪念的；不朽的', '1. Monumental heritage appears after them. 纪念碑的遗产在他们身后出现。 2. I have a monumental brass medal. 我有一枚有纪念意义的铜牌。 3. The earlier characteristics is monumental and symbolic. 前期特征是纪念性和象征性。 4. It\'s an absolutely monumental waste of energy and resources. 这绝对是种对能源和资源的不朽浪费。', '副词: monumentally 名词: monumentality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('propel', '[prə\'pel]', 'v.推进；驱使', '1. He used a paddle to propel the boat. 他用船桨将船推进。 2. The proper use of imagination can then propel ideas in the directions you desire. 适当运用想象力可以将思想往你所希望的方向推进。', '过去式: propelled 过去分词: propelled 现在分词: propelling 第三人称单数: propels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scoff', '[skɔːf]', 'n.嘲笑；笑柄；愚弄 v.嘲笑；嘲弄；愚弄；狼吞虎咽', '1. You should not scoff at others\'belief. 你不能嘲笑别人的信仰。 2. Initially, the\" core\" of any industry will scoff. 最初，任何一个行业的核心拥趸都会嘲笑这种自讨苦吃的做法。 3. You should not scoff at others\'belief. 你不能嘲笑别人的信仰。 4. Initially, the\" core\" of any industry will scoff. 最初，任何一个行业的核心拥趸都会嘲笑这种自讨苦吃的做法。', '副词: scoffingly 名词: scoffer 过去式: scoffed 过去分词: scoffed 现在分词: scoffing 第三人称单数: scoffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nib', '[nɪb]', 'n.鸟嘴；鹅管笔的尖端；笔尖 v.装上笔尖', '1. The nib is blunted. 钢笔尖儿戳了。 2. The sharp nib scratched through the paper. 笔尖把纸戳穿了。 3. The lawyer nib his pen, spread out his paper, and prepared to write. 那律师装上笔尖,摊开纸张,准备开始写东西。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('irritate', '[\'ɪrɪteɪt]', 'v.激怒；使疼痛或发炎', '1. His letter irritated me a little. 他的信使我有点恼怒。 2. Don\'t irritate her, she\'s on a short fuse today. 别惹她，她今天动不动就发火。 3. Wool irritates my skin. 毛织物会使我的皮肤过敏。 4. Insect bites irritate your skin. 虫子叮疼了你的皮肤。', '副词: irritatingly 名词: irritator 过去式: irritated 过去分词: irritated 现在分词: irritating 第三人称单数: irritates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exude', '[ɪɡ\'zuːd]', 'v.流出；渗出', '1. The hot sun made him exude sweat. 烈日晒得他汗流浃背。 2. Some successful men exude self-confidence. 有些成功的人流露出自信。 3. She does not exude maternal warmth. 她没有散发出母性的温暖。 4. Sweat exudes through the pores. 汗从毛孔中渗出。', '过去式: exuded 过去分词: exuded 现在分词: exuding 第三人称单数: exudes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cringing', '[krɪndʒŋ]', 'adj.谄媚的；奉承的 n.谄媚；奉承 动词cringe的现在分词形式.', '1. He had a cringing manner but a very harsh voice. 他有卑屈谄媚的神情，但是声音却十分粗沙。 2. He had a cringing manner but a very harsh voice. 他有卑屈谄媚的神情，但是声音却十分粗沙。 3. Staggering out of their fortresses, they came to me cringing and trembling. 外邦的子民向我谄媚奉承，一听到是我，即刻向我服膺。 4. Staggering out of their fortresses, they came to me cringing and trembling. 外邦的子民向我谄媚奉承，一听到是我，即刻向我服膺。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recant', '[rɪ\'kænt]', 'v.放弃主张；撤回；公开宣布', '1. The torture can not make the man recant. 拷问者不能使那个人放弃他的主张。 2. Though he was forced to change his religion,he would not recant. 虽然强迫他改变宗教信仰，但他绝不改变。', '名词: recantation 过去式: recanted 过去分词: recanted 现在分词: recanting 第三人称单数: recants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('address', '[ə\'dres]', 'n.住址；网址；电子邮箱地址；称呼；致词；讲话；演讲；谈吐 v.称呼；发表演说；提出；写地址；处理', '1. Please write your home address on the registration form. 请在这张登记表上写下你的家庭住址。 2. I\'ll log in to the internet to know about you. I know your address. 我还是上因特网去看吧，我知道你们的网址。 3. Can you tell me your E-mail address? 能告诉我你的电子邮箱地址吗? 4. What form of address should one use when writing to a bishop? 给主教写信应该怎样称呼? 5. Most people call me Bob. How do I address you? 大家叫我鲍勃,我怎么称呼你?', '过去式: addressed 过去分词: addressed 现在分词: addressing 第三人称单数: addresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('capillary', '[\'kæpəleri]', 'n.毛细管 adj.毛状的；毛细管的', '1. Every bite you take closes another capillary. 每吃一块肉都会阻塞你的一根毛细管。 2. The gasoline detection system consists of a capillary restriction. 汽油检测系统由毛细管节流器组成。 3. Two new methods for making taper glass capillary tubes with ordinary drawing machine were developed. 提出两种用普通毛细管拉制机制备变径玻璃毛细管的新方法。', '名词复数: capillaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quiver', '[\'kwɪvər]', 'v.颤抖；振动 n.颤抖；箭袋；箭袋内的箭', '1. The old man quivered with rage. 这位老人气得发抖。 2. The skylark quivered its wings. 云雀抖动它的双翼。 3. There was a slight quiver in his voice as he spoke. 他说话时声音有些颤抖。 4. A quiver of fear ran through her. 一阵恐惧的颤抖传遍了她的全身。', '形容词: quivery 过去式: quivered 过去分词: quivered 现在分词: quivering 第三人称单数: quivers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('untoward', '[ʌn\'tɔːrd]', 'adj.麻烦的；不利的；不适当的；失控的', '1. Indeed, anything untoward was now kept from James. 的确，现在一切不顺心的事都小心瞒着詹姆士。 2. Subconsciously I felt something untoward was going to happen. 我下意识地感到要出事。 3. He had noticed nothing untoward. 他没有注意到有何特殊情况。 4. There were no reports of untoward incidents during these protest programmes. 至今还没有发生恶性事件的报道。', '副词: untowardly 名词: untowardness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('requite', '[rɪ\'kwaɪt]', 'vt.报答；报酬；还礼；报复', '1. Later, she thought that all the people should choose a day to cherish the memory of our mothers so as to requite mothers for the care and upbringing. 后来，她认为所有的人都应该选定一天来怀念母亲，报答母亲的养育之恩。 2. I\'ll requite you for your help. 我想报答你的帮助。 3. He may freely receive courtesies that know how to requite them. 知道如何还礼的人可以随意收礼。', '形容词: requitable 名词: requiter 过去式: requited 过去分词: requited 现在分词: requiting 第三人称单数: requites');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('symbiosis', '[ˌsɪmbaɪ\'oʊsɪs]', 'n.共生；共栖', '1. There is a symbiosis between large and small. 大公司和小公司可以共存。', '形容词: symbiotic 副词: symbiotically 名词复数: symbioses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hemostat', '[\'hiːməˌstæt]', 'n.止血钳子；止血剂', '1. In addition,the use of chitosan in hemostat is indicated in this paper. 另外，本文对壳聚糖在止血剂中的应用也作了简要的介绍。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interdisciplinary', '[ˌɪntər\'dɪsəplɪneri]', 'adj.各学科间的；跨学科的', '1. Interdisciplinary research on climate change in the Massachusetts Institute of Technology\'s science and engineering schools. 马萨诸塞州科学工程部技术研究所有关气候变化的学科间研究。 2. As a new interdisciplinary concept, social capital is a unique concept and has its own advantages, and it is possible to promote the harmonious campus construction realistically. 摘要社会资本作为一个跨学科的新概念，有着独特的理念和优势，对于推动和谐校园构建有着现实的意义。 3. This textbook is an introduction to environmental science ,an interdisciplinary study of humanity\'s relationships with the earth\'s living and nonliving things. 这本教科书是介绍环境科学的，跨学科的探讨研究人类与地球上生命体与非生命体之间的关系。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unspoiled', '[ˌʌn\'spɔɪld]', 'adj.未损坏的；未宠坏的', '1. This is a natural and unspoiled breed. 是一种自然的、未加修饰的品种。 2. Beautiful and unspoiled, it was difficult to farm. 格兰扁山区景色怡人，还没有受到现代文明的污染。 3. This city is flanked on all sides by unspoiled country. 城市四面是天然风光。 4. A comprehensive park with an unspoiled view of the woods and hills. 带有独特山林景色的大型城市公园。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accede', '[ək\'siːd]', 'v.同意；继承；即位；加入', '1. We acceded to his request. 我们同意他的请求。 2. The only child acceded to the family estate. 这个独生子继承了家产。 3. Queen Victoria acceded to the throne in 1837. 维多利亚女王于1837年即位。 4. Our government acceded to the treaty. 我国政府加入了该条约。', '名词: accedence 过去式: acceded 过去分词: acceded 现在分词: acceding 第三人称单数: accedes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anthology', '[æn\'θɑːlədʒi]', 'n.选集；文选', '1. We have some miniature editions of this anthology. 我们有这本文集的袖珍本。 2. The anthology reveals a prejudice in favour of lyric poets. 这部选集显示出对抒情诗人有所偏爱。 3. This anthology comprises samples from the work of ten authors. 这本文选包含了十个作家的作品范例。', '形容词: anthological 名词复数: anthologies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('constringe', '[kən\'strɪndʒ]', 'vt.使收缩；压缩', '1. Constringe pore, restrain skin and get rid of the scars of acne. 有效控制油脂分泌，收缩扩大的毛孔，改善皮肤质感，并具减少黑头、刺、止暗疮留印等功效，令肌肤光泽无暇。 2. It helps to constringe pores, balance sebum secretion and moisturize skin. 具有良好的保湿作用，防止肌肤干燥，为肌肤带来透明感与光泽。 3. It can constringe and clean the pores of face. accelerate the cicatrization of wounds. 刺激毛发生长，收敛及清洁毛孔，促进伤口愈合。 4. Ingredients: natural herbage whiten essence、green tea extracts、wild chrysanthemum、aloe、constringe agency ets. 成份：天然本草美白精华、绿茶提取液、野菊花、芦荟、收敛剂等。', '形容词: constringent 名词: constringency 过去式: constringed 过去分词: constringed 现在分词: constringing 第三人称单数: constringes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('render', '[\'rendər]', 'vt.提供；表现；使成为；宣布；翻译；回报；给予补偿；【计】渲染 n.粉刷；打底；交纳', '1. We are going to render them economic assistance. 我们打算向他们提供经济援助。 2. The power of the ocean was beautifully rendered in the poem. 这首诗将大海的力量表现得非常完美。 3. His back injury had rendered him unfit for work. 他的背伤使他无法胜任这份工作。 4. The jury has rendered its verdict. 陪审团已经作出了裁决', '形容词: renderable 名词: renderer 过去式: rendered 过去分词: rendered 现在分词: rendering 第三人称单数: renders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('limp', '[lɪmp]', 'n.跛行 adj.柔软的；无力的；软弱的 vi.跛行；蹒跚', '1. Two weeks later, the dog could walk with a limp. 两周后，狗儿可以跛行了。 2. The injury left him with a permanent limp. 他受伤后就一直瘸了。 3. This young man is wearing a limp grey sweater. 这个年轻人穿着一件柔软的灰色运动衫。 4. The man\'s shrieked whistle struck his limp ears. 男人尖细的口哨声传到它那柔软的耳朵里。 5. He that lives with cripples learns to limp. 近朱者赤，近墨者黑。', '副词: limply 比较级: limper 最高级: limpest 名词: limpness 过去式: limped 过去分词: limped 现在分词: limping 第三人称单数: limps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gorge', '[ɡɔːrdʒ]', 'n.峡谷；咽喉；大量食物；饱食；阻碍物；厌恶 vt.暴食；贪婪地吞咽 vi.狼吞虎咽', '1. A deep gorge separates the two halves of the city. 有一道深谷把这座城市分成两部分。 2. Have you been to the Yangtse Gorges? 你去过长江三峡吗？ 3. His gorge was stuck by a fish bone. 鱼刺卡在他的咽喉。 4. An ice gorge has blocked the shipping lane. 冰块阻碍了航道。 5. The fat man gorged himself constantly with enormous desserts. 那个胖子经常大吃甜食。 6. The boy gorged on turkey on Christmas Day. 这男孩耶诞节那天大吃火鸡。', '名词: gorger 过去式: gorged 过去分词: gorged 现在分词: gorging 第三人称单数: gorges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('externalize', '[ɪk\'stɜːrnəlaɪz]', 'vt. 使外在化； 把 ... 归于外因', '1. There is a tendency to externalize all religions. 存在把一切宗教都视为仅具外表形式的倾向。 2. To impart reality to;make objective;externalize. 使客观化使具体化;使客观;使客观化，使具体化 3. To impart reality to; make objective; externalize. 使客观化使具体化；使客观；使客观化，使具体化 4. NL]Muis Netwerken - Extern Systeembeheer Op Afroep. 访问数/每百万人：Reach for [MUISNETWERKEN.', '名词: externalization 过去式: externalized 过去分词: externalized 现在分词: externalizing 第三人称单数: externalizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repulse', '[rɪ\'pʌls]', 'n.击退；拒绝 v.击退；拒绝', '1. After the second repulse, the enemy surrendered. 在第二次击退之后，敌人投降了。 2. Her repulse was quite unexpected. 她的拒绝是完全出人意料的。 3. Her request for a donation met with a rude repulse. 她要求赞助却遭到粗暴拒绝。 4. Do I repulse you with my queasy smile? 我诡异的笑脸让你知难而退了吗？', '名词: repulser 过去式: repulsed 过去分词: repulsed 现在分词: repulsing 第三人称单数: repulses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pretension', '[prɪ\'tenʃn]', 'n.声称；自命；要求；自负；狂妄；炫耀', '1. His social pretensions make him appear ridiculous. 他冒充上流社会人士而出尽洋相。 2. He has no pretensions to being an expert on the subject. 他并不以这方面专家自居。 3. Readers may find the pretension and arrogance of her style irritating. 读者可以感觉到她文章中的狂妄自负令人反感。 4. The play mocks the pretensions of the new middle class. 这出戏讽刺了新中产阶级的装模作样。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eugenic', '[juː\'dʒenɪk]', 'adj.优生（学）的；优种的', '1. An advocate of or a specialist in eugenics. 优生学家优生学方面的专家或倡导者 2. Politician take no interest in eugenics because the unborn have not vote. 政治家对优生学不感兴趣，因为未出生者并无选举权。', '副词: eugenically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('outset', '[\'aʊtset]', 'n.开始；开端', '1. At the outset, it looked like a nice day. 开始的时候，天看上去很晴朗。 2. You should explain this to him from the outset. 你应该一开始就向他解释这事。 3. An ardent outset may be followed by declension. 热情的开端可能继之以冷漠。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('partial', '[\'pɑːrʃl]', 'adj.不完全的；部分的；偏袒的；偏爱的', '1. around three 2. The research project was only a partial success. 那个研究课题只取得部分成功。 3. You will receive some partial credit even you don\'t finish it. 如果你没作完的话,你还是可以得到部分的分数。 4. His partial attitude called forth a lot of criticism. 他的偏袒态度招致了不少批评。', '名词: partialness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('asphalt', '[\'æsfɔːlt]', 'n.沥青；柏油 v.用沥青铺路', '1. Asphalt is used for making road surfaces. 沥青常用于铺路。 2. The asphalt pavements are very clean. 那些沥青的铺道，是很干净的。 3. It is so hot that the asphalt roads are bubbling. 天太热了，柏油路面上都被晒起了泡泡。 4. Up the pavement ahead of me, dogs doze in the sun as children run backforth across the otherwise empty road\'s chipped asphalt. 在我前方的路面上，狗在阳光下打盹，孩子们则在柏油已经碎裂的空旷道路上跑来跑去，除了他们之外四下无人。', '形容词: asphaltic 过去式: asphalted 过去分词: asphalted 现在分词: asphalting 第三人称单数: asphalts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('metaphysical', '[ˌmetə\'fɪzɪkl]', 'adj.形而上学的；抽象的 Metaphysical. adj.(英国)玄学派诗歌或诗人的', '1. He was a metaphysical puzzle to me. 他对我是一个形而上学的谜语。 2. It\'s wrong to approach a problem from a metaphysical point of view. 用形而上学的观点看待问题是错误的。 3. Their argument was too metaphysical for me to follow. 他们的辩论太深奥，我搞不懂。', '副词: metaphysically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bedizen', '[bɪ\'daɪzən]', 'vt.俗丽地穿着或装饰', '1. To deck out in fine clothes and ornaments; bedizen. 穿着俗丽以华丽的衣服和饰品来装饰；穿着俗丽 2. To deck out in fine clothes and ornaments;bedizen. 穿着俗丽以华丽的衣服和饰品来装饰； 3. Dizen:To deck out in fine clothes and ornaments; bedizen. 穿着俗丽:以华丽的衣服和饰品来装饰;穿着俗丽. 4. Prithee, young one, who art thou, and what has ailed thy mother to bedizen thee in this strange fashion? 请问你,小家伙,你是谁呀?你母亲为什么把你打扮成这副怪模样啊?', '名词: bedizenment 过去式: bedizened 过去分词: bedizened 现在分词: bedizening 第三人称单数: bedizens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('paranoid', '[\'pærənɔɪd]', 'n.(=paranoiac)患妄想狂者 adj.类似妄想狂的；多疑的', '1. Beyond that, he developed traits that we came to view as paranoid. 除此之外，他展现了我们视为偏执狂的特徵。 2. There\'s a simple way to determine if I am paranoid. 这里有个简单的方法来决定我是否有偏执狂。 3. He became more paranoid than ever. 他的迫害狂变得比过去任何时候都严重了。 4. Dean is suffering from paranoid anxiety. 迪恩饱受妄想性焦虑症的折磨。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indelible', '[ɪn\'deləbl]', 'adj.不能擦除的；不能磨灭的；难忘的', '1. The scandal entailed on the government indelible disgrace. 那件丑闻给政府带来了难以洗掉的耻辱。 2. The markings dry instantly and they are indelible. 这些记号很快就会风干，很难洗掉。 3. He has made indelible contributions during the entire course of the revolution. 在整个革命过程中，他树立了不可磨灭的功绩。 4. The experience made an indelible impression on me. 那次经历使我难以忘怀。', '副词: indelibly 名词: indelibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gander', '[\'ɡændər]', 'n.雄鹅；一瞥', '1. What\'s good for the goose is good for the gander . 对雌鹅有用的东西自然对雄鹅也有用。 2. The gander circled the pond for days, and more days after that. 那雄鹅成天围着池塘转,日复一日。 3. I had a gander at the new book but decided not to buy it. 我瞧了一眼那本新书，决定不买它。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interference', '[ˌɪntər\'fɪrəns]', 'n.干扰；妨碍', '1. Her mother\'s interference exacerbated the difficulties in their marriage. 她母亲从中干预使他们的婚姻雪上加霜。 2. Her interference was not warranted. 她干涉得毫无道理。 3. I resented his interference in my affairs. 我很不满他干预我的私事。 4. I can not hear the talk, you see, there\'s so much interference. 我听不见那谈话，你瞧，干扰这么多。', '形容词: interferential');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('etiquette', '[\'etɪket]', 'n.礼仪；礼节；规矩', '1. The rules of etiquette are not so strict nowadays. 如今的礼仪规则已不那么严格了。 2. Etiquette was considered very important in Victorian England. 英国在维多利亚时代非常注重礼仪。 3. He understands well about diplomatic etiquette. 他熟知外交礼节。 4. He dared not break the etiquette. 他不敢破坏规矩。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lust', '[lʌst]', 'n.贪欲；欲望；色欲 v.贪求；渴望', '1. The lust for the superfluous is folly, for it has no bounds. 贪欲过多就是愚蠢,因为欲望无穷无尽。 2. It is quite obvious that he has a lust for power. 很显然他渴求权势。 3. The lust of men must not be overdone. 人们的欲望不应过分。 4. She felt no lust whatsoever for him. 她对他没有丝毫欲望。 5. Do not lust in your heart after her beauty or let her captivate you with her eyes, 你心中不要恋慕她的美色,也不要被她眼皮勾引。', '过去式: lusted 过去分词: lusted 现在分词: lusting 第三人称单数: lusts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('humane', '[hjuː\'meɪn]', 'adj.仁慈的；人道的', '1. A humane society always does well by its old people. 一个仁慈的社会对待老人总是很好。 2. Accommodate the interests of infected patients in a sensitie and humane manner. 以一个灵敏和仁慈的方式调和感染病人的利益。 3. The logical answer, in this case, is the humane one. 既然如此，那么合乎逻辑的答案就是人道的那种选择。 4. The purpose of this public festival was to promote a healthy and humane lifestyle. 这个公开的庆祝活动目的是要倡导健康及合乎人道的生活方式。', '副词: humanely 名词: humaneness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('albeit', '[ˌɔːl\'biːɪt]', 'conj.虽然(即使)', '1. I tried, albeit unsuccessfully, to contact him. 尽管未与他联系上，可是我已尽力而为了。 2. I hate him albeit he helped me. 尽管他帮助过我，可是我还是恨他。 3. Answers may now be coming, albeit slowly. 也许对此问题的答案就会揭晓，虽然慢了点。 4. Albeit fair, the girl was not sought after. 那姑娘虽然漂亮,但不是被爱慕的女子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wrest', '[rest]', 'v.夺取；费力取得；歪曲 n.扭；拧；调音键', '1. He wrested it from her hands. 他从她的手中把它抢夺过来。 2. The policeman wrested the truth out of her. 那警察好不容易才从她那儿了解到真情。 3. The report wrests the facts out of their true meaning. 这篇报导歪曲了事实真相。', '名词: wrester 过去式: wrested 过去分词: wrested 现在分词: wresting 第三人称单数: wrests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reciprocal', '[rɪ\'sɪprəkl]', 'adj.互惠的；相互的；互补的 n.相互；互惠；[数]倒数', '1. Thus there is an important reciprocal relationship between honesty and trust. 基于此,诚实与信任成为重要的互惠关系。 2. It is mutually Beneficial and reciprocal to do this deal with the Japanese. 与日本人做这笔生意，互利互惠。 3. They show reciprocal affection to each other. 他们表达了彼此之间的爱慕。 4. Although I gave him many presents, I had no reciprocal gifts from him. 虽然我给他很多礼物, 但我没有收到过他给我的礼物。 5. I trust the reciprocal nature of our love. 我相信爱情是相互的。', '副词: reciprocally 名词: reciprocality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discerning', '[dɪ\'sɜːrnɪŋ]', 'adj.有见识的', '1. She is a very discerning art critic. 她是位眼光敏锐的艺术评论家。 2. All the Chinese army was aware of it and even the more discerning civilian officials. 军事部门的人全都知道，连稍有见识的文职官员也是心里有数的。', '副词: discerningly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blithe', '[blaɪð]', 'adj.快乐的；无忧无虑的；轻率的', '1. She seems quite blithe. 她看上去很快乐。 2. Sunday\'s child is bonny, blithe, good and gay. 星期日出生的孩子漂亮，愉快，乖巧又有朝气。 3. Though we had never done it, as blithe and hardworking spirits we felt that we could too. 虽然还没做到这一点，但无忧无虑而又勤劳刻苦的我们，相信自己一定能行。 4. He showed a blithe indifference to her feelings. 他显得毫不顾及她的感情。', '副词: blithely 比较级: blither 最高级: blithest 名词: blitheness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vulture', '[\'vʌltʃər]', 'n.秃鹰；兀鹰；贪婪的人', '1. We saw a vulture gorging on some rotting carcase. 我们看见一只秃鹫正在贪婪地啄食腐尸。 2. Vulture is a large bird usually with a head and neck almost bare of feathers. 秃鹰是一种头和脖子几乎没毛的大鸟。 3. A vulture usually lives on the flesh of dead animals. 兀鹰靠死去的动物的肉来维生。 4. That vulture is capable of doing anything. 那个贪得无厌的人什么事都能干得出来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('draft', '[dræft]', 'n.草稿；草图；汇票；征兵 vt.起草；征兵；选秀 adj.酝酿中的', '1. He drew a draft of the car. 他画了一张汽车的草图。 2. He has drawn up the design draft. 他拟订了设计草图。 3. He drew a draft on a pad then began his formal work. 他在便笺簿上画了草图，然后就开始正式工作了。 4. I propose issuing a time draft for US $ 100,000. 我建议开具价值10万美元的远期汇票。 5. Who will draft the indictment? 谁将起草起诉状？ 6. The Authority may suggest any other proposal it thinks fit for inclusion into the draft corporate plan. 市建局可提议其认为适合包括在事务计划草案内的任何其他提案。', '过去式: drafted 过去分词: drafted 现在分词: drafting 第三人称单数: drafts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('duplicity', '[duː\'plɪsəti]', 'n.欺骗；口是心非；不诚实；二重性', '1. They were accused of duplicity in their dealings with both sides. 他们被指控双方都存在欺骗行为。 2. His duplicity caused us to distrust him. 他的口是心非使我们不相信他。 3. The structure of social consciousness is unified by the duplicity and dual-structure. 社会意识的结构是两重性和两层性的统一。', '名词复数: duplicities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('audible', '[\'ɔːdəbl]', 'adj.听得见的', '1. He sang with no visible or audible strain. 听上去和看起来，他唱得不费劲。 2. The shot was clearly audible in the silence. 寂靜中枪声听得很清楚。 3. Their voices were audible to the neighbors. 他们的声音邻居都听得到。 4. Her voice was scarcely audible above the noise of the wind. 在风中她的声音几乎听不见。', '副词: audibly 名词: audibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appellation', '[ˌæpə\'leɪʃn]', 'n.名称；称呼', '1. Name address is an important part of the appellation system. 姓名称谓是整个称谓系统中的重要组成部分。 2. Apt appellation will make the communication go smoothly. 适当的称呼有利于交流的顺利进行.', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('broach', '[broʊtʃ]', 'n.烧叉肉；叉子；凿子；拉刀 n.胸针（=brooch） vt.钻孔开启；凿大；初次提起；开始商讨 vi.（船）突然横转', '1. I will broach your idea to the committee. 我要把你的想法提交委员会考虑。 2. Let\'s broach another bottle of wine. 我们再打开一瓶酒吧。 3. He broached the subject of a loan with his bank manager. 他向银行经理提出贷款问题。', '名词: broacher 过去式: broached 过去分词: broached 现在分词: broaching 第三人称单数: broaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dappled', '[\'dæpld]', 'adj.斑纹的；花的', '1. The dappled horse now began to go ahead. 花马开始领先了。 2. The light from the high windows is dappled, as if in a church. 高高的窗户中透出的光线斑杂，仿佛身处教堂。 3. Generally, the types of shade can be divided into deep shade, part shade, and dappled shade. 一般来说，树荫的种类可以分为深度树荫，局部树荫和斑点树荫。 4. It was a close, sultry day, devoid of sunshine, but with a sky too dappled and hazy to threaten rain. 那是一个郁闷酷热的日子，没有阳光，天上却阴霾不雨。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('comprehensive', '[ˌkɑːmprɪ\'hensɪv]', 'adj.全面的；广泛的；综合的；理解的', '1. The reporter has made a comprehensive report. 记者已做了全面的报道。 2. She has a comprehensive grasp of the subject. 她已全面掌握了这一学科。 3. Applying the most comprehensive metal is iron. 应用最广泛的金属是铁。 4. We have a rather comprehensive subway system here. 我们这儿有相当广泛的地铁系统。', '副词: comprehensively 名词: comprehensiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('entrench', '[ɪn\'trentʃ]', 'v.以壕沟防护；(牢固地）确立；侵犯', '1. The enemy were strongly entrenched on the other side of the river. 敌军在河的对岸用坚固的壕沟防守。 2. She is entrenched in her right-wing views. 她的右翼观点根深蒂固。 3. They entrench themselves behind undeniable facts. 他们在无可否认的事实后面固守着自己。', '异体字: intrench 名词: entrenchment 过去式: entrenched 过去分词: entrenched 现在分词: entrenching 第三人称单数: entrenches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clumsy', '[\'klʌmzi]', 'adj.笨拙的；不得体的；笨重的', '1. The clumsy boy bumped into the table. 笨拙的男孩撞到桌子上。 2. My clumsy answer hurt her feelings. 我笨拙的回答伤了她的感情。 3. He chided his son for being clumsy. 他斥责儿子笨手笨脚。 4. This cobbler is rather clumsy. 这个补鞋匠真是笨手笨脚。', '副词: clumsily 比较级: clumsier 最高级: clumsiest 名词: clumsiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subvert', '[səb\'vɜːrt]', 'vt.推翻；颠覆；毁灭；使败坏', '1. The rebellious troops attempted to subvert the present government. 叛军曾企图推翻现政府。 2. He intended to subvert lawful government in his country. 他阴谋颠覆自己国家的合法政府。 3. This doctrine would subvert the very foundation of all written constitutions 这种论说将使一切成文宪法的根本基础遭到破坏。 4. Democracy can easily be subverted from within. 民主政体容易自内部加以破坏。', '名词: subverter 过去式: subverted 过去分词: subverted 现在分词: subverting 第三人称单数: subverts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('patina', '[pə\'tiːnə]', 'n.铜绿；光泽；神情', '1. The cross is finished with an antiqued brown patina. 它是古铜色的。 2. This tripod has a beautiful patina and an air of great antiquity. 这个鼎土花斑驳，古色古香。 3. He looked relaxed and elegant and had the patina of success. 他神态轻松潇洒，给人成功的印象。', '名词复数: patinae');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('torque', '[tɔːrk]', 'n.转力；扭矩', '1. The cathead can\'t give enough torque. 猫头力量不够。 2. This engine develops a high torque. 这台发动机产生的转矩很大。 3. If nothing is wrong with it, please examine the torque. 如果都没有问题，请检查扭转负荷。 4. It is difficult to measure the torque for a rotating shaft. 转轴的扭矩测量一直是一个难解决的问题。', '形容词: torquey 名词: torquer 过去式: torqued 过去分词: torqued 现在分词: torquing 第三人称单数: torques');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discretionary', '[dɪ\'skreʃəneri]', 'adj.自由裁量的；任意的， 自由决定的，酌情行事的， 便宜行事的', '1. The enactment of this regulation gives us discretionary power. 这个法规的颁布，犹如给我们配备了上方宝剑。 2. The judge has the power to make discretionary awards. 法官有权自行作出裁决，决定赔偿额。 3. You may be eligible for a discretionary grant for your university course. 读大学课程可能会有资格获得学校自行决定是否发放的助学金。', '副词: discretionarily');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distress', '[dɪ\'stres]', 'n.不幸；危难；苦恼；痛苦 vt.使苦恼；使痛苦', '1. I pray that you will have pity on my distress. 我请求你可怜可怜我的不幸遭遇。 2. I gripe more from habit than from genuine distress. 我抱怨是出于我的习惯，并非遭遇真正的不幸。 3. They sent a distress rocket. 他们发出了一枚呼救信号火箭。 4. His wild behavior was a great distress to his mother. 他的放荡的行为使他的母亲极为苦恼。 5. Don\'t distress yourself about it. 别为那件事苦恼了。', '副词: distressingly 过去式: distressed 过去分词: distressed 现在分词: distressing 第三人称单数: distresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scythe', '[saɪð]', 'n.长柄的大镰刀 v.以大镰刀割', '1. I use a scythe for cutting grass. 我用大镰刀割草。 2. The workers are scything in the meadow. 工人们正在草地上割草。', '过去式: scythed 过去分词: scythed 现在分词: scything 第三人称单数: scythes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lopsided', '[ˌlɑːp\'saɪdɪd]', 'adj.倾向一方的；不平衡的', '1. We won a game by a lopsided score of 14 to 2. 我们以14比2的悬殊比分赢了一局。 2. The lopsided load on the lorry looked dangerous. 货车上倾斜的货物看样子很危险。 3. The article presents a somewhat lopsided view of events. 这篇文章对事情的看法显得有些片面。 4. The occurrence of that type of lopsided economic development has been checked. 这种经济畸形发展的现象被纠正了。', '副词: lopsidedly 名词: lopsidedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snitch', '[snɪtʃ]', 'n.告密者；告发者 vi.偷；告密 vt.偷取', '1. He has taken care of the girl who wanted to snitch. 他已经干掉要告密的女孩了。', '名词: snitcher 过去式: snitched 过去分词: snitched 现在分词: snitching 第三人称单数: snitches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prune', '[pruːn]', 'v.修剪；削减 n.梅干；洋李脯', '1. You should prune your roses in the spring. 你应该在春天修剪一下你的玫瑰花。 2. It is our job to prune the side branches of these trees. 我们的工作就是修剪这些树的侧枝。 3. The gardener pruned the dead branches. 园丁剪去枯枝。 4. Next year\'s budget will have to be drastically pruned. 下一年度的预算将大幅度削减。', '名词: pruner 过去式: pruned 过去分词: pruned 现在分词: pruning 第三人称单数: prunes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reptile', '[\'reptaɪl]', 'n.爬行动物；卑鄙的人 adj.爬虫类的', '1. Snakes and crocodiles are reptiles. 蛇和鳄鱼都是爬行动物。 2. Strictly speaking,a slow-worm is a kind of reptile. 严格地说，蛇晰是一种爬行动物。 3. This creature can be subsumed in the class of reptile. 这种生物可以归入爬行动物一类. 4. The land is teeming with reptile life. 这片土地多爬行动物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('convalescent', '[ˌkɒnvə\'lesənt]', 'adj.恢复期的；渐愈的；调养的', '1. Convalescent children are difficult to keep in bed. 很难让康复期的孩子们待在床上。 2. He\'s getting along hand over hand; he\'ll soon be convalescent. 他的情况逐步有了起色，不久就会康复的。 3. After a long time in the convalescent home,Johnson is once again a healthy man. 约翰逊在疗养院呆了很长一段时间之后身子骨又硬实了起来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recantation', '[ˌriːkæn\'teɪʃn]', 'n.取消；撤回；改变宗教信仰', '1. To recant or retract something sworn. 食言取消或撤回所发的誓 2. The torture can not make the man recant. 拷问者不能使那个人放弃他的主张。 3. The torture can not make the man recant . 拷问者不能使那个人放弃他的主张。 4. What if I had to get you to recant? 如果我不得不让你放弃信仰?', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grind', '[ɡraɪnd]', 'v.磨；压迫；碾碎；磨得吱吱响；逐渐停顿 n.苦事；磨；碾', '1. It won\'t grind down any finer than this. 不能磨得比这个再细了。 2. Some people grind their teeth while they are asleep. 有些人睡觉时磨牙齿。 3. People in this area were ground down by hunger and poverty. 这个地区的人们受着饥饿和贫穷的折磨。 4. We grind up the wheat to make flour. 我们把小麦磨成面粉。 5. Marking examination papers is a real grind. 批改试卷的确是个苦事。', '副词: grindingly 过去式: ground 过去分词: ground 现在分词: grinding 第三人称单数: grinds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immune', '[ɪ\'mjuːn]', 'adj.免疫的；免除的', '1. This patient\'s immune system has been destroyed. 这位病人的免疫系统受到了破坏。 2. I\'m immune to smallpox as a result of vaccination. 我接种过疫苗了,所以对天花有免疫力。 3. Nobody is immune from criticism. 谁都难免受批评。 4. The criminal was told he would be immune if he helped the police. 这个罪犯被告知，如果他协助警方就可以免于被起诉。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pollinate', '[\'pɑːləneɪt]', 'v.给 ... 授粉', '1. Bees and butterflies pollinate the trees in the orchard. 蜜峰与蝴蝶将果园里的树授粉。 2. Many garden plants need butterflies to pollinate them. 许多园林植物需要蝴蝶授粉他们。', '名词: pollination');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intangibility', '[ɪnˌtændʒə\'bɪlətɪ]', 'n.不可捉摸；不确定；无形', '1. The valuation of intangible assets is not only the important point,but also the diffculty point because of its intangibility and late emergence. 同时，由于无形资产的无形性及其评估在我国出现较晚，无形资产也是资产评估中的一个难点。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monograph', '[\'mɑːnəɡræf]', 'n.专题论文', '1. The latter two published a monograph on semigroup theory in 1961. 后面二人在 1961 年出版了半群理论的专论。', '形容词: monographic 副词: monographically 名词: monographer 过去式: monographed 过去分词: monographed 现在分词: monographing 第三人称单数: monographs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shirk', '[ʃɜːrk]', 'v.逃避；躲避', '1. He decided to shirk his duty. 他决定要逃避责任。 2. It is dishonorable to shirk military service. 逃避兵役是可耻的。 3. She is shirking going to the dentist. 她躲著不愿意去治牙。', '名词: shirker 过去式: shirked 过去分词: shirked 现在分词: shirking 第三人称单数: shirks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resplendent', '[rɪ\'splendənt]', 'adj.辉煌的；灿烂的', '1. Chariness brings refinement life, MEIOU Sanitary will go to try its best to create more glorious and resplendent future. 精心带动精致生活，在新的世纪里，美鸥洁具将继续为更加灿烂辉煌的明天而努力！ 2. We will be creating resplendent future with you and warmly welcome the worldwide customers to patronize and cooperation with us. 以质量求生存，以信誉求发展，竭诚为广大用户提供优良服务，杰龙将与您携手创造辉煌的明天，欢迎世界各地客商惠顾和合作。 3. At times Mandela, in a trademark batik silk shirt, and his wife, resplendent in yellow, exchanged words and held hands like any elderly couple in the theatre stalls. 曼德拉，穿着印有商标的蜡染丝绸衬衫，和他的妻子，穿着灿烂的黄色衣衫，在剧院座位拉着手互相交谈，如同一般老年夫妇。', '副词: resplendently 名词: resplendence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bedlam', '[\'bedləm]', 'n.混乱；喧嚣；疯人院', '1. What\'s happening in that room? It\'s (like) bedlam in there. 那个房间里怎麽了? 乱哄哄的。 2. When the moment arrives bedlam breaks forth. 当新的一年的一刹那到来时，喧闹声骤然四起。 3. It was bedlam at our house on the morning of the wedding. 婚礼的那天早上，我们家闹哄哄的。 4. When the teacher was called away the classroom was a regular bedlam. 当老师被叫走的时候，教室便喧闹不堪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interrogate', '[ɪn\'terəɡeɪt]', 'v.质问；讯问；审问', '1. I decide to interrogate the abductors. 我决定去质问那帮绑架犯。 2. The judges may interrogate the defendant. 审判人员可以讯问被告人。 3. Now we shall interrogate you according to law. 我们现在依法对你进行讯问。 4. Mason decides to interrogate Penticoff himself. 梅森决定亲自审问彭蒂科夫。', '形容词: interrogational 名词: interrogation 过去式: interrogated 过去分词: interrogated 现在分词: interrogating 第三人称单数: interrogates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plinth', '[plɪnθ]', 'n.柱脚；底座', '1. It stands on a high marble plinth with a minaret at each corner. 整个建筑建立在一个高大的大理石底座上,每个角上都有一个尖塔。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beam', '[biːm]', 'vi.微笑；发光 vt.播送；发射；用梁支撑 n.桁条；光线；(光线的)束；(横)梁', '1. She beamed at me. 她对我微笑。 2. His face(He) is beaming with delight. 他高兴得笑容满面。 3. From a sky of untarnished blue the sun beamed down upon Beijing. 阳光透过万里碧空照耀着北京城。 4. Television began beaming the national nominating conventions into the homes of Americans. 电视开始向美国家庭播放总统候选人全国提名大会的情况。 5. A rotary table helps to optimize the beam incidence angle. 一张旋转的桌子有助于将光线影响之方式角最佳化。', '过去式: beamed 过去分词: beamed 现在分词: beaming 第三人称单数: beams');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pied', '[paɪd]', 'adj.斑驳的；杂色的；花衣服的', '1. The pied piper had all the children of Hamlin on his heels. 穿彩衣的吹笛人使得汉姆林镇所有的孩子都跟着他走。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glut', '[ɡlʌt]', 'n.供过于求；过量 v.使充满；过量供应', '1. The glut of fruit sent the prices down. 水果供过于求使价格降低了。 2. The glut of movie screens has also prompted the big chains to shutter their own historic theaters. 影院供过于求还导致大型连锁影院关闭自己的老影院。 3. What\'s more, the glut of prohibitions is tantamount to treating the driver like a child and it also foments resentment. 更有甚者，过量的规定就等于将司机象孩子一样对待，并且招来怨恨。 4. What started out as a slight oversupply is turning into a full-blown supply glut which is sending shockwaves through the whole industry and which could take years to play out. 起初只是略微的供过于求，如今却开始演变成一场声势浩大的严重供应过量，整个行业都因此受到了影响，这种情况或许需要数年时间才能结束。', '过去式: glutted 过去分词: glutted 现在分词: glutting 第三人称单数: gluts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yowl', '[jaʊl]', 'n.号叫；吼声；哀号 v.号叫；吼；哀号', '1. Suddenly, the cat lets out a heart-rending yowl. 突然，那猫发出一声撕心的嚎叫。 2. The cat set up a frightful yowl when the dog appear. 猫看到那条狗就都大声叫起。 3. The cat sets up a frightful yowl when the dog appears. 猫看到那条狗就都大声叫起来。 4. The cat.set up a frightful yowl when the dog appear. 猫看到那条狗就都大声叫起。', '过去式: yowled 过去分词: yowled 现在分词: yowling 第三人称单数: yowls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pamper', '[\'pæmpər]', 'v.纵容；溺爱', '1. Grandparents often pamper the children. 祖母经常纵容这些孩子。', '名词: pamperer 过去式: pampered 过去分词: pampered 现在分词: pampering 第三人称单数: pampers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insinuate', '[ɪn\'sɪnjueɪt]', 'v.暗示；迂回进入；迂回进行；含沙射影的说', '1. He insinuated his doubt of her ability. 他暗示了他对她能力的怀疑。 2. He tried to insinuate himself into the boss\'s favor. 他设法巧妙地渐渐取得老板的欢心。 3. She insinuate to us that her partner have embezzle fund. 她旁敲侧击地指出她的合夥人盗用了资金。 4. I didn\'t insinuate anybody or anything. 我并未影射如何人或任何事。', '形容词: insinuative 名词: insinuator 过去式: insinuated 过去分词: insinuated 现在分词: insinuating 第三人称单数: insinuates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spear', '[spɪr]', 'n.矛；标枪 v.刺穿', '1. The fisher used a spear as his weapon. 渔夫用矛作为武器。 2. The hunter hurled his spear at the tiger. 猎人用力把他的长矛向虎投去。 3. The spear curved through the air. 标枪在空中沿曲线运动。 4. The athlete is trying to launch a spear. 运动员正在用力投掷标枪。 5. They were standing in the river spearing fish. 他们站在河里叉鱼。', '形容词: spearlike 名词: spearer 过去式: speared 过去分词: speared 现在分词: spearing 第三人称单数: spears');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rabble', '[\'ræbl]', 'n.乌合之众；暴民；下层民众；长柄耙；拔火棒 v.聚众闹事；用拔火棒搅动', '1. The rabble soon grew violent and unmanageable. 暴民们很快地变得狂暴和无法控制。 2. A rabble of angry citizens stormed the embassy. 一群愤怒的暴徒冲击了大使馆。 3. It was really a speech that appealed to the rabble. 这确实是很吸引民众的一次演讲。 4. He doesn\'t mix with the rabble here. 他不与这里的下等人交往。', '名词: rabbler 过去式: rabbled 过去分词: rabbled 现在分词: rabbling 第三人称单数: rabbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eavesdrop', '[\'iːvzdrɑːp]', 'v.偷听', '1. It is not polite to eavesdrop on the conversation of other people. 偷听他人说话是很不礼貌的。 2. I\'m not gonna eavesdrop on my friend. 我不会偷听我朋友的。', '名词: eavesdropper 过去式: eavesdropped 过去分词: eavesdropped 现在分词: eavesdropping 第三人称单数: eavesdrops');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sheriff', '[\'ʃerɪf]', 'n.郡治安官；郡长', '1. In the nearby town of Banbury, however, the sheriff found his help. 不过，在附近的班百瑞镇，郡长找到了愿帮助他的人。 2. Angrily, the Sheriff crumpled the note and threw it into the fire. 郡长很生气地把信揉成一团丢到火炉里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('substantive', '[səb\'stæntɪv]', 'adj.独立的；真实的；持久的；本质的；名词性的；大量的；规定义务与责任的；实质的 n.作名词用的词或词组', '1. The airwaves are noisy with nonsense at a time when we need serious, substantive information. 当我们需要严肃而真实的信息的时候，电视广播却是充斥着废话的噪声。 2. The paper uses substantive cases to make it demotic and pellucid. 本文通过运用大量的案例分析，希望能使行文表达通俗易懂。 3. Its importance was evident from the large number of substantive proposals tabled during the ongoing discussion. 目前正进行的讨论中出现了大量的实质性提案体现了其重要意义。 4. It was a lengthy speech but he made few substantive points. 那是一个冗长的演说但是他整理很少实质的要点。', '副词: substantively 名词: substantiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lackadaisical', '[ˌlækə\'deɪzɪkl]', 'adj.无精打采的；懒散的', '1. Lao Wang is very serious with work, so don\'t be lackadaisical. 老王干活可较真儿啦，你可别马马虎虎的。 2. So, Cicero first warned us against the danger of being lackadaisical. 西塞罗首先警告我们要注意萎靡不振的危险。 3. The lackadaisical clerk threw my change on the counter. 那个懒散的店员将我的零钱扔在柜台上。', '副词: lackadaisically 名词: lackadaisicalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sequential', '[sɪ\'kwenʃl]', 'adj.连续的(序贯的)', '1. The Power test executes a single stream of database queries in sequential order. 能力测试将以连续的次序执行一个数据库查询流。 2. This production of items follows a sequential production life cycle. 物料的生产跟随着一个连续的产品生命周期。', '副词: sequentially 名词: sequentiality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clammy', '[\'klæmi]', 'adj.潮湿的；湿冷的；冷黏的；冷漠的', '1. It was a hot and clammy day. 那是个炎热又潮湿的日子。 2. He clutched the cane in his clammy hand. 他那湿冷的手紧抓住手杖。 3. She put a clammy hand to his cheek. 他把一只汗津津的手放在他的脸颊上。 4. The ghost town gave us a clammy feeling. 鬼城给我们令人不安的感觉。', '副词: clammily 比较级: clammier 最高级: clammiest 名词: clamminess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pelt', '[pelt]', 'n.皮毛；投掷；疾行 v.剥去皮毛；（连续）投掷；猛落；大步走', '1. My hat is made of beaver pelts. 我的帽子是用海狸皮做的。 2. The boys were running at full pelt. 男孩子们急速地奔跑著。 3. The crowds pelted bad eggs at the speaker. 群众纷纷向演讲人扔臭鸡蛋。 4. The rain was pelting down. 大雨倾盆。', '名词: pelter 过去式: pelted 过去分词: pelted 现在分词: pelting 第三人称单数: pelts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('periodical', '[ˌpɪri\'ɑːdɪkl]', 'n.期刊 adj.定期的', '1. The periodical is obtainable on the very first day of every month. 这本杂志每月一号出版。 2. She refereed for a periodical a few years ago. 几年前她为一期刊担任编审。 3. They have already put out a new periodical. 他们已经出版了一种新的期刊。 4. I should be glad if you could insert this article into your periodical. 如果能把这篇文章登在你的期刊上我将很高兴。 5. I expect regular periodical reports from you. 我期待你定期汇报。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('buffet', '[bə\'feɪ]', 'n.自助餐；饮食柜台；打击 vt.连续猛击；打击', '1. We serve buffet during lunchtime only. 我们只在午餐时间供应自助餐。 2. We had a buffet supper last evening. 昨天晚上，我们吃了一次自助晚餐。 3. In the corner of the room there was a small buffet. 在屋子角落里有一小的餐具柜。 4. There was a caterers\' buffet stretching all around the dining room. 餐厅周围有一排饮食承办者的冷餐台。 5. Strong winds buffet the ship from time to time. 狂风时不时地击打着航船。', '名词: buffeter 过去式: buffeted 过去分词: buffeted 现在分词: buffeting 第三人称单数: buffets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('optimization', '[ˌɒptɪmaɪ\'zeɪʃən]', 'n.优化；最佳化', '1. It also incorporate new optimization specific to particular server and local database format. 它也把新的优化细节合并到特殊服务器与本地数据库格式中。 2. A group of optimization parameters can be consulted by the mould designer . 给出了一组模具优化参数，可以作为模具设计者参考。 3. We should emphasize that the optimization process must take into account the fact. 我们要强调指出，最佳化过程应考虑到这种事实。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sardonic', '[sɑːr\'dɑːnɪk]', 'adj.讥讽的；嘲笑的；冷笑的', '1. There was a sardonic expression on her face. 她脸上有一种嘲讽的表情。 2. There is little of Satie\'s sardonic wit to be heard in Skempton\'s works. 在斯开普顿的作品里几乎听不到萨蒂那种讥讽的智慧。 3. Her voice faded away at the sardonic gleam in his eyes. 在他嘲笑的眼神中，她的声音慢慢低下去。 4. Creole started into something else, it was almost sardonic. 克里奥尔又开始了，这次几乎是在嘲笑。', '副词: sardonically 名词: sardonicism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('favorable', '[\'feɪvərəbəl]', 'adj.有利的；顺利的；良好的；赞同的', '1. The conditions are favorable for opening a new business. 各种条件有利于开办新企业。 2. He made several favorable comments about their candidate. 他对他们的候选人发表了一些有利的评论。 3. \"Our expedition made a favorable beginning. 我们远航开始的时候很顺利。 4. The book met with a favorable reception. 此书受到好评。', '副词: favorably 名词: favorableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('authoritarian', '[əˌθɔːrə\'teriən]', 'adj.权力主义的；独裁主义的 n.独裁主义者；权力主义者', '1. Uzbekistan is one of the two most authoritarian states of the former Soviet Union. 乌兹别克斯坦是前苏联体系中最独裁主义的其中两个国家之一。 2. It heralded a turn away from the liberalism of the 1990s towards an authoritarian corporatism. 这也标志着俄罗斯由二十世纪九十年代的自由主义向独裁主义的转变。 3. Uzbekistan is one of the two most authoritarian states of the former Soviet Union. 乌兹别克斯坦是前苏联体系中最独裁主义的其中两个国家之一。 4. A dystopia is usually characterized by an authoritarian or totalitarian form of government, or some other kind of oppressive social control. 反乌托邦通常具有以下特点，独裁主义者或极权主译者的政府形式，或者一些其他压迫性的社会控制。', '名词: authoritarianism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('artless', '[\'ɑːrtləs]', 'adj.单纯自然的；不造作的；质朴的', '1. The artless woman had made a confidant of the boy. 这个心地单纯的女人把孩子当作心腹朋友。 2. You can\'t get up that naturalness and artless rosy tint in after days. 你今后不再会有这种自然和朴实无华的红润脸色。 3. My artless comment was mistaken for rudeness. 我直言不讳的评论被误会为粗暴无礼. 4. She was a single-minded, artless girl. 她是一个诚实天真的女孩子。', '副词: artlessly 名词: artlessness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('codify', '[\'kɑːdɪfaɪ]', 'v.把…编成法典；整理；编纂', '1. The noble, Dracon, was asked to codify the laws. 贵族德拉古被选为立法者。 2. The new government promised to codify the laws. 新政府应允要整编法典。 3. The main problem remains the same: how to codify a complex frame of reference. 其重点问题仍然是如何编纂出一个复杂的理论。', '名词: codification 过去式: codified 过去分词: codified 现在分词: codifying 第三人称单数: codifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ensure', '[ɪn\'ʃʊr]', 'vt.担保；保证；使安全；确保', '1. We have worked closely with the Deaf community first, on passage of ADA, and most recently, to ensure that the Act is enforced. 我们最近经常在ada路边的聋人社会附近工作，可以担保该法案得到了实施。 2. I can\'t ensure that he will be there on time. 我不能担保他会及时到那儿。 3. This medicine will ensure you a good night\'s sleep. 这药保证能让你好好睡一觉。 4. People should wash regularly to ensure personal hygiene. 人们应经常洗澡以保证个人卫生。', '过去式: ensured 过去分词: ensured 现在分词: ensuring 第三人称单数: ensures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('audience', '[\'ɔːdiəns]', 'n.听众；观众；读者；倾听；拥护者；正式会见', '1. The audience was no less than five thousand. 听众有五千人之多。 2. Someone in the audience began to laugh. 观众中有人开始笑起来。 3. The concert drew a large audience. 音乐会吸引了大量的观众。 4. The article was put out in a national magazine to reach a larger audience. 为了能影响更多的读者,文章被登发在一份国家级杂志上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foodstuff', '[\'fuːdstʌf]', 'n.食品；食料', '1. Nowadays,the foodstuffs in our life are more various. 如今，我们生活中的食品越来越五花八门了。 2. Rice is our essential foodstuff in life. 大米是我们生活的基本食物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('strut', '[strʌt]', 'n.高视阔步；支柱 v.趾高气扬地走；支撑', '1. The strut has a positive angle when the prop shaft points upwards towards the water surface. 高视阔步有一个正面角度当支柱轴指向向上往水表面。 2. Remove the steering knuckle from the strut. 自支柱拆除转向关节。 3. On this second impact the left wheel strut broke and the right tire blew out! 这第二次接舰的时候，左起落架支柱折断，右轮胎也爆了！ 4. The circulation economy development needs the green science and technology innovation as the strut. 循环经济的发展需要绿色科技创新生态化作为支撑。', '副词: struttingly 名词: strutter 过去式: strutted 过去分词: strutted 现在分词: strutting 第三人称单数: struts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('volley', '[\'vɑːli]', 'n.齐发；齐射 v.齐射；迸发；[体]截击', '1. He let out a volley of oaths. 他像发连珠炮似地破口大骂。 2. He was hit by a volley of snowballs. 他被一阵投来的雪球击中了。 3. Police fired a volley over the heads of the crowd. 警察朝人群上方射出一排子弹。 4. I tried to volley it back to you. 我尽力截击球来反击你。', '名词: volleyer 名词复数: volleys 过去式: volleyed 过去分词: volleyed 现在分词: volleying 第三人称单数: volleys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('byproduct', '[\'baɪˌprɒdəkt]', 'n.副产品', '1. Sugar and its byproduct are the basis of the island\'s economy. 糖及其副产品是这个岛国经济的基础。 2. Silver is often obtained as a byproduct during the separation of lead from rock. 从矿石中提取铅时，常可获得银这种副产品。', '异体字: by-product');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incongruent', '[ɪn\'kɒŋgrʊənt]', 'adj.不协调的；不和谐的', '1. Falls are incongruent in the normal course of life in that they are unexpected. 摔倒事件在通常的生活中是不够协调的，它们显得出乎人们的意料。 2. The most positive affect should result when the name is mildly incongruent. 最积极的反应应当出现在该名称有适度的不一致性时。” 3. An equilateral triangle cannot be dissected into finitely many incongruent equilateral triangles. 等边三角形不能分成有限多个不全等的等边三角形。 4. Suffering will come from your not attending to the next step .Discomfort comes from being incongruent with your Self . 你不走你的下一步才会付出代价，你任何的不安都是因为你不顺从你自性的要求所致。', '副词: incongruently 名词: incongruence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infant', '[\'ɪnfənt]', 'n.婴儿；幼儿 adj.婴儿的；初期的；幼稚的', '1. She gazed at the newborn infant and smiled. 她望着这个初生的婴儿笑了。 2. My sister\'s infant is very lovely. 我姐姐的小婴儿非常可爱。 3. A 35-day-old male infant was scheduled for bilateral inguinal herniorrhaphy. 摘要一个三十五天大的幼儿接受二沟腹股沟疝气门诊手术。 4. Infant family education is an important education environment which can\'t be irreplaceable by preschool education and social education. 幼儿家庭教育是幼儿园教育和社会教育所不能替代的重要教育环境。 5. Infant mortality is still very high in some developing countries. 某些发展中国家的婴儿死亡率仍然很高。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('psalm', '[sɑːm]', 'n.圣诗；圣歌；诗篇 v.唱圣歌赞美或庆祝', '1. You can find this psalm in the Bible. 你可以在圣经上找到这篇赞美诗。 2. This psalm talks about how God should be praised. 这篇诗篇说到该怎样来赞美神。', '过去式: psalmed 过去分词: psalmed 现在分词: psalming 第三人称单数: psalms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arthritis', '[ɑːr\'θraɪtɪs]', 'n.关节炎', '1. Gout is a form of arthritis. 痛风是关节炎的一种。 2. He suffers from arthritis in his leg joints. 他的腿有关节炎。 3. Her arthritis troubles her greatly. 关节炎把她折腾得够呛。', '形容词: arthritic 副词: arthritically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gingerly', '[\'dʒɪndʒərli]', 'adv.极度小心谨慎地', '1. I reached out gingerly to touch the snake. 我小心翼翼地伸手去摸那条蛇。 2. Gingerly he opened the door of the rat\'s cage. 他小心翼翼地打开鼠笼的门。 3. He walked gingerly over the rotten floorboard. 他小心翼翼地走过那腐烂的地板。 4. We had to explore this possibility very gingerly. 我们必须极其小心地探索这个可能性。', '名词: gingerliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prehensile', '[prɪ\'hensl]', 'adj.(动物的尾足等)适于抓握的；有理解力的；贪婪的', '1. Poets are those strangely prehensile men. 诗人是那些具有深刻洞察力的人们。 2. This type of monkey has a prehensile tail. 这种猴子有可以盘住树枝的尾巴。 3. They have prehensile lips for feeding on leaves and saplings. 它们都具有能卷握东西的嘴唇,可用于取食树叶和树苗。 4. Buy a bridle, north city NaShi prehensile bullwhip buy. 南市买辔头，北市买长鞭。', '名词: prehensility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vacuous', '[\'vækjuəs]', 'adj.空的；发呆的；心灵空虚的', '1. The lyrics are completely vacuous. 歌词毫无内涵。 2. We would be satisfied with any draft document, however vacuous . 我们对任何草案都会感到满意，即使草案的内容非常空洞也无所谓。 3. His eyes looked dull, almost vacuous. 他看上去目光呆滞，茫然若失。 4. Both are equally remote and vacuous. 二者都同样是遥远和空虚的。', '副词: vacuously 名词: vacuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exigent', '[\'eksədʒənt]', 'adj.紧急的；迫切的；急需的', '1. Building resource-conserving society was an exigent mission. 摘要建设资源节约型社会是当前中国极为迫切的任务。 2. To explain the current tense physician-patient relationship is an exigent social problem. 解读目前紧张的医患关系是一个迫切的社会课题。', '副词: exigently');
