INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('serpentine', '[\'sɜːrpəntiːn]', 'adj.蛇形的；弯曲的；阴险的 n.蛇纹石；古时候大炮的一种；S字曲线 v.像蛇般行进；缓慢地流', '1. It cavernous, serpentine form resembles a dragon, a symbol of China . 它曲折蜿蜒的结构与中国的另一个标志——龙——相似。 2. In hydroseeding, my main responsibility is to guide 200 feet of heavy, serpentine hose while the boss sprays the slime. 在播种的时候，我的主要工作是在老板向地上喷洒种子和黏胶混合物的时候，拖着200英尺长的沉重的蛇形管。 3. From each island proceeded a serpentine trail. 每一个绿岛旁边，都伸出一道蜿蜒曲折的踪迹。 4. Serpentine often contains some asbestos , and should be used with caution . 因为蛇纹石往往包含了一些石棉，收集时应谨慎。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expenditure', '[ɪk\'spendɪtʃər]', 'n.开支；消耗', '1. We must try our best to control our expenditure. 我们必须尽力控制开销。 2. The government intends to cut expenditure on arms. 政府打算削减军备开支。 3. Such a great task requires the expenditure of much money and time. 这么庞大的任务需要消耗许多的金钱和时间。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prowl', '[praʊl]', 'v.潜行以觅食；窥伺；逡巡于 n.潜行；徘徊；悄悄踱步', '1. Many wild animals prowl at night. 许多野生动物在夜间觅食。 2. He saw a hungry wolf on the prowl with his telescope. 他通过望远镜看到了一头四处觅食的饿狼。 3. I saw someone prowling around among the trees. 我见有人在树林里鬼鬼祟祟地走动。 4. Robbers always prowl in this area, so you\'d better not walk alone. 这里经常有寇盗出没，你们最好不要单独行动。 5. They\'ve even been known to stalk birds like a lion on the prowl. 它们也可以像潜行的狮子一样跟踪鸟类。', '名词: prowler 过去式: prowled 过去分词: prowled 现在分词: prowling 第三人称单数: prowls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('liquidate', '[\'lɪkwɪdeɪt]', 'v.清算；清偿；消除', '1. I had to liquidate my holdings to pay off my ex-husband. 我必须清算我所有的财产，以便还清对前夫的欠款。 2. They have decided to liquidate the corporation by the end of the next month. 他们已经决定在下月底之前对公司进行清算。 3. The court decided to help the company liquidate its chain debts. 法院决定帮助企业清偿三角债。 4. We were forced to liquidate some of our assets to pay the debts. 我们被迫变卖一些资产以偿还债务。', '名词: liquidation 过去式: liquidated 过去分词: liquidated 现在分词: liquidating 第三人称单数: liquidates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stipulate', '[\'stɪpjuleɪt]', 'v.规定；保证 adj.有明文规定的', '1. The Constitution stipulate that women shall have equal rights with men in voting and being elected. 宪法规定妇女和男子一样，有同等的选举权和被选举权。 2. We stipulate that our salesgirl must be polite to customers . 我们规定售货小姐们必须礼貌待客。 3. Can you stipulate they would carry out the treaty? 你能保证他们会执行该条约吗? 4. The company fails to pay on the date stipulate in the contract. 该公司没有按合同中规定的日期付款。', '名词: stipulator 过去式: stipulated 过去分词: stipulated 现在分词: stipulating 第三人称单数: stipulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mountainous', '[\'maʊntənəs]', 'adj.多山的；如山一般的', '1. He lives in a mountainous district. 他住在山区。 2. Our country is very mountainous. 我国是一个多山的国家。 3. The mountainous waves swallowed up the ship. 山一般的巨浪吞没了那艘航船。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nutrition', '[nu\'trɪʃn]', 'n.营养', '1. Variety is not a guarantee of good nutrition. 品种多并不能确保营养好。 2. This food provides all the nutrition your dog needs. 本食品含有狗所必须的一切营养。 3. A balanced diet provides nutrition for your body. 均衡的食物使你的身体获得营养。', '形容词: nutritional 副词: nutritionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impeach', '[ɪm\'piːtʃ]', 'v.归咎；怀疑；控告；弹劾', '1. Many people impeached the judge for taking bribes. 很多人控告法官受贿。 2. The Parliament decided to impeach the President. 国会决定弹劾总统。', '名词: impeacher 过去式: impeached 过去分词: impeached 现在分词: impeaching 第三人称单数: impeaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unbridled', '[ʌn\'braɪdld]', 'adj.无拘束的；激烈的；放纵的 unbridle的过去分词.', '1. But now he and Han Dan cried with unbridled joy. 但这一次，他和韩丹无拘无束快乐地叫了起来。 2. Mr. Wilson made unbridled attacks against this policy. 威尔逊先生对这个政策进行了肆无忌惮的攻击。 3. Does his unbridled behaviour surprise you? 是不是他的放肆行为令你感到不快?', '副词: unbridledly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('noose', '[nuːs]', 'n.套索；陷阱 v.用套索捕捉；使落入圈套', '1. They tied a noose round her neck. 他们在她脖子上系了一个活扣。 2. His debts were a noose around his neck. 债务就像套索一样套在他的脖子上。 3. This time you have really put your head in the noose. 这次你真是自投罗网了。 4. But I don\'t see why I should put my head in a noose to conceal his affair. 但我不明白我为什么要自讨苦吃，去帮他隐瞒他的风流韵事。 5. He cut the rope then and went astern to noose the tail. 然后他割下一截绳子，走到船梢去套住鱼尾巴。', '过去式: noosed 过去分词: noosed 现在分词: noosing 第三人称单数: nooses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prolong', '[prə\'lɔːŋ]', 'vt.延长；拖延', '1. How can we endeavor to prolong the brevity of human life? 我们怎样才能延长短促的人生？ 2. The meeting may be prolonged into the evening because so many problems have to be solved tonight. 会议可能要延长到夜里，因为今晚有太多问题要解决。 3. Low leakage current helps to prolong battery life. 低漏电流有助于延长电池使用寿命。 4. Clear evidence of his intent is to prolong the ritual. 显然他意在拖延典礼时间。', '名词: prolonger 过去式: prolonged 过去分词: prolonged 现在分词: prolonging 第三人称单数: prolongs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('landmark', '[\'lændmɑːrk]', 'n.陆标；地界标；里程碑；划时代的事', '1. The tower was once a landmark for ships. 这座塔曾是船只的陆标。 2. Every snapshot consists of smiling expression what converts the minutes of joy into a landmark of glitter. 一张张充满笑脸的快照，将无限欢愉的每一刻变为闪闪动人的陆标。 3. A three-month anniversary is a landmark feat at her age. 在他的岁数三个月就是一个地界标。 4. It\'s a landmark in the history of architecture. 它是建筑史上的一个里程碑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deliberate', '[dɪ\'lɪbərət]', 'adj.深思熟虑的；故意的；从容不迫的 v.仔细考虑；研讨', '1. She has a slow, deliberate way of talking. 她谈话的方式缓慢而审慎. 2. He told us a deliberate lie. 他存心说谎。 3. It had more the appearance of a deliberate crime than an accident. 那很像是蓄意的罪行，而不像是意外的事故。 4. He entered the room with deliberate steps. 他从容不迫地走进室内。 5. We had no time to deliberate on the problem. 我们没有时间仔细思考这个问题.', '副词: deliberately 名词: deliberateness 过去式: deliberated 过去分词: deliberated 现在分词: deliberating 第三人称单数: deliberates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('duel', '[\'duːəl]', 'n.决斗；斗争 v.决斗；斗争', '1. Mr William challenged the young man to a duel. 威廉先生向这位年轻人提出要求与他决斗。 2. This card cannot be used in a Duel. 此卡不能在决斗中使用。 3. Mr William challenged the young man to a duel. 威廉先生向这位年轻人提出要求与他决斗。 4. This card cannot be used in a Duel. 此卡不能在决斗中使用。', '名词: dueler 过去式: dueled/duelled 过去分词: dueled/duelled 现在分词: dueling/duelling 第三人称单数: duels/duels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hazy', '[\'heɪzi]', 'adj.朦胧的；模糊的', '1. The mountains were hazy in the distance. 远处的群山笼罩在雾霭之中。 2. Since it was hazy, we couldn\'t see the mountains. 因为是雾蒙蒙的，所以我们看不见山脉。 3. I have a hazy memory of those early years. 对那些早先的岁月我有著朦胧的记忆。 4. I have only a hazy idea about Chinese grammar. 我对汉语语法只有一点模糊的概念。', '副词: hazily 比较级: hazier 最高级: haziest 名词: haziness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pillar', '[\'pɪlər]', 'n.柱子；支柱；核心(人物) vt.用柱支持', '1. The robber tied him to a pillar. 强盗把他捆在柱子上。 2. A creeper was entwined round the pillar. 一根攀缘植物缠绕在柱子上。 3. The enemy was hurried from pillar to post. 敌人被赶得东逃西窜走投无路。 4. The textile industry is a traditional pillar industry in China. 纺织工业是中国传统的支柱产业。', '过去式: pillared 过去分词: pillared 现在分词: pillaring 第三人称单数: pillars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('copious', '[\'koʊpiəs]', 'adj.丰富的；大量的；(指作家)多产的', '1. Every star is a copious source of neutrinos. 每颗恒星都是丰富的中微子源。 2. He is possessed of a copious vocabulary. 他的词汇量很大。 3. She supports her theory with copious evidence. 她以大量的例证来充实自己的理论。 4. She took copious notes of the professor\'s lecture. 上教授的课她记了大量的笔记。', '副词: copiously 名词: copiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sensitization', '[ˌsensətaɪ\'zəɪʃn]', 'n.致敏；致敏作用；敏感化', '1. Hence, islet transplant recipients are at risk of sensitization after transplantation. 因此，胰岛的受者移植后有致敏的高危因素存在。 2. The sensitization of adiponectin to insulin is implemented by increasing fatty acid oxidation in skeletal muscle and restraining er gluconeogenesis in liver. 脂联素的胰岛素增敏作用是通过增加骨骼肌脂肪酸氧化以及抑制肝糖异生实现的。 3. An MTrP is a hyperirritable spot in a taut band of skeletal muscle fibers with characteristics related to central sensitization in the spinal cord. 肌筋膜激痛点是骨骼肌肉纤维里紧绷肌带上的过度激活点，伴随着与脊髓里中枢性敏感化有相关联的特征。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snub', '[snʌb]', 'v.冷落；斥责；止住；掐灭（香烟等） n.怠慢；冷落 adj.(鼻子等)短平而上翘的', '1. She snubbed them by not replying to their invitation. 她没答复他们的邀请,以示冷落。 2. She was repeatedly snubbed by her neighbours. 她多次遭到邻居的冷遇。 3. He snubbed his son into silence. 他把儿子骂得一声不吭。 4. He snubbed out the butt with the foot. 他用脚踩灭了烟头。 5. The snub was clearly intentional. 那种怠慢明显是故意的。 6. She had an interesting face with a snub nose and large appealing eyes. 她的脸很有意思，长着一个翘鼻子和一双楚楚动人的大眼睛。', '名词: snubber 过去式: snubbed 过去分词: snubbed 现在分词: snubbing 第三人称单数: snubs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reconcile', '[\'rekənsaɪl]', 'v.调和；和解；妥协；一致', '1. I can\'t reconcile the two extreme views. 我无法调和这两种极端的观点。 2. We tried to reconcile her with her family. 我们试图让她和她的家庭和好。 3. We were finally reconciled when he apologized. 他道歉以后我们终于言归于好了. 4. He had to reconcile himself to his fate. 他必须接受自己的命运。', '形容词: reconciliatory 名词: reconcilement 过去式: reconciled 过去分词: reconciled 现在分词: reconciling 第三人称单数: reconciles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parameter', '[pə\'ræmɪtər]', 'n.参量；参数；决定因素；界限', '1. One parameter which always comes into play is the national economy. 国民经济是一个经常起作用的参量。 2. Spend by each department have to fall within certain parameter. 每个部门的开支必须属于确定的系数之内。 3. You can pass report parameters to a DMX query parameter. 您可以将报表参数传递到DMX查询参数。 4. A notable question is whether there is parameter in it. 一个值得注意的问题是是否有限定因素.', '形容词: parametric 副词: parametrically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decorum', '[dɪ\'kɔːrəm]', 'n.礼貌合宜', '1. Can you cancel a date with decorum? 你能够有礼貌地取消约会吗? 2. I hope you will behave with decorum at the funeral. 我们希望你在葬礼上做到得体有礼。 3. Each had enough decorum to suspend further hostilities. 双方都还有足够的礼貌，总算暂时停止了进一步的敌对行为。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unwitting', '[ʌn\'wɪtɪŋ]', 'adj.不知情的；无意的', '1. The prime minister was an unwitting tool of the president. 首相不知不觉被总统利用了。 2. Please forgive his unwitting insult. 请原谅他无意的伤害。 3. She is their unwitting accomplice. 她无意中成了他们的帮凶', '副词: unwittingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('handle', '[\'hændl]', 'v.处理；对待；操作；触；买卖 n.把手；柄', '1. I was impressed by her handling of the affair. 我觉得她对此事的处理很了不起。 2. The speaker was roughly handled by the mob. 演说者受到暴民的粗暴对待。 3. He\'s not a very good teacher---he doesn\'t know how to handle children. 他不是一个好的老师---他不懂得如何对待孩子。 4. He knows how to handle the machine. 他会操作这台机器。 5. I turned the handle and opened the door. 我转了转拉手,把门打开。', '形容词: handleless 过去式: handled 过去分词: handled 现在分词: handling 第三人称单数: handles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stalwart', '[\'stɔːlwərt]', 'adj.坚定的；健壮的 n.坚定分子', '1. They suffered from stalwart resistance. 他们遭受到顽强的抵抗。 2. Republicans are viewed as more stalwart defenders of free trade. 共和党一般被认为是更加坚定的自由市场主义的守护者。 3. The prince is tall and stalwart. 这个王子高大魁伟。 4. Stalwart policemen stood guard outside. 强壮的警察在外面警戒。 5. Let me introduce Bob, one of the club\'s stalwarts. 让我来介绍鲍伯', '副词: stalwartly 名词: stalwartness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ram', '[ræm]', 'n.公羊；撞锤；撞击装置；有撞角的军舰；（水压机的）活塞 v.撞击；填塞；强迫通过或接受 abbr.随机存取存储器(=random access memory) Ram. n.白羊座', '1. Then Abraham looked up, and he saw a ram. 亚伯拉罕昂起头，看见一只公羊。 2. The catalyst is subjected to a uniform ram pressure. 催化剂承受均匀活塞压力。 3. The ship rammed the other ship. 两船相撞。 4. He rammed the tobacco into his pipe. 他把烟丝塞进烟斗。', '名词: rammer 过去式: rammed 过去分词: rammed 现在分词: ramming 第三人称单数: rams');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saucy', '[\'sɔːsi]', 'adj.无礼的；莽撞的；活泼的', '1. She\'s a saucy little miss! 她是个黄毛丫头！ 2. Don\'t be saucy with me! 别对我太鲁莽！ 3. His daughter is a saucy tomboy. 他女儿是一个调皮的假小子。', '副词: saucily 比较级: saucier 最高级: sauciest 名词: sauciness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pleonastic', '[ˌpliːə\'næstɪk]', 'adj.啰嗦的；冗言的', '1. Without the noisy music and pleonastic governmental documents, such life is as happy as that in Zhu Geliang’s Mao Cottage in Nan Yang and in Yang Ziyun’s Xuan Pavilion in West Sichuan Province. 没有嘈杂的音乐扰乱两耳，没有官府公文劳累身心。它好比南阳诸葛亮的茅庐，西蜀扬子云的玄亭。 2. An instance of pleonasm. 冗笔的例子 3. in this sense it is not a pleonasm to say, as many have, that the morally virtuous life is the good or best life. 在这个意义上它不是一种重复，正如许多人认为的道德上有德行的生活是好的或最好的生活。 4. pleonastic expressions 重复的表达形式', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disentangle', '[ˌdɪsɪn\'tæŋɡl]', 'v.解开；松开；摆脱；解决（纠纷等）', '1. This skein of wool won\'t disentangle. 这束毛线解不开。 2. Shake your rope and let it disentangle gradually. 你把绳子抖动抖动，让它慢慢松开。 3. I finally managed to disentangle myself from perplexity. 我终于摆脱了困境。 4. It is sometimes difficult to disentangle truth from falsehood. 从虚假中解开事实有时是困难的。', '名词: disentanglement 过去式: disentangled 过去分词: disentangled 现在分词: disentangling 第三人称单数: disentangles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plaudit', '[\'plɔːdɪt]', 'n.赞美；喝彩', '1. A new play that opened to the plaudits of the critics. 受到评论家们喝彩的一出新戏剧 2. She won plaudits for the way she presented her case. 她妙语陈情博得众口交赞。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hold', '[hoʊld]', 'v.拿着；控制；容纳；握住；持有；保持；掌握；认为；举行 n.握住；控制；把握；立足点；延误；影响', '1. I want you to stand beside me and hold the torch. 我要你拿着手电筒站在我旁边。 2. He has been trying hard to hold his temper. 他一直尽力控制自己不发脾气。 3. The new football stadium can hold eighty thousand people. 新的足球场可以容纳八万人。 4. I\'ll always be the one to firmly hold your hands. 我永远都会坚定地握住你的手。 5. His hold on her arm tightened. 他把她的胳膊抓得更紧了。', '过去式: held 过去分词: held 现在分词: holding 第三人称单数: holds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('augmentation', '[ˌɔːɡmen\'teɪʃn]', 'n.增加；增大', '1. Method does not perform infoset augmentation. 方法不执行信息集补充。 2. The approach is called the wide-area augmentation system, or WAAS. 这种方法称为广域扩增系统,简写为WAAS。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('matriarchy', '[\'meɪtriɑːrki]', 'n.母权制；母系氏族制；女家长制；女族长制', '1. The interpretation of matriarchy and patriarchy is pertinent to our interpretation of history and to the prospect of human future. 对母系制与父权制的解释，关系到我们对整个历史的解释以及对人类未来的期望。 2. That is due to the matriarchy of its society. 那是因为他们仍然是母系社会。', '名词复数: matriarchies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('colossus', '[kə\'lɑːsəs]', 'n.庞然大物；巨人；巨型雕像', '1. The colossus would soar higher into the sky. 这庞然大物高耸入云。 2. Mozart is a colossus among composers. 莫札特是作曲家中的巨匠。 3. A copper colossus of their leader stood in the middle of the square. 他们领袖的铜巨像耸立在广场中央。', '名词复数: colossi');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subterranean', '[ˌsʌbtə\'reɪniən]', 'adj.地下的；隐蔽的', '1. The subterranean passage led to a cave. 地下的通道通向一个山洞。 2. A subterranean stream is flowing through this area. 有一条地下河流经这个区域。 3. It is impossible to pack so many refugees into the subterranean dwelling. 这地下住所挤不下那么多的难民。 4. All night he heard the subterranean workman, who continued to mine his way. 他整夜都听着那个隐蔽的工作者，那个人在继续他的挖掘工程。', '副词: subterraneanly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corrode', '[kə\'roʊd]', 'v.腐蚀；侵蚀；损害', '1. Iron corrodes easily. 铁易锈损。 2. This acid may corrode iron. 这种酸能腐蚀铁。 3. Certain chemicals will corrode if left on bare metal. 有些化学药品如留在裸露的金属上会起腐蚀作用。 4. The furniture should be of smooth, hard material not liable to warp or corrode. 家具应使用光滑、坚硬、不易变形和腐蚀的材料制作。', '形容词: corrodible 过去式: corroded 过去分词: corroded 现在分词: corroding 第三人称单数: corrodes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sacrilegious', '[ˌsækrə\'lɪdʒəs]', 'adj.亵渎神圣的', '1. It is sacrilegious to wear shoes inside a mosque. 在回教教堂内穿鞋子是亵渎神圣的. 2. This sacrilegious incident led to a Senate investigation. 这次的渎圣事件导致了元老院的调查。', '副词: sacrilegiously 名词: sacrilegiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intrude', '[ɪn\'truːd]', 'v.闯入；侵入；打扰；干涉', '1. The angry visitor tried to intrude himself into the council meeting. 愤怒的来访者试图闯入会场。 2. He had no wish to intrude on their privacy. 他原本就不想触犯他们私人活动的自由。 3. A translator shouldn\'t intrude his own opinions into what he\'s translating. 译者不应该擅自把自己的意思加进译文中。 4. I don\'t want to intrude on you if you are very busy. 如果你很忙的话，我就不打扰了。', '名词: intruder 过去式: intruded 过去分词: intruded 现在分词: intruding 第三人称单数: intrudes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plump', '[plʌmp]', 'adj.丰满的 v.下降；支持；变丰满 n.突然重重落下（的声音） adv.骤降；直接地', '1. The baby is plump and very cute. 那个婴儿白白胖胖的，十分可爱。 2. She is too plump to fit into this dress. 她太富态了，穿不下这件衣服。 3. Special injections can make lips look attractively young and plump. 注射特殊药物可使嘴唇年轻饱满，更加迷人。 4. The ducklings plumped into the water. 小鸭们突然跳进水中。 5. He told me plump that he would not give in. 他直截了当告诉我,他决不让步。', '形容词: plumpish 副词: plumply 比较级: plumper 最高级: plumpest 名词: plumpness 过去式: plumped 过去分词: plumped 现在分词: plumping 第三人称单数: plumps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distinction', '[dɪ\'stɪŋkʃn]', 'n.荣誉；差别；优秀；对比；区分', '1. These are the highest distinctions that have ever been given by our government. 这些是我国政府迄今授予的最高荣誉称号。 2. Keller received many awards of great distinction. 凯勒被授予很多殊荣奖。 3. He had the distinction of being the first man to walk on the moon. 他以月球上第一个行走而闻名于世。 4. There is a fine distinction between the two words. 这两个字之间有细微区别。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('landlocked', '[\'lændlɑːkt]', 'adj.陆地包围的；内陆水域的', '1. Austria is a landlocked country of central Europe. 奥地利是欧洲中部的内陆国。 2. Switzerland is a landlocked country, with no port for sea trade. 瑞士是内陆的国家，没有海上贸易港口。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bigot', '[\'bɪɡət]', 'n.(宗教、政治等的)盲信者；顽固者', '1. His words stamped him to be a bigot. 他讲的话表明他是个偏执的人。 2. Pretty soon everyone in his dorm labels him as an intolerant bigot. 很快他就被宿舍其他人打上“偏执的盲目信仰者”的标签。 3. When you try to impose them on others, you make yourself into a self-righteous bigot. 当你试图把这些向他人推行时，你让你自身变成了一个伪善的老顽固。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desultory', '[\'desəltɔːri]', 'adj.散漫的；断断续续的；不连贯的；杂乱的', '1. His conduct during these first weeks had been desultory beyond description. 在这两三个礼拜之内，他的行动可以说是散漫得没法形容。 2. He broke into a desultory chat with me over his business affairs. 他突然开始和我漫无边际地谈起他的生意来了。 3. Our planning proceeded in a desultory fashion. 我们的计划工作是以一种杂乱无章的方式进行的。', '副词: desultorily 名词: desultoriness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apocryphal', '[ə\'pɑːkrɪfl]', 'adj.伪的；不足凭信的', '1. The apocryphal story of Columbus and the egg is very interesting. 哥伦布竖蛋这个真伪不明的故事十分有趣。 2. These are apocryphal advertisements in order to racket from customers. 那些都是欺骗顾客花钱的虚假广告。 3. Most of the story about his private life was probably apocryphal. 有关他私生活的事可能大部分都是虚构的。 4. Apocryphal tales gallop across the country with lightning speed. 不真实的谣言以闪电般的速度在这个国家飞速传播。', '副词: apocryphally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insentient', '[ɪn\'senʃənt]', 'adj.无知觉的；无生命的', '1. Having no physical feeling or sensation; insentient. 失去知觉的没有肉体感觉或知觉的；无知觉的 2. Regarding insentient beings, are they able to recover their spirits? 至于无情的众生，能不能恢复灵性呢？ 3. As such , it is the life force that is present in all beings , whether sentient or insentient. 只有这样，无论有无感觉或知觉，她都在世界的每一角落发挥着巨大的作用。 4. How could the aggregation of millions of individually insentient neurons generate subjective awareness? 数百万的、个体的、无知觉的神经元集合在一起时如何产生出主体意识呢？', '名词: insentience');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('niche', '[niːʃ]', 'n.壁龛；适当的位置；（特定产品或服务的）用户群；[生]生态龛；生态位；小生态环境 vt.放在适当的位置', '1. This is a stupa niche from the Sui Dynasty. 你看这是隋代的塔龛。 2. He found the right niche for himself. 他发现了一个适合他的职位。 3. He eventually found his niche in sports journalism. 最后他在体育新闻界找到了理想的工作。 4. Your market niche is big women. 你们的服装目标是体胖的女士。', '过去式: niched 过去分词: niched 现在分词: niching 第三人称单数: niches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hale', '[heɪl]', 'adj.(尤指老人)健壮的；矍铄的 v.强拉硬拖', '1. Although he is over eighty, he looks hale and healthy. 尽管他已经八十多岁了，看上去还很健壮。 2. Because he was tall and hale, he was chosen to join the School Guard Team. 他因身体高大健壮，被学校选入了护校队。 3. Grandfather will be 80 years old, but he is hale and hearty. 祖父就要80高龄了，但仍精神矍铄。 4. Having white hair and ruddy complexion, my grandfather is hale and hearty. 我爷爷是位鹤发童颜的矍铄老人。 5. It took me half an hour to hale the heavy box down the stairs. 我费了半个小时的工夫才把那只重箱子拖到楼下。', '比较级: haler 最高级: halest 名词: haleness 过去式: haled 过去分词: haled 现在分词: haling 第三人称单数: hales');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loquacious', '[lə\'kweɪʃəs]', 'adj.多话的；唠叨的', '1. Kennedy had become almost as loquacious as Joe. 肯尼迪变得和乔一样唠叨了。 2. His loquacious good-humour infected every one. 司炉们烧起火来象英雄一样不顾疲劳。 3. Please be quiet; you are too loquacious. 请安静点，你话太多了。 4. I just mean he\'s not particularly loquacious. 别误会，我是说他不太喜欢说话。', '副词: loquaciously 名词: loquaciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retentive', '[rɪ\'tentɪv]', 'adj.记性好的；有保持力的', '1. She has an amazingly retentive memory. 她有着一个惊人的好记性。', '副词: retentively 名词: retentiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('observance', '[əb\'zɜːrvəns]', 'n.遵守；仪式；纪念', '1. The worker was praised for his observance of the rules. 这个工人因为严格遵守规则而受到了表扬。 2. The company holds its people to strict observance of that code. 公司要求所属人员严格遵守那项规章制度。 3. The speaker advocated a less austere observance of the Sabbath. 演讲者倡导放宽安息日的严格规定。 4. For this reason they are tolerated in the observance of their rites. 所以犹太人是被容许举行他们的宗教仪式的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('goblet', '[\'ɡɑːblət]', 'n.高脚杯；酒杯', '1. He poured some wine into the goblet. 他向高脚酒杯里倒了一些葡萄酒。 2. He swirled the brandy around in the huge goblet. 他摇晃着高脚大玻璃杯使里面的白兰地酒旋动起来。 3. Delicate goblet, often become beautiful to match with good beautiful wine. 精致的酒杯，常与上等的美酒成为佳配。 4. Suddenly, his friend saw the reflection of a snake swimming in the goblet. 忽然，朋友看见酒杯里有条蛇影在游动。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disport', '[dɪ\'spɔːrt]', 'v.玩；耍；使快乐 n.玩；耍', '1. Disport oneself to one\'s heart\'s content. 玩个痛快什么也不会使他满足。 2. Disport oneself to one\'s heart\'s content. 玩个痛快什么也不会使他满足。', '过去式: disported 过去分词: disported 现在分词: disporting 第三人称单数: disports');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('matador', '[\'mætədɔːr]', 'n.斗牛士', '1. The matador profiled, his thin silver blade raised. 斗牛士左肩对着牛，举起他的锋利的银色尖刀。 2. The matador and the bull performed wonderfully in the ring. 斗牛士和公牛在斗牛场中进行着精彩的表演。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fulsome', '[\'fʊlsəm]', 'adj.虚伪的；令人生厌的', '1. He was too fulsome in his praise. 他的赞美太虚假。 2. I was disgusted by his fulsome flattery. 我讨厌他那过分的谄媚。', '副词: fulsomely 名词: fulsomeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tenacious', '[tə\'neɪʃəs]', 'adj.抓紧的；坚决的；(记忆力)强的', '1. He hold on to my arm with a tenacious grip. 他紧紧抓住我的手臂不放。 2. The eagle seized its prey in a tenacious grip. 鹰将捕获物紧紧抓住。 3. She is tenacious in defence of her rights. 她坚决维护自己的权利. 4. He is tenacious of his opinions. 他固执己见。', '副词: tenaciously 名词: tenaciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('affirm', '[ə\'fɜːrm]', 'vt.证实；断言；肯定', '1. Scientists cannot affirm the existence of life on other planets. 科学家们还不能证实在其它星球上有生命存在。 2. I affirm that what he said is true. 我断言他所说的是实情。 3. They affirmed that the girl did quite a bit of reading. 他们断言这个女孩子读了不少书。 4. I can affirm that no one will lose their job. 我可以肯定，谁都不会丢掉工作。', '形容词: affirmable 副词: affirmably 名词: affirmer 过去式: affirmed 过去分词: affirmed 现在分词: affirming 第三人称单数: affirms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('droplet', '[\'drɑːplət]', 'n.小滴；微滴', '1. I am a droplet in the ocean of divinity. 我是神性的海洋中的一滴水。 2. The other process of droplet growth is by collision and coalescence. 云滴增长的另一个过程是各云滴间的碰撞和并合。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('farrow', '[\'færoʊ]', 'n.一窝小猪；产仔 v.(母猪)产仔 adj.(母牛）不孕的', '1. Our sow had 15 at one farrow. 我们的母猪一胎下了15个小猪。 2. When will the sow farrow? 这头母猪何时产小猪? 3. They planned to have the gilts farrow down about the end of this month. 他们计划让母猪约在本月底下仔。', '过去式: farrowed 过去分词: farrowed 现在分词: farrowing 第三人称单数: farrows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remnant', '[\'remnənt]', 'n.残余；残剩余；残存者；零头 adj.剩余的', '1. If something has been partly used or destroyed, we use remains or remnants. 若某物的一部分已用掉或毁掉，其剩余或残存部分可用。 2. I will sell this remnant to you, at cost. 我愿将此剩货照成本卖给你。 3. The remnants of last night\'s meal were still on the table. 昨天晚上的剩余物还在桌子上。 4. The Ainu settlers in Hokkaido are the last remnant of a prehistoric race. 北海道的阿伊努人是史前某个种族的最后残存者。 5. The beautiful curtain is made of remnant materials. 这个漂亮的窗帘是用零头布做的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jamboree', '[ˌdʒæmbə\'riː]', 'n.庆祝会；喧闹的集会；童子军大会', '1. She will take part in the movie industry\'s annual jamboree at Cannes. 她将会去戛纳参加电影业年度盛会。 2. But this week\'s jamboree suggests the true headquarters of African. 但是，本周的盛会已然表明了哪里才是非洲真正的总部。 3. The 19th World Scout Jamboree held in Picarquin, Chile. 第十九届世界童军大露营在智利举行。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forge', '[fɔːrdʒ]', 'vt.锻造；伪造；建立 vi.伪造；做铁匠 n.锻炉；铁匠铺；锻造车间', '1. These machine parts have been forged with the finest steel. 这些机器零件得用优质的钢锻造。 2. George was forced to forge a signature. 乔治被迫伪造签名。 3. They forged their manager\'s signature on the cheque. 他们在支票上伪造了经理的签名。 4. They tried to forge an alliance. 他们试图建立同盟。 5. Some people forge official documents. 有些人伪造公文。 6. He began to heat, like iron in the forge. 他象锻炉里的铁一样热起来。', '形容词: forgeable 名词: forgeability 过去式: forged 过去分词: forged 现在分词: forging 第三人称单数: forges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deprecate', '[\'deprəkeɪt]', 'v.声明不赞成；抨击；反对', '1. The peace-loving people deprecate war. 爱好和平的人民反对战争。', '副词: deprecatingly 名词: deprecation 过去式: deprecated 过去分词: deprecated 现在分词: deprecating 第三人称单数: deprecates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stream', '[striːm]', 'n.(小)河；水流；(人；车；气)流；组 v.流动；流出；飘动；将(学生)按能力分组', '1. On either bank of the stream stand rows of willow trees. 小河两岸柳树成行。 2. Sand and leaves trapped the water in the stream. 沙子和树叶堵住了小河的水流。 3. Visitors to the exhibition came in an endless stream. 参观展览会的人络绎不绝。 4. Cars stream along the highway. 汽车在公路上流水般地行驶。', '形容词: streamy 过去式: streamed 过去分词: streamed 现在分词: streaming 第三人称单数: streams');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scruffy', '[\'skrʌfi]', 'adj.邋遢的；肮脏的；破旧的', '1. You can\'t go to a job interview looking so scruffy! 你求职去面试不能这邋里邋遢的！ 2. His scruffy appearance does not reflect his character. 他邋遢的外表并不反映他的性格。 3. She was wearing a scruffy pair of jeans. 她穿着一条脏兮兮的牛仔裤。 4. It is not proper to wear a scruffy jeans in a dinner party. 穿着破旧的牛仔裤在宴会上显得不太得体。', '副词: scruffily 比较级: scruffier 最高级: scruffiest 名词: scruffiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confine', '[kən\'faɪn]', 'vt.限制；禁闭 n.范围；界限；约束；限制', '1. I wish the speaker would confine himself to the subject. 我希望演说者不要离题。 2. I am sick, I have to confine to bed. 我病了，我得卧床休息。 3. The thief was confined in a prison. 窃贼被关押在监狱里。 4. Is it cruel to confine a bird in a cage? 把鸟关在笼子里残忍不残忍? 5. This is outside the confines of human knowledge. 这超出了人类知识范畴。', '形容词: confinable 名词: confiner 过去式: confined 过去分词: confined 现在分词: confining 第三人称单数: confines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aberration', '[ˌæbə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.越轨；误差；偏差；失常', '1. These events were aberrations from the norm. 这些事件不合常规。 2. The resultant defect is known as chromatic aberration. 由此而产生的缺陷叫做色差。 3. She hit him in a moment of aberration. 她一时精神失常打了他。 4. Owing to a strange mental aberration he forgot his own name. 由于一种莫名的精神错乱,他把自己的名字忘了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('candor', '[\'kændə]', 'n.坦白；直率', '1. Their candor is a very pleasing feature. 他们的坦白是很愉快的特征。 2. He spared no one\'s feelings and expressed his views with great candor. 他在不伤害他人的感情下，把自己的意见表示得很坦白。 3. He has earned a reputation for candor and integrity. 他以直率和正直著称。 4. Mullen already is on record expressing his war worries with an unusual degree of candor. 穆林已经是有史以来以最不寻常的的直率来表达他对战争的担心。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anathema', '[ə\'næθəmə]', 'n.咒逐；革出教门；被咒逐的人(物)；令人极其讨厌的事', '1. They launched a fresh anathema against him. 他们又发起了把他赶出教门的运动。 2. Racial prejudice is (an) anathema to me. 我对种族偏见深恶痛绝。 3. Government-run health care is still anathema to many Americans. 很大一部分美国人仍旧对政府经营的卫生保健不存好感。', '名词复数: anathemas');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remains', '[rɪ\'meɪnz]', 'n.剩余物；遗迹；遗体', '1. After maintenance the main remains and remainders are left on the domain. 维修之后，主要遗骸和剩余物留在了领地上。 2. After the wheat crop has been gathered, many farmers burn the remains and plough the ash into the soil, so as to enrich it. 小麦收割完成后，农夫们把剩余物烧掉，然后用犁把灰埋入地里，使土地更肥沃。 3. Not a vestige of the abbey remains. 那修道院的遗迹已荡然无存。 4. They have found prehistoric remains. 他们发现了史前遗迹。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pompous', '[\'pɑːmpəs]', 'adj.傲慢的；自大的；浮华的', '1. He\'s a real gentleman, if a little pompous at times. 他可是个正人君子，虽然有时略显得傲慢了些。 2. He is a pompous official. 他是个自命不凡的官员。 3. We should be modest, not be pompous. 我们应该谦虚，不应该自大。 4. Children dislike being spouted at by pompous teachers. 学生不喜欢听自命不凡的教师对他们夸夸其谈。', '副词: pompously 名词: pomposity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demagogue', '[\'deməɡɑːɡ]', 'n.煽动者；蛊惑民心的政客', '1. The demagogue has won people\'s support. 那个煽动者赢得了人们的支持。 2. It also exposed Mr Thaksin as a demagogue who is ready to incite a revolt from his Dubai redoubt. 也暴露出他信作为煽动者想从其流亡地，迪拜，就激起一场叛乱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('egotist', '[\'iːɡətɪst]', 'n.自大者；自我中心的人', '1. You need to be an egotist to succeed in politics. 要在政治上成功就必须自负。 2. I think you mean egotist， Tom said. 我想是你把我看成自我主义者了。 3. Richter：Because I\'m an egotist. 李希特：因为我很自我中心。 4. If your club tries to big itself up, you are a monstrous egotist. 如果你的俱乐部想要充大，那你也是一个恶魔般的自我中心论者。', '形容词: egotistic 副词: egotistically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trivial', '[\'trɪviəl]', 'adj.不重要的；琐碎的', '1. It\'s a trivial matter and not worth fighting about. 区区小事不值得争吵。 2. He could remember every trivial incident in great detail. 他能把每件小事的细节都记得很清楚。 3. I object to being jumped upon for trivial matter like this. 我讨厌因这种小事而受人责备。 4. Don\'t be angry over such trivial matters. 别为这些琐事生气。', '副词: trivially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ravenous', '[\'rævənəs]', 'adj.贪婪的；极饿的', '1. The country has also become a ravenous consumer. 这个国家还成为一个贪婪的消费者。 2. The ravenous lion tore the quarry. 饥饿的狮子撕碎了猎物。 3. The ravenous children ate everything on the table. 饿极了的孩子把桌上所有东西吃掉了。', '副词: ravenously 名词: ravenousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('officious', '[ə\'fɪʃəs]', 'adj.多管闲事的；<古>乐于助人的', '1. He is a harsh man, at once pompous and officious. 他是个严酷的人，既自负又爱管闲事。 2. I disliked Betty because she was officious. 我不喜欢贝蒂,因为她好管闲事。', '副词: officiously 名词: officiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defense', '[dɪ\'fens]', 'n.防卫；防卫物；辩护 vt.防守', '1. We must gear up industry to meet defense needs. 我们必须促进工业生产，以适应防卫的需要。 2. The magazine\'s disclosure of defense secrets caused great attention. 该杂志对防务内幕的透露引起了极大的关注。 3. The Senate has voted to support the President\'s defense plans. 参议院已经投票支持总统的防卫计划。 4. Good strong locks are the best defense against burglars. 坚固的锁是防盗贼的最好防御物。 5. The defense was overwhelmed by superior numbers. 防守被优势的兵力摧垮了。', '形容词: defenseless 副词: defenselessly 名词: defenselessness 过去式: defensed 过去分词: defensed 现在分词: defensing 第三人称单数: defenses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('populace', '[\'pɑːpjələs]', 'n.平民；大众', '1. He attends the education of the populace by himself. 第三，毛泽东亲身从事过平民教育。 2. There are powerful arguments for more economic growth in countries where a large proportion of the populace lives in poverty. 有很多强有力的理由证明一些大部分平民都生活在贫困中的国家的经济增长率更高。 3. A newspaper circulates among the general populace. 报纸广售于一般大众之间。 4. In this kind of situation the community sports project development into solves populace sports demand better means. 这种情况下社区体育项目的开发成为解决大众体育需求的一个较好的办法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bracket', '[\'brækɪt]', 'n.档次；括号；支架 vt.支撑；放在括号内；归入一类', '1. Their incomes are brought into a higher bracket. 他们的收入已进入一个较高的等级段。 2. Put your name in brackets at the top of each page. 把你的名字填写在每页上端的括号内。 3. The worker fixed a bracket on the wall. 工人在墙上固定了一个支架。 4. You\'d better bracket those shelves with two-by-fours. 你最好用截面为2英寸×4英寸的木材为那些架子做托架。', '过去式: bracketed 过去分词: bracketed 现在分词: bracketing 第三人称单数: brackets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flaw', '[flɔː]', 'n.瑕疵；缺陷；破绽；裂缝 v.使破裂；有瑕疵', '1. Unfortunately, I found that your work had a tiny flaw. 很不幸 2. The flaw in this vase makes it less valuable. 这个花瓶因为有点缺陷，不那么值钱了。 3. I can\'t find a flaw in his argument. 在他的论点中,我找不到任何破绽。 4. Your argument has a fatal flaw. 你的论点有一个致命的错误。 5. The jealous colleague decided to flaw the project plans. 这名嫉妒的同事决定给这些项目计划搞破坏。', '形容词: flawy 过去式: flawed 过去分词: flawed 现在分词: flawing 第三人称单数: flaws');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('biosphere', '[\'baɪoʊsfɪr]', 'n.生物圈', '1. The entire biosphere was becoming more transparent. 整个生物圈越来越透明。 2. The biosphere is being destroyed by economic growth! 经济增长正在破坏生物圈!', '形容词: biospheric');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disjunction', '[dɪs\'dʒʌŋkʃn]', 'n.析取；分离；分裂', '1. Operator performs logical disjunction on two expressions. 运算符对两个表达式执行逻辑析取。 2. This will no doubt lead in the coming decade to the creation of a real Euro pean army, and thereby a military disjunction from the US. 这无疑在未来十年会导向设置真正的欧洲军队，因而与美国在军事上分离。 3. Like society, it builds its unity on the disjunction. 每次统一都以剧烈的分裂为基础。 4. There is an interesting disjunction between the two halves of this argument. 这次争论的双方之间有一个有趣的分裂。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crotchety', '[\'krɑːtʃəti]', 'adj.思想奇怪的；脾气坏的', '1. His crotchety, even cruel behavior must be mischaracterized too. 他反复无常、甚至是残酷的行为一定也是由于复杂的性格原因。 2. It seems that he is in crotchety opposition to his father. 看起来，他对他爸爸火气很大，也很敌对。 3. It was one of thoes rare occasions when I ignored the crotchety old voice that spoiled my fun. 像这样无视那扼杀了我的乐趣的古怪声音，还真是屈指可数。 4. It\'s hardly surprising that this bold, or perhaps crotchety, proposal was instantly controversial. 不出所料，这个大胆，些许有些离奇的建议一经提出便立刻引起争议。', '名词: crotchetiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('celibate', '[\'selɪbət]', 'adj.独身的；禁欲的 n.独身者；无性生活的人', '1. Maybe I should just be celibate. 可能我应该保持单身算了。 2. I\'m celibate and I live a very serene lifestyle. 我是一个独身主义者，过着一种非常平静的生活。 3. I\'ve been celibate for the past six months. 我已禁欲六个月。 4. I will become a celibate, and join a monastery. 我要成为独身者，去加入一个修道院。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('facsimile', '[fæk\'sɪməli]', 'n.摹本；传真 v.摹写；传真', '1. A fax is a facsimile of the original,and looks exactly like it. 传真是原件的摹本,看上去与原件一模一样。 2. I can use a facsimile machine skillfully. 我能熟练地使用传真机。 3. In order to meet the requirements in these respects, facsimile transceivers have been devised. 为了满足这方面的需要，人们设计了无线电传真收发机。 4. As a technology, facsimile transmission is more than a century old. 作为一项技术，传真传送的历史已有一个多世纪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bondage', '[\'bɑːndɪdʒ]', 'n.奴役；束缚', '1. They seem to love bondage more than liberty. 他们似乎喜欢被奴役胜于自由。 2. In modern time, it is easy for one to fall under the bondage of gold. 在现代社会，一个人很容易为金钱所奴役。 3. We should break the bondage of ossified thinking. 我们要冲破保守僵化思想的束缚。 4. They aim to deliver the people who are in bondage to superstitious belief. 他们的目的在于解脱那些受迷信束缚的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immemorial', '[ˌɪmə\'mɔːriəl]', 'adj.远古的；极古的；久远的', '1. The story has come down from time immemorial. 这个故事从远古流传至今。 2. The museum has many immemorial cultural relics. 该博物馆收藏了很多极其古老的文物。 3. My family has lived in this village since time immemorial. 我家很早以前就一直住在这个村子里。', '副词: immemorially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fatuous', '[\'fætʃuəs]', 'adj.愚昧的；发呆的；愚笨的', '1. He seems take pride to make such fatuous remarks. 他好像对自己愚蠢的讲话还洋洋自得。 2. Television commercials seem more smug and fatuous than ever. 电视的广告似乎比以前更沾沾自喜和愚蠢。', '副词: fatuously 名词: fatuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hortative', '[\'hɔːtətɪv]', 'adj.激励的', '1. The hortative smile is useful for us. 鼓励的笑靥于你我大有裨益。 2. Citrus grandis Osbeck var.tomentosa Hort. 化州柚 3. Two days are too hort for this job. 要两天完成工作，太局促了。 4. Cirus grandis var. Shatinyu Hort. 沙田柚', '副词: hortatively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wont', '[wɔːnt]', 'adj.习惯的 n.习惯；习俗 v.习惯；使习惯于', '1. He was wont to give lengthy speeches. 他惯于做长篇大论的演说。 2. This is the chair where the author was wont to sit. 这是作家习惯坐的椅子。 3. It is my wont to rise at six. 六点起床是我的习惯。 4. She went for a walk after breakfast, as was her wont. 她早饭后要散散步已成了习惯。', '过去式: wont/wonted 过去分词: wont/wonted 现在分词: wonting 第三人称单数: wonts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accost', '[ə\'kɔːst]', 'v.搭话；搭讪', '1. She is too shy to dare accost him. 她太害羞了,不敢和他搭话。 2. She was accosted by a complete stranger. 有一个她完全不认识的人过来和她搭讪。', '过去式: accosted 过去分词: accosted 现在分词: accosting 第三人称单数: accosts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impuissance', '[ɪm\'pjuːɪsəns]', 'n.无力；虚弱', '1. impuissance n. 无能;无力;', '形容词: impuissant');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obtuse', '[əb\'tuːs]', 'adj.钝的；不尖的；钝角的；愚钝的', '1. \"Sometimes it looks more like an obtuse triangle,\" Winter said. “有时候它看起来更像一个钝角三角形。”温特说。 2. You were too obtuse to take the hint. 你太迟钝了，没有理解这种暗示。 3. The obtuse editor did not know he was being nibbled at. 这位脑筋迟钝的编辑并不知道人家是在向他试探消息。', '副词: obtusely 比较级: obtuser 最高级: obtusest 名词: obtuseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('paroxysm', '[\'pærəksɪzəm]', 'n.(疾病周期性)发作；(感情)爆发', '1. The smoking will raise the cancer paroxysm outbreak rate. 吸烟会提高癌症疾病的发病率。 2. He went into a paroxysm of rage for what happened. 他对发生的事勃然大怒。', '形容词: paroxysmal 副词: paroxysmally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lackluster', '[\'lækˌlʌstə]', 'adj.无光泽的；暗淡的；无生气的 n.无光泽；暗淡 无生气；平凡', '1. The audience was disappointed and rather angry when the famous musician performed in a lackluster manner after arriving late for the concert. 这位著名的音乐家演出迟到后平平淡淡地表演了一番，观众很失望，非常生气。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('virus', '[\'vaɪrəs]', 'n.病毒；病原体', '1. Scientists have isolated the virus causing the epidemic. 科学家们已分离出引起这种流行病的病毒。 2. We should be watchful of computer viruses. 我们应该警惕计算机病毒。 3. HBV is a virus that causes inflammation of the liver. HBV是一种会引起肝脏发炎的病毒。 4. Could you do me a favor? My computer suffered from computer virus. 能帮帮我吗?我电脑中病毒了。', '名词复数: viruses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pillory', '[\'pɪləri]', 'n.颈手枷；示众；嘲弄 v.套上枷锁；使遭人嘲笑', '1. The world mocks at it and sometimes puts one in the pillory for it. 世人对它大加嘲笑,有时甚至还给它带上颈手枷。 2. She was pilloried in the press for her extravagant parties. 她的聚会十分铺张，新闻界对她大加嘲弄。', '名词复数: pillories 过去式: pilloried 过去分词: pilloried 现在分词: pillorying 第三人称单数: pillories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prude', '[pruːd]', 'n.过份正经的女人', '1. Don\'t be such a prude. 别那么拘谨。 2. She always give clients an impression of humourless prude. 她一直都给客户一副不苟言笑、一本正经的印象。 3. She was such a prude that she was even embarrassed by the sight of naked children. 她正经得出了格，甚至见了赤身露体的孩子也难为情。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mingle', '[\'mɪŋɡl]', 'vt.使混合；使结合 vi.交往；联合；混在一起', '1. You can not mingle oil and water . 你不能把油和水混合在一起。 2. She accepted the money with mingled feelings. 她悲喜交集地收下了这笔钱。 3. The two rivers mingle their waters here. 这两条河在这里汇合起来了。 4. He is too shy to mingle with others. 他由于太内向而怯于与他人交往。', '名词: mingler 过去式: mingled 过去分词: mingled 现在分词: mingling 第三人称单数: mingles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ostrich', '[\'ɑːstrɪtʃ]', 'n.驼鸟；驼鸟般的人', '1. Ostrich is a type of large bird that can run very fast. 鸵鸟是一种跑得很快的大鸟。 2. The short-distance runner wishes he could run as fast as the ostrich. 这位短跑运动员真希望自己能跑得像驼鸟一样快。 3. Face the reality. Stop being an ostrich. 面对现实吧。不要再做逃避现实的人。 4. He\'s such an ostrich he doesn\'t want to know about his wife\'s love affairs. 他真是自己骗自己--对妻子有外遇不闻不问。', '名词复数: ostrich');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('escapism', '[ɪ\'skeɪpɪzəm]', 'n.逃避现实；逃避主义', '1. Drug-taking is a form of escapism for some people. 对有些人来说，吸毒是一种逃避现实的手段。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('innovation', '[ˌɪnə\'veɪʃn]', 'n.创新；革新', '1. There is no end to practice or innovation. 实践永无止境,创新永无止境。 2. In the age of global competition, design innovation is vital. 在全球激烈竞争的时代,设计创新至关重要。 3. It was a period of innovation. 这是革新时期。 4. A surge of innovation in techniques is on the horizon. 技术改进的浪潮即将出现。', '形容词: innovational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('levity', '[\'levəti]', 'n.轻浮；轻率；不稳定；多变', '1. I am sure foreigners must think our levity is baffling. 外国人肯定认为我们的轻浮举止不可理喻。 2. We need to ensure the freedom of divorce, as well as oppose levity divorce. 我们既要保障离婚自由，又要反对轻率离婚。', '名词复数: levities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revenge', '[rɪ\'vendʒ]', 'n.报仇；报复；报复心；雪耻机会 vt.报复；报仇', '1. They vowed revenge on their enemies. 他们发誓要向敌人报仇。 2. She said she would take her revenge on Tom. 她说她要向汤姆报仇。 3. Thoughts of revenge kept running through his mind. 他脑海里时刻萦绕着复仇的念头。 4. I want revenge against her on more scores than one. 我有种种理由要向她报复。 5. They thirsted to revenge themselves upon the enemy. 他们渴望向敌人报复。', '名词: revenger 过去式: revenged 过去分词: revenged 现在分词: revenging 第三人称单数: revenges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exiguous', '[eɡ\'zɪɡjuəs]', 'adj.稀少的；极度不足的', '1. Or exiguous not neat, color is dim. 或稀少不齐，颜色暗淡。 2. My secretary is a exiguous talent. 我的秘书是个难得的人才。 3. Actually, economics is studying how to assign the exiguous resources. 经济学实际上是研究具有稀缺性的资源如何达到最佳配置的问题。 4. This area undulating hills, vegetation is exiguous, land backbone is thin. 该地区山峦起伏，植被稀少，土地脊薄。', '副词: exiguously 名词: exiguousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imbue', '[ɪm\'bjuː]', 'v.灌输；使感染；使充满', '1. He managed to imbue his employees with team spirit. 他成功激发起雇员的团队精神。 2. You should imbue your children with ambition to succeed 你应该使你的孩子充满希望成功的雄心。', '过去式: imbued 过去分词: imbued 现在分词: imbuing 第三人称单数: imbues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tasty', '[\'teɪsti]', 'adj.好吃的；有品位的；有趣的', '1. These pancakes made by my mother are really tasty. 我妈妈做的这些煎饼非常好吃。 2. He larded the duck with pig fat to make it tasty. 他给鸭肉加了点猪油使它美味可口。 3. Dried cuttlefish is a tasty snack. 鱿鱼丝是很好吃的点心。 4. All of us have a tasty meal yesterday. 我们昨天都享受了一顿美味的饭食。', '副词: tastily 比较级: tastier 最高级: tastiest 名词: tastiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cast', '[kæst]', 'v.掷；抛；投；铸造；指定演员；加起来；投射(目光)；投(票)；预测 n.演员阵容；投掷；[医]固定用敷料', '1. The angler cast her line into the stream. 那个垂钓者把鱼线掷进了小溪里。 2. The storm cast the little rowboat onto the rocks. 风暴把这条小划艇抛到岩石上。 3. The two world wars cast a shadow over the people all over the world. 两次世界大战在全世界人民中投下了阴影。 4. The metals most frequently cast are iron, steal, aluminum and so on. 最常用来铸造的金属是铁、钢、铝等。 5. The play succeeded thanks to the wonderful performance of all the cast. 由于演员们的精彩表演,这部戏获得了成功。', '过去式: cast 过去分词: cast 现在分词: casting 第三人称单数: casts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hovel', '[\'hʌvl]', 'n.不适宜居住的小屋；杂物间；家畜小屋', '1. This hovel was only one story high. 那所破屋只有一层楼。 2. She\'s back in the old hovel already. 她已回到原来的破屋里去了。 3. It\'s very uncomfortable living in a dirty hovel like ours. 住在我们这样肮脏的破屋子里，太不舒服了。 4. I don\'t know how you can bear to live in this hovel. 我不知道你怎能忍受住在这狗窝里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incubation', '[ˌɪŋkju\'beɪʃn]', 'n.孵化；熟虑；[医]潜伏期', '1. The four stages of creative thought are preparation, incubation, illumination, and verification. 创造性思考的四个阶段是准备、沉思、启迪、求证。 2. The incubation period usually is 8 to 14 days. 潜伏期通常为8-14天。', '形容词: incubational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('panacea', '[ˌpænə\'siːə]', 'n.万灵药；灵丹妙药', '1. There\'s no single panacea for the country\'s economic ills. 国家经济弊病百出，并无万灵药可以医治。 2. It is not a panacea, but a stimulus to the economy is correct. 它不是什么万灵药，但给经济一个刺激是正确的。 3. Love is a panacea that cures spiritual wounds. 爱是一剂治疗心灵创伤的灵丹妙药。 4. Actually you have not taken any panacea and the tonic. 其实你没有吃过什么灵丹妙药和补品。', '形容词: panacean');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('magisterial', '[ˌmædʒɪ\'stɪriəl]', 'adj.有权威的；威严的；专横的；地方法官的', '1. believe irrationally 2. He talked with the magisterial authority of the head of the family. 他说起话来俨然一副一家之主的口吻。 3. The boss managed the employees in an aloof, magisterial way. 老板以冷漠专断的态度来对待这些雇员。', '副词: magisterially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('artificial', '[ˌɑːrtɪ\'fɪʃl]', 'adj.人造的；虚伪的；武断的', '1. This orange drink contains no artificial flavourings. 这种橙汁饮品不含人工调味料。 2. This dress is made of artificial fibers. 这件衣服是人造纤维的。 3. She welcomed us with an artificial smile on her face. 她脸上挂着虚委的笑容来迎接我们。 4. Her artificial manner made me sick. 她那装腔作势的样子令我恶心。', '副词: artificially 名词: artificiality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('juncture', '[\'dʒʌŋktʃər]', 'n.时刻；关头；接合；连接；[语]连音', '1. At the most critical juncture we took turns in watching that point. 在最为紧急的时刻，我们轮流监视着那个地方。 2. At this juncture his office door opened. 正在这个关头，他的办公室的门开了。 3. The project is situated at the juncture of the new and old urban districts. 该项目位于新老城区交界处。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('toxin', '[\'tɑːksɪn]', 'n.毒素；毒质', '1. Our toxin will destroy the enemy. 我们的毒素将毁灭敌人。 2. Five people died after being exposed to the toxin. 有五人因暴露在该种毒素下死亡。 3. This type of vaccine is prepared when the microorganism itself does little damage but the toxin with the microorganism is extremely harmful. 当微生物本身害处不大，而微生物的毒质危害极大时，便制取这类疫苗。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commission', '[kə\'mɪʃn]', 'n.佣金；委员会；委托；委任；犯罪 vt.授予；使服役；委托', '1. Do not deduct any commission from the consignment value. 不要从货物的价值中扣除佣金。 2. The report was submitted to the commission for consideration. 这份报告已呈报委员会审批。 3. He had received the commission to build a new bridge over the river. 他受委托在这条河上建一座新桥。 4. We all approve of the commission of authority to him. 我们都赞成把职权委任於他。 5. He was commissioned captain of the United States Air Force. 他被授予美国空军上校。', '形容词: commissional 过去式: commissioned 过去分词: commissioned 现在分词: commissioning 第三人称单数: commissions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('habituate', '[hə\'bɪtʃʊˌeɪt]', 'v.使习惯于', '1. You must habituate yourself to hard work. 你必须使自己习惯于艰苦的工作。 2. He used to habituate the dirty bars during those days in Europe. 在欧洲的那些日子他常常去下等酒吧。 3. Many things to habituate, someone said, could be given up. 有些专家说，很多成瘾性的行为可以戒除掉。 4. One can habituate oneself to living alone,though rarely with any pleasure. 虽然独自一人生活很少会有乐趣，但还是可以习惯的。', '过去式: habituated 过去分词: habituated 现在分词: habituating 第三人称单数: habituates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('die', '[daɪ]', 'v.死；枯竭；消失；渴望 n.骰子；印模；金属模子', '1. Nowadays many people die of cancer. 现在有很多人死于癌症。 2. Many people die from famine in Africa. 在非洲许多人死于饥荒。 3. My grandfather died at the age of 86. 我爷爷在86岁时去世了。 4. Flowers soon die if they are left without water. 如果不给花儿浇水,很快它们就会枯死。', '名词复数: dies 过去式: died 过去分词: died 现在分词: dying 第三人称单数: dies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blare', '[bler]', 'n.巨响；吼叫声 v.高声鸣叫；大叫', '1. The blare of the speaker burst upon our ears. 扩音器的噪音突然传进我们的耳中。 2. The trumpets blared out. 喇叭齐鸣。', '过去式: blared 过去分词: blared 现在分词: blaring 第三人称单数: blares');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tortuous', '[\'tɔːrtʃuəs]', 'adj.弯曲的；曲折的；转弯抹角的', '1. It took all he could do to keep his cart from going over in the tortuous mountain trails. 他竭尽全力才算保住大车，没有在曲曲弯弯的山路上翻倒。 2. History follows a tortuous course. 历史是循着一条曲折的道路发展的。 3. We still have a long and tortuous road to travel. 我们还要走一条漫长而曲折的过路。 4. But the negotiations proved long and tortuous. 但谈判还是转弯抹角地拖了很久。', '副词: tortuously 名词: tortuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('votary', '[\'voʊtəri]', 'n.崇拜者；热心支持者；信徒', '1. Then at last the votary of venus found words to thank the goddess. 这个时候，维纳斯的信徒才想起来向维纳斯女神感谢了一番。', '名词复数: votaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jingoism', '[\'dʒɪŋɡoʊɪzəm]', 'n.沙文主义；侵略主义', '1. Patriotism can turn into jingoism very quickly. 爱国主义可以很快转变为沙文主义。', '形容词: jingoistic 副词: jingoistically 名词: jingoist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('humble', '[\'hʌmbl]', 'adj.谦逊的；粗陋的；卑下的；微末的 vt.使 ... 卑下；贬低', '1. Knowledge makes humble, ignorance makes proud. 博学使人谦逊，无知使人骄傲。 2. The duke did well by people in humble stations. 那位公爵善待地位低下的人。 3. The family lived in a humble cottage. 这户人家住在一所简陋的农舍里。 4. You are welcome to my humble home. 非常欢迎您光临寒舍。 5. She\'ll humble you to the dust. 她一定要把你糟蹋得一文不值。', '副词: humbly 比较级: humbler 最高级: humblest 名词: humbleness 过去式: humbled 过去分词: humbled 现在分词: humbling 第三人称单数: humbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('redirect', '[ˌriːdə\'rekt]', 'adj.再直接的 v.重新传入；重新寄送', '1. Standard output is just as easy to redirect. 标准的输出正如是当做容易的重新传入。', '名词: redirection 过去式: redirected 过去分词: redirected 现在分词: redirecting 第三人称单数: redirects');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ingress', '[\'ɪnɡres]', 'n.进入；入口；入境', '1. Wheel control joint corroded due to moisture ingress and worn out as a result. 车轮转向节因为进入了湿气而腐蚀,从而导致磨损的结果。 2. The touch-screen surface eliminates pushbutton cavities which prevents liquid ingress. 触摸屏表面没有按钮腔，这就避免了液体的进入。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bilious', '[\'bɪliəs]', 'adj.胆汁的；胆汁过多的；坏脾气的', '1. Symptoms of high gastrointestinal obstruction were severe, with bilious and large amounts of nasogastric effluent. 大量含胆汁的胃引流物表示有高度的肠道阻塞。', '副词: biliously 名词: biliousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prestigious', '[pre\'stɪdʒəs]', 'adj.享有声望的；声望很高的；<古>魔术的', '1. Her first novel won a prestigious literary prize. 她的第一部小说就获得了一个颇具声望的文学奖。 2. After all,she\'s the most prestigious wedding planner in San Francisco. 她毕竟是旧金山最负盛名的婚礼策划人。 3. He is prestigious professor in this field. 他是这个领域里有声望的教授。 4. He is a prestigious figure in his village and what he says carries a lot of weight. 他在村里是个有头有脸的，说话很有分量。', '副词: prestigiously 名词: prestigiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('advertise', '[\'ædvərtaɪz]', 'v.登广告；宣传；告知', '1. We decided to advertise our new product. 我们决定为我们的新产品做广告。 2. We can advertise on the Internet. 我们可以在网上登广告。 3. I must advertise for a new secretary. 我得刊登广告聘请一位新秘书。 4. It was time to advertise our cause instead of our cars. 当时的当务之急是我们的事业可不是为我们的汽车进行广告宣传。', '名词: advertiser 过去式: advertised 过去分词: advertised 现在分词: advertising 第三人称单数: advertises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stalk', '[stɔːk]', 'n.茎；梗 n.跟踪；高视阔步 v.悄悄靠近；跟踪；蔓延；高视阔步地走', '1. It doesn\' t produce a stalk at all the first year? 在头一年绝对长不出茎秆? 2. He cut off the flowers at the stalk with a pair of scissors. 他用剪子连花带茎都剪下来。 3. He ate the apple, stalk and all. 他把那个苹果吃了个干净，连梗都没剩下。 4. He moved like a tiger stalking its prey. 他像老虎一样悄悄潜近他的猎物。', '形容词: stalky 名词: stalker 过去式: stalked 过去分词: stalked 现在分词: stalking 第三人称单数: stalks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conform', '[kən\'fɔːrm]', 'v.使一致；遵从', '1. His ideas do not conform to mine. 他的想法和我的不一致。 2. He doesn\'t conform to the usual stereotype of the city businessman with a dark suit and rolled umbrella. 他不像典型的城市商人那样，穿一身深色的套服、 带一把收好的雨伞。 3. She refused to conform to the normal social conventions. 她拒绝遵从正常的社会习俗。 4. She left home to escape the pressure to conform to her family\'s way of life. 她离家出走以求摆脱她家生活方式对她的束缚。', '名词: conformer 过去式: conformed 过去分词: conformed 现在分词: conforming 第三人称单数: conforms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dogma', '[\'dɔːɡmə]', 'n.教条；教义；信条', '1. Beliefs have ossified into rigid dogma. 信仰已僵化为不可更动的教条。 2. He conquered the old code and the old dogma. 他战胜了陈旧的秩序和陈旧的教条。 3. The Catholic dogma was to her nothing more than a set of rules. 天主教的教义对她只是一套清规戒律罢了。 4. The newspaper seeks to be independent of political dogma. 这份报纸力求不受政治信条影响。', '名词复数: dogmas');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('purgatory', '[\'pɜːrɡətɔːri]', 'n.灵魂的净化；涤罪；炼狱 adj.涤罪的', '1. As a matter of fact, the pope remits to souls in purgatory no penalty which, according to canon law, they should have paid in this life. 如同事实上的事情，教宗赦免涤罪中的灵魂无罪，因根据教义上的法规，他们应已在生命中付出代价。 2. But a funny thing happened to the Lakers on their way to purgatory. 但是在湖人炼狱的路上发生了一件有趣的事。 3. It functions as a sort of mid-life purgatory for hopeless souls on Earth. 它的职能作为一种中年炼狱为无可救药的灵魂在地球上。 4. As a matter of fact, the pope remits to souls in purgatory no penalty which, according to canon law, they should have paid in this life. 如同事实上的事情，教宗赦免涤罪中的灵魂无罪，因根据教义上的法规，他们应已在生命中付出代价。', '名词复数: purgatories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mend', '[mend]', 'vt.修理；修补；改进 vi.改过自新；改进；痊愈 n.修补；改进；修补处', '1. We need an electrician to mend the iron. 我们要请电工修理熨斗。 2. It won\'t take long to mend the car. 修理这辆汽车用不了很长时间。 3. He sent for someone to mend the broken window. 他叫人来修补破窗子。 4. You\'ll have to mend your ways if you want to be successful in your job. 如果你想在你的工作中取得成绩的话，你一定要有所改进。 5. It is never too late to mend. 改过不嫌晚。 6. The mends were almost invisible. 修补过的地方几乎看不出来。', '形容词: mendable 名词: mender 过去式: mended 过去分词: mended 现在分词: mending 第三人称单数: mends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spell', '[spel]', 'v.拼写；拼成；导致；暂时代替 n.咒语；魔力；一段时间；一阵发作；轮班', '1. I don\'t know how to spell your name. 我不会拼写你的名字。 2. Can you spell the word\" metropolis\"? 你会拼写“metropolis”这个词吗? 3. Her writing is neat, but she can\'t spell. 她的书写很工整，但是她不会拼写。 4. Put them all together, and they spell MOTHER. 把它们拼在一起 5. The witch put the princess under a spell, and she fell asleep for ten years. 这女巫使公主中了巫术，沉睡了十年。', '过去式: spelled/spelt 过去分词: spelled/spelt 现在分词: spelling 第三人称单数: spells');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('caption', '[\'kæpʃn]', 'n.说明文字 v.给（图片、照片等）加说明文字', '1. There is a caption under the picture. 图片下边附有说明。 2. The Vatican said it wanted the caption removed. 梵蒂冈说，它希望撤掉这段文字。', '过去式: captioned 过去分词: captioned 现在分词: captioning 第三人称单数: captions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rectangle', '[\'rektæŋɡl]', 'n.长方形；矩形', '1. Rectangle is coming into fashion. 长方形开始流行了。 2. He folded his newspaper into a neat rectangle. 他将报纸折成一个整整齐齐的长方形。 3. A rectangle has four right angles. 一个矩形有四个直角。 4. He drew a rectangle on the blackboard. 他在黑板上画了个矩形。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ellipsis', '[ɪ\'lɪpsɪs]', 'n.省略；省略号', '1. There is an ellipsis of \"that\" in that sentence. 那个句子省略了\"that\"。', '名词复数: ellipses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('span', '[spæn]', 'n.时期；跨度；间距 vt.延续；横跨；贯穿；遍及；弥补 动词spin的过去式形式.', '1. Modern medicine has increased man\'s life span. 现代医学延长了人的寿命。 2. He has settled here for a long span of time. 他已经在这儿定居很长一段时间了。 3. The arch has a span of 60 meters. 拱门的跨度为60米。 4. The spider has a leg span of 3 inches. 这个蜘蛛的腿的长度为3英寸。 5. The shipwrecks span nearly a century. 这些船只残骸已有近百年历史。', '过去式: spanned 过去分词: spanned 现在分词: spanning 第三人称单数: spans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('securities', '[sɪ\'kjʊərɪtɪs]', 'n.股票；有价证券 名词security的复数形式.', '1. He made a killing in railway securities. 他在铁路股票上发了大财。 2. Securities crime is the inevitable phenomenon as the development of the stock market. 证券犯罪是随着证券市场的发展而必然出现的现象。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bumpkinly', '[bʌmp\'kɪnlɪ]', 'adj.粗人地；乡下佬地；土包子地', '1. bumpkinly country boys; rustic farmers; a hick town; the nightlife of Montmartre awed the unsophisticated tourists. 天真的乡村男孩；粗俗的农民；乡野小镇；蒙特马特的夜生活让天真纯洁的旅行者望而生畏。 2. bumpkinly country boys; rustic farmers; a hick town; the nightlife of Montmartre awed the unsophisticated tourists 天真的乡村男孩；粗俗的农民；乡野小镇；蒙特马特的夜生活让天真纯洁的旅行者望而生畏 3. 8. bumpkinly country boys; rustic farmers; a hick town; the nightlife of Montmartre awed the unsophisticated tourists. 天真的乡村男孩；粗俗的农民；乡野小镇；蒙特马特的夜生活让天真纯洁的旅行者望而生畏。收藏指正 4. 6. bumpkinly country boys; rustic farmers; a hick town; the nightlife of Montmartre awed the unsophisticated tourists. 天真的乡村男孩；粗俗的农民；乡野小镇；蒙特马特的夜生活让天真纯洁的旅行者望而生畏。收藏指正', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surge', '[sɜːrdʒ]', 'n.汹涌；波涛；猛增 v.汹涌；涌起；激增；[海]缆绳滑脱', '1. A surge of demonstrators broke through the fence. 汹涌而来的示威者冲破了围栏。 2. The great surge had built up in the Gulf Stream. 汹涌的巨浪在墨西哥湾流形成了。 3. Oil was the prime cause of the price surge. 石油是物价上涨的主要原因。 4. The tides surged over the rocks. 潮水奔腾着涌过礁石。', '过去式: surged 过去分词: surged 现在分词: surging 第三人称单数: surges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ineffectual', '[ˌɪnɪ\'fektʃuəl]', 'adj.（东西）无效的；无益的；白费的；（人）无能的', '1. The searchlights were ineffectual in the fog. 探照灯在雾中不起作用。 2. All rescue measures proved ineffectual. 所有抢救措施都证明无效。 3. Her hands were almost ineffectual. 她的手也几乎没有用。 4. She had felt at the same time that he was helpless and ineffectual. 同时她也看到了他的孤弱无能，无所作为。', '副词: ineffectually 名词: ineffectuality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prosaic', '[prə\'zeɪɪk]', 'adj.单调乏味的；散文的；平淡无奇的；无想象力的', '1. It was a prosaic description of the scene. 这是对场景没有想象力的一个描述。', '副词: prosaically 名词: prosaicness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pretence', '[\'priːtens]', 'n.假装；自命；无事实根据的要求 =pretense（美）.', '1. He made a pretence of ignorance. 他假装不知道。 2. The boy didn\'t take the exam under the pretence of sickness. 那个男孩借口生病没有参加考试。 3. She was unable to keep up the pretence that she loved him. 她无法继续假装爱他了。 4. I make no pretence to being an expert on the subject. 我不敢自诩为这方面的专家。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gastritis', '[ɡæ\'straɪtɪs]', 'n.胃炎', '1. A couple of days ago she had a bout of gastritis. 前两天她闹胃炎。 2. One symptom of chronic gastritis is flatulence. 慢性胃炎的症状之一就是气胀。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surly', '[\'sɜːrli]', 'adj.脾气坏的；乖戾的；不友好的；(天气)阴沉的；傲慢的', '1. She is always so surly,she never smiles at anyone. 她总是那么个坏脾气，对谁也没有一个笑脸。 2. Don\'t look so surly. 别那么横眉立目的。 3. We were served by a very surly waiter. 一个非常傲慢的服务员招待了我们。', '副词: surlily 比较级: surlier 最高级: surliest 名词: surliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chalice', '[\'tʃælɪs]', 'n.杯；圣餐杯', '1. The destiny offers not the cup of despair, but the chalice of opportunity. 命运给于我们的不是失望之酒，而是机会之杯。 2. He slowly drank from a golden chalice by his side and ate a few pieces of fruit. 他慢慢地喝了身旁黄金酒杯里的酒，又吃了几片水果。 3. From one end of the world to the other he has drained deep the chalice of courage. 从世界的一端到另一端，他喝干了勇气之杯里的醇美汁液。 4. The Pope then brought out a communion wafer and a chalice of wine. 教皇拿出了领圣体用的饼,还有一杯圣酒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muffle', '[\'mʌfl]', 'v.围裹；抑制；发低沉的声音', '1. He did his utmost to muffle his feelings. 他竭力抑制自己的感情。', '过去式: muffled 过去分词: muffled 现在分词: muffling 第三人称单数: muffles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('occurrence', '[ə\'kɜːrəns]', 'n.发生；事件；出现', '1. Unfortunately, computer errors are a common occurrence. 不幸的是,计算机错误常常发生。 2. Riots are of frequent occurrence in this province. 这省经常发生骚乱。 3. It is more a made-up story than a real occurrence. 那是杜撰的故事，而不是真实发生的事情。 4. This is a rare occurrence as our climate seldom goes to extremes. 由于这里的气候很少出现极端，所以这是很罕见的情况。', '形容词: occurrent');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accord', '[ə\'kɔːrd]', 'n.协议；一致；符合 v.与...一致；给予；调解', '1. The two countries reached an accord. 两国签订了一项协议。 2. His words are in accord with his ideas. 他心口一致。 3. Their views were found to be in perfect accord. 人们发现他们的意见是完全一致的。 4. Your behavior is not in accord with your principle. 你的行为与你的原则不符。 5. Our information does not accord with his reports. 我们所了解的情况与他的报告不一致。', '过去式: accorded 过去分词: accorded 现在分词: according 第三人称单数: accords');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impel', '[ɪm\'pel]', 'v.驱使；激励', '1. The President\'s speech impelled the nation to greater efforts. 总统的讲话激励国民更加努力。 2. Impelled by feelings of guilt, John wrote to apologize. 约翰有感愧疚，於是写信道歉。 3. I felt impelled to investigate the matter further. 我觉得自己有责任对事情作进一步调查。 4. I was so annoyed that I felt impelled to write a letter to the paper. 我非常恼怒，以致觉得非给报社写封信不可。', '过去式: impelled 过去分词: impelled 现在分词: impelling 第三人称单数: impels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subversive', '[səb\'vɜːrsɪv]', 'adj.颠覆性的；破坏性的 n.破坏份子；危险份子', '1. The new party has subversive ideas. 新政党有颠覆的意图。 2. He was read out of the association because of alleged subversive activities. 由于有人说他搞颠覆活动，所以他被宣布开除出协会。 3. Both were new and radical experiments, considered by other countries subversive. 两者都是又新又猛的试验。其他国家都认为它们起的是破坏作用。 4. He was a known political subversive. 他是一个有名的政治颠覆分子。', '副词: subversively 名词: subversiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('serrate', '[\'serɪt]', 'adj.锯齿状的；有锯齿的 v.使成锯齿状', '1. To notch or serrate the edge of;make jagged. 做成锯齿状凿或刻边缘；使成锯齿状 2. To notch or serrate the edge of; make jagged. 做成锯齿状凿或刻边缘；使成锯齿状 3. Leaves undivided or 3-lobed, margin serrate. 叶不裂或者3裂，边缘有锯齿。 4. Leaves simple, hairy, margin serrate. 单叶，有毛，边缘有锯齿。', '过去式: serrated 过去分词: serrated 现在分词: serrating 第三人称单数: serrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('treatise', '[\'triːtɪs]', 'n.论文；论述；<废>故事', '1. The treatise he wrote is excellent. 他写的论文很优秀。 2. This is not a treatise on statistical theory. 这不是一篇有关统计理论的论文。 3. Our professor asked him to write a treatise on the subject. 我们的教授要求他就这个课题写篇论文。 4. The writer makes further analytical treatise on their relations. 笔者将就二者的关系作进一步的分析论述。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('understatement', '[\'ʌndərsteɪtmənt]', 'n.轻描淡写；有保留地陈述', '1. To say the film is bad is an understatement. 说这部影片不好是比较温和的说法。 2. The description above is quite an understatement. 上文的评价其实很保守。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overpowering', '[ˌoʊvər\'paʊərɪŋ]', 'adj.压倒性的；强烈的；使人无法忍受的 动词overpower的现在分词形式.', '1. It was as overpowering and imaginative as homesickness. 那像思乡一样,是一种压倒一切的遐想。 2. There was an overpowering smell of burning tyres. 有一股浓烈的烧轮胎的气味。 3. Captain Yolles wrinkled his nose at the overpowering odor of garbage. 约里斯处长闻到一股垃圾的恶臭。 4. The air was filled with the overpowering stench of decomposing vegetation. 空气中充满了令人难以忍受的腐烂植物的恶臭。', '副词: overpoweringly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fleck', '[flek]', 'n.斑点；微粒 v.使有斑点', '1. The garlic moss has no yellow fleck or other virus. 蒜苔没有黄斑点及其它病毒。 2. Every fleck of light reminds me how much I\'ve yet to see. 每一点光芒都提醒我世界万千，没看到的还很多。 3. The bird\'s egg is pale blue with some brown flecks on it. 这种鸟的蛋呈淡蓝色，上面还有一些褐色斑点。 4. The sea was flecked with foam. 大海上涌起点点泡沫。', '过去式: flecked 过去分词: flecked 现在分词: flecking 第三人称单数: flecks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tonic', '[\'tɑːnɪk]', 'n.补药；奎宁水；[音]主音 adj.滋补的；振奋精神的；[医]肌肉紧张的；[音]主音的', '1. This tonic will help to set you up. 这补药会帮助你变得更加健壮。 2. This tonic will work miracles for your depression. 这种补药对治疗你的忧郁症十分有效。 3. I\'ll have a gin and tonic, please. 请来一杯加奎宁水的杜松子酒。 4. The tonic is carried inside the listener\'s head. 主音一直在听者头脑中回旋。 5. Ginseng is well known for its tonic effect. 人参是滋补身体的名药。', '副词: tonically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('virago', '[vɪ\'rɑːɡoʊ]', 'n.泼妇；悍妇；高大魁梧而有勇气的女子', '1. The virago vomited out curses on that tramp. 那悍妇怒骂那流浪汉。 2. Danty says those women who make constant mistakes are Virago but men Iago. 但丁说过，女人犯错是英雄，男人犯错会是懦夫。', '形容词: viraginous 名词复数: viragoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assiduous', '[ə\'sɪdʒuəs]', 'adj.勤勉的；刻苦的', '1. He was assiduous in performance of duty. 他勤勉地履行职责。 2. The book was the result of ten years of assiduous research. 那本书是十年苦心钻研的成果。', '副词: assiduously 名词: assiduousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quail', '[kweɪl]', 'n.鹌鹑 vi.畏缩；胆怯', '1. Suddenly the quail hunter threw his net over the remaining quails. 很快鹌鹑猎手就把他的网撒到了剩下的鹌鹑上。 2. But if you need a right quail, it has to be fleshly or it dries out too easily. 不过要挑对新鲜鹌鹑，肉质要丰嫩，不然很容易干粗。', '名词复数: quail 过去式: quailed 过去分词: quailed 现在分词: quailing 第三人称单数: quails');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('astigmatic', '[ˌæstɪg\'mætɪk]', 'adj.散光的；乱视的 n.散光', '1. Astigmatic dials are targets used for the detection and correction of astigmatism. 散光盘是用于辅助检测并矫正散光的视标。 2. Astigmatic dials are targets used for the detection and correction of astigmatism. 散光盘是用于辅助检测并矫正散光的视标。 3. Conclusion This calculation is useful to understand and correctly use the astigmatic dials test. 结论被检者对散光视标辨认结果和散光轴位之间关系的定量推导有助于正确的理解和临床应用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('squalor', '[\'skwɑːlər]', 'n.肮脏；不干净', '1. There is indescribable squalor in those books. 那些书简直污秽不堪。 2. He was born in squalor next to London\'s docks. 他出生在伦敦码头附近肮脏的地区。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fender', '[\'fendər]', 'n.挡泥板；护舷的垫子等', '1. His car bruised the auto fender of my car. 他的汽车撞瘪了我的汽车挡泥板。 2. A passing car banged up our fender. 一辆过路的车把我们的挡泥板撞坏了。 3. The foam fender shall be installed onto a solid structure or reaction panel. 漂浮护舷应须安装在坚固的结构或安装板上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quasi', '[\'kweɪsaɪ]', 'adj.类似的；外表的', '1. Earls of Wilbraham, quasi wild boar ham. 威尔白莱罕(即“野猪大腿肉”)伯爵家。 2. Earls of Wilbra ham, quasi wild boar ham . 威尔白莱罕(即“野猪大腿肉”)伯爵家。 3. Piano Sonata No. 13 in E flat major (\"Quasi una fantasia\"), Op. 钢琴奏鸣曲第13号在电子商务大调（“准联合国协会幻想曲”），作品。 4. Quasi Velocity Matched Electrooptic Phase Modulator[J]. 引用该论文 郭凤珍;于长泰;小林哲郎.', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('advocacy', '[\'ædvəkəsi]', 'n.拥护；支持；鼓吹', '1. The police have already rejected applications by different pet advocacy groups to stage demonstrations. 警方已拒绝不同的宠物拥护团体举行游行的申请。 2. The study has also been cited as compelling evidence for screening by the patient advocacy group Lung Cancer Alliance. 此研究已经被肺癌联盟的拥护此筛查方案的病人群体作为一种强有力的证据所引用。 3. And the actions of the newly empowered advocacy groups like the ACEF can be quickly reversed. 像中华环保联合会这样新近得到支持的环保组织的行动有可能在短时期内走向倒退。 4. To them, my advocacy of higher Pigovian taxes is a sure sign that I am another one of those pantywaist Harvard liberals. 在他们看来，对提高庇古税的支持，就是一项明证，说明我是又一个没有男子汉气概的哈佛自由主义者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forensic', '[fə\'rensɪk]', 'adj.法院的；关于法庭的；适合于辩论的', '1. A specialist in forensic medicine was called as a witness in the murder trial. 在那桩谋杀案的审理中，一名法医专家被召来作证。', '副词: forensically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('testament', '[\'testəmənt]', 'n.证明；自白；[律]遗嘱；<古>圣约 Testament n.圣经旧约；圣经新约', '1. The building is a testament to their success. 这一建筑是他们成功的证明。 2. This aircraft\'s safety record is an impressive testament to its designers\' skill. 这种飞机的飞行安全记录令人印象深刻，证明了该机种设计师本领非凡。 3. Her solicitor drew up her last will and testament. 她的律师拟就了她的遗嘱。 4. The event was prophesied in the Old Testament. 这事件在《〈圣经〉旧约》中有过预言。', '形容词: testamentary');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slobber', '[\'slɑːbər]', 'v.流口水；毫不遮掩地示爱 n.口水；语无伦次的表达', '1. I still slobber when thinking of the dishes. 想起美餐，我仍流口水。 2. Someone will slobber and someone will ask price? 呵呵，有人要流口水要开价了！ 3. I still slobber when thinking of the dishes. 想起美餐，我仍流口水。 4. Someone will slobber and someone will ask price? 呵呵，有人要流口水要开价了！', '形容词: slobbery 名词: slobberer 过去式: slobbered 过去分词: slobbered 现在分词: slobbering 第三人称单数: slobbers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incompetent', '[ɪn\'kɑːmpɪtənt]', 'adj.无能力的；不称职的；不能胜任的 n.没有能力的人', '1. The company cleaned out the incompetent workers. 公司把不称职的员工解雇了。 2. One incompetent manager brings along another. 一个不称职的经理人员带进来另一个不胜任的人。 3. One incompetent manager brings along another. 一个不称职的经理人员带进来另一个不胜任的人。 4. His incompetent colleague was axed as a warning to other employees. 作为对其他员工的警告，他的一个不胜任的同事被解聘了。 5. I\'ve had it with these incompetent employees. 我对这些没有能力的员工失去了耐心。', '副词: incompetently 名词: incompetence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('finicky', '[\'fɪnɪki]', 'adj.过分挑剔的；苛求的；过分讲究的', '1. He is the most finicky eaters I\'ve ever met. 他是我所见到过的对食物最挑剔的人。 2. Eat up your fish and don\' t be so finicky. 把你的鱼吃完,别太挑剔了。 3. But, as Mr Midler discovers, they are finicky about what is found. 但是正如米得勒先生发现的那样，他们对调查结果极其严苛。', '比较级: finickier 最高级: finickiest 名词: finickiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dispel', '[dɪ\'spel]', 'v.驱散；消除', '1. It is the task of a fighter to dispel darkness. 驱散黑暗，这是战士的任务。 2. Nothing could dispel the torpidity of the indifferent audience. 任何东西都无法驱散那些冷漠观众的困倦。 3. I thought,if I had caused the cloud,it was my duty to make an effort to dispel it. 我想，如果是我引起了这块乌云，那我就该负责努力驱散它。 4. The wind soon dispelled the fog. 风很快就把雾吹散了。', '过去式: dispelled 过去分词: dispelled 现在分词: dispelling 第三人称单数: dispels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rapprochement', '[ˌræproʊʃ\'mɑːn]', 'n.(友好关系)建立；(友好关系)恢复；和解', '1. Mr Brown has inherited the British-Libyan rapprochement engineered by Tony Blair. 布朗首相沿袭了托尼-布莱尔促成的英国和利比亚建立的友好关系。 2. There\'re signs of rapprochement between George and his son. 乔治和他儿子间有恢复关系的迹象。 3. There now seems little chance of rapprochement between the warring factions. 目前，敌对双方和解的可能性似乎很渺茫。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hangdog', '[\'hæŋdɔːɡ]', 'adj.羞愧的；卑躬屈膝的 n.卑微的人', '1. It was a painful, hangdog progress for him. 对他而言，那是一个痛苦而受屈的过程。 2. After he got out of jail, he always had a hangdog look. 他出狱后，总是一副羞愧的神色。 3. Mr. B sometimes shows a hangdog look in front of his wife. 先生与其他女人有染后，在老婆面前显出有罪恶感的神色。 4. A man sat at a bar,had the saddest hangdog expression. 一个男子坐在一间酒吧里;脸色特别难看.', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('studio', '[\'stuːdioʊ]', 'n.画室；工作室；播音室；制片厂；摄影场', '1. Upstairs he has a studio where he paints a little. 他在楼上有一个画室，有时在那里作一点画。 2. I was talking to her in the studio. 我那时正在工作室跟它谈话。 3. The studio is being wired for sound. 这个播音室正在安装音响设备用的电线。 4. She must be in the television studio at the moment. 她现在一定在电视演播室。', '名词复数: studios');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sluggard', '[\'slʌɡərd]', 'n.游手好闲的人；懒鬼 adj.游手好闲的', '1. Seryozhka is a sluggard, a drunkard. 谢辽日卡是个懒汉，酒鬼。 2. How long will you lie there you sluggard? 懒惰人哪，你要睡到几时呢? 3. You are only loitering and sluggard. 你只是虚度时光的闲散人罢了. 4. How long will you sleep, sluggard? 懒惰人哪，你要睡到几时呢？', '形容词: sluggardly 名词: sluggardness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overexposure', '[ˌəʊvərɪk\'spəʊʒə(r)]', 'n.感光过度；[摄]过度曝光', '1. Red overexposure color shift in direct sunlight! 阳光直射下红色曝光过度! 2. Effects of Overexposure:EYE:POSSIBLE IRRITATION. 感光过度的效果:注意:可能的刺激。 3. Banks can set rules to prevent overexposure to any single borrower. 为防止风险过度集中在单一借款人上，银行通常会制定避险措施。 4. Each year in Canada, more than 80 people die from overexposure to the cold. 在加拿大，每年都有80多人因为皮肤过多暴露在寒冷的空气中而死亡。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('doleful', '[\'doʊlfl]', 'adj.悲哀的；寂寞的；阴沉的', '1. His doleful expression told me everything. 他悲哀的表情让我知道了一切。 2. He pauses and gathers himself for a moment before fixing me with doleful eyes. 皮特停顿了，他蹙眉，有着悲伤落寞的眼神。 3. His countenance, as he came on, wore an abstracted and somewhat doleful air. 他走上来的时候，面上有着一种茫然，而且好象阴郁的神气。', '副词: dolefully 名词: dolefulness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('query', '[\'kwɪri]', 'n.疑问；质问；疑问号 vt.质问；对 ... 表示怀疑', '1. Your interesting report raises several important queries. 你的精彩报告引出了几个重要问题。 2. I send all my income tax query to my accountant. 我把所有有关所得税的疑问送交会计师。 3. Put a query. 打一个问号。 4. The minister was queried about his plans for the industry. 有人向部长提出了工业计划问题。', '名词: querier 名词复数: queries 过去式: queried 过去分词: queried 现在分词: querying 第三人称单数: queries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contrition', '[kən\'trɪʃn]', 'n.悔罪；痛悔', '1. She forgave him because his contrition was real. 她原谅了他是由于他的懊悔是真心的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('giddy', '[\'ɡɪdi]', 'adj.眼花的；头晕的；轻率的；轻浮的 v.(使)眼花', '1. The world spun about him in a giddy dance. 天地在他四周旋转着，让他眼花缭乱。 2. They looked down from a giddy height. 他们从令人眩晕的高度往下看。 3. She felt giddy and then crumpled up. 她感到一阵头晕，随后就无力地倒下了。 4. He married a young and giddy girl. 他又娶了一个轻佻的年轻姑娘。', '副词: giddily 比较级: giddier 最高级: giddiest 名词: giddiness 过去式: giddied 过去分词: giddied 现在分词: giddying 第三人称单数: giddies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('physiological', '[ˌfɪziə\'lɒdʒɪkl]', 'adj.生理的；生理学的', '1. The physiological needs are reasonably satisfied. 生理的需要得到合理的满足。 2. Objective To Study the effect of Haematococcus pluvialis powder on physiological metabolism of Wistar rats. 目的观察红球藻粉对大鼠生理的影响。 3. Certain species of aquatic animals are capable of producing physiological shocks. 某些种类的水生生物能够引起生理学的电击。 4. From a physiological standpoint \"health\"refers to a persons quality of health and their ability to adapt to the outer world. 从生理学的角度来看，体质是指人的健康水平和对外界的适应能力。', '副词: physiologically 异体字: physiologic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tend', '[tend]', 'v.趋向；易于；朝向 v.照料；照管', '1. Weeds tend to displace other plants. 杂草越来越多，有取代其他植物之势。 2. During the interview, some interviewees tend to exaggerate. 面试时,有些面试者会有夸大的倾向。 3. He\'s a good salesman, but his offhand manner does tend to put people off. 他是个很好的推销员，可是他那随便的态度容易使人产生反感。 4. Prices are tending upward. 物价在上涨。 5. Mother being ill, he had to tend her at home. 母亲病了,他得在家照料她。', '过去式: tended 过去分词: tended 现在分词: tending 第三人称单数: tends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obsessive', '[əb\'sesɪv]', 'adj.着迷的；困扰的；强迫性的', '1. The man is obsessive in gambling. 他着迷于赌博。 2. I try to stay fit, but I\'m not obsessive about it. 我试图保持体形，但是我不执着于此。 3. Obsessive worry will never make things any better. 过分的担心绝对不会使事情变得更好。 4. She\'s obsessive about punctuality. 她对守时十分固执.', '副词: obsessively 名词: obsessiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brutal', '[\'bruːtl]', 'adj.野蛮的；残暴的', '1. The people have been kept down for years by a brutal regime. 人民多年遭受野蛮制度压迫。 2. The enemy made a brutal attack upon the villagers. 敌人对村民们进行了野蛮的攻击。 3. NATO\'s invasion of this independent country is a brutal violation of human rights. 北约对这个独立的国家的侵略是对人权的野蛮侵犯。 4. The brutal soldiers beat their prisoners ruthlessly. 残暴的士兵野蛮地抽打俘虏。', '副词: brutally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chasten', '[\'tʃeɪsn]', 'vt.(通过惩罚而使坏习惯等)改正、磨炼', '1. I have learned a lot from the chastening experience. 我从这个可以引以为戒的经历中学到了很多。 2. He was chastened by his failure. 他因失败而得到了教训。', '名词: chastener 过去式: chastened 过去分词: chastened 现在分词: chastening 第三人称单数: chastens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gaudy', '[\'ɡɔːdi]', 'adj.俗丽的 n.(英)盛大宴会(尤指大学年会)', '1. He dislikes gaudy decorations. 他不喜欢俗丽的装饰。 2. These are cheap and gaudy clothes. 这是些廉价而花哨的衣服。 3. She wore a gaudy costume to the party. 她著一身色彩艳丽的服装参加宴会。', '副词: gaudily 比较级: gaudier 最高级: gaudiest 名词: gaudiness 名词复数: gaudies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remittance', '[rɪ\'mɪtns]', 'n.汇款', '1. He has returned the completed form with your remittance. 他已经把填好的表格连同你的汇款一并寄回了。 2. Sorry, your remittance has not reached us yet. 对不起，您的汇款还没有到我们这儿。 3. We will forward the goods on remittance of $10. 我们收到十英镑的汇款之后立即装货寄出。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commensurate', '[kə\'menʃərət]', 'adj.相称的；成比例的；适当的', '1. He was given a job commensurate with his abilities. 他得到一份与他能力相称的工作。 2. Salary will be commensurate with experience. 薪金将会与资历相称。 3. The salary will be commensurate with your age and experience. 工资将会与你的年龄和经历相称。 4. Six yards is commensurate with eighteen feet. 6码相当于18英尺。', '副词: commensurately 名词: commensuration');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sleazy', '[\'sliːzi]', 'adj.质地薄的；肮脏的；低廉的；低劣的', '1. They took me to a sleazy back-street hotel. 他们把我带到一个后街的肮脏的旅馆。 2. Her sleazy gossip was very off-putting. 她那低级的闲话令人倒胃口。', '副词: sleazily 比较级: sleazier 最高级: sleaziest 名词: sleaziness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tributary', '[\'trɪbjəteri]', 'adj.纳贡的；从属的；辅助的；支流的 n.支流；纳贡者；属国', '1. Sino-Siamese trade had two forms, tributary trade and civil trade. 中暹贸易主要分为两种形式：朝贡贸易与民间贸易。 2. Like Silla, Parhae was a tributary state of Tang-dynasty China. 如新罗一样，渤海国是中国唐朝的属国。 3. About half the 22 Ovimbundu chiefdoms were tributary to a larger chiefdom before Portuguese intervention in the 20th century. 在20世纪葡萄牙人实际占领之前，约有半数酋长领地臣服于一个大酋长。 4. The software of master station and tributary station are designed by VC ++ and configuration soft. 利用VC++和组态软件设计出了煤矿通风自动化系统的主站和分站软件。 5. This is a tributary of Zhujiang River. 这是珠江的一条支流。', '名词复数: tributaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bent', '[bent]', 'bend的过去式和过去分词. adj.下定决心的；弯曲的 n.嗜好', '1. The branches bent in the wind. 树枝被风吹弯了。 2. Judy bent her face low over the notebook. 朱迪把脸凑近笔记本。 3. The branch bent but didn\'t break when the boy climbed along it. 那男孩爬上树枝时，树枝弯曲了，但是没有折断。 4. He\'s bent on completing his essay. 他决心要写完他的随笔。 5. He has a bent for art. 他生性爱好艺术。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clarity', '[\'klærəti]', 'n.清楚；透明', '1. These adjectives mean lacking clarity of meaning. 这些形容词都有意思不清楚的含义。 2. Let me try to provide some clarity. 让我提供一些清楚的信息。 3. Clarity is very important for a business letter. 文笔清晰对于商业信件非常重要。 4. Clarity of dictionis vital for a public speaker. 发音清晰对演说家至关重要。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reedy', '[\'riːdi]', 'adj.芦苇丛生的；芦苇做的；细长的；(声音)似笛声的', '1. Leaning her breast against the reedy shore, 斜倚她柔胸，在那芦苇岸， 2. The reedy grass covered the whole area. 又细又长的草覆盖着整个地区。 3. \"I\'ve been sick all fall,\" she said in a reedy voice. \"我整整一个秋天都在生病，\"她说，嗓门很尖。', '比较级: reedier 最高级: reediest 名词: reediness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vertigo', '[\'vɜːrtɪɡoʊ]', 'n.眩晕', '1. It is very important to determine if vertigo truly exists. 要确定是否真的有眩晕困扰是十分重要的。', '名词复数: vertigoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abide', '[ə\'baɪd]', 'v.遵守；忍受；坚持', '1. Everyone must abide by the law. 所有的人都应遵守法律。 2. Once you make a promise, you must abide by it. 一旦你许诺,你必须遵守你的诺言。 3. She can\'t abide that man. 她不能忍受那个人。 4. I cannot abide the loud noise anymore. 我再也无法忍受这么大的噪音。', '名词: abider 过去式: abode/abided 过去分词: abode/abided 现在分词: abiding 第三人称单数: abides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contradict', '[ˌkɒntrə\'dɪkt]', 'vt.反驳；与 ... 矛盾', '1. He did not contradict his attorney\'s comment. 他没有反驳律师的意见。 2. She doesn\'t like to contradict her husband in public. 她不愿在众人面前反驳她丈夫。 3. Don\'t contradict your father. 别和你父亲犟嘴。 4. The report contradicts what we heard yesterday. 这个报道与我们昨天听到的有矛盾。', '形容词: contradictable 名词: contradicter 过去式: contradicted 过去分词: contradicted 现在分词: contradicting 第三人称单数: contradicts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parlous', '[\'pɑːrləs]', 'adj.危险的；靠不住的；狡猾的 adv.非常地；极度地', '1. English tennis is in a parlous condition. 英国网球运动不堪设想。 2. They had a parlous journey on stormy seas. 他们在风暴海洋上进行了一次危险的旅行。', '副词: parlously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jubilant', '[\'dʒuːbɪlənt]', 'adj.扬声欢呼的；喜洋洋的', '1. Before his eyes was a sea of jubilant people. 他眼前是一片欢腾的人海。 2. The jubilant crowds fell silent at his approach, parting to allow him through. 欢呼的人们看到他都安静了下来，让开路让他过去。 3. Liverpool were in a jubilant mood after their cup victory. 利物浦队夺得优胜杯后喜气洋洋。', '副词: jubilantly 名词: jubilance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stock', '[stɑːk]', 'n.存货；储备；树干；股票；股份；家畜；血统；汤汁；声望 v.采购；储存；供给；发新芽 adj.惯用的；存货的', '1. We have a large stock of tinned fruit. 我们有大批水果罐头的存货。 2. The grocer\'s has plenty varieties of goods in stock. 杂货商有种类繁多的存货。 3. We need to replenish our stocks of coal. 我们需要再次补充煤的储备。 4. Branches grow from the stock of the tree. 树枝是从树干上生长出来的。 5. We must stock up with food for the holiday. 我们必须采购一些食品以备假期之需。 6. She\'s tired of her husband\'s stock jokes. 她已听厌了丈夫那老一套的俏皮话。', '名词: stockage 过去式: stocked 过去分词: stocked 现在分词: stocking 第三人称单数: stocks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impolitic', '[ɪm\'pɑːlətɪk]', 'adj.不明智的；失策的 =impolitical.', '1. It would have been impolitic to refuse his offer. 当时若拒绝了他的好意当然是不明智的。 2. It is impolitic to offend people who can help you. 触怒能帮助你的人是很失策的。', '副词: impoliticly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vindication', '[ˌvɪndɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.辩护；证明无罪或正确；洗冤；证实', '1. Truth is generally the best vindication against slander. 事实通常是防备诋毁的最佳辩护。 2. The army\'s victory is being seen as vindication of their tactics. 军队的胜利被认为是证明他们的战术是正确的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prescribe', '[prɪ\'skraɪb]', 'v.开处方；规定，命令，指示；限制，限定', '1. I\'ll prescribe for you as soon as I get the report. 我拿到报告就给你开处方。 2. What medicine did the doctor prescribe for your illness? 医生开了什么药来治你的病？ 3. The law prescribes heavy penalties for this offence. 法律规定对这种不法行为从严惩处。 4. Regulations prescribe that a lawyer draw up the paper. 条文规定必须由律师拟定此公文。', '名词: prescriber 过去式: prescribed 过去分词: prescribed 现在分词: prescribing 第三人称单数: prescribes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('epilogue', '[\'epɪlɔːɡ]', 'n.结尾；收场白 =epilog(美).', '1. I am deeply moved by his epilogue. 我看了他写的编余，很有感触。 2. The play ended with a humorous epilogue. 这出戏以幽默的收场白结束。 3. Fortinbras speaks the epilogue in Shakespeare\'s Hamlet. 在莎士比亚的《哈姆雷特》中，由福丁布拉斯念收场白。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('devotee', '[ˌdevə\'tiː]', 'n.爱好者；献身者；虔诚的宗教信徒', '1. He has been a golf devotee for 25 years. 他成为一个高尔夫爱好者已经有25年了。 2. He is a devotee of Krishna. 他是印度克利须那神教的一名虔诚的信徒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ticklish', '[\'tɪklɪʃ]', 'adj.难对付的；易怒的；怕痒的', '1. The news is quite ticklish to the ear. 这消息听起来使人觉得有些难办。 2. I cannot handle such a ticklish matter. 这种难人的事，我办不了。 3. I seemed to at my wits end before those ticklish questions. 面对那些棘手的问题我显得束手无策。 4. I\'m terribly ticklish. 我特别怕痒。', '副词: ticklishly 名词: ticklishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('herald', '[\'herəld]', 'n.使者；传令官；先驱；预兆 vt.预报；标志', '1. The robin is a herald of spring. 知更鸟是预告春天到来的使者. 2. The cuckoo is the herald of the spring. 杜鹃报春。 3. He had the important manner of an official herald. 他像个神气十足的官方传令官。 4. He became a reporter for the Herald Tribune. 他成为《先驱论坛报》的记者。 5. To us this oracular remark seemed to herald Hitler. 这番玄妙深奥的话在我们看来仿佛预示着希特勒的来临。', '过去式: heralded 过去分词: heralded 现在分词: heralding 第三人称单数: heralds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forte', '[fɔːrt]', 'n.[C, sing]长处；特长；优点；[音乐]强音记号', '1. Singing is not really my forte, but I\'ll try. 唱歌实在不是我擅长的，但是我试着唱唱看。 2. Diplomacy was not Margaret\'s forte . 玛格丽特对外交事务不内行。 3. His forte is after-dinner speeches. 他的特长是饭后演说。 4. To negotiate with our buyers is my forte. 与买方谈判是我的特长。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('felicitous', '[fə\'lɪsɪtəs]', 'adj.巧妙的；极为适当的；可喜的', '1. His work is rather fluent and felicitous. 他的作品十分流畅，措辞巧妙。 2. You need to handle the delicate matter in a most felicitous manner. 你需要用得体的方式处理这件微妙的事。 3. Her choice of music is felicitous. 她选择的音乐很适当. 4. The intensity is determined by a felicitous arrangement of the atomic energy levels. 这一强度取决于原子能级的适当排列。', '副词: felicitously 名词: felicitousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acrophobia', '[ˌækrə\'foʊbɪə]', 'n.恐高症', '1. Many people suffer from very serious acrophobia. 许多人患有严重的恐高症。 2. Do you know how to overcome acrophobia. 你知道怎么才能克服恐高症。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('limited', '[\'lɪmɪtɪd]', 'adj.有限的；被限制的 动词limit的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. We had only limited communion with the natives. 我们与本地人的交往有限。 2. We have limited funds and several competing claims. 我们的基金有限而争相申请的却有几处。 3. His intelligence is rather limited. 他的智力相当有限。 4. A limited number of cars is available. 汽车使用数目有限制。', '副词: limitedly 名词: limitedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defame', '[dɪ\'feɪm]', 'vt.诽谤；中伤；损毁名誉', '1. We expect politicians to defame each other in an election year. 我们预料政客们在选举年会互相诽谤。', '名词: defamer 过去式: defamed 过去分词: defamed 现在分词: defaming 第三人称单数: defames');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inclement', '[ɪn\'klemənt]', 'adj.气候严酷的；寒冷的；狂风暴雨的', '1. The inclement weather brought forth a host of disease. 严酷的天气引起了种种疾病。', '副词: inclemently 名词: inclemency');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pith', '[pɪθ]', 'n.（木）髓；精髓；要旨 v.去髓；破坏脊髓；杀死；瘫痪', '1. The stem is hollow with pith cavity. 茎中空,具较大的髓腔。 2. Both the rubber and the pith ball are negatively charged. 橡胶棒和木髓球两者都带负电荷。 3. The pith of that theory is serving for people. 那个理论的精髓是为人民服务。 4. That was the pith of his argument. 那就是他论据的要点。', '过去式: pithed 过去分词: pithed 现在分词: pithing 第三人称单数: piths');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contraband', '[\'kɑːntrəbænd]', 'n.违禁品；走私品', '1. The policemen were searching for contraband. 警察正在搜查违禁品。 2. The customs inspectors found no contraband in the vehicle. 海关检查员并未在这辆车上发现违禁品。 3. The customs officials confiscated the contraband. 海关官员没收了走私物品。 4. Contraband goods were found in the storehouse of the hotel. 在旅馆的储藏室里发现了走私货。', '名词: contrabandage');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tenet', '[\'tenɪt]', 'n.教义；信条；原则；宗旨', '1. This is a basic tenet of capitalism. 这是资本主义的一则基本信条。 2. We accepted the article upon the tenet. 我们在原则上接受了这个条款。 3. That\'s also the tenet of Diamond Business Club. 这也正是达盟商务俱乐部的宗旨。 4. The tenet of CCIA is to serve the nation and society as a whole on behalf of carpet industry in China. 地毯协会的宗旨是立足行业，服务全国，面向社会。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aver', '[ə\'vɜːr]', 'v.极力声明；断言', '1. He avers he will not attend the meeting. 他断言不会参加那个会议。 2. She averred that she had never seen the man before. 她斩钉截铁地说以前从未见过这个男人。 3. I aver it will not rain tomorrow. 我断言明天不会下雨。', '形容词: averrable 名词: averment 过去式: averred 过去分词: averred 现在分词: averring 第三人称单数: avers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enumerate', '[ɪ\'nuːməreɪt]', 'vt.数；列举；枚举', '1. We found more children at the circus than we could enumerate. 我们见到数不清的孩子在看马戏。 2. Can you enumerate the capitals of the50 states? 你能把五十州的首府列举出来吗？ 3. Let me enumerate many flaws in your hypothesis. 让我列举你前提中的许多谬误。 4. Provide the path of the root folder to enumerate. 提供要枚举的根文件夹的路径。', '形容词: enumerative 名词: enumeration 过去式: enumerated 过去分词: enumerated 现在分词: enumerating 第三人称单数: enumerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('striated', '[\'straɪeɪtɪd]', 'adj.有条纹的；有条痕的；有线纹的 动词striate的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. The cilia are longer and less regular than the microvilli of a striated border. 纤毛比微绒毛长，但排列不如纹状缘紧密整齐。 2. The striated and polished surfaces are called slicken-sides. 有条痕的磨光面则称为擦痕面。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exhilarate', '[ɪɡ\'zɪləreɪt]', 'vt.使高兴；使愉快；使振奋', '1. This dangerous task did not defeat but exhilarate him. 这件危险的任务不但没有击垮他反而使他振奋。', '形容词: exhilarative 名词: exhilarator 过去式: exhilarated 过去分词: exhilarated 现在分词: exhilarating 第三人称单数: exhilarates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beholden', '[bɪ\'hoʊldən]', 'adj.蒙恩的；有义务的', '1. We were much beholden to him for his kindness. 我们对他的好意感激万分。 2. He works with kings and magistrates but does not feel beholden to them. 他配合国王和大臣们的工作，但并不感到蒙恩于其。 3. And not all of the DPJ\'s new recruits will feel beholden to him. 而且不是所有民主党新成员都感觉对他有义务。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unimpassioned', '[ˌʌnɪm\'pæʃənd]', 'adj.没有激情的；不感情用事的；平静的', '1. She was apparently doing so in a deliberate and unimpassioned manner, with a view of making the best of it. 很显然她用从容不迫、沉着冷静的方式想尽量考虑出个名堂来。 2. All acstasies, of love and anger, joys and agonies, and all the passions, that plague man from birth, are lapped at in unimpassioned earth. ________Gibson 一切狂喜 爱与恨 乐与哀 一切与生俱来的折磨 人的情感 最终被无情的尘土掩埋。 3. answered the charges with an unimpassioned defense. 以没有热情的辩护回答控告 4. answered with an unimpassioned defense; the unimpassioned intellect. 以没有热情的辩护回答控告；冷静的理解力。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dehydrate', '[diː\'haɪdreɪt]', 'v.脱水；去水', '1. People can very quickly dehydrate in the desert. 人在沙漠里很快就会脱水。 2. Her body had dehydrated dangerously with the heat. 她因受酷热身体脱水。 3. When I forget to water my plants, they dehydrate and die. 如果我忘记给花浇水，他们就会缺水而死。', '名词: dehydrator 过去式: dehydrated 过去分词: dehydrated 现在分词: dehydrating 第三人称单数: dehydrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proboscis', '[prə\'bɑːsɪs]', 'n.鼻子；长嘴；喙', '1. Its proboscis has got stuck to a lot of pollen. 它的喙上粘了很多花粉。', '名词复数: proboscises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foray', '[\'fɔːreɪ]', 'v.突袭；侵略；劫掠 n.突袭；尝试', '1. They forayed into enemy territory. 他们对敌军领土进行了突袭。 2. The officer sent a few of his men on a foray. 军官送了一些他的人去突袭。 3. This is the company\'s first foray into the computer market. 这是该公司打入计算机市场的首次尝试。', '过去式: forayed 过去分词: forayed 现在分词: foraying 第三人称单数: forays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('waste', '[weɪst]', 'n.废物；浪费；荒地 v.浪费；滥用；消耗 adj.荒芜的；无用的；浪费的', '1. The city waste is disposed of in the sea. 城市垃圾倒在海里处理掉。 2. The safe disposal of nuclear waste is a major problem. 安全处置核废料是个大问题。 3. It\'s only a waste of time to speak to her. 和她说话纯粹是浪费时间。 4. The routine work is a waste of her talents. 做这样千篇一律的工作,是浪费了她的才能。 5. All his efforts were wasted. 他的所有努力都白费了。 6. They are turning waste land into paddy fields. 他们正在使荒地变为稻田。', '过去式: wasted 过去分词: wasted 现在分词: wasting 第三人称单数: wastes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('salutation', '[ˌsælju\'teɪʃn]', 'n.招呼；致敬；问候 n.(信函开头)称呼语', '1. After hailing the morn with this second salutation, he threw a boot at the woman as a third. 他用这种致敬的方式问了早安之后，便把靴子向那女人掷去作为第三次问候。 2. After hailing the morn with this second salutation, he threw a boot at the woman as a third. 他用这种致敬的方式问了早安之后，便把靴子向那女人掷去作为第三次问候。', '形容词: salutational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('benediction', '[ˌbenɪ\'dɪkʃn]', 'n.祝福；恩赐', '1. She conferred her benediction to me when I left. 当我离开的时候，她向我祝福。 2. I say the benediction to my father\'s birthday. 我祝福父亲的生日。 3. The appearance of the sun after the many rainy days was like a benediction. 人们把久雨后出现的太阳看成是上帝的恩赐。', '形容词: benedictive');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marvel', '[\'mɑːrvl]', 'n.奇异的事物；令人吃惊的人 v.惊异于；惊异', '1. Your room is a marvel of neatness and order. 你的房间整洁得出奇。 2. The operation was a marvel of medical skill. 这个手术是医术的一个非凡范例。 3. It was a real marvel that the baby was unhurt when he fell from the fifth floor. 那婴儿从五楼摔下来竟没受伤真是一个奇迹。 4. You\'re a marvel; how can you work so hard at your age. 您是一位奇才;象您这么大年纪的人怎么会这么拼命干呢。 5. I marvel at the felicity of his style. 我惊叹他的精巧的文体。', '过去式: marveled/marvelled 过去分词: marveled/marvelled 现在分词: marveling/marvelling 第三人称单数: marvels/marvels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mesmerize', '[\'mezməraɪz]', 'v.施以催眠术；迷住；迷惑', '1. These liquid backgrounds will mesmerize you and add real production value to any project. 这些液体会迷住你的背景和增加实际生产价值的任何项目。', '名词: mesmerization 过去式: mesmerized 过去分词: mesmerized 现在分词: mesmerizing 第三人称单数: mesmerizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bibliography', '[ˌbɪbli\'ɑːɡrəfi]', 'n.参考书目；文献学', '1. Bibliography usually appears at the end of a book. 参考书目通常在书后列出。 2. The book ought to include a bibliography of the subject. 这本书应包括一份关于这一学科的参考书目。 3. Please include your quotations in the bibliography. 请在参考文献处标明你的引文出处。 4. We have quoted in the bibliography a large number of items. 文献目录中列举了大量文献。', '形容词: bibliographical 副词: bibliographically 名词复数: bibliographies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('astray', '[ə\'streɪ]', 'adv.迷途地 adj.迷途的；误入歧途的', '1. The first thing we did was look for errors in our experimental design and for every conceivable scenario that could have led us astray. 我们的第一个动作是寻找的实验设计哪里出了差错，并想遍每一种可能让我们误入歧途的状况。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scrap', '[skræp]', 'n.碎片；废品；少许；瘦小的人；争斗；打架 v.报废；舍弃；打架', '1. They wrote messages to each other on scraps of paper. 他们用一些碎纸片互传信息。 2. The cars have been broken down for scraps. 那些汽车已经拆掉当废铁。 3. It won\'t make a scrap of difference. 这不会有丝毫的差别。 4. There is not a scrap of truth in what he has said. 他说的话没有半点是真的。 5. I\'ll soon have to scrap this lawn mower,it\'s beyond repair and on its last legs. 不久将不得不把我这台割草机废弃掉，因它已不能修理，即将报废了。', '名词: scrapper 过去式: scrapped 过去分词: scrapped 现在分词: scrapping 第三人称单数: scraps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impugn', '[ɪm\'pjuːn]', 'v.责难；抨击；对...表示怀疑', '1. It is they who give the rest of us a smudge on our reputations and impugn our character. 那些人给我们其他人抹了黑，破坏了我们的名声。 2. Nobody can impugn his ability. 没有人对他的能力表示怀疑。', '形容词: impugnable 名词: impugner 过去式: impugned 过去分词: impugned 现在分词: impugning 第三人称单数: impugns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('viaduct', '[\'vaɪədʌkt]', 'n.高架桥', '1. They shot sequences on the line and at the viaduct. 他们拍了在高架桥和在普通线路上的片断。 2. An overhead road for cars or trains is called a viaduct. 在公路上有高架桥供火车和汽车通过。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assay', '[ə\'seɪ]', 'n.化验；分析 v.化验；分析', '1. Do not cross you or go to a hospital assay. 不过你还是去医院化验一下吧。 2. The assay result of that material is rich in iron. 化验结果表明那种物质含铁量丰富。 3. They made an assay of the contents. 他们对内容进行了全方位的分析。 4. When they assay the ore, they found that they had discovered a very rich vein. 在对矿石进行分析后才知道，原来他们找到的是一个非常富的矿脉。 5. Do not cross you or go to a hospital assay. 不过你还是去医院化验一下吧。', '形容词: assayable 名词: assayer 过去式: assayed 过去分词: assayed 现在分词: assaying 第三人称单数: assays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plumber', '[\'plʌmər]', 'n.管道工', '1. He is an apprentice plumber. 他是个见习水管工人。 2. The plumber went down to the cellar to fix the leaky pipe. 管道工到地下室去修漏水的管子。 3. We had to call a plumber to unblock the drains. 我们得叫管道工来通一通下水道。 4. The plumber stowed all his gear in a canvas bag. 管子工把他所有的工具都装进一只帆布袋里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seafaring', '[\'siːferɪŋ]', 'adj.航海的；跟航海有关的 n.海上航行', '1. Britain has always been a seafaring nation. 英国一直是一个航海的民族。 2. He had sole jurisdiction in maritime and seafaring causes. 他对海商案件拥有专属管辖权。 3. Owing to the development of seafaring, there are so many idioms relative to the voyage emerged. 航海业的发展使得英语中出现了大量与航海有关的习语。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rival', '[\'raɪvl]', 'n.竞争者；对手；同伴 adj.竞争的 v.竞争；与 ... 相匹敌', '1. He is hound out of his job by jealous rival. 他受到忌妒他的竞争者的算计而被迫离职。 2. The party leader has been supplanted by his rival. 那位政党领导已被他的对手取而代之了。 3. He was utterly unscrupulous in his competition with rival firms. 他与对立公司竞争完全不讲道德。 4. Ships can\'t rival aircraft for speed. 轮船在速度方面无法与飞机匹敌。', '过去式: rivaled/rivalled 过去分词: rivaled/rivalled 现在分词: rivaling/rivalling 第三人称单数: rivals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('artifact', '[\'ɑrtəˌfækt]', 'n.人工制品；典型产物；【医】非源自脑中的电波，伪差，假象，人为现象', '1. In the wrong hands this powerful artifact has the ability to unravel the soul. 在错误手这强有力的人工制品有能力解开灵魂。 2. A user interface is an artifact, not directly associated with the goals of a user. 用户界面是人造的，并非直接和用户的目标相关。 3. Working code is the single most important artifact. 工作代码是一个最重要的工件。', '形容词: artifactual');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('paleontology', '[ˌpeɪlɪɒn\'tɒlədʒɪ]', 'n.古生物学', '1. He visited the paleontology museum today. 他今天去参观了古生物博物馆。 2. This is big news in the paleontology field, and will re-write Earth-life history. 这项消息是全球古生物学界的大消息，势将改写地球生命史。', '形容词: paleontologic 名词: paleontologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cypress', '[\'saɪprəs]', 'n.丝柏；丝柏木', '1. Nor shady cypress tree. 也无须柏树来荫覆。 2. Cypress branches used as a symbol of mourning. 柏枝作为悲哀象征的柏树枝 3. This cypress is tall and thin. 这棵柏树又高又细。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illegible', '[ɪ\'ledʒəbl]', 'adj.难辨认的；(字迹)模糊的', '1. The lettering on the gravestone was badly worn and almost illegible. 墓碑上的文字已严重磨损难以辨认。 2. Her signature was an illegible scrawl. 她的签字潦草难辩。 3. The writing is illegible; I cannot read what it says. 字迹不清楚，我看不清上面写的是什么。', '副词: illegibly 名词: illegibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('redundant', '[rɪ\'dʌndənt]', 'adj.多余的，过多的；累赘的，冗长的；解雇的；重复的，千篇一律的', '1. Skill has been made redundant by machine. 由于使用机器，手艺已变得多余。 2. This word is redundant, it can be left out. 这个字是多余的, 可以去掉。 3. There are too many redundant words in this book. 这本书里多余的词太多。', '副词: redundantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('predilection', '[ˌpredl\'ekʃn]', 'n.偏好；袒护', '1. He has a predilection for rich food. 他偏好油腻的食物。 2. Predilection towards children is conniving them, which is adverse for their growth. 袒护孩子等于纵容孩子,这样做不利于孩子的成长。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('specialized', '[\'speʃəlaɪzd]', 'adj.专门的；专科的 动词specialize的过去式和过去分词.', '1. Both games require strength and specialized skills. 两者都要求力量强度和专门的运动技巧。 2. How much experience does he bring to this specialized work? 他使用了多少经验来干这项专业工作？ 3. Specialized knowledge is sometimes more valuable than general knowledge. 专科知识有时比常识更有价值。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forbearance', '[fɔːr\'berəns]', 'n.节制；克制；容忍；〈法律〉债务偿还期的延展', '1. He acted with forbearance toward the hecklers. 他对质问者表现出极大的克制。 2. We\'ve always taken an attitude of forbearance. 我们一向采取克制态度。 3. I have shown enough forbearance toward him. 我已经对他很有耐心了。 4. He exercises forbearance in dealing with people. 他宽以待人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hiss', '[hɪs]', 'n.嘘声；嘶嘶声 v.发出嘘声（表示不满）；发嘶嘶声', '1. However, they occasionally snort, hiss, or bark. 不过哑天鹅偶尔会发出呼哧声，嘘声，或吼声。 2. With a sibilant hiss, the Things began to move. 藉由一声丝丝作声的嘘声，事物开始移动。 3. When hearing the snake hiss, I felt creepy. 听见蛇的嘶嘶声，我感到毛骨悚然。 4. The hiss came from an open comms line. 的嘶嘶声来自一个开放的通信线。 5. Even if you don\'t like one of the players you should not boo and hiss at them. 即使是你不喜欢其中的一个球员，你不应该对他们发出嘘声。', '副词: hissingly 名词: hisser 过去式: hissed 过去分词: hissed 现在分词: hissing 第三人称单数: hisses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spectator', '[\'spekteɪtər]', 'n.观众；旁观者', '1. Baseball is largely a spectator sport. 棒球在很大程度上是一种观众型运动。 2. Many a spectator poured down the street to the football ground. 许多观众沿街向足球场走去。 3. Hanlei looks at the world as a spectator, waiting. 韩磊以一个旁观者的身份观察世界,他善于等待。 4. It is the spectator, and not life, that art really mirrors. 艺术所真正要反映的是旁观者，而不是生活。', '形容词: spectatorial 名词: spectatorship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lament', '[lə\'ment]', 'n.悲叹；悼词 v.哀悼；惋惜；悲叹', '1. It is the lament of an impoverished peasant. 它是一个已贫穷化的农民的哀词。 2. This poem can be characterized as a lament for a dead lover. 这首诗可以看作是对死去情人的悼词。 3. The children lament the death of their mother. 孩子们哀悼母亲的去世。 4. She lament her son\'s death all night. 她整夜为儿子之死而悲伤。', '名词: lamenter 过去式: lamented 过去分词: lamented 现在分词: lamenting 第三人称单数: laments 形容词: lamenting 副词: lamentingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overwrought', '[ˌoʊvər\'rɔːt]', 'adj.过分劳累的；过度兴奋的；过分紧张的', '1. And usually what they\'re feeling is something rather shrill and overwrought. 而且通常他们所正在感觉的是相当尖锐的事物而且过度工作。 2. She was in a very overwrought state after the accident. 事故发生后她精神十分紧张。 3. She didn\'t mean to offend you, she was only overwrought. 她无意得罪你，她是情绪不好。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('genuflect', '[\'dʒenjuflekt]', 'v.屈膝；跪拜(尤指做宗教仪式时)；屈从', '1. Be true A?Everybody helped, genuflect withers! 是不是真的吖?各位帮帮忙了,跪谢! 2. Genuflect begs leukaemia to treat a method! 跪求白血病治疗方法! 3. What good method can treat pouch. . Genuflect is begged solve. . . 有甚么好方法能够治疗眼袋。。跪求解答... 4. Genuflect begs department of gynaecology, mom is ill. 跪求妇科;妈妈病了.', '名词: genuflection 过去式: genuflected 过去分词: genuflected 现在分词: genuflecting 第三人称单数: genuflects');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mighty', '[\'maɪti]', 'adj.强大的；巨大的 adv.很；极其', '1. The United Kingdom was a mighty empire before World War I. 英联邦在第一次世界大战前曾是一个强大的帝国。 2. The mighty empire finally crumbled. 这个强大的帝国最终瓦解了。 3. The mighty iceberg came into view. 巨大的冰山出现在眼前。 4. A mighty force was about to break loose. 一股巨大的力量即将迸发而出。 5. He was mighty hungry. 他肚子很饿。', '比较级: mightier 最高级: mightiest 名词: mightiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('munition', '[mjuː\'nɪʃn]', 'adj.军火的 (复)munitions：. n.军火；军需品', '1. She even induced Winston to mortgage yet another of his evenings by enrolling himself for the part-time munition work which was done voluntarily by zealous Party members. 她甚至说服温斯顿，献出他一个晚上，参加热心的党员制造军火的义务献工。', '过去式: munitioned 过去分词: munitioned 现在分词: munitioning 第三人称单数: munitions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rostrum', '[\'rɑːstrəm]', 'n.演讲坛；喙形船首；[生]喙；吻突', '1. He mounted the rostrum in vigorous strides. 他健步登上演讲台。 2. He was cheered as he got on the rostrum. 他走上主席台时受到群众的欢呼。 3. It grasps its victim in its forelegs and pierce it with its rostrum. 它用前腿抓住牺牲品，把喙刺入对方身体。', '形容词: rostral 名词复数: rostrums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('complaisant', '[kəm\'pleɪzənt]', 'adj.殷勤的；顺从的；彬彬有礼的', '1. A good servant should be complaisant but not servile. 一个好的仆人应该是殷勤的，而不是卑屈的。', '副词: complaisantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('veil', '[veɪl]', 'n.面纱；面罩；掩饰物 vt.使戴面纱；遮蔽 vi.戴面纱', '1. The bride\'s face was covered in a white veil. 新娘的脸上蒙著白色的面纱。 2. Most Moslem women wear veils in public places. 大多数穆斯林妇女在公共场所都戴着面纱。 3. Rochester assures her it is only a bad dream, but in the morning Jane finds the ripped fragments of the veil. 罗切斯特安慰她说这只是一个恶梦，但清晨简却发现了被撕破的婚纱碎片。 4. Her face was buried behind a veil. 她的脸被面罩遮起来了。 5. The women there used to veil their faces in public. 那里的妇女过去在公共场合通常戴面纱。 6. The women there used to veil their faces in public. 那里的妇女过去在公共场合通常戴面纱。', '过去式: veiled 过去分词: veiled 现在分词: veiling 第三人称单数: veils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('douse', '[daʊs]', 'v.浸入；浇灭；泼水；熄灭', '1. The car was doused in petrol and set alight. 这辆汽车被浇上汽油点燃了。 2. He doused the flames with a fire extinguisher. 他用灭火器把火焰扑灭。', '名词: douser');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preamble', '[pri\'æmbl]', 'n.前文；序文；前言', '1. He spoke without preamble. 他没有开场白地讲起来。 2. He launched into his statement without any preamble. 他开门见山地发表言论。 3. The aims of the treaty are stated in its preamble. 条约的宗旨已在序言中说明。 4. Museum stills from the preamble, stills, introduced the story of three parts. 剧照馆由前言、剧照、剧情介绍三部分组成。', '形容词: preambulary');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resignation', '[ˌrezɪɡ\'neɪʃn]', 'n.辞职；辞呈；顺从', '1. Her resignation caused much public debate. 她辞职一事引起群众议论纷纷。 2. His resignation is a measure of how angry he is. 从他辞职一事可见其气愤的程度。 3. The revelation of his scandalous past led to his resignation. 他那不光彩历史的揭露导致了他的辞职。 4. We haven\'t yet received his resignation. 我们尚未收到他的辞呈。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antagonism', '[æn\'tæɡənɪzəm]', 'n.对抗；对立；敌对状态（行为）', '1. It may be regarded as an example of antagonism. 这可看作是对抗效应。 2. They tolerated their new neighbors, there was no antagonism. 他们对他们的新邻居很容忍，所以没有产生任何对抗状态。 3. You could sense the antagonism between them. 你能觉察出他们之间有对立情绪。 4. Let us examine both sides of this antagonism. 让我们来看看这种对立的两个方面吧。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alimentary', '[ælɪ\'mentərɪ]', 'adj.食物及消化的；营养的；供养的', '1. He had the disease of alimentary canal. 他患了消化道疾病。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yoke', '[joʊk]', 'n.轭；轭状物；共轭牛；束缚；纽带；（女）上衣抵肩、裙腰 vt.把 ... 套上轭；使结合；使成配偶 vi.紧密联结', '1. An ass and an ox, fastened to the same yoke, were drawing a wagon. 驴子和公牛一起套在轭上拉车。 2. The plow was pulled by a yoke of oxen. 一对公牛同轭拉着一头犁。 3. Slaves are under the yoke of their masters. 奴隶们受其主人的束缚。 4. He had got his neck out of the yoke of matrimony. 他已经摆脱了婚姻的枷锁。 5. Every farmer knows how to yoke the oxen together. 每个农民都知道怎样把牛拴在一起。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('breadth', '[bredθ]', 'n.宽度', '1. The length of the table is twice its breadth. 桌子的长度是它的宽度的两倍。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('botch', '[bɑːtʃ]', 'v.拙笨地修补；糟蹋 n.拙笨的修补；难看的补缀', '1. The mechanic tried to repair my car,but he really botched it up. 那个技工想把我的汽车修好，可是他一修更糟了。 2. I\'m afraid the unexpected accident may botch up the dinner tonight. 恐怕这意想不到的事故会把今天的晚宴搞糟。 3. You\'ve probably made a botch-up of repairing the computer. 你好象把这电脑越修越糟。', '形容词: botchy 名词: botcher 过去式: botched 过去分词: botched 现在分词: botching 第三人称单数: botches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mournful', '[\'mɔːrnfl]', 'adj.悲恸的；悲哀的；令人惋惜的', '1. She was mournful for the whole of the day. 她悲恸终日。 2. He looks mournful. 他看上去神色悲哀。 3. He took a mournful view on human affairs. 他对人世持悲观的态度。 4. He sang a mournful song at her funeral. 在她的葬礼上他唱起了一首忧伤的歌。', '副词: mournfully 名词: mournfulness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harden', '[\'hɑːrdn]', 'v.(使)变硬；(使)坚强', '1. They harden clay by putting it in a fire. 他们把粘土坯放在炉火里使其变硬。 2. The varnish takes a few minutes to harden. 清漆几分钟就能变硬。 3. Missus Lederer later said that one Sun-Times editor helped her harden herself to those stories. 莱德尔太太后来说，有一位晨报的编辑帮助她，让她面对这些信件而变得坚强。 4. Hardship can harden your will. 艰难困苦可以使你意志坚强。', '过去式: hardened 过去分词: hardened 现在分词: hardening 第三人称单数: hardens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('duct', '[dʌkt]', 'n.管道；导管 vt.用导管输送', '1. One of the air-ducts has become blocked. 有一条输气管堵塞了。 2. Air is heated and then circulated through large ducts to all parts of the house. 空气被加热，然后通过大的管道传送到房间的各个角落。 3. In the center is a duct lined by carcinoma cells. 中央为有癌细胞排列于其中的导管。 4. Remove the defroster duct from the instrument panel. 从仪表板上拆下除霜器导管。 5. They duct the moist air away. 他们用管道排除湿气。', '形容词: ductal 过去式: ducted 过去分词: ducted 现在分词: ducting 第三人称单数: ducts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('faze', '[feɪz]', 'v.使担忧；使慌乱；使为难或紧张', '1. The news did not faze him. 这个消息并没有使他担心。 2. Nothing they say could faze him. 他们说什麽都烦扰不了他。', '过去式: fazed 过去分词: fazed 现在分词: fazing 第三人称单数: fazes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enclosure', '[ɪn\'kloʊʒər]', 'n.附件；围墙；围绕', '1. Please see enclosure for details. 详细资料请看附件! 2. I received your enclosure with gratitude. 附件收到, 十分感谢。 3. There are several enclosures in the envelope. 信封内装有几份附件。 4. She keeps a horse in that enclosure. 她在那个围栏里养了一匹马。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disregard', '[ˌdɪsrɪ\'ɡɑːrd]', 'vt.不顾；忽视 n.漠视；不理会', '1. We cannot disregard his coming late to work so often. 对他上班经常迟到,我们不能不管。 2. He doesn\'t disregard the footnotes. 他并没有不注意脚注。 3. He disregarded his doctor\'s advice. 他无视医生的劝告。 4. You can\'t just disregard the security problem. 你可不能忽视安全问题。 5. The official has shown a total disregard for the needs of the poor. 这个官员对穷人的需求表现出完全漠视的态度。', '形容词: disregardful 名词: disregarder 过去式: disregarded 过去分词: disregarded 现在分词: disregarding 第三人称单数: disregards');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dearth', '[dɜːrθ]', 'n.缺乏；粮食不足', '1. There was a dearth of reliable information on the subject. 关于这个课题还缺乏可靠资料。 2. There seems to be a dearth of good young players at the moment. 目前似乎好的年轻选手太少了。 3. Many soldiers died because of dearth of food. 很多士兵因为缺少粮食死去。 4. A dearth of corn caused the prices to go up. 谷物匮乏造成价格上涨。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glower', '[\'ɡlaʊər]', 'v.怒目而视 n.怒视', '1. He sat glowering at his opponent. 他坐在那里怒视著对手。 2. They do not fright, but just stand and glower each other. 他们没有打架，只是站在那里互相怒目而视。', '副词: gloweringly 过去式: glowered 过去分词: glowered 现在分词: glowering 第三人称单数: glowers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('natation', '[neɪ\'teɪʃən]', 'n.游泳；游泳技术', '1. J’aime bien la natation, mais je n’aime pas le volley-ball. 我很喜欢游泳，但是不喜欢排球。 2. The founding of the Fd ration Internationale de Natation (FINA) in 1908 was a pragmatic response to an increase in international sporting events, crowned by the Olympic Games. 20世纪初，国际性的体育运动会日渐增多，而奥运会的出现则使这一趋势达到顶峰。正是在这个时期，国际游泳联合会（简称“国际泳联”）于1908成立。在1896年首届现代奥运会上设置了3个游泳比赛项目。 3. Federation Internationale de Natation Amateur 国际业余游泳联合会 4. Faire les excises san relache,natation,yoga,courir,si un peu plus de temps,danser avec des amis。Enlever la mauvais habitude parresse,elever le rendement du travail, 1坚持锻炼，游泳俞加跑步，有空就和朋友一起跳舞。要改掉拖延的毛病，提高做事效率，规划管理自己的时间和生活。做个身心平衡的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('script', '[skrɪpt]', 'n.剧本；脚本；手稿；手迹；字体；考卷', '1. The script won\'t play well. 那个剧本不适于在舞台上演出。 2. If the trust is verified, the script runs. 如果确定可信,则会运行该脚本。 3. The truthfulness of the script is undoubtable. 手稿的真实性是毋庸置疑的。 4. Sanskrit historically has had no single script associated with it. 梵语，从历史上看，没有单一的手稿与它联合起来。', '过去式: scripted 过去分词: scripted 现在分词: scripting 第三人称单数: scripts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('murmur', '[\'mɜːrmər]', 'v.低语；发出连续轻柔的声音；低声抱怨 n.低语；连续轻柔的声音；低声的抱怨；[医]心区杂音', '1. Some of the sailors began to murmur about it bringing bad luck. 一些水手开始低声说这带来了噩运。 2. The old man drooped his head and began to murmur to himself my father\'s name. 老人低下头，低声念叨我父亲的名字。 3. The breeze murmured in the pines. 松林里微风沙沙作响。 4. The little stream murmured at the foot of the hill. 小溪在山脚下潺潺流动。 5. The murmur swelled into a roar. 窃窃私语的声音变大形成一片喧哗。', '形容词: murmurous 副词: murmuringly 名词: murmurer 过去式: murmured 过去分词: murmured 现在分词: murmuring 第三人称单数: murmurs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rigid', '[\'rɪdʒɪd]', 'adj.坚硬的；严格的；固执的；僵硬的；刻板的', '1. The tent has a rigid support. 帐篷有一个坚硬的支柱。 2. He is a man of very rigid principles. 他是一个原则性很强的人。 3. He\'s very rigid in his ideas. 他的想法非常固执。 4. She was rigid with fear. 她害怕得全身僵住了。', '副词: rigidly 名词: rigidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glance', '[ɡlæns]', 'v.扫视；匆匆一看；一瞥；反光；闪烁；掠过 n.一瞥；扫视', '1. She glanced round the room before she left. 她略微环视了一下房间才离开。 2. I\'m just going to glance over these documents, then we can go. 我再看一下这些文件，然后我们就可以走了。 3. On the bus I always manage to glance at the headline in the newspaper. 在公共汽车上我总能设法匆匆看一眼报纸大标题。 4. He glanced at the envelope and recognized his uncle\'s handwriting. 他瞥了一眼那个信封,认出是他叔父的笔迹。 5. He gave her an admiring glance. 他向她投以敬慕的一瞥。', '过去式: glanced 过去分词: glanced 现在分词: glancing 第三人称单数: glances');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cabal', '[kə\'bæl]', 'n.(尤指政治上的)阴谋；阴谋集团；秘密结社 v.密谋策划', '1. Next is the role of Cabal Online. 接下来是黑色阴谋的角色。 2. They are stories of conspiracy, of America being hijacked by an evil cabal. 像一个阴谋故事，故事里说美国人被邪恶的政治集团揩了油。 3. And Fabricio counter-attacked, accusing his brother of harboring a “pinkish” cabal of sycophantic aides. 同时,法布里西奥发起反击,指责其弟纵容谄媚之人、包庇阴谋集团。 4. A cabal of Appalachian district directors will undertake a palace revolution. 阿巴拉契山脉地区的一小撮头面人物正企图谋反。', '过去式: caballed 过去分词: caballed 现在分词: caballing 第三人称单数: cabals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marginal', '[\'mɑːrdʒɪnl]', 'adj.边际的；末端的；仅以微弱多数获胜的；微小的', '1. Economists call these marginal changes. 经济学家称这些为边际的变化。 2. The marginal illustration is very interesting. 页边的插图很有趣。 3. He won the most marginal seat by only two votes. 他只以两票的微弱优势当选。 4. He had a very marginal victory with only 180 more votes in his favor. 他仅以180票的微弱优势赢得了胜利。', '副词: marginally 名词: marginality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pliable', '[\'plaɪəbl]', 'adj.易曲折的；柔软的；圆滑的', '1. These tubes are lightweight, soft and pliable. 这些管子重量轻，柔软易弯曲。', '副词: pliably 名词: pliability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('founder', '[\'faʊndər]', 'n.创立者 v.摔倒；失败；沉没；弄跛', '1. He is the founder of the party. 他是该党的创建者。 2. He was the founder of this society. 他是这一团体的创立者。 3. For a while it looked as if their scheme would founder. 一时间，他们的计划眼看要落空了。 4. But the boat-swain protesting to him, that if he did not, the ship would founder, he consented 但水手长抗议说,如果船长不同意砍掉前桅,船就会沉没。这样,船长也只好答应了。', '过去式: foundered 过去分词: foundered 现在分词: foundering 第三人称单数: founders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gnat', '[næt]', 'n.蠓虫；蚊；蚋；琐事', '1. There is a gnat bite on my hand. 我的手上有个小虫叮的包。 2. You need not sing to me like a gnat to profound that question. 你用不着象蚊子那样哼哼唧唧地提出这个问题。 3. Then a single gnat got into his ear and stung him. 然后，一只小蚊蚋跳进他的耳朵，蜇了他。 4. He\'s always straining at a gnat. 他总是对小事很拘谨。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nugatory', '[\'nuːɡətɔːri]', 'adj.无价值的；无效的；无关紧要的', '1. In determining the question whether or not an appeal would be rendered nugatory, the court must of course first have regard to the nature of the order that is the subject matter of the appeal. 即是说法庭会考虑的问题会包括：如果不暂缓执行，会否使上诉变得没有意义。例如，付了钱给对方，但上诉成功之时，对方已没有能力还钱。 2. a nugatory idea, argument, proposal, etc 无意义的想法﹑ 争论﹑ 建议等. 3. Don\'t waste time to do such nugatory things. 不要为这种琐事浪费时间。 4. With so little life left in the government, the cost to the careers of Labour mutineers would be nugatory; 能呆在政府里的时间也就只有那么点了，工党哗变者的事业成本没有多少价值；', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cemetery', '[\'seməteri]', 'n.墓地', '1. He was buried in this cemetery. 他被安葬在这个公墓里。 2. They buried the urn in the cemetery. 他们将骨灰瓮埋在了公墓里。 3. His remains were shipped back and laid away in a cemetery. 他的遗体被运回，埋葬在一个公墓里。', '名词复数: cemeteries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demystify', '[ˌdiː\'mɪstɪfaɪ]', 'vt.使非神秘化', '1. We are trying to demystify the workings of government. 我们要尽量使政府工作公开化。', '名词: demystification 过去式: demystified 过去分词: demystified 现在分词: demystifying 第三人称单数: demystifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('serenade', '[ˌserə\'neɪd]', 'n.小夜曲 v.为 ... 弹奏或歌唱小夜曲；演奏小夜曲', '1. Here is a song, a serenade to you. 这是我唱给你的一首小夜曲。 2. I never tire of listening to this serenade. 这支小夜曲我听多少遍也不觉得厌烦。 3. I use my guitar to serenade my girlfriend every Friday night. 每个星期五的晚上，我都弹着我的吉他为的女朋友唱情歌。 4. Birds high up on the trees , serenade the clouds with their melodies . 鸟儿高处在树上，对著云儿唱著他们的情歌。', '名词: serenader 过去式: serenaded 过去分词: serenaded 现在分词: serenading 第三人称单数: serenades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gaseous', '[\'ɡæsiəs]', 'adj.气体的；气态的；似气体的；无实质的', '1. The lamp is full of gaseous nitrogen. 灯里充满了气体氮。 2. The ball is filled with gaseous mixture. 那个球充满了气体混合物。 3. Steam is water is the gaseous state. 蒸汽是气态的水。 4. Air whether in the gaseous or liquid state is a fluid. 空气，无论是气态的还是液态的，都是一种流体。', '名词: gaseousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mold', '[moʊld]', 'n.模式；类型；模子；模型；真菌；软土 vt.形成；制模；发霉 vi.发霉；符合形状', '1. Pictures help you to form the mental mold. 想象有助于你形成思想模式。 2. Chiefly the mold of a man\'s fortune is in his own hands. 一个人的命运模式主要是由自己决定的。 3. We need more people of his mold. 我们需要更多他那种类型的人。 4. And then you put them in a mold. 然后把它们放到一个模子里。 5. West culture has been molded by the Bible. 西方文化的形成受到《圣经》的巨大影响。 6. The cheese molded in the damp cellar. 乳酪在潮湿的地下室中长了霉。', '形容词: moldable 名词: molder 过去式: molded 过去分词: molded 现在分词: molding 第三人称单数: molds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cell', '[sel]', 'n.单人牢房；小房间；细胞；蜂房的巢室；电池；政治小组；(计算机电子表格的)单元格；<美口>手机', '1. The prisoner was locked in a cell. 那囚犯被关在单人牢房内。 2. She was found prostrate on the floor of the cell. 有人发现她趴在小屋的地板上。 3. The cancer cell may invade other parts of the body. 癌细胞可能侵袭身体的其他部分。 4. There is a queen bee in the cell. 蜂房里有一只蜂王。', '过去式: celled 过去分词: celled 现在分词: celling 第三人称单数: cells');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('access', '[\'ækses]', 'n.入口；通道 n.接近(的机会)；使用之权 vt.进入；(电脑)存取', '1. This is the only means of access to the building. 这是进入这栋楼的唯一入口。 2. The avalanche cut off the access to the mountain village. 雪崩切断了进入山村的通道。 3. The only access to that building is along the track. 到那座大楼的唯一通道就是沿这条小路走。 4. Only high officials have access to the president. 只有高级官员才可以接近总统。 5. An error occurred when we tried to access the inventory database. 当我们试图进入存货数据库时，屏幕上显示出现了错误。', '过去式: accessed 过去分词: accessed 现在分词: accessing 第三人称单数: accesses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('niggling', '[\'nɪɡlɪŋ]', 'adj.琐碎的；费神的 n.琐碎 动词niggle的现在分词形式.', '1. I work hard and I always train even if I\'ve got a niggling injury. 我很努力，即便有点小伤也还坚持训练。 2. I don\'t see why they should be niggling over paying a few pounds into the fund. 我不明白他们为什么对这笔基金投入几镑钱而如此在乎。', '副词: nigglingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proscenium', '[prə\'siːniəm]', 'n.舞台前部；幕前部分', '1. In theaters, the loft is the area above and Behind the proscenium. 剧场里的阁楼是在台口上面和后面的区域。 2. He seems to bring his armchair to the proscenium and chat with us in all the lusty ease of his fine English. 他好象搬了一张扶手椅,坐在舞台前部,用他明快有力的英语,娓娓动人地跟我们闲谈。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expiration', '[ˌekspə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.终止；期满；呼出；呼气', '1. This Contract shall be terminated on the expiration date. 劳动合同期满，即行终止。 2. A contract subject to a time of expiration is extinguished at such time. 附终止期限的合同，自期限届满时失效。 3. The expiration of contract is coming. 合同快到期了。 4. When is the expiration of your driving license? 你的驾驶执照何时到期？', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dogged', '[\'dɔːɡɪd]', 'adj.顽固的；顽强的 动词dog的过去式和过去分词.', '1. His dogged pursuit of the presidency was turning into a national joke. 他执拗地谋求总统职位的行为变成了全国的笑柄。 2. He did it with dogged determination. 他以顽强的决心做了这件事。 3. They are met with dogged resistances. 他们遭受到顽强的抵抗. 4. Although he\'s less talented, he won by sheer dogged persistence. 他虽天赋不高，但全凭坚韧的毅力赢得了胜利。', '副词: doggedly 名词: doggedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clip', '[klɪp]', 'vt.夹住 v.剪短 v.疾驰；猛击 n.夹子；弹夹；回形针；钳 n.修剪；(羊毛的)剪下量；(被剪下的)东西', '1. Do you clip those ear-rings on/Do those ear-rings clip on 你的[这种]耳环是夹上去的吗? 2. There was a cheque clipped to the back of the letter. 在信背面夹着一张支票。 3. The dog\'s fur was clipped short for the show. 为参加狗展狗的毛剪短了。 4. A horse is clipping down the road. 一匹马正沿路奔驰。 5. Winston stroked his nose gently with a paper clip. 温斯顿用一个纸夹子轻轻地擦着鼻子。 6. He gave the sheep a close clip. 他把羊的毛剪得很短。', '过去式: clipped 过去分词: clipped 现在分词: clipping 第三人称单数: clips');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('allowance', '[ə\'laʊəns]', 'n.零用钱；津贴；限额，定量；允许；折扣；考虑', '1. I didn\'t receive any allowance from my father. 我没有收到父亲给的零用钱。 2. I have to work to earn my allowance. 我非得工作挣零用钱。 3. She receives a monthly allowance of $500. 她每月收到500美元的津贴。 4. Your baggage allowance is 75 pounds. 你行李的重量限额是七十五英镑。', '过去式: allowanced 过去分词: allowanced 现在分词: allowancing 第三人称单数: allowances');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('even', '[\'iːvn]', 'adj.平坦的；平和的；偶数的；相等的 adv.甚至；正当；更；恰好 v.使平坦；相等', '1. A billiard-table must be perfectly even. 台球桌必须十分平. 2. He spoke lightly in even tones. 他以平和的语调温和地讲话。 3. Cars with license plates ending in even numbers must go in this way. 牌照以偶数结尾的汽车必须走这条路。 4. He has an even chance of success. 他成败的机会参半。 5. He didn\'t even have the decency to show me the way. 他甚至连指点我路的礼貌也没有。 6. The path ran steeply up the hill and then evened out. 这条路很陡，到山上就平坦了。', '副词: evenly 名词: evener 过去式: evened 过去分词: evened 现在分词: evening 第三人称单数: evens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spoor', '[spʊr]', 'n.(野兽的)足迹或臭迹 v.跟踪', '1. The hounds followed the fox\'s spoor. 猎人跟踪了这条狐狸的足迹。', '过去式: spoored 过去分词: spoored 现在分词: spooring 第三人称单数: spoors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('feedback', '[\'fiːdbæk]', 'n.反馈；反馈意见', '1. Did you get any feedback from your clients? 你从顾客那儿得到什么反馈了吗? 2. The writer gets no immediate feedback and simply has to imagine the reader\'s reaction. 作者没有得到及时的反馈,只能猜测读者的反应。 3. Try to give each student some feedback on the task. 针对这项作业,尽量给每位学生提出反馈意见。 4. I\'d appreciate some feedback on my work. 如果有人对我的工作提出意见我将感激不尽。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expeditious', '[ˌekspə\'dɪʃəs]', 'adj.〈正式或文〉迅速而有效率的；迅速完成的', '1. Sent the package by the most expeditious means. 以最快速有效的方式送包裹', '副词: expeditiously 名词: expeditiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bump', '[bʌmp]', 'v.碰撞；颠簸而行；提高 n.肿块；撞击；表面隆起 adv.突然的；猛烈的', '1. I\'ve bumped my knee on the wall. 我的膝盖撞上了墙壁。 2. I am so sorry to bump into you. 对不起，我撞到你了。 3. The old bus bumped along the mountain road. 旧公共汽车沿著山路颠簸行驶。 4. We bumped up and down along the gravel path. 我们沿砾石小路颠簸而行。 5. She got a bump on her head. 她头上撞起了一个包。', '过去式: bumped 过去分词: bumped 现在分词: bumping 第三人称单数: bumps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('legerdemain', '[\'ledʒərdəmeɪn]', 'n.手法；戏法；诈术', '1. By a feat of legerdemain , the magician produced a rabbit from his hat. 魔术师利用戏法从帽子里变出一只兔子来。 2. His door stood open to the morning, and he hummed under his breath while his right hand practiced legerdemain. 他的门对着早晨敞开着，他一面轻轻地哼唱，一面他的右手练着戏法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('libel', '[\'laɪbl]', 'n.诽谤的文字；诽谤(罪)；侮辱 v.诽谤；中伤；损害名誉', '1. She sued a newspaper for libel. 她控告某报刊登诽谤性文字。 2. I\'ll sue you for libel. 我要以诽谤罪控告你。 3. His attempt to discredit his opponent boomeranged (on him) when he was charged with libel. 他企图败坏对手名声反而自食其果，被控以诽谤罪。 4. That interview was an absolute libel on the honest man. 那篇报道完全是对那个老实人的侮辱。 5. He libel(l)ed against her character in an article. 他在一篇文章中诽谤她的人格。', '名词: libeler 过去式: libeled/libelled 过去分词: libeled/libelled 现在分词: libeling/libelling 第三人称单数: libels/libels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lampoon', '[læm\'puːn]', 'n.讽刺文章 vt.嘲讽', '1. What is lampoon is we have to rush under the reality, although an adult never lose the imagination drew from childhood. 讽刺的是尽管一个成年人永远不会彻底失去童年时代的想象力,然而不久我们不得不在现实下疲于奔命。 2. His cartoons mercilessly lampooned the leading politicians of the day. 他的讽刺漫画无情地挖苦了当今的政界要人。', '名词: lampooner 过去式: lampooned 过去分词: lampooned 现在分词: lampooning 第三人称单数: lampoons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reproach', '[rɪ\'proʊtʃ]', 'n.责备；耻辱 v.责备；申斥', '1. His reply sounded to me like a reproach. 他的回答在我听来象是责备。 2. Her behaviour was above/beyond reproach. 她的行为是无可指责的。 3. His reply sounded to her like a reproach. 他的回答在她听来像是责备。 4. A coward is a reproach to an army. 懦夫是军队的耻辱。 5. She reproached her husband for having forgotten their wedding anniversary. 她责怪丈夫忘了他们的结婚周年纪念日。', '形容词: reproachable 副词: reproachably 名词: reproachableness 过去式: reproached 过去分词: reproached 现在分词: reproaching 第三人称单数: reproaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overthrow', '[\'oʊvərθroʊ]', 'v.推翻；打倒；颠覆；[体]高投 n.推翻；瓦解；颠覆；[体]高投', '1. They attempted to overthrow the monarch. 他们企图推翻国王。 2. They were plotting the overthrow of the government. 他们正在策划推翻政府。 3. The big Sam absolutely has the strength to overthrow Jerry. 高大的山姆绝对有力量打倒杰瑞。 4. Indeed,the day when this gigantic net is formed will undoubtedly be the day of the complete overthrow of Japanese imperialism. 实际上，日本帝国主义完全打倒之日，必是这个天罗地网大体布成之时。 5. They schemed for the overthrow of the government . 他们阴谋推翻政府。', '过去式: overthrew 过去分词: overthrown 现在分词: overthrowing 第三人称单数: overthrows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('raffle', '[\'ræfl]', 'n.废物；垃圾；抽奖售物 v.以抽彩出售（某物）', '1. Buy lots of raffle tickets and multiply your chances of success. 多买彩票，增加你中奖的机会。 2. After losing my job it was cold comfort to be told I\'d won the office raffle. 我失去工作以后，听说我抽中了公司的奖券，有同画饼。 3. First prize in the raffle is a holiday for two in Paris. 抽奖销售的头奖是两个人到巴黎度假旅游。 4. My luck\'s in I won a new car in a raffle. 我的运气来了－－在有奖抽彩中我得了一辆新汽车。', '名词: raffler');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flounder', '[\'flaʊndər]', 'v.挣扎；踌躇；笨拙而错乱地说或做 n.挣扎；错乱的行动 n.比目鱼；鲽', '1. His flounder in pain and sufferings dying. 他挣扎着在痛苦中死去。 2. They have to flounder in a morassof contradictions. 他们不得不在矛盾重重的困境中挣扎。 3. She could only flounder in the water. 她只能慌乱地在水里挣扎。 4. They have to flounder in a morassof contradictions. 他们不得不在矛盾重重的困境中挣扎。 5. I consider a flounder to be flat. 我以为比目鱼是扁平的。', '名词复数: flounder 过去式: floundered 过去分词: floundered 现在分词: floundering 第三人称单数: flounders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meld', '[meld]', 'v.合并；出示得分的牌 n.合并；摊牌', '1. After meld mother pulls the tablecloth over the table. 饭后，妈妈把桌布蒙在桌子上。', '过去式: melded 过去分词: melded 现在分词: melding 第三人称单数: melds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incarcerate', '[ɪn\'kɑːrsəreɪt]', 'vt.监禁；幽闭', '1. Limits court authority to incarcerate offenders who commit certain drug crimes, break drug treatment rules or violate parole. 限制法院的权力监禁罪犯谁犯下某些毒品犯罪，打破药物治疗的规则或违反假释。', '名词: incarceration 过去式: incarcerated 过去分词: incarcerated 现在分词: incarcerating 第三人称单数: incarcerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('soar', '[sɔːr]', 'vi.翱翔；高飞；猛增；高涨；高耸 n.翱翔；高飞', '1. The eagle can soar without flapping their wings. 老鹰无需振翼就能翱翔。 2. Food prices soar during the cold weather. 这个寒冷的冬季食品价格猛涨。 3. Air pollution will soon soar above safety levels. 空气污染会很快突破安全标准。 4. Finally, the river continued to soar, the priest was merciless floods drowned. 最后，河水继续高涨，神父被无情的洪水淹死了。 5. The soar of trade brings big benefits to the two countries. 贸易的剧增给两国带来了极大的好处。', '副词: soaringly 名词: soarer 过去式: soared 过去分词: soared 现在分词: soaring 第三人称单数: soars');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('haggard', '[\'hæɡərd]', 'adj.憔悴的；野性的 n.野鹰 Haggard. n.哈格德(姓氏)', '1. He looks haggard. 他显得很憔悴。 2. The old lady has a haggard face. 老太太的脸很枯槁。 3. He came out of the hot mill, haggard and worn. 他从闷热的工厂里走出来，形容憔悴，精疲力竭。 4. There was a drawn and haggard look about his eyes. 他的眼睛露出疲劳而又憔悴的神色。', '副词: haggardly 名词: haggardness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sloth', '[sloʊθ]', 'n.树獭；懒惰', '1. Sloths live in trees and move very slowly. 树獭生活在树上而且行动缓慢。 2. He has kept sloth out. 他已经克服了懒惰。 3. Sloth is one of human being\'s weaknesses. 人性的弱点之一是懒惰。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slacken', '[\'slækən]', 'v.使松弛；使缓慢；变弱', '1. We\'re on the last lap, so don\'t slacken! 我们已处最後阶段，可不要松劲啊！ 2. The bonds of traditional family life began to slacken. 传统的家庭生活的纽带开始松弛。 3. There is no reason to believe that this pace will slacken. 没有理由使人们相信这个速度会变慢。 4. The train slackened speed as we approached the station. 当我们快到车站时，火车减慢了速度。', '过去式: slackened 过去分词: slackened 现在分词: slackening 第三人称单数: slackens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('counteract', '[ˌkaʊntər\'ækt]', 'v.抵制；清除；中和；对抗', '1. We must counteract extremism in the party. 我们应该抵制党内的极端主义。 2. They will counteract the effects of his bad influence. 他们要清除他的不良影响。 3. We must try to counteract the present current of anti-government feeling. 我们应该努力消除目前的这股反政府情绪。 4. One way to counteract hard water is by using a water softener. 中和硬水的方法是使用软水剂。', '形容词: counteractive 副词: counteractively 名词: counteraction 过去式: counteracted 过去分词: counteracted 现在分词: counteracting 第三人称单数: counteracts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bustle', '[\'bʌsl]', 'n.喧哗；匆忙；<旧>裙撑；衬垫 v.匆忙；催促', '1. He hated being transplanted from his home in the country to the noise and bustle of life in the city. 他很不喜欢从乡间的居所迁居到了喧闹的城市里。 2. It seems that he enjoys the hustle and bustle of life in the big city. 看起来他似乎很喜欢大城市的热闹繁忙的生活。 3. She is always bustling about the house. 她总是为家务忙个没完。 4. She bustled the children off to school. 她催促孩子们上学去。', '过去式: bustled 过去分词: bustled 现在分词: bustling 第三人称单数: bustles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('horrific', '[hə\'rɪfɪk]', 'adj.可怕的；恐怖的；很不愉快的', '1. He stiffened at the horrific sight. 他看到那恐怖的情景吓呆了。 2. The film showed the most horrific murder scenes. 那部影片有极恐怖的谋杀场面。 3. We had a horrific trip. 我们的旅行糟糕透顶。', '副词: horrifically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swallow', '[\'swɑːloʊ]', 'n.燕子；吞咽；一次吞咽的量 v.忍受；吞下；咽下；轻信；不流露感情；收回', '1. There are many swallows flying in the sky. 天空中有许多燕子。 2. The swallow has made a nest under our eaves. 燕子在我们的屋檐下垒了一个窝。 3. He downed the medicine at one swallow. 他一口便把药全吞下了。 4. Let me take a swallow of beer. 让我喝口啤酒。 5. They can\'t treat me like that; I\'m not going to swallow it. 他们不能这样对待我，我忍不下这口气。', '名词: swallower 过去式: swallowed 过去分词: swallowed 现在分词: swallowing 第三人称单数: swallows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prophetic', '[prə\'fetɪk]', 'adj.预言的；先知的；预示的', '1. His prophetic remarks frightened us. 他那预言性的话吓着了我们。 2. A person considered to be a source of wise counsel or prophetic opinions. 先知被认为具有明智意见或先知见解的人 3. Her early achievements were prophetic of her future greatness. 她早期的成就预示了她日後卓尔不群.', '副词: prophetically 异体字: prophetical 名词: propheticalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overlap', '[ˌoʊvər\'læp]', 'vt.重叠；重复 vi.有重叠部分 n.重叠部分；重复', '1. A fish\'s scales overlap each other. 鱼鳞是一片片上下交叠起来的。 2. You need to overlap the pieces of wood slightly. 你需要把这些木片搭叠起来。 3. These two papers overlap in content. 这两篇论文有交叉的内容。 4. The programme has been so organized that none of the talks overlap. 日程做了精心安排，以使每一讲都没有重复内容。 5. Channel ranges must not overlap. 频道范围不能重叠。 6. There is a small overlap between the two circles. 在这两个圆周有一小部分重叠。', '过去式: overlapped 过去分词: overlapped 现在分词: overlapping 第三人称单数: overlaps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dank', '[dæŋk]', 'adj.阴湿的 n.潮湿；沼泽地', '1. The dark, dank cave gave me the willies. 这阴暗潮湿的山洞使我感到心惊肉跳。 2. The air was so dank that the smoke hung heavily. 空气十分潮湿，所以烟气沉重地悬浮着。 3. The basement in our house is dark and dank, so it is full of mold. 我们家的地下室又暗又潮湿，里面长满了霉。', '副词: dankly 比较级: danker 最高级: dankest 名词: dankness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contrast', '[\'kɑːntræst]', 'n.对比；差别；对照物 v.对比；成对照 n.[计算机] 反差', '1. Black and white shows a striking contrast. 黑和白形成明显的对比。 2. There is a great contrast between good and evil. 善与恶有明显的差别。 3. The little village was a total contrast to San Francisco. 这个小村庄与圣弗朗西斯科形成强烈对照。 4. When you contrast their work records, Julie is clearly more qualified. 对比他们的工作记录,你会发现茱莉更有能力。 5. The microscope image contains contrast effects. 显微镜所成的图像具有反差效应。', '形容词: contrastable 副词: contrastingly 过去式: contrasted 过去分词: contrasted 现在分词: contrasting 第三人称单数: contrasts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('totalitarian', '[toʊˌtælə\'teriən]', 'adj.极权主义的 n.极权主义者', '1. Almost all government adopt totalitarian measures in time of war. 几乎所有的政府在战时都采取极权主义的措施。 2. A totalitarian government often takes basic freedoms away from the citizens. 极权主义国家的政府通常会剥夺公民的基本权利。', '名词: totalitarianism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chortle', '[\'tʃɔːrtl]', 'v.咯咯地笑 n.咯咯的笑', '1. When I told them what had happened to me, they all chortled with mirth. 我把我的事告诉他们以后,他们咯咯地笑起来了。', '名词: chortler 过去式: chortled 过去分词: chortled 现在分词: chortling 第三人称单数: chortles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('logjam', '[\'lɔːɡdʒæm]', 'n.浮木阻塞；僵局 vt.阻塞；妨碍', '1. Israel may be able to help break the logjam in Lebanon too. 以色列或许也能帮忙打破黎巴嫩的僵局。 2. So I realized that she took the initiative to break the logjam! 所以我一下子意识到她是在采取主动打破僵局。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sect', '[sekt]', 'n.宗派；教派', '1. Each religious sect in the town had its own church. 该城每一个宗教教派都有自己的教堂。 2. When he was sixteen he joined a religious sect. 他16岁的时候加入了一个宗教教派。 3. Hundreds are initiated into the sect each year. 每年有好几百人被接纳到这个教派中。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surcharge', '[\'sɜːrtʃɑːrdʒ]', 'n.额外费；装载过多；改值印记 vt.索高价；使超载；盖改值印记', '1. What\'s the surcharge on this express parcel? 这个快邮包裹的额外邮资是多少? 2. We had to pay a surcharge for the extra service. 我们接受了额外服务，被要求需要额外付费。 3. They\'ve surcharged us 10% on the price of the holiday because of a rise in air fares. 因飞机票涨价，他们在度假费用中向我们增收了10%25附加费。 4. The street now is surcharged with cars. 现在大街上挤满了汽车。', '过去式: surcharged 过去分词: surcharged 现在分词: surcharging 第三人称单数: surcharges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stroke', '[stroʊk]', 'n.中风；击打；一笔（画）；意外的运气 v.击打 v.轻抚；奉承', '1. I know a doctor. He is expert in curing stroke. 我认识一个医生,专治中风。 2. He fell the tree with one stroke of the axe. 他一斧头就将树砍倒。 3. It\'s easy to draw a snake. Just one stroke. 画蛇不难,一笔就可以完成拉。 4. It was a stroke of luck that I found you here. 我在这里碰见你真是运气。 5. She stroked the ball cleverly past her opponent. 她巧妙地一击把球打过对手。 6. The cat likes being stroked. 猫喜欢让人抚摸。', '名词: stroker 过去式: stroked 过去分词: stroked 现在分词: stroking 第三人称单数: strokes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('investigate', '[ɪn\'vestɪɡeɪt]', 'v.调查；研究', '1. The police are investigating the murder. 警察正在调查这件谋杀案。 2. We might be able to help you; I\'ll investigate the possibilities. 我们也许能帮助你，我要研究一下这种可能性。', '形容词: investigable 过去式: investigated 过去分词: investigated 现在分词: investigating 第三人称单数: investigates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intransigent', '[ɪn\'trænzɪdʒənt]', 'adj.不妥协性的 n.不妥协的人', '1. They promoted an intransigent revolutionary strategy. 他们采取一种毫不妥协的革命战略。 2. He can be intransigent and pigheaded at times. 他有时候会很固执,寸步不让。 3. The intransigent can be isolated. 不妥协的人就会被孤立。', '副词: intransigently 名词: intransigence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stately', '[\'steɪtli]', 'adj.庄严的；堂皇的；高贵的 adv.庄严地；堂皇地', '1. The stately mansion crested the hill. 庄严的大厦位于山顶。 2. The organ rolled out a stately melody. 风琴奏出庄严的乐曲。 3. Burglars ransacked the stately home. 盗贼洗劫了这所富丽堂皇的住宅。 4. Her gestures and movements were distinguished by a noble and stately grace. 她的举动和姿势也很出色，显示一种高贵和端庄的魅力。 5. Swift and stately she moved away through the dusk. 她迅速而庄严地从暮色中离去。', '比较级: statelier 最高级: stateliest 名词: stateliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deface', '[dɪ\'feɪs]', 'v.损坏外观；污损；涂掉', '1. Don\'t deface library books. 不要污损图书馆的书籍。 2. The wall has been defaced with slogans. 那堵墙因贴有标语而面目全非。', '形容词: defaceable 名词: defacement 过去式: defaced 过去分词: defaced 现在分词: defacing 第三人称单数: defaces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nocturnal', '[nɑːk\'tɜːrnl]', 'adj.在夜间的；（指生物）夜间活动的', '1. Stars are a nocturnal sight. 星星是夜间的景观。 2. Ali was his principal attendant during this nocturnal survey. 阿里陪着他作这次夜间视察。 3. A nocturnal animal hunts its food at night. 夜间活动的动物在夜间猎食。 4. The dormouse is a shy, nocturnal creature. 榛睡鼠是一种在夜间活动的胆小动物。', '副词: nocturnally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coup', '[kuː]', 'n.政变；意外而成功的行动', '1. He pulled off a spectacular coup. 他发动一次政变而获得成功。 2. The party staged a bloodless coup. 该政党发动了一起不流血的政变。 3. It was a major coup for us to get such a prestigious contract. 赢得如此漂亮的合同对我们来说是巨大的成功。', '名词复数: coups');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cuisine', '[kwɪ\'ziːn]', 'n.烹饪；佳肴', '1. Chinese cuisine is very different from European. 中国烹饪与欧洲烹饪有很大区别。 2. I studied Greek cuisine for one year. 我学了一年的希腊菜烹饪法。 3. After that, they might end their day dining in a restaurant that serves Chinese cuisine. 然后他俩可能会去一家中国餐馆吃晚饭，以此来结束一天的活动。 4. The hotel restaurant is noted for its excellent cuisine. 这家旅馆的餐厅以美味佳肴闻名遐迩。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stray', '[streɪ]', 'n.走失的家畜；浪子 adj.迷途的；偏离的 v.迷路；偏离', '1. That cat is a stray that we took in. 那是我们收养的一只走失的猫。 2. We were befriended by a stray dog. 有一只失散的狗和我们很好。 3. A stray bullet hit her in the leg. 一颗流弹击中她的腿部。 4. The streets were empty except for a few stray taxis. 除了偶然可以看到的 几辆出租车外 5. Pound the cows so they don\'t stray. 把这些走失的牛关进待领场，这样它们就不会乱跑了。', '名词: strayer 过去式: strayed 过去分词: strayed 现在分词: straying 第三人称单数: strays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foreshadow', '[fɔːr\'ʃædoʊ]', 'v.预示；预兆', '1. Those dark clouds foreshadow a storm. 那些乌云预示着有一场暴风雨。 2. Their words foreshadow events to come. 他们的话预示了所将要发生的事情。 3. The book then uses this information to foreshadow the direction that future anti-neoplastic therapies will take. 书然后使用这讯息预兆将来的反新生物的治疗将带的指示。', '名词: foreshadower 过去式: foreshadowed 过去分词: foreshadowed 现在分词: foreshadowing 第三人称单数: foreshadows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pulverize', '[\'pʌlvəraɪz]', 'v.磨成粉；粉碎', '1. On other occasions I threatened to pulverize it. 在其他的时刻，我扬言要粉碎它。', '形容词: pulverizable 名词: pulverization 过去式: pulverized 过去分词: pulverized 现在分词: pulverizing 第三人称单数: pulverizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('defendant', '[dɪ\'fendənt]', 'n.被告', '1. The plaintiff accused the defendant of fraud. 原告指控被告欺诈。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coterie', '[\'koʊtəri]', 'n.小圈子；小集团；志同道合的一伙', '1. The name is known to only a small coterie of collectors. 这个名字只有收藏家的小圈子才知道。 2. We three formed a little literary coterie. 我们三人组成一个小文学团体。 3. Helen won\'t bowl with us; she has her own coterie of bowling friends. 海伦不会跟我们打保龄球；她自己有一群打保龄球的朋友。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harrowing', '[\'hæroʊɪŋ]', 'adj.悲痛的；难受的 动词harrow的现在分词形式.', '1. This ground harrows well. 这块地很好耙。 2. The shipwreck was a harrowing experience. 那次船难是一个惨痛的经历。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('funky', '[fʌŋki]', 'adj.新式的；时髦的；<美俚>绝妙的，极好的 adj.惊恐的；霉臭的；（俚）稀奇古怪的', '1. Hey, that\'s a funky car. 嘿！那是一部新式车。 2. On the screen Moxy the cartoon dog in his funky toon room dances in unison. 与此同时，卡通狗莫西也会在屏幕上他那个时髦的桃木屋里随之起舞。 3. This funky bear has soul to spare! 这只胆战心惊的熊精力过剩！ 4. Get your funky socks out of here. 把你的臭袜子拿出去。', '比较级: funkier 最高级: funkiest 名词: funkiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pincers', '[\'pɪnsəz]', 'n.钳子；镊子；螯 名词pincer的复数形式.', '1. He worked with a pair of pincers. 他用一把钳子工作。 2. Crabs have two sharp and large pincers. 螃蟹有两个又大又锋利的钳子。 3. The torso of a drow emerges from the body of a scorpion, but pincers replace the arms. 他们长着蝎子的身体，黑暗精灵的头，臂膀被螯取代。', '异体字: pinchers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imperative', '[ɪm\'perətɪv]', 'adj.紧要的；必要的；祈使的 n.紧要的事；命令；义务；驱使', '1. It is imperative that we make a quick decision. 我们要尽快做出决定。 2. It\'s imperative that you apologize to him immediately. 你必须立即向他道歉。 3. \"Go!\" is in the imperative mood. “Go！”是祈使语气的句子。 4. Survival is our first imperative. 我们当务之急是设法生存下来。', '副词: imperatively 名词: imperativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forbidding', '[fər\'bɪdɪŋ]', 'adj.可怕的；令人反感的；令人生畏的 动词forbid的现在分词形式.', '1. The coast was rocky and forbidding. 这个海岸是多岩石的和险峻的。 2. The house looked dark and forbidding. 这房子黑森森的,令人害怕。 3. That\'s why the chapter is so forbidding. 这是为何这一章圣经令人感到可怕不畅快的原因。 4. She has a forbidding manner , she is slow in making friends. 她有种拒人千里的样子，难于交朋友。', '副词: forbiddingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mechanism', '[\'mekənɪzəm]', 'n.机制；原理 n.结构；机构；机械装置', '1. The WTO provides a mechanism for resolving trade disputes. 世贸组织提供了一种解决贸易争端的机制。 2. The acting mechanism of coating mist polycoagulant is introduced. 介绍了漆雾凝聚剂的作用原理及选择漆雾凝聚剂的方法。 3. Analyzing the velocity and acceleration of the follower based on the Assur-group method and the inversion of the mechanism. 以杆组分析方法为基础，结合转化机构原理及凸轮机构的相对速度理论进行从动件的速度和加速度分析。 4. She studied the mechanisms of the body. 她研究身体的结构。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('determinant', '[dɪ\'tɜːrmɪnənt]', 'n.决定因素；[数]行列式 adj.决定性的', '1. Education is an important determinant of one\'s outlook on life. 教育是一个人人生观的重要决定因素。 2. Cost is not the sole or even primary determinant. 费用并不是唯一或甚至是主要的决定因素。 3. The determinant can be evaluated from the cofactors of any column. 行列式可根据任何一列余因子来求算。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('placebo', '[plə\'siːboʊ]', 'n.安慰剂；安慰话', '1. The placebo has been found to work with a lot of different cases. 人们已发现安慰剂能在很多不同的病例中发挥作用。 2. Does endowment insurance really matter to everyone? Or is it just a placebo? 养老保险对我们真的重要吗？还是只是一种心理安慰？', '名词复数: placebos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rung', '[rʌŋ]', 'n.阶梯；横档；(社会、职业、组织等的)阶层 动词ring的过去分词.', '1. Hold the ladder tightly and move up a rung at a time. 抓紧梯子一级一级地往上爬。 2. Finally, envision yourself climbing the ladder and writing down the pairs of letters that make up each rung. 最后，想像自己正在爬梯子，将构成每对字母的梯级写下来。 3. He put his foot on the bottom rung to keep the ladder steady. 他用脚踩住最底下的横档稳住梯子。 4. \"Get out!\" he exclaimed, lifting his feet to the rung of the chair “滚开！”他大声叫道，提起了双脚，搁在椅子下面的横档上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jurisprudence', '[ˌdʒʊrɪs\'pruːdns]', 'n.法律学；法学体系；判例，判例法', '1. There is natural relationship between philosophy and jurisprudence. 法学与哲学之间存在着天然的亲缘关系。 2. Hobbes is a precursor of modern positivism and analytical jurisprudence. 霍布斯是现代实证主义法学和分析法学的先驱。 3. Human rights don\'t belong to the constitutional jurisprudence,but to moral ethnics. 人权不是宪法学的范畴,而是道德伦理学的范畴。', '形容词: jurisprudential 副词: jurisprudentially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obliterate', '[ə\'blɪtəreɪt]', 'v.涂去；擦去；删除；盖销（邮票等）', '1. Can you obliterate the letters on the edge in this paper with correction fluid? 你能用涂改液涂去这一页边上的这些字母吗？ 2. Don\'t obliterate a file simply because you discovered it to be a bad idea. 不要因为你发现它不好就删除一个文件。', '形容词: obliterative 名词: obliteration 过去式: obliterated 过去分词: obliterated 现在分词: obliterating 第三人称单数: obliterates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insidious', '[ɪn\'sɪdiəs]', 'adj.隐伏的；暗中为害的；阴险的；诱人上当的；（疾病等）不知不觉恶化的', '1. That insidious man bad-mouthed me to almost everyone else. 那个阴险的家伙几乎见人便说我的坏话。 2. Wormtongue\'s insidious advice poisons the mind of good King Theoden. 巧言阴险的谗言毒害了优秀的希优顿王。', '副词: insidiously 名词: insidiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tweak', '[twiːk]', 'v.拧；扭；拉；微调 n.拧；扭；捏；<俚>妙计', '1. He gave the boy\'s ear a painful tweak. 他用力拧了一下那男孩的耳朵。 2. Maybe you should tweak a few sentences before you send in the report. 也许在你递交报告之前应该稍微修改一下句子。 3. She tweaked his ear playfully. 她拧他的耳朵玩儿。 4. Setting up the chat is really easy and you can tweak it to suit you and your audience. 建立聊天确实是容易的，你能捏它适合你和你的观众。', '形容词: tweaky 过去式: tweaked 过去分词: tweaked 现在分词: tweaking 第三人称单数: tweaks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bedraggled', '[bɪ\'dræɡld]', 'adj.全身泥污的；满身湿透的；破旧的；荒废的 动词bedraggle的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. Do you want to see your own sister in such a bedraggled condition? 你愿意看见你的亲妹妹弄得这么一身泥，一身水的吗？ 2. You look like a bedraggled chicken! 睢你像只落汤鸡! 3. Billy came to school in soiled, bedraggled hand-medowns. 比利上学穿的是肮脏破旧的衣服。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('doze', '[doʊz]', 'v.打瞌睡 n.瞌睡', '1. He dozed off during the class. 他上课打瞌睡。 2. He closed his eyes and seemed to doze. 他闭上眼睛，好像在打瞌睡。 3. We couldn\'t help but doze off during his lecture. 他演讲时我们不得不打瞌睡。 4. He fell into a doze. 他打起盹儿来了。', '名词: dozer 过去式: dozed 过去分词: dozed 现在分词: dozing 第三人称单数: dozes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rescind', '[rɪ\'sɪnd]', 'v.废除；取消', '1. The agreement on cultural cooperation between the two countries was rescinded. 两国间的文化合作协定废除了。 2. They accepted his advice and rescinded the original plan. 他们听从了他的劝告，撤销了原计划。', '形容词: rescindable 名词: rescinder 过去式: rescinded 过去分词: rescinded 现在分词: rescinding 第三人称单数: rescinds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aberrant', '[æ\'berənt]', 'adj.脱离正道的；脱离常轨的；变体的；畸变的', '1. Tending to deviate, as from a normal or recognized type; aberrant. 变异的倾向于偏离，如从一个正常的或被承认了的类型; 畸变的', '副词: aberrantly 名词: aberrance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trawl', '[trɔːl]', 'n.拖网；排钩 v.用拖网捕鱼；搜罗；查阅（资料）', '1. In trawl fishing, huge nets are slowly pulled below the water to collect fish. 拖网捕鱼时，巨大的网被缓缓地在水下拉过以捕捉鱼群。 2. But the negotiations , they say , have been more about preserving EU and Norwegian catching rights than letting them trawl for the teeming mackerel in their own seas . 但他们也表示，这次的协商的内容很大程度上商议的是保留欧盟和挪威捕鱼的权利而不是同意让他们在自己的海域内拖网抓捕鲭鱼。 3. Top companies trawl a global talent pool. 顶尖公司网罗全球人才. 4. The internet has made it easy for would -be journalists to trawl information and repackage news . 互联网的出现，使那些自封为记者的人也很容易把搜罗来的信息重新包装成一条条新闻。', '过去式: trawled 过去分词: trawled 现在分词: trawling 第三人称单数: trawls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gripe', '[ɡraɪp]', 'n.抱怨；肠绞痛 v.抱怨；使 ... 痛苦；抓住；掌握', '1. My only gripe about the hotel was the food. 我对这家旅馆唯一不满的是食物。 2. He likes to have a good gripe from time to time. 他时常爱发上一通牢骚. 3. My main gripe is that the heater doesn\'t work in the hotel room. 我最大的抱怨就是旅馆里房间的暖气是坏的。 4. Take medicine when you get gripes. 肚子痛时吃些药。 5. He\'s always griping about people at work. 他老是抱怨共事的人。', '名词: griper 过去式: griped 过去分词: griped 现在分词: griping 第三人称单数: gripes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('miracle', '[\'mɪrəkl]', 'n.奇迹', '1. Her life was saved by a miracle. 她的生命是靠奇迹救活的。 2. The compact disc is a miracle of modern technology. 激光唱片是当代技术的奇葩。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vest', '[vest]', 'n.背心；内衣；汗衫；马甲 vt.授予；使穿衣 vi.穿衣服；(权力、财产等)归于', '1. One button on the vest is loose. 背心上的一粒鈕扣松了。 2. Jimmy is wearing a vest under a coat. 吉米在外套里面穿着一件背心。 3. Then I became aware of his hand drifting lower and suddenly I was wide awake as he stroked my neck and started sliding his hand down my vest top. 接着我意识到他的手向下滑去，当他抚摸着我的脖子并开始将手滑向我的内衣时，我猛地清醒起来。 4. She was dressed only in a vest and underpants. 她只穿了一件汗衫和一条短裤。 5. Parliament is vested with the power of making laws. 国会有立法权.', '过去式: vested 过去分词: vested 现在分词: vesting 第三人称单数: vests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('divergent', '[daɪ\'vɜːdʒənt]', 'adj.分歧的；分开的；偏离的', '1. For the Jazz, the loss produced divergent viewpoints afterward. 失利后的爵士出现了很多有分歧的观点。 2. Not surprisingly, studies that try directly to measure the distributional consequences reach divergent conclusions. 试图直接估量分配结果而导致结论分歧的研究毫不奇怪。', '副词: divergently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('osseous', '[\'ɑːsiəs]', 'adj.骨的；多骨的', '1. He proposed an indicator of osseous development in children. 他提出了一个儿童骨骼发育的指标。 2. Conclusion: The Osseous labyrinth is ossified by endochondral Ossification. 结论：骨迷路的形成是以软骨内成骨的方式进行的。 3. All nonviable tissue, both osseous and soft tissue, should be removed. 所有无活性的组织，包括骨组织和软组织，都应清除。 4. All patients underwent an elective osseous surgical procedure on the forefoot. 所有病人都作了前足的选择性骨手术。', '副词: osseously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mechanical', '[mə\'kænɪkl]', 'adj.机械的；力学的；呆板的', '1. The new car had to be withdrawn from the market because of a mechanical defect. 那种新汽车因有机械缺陷只好撤出市场。 2. They were using a mechanical shovel to clear up the streets. 他们用机械铲土机清理街道。 3. The inhomogeneity of the physical and mechanical characteristics can be considered in these models. 在这些模型中考虑了土的物理和力学的非线性特性。 4. Blinking is a mechanical action of the eyelids. 眨眼是眼睑的无意识动作。', '副词: mechanically 名词: mechanicalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intellectual', '[ˌɪntə\'lektʃuəl]', 'n.凭理智做事者；知识分子 adj.智力的；聪明的', '1. He likes to set himself up as an intellectual. 他喜欢自命为知识分子。 2. These views were common among intellectuals. 这些观点在知识分子中很普遍。 3. The argument was too intellectual for me; I couldn\'t follow a word of it. 这场争论对我来说太深奥了，我一点都搞不明白。 4. Chess is a highly intellectual game. 象棋是需用高度智力的运动项目。', '副词: intellectually 名词: intellectuality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('archaeology', '[ˌɑːrki\'ɑːlədʒi]', 'n.考古学', '1. He displayed interest in archaeology. 他对考古学有兴趣。 2. She teaches archaeology at the university. 她在大学里教考古学。 3. The newspaper article waked my interest in archaeology. 报纸上的文章激起了我对考古学的兴趣。', '形容词: archaeological 异体字: archeology 名词: archaeologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('instinctive', '[ɪn\'stɪŋktɪv]', 'adj.本能的；天性的；直觉的', '1. He tried to conceal his instinctive revulsion at the idea. 他试图饰盖自己对这一想法本能的厌恶。 2. Perhaps an analogy with what happens to us when we visit the theater will make this instinctive correlation clearer. 也许将此与我们看戏时的情况相比可以把这种本能的联系说得更清楚些。 3. Was there a foundation for the tenuous, instinctive fears that I couldn\'t seem to shake? 能不能给这微妙的，直觉的恐惧下个定论让我不再忐忑不安？ 4. I think most of us have the instinctive ability to discern between the merely obsequious and the purely altruistic. 我想我们大部分人都可以直觉的辨认出逢迎谄媚和纯粹的利他行为。', '副词: instinctively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('analogy', '[ə\'nælədʒi]', 'n.类比；相似；类似', '1. It is not always reliable to argue by analogy. 用类推法论证并不总是可靠的。 2. He offers an analogy to explain how it works. 他用一个类比来解释这个过程。 3. He drew this conclusion on the analogy of yours. 他根据你的理论类推得出这个结论。 4. No analogy exists between you and me. 你和我之间没有相似之处。', '名词复数: analogies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rue', '[ruː]', 'n.懊悔；后悔；芸香 v.后悔；懊悔；悲伤', '1. To his rue, the error cost him the game. 让他后悔的是，这个错误让他满盘皆输。 2. Rue and thyme grow both in one garden. 花园里同时种着芸香和百里香。 3. I rue never having been to university. 我后悔从未上过大学。 4. He\'ll rue the day he married her. 他将会因为和她结婚而抱恨终身。', '名词: ruer 过去式: rued 过去分词: rued 现在分词: ruing 第三人称单数: rues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desideratum', '[dɪˌzɪdə\'rɑːtəm]', 'n.所愿望之物；迫切需要之物', '1. The report on the hospital mentions such desiderata as a supply of clean laundry. 报告中提到该医院需要乾净的洗换物品。', '名词复数: desiderata');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('predominate', '[prɪ\'dɑːmɪneɪt]', 'v.占优势；支配', '1. Conservatives might predominate in the government. 保守派人士有可能在政府中占优势。 2. Pine trees predominate the woods here. 这儿的树林中最多的是松树。 3. Red and scarlet predominate in these flowers. 这些花中大都是红色和鲜红色的。 4. He soon began to predominate over them. 他不久就开始支配他们了。', '副词: predominately 名词: predomination 过去式: predominated 过去分词: predominated 现在分词: predominating 第三人称单数: predominates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('informer', '[ɪn\'fɔːrmər]', 'n.告发者；告密者', '1. An informer supplied the police with the names of those involved in the crime. 一位告发者向警察局提供了涉及这次犯罪的人员名单。 2. The Inspector had received a phone call from an informer. 警长刚刚接到一名通报者的电话。 3. Any one of our employees could be the informer. 我们的任何一位雇员都有可能成为告密者。 4. I would never act as an informer against you . 我永远也不会做对你不利的告密者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scant', '[skænt]', 'adj.不充分的；不足的 v.减缩；限制；忽略', '1. Your attachment to substandard lodgings and scant tuition in Dover is clearly irrational. 你留恋多佛低于标准的住宿条件和不足的奖学金，这明显是非理性的。', '副词: scantly 比较级: scanter 最高级: scantest 名词: scantness 过去式: scanted 过去分词: scanted 现在分词: scanting 第三人称单数: scants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('paragon', '[\'pærəɡɑːn]', 'n.模范；典型 v.与 ... 比较；比得上', '1. He is a paragon of husband. 他是个模范丈夫。 2. I make no claim to be a paragon. 我决不认为自己是完人。 3. My young lady was no philosopher, and no paragon of patience. 我的小姐不是一个哲人，不是一个忍耐的模范。 4. She is a paragon of virtue. 她是美德的典范。', '过去式: paragoned 过去分词: paragoned 现在分词: paragoning 第三人称单数: paragons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('purport', '[pər\'pɔːrt]', 'v.意味着；声称；意图 n.意义；要旨；大要', '1. Her letter may purport her forthcoming arrival. 她的来信可能意味着她快要到了。 2. His plans are not what they purport to be. 他的计划并不如他们所声称的那样。 3. I do not understand the purport of your question. 我不知道你的意思。 4. Even now, there is someone else who gives us special purport in life. 尽管如此,还会有其他人对我们有着特殊的意义。', '过去式: purported 过去分词: purported 现在分词: purporting 第三人称单数: purports');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spoil', '[spɔɪl]', 'v.宠坏；溺爱；破坏；腐坏；使索然无味 n.战利品；奖品', '1. A fond mother may spoil her child. 溺爱的母亲可能会宠坏她的孩子。 2. The child was spoilt by his grandfather. 这个孩子被他的爷爷给惯坏了。 3. The children kept quarreling and spoiled our holiday. 孩子们不断吵架，破坏了我们的假期。 4. He had spoiled the soup by putting in too much salt. 他往汤里放盐太多，把汤给糟蹋了。 5. The invaders made spoil of all in their way. 侵略者所到之处无不洗劫一空。', '过去式: spoiled/spoilt 过去分词: spoiled/spoilt 现在分词: spoiling 第三人称单数: spoils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prig', '[prɪɡ]', 'n.一本正经的人；自命不凡者；道学先生；<俚>小偷 v.偷', '1. He had been railed against by them as a prig and a poseur. 他们责骂他是一个沾沾自喜、装腔作势的人。 2. Charles thinks he\'s better than the rest of us, the self-righteous prig! 查尔斯认为他比我们大家都强，真是个自以为是的家伙！ 3. The transition from libertine to prig was so complete. 一个酒徒色鬼竟然摇身一变就成了道学先生。 4. If one wishes to be a prig or a Puritan, one can flaunt one\'s moral views about them. 一个人要是愿意当道学先生或清教徒，当然可以炫耀自己的伦理观点。', '形容词: priggish 副词: priggishly 名词: priggery 过去式: prigged 过去分词: prigged 现在分词: prigging 第三人称单数: prigs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dormancy', '[\'dɔːmənsi]', 'n.休眠；冬眠；潜伏', '1. Eggs hatch as turf comes out of dormancy. 草地的休眠结束他也开始孵化。 2. Promethean\'s Azothic radiance awakens Pandorans from Dormancy. 活尸的水银辐射会将尸祸从休眠中唤醒。 3. What makes it alternate between quiet dormancy and exploding action? 那么，到底是什么让它一会儿静如冬眠的小兽，一会儿又喷薄不止？ 4. Although non-deciduous, olive trees do require a cold period to go into semi dormancy. 尽管是不落叶植物，橄榄树也需要一个半冬眠时期。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transient', '[\'trænʃnt]', 'adj.短暂的 n.短期居留者；<电>顺变电流', '1. Her feeling of depression was transient. 她那抑郁的心情一会儿就过去了。 2. Their happiness was transient,for the war broke out soon after they got married. 他们的幸福是短暂的，因为他们婚后不久就爆发了战争。 3. We stayed at the inn as transient guests. 我们在小酒馆中只作短暂停留。 4. We are just the transients at the hotel. 我们只是旅馆里的过往旅客。', '副词: transiently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fractious', '[\'frækʃəs]', 'adj.脾气不好的；易怒的；表示不满的；捣乱的', '1. Children often get fractious and tearful when tired. 孩子们疲倦时易怒好哭。 2. The six fractious republics are demanding autonomy. 这六个闹分裂的加盟共和国要求自治。', '副词: fractiously 名词: fractiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desist', '[dɪ\'zɪst]', 'v.停止；中止；打消念头；忍住；克制', '1. I wish he would desist from entertaining his friends. 我希望他别再招待他的朋友了。 2. We have desisted our work. 我们已经停止我们的工作了。 3. You ought to desist from such foolish activities. 你们必须停止这种如此愚蠢的行动国。 4. He made several attempts to rise but was obliged to desist . 他多次想站起来但不得不放弃了这个念头。', '过去式: desisted 过去分词: desisted 现在分词: desisting 第三人称单数: desists');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quintessence', '[kwɪn\'tesns]', 'n.精华；典型；精髓；第五元素', '1. The wick is the quintessence of the candle. 灯芯是蜡烛的精华。 2. Therefore, the research on idioms as a type of linguistic quintessence contributes to enhancing understanding of national culture. 探讨这类语言精华可提升对该民族文化的认知。 3. It was the quintessence of an English manor house. 那是典型的英式庄园宅第。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infuriate', '[ɪn\'fjʊrieɪt]', 'adj.狂怒的 v.激怒', '1. I feel infuriate and humiliating!! 我感到震惊和耻辱!! 2. In a languid manner he designed to infuriate her. 他显出无精打采的样子,故意想激怒她。 3. I was infuriated by/with their constant criticism. 他们没完没了地批评把我给气坏了。', '副词: infuriatingly 名词: infuriation 过去式: infuriated 过去分词: infuriated 现在分词: infuriating 第三人称单数: infuriates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sapient', '[\'seɪpiənt]', 'adj.有智慧的；聪明的；伶俐的', '1. If you follow her sapient advice, you will be sure to succeed. 假如你遵照她明智的建议，你一定能够成功。', '副词: sapiently 名词: sapience');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('empiricism', '[ɪm\'pɪrɪsɪzəm]', 'n.经验主义；经验论', '1. It is in this sense that Comte repudiates empiricism. 正是从这个意义上说,孔德抛弃了经验主义。 2. The opposite of empiricism is rationalism. 经验论的对立面是唯理论。', '名词: empiricist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glorify', '[\'ɡlɔːrɪfaɪ]', 'v.美化；赞美', '1. The setting sun glorified the scene. 落日使景色更美。 2. The newspapers glorified their heroic deeds. 报纸称颂了他们的英雄事迹。 3. Singing hymns is one of the ways to glorify god. 唱圣歌是赞美上帝的一种方式。', '名词: glorification 过去式: glorified 过去分词: glorified 现在分词: glorifying 第三人称单数: glorifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gracious', '[\'ɡreɪʃəs]', 'adj.亲切的；高尚的；仁慈的；和蔼的；优雅的', '1. The Queen greeted the crowed with a gracious smile. 女王带着亲切的微笑向人群致意。 2. I received a gracious letter of acknowledgement. 我收到一封有礼貌的感谢信。 3. I\'ll be greatly honoured by your gracious presence. 如蒙光临，不胜荣幸。 4. Insist the gracious living style to experience the essential life spirit. 坚持以高尚的生活方式，体验生活本质的精神态度。', '副词: graciously 名词: graciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scathing', '[\'skeɪðɪŋ]', 'adj.严厉的；尖刻的 动词scathe的现在分词形式.', '1. He made a scathing attack on the statement. 他对那声明进行了严厉的抨击。 2. It is a scathing tract on the uselessness of war. 这是一本对战争无用性进行严厉批评的小册子。 3. He is given to making scathing remarks. 这人说起话来老这么尖酸刻薄。 4. I think such a scathing attack on my idea was not necessary. 我觉得没有必要这么尖刻地抨击我的想法。', '副词: scathingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barter', '[\'bɑːrtər]', 'v.物物交换；以货易货 n.物物交换；实物交易', '1. They used to barter for horses with salt. 他们过去以食盐交换马匹。 2. The colonists bartered calico for Indian land. 殖民者以印花布交换印地安人的土地。 3. The prisoners tried to barter with the guards for their freedom. 囚犯们企图和看守做换取自由的交易。 4. Some countries had to resort to barter to obtain foreign goods. 一些国家不得不采取以货易货的方法以得到外国货物。 5. On these islands a system of barter is used. 在这些岛上仍然实行着物物交换的制度。', '名词: barterer 过去式: bartered 过去分词: bartered 现在分词: bartering 第三人称单数: barters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('woodcut', '[\'wʊdkʌt]', 'n.木刻；木刻画', '1. The woodcut \"Autumn\" was conceived as a harvest scene. 木刻《秋》是按丰收的景象来构思的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prey', '[preɪ]', 'n.牺牲者；被掠食者，猎物 vi.掠夺；捕食；使 ... 苦恼', '1. She fell (a) prey to melancholy. 她为忧郁所折磨。 2. She was easy prey for dishonest salesmen. 她很容易地让奸商敲了竹杠。 3. The lion seized its prey and ate it. 狮子抓住猎物，把它吃了。 4. The eagle seized its prey in a tenacious grip. 鹰将捕获物紧紧抓住。 5. In those far- off times Viking pirates used to prey on the coasts of Europe. 在那些遥远的时代里，北欧海盗经常在欧洲海岸一带进行掠夺。', '名词: preyer 过去式: preyed 过去分词: preyed 现在分词: preying 第三人称单数: preys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brash', '[bræʃ]', 'adj.鲁莽的；自以为是的；无礼的；俗气的；易碎的 n.胃灼热；骤雨；碎石堆', '1. Brash journalists were crowding around the ambassador. 鲁莽的记者们围拢在大使周边。 2. His brash answers annoyed the interviewers. 他回答问题自以为是，面试的人感到很不痛快。 3. Don\'t you think that suit\'s a bit brash for a funeral? 难道你不认为那套衣服对于葬礼而言有点无礼吗？ 4. He was wearing a rather brash tie. 他系著一条颇为显眼的领带。', '副词: brashly 比较级: brasher 最高级: brashest 名词: brashness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hemorrhage', '[\'hemərɪdʒ]', 'n.出血；溢血；失控的行为', '1. It is really just fibrinous pericarditis with hemorrhage. 但是它仅为纤维素性心包炎合并出血。 2. The hemosiderin from the hemorrhage produces the grossly brown color. 出血形成的血铁黄素使病变肉眼观察呈深棕色。', '形容词: hemorrhagic 过去式: hemorrhaged 过去分词: hemorrhaged 现在分词: hemorrhaging 第三人称单数: hemorrhages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('siren', '[\'saɪrən]', 'n.汽笛；警报器 n.[希神]塞壬（半鸟半女人的怪物）；妖妇；迷人的女人', '1. He made out of the cabin at once on hearing the siren. 他一听到汽笛声就立即走出船舱。 2. The wails of the siren woke the people out of their dreams. 汽笛的啸鸣把人们从睡梦中惊醒。 3. The siren went off at noon. 警笛在正午鸣响 4. We all heard the air-raid siren. 我们都听到了空袭警报器的声音。 5. Who can resist your temptation like a siren. 有谁能抗拒你那份像塞壬一样的诱惑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illuminate', '[ɪ\'luːmɪneɪt]', 'vt.照明；阐释；说明', '1. plastic food 2. A sudden smile illuminated her face. 突然的微笑使她容光焕发。 3. Footnotes illuminate the difficult passage of the book. 脚注中解释了书中许多难懂的道理。 4. Our interesting teacher could illuminate almost any subject we studied. 我们这位有趣的老师几乎能解释清楚我们所学的所有科目。', '副词: illuminatingly 过去式: illuminated 过去分词: illuminated 现在分词: illuminating 第三人称单数: illuminates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rectify', '[\'rektɪfaɪ]', 'vt.改正；[化]精馏；[电]整流', '1. Please rectify the mistake in my bill. 请改正我帐单上的错误。 2. The captain had to rectify the compass reading. 船长不得不校正罗盘读数。 3. He cleaned the bottle with rectified spirit. 他用精馏酒精清洗瓶子。 4. Diodes are electronic devices which rectify alternating current to direct current. 二极管是将交流电整流成直流电的电子装置。', '形容词: rectifiable 名词: rectification 过去式: rectified 过去分词: rectified 现在分词: rectifying 第三人称单数: rectifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compress', '[\'kɑːmpres]', 'vt.压缩；压榨 n.[医]敷布', '1. Compress this clay into a small ball. 把这块粘土压缩成一个小球。 2. Click the picture that you want to compress. 单击要压缩的图片。', '过去式: compressed 过去分词: compressed 现在分词: compressing 第三人称单数: compresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spectral', '[\'spektrəl]', 'adj.幽灵的；光谱的', '1. There was no change in his father\'s position, or in his spectral look. 他父亲的姿势一点没有更动，阴沉的脸色也依然不变。 2. At times he seems rather ordinary. At other times ethereal, perhaps even spectral. 有时他好像很正常,有时又难以捉摸,甚至像个幽灵。 3. Beings without form and intelligences without bodies are spectral ghosts guaranteed to mislead. 无体生命和无形智能，注定是引人误入歧途的鬼怪幽灵。 4. I am studying spectral classification. 我在学习光谱分类。', '副词: spectrally 名词: spectrality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gaunt', '[ɡɔːnt]', 'adj.憔悴的；荒凉的', '1. He has gaunt cheeks. 他双颊消瘦。 2. The old man was thin and gaunt with deep wrinkles in the back of his neck. 老人消瘦而憔悴，脖颈上有些很深的皱纹。 3. The old house stood gaunt and empty, a complete ruin. 那栋旧房子荒凉空洞地伫立着，像一堆废墟。', '副词: gauntly 比较级: gaunter 最高级: gauntest 名词: gauntness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('devout', '[dɪ\'vaʊt]', 'adj.虔诚的；虔敬的；衷心的', '1. The devout Christian persists in his belief. 那个虔诚的基督教徒坚持他的信念。 2. Devout Moslems oBserve Ramadan punctiliously. 虔诚的穆斯林准时地遵守斋月。', '副词: devoutly 比较级: devouter 最高级: devoutest 名词: devoutness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('escort', '[\'eskɔːrt]', 'n.护送者；护航舰；陪伴者；陪游；妓女 vt.护送；陪伴', '1. He offered to be her escort, but she declined it. 他提出护送她，但她谢绝了。 2. The government provided an armed escort for the visiting head of State. 政府为到访的元首派出了武装卫队。 3. He is the commander in chief of this escort ,and he holds great power. 他是这艘护航舰的总指挥，权利很大。 4. The Queen\'s yacht had an escort of ten destroyers. 有十艘驱逐舰为女王的游艇护航. 5. He will escort you through the forest. 他护送你穿过森林。', '过去式: escorted 过去分词: escorted 现在分词: escorting 第三人称单数: escorts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('veritable', '[\'verɪtəbl]', 'adj.真实的；确实的；真正的', '1. This campaign took on the proportions of a veritable war against the peasantry . 这次运动很大部份是反农民的真实的战争。 2. The show is a veritable reservoir of new talent. 这个演出真是新秀集萃。 3. We found ourselves in the midst of a veritable fairyland. 我们发现我们在名副其实的仙境中。 4. It was not easy to work in the shed; in winter it was a veritable ice-box. 在这木棚里工作可不轻松，冬天简直是个冰箱。', '副词: veritably 名词: veritableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corrosive', '[kə\'roʊsɪv]', 'adj.腐蚀的；腐蚀性的；蚀坏的 n.腐蚀物；腐蚀药', '1. It\'s quite important to gain the ability to cope successfully with corrosive atmospheres and particles. 很重要的是获得能够成功地克服气体和粒子腐蚀的能力。 2. To use correctly negative corrodent is to the effective method of preventing metal and its alloy from corroding in the corrosive condition. 正确使用缓蚀剂是防止金属及其合金在腐蚀环境中产生腐蚀的有效方法。 3. With corrosive fluids, the dampener case must also be selected carefully. 由于腐蚀性的液体，减弱器的外壳也须仔细选择。 4. Fasteners should be no corrosive and may consist of self-taping screws, weldable studs, cleats, and clips. 固定的装置不能有腐蚀性的物质，一般自带螺钉，可焊接的螺钉，防滑拴和夹子。', '副词: corrosively 名词: corrosiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sluice', '[sluːs]', 'n.水闸；堰；泄洪；斜水槽 v.冲洗；开水闸放水；奔流', '1. They open the sluice gates of reservoir. 他们打开水库的闸门。 2. We opened the sluice and the water poured in. 我们打开闸门，水就涌了进来。 3. Flood water is discharged through the sluice on the Three Gorges Dam on June 19, 2007. 2007年6月19日随着三峡大坝的泄洪，滞留了多天的洪水倾泻而下。 4. The stables were sluiced out with water from a hose. 马厩已经用水管子冲洗过了。', '过去式: sluiced 过去分词: sluiced 现在分词: sluicing 第三人称单数: sluices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('garland', '[\'ɡɑːrlənd]', 'n.花环 v.戴花环', '1. I wove a garland of flowers. 我编了一个花环。 2. One flower makes no garland. [谚]一朵鲜花，难做花环。 3. The little girl presented the champion with a victory garland. 小女孩给冠军献上了胜利的花环。 4. They garlanded him with roses. 他们给他戴上玫瑰花环。', '过去式: garlanded 过去分词: garlanded 现在分词: garlanding 第三人称单数: garlands');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('susceptible', '[sə\'septəbl]', 'adj.易受外界影响的；易受感染的；容许…的', '1. Children are more susceptible than adults. 孩子比成人易受外界的影响。 2. Some people are susceptible to advertising. 一些人易受广告的影响。 3. The plant is not susceptible to disease. 这种植物不容易受病害侵袭。 4. Children are susceptible to various illnesses. 孩子易患各种疾病。', '副词: susceptibly 名词: susceptibleness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scuff', '[skʌf]', 'v.磨损；拖着脚走 n.拖着脚走；磨损', '1. I scuff the heel of my boot on the step. 我的靴子后跟在台阶上磨坏了。 2. I scuffed the heel of my boot on the step. 我的靴子後跟在台阶上磨坏了。 3. She scuffed past in her mother\'s slippers. 她趿拉著她母亲的拖鞋走过去了。 4. If you scuff (your feet) like that, you\'ll wear the heels out. 你那麽拖著脚走路，就要把鞋跟磨坏了。', '名词: scuffer 过去式: scuffed 过去分词: scuffed 现在分词: scuffing 第三人称单数: scuffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('colon', '[\'koʊlən]', 'n.冒号；结肠；科朗(哥斯达黎加和萨尔瓦多的货币单位) Colon. n.科隆(巴拿马港市)', '1. There is a colon omitted in this sentence. 这个句子中丢了一个冒号。 2. Why do we put a colon after this word? 这个词后面为什么加冒号? 3. The old man died from colon cancer. 这位老人死于结肠癌。', '形容词: colonic 名词复数: colons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corrugated', '[\'kɔːrəɡeɪtɪd]', 'adj.缩成皱纹的；使起波状的', '1. She wished she could smooth away the wrinkles from his corrugated brow. 她希望将皱纹从额头上除掉。 2. Sheets of corrugated iron are often used for roofs and fences. 波纹铁皮常用以建造屋顶和围墙。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interlock', '[ˌɪntər\'lɑːk]', 'v.连结；连锁 n.连锁', '1. The US space shuttle will interlock with the Russian space station later today. 美国航天飞机将于今天稍后和俄罗斯航天站对接。 2. All the units interlock with one another rigidly. 所有的元件严密地连锁在一起。', '过去式: interlocked 过去分词: interlocked 现在分词: interlocking 第三人称单数: interlocks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fawn', '[fɔːn]', 'n.未满周岁的小鹿；浅黄褐色 v.奉承；讨好', '1. A fawn behind the tree looked at us curiously. 树后面一只小鹿好奇地看着我们。 2. And once you\'re rich, you fawn over others. 你一有了钱，就会去巴结别人。 3. Many people fawn on him only because of his wealth. 许多人奉承他就因为他有钱。 4. The puppy was fawning on its master. 小狗朝着主人摇尾乞怜。', '副词: fawningly 名词: fawner 过去式: fawned 过去分词: fawned 现在分词: fawning 第三人称单数: fawns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('polemic', '[pə\'lemɪk]', 'n.慷慨陈词；辩论法；争辩术 adj.争论的', '1. He wrote a splendid polemic in my favour. 他写了一篇出色的文章为我辩护。 2. He launched into a fierce polemic against the government\'s policies. 他猛烈地抨击政府的政策。 3. Her speech was memorable for its polemic rather than its substance. 她的演说之所以令人难忘，不是因其内容而是因其辩论方法。 4. Is my polemic skill worse than his? 是我的辩论技巧不如庄子？', '副词: polemically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deed', '[diːd]', 'n.行为；事迹；[法]契约 vt.立契转让', '1. His deed claims our respect. 他的行为值得我们尊敬。 2. His deed revealed him to be a kind man. 他的行为显示他是个好心的人。 3. We must take the consequences of our own deed. 我们必须承担自己行为的后果。 4. We had a heated discussion in honour of their heroic deed. 为了纪念他们的英雄事迹,我们举行了一次热烈的讨论会。 5. The widow decided to deed the house over to her nephew before she died. 那寡妇决定在去世前把房子立契转让给她侄子。', '过去式: deeded 过去分词: deeded 现在分词: deeding 第三人称单数: deeds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retrace', '[rɪ\'treɪs]', 'v.重描；折回；追溯', '1. We should not retrace the route our forefathers had taken. 我们不应重走我们祖先走过的老路。 2. I need to retrace my steps and find that location. 我需要循着原路返回。 3. I dropped my keys and had to retrace my steps for nearly a mile before I found them. 我把钥匙丢失了，结果只得顺原路折回，走了差不多一英里才找到。 4. He often retraces the happy time during his young age. 他经常回忆起年轻时代的幸福时光。', '形容词: retraceable 名词: retracement 过去式: retraced 过去分词: retraced 现在分词: retracing 第三人称单数: retraces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dexterous', '[\'dekstrəs]', 'adj.灵巧的；机灵的；惯用右手的 =dextrous.', '1. A good pianist must be dexterous. 一个好的钢琴家必须要灵巧。 2. The manager was dexterous in handling his staff. 那位经理善于运用他属下的职员。 3. The English Minister can often gain a point by dexterous dealing in Parliament. 英国的内阁成员在议会中以巧妙应付的手段往往可以获得成功。', '副词: dexterously 异体字: dextrous 名词: dexterousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prophet', '[\'prɑːfɪt]', 'n.预言者；先知', '1. Once in a while, the prophet indulges in fantasy. 偶尔，那个预言家会纵情于幻想。 2. A prophet made a prophecy that the kingdom would fall. 一位预言家预言那个王国将要灭亡。 3. The prophet said that war will break out. 先知预言战争将爆发。 4. No man is a prophet in his own country. 先知在自已家乡从来不被认可。', '名词: prophethood');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hone', '[hoʊn]', 'n.细磨刀石；磨孔机 vt.磨刀；磨练', '1. Other villagers brought me goat\'s cheese and hone. 其他村民给我带来了羊奶干酪和磨石。 2. He was honing his razor although it\'s very sharp. 尽管他的剃刀十分锋利了，可他还是不停地磨它。 3. They hone their skills in their everyday lives. 他们在日常生活中磨炼才能。 4. He runs every day to hone his stamina. 为了增强耐力，他每天都进行跑步锻炼。', '过去式: honed 过去分词: honed 现在分词: honing 第三人称单数: hones');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impact', '[\'ɪmpækt]', 'n.影响；冲击力；撞击 vt.挤入；压紧；撞击；对 ... 发生影响 vi.冲击；撞击；产生影响', '1. Seasonality or economic cycles will have minimal impact on secular trends. 季节性或经济周期两者对长期趋势的影响都不大。 2. But what these people fail to see is that international tourism may bring about a disastrous impact on our environment and local history. 但是这些人忽视了国际旅游可能会给当地环境和历史造成的灾难性的影响。 3. The impact of the crash hurtled the driver against the windshield of the car. 碰撞的震力使驾驶员猛撞于车子的挡风玻璃上。 4. The impact of the stone against the windowpane shattered the glass. 石头撞击窗户打碎了玻璃。 5. A vast crowd impacted the square. 广场上挤集了一大群人。 6. The company\'s performance was impacted by the high value of the pound. 公司的业绩受到了英镑高值的冲击。', '名词: impaction 过去式: impacted 过去分词: impacted 现在分词: impacting 第三人称单数: impacts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petulance', '[\'petjuləns]', 'n.发脾气；生气；易怒；暴躁；性急', '1. But Mourinho insists the Ivory Coast international\'s actions were caused by frustration rather than petulance. 但是穆帅坚持认为这位象牙海岸国脚的行为是被不顺心引起的，而不是发脾气。 2. I write you to address my growing concerns regarding your recent petulance and that of your fellow Archbishops. 我怀着对你和手下近日无常的暴躁的担忧给你写这封信。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immanent', '[\'ɪmənənt]', 'adj.内在的；固有的；无所不在的', '1. A cognition is an immanent act of mind. 认知是头脑的内在活动。 2. He believed that beauty was not something imposed, but something immanent. 他认为美丽不是外在的而是内在的。 3. Color is a kind of medium which can evoke feelings immeasurably, and its immanent power can provoke direct and obvious reaction of human beings. 色彩是一种能无限唤起感觉的媒介,它所固有的力量可以激起人们直接而显著的反应。 4. You should hear the great immanent pull out all its stop. 你会听到这个巨大的乐器的所有的音栓都被拨动了。', '副词: immanently 名词: immanence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rumble', '[\'rʌmbl]', 'n. 隆隆声； 辘辘声 n. (旧式汽车车厢后的)折叠加座 <俚>打群架 v. 发隆隆声； 使辘辘响', '1. We heard the occasional rumble of a passing truck. 我们偶尔听到卡车驶过的隆隆声。 2. Far below I could hear the rumble of tube trains carrying commuters to the West End. 我能听到把使用月票的乘客送往西区的地铁火车在地下深处行驶时发出的隆隆声。 3. We heard the occasional rumble of a passing truck. 我们偶尔听到卡车驶过的隆隆声。 4. Far below I could hear the rumble of tube trains carrying commuters to the West End. 我能听到把使用月票的乘客送往西区的地铁火车在地下深处行驶时发出的隆隆声。', '形容词: rumbly 副词: rumblingly 名词: rumbler 过去式: rumbled 过去分词: rumbled 现在分词: rumbling 第三人称单数: rumbles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discomfiture', '[dɪs\'kʌmfɪtʃə(r)]', 'n.狼狈；难堪；挫败', '1. He was clearly taking delight in her discomfiture. 他显然以她的窘迫为乐。 2. I laughed my head off when I heard of his discomfiture. 听到别人说起他的狼狈相,我放声大笑。 3. He mangers to cope with a discomfiture skillfully. 他很巧妙地应付了一个尴尬局面。 4. She couldn\'t disguise her glee at their discomfiture. 他们受挫，她不禁喜形於色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('file', '[faɪl]', 'n.档案；卷宗；文件；锉刀，指甲锉 vt.把 ... 归档；提出(申请书、议案等)', '1. Put this letter in the main file. 把这封信放在主要文件夹中。 2. Would you please take a seat while I look into our file? 你先坐一下,我给你查一下我们的卷宗? 3. Put this letter in the main file. 把这封信放在主要文件夹中。 4. Please file those letters. 请把这些信件存档。', '过去式: filed 过去分词: filed 现在分词: filing 第三人称单数: files');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('generation', '[ˌdʒenə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.代；（产品类型的）代；产生；繁殖', '1. There is a generation gap between my parents and I. 我父母和我之间有代沟。 2. One generation blows bubbles, and the next breaks them. 前一代人制造出来的空洞理论，下一代人把它们打破。 3. Their visionary ideas are often misunderstood by their own generation. 他们有远见的理想往往招致同时代人的误解。 4. Each generation has its own standards of judgement. 每一代都有它自己的判断标准。', '形容词: generational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gaze', '[ɡeɪz]', 'vi.凝视 n.凝视', '1. She sat gazing out of the window. 她坐着凝视着窗外。 2. He gaze ruefully in the mirror at his greying lock. 他凝视著镜中自己日见花白的头发，感慨岁月不待人。 3. She gazed at me in disbelief when I told her the news. 我告诉她这消息时，她以怀疑的目光注视著我。 4. Your intent gaze made her uncomfortable. 你的注目凝视使她感到不自在。', '名词: gazer 过去式: gazed 过去分词: gazed 现在分词: gazing 第三人称单数: gazes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('atheism', '[\'eɪθiɪzəm]', 'n.无神论；不信神', '1. Inclined to atheism. 倾向无神论的', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chauvinistic', '[ˌʃəʊvɪ\'nɪstɪk]', 'adj.沙文主义的；盲目爱国的', '1. However, many modem women consider this practice sexist and chauvinistic. 但是，很多时髦的女士认为这种行为是男性至上主义和沙文主义的作风。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('presumable', '[prɪ\'zuːməbəl]', 'adj.可推测的；可能的', '1. The presumable result is an election defeat. 推测结果是竞选可能会失败。', '副词: presumably');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brew', '[bruː]', 'v.酿造；泡（茶）；酝酿；策划 n.酿造物；（酿造物的）质地；混合物', '1. He brews his own beer at home. 他在家自己酿造啤酒。 2. The tea is brewing and will be served soon. 茶正在泡，一会儿就送来。 3. A storm is brewing. 暴风雨正在酝酿中。 4. They are brewing a plot behind the scenes. 他们正在幕后策划一个阴谋。 5. The machine produces a brew that is dark in colour and complex in taste. 这台机器酿造出来的酒颜色很深，味道很复杂。', '名词: brewage 过去式: brewed 过去分词: brewed 现在分词: brewing 第三人称单数: brews');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('minuscule', '[\'mɪnəskjuːl]', 'n.小写字 adj.小写字的；很小的', '1. This manuscript was written in a minuscule script. 原稿是用很小的字体写的。 2. If the plane has empty seats,the cost of adding one more passenger is minuscule. 如果飞机有空座位，因为多一个顾客而增加的成本是微乎其微的。', '形容词: minuscular 异体字: miniscule');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rapacious', '[rə\'peɪʃəs]', 'adj.贪婪的；强夺的', '1. Several of the Arab countries represented in the President\'s office needed the United States to fend off threats from rapacious neighbors. 有几个阿拉伯国家派人到总统办公室声称，它们需要美国的援助，来抵挡贪得无厌的邻国的威胁。 2. Hawks and other rapacious birds prey on variety of small animals. 老鹰和其他贪婪的鸟类捕食各种小动物。 3. Mr Brown said there was also a global perspective to America\'s rapacious model of consumption. 布朗先生说，还有一个研究美国掠夺资源模式的全球视角。', '副词: rapaciously 名词: rapacity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embody', '[ɪm\'bɑːdi]', 'vt.使具体化；包含；代表，体现；使(精神)肉体化', '1. The country\'s constitution embodies the ideals of freedom and equality. 这个国家的宪法体现了自由和平等的理想。 2. He embodies a new idea in his paintings. 他在画中体现思想。 3. The latest computer model embodies many new features. 最新型的计算机具备许多新功能。 4. The new car embodies many improvements. 这辆新车包含了许多改进的项目。', '过去式: embodied 过去分词: embodied 现在分词: embodying 第三人称单数: embodies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bandy', '[\'bændi]', 'v.（恶意地）议论；来回传递；把 ... 打来打去；往复投掷 adj.向外弯曲的', '1. Don\'t bandy words with me, young man! 别跟我强嘴，小伙子！ 2. An upstart like that dares to bandy words with me! 这样一个小财主也敢跟我逗嘴皮子。 3. We are not going to bandy words. We just require you to vacate this room. 我们不是来扯皮的，我们只是要你腾出这间房子。 4. The stories being bandied about are completely false. 这些道听途说的事全属子虚。', '名词复数: bandies 过去式: bandied 过去分词: bandied 现在分词: bandying 第三人称单数: bandies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suture', '[\'suːtʃər]', 'n.缝合；缝合处；缝合用的线 v.缝合', '1. The methods of tendon suture are discussed in Chapter 63. 肌腱缝合方法将在63章介绍。 2. This is an absorbable suture thread which leaves no trace after an operation. 这是一种可吸收式缝合线，术后愈合快，不易留疤痕。 3. There is little available musculature to suture anterior to the sternum. 在胸骨前只有很少可用的肌肉能够缝合。', '形容词: sutural 副词: suturally 过去式: sutured 过去分词: sutured 现在分词: suturing 第三人称单数: sutures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carp', '[kɑːrp]', 'n.鲤鱼 vi.吹毛求疵', '1. I like the white carp most. 我最喜欢白色的鲤鱼。 2. They restocked the pond with carp. 他们重新给池塘放了鲤鱼。 3. It would be wise not to carp or criticize . 不吹毛求疵或批评将是明智的。 4. We will not carp at this great writer . 我们不会对这位伟大的作家吹毛求疵。', '名词: carper 名词复数: carp 过去式: carped 过去分词: carped 现在分词: carping 第三人称单数: carps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impalpable', '[ɪm\'pælpəbl]', 'adj.感触不到的；无形的；难以理解的', '1. An impalpable emanation; an aura. 气味摸不着的排放物；气流 2. Results:Undifferent methods have impalpable effect. 结果:拔除的方法不一,其效果差异不大。 3. An impalpable emanation;an aura. 气味摸不着的排放物；气流 4. The commonplace is just that light, impalpable, aerial essence. 平凡才是一种要素，轻盈、无形、难以捉摸。', '副词: impalpably 名词: impalpability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deforestation', '[ˌdiːˌfɔːrɪ\'steɪʃn]', 'n.森林开伐；滥伐森林', '1. The biggest driver of deforestation is agriculture. 也就是说森林开伐的始作俑者莫过于农业。 2. The quickest solution to deforestation would be to simply stop cutting down trees. 停止森林开伐是森林资源退化的最快解决方案。 3. Angkor may have suffered problems common to modern times, including deforestation, overpopulation, topsoil degradation and erosion. 吴哥可能已经遭受过和现代相同的问题，包括滥伐森林，人口过剩，表土退化和侵蚀。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('induction', '[ɪn\'dʌkʃn]', 'n.归纳法；感应；就职；诱发', '1. My argument follows the rules of logical induction. 我是遵循逻辑归纳的法则进行论证的。 2. The magnetic signals are sensed by induction coils. 磁信号由感应线圈所检测。 3. If you want to start again after flameout, you need to touch the induction spot. 当摩托车熄火之后，要再起动，必须用手触摸感应点才能点火。 4. Mrs.Simpson is responsible for the induction of new library staff. 辛普森夫人负责图书馆新职员的入职。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('figurehead', '[\'fɪɡjərhed]', 'n.装饰船头的人像；傀儡领袖', '1. The queen of that country is only a figurehead. 那个国家的女王只是个有名无实的首脑。 2. He is the son of another Maldini, our figurehead. 他是马尔蒂尼家族的儿子，是米兰的另一个代名词。 3. The chairperson was really just a figurehead. 主席只是一位有名无实的首脑。 4. Otherwise Miller would become a dispensable figurehead. 否则米勒就会变成可有可无的傀儡。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('militant', '[\'mɪlɪtənt]', 'adj.好战的；积极从事或支持使用武力的 n.斗士；激进分子', '1. We have militant bonds of friendship. 我们有战斗情谊。 2. We have never been so inspired and militant. 我们从来没有像现在这样意气风发,斗志昂扬。 3. The speaker is shouted down by militant union members. 演讲者被富有战斗精神的工会会员声音所压倒。 4. The militant group has suspected links to al-Qaeda. 该组织被怀疑与基地组织有关联。 5. Our Militant Life is Like a Poem. 我们的战斗生活像诗篇。', '副词: militantly 名词: militance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pirate', '[\'paɪrət]', 'n.海盗；盗版者 v.盗版；抢劫；剽窃', '1. The sailor suddenly saw a pirate jumping onto the deck. 那水手忽然看到一名海盗跳上了甲板。 2. Those software pirates have made a great fortune. 这些软件的盗版者发了大财。 3. We will immediately call the police once we find our CDs being pirated. 一旦发现我们的唱片被盗版,我们会立即报警。 4. A gang of bandits pirated the cargo ship. 一帮土匪抢劫了那艘货船。', '形容词: piratic 副词: piratically 过去式: pirated 过去分词: pirated 现在分词: pirating 第三人称单数: pirates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tousle', '[\'taʊzl]', 'vt.弄乱(头发) n.被弄乱的一大团', '1. To achieve best result, when blowing a hair, play tousle root with another hand. 为了达到最好的效果，在吹头发时，用另一只手弄乱发根。 2. You can\'t see their smile or bring them food or tousle their hair or move them around a dance floor. 你虽然见不到他们的笑容，不能给他们端食物来，不能揉乱他们的头发，不能带他们在舞池跳舞。 3. And disposition of unbridled ground tousle can be met only make the mood worse, even disaster and other. 而肆无忌惮地乱发脾气只能会使心情更坏，甚至殃及他人。 4. Joey: No, no, no. This is running fingers your hair, okay? Now this is a tousle. 她刚刚用她的手指缕我的头发。你还念那种作用力吗？', '过去式: tousled 过去分词: tousled 现在分词: tousling 第三人称单数: tousles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sling', '[slɪŋ]', 'v.投掷；抛；吊起；悬挂；驱逐；遣送 n.投石器；投掷；吊索；悬带；斯林酒', '1. The boys slung stones at the miserable cat. 这些男孩向那只可怜的猫扔石头。 2. Don\'t just sling your clothes on the floor. 不要把衣服往地板上一扔就不管了。 3. They sling up boxes from the cellar. 他们把箱子从地窖中吊挂上来。 4. The line of flags was slung up between two trees. 一排旗帜悬挂在两棵树之间。 5. The boy discharged a stone from a sling. 这个男孩用弹弓射石子。', '名词: slinger 过去式: slung 过去分词: slung 现在分词: slinging 第三人称单数: slings');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('legislature', '[\'ledʒɪsleɪtʃər]', 'n.立法机关', '1. He was an outstanding member of the legislature. 他是立法机关的杰出成员。 2. Do you know what is the legislature in China? 你知道中国的立法机关是哪个吗？', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sultry', '[\'sʌltri]', 'adj.闷热的；风骚的；淫荡的；易怒的；激烈的', '1. I met her in a sultry summer afternoon. 我在夏天一个闷热的下午遇见了她。 2. She gave him a sultry look. 她撩拨春心地看了他一眼。', '副词: sultrily 比较级: sultrier 最高级: sultriest 名词: sultriness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('banish', '[\'bænɪʃ]', 'vt.驱逐；流放；消除', '1. His lies caused his wife to banish him from the house. 他因说谎而被老婆驱逐出家门。 2. The sound of doctrine rings out daily in order to banish various curiosities about this world. 一种主义的声响日以夜继，千日不绝，用以驱逐人们对这个世界的种种好奇与揣测！ 3. You can banish that idea from your mind. 你能消除心中的那种念头。 4. The doctor advised her to banish fear and anxiety. 医生劝她消除恐惧和忧虑。', '名词: banisher 过去式: banished 过去分词: banished 现在分词: banishing 第三人称单数: banishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('porcelain', '[\'pɔːrsəlɪn]', 'n.瓷器；瓷', '1. The museum displays the specimen of ancient Chinese porcelain. 这个博物馆展出中国古瓷器标本。 2. I don\'t know enough about porcelain to be able to price these plates. 我不太懂得瓷器，估计不出这些盘子的价钱。 3. The porcelain is fine and glossy. 瓷质细润。 4. There is a porcelain figure on the table. 桌子上有一个瓷像。', '形容词: porcelaneous');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vent', '[vent]', 'n.排气口；火山口；发泄；表达 v.发泄；表达；排放', '1. The steam found a vent through a crack in the pipe. 蒸气从管子的裂缝漏出去。 2. The vent is not big enough to get the smoke out. 通风孔太小,不能让烟排出去。 3. The explosion cracks the earth\'s surface and scatters ash and huge chunks of rock for many kilometers around the vent. 这样的爆炸把地表炸开以后，其火山灰和巨大石块可散落到火山口周围好几公里远的地方。 4. Foraging crabs and hungry fish feed on bacteria from giant tube worms near a deep sea vent in the Pacific Ocean. 在太平洋里的一座深海火山口附近，饥肠辘辘的螃蟹和鱼类正享用着来自巨型管虫的细菌。 5. I look down on man who vents his anger on his family after having a bad day at work. 我瞧不起那些工作不顺心就拿家里人出气的男人。', '名词: venter 过去式: vented 过去分词: vented 现在分词: venting 第三人称单数: vents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glimmer', '[\'ɡlɪmər]', 'n.微光；少许 vi.发出微光', '1. He can see a glimmer of light through the curtain. 他能透过窗帘看到一丝微光。 2. The candle made only a glimmer in the vast room. 蜡烛在这个很大的房间里仅仅发出一线微光。 3. He showed no glimmer of interest in what you had offered. 他对你给他的东西没流露出一丝兴趣。 4. I didn\'t have a glimmer of what he meant. 我一点也不了解他说的意思。 5. From the cottage window a few lamps were glimmering in the distance. 远处的农舍窗户闪烁着几盏微弱的灯。', '过去式: glimmered 过去分词: glimmered 现在分词: glimmering 第三人称单数: glimmers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('excel', '[ɪk\'sel]', 'vt.优于；超过 vi.胜出 n.[计] 电子表格（软件名称）', '1. He excels in painting. 他擅长绘画。 2. His wife excels him in strategical ability. 他的妻子在战略上胜过他。 3. We strive to excel in bringing out our clients vision and style. 我们努力在带给我们的客户不同的观念和风格上优于他人。 4. They each excel in their respective fields. 他们在各自领域里都是出类拔萃的。 5. He always hopes that his son will excel over him someday. 他总是希望他的儿子有天能胜过他. 6. Excel is widely applied in the vacuum metrology. 在真空计量领域中，Excel电子表格软件得到了广泛的应用。', '过去式: excelled 过去分词: excelled 现在分词: excelling 第三人称单数: excels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('uxorious', '[ʌk\'soʊrɪəs]', 'adj.（过分）宠爱妻子的', '1. Uxorious：excessively submissive or devoted to one\'s wife. 过分溺爱妻子； 2. The most uxorious are probably Switzerland(3%) and Australia(2.5%). 对老婆最用情专一的国家大概是瑞士(%25和澳大利亚(.;5%25。 3. The most uxorious are probably Switzerland (3%) and Australia (2.5%). 对老婆最用情专一的国家大概是瑞士(3%25)和澳大利亚(2.;5%25)。 4. His friends laughed at him because he was so uxorious and submissive to his wife\'s desires. 他的朋友们嘲笑他,因为他溺爱妻子到了百依百顺的程度。', '副词: uxoriously 名词: uxoriousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emolument', '[ɪ\'mɑːljumənt]', 'n.薪资；报酬；<古>优势', '1. The emolument of this profession is not satisfactory. 此行业的报酬不令人满意。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hypocritical', '[ˌhɪpə\'krɪtɪkl]', 'adj.伪善的', '1. Don\'t believe his hypocritical words. 不要相信他那伪善的言词。 2. Their hypocritical lies can not cover the ironclad facts. 伪善的谎言掩盖不了铁的事实。', '副词: hypocritically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cogent', '[\'koʊdʒənt]', 'adj.有说服力的；令人信服的', '1. The lawyer\'s cogent arguments convinced the jury. 这位律师很有说服力的争辩使陪审团信服。 2. She put forward some cogent reasons for abandoning the plan. 她为放弃这个计划提出了一些具有说服力的理由。', '副词: cogently 名词: cogency');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('procrustean', '[ˌproʊ\'krʌstiən]', 'adj.强求一致的', '1. We are firmly opposed to the policy of a Procrustean bed. 我们坚决反对强求一致的政策。 2. I didn\'t put forth the plan as a Procrustean bed,to which exact conformity is to be indispensable. 我不能发表强求一致的计划书，精确的一致性是绝对必要的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bulb', '[bʌlb]', 'n.球茎；电灯泡；球状物', '1. Onions and lilies grow from bulbs. 洋葱和百合是从球茎中长出的。 2. This light bulb has gone. 这灯泡不亮了。 3. The light bulb imploded. 这灯泡是向内侧爆裂的。 4. I can see clearly that the filament in the bulb is broken. 我可以很清楚地看到灯泡里的细丝断了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('episodic', '[ˌepɪ\'sɑːdɪk]', 'adj.插曲式的；偶然发生的；短暂的；由一系列片段组成的', '1. This is an old-fashioned episodic show. 这是个老式的插话式系列剧。 2. The book is episodic and the incidents don\'t always hang together. 这本书是插话式的,事件并不总是连贯发生的。 3. Bleeding may be continuous but is usually episodic. 出血可以是持续的，但常是间歇的。 4. The pain initially was steady, but after seeral hours became episodic. 起初疼痛无变化,但数小时后变成发作性的痛。', '副词: episodically 异体字: episodical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reagent', '[ri\'eɪdʒənt]', 'n.试药；试剂', '1. The reagent possesses specificity for water. 这种试剂对水有特殊的作用。 2. This bifunctional reagent links protein molecules to one another. 这种双用试剂把蛋白质分子彼此连接起来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('paean', '[\'piːən]', 'n.欢乐歌；赞美歌', '1. It is a paean of the history of mankind. 那是人类历史上不断重演着的赞歌。 2. The novel is a paean to the end of empire. 该小说奏响了一个帝国落寞的赞歌。', '形容词: paeanistic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('octogenarian', '[ˌɑːktədʒə\'neriən]', 'n.八旬老人(八十到八十九岁间)', '1. She is very active for an octogenarian. 她已经是八旬老人了，还很精神。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insular', '[\'ɪnsələr]', 'adj.岛的；岛民的；岛特有的；与世隔绝的；保守的', '1. A continental climate is different from an insular one. 大陆性气候不同于岛屿气候。 2. The British caricature themselves as a nation of insular xenophobes. 英国人自嘲为惧怕外族、与世隔绝的民族。 3. They are insular--and proud of it. 他们保守，并对此感到自豪。', '副词: insularly 名词: insularism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prodigious', '[prə\'dɪdʒəs]', 'adj.巨大的；惊人的；奇异的', '1. A nuclear reactor generates prodigious amounts of heat. 一座核反应堆能发出巨大的热量。 2. We are all overwhelmed by his prodigious memory. 我们都被他那惊人的记忆力折服了。 3. The Sussex ironworks were carried on at such a prodigious expense of wood. 苏塞克斯铁厂象这样办下去使木材造成如此惊人的耗费。 4. She was shocked by the prodigious view. 她对这奇异的景象感到震惊。', '副词: prodigiously 名词: prodigiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('implode', '[ɪm\'ploʊd]', 'v.内爆；向内聚爆；崩溃，瓦解', '1. China, to beat my old drum, is not going to collapse or implode. 请容许我重申我的意见，中国是不会倒塌或内爆的。 2. Do we have a strategy in place about what to do if Pakistan should begin to implode? 如果巴基斯坦开始内爆，我们有没有什么应对战略？', '过去式: imploded 过去分词: imploded 现在分词: imploding 第三人称单数: implodes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peddle', '[\'pedl]', 'v.兜售；(沿街)叫卖；散播', '1. He peddled small household articles around the town. 他在城里挨家挨户兜售日用百货。 2. Beside them, excitable young men peddle DVDs and designer sunglasses. 就在她们身边不远，热火朝天的年轻人们叫卖着DVD和设计新潮的太阳镜。 3. The man loves to peddle gossip all over the office. 这个人喜欢满办公室散布流言蜚语。', '过去式: peddled 过去分词: peddled 现在分词: peddling 第三人称单数: peddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('winsome', '[\'wɪnsəm]', 'adj.迷人的；可爱的；快活的', '1. She was young, beautiful, and winsome. 当时的她，青春美貌，魅力四射。 2. She looked around throwing him a winsome smile. 她环顾了一下四周,给他迷人的一笑。', '副词: winsomely 名词: win-someness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verdant', '[\'vɜːrdnt]', 'adj.翠绿的；青翠的；稚嫩的', '1. Children are playing on the verdant lawn. 孩子们在绿茵茵的草坪上嬉戏玩耍。 2. The verdant mountain forest turns red gradually in the autumn wind. 苍翠的山林在秋风中渐渐变红了。 3. Wide roads lead to the top of the mountain covered with verdant tea-gardens. 宽阔的大道通向布满翠绿茶园的山顶。 4. They soon found him in a verdant valley. 不久他们便在一个青翠的山谷里找到了他。', '副词: verdantly 名词: verdancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infringe', '[ɪn\'frɪndʒ]', 'v.违反；侵犯', '1. We\'d better not infringe any of the rules. 我们还是不要违反规定才好。 2. They infringe the principle of non-discrimination. 他们违犯了非歧视原则。 3. They infringed on her rights. 他们侵犯了她的权力。 4. The publishing house infringed his copyright. 出版社侵犯了他的版权。', '名词: infringer 过去式: infringed 过去分词: infringed 现在分词: infringing 第三人称单数: infringes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('premonition', '[ˌpriːmə\'nɪʃn]', 'n.（不祥的）预感', '1. He had a premonition of impending doom. 他有一种不祥的预感。 2. The day before her accident, she had a premonition of danger. 在发生事故的前一天，她有一种会发生危险的预感。', '形容词: premonitory 副词: premonitorily');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('allusion', '[ə\'luːʒn]', 'n.暗指；暗示', '1. I was mentioned in the meeting by an allusion. 我在会议上被暗指。 2. The allusion served as a timely reminder to Darnay. 这暗示即刻提醒了代尔那。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('baton', '[bə\'tɑːn]', 'n.指挥棒；接力棒；警棍；权杖；短棍', '1. The conductor swept her baton through the air. 指挥家将她的指挥棒在空中挥。 2. The policeman used his baton to battle with the rascal. 警察用警棍和歹徒搏斗。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enlist', '[ɪn\'lɪst]', 'vt.征募；使入伍；获得...支持 vi.入伍；参与', '1. We must enlist more men. 我们必须征募更多士兵。 2. We enlisted them to serve as ushers at the meeting. 我们征集他们当会议招待员。 3. She tried to enlist our support in the cause of the charity. 她试图招揽我们在那慈善事业上的支持。 4. He enlisted when he was 18. 他18岁时入伍。', '名词: enlistment 过去式: enlisted 过去分词: enlisted 现在分词: enlisting 第三人称单数: enlists');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concord', '[\'kɑːŋkɔːrd]', 'n.和睦；协约；和谐；一致；康科德镇（位于美国马萨诸塞州）', '1. These neighboring states had lived in concord for centuries. 这些相互毗邻的国家几个世纪以来一直和睦相处。 2. His speech did nothing for racial concord. 他的讲话对种族和谐没有作用。 3. The stars move in harmony and concord. 星辰在和谐一致中运行。 4. In English, there must be concord between a verb and its subject. 英语中动词与主语必须一致。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trek', '[trek]', 'vi.长途跋涉 n.艰苦跋涉', '1. It took us a week to trek to the foot of the mountain. 我们花了一星期才跋涉到山脚。 2. I hate having to trek up that hill with all the groceries. 我很不愿意得带着这么多吃用杂物爬上那个山头。 3. The trek is especially difficult for us. 我们走起来更加艰难。 4. My boots were punished by our long trek in the mountains. 我的靴子因为我们在山中漫长的徒步而受损。', '名词: trekker 过去式: trekked 过去分词: trekked 现在分词: trekking 第三人称单数: treks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appeal', '[ə\'piːl]', 'n.恳求；呼吁；上诉；吸引力 n.(体育比赛中)诉请裁决 v.呼吁；有吸引力；求助；诉请', '1. Their appeal for help went unheeded. 他们求助的呼吁未受到注意。 2. He made one last appeal to his father to forgive him. 他最後一次恳求父亲宽恕他。 3. His appeal to a higher court was set aside. 他的上诉被驳回。 4. The judge rejected the appeal made by the prisoner for a new trial. 法官驳回了犯人提出重新审理的上诉。 5. The police appealed to the crowd not to panic. 警方向群众呼吁不要惊慌。', '形容词: appealable 名词: appealability 过去式: appealed 过去分词: appealed 现在分词: appealing 第三人称单数: appeals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bravura', '[brə\'vjʊrə]', 'n.华美的乐曲；勇敢大胆的表现 adj.雄壮华丽的；气势磅礴的', '1. This picture has a bravura of execution. 这幅画作风大胆。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spout', '[spaʊt]', 'n.【C】喷口；水管；水柱 v.喷出；滔滔不绝地说', '1. The spout of the teapot is jammed by tea. 茶壶的壶口被茶叶堵住了。 2. A thin cloud of steam was rising from the spout . 喷口处冒出一股薄薄的水蒸气。 3. The eensy weensy spider went up the water spout. 小蜘蛛顺着水管向上爬， 4. Rain runs down a spout from our roof to the ground. 雨水经过雨水管从我们的屋顶流到了地上。 5. Water is spouting out of the pipe. 水正从管子里喷出来。', '名词: spouter 过去式: spouted 过去分词: spouted 现在分词: spouting 第三人称单数: spouts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('centigrade', '[\'sentɪɡreɪd]', 'adj.摄氏的；百分度的', '1. This thermometer is calibrated by centigrade. 这种温度计是用摄氏百分度标定的。 2. It is therefore usually expressed in percentage terms rather than in engineering units such as degrees centigrade. 因此它往往用一个百分比来表示而不是机械单位如百分度表示。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vanilla', '[və\'nɪlə]', 'n.香草', '1. He used to love milk flavoured with vanilla. 他过去常爱喝带香草味的牛奶。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stir', '[stɜːr]', 'vt.激起；惹起；搅和 vi.活动；引起；挪动 n.骚乱；感动(激动；愤怒或震动)；搅拌', '1. The story stirred her sympathy. 这故事激起了她的同情心。 2. They tried to stir the peoples of the world into triumphant action. 他们试图激励人民大众的无限热情。 3. The oatmeal lumps if you don\'t stir it well. 如果你不好好搅拌，麦片粥会结块。 4. He didn\'t stir while sitting there. 他坐在那里一动不动。 5. The news caused quite a stir in the village. 那消息在村里引起了一片混乱。', '名词: stirrer 过去式: stirred 过去分词: stirred 现在分词: stirring 第三人称单数: stirs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mordant', '[\'mɔːrdnt]', 'adj.尖酸的；有腐蚀性的 n.金属腐蚀剂；金箔粘著剂 v.用媒染剂处理', '1. His mordant wit appealed to students. 他那尖刻的妙语受到学生们的欢迎。 2. Actors feared the critic\'s mordant pen. 演员都惧怕这位批评家辛辣尖刻的笔调。 3. Cannot use wet mop or mordant liquid (like suds, benzine) wipe a floor. 不能用湿拖把或有腐蚀性的液体（如肥皂水、汽油）擦拭地板。 4. A solution called a modernt mordant is used in the dying dyeing process. 染色的过程中要用到一种被称为媒染剂的溶液。', '副词: mordantly 名词: mordancy 过去式: mordanted 过去分词: mordanted 现在分词: mordanting 第三人称单数: mordants');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distend', '[dɪ\'stend]', 'v.扩大；扩张；吹大；膨胀', '1. Swollen or distended beyond normal size by fluid or gaseous material. 肿胀的液体或气体材料超过正常尺寸的肿胀或膨胀 2. Having eyes with greatly distended pupils. 眼珠暴突的具有带有膨大的瞳孔的眼睛的', '过去式: distended 过去分词: distended 现在分词: distending 第三人称单数: distends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('individual', '[ˌɪndɪ\'vɪdʒuəl]', 'adj.单独的；一个人的；独有的 n.个人；个体', '1. A teacher can\'t give individual attention to each pupil if his class is large. 如果班上的人数多，老师就不能给予个别辅导了。 2. It is difficult for a teacher to give individual attention to children in a large class. 教师在人数多的班上，很难对各个学生都照顾到。 3. She has her own individual style of doing things. 她有自己独特的行事风格。 4. No individual shall overtop the law. 任何个人的权力都不能凌驾于法律之上。', '副词: individually');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('molt', '[moʊlt]', 'n.换毛；脱皮；换毛期 v.换毛；脱皮 =moult(美).', '1. This veterinary product is very effective in preventing animal molt. 这种兽药对于防治兽类掉毛很有效。 2. Generally, molt occurs at the time of least stress on the birds. 通常，换羽期发生在小鸟压力最小的时候。 3. They want to check the effect on forcing breeder broilers to molt in different feeding way. 他们想要检查肉种鸡在不同饲养方式下强制换羽的效果。 4. The fourth time they molt, they change into pupae. 换第四次皮时,它们蜕变成蛹。', '名词: molter 过去式: molted 过去分词: molted 现在分词: molting 第三人称单数: molts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bourgeois', '[ˌbʊr\'ʒwɑː]', 'n.中产阶级的人；资产阶级的人 adj.中产阶级的；追求名利的；资产阶级的', '1. The French Revolution was inspired by the bourgeois. 法国革命受到中产阶级的鼓励。 2. After he bought the new car, his friends started to call him a bourgeois. 他买了新车之后,朋友们开始称他为中产阶级。 3. She seemed to think every man I a suit was bourgeois, which was just inverted snobbery of the worst kind. 她似乎认为穿西服的人都是资产阶级分子，这是最极端的反势利行为。 4. This is a typical bourgeois neighborhood. 这是一个典型的中产阶级地区。', '名词复数: bourgeois');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trickery', '[\'trɪkəri]', 'n.欺骗；诡计', '1. He is suspected of employing trickery. 他有弄虚作假的嫌疑。 2. He\'ll be found out,sure as fate,if he tries a silly piece of trickery like that. 如果他想耍那愚蠢的诡计，他肯定会被发现。', '名词复数: trickeries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fantasia', '[fæn\'teɪziə]', 'n.幻想曲', '1. Can\'t wait to listen to the fantasia! 等不及想听狂想曲了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('operetta', '[ˌɑːpə\'retə]', 'n.小歌剧；轻歌剧', '1. My heart beat wildly at my first public performance, a school operetta. 在第一次学校小歌剧的公开表演时，我的心疯狂地跳著。 2. In his adopted country his family ran a Spanish operetta troupe. 在他的第二祖国，家人经营一个西班牙轻歌剧团。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('occidental', '[ˌɒksɪ\'dentl]', 'n.西洋人；西方人 adj.西洋的；西方的', '1. Whether they are oriental or occidental,they all love peace. 不管是东方人还是西方人，他们都爱和平。 2. I think the Occidental ways are better. 我认为西方的方式。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slough', '[slaʊ]', 'n.泥坑；沼泽；沮丧的情况；(蛇等)蜕皮 v.蜕皮；摆脱 =sluff.', '1. Simon fell Into a dirty slough. 西蒙掉下来落在肮脏的泥沼里。 2. The horses were stalled in a slough. 马陷入泥沼中进退不得。 3. He saved her from the slough of despond. 他把她从绝望的深渊中拯救了出来。 4. There is no hopeless situation that is insurmountable but people with a slough of despond. 世上没有绝望的处境，只有对处境绝望的人。 5. Snakes slough off their skins once a year. 蛇每年蜕皮一次。', '形容词: sloughy 异体字: slew');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jocund', '[\'dʒɑːkənd]', 'adj.快乐的；高兴的', '1. Her jocund character made her the most popular girl in the county. 她快乐的个性使她成为这个郡最受欢迎的女孩。', '副词: jocundly 名词: jocundity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conjoin', '[kən\'dʒɔɪn]', 'v.结合；连结；联合', '1. On those days Mercury will conjoin Jupiter, a lovely influence. 届时水星将结合木星，产生可爱的影响力。 2. We know evolution happened because innumerable bits of data from myriad fields of science conjoin to paint a rich portrait of life\'s pilgrimage. 我们知道演化确实发生过，因为科学中各式各样的领域提供了无数的素材，结合起来描绘出多采多姿的生命演化图像。', '名词: conjoiner 过去式: conjoined 过去分词: conjoined 现在分词: conjoining 第三人称单数: conjoins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elegy', '[\'elədʒi]', 'n.悲歌；哀歌；挽歌', '1. Critics have spent entire books interpreting Gray\'s \"Elegy. 批评家们整本整本的书长篇累牍的来诠释格雷的“挽歌”。', '名词复数: elegies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aviary', '[\'eɪvieri]', 'n.大鸟笼；鸟舍', '1. There are many different kinds of birds in the aviary. 大鸟笼里有很多不同种类的鸟。 2. A cat heard that the birds in a certain aviary were ailing. 猫听说在某鸟舍内的鸟患病。', '名词: aviarist 名词复数: aviaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('salvage', '[\'sælvɪdʒ]', 'vt.救助；打捞；抢救 n.海上救助；打捞；抢救', '1. The government tried to salvage several business companies from bankruptcy. 政府设法把这几个商业公司从破产境地中拯救出来。 2. They are trying to salvage the wrecked ship. 他们努力抢救遇难的船只。 3. All attempts to salvage the wrecked ship failed. 抢救失事船只的一切努力都失败了。 4. It is time for Morrison to salvage his career. 这是莫里森拯救他职业生涯的时代。 5. Salvage of the wreck is made difficult by bad weather. 船遇难後因天气恶劣救援工作十分困难。', '形容词: salvageable 名词: salvageability 过去式: salvaged 过去分词: salvaged 现在分词: salvaging 第三人称单数: salvages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ostracism', '[\'ɑːstrəsɪzəm]', 'n.流放；放逐；排斥', '1. Questioning the status quo carries the danger of ostracism, possibly persecution. 质疑现状带来被排斥的危险，还很可能受到迫害。 2. For the first time in her life the import and horror of social ostracism flashed upon her. 她生平第一次突然想到遭受社交界排斥的意义与可怕。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chaperone', '[\'ʃæpəroʊn]', 'n.女伴；陪伴人 v.伴护', '1. The old chaperon grouped the younger children together. 那年长女伴将年纪较小的孩子聚集在一起。 2. He has signed up to be the chaperone at the dance. 他已答应在舞会中担任监护任务。 3. Teachers often chaperon their classes on field trips. 在野外郊游时老师常看护着班上的学生。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detraction', '[dɪ\'trækʃən]', 'n.诽谤；减损', '1. The scandal will not detract from his fame. 这一丑闻无损於他的名声。 2. His bad manners detract from his good character. 他的不礼貌减损了他的品质。 3. Do they detract from the clarity of the articles? 他们是否有损于文章的清晰? 4. This will detract from his reputation. 这件事有损他的名誉。', '形容词: detractive 副词: detractively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('depict', '[dɪ\'pɪkt]', 'vt.描述；描绘；画', '1. Her novel depicts life in modern London. 她的小说描写的是伦敦现代的生活。 2. The book depicts him as a rather unpleasant character. 这本书把他刻画成一个相当令人讨厌的人物。 3. This painting depicts the birth of Venus. 这幅画描绘的是维纳斯的诞生。 4. It\'s a picture depicting him as a clown. 这是一幅把他画成小丑的画。', '名词: depiction 过去式: depicted 过去分词: depicted 现在分词: depicting 第三人称单数: depicts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deadpan', '[\'dedpæn]', 'adj.表情冷淡的的 v.面无表情地表达 n.冷面孔；面无表情的人', '1. He is good at delivering jokes in a deadpan way. 他很擅长不动声色的讲笑话。 2. Some people find it harder to catch a deadpan humor, which makes it more charming. 一些人认为冷面笑话更难理解，这让它更具魅力。 3. When you come on stage, look like a deadpan. 你在舞台上面无表情，像具僵尸。', '过去式: deadpanned 过去分词: deadpanned 现在分词: deadpanning 第三人称单数: deadpans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('asylum', '[ə\'saɪləm]', 'n.收容所；避难所；（政治）庇护；精神病院', '1. Here is an asylum for the care of mentally ill or destitute people. 这儿是一家照顾精神病患者和赤贫人员的收容所。 2. We\'ll start an asylum for old-time people. 我们要给老一代人准备一个避难所。 3. The people ask for political asylum. 人们请求政治避难。 4. He was soon committed to an insane asylum. 不久他就给送进了疯人院。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insoluble', '[ɪn\'sɑːljəbl]', 'adj.[化]不能溶解的；不能解决的', '1. These chemicals are practically insoluble in water. 这些化学物质几乎不溶于水。 2. We couldn\'t finish the insoluble problem given by our teacher. 我们没法解决老师给的那个不能解决的问题。', '副词: insolubly 名词: insolubility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flummox', '[\'flʌməks]', 'vt.使混乱；使迷惑；使失措', '1. She can flummox anybody by the lip. 她能把任何人数落得狼狈不堪。 2. The politician was completely flummoxed by the questions put to her. 那位女政治家被问得十分狼狈。', '过去式: flummoxed 过去分词: flummoxed 现在分词: flummoxing 第三人称单数: flummoxes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('standstill', '[\'stændstɪl]', 'n.停顿', '1. Work is grinding to a standstill. 工作逐渐陷入停顿。 2. The strike has brought production to a standstill. 罢工已使生产停顿。 3. Smog used to bring London traffic to a standstill. 过去伦敦的交通常因烟雾而受阻。 4. This brought all trade to a standstill. 这使一切贸易陷于停顿。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('autonomous', '[ɔː\'tɑːnəməs]', 'adj.自治的', '1. Each of the U.S. states has an autonomous government. 美国的每个州都有一个自治政府。 2. The former Soviet Union is formed of several autonomous republic. 前苏联是由数个自治共和国组成的。', '副词: autonomously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hallmark', '[\'hɔːlmɑːrk]', 'n.纯度标记；标志；特征 vt.标纯度', '1. One hallmark of a good politician is his ability to influence people. 衡量一个优秀政治家的标志之一就是他影响大众的能力。 2. Clear expression is the hallmark of a good speaker. (喻)清晰的表达能力是一位出色的演说家的特征。 3. The research, carried out on mice, suggested caffeine hampered the production of the protein plaques which are the hallmark of the disease. 研究人员用老鼠做实验，发现咖啡因可以阻止蛋白斑块积聚，而这种蛋白是早老年性痴呆发病的典型特征。 4. Given the prevalence of synthetic Alexandrite, they are also a fascinating hallmark of authenticity that helps us distinguish real gems from artificial impostors. 在人工合成亚力山大石流行的今天，内含物是鉴别宝石天然纯度的一个重要标志，有助于我们将天然宝石与人工合成赝品区别开来。', '过去式: hallmarked 过去分词: hallmarked 现在分词: hallmarking 第三人称单数: hallmarks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hearsay', '[\'hɪrseɪ]', 'n.传闻', '1. Hearsay definitely can\'t be regarded as accurate information. 道听途说的决然不能算作很准确的消息。 2. I knew by hearsay that he was the editor of the American Mercury. 我听说他是《美国信使》的编辑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lamentable', '[\'læməntəbl]', 'adj.可悲的；哀伤的；可怜的', '1. And then they disappeared, which was a lamentable development. 但是，很快这些面包圈就消失了，这真是个可悲的变化。 2. India\'s willingness to open its economy in reality is in lamentable contrast to its inability to commit itself at the WTO. 印度开放经济的意愿与其无法兑现向世贸组织所承诺的现实相比是非常可悲的。', '副词: lamentably');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('poncho', '[\'pɑːntʃoʊ]', 'n.斗篷；雨衣', '1. The original pattern in the book was a baby poncho. 原本书上的织图是小宝贝的斗篷， 2. I could make a poncho out of the shower curtain. 我可以把浴帘做个雨衣穿着。 3. He yawned and curled his body down farther beneath the poncho. 他打了个呵欠，把身子再蜷拢点儿，往雨披里缩了缩。', '名词复数: ponchos');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gridiron', '[\'ɡrɪdaɪərn]', 'n.橄榄球场；烤架', '1. He is the greatest quarterback in gridiron history. 他是橄榄球场历史上最伟大的四分卫。 2. She turned a cake on the gridiron. 她在烤架上翻着饼。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('composed', '[kəm\'poʊzd]', 'adj.镇静的；沉着的；由…组成的', '1. He was pale but perfectly composed. 他脸色苍白，却十分镇静。 2. Though badly frightened, she remained outwardly composed. 她虽然非常害怕，但表面上依然很镇静。 3. The performer was composed as she readied herself for her entrance on stage. 这位演员在准备上场时沉着冷静。 4. Water is composed of hydrogen and oxygen. 水由氢和氧组成。', '副词: composedly 名词: composedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('leach', '[liːtʃ]', 'n.垂直帆缘；后缘 =leech. v.过滤；萃取；溶解出', '1. You should open the leach a little bit. 你应当将帆后边打开。 2. It\'s not easy to leach out the black colour 将那黑色去掉是不容易的。 3. Nitrates leach from the soil into rivers. 硝酸盐由土壤渗入江河。 4. Liquid water can leach soluble materials from the interface. 液态水能够从界面溶解出可溶性物质。', '形容词: leachable 名词: leachability 过去式: leached 过去分词: leached 现在分词: leaching 第三人称单数: leaches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exaggerate', '[ɪɡ\'zædʒəreɪt]', 'vt.夸张；夸大；对...言过其实 vi.夸张；夸大其词', '1. Don\'t exaggerate the parallelism between the two cases. 不要夸大那两件事的相似性。 2. The seriousness of the situation has been much exaggerated by the press. 形势的严重性被报纸夸大了。 3. He tends to exaggerate the difficulties. 他往往夸大困难。 4. We should neither exaggerate nor ignore the differences. 虽然我们不能夸大这些不同，但是我们也不能忽视它们的存在。 5. If you exaggerate, you will sound fantastically American. 如果你发音夸张听起来会特别有美国味。', '形容词: exaggerative 副词: exaggeratedly 名词: exaggeration 过去式: exaggerated 过去分词: exaggerated 现在分词: exaggerating 第三人称单数: exaggerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distracted', '[dɪ\'stræktɪd]', 'adj.注意力不集中的；心烦意乱的 动词distract的过去式和过去分词.', '1. She didn\'t realize the extent to which she had been distracted. 她没有意识到她心烦意乱的程度。 2. The damsel distracted the Asuras, while the Devas secretly drank the Nectar. 正当这个少女使阿修罗心烦意乱的时候，天神们背地里喝了甘露。', '副词: distractedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('frond', '[frɑːnd]', 'n.蕨叶；叶状体；藻体', '1. The road stretches in frond of and behind the car . 那条路在车子的前面和后面伸展着。 2. The road stretches in frond of and behind the car. 那条路在车子的前面和后面伸展着。 3. The man in frond of you is a thief from England. 你前面的那个人是一个从英国来的贼。 4. Her peaceful aspect is depicted by the lotus frond. 她平静的一面是用莲化来描绘。', '形容词: fronded');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('delineate', '[dɪ\'lɪnieɪt]', 'vt.描绘；叙述；画出', '1. Control uses steps to delineate different sections of user data input. 控件使用多个步骤来描绘用户数据输入的不同部分。 2. You can use semicolons to delineate multiple filter patterns within a filter option. 您可以使用分号来描绘一个筛选选项中的多个筛选模式。', '形容词: delineative 名词: delineation 过去式: delineated 过去分词: delineated 现在分词: delineating 第三人称单数: delineates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thrash', '[θræʃ]', 'n.打(谷)；鞭打 vt.抽打；彻底击败 vi.痛打；猛烈移动（动荡）', '1. Farmers used to thrash their wheat by hand. 农民过去用手打麦脱粒。 2. They thrash him until he could not stand. 他们直到把他打得站不起来才住手。 3. She would never thrash her children. 她绝不会鞭打她的孩子。 4. Of course it is out of the question that Johnson should thrash Wolf Larsen. 约翰森当然不会痛打海狼赖生的。', '名词: thrasher 过去式: thrashed 过去分词: thrashed 现在分词: thrashing 第三人称单数: thrashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suffragist', '[\'sʌfrədʒɪst]', 'n.参政权扩大论者；妇女政权论者', '1. Location Criterion Revive Pit - Replaced Enlivened Stone’s Suffragist Beat Powerfulness with a version of Unstable Boom. 股票本金一旦交给公司，就不能再收回，只要公司存在，就永远归公司支配。 2. This set grants neither.Location Criterion Revive Pit - Replaced Enlivened Stone’s Suffragist Beat Powerfulness with a version of Unstable Boom. 之前，她已经在网络的论坛里听说过这条消息，据说呛了孩子的特级月嫂根本不具备带小婴儿的能力。 3. In 1873, suffragist Susan B. Anthony was fined 100 dollars for attempting to vote in the 1872 presidential election (however, the fine was never paid). 1873年，妇女政权论者苏姗B.;安东尼因为试图在1872年总统选举中投票而被处以100美元的罚款（但是罚金没有交） 4. The whole argument with the anti-suffragists，or even the critical suffragist man，is this：that： youcan govern human beings without their consent. 对争取妇女选举权持反对态度的人或持批评意见的人的全部论点只是：你可以统治别人而不必得到他们的同意。', '名词: suffragism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('silt', '[sɪlt]', 'n.淤泥 v.(使)淤塞', '1. The harbor is being up with silt. 那海港被淤泥阻塞了。 2. A concrete wall is built to stop silt from leaking to the conservation land. 一道水泥墙修筑起来，用以防止泥沙流进保留地。 3. The sand have silt up the mouth of the river. 泥沙已把河口堵住了。', '形容词: silty 名词: siltation 过去式: silted 过去分词: silted 现在分词: silting 第三人称单数: silts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('potboiler', '[\'pɑːtbɔɪlər]', 'n.为混饭吃而粗制滥造的文艺作品；粗制作品作家(或画家)', '1. This is just another legal potboiler. 这就是另一本法律题材的烂作。 2. The man who has to potboil for a living seldom accomplishes anything of an exceptional character. 为维持生计而粗制滥造文艺作品的人很少能创作出了不起的作品。 3. potboil vi. 为混饭吃而粗制滥造', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arena', '[ə\'riːnə]', 'n.竞技场', '1. The Roman arena was very famous. 罗马竞技场是很出名的。 2. The arena was crowded with thousands of spectators. 竞技场中挤满了数千名观众。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('canvass', '[\'kænvəs]', 'v.游说；兜售；详细检查；细究 n.细查；论究；劝诱；民意调查', '1. The party needs to canvass the uncommitted voters. 这个党需要向未表明态度的选民游说拉票。 2. These days they\'re busy for canvass. 这些天他们在忙着做民意调查。', '名词: canvasser 过去式: canvassed 过去分词: canvassed 现在分词: canvassing 第三人称单数: canvasses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grain', '[ɡreɪn]', 'n.谷物；谷类；微量；颗粒；纹理；格令 v.形成(颗粒)；(用谷物)喂养', '1. We ship grain to Africa. 我们把谷物运往非洲。 2. There are a few grains of rice in a bowl. 碗中有几颗米粒。 3. There isn\'t a grain of truth in it. 那事无丝毫真实性。 4. The coffee was good, but thick with grains. 咖啡很好, 但满是粒子。 5. Physical isolation goes against the corporate grain, the hierarchy being organized around the office. 身体上的隔绝违反合作意愿，使办公室周围形成特定阶层。', '名词: grainer 过去式: grained 过去分词: grained 现在分词: graining 第三人称单数: grains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thorn', '[θɔːrn]', 'n.刺；荆棘', '1. She got her finger pricked by a thorn. 她的手指被刺扎了一下。 2. One puts on gloves before grasping a thorn cudgel. 为了要握有刺的棍子，首先得戴上手套。 3. Priestesses are immune to their own thorn effects. 女祭司不会受自己创造的荆棘刺影响。 4. And still, we choose the pain of the thorn. 我们仍然选择了那痛苦的荆棘。', '形容词: thornless');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stratify', '[\'strætɪfaɪ]', 'v.（使）成层；分层', '1. Stratify teaching to be one to plant in lower individual-rization collective teaching form teaching tactics. 分层教学是一种在集体教学形式下的个别化教学策略。', '过去式: stratified 过去分词: stratified 现在分词: stratifying 第三人称单数: stratifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('garnish', '[\'ɡɑːrnɪʃ]', 'n.装饰；装饰品；勒索金 v.装饰；配菜；[法]传讯', '1. The turkey was served with a garnish of parsley. 做好的火鸡上面配上芫荽菜做点缀。 2. I\'d rather you didn\'t serve the dish with a garnish. 我希望菜上面没有什么点缀。 3. They garnish the room with modern painting. 他们以现代画装饰此房间。 4. Garnish the fish with cucumber slices. 这个鱼就用黄瓜片作配菜。', '过去式: garnished 过去分词: garnished 现在分词: garnishing 第三人称单数: garnishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stupefy', '[\'stuːpɪfaɪ]', 'v.(使)茫然；失去知觉', '1. Exhilarated or stupefied by or as if by alcohol; intoxicated. 醉的，陶醉的因(仿佛)喝酒类饮料而兴奋或木然的; 醉的 2. I was stupefied by what I read. 我读到的内容把我惊呆了。', '副词: stupefyingly 名词: stupefier 过去式: stupefied 过去分词: stupefied 现在分词: stupefying 第三人称单数: stupefies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monotone', '[\'mɑːnətoʊn]', 'n.(说话或唱歌)单调；(文体的)单调；单调音 adj.单调的；无变化的', '1. He speaks in a monotone and makes us want to sleep. 他说话声音单调，让人想要睡觉。 2. These are just some monotone concrete buildings. 这些只是些单调的混凝土建筑。', '形容词: monotonic 副词: monotonically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detract', '[dɪ\'trækt]', 'vi.减损 vt.转移', '1. His bad manners detract from his good character. 他的不礼貌减损了他的品质。 2. Pointing fingers will merely take up more time and detract from the argument for practicality. 用手指指向对方只会浪费更多的时间，并减损实用性的根据。', '名词: detractor 过去式: detracted 过去分词: detracted 现在分词: detracting 第三人称单数: detracts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tension', '[\'tenʃn]', 'n.紧张；拉力；张力；紧张状态；[电]电压 vt.使拉紧；使绷紧', '1. The tension is building up. 形势逐步紧张起来。 2. The tension soon transmitted itself to all the members of the crowd. 这种紧张情绪很快感染了人群中所有的人。 3. A positive-stress component means tension. 正应力分量表示拉力。 4. If a wire is held under tension, it gets slightly longer. 电线在拉力状态下会变得略微长点。', '形容词: tensional 过去式: tensioned 过去分词: tensioned 现在分词: tensioning 第三人称单数: tensions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bud', '[bʌd]', 'n.芽；花蕾 vi.发芽；萌芽 vt.使发芽', '1. The roses are in bud. 玫瑰花正含苞待放。 2. Summertime bud grafting can be cut take shoot piece, or take xylem shoot less piece, in stock bine dry place decorticates. 夏季芽接可削取芽片,或少带木质部芽片,在砧木茎干处剥皮。 3. The bud developed into a blossom. 花蕾开出了鲜花。 4. The magnolia tree is in bud already. 木兰树已经长出花蕾了。 5. Trees begin to bud in the spring. 树在春天开始发芽。 6. Some flowers bud their leaves very early in spring. 有些花在春季里很早发出叶来。', '名词: budder 过去式: budded 过去分词: budded 现在分词: budding 第三人称单数: buds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('replica', '[\'replɪkə]', 'n.复制品', '1. This replica is every inch as good as the original. 这种复制品完全和原版一样地好。 2. I had a replica in little of Independence Hall. 我有一件独立纪念堂的小型复制品。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('calibrate', '[\'kælɪbreɪt]', 'vt.校准；测定口径；使标准化', '1. My watch is faster, and I need calibrate it. 我的表走快了,我得把它校准。 2. You do not need to calibrate the motion sensor. 你无需校准运动传感器。 3. This thermometer is calibrated by centigrade. 这种温度计是用摄氏百分度标定的。', '名词: calibrator 过去式: calibrated 过去分词: calibrated 现在分词: calibrating 第三人称单数: calibrates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('geometrician', '[ˌdʒɪəme\'trɪʃən]', 'n.几何学者', '1. One felt that the chief of this barricade was a geometrician or a spectre. 我们感到这个街垒的首领是一个几何学家或一个鬼怪。 2. This article introduces the mathematic models of ass essing the geometri c error to be conveniently processed by MATLAB. The typical progrm is given. 本文介绍了适用MATLAB语言处理的有关形位误差评定的数学模型,以及相应数据处理方法,并给出典型实例。 3. The article discusses some conceptions such as MIPS, MFLOPS, synthetic testing program and characteristics geometri mean value, analyzes misunderstanding of them and puts forward the solutions. 本文针对MIPS、MFLOPS、合成测试程序和几何性能平均值几个概念及其主观误区的产生和解决方法作了详细分析和研究。 4. Dr Butterworth recalls an eminent geometrician (\"I won\'t say his name; 巴特沃斯博士回忆一个著名的几何学家（“我不会说他的名字，这会让他很难堪”）的故事。', 'none');
