INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coddle', '[\'kɑːdl]', 'v.娇养；溺爱；用文火煮', '1. He\'ll need to be coddled after his illness. 他病后需要悉心照料。 2. I would not coddle the child. 我不愿意溺爱这个孩子。 3. He never go to coddle his superior. 他从不去讨好上司。', '名词: coddler 过去式: coddled 过去分词: coddled 现在分词: coddling 第三人称单数: coddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('predecessor', '[\'predəsesər]', 'n.祖先；前任；原有事物', '1. The Yunxian Man fossil skull is believed by scientists to belong to homo erectus, a predecessor of homo sapiens that walked on their two legs with an upright body posture. 科学家们认为袁县人属于直立人，是靠两条腿直立行走的智力人的祖先。 2. Recently unearthed fossils trace whales to a doglike predecessor of hoofed plant-eaters, and genetic analysis has identified hippos as whales\' closest living relatives. 最近出土的化石使鲸的祖先可追溯到一种有蹄外形像狗的植食动物，而且基因分析证实了现存动物中河马是鲸的近亲。 3. He undid most of the good work of his predecessor. 他把前任的大部分业绩毁掉了。 4. Our new doctor is much younger than his predecessor. 我们新来的医生比他的前任年轻许多。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('purloin', '[pɜːr\'lɔɪn]', 'vt.偷窃', '1. What person purloin be after all their money? 究竟是什么人盗取了他们的钱呢？ 2. What person purloin be after all the money of these people? 究竟是什么人盗取了这些人的钱呢？ 3. \"It was so good, both my sons wanted to purloin it when I brought it back,\" he said. 他说：“那件衣服太棒了，我带回来之后，我的两个儿子都想将它据为己有。” 4. Struts are fixed to each side of the posts to provide further support to the ridge purloin. 立柱两侧安有对角撑,作为对脊檩的进一步支承。', '名词: purloiner 过去式: purloined 过去分词: purloined 现在分词: purloining 第三人称单数: purloins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('convulse', '[kən\'vʌls]', 'v.（使）震动；（使）抽搐', '1. This event convulse the whole world . 这个事件震惊中外。 2. Suddenly, he starts to convulse and his pulse goes into hyperdrive. 突然他开始痉挛', '过去式: convulsed 过去分词: convulsed 现在分词: convulsing 第三人称单数: convulses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insolate', '[\'ɪnsoʊˌleɪt]', 'vt.使曝晒', '1. The farmers insolate grains for storage. 农民们晒粮食以便储藏。 2. Plough deeply in 30cm, and insolate in the sun to disinfect. 深耕30厘米,翻晒日光消毒。 3. Insolate below burning sun, the skin is aglow now, should do how? ? 烈日下暴晒，现在皮肤发红，该咋办？？ 4. Insolate ageing of meeting hurried skin, give birth to cancer even. 暴晒会促皮肤老化，甚至生癌。', '过去式: insolated 过去分词: insolated 现在分词: insolating 第三人称单数: insolates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('refraction', '[rɪ\'frækʃn]', 'n.折光；折射', '1. Over water the diurnal change in refraction is likely to be small. 在水面上，折光的周日变化可能是很小的。 2. Refraction of light gives the above results. 光的折射会产生上述的结果。 3. This is a very good light refraction type of puzzle mobile games. 这是一款非常不错的光线折射类型的益智手机游戏。', '形容词: refractional 副词: refractively 名词: refractiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rip', '[rɪp]', 'v.撕裂；扯开 n.裂口；裂缝；撕裂', '1. The poster had been ripped to pieces. 那张广告画已被撕得粉碎。 2. I ripped my stocking on a nail. 一个钉子挂破了我的袜子。 3. You should rip the cover off the box first. 你首先应当把这个盒子的封套扯掉。 4. She sewed up the rip in his sleeve. 她缝好了他衣袖上的裂口。', '名词: ripper 过去式: ripped 过去分词: ripped 现在分词: ripping 第三人称单数: rips');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sewer', '[\'suːər]', 'n.下水道；阴沟 n.缝纫者 n.管家', '1. The sewer is choked up with rubbish. 下水道被垃圾堵住了。 2. The boy kicked a stone into the sewer . 那个男孩把一石子踢进下水道。 3. They are tearing up the street to repair a sewer. 他们正挖开马路修下水道。 4. The sewer in the kitchen clogs easily. 厨房的下水道很容易堵塞。 5. She became the best sewer in the factory. 她成了该厂最好的缝纫工。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discredit', '[dɪs\'kredɪt]', 'v.败坏…的名声；怀疑；不信 n.丧失名誉；怀疑；不信任；丢脸', '1. They concocted a plot to discredit the governor. 他们捏造了一个故事来败坏州长的名誉。 2. There was good reason to discredit the witness 有充足的理由怀疑证人。 3. There was good reason to discredit the witness. 有充分理由不相信那位证人。 4. There is no reason to discredit what she says. 没理由不信她说的话. 5. That brought discredit on his name. 那件事使他的名誉受损。', '过去式: discredited 过去分词: discredited 现在分词: discrediting 第三人称单数: discredits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trident', '[\'traɪdnt]', 'n.三叉戟 adj.三齿的', '1. Shemsen cast aside his trident and swam against the surge. 舍姆森把他的三叉矛放到一边，逆着巨浪游行。 2. The second person attacked the first and killed him with the trident. 第二个人向第一个人展开进攻，用三叉戟杀死了他。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fencing', '[\'fensɪŋ]', 'n.围墙；剑术；栅栏 动词fence的现在分词.', '1. The fencing of the farm was in poor repair. 该农场的围墙失修。 2. He said the fencing was being put up to deter trespassers. 他说将修建一座围墙来防止入侵者。 3. I use a heavy sabre in fencing. 我在击剑时用的是把重剑。 4. Her fencing is very consummating. 她的剑术非常精湛。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inflict', '[ɪn\'flɪkt]', 'vt.使遭受；施以；加害；折磨', '1. We inflicted a crushing defeat on the enemy. 我们把敌军打得一败涂地。 2. We should inflict severe chastisement on criminals. 我们应该对罪犯施加严厉的惩罚。 3. Don\'t inflict your belief on me. 不要把你的想法强加于我。 4. Don\'t inflict damage on any person. 不要伤害任何人。', '形容词: inflictive 名词: inflicter 过去式: inflicted 过去分词: inflicted 现在分词: inflicting 第三人称单数: inflicts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('implore', '[ɪm\'plɔːr]', 'v.恳求；哀求', '1. I implore you to go now. 我恳求你现在就走吧。 2. She implored me to do her a favor. 她恳求我帮她这个忙。', '副词: imploringly 名词: imploration 过去式: implored 过去分词: implored 现在分词: imploring 第三人称单数: implores');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gadfly', '[\'ɡædflaɪ]', 'n.虻；牛虻；惹人讨厌的人', '1. The Gadfly\'s endurance was failing him at last. 牛虻的忍受力也终于不能维持了。 2. The Gadfly insisted that the work should be finished by the middle of June. 牛虻坚持必须在六月中旬之前把工作做完。', '名词复数: gadflies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('argot', '[\'ɑːrɡət]', 'n.隐语；暗语；暗号；行话', '1. The argot and proverb created by them enrich Chinese language. 他们创造的隐语、歇后语、谚语等丰富了中国的语言。 2. Slang is an active linguistic constituent of English, which has entered dominant culture from cant, jargon, and argot of different sub-cultures. 俚语是英语中较为活跃的语言成分,它从大量不同亚文化的黑话、行话及暗语中溢出而进入主流文化。 3. For, it must be stated to those who are ignorant of the case, that argot is both a literary phenomenon and a social result. 因此，必须向不明真相的人说清楚，黑话是文学范畴中的一种奇迹，也是人类社会的一种产物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('odium', '[\'oʊdiəm]', 'n.憎恶；厌恶', '1. He incurred the odium of everyone by sacking the old caretaker. 他因解雇老管理员而激起公愤。 2. Her manner acquired her universal odium. 她的举止遭到普遍的非议。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('usury', '[\'juːʒəri]', 'n.高利；高利贷', '1. He returned her love and devotion with usury. 他给她的爱恋和忠诚以加倍地回报。 2. The interest of usury is unfairly high. 高利贷的利息惊人得高。 3. Usury is interest in excess of a legal rate. 高利贷是指超过法定利率取息。', '名词复数: usuries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pandemonium', '[ˌpændə\'moʊniəm]', 'n.喧嚣；极端混乱嘈杂的地方', '1. There was pandemonium when the news was announced. 消息宣布後一片混乱。 2. Pandemonium reigned in the classroom until the teacher arrived. 教师来到之前教室里乱哄哄的。', '形容词: pandemoniac');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concatenate', '[kɒn\'kætəˌneɪt]', 'v.连结；连锁 adj.连锁的', '1. Do not concatenate user input before validating it. 验证之前,不要串联用户输入。 2. The sequence to concatenate to the first sequence. 要与第一个序列连接的序列。 3. CONCATENATE P_YEAR \'年\' P_MONTH \'月\' INTO G_DATE. \'其他业务销售利润明细表（本月）\'. 4. Action: Use CONCATENATE or CONTINUEIF. 可是我试过只导入下一行，也是成功的，那说明下一行并没有超过长度限制了？', '名词: concatenation 过去式: concatenated 过去分词: concatenated 现在分词: concatenating 第三人称单数: concatenates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('atone', '[ə\'toʊn]', 'v.补偿；赎罪；偿还', '1. Nothing could atone for the loss of good blood. 没有什么能补偿优良血统的丧失。 2. He wished to atone for the wrong he had done. 他希望为他从前所犯的过错赎罪。 3. He could not avoid having to atone for what he had done. 他干了坏事，免不了要自食其果。 4. I am afraid he can not atone for all his misdeed . 恐怕他无法抵偿他所有的罪行。', '形容词: atonable 名词: atoner 过去式: atoned 过去分词: atoned 现在分词: atoning 第三人称单数: atones');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cadence', '[\'keɪdns]', 'n.节奏；韵律；降调句；抑扬顿挫', '1. The cadence of modern life constantly accelerates. 现代生活的节奏不断地加快。 2. The constant cadence of surf lulled us to sleep. 持久而有节奏的海浪声使我们睡着了。 3. Frances spoke with a soft, musical Edinburgh cadence. 弗朗西丝讲话时用一种柔和悦耳的爱丁堡声调。 4. He read the poems with cadence. 他抑扬顿挫地朗诵诗歌。', '形容词: cadenced 名词复数: cadences');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inhibit', '[ɪn\'hɪbɪt]', 'v.抑制；阻止；使不能', '1. You should inhibit wrong desires and impulses. 你应当抑制不正当的欲望和行动。 2. These compounds inhibit microbial growth. 这些化合物能抑制微生物的生长。 3. Why didn\'t you inhibit him from doing that? 为何你不阻止他做那种事? 4. They passed a law to inhibit people from parking in the street. 他们通过一项法令以阻止人们在街上停车。', '形容词: inhibitable 过去式: inhibited 过去分词: inhibited 现在分词: inhibiting 第三人称单数: inhibits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scowl', '[skaʊl]', 'n.愁容；皱眉 v.皱眉；（天空）变阴沉晦暗', '1. That scowl he\'s wearing on his face should tell you so. 他满脸的愁容告诉你他准备好了。 2. The boss manifested his disgust with a scowl. 老板皱皱眉表露出厌恶。 3. The boss manifested his disgust with a scowl. 老板皱皱眉表露出厌恶。', '副词: scowlingly 名词: scowler 过去式: scowled 过去分词: scowled 现在分词: scowling 第三人称单数: scowls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('genteel', '[dʒen\'tiːl]', 'adj.文雅的；有教养的', '1. She is too genteel for words. 她说话太咬文嚼字了。 2. You are genteel enough, you look like a lady. 你是够文雅的，看上去象个大家闺秀。 3. He came from a genteel family. 他出身於有教养的家庭。', '副词: genteelly 名词: genteelness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exclaim', '[ɪk\'skleɪm]', 'v.大叫；呼喊；大声说出', '1. The children exclaimed with excitement. 孩子们兴奋地大叫。 2. \"How beautiful the lake is!\" we exclaimed. 我们叫喊着说,\"这个湖多美啊!\" 3. She exclaimed at the beautiful view. 她对这美丽的景色感到惊奇。 4. She exclaimed that she was innocent. 她大声呼喊她是无辜的。', '名词: exclaimer 过去式: exclaimed 过去分词: exclaimed 现在分词: exclaiming 第三人称单数: exclaims');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('farewell', '[ˌfer\'wel]', 'int.再会；别了 n.告别 adj.告别的', '1. Farewell until we meet again! 下次再见！ 2. Farewell! I hope we meet again soon. 别了！希望很快我们能再见面。 3. I bade farewell to my parents. 我告别了双亲。 4. It\'s time to say our farewells. 是我们该告辞的时候了。 5. She had a fervent farewell speech. 她发表了热情的告别演说。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hypodermic', '[ˌhaɪpə\'dɜːrmɪk]', 'adj.皮下注射的；表皮的 n.皮下注射；皮下注射器', '1. He was frightened at seeing the hypodermic needle. 看到那个皮下注射针头他害怕极了。', '副词: hypodermically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('leeway', '[\'liːweɪ]', 'n.余地', '1. Give me lots of leeway around the chest. 胸围部分多给我留些余地。 2. This point is no leeway for dispute. 这一点是没有争论的余地的。 3. Better to be quiet and leave a little leeway. 还是少说几句，留点余地罢。 4. We have an hour\'s leeway to catch the express. 我们还有一小时的充裕时间搭那班快车。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forager', '[\'fɒrɪdʒə]', 'n.觅食者；强征(粮食)的人', '1. \"Only a few words,\" replies the forager. \"我只会说几个词。\"抢劫犯回答。 2. In Japan a fungus forager can earn a good living. 在日本，采蘑菇可以过上富足的生活。 3. \"A forager won\'t come back until it finds something,\" Gordon says. “一只觅食蚁在发现食物之前是不会返回蚁巢的”，戈尔顿博士讲道。 4. Stom J A ,Buttery B R .vine forager and the aggegation of a clavy loam soil[J]. 席远官.;有机农业生产基地建设、质量控制及关键技术。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('besot', '[bɪ\'sɒt]', 'v.使糊涂；使迷糊；使醉', '1. He is besotted by her beauty. 她的美丽使他如痴如醉。 2. He is besotted with love. 他被爱情弄昏了头。', '过去式: besotted 过去分词: besotted 现在分词: besotting 第三人称单数: besots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('domicile', '[\'dɑːmɪsaɪl]', 'n.住所；住宅', '1. Domicile is distinct from nationality. 住所与国籍不同。 2. Article 10 A company shall regard the locus of its main office as its domicile. 第十条公司以其主要办事机构所在地为住所。', '形容词: domiciliary 过去式: domiciled 过去分词: domiciled 现在分词: domiciling 第三人称单数: domiciles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concoct', '[kən\'kɑːkt]', 'v.捏造；调制', '1. And they had taken me so long to concoct. 我花了好长时间编造这些谎言。 2. She\'d concocted some unlikely tale about the train being cancelled. 她胡编了一通瞎话,说什么那班火车给取消了。 3. I gave her a tip on how to concoct a new kind of soup. 我教她配制一种新汤的诀窍。', '名词: concocter 过去式: concocted 过去分词: concocted 现在分词: concocting 第三人称单数: concocts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disagreeable', '[ˌdɪsə\'ɡriːəbl]', 'adj.不愉快的；厌恶的；不为人喜的', '1. He always tried to avoid disagreeable topics. 他总是努力避免不愉快的话题。 2. She is always so disagreeable when we ask her to help. 我们请她帮忙时，她总是那么不友好。 3. Some fruits are disagreeable to the taste. 有几种果子味道不好。', '副词: disagreeably 名词: disagreeableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('texture', '[\'tekstʃər]', 'n.质地；手感；口感；组织；结构；纹理；特点 vt.给予结构', '1. This kind of cloth has a close texture. 这种布质地很紧密。 2. We could feel the smooth texture of silk. 我们能感觉出丝绸的光滑质地。 3. The texture of the rug was very soft. 毯子的手感非常柔软。 4. The cake has a nice light texture. 这蛋糕松软可口。', '形容词: textural 副词: texturally 过去式: textured 过去分词: textured 现在分词: texturing 第三人称单数: textures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('personable', '[\'pɜːrsənəbl]', 'adj.风度翩翩的', '1. The salesman was a very personable young man. 推销员是个风度翩翩的年轻人。 2. The manager\'s wife is both personable and smart. 经理的妻子优雅又精明。', '副词: personably 名词: personableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grim', '[ɡrɪm]', 'adj.严厉的；冷酷的；可怕的；不愉快的', '1. Her face wore a grim, set look. 她脸上显出严厉、 木然的神情。 2. His expression was grim when he told them they had lost their job. 当他告诉他们说他们已被解雇时，他的表情十分冷酷。 3. A grim and unsightly picture met his eye. 一幅可怕和难看的情景映入他的眼帘。 4. I had a pretty grim day yesterday. 我昨天很不愉快。', '副词: grimly 比较级: grimmer 最高级: grimmest 名词: grimness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gristle', '[\'ɡrɪsl]', 'n.软骨结构；软骨', '1. Because in the day, their vertebral gristle can be easily tread down. 因为在白天脊椎的软骨组织容易遭到压迫。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coop', '[kuːp]', 'n.笼子 v.把…关起来', '1. He is mending the wire mesh in front of the chicken coop. 他正在鸡笼前面修理铁丝网。 2. We have to coop the dog up all day. 我们只得把狗整天关起来。', '过去式: cooped 过去分词: cooped 现在分词: cooping 第三人称单数: coops');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sensitize', '[\'sensətaɪz]', 'v.（使）敏感；（使）具有感光性；（使）意识到', '1. This regulation is time sensit... 这种调整具有时间敏感性。 2. Conclusion:KLT could sensitize 95D cells to Gemzar in vitro. 康莱特先于健择加入对95D的抑制最强。 3. A silver salt, especially silver nitrate, used to sensitize paper. 银盐，硝酸银：一种银酸盐，尤指硝酸银，用于使纸感光 4. Depilatory Hot Wax (Hard).This product is used for hair removal for sensit... 我方应客户要求寻找以下两种脱毛蜡: 1.', '名词: sensitization 过去式: sensitized 过去分词: sensitized 现在分词: sensitizing 第三人称单数: sensitizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mulish', '[\'mjuːlɪʃ]', 'adj.骡似的；执拗的；杂种的', '1. He was so mulish that my admonitions just flowed over him. 他很顽固，我的告诫对他只不过是耳边风。 2. \"Obstinate is no word for it, for she is mulish\" (Ouida). “固执到无法形容，她太执拗了” （维达）。 3. What carry on the back on mulish horse is commissariat. 骡马上驮的都是粮食。 4. She would have to use more finesse to rein in this big mulish creature who would buck if provoked. 因此，她才越觉得有点意思，她颇得用点心思才能拢得住这个急了也会尥蹶的大人，或是大东西。', '副词: mulishly 名词: mulishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lance', '[læns]', 'n.枪矛；矛状器具；鱼叉；配矛骑兵 v.以枪矛攻击；投掷；用柳叶刀切开；快速向前', '1. The horseman aimed his lance at his quarry. 骑手把长矛对准了他的猎物。 2. He was so vain and reckless that he would break a lance or two with his general. 年轻的军官一心取胜，他并不害怕与自己的将军比试一下。 3. It doesn\'t like dragger, but likes lance. 看起来不像是匕首，更像矛。 4. I\'ll break a lance with you in argument. 我要和你辩论，一决胜负。', '过去式: lanced 过去分词: lanced 现在分词: lancing 第三人称单数: lances');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ostentation', '[ˌɑːsten\'teɪʃn]', 'n.卖弄；虚饰；炫耀；<古>摆阔；讲排场', '1. He ignored the public ostentation of his time, as well as the private misery. 他忽视了当时在社会上流行的卖弄浮夸和一般平民的悲困痛苦。 2. The statue had beauty without ostentation. 那座雕像有一种非虚饰的美。 3. Their daughter\'s wedding reception was sheer ostentation. 他们女儿大办婚事纯然是为了炫耀. 4. He objected on principle to luxury and ostentation. 他反对奢侈摆阔。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('garment', '[\'ɡɑːrmənt]', 'n.衣服 vt.给 ... 披上衣服；覆上 ...', '1. This garment should be washed carefully. 这件衣服应该小心地洗涤。 2. The garment fits her perfectly. 这件衣服她穿上很合适。 3. In spring nature wears a new garment. 春天', '过去式: garmented 过去分词: garmented 现在分词: garmenting 第三人称单数: garments');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('masticate', '[\'mæstɪkeɪt]', 'v.咀嚼（食物）', '1. Americans now masticate 86 million pounds of meat every day. 美国人现在每天要吃掉八千六百万磅的肉。 2. The mouth is so dry that it is difficulty for the patient to masticate and swallow food. 口内大干，以致病人咀嚼和吞下食物，都有困难。', '名词: mastication 过去式: masticated 过去分词: masticated 现在分词: masticating 第三人称单数: masticates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dormant', '[\'dɔːrmənt]', 'adj.休眠的；睡眠的；静止的；潜伏的；匿名的；（动物等）冬眠的', '1. Many living things are dormant in winter. 很多生物到了冬季都休眠。 2. The professor would try to awake their dormant and sluggish faculties. 这位教授应该试图唤醒他们沉睡和懒散的天赋。 3. A dormant volcano may erupt after an interval. 睡眠状态的火山经过一段时间后还会喷发。 4. Many dormant branches of our organization are now springing to active life. 我们组织中有许多沉寂的部门现在突然活跃起来。', '名词: dormancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reminisce', '[ˌremɪ\'nɪs]', 'v.追忆；缅怀', '1. She likes to reminisce about her childhood. 她喜欢回忆她的童年时代。 2. Old friends like to reminisce about the \"good old days\". 老朋友们总喜欢追忆那“美好的往昔”。 3. Grandfather likes to reminisce with other old people after supper. 爷爷喜欢饭后跟几位老人叙旧。 4. They can now only fondly reminisce about the Age of Aquarius. 现在他们只能深情地缅怀以往的“宝瓶时代”。', '名词: reminiscer 过去式: reminisced 过去分词: reminisced 现在分词: reminiscing 第三人称单数: reminisces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mallet', '[\'mælɪt]', 'n.木槌；[体]球棍；[音]小音槌', '1. Could I get some cream and a mallet? 可以给我一些奶油和一把木槌吗？ 2. Slight tapping with a mallet may be required. 如果需要用木槌轻轻敲打。 3. The young man swung his mallet for another blow. 这个年轻人挥动球棍准备击球。 4. The drummer was worried because his mallet was missing one minute before the concert. 鼓手很著急，因为他的小音槌在音乐会开始前一分钟不见了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scorpion', '[\'skɔːrpiən]', 'n.蝎子；心黑的人；蝎子鞭 Scorpion：天蝎座.', '1. The sting of a scorpion is in its tail. 蝎子的毒钩在其尾部。 2. Always flank with small groups of Scorpion Tanks. 总是用小股蝎子做策应。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gentry', '[\'dʒentri]', 'n.绅士；名流；贵族们', '1. The English gentry is next below the nobility. 英国绅士的地位仅次于贵族。 2. The peasants\' revolt disturbed the gentry\'s sweet dreams. 农民在乡里造反，搅动了绅士们的酣梦。 3. In the Eighteenth Century, the clergy, like the nobility and gentry, often rode to hounds. 在18世纪，神职人员跟贵族和上流社会人士一样，常常骑马打猎。 4. In old society, the gentry lived in luxury. 在旧社会，贵族们生活奢侈。', '名词复数: gentries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exert', '[ɪɡ\'zɜːrt]', 'vt.运用；施加', '1. He exerted all his influence to make them accept his plan. 他用尽一切影响力使他们接受他的计划。 2. He doesn\'t have to exert himself on my behalf. 他不必为我费那么大力气。 3. You have to exert more efforts if you want to catch up with your classmates. 你要想赶上你的同学的话,就得多花些功夫。 4. His teachings still exert a strong influence. 他的教导仍在产生巨大影响。', '过去式: exerted 过去分词: exerted 现在分词: exerting 第三人称单数: exerts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('smart', '[smɑːrt]', 'adj.时髦的；漂亮的；聪明的；敏捷的；整洁的；厉害的 vi.刺痛；难过；烦恼 n.刺痛；苦恼 adv.（=smartly）', '1. I\'m a smart girl that speaks with a smart accent. 我是个机灵的姑娘，说话带有时髦的腔调。 2. A few months ago they opened a new shop catering exclusively to the smart set. 几个月前他们新开了一家商店，专门向最时髦的人士出售物品。 3. He really cuts a dash in his smart new uniform. 他穿著漂亮的新制服真是神气十足。 4. A smart tie and a dirty collar don\'t go well together. 漂亮的领带与肮脏的领口在一起不相称。 5. His eyes smart at the smoke. 他的眼睛被烟熏痛了。 6. The smart of his wound kept him awake. 伤痛使他无法入睡。', '副词: smartly 比较级: smarter 最高级: smartest 名词: smartness 过去式: smarted 过去分词: smarted 现在分词: smarting 第三人称单数: smarts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reserve', '[rɪ\'zɜːrv]', 'vt.保留；预订；延期 n.候补；预备品；贮存 n.含蓄；克制', '1. We reserve the right to lodge a claim for loss. 我们保留要求赔偿损失的权利。 2. I have reserved a table at the restaurant. 我已在饭店预订了一桌菜。 3. The court will reserve judgement. 法庭将延期判决。 4. He has played very well on the reserve side but this chance in the first team should put him on his mettle. 他在候补队中表现非常出色,但这次作为正式队员参赛将对他的能力进行考验。 5. He spoke with reserve. 他说话谨慎。', '形容词: reservable 名词: reserver 过去式: reserved 过去分词: reserved 现在分词: reserving 第三人称单数: reserves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beacon', '[\'biːkən]', 'n.烽火；灯塔；基地', '1. The beacon fire shines on the capital. 烽火照西京。 2. We climb the hill by day to watch for beacon fires and water horses by riverside when day expires. 白日登山望烽火，黄昏饮马傍交河。 3. These beacons on the coast are to warn and guide ships. 这些海滩上的信号灯是用来提醒和指示船舶的。 4. A beacon flamed out against the night sky. 灯塔在夜空衬托下闪亮。', '过去式: beaconed 过去分词: beaconed 现在分词: beaconing 第三人称单数: beacons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imperial', '[ɪm\'pɪriəl]', 'adj.帝国的；皇帝的；特大的；英制的 n.皇帝；女皇；马车车顶；特大号', '1. Imperial sovereignty rests on a mixed constitution. 帝国的主权基于一种复杂的构成。 2. There are many ways to get to the imperial Theater. 到帝国戏院有很多条路。 3. The Palace Museum is the imperial palace of ancient Chinese emperors. 故宫是中国古代皇帝的皇宫。 4. Imperial gardens occupy large areas. 皇家园林占地很广。 5. An imperial edict is a writ in the name of an emperor. 诏书是以皇帝名义发布指令的专用文书。', '副词: imperially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ratify', '[\'rætɪfaɪ]', 'v.批准；认可', '1. They ratify the pact because they think it will bring peace. 他们批准了这项协定，因为他们认为它将能带来和平。 2. The government of Honduras refused to ratify the convention. 洪都拉斯政府拒不批准该约。 3. It would reinforce the tendency to use the UN to ratify the gains of surprise attack. 这会助长利用联合国使通过突然袭击的办法夺占的领土得到认可的倾向。 4. He said Lebanese President Emile Lahoud and his council are expected to ratify the plan during the coming week. 他说，黎巴嫩总统拉胡德和议会将在本星期认可这个计划。', '名词: ratifier 过去式: ratified 过去分词: ratified 现在分词: ratifying 第三人称单数: ratifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pittance', '[\'pɪtns]', 'n.少量；少量津贴；微薄的工资', '1. We aren\'t talking a pittance here. 这可不是一笔小数目。 2. She could barely survive on the pittance she received as a widow\'s pension. 她靠着极少的孤寡抚恤金仅够糊口. 3. Lawrence fags away for a pittance. 劳伦斯为了一点微薄的收入而辛苦地工作。 4. The widow must live on her slender pittance. 那寡妇只能靠自己微薄的收入过活。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lurk', '[lɜːrk]', 'v.潜藏；潜伏；埋伏 n.潜伏；隐藏', '1. Danger lurked in the atmosphere. 氛围中隐藏着危险。 2. Dangers seem to lurk beneath this river. 这条河流潜藏许多危险。 3. The terrorists lurk in an apartment in downtown Copenhagen. 恐怖分子潜伏哥本哈根闹市区一处公寓。 4. The thief lurked in the shadows. 小偷埋伏在阴暗处。 5. The terrorists lurk in an apartment in downtown Copenhagen. 恐怖分子潜伏哥本哈根闹市区一处公寓。', '副词: lurkingly 过去式: lurked 过去分词: lurked 现在分词: lurking 第三人称单数: lurks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heyday', '[\'heɪdeɪ]', 'n.全盛期 int.<古>嘿（喜悦、惊奇时所发声音）', '1. In his heyday, he was a great tennis player. 他年轻力壮时, 是一位了不起的网球运动员。 2. By the 80s, punk rock had really had its heyday. 到了80年代朋克摇滚已过了全盛时期。 3. Steam railways had their heyday in the 19th century. 19世纪是蒸汽机车的全盛时期。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pack', '[pæk]', 'n.一群；一副；包裹；一包 v.包装；解雇；塞满；收拾行李；佩戴', '1. The hare could find no safety, a pack of jackals had it in the wind. 野兔无处逃生,一群豺狗在追踪它。 2. He rounded on journalists, calling them \'a pack of vultures\'. 他突然对记者们大发雷霆，称他们是一帮贪婪的家伙。 3. A pack of cards has been spread on the table. 一副牌在桌被传播了。 4. Try to pair this card with one exactly the same from the other pack. 设法从另一副牌中取出一张和这张完全一样的牌。 5. In order to avoid any possible damage in transit, we would ask you to pack the goods in strong but small wooden cases. 为避免运送过程中的任何损坏,我方希望贵方用牢固且小巧的木箱来包装这些货物。', '形容词: packable 名词: packability 过去式: packed 过去分词: packed 现在分词: packing 第三人称单数: packs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arboretum', '[ˌɑːrbə\'riːtəm]', 'n.植物园；树木园', '1. We can go to the arboretum in the southern suburb. 我们可以去南郊的植物园。 2. The arboretum is full of exotic flowers and rare herbs. 植物园里长满了各种奇花异草。 3. How many golden larches are there in the arboretum? 植物园里有几棵金钱松? 4. The arboretum is a world treasure trove of botanical resources. 这个植物园是世界植物资源的宝库。', '名词复数: arboretums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('supervise', '[\'suːpərvaɪz]', 'vt.监督；管理；指导', '1. I supervised the workers loading the lorry. 我监督工人把货物装上卡车。 2. The chief clerk supervises the work of the department. 文书组长负责监督该部门的工作。 3. She wants to supervise the cosmetics shop. 她想自己管理那间化妆品店。 4. How many people did you supervise on your last job? 你的上一份工作需要管理多少人?', '过去式: supervised 过去分词: supervised 现在分词: supervising 第三人称单数: supervises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conjunction', '[kən\'dʒʌŋkʃn]', 'n.结合；关联；连词；(事件等的)同时发生', '1. The novel should be read in conjunction with the author\'s biography. 这本小说应该和作者传记一起读。 2. The conjunction of workmanship and artistry in making jewelry decides the value of the jewelry. 在珠宝饰物的制造中，手工与艺术的结合决定了珠宝的价值。 3. The word is a temporal conjunction. 该词是表示时间的连词。 4. An unusual conjunction of circumstances led to the incident. 各种情况的偶然巧合导致了这件事的发生。', '形容词: conjunctional 副词: conjunctionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('continuation', '[kənˌtɪnjʊ\'eɪʃən]', 'n.继续；延续；续集', '1. He argued for a continuation of the search. 他主张继续搜查。 2. This road is a continuation of the motorway. 这条公路是高速公路的延伸。 3. Tune in again tomorrow to hear the continuation of our exciting story. 明天接着收听这个激动人心故事的续集。 4. This is the continuation of the story. 这是故事的后续部分。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('offish', '[\'ɔːfɪʃ]', 'adj.冷淡的；疏远的', '1. The scene includes many different species offish. 该场景包含了许多不同种类的鱼。 2. There was a weak &offish smile on his face. 他的脸上挂着淡淡的、冷漠的微笑。 3. He has a feint and offish smile on his face. 他的脸上挂着淡淡的、冷漠的微笑。 4. There is a slipslop and offish smile on his face. 他的脸上挂着淡淡的、冷漠的微笑。', '副词: offishly 名词: offishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('harp', '[hɑːrp]', 'n.竖琴 v.反复诉说；唠叨', '1. He can play the harp and violin. 他能演奏竖琴和提琴。 2. He played an Irish melody on the harp. 他用竖琴演奏了一首爱尔兰曲调。 3. I wish you wouldn\'t harp on about it all the time. 我希望你不要老是喋喋不休地谈论那件事了。 4. The old man still harps on a bout the death of his wife. 老人仍在反复诉说他妻子去世的事。', '名词: harper 过去式: harped 过去分词: harped 现在分词: harping 第三人称单数: harps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incorruptible', '[ˌɪnkə\'rʌptəbl]', 'adj.（道德上）不受腐蚀的（如不受贿）；不可摧毁的', '1. Judges should be incorruptible. 法官应当廉洁。 2. Bribery won\'t work with him. He\'s incorruptible. 贿赂对他不起作用。他为人清廉。 3. Incorruptible, and just officials will surely be supported by the common people. 廉正清明的官吏肯定会受老百姓拥护的。', '副词: incorruptibly 名词: incorruptibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('voracity', '[və\'ræsəti]', 'n.贪食；贪婪', '1. Hunt and voracity are unnatural to him. 捕杀动物与贪食不是人类的本性。 2. Their voracity is legendary and even the most hardened warriors cannot repress a shiver if one speaks about them. 他们的贪食是传奇性的，甚至强壮的战士也会因为提起他们而无法抑制的颤抖。 3. He ate with the voracity of a starving man. 他饿鬼似的贪婪地吃着。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lethargic', '[lə\'θɑːdʒɪk]', 'adj.昏睡的；困倦的；无生气的', '1. The hot weather made me feel lethargic. 炎热的天气使我昏昏欲睡。 2. In fact they looked tired and lethargic and old. 事实上,他们看上去很疲惫、困乏、衰老。 3. The bird became lethargic at noon. 这只鸟在中午时就不活泼了。 4. The weather made her listless and lethargic. 那天气弄得她百无聊赖、无精打采。', '副词: lethargically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gangling', '[\'ɡæŋɡlɪŋ]', 'adj.瘦长难看的', '1. He is a gangling youth. 他是一个瘦长难看的年轻人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meditative', '[\'medɪteɪtɪv]', 'adj.沉思的；冥想的；善於思考的', '1. She found him in a meditative mood. 她见他正在沉思。 2. She stood looking at him with meditative eyes. 她站着用沉思的目光打量他。 3. He is a meditative story-teller or romancer. 他是个善于深入思考的故事家。', '副词: meditatively 名词: meditativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boredom', '[\'bɔːrdəm]', 'n.无聊；厌烦；厌倦；令人厌烦的事物', '1. Unemployment can drive you mad with boredom. 失业会让你无聊得发疯。 2. The best cure for boredom is hard work. 治疗无聊最好的办法是努力工作。 3. He found the boredom scarcely endurable. 他觉得这种厌烦难以忍受。 4. Boredom is not a ground for divorce. 日久生厌不能成为离婚的理由。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sprawl', '[sprɔːl]', 'vi.躺卧；扩张；蔓延 vt.使蔓延 n.躺卧；蔓延', '1. Corporate sprawl distracts managers, diverts resources and muddies valuations. 公司扩张吸引管理层，转移资源和扰乱估价。 2. By designing new neighborhoods with pedestrians in mind, they can promote slimmer lifestyles and cut down on this new kind of suburban sprawl. 如果在规划设计时就能更多地考虑到步行的需要，就能促使人们采用更健康的生活方式，并遏制市郊的无限扩张。 3. Urban sprawl was essentially unplanned. 城市蔓延是生来无计划的。 4. Sprawl is common in the United States. 城市蔓延在美国非常普遍。 5. Urban sprawl was essentially unplanned. 城市蔓延是生来无计划的。 6. Urban sprawl was essentially unplanned. 城市蔓延是生来无计划的。', '名词: sprawler 过去式: sprawled 过去分词: sprawled 现在分词: sprawling 第三人称单数: sprawls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alter', '[\'ɔːltər]', 'v.改变；更改；阉割；切除卵巢', '1. But nothing can alter the facts. 但任何东西也改变不了这些事实。 2. Alter Current Boot Record Serial Number. 更改当前引导纪录序列号。 3. Marshaling the structure can transform the layout and alter the offset. 封送结构可转换布局并更改偏移量。', '过去式: altered 过去分词: altered 现在分词: altering 第三人称单数: alters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whittle', '[\'wɪtl]', 'v.削(木头)；削减', '1. Don\'t whittle the stick into a short one. 别把木棍削成短的棍。 2. They are trying to whittle down our salaries. 他们正著手削减我们的薪水。 3. Furthermore, with the equity markets still in turmoil, Freescale may not be able in the near future to whittle down its debts by selling shares to the public. 更糟糕的是，资本市场仍然一片混乱，飞思卡尔在近期通过出售股票来削减债务压力的可能性也不大。', '名词: whittler 过去式: whittled 过去分词: whittled 现在分词: whittling 第三人称单数: whittles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quandary', '[\'kwɑːndəri]', 'n.困惑；迷惑；为难', '1. He\'s caught in a little bit of a quandary. 海德处于一个困惑的境地。 2. But it leaves the US and her Asian allies in a quandary over their long-term strategy toward Pyongyang. 但同时让美国及其亚洲盟国在处理平壤核问题的长期战略上陷于困惑。 3. The man\'s request put me in a quandary, I didn\'t know what to do. 那个人的要求使我为难，我不知道如何是好。', '名词复数: quandaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rift', '[rɪft]', 'n.裂口；隙缝；切口 v.裂开；割开；渗入', '1. Many years passed as the Warlocks sought to unlock the mysteries of this tiny rift. 术士花了许多年寻找扩大这个微小裂口的神秘方法。 2. Functionally a warp gate is similar to a gateway in that both devices open a spatial rift. 偏位门的运作方式和传送门一样都是通过用一个设备打开空间裂口。 3. Just then, the wind blew a rift in the grey clouds, and in silver moonlight they reached the north end of the street. 这时，风把灰云吹裂开一块，露出月光，二人已来到街的北头。', '过去式: rifted 过去分词: rifted 现在分词: rifting 第三人称单数: rifts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('earnest', '[\'ɜːrnɪst]', 'adj.认真的；真诚的 n.定金；预示；保证 n.认真；诚挚', '1. I\'m sure he was earnest when he said he would come. 我相信他说他会来是认真的。 2. He is a good, earnest, diligent student. 他是一个认真勤奋的好学生。 3. I strive to live each day with earnest gratitude. 我努力使生活的每一天都充满真诚的感激。 4. Earnest was legally unnecessary. 法律上并不要求必须有定金。 5. She spoke half in sport, half in earnest. 她半开玩笑半认真地说。', '副词: earnestly 名词: earnestness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imp', '[ɪmp]', 'n.小恶魔；顽童 v.装上翅膀；移植羽毛 abbr.工业管理程序（=Industrial Management Program) abbr.接口信息处理（=Interface Message Processor) abbr.星际监视探测人造卫星（=Interplanetary Monitoring Probe Satellite)', '1. What a little imp you are! 你这个淘气包！', '过去式: imped 过去分词: imped 现在分词: imping 第三人称单数: imps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resent', '[rɪ\'zent]', 'vt.恨；生气', '1. Kate said she felt we resent her. 凯特说她感到我们大家恨她。 2. I resent the encroachment on my time. 我讨厌别人侵占我的时间。 3. I bitterly resent his attempts to interfere in my work. 我非常讨厌他企图干涉我的工作。 4. I resent having to get his permission for everything I do. 我讨厌做每件事都要得到他的许可。', '过去式: resented 过去分词: resented 现在分词: resenting 第三人称单数: resents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('double-cross', '[\'dʌbl krɔːs]', 'n.欺骗行为；出卖行为；[遗]双杂交 v.出卖；欺骗', '1. They say that he would even double-cross his own mother. 他们说他甚至会欺骗他自己的母亲。', '名词: double-crosser 过去式: double-crossed 过去分词: double-crossed 现在分词: double-crossing 第三人称单数: double-crosses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overflow', '[ˌoʊvər\'floʊ]', 'v.泛滥；溢出；充满；洋溢 n.泛滥；溢值；剩出', '1. We must harness the rivers which overflow annually. 我们必须治理那些每年泛滥的河流。 2. The river overflowed its banks. 河水漫过了两岸。 3. The crowd overflowed the auditorium. 人群挤得礼堂无法容纳。 4. Her heart was overflowing with joy. 她的心里洋溢着喜悦。 5. Put a bowl underneath to catch the overflow. 把盆放在下面接住溢出物。', '过去式: overflowed 过去分词: overflowed 现在分词: overflowing 第三人称单数: overflows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abstentious', '[æb\'stenʃəs]', 'adj.有节制的', '1. But his abstentious parishioners, who could accept abstention from all alcohol, could not abstain from living without owning people. 然而他的有节制的教区居民们,虽可以接受戒酒，却不能在生活中戒掉不拥有人。 2. Chapter four puts forward our nation’s GMO international trade strategy---ration, profit, abstentious, and our nation’s GMO international trade developing measures. 第四章提出我国转基因农产品国际贸易“有理、有利、有节”的战略选择以及我国转基因农产品国际贸易的发展对策。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('efficacy', '[\'efɪkəsi]', 'n.功效', '1. We are testing the efficacy of a new drug. 我们正在测试新药的功效。 2. Exogenously administered ozone may, in this model, amplify the efficacy of antigen-antibody dynamics. 在这个情况中，从外施加的臭氧会扩大抗原抗体作用的功效。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('matriculate', '[mə\'trɪkjuleɪt]', 'v.准许入学；录取', '1. Edward: Private joke. We matriculate a lot. 家族私人笑话. 2. Now it isn\'t a piece of work to matriculate for us. 如今进大学读书并不是难事. 3. Edward Cullen: Private joke. We matriculate a lot. 爱德华：自家人的笑话，我们上了很多学校。 4. At the same tine, some new problems and changes in the graduate matriculate quality have appeared in this process. 在这个过程中，研究生生源质量出现了一些新的问题和变化。', '名词: matriculation 过去式: matriculated 过去分词: matriculated 现在分词: matriculating 第三人称单数: matriculates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('control', '[kən\'troʊl]', 'n.掌控；控制；管制；克制；操作装置 v.控制；支配；掌管；抑制；克制', '1. Don\'t worry, we have everything under control. 别担心,一切都在我们掌控之中。 2. Inflation has got out of control. 通货膨胀失去了控制。 3. The government has imposed strict controls over the import of luxury goods. 政府对奢侈品的进口采取了严格的管制。 4. He has little control over his emotions. 他控制不住自己的感情。 5. The firemen were unable to control the blaze. 消防队员无法控制这场大火。', '形容词: controllable 名词: controllability 过去式: controlled 过去分词: controlled 现在分词: controlling 第三人称单数: controls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bargain', '[\'bɑːrɡən]', 'n.交易；便宜货；契约 v.讨价还价；议价；(谈价钱后)卖', '1. He made a satisfactory bargain with them. 他和他们做了一笔满意的交易。 2. If you promote our goods, we will give you a good discount as our part of the bargain. 若你方经销我们的货物，我方愿给予你相当大的优惠作为回报。 3. She knows a bargain when she sees one. 她有辨别便宜货的能力。 4. There never was a better bargain driver. 再没有比这更美好的契约。 5. The salesman refused to bargain over the price. 推销员拒绝讨价还价。', '名词: bargainer 过去式: bargained 过去分词: bargained 现在分词: bargaining 第三人称单数: bargains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hangar', '[\'hæŋər]', 'n.飞机库', '1. The plane nosed into the hangar. 飞机缓缓地进入机库。 2. The plane stopped in that big hangar. 飞机停在那个大机库里。 3. The airport hangar was freshly painted. 机场的飞机库是新油漆过的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obnoxious', '[əb\'nɑːkʃəs]', 'adj.可憎的；不愉快的；讨厌的', '1. He is the most obnoxious man I know. 他是我认识的最可憎的人。 2. Even that obnoxious conduct by the child was not sufficient to spark a defensive reaction. 即使是这个小孩如此可憎的行为，也不足以引发一个防御性的反应。 3. We told the obnoxious guest to give over. 我们让讨厌的客人放弃。 4. I will not have another of those obnoxious little human things. 我不会再要另一个讨厌的人类小东西了。', '副词: obnoxiously 名词: obnoxiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cumulus', '[\'kjuːmjələs]', 'n.积云；堆积', '1. A band of cumulus lingered over the Great Hall of the People. 一条积云带在人民大会堂上空徘徊。 2. Piles of cotton-like cumulus clouds fill the sky on a clear day. 晴朗天空堆满了像棉花一样的积云。', '名词复数: cumuli');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invert', '[ɪn\'vɜːrt]', 'v.倒置；反转；颠倒 adj.转化的 n.颠倒物；[心]同性恋者', '1. The little boy caught the insect by inverting the cup over it. 小男孩把杯子倒过来就逮住了那只昆虫。 2. The chairs were inverted on the table. 椅子被倒置过来放在了桌子上。 3. Place a plate over the cake tin and invert it. 在蛋糕烤模上盖一个盘子，然后将其翻倒过来。 4. Please invert the word order in a sentence. 请把句中的词序颠倒下。', '形容词: invertible 过去式: inverted 过去分词: inverted 现在分词: inverting 第三人称单数: inverts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enmesh', '[ɪn\'meʃ]', 'vt.使绊住；使陷入 =immesh.', '1. The fishline became enmeshed in roots under the water. 钓鱼线给水下的草木根缠住了。 2. He was enmeshed in a web of deceit and lies. 他陷入充满诡计和谎言的圈套。', '异体字: immesh 名词: enmeshment 过去式: enmeshed 过去分词: enmeshed 现在分词: enmeshing 第三人称单数: enmeshes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ghastly', '[\'ɡæstli]', 'adj.可怕的；恐怖的；惨白的；不适的；糟透的；令人不快的 adv.可怖地；惨白地', '1. What a ghastly place that house is! 那座房子是个多么可怕的地方啊！ 2. The ghastly sight gave him the shudders. 那恐怖的景象使他感到恐惧。 3. She woke up in the middle of a ghastly nightmare. 她从恐怖的噩梦中惊醒。 4. The sick woman\'s face was ghastly. 那女病人面色苍白。 5. A ghastly bluish light smoldered along its edge. 它的边缘，有一道带着蓝色的苍白的光，非常阴暗。', '比较级: ghastlier 最高级: ghastliest 名词: ghastliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intersperse', '[ˌɪntər\'spɜːrs]', 'vt.散布；散置；点缀', '1. Intersperse advertisements throughout your content by using the playlist editor to insert interstitial advertisement to the server side playlist. 在您的内容中散布广告，方法是利用播放列表编辑器，将间隙广告插入服务器端的播放列表。 2. Because the regulations of protecting the media consumer interests and rights intersperse among all sorts of civil laws, few people in our country made conclusions about them. 由于保护媒介消费者利益和权利的民事法律规范散布于各种各样的法律法规之中，国内鲜有人对其进行归纳和列举。 3. I will intersperse today with laughter,and I will lighten the night with songs. 我要用笑声点缀今天，我要用歌声照亮黑夜。', '副词: interspersedly 名词: interspersion 过去式: interspersed 过去分词: interspersed 现在分词: interspersing 第三人称单数: intersperses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prosperous', '[\'prɑːspərəs]', 'adj.繁荣的；兴旺的', '1. At no time has the country been more prosperous than at present. 我国任何时候都没有现在这样繁荣。 2. There are some areas of poverty, but the country as a whole is fairly prosperous. 这个国家有些地区比较贫困, 但总的来说是相当富裕的。 3. The city at one time must have been prosperous, for It enjoyed a high level of civilization. 这座古城在一个时期准是很繁荣的，因为它曾享有高度文明。 4. His business is prosperous. 他的事业兴旺发达。', '副词: prosperously 名词: prosperousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nonporous', '[\'nɒn\'pɔːrəs]', 'adj.无细孔的', '1. These nonporous surfaces paint badly with a brush. 这些不渗透的表面很难被刷子刷漆 2. Fine point dry ease markers for white board and other nonporous surface. 圆头笔尖，书写笔型白板笔，可在各种白板和光滑表面书写。 3. Petroleum stores, however, are sometimes overlain with nonporous rock. 但是,有时覆盖油藏的岩石是非渗透的。 4. Powdered Metals alloying of metals involves melting the main ingredients together so that on cooling ,the metal alloy is generally a nonporous solid. 粉末合金金属是通过熔化主要金属元素并结合在一起，然后使之冷却而形成的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gush', '[ɡʌʃ]', 'v.迸出；涌出；滔滔不绝地说 n.涌出', '1. Oil gushed out from the broken pipe. 油从断裂的管道中涌出。 2. A fountain of water gush from the break fire hydrant. 从损坏的消防栓里喷出水来。 3. In a moment more, the crowd began to gush forth from the doors of the church. 过了一会儿，人群便开始从教堂的大门蜂拥而出。 4. His words gushed out. 他的话滔滔不绝。 5. From the cellar grating floated up the flabby gush of porter. 隔着地窖的格子窗飘出走了气的黑啤酒味儿。', '过去式: gushed 过去分词: gushed 现在分词: gushing 第三人称单数: gushes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('viral', '[\'vaɪrəl]', 'adj.病毒的 n.病毒式传播；【经】病毒式营销', '1. A viral illness left her barely able to walk. 一场病毒引起的疾病使她走路都十分困难。 2. Mumps is an acute contagious viral infection. 流行性腮腺炎是一种急性接触性病毒传染 3. Animals may serve as a vehicle for viral transmission. 动物可能成为病毒传播的媒介。 4. Some viral diseases are more severe during pregnancy. 有些病毒病在妊娠期间比较严重。', '副词: virally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sketchy', '[\'sketʃi]', 'adj.概略的；不完全的；略图的；不确定的', '1. Your essay gives a rather sketchy treatment of the problem. 你的文章只粗略地涉及到这个问题。 2. We managed to piece together the truth from several sketchy accounts. 我们从几方面粗略的说法中设法弄清了真相。 3. I have only a sketchy knowledge of geography. 我对地理只是一知半解。 4. Information about the crisis was sketchy and hard to get. 关于这次危机的消息所知甚少并且很难获得。', '副词: sketchily 比较级: sketchier 最高级: sketchiest 名词: sketchiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emblematic', '[ˌemblə\'mætɪk]', 'adj.作为象征的；典型的', '1. The crown is emblematic of power of a king. 王冠是国王权力的象征。 2. The violence is emblematic of what is happening in our inner cities. 这种暴力行为正标示了我们市中心贫民区的状况。', '副词: emblematically 异体字: emblematical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('generalize', '[\'dʒenrəlaɪz]', 'v.概括；归纳；使一般化', '1. It is dangerous to generalize about people. 以偏概全地谈论人是危险的。 2. You cannot generalize about the effects of the drug from one or two cases. 不能根据一两个病例就得出该药是否有效的结论。 3. It is difficult to generalize about job trends in the West. 对西方的就业趋势做一个归纳概括并非易事。 4. Don\'t generalize a conclusion from a few examples. 不要从几个事例中归纳出结论。', '过去式: generalized 过去分词: generalized 现在分词: generalizing 第三人称单数: generalizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('strife', '[straɪf]', 'n.争吵；冲突；倾轧；竞争', '1. She was faint with strife and dejected. 她被争吵弄得精疲力竭，情绪低落。 2. We really shouldn\'t intervene in their marital strife. 我们不该介入他们夫妻间的争吵。 3. The internecine strife was caused by a shortage of food. 这次内部冲突，是由于食物匮乏而引致的。 4. And he remains edgy about the continuing strife in Somalia. 梅莱斯也对索马里冲突不止而烦躁。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vehicle', '[\'viːɪkl]', 'n.车辆；交通工具；传播媒介；手段；工具', '1. No entry for vehicle! 禁止车辆入内！ 2. It is time for the yearly check of vehicle safety. 到车辆安全年审的时间了。 3. Subway is a convenient vehicle for those white collars. 地铁对于白领阶层来说是很方便的交通工具。 4. Television has become an important vehicle for spreading political ideas. 电视已成为传播政治思想的重要媒介。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('undeserved', '[ˌʌndɪ\'zɜːrvd]', 'adj.不恰当的；不应得的', '1. The criticism was totally undeserved. 这批评纯属冤枉人。 2. His reputation as a Romeo is quite undeserved. 他有罗密欧之称是名不副实的.', '副词: undeservedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hoax', '[hoʊks]', 'v.欺骗；哄骗；愚弄 n.愚弄人；恶作剧', '1. All hoax viruses are essentially chain letters. 所有的欺骗性病毒基本都是连续性的字母。 2. Some posters on Chinese bulletin boards and blogs have argued that Mr Zhou was perhaps merely a hapless tool in a hoax perpetrated mainly by bureaucrats. 一些中文的贴子和博客提出，周也许不过是官方欺骗闹剧中的一个不幸的工具而已。 3. Mainstream critics argue that the entire affair is a hoax. 主流的批评家批评整件事是一场愚弄。 4. Authorities call the apparent hoax reprehensible, but even with just five feet. 官方称这是明显的愚弄行为，应该遭受斥责，但是仍然还有五只断脚。 5. They considered the phone call a hoax. 他们认为那个电话是恶作剧。', '名词: hoaxer 过去式: hoaxed 过去分词: hoaxed 现在分词: hoaxing 第三人称单数: hoaxes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trifle', '[\'traɪfl]', 'n.琐事；少量 v.浪费；玩弄', '1. I do not want to make a fuss over such a trifle. 我不想为这种小事大惊小怪。 2. They had an altercation about a trifle. 他们为一点小事争吵起来。 3. He told her not to pester him with trifles. 他告诉她别拿些琐事来烦他。 4. I have only a trifle of wine left. 我只剩下一点点酒了。 5. Don\'t trifle away your time on curio hunting. 别把时间都浪费在搜集古玩上面。', '名词: trifler 过去式: trifled 过去分词: trifled 现在分词: trifling 第三人称单数: trifles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forebode', '[foʊr\'boʊd]', 'v.预兆；预感', '1. These developments forebode disaster. 这些情况预示著要有灾祸。 2. Her angry face forbode a confrontation. 她一脸怒气预示将有一场冲突。', '名词: foreboder 过去式: foreboded 过去分词: foreboded 现在分词: foreboding 第三人称单数: forebodes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pedestrian', '[pə\'destriən]', 'adj.徒步的；缺乏想像的 n.行人', '1. We enjoy all pedestrian activities. 我们喜欢所有的步行活动。 2. They ought to stop at the pedestrian crossing. 他们该停在人行横道上。 3. He was rather a pedestrian student. 他原是个相当平常的学生。 4. We present this approach in a pedestrian version. 我们用平铺直叙的方式介绍这个方法。 5. The driver was slanging a pedestrian who had got in his way. 那司机破口大骂挡他的路的行人。', '名词: pedestrianism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('calculating', '[\'kælkjuleɪtɪŋ]', 'adj.深谋远虑的；精明的；计算的 动词calculate的现在分词.', '1. Aleck was a good and faithful mother and housewife, and thoughtful and calculating business woman; 艾莱柯是个尽职尽责的好母亲、好主妇，也是一个深谋远虑、有生意头脑的妇女。 2. He has a cold and calculating mind. 他既冷漠又有心计。 3. In the desperation of elections however, calculating politicians will often play the race card. 但如果选举结果让人绝望，精明的政客就会打出民族主义这张牌。 4. He can make calculations even faster than a calculating machine. 他运算得经计算器还快。', '副词: calculatingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dexterity', '[dek\'sterəti]', 'n.灵巧；机敏；熟练；手艺', '1. The circus acrobats performed feats of dexterity and strength. 马戏团的杂技艺人表演了显示灵巧和力度的高超技艺。 2. The negotiations will call for considerable dexterity. 进行这些谈判需要相当圆滑的手腕。 3. He played the piano with dexterity. 他以纯熟的指法弹奏钢琴。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ossify', '[\'ɑːsɪfaɪ]', 'v.骨化；硬化；僵化', '1. It is easy for the mind to ossify. 脑筋是易于僵化的。 2. All fixed,fast-frozen relations,with their train of ancient and venerable prejudices and opinions,are swept away,all new-formed ones become antiquated before they can ossify. 一切固定的僵化的关系以及与之相适应的素被尊崇的观念和见解都被消除了，一切新形成的关系等不到固定下来就陈旧了。', '形容词: ossific 过去式: ossified 过去分词: ossified 现在分词: ossifying 第三人称单数: ossifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nicety', '[\'naɪsəti]', 'n.准确；精确；细微的区别；优美的东西', '1. The job calls for nicety of judgment. 这一工作要求判断准确。 2. This is a point of great nicety. 这是非常细微的一点。 3. Having a bosom friend is one of the niceties of life. 得一知己乃人生一大乐事。', '名词复数: niceties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('striking', '[\'straɪkɪŋ]', 'adj.显著的；吸引人的 动词strike的现在分词形式.', '1. Visually, the decor was very striking. 这个房间的装饰看上去非常醒目。 2. Her big eyes are her most striking feature. 大眼睛是她容貌最显著的特点。 3. What is immediately striking is how resourceful the children are. 最令人注目的是孩子们的机智聪明。', '副词: strikingly 名词: strikingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('profligate', '[\'prɑːflɪɡət]', 'adj.放荡的；不检点的；浪费的 n.放荡者；享乐者', '1. We both know that he has been profligate in every sense of the world. 我们都知道他已变成不折不扣的淫棍。 2. These profligate sons of the rich used to get away with all sorts of crimes. 这些纨绔子弟犯下种种罪行，但常能逍遥法外。 3. Similarly Americans have been profligate in the handling of mineral resources. 同样的，美国在处理矿产资源方面亦多浪费。 4. Thus the crisis punishes the frugal more than the profligate. 如此看来，危机对节俭者的惩罚，要比对恣意挥霍者更为严厉。', '副词: profligately 名词: profligacy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vernacular', '[vər\'nækjələr]', 'n.【C】本地话；方言', '1. In some churches, they speak Latin, but in others they use the vernacular. 在一些教堂中，人们讲拉丁语，但在其他一些教堂中，人们使用本地话。 2. The vernaculars of these African tribes have never been written down. 这些非洲部落的土话没能被记载下来。 3. We must master the local vernacular. 我们必须掌握当地的方言。 4. He speaks an incomprehensible vernacular. 他说的是一种无法听得懂的方言。', '副词: vernacularly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detection', '[dɪ\'tekʃn]', 'n.探测；侦查；察觉；发觉', '1. Our main detection device is sonar. 我们主要的探测装置是声波定位仪。 2. The word radar means radio detection and ranging. 雷达这个词的意思是指无线电探测和测距。 3. The detection of crime is not always easy. 侦查罪行并非易事。 4. Detection is not properly a function of the customs service. 严格地说来，侦查工作不是海关的一项职责。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('poignant', '[\'pɔɪnjənt]', 'adj.悲伤的；痛切的；严厉的；尖锐的；剧烈的；浓烈的', '1. A poignant memory. 一段悲伤的记忆。', '副词: poignantly 名词: poignance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rifle', '[\'raɪfl]', 'n.步枪 v.洗劫；抢劫', '1. Rifle reports could be heard in the distance. 听得见远处传来的步枪声。 2. He accidentally triggered his rifle. 他无意中扣发了他步枪的扳机。 3. The officer was fatally shot with an assault rifle yesterday morning while responding to the robbery in northeast Philadelphia. 在费城东北部，该警察昨天早晨在应付抢劫案的过程中遭到歹徒的来福枪的射击。', '名词: rifler 过去式: rifled 过去分词: rifled 现在分词: rifling 第三人称单数: rifles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vanguard', '[\'vænɡɑːrd]', 'n.前锋；先锋；先驱', '1. The vanguard units started off last night. 前锋部队昨晚已经出发。 2. He is the vanguard of the avant-garde who, on the back line is a waste. 他是打前锋前卫出身的，放在后卫线上是一种浪费。 3. In a way they played a vanguard role. 在某种意义上说，他们起了先锋的作用。 4. They are not bookworm, is the master of books, updating knowledge is the vanguard. 他们不是书呆子，是书本的主人，是知识更新的先锋。', '名词: vanguardism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appreciate', '[ə\'priːʃieɪt]', 'vt.欣赏；赏识；感激；领会；意识到 vi.增值', '1. I really appreciate his complete absorption in his work. 我很欣赏他对工作的极端专注。 2. I\'ve decided to learn photography in order that I may better appreciate the beauty of nature. 我决定学摄影以便能更好地欣赏自然的美。 3. Very few people really appreciate his works. 没人赏识他的作品。 4. His talents are not fully appreciated in that company. 他的才干在那家公司未受到充分赏识。 5. Land will continue to appreciate. 土地将继续增值。', '形容词: appreciatory 名词: appreciator 过去式: appreciated 过去分词: appreciated 现在分词: appreciating 第三人称单数: appreciates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('limestone', '[\'laɪmstoʊn]', 'n.石灰石', '1. Caves form when water infiltrates limestone. 水渗透石灰石则形成洞穴。 2. We may burn limestone to obtain lime. 我们可以通过烧石灰石来得到石灰。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corporeal', '[kɔːr\'pɔːriəl]', 'adj.肉体的；有形的；物质的', '1. He is very religious; corporeal world has little interest for him. 他虔信宗教，对物质上的享受不感兴趣。', '副词: corporeally 名词: corporeality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('effluvia', '[ɪ\'fluːvjə]', 'n.臭气；没用的副产品 名词effluvium的复数形式.', '1. One inhales the effluvia of the great black void. 我们常会嗅到黑暗中太空的气息。 2. Chronic telogen effluvium or early androgenetic alopecia? 是慢性静止期脱发还是雄性秃发? 3. Divide into :1 all the year flux set free effluvium 2 long rush down no Yu 3. 分为:1整年泻痢放臭气 2久泻不愈 3.;便臭下痢 。 4. At its farthest end, three glaciers meet to dump their effluvia into the milky grey glacial water, launching massive igloo icebergs into the lake with thunderous splashes. 在最远的一端，三条冰河汇聚到一处，将硕大的冰块注入奶白色的河流中，冰块互相碰撞，水花四溅，形成令人叹为观止的奇景。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malfeasance', '[ˌmæl\'fiːzəns]', 'n.渎职；不正当；不法行为', '1. For me they are only entities, emblems of social malfeasance. 他们对我来说只不过是几个客观存在的人，社会上渎职行为的代表而已。 2. Professional human capital serves as a bond against malfeasance when its value is sensitive to performance. 当专业的人力资本的价值敏于表现时，专业的人力资本可以对渎职行为起到一种担保的作用。', '形容词: malfeasant');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apparel', '[ə\'pærəl]', 'n.衣服；装具 vt.装饰；使 ... 穿衣', '1. Apparel make the man. 人靠衣装，佛靠金装。 2. Her wedding apparel is made by a very famous fashion designer. 她的结婚礼服是由一位非常著名的时装设计师制作的。 3. His house is tastefully appareled. 他的房子装帧雅致。', '过去式: appareled/apparelled 过去分词: appareled/apparelled 现在分词: appareling/apparelling 第三人称单数: apparels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('authenticity', '[ˌɔːθen\'tɪsəti]', 'n.真实性', '1. The authenticity of the manuscript is beyond doubt. 手稿的真实性是毋庸置疑的。 2. The story bore the stamp of authenticity. 这个故事具有真实性。 3. You don’t mind if I check its authenticity? 你不介意我来验证它的真实性吧？ 4. Experts vouch for the painting\'s authenticity. 由专家确认该画是否为真迹。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('liability', '[ˌlaɪə\'bɪləti]', 'n.责任；债务；倾向；可能性；不利因素', '1. He admitted his liability for the accident. 他承认自己对这起事故应负责任。 2. The judge exempted them from all liability in these matters. 法官免除了他们在这些事上的所有责任和义务。 3. If your liabilities exceed your assets, you may go bankrupt. 如果你所负的债超过你的资产，你就会破产。 4. But the court ruled in favour of Wilson Parking due to a liability disclaimer printed at the entrance. 但法院统治了倾向于威尔逊停放由于责任声明列印在入口。', '名词复数: liabilities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bombardment', '[bɒm\'bɑːdmənt]', 'n.炮击；轰炸', '1. The night sky flared with the massive bombardment. 夜晚的天空被大规模炮击照得通明。 2. The town lay in ruins after a heavy bombardment. 在猛烈轰炸以后城镇成了一片废墟。 3. The enemy kept up their bombardment day and night. 敌军一直日夜不停地狂轰滥炸。 4. The ship went ahead against the enemy bombardment. 船冒着敌机的轰炸继续前进。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('finery', '[\'faɪnəri]', 'n.装饰；服饰；鲜艳服装', '1. Her skirt was bedaubed with cheap finery. 她的裙子上俗丽地缀满了便宜华丽的饰品。 2. She had no finery except her wedding ring. 除了结婚戒指外，她没有别的饰物。 3. She equipped herself in all her finery. 她穿上她最好的衣服。 4. Finery industry is a traditional and special industry. 服饰业是一个传统而特殊的行业。', '名词复数: fineries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mesmerism', '[\'mesməˌrɪzəm]', 'n.催眠术；催眠状态；难以抗拒的魅力', '1. Mesmerism: A class of Transmutations. 迷术：嬗变术的一类。 2. Und jetzt die 5000, Monsieur Mesmer. 5000元，麦斯墨先生，现在。 3. The choice is yours: Warrior, Ranger, Monk, Elementalist, Mesmer, or Necromancer. 您的选择有：战士、射手、僧侣、元素使、催眠师和死灵法师。 4. Your Monk/ Mesmer can subvert enemies\' Energy and use it to defend and heal allies. 僧侣/眠师可以汲取敌人的能量并利用来保护和治疗盟友。', '形容词: mesmeric 副词: mesmerically 名词: mesmerist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sidereal', '[saɪ\'dɪriəl]', 'adj.恒星的', '1. The sidereal year is not used to construct a calendar. 恒星年不用于编制年历。 2. A sidereal day is about 4 minutes shorter than a solar day. 一个恒星日比一个太阳日大约短4分钟。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stall', '[stɔːl]', 'n.栅栏；小隔间；货摊；座位 v.把...关进畜舍里；失速；熄火；拖延；（使）动弹不得', '1. The excited horse flung about in the stall. 受惊的马在马厩里乱冲乱踢。 2. The horse chafed against his stall. 马在厩栏上擦著身子。 3. Our house has a shower stall. 我们房子里有淋浴小隔间。 4. Never buy food from a market stall. 千万别在小摊上买食物。 5. You\'d better stall the pigs. 你最好把猪关在猪圈里饲养。', '过去式: stalled 过去分词: stalled 现在分词: stalling 第三人称单数: stalls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('goldbrick', '[\'ɡoʊldbrɪk]', 'v.偷懒；逃避义务；欺诈 n.逃避义务的人；假金砖', '1. But this lance head gives us the feeling that it\'s not consistent because of the goldbrick. 但这只矛头给我们的感觉有点像铁匠偷懒了，与整体不甚协调。', '名词: goldbricker 过去式: goldbricked 过去分词: goldbricked 现在分词: goldbricking 第三人称单数: goldbricks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fiasco', '[fi\'æskoʊ]', 'n.惨败', '1. The film is a box-office fiasco. 这部电影在票房上遭到惨败。 2. No true fiasco ever began as a quest for mere adequacy. 如果只是追求简单的满足感，那永远不会尝到失败的滋味。', '名词复数: fiascoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('leisureliness', '[leʒə\'laɪnəs]', 'n.悠然的；从容的', '1. In 2009, we need more leisureliness and confidence. 2009年需要的是多一份从容，多一点自信。 2. That is the all forgotten ambit of your leisureliness in it . 身处其中，悠然自在，神游万里而至物我两忘之境界。 3. Return of life, is always between the effulgence and the leisureliness. 生命的回旋，总是在灿烂和悠远之间。那一抹流蓝就是你的语言。 4. The young butterfly flies earnestly. In the quiet leisureliness returns some broad-minded selfhood. 幼蝶认真地飞着，安静里的从容中又回归了几分豁达的自我。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('magnate', '[\'mæɡneɪt]', 'n.巨头', '1. Mcdonald\'s is a global snack magnate. 麦当劳集团是全球快餐业巨头。 2. The newspaper was owned by a famous publishing magnate. 这家报纸为一位著名的出版业巨头所有。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meet', '[miːt]', 'v.遇见；满足 n.运动会；集会 adj.合适的', '1. I chanced to meet an old friend in the park today. 今天我在公园碰巧遇见一位老朋友。 2. She is the girl whom you meet at the airport. 她就是你在机场遇见的那个女孩。 3. Ensure that your request be the fastest meet. 保证你的要求得到最快的满足。 4. What criteria should the memorial meet? 纪念碑要满足那些条件？ 5. The sports meet was postponed because of rain. 运动会因雨延期。 6. It is easy to fall in love when you meet the right person. 当你遇到合适的对象就很容易恋爱。', '副词: meetly 过去式: met 过去分词: met 现在分词: meeting 第三人称单数: meets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blighted', '[b\'laɪtɪd]', 'adj.枯萎的；摧毁的 动词blight的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. His reputation was blighted by his bad behavior. 他的名誉为他的行为不检所毁。 2. The apple trees were blighted by frost. 苹果树因严寒而枯萎。 3. Her life was blighted by ill health. 她的一生被疾病所摧残。 4. Blighted, withered, or shriveled. 枯萎的，萎缩的，皱缩的', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sober', '[\'soʊbər]', 'adj.清醒的；稳重的；沉着冷静的；颜色暗淡的 vt.使清醒；使沉着 vi.清醒；冷静下来', '1. He was tipsy yesterday , but now is sober. 他昨天醉醺醺的,但现在是清醒的。 2. We should make a sober estimate of the situation. 我们对形势要有清醒的估计。 3. He is a very sober and hard-working young man. 他是一个非常稳重而勤奋的年轻人。 4. He talked with us in a sober and friendly fashion. 他以冷静而友好的方式同我们交谈。 5. He drank a cup of strong tea to sober himself up. 他喝下一杯浓茶以使自己清醒过来。 6. He sobered up quickly when he heard the terrible news. 他听到这个坏消息，马上就清醒过来了。', '副词: soberly 比较级: soberer 最高级: soberest 名词: soberness 过去式: sobered 过去分词: sobered 现在分词: sobering 第三人称单数: sobers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('isthmus', '[\'ɪsməs]', 'n.地峡；[解]峡，管峡', '1. In which part of the world is the Isthmus located? 苏伊士地峡位于世界的哪一部分？ 2. The southern isthmus is always hot and humid. 南部地峡总是炎热和潮湿。 3. The thyroid gland has a right lobe and a left lobe connected by a narrow isthmus. 位于颈部气管前，由左右两叶及中间狭窄的的峡部构成。 4. The ablation target site was the isthmus between tricuspid valve annulus and inferior vana cava. 位于三尖瓣环和下腔静脉口间的峡部为消融部位。', '名词复数: isthmuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prejudice', '[\'predʒudɪs]', 'n.偏见；伤害 vt.伤害；使 ... 存偏见；使偏袒', '1. She has a prejudice against modern music. 她对现代音乐怀有偏见。 2. A judge must be free from prejudice. 法官必须不抱成见。 3. The offer was accepted without prejudice to the current pay negotiations. 该提议获得接纳，但对目前正在进行的工资谈判并无影响。 4. A new law has been brought in to discourage racial prejudice. 一项反对种族歧视的新法律已被提出。 5. Your bad spelling may prejudice your chances of getting this job. 你糟糕的拼写会妨碍你获得这个工作的机会。', '过去式: prejudiced 过去分词: prejudiced 现在分词: prejudicing 第三人称单数: prejudices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('augury', '[\'ɔːɡjʊri]', 'n.预言；征兆；占卜', '1. At last, the augury came ture unexpectedly. 最后，这句谶语居然应验了。 2. The maritime passage was a good augury for the aerial passage. 顺利的航海仿佛也是航空的好预兆。 3. This is not a happy augury for the interval between these elections and the next. 在这些选举的间隔中这不是一个快乐的征兆。 4. Augury is the important part of Chinese traditional culture. 占卜是中国传统文化中的一个重要组成部分。', '名词复数: auguries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wrangler', '[\'ræŋɡlər]', 'n.牧人；争论者 Wrangler. n.牧马人(品牌名)', '1. My brother is a skilled wrangler who can keep a dozen horses calm during a storm. 我的兄弟是个技术高超的牛仔，在风暴到来时能让几十匹马保持平静。 2. A newspaper reader, by comparison, is a swordsman, a wrangler, a private eye. 相比之下，读报纸的人就是剑客、辩论家、私家侦探。 3. Jeep\'s Wrangler continued to gain momentum; sales are up 11 percent this year. 吉普的牧马人有继续上涨的势头；今年的销售额增长了11个百分点。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('voluble', '[\'vɑːljəbl]', 'adj.健谈的；口若悬河的；流利的；易旋转的', '1. The new comer in our company is voluble. 我们公司新来的同事很健谈。 2. Evelyn was very voluble on the subject of women\'s rights. 伊夫林谈起女权这个话题口若悬河。 3. The Englishman broke into voluble and perfect Italian. 那个英国人突然讲起流利而纯正的意大利语来。', '副词: volubly 名词: volubility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cargo', '[\'kɑːrɡoʊ]', 'n.货物；船货', '1. The ship is discharging the cargo. 船正在卸货。 2. Cargo insurance is a major item of our business. 货物保险是我公司的一大项目。 3. The cargo was seriously damaged by water. 船货被水严重损坏。 4. This port handles 100 million tons of cargo each year. 这个港口每年货物吞吐量达1亿吨。', '名词复数: cargoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brittle', '[\'brɪtl]', 'adj.易碎的；尖利的；脆弱的 n.果仁薄脆糖', '1. The ice is brittle as the thin glass. 这些冰像薄的玻璃一样易碎。 2. The pond was covered in a brittle layer of ice. 池塘覆盖了一层易碎的冰。 3. Constant stress has made our nerves brittle. 我们长期处于紧张状态，神经已经吃不消了。 4. The orchestra was brittle in tone. 管弦乐队演奏的曲调尖利刺耳。', '副词: brittlely 比较级: brittler 最高级: brittlest 名词: brittleness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('truce', '[truːs]', 'n.休战；(争执；烦恼等的)缓和 v.以停战结束', '1. A truce should be made in the interval. 在接着的一个时期中，双方实行休战。 2. This truce lasts for several days, depending on the location. 这次休战据所处位置的不同持续了数日。', '过去式: truced 过去分词: truced 现在分词: trucing 第三人称单数: truces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barb', '[bɑːrb]', 'n.倒钩；刻薄的言语', '1. Surgeons removed a foot-long barb from his heart. 外科医生正从他的心脏移出一英尺长的倒钩。 2. A fish hook has a barb to prevent the fish from escaping after being hooked. 鱼钩上都有一个倒钩以防上了钩的鱼逃走. 3. And with that last barb, Harry\'s slowly unravelling grip on his temper gave way. 他一直听到最后那句挖苦话，结果先前的忍耐终于失去控制了。', '过去式: barbed 过去分词: barbed 现在分词: barbing 第三人称单数: barbs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unification', '[ˌjuːnɪfɪ\'keɪʃn]', 'n.统一；一致', '1. The Franco-German war completed the unification of Germany . 普法战争完成了德国的统一。 2. If unification is sought on the opposite basis, the country will perish. 如果向相反的方面统一，那中国就会亡国。 3. The unification of Italy resulted in a single country instead of several kingdoms. 意大利统一的结果是出现了一个国家,而不是好几个王国。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aphorism', '[\'æfərɪzəm]', 'n.格言；警语', '1. It is the aphorism of the Asian Games. 这是亚运会的格言。', '形容词: aphoristic 副词: aphoristically 名词: aphorist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trounce', '[traʊns]', 'vt.痛打；痛骂；严责', '1. Former Manchester United striker Cristiano Ronaldo has given his verdict on British music, and according to him, Oasis trounce The Beatles. 前曼联前锋罗纳尔多给他翻案，英国音乐，并根据他的说法，绿洲痛打披头士。 2. Sadly, too many individual investors do not fully exploit these advantages, and never reach their true potential to trounce the market. 可悲的是，太多的个人投资者并没有充分利用这些优势，并没有达到其真正的潜力，以痛打市场。', '过去式: trounced 过去分词: trounced 现在分词: trouncing 第三人称单数: trounces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blooming', '[\'bluːmɪŋ]', 'adj.正开花的；妙龄的 动词bloom的现在分词.', '1. A blooming tree absorbs the sun\'s rays. 郁郁葱葱的树木沐浴着阳光。 2. Hundreds of flowers are blooming in profusion. 百花怒放。 3. The children are blooming! 孩子们正在健康成长。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barrage', '[bə\'rɑːʒ]', 'n.弹幕；掩护炮火 n.拦河坝 vt.以密集火力进攻', '1. Make your opponents spin and crash as you bombard them with a barrage of weapons. 向你的竞争对手们进行弹幕式的炸掉袭击，让他们团团转并一一被摧毁。', '过去式: barraged 过去分词: barraged 现在分词: barraging 第三人称单数: barrages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repellent', '[rɪ\'pelənt]', 'n.驱虫剂；防水剂 adj.令人厌恶的；排斥的；驱除的；防水的', '1. Then we passed on to an equally repellent sight. 接着我们又去参观了另一个同样令人厌恶的地方。 2. His behavior was repellent to her. 对她而言,他的行为是令人感到排斥的。', '副词: repellently 名词: repellence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('taboo', '[tə\'buː]', 'n.禁忌；禁止接近；禁止使用 adj.禁忌的 vt.禁忌', '1. Cannibalism is perhaps the ultimate cultural taboo. 同类相食也许是人类文化的最高禁忌。 2. There\'s a taboo on smoking in this office. 在这个办公室里一向是都不吸烟的。 3. Among Hindus there is a taboo against killing cows. 印度教徒有禁止杀牛的戒律。 4. Any mention of politics is taboo in his house. 在他家里一提政治就犯忌。 5. Sex is no longer the taboo subject it used to be. 现在不再像过去那样把性的问题视为禁区。 6. A man should taboo bad hobbies, and cultivate good habits. 作为男人应该避讳不良嗜好,培养良好的习惯。', '过去式: tabooed/tabued 过去分词: tabooed/tabued 现在分词: tabooing/tabuing 第三人称单数: taboos/tabus');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lore', '[lɔːr]', 'n.学问；知识；传说；(鸟等的)眼端', '1. The older man has gypsy lore. 那个老者有吉卜赛人的学问。 2. I will seek and question him of his lore. 我倒要找上他，向他讨教他的渊博的学问。 3. Tribal lore and custom have been passed down orally. 部落的知识和风俗口耳相传保存下来。 4. They learned the lore of herbs from their ancestors. 他们从祖先那里学到药草的知识。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('digestion', '[daɪ\'dʒestʃən]', 'n.消化；吸收；领悟；[生]细菌分解', '1. Porridge is good for digestion. 粥有益于消化。 2. He has a good digestion. 他消化能力很强。 3. It is concluded that the quality of feed is closely related with the digestion,absorption and excretion of the eel. 饲料质量与鳗鱼的消化吸收和排泄也有密切关系。 4. The emulsifier OP is added to dissolve the fat produced during the digestion process. 建立了用火焰原子吸收光谱法测定鸡蛋中钙和镁的快速分析方法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('puerile', '[\'pjʊrəl]', 'adj.青春期的；孩子气的；未成熟的', '1. He was trying to give puerile excuses. 他给出的借口总是愚蠢至极。 2. She was tired of answering these puerile questions. 她回答这些幼稚的问题觉得不胜其烦. 3. John made mincemeat of all her arguments, and said that he had never heard anything so puerile before. 约翰把她的论点驳得体无完肤，并说他从来没有听过这样幼稚可笑的道理。', '副词: puerilely 名词: puerility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discrete', '[dɪ\'skriːt]', 'adj.不连续的；分离的', '1. They give off discrete amounts of radiant energy. 它们放出不连续的辐射能量。 2. The proteins initially appear as discrete bodies. 蛋白质体最初作为分离体而出现。', '副词: discretely 名词: discreteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inkling', '[\'ɪŋklɪŋ]', 'n.暗示；略知', '1. I will try to give you an inkling. 我会试着给你一些提示。 2. My friend gave an inkling of his intention to leave the company. 我朋友暗示他有意离开这家公司。 3. He had some inkling of the difficulties. 他对困难略有所知。 4. I had an inkling of what he intended to do. 我略知他打算做什么。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ardent', '[\'ɑːrdnt]', 'adj.热心的；激烈的；热情的', '1. Some industrialists are at heart ardent reformers. 有些企业家实际上都是热心的改革家。 2. The satisfaction derived from this act was all that the most ardent moralist could have desired. 这个行动使自己得到了连最热心的慈善家都希冀得到的满足。 3. An ardent outset may be followed by declension. 热情的开端可能继之以冷漠。 4. I\'ve never met such an ardent pacifist as Terry. 我从未见过像特里这样热情的和平主义者。', '副词: ardently 名词: ardency');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tedium', '[\'tiːdiəm]', 'n.单调乏味；沉闷', '1. He has got used to the tedium of life here. 他已经习惯了这里单调的生活。 2. I didn\'t know how to while away my tedium. 我不知道如何度过乏味的时刻。 3. Risk is what separates the good part of life from the tedium. 风险把生活中的精彩篇章与单调无聊区分开。 4. We played games to relieve the tedium of the journey. 我们玩游戏,来解除旅行的沉闷。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saunter', '[\'sɔːntər]', 'v.闲逛；漫步 n.闲逛；漫步', '1. He sauntered by with his hands in his pockets. 他双手插在口袋里悠闲地走了过去。 2. Sometimes in the summer my wife and I saunter there in the cool of the evening. 在夏日,内子和我有时会在黄昏阴凉时分到那里散步。 3. This part of the route should be an easy saunter. 这段路想必好走。 4. Let\'s go for a saunter along the river. 我们沿着河走走吧。', '名词: saunterer 过去式: sauntered 过去分词: sauntered 现在分词: sauntering 第三人称单数: saunters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rind', '[raɪnd]', 'n.皮；壳', '1. Please help me to cut off the rinds of lemons. 请帮我去掉柠檬的皮。 2. Those apple rinds are green. 那些苹果的皮是绿的。 3. Bacon rind could be rendered down to provide enough fat to fry doughnuts. 熏肉皮被熬成油，足以用来炸油炸圈饼了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grope', '[ɡroʊp]', 'v.(暗中)摸索；探索；<口>(调情时)抚摸…身体', '1. I groped for the door handle in the dark. 我在黑暗中摸索着门把手。 2. We groped our way through the dark streets. 我们摸索着走过黑暗的街道。 3. We have to grope for ways to do thing. 我们只能边探索边干。 4. Just friends. I won\'t grope you, I promise. 只是朋友嘛。我不会对你动手动脚的，我保证。', '副词: gropingly 名词: groper 过去式: groped 过去分词: groped 现在分词: groping 第三人称单数: gropes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saddle', '[\'sædl]', 'n.鞍；车座；山脊；当权 vt.装以马鞍；使负担 vi.装马鞍', '1. The jockey vaulted into the saddle . 骑士一跃而跨坐鞍上。 2. The saddle galled the horse\'s back. 马鞍擦伤了马背。 3. The bicycle saddle is too high for this child. 这辆自行车车座对这孩子来说太高了。 4. He is determined to stay in the saddle at all cost. 他打定主意要不惜一切代价继续掌权。 5. I had to saddle for him the first few times. 头几次我得替他套马鞍。 6. He saddled up his horse and rode away. 他给马装上鞍子便骑马离去了。', '过去式: saddled 过去分词: saddled 现在分词: saddling 第三人称单数: saddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spew', '[spjuː]', 'v.喷出；涌出；呕吐；吐出 n.呕吐物；喷出物', '1. The volcano spewed molten lava. 火山喷出了熔岩。 2. Water spewed out of the hole. 水从孔中射出。 3. She spewed up the entire meal. 她把吃的饭全吐出来了。', '名词: spewer 过去式: spewed 过去分词: spewed 现在分词: spewing 第三人称单数: spews');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aspect', '[\'æspekt]', 'n.方面；方位；外观；外貌', '1. This is only one aspect of the problem. 这只是问题的一个方面。 2. He has made progress in every aspect. 他在各方面都有起色。 3. The building has a southern aspect. 那座建筑是朝南的。 4. The open spaces differ according to aspect. 开敞空地随方位而不同。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brag', '[bræɡ]', 'v.吹牛；自夸 n.大话；吹牛的人；傲慢的态度 adj.一流的；特别好的', '1. He used to brag that he would make lots of money. 他经常吹牛说自己会赚很多很多钱。 2. She bragged that she could run faster than I. 她夸口说她比我跑得快。 3. He often brag that how well he plays golf. 他常常自夸他高尔夫球打得如何如何好。 4. He made a great brag of his ability. 他夸耀自己的能力。', '比较级: bragger 最高级: braggest 名词: bragger 过去式: bragged 过去分词: bragged 现在分词: bragging 第三人称单数: brags');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alienate', '[\'eɪliəneɪt]', 'vt.使疏远；离间；让与；麻木', '1. We\'d better not alienate ourselves from the colleagues. 我们最好还是不要与同事们疏远。 2. The Prime Minister\'s policy alienated many of her followers. 首相的政策使很多拥护她的人疏远了她。 3. His attempts to alienate the two friends failed. 他离间那一对朋友的企图失败了。 4. She tried to alienate him from his brother 她企图离间他和他的兄弟。', '名词: alienator 过去式: alienated 过去分词: alienated 现在分词: alienating 第三人称单数: alienates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('secular', '[\'sekjələr]', 'adj.世俗的；现世的；不朽的；非宗教的 n.牧师；凡人', '1. The choir sings both sacred and secular music. 唱诗班既唱圣乐也唱世俗歌曲。 2. Secular music was flatly prohibited. 世俗音乐是绝对禁止的。 3. Even in such secular, permissive countries as Sweden, doctors tell surveys they oppose euthanasia by large margins. 即使在瑞典这样一个开化的国家，大部分的医生告诉调查者他们反对安乐死。 4. We live in an increasingly secular society. 我们生活在一个日益非宗教的社会。', '副词: secularly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('opportune', '[ˌɑːpər\'tuːn]', 'adj.合时宜的；适当的', '1. It\'s an opportune rain. 这是一场及时雨。 2. We must seize this highly opportune moment for reform. 我们要抓住时机，现在是改革的最好时机。 3. The opportune arrival of the bus cut short the boring conversation. 公车的适时到来缩短了这场无聊的谈话。 4. He arrived at the most opportune moment. 他在最适当的时候到达。', '副词: opportunely 名词: opportuneness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nitpick', '[\'nɪtpɪk]', 'v.挑剔；吹毛求疵', '1. You shouldn\'t nitpick, I had done my best. 你别太挑剔，我已经尽力了。 2. It is much easier to nitpick than to invent. 挑剔总是比发明更为容易。 3. They\'re less likely to nitpick about details that aren\'t relevant at this stage. 减少他们在与主题不相关的细节上的吹毛求疵。', '名词: nitpicker 过去式: nitpicked 过去分词: nitpicked 现在分词: nitpicking 第三人称单数: nitpicks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('parsimony', '[\'pɑːrsəmoʊni]', 'n.过度节俭；吝啬；简约性', '1. The Asians\' parsimony made the Anglo-Saxons’ profligacy possible. 亚洲人过度节俭的生活习惯成就了盎格鲁萨克森人的奢华。 2. A classic example comes from comedian Jack Benny, famous for his parsimony. 有个经典例子出自以吝啬著称的喜剧演员杰克·班尼。 3. Reconstruction method includes maximum parsimony (MP) and Bayesian. 重建法包括最大简约法和贝叶斯法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appetizer', '[\'æpɪtaɪzər]', 'n.【C】开胃食品；开胃菜', '1. Small savoury biscuits provide a simple appetizer. 可口的小饼乾就是简单的开胃品。 2. We served some crackers and cheese as an appetizer. 我们上了些饼干和奶酪作为开胃品。 3. I\'d like appetizer and fish dish. 我想要一份开胃菜与鱼餐。 4. I would like a cucumber salad for an appetizer. 我要一份黄瓜沙拉作为开胃菜。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discrepancy', '[dɪs\'krepənsi]', 'n.差异；不一致；分歧', '1. We\'d like to discuss the details of the contract, especially discrepancy and claim. 我们想讨论合同的各项细目,特别是差异和索赔。 2. The price tag says$100 and you charged me for$120; how do you explain the discrepancy? 货物标签上写的是一百美元,你向我索价一百二十美元,这个差异该怎么解释？ 3. There was a discrepancy in the two reports. 在两个报告中有不一致之处。 4. Shakespeare did not acquiesce in discrepancy. 莎士比亚对于分歧并不是采取默认的态度。', '名词复数: discrepancies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seine', '[seɪn]', 'n.围网 v.用围网捕鱼 Seine. n.塞纳河(法国北部河流)', '1. The boat is sailing up the Seine. 小船在塞纳河中逆流而上。 2. This point of the Seine is dreaded by mariners. 塞纳河的这一处是水手们害怕的场所。 3. Seine is a famous river of the world. 塞纳河是世界上著名的河流。 4. Seine River and its branches form the chief commercial waterway of France. 塞纳河及其支流构成了法国主要的商业运输水路。', '名词: seiner 过去式: seined 过去分词: seined 现在分词: seining 第三人称单数: seines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pan', '[pæn]', 'n.平底锅；盘子；盘状物；淘盘；<俚>脸；严厉批评 v.严厉批评；（用淘盘）淘金', '1. I cracked two eggs into the frying pan. 我往平底锅里打了两个鸡蛋。 2. Take a pan or box and fill it with sand or cat litter. 拿一个盘子或盒子，里面装上沙子或者干草。 3. The water was run off from the pan so that the sand remained. 把淘盘里的水放掉，让沙留着。 4. They dip the pan into the bed of the stream, and then pan out the sand and dirt, hoping that some gold will be left. 他们用淘盘舀出小溪溪底泥沙，然后淘去泥沙，希望有金子留下来。 5. His new film was really panned by the critics. 他新拍摄的电影确实受到评论家严厉的批评。', '过去式: panned 过去分词: panned 现在分词: panning 第三人称单数: pans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deference', '[\'defərəns]', 'n.顺从；敬重', '1. His immediate deference made her regretful. 他毫不迟疑的顺从使她感到有些抱歉。 2. I changed my plan in deference to your opinion. 我听从你的意见，改变了计划。 3. They are married in church out of deference to their parents\' wish. 他们遵从父母的愿望在教堂举行了婚礼。 4. We all showed deference to his skill. 我们都敬重他的熟练技巧。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('affinity', '[ə\'fɪnəti]', 'n.姻亲；密切关系；吸引力', '1. He is not an impartial witness because of his affinity with the accused. 他不是公正的见证人,因为他与被告有姻亲关系。 2. There is an affinity between Chinese and Japanese character. 汉字与日文之间有密切关系。 3. She feels a strong affinity to him. 她感到他对她有很强的吸引力。 4. This substance has an affinity for water. 这物质和水有亲和力。', '名词复数: affinities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slog', '[slɑːɡ]', 'v.艰难行进；猛击；苦干；决出胜负 n.苦工；长途跋涉', '1. He started to slog his way through the undergrowth. 他踏上了穿越林莽的艰难征程。 2. I slog my guts out and get paid only a hundred pounds a week. 我工作非常努力，但每星期只有100英镑的报酬。 3. The two teams will slog it out for second place. 这两个队将争夺第二名。 4. The party leader be slog it out in a Tv debate. 政党领袖在电视辩论中一决雌雄。 5. Marking the exam papers was quite a slog. 评阅试卷是很辛苦的工作。', '名词: slogger 过去式: slogged 过去分词: slogged 现在分词: slogging 第三人称单数: slogs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abash', '[ə\'bæʃ]', 'vt.使羞愧；使困窘', '1. His boss\'s criticism left him feeling rather abashed. 老板批评了他，他感到有些难为情。 2. Nothing can abash him. 没有什麽事能让他脸红。', '名词: abashment 过去式: abashed 过去分词: abashed 现在分词: abashing 第三人称单数: abashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dregs', '[dreɡz]', 'n.渣滓；糟粕；废物 名词dreg的复数形式.', '1. These criminals are the dregs of society. 这些罪犯都是社会的渣滓。 2. The dregs have settled at the bottom of the bottle. 渣滓都沉到瓶底了。 3. What we should make sure is to absorb the essence and discard the dregs. 我们要明确的是取其精髓,去其糟粕。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stranded', '[\'strændɪd]', 'adj.搁浅的；处于困境的 动词strand的过去式和过去分词.', '1. A crab was left stranded on the beach when the tide ebbed. 退潮时，一只蟹被困留在沙滩上。 2. The crew of the stranded yacht were in danger but we got them off. 那艘搁浅快艇上的船员处于危险之中，但我们把他救了上来。 3. The stranded tourists were finally flown home. 受困的游客终于由飞机送返家园。 4. The stranded survivor was thirsty and hungry. 被困的幸存者饥渴交加。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snatch', '[snætʃ]', 'n.抢夺；一阵；一点点 v.夺取；抓住', '1. The thief made a snatch at the woman\'s purse. 小偷试图抢夺那妇女的钱包。 2. He made a brave snatch at victory but failed. 他奋力争取胜利，但是失败了。 3. He has a snatch of sleep sitting in his chair. 他坐在椅子里稍睡片刻。 4. They put the snatch on him for a cut of the take. 他们强要他分给他们一分。 5. He snatched up his gun and fired. 他突然拿起枪来射击。', '名词: snatcher 过去式: snatched 过去分词: snatched 现在分词: snatching 第三人称单数: snatches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peerless', '[\'pɪrləs]', 'adj.无比的；出类的；无双的', '1. Chinese silk is peerless in the world simply Because long practice has led to the way of perfection. 中国丝绸之所以天下夺魁，是因为长久的实践创造了完美。 2. To be a peerless man is very difficult. 做一个出类拔萃的人是很不容易的。 3. His Chinese kung fu is peerless. 他的中国功夫是无敌的。 4. Welcome to HongKong, a peerless city in entire world. 欢迎莅临香港，一个举世无双的城市。', '副词: peerlessly 名词: peerlessness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('court', '[kɔːrt]', 'n.法院；庭院；宫廷；球场；奉承 v.献殷勤；追求；招致；设法获得', '1. Sherman recommended that Clarke be disciplined, but higher-ups rejected the idea. 谢尔曼建议对克拉克进行纪律惩戒，但高层拒绝了这个意见。 2. My court is deserted but I do not care. 我的庭院一片荒芜但是我无心照看。 3. The court of King Solomon was noted for its splendor. 所罗门国王的宫廷以其华丽著称。 4. The court moves to the country in the summer. 夏天王室上下都移居到乡下去。 5. He has been courting the director, hoping to get the leading role in the play. 他一直在讨好导演，想在剧中扮演主角。', '过去式: courted 过去分词: courted 现在分词: courting 第三人称单数: courts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quixotic', '[kwɪk\'sɑːtɪk]', 'adj.唐吉诃德式的；狂想家的；不切实际的', '1. I was dumbfounded to hear him say that I was on a quixotic enterprise 听到他说我在从事一项不切实际的事业,我大吃一惊。', '副词: quixotically 异体字: quixotical 名词: quixotism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elicit', '[i\'lɪsɪt]', 'vt.引出；诱出；探出', '1. The detectives tried to elicit where he had hidden his loot. 侦探试图诱使他说出他藏匿赃物的地方。 2. I could elicit no response from him. 我从他那里套不出任何反应。 3. At last we have elicited the truth from him. 我们终于从他那里探得真相。 4. He succeeded in eliciting the information he needed from her. 他从她那里问出了他所需要的信息。', '名词: elicitation 过去式: elicited 过去分词: elicited 现在分词: eliciting 第三人称单数: elicits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thresh', '[θreʃ]', 'v.打谷；脱粒；反复地做', '1. The farmers used to thresh the grain by hand, but now machines thresh it. 农民过去用手工打谷，但现在用机器脱粒。 2. In some villages farmers use a machine to thresh wheat. 在一些村子里，农民用机器来打麦。 3. They are separating the grains from wheat with a threshing machine. 他们正在用打谷机给小麦脱粒。 4. Farmers thresh grain with threshing machines. 农民用脱粒机脱粒。', '过去式: threshed 过去分词: threshed 现在分词: threshing 第三人称单数: threshes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('precede', '[prɪ\'siːd]', 'vt.在 ... 之前；先于 vi.在前面；领先', '1. He precede his speech with a welcome to the guest. 他演讲前先对来宾表示欢迎。 2. He came in, preceded by his wife. 他和他的妻子一前一后地走了进来。 3. The we should always precede the I. 集体总应先于个人。 4. This duty should precede all others. 此项义务应该优先于其他一切义务。 5. The days that preceded were filled with activity. 前几天排满了活动。', '过去式: preceded 过去分词: preceded 现在分词: preceding 第三人称单数: precedes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('indurate', '[\'ɪndjʊˌreɪt]', 'vt.使坚固；使硬化 vi.硬化；巩固起来 adj.硬的', '1. TPU material indurate sole as well as protecting ankle. TPU后跟杯起到坚固大底强度的作用，有防止脚部扭伤。 2. Styles 2, persistent, enlarged and indurate at maturity, apex hooked. 花柱2，宿存，扩大和成熟时使硬化，先端具钩。 3. At surgical exploration, and indurate mass consisting of abscess within the omentum was identified. 于手术当中发现在大网膜中有一个含有脓疡的硬块。 4. At surgical exploration, an indurate mass consisting of abscess within the omentum was identified. 于手术当中发现在大网膜中有一个含有脓疡的硬块。', '形容词: indurative 过去式: indurated 过去分词: indurated 现在分词: indurating 第三人称单数: indurates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recuperate', '[rɪ\'kuːpəreɪt]', 'v.（使）恢复；（使）复原', '1. Stay in the hospital for a few more days to recuperate. 再住院几天，好好地恢复。 2. After an exhausting few weeks I needed some time to recuperate. 累了几个星期之后，我需要时间恢复一下。 3. The patient did not recuperate as rapidly as the doctor had expected. 这位病人并没有像医生所期望的那样很快就复原。 4. She went to the country to recuperate. 她去乡村休养。', '形容词: recuperative 名词: recuperation 过去式: recuperated 过去分词: recuperated 现在分词: recuperating 第三人称单数: recuperates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('metabolism', '[mə\'tæbəlɪzəm]', 'n.新陈代谢', '1. Their rate of metabolism may slow down. 他们的新陈代谢率可能会降低。 2. I do exercise every day to increase my metabolism. 我每天运动以促进新陈代谢。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vicar', '[\'vɪkər]', 'n.(教区或教堂)牧师；代理人', '1. He is vicar of a large rural parish. 他是农村一大牧区的牧师。 2. The vicar gave a sermon on the evils of gambling. 教区牧师作了一次布道，宣讲赌博的危害。 3. The vicar preached to the congregation for half an hour. 那位教区牧师向会众讲道半个小时。 4. Our vicar often leaves off his dog collar and comes to the discos at the youth club. 我们的教区牧师经常不穿牧师领去参加青年俱乐部的迪斯科舞会。', '名词: vicarship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impart', '[ɪm\'pɑːrt]', 'vt.传授；赋予；告知', '1. A teacher\'s aim is to impart knowledge. 教师的作用是传授知识。 2. They had come to impart their experience in stock raising. 他们是来传授饲养牲畜的经验的。 3. The red curtains impart a certain elegance to the room. 红色的窗帘使房间平添几分雅致。 4. Your presence will impart an air of elegance to the party. 您的光临将会为宴会增添优雅的气氛。', '过去式: imparted 过去分词: imparted 现在分词: imparting 第三人称单数: imparts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('riveting', '[\'rɪvɪtɪŋ]', 'adj.动听的；令人着迷的；非常精彩的 动词rivet的现在分词形式.', '1. Can I fasten these metal plates with rivets? 我可以用铆钉把这些金属板固定在一起吗？ 2. Only by riveting her attention on her work could she forget her worries. 只有全身心投入到工作上她才能忘记烦恼。', '副词: rivetingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('headway', '[\'hedweɪ]', 'n.前进；航行速度；进展；（前后两车间的）车间时距', '1. The work is steadily making headway. 这项工作正在取得稳步进展。 2. The boat made slow headway against the tide. 那船逆着潮水缓慢地前进。 3. I can not make any headway on this problem. 我无法突破获这个问题。 4. Did you make any headway in your research work? 你们的研究工作有进展吗？', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('content', '[\'kɑːntent]', 'n. 内容； 目录； 含量 adj. 满足的； 满意的 vt. 使 ... 满足； 使 ... 安心', '1. Teaching content should be concise. 教学内容要少而精。 2. The book is rich in content and succinct in style. 这本书内容丰富，文字简练。 3. Define content sections of status reports. 定义状态报告的目录部分。 4. Using file shares that provide only a hierarchical directory structure as a means of organizing content. 将只提供一个层次目录结构的文件共享作为内容组织方式使用。 5. We\'re also in the content business. 我们是也在满足的生意方面。 6. Disport oneself to one\'s heart\'s content. 玩个痛快什么也不会使他满足。', '过去式: contented 过去分词: contented 现在分词: contenting 第三人称单数: contents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rosy', '[\'roʊzi]', 'adj.玫瑰色的；美好的', '1. Her normally rosy face took on a deeper hue. 她平常玫瑰色的脸上呈现出更深的色彩。 2. The rosy light yet beamed like a celestial dawn. 玫瑰色的红光依然象天上的朝霞一样绚丽。 3. She painted a rosy picture of the firm\'s future. 她为公司的前景描绘了一幅美好的图画。 4. But life is not rosy for the closeted cross dresser. 但是，对于变装者来说，生活并不是美好的。', '副词: rosily 比较级: rosier 最高级: rosiest 名词: rosiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('admission', '[əd\'mɪʃn]', 'n.承认；入会费；许可', '1. He is a coward by his own admission. 他自己承认是个胆小鬼。 2. He was, on his own admission, impulsive by nature. 他承认自己生性易于感情冲动。 3. Do they charge for admission? 入场要收费吗? 4. The charge for admission is US$5. 入场费五美元。', '形容词: admissive');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('startle', '[\'stɑːrtl]', 'v.（使）吃惊；（使）惊愕 n.吃惊；惊恐', '1. He was startled by the news. 这消息使他大吃一惊。 2. He startled from sleep. 他从睡梦中惊醒起来。 3. The least noise would startle the timid child. 最小的响声也会吓着这个胆小的孩子的。 4. Let\'s hide ourselves behind the door and startle her. 藏在门后面，咱们吓她一下。 5. He gave me a startle. 他吓了我一跳。', '副词: startlingly 名词: startlingness 过去式: startled 过去分词: startled 现在分词: startling 第三人称单数: startles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perishable', '[\'perɪʃəbl]', 'adj.易腐烂的；会枯萎的；会死的 （复数）perishables:易腐烂的东西（尤指食物）.', '1. Perishable goods are piling up at the docks. 码头上易腐烂的货物堆积如山。 2. Unlike perishable agricultural products, oil can be stored in the ground. 不同于易腐烂的农产品，石油可以长期埋在地下。', '副词: perishably 名词: perishability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deactivate', '[ˌdiː\'æktɪveɪt]', 'v.使无效；使不活动；解散部队', '1. The bomb squad was called in to deactivate the car bomb. 请来爆破小组拆除这枚汽车炸弹。 2. We would immediately deactivate your service on the SIM card. 我们立即为您挂失。 3. If you don\'t wish to use a feature, you can deactivate it. 而如果你不想使用某个特点的话，可以将其禁用。', '名词: deactivation 过去式: deactivated 过去分词: deactivated 现在分词: deactivating 第三人称单数: deactivates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('punctilious', '[pʌŋk\'tɪliəs]', 'adj.精密细心的；一丝不苟的；谨小慎微的', '1. He is the most punctilious blockhead under heaven. 他是个拘泥刻板、仔细精确到极点的笨蛋，世上无人能出其右； 2. Billy is punctilious in the performance of his duties. 毕利执行任务总是一丝不苟的。', '副词: punctiliously 名词: punctiliousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('robust', '[roʊ\'bʌst]', 'adj.强健的；稳固的；耐用的；粗野的；浓的', '1. She was almost 90, but still very robust. 她将近90岁了，但身体仍然十分强健。 2. But I can say for sure that our monetary system is robust. 但是,我可以很肯定地讲,我们的货币体系是稳固。 3. He bought a robust metal cabinet for his new house. 他为新家购置了一个坚固耐用的金属柜。 4. He is a man with a rather robust sense of humor. 他具备颇为粗俗的幽默感。', '副词: robustly 名词: robustness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('factotum', '[fæk\'toʊtəm]', 'n.杂役；听差；家务总管', '1. The old man who was his indoor factotum came at the same moment to the foot of the stairs. 与此同时，那位担任家务总管的老头儿来到了楼梯下。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acute', '[ə\'kjuːt]', 'adj.严重的；敏锐的；急性的；剧烈的', '1. He suffers from acute depression. 他患有严重的抑郁症。 2. This area has an acute shortage of water. 这个地方缺水严重。 3. She has acute hearing. 她有很敏锐的听力。 4. The doctor said that you had acute appendicitis. 医生说您患的是急性阑尾炎。', '副词: acutely 名词: acuteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vagary', '[\'veɪgərɪ]', 'n.奇特；好奇；奇特行为；变幻莫测', '1. Betting on sport, in particular, is vagary. 如果赌的是体育运动，那就更说不清楚了。 2. The building of this house in the shape of the temple was a rich man\'s vagary. 这栋房屋庙宇式的外形，是一位富人的奇想。 3. The style of vagary and ghastfulness and the sense of mystery are full of thestory of Edgar Allan Poe. 艾德加·爱伦·坡的小说风格奇特恐怖,充满了神秘感。 4. The style of vagary and ghastfulness and the sense of mystery are full of thestory of Allan. 爱伦的小说风格奇特恐怖,充满了神秘感。', '名词复数: vagaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('affable', '[\'æfəbl]', 'adj.谦恭有礼的；和蔼可亲的；易于交谈的；慈祥的；殷勤的', '1. I am affable to everyone. 我对每个人都彬彬有礼。 2. We all like this affable teacher. 我们都喜欢这位和蔼可亲的老师。 3. He found her parents very affable. 他觉得她父母很好说话。 4. Granny smiled an affable smile. 奶奶慈祥地笑了笑。', '副词: affably 名词: affability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inscribe', '[ɪn\'skraɪb]', 'v.题写；题赠；铭刻于；铭记 （英）登记. [数] 使内接.', '1. Will you inscribe your name in the book? 能否请你在这本书上签名? 2. To inscribe a poem on a painting is what painters like to do. 画家们爱在画上题诗。 3. I told the jeweler to inscribe the ring with my name. 我叫珠宝商把我的名字刻在那只戒指上。 4. My father\'s words are inscribed on my memory. 父亲的话我铭记於心。', '名词: inscriber 过去式: inscribed 过去分词: inscribed 现在分词: inscribing 第三人称单数: inscribes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proscribe', '[proʊ\'skraɪb]', 'v.禁止；放逐；排斥；剥夺…的公权', '1. The sale of narcotics is proscribed by law. 法律禁止贩卖毒品。', '名词: proscriber 过去式: proscribed 过去分词: proscribed 现在分词: proscribing 第三人称单数: proscribes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('capture', '[\'kæptʃər]', 'vt.捕获；占领；夺取；吸引；(用照片等)留存 n.捕获；战利品', '1. The animals are captured in nets and sold to local zoos. 那些动物用网捕获后被卖到当地的动物园。 2. Rebel forces finally captured the village. 叛军最终占领了这个村庄。 3. The company looks forward to capturing the Canadian market. 该公司期待获得加拿大市场。 4. The novel captured the imagination of thousands of readers. 这部小说引起了千万读者的想象。 5. The revolutionist eluded capture for weeks by hiding underground. 那位革命者为避免被捕在地下躲藏了几个星期。', '过去式: captured 过去分词: captured 现在分词: capturing 第三人称单数: captures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contumacious', '[ˌkɑːntu\'meɪʃəs]', 'adj.不听命令的；顽固的；拒不服从的', '1. On his refusal to appear in person or by his attorney, he was pronounced contumacious. 由于他拒绝亲自出庭或派他的律师出庭， 被宣布为抗传。 2. There is another efficacious method for subduing the most obstinate, contumacious sinner. 有另一个有效的方法来镇压那最为顽固、抗命不从的罪人。 3. On his refusal to appear in person or by his attorney,he was pronounced contumacious. 由于他拒绝亲自出庭或派他的律师出庭，被宣布为抗传。 4. WORD OF THE DAY: contumacious: stubbornly disobedient. Some parents wonder why their children are so contumacious. 不听命令的;(尤指对法庭命令)抗拒的有些父母无法理解他们的孩子，为何如此不听父母的命令。', '副词: contumaciously 名词: contumaciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assured', '[ə\'ʃʊrd]', 'adj.确实的；保障的；有自信的 动词assure的过去式和过去分词.', '1. Please rest assured that repayment is ensured. 请您放心，还款是有保障的。', '副词: assuredly 名词: assuredness 名词复数: assured');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abhor', '[əb\'hɔːr]', 'vt.憎恶；厌恶；痛恨', '1. They abhor all forms of racial discrimination. 他们憎恶任何形式的种族歧视。 2. Most people abhor cruelyt to children. 大部分人憎恶虐待儿童。 3. I abhor every commonplace phrase by which wit is intended. 我厌恶所有那些力图表现智慧的陈腐不堪的俗话。 4. I will put my dwelling place among you, and I will not abhor you. 我要在你们中间立我的帐幕，我的心也不厌恶你们。', '名词: abhorrer 过去式: abhorred 过去分词: abhorred 现在分词: abhorring 第三人称单数: abhors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('code', '[koʊd]', 'n.密码；法规；准则 v.制成法典；把 ... 编码', '1. I can break the code of this box. 我能破译这个箱子的密码。 2. She tapped out in code to headquarters. 她给总部发出密码电报。 3. The Highway Code has been carried out. 公路法规已经被执行。 4. Managers are expected to comply with the company\'s code of conduct. 希望经理能够遵守公司的行为准则。 5. They coded each sample and sent them to the lab for analysis. 他们把每个样本都编了代码并送到实验室分析。', '过去式: coded 过去分词: coded 现在分词: coding 第三人称单数: codes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cross', '[krɔːs]', 'v.穿过；交叉；杂交；反对；勾掉；碰见；阻挠 n.十字架；十字形；杂交动植物；苦难 adj.交叉的；相反的；生气的；杂交的', '1. It\'s very dangerous for children to cross the busy street. 对孩子们来说,穿过车来车往的街道很危险。 2. Meet me at the point where the two paths cross. 我们在那两条路的交叉点见面吧。 3. The experts in the zoo tried to cross a leopard with a lion. 动物园里的专家们试图使豹与狮子杂交。 4. He crosses me in everything. 他处处与我作对。 5. She wore a small silver cross on a chain round her neck. 她脖子上戴著项链,上面挂着个小的银制十字架。 6. There was an accident yesterday at the cross part of three roads. 昨天,在三条路的交叉路段,发生了一起事故。', '副词: crossly 名词: crosser 过去式: crossed 过去分词: crossed 现在分词: crossing 第三人称单数: crosses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hassle', '[\'hæsl]', 'n.困难；争吵；麻烦 v.烦扰；麻烦', '1. Traveling during peak season can be a hassle. 在旺季旅行可能是个麻烦。 2. I like this restaurant even though finding a parking space is a hassle. 虽然要找到停车位很困难，我还是很喜欢这家餐厅。 3. It\'s a real hassle to get this child to eat. 使这孩子吃东西，真要费九牛二虎之力。 4. Try not to get into a hassle with this guy. 尽量别跟这家伙争吵。 5. The secretary told me no man would hassle her boss. 那位秘书告诉我那会儿谁也不能打扰她的老板。', '过去式: hassled 过去分词: hassled 现在分词: hassling 第三人称单数: hassles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disrupt', '[dɪs\'rʌpt]', 'vt.干扰；打断；妨碍；使分裂；使破裂', '1. Protesters tried to disrupt the meeting. 抗议者试图扰乱会议。 2. The communication was disrupted by the storm. 暴风雨使交通中断。 3. The bad weather has seriously disrupted supplies of food. 恶劣的天气严重地妨碍了食品的供应。 4. The war seemed likely to disrupt the state. 战争可能使这个国家分裂。', '名词: disrupter 过去式: disrupted 过去分词: disrupted 现在分词: disrupting 第三人称单数: disrupts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('buckle', '[\'bʌkl]', 'n.扣子；皮带扣 v.扣住；弯曲；专心做事；屈服', '1. He unfastened the buckles and took off the coat. 他解开扣子，把上衣脱掉。 2. Mary clasped her belt with a silver buckle. 玛莉用银色扣子扣紧她的腰带。 3. He buckled up his belt tightly. 他把裤带扣得紧紧的。 4. The shock buckled the wheel of my bicycle. 这一碰把我自行车的轮子碰歪了', '过去式: buckled 过去分词: buckled 现在分词: buckling 第三人称单数: buckles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interstice', '[ɪn\'tɜːrstɪs]', 'n.细裂缝；空隙', '1. There is a gleam of luminous gold, where the sinking western sun has found a first direct interstice in the clouds. 从西落太阳在云层里发现的一个直接空隙处，透出一缕金光。 2. A small space or interstice in a tissue or part,such as the area bounded by small veins in a leaf or the wing of an insect. 小区，细隙，叶脉网隙组织或部分的小空间或空隙，如叶子中的细脉或昆虫的翼周围的区域。', '名词复数: interstices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prod', '[prɑːd]', 'n.刺针；刺棒；戳；刺激；激励 v.戳；刺；刺激', '1. She gave the man a prod with her umbrella. 她用伞捅了那男子一下。 2. He\'s forgetful, so I\'ll give his memory a prod. 他很健忘,所以我要提醒他一下。 3. You\'ll have to give him a prod or he\'ll never get it finished. 你要给他一些激励，否则他永远都完不成。 4. He prodded at the pig with his walking-stick. 他用手杖推那口猪。', '名词: prodder 过去式: prodded 过去分词: prodded 现在分词: prodding 第三人称单数: prods');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tamp', '[tæmp]', 'vt.夯实；减少 n.夯具', '1. Thousands of troops were deployed across a wide swath of the country to tamp down unrest and restore order. 成千上万的部队部署在全国广泛的小水线面双体该国夯实下跌动乱和恢复秩序。', '过去式: tamped 过去分词: tamped 现在分词: tamping 第三人称单数: tamps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('calcium', '[\'kælsiəm]', 'n.钙', '1. We need some calcium everyday. 我们每天需要些钙。 2. I have a slight calcium deficiency. 我有点缺钙。 3. Like most dairy products, such as milk and cheese, yogurt contains a lot of calcium. 像大部分的乳制品，如牛奶和奶酪一样，优酪乳含有许多钙质。', '简写符号: Ca');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('penalize', '[\'piːnəlaɪz]', 'v.处罚；使不利', '1. People who drive when they are drunk should be heavily penalized. 对酒醉开车者应予重罚。 2. How can a referee penalize a player? 裁判怎样处罚犯规运动员？ 3. The new law penalizes the poorest members of society. 新法规对社会中最贫困者不利。', '名词: penalization 过去式: penalized 过去分词: penalized 现在分词: penalizing 第三人称单数: penalizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intricate', '[\'ɪntrɪkət]', 'adj.复杂的；难懂的', '1. It was an intricate and ingenious system. 这是一个复杂而精致的体系。 2. The prisoners designed the intricate escape. 囚犯们策划了那起周密的越狱事件。 3. Taiwan is a complex of intricate relationships. 台湾是个各种关系错综复杂的地方。 4. The situation seems to be intricate. 局势似乎错综复杂。', '副词: intricately 名词: intricateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wanton', '[\'wɑːntən]', 'adj.淫乱的；肆无忌惮的；无节制的 n.荡妇；水性杨花的女人；贪图享乐的人 v.放肆；挥霍', '1. The Fundies believe that these wanton women know too much about sex. 专家相信放荡的女人对性过于了解。 2. She was surprised by a wanton thought that rushed into her mind. 一个放肆的念头在她心里闪过，叫她吃了一惊。 3. The weeds grew in wanton profusion. 遍地野草丛生。 4. The cachinnation that we wanton, have no the madness for having scruples about. 我们放肆的大笑，毫无顾忌的疯狂。', '副词: wantonly 名词: wantonness 过去式: wantoned 过去分词: wantoned 现在分词: wantoning 第三人称单数: wantons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cynic', '[\'sɪnɪk]', 'n.愤世嫉俗者；悲观者；犬儒主义者；好挖苦的人 adj.犬儒学派的；好讥讽的', '1. I\'m too much of a cynic to believe that he\'ll keep his promise. 我太愤世嫉俗了，不能相信他会遵守诺言。 2. Cynics will say that there is not the slightest chance of success. 悲观的人会说根本不可能取得成功。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('poke', '[poʊk]', 'n.戳；刺；拨；钱袋 v.戳；捅；刺；拨开；伸出', '1. In his view, a pinch, a whack or a poke essentially tugged on a neural rope that then rang a pain alarm bell in the brain. 他的看法是，无论是捏、打或戳的动作，基本上都拉动了某根神经索，而敲响脑中某个疼痛的警铃。 2. I didn\'t know Haku had a fast poke. 我还不知道白有快速刺拳这一手。 3. He used a nail to poke a hole. 他用钉子刺了个洞。 4. At frequent intervals the driver used to stop, poke the fire and add fresh fuel. 在经常性的间歇中，司机常常停下来拨一下火，加上新的汽油。 5. Don\'t poke her eye out with that stick! 别让那根棍子戳着她的眼！', '过去式: poked 过去分词: poked 现在分词: poking 第三人称单数: pokes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sanatorium', '[ˌsænə\'tɔːriəm]', 'n.疗养院；休养所', '1. The sanatorium stands by the sea. 疗养院靠海。 2. This is a sanatorium for textile workers. 这是一所纺织工人疗养院。 3. She is now at Lushan sanatorium and endeavouring to pull round. 她目前在庐山休养所，力图把身体养好。', '异体字: sanatarium 名词复数: sanatoriums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diehard', '[\'daɪhɑːrd]', 'n.顽固分子 adj.顽固的', '1. He was much annoyed at my remark and called me a diehard. 他听了非常不高兴，竟骂我思想顽固。 2. I heard we had a diehard audience member. 听说咱们又有一位铁杆观众。 3. John is a diehard conservative and is completely against abortion. 约翰是个顽固的保守主义者,他坚决反对堕胎。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mansion', '[\'mænʃn]', 'n.大厦；宅邸；公寓', '1. The family owns a lordly mansion. 那个家族拥有一座气派的大厦。 2. The portal of the mansion looks magnificent. 这座大厦的正门看上去富丽堂皇。 3. The poor girl was astonished by the sumptuous furnishings of the mansion. 这个贫穷的女孩被大厦里的豪华的陈设惊呆了。 4. The broad steps in front of the mansion made it look very dignified. 宽阔的台阶使大厦的正面显得很气派。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('duplicitous', '[djuː\'plɪsɪtəs]', 'adj.搞两面派的；奸诈的；双重的', '1. Willing to work for anyone who could afford her astronomical fee, the duplicitous Parasitti knew no loyalty other than cold hard cash. 奸诈的帕拉西蒂只为那些能给她巨额报酬的人效力，她不知道什么叫忠诚，她的眼里只有金钱。', '副词: duplicitously 名词: duplicitousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infernal', '[ɪn\'fɜːrnl]', 'adj.地狱的；恶魔似的；极度的', '1. People still have a general fear for the imaginary infernal powers. 人们对于虚构的地狱中的鬼神仍具有一种普遍的恐惧。 2. You infernal scoundrel, how dare you tell me that? 你这个无法无天的流氓，好大胆子，竟敢跟我说这种话。 3. That infernal telephone hasn\'t stopped ringing all day! 那讨厌的电话整天响个不停！', '副词: infernally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nippy', '[\'nɪpi]', 'adj.刺骨的；锐利的；（狗）爱咬人的', '1. It was obvious that he had been blew through by the nippy wind. 它是明显的他是藉着刺骨的风吹过。 2. You\'ll have to be nippy if you want to be on time. 如果你想准时到达，就得赶快些。 3. But now the current Chelsea manager wishes to drive a trimmed down, more nippy model, and he has been justifying why. 但现在切尔西的教练希望走精简的模式，并且说明了原因。', '副词: nippily 比较级: nippier 最高级: nippiest 名词: nippiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mutilate', '[\'mjuːtɪleɪt]', 'v.切断(手足等)；使残缺不全；毁坏', '1. She was mutilated in the accident and now has only one leg. 她在那次事故中致残，现在只有一条腿了。 2. A madman mutilated the painting by cutting holes in it. 有个疯子破坏了那幅画，在上面划了许多窟窿。 3. Someone mutilated the book by tearing out the illustrations. 有人撕掉插图,把那本书弄得残缺不全。', '形容词: mutilative 名词: mutilation 过去式: mutilated 过去分词: mutilated 现在分词: mutilating 第三人称单数: mutilates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resilient', '[rɪ\'zɪliənt]', 'adj.适应力强的；有弹力的', '1. She is very resilient to change. 她对变化有很强的适应力. 2. He\'ll get over it,young people are amazingly resilient. 他会克服这些的，年轻人的适应力惊人。 3. The state and Confucianism were remarkably resilient. 这种政治体制及儒学有着了不起的适应性。 4. Rubber is more resilient than wood. 橡胶比木头弹性好。', '副词: resiliently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nubile', '[\'nuːbaɪl]', 'adj.适婚的；性感的', '1. Rich old men often like to be surrounded by nubile young women. 一些上了年纪的富翁总喜欢被到了适婚年龄的年轻女人围绕。 2. Mind you, nearly more than 50% of my friends who are far beyond their nubile age are still unmarried. 事实上，我半数以上的朋友都已经远远过了适婚年龄却还是孤身一人。 3. He got a photograph of a nubile young woman. 他拿到了一张妙龄女郎的艳照。 4. I rather enjoy looking at a nubile beautiful yoga teacher posing in front of me, as I try desperately to imitate her flexibility. 我也喜欢看美女瑜伽老师在我前面伸展，教傻傻的我怎么放我的手放我的腿。', '名词: nubility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fundamental', '[ˌfʌndə\'mentl]', 'adj.基本的；根本的；重要的 n.基础；基本原理', '1. For something fundamental has changed in Venezuela. 因为在委内瑞拉，有一些基本的东西已经改变了。 2. Trial by the jury is a fundamental right. 有陪审团陪同审判是一项基本的权利。 3. From the outset, it had two fundamental flaws. 从一开始，这一合作就有两个根本的缺陷。 4. The fundamental ones are embodied in the Party Constitution. 党章是最根本的党规党法。 5. Primary is about fundamental play. 原始与基础游戏有关。', '副词: fundamentally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exaggeration', '[ɪɡˌzædʒə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.夸张；夸大', '1. It is no exaggeration to say that she is fat. 说她胖决不夸张。 2. I can say without exaggeration that she is an angel. 我可以毫不夸张地说她是个天使。 3. I think that is an exaggeration. 我认为这是一种夸大。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('manifest', '[\'mænɪfest]', 'vt.显示；证实；表露 adj.明白的；显然的 n.旅客名单；载货单', '1. His generosity manifests itself in times of difficulties. 他的慷慨在困境中表现了出来。 2. Opportunities will manifest in ways you never even dreamed of. 机会的到来出乎你的意料。 3. No one can manifest the truth of his statement. 没人能证明他讲的是真话。 4. The contradiction manifested itself in the employment situation. 在就业问题上矛盾暴露了。 5. It was manifest to us at a glance. 我们对此事一目了然。 6. Can you give us a copy of import manifest? 能给我们一份进口舱单吗?', '副词: manifestly 过去式: manifested 过去分词: manifesed 现在分词: manifesting 第三人称单数: manifests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acumen', '[\'ækjəmən]', 'n.敏锐；聪明', '1. His business acumen helped him to succeed where others had failed. 他在商业上的敏锐帮他在其他人失败的地方获得成功。 2. Her business acumen has made her very successful. 她灵活的经商头脑使她的生意十分兴隆。 3. The Parisian police, so much extolled for acumen, are cunning, but no more. 巴黎警察一向以聪明称道于世，其实不过是狡猾罢了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fad', '[fæd]', 'n.时尚；一时流行的狂热', '1. Direct investment can become a fad just like any other activity of an economic, social, or cultural character. 就象经济，社会或文化性质的任何其他活动一样，直接投资也可成为一种一朝风行的时尚。 2. This can lead to thriftiness to the point of denying yourself pleasure, or embracing some health fad to ward of disease. 也许这会导致你节俭到否定自我愉快感或拥抱某个健康时尚来避开疾病。', '形容词: faddy 名词: faddism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('axis', '[\'æksɪs]', 'n.轴；中枢', '1. The earth turns (ie rotates) on its axis once every 24 hours. 地球每24小时自转一圈。 2. A wheel revolves round/on its axis. 轮子是绕轴旋转的。 3. The earth\'s axis is the line between the North and South Poles. 地轴是南北极之间的线。 4. The axis of a circle is its diameter. 圆的轴线是其直径。', '名词复数: axes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inferior', '[ɪn\'fɪriər]', 'adj.较低的；次等的；不如的；下级的 n.下级；属下；[印]下标符号', '1. These people occupy an inferior position in local society. 这些人在当地社会居于下等地位。 2. Captain is an inferior rank to major. 上尉是低于少校的一个官阶 3. A cheaper camera is not always inferior to a more expensive one. 廉价照相机的质量并总不比昂贵的差。 4. They never sell inferior goods. 他们从不销售次货。 5. A gentleman should always be civil, even to his inferiors. 有教养的人应该一直很有礼貌，甚至对待下属也一样。', '名词: inferiority');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('filigree', '[\'fɪlɪɡriː]', 'n.金银丝做的工艺品 v.用金银丝装饰', '1. The art filigree tapestry is elegant and magnificent. 嵌金银丝艺术挂毯，绚丽雅典。', '过去式: filigreed 过去分词: filigreed 现在分词: filigreeing 第三人称单数: filigrees');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eucalyptus', '[ˌjuːkə\'lɪptəs]', 'n.桉树', '1. Eucalyptus oil is good for easing muscular aches and pains. 桉树油可以很好地缓解肌肉的疼痛。 2. Eucalyptus leaves twirled above her head in the whistling breeze. 头上的桉树叶在呼呼的风中摇晃着。', '名词复数: eucalyptuses/eucalypti');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('congenital', '[kən\'dʒenɪtl]', 'adj.天生的；先天的', '1. The congenital form is spread to the fetus through the bloodstream. 先天的形式是通过血液传播给胎儿。 2. In most cases, a hydrocele is congenital, i.e. a baby boy is born with it. 大多数睾丸鞘膜积液是先天的，也就是说，男婴生下来就带有积液。', '副词: congenitally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extant', '[ek\'stænt]', 'adj.现存的', '1. This law is ancient but still extant. 这一法律古老但仍然有效。 2. This is the extant manuscript of the poem. 这是现存的该诗的原稿。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extricate', '[\'ekstrɪkeɪt]', 'v.使解脱；救出', '1. No one could extricate him from difficulty. 没有人能够使他从困难中摆脱出来。 2. Developers can extricate itself from the long-term maintenance. 开发商也可从长期维修中解脱出来。 3. The bird had to be extricated from the netting. 要把小鸟从网中救出。 4. They managed to extricate the pilot from the tangled control panel. 他们设法把困在控制盘里的飞行员救了出来。', '形容词: extricable 名词: extrication 过去式: extricated 过去分词: extricated 现在分词: extricating 第三人称单数: extricates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sacrifice', '[\'sækrɪfaɪs]', 'n.牺牲；祭品；供奉 vt.牺牲；亏本出售；供奉 vi.献祭；(棒球)作牺牲一击', '1. He gave his life as a sacrifice for his country. 他为国牺牲了。 2. She made a big sacrifice for her position today. 她为今天的职位付出了很大的代价。 3. They offered a sacrifice to propitiate the god. 他们供奉祭品以慰诸神。 4. A calf was offered up as a sacrifice to the goddess. 向女神祭献了一头牺牲小牛。 5. You must not sacrifice studies for pleasure. 你不能为享乐而牺牲学业。 6. Sacrifice is the ultimate act of self-giving love. 献祭却是最舍己的爱的行动。', '名词: sacrificer 过去式: sacrificed 过去分词: sacrificed 现在分词: sacrificing 第三人称单数: sacrifices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snarl', '[snɑːrl]', 'v.吼叫；嚎叫；咆哮；怒骂 v.纠缠；混乱 n.咆哮 n.混乱；缠结', '1. The tiger snarled frighteningly. 老虎发出可怕的吼声。 2. The dog snarled at the milkman. 那条狗对着送牛奶的人低声吠叫。 3. He snarled himself hoarse. 他咆哮得嗓子都哑了 4. Her hair is snarled. 她的头发缠结在一起。 5. At the seaside we could hear the snarl of the waves. 在海滨我们可以听见波涛的咆哮。 6. My knitting was in a terrible snarl. 我织的东西都乱成一团了。', '形容词: snarly 副词: snarlingly 名词: snarler 过去式: snarled 过去分词: snarled 现在分词: snarling 第三人称单数: snarls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inveigle', '[ɪn\'veɪɡl]', 'v.诱骗；骗取', '1. She inveigle him into the house and rob him while he sleep. 她把他骗进房子，趁他睡着时偷走了他的东西。 2. He inveigled them into buying a new car, even though they didn\'t really want one. 他诱惑他们买了一辆新汽车，其实他们并不真正需要。 3. She inveigled him into the house and robbed him while he slept. 她把他骗进房子，趁他睡著时偷走了他的东西。', '名词: inveiglement 过去式: inveigled 过去分词: inveigled 现在分词: inveigling 第三人称单数: inveigles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muscular', '[\'mʌskjələr]', 'adj.肌肉的；肌肉发达的', '1. In order to climb hills, muscular power is another key trait. 为了爬坡，肌肉的力量是另一种关键特性。 2. Eucalyptus oil is good for easing muscular aches and pains. 桉树油可以很好地缓解肌肉的疼痛。 3. The rib cage is moderately sprung and extends back to a short and muscular loin. 肋骨适度撑起，向后延伸到短而肌肉发达的腰部。 4. Her gaze rested for a moment on the muscular neck,heavy corded,almost bull-like,bronzed by the sun,spilling over with rugged health and strength. 她的目光在那肌肉发达的脖子上停留了片刻，那脖子被太阳晒成了青铜色，筋位突出，洋溢着粗糙的健康与强力，几乎像公牛。', '副词: muscularly 名词: muscularity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dominate', '[\'dɑːmɪneɪt]', 'v.支配；控制；统治；占优势；俯视；高耸于', '1. That way, he can dominate the game. 那样他才能支配比赛。 2. He desires to dominate over others. 他很想支配别人。 3. He has authority, but he doesn\'t try to dominate (others). 他有权威 4. They had the ambition to dominate this small country. 他们有控制这个小国的野心。', '形容词: dominative 名词: dominator 过去式: dominated 过去分词: dominated 现在分词: dominating 第三人称单数: dominates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('linen', '[\'lɪnɪn]', 'n.亚麻布；亚麻线；亚麻制品 adj.亚麻布制的；亚麻的', '1. The old linen smelled of the tomb. 旧亚麻布散发出墓地的气味。 2. Flax is used to make linen. 亚麻用来织亚麻布。 3. Low elasticity, imparting a hard, smooth texture, makes linen subject to wrinkling. 弹性较低，使得质地坚硬光滑，亚麻制品容易起皱纹。 4. He has abandoned suits in favour of linen jackets and khaki trousers and no tie. 他不穿西装，喜欢穿亚麻夹克和卡其布长裤，而且不打领带。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scarp', '[skɑːrp]', 'n.陡坡；悬崖 v.挖或使成陡坡', '1. The scarp has slopes with grades greater than 60 degrees. 这个悬崖的斜坡角度大于60度。 2. Sometimes you may not even know that you are looking at a fault scarp. 甚至有时你都不知道你正在看的恰恰就是一个断层。', '过去式: scarped 过去分词: scarped 现在分词: scarping 第三人称单数: scarps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maize', '[meɪz]', 'n.玉米', '1. Maize is widely planted in the America. 玉米在美洲广泛种植。 2. We can grow sorghum or maize on this plot. 我们可以在这块地可以种高粱或玉米。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trespass', '[\'trespəs]', 'n.非法侵入；罪过；[法]侵害诉讼 v.非法侵入；侵害；冒犯', '1. They forgive the people who trespass against them. 他们总是宽恕冒犯他们的人。', '名词: trespasser 过去式: trespassed 过去分词: trespassed 现在分词: trespassing 第三人称单数: trespasses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('purge', '[pɜːrdʒ]', 'n.整肃；清除；泻药；净化 v.净化；清除；清洗', '1. The new president carried out a purge of disloyal army officers. 新总统对不忠诚的陆军军官进行了一次整肃。 2. The Red Guards carried out the purge too enthusiastically, often acting without close direction from Peking. 红卫兵非常狂热地贯彻执行了清除，横扫了北京的各个方面。 3. The medicine was an effective purge. 这是疗效很好的泻药。 4. We may purge water by distillation. 我们可以用蒸馏法使水净化。 5. We may purge water by distillation. 我们可以用蒸馏法使水净化。', '名词: purger 过去式: purged 过去分词: purged 现在分词: purging 第三人称单数: purges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vitriolic', '[ˌvɪtri\'ɑːlɪk]', 'adj.硫酸的；刻薄的；挖苦的', '1. The newspaper launched a vitriolic attack on the president. 这家报纸对总统发起了一场恶意的攻击。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ironic', '[aɪ\'rɑːnɪk]', 'adj.说反话的；讽刺的', '1. At the early stage of Requirements Definition, brainstorming assumes a somewhat ironic purpose. 在需求定义阶段的早期进行头脑风暴在某种程度上呈现出一种说反话的意图。 2. In his early and lightly ironic work, his criticism was restrained. 在他早期稍含讽刺的作品里，批评口吻也很克制。 3. It would be ironic if, in the process, it is creating its own eventual crisis. 然而，如果这过程中，中国最终是在制造自己的危机，那将是十分讽刺的。', '副词: ironically 异体字: ironical 名词: ironicalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('minimize', '[\'mɪnɪmaɪz]', 'v.将 ... 减到最少；贬低', '1. Governments consider it prudent to minimize the risk. 各国政府均认为把这种危害降低到最小程度的做法是明智的。 2. The polar explorers took every precaution to minimize the dangers of their trip. 极地探险者十分小心谨慎，以便使旅途的危险性减少到最小。 3. A sound approach to the problem is to minimize the number of parts. 正确解决这一问题的方法是把零件的数目减至最少。 4. He minimized the value of her contribution to his research so that he got all the praise. 他极力贬低她在那项研究中的贡献，从而独获全部奖励。', '名词: minimization 过去式: minimized 过去分词: minimized 现在分词: minimizing 第三人称单数: minimizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('castigation', '[ˌkæstɪ\'ɡeɪʃn]', 'n.惩罚；苛评', '1. Some people believe that work is a better means of order and discipline than chains and castigation for criminals. 有些人认为要使犯人遵纪守法劳动是比镣铐和惩罚更有效的手段。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('magenta', '[mə\'dʒentə]', 'n.碱性品红；紫红色(的染料)', '1. It is a maze of low-ceilinged corridors and linoleum floors, in shades of magenta, brown and nicotine yellow. 这栋象迷宫一样的大楼中，过道的天花板很低，地上铺着亚麻油毡地毯，暗暗的紫红色，棕色和烟焦黄构成大楼内部的主色调。 2. An ancient magazine photograph of some dark-haired movie star was taped to the wall beside the bed, the skin tone gone magenta. 床边的墙上贴着一张旧杂志上剪下来的明星照，一个黑头发的电影明星，因为年头已久，画已经变成了紫红色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('collateral', '[kə\'lætərəl]', 'adj.旁系的；并行的；附属的 n.附属担保物；支亲；副保', '1. Cousins are collateral relatives. 表堂兄弟姊妹都是旁系亲属。 2. Security market and property right trade market are two collateral markets. 证券市场和产权交易市场是两个并行的市场。 3. He offered me a lot of collateral readings. 他为我提供了许多平行读物。 4. He offered some collateral evidences. 他提供了一些旁证。 5. He used his house as a collateral for the loan. 他用房子作这笔贷款的担保品。', '副词: collaterally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('passionate', '[\'pæʃənət]', 'adj.热情的；激情的；易怒的', '1. His passionate speech had an effect on our emotions. 他的热情的演讲打动了我们的感情。 2. She is a passionate advocate of education reform. 她是一名教育改革的热情拥护者。 3. He made a passionate speech about the sufferings of the poor. 他就穷人的苦难做了一个充满激情的演讲。 4. His early experience turn him into a passionate social reformer. 他早年的经历使他变成了一个狂热的社会改革者。', '副词: passionately 名词: passionateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commit', '[kə\'mɪt]', 'v.犯罪；承诺；委托；托付', '1. They committed outrages on innocent citizens. 他们对无辜的市民犯下了暴行。 2. He committed suicide rather than sell out to the enemy. 他宁愿自杀而没有向敌人投降。 3. He didn\'t commit himself to anything. 他没有作任何承诺。 4. The girl was committed to the care of an aunt. 这女孩被交给姨母照顾。', '形容词: committable 过去式: committed 过去分词: committed 现在分词: committing 第三人称单数: commits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muzzy', '[\'mʌzi]', 'adj.模糊不清的；昏迷的', '1. The television picture\'s muzzy. 电视画面模糊不清。 2. After a couple of whiskies my head felt all muzzy. 我喝了两杯威士忌，就昏头昏脑的了。', '副词: muzzily 比较级: muzzier 最高级: muzziest 名词: muzziness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('motility', '[moʊ\'tɪlətɪ]', 'n.运动性；自动力', '1. All of these cells exhibit motility. 所有这些细胞均表现移动性。 2. For differentiating bacteria based on motility and nitrate reduction test. 用于鉴别细菌动力和硝酸盐还原试验。 3. Sedentary life-style: Lack of physical activity can reduce gut motility. 缺乏运动:平日少做运动,令肠道活动减慢。 4. Conclusion TFD facilitates the motility of stomach, duodenum and ileum. 结论：通腑汤对胃、十二指肠乃至回肠均有较好的促动力作用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('racy', '[\'reɪsi]', 'adj.(文章等)活泼的；生动的；独特风味的；不雅的', '1. The book is racy rather than obscene. 那本书与其说是猥亵的,倒不如说是活泼的。 2. She is trying to create a racier image for herself. 她正试图为自己创造一个更为生动活泼的形象。 3. The food here have a racy flavor. 这里的食物风味独特。 4. Her racy stories can be rather shocking. 她那些下流的故事讲起来有时很让人吃惊。', '副词: racily 比较级: racier 最高级: raciest 名词: raciness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oration', '[ɔː\'reɪʃn]', 'n.演说；致辞；叙述法', '1. He was asked to deliver an oration at the meeting. 他被邀请在会议上发表演说。 2. He was asked to give a funeral oration. 他被要求在葬礼上宣读悼词。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('estimable', '[\'estɪməbl]', 'adj.〈旧或文〉值得尊敬的；可估计的', '1. Firstly, under the condition that the nonlinear dynamic function of the systems is estimable and bounded, sliding mode control law is presented. 首先，在系统的非线性动态函数满足可估计和有界两个基本假设的条件下，给出了此类系统基于非线性动态函数估计的一般滑模控制律设计。', '副词: estimably 名词: estimableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gaiety', '[\'ɡeɪəti]', 'n.愉快；喜庆；(服装等)华丽', '1. Color flags added to the gaiety of the festival. 彩旗增加了节日的欢乐。 2. Her artificial gaiety disguised the inner sadness. 她以矫揉造作的快乐掩饰着内心的悲痛。 3. We all immersed in the gaiety of the Spring Festival. 我们都沉浸在春节的欢乐之中。 4. Mary\'s gaiety and wit have enchanted us all. 玛丽的华丽服饰和风趣令我们大家着迷。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overdose', '[\'oʊvərdoʊs]', 'n.配药量过多；过量 v.（使）服过量的药', '1. An overdose of this drug can kill. 这种药服用过量可引起死亡。 2. To get their own bread they must overdose the king\'s lieges. 为了多挣一些钱，他们不惜对英王的臣民用药过量。', '过去式: overdosed 过去分词: overdosed 现在分词: overdosing 第三人称单数: overdoses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unqualified', '[ˌʌn\'kwɑːlɪfaɪd]', 'adj.不合格的；无资格的；不适任的；绝对的；无限制的', '1. We\'ll change the unqualified product absolutely. 我们保换质量不合格的产品。 2. They will surely try to ring in an unqualified delegate. 他们肯定想塞进一名不合格的代表进来。 3. He is an unqualified practitioner of law. 他是个无资格的律师。 4. You have my unqualified support in this matter. 在这件事上我绝对支持你。', '副词: unqualifiedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('simian', '[\'sɪmiən]', 'adj.猿的；类人猿的；猴子一般的 n.猴子；类人猿', '1. They came to this conclusion by looking at those simian immunodeficiency virus. 他们得出这一结论的依据来自于对猿免疫缺陷病毒的观察。 2. Curiosity is the taproot of an intellectual life, the most valuable of our simian traits. 好奇是高智生命的根源，也是我们类人猿特征中最有价值的部分。 3. The simian figure is Cornelius, Suzanne\'s baby brother. 这只猴子名叫科尼利厄斯，苏珊娜的弟弟。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('moldy', '[\'moʊldi]', 'adj.发霉的', '1. She tossed the moldy bread into the garbage. 她把发霉的面包扔进了垃圾箱。 2. More owners brought the roof and moldy as a result of leakage of photographs. 更有业主拿来了屋顶因渗漏而发霉的照片。', '比较级: moldier 最高级: moldiest 名词: moldiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surpass', '[sər\'pæs]', 'vt.超越；胜过', '1. To be in love is to surpass oneself. 人在爱中超越自我。 2. You seem to surpass yourself in this painting. 你在这幅画的创作上似乎超越了你自己。 3. Her sweetness nothing can surpass. 温柔甜蜜世无双。 4. It is hard to surpass Evans in speed. 要在速度上胜过艾文斯很难。', '过去式: surpassed 过去分词: surpassed 现在分词: surpassing 第三人称单数: surpasses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('besiege', '[bɪ\'siːdʒ]', 'v.围攻；包围', '1. When they came to besiege Kir Haraseth, Mesha did an abominable thing. 当他们来围攻吉珥哈列设时，米沙做了一件可憎的事。 2. The city was besieged by the enemy for a few days. 这座城市被敌人围困了几天。', '名词: besiegement 过去式: besieged 过去分词: besieged 现在分词: besieging 第三人称单数: besieges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spindly', '[\'spɪndli]', 'adj.细长的；纤弱的', '1. He was followed by a sallow, spindly lawyer. 跟在他后面的是一个面色灰黄，细长个子的律师。 2. Of a scrawny build;spindly or gawky. 骨瘦如柴的；瘦长的或笨拙的 3. Of a scrawny build; spindly or gawky. 骨瘦如柴的；瘦长的或笨拙的 4. While the talk was loud, the stick was spindly. 话讲得很大声，但是棒子却有点虚弱。', '比较级: spindlier 最高级: spindliest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('calorie', '[\'kæləri]', 'n.卡；卡路里(热量单位) =calory.', '1. The calorie is a historical relic. 卡是历史的遗迹。 2. The calorie content in this ice cream is very high. 这种冰激凌的卡路里含量很高。 3. Diving can be as calorie consuming as you would like it to be. 潜水可以尽可能多地消耗卡路里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ruffle', '[\'rʌfl]', 'n.褶饰；花边 v.弄皱或弄乱某物；扰乱；激怒', '1. Her blouse has a ruffle of lace around the neck. 她的衬衫领子镶有褶裥花边。 2. The seamstress bound the hem of the dress with a ruffle. 女裁缝用褶裥饰边给女上衣镶边。 3. A flag ruffled in the breeze. 旗帜迎风飘扬。 4. A breeze ruffled the surface of the lake. 一阵微风吹皱了湖面。', '名词: ruffler 过去式: ruffled 过去分词: ruffled 现在分词: ruffling 第三人称单数: ruffles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('planet', '[\'plænɪt]', 'n.行星', '1. The Earth is a planet. 地球是一颗行星。 2. Mars is the fourth planet in order from the sun. 火星是太阳系的第四颗行星。 3. They claimed to have discovered a new planet. 他们宣称发现了一颗新的行星。 4. It is the only planet that we know harbors life. 它是我们所知唯一适合生物生存的行星。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fetching', '[\'fetʃɪŋ]', 'adj.动人的；引人的；迷人的 动词fetch的现在分词形式.', '1. She looked very fetching in a little red hat. 她戴着小红帽妩媚动人。 2. You look very fetching in that hat with the purple dress. 你戴上那顶帽子配上这紫色衣服显得非常动人。 3. She had a cute nose and a radiant complexion dotted with fetching sprays of adorable freckles. 她有一个逗人喜欢的鼻子，生气勃勃的脸庞上布满了一片片迷人的，俊俏可笑的雀斑。', '副词: fetchingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eclectic', '[ɪ\'klektɪk]', 'n.折衷主义者；折衷派的人 adj.选择的；折衷的；兼收并蓄的', '1. Hudec\'s Shanghai buildings are strikingly eclectic. 邬达克在上海的建筑具有明显的折衷主义。 2. P&G is devoted to fostering a diverse and eclectic company culture that is simultaneously focused on common goals. 宝洁致力于培养聚焦于共同目标泊多元化和折衷主义的公司文化。 3. His habitual touch was that of the eclectic. 他惯用的是折衷的语言。 4. There are some Zoroastrians who are influenced by Theosophy, an eclectic esoteric movement of the nineteenth century. 一些琐罗亚斯德教徒受到见神论的影响，一种十九世纪的折衷的深奥运动。', '副词: eclectically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('affront', '[ə\'frʌnt]', 'n.侮辱 v.侮辱；冒犯', '1. He put an affront upon me. 他当众侮辱我。 2. He was not a man to sit down with affront. 他并不是一个可以忍受当众侮辱的人。 3. His speech was an affront to all members of the community. 他的话对社区所有成员是故意的侮辱。 4. Her mind was now very susceptible to affront . 如今她的意志动不动就受到冒犯。', '过去式: affronted 过去分词: affronted 现在分词: affronting 第三人称单数: affronts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('convertible', '[kən\'vɜːtəbəl]', 'adj.可改变的；可转换的；同意义的 n.敞篷车', '1. This sofa is convertible into a bed. 这张沙发可改变成床。 2. This table is convertible into an ironing board. 这个桌子是可转变的，而成烫衣板。 3. Heat is convertible into electricity. 热可以转换为电。 4. They don\'t have access to a convertible currency. 他们无法得到可兑换货币。 5. You can hire a small convertible for $100 a day. 你可以以100美元一天的价格租一辆敞篷车。', '副词: convertibly 名词: convertibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('augur', '[\'ɔːɡər]', 'n.占兆官；占卜师；相命者 v.预言；预测', '1. It is surprising that an augur can see an augury without smiling. 出乎意外,占卜家能知预兆而不笑。 2. Does this unfortunate news augur war in the near future? 这个不幸消息预示最近的将来会发生战争吗？ 3. Mounting sales augur a profitable year. 不断增加的销售量预示着好年景。 4. I augur from all circumstances a prosperous voyage. 从各种情况推断， 我预料航行将会顺利。', '形容词: augural 过去式: augured 过去分词: augured 现在分词: auguring 第三人称单数: augurs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invertebrate', '[ɪn\'vɜːrtɪbrət]', 'n.无脊椎动物 adj.无脊椎的', '1. Insects and worms are all invertebrates. 昆虫和蠕虫都是无脊椎动物。 2. Half of all invertebrate species live in tropical rain forests. 一半的无脊椎动物物种生活在热带雨林中。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inhabit', '[ɪn\'hæbɪt]', 'v.居住于；占据；栖息', '1. Broadly, we investigate the world\'s lakes and rivers and the creatures which inhabit them. 宽广地，我们调查世界的湖和河和居住于他们的人。 2. Wookiees inhabit the upper levels of the forest, having built their massive cities within the interwoven canopy. 伍基人占据了树林的上层，并在交织的树冠上建造了巨大的城市。 3. Under Forman\'s tutelage, actors fully inhabit their roles, the hospital becomes an evil institution, and the movie poignantly celebrates the human spirit. 根据福尔曼的指导，演员完全占据自己的角色，医院成为一个邪恶的机构，和电影尖锐地庆祝人类的精神。 4. Many types of seabirds inhabit the coral island. 这个珊瑚岛上栖息着很多种海鸟。', '形容词: inhabitable 名词: inhabitability 过去式: inhabited 过去分词: inhabited 现在分词: inhabiting 第三人称单数: inhabits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stagnant', '[\'stæɡnənt]', 'adj.不流动的；停滞的；不景气的', '1. Stagnant water breeds mosquitoes. 死水滋生蚊子。 2. There were stagnant ponds in the streets, here and there. 街上到处都有死水潭。 3. Due to low investment, our industrial output has remained stagnant. 由于投资少，我们的工业生产一直停滞不前。 4. The balance sheet clearly shows that the company has a stagnant economy. 资产负债表清楚地表明公司的经营情况不景气。', '副词: stagnantly 名词: stagnancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('margarine', '[\'mɑːrdʒərən]', 'n.人造黄油', '1. Margarine is derived from vegetable oils. 人造黄油是从植物油提取的。 2. I can\'t tell the difference between margarine and butter. 我尝不出人造黄油和黄油有什么区别。 3. One in ten say they preferred their old brand of margarine. 有十分之一的人说比较喜欢老牌子的人造黄油。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snide', '[snaɪd]', 'adj.嘲笑的；卑鄙的；恶意的；假冒的 n.骗子；赝造的宝石', '1. He\'s always making snide comments about her appearance. 他总是对她的外表冷嘲热讽。 2. Her new boyfriend is a snide merchant. 她的新男友是个奸商。 3. She couldn\'t tell if he was being snide,so she took the question straight. 她不能分辨他是否假冒的，所以她直接地提出了问题。', '副词: snidely 比较级: snider 最高级: snidest 名词: snideness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('despicable', '[dɪ\'spɪkəbl]', 'adj.可鄙的；卑劣的', '1. Ingratitude is a despicable vice. 忘恩负义是可鄙的不道德行为。 2. It\'s despicable the way he treats those kids. 他对待那些孩子的方式是可鄙的。 3. It is despicable to desert your children. 你抛弃你的孩子是卑劣的。 4. Despicable as the fat restaurant detective was, his crime was less than theirs. 虽然那个饭店的胖侦探长行为卑劣，但他所犯的罪却要比他们的轻一些。', '副词: despicably 名词: despicableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pretext', '[\'priːtekst]', 'n.借口 v.以…为借口', '1. He stayed away under the pretext of ill health. 他以身体不佳为借口而避开了。 2. He refused to see them on one pretext or another. 他以种种借口拒绝见他们。', '过去式: pretexted 过去分词: pretexted 现在分词: pretexting 第三人称单数: pretexts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stem', '[stem]', 'n.柄；茎；干；船首 vi.起源于 vt.抽去 ... 的梗；给 ... 装柄；逆 ... 而行；阻止，遏制', '1. Don\'t eat the stem of a mushroom. 不要吃蘑菇的梗。 2. This is a plant stem that has been pithed. 这是一根已经除去木髓的植物的茎。 3. Crime and punishment grow out of one stem. 罪与罚本是同茎生。 4. She bought some roses with long stems. 她买了一些枝干很长的玫瑰花。 5. Your errors stem all from your carelessness. 你犯的错误全都是由于你的粗心。 6. Our ship stemmed on against the current. 我们的船逆流而上。', '过去式: stemmed 过去分词: stemmed 现在分词: stemming 第三人称单数: stems');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inverse', '[ˌɪn\'vɜːrs]', 'adj.倒转的；相反的 n.倒数；相反的事物；(数学)逆反函数；负数', '1. Subtraction is the inverse operation of addition. 减法是加法的逆运算。 2. When you define certain operators, Visual Basic requires that you also define the operator for the inverse operation. 当定义某些特定的运算符时,Visual Basic还要求定义该运算符的逆运算。 3. The inverse of its slope is the speed of light. 其倾斜的倒数是光速。 4. The logarithmic function is defined as the inverse of the exponential function. 对数函数是作为指数函数的反函数来定义的。', '副词: inversely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('encumber', '[ɪn\'kʌmbər]', 'v.妨害；阻害', '1. The girl\'s long skirt encumber her while running. 这女孩子的长裙在她跑的时候阻碍她的行动。 2. Objects, such as provisions or baggage, that impede or encumber. 包袱妨碍或拖累的物体，如装备或者行李 3. He is encumbered with a large family. 他被一个大家庭所拖累。 4. Travelling is difficult when you\'re encumbered with two small children and a heavy suitcase. 旅行时带着两个孩子和一个沉重的手提箱，真是寸步难行。', '过去式: encumbered 过去分词: encumbered 现在分词: encumbering 第三人称单数: encumbers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('halo', '[\'heɪloʊ]', 'n.(日月等)晕；神像之光环', '1. The halo of the moon tonight is bright. 今晚月亮周围的光晕非常明亮。 2. They began sloshing of the network, to a large halo. 他们的网又开始晃荡了，又晕到一大片。', '名词复数: halos 过去式: haloed 过去分词: haloed 现在分词: haloing 第三人称单数: haloes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gossamer', '[\'ɡɑːsəmər]', 'n.小蜘蛛网；轻而弱者；薄纱 adj.薄弱的；轻飘飘的', '1. They quickly stripped me of my clothes and bound me like a mummy in a gossamer web. 他们飞快地扒了我的衣服，把我绑得像个蜘蛛网里的木乃伊。 2. Gossamer is floating in calm air. 空中飘浮着游丝。 3. The prince helped the princess, who was still in her delightful gossamer gown. 王子搀扶着仍穿著那套美丽薄纱晚礼服的公主。', '形容词: gossamery');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adverse', '[\'ædvɜːrs]', 'adj.不利的；逆向的；有害的', '1. The judge gave us an adverse decision. 法官作出对我们不利的判决。 2. He ignored all kinds of adverse comments about him. 他不理睬各种各样对他不利的评论。 3. The development was adverse to our interests. 这种发展与我们的利益背道而驰。 4. Diseases are adverse to the best growth of children. 疾病对儿童的健康成长是有害的。', '副词: adversely 名词: adverseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('internecine', '[ˌɪntər\'niːsaɪn]', 'adj.两败俱伤的；内讧的；致命的', '1. Strife was internecine during the next fortnight. 在以后两个星期的冲突中我们两败俱伤。 2. Internecine warfare is the consequence of this mistake. 中国日益成为世界的加工厂。 3. Therefore, is unavoidable the internecine strife started. 于是，一场在所难免的火拼开始了。 4. The internecine strife was caused by a shortage of food. 这次内部冲突，是由于食物匮乏而引致的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('embargo', '[ɪm\'bɑːrɡoʊ]', 'n.封港令；禁运；禁止（通商）', '1. Cuba insisted on removal of the embargo. 古巴方面坚持要求美国撤消封港令。 2. The country has put an embargo on all imports. 该国对所有进口品实行禁运。 3. The embargo impacted on export revenues. 禁运对出囗总收入有很大的影响。 4. During the war,they laid an embargo on commerce with enemy countries. 在战争期间，他们禁止与敌国通商。', '名词复数: embargoes 过去式: embargoed 过去分词: embargoed 现在分词: embargoing 第三人称单数: embargoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stasis', '[\'steɪsɪs]', 'n.静止；[医]血行停滞；淤滞', '1. In treatment,blood stasis is an important factor that should be seized. 在治疗中', '名词复数: stases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expire', '[ɪk\'spaɪər]', 'vi.终止；期满；失效；呼气；断气', '1. Our holidays expire next week. 我们的假期于下星期结束。 2. My passport is due to expire in two months. 我的护照再过两个月就到期了。 3. When does your driving licence expire? 你的驾驶执照何时到期? 4. My credit card will expire in June. 我的信用卡六月过期。', '过去式: expired 过去分词: expired 现在分词: expiring 第三人称单数: expires');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blotch', '[blɑːtʃ]', 'n.(皮肤上的)红斑点；(墨水等)斑点 v.标上斑点；弄脏', '1. Blotch is a typical defection in degraded motion picture material. 斑点是电影档案中比较常见的一种失真。 2. Sometimes, motion vectors may be far away from the true motion vector in the blotch area. 在斑点存在的区域，运动向量的估计可能会出现较大的偏差。', '形容词: blotchy 副词: blotchily 名词: blotchiness 过去式: blotched 过去分词: blotched 现在分词: blotching 第三人称单数: blotches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dent', '[dent]', 'n.凹痕；心理阴影；挫伤 vt.弄凹 vi.形成凹陷', '1. The front of the car has a dent in it. 小汽车的前面有一个凹痕。 2. I\'d like an estimate for repairing this dent. 我想估计一下修这凹痕要多不少钱？', '过去式: dented 过去分词: dented 现在分词: denting 第三人称单数: dents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apothecary', '[ə\'pɑːθəkeri]', 'n.药剂师；药师', '1. Peter is a famous apothecary of this town. 彼得是这个镇上有名的药剂师。', '名词复数: apothecaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surfeit', '[\'sɜːrfɪt]', 'n.过食；过量 v.暴食；过分沉溺', '1. A surfeit of rich food is bad for you. 多吃油腻食物对身体有害。 2. There has been a surfeit of plays about divorce on the TV recently. 最近有关离婚的电视剧太多了。 3. It\'s no good for your health to surfeit yourself. 暴饮暴食有碍你的健康。 4. They were surfeited with entertainment. 他们过分沉溺于玩乐了。', '名词: surfeiter 过去式: surfeited 过去分词: surfeited 现在分词: surfeiting 第三人称单数: surfeits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alphabetical', '[ˌælfə\'betɪkl]', 'adj.按字母表顺序的', '1. Put these words in alphabetical order. 把这些字按字母表顺序排列起来。', '副词: alphabetically 异体字: alphabetic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fitful', '[\'fɪtfl]', 'adj.断断续续的；一阵阵的', '1. The whole debate was rather fitful. 整个辩论断断续续地进行。 2. I studied english fitful for four years. 我断断续续学了四年英语了。 3. I worried half the night and have a fitful sleep. 我半个晚上都一直在担心，故而时醒时睡。', '副词: fitfully 名词: fitfulness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tyro', '[\'taɪroʊ]', 'n.初学者；生手；新手 =tiro.', '1. She is a tyro in the art of writing poetry. 她是一名诗歌创作艺术的初学者。 2. What separates the professional from the tyro is the perfect timing. 专家和新手的区别在于', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('furrow', '[\'fɜːroʊ]', 'n.犁沟；车辙；皱纹 v.（使）起皱纹；形成深痕', '1. An old ox makes straight furrow. 老牛拉犁犁沟直。 2. The tractor has make deep furrow in the loose sand. 曳引机在松软的沙土上留下了深深的车辙。 3. The country roads were muddy and full of furrows left by farm carts. 乡间道路泥泞不堪，布满了牛车压出的车辙。 4. The furrow in Mei\'s brow deepened. 梅额上的那一条皱纹越发显著了。 5. The pain of the disease caused him habitually to furrow his brow. 病痛使他习惯性地紧皱眉头。', '过去式: furrowed 过去分词: furrowed 现在分词: furrowing 第三人称单数: furrows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('supreme', '[suː\'priːm]', 'adj.最高的；至上的；极度的', '1. The general was girded with the supreme power. 将军被授予最高权力。 2. The safety of the people is the supreme law. 人民的安全是最高的法律。 3. Supreme authority resides in the State. 最高权力属于国家。 4. Wisdom is the supreme part of happiness. 智慧是幸福的顶峰。', '副词: supremely 比较级: supremer 最高级: supremest 名词: supremeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inelasticity', '[ˌɪnɪlæs\'tɪsətɪ]', 'n.无弹力；坚硬性；不适应性', '1. Diets the moisture content which in the process drains to cause the skin will also become rough, inelasticity. 节食过程中所流失的水分还会使皮肤变得粗糙，无弹性。 2. \"Su Na mode \" earlier property right form and structure, expose stage by stage in process of market economy development gave inelasticity. “苏南模式”初期的产权形式与结构，在市场经济发展过程中逐步暴露出了不适应性。 3. The inelasticity of road network position, the supply and demand that can increase train wagon, ticket is contradictory. 市场经济发展的不平衡性、资源分布的不均匀性。 4. There is a tradition of research and teaching in inelasticity at Stanford that goes back at least to Wilhelm Flugge and Erastus Lee. 在取材上，本书考虑到不同专业背景学生的特点，为了让他们更好地掌握统计学知识，保留了概率论基础部分。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mottle', '[\'mɒtəl]', 'vt.使成杂色；弄成斑驳 n.斑点；杂色', '1. Hills and parks mottle the urban landscape. 桂林市是首批 “中国优秀旅游城市”； 2. Surface mottle of BMC parts is one of common quality defects. 不饱和聚酯树脂模塑料压制件表面颜色不均匀是常见的质量难题之一。 3. In tubers from such potatoes stem mottle symptoms are rarely observed. 由这类马玲薯产生的块茎中茎斑驳症状不易观察到。 4. Ingrain paper: Paper finished with a mottle surface used for book covers, etc. 斑纹纸:加工造成有斑点花纹的纸，作书皮等用。', '名词: mottler 过去式: mottled 过去分词: mottled 现在分词: mottling 第三人称单数: mottles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('idolater', '[aɪ\'dɒlətə]', 'n.偶像崇拜者；崇拜者；皈依者', '1. Being an idolater is not something we want to be! 我们并不希望成为偶像崇拜者，这是消极面却真实且必要的警告。', '异体字: idolator');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('astrology', '[ə\'strɑːlədʒi]', 'n.占星术；占星学', '1. The zodiac is used in astrology to predict the future. 十二宫图用于占星术中预测未来。 2. Nowadays, many young people believe in astrology. 现在很多青年男女相信占星术。 3. Astronomy, as distinct from astrology, is an exact science. 天文学是一门严谨的科学，与占星术完全不同。 4. Many people have misconceptions about astrology. 许多人对占星学有误解。', '形容词: astrological 副词: astrologically 名词: astrologer');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lexicon', '[\'leksɪkən]', 'n.词典；词汇', '1. It is not possible for a lexicon to provide full coverage of language. 词典不可能完全覆盖一个语言。 2. Categorization in mental lexicon is an intriguing phenomenon. 范畴化是心理词典研究中一个非常有趣的现象。 3. Expanding your lexicon in this technical field will help you a great deal. 扩大你的技术领域的词汇量将对你帮助很大。', '名词复数: lexicons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incubate', '[\'ɪŋkjubeɪt]', 'v.孵；(细菌等)培养；逐渐发展；酝酿，深思；(传染病)潜伏', '1. The female bird incubates the eggs for about sixteen days while the male brings food. 雌鸟孵蛋差不多十六天，在这期间，雄鸟带回食物。 2. He incubated germs in a laboratory. 他在实验室中培养细菌。 3. The plans for revolution has long been incubating in their minds. 革命计划在他们心中酝酿已久。 4. The BSE bug incubates for three years. 疯牛病病毒的潜伏期为三年。', '形容词: incubative 过去式: incubated 过去分词: incubated 现在分词: incubating 第三人称单数: incubates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enamored', '[en\'æməd]', 'adj.倾心的；被迷住的 动词enamor的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. I\'m not too enamored with the idea of spending a whole day with him. 我可不喜欢整天和他在一起。 2. He is enamored with scientific research. 他沉迷于科学研究。 3. She is enamored of the sound of her own voice. 她陶醉于自己的嗓音。 4. He is enamored of stamp collecting. 他迷恋于集邮。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demanding', '[dɪ\'mændɪŋ]', 'adj.要求多的；吃力的 动词demand的现在分词.', '1. Teaching is a demanding profession. 教学工作是个要求很高的工作。 2. Certainly I can agree with you that such duty is both dangerous and demanding. 我当然能同意你的看法，这种任务既危险，要求又严格。 3. During that time, messages on the picket signs became more demanding. 在那个时候，抗议海报上的要求也越来越积极。 4. He is a demanding child. 他是个很难满足的孩子。', '副词: demandingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('score', '[skɔː]', 'vt.得分；获胜；刻划；划线；批评；给 ... 谱曲 n.得分；刻痕；二十；乐谱 vi.得分；记分；得胜', '1. Hughes scored two goals before half-time. 休斯在上半场进了两个球. 2. The army continued to score successes in the south. 军队在南方不断取得胜利。 3. They scored the floor-boards by pushing furniture about. 他们推动家具 4. could you please score my name off? 请把我的名字从名单中划掉好吗? 5. I recorded the score in a notebook. 我在笔记本上记下了分数。 6. The home team has yet to score. 主队还没有得分.', '名词: scorer 过去式: scored 过去分词: scored 现在分词: scoring 第三人称单数: scores');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stencil', '[\'stensl]', 'n.模版；型版；蜡纸 v.用模版印刷', '1. The stencil and print process will not change. 模板和印刷工艺无需更改。 2. Do you know how to cut a stencil? 你会刻蜡版[打蜡纸]吗？ 3. He can stencil the following same shipping mark on all the packages. 他就可以在所有的包装上刷下同样的唛头。', '名词: stenciler 过去式: stenciled/stencilled 过去分词: stenciled/stencilled 现在分词: stenciling/stencilling 第三人称单数: stencils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disburse', '[dɪs\'bɜːrs]', 'v.支付；支出；分配', '1. We disburse payments to members on a monthly basis. 我们支付款项成员在每月的基础。 2. Receive and disburse money in establishments other than financial institutions. 负责公司和相关财务机构的资金收付。 3. Trials to disburse official business expenses with credit cards continued. 推进公务卡管理试点。 4. On approval, we will disburse the fund to your designated bank account directly. 一经批核，贷款将于扣除手续费后直接存入您指定的银行账户。', '形容词: disbursable 名词: disburser 过去式: disbursed 过去分词: disbursed 现在分词: disbursing 第三人称单数: disburses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foresight', '[\'fɔːrsaɪt]', 'n.远见；深谋远虑', '1. No one had enough foresight to predict the winner. 谁也没有足够的远见能预测哪一个获胜。 2. The decision they made is a lamentable lack of foresight. 他们做的决定实在缺乏远见。 3. A fool acts recklessly while a wit has a foresight. 愚者鲁莽从事,智者深谋远虑。', '形容词: foresighted 副词: foresightedly 名词: foresightedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('voluptuous', '[və\'lʌptʃuəs]', 'adj.激起性欲的；沉溺酒色的；撩人的', '1. She was a voluptuous creature with blonde hair. 她是个性感十足的金发尤物。 2. The dancer\'s movements were slow and voluptuous. 舞女的动作缓慢而富挑逗性。', '副词: voluptuously 名词: voluptuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abstinent', '[\'æbstɪnənt]', 'adj.饮食有度的；有节制的；禁欲的 n.禁欲者', '1. Since time immemorial, countless females and males in every culture and global region have ignored pleas to remain abstinent. 因为过去的时光不再重现，在每一个文化体系里和世界各个地区的无数男男女女们已经忘却了禁欲的呼吁。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('squander', '[\'skwɑːndər]', 'vt.浪费；挥霍', '1. It\'s a crime to squander our country\'s natural resources. 浪费我们国家的自然资源是一种罪恶 2. Don\'t squander your affection on him, he\'ll never love you. 不要把感情浪费在他身上，他是永远不会爱你的。 3. He has squandered all his savings on drink. 他把存的钱全买酒喝了。 4. Addictions are good ways to squander wealth and health. 上瘾是挥霍健康和金钱的好办法。', '副词: squanderingly 名词: squanderer 过去式: squandered 过去分词: squandered 现在分词: squandering 第三人称单数: squanders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bewilder', '[bɪ\'wɪldər]', 'vt. 使迷惑； 使 ... 不知所措', '1. You bewildered me. 你把我搞糊涂了。 2. Big city traffic bewilders me. 大城市的交通使我晕头转向。', '副词: bewilderedly 名词: bewilderedness 过去式: bewildered 过去分词: bewildered 现在分词: bewildering 第三人称单数: bewilders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('temporal', '[\'tempərəl]', 'adj.现世的；暂时的；当时的；太阳穴的；颞的', '1. He cares for nothing but temporal affairs. 他只关心世俗之事。 2. The Pope has no temporal power in modern society. 教皇在当代社会没有世俗方面的权利。 3. Temporal isolation appears to be possible. 暂时隔离是可行的。 4. Place your sword upon the ground, and rest in the temporal peace. 放下你的剑吧，静享这暂时的和平。', '副词: temporally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('centaur', '[\'sentɔːr]', 'n.[希神]人首马身的怪物', '1. His face reminded me somehow of a centaur. 他的脸使我想起半人半马的怪物。 2. The astronomer looked at the starry sky, trying to locate Centaur. 这位天文学家看著满天星斗的天空,试著找到半人马星座。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malinger', '[mə\'lɪŋɡər]', 'vi.装病（以逃避工作）', '1. We were told by her doctor that she was malingering. 医生告诉我们，她这是在装病。', '名词: malingerer 过去式: malingered 过去分词: malingered 现在分词: malingering 第三人称单数: malingers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('invulnerable', '[ɪn\'vʌlnərəbl]', 'adj.固若金汤的；无法伤害的', '1. The banks are not invulnerable. 银行并非固若金汤。 2. The submarine is invulnerable to attack while at sea. 潜艇固若金汤，海上攻击打不倒。 3. They are invulnerable, because no animal can actually kill them. 因为没有动物能实际上杀他们，所以他们是不会受伤害的。 4. The oceans, vast as they are, are not invulnerable to pollution. 海洋虽然辽阔,但也不是不会受到污染的侵害。', '副词: invulnerably 名词: invulnerability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('propagation', '[ˌprɒpə\'ɡeɪʃn]', 'n.增殖；繁殖；传播；传送', '1. MS-medium can promote callus growing and propagation. MS培养基有利于愈伤组织生长增殖。 2. Rose propagation has a long and rich history. 玫瑰繁殖有着悠久的历史。 3. The phenomenon is called anomalous propagation. 这种现象被称为异常传播。 4. The sun sometimes spoils the propagation of radio waves. 太阳有时会影响无线电波的传播。', '形容词: propagational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wholesome', '[\'hoʊlsəm]', 'adj.有益健康的；合乎卫生的', '1. Bread and milk is wholesome breakfast. 面包和牛奶加有益于健康的早餐。 2. You should read some wholesome books. 你应当读些有益的书。 3. It is not wholesome to eat without washing your hands. 不洗手吃饭是不卫生的。', '副词: wholesomely 比较级: wholesomer 最高级: wholesomest 名词: wholesomeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crabbed', '[\'kræbɪd]', 'adj.暴躁的；难辨认的；难懂的', '1. They even wanted to take away the love she depended upon to live, to present her verdant spring to a crabbed old man. 人们甚至连她所赖以生活的爱情也要给她夺去了。 把自己的青春拿去服侍一个脾气古怪的老头子，得不到一点怜惜。 2. I simply cannot decipher his crabbed handwriting. 我简直无法辨认他那些潦草的字迹。 3. His mature compositions are generally considered as the more rational and crabbed. 他成熟的作品一般被认为拥有更多理智但也难于理解。 4. Do not imagine that mathematics is crabbed and repulsive to common sense, it is merely the etherealization of common sense. 别把数学想象为无法理解的、令人讨厌的、有悖于常识的东西，它只不过是赋予常识以灵性的东西。', '副词: crabbedly 名词: crabbedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heckle', '[\'hekl]', 'vt.以麻梳梳理；激烈质问；使困惑', '1. The reporter wants to heckle the candidate with those embarrassing question. 记者想用那些让人难为情的问题来刁难这位候选人。 2. The Socialist candidate was heckled continuously. 社会党候选人不断受到诘问。', '名词: heckler 过去式: heckled 过去分词: heckled 现在分词: heckling 第三人称单数: heckles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rave', '[reɪv]', 'v.极力赞扬；说胡话；咆哮 n.喧闹的宴会；极力赞扬；胡说；(货车等的)围栏板', '1. It\'s quite a good film, but it\'s nothing to rave about. 影片倒是好影片，但也不值得大肆吹捧。 2. The patient began to rave incoherently at the nurses. 病人对护士说起胡话来。 3. When he was accused of stealing, he raved wildly against me. 当他被控犯偷窃罪时，他气呼呼地把我臭骂一顿。 4. The Saturday rave craze seems to be on the way out. 星期六狂欢聚会热似乎就要过时了。', '过去式: raved 过去分词: raved 现在分词: raving 第三人称单数: raves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('caper', '[\'keɪpər]', 'n.跳跃；恶作剧；罪恶的勾当；续随子（有刺灌木） v.雀跃；蹦跳', '1. The children cut a caper in the yard. 孩子们在院子里兴高采烈地乱蹦乱跳。 2. The girl\'s caper cost her a twisted ankle. 小姑娘又蹦又跳,结果扭伤了脚踝。 3. I\'d like to know what caper he is up to now. 我倒想知道他现在又在玩什么鬼把戏了。 4. He is planning his next caper -- the stick-up of the city bank. 他正在计划下一次的罪恶勾当--抢劫市银行。 5. The lambs were capering about in the fields. 小羊羔在田野里跳跃嬉戏。', '过去式: capered 过去分词: capered 现在分词: capering 第三人称单数: capers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('restitution', '[ˌrestɪ\'tuːʃn]', 'n.归还；赔偿；恢复原状', '1. These goods were compelled restitution. 这些物品被责令退回。 2. Restitution is more important than retribution . 赔偿比惩罚重要。 3. You should make restitution for the damage done. 你应该为所造成的损害赔偿。 4. His fight for freedom and privilege and restitution was not over yet. 他为自由、权利、复业的斗争还在进行。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scarcity', '[\'skersəti]', 'n.缺乏；不足；缺少', '1. There is a scarcity of trained staff. 缺乏受过训练的人员。 2. This scarcity of non-grain foods exists not only in Sichuan but in many other places as well. 不仅是四川，还有好多地方都有这个缺乏副食品的问题。 3. The factory is in frequent scarcity of raw materials. 这个工厂经常原料不足。 4. Higher prices are often a symptom of scarcity. 高价往往是短缺的信号。', '名词复数: scarcities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heirloom', '[\'erluːm]', 'n.传家宝；〈法律〉动产继承物', '1. It was an ordinary vase, but to save appearances, she said it was a family heirloom. 它本来是一个普通花瓶，为了装门面，她却说它是一件传家宝。 2. She treasured the brooch because it was an heirloom. 她把这枚饰针视为珍宝，因为这是祖上传下来的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lethargy', '[\'leθərdʒi]', 'n.昏睡；倦怠；无精打采', '1. Several hours after the surgery, she was still in her lethargy. 手术过後几小时,她仍然昏睡不醒。 2. She was suddenly overcome by lethargy. 她突然委靡不振。 3. Winston roused himself a little from his lethargy. 温斯顿从懒洋洋的惰性中振作起一些来。 4. The bird\'s lethargy in the morning was unusual. 这只鸟在早上就无生气,很不寻常。', '名词复数: lethargies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gem', '[dʒem]', 'n.宝石；珍品；受到宠爱或评价很高的人；松糕 vt.用宝石装饰', '1. He beguiled me into parting with the gem. 他诱骗我把那枚宝石割爱。 2. Saphhire is a very hard blue gem. 一种蓝色的非常坚硬的宝石。 3. This picture is the gem of the collection. 这幅画是收藏的珍品. 4. My secretary is an absolute gem. 我的秘书真是个难能可贵的人。', '过去式: gemmed 过去分词: gemmed 现在分词: gemming 第三人称单数: gems');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stinginess', '[\'stɪndʒinəs]', 'n.刺骨(刺；吝啬；缺乏)', '1. Such stinginess came from my side of the family. 这种吝啬是我这边的祖先遗传下来的。 2. We must not equate thrift with stinginess. 我们不能把勤俭和吝啬等同起来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('atrocious', '[ə\'troʊʃəs]', 'adj.残暴的；骇人听闻的；糟透的', '1. They committed the most atrocious cruelties. 他们犯下了极其凶残的暴行。 2. An atrocious accident happened this morning. 今天上午发生了一起使人震惊的事故。 3. Isn\'t the weather atrocious? 天气真糟透了,是吧?', '副词: atrociously 名词: atrociousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jockey', '[\'dʒɑːki]', 'n. 赛马的骑师； 驾驶员； 操作工 vt. 骑马； 驾驶（操作）； 瞒骗； 骗人使做 ... vi. 当骑士骑马； 运用手段谋利', '1. The jockey is unlucky to meet an accident. 这个驾驶员倒霉透了，出了车祸。 2. A camel foams at the mouth as he is whipped by a robot jockey during a race at Nad al-Sheba in Dubai, United Arab Emirates. 在阿联酋迪拜举办的一次比赛中，一匹被机器人驾驶的骆驼正口吐白沫。 3. Along its two dusty lanes, local trucks and buses jockey with Cadillacs driven by financiers from Taiwan and Hong Kong investors. 沿着这条国道的两条尘土飞扬的车道穿梭来往着当地的卡车和公交车，以及台湾和香港投资者中的金融家所驾驶的卡迪拉克轿车。', '名词复数: jockeys 过去式: jockeyed 过去分词: jockeyed 现在分词: jockeying 第三人称单数: jockeys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('falcon', '[\'fælkən]', 'n.猎鹰；隼；轻炮', '1. The boys went hunting with their falcon. 男孩子们带着猎鹰出去打猎了。 2. He can track a falcon on a cloudy day. 他阴天里也看得到藏在云后的鹰。 3. This royal falcon wears an owl\'s face. 光荣的鹰隼却戴着猫头鹰的脸孔。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quest', '[kwest]', 'n.探索；寻求 v.寻找；搜索', '1. This fruitless quest was called alchemy by the Arabs. 这种无谓的的探索被阿拉伯人称作炼金术。 2. Man will suffer many disappointments in his quest for truth. 人类在探索真理过程中必然会遭受挫折。 3. The quest for gold was difficult. 寻找金矿是很困难的。 4. The lawyer was on a quest for further evidence. 律师正在到处找寻更多的证据。 5. He decided to go on and continue with his quest. 他决定继续前进，继续寻找问题的答案。', '名词: quester 过去式: quested 过去分词: quested 现在分词: questing 第三人称单数: quests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plagiarize', '[\'pleɪdʒəraɪz]', 'vt.抄袭；剽窃', '1. Actually, I also think there\'s no reason for Professor Song to plagiarize. 其实我也觉得宋教授没理由抄袭。 2. It\'s not a viable option to plagiarize someone else\'s work. 剽窃他人作品的行为是不可取的。', '名词: pla-giarizer 过去式: plagiarized 过去分词: plagiarized 现在分词: plagiarizing 第三人称单数: plagiarizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('satire', '[\'sætaɪər]', 'n.讽刺文；讽刺', '1. Satire is a high and subtle art. 讽刺是一门崇高而又含蓄的艺术。 2. Politicians are legitimate targets for satire. 政治家理所当然是讽刺的靶子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gynaecocracy', '[dʒaɪnɪ\'kɒkrəsɪ]', 'n.妇人政治', '1. Here it must be observed that \"Matriarchate \"(q.v.) is a misleading term, as is \"Gynaecocracy,\" for the custom of deducing descent on the spindle side . 这里要指出对以女系为推衍世系的主轴的习惯，“女家长制社会”是一个易被误解的术语，就像“女权政治”这个术语。 2. Here it must be observed that \" Matriarchate \" (q.v.) is a misleading term, as is \" Gynaecocracy,\" for the custom of deducing descent on the spindle side . 这里要指出对以女系为推衍世系的主轴的习惯，“女家长制社会”是一个易被误解的术语，就像“女权政治”这个术语。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('summarily', '[\'sʌmərəli]', 'adv.概括地；立刻地', '1. Please give your views summarily. 请把你的看法概括地讲一讲。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acorn', '[\'eɪkɔːrn]', 'n.橡树果实；橡子', '1. There are many acorns on the oak tree. 这棵橡树上有很多橡子。 2. It was an acorn that the monkeys are fighting for. 这些猴子在抢橡子。 3. We will live on acorn noodles for the winter this year. 今年冬天，我们家就靠橡子面生活。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('licit', '[\'lɪsɪt]', 'adj.法律准许的；合法的', '1. She made some money by licit means. 他用正当的手段挣了一些钱。 2. Losses would then be a licit investment in future profits. 眼前的损失会成为未来利润的一种投资。 3. The power of the government must be restricted and the licit right of people must he insured. 政府部门的权力要受到约束,人们的合法权利要得到充分保障。', '副词: licitly 名词: licitness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mermaid', '[\'mɜːrmeɪd]', 'n.美人鱼', '1. Have you read the story of mermaids? 你看过关于美人鱼的故事吗？ 2. The little mermaid took the prince to shore. 小美人鱼把王子带到岸边。 3. Quickly, the little mermaid dived under the water. 小美人鱼很快地潜入水里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nick', '[nɪk]', 'v.刻痕；赶上；说中；<俚>欺骗；偷盗；逮捕 n.刻痕；缺口；情况；<俚>监狱 Nick n.尼克(男子名)', '1. A bullet nicked his leg. 一颗子弹擦伤了他的腿。 2. We nicked the last bus. 我们刚好赶上末班公车。 3. I nicked what he wanted to do. 我刚好猜中了他要去做什么。 4. He nicked me for a thousand dollars. 他骗我一千美元。 5. There is a nick on my hand. 我的手上有个小伤口。', '过去式: nicked 过去分词: nicked 现在分词: nicking 第三人称单数: nicks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antiquated', '[\'æntɪkweɪtɪd]', 'adj.陈旧的；过时的；古老的；废弃的 动词antiquate的过去式和过去分词.', '1. A train of antiquated coaches was waiting for us at the siding. 一列陈旧的火车在侧线上等着我们。 2. They attempted to modernise these antiquated industries, but in vain. 他们企图使这些陈旧的工业现代化，结果劳而无功。 3. The method is already slightly antiquated. 这个办法现在已经有点过时了。 4. The butler was almost invisible in the stream of an antiquated geyser. 在这座古老的热水锅炉产生的水蒸汽中隐隐约约可以看到那个男仆的影子。', '名词: antiquatedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pluck', '[plʌk]', 'v.摘；猛拉；拔；拨弹（乐器） n.猛拉；勇气；动物内脏', '1. He plucked a rose for his lover. 他为情人摘了一朵玫瑰花。 2. A stranger plucked at my sleeve as I was leaving. 我刚要离去，一个陌生人拽我的袖子。 3. When you kill a chicken to eat, you have to pluck it. 当你杀鸡吃时，你得拔去鸡毛。 4. Her long graceful fingers pluck the strings. 她的修长优雅的手指拉弦乐器。 5. He felt a pluck on the fishing line 他感到鱼钩拉了一下。', '名词: plucker 过去式: plucked 过去分词: plucked 现在分词: plucking 第三人称单数: plucks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('layman', '[\'leɪmən]', 'n.俗人(对僧侣而言)；门外汉', '1. He is a layman in politics. 他对政治是个门外汉。 2. This book is written for professionals and laymen alike. 这本书既可供专业人员阅读，又可供外行人看。 3. Where the law is concerned, I am only a layman. 谈到法律, 我不过是门外汉。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detonation', '[ˌdetə\'neɪʃn]', 'n.爆炸；引爆；爆炸声', '1. Could there be an accidental detonation of a nuclear weapon? 有没有可能会有核武的意外爆炸? 2. A detonation projects an instantaneous pulse of pressure outward in all directions. 爆炸的瞬间会朝各个方向发出向外的压力波。 3. Obviously, the detonation of a nuclear warhead is a high-amplitude event. 很明显，核弹头的引爆是一个高烈度事件。 4. Claymores can now be set for controlled or uncontrolled detonation. 克莱默地雷现在可以被安放并设定为遥控引爆或非遥控引爆。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pollen', '[\'pɑːlən]', 'n.花粉 vt.授粉给', '1. Ben is allergic to pollen. 班对花粉过敏。 2. Anther is a part of a flower that contains the pollen. 花药是花的雄蕊上带花粉的部分。 3. There is a high pollen count in the air. 空气中有很高的花粉计数。 4. Stamen is in the middle of a flower and may produce pollen. 雄蕊长在花的中央，能产生花粉。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('balky', '[\'bɔːlki]', 'adj.停蹄不前的；突然停止的；难以启动的；固执的', '1. The increased funding would require approval from a balky Congress. 增加融资可能需要得到固执的美国国会批准。', '比较级: balkier 最高级: balkiest 名词: balkiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('squeamish', '[\'skwiːmɪʃ]', 'adj.易恶心的；易受惊的；过分正经的；过分拘谨', '1. I\'m a little squeamish about dissecting things. 解剖东西让我觉得有点恶心。 2. I was squeamish about seeing the terrible accident. 我看到可怕的事故就会作呕。 3. It\'s a violent film, so don\'t go if you\'re squeamish. 这是一部暴力影片，如果你容易受惊，就别去看了。 4. To attain full growth, one mustn\'t be squeamish. 一个人要充分成长，绝不能太拘小节。', '副词: squeamishly 名词: squeamishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whet', '[wet]', 'n.磨；磨利之物；开胃物 v.磨（刀）；刺激（欲望、兴趣）', '1. The material is sent in the whet room directly. 物料直接送进磨室。 2. This product is suitable for fixing and throwing light whet superficially after welding. 本产品适用于焊接前坡口及焊接后缝焊表面的修磨。 3. He whetted his knife on the stone. 他在石头上磨刀。 4. The dish will whet your appetite. 这盘菜能促进你的食欲。', '过去式: whetted 过去分词: whetted 现在分词: whetting 第三人称单数: whets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('podium', '[\'poʊdiəm]', 'n.讲台；（乐队）指挥台；建筑物的墩座；矮墙 n.[生]管足', '1. She was introduced and stepped up to the podium. 介绍完毕后她就登上讲台。 2. She walked up to the podium, just like a teacher. 她走上讲台，俨然是个老师。 3. The conductress took the podium. 这位女指挥开始指挥乐队演奏。 4. The conductor stepped down from the podium. 指挥从指挥台上踏步走下来。', '名词复数: podia');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('effete', '[ɪ\'fiːt]', 'adj.贫瘠的；衰弱的；无能力的', '1. People said the aristocracy was effete. 人们说贵族阶级已是日薄西山了。 2. During the middle ages, Greek civilization declined and became effete. 在中世纪期间，希腊文明开始衰落直至衰败。', '副词: effetely 名词: effeteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cacophony', '[kə\'kɑːfəni]', 'n.刺耳的声音；杂音', '1. The drivers behind him honked, and the cacophony grew louder. 后面的司机还在按喇叭，且那刺耳的声音越来越大。 2. From its cacophony of sound, the room has suddenly become very still. 本来众声嘈杂的屋子里，突然变得非常肃静。', '名词复数: cacophonies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('judicious', '[dʒu\'dɪʃəs]', 'adj.明智的；贤明的；审慎的', '1. It would be judicious to remain silent. 保持沈默是明智的。 2. I believe that he can make a judicious choice. 我相信他能作出明智的选择。 3. A judicious parent encourages his children to make their own decisions. 贤明的父亲鼓励儿女自作抉择。 4. It was in this manner that Teroro, bearing in his hands the rock of Pere, stepped ashore to become the compationate and judicious priest of Havaiki. 蒂罗罗双手捧着佩丽的神石下了船，从此，他成了夏伐伊基的仁慈贤明的祭司。', '副词: judiciously 名词: judiciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disarray', '[ˌdɪsə\'reɪ]', 'v.弄乱；使混乱 n.无秩序；混乱', '1. The child had disarrayed the books. 孩子把书弄乱了。 2. The naughty pupils disarray the class. 顽皮的学生打乱了班上的秩序。 3. The troops fled in disarray. 部队仓皇逃散。 4. Changing offices has left my papers in complete disarray. 办公室搬迁，使我的文件全部乱了套了。', '过去式: disarrayed 过去分词: disarrayed 现在分词: disarraying 第三人称单数: disarrays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('compose', '[kəm\'poʊz]', 'v.作曲；创作；编排；形成；使镇静', '1. She began to compose songs at an early age. 她还很年轻时就已经开始创作歌曲。 2. He was composing at the piano at the age of seven. 他7岁时就会钢琴作曲。 3. He sat down and composed a letter of resignation. 他坐下来,写了一封辞职信。 4. It is the law-makers\'s duty to compose laws into a coherent system. 将各项法律编排成为一个连贯的体系是立法者的职责。', '过去式: composed 过去分词: composed 现在分词: composing 第三人称单数: composes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('decry', '[dɪ\'kraɪ]', 'v.责难；诽谤', '1. Many people decry flogging. 许多人反对鞭打。 2. All the mayors decry gambling in all its forms. 所有市长都谴责各式各样的赌博。 3. Environmental activists decry destruction in Amazon. 环保人士谴责破坏亚马逊热带雨林的活动。', '名词: decrier 过去式: decried 过去分词: decried 现在分词: decrying 第三人称单数: decries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('additive', '[\'ædətɪv]', 'n.添加剂 adj.加添的', '1. Food additive can cause allergies. 食品添加剂可能引起过敏。 2. Glycyrrhizin is a kind of food additive which has a bright future. 甘草素是一种很有发展前途的食品添加剂。 3. We can use the additive property of the integral. 我们可利用积分的可加性。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sedentary', '[\'sednteri]', 'adj.久坐的；固定不动的', '1. People in sedentary jobs need to take exercise. 工作上要久坐的人需要做运动。 2. We should do away with the sedentary lifestyle. 我们应该抛弃久坐的生活方式。', '副词: sedentarily 名词: sedentariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vaporous', '[\'veɪpərəs]', 'adj.空想的；蒸汽的；雾状的；易挥发的', '1. A cloud is a mass of vapor in the sky. 云是天空中的水汽团。 2. Chemicals that produce a noxious vapor when mixed. 化学物质混合后会放出有毒气体 3. Water can be changed into vapor when heated. 水被加热时，可以变成水蒸汽。 4. A liquid condensed from vapor in distillation. 蒸馏液; 馏出物在蒸馏中，从蒸汽浓缩的液体', '副词: vaporously 名词: vaporosity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pledge', '[pledʒ]', 'vt.发誓；保证；以 ... 抵押；向 ... 祝酒 n.保证；抵押；誓言；抵押品', '1. They pledged never to tell the secret. 他们发誓决不泄密。 2. We all had to pledge allegiance to the flag. 我们大家都得发誓忠于这面旗帜。 3. She pledged her support to us. 她保证支持我们。 4. I pledge myself to fulfil the promise I have made. 我保证实践自己的诺言。 5. And as we walk, we must make the pledge that we shall march ahead. 当我们行动时,我们必须保证勇往直前。', '过去式: pledged 过去分词: pledged 现在分词: pledging 第三人称单数: pledges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pendulum', '[\'pendʒələm]', 'n.摆锤；钟摆；摇摆不定', '1. A pendulum oscillates. 摆锤能摆动。 2. The pendulum of the clock in my room is a bear. 我房间的钟摆是小熊形状的。 3. The pendulum swings with great regularity. 钟摆很有规律地摆动着。 4. Since the last election, the pendulum of public opinion has swung back against the government. 自从上次大选以来,公众舆论又转回到反对政府。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grounded', '[\'ɡraʊndɪd]', 'adj.(情绪上)稳定的；[计算机] 接地的 动词ground的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. He went on by train after the plane was grounded on account of the fog. 飞机因雾停飞后，他改乘火车继续前进。 2. All aircraft at London Airport were grounded by fog today. 因今天有雾，伦敦机场的所有飞机都被迫停飞。 3. Our ship grounded in shallow water/on a sandbank. 我们的船在浅水中[在沙滩上]搁浅。 4. She grounded her pupils well in arithmetic. 她给自己的学生打下良好的算术基础。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('redistribution', '[ˌriːdɪstrɪ\'bjuːʃn]', 'n.重新分配；再区分', '1. Redistribution of land was a fundamental of Red policy. 重新分配土地是红区政策中的一个根本要素。 2. After redistribution, everyone\'s payment is almost the same. 经过重新分配，每个人得到的酬金都扯平了。', '形容词: redistributionist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('furor', '[\'fjʊərɔː(r)]', 'n.激怒；狂热；骚乱', '1. In the United States, there is a furor over the standard of Chinese imports. 美国对中国进口商品的标准有了狂热的反应。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('congruous', '[\'kɒngrʊəs]', 'adj.一致的；适合的', '1. The authors have proved that the two types of definitions are congruous by using limit theory, while discussing the correlation among the subclasses of heavy-tailed distributions. 利用分析中的极限理论等方法，证明了重尾分布的这两种定义是一致的，并给出了重尾分布子族间的相互关系。', '副词: congruously 名词: congruousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('projectile', '[prə\'dʒektl]', 'n.发射体；抛射物（尤指子弹、炮弹） adj.发射的；向前开进的；〈动物学〉（触角）可伸出的', '1. The vertical and horizontal motions of a projectile can be treated independently. 发射体的垂直方向和水平方向的运动能够分开来处理。 2. The path followed by a projectile is called its trajectory. 发射体所循的路径称为它的轨道。 3. The question of the projectile was definitely settled. 炮弹问题已经正式解决了。 4. Have you altered the plans of the projectile as the telegram suggests? 你已经按照电报的要求修改炮弹图样了吗? 5. A javelin is a projectile weapon. 标枪是一种投射武器', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('numb', '[nʌm]', 'adj.麻木的；失去知觉的 vt.使麻木；使失去知觉', '1. My fingers were so numb that I could hardly write. 我的手指都麻木了几乎不能写字。 2. I\'ve just been to the dentist and my face is still numb. 我刚刚去看了牙医，脸上现在还没知觉呢。 3. The anaesthetic made his whole face go numb. 麻醉药使他的整张脸失去了知觉。 4. His leg was numbed by the intense pain. 他的腿因剧痛而麻木。', '副词: numbly 比较级: number 最高级: numbest 名词: numbness 过去式: numbed 过去分词: numbed 现在分词: numbing 第三人称单数: numbs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('panorama', '[ˌpænə\'ræmə]', 'n.全景；全景画；概观；一连串景象或事物', '1. promise graciously 2. As we stood at the top of the mountain, a beautiful panorama spread out before us. 我们登上山顶时，一幅美丽的景色展现在我们的面前。 3. The book presents a panorama of British history since the Middle Ages. 该书概述了中世纪以来的英国历史。 4. Henry watched the panorama of pass people with wide eyes. 亨利观看着一连串过往的人群。', '形容词: panoramic 副词: panoramically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aesthetic', '[es\'θetɪk]', 'adj.美学的；审美的；有美感的 n.(复数)审美观', '1. Later he also gained in aesthetic knowledge. 后来他的美学知识也增加了。 2. From an aesthetic point of view it\'s a thetic view. 从美学观点来说, 这是个武断的看法。 3. The professor advanced a new aesthetic theory. 那位教授提出了新的美学理论。 4. His aesthetic ideas were his own. 他有他自己的审美观念。 5. Natural aesthetic is the core of Chinese aesthetics. 自然审美是中国古代美学的核心。', '副词: aesthetically 异体字: esthetic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lode', '[loʊd]', 'n.<古>水道；矿脉；丰富的来源或供给', '1. Her own experiences have provided her with a mother lode of material for her songs. 她自身的经历为她的歌曲提供了取之不尽的素材。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demography', '[dɪ\'mɑːɡrəfi]', 'n.人口统计学', '1. Demography is the analysis of population variables. 人口学是对人口变量的分析。 2. The study\'s findings were reported in the publication Demography. 人口统计学刊上报道了该研究结果。', '名词: demographer');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('warden', '[\'wɔːrdn]', 'n.看守人', '1. They baksheeshed the game warden. 他们向渔猎监督官行贿。 2. He was taken to the warden\'s office. 他被带到看守长的办公室。 3. The most anxious man in a prison is the warden. 在监狱里最担忧的人是监狱长。 4. The warden\'s authority diminished after the revolt. 典狱长的权威在动乱后下降了。', '名词: wardenship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antedate', '[ˌænti\'deɪt]', 'v.使 ... 提前发生；先于；提早日期 =predate n.比实际早的日期', '1. The cold weather antedate ed their departure. 寒冷的天气使他们提前离开。 2. This event antedates the discovery of America by several centuries. 这件事比发现美洲早几个世纪。', '过去式: antedated 过去分词: antedated 现在分词: antedating 第三人称单数: antedates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('puissance', '[\'pwɪsəns]', 'n.权力；势力；力量', '1. Chine future puissance mondiale... 未来世界的强国！ 2. La puissance de yinian est parfois miraculeuse. 意念的力量有时是很神奇的。 3. Ceremonie : du grand art, de la grandeur, de la puissance .... 开幕式：至上的艺术，宏大的场面，强大的国家！ 4. Whether or notthe bones are strong decides the strength and puissance of theorganic body. 骨头是否坚硬决定了机体的强度和耐力，...肌肉充实了身体使得集体不再枯燥。', '形容词: puissant 副词: puissantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shambles', '[\'ʃæmblz]', 'n.凌乱；混乱；混乱之处', '1. Your room is (in) a shambles. Tidy it up! 你的房间乱七八糟. 2. The meeting ended in a complete shambles. 会议结束时混乱不堪。 3. The twister turned this city into a shambles. 卷风将这个城市变成了一片废墟。 4. After the party the house was a shambles. 宴会之后，屋子里一片狼藉。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dash', '[dæʃ]', 'v.猛冲；猛掷；泼溅；匆忙完成 n.破折号；短跑；猛冲；冲', '1. He dashed across the street and ran towards me. 他冲过马路，向我跑过来。 2. He dash the glass bowl to bit on a rock. 他对著石块把玻璃碗砸得粉碎。 3. Don\'t dash the paint on the wall like that. 别那样在墙上乱涂漆。 4. She dashed off a letter to her mother. 她给母亲匆匆写了一封信。 5. The dash is used in writing to show a pause. 在写作上破折号用来表示停顿。', '过去式: dashed 过去分词: dashed 现在分词: dashing 第三人称单数: dashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amity', '[\'æməti]', 'n.友好关系', '1. He lives in amity with his neighbours. 他和他的邻居相处得很和睦。 2. For a county, amity between nations is important. 对于一个国家，与各国友好相处是很重要的。 3. Not olny you but aslo your wife are amity with me. 你和你的妻子对我都很友好。 4. They parted on a high plane of amity and Christian helpfulness. 他们在十分友好、洋溢着基督教徒助人为乐精神的气氛中分了手。', '名词复数: amities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('execrable', '[\'eksɪkrəbl]', 'adj.恶劣的；该诅咒的；极坏的', '1. What an execrable weather! 这天气真恶劣。 2. She always has execrable taste in men. 她总是对男人有着极差的品味。', '副词: execrably 名词: execrableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acrimony', '[ækrɪmoʊni]', 'n.(语言；态度等)刻薄；辛辣', '1. This book review was written with acrimony. 这篇书评语调刻薄。 2. The acrimony of his remarks alienated his audience. 他说话尖刻, 这使观众和他疏远了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sublimate', '[\'sʌblɪmeɪt]', 'v.使（心灵或物质）升华 n.升华物 adj.升华的；纯净的；高尚的；理想化的', '1. Her sublimate future husband will be tall, dark, and handsome. 她理想化的未来丈夫将是身材高大，皮肤浅黑，相貌英俊。', '过去式: sublimated 过去分词: sublimated 现在分词: sublimating 第三人称单数: sublimates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conventional', '[kən\'venʃənl]', 'adj.传统的；惯例的；常规的', '1. Her book is a hilarious send-up of a conventional spy story. 她写的书用的是取笑传统侦探小说的笔法，令人捧腹。 2. According to conventional wisdom, voters usually make their choice on the basis of domestic issues. 按一般人在这些问题上的看法，选民常常着眼于国内问题来选择候选人。 3. After a conventional opening remarks, he made a brilliant speech. 在一个常规的开场白后,他做了个很精彩的演讲。 4. I can never get a girl like that with conventional methods. 我用寻常套路可永远也得不到这样的女孩。', '副词: conventionally 名词: conventionalism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vicious', '[\'vɪʃəs]', 'adj.恶毒的；恶意的；剧烈的；堕落的', '1. I won\'t listen to such vicious remarks. 我不想听这种恶毒的话。 2. She used vicious remarks to insult people. 她恶言伤人。 3. Vicious gossip is spreading throughout the school. 校园里到处流传着恶意的闲言碎语。 4. He made a vicious stab at me with a broken bottle. 他用破瓶子向我猛烈地刺过来。', '副词: viciously 名词: viciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('erratic', '[ɪ\'rætɪk]', 'adj.古怪的；飘忽不定的；不稳定的', '1. He was like a stormy, erratic boy. 他好象是个性急的古怪的孩子。 2. Though occasionally chatty, his moods were erratic. 他虽然有时健谈，但是他的脾气却很难捉摸。 3. An erratic mind jump from one idea to another. 心意不定的人反复无常。 4. They no longer fear the erratic behavior of the market. 他们永远不害怕市场飘忽不定的行为。', '副词: erratically 名词: erraticism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meager', '[\'miːgə]', 'adj.贫乏的；不足的；瘦的', '1. It was medieval European monks who introduced scientific brewing techniques in an effort to produce a nutritious beverage to supplement their meager diets. 正是中世纪欧洲的僧侣们引进科学的啤酒酿造技术，制造有营养的饮料，从而补充了他们贫乏的饮食。', '副词: meagerly 名词: meagerness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ditch', '[dɪtʃ]', 'n.沟渠；壕沟 vt.丢弃；坠入沟中；飞机（在海上）迫降 vi.挖渠；飞机紧急降落', '1. The car ran off the road into a ditch. 汽车驶离道路跌进沟中。 2. The frog jumped into the ditch. 青蛙跳进了沟里。 3. The invaders cut off their prisoners\' arms and legs and threw their mutilated bodies into the ditch. 侵略者把俘虏的四肢砍掉,然后把残缺不全的躯体扔进沟里。 4. The soldier made a dive for the ditch. 这名战士向壕沟冲去。 5. When the road becomes impassable,we have to ditch the car and walk. 道路无法通行时,我们只好弃车步行。 6. The plane had to ditch over rough waters. 飞机只能在汹涌的水面进行紧急迫降。', '过去式: ditched 过去分词: ditched 现在分词: ditching 第三人称单数: ditches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eviction', '[ɪ\'vɪkʃn]', 'n.逐出；赶出；收回（租房或租地等）', '1. He\'s had nowhere to live since his eviction. 他自从被驱逐出住所以来，就一直无处栖身。 2. The family have won a temporary reprieve from eviction. 这个家庭暂时免于被逐出。 3. Non payment of rent can mean eviction. 不交租金就可能被赶出去. 4. We had to fork up money for our rent or face eviction. 我们得付租金了，不然会被赶出去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('furbish', '[\'fɜːbɪʃ]', 'vt.磨光；刷新', '1. I wish to furbish up the Russian I learnt at college. 我要重温一下我在大学里学过的俄语。', '名词: furbisher 过去式: furbished 过去分词: furbished 现在分词: furbishing 第三人称单数: furbishes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sadden', '[\'sædn]', 'v.(使)黯淡；(使)悲伤', '1. That dark Egyptian seems to me to sadden the very sun. 在我看来那个阴森的埃及人似乎会使太阳都变得黯淡无光。 2. But I would not sadden you by the mortal plaint. 但我不愿以生命必有终结的哀叹使你悲伤。', '过去式: saddened 过去分词: saddened 现在分词: saddening 第三人称单数: saddens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bog', '[bɑːɡ]', 'n. 沼泽 v. 使 ... 陷于泥沼； 陷于困境', '1. Ren took Gerin to the bog moon of Bogden. 伦把婕琳带到博格登的沼泽卫星。 2. In later years when the bog is drained, the peat can be dug out and used as fuel. 再过几年，当沼泽干涸之后，泥煤可以挖出来用作燃料。', '形容词: boggy 名词: bogginess 过去式: bogged 过去分词: bogged 现在分词: bogging 第三人称单数: bogs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fleeting', '[\'fliːtɪŋ]', 'adj.短暂的；疾驰的 动词fleet的现在分词形式.', '1. He made only a fleeting reference to his resignation. 他只提了一下他辞职的事。 2. The prime of life is that fleeting time between green and overripe. 人生盛年是处于青涩和过孰之间的短暂时光。 3. They fired at a fleeting enemy. 他们向正在逃跑的敌人开火。', '副词: fleetingly 名词: fleetingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bark', '[bɑːrk]', 'v.(狗)吠；咆哮 v.剥皮；擦伤 n.狗吠；咆哮 n.树皮', '1. The dog barked when the stranger came near. 当陌生人走近时，狗叫了起来。 2. An old dog does not bark for nothing. 老狗不会无事而吠。 3. When you speak to people, don\'t bark at them. 当你和人说话时不要咆哮。 4. Some officers bark out their orders. 有些军官以粗暴的声音发布命令。 5. He barked his elbow on the wall. 他碰到墙上，肘部擦破了皮。 6. Those trees have very beautiful white bark. 那些树长着非常漂亮的白色树皮。', '过去式: barked 过去分词: barked 现在分词: barking 第三人称单数: barks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transfuse', '[træns\'fjuːz]', 'vt.移注；输血；渗入；灌输', '1. Doctors are looking for a blood donor to transfuse to an unusual patient. 医生正在寻找能给一个血型罕见的病人输血的献血者。', '形容词: transfusible 名词: transfuser 过去式: transfused 过去分词: transfused 现在分词: transfusing 第三人称单数: transfuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evacuate', '[ɪ\'vækjueɪt]', 'v.疏散；撤出；排泄', '1. There\'s been a bomb threat we need to evacuate. 有人威胁说在这安放了炸弹 我们需要紧急疏散 2. Please evacuate the building immediately. 请立刻自大楼疏散。 3. The first priority shall be to evacuate the bus. 汽车着火后的第一要务是疏散乘客。 4. All people would evacuate the area. 所有人员也都全部撤离这一地区。', '形容词: evacuative 名词: evacuator 过去式: evacuated 过去分词: evacuated 现在分词: evacuating 第三人称单数: evacuates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marshal', '[\'mɑːrʃl]', 'n.陆空军元帅；典礼官；司仪官 v.整顿；配置；汇集', '1. The marshal rode at the head of the parade. 典礼官在检阅队伍的前面骑马行进。 2. The idea is to marshal the body\'s own immune system to fight cancer. 这个思路是重新配置机体自身的免疫系统来对抗肿瘤。', '名词: marshalcy 过去式: marshaled/marshalled 过去分词: marshaled/marshalled 现在分词: marshaling/marshalling 第三人称单数: marshals/marshals');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('candid', '[\'kændɪd]', 'adj.率直的；坦诚的；公正的；偷拍的', '1. His words are always more candied than candid. 他话语中阿谀多于诚恳。 2. To be perfectly candid, I think you acted foolishly. 十分坦率地说，我认为你做得很愚蠢。 3. He is a very candid man and never talks in a roundabout way. 他生性坦直，说话办事从来不会拐弯抹角。 4. He was quite candid about the way the case had been handled. 对于这个案子的处理手法他直言不讳。', '副词: candidly 名词: candidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scoop', '[skuːp]', 'n.铲子；勺；舀取；穴；独家新闻 vt.挖空；舀取；抢先报道（获得）', '1. he used a scoop to serve the ice cream. 他用铲子来吃冰激凌。 2. There are several scoops in my kitchen. 我的厨房里有好几个勺子。 3. The newspaper got a scoop on the airplane crash. 该报独家报导了那次飞机失事。 4. This small rodent can scoop a long , narrow tunnel in a very short time . 这只海狸能在短时间内挖出一条长且窄的洞。', '名词: scooper 过去式: scooped 过去分词: scooped 现在分词: scooping 第三人称单数: scoops');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fungicide', '[\'fʌnɡɪsaɪd]', 'n.杀菌剂', '1. It is a very good insecticide, fungicide, herbicide synergist. 它是非常理想的杀虫剂、杀菌剂、除草剂的增效剂。 2. They treat their seeds with fungicide to combat seedling disease. 他们用杀真菌剂浸泡种子来防止秧苗受病。 3. Seed can be coated with fungicide to provide protection before emergence. 种子可以用杀真菌剂包衣,使其在萌芽前受到保护。', '形容词: fungicidal 副词: fungicidally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sage', '[seɪdʒ]', 'n.圣人；哲人 n.鼠尾草；蒿属植物 adj.贤明的；明智的', '1. A sage has more than one teacher. 圣人无常师。 2. Confucius is considered the greatest of the ancient Chinese sages. 孔子被认为是中国古代最伟大的圣贤。 3. The sage is the instructor of a hundred ages. 这位哲人是百代之师。 4. Sage has been known to symbolize strength for thousands of years. 鼠尾草千百年来被当作强有力的象征。 5. I was grateful for the old man\'s sage advice. 我很感激那位老人贤明的忠告。', '副词: sagely 比较级: sager 最高级: sagest 名词: sageness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('canker', '[\'kæŋkər]', 'n.溃疡；(树的)癌肿病；毒害；弊害 v.患溃疡；腐蚀；溃烂', '1. Fatigue, stress or allergies can increase the likelihood of a canker sore. 疲劳，压力或过敏能增加口腔溃疡发作的可能性。 2. Anecdotal evidence suggests that diets high in sugar, citrus, and cereal grains may trigger canker sores. 有事实证据表明大量饮用糖，柑橘，谷粒或许会触发口腔溃疡。 3. When with stainless steel or carbon steel, the interior must line with rubber processing, preventing to canker shell material. 用不锈钢或碳钢制作时，内部需衬胶处理，以防止腐蚀壳体材料。', '过去式: cankered 过去分词: cankered 现在分词: cankering 第三人称单数: cankers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('morbid', '[\'mɔːrbɪd]', 'adj.病态的；不正常的', '1. She always has a morbid imagination. 她总在做病态的想像。 2. Why do you like going to cemeteries so much? Is it some kind of morbid curiosity? 你为什么这么爱去墓地？是不是有些不太正常？', '副词: morbidly 名词: morbidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insulate', '[\'ɪnsəleɪt]', 'vt.使绝缘；隔离', '1. We can insulate a live wire with rubber. 我们可用橡胶使带电的电线绝缘。 2. Rubber is used to insulate electric wires. 橡胶被用来使电线与外界绝缘。 3. Her parents tried to insulate her from dangerous influences. 她的父母试图把她与危险的影响隔绝。 4. It is important to insulate the furnace from any neighbouring woodwork with brick and asbestos. 用砖和石棉把炉子与周围所有的木制品隔开，这很重要。', '过去式: insulated 过去分词: insulated 现在分词: insulating 第三人称单数: insulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spin', '[spɪn]', 'v.(使)旋转；疾驰；纺织；结网；眩晕 n.纺织；旋转；眩晕；疾驰', '1. My sister can spin on her toes like a dancer. 我妹妹能像舞者一样踮着脚尖旋转。 2. The motorcycles were spinning along at full speed. 摩托车正全速疾驰。 3. Mother used to spin her own yarn. 母亲过去一直是自己纺纱的。 4. In spring, they spin their cocoons. 到了春天，它们才吐丝结茧。 5. Before the invention of spin technology, zoic fur were mainly material. 在纺织技术尚未发明之前，动物的毛皮是人们服装的主要材料。', '过去式: spun/span 过去分词: spun 现在分词: spinning 第三人称单数: spins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meteoric', '[ˌmiːti\'ɔːrɪk]', 'adj.流星的；昙花一现的；大气的', '1. Scientists found the celestial origin of the meteoric shower. 科学家发现了那场流星雨的太空源。 2. Many wonderful things are just meteoric. 很多美好的事物只是昙花一现。 3. The main ore fluid was magma water mixed with meteoric water. 成矿流体是以岩浆水为主,混有古大气水的混合流体。', '副词: meteorically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lush', '[lʌʃ]', 'adj.苍翠繁茂的；茂盛的；丰富的 n.酒；酒鬼 v.喝酒', '1. Trains pass through the lush countryside. 火车通过苍翠繁茂的乡下。 2. Ireland is famous for its lush green hills. 爱尔兰以其苍翠的绿色山丘而闻名。 3. The lush vegetation spoke of a damper climate here. 茂盛的植物说明这里的气候是潮湿的。 4. The hills are covered in lush green vegetation. 这片丘岭草木茂盛，郁郁葱葱。 5. This handcrafted Chardonnay is rich with white peach, spice, tropical fruit and has a lush velvety texture. 而此酒正由人工采收，有白桃，香料，热带水果的香味，如丝柔滑的口感更让人一试难忘。', '副词: lushly 比较级: lusher 最高级: lushest 名词: lushness 过去式: lushed 过去分词: lushed 现在分词: lushing 第三人称单数: lushes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('queasy', '[\'kwiːzi]', 'adj.反胃的；恶心的；不稳定的；不安的', '1. There was a queasy mess upon the plate. 盘子上有一堆令人作呕的食物。 2. Those greasy French fries made me queasy. 那些油腻的薯条让我想吐。 3. I felt a little queasy on the ship. 我在船上觉得有点晕眩想呕吐。 4. I was developing the queasy feeling that we were being tested. 我心中顿起疑云，莫非人家在考验我们?', '副词: queasily 名词: queasiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retrenchment', '[rɪ\'trentʃmənt]', 'n.减少；删除', '1. This will force a retrenchment on the part of consumers and lead to the postponement of many investment decisions. 这将迫使消费者数量的减少以及许多投资决定的推迟。 2. Sallie Mae\'s retrenchment, resulting from a renewed focus on credit quality, could force prospective students to scramble for loans and pay more when they get them. 学生贷款营销协会减少助学贷款的发放数量是因为它重新关注起信贷质量，此举有可能增加拟去上述高校就读学生申请贷款的难度，并加重他们的还款负担。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accountability', '[əˌkaʊntə\'bɪləti]', 'n.有责任；有义务', '1. Having a supervisor sign does not give the same level of accountability. 有监管人员的签名并不能说明同样层次的责任性。 2. This is within his sphere of accountability. 这在他的责任范围之内。 3. Without accountability, there can be no respect. 没有责任,就没有尊重。 4. They are accountability inform when he signed contract with their company，but they didn\'t. 在他和他们公司签合同的时候,他们有义务告知,但他们没有。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sprightly', '[\'spraɪtli]', 'adj.（老人）精力充沛的；轻快的 adv.有生气地；轻快地', '1. He\'s surprisingly sprightly for an old man. 他这把年纪了，还这麽精神，真了不起。 2. As an old man of 75, he is surprisingly sprightly. 作为一个75岁的老人，他可谓精神矍铄，令人称奇。 3. As a sprightly comedy, this show fills the bill. 作为轻喜剧，这样演是适宜的。 4. The patient smiled when he heard the sprightly music on the radio. 听到收音机里传来的轻快乐曲，这个病人笑了。 5. Judith is a sprightly young woman. 朱迪思是个机灵的姑娘。', '比较级: sprightlier 最高级: sprightliest 名词: sprightliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infelicity', '[ˌɪnfə\'lɪsətɪ]', 'n.不幸；不吉；不适当', '1. There is so much infelicity in the world. 人世间有很多不幸的事。', '名词复数: infelicities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inane', '[ɪ\'neɪn]', 'adj.愚蠢的；空虚的；无意义的', '1. The woman Folly is fickle and inane, and knows nothing. 愚昧太太，浮燥愚蠢，一无所知。 2. She made up her mind that their lives were, though luxurious, inane. 她坚决相信，他们的生活虽然奢侈，但很空虚。 3. These inane literary works have no affinity to the masses. 这些文学作品空洞无物, 丝毫没有人民性。', '副词: inanely 比较级: inaner 最高级: inanest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('termite', '[\'tɜːrmaɪt]', 'n.白蚁', '1. Remedy is spraying anti - termite syrup. 补救方法是喷洒防白蚁药水。 2. Termite fishing with twigs and the mid-ribs of leaves were two. 用小树枝和树叶中脉钓取白蚁是其中的两种模式。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('libertine', '[\'lɪbərtiːn]', 'n.性行为放纵者；浪荡子；持自由思想者 adj.放荡的；不务正业的', '1. The transition from libertine to prig was so complete. 一个酒徒色鬼竟然摇身一变就成了道学先生。 2. I believe John is not a libertine any more. 我相信约翰不再是个浪子了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carillon', '[\'kærəlɑːn]', 'n.排钟；钟琴；钟乐器', '1. The shattering tones of the enormous carillon. 巨钟发出的嘈杂的声音。 2. C. is composed of a large Collegiate Gothic section, crowned by Cleveland Tower, a local landmark that also houses a world-class carillon. 普林斯顿很爽快地用收到的捐款把贫困学生无法支付的学费都减免而不像其他大学强加学生背上沉重的贷款包袱。 3. Carillon Ringers is a newly expended community handbell choir in Hong Kong.We aimed at serving the society by making high quality handbell music. Carillon Ringers是植根于本港的手铃队，成立目的为推广手铃表演艺术及带动手铃音乐的普及化与发展。 4. Twice a day, the square fills with people gathering to watch nearly life-size figurines act out scenes from the city\'s history on the famous carillon clock tower. 一天两次，广场上充满人们聚集在一起，观看了近似真人大小的雕像演出从该市的历史在著名的钟乐器钟楼。', '过去式: carillonned 过去分词: carillonned 现在分词: carillonning 第三人称单数: carillons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muggy', '[\'mʌɡi]', 'adj.闷热的', '1. Muggy weather and hot carriage make me crazy! 闷热的天气，闷热的车厢，简直让我抓狂。 2. We may expect muggy weather when the rainy season begins. 雨季开始时, 我们预料有闷热的天气。', '比较级: muggier 最高级: muggiest 名词: mugginess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crockery', '[\'krɑːkəri]', 'n.陶器；瓦器', '1. I have a slight accident at home and break some crockery. 我在家出了点儿小事，打碎了些陶器。 2. His room was a litter of old clothes,dirty crockery and broken furniture. 他的屋子里到处都是旧衣物,脏陶器和破家具。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stilted', '[\'stɪltɪd]', 'adj.踩高跷的；虚饰的；生硬的 动词stilt的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. A stilted heron labored up into the air and pounded down river. 一只长脚鹭费劲地飞起来，又重重地掉到水里了。 2. He fashioned no stilted epigram. 他不追求夸张的警句。 3. There is no doubt that he writes in a stilted style. 毫无疑问，他写作的文体浮夸。 4. We made stilted conversation for a few moments. 我们不自然地客套了几句。', '副词: stiltedly 名词: stiltedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('canine', '[\'keɪnaɪn]', 'adj.犬的；似犬的；犬科的 n.犬；犬齿；犬科动物', '1. Gula, often envisioned in canine form, was one of the more significant gods of healing. 古拉，通常被想象成是似犬的形象，是其中一位最重要的治愈之神。 2. The German post office has started giving mail workers lessons in canine psychology. 德国邮局开始为投递员开设犬的心理学课程。 3. Gula, often envisioned in canine form, was one of the more significant gods of healing. 古拉，通常被想象成是似犬的形象，是其中一位最重要的治愈之神。 4. Do wolves belong to the canine species? 狼是犬科动物吗？', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wrench', '[rentʃ]', 'n.扳钳，扳手；猛扭；痛苦 vt.扭伤；挣脱 vi.猛扭；曲解', '1. It\'s hard to get at the spark plug without a proper wrench. 没有一把合适的扳钳，要抓住那个火花塞是困难的。 2. The knob broke off when he gave it a sudden wrench. 当他突然扭了一下球形把手，它便断了。 3. Leaving home was a terrible wrench for him. 他觉得离开家十分痛苦。 4. She couldn\'t stand the wrench of departure. 她受不了离别的痛苦。 5. Be careful. Don\'t wrench yourself. 小心点，别扭伤了。 6. I had to wrench the lid off the bottle. 我只好把瓶盖拧开。', '副词: wrenchingly 过去式: wrenched 过去分词: wrenched 现在分词: wrenching 第三人称单数: wrenches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flabby', '[\'flæbi]', 'adj.软弱的；松弛的；没气力的；不稳的', '1. The fellow was not as flabby as he looked and I began to fear I had met my match. 那家伙并非像他看上去那么弱。我开始担心自己是碰上了对手。 2. He\'s got soft and flabby since he gave up running. 他停止跑步锻炼以后肌肉就松弛了。 3. He\'s getting fat and flabby because he doesn\'t have enough exercise. 他因为缺少锻炼而日见肥胖肌肉松弛.', '副词: flabbily 比较级: flabbier 最高级: flabbiest 名词: flabbiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pristine', '[\'prɪstiːn]', 'adj.原始的；未受损的；清新的；纯朴的', '1. The jungle was pristine; it looked like no person had ever been there. 这个丛林是原始的,看起来像没有人到过那里。 2. The car is in pristine condition. 这辆汽车是全新的。 3. It is wondrously clean, emitting mainly pristine steam when burned. 它出奇的洁净，燃烧时排放出基本上是新鲜的蒸汽。 4. No man ever looks at the world with pristine eyes. 没有一个人以纯净而无偏见的眼光来看待世界。', '副词: pristinely');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malicious', '[mə\'lɪʃəs]', 'adj.怀恶意的；恶毒的', '1. He was bespattered by malicious gossip . 他遭到恶意的流言蜚语的诋毁。 2. This malicious and unprovoked attack astounded him. 这个恶意的无端攻击使他吃惊。 3. You ought to kick back at such malicious slander. 你应当反击这种恶毒的污蔑。 4. The girl\'s reputation was defiled by malicious gossips. 那位姑娘的名誉因为恶毒的流言蜚语而受损。', '副词: maliciously 名词: maliciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mediocrity', '[ˌmiːdi\'ɑːkrəti]', 'n.平常；平庸之才', '1. It\'s the difference between success and mediocrity. 这就是成功和平凡的区别。 2. You\'ll wind up a rich mediocrity. 你最后会成为富有的庸才。', '名词: mediocritization 名词复数: mediocrities 动词: mediocritize');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obtrude', '[əb\'truːd]', 'v.强使接受；打扰；闯入', '1. Don\'t obtrude your opinions on others. 不要把你的观点强加给别人。 2. I\'m sorry to obtrude on you at such a time. 我很抱歉在这个时候打扰你。', '名词: obtruder 过去式: obtruded 过去分词: obtruded 现在分词: obtruding 第三人称单数: obtrudes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forum', '[\'fɔːrəm]', 'n.讨论会；论坛', '1. This is a forum for education and technology. 这是一个有关教育和技术的讨论会。 2. I believe that this is the key issue of the Forum. 我相信,这个问题正是这次研讨会的要旨所在。 3. The letters page of this newspaper is a forum for public argument. 这份报纸的读者来信栏是公众意见的论坛。 4. Wonderful! I put it to the English forum. 太好了!我转到英文论坛去。', '名词复数: forums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('endemic', '[en\'demɪk]', 'adj.风土的；地方的 n.地方病；风土病', '1. Endemic diseases are common in this area. 这个地区地方病流行。 2. With the efforts for many years, great achievements have been made in the prevention of the endemic diseases. 经过多年的努力，地方病防治工作取得了很大成绩。', '副词: endemically 名词: endemism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plume', '[pluːm]', 'n.羽毛；羽饰；羽状物 v.整理羽毛；用羽毛装饰；骚首弄姿；自夸', '1. Her hat was decorated with a plume. 她帽子上装饰着羽毛。 2. The red plume on the horse\'s head was nodding to the rhythm of its steps. 马头上的红色羽饰随着马步的节律抖动着。 3. The tail is profusely coated and forms a plume. 尾巴毛量丰厚形成羽毛状。 4. If a plume blows out and rises, it can sink the ship. 如果羽状的烟雾窜出并且上升，将足以使船沉没。 5. The eagle plumed its wing. 鹰整理它翅膀上的羽毛。', '过去式: plumed 过去分词: plumed 现在分词: pluming 第三人称单数: plumes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('meritorious', '[ˌmerɪ\'tɔːriəs]', 'adj.值得嘉奖的', '1. His meritorious deeds are very moving. 他的先进事迹十分感人。 2. He was praised for his meritorious service. 他由于出色地工作而受到称赞。 3. He wrote a meritorious theme about his visit to the cotton mill. 他写了一篇关于参观棉纺织厂的有价值的论文。', '副词: meritoriously 名词: meritoriousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('supercilious', '[ˌsuːpər\'sɪliəs]', 'adj.目中无人的；高傲的', '1. I resent your supercilious and arrogant attitude. 我讨厌你这种目中无人的傲慢态度。 2. Parkman occasionally allows a supercilious tone to creep into his writing. 帕克曼间或在文章里流露了高傲的态度。', '副词: superciliously 名词: superciliousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slink', '[slɪŋk]', 'v.偷偷溜走；扭捏招摇地走；早产 n.早产的动物 adj.早产的', '1. The thief slunk down the dark alley. 那个贼偷偷钻进黑胡同里。 2. Don\'t slink away without apologizing. 不要不道歉就偷偷溜走。 3. The dog slunk out when I shouted at him. 我向那条狗一喊，它就溜出去了。 4. She was slinking around in a tight black dress. 她穿着黑色紧身连衣裙媚态十足地走来走去。', '副词: slinkingly 过去式: slunk/slinked 过去分词: slunk/slinked 现在分词: slinking 第三人称单数: slinks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trite', '[traɪt]', 'adj.平庸的；陈腐的', '1. For the rest, she was a strong-minded woman; never said a weak or a trite thing. 此外，她还是个意志坚强的女人，从来不说一句示弱或者平庸的话。 2. He ended his lecture with a trite morality. 他以陈腐的说教结束了演讲。', '副词: tritely 比较级: triter 最高级: tritest 名词: triteness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('depute', '[dɪ\'pjuːt]', 'v.委任；委托；派 ... 为代表或代理', '1. He deputed the running of the department to an assistant. 他把部门的管理工作委托给助手了。 2. We will depute your company as the sole operation agent in China. 我们将委托贵公司作为我公司在中国的独家业务代理。 3. They were deputed to put our views to the Parliament. 他们代表我们向议会表达我们的观点。', '过去式: deputed 过去分词: deputed 现在分词: deputing 第三人称单数: deputes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('florid', '[\'flɔːrɪd]', 'adj.过分装饰的；华丽的；红润的', '1. The senator gave a florid speech. 议员作了一番词藻华美的演说。 2. Nobody likes this florid style with little content. 没有人喜欢这种缺乏内容的华丽文风。 3. Do you like florid baroque architecture? 你喜欢华丽的巴洛克式建筑吗? 4. He was a good-looking man in a kind of coarse, florid way, aged about fifty. 他是那种粗糙的好看，面色红润健康的人，年龄大约在五十岁左右。', '副词: floridly 名词: floridity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('witticism', '[\'wɪtɪsɪzəm]', 'n.妙语；俏皮话', '1. He tries to lighten his lectures with an occasional witticism. 他有时想用俏皮话使课堂活跃。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rhubarb', '[\'ruːbɑːrb]', 'n.大黄；大黄的叶柄；激烈的争论', '1. I had rhubarb tart with a lot of cream. 我吃了添加了许多奶油的大黄小馅饼。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('settle', '[\'setl]', 'v.解决；定居；安顿；平静；结算 n.背长椅，座位；定居，安顿', '1. If you pay for both of us now, we can settle up later. 你要是现在先付清咱们两人的帐，事后咱们俩再细算。 2. An official mission was sent to settle the dispute. 一个官方使团被派去解决争端。 3. The two companies settled out of court. 两家公司在法院外了结了争端。 4. They moved the local people and settle them in another place. 他们把当地人迁移到别处定居。', '形容词: settleable 过去式: settled 过去分词: settled 现在分词: settling 第三人称单数: settles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gerontology', '[ˌdʒerən\'tɑːlədʒi]', 'n.老年学；老年病学', '1. Gerontology has suddenly become popular. 老年学突然变得受欢迎了。', '形容词: gerontological 名词: gerontologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('square', '[skwer]', 'n.正方形；广场；街区；平方；直角尺；<俚>古板的人 adj.正方形的；规矩的；结实的；公正的；断然的 v.一致；结清；收买；使 ... 成方形；使成平方；调整 adv.成直角；直接的；正方形地', '1. The little girl drew a square on the paper. 小女孩在纸上画了一个正方形。 2. Everybody goes to this vast square in the evening. 每天傍晚，人人都上这宽阔的广场上来。 3. The crowds in the square were elated by the news. 这消息使广场上的人群欢欣鼓舞。 4. 25 is a perfect square of 5. 25是5的完全平方。 5. A handkerchief is usually square. 手帕通常是正方形的。 6. His conduct does not square with his words. 他言行不一致。 7. The road turned square to the left. 这条路成直角向左转去。', '副词: squarely 比较级: squarer 最高级: squarest 名词: squareness 过去式: squared 过去分词: squared 现在分词: squaring 第三人称单数: squares');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agrarian', '[ə\'ɡreriən]', 'adj.土地的；耕地的 n.平均地权论者', '1. This was a feature of agrarian development in Britain. 这是大不列颠土地发展的一个特征。 2. In Lincoln\'s time the US was largely an agrarian society. 在林肯时代，美国大部分地区还是农业社会。 3. Since the agrarian reform polarization has taken place among the peasants 在土地改革后，农民发生了分化。', '副词: agrarianly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('regal', '[\'riːɡl]', 'adj.帝王的；尊贵的', '1. The scepter is a token of regal status. 节杖是王权的象征 2. The regal lady had made a deep impression on him. 那位雍容华贵的妇人给他留下了深刻的印象。', '副词: regally 名词: regality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pitiful', '[\'pɪtɪfl]', 'adj.慈悲的；可怜的；凄惨的', '1. The patient was in a pitiful condition. 那个病人处于一种非常可怜的状况。 2. What a pitiful man he is! You should help him. 多可怜的人啊 3. The ruined house after the earthquake looked a pitiful sight. 地震后倒塌的房屋一片凄惨景象。 4. I never saw a sight so pitiful as this before! 我从来没有见过这样惨的事情！', '副词: pitifully 名词: pitifulness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rubble', '[\'rʌbl]', 'n.瓦砾；碎石', '1. The explosion reduced the house to rubble. 爆炸把房子变成一堆瓦砾。 2. Firemen were still clearing rubble from apartments. 消防队员还在从单元房里清理出瓦砾。 3. The little statue was made of rubble. 这座小塑像是用碎石拼合起来的。 4. Li\'s arm became gangrenous after being crushed in the rubble. 李婉芝的手臂被压在碎石底下后来腐烂了。', '形容词: rubbly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('functionary', '[\'fʌŋkʃəneri]', 'n.(尤指政府；政党等的)官员；公务员', '1. Everything was not settled in the orders given by the State to the functionary! 政府对职员所下的命令并不都是确实可靠的! 2. The research on competitive mechanism of functionary institution is of great importance to better our civil service system. 研究我国公务员制度的任用和淘汰竞争机制对进一步完善我国公务员制度具有十分重要的现实意义。', '名词复数: functionaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wade', '[weɪd]', 'v.跋涉；涉水 n.跋涉', '1. I wade down a shallow pebbly stream daily. 我每天沿着一条浅的有卵石的小溪跋涉。 2. I assume that Wade discussed the quality issues with you. 我承担那跋涉与你讨论质量议题。 3. We\'ll wade the stream at its shallowest point. 我们将在小河最浅的地方涉水过去。 4. A child can wade across them without a parent\'s cautions. 无须父母的告诫，孩子们就可以涉水而过。 5. I wade down a shallow pebbly stream daily. 我每天沿着一条浅的有卵石的小溪跋涉。', '过去式: waded 过去分词: waded 现在分词: wading 第三人称单数: wades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carrion', '[\'kæriən]', 'n.腐肉 adj.腐肉的；以腐肉为生的', '1. Vultures usually feed on carrion or roadkill. 兀鹫通常以腐肉和公路上的死伤动物为食。 2. A crow of bloodthirsty ants is attracted by the carrion. 一群嗜血的蚂蚁被腐肉所吸引。 3. Carrion crows bewail the dead sheep and then eat them. 乌鸦吃死羊，先要哭一场。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('refugee', '[ˌrefju\'dʒiː]', 'n.难民', '1. The refugee was condemned to a life of wandering. 这个难民注定要过流浪的生活。 2. The refugee is is lodge in an old army camp. 难民暂时安置在一座旧军营里。 3. The television picture bring home to us all the plight of the refugee. 我们从电视上知道了难民所处的一切困境。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pose', '[poʊz]', 'v.摆姿势；把...摆正位置；造成；提出；假装 n.姿态；姿势；装腔作势', '1. Please sit still while you pose for your photo. 你摆好姿势拍照时请坐着别动。 2. The artist posed his model carefully. 这个艺术家仔细地把他的模型放好。 3. All the subjects are well posed. 所有的东西都摆好了位置。 4. Pollution poses a threat to the continued existence of this species. 污染对这一物种的继续生存造成了威胁。 5. She always liked to strike a noble pose. 她总是喜欢摆出一副高贵的样子。', '形容词: posable 过去式: posed 过去分词: posed 现在分词: posing 第三人称单数: poses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cronyism', '[\'kroʊniɪzəm]', 'n.任人唯亲', '1. The company was thought to be relatively free from the corruption and cronyism that had spread through Venezuela, fuelled by oil wealth. 在委内瑞拉这个以石油财富作为推动力的国家，人们认为该公司基本不存在席卷全国的贪污腐败和任人唯亲等弊病。 2. But several countries in Asia have grown rapidly at a time when cronyism was common, including Indonesia and South Korea in their time. 但是亚洲不少国家一度迅速增长之时，任人唯亲也很普遍，包括印尼和南韩当时都是如此。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('waspish', '[\'wɑːspɪʃ]', 'adj.易怒的；尖刻的', '1. Beware her waspish wit. 提防她的刻毒的妙语。 2. As this insightful, waspish book shows, the hidden similarities were greater than the visible differences. 正如这本深刻、尖锐的著作所指出的，暗藏的相似点大于可见的不同点。', '副词: waspishly 名词: waspishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hereditary', '[hə\'redɪteri]', 'adj.世袭的；遗传的', '1. That family is a hereditary ruler. 那个家族是世袭的统治者。 2. Pray for the salvation of Badawi, Razak and nine hereditary state sultans. 为巴达威及拉兹克及九位国家世袭的君王人选得救祷告。 3. I think such mental disorders are hereditary. 我认为这种精神失调是遗传的。 4. The rich were not a hereditary class, for most wealthy men were self-made. 富豪不是遗传的，大多数的有钱人是靠自己的努力。', '副词: hereditarily 名词: hereditariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('canonical', '[kə\'nɑːnɪkl]', 'adj.依教规的；圣典的；权威的；牧师的', '1. He was excommunicated because he violated canonical law. 他因违反教规被革出教派。 2. The construction is canonical in a sense. 这个构选法在某种意义上是标准的。 3. Every sentence has a canonical derivation. 每个句子都有一个规范推导。', '副词: canonically 异体字: canonic 名词: canonicity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('congruent', '[\'kɒŋgrʊənt]', 'adj.合适的；一致的；全等的', '1. But not all practices are congruent. 但不是所有的实践都是合适的。 2. And there are many areas of congruent interests. 而在其他诸多领域中，双方不乏和谐一致的利益。 3. In addition, care should be made to only use leverage which is congruent with your personal risk tolerance. 此外，应注意只使用了杠杆作用是相一致的个人风险承受能力。', '副词: congruently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interrogative', '[ˌɪntə\'rɑːɡətɪv]', 'adj.疑问的 n.疑问词；疑问句', '1. Please change the declarative sentence into an interrogative one. 请将这个陈述句变为疑问句。 2. Turn these sentences into interrogative. 把下列句子改成疑问句并回答。', '副词: interrogatively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gross', '[ɡroʊs]', 'adj.总的；粗鲁的；公然的；荒唐的；令人讨厌的 n.总量；总额 vt.总共赚得 adv.总共地', '1. The gross national product had increased 5 percent last year. 去年的国民生产总值提高了百分之五。 2. You can tell from his gross language that the man was uneducated. 从他那粗俗的语言可以看出，这个人没受过教育。 3. They were accused of gross negligence. 他们因公然渎职而被指控。 4. That is a gross distortion of the truth. 这是对真相的荒唐歪曲。 5. The goods are to be sold by the gross. 这些货物是要趸批出售的。 6. The new movie grossed an estimated $36.4 million at the box office. 这部新电影总共收获了3640万美元的票房成绩。 7. He earned $60,000 gross. 他总共赚了6万美元。', '副词: grossly 比较级: grosser 最高级: grossest 名词: grosser 过去式: grossed 过去分词: grossed 现在分词: grossing 第三人称单数: grosses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eclecticism', '[ɪ\'klektɪsɪzəm]', 'n.折衷主义', '1. This was a period of great eclecticism. 这是 一个重要的折衷主义的时期。 2. Decorations show the eclecticism of the global market. 装饰品表明全球市场的折衷和兼容。 3. In this, as in so many other realms, eclecticism is misplaced. 如此一来，正像其他许多领域一样，折衷主义行不通。 4. And all of the groups moved towards a broader eclecticism and synthesis. 所有的乐队都朝着更广泛的折衷主义和结合主义的方向前进。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suspense', '[sə\'spens]', 'n.悬疑；焦虑；悬念', '1. Suspense adds interest to a story. 故事中的悬疑情节更加引人入胜。 2. The movie kept the audience in suspense until the end. 那部电影让观众一直在悬疑之中直到最后。 3. Three thousand spectators waited in suspense on the White House lawn. 当时有三千观众怀着焦虑心情等待在白宫的草坪上。 4. She waited in an agony of suspense. 她在悬念的煎熬中等待着。', '形容词: suspenseful');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nonradioactive', '[\'nɒnreɪdɪə\'æktɪv]', 'adj.非放射性的', '1. How it works: A patient inhales haimless nonradioactive Xenon gas,which is tracked by a scanner as it enters the brain. 工作原理：病人吸人无害的、无放射性的氙气。氙气进人大脑后由扫描仪进行跟踪。 2. One drawback: a nonradioactive dye must be administered through the child\'s rectum before a CAT scan can be performed. 但是有一个缺点：在做CAT射线之前，必须用一种非放射性的染料给孩子的直肠染色。 3. How it works: A patient inhales haimless nonradioactive Xenon gas, which is tracked by a scanner as it enters the brain. 工作原理病人吸人无害的、无放射性的氙气。氙气进人大脑后由扫描仪进行跟踪。 4. British chemist and physicist.He won a1922Nobel Prize for developments that led to the discovery of isotopes in nonradioactive elements. 阿斯顿，弗朗西斯·威廉1877－1945英国化学家及物理学家。他因在非放射性元素的同位素的发现过程中取得重大进展而获1922年诺贝尔奖', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anomaly', '[ə\'nɑːməli]', 'n.异常；反常；不规则', '1. A cat with no tail is an anomaly. 没尾巴的猫是一只畸形猫。 2. NASA\'s system for tracking anomalies for flight readiness reviews failed. 在飞行准备阅兵式中，美国航空及太空总署的异常情况追踪系统失败了。 3. In those days, a woman professor was still an anomaly. 当时，女教授仍然是一种反常现象。 4. This should probably be considered an annoying anomaly rather than anything more significant. 这应该可能被看作是一个讨厌的不规则而非任何更有意义的事。', '形容词: anomalistic 副词: anomalistically 名词复数: anomalies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petrify', '[\'petrɪfaɪ]', 'vt.使石化；使发呆 vi.石化', '1. To convert to a mineral substance;petrify. 使成矿使转化为矿物质；使石化 2. To convert to a mineral substance; petrify. 使成矿使转化为矿物质；使石化 3. Redundant slogans are apt to petrify a man\'s thinking. 口号过多容易使人思想僵化。 4. A mutation of a gateway decoration. Uses Petrify attacks. 由凯旋门上的装饰品变化而来。使用可造成石化的攻击。', '过去式: petrified 过去分词: petrified 现在分词: petrifying 第三人称单数: petrifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vermin', '[\'vɜːrmɪn]', 'n.害兽；害鸟；害虫；害人虫', '1. On farms the fox is considered vermin. 在农场，狐狸被认为是害兽。 2. The room was crawling with vermin. 这房间里有害虫在爬。 3. He thought all terrorists were vermin and that prison was too good for them. 他认为所有恐怖分子都是害人虫，监狱对于他们来说都嫌太好了。', '名词复数: vermin');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('platitude', '[\'plætɪtuːd]', 'n.陈词滥调；平凡；陈腐', '1. It was a platitude to maintain the fiction that he was conferring a great boon on me. 这是一种陈腐的老生常谈，旨在维护似乎他给了我极大恩惠的假象。', '形容词: platitudinous 副词: platitudinously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('premium', '[\'priːmiəm]', 'n.额外费用；奖金；保险费 n.(商)溢价 adj.高价的；优质的', '1. Who will pay the premium for the risk of breakage? 加保破碎险的费用由谁负担? 2. A premium of 2 percent is paid on long-term investments. 对投资期限较长者可获百分之二的奖励。 3. He\'s had to lay his car up for he can\'t afford the insurance premiums. 因付不起保险费他只得把汽车搁置起来。 4. Shares are selling at a premium. 股票溢价出售。 5. People are prepared to pay premium prices for quality products. 人们已经作好为优质产品花费更多的准备。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('holocaust', '[\'hɑːləkɔːst]', 'n.大屠杀；浩劫；燔祭', '1. Suddenly there is a nuclear holocaust. 突然之间产生了一个核弹大屠杀。 2. He was a descendent of Holocaust survivors. 他是大屠杀幸存者的后代。 3. He predicted that there would be a world holocaust. 他预言将有一场世界性的浩劫。 4. I know this sounds like preparations for a nuclear holocaust, but the effects could be horrifyingly similar. 我知道这听起来一定像是为核浩劫提前准备，但其结果其实都挺恐怖的。', '形容词: holocaustal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scripture', '[\'skrɪptʃər]', 'n.经文 Scripture: 《圣经》；《圣经》中的一段.', '1. You\'ve read about them in scripture. 你曾经在经文中读到关于他们的事。 2. They invoked Hindu scripture to justify their position. 他们援引印度教的经文为他们的立场辩护。 3. He reads the Holy Scripture everyday. 他每天都读《圣经》。 4. negotiate these steps', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nethermost', '[\'neðəˌmoʊst]', 'adj.最低的；最下方的', '1. You are Ruarc the Barbarian, set to slay Azmoth, a demon that inhabits the nethermost catacombs. 很不错的角色探险游戏，可以收集武器、装甲和药水瓶对抗敌人。 2. Nethermost part, can use a few deeper color, or with flat or inclined chessboard case, the color that should have with clean closes suitably. 最下面的部分，可以用深一些的颜色，或用平直或斜的棋盘格，要和洁具的颜色相配合。 3. For a fire is kindled in My anger And burns unto nethermost Sheol. And it devours the earth and its produce And sets ablaze the foundations of the mountains. 22因为在我怒中有火烧起，直烧到极深的阴间，把地和地的出产尽都吞灭，山的根基也烧着了。 4. The CCD is constituted to is mainly from a mesh that is similar to the mosaic and gather the light mirror slice and mats in the nethermost electronics circuit matrix constitute. CCD 的组成主要是由一个类似马赛克的网格、聚光镜片以及垫于最底下的电子线路矩阵所组成。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ulcerate', '[\'ʌlsəreɪt]', 'v.溃烂；溃疡', '1. The infiltrated tissue is prone to ulcerate and the process may then cause some moderate pain or discomfort. 侵入的组织很容易溃烂和随后的过程可能导致某些中度疼痛或不适。 2. Aspirin can ulcerate the stomach lining. 阿司匹林能造成胃壁溃疡。 3. Regional lymph nodes become swollen and eventually ulcerate. 局部淋巴结先是肿胀而最后发生溃疡。', '形容词: ulcerative 过去式: ulcerated 过去分词: ulcerated 现在分词: ulcerating 第三人称单数: ulcerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('preclude', '[prɪ\'kluːd]', 'vt.阻止；排除', '1. That will preclude him from escaping. 那将阻止他逃走，那将使他无法逃走。 2. Their move does not preclude others from investing. 他们这一行动并不影响其他人进行投资。 3. My present finances preclude the possibility of buying a car. 按我目前的财务状况我是不可能买车的。 4. Small volume this year does not preclude huge volume next year. 今年业绩不多，不代表明年就一定会很少，', '形容词: preclusive 副词: preclusively 名词: preclusion 过去式: precluded 过去分词: precluded 现在分词: precluding 第三人称单数: precludes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repugnance', '[rɪ\'pʌɡnəns]', 'n.不一致；厌恶；反感', '1. He has a great repugnance to writing letters. 他非常厌恶写信。 2. The woman tried to fight down a feeling of repugnance to speak to her ex-husband. 那女人努力抑制反感来跟她前夫说话。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obliging', '[ə\'blaɪdʒɪŋ]', 'adj.乐于助人的 动词oblige的现在分词.', '1. He is a very obliging, amiable person. 他是一个非常乐于助人的和蔼可亲的人。 2. They were very obliging and offered to wait for us. 他们非常热情，主动提出等候我们。', '副词: obligingly 名词: obligingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('alacrity', '[ə\'lækrəti]', 'n.敏捷；活泼；乐意', '1. She sprang to the door with alacrity. 她敏捷地跳到门口。 2. Although the man was very old, he still moved with alacrity. 他虽然很老,动作仍很敏捷。 3. He accepted her offer with alacrity. 他欣然接受了她的建议。 4. He carved, and ate, and praised with delighted alacrity. 他边切边吃，又兴致勃勃地赞不绝口。', '形容词: alacritous');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('steep', '[stiːp]', 'adj.险峻的；陡峭的；急剧的、大起大落的 v.浸泡，浸透，湿透；沉浸，笼罩', '1. This hill is too steep to ride up on a bicycle. 这山太陡了，骑自行车可上不去。 2. The last part of the ascent is very steep. 最后一段上坡路很陡。 3. The bus toiled up the steep hill. 公共汽车艰难地爬上陡峭的山岗。 4. It’s priced at fifty pounds, and I think that’s a bit steep for a secondhand lawn mower. 那东西标价50英镑，而我认为对于一部二手货的割草机来说，那个价钱不合理。', '副词: steeply 比较级: steeper 最高级: steepest 名词: steepness 过去式: steeped 过去分词: steeped 现在分词: steeping 第三人称单数: steeps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lair', '[ler]', 'n.(野兽的)巢穴；(人的)藏身处', '1. A wounded wolf lay recovering in his lair. 受伤的狼躺在自己的巢穴里养伤。 2. The hunter trailed the beast to its lair. 猎人追捕野兽直到兽穴。 3. The kidnappers\' lair was an old farm in the hills. 绑架者的藏身处是一座山上的旧农场。 4. The police tracked the thieves to their lair. 警察跟踪小偷找到他们的巢穴。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assoil', '[ə\'sɔɪl]', 'vt.赦免；释放；补偿', '1. assoil one\'s fault 赎罪 2. assoil sb. of [from] sin 赦免某人的罪过', '过去式: assoiled 过去分词: assoiled 现在分词: assoiling 第三人称单数: assoils');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('attorney', '[ə\'tɜːrni]', 'n.(辩护)律师', '1. He became a prominent attorney. 他成了有名的律师。 2. His uncle obtained an attorney for him. 他的叔叔为他请了律师。 3. The attorney is working in a divorce case. 律师正忙于一个离婚案件。', '名词: attorneyship 名词复数: attorneys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('oddments', '[\'ɑːdməntz]', 'n.残余物；零头', '1. Just curtail the oddments and keep the integers. 去掉零头只保留整数就行了。 2. Cut the oddment, just remain the integer. 去掉零头只保留整数就行了。 3. Take out the oddment and hold the integer. 去掉零头只保留整数就行了。 4. It is ok to ake out oddment and keep whole numble. 去掉零头只保留整数就行了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('costume', '[\'kɑːstuːm]', 'n.服装；剧装 vt.提供服装；为 ... 设计服装 adj.服装打扮的', '1. This traditional costume is of indigo blue. 这件传统服装是靛蓝色的。 2. Her funny costume caused much mirthful laughter among the guests. 她那滑稽的服装引得客人哄堂大笑。 3. The kimono is part of the national costume of Japan. 和服是日本民族服装的一部分。 4. We patched up a costume for the play . 我们临时凑成了一件戏装。 5. Jane costumed a historical play. 简曾为一出历史剧设计服装。 6. A friend of mine was asked to a costume ball a short time ago. 不久前，我的一个朋友被邀请参加一个化装舞会。', '过去式: costumed 过去分词: costumed 现在分词: costuming 第三人称单数: costumes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('encomiast', '[ɪn\'koʊmɪæst]', 'n.宣读或写作颂辞之人；赞美者；阿谀者', '1. Since 90 time metaphase, globalization became the heat that people argues stage by stage, to the research manner of this problem, encomiast has, the; 自90年代中期以来,全球化逐步成为了人们争论的热点,对此问题的研究态度,赞美者有之,诅咒者也有之;', '形容词: encomiastic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dashing', '[\'dæʃɪŋ]', 'adj.时髦的；冲劲足的 动词dash的现在分词形式.', '1. He made dashing appearance. 他身穿时髦的服装当众露面。 2. She put the glasses on and felt very dashing, like an actress in the movies. 她戴上眼镜,觉得时髦得很,很象电影里的女明星。 3. His dashing spirit has diminished. 他的锐气消损了。 4. There are several dashing figures in the painting. 那幅画里画了几个雄纠纠的人。 5. Standing on the beach I saw a very big wave dashing over the boat. 站在海边，我看到一个大浪朝那条船扑去。', '副词: dashingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shimmer', '[\'ʃɪmər]', 'n.微光；闪光；摇曳的光 v.（使）闪烁；（使）发微光', '1. The colours that shimmer across its surface are unbelievable. 海面上泛着微光，闪烁着神奇的色彩。 2. Then everything began to shimmer and I slipped, fell back into my physical body. 一切开始发出微光，我感到自己在滑向自己的物质躯体。 3. The air began to bend and shimmer between the doctor and the startled soldiers. 在大夫和这惊呆了的卫兵们之间，空气开始弯曲，闪光。 4. It may slightly shimmer or sparkle, or look darker than a comparable screen. 可能这些颗粒还发出细微的闪光，或者看起来比一块可以比较的其他屏幕更暗。 5. The colours that shimmer across its surface are unbelievable. 海面上泛着微光，闪烁着神奇的色彩。', '形容词: shimmery 副词: shimmeringly 过去式: shimmered 过去分词: shimmered 现在分词: shimmering 第三人称单数: shimmers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yaw', '[jɔː]', 'v.(船、飞机等)偏航 n.偏航', '1. The ship yawed as the heavy wave struck abeam. 当巨浪向船舷撞击时,船开始左右摇摆。 2. We have got control problem, yaw damper inoperative. 我们操作系统故障，偏航阻尼器不工作了。', '过去式: yawed 过去分词: yawed 现在分词: yawing 第三人称单数: yaws');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diverge', '[daɪ\'vɜːrdʒ]', 'v.分歧；分叉；[数]发散', '1. Our views diverged so greatly that it was impossible to agree. 我们的观点存在着严重的分歧，绝无调和余地。 2. These figures and the last ones diverge greatly. 这些数字与上次的数字有很大差异。 3. The stream diverges here. 小溪在这儿分岔。 4. Unfortunately, the iteration is easy to diverge and difficult to control. 计算时若初始形状与找形形状差异较大，则会使迭代计算发散。', '过去式: diverged 过去分词: diverged 现在分词: diverging 第三人称单数: diverges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consolidation', '[kənˌsɒlə\'deɪʃən]', 'n.巩固；加强；统一；合并；联合', '1. Let\'s collect the sap before its consolidation into a hard mass. 让我们在树液坚固成团之前将之收集起来。 2. The State ensures the consolidation and development of the state-owned economy. 国家保障国有经济的巩固和发展。 3. Consolidation of standardized management for international income and related laws is urgent. 加强对国际所的规范管理,明确相关法律问题刻不容缓。 4. It should be noted that this concept of a unified multi-ethnic country consolidation and development are positive. 应该说,这种观念对统一多民族国家的巩固与发展是有积极意义的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sour', '[\'saʊər]', 'adj.酸的；酸腐的；刻薄的 v.变酸', '1. Most green fruit is sour. 大多数未熟的水果都是酸的。 2. The dish\'s gone sour. 这菜已经变质了。 3. He\'s always got a sour look on his face, and he has never said anything friendly. 他总是板着脸,从来不说一句好听的话。 4. The hot weather has soured the milk. 炎热的天气使牛奶变酸了。', '形容词: sourish 副词: sourly 比较级: sourer 最高级: sourest 名词: sourness 过去式: soured 过去分词: soured 现在分词: souring 第三人称单数: sours');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dissertation', '[dɪsər\'teɪʃn]', 'n.论文', '1. I\'m working my notes up into a dissertation. 我正在把我的笔记修改成论文。 2. I have not yet footnoted my dissertation. 我还没有给我的论文加上脚注。 3. She wrote a dissertation on superrealism. 她写了一篇关於超现实主义的论文。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fluffy', '[\'flʌfi]', 'adj.毛绒绒的；蓬松的；空洞的', '1. He found that fluffy puppy on the street. 他在路上捡来那只毛绒绒的小狗。 2. Dasey also was wearing fluffy pink slippers that Frank had given her. 德茜也喜欢穿毛绒绒的粉红色拖鞋，那是福兰克送给她的。 3. A fluffy gray mantle and patches of tall grass help a cub hide on the open savanna. 在辽阔开放的热带草原上，小猎豹可以凭借身上蓬松的灰色毛皮隐藏在长长的草丛中。 4. In this beautiful head study, you can easily see the exaggerated feathering that forms the fluffy coat. 你可以容易看出夸张的羽毛似的蓬松的毛发。', '副词: fluffily 比较级: fluffier 最高级: fluffiest 名词: fluffiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('queue', '[kjuː]', 'n.长队；行列；辫子 v.排队', '1. People had to stand in a queue for hours to buy a ticket. 人们买票得排几小时的队。 2. At the head of the queue was an old woman. 在队列的前面有一个老妇人。 3. It was quite easy to tell that this queue was false. 很容易看出这个辫子是假的。 4. We queued up for the bus. 我们排队等公共汽车。', '过去式: queued 过去分词: queued 现在分词: queuing 第三人称单数: queues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('droop', '[druːp]', 'v.低垂；下垂；(草木)枯萎；(精神)萎靡 n.下垂；消沉', '1. She sat there with her head drooping. 她垂着头坐在那儿。 2. She was so tired, her eyelids were beginning to droop. 她太疲倦了，眼睑开始往下垂。 3. The crops were drooping for want of water. 农作物缺水枯萎了。 4. His spirits drooped after he failed the exam. 在考试没能及格之后，他精神就萎靡了。 5. In the droop of her lip there was something sensuous. 在她那下垂的嘴唇上的确有点儿敏感的意味。', '形容词: droopy 副词: droopily 过去式: drooped 过去分词: drooped 现在分词: drooping 第三人称单数: droops');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('touchstone', '[\'tʌtʃstoʊn]', 'n.试金石；检验标准', '1. Love is the touchstone of virtue. 爱情是美德的试金石。 2. Adversity is man\'s true touchstone. 逆境是人真正的试金石。 3. The greatest touchstone of any work is time. 时间是检验一切的最好的试金石。 4. The touchstone of a contract is the notion of equality. 检验契约的标准是平等的观念。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('choke', '[tʃoʊk]', 'vi.窒息；阻塞；说不出话 vt.使窒息；阻塞；抑制；使说不出话 n.窒息；阻塞；阻风门', '1. She looked like she was going to choke. 她看起来仿佛都要窒息了。 2. She found it hard to choke down her anger. 她感到难以压下心中的怒火。 3. She choked with emotion. 她激动得说不出话来。 4. Very small toys can choke a baby. 很小的玩具可使婴儿窒息。 5. Very small toys can choke a baby. 很小的玩具可使婴儿窒息。', '过去式: choked 过去分词: choked 现在分词: choking 第三人称单数: chokes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consternation', '[ˌkɑːnstər\'neɪʃn]', 'n.惊愕；恐怖；惊惶失措', '1. Marie looked at her daughter with consternation. 玛丽惊愕地看着女儿。 2. To her consternation, he asked her to make a speech. 她感到惊慌的是他要求她发言. 3. I saw with consternation that she was in tears. 我惊恐地看到她泪流满面。 4. The company looked at each other in consternation. 人们神色惊奇面面相觑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mature', '[mə\'tʃʊr]', 'adj.成熟的；(保单）到期的；考虑周到的 v.成熟；长成', '1. This is the most mature of his plays. 这是他最成熟的一部剧作。 2. She swept her hair back, so she looks more mature than before. 她把头发往后梳，所以显得比以前成熟。 3. Your fixed account is mature and can be withdrawn any time. 您的定期存款已经到期了，随时可以提取。 4. Young as she is, she cares for others and has a mature mind. 她虽然年轻,但却很为他人着想,考虑周到。 5. Girls mature earlier than boys. 女孩比男孩成熟得早些。', '副词: maturely 比较级: maturer 最高级: maturest 名词: matureness 过去式: matured 过去分词: matured 现在分词: maturing 第三人称单数: matures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rejuvenate', '[rɪ\'dʒuːvəneɪt]', 'v. 使 ... 年轻； 使 ... 恢复精神； 变年轻', '1. The mountain air will rejuvenate you. 山上的空气将使你变得年轻。 2. Only barbarians are able to rejuvenate a world in the throes of collapsing civilization. 的确，只有野蛮人才能使一个在垂死的文明中挣扎的世界年轻起来。', '名词: rejuvenation 过去式: rejuvenated 过去分词: rejuvenated 现在分词: rejuvenating 第三人称单数: rejuvenates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vulnerable', '[\'vʌlnərəbl]', 'adj.易受伤害的；有弱点的；脆弱的', '1. Achilles was vulnerable only in his heel. 阿基里斯只有脚后跟会受伤害。 2. The potato is vulnerable to several pests. 马铃薯易受几种害虫的侵害。 3. Young birds are very vulnerable to predators. 幼小的鸟易受食肉动物伤害。 4. Satellites are as vulnerable as they are valuable. 卫星价值很大但也很脆弱。', '副词: vulnerably 名词: vulnerability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debilitate', '[dɪ\'bɪlɪteɪt]', 'vt. 使 ... 衰弱', '1. The patient had been so debilitate by the fever that he lacked the strength to sit up. 这病人因发烧而一直很虚弱，以至于连坐起来的力气都没有。 2. Her course of life had always been full of up’s and down’s, and she didn’t let another ‘down’ debilitate her. 她的一生饱经起起落落，再也不会为任何困难所屈服。 3. I understand then why the doctrines that explain everything to me also debilitate me at the same time. 于是，我认识到，为何向我解释一切的种种理论学说为什么会同时促进我的衰亡。 4. Too much activity tires the body; too many interests debilitate the mind; too many enemies weaken the psyche. You must limit your efforts. 太多行动使身体疲倦;太多影响使头脑虚弱;太多敌人使心智削弱。你必须限制你的努力。', '形容词: debilitative 名词: debilitation 过去式: debilitated 过去分词: debilitated 现在分词: debilitating 第三人称单数: debilitates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('profile', '[\'proʊfaɪl]', 'n.侧面；轮廓；形象；简介 v.描绘 ... 轮廓；评论人物', '1. I photographed him in profile. 我从侧面给他拍照。 2. She is prettier in profile than at full face. 她的侧面比正面好看。 3. We could see the profile of a distant hill if it is very clear. 如果天气晴朗, 我们可看到远山的轮廓。 4. The deal will certainly raise the company\'s international profile. 这宗交易肯定会提高这家公司的国际形象。 5. The huge trees were profiled against the night sky. 在夜空的映衬下显出大树的轮廓。', '名词: profiler 过去式: profiled 过去分词: profiled 现在分词: profiling 第三人称单数: profiles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('asunder', '[ə\'sʌndər]', 'adv.分离地；化为碎片', '1. Our opinions are wide as the poles asunder. 我们的意见截然相反。 2. Parents and children were driven asunder by the war. 父母和子女因战争而分离。 3. The limbs of the animal were torn asunder. 那动物的肢体已被撕裂。 4. The missile had blown the battleship asunder. 炮弹把战舰炸碎了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transitory', '[\'trænsətɔːri]', 'adj.暂时的；瞬息的；短暂的；片刻的', '1. Hunger may be long-term, or it may be transitory. 饥饿可能是长期的，也可能是暂时的。 2. These feelings tend to be transitory. 这些感觉多是暂时的。 3. We do not even have a transitory glimmer of hope. 我们连昙花一现的希望都没有。 4. Love is transitory but it is eternal. 爱情短暂却永恒。', '副词: transitorily 名词: transitoriness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trio', '[\'triːoʊ]', 'n.三个一组；三重唱（奏）', '1. Simply maneuver each stone pair or trio together in order for them to disintegrate. 无需苦思冥想，只需将石头弄成两个一双或者三个一组即可将其消除。 2. Soon the duet will become a trio. 很快地二重奏形成了三重唱。 3. An Italian trio was heading the bill at the charity event. 一个意大利三重唱在慈善晚会上领衔主演。', '名词复数: trios');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pugilism', '[\'pjuːdʒɪlɪzəm]', 'n.拳击；搏击', '1. The term pugilism is sometimes used for the sport. 拳击这个词经常用在体育中。', '形容词: pugilistic 名词: pugilist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('baste', '[beɪst]', 'v.疏缝；痛斥；大骂；润以油脂；涂以奶油', '1. They bast me without any reason. 他们无缘无故地大骂我。 2. Mother used a large spoon to baste the chicken. 母亲在鸡肉上润以一大匙的油脂。 3. You must baste the duck with its own fat every time you turn the duck. 每次转换位置时，必须在整只鸭上涂满鸭身渗出的油脂。', '名词: baster 过去式: basted 过去分词: basted 现在分词: basting 第三人称单数: bastes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aggregate', '[\'æɡrɪɡət]', 'adj.合计的；总的 n.总计；进球总数；集料 v.（使）聚集；总计', '1. What were your aggregate wages last year? 去年你的工资一共是多少? 2. The cause of unemployment was inadequate aggregate demand. 失业的原因在于总需求不足。 3. Manager wants to know the aggregate sales in that market. 经理想知道那个市场的总销售量。 4. The tax increases will, in the aggregate, cause much hardship. 增加税收归结起来将造成很多困难。 5. Occasionally the cells might aggregate to form lentoid bodies. 偶而，细胞能聚集形成类晶体球体。', '形容词: aggregative 副词: aggregately 名词: aggregation 过去式: aggregated 过去分词: aggregated 现在分词: aggregating 第三人称单数: aggregates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prognosis', '[prɑːɡ\'noʊsɪs]', 'n.预断病情；预后；预测', '1. The prognosis depends on the source of the vertigo. 对于病情的预判要视形成眩晕的原因而定。 2. The medical prognosis was not good. 医疗预后不良。 3. The prognosis for the future of the electronics industry is encouraging. 预测电子工业的前途一片大好。 4. The prognosis for the economy is uncertain. 对经济的前景预测还不确定。', '名词复数: prognoses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amnesia', '[æm\'niːʒə]', 'n.健忘症；记忆缺失', '1. A bump on the head caused her amnesia. 她因头部撞了一下而得了健忘症。 2. Past-hypnotic amnesia frequently occurs. 经常会发生催眠术后的健忘症。', '形容词: amnestic 名词: amnesiac');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('steer', '[stɪr]', 'v.操纵；驾驶；掌舵；引导', '1. Sometimes an oar is used to steer a boat. 有时桨用以操纵小舟。 2. He steered the car skillfully through the narrow streets. 他熟练地驾驶着汽车穿过狭窄的街道。 3. People used to steer by the stars. 过去人们常常参照星星的方位来驾驶。 4. The old man settled himself to steer. 老人坐定下来掌舵。', '形容词: steerable 名词: steerer 过去式: steered 过去分词: steered 现在分词: steering 第三人称单数: steers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gloaming', '[\'ɡloʊmɪŋ]', 'n.黄昏', '1. The square tower of a church loomed through the gloaming. 在薄暮中隐约可以看见一个教堂的方塔。 2. In the gloaming, the crows flew in to gather for the night in a stand of bare oaks. 薄暮时分，鸦群飞向光秃秃的橡树枝条上过夜。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('equate', '[i\'kweɪt]', 'v.同等看待；等同；使相等', '1. He equates poverty with misery. 他认为贫穷就是不幸。 2. You can\'t equate the education system of Britain to that of Germany. 不能把英国教育制度与德国教育制度等同起来。 3. We must not equate thrift with stinginess. 我们不能把勤俭和吝啬等同起来。 4. It \'s impossible to equate wealth and happiness . 财富与幸福无法等同。', '过去式: equated 过去分词: equated 现在分词: equating 第三人称单数: equates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skit', '[skɪt]', 'n.滑稽短剧；讽刺文章', '1. They performed a skit to amuse the crowd. 他们表演了一个幽默小品来娱乐观众。 2. The comic skit sent up the foolishness of young men in love. 那幅漫画把沉溺于热恋中的男子的痴态勾勒得滑稽可笑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('denote', '[dɪ\'noʊt]', 'vt.表示；象征', '1. A smile often denotes pleasure and friendship. 微笑常常表示高兴和友善。 2. These nouns denote a state of joyful exuberance. 这些名词都指示洋溢着欢乐的状态。 3. Dark clouds denote a coming storm. 黑云表明风暴要来临。 4. We often denote danger by red letters. 我们常常用红字表示危险。', '形容词: denotable 过去式: denoted 过去分词: denoted 现在分词: denoting 第三人称单数: denotes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stagger', '[\'stæɡər]', 'vi.蹒跚；犹豫；动摇 vt.使摇晃；使吃惊；使犹豫 n.蹒跚；踌躇；摇摆不定', '1. She staggered and fell. 她踉跄了几步，跌倒在地。 2. The drunk man staggered across the room. 那个醉汉摇摇晃晃地穿过房间。 3. His resolution had begun to stagger. 他的意志开始动摇了。 4. Such a heavy load would stagger an elephant. 这么重的担子，大象担着也得摇晃。 5. He gave a stagger on hearing the news. 他听到这一消息两腿摇晃起来。', '形容词: staggery 名词: staggerer 过去式: staggered 过去分词: staggered 现在分词: staggering 第三人称单数: staggers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hideous', '[\'hɪdiəs]', 'adj.丑陋的；可怕的；可憎的；令人惊骇的', '1. They wear hideous clothes to cover their mostly monstrous bodies. 他们穿着丑陋的衣服以便掩盖畸形的身躯。 2. As punishment, she transformed him into a hideous beast and placed a spell on everyone in the castle. 为了惩罚王子，她把王子变成了一头丑陋的野兽，还对城堡里的每个人都施了魔法。 3. The hideous tale made the children cry. 那个可怕的故事把孩子们吓哭了。 4. I had walked straight into a hideous trap. 我一下子踏进了一个可怕的陷阱里。', '副词: hideously 名词: hideosity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bulldoze', '[\'bʊldoʊz]', 'v.（用推土机）推平某物；强迫；强力推动某物；毁坏；威胁', '1. They bulldozed me into signing the agreement. 他们胁迫我签约。 2. The area was bulldozed to make way for a new road. 那片地已被推土机推平用以修筑新路。', '过去式: bulldozed 过去分词: bulldozed 现在分词: bulldozing 第三人称单数: bulldozes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inept', '[ɪ\'nept]', 'adj.不适当的；无能的；笨拙的', '1. Only inept officials would burden children with such a requirement rather than install speed bumps, others insisted. 另有人认为，只有无能的官员才会用这样的规定来加重孩子们的负担，而不采取安装减速装置。 2. Why do you give me this tainted Apocrypha, this thousandth copy, this inept falsification? 为什么给我这本污损过的伪经，这第一千次的抄本，笨拙的伪造？', '副词: ineptly 名词: ineptness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('permeate', '[\'pɜːrmieɪt]', 'v.弥漫；渗透；普及', '1. His subtle satisfaction seemed to permeate the space around them. 他难以捉摸的满足感好像弥漫在了他们的周围。 2. If your wine is still, pour it into the centre of the glass to let the bouquet permeate the vessel. 如果是无汽泡的酒，直接倒入杯子中央，使酒的香气充分散发，弥漫整个酒杯。 3. Water will permeate blotting paper. 水能渗透吸水纸。 4. Functional relationships permeate every part of science. 函数关系渗透自然科学的每个部分。', '形容词: permeant 名词: permeation 过去式: permeated 过去分词: permeated 现在分词: permeating 第三人称单数: permeates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eaglet', '[\'iːɡlət]', 'n.小鹰', '1. The eagle\'s egg hatched along with the other eggs in the prairie chicken\'s nest, and the little eaglet grew up with the other baby birds. 这只鹰蛋和其他许多松鸡蛋一起在松鸡窝里被孵化出来，小鹰和小松鸡们一起长大了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('encyclopedic', '[ɪnˌsaɪklə\'piːdɪk]', 'adj.百科全书的；知识渊博的', '1. This dictionary contains over 2,000 individual encyclopedic topics. 这本词典包括了超过2000条独立的百科全书式主题。 2. She has a Blackwell Encyclopedic Dictionary of Operations Management. 她有一本《布莱克韦尔运筹管理百科辞典》。 3. She has an encyclopedic knowledge of natural history. 她具有广博的自然史知识。 4. Possessing encyclopedic knowledge, he is fully capable of doing this job. 他是一个博闻强识的人，可以胜任这份工作。', '副词: encyclopedically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pertinacious', '[ˌpɜːrtn\'eɪʃəs]', 'adj.执拗的；顽固的；坚持的', '1. She is the most vocal and pertinacious of all the critics of the policy. 在所有的政策批评家中，她是陈词最多而且最为固执的。 2. His style of argument in meetings is not so much aggressive as pertinacious. 他在会议上的辩论态度并非锋芒逼人而是坚持己见。', '副词: pertinaciously 名词: pertinaciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anemia', '[ə\'niːmiːə]', 'n.贫血；贫血症', '1. The doctors analyzed the blood sample for anemia. 医生们分析了贫血的血样。 2. Anemia is frequently seen in advanced disease. 贫血在进展期中最常见。 3. Low consumption of iron can cause anemia, but I don\'t think that\'s the case here. 铁摄入量不足容易造成贫血症，但我想这不是问题所在。 4. Victims of this disease suffer from a severe and usually fatal anemia. 这种疾病的患者常患严重的，往往是致命性的贫血症。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bawl', '[bɔːl]', 'v.大叫；大哭；大声训斥 n.叫骂声；放声痛哭', '1. He bawls at me across the street. 他在街道的另一边冲我大声喊。 2. Don\'t bawl like that, I can hear you. 那别样大喊大叫了,我能听见。 3. Oh, hush ! You know how I hate people who bawl all the time. 哦，你不要闹啊！我就最恨动不动就哭的人。 4. The sergeant bawled out a command to his men. 那个中士向士兵大声发令。 5. A good bawl usually makes her feel better. 一场号哭通常会使她好过些。', '名词: bawler 过去式: bawled 过去分词: bawled 现在分词: bawling 第三人称单数: bawls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('visage', '[\'vɪzɪdʒ]', 'n.脸；面貌；容貌', '1. Jack gets blushed at once as if his visage is palled with a piece of red cloth. 杰克登时感到脸上一阵发热，好像蒙上一块红布。 2. China has emerged with a new visage in the East. 中国以新的面貌出现在世界的东方。 3. His visage is a fine and venerable one. 他的容貌很漂亮，很可敬。 4. She is always wimpled that no man can see her visage. 她总是用包头巾围包著，没有任何男人能看见她的容貌。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intermission', '[ˌɪntər\'mɪʃn]', 'n.中止；中断；停顿；幕间休息', '1. Her fever lasted five days without intermission. 她连续五天一直发烧。 2. Drills were set to work without intermission. 螺旋钻在一刻不停地挥舞着。 3. The violinist resumed playing after the intermission . 幕间休息之后,那小提琴手又重新开始演奏。 4. We had a short intermission halfway through a film. 我们电影放映中途做了短暂的休息。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sentiment', '[\'sentɪmənt]', 'n.情绪；感情；观点；感伤', '1. He could feel the sentiment stirring within him. 他可以感觉到这种情绪在心中波动。 2. His speech loosed a tide of nationalist sentiment. 他的讲话表露出一种强烈的民族主义情绪。 3. He could not adequately express his sentiment. 他无法恰当地表达出他的感情。 4. What are his sentiments on this issue? 他对这个问题持什么观点？', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pontificate', '[pɑːn\'tɪfɪkeɪt]', 'v.武断地或自封为权威地谈论某事物 n.(教皇的)职位或任期', '1. Politicians like to pontificate the reason about falling standards. 政治家喜欢自大地表示下降标准的原因。 2. He sat there pontificating about the legal system although it was clear that he knew very little about it. 他坐在那儿发表他对法制的高论，虽然他对此一窍不通。 3. His was the second-longest pontificate. 他任职教宗时间是第二长的。 4. The central meaning of his pontificate is to restore papal authority 他任职教皇的中心意图就是要恢复教皇权力', '名词: pontification 过去式: pontificated 过去分词: pontificated 现在分词: pontificating 第三人称单数: pontificates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('speck', '[spek]', 'n.斑点；灰尘；污点；少量 v.用斑点标记', '1. You can\'t eat bread covered with dark specks. 你可不能吃满是黑斑的面包啊。 2. I\'ve got a speck in my left eye. 我左眼里掉进一颗灰尘。 3. There\'s not a speck of dust in their house. 他们的屋里没有一点儿灰尘。 4. He looked at a speck on the window glass. 他看着窗玻璃上的一个污点。', '过去式: specked 过去分词: specked 现在分词: specking 第三人称单数: specks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fledgling', '[\'fledʒlɪŋ]', 'n.刚会飞的幼鸟；尚缺乏经验的人 adj.刚开始的；无经验的 =fledgeling.', '1. The pressure on the fledgling entrepreneur is intense. 这个没有经验的企业家压力很大。 2. China\'s fledgling gold market is still evolving. 中国的初期黄金市场仍在发展中。 3. The fledgling man always offends his boss. 这个没经验的人总是顶撞他的老板。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('histrionic', '[ˌhɪstri\'ɑːnɪk]', 'adj.做作的；表演的；戏剧的', '1. The improvement of parents\'breeding model can prevent histrionic personality disorder. 改善父母的养育方式可以预防表演型人格障碍。 2. She had never forgotten her one histrionic achievement in Chicago. 她从未忘记过她在芝加哥的那一次成功的演出。 3. Don\'t ever tell me any more that a nigger ain\'t got any histrionic talent. 别再告诉我说黑奴没有演戏的天才啦。', '副词: histrionically 异体字: histrionical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illusory', '[ɪ\'luːsəri]', 'adj.虚幻的；幻觉的', '1. The certainties proclaimed by Newton mechanics are illusory. 由牛顿力学所表明的确定性是一种错误。 2. Its the same with all the illusory worlds we see in the higher dimensions. 我们在高境界看所有的虚幻世界,也是像这样。 3. I am afraid this hope is illusory. 恐怕这个愿望只是幻想。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sledge', '[sledʒ]', 'n.雪橇；大锤 v.用雪橇搬运；坐雪橇；用大锤敲打 =sleigh(英)；sled(美).', '1. The sledge coasted down the mountain slope. 雪橇滑下山坡。 2. The sledge gained momentum as it ran down the hill. 雪橇从山上下冲时动量越来越大。 3. As far as Christmas presents were concerned, the family agreed that Aunt Helen had hit the bull\'s eye by giving them a sledge. 谈到圣诞礼物，全家都认为海伦姑妈说到点子上了，那就是送给他们一付雪橇。 4. I smashed it with a sledge hammer. 我用大锤把它敲烂了。 5. The stones were brought by boat from the mountains and pulled from the coast by sledge to the site. 巨石从大山里开采出来后,先用船只运抵海岸,然后再利用撬具从海岸运到现在的地址。', '过去式: sledged 过去分词: sledged 现在分词: sledging 第三人称单数: sledges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gratuitous', '[ɡrə\'tuːɪtəs]', 'adj.无缘无故的；无必要的；免费的', '1. I did not want to be singled out for gratuitous punishment. 我不愿意被叫出来遭受这无缘无故的惩罚。 2. His films are full of gratuitous violence. 他拍的影片充满了不必要的暴力。 3. His criticism is quite gratuitous. 他的批评完全没有根据。', '副词: gratuitously 名词: gratuitousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('access', '[\'ækses]', 'n.入口；通道 n.接近(的机会)；使用之权 vt.进入；(电脑)存取', '1. This is the only means of access to the building. 这是进入这栋楼的唯一入口。 2. The avalanche cut off the access to the mountain village. 雪崩切断了进入山村的通道。 3. The only access to that building is along the track. 到那座大楼的唯一通道就是沿这条小路走。 4. Only high officials have access to the president. 只有高级官员才可以接近总统。 5. An error occurred when we tried to access the inventory database. 当我们试图进入存货数据库时，屏幕上显示出现了错误。', '过去式: accessed 过去分词: accessed 现在分词: accessing 第三人称单数: accesses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marked', '[mɑːrkt]', 'adj.有记号的；显著的；受监视的 v.弄污；打分；留意；做标记（动词mark的过去式和过去分词）', '1. They set a trap for him by putting marked money in to the till. 他们把有记号的钱放在钱屉里，设圈套抓他。 2. The voltage values at the marked locations should be measured and recorded. 应当把有记号处的电压值测量并记录下来。 3. They have made marked achievements in all fields. 他们在各个领域都取得了显著的成绩。 4. The output of cars shows a marked increase over last year. 汽车的产量比较去年有显著的增长。', '副词: markedly 名词: markedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petal', '[\'petl]', 'n.花瓣', '1. A petal fluttered to the ground. 一片花瓣飘落到地上。 2. The doorway is shaped like a moon, a vase or a flower petal. 门洞有的像月亮有的像花瓶还有的像花瓣。', '形容词: petaled');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('homiletics', '[ˌhɒmə\'letɪks]', 'n.讲道术；说教术', '1. J.Deane, homiletics by T.Whitelaw. 第 9 笔 Ecclesiastes / exposition by W. 2. L.Alexander, homiletics by C.Clemance. 第 10 笔 Deuteronomy / exposition by W. 3. Payne Smith, homiletics by C.Chapman. 第 11 笔 Samuel / exposition by R. 4. Jenkins. (Both are said to have sold in the tens of millions.) And if you can sprinkle your homiletics with scientistic jargon, so much the better. 如果你的教材里可以再点缀些科学术语，效果就会更好。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('safeguard', '[\'seɪfɡɑːrd]', 'n.保卫者；保护措施 vt.保卫；保护', '1. There is no safeguard against inappropriate data types being added. 没有保护措施来防止添加不适当的数据类型。 2. We must safeguard our national interests. 我们必须保卫国家的利益。 3. To safeguard the peace is one of the important tasks of the army. 军队的重要任务之一是保卫和平。 4. Safeguard records from damage or deterioration. 保护以防记录损坏或变质。', '过去式: safeguarded 过去分词: safeguarded 现在分词: safeguarding 第三人称单数: safeguards');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fidget', '[\'fɪdʒɪt]', 'vt.使坐立不安 vi.坐立不安 n.烦躁；烦躁之人', '1. Some people stare at their screen and fidget. 有些人盯住屏幕，坐立不安。 2. Presently he began to fidget on his seat. 接着他就坐立不安起来。 3. You\'ll fidget, and you\'ll be tempted to light up. 您会烦躁不安而且有点燃香烟的冲动。 4. They tend to fidget and lose focus easily. 他们容易烦躁，精力不够集中。', '过去式: fidgeted 过去分词: fidgeted 现在分词: fidgeting 第三人称单数: fidgets');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('luxury', '[\'lʌkʃəri]', 'n.奢侈品；奢侈；豪华', '1. The increasing sale of luxury goods is an index of the country\'s prosperity. 奢侈商品销售量日增是该国繁荣的标志。 2. The government has imposed strict controls over the import of luxury goods. 政府对奢侈品的进口采取了严格的管制。 3. If he can afford a luxury yacht, then a fortiori he can afford to pay his debts. 他若能买得起豪华的快艇，就更能匀出钱来还债了。 4. In old society, the gentry lived in luxury. 在旧社会，贵族们生活奢侈。', '名词复数: luxuries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('optimism', '[\'ɑːptɪmɪzəm]', 'n.乐观；乐观主义', '1. A mood of optimism pervaded the gathering. 会上充满乐观的气氛。 2. We view these changes with guarded optimism. 我们以审慎的乐观看待这些变化。 3. They professed optimism about the outcome. 他们对结果表示乐观。 4. We are influenced by his radiant optimism. 他那具有感染力的乐观主义影响了我们。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('buttress', '[\'bʌtrəs]', 'n.扶墙；拱壁 v.支持', '1. He was a buttress against extremism in the party. 他是党内反对极端主义的中坚分子. 2. I don\'t think they have any buttress behind them. 我认为他们背后没有什么支持力量。 3. To stabalize the building, the concrete walls next to the stairs are built as buttress walls. 为了稳定整个建筑，靠近楼梯位置的混凝土墙设置了扶壁柱。 4. He buttressed up the argument with lots of solid facts. 他以大量确凿的事实支持这个论点。', '过去式: buttressed 过去分词: buttressed 现在分词: buttressing 第三人称单数: buttresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('persistence', '[pər\'sɪstəns]', 'n.坚持；毅力', '1. The art of love is largely the art of persistence. 爱的艺术在很大程度上就是坚持的艺术。 2. Energy and persistence conquer all things. 能量和坚持可以征服一切事情。 3. Persistence is one of your greatest assets in life. 努力不懈、坚持到底，是人生最大的资产。 4. Persistence is the direct result of habit. 恒心毅力是习惯的直接产物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incur', '[ɪn\'kɜːr]', 'vt.招致；遭受；惹起', '1. Your despite at him will incur his revenge. 他会因你的藐视态度而报复你的。 2. If you don\'t do the job properly, you will incur blame. 如果你不把工作做好,你将会招人责难。 3. A slowdown in the economy caused us to incur great losses. 经济的减缓使我们遭受了很大的损失。 4. He incurred substantial losses during the stock market crash. 他在股市猛跌时蒙受了巨大的损失。', '过去式: incurred 过去分词: incurred 现在分词: incurring 第三人称单数: incurs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obligation', '[ˌɑːblɪ\'ɡeɪʃn]', 'n.义务；责任', '1. We are invited, but we are under no obligation to go. 我们是被邀请了,但并不意味着我们有义务一定要去。 2. Some people suggest that the old people\'s children have the obligation to look after their old parents. 一些人认为：老年人的子女有义务照看他们的父母。 3. I have an obligation to keep secret for the taxpayer. 我有责任为纳税人保密。', '形容词: obligational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('josh', '[dʒɑːʃ]', 'v.<口>说笑；戏弄 n.无恶意的戏虐；玩笑', '1. \"There was glass flying all over the place, \" she said. \"I got hit in the head by something. I looked down and saw Josh holding his chest. I was kind of scared because the way he was holding his chest I didn\'t think he was going to make it.\" \"玻璃到处乱飞，\"她说。\"我的头不知被什么打中。我低头一看，乔希用手抚着胸口。他抚住胸口的样子令我有些害怕，我想他恐怕撑不过去。\"', '副词: joshingly 名词: josher 过去式: joshed 过去分词: joshed 现在分词: joshing 第三人称单数: joshes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('auction', '[\'ɔːkʃn]', 'n.拍卖 vt.拍卖', '1. We will put the car up for auction. 我们将把这辆小车拍卖。 2. The picture should fetch 2000 pounds at auction. 这张画拍卖可得2000英镑。 3. We had a private view of the jewels before the public auction. 那些珠宝公开拍卖以前我们私下看了预展。 4. They will auction off a collection of oils. 他们将拍卖一批收藏的油画。', '过去式: auctioned 过去分词: auctioned 现在分词: auctioning 第三人称单数: auctions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inert', '[ɪ\'nɜːrt]', 'adj.无行动的；惰性的；迟钝的', '1. She lay there inert, I thought she must be dead. 她躺在那儿一动不动，我想她一定是死了。 2. Stone is an inert mass of matter. 石头是一块无生命的物体。 3. Helium and neon are inert gases. 氦和氖为惰性气体。 4. He stood inert as the car came towards him. 汽车朝他开来时,他还呆呆地站著。', '副词: inertly 名词: inertness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reshuffle', '[ˌriː\'ʃʌfl]', 'v.重新洗牌；改组 n.改组；重新安排', '1. So as to prevent cheating, he was asked to reshuffle the cards. 为了防止作弊，他重新洗牌。 2. The CEO decided to reshuffle the company\'s top management. 执行长决定对公司管理高层进行改组。 3. Who let out the details of the reshuffle in the department? 是谁泄漏了部门重组的细节? 4. The prime minister hinted at a possible reshuffle of the cabinet. 首相暗示内阁可能要进行改组。', '过去式: reshuffled 过去分词: reshuffled 现在分词: reshuffling 第三人称单数: reshuffles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('equilibrium', '[ˌiːkwɪ\'lɪbriəm]', 'n.平衡；均衡；平静', '1. He lost his equilibrium and fell into the lake. 他失去平衡，跌进湖里。 2. We have achieved an equilibrium in the economy. 我们已在经济上达到平衡。 3. He can\'t maintain enough equilibrium to ride a bike. 他骑自行车不能保持平衡。 4. We must try to maintain the equilibrium of supply and demand. 我们必须努力保持供求均衡。', '名词复数: equilibriums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amulet', '[\'æmjʊlət]', 'n.护身符', '1. Around the man\'s neck was his father\'s amulet. 那个人的脖子上还带着他父亲的护身符。 2. We\'re down here investigating a stolen amulet. 我们来到这里调查一个失窃的护身符。 3. The amulet she is wearing has been blessed by eminent monks. 她戴的那个护身符，是经过寺院高僧开光的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spasmodic', '[spæz\'mɑːdɪk]', 'adj.间歇的；痉挛的；突发性的', '1. Their benevolence took spasmodic forms. 他们的善心忽冷忽热。 2. There\'s a spasmodic nature to Chinese history. 中国人历史的一种间歇性的本性。 3. Our body\'s spasmodic response to tickling is beyond our control. 我们的身体对痒的痉挛反应是超逾我们所能控制的。 4. Mr Marvel was suddenly whirled about and started marching off in a curious spasmodic manner. 马弗尔先生突然兜了个圈子，古怪地，痉挛地走开了。', '副词: spasmodically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('taut', '[tɔːt]', 'adj.拉紧的；绷紧的；紧张的；整洁的', '1. If a bow-string is too taut, it will snap. 拉得太紧，弓弦就会断。 2. The lovely mouth was taut with irony. 漂亮的嘴讥讽地绷紧着。 3. He had a taut expression on his face, apparently very angry. 他脸紧绷绷的，像很生气的样子。 4. As she rubbed those taut muscles, she hummed and prayed. 她一边蹭着紧张的肌肉，一边嘟嘟囔囔地祈祷着。', '副词: tautly 比较级: tauter 最高级: tautest 名词: tautness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vaporize', '[\'veɪpəraɪz]', 'v.（使）蒸发 =vaporise（英）', '1. The heat from the water is used to vaporize a low-boiling liquid. 从水中得到的热用来使一种低沸点的液体蒸发。 2. Particles moving at these speeds vaporize if they hit any other material. 微粒以这样的速度撞上任何其他物质会被蒸发掉。', '形容词: vaporizable 名词: vaporization 过去式: vaporized 过去分词: vaporized 现在分词: vaporizing 第三人称单数: vaporizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('critic', '[\'krɪtɪk]', 'n.评论家；批评家', '1. She is a very discerning art critic. 她是位眼光敏锐的艺术评论家。 2. He has a reputation for being a forthright critic. 他是以直率著称的评论家。 3. Have you read the article written by that famous critic? 你读过那个著名的批评家写的这篇文章吗？ 4. A critic is a man whose watch is five minutes ahead of other people\'s watch. 批评家，是一个他的表要比别人的表快上五分钟的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slight', '[slaɪt]', 'adj.轻微的；纤弱的；微小的 vt.轻视；忽略 n.轻蔑；怠慢', '1. He has a slight wheeze in his chest. 他呼吸时胸部发出轻微的响声。 2. Our army suffered a slight reverse. 我们的部队受到轻微的挫败。 3. The salve will heal slight burns. 这药膏能治疗轻微烧伤。 4. Her slight frame was shaken by bouts of coughing. 她纤弱的身躯因阵阵咳嗽而发颤。 5. We shouldn\'t slight anybody even if he\'s a nobody. 我们不应该轻视任何人，即使他是一个小人物。 6. I was hurt by the obvious slight. 这种明显的怠慢伤害了我的感情。', '比较级: slighter 最高级: slightest 名词: slightness 过去式: slighted 过去分词: slighted 现在分词: slighting 第三人称单数: slights');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deserter', '[dɪ\'zɜːrtər]', 'n.背弃者；逃兵；擅离职守者', '1. They officially and personally regarded De Gaulle as a deserter. 他们官方和私人方面皆视戴高乐谨系一流亡者。 2. He is a craven deserter. 他是个胆小的逃兵。 3. The deserter has escaped. 那名逃兵已经逃走。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fancied', '[\'fænsɪd]', 'adj.空想的；虚构的；受喜爱的 动词fancy的过去式和过去分词.', '1. Fancied wealth sank out of sight. 空想出来的财富已经消失不见。 2. The country is now the fancied land of milk and honey. 那个国家现在成了人们向往的安乐乡。 3. They thought that America was the fancied land of milk and honey. 他们过去认为美国是牛奶和蜂蜜的天堂。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gracile', '[\'græsəl]', 'adj.细长的；纤弱的；优美的', '1. Clinopodium gracile(Benth.)Matsum. 瘦风轮 2. Gracile levers and springs oscillate in discreet elegance, following the program of the column wheel in their motion. 在轻盈地摆杆和弹簧优美而柔和的摆动中,控制轮也跟着发挥其作用。 3. The processing technology of a health beverage by using Balsam pear, Honeysuckle and Lophatherum gracile Brongn as raw materials was studied. 研究以苦瓜、金银花、淡竹叶为主要原料加工制成一种新型保健饮料的工艺,并对苦瓜汁澄清,金银花、淡竹叶的浸提和产品配方等工艺条件进行了探讨。 4. The best concentrations of balsam pear juice, honeysuckle extract, Lophatherum gracile Brongn extract and sirup were 25%, 1.5%, 1% and 8%, respectively. 最佳配比为25%25苦瓜汁、1.;5%25金银花浸出汁、1%25淡竹叶浸出汁、8%25糖浆。', '名词: gracility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assault', '[ə\'sɔːlt]', 'n.攻击；突袭；抨击 vt.袭击；突袭', '1. Trainee commandos are put through an exhausting assault course. 受训的突击队员要参加令人筋疲力尽的突击课程。 2. The court determined that the man was guilty of assault. 法庭裁定那个人犯了侵犯人身罪。 3. A deep, wide ditch, usually filled with water, typically surrounding a fortified medieval town, fortress, or castle as a protection against assault. 护城河一条深而宽的、通常有水沟环绕设防的中世纪城镇城堡或堡垒，用以抵抗外来袭击 4. The article was a vicious assault on Bell\'s integrity. 这篇文章是对贝尔完整性的恶劣抨击。 5. Six women have been sexually assaulted in the area recently. 最近这一带有六个女子遭受强奸猥亵。', '名词: assaulter 过去式: assaulted 过去分词: assaulted 现在分词: assaulting 第三人称单数: assaults');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vantage', '[\'vɑːntɪdʒ]', 'n.优势；有利情况', '1. The famous athlete had no vantage to win the game. 那个有名的运动员已经没有优势赢得那场比赛了。 2. Maybe it is bad to them, but it is just our vantage. 或许对他们是坏事，但对我们正是优势。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('institution', '[ˌɪnstɪ\'tuːʃn]', 'n.制定；制度；机构；名流', '1. The institution of school rules is necessary. 制定学校规则的是很有必要的。 2. Marriage is an institution in most societies. 婚姻是大多数社会早已确立的制度。 3. Marriage is love. Love is blind. Therefore marriage is an institution for the blind. 婚姻就是爱情,爱情是盲目的,所以婚姻是一所收容盲人的机构。 4. My uncle has become quite an institution at the club. 我叔叔在俱乐部里已是颇有名气的人物了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('balloon', '[bə\'luːn]', 'n.气球；球状物 vt.使膨胀 vi.乘气球飞行；激增；如气球般膨胀 adj.气球状的', '1. A balloon floated across the sky. 有个气球从空中飘过。 2. He balloons his cheeks when he is hesitant. 他迟疑不决时会鼓起双颊。 3. He tried to balloon around the earth but storms forced him to land in China. 他试图乘气球做环球旅行，但风暴迫使他降落在中国。 4. Our expenses had ballooned. 我们的开销大大增加了。', '名词: balloonist 过去式: ballooned 过去分词: ballooned 现在分词: ballooning 第三人称单数: balloons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anaerobic', '[ˌæne\'roʊbɪk]', 'adj.厌氧的', '1. The anaerobic exercise is good for your muscle. 无氧运动有助于锻炼肌肉。 2. The anaerobic breakdown of glucose is called glycolysis. 厌氧分解葡萄糖称为酵解。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('integral', '[\'ɪntɪɡrəl]', 'adj.完整的；构成整体所必需的 n.[数] 积分；完整', '1. The transit line is an integral transportation link for the 2010 Winter Olympics. 该隧道是温哥华为2010年冬季奥运会打造的一条完整地下线路。 2. The kitchen is an integral part of a house. 厨房是房子不可缺的部分 3. These policies form an integral whole. 这是很完整的。 4. The bodies of the carts were integral, that is made of one moulding. 马车的车身是完整的，而且是根据同一个模型做出来的。', '副词: integrally 名词: integrality');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('endure', '[ɪn\'dʊr]', 'vt.容忍 vi.忍耐；持久；持续', '1. I could not endure the insolence of his behaviour. 我不能再忍受他那傲慢无礼的行为了。 2. I cannot endure listening to that any longer. 我再也不耐烦听那一套了。 3. If help doesn\'t come,we must endure to the end. 如果没人来帮助,我们必须忍耐到底。 4. They vowed their love would endure forever. 他们海誓山盟地久天长。', '过去式: endured 过去分词: endured 现在分词: enduring 第三人称单数: endures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loaf', '[loʊf]', 'n.（一条）面包；块 vi.游手好闲；虚掷光阴', '1. That small loaf won\'t go far among this large family! 那一小条面包全家人吃不了多久的。 2. He bought a loaf of bread. 他买了一大块奶酪。 3. He used to loaf about and ultimately took to drink. 他过去终日游手好闲，最终沉溺于酗酒。 4. Those who loaf all day and do nothing are social parasites. 饱食终日，无所事事的人是社会上的寄生虫。', '名词复数: loaves 过去式: loafed 过去分词: loafed 现在分词: loafing 第三人称单数: loafs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('negligence', '[\'neɡlɪdʒəns]', 'n.疏忽；不修边幅；渎职', '1. He was sharply reprimanded for his negligence. 他因玩忽职责而受到严厉的申斥。 2. The accident was due to her negligence. 这次事故是因她疏忽所致。 3. His negligence was nothing less than criminal. 他的粗心大意无异於犯罪。 4. He dressed with easy negligence. 他穿着潇洒随便。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expostulate', '[ɪk\'spɑːstʃuleɪt]', 'v.规劝；告诫；抗议', '1. They expostulated with him about the risks involved in his plan. 他们指出他的计划有风险，劝他放弃。', '形容词: expostulatory 名词: expostulation 过去式: expostulated 过去分词: expostulated 现在分词: expostulating 第三人称单数: expostulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('literati', '[ˌlɪtə\'rɑːti]', 'n.文人；文学界；学者(复数)', '1. Each Kunqu play was an exquisite literary work by some lofty-minded literati. 昆曲的剧本大都是文人雅士精心创作的文学作品。 2. This development serves as an opportunity for the literati here. 这个发展是这儿的文坛的机遇。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crease', '[kriːs]', 'n.折痕；皱痕；(板球球手位置的)界限线 v.起皱；弄皱；使某人乐不可支', '1. he had a sharp crease in his trousers. 他裤子上有一条明显的折痕。 2. She made a crease in the paper and carefully tore it in two. 她在纸上留下一道折痕，然后小心地把它撕成两半。 3. You\'ve got a crease in your dress where you\'ve been sitting. 你把衣服坐出了一条皱痕。 4. The flaps of his jacket pocket were sewn down so that they did not crease or wrinkle. 他的夹克口袋上的口袋盖给缝上了，这样就不会打皱。', '形容词: creaseless 名词: creaser 过去式: creased 过去分词: creased 现在分词: creasing 第三人称单数: creases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crypt', '[krɪpt]', 'n.土窖；地穴；(教堂的)地下室 n.[解剖学]小囊；腺窝 pref.隐藏的；秘密的（=crypto)', '1. Crypt Fiend pathing size slightly increased. 地穴恶魔的碰撞体积稍微增大。 2. Isabel will have to fight the restless spirits who haunt the crypt in order to get the artifact. 为得到宝物，伊莎贝尔必须与那些游荡在地穴中无法安息的鬼魂作战。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transgress', '[trænz\'ɡres]', 'v.违背；越界；违法', '1. His behavior transgressed the moral rules of the social conduct. 他的行为违背了社会行为的道德准则。 2. Her behavior transgressed all boundaries of good taste. 她的行为越了雅的界限。 3. No one is permitted to have privileges to transgress the law. 不允许任何人有超越法律的特权。', '形容词: transgressible 副词: transgressively 名词: transgressor 过去式: transgressed 过去分词: transgressed 现在分词: transgressing 第三人称单数: transgresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('plethora', '[\'pleθərə]', 'n.过量；多血症', '1. The report contained a plethora of detail. 报告中细节过多。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('presenter', '[prɪ\'zentər]', 'n.主持人；提出者；呈献者', '1. They\'re trying out a new presenter for the show. 他们正在为这个节目试用一位新的主持人。 2. Spencer Keith is a local radio presenter and Beatles historian. 斯宾瑟基斯是位当地电台主持人，和研究披头四合唱团的历史学家。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insurrection', '[ˌɪnsə\'rekʃn]', 'n.叛乱；暴动', '1. The insurrection was easily suppressed. 那次叛乱很快就被平定了。 2. It organized an insurrection against the aggressors. 它组织了一个反对侵略者的起义。 3. In all countries any person who incites others to insurrection is guilty of treason. 在任何国家里，煽动他人谋反者，都属犯叛国罪。 4. The insurrection can create the conditions. 暴动会创造这些条件。', '形容词: insurrectional 名词: insurrectionism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reclaim', '[rɪ\'kleɪm]', 'v.收回；回收；纠正；开垦', '1. After he stopped paying the hire purchase installment, the finance company tried to reclaim his car. 在他停止支付租购分期付款后，该金融公司试图收回他的汽车。 2. You may be entitled to reclaim some of the tax you paid last year. 你或许有权要求退回去年你交付的部分税金。 3. Their daily work is to reclaim rubber from old tyres. 他们的日常工作是用旧轮胎再生橡胶。 4. It is incumbent on me to reclaim him. 劝他改过是我义不容辞的义务。', '形容词: reclaimable 名词: reclaimant 过去式: reclaimed 过去分词: reclaimed 现在分词: reclaiming 第三人称单数: reclaims');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('restless', '[\'restləs]', 'adj.不安宁的；焦虑的；得不到休息的', '1. His father, a Virginian, was a restless man. 他的父亲是弗吉尼亚人，从不安于现状。 2. His manacled hands were restless in his lap. 他那双上了铁镣的手在膝盖上不知放在哪里才好。 3. The audience was becoming restless. 观众渐渐地不耐烦了。 4. After only a month in the job, he felt restless and decided to leave. 那工作他只干了一个月就厌倦了，决定不干了。', '副词: restlessly 名词: restlessness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flammable', '[\'flæməbl]', 'adj.易燃的；可燃性的 n.易燃品', '1. Hydrogen gas is extremely flammable. 氢气是特别易燃的气体。 2. Sunbeams may focus through the bauble and ignite flammable material. 阳光会在球体上聚焦,点燃可燃性材料。', '名词: flammability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('veterinary', '[\'vetərəneri]', 'adj.兽医的 n.兽医', '1. A veterinary surgeon\'s services will be necessary to file the teeth correctly. 正确地磨平牙齿，对于一个兽医的服务来说，那是必需的。 2. Veterinary advice must be obtained without delay as a course of injectable antibiotic will usually be necessary. 由于通常需要注射抗生素，必须马上获得兽医的建议。 3. A veterinary surgeon is a doctor of a sort. 兽医是一类医生。 4. Aloe Veterinary Formula is an animal\'s best friend. 芦荟宠物喷剂是动物最好的朋友。', '名词复数: veterinaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('charitable', '[\'tʃærətəbl]', 'adj.仁慈的；(为)慈善事业的；宽恕的', '1. Acting under the cloak of charity, he made a good income for himself from the gifts of charitable people. 他打着办慈善事业的幌子，用慈善家们的捐献中饱私囊。 2. Charity is a kind of salvation, and now it\'s even more to charity as the spirit of self-redemption, to participate in charitable initiative getting higher and higher. 慈善是一种救赎，如今的人们更把慈善作为自我精神的救赎，参与慈善事业的积极性越来越高。', '副词: charitably 名词: charitableness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rudder', '[\'rʌdər]', 'n.舵；方向舵；指导原则', '1. The wood rudder of the ship was broken. 船的木头舵坏了。 2. Without a rudder the ship was not navigable. 这船没有舵无法驾驶。 3. The rudder of that ship suddenly failed. 那艘船的方向舵突然失灵了。 4. A life without a purpose is a ship without a rudder. 没有目标的生活好比没有船舵的船。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kinetic', '[kɪ\'netɪk]', 'adj.运动的；动力学的', '1. Kinetic energy is a scalar property of motion. 动能是运动的一种标量属性。 2. Bodies traveling in a gravitational field are always undergoing an exchange of gravitational and kinetic energy. 在重力场中运动的物体会不停地改变其动能与重力位能。 3. By the research of the ethylene slurry polymerization mechanism and kinetics, the corresponding kinetic and moment ordinary differential equations were built and solved. 在研究了淤浆法乙烯聚合反应机理与动力学的基础上，建立并求解了相应的动力学与矩常微分方程组。', '副词: kinetically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('desirous', '[dɪ\'zaɪərəs]', 'adj.渴望的；想要的', '1. We are desirous of peace. 我们渴望和平。 2. Jane was desirous of meeting her mother . 珍渴望见到她的妈妈。 3. I am desirous to know further details. 我想要知道更多的细节。 4. She has always been desirous of fame. 她一直想成名。', '副词: desirously 名词: desirousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vault', '[vɔːlt]', 'n.窖；穹；地下室；撑竿跳 vt.做成圆拱形；撑竿跳跃 vi.跳跃', '1. He was buried in the family vault. 他被安葬在家庭的墓穴里。 2. In medieval times, poets often called the sky \"the vault of heaven\". 在中世纪时期，诗人常把天空叫作“苍穹”。 3. She put her jewels in a vault at the bank. 她将珠宝放在银行的金库里。 4. This underground vault is theftproof. 这所地下保管库是防盗的。 5. I don\'t think I can vault over. The wall is so high. 我想我跳不过去，这墙太高。', '名词: vaulter 过去式: vaulted 过去分词: vaulted 现在分词: vaulting 第三人称单数: vaults');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scrimp', '[skrɪmp]', 'v.节省；过度缩减；吝啬', '1. They scrimp on oil as much as they can during the energy crisis. 他们在能源危机时期尽量节省汽油。 2. She have to scrimp and save to pay for her holiday. 她必须节省开支以支付度假的费用。 3. Time for yourself is often where most people tend to scrimp. 通常大多数人留给自己的时间很少。', '形容词: scrimpy 名词: scrimper 过去式: scrimped 过去分词: scrimped 现在分词: scrimping 第三人称单数: scrimps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('classify', '[\'klæsɪfaɪ]', 'vt.分类；归类', '1. The books in the library are classified by subject. 图书馆的书是按科目分类的。 2. We can classify these subjects under three headings. 我们可以将这些题目加以分类成三个主题。 3. Would you classify her novels as serious literature or other? 你认为她的小说属于文学类，还是其它类? 4. It is entirly proper to classify Kant as a transcendental idealist. 把康德化归类为先验的唯心主义者是完全正确的。', '形容词: classifiable 过去式: classified 过去分词: classified 现在分词: classifying 第三人称单数: classifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('uphold', '[ʌp\'hoʊld]', 'v.支持；维护；维持；举起', '1. Eight columns uphold the big dome. 八根柱子支撑着这个大圆顶。 2. The President swore to uphold the constitution. 总统宣誓维护宪法。 3. He proffered to uphold justice. 他表示愿意维护正义。 4. The judge upheld the lower court\'s decision. 法官维持初级法院的判决。', '名词: upholder 过去式: upheld 过去分词: upheld 现在分词: upholding 第三人称单数: upholds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('redemptive', '[rɪ\'demptɪv]', 'adj.救赎的；买回的；赎身的', '1. We understand how great he is because of his redemptive work. 我们了解了祂救赎之功的伟大。 2. Continuing to work with the faith that honor in suffering is redemptive. 坚持以受苦为荣的信念来工作是一种赎罪。 3. God has redemptive purposes in mind which will ultimately lead to Satan\'s defeat. 神的心意是救赎，这救赎至终会把撒但彻底击败。', 'none');
