INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mutinous', '[\'mjuːtənəs]', 'adj.暴动的；反叛的', '1. The mutinous sailors were marooned on an island. 这些参加暴动的海员被放逐到一个孤岛上。 2. Mutinous farm animals run off their oppressor to establish a livestock utopia. 暴动的农场家畜们逃离了它们的压迫者建立起一个家畜乌托邦。 3. My baby was a mutinous child. 我的孩子是个不听话的孩子。 4. The mutinous children refused to obey the rules. 有反抗心理的孩子们拒绝遵守规章制度。', '副词: mutinously 名词: mutinousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beckon', '[\'bekən]', 'v.召唤；吸引；示意某人按自己的指示行动', '1. He beckoned to me from across the street. 他在马路对面向我招手致意。 2. This distant land of deep spirituality, legendary art, architecture, and dramatic scenery beckon the explorer. 这片遥远的乐土以深沉的灵性、传奇的艺术、建筑，以及富有戏剧色彩的风光召唤四方八面的探险家。 3. She crooked her finger to beckon him. 她勾勾手指向他示意。 4. Surrounded by many acres of car parks, laden with costly merchandise from all over the world, America\'s malls beckon with glitter and lights. 美国商场四周是大面积的停车场,从世界各地来的昂贵商品琳琅满目,闪烁的灯光吸引着顾客。', '副词: beckoningly 名词: beckoner 过去式: beckoned 过去分词: beckoned 现在分词: beckoning 第三人称单数: beckons');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('capsize', '[\'kæpsaɪz]', 'v.倾覆；翻转', '1. I try to navigate my little craft so as not capsize before either. 我驾驶着小舟在二者之间小心航行，以免被其中一股狂风颠覆。 2. In fact, it may be good to practice this maneuver until you capsize a few times. 事实上，它可能是很好的做法这个动作，直到您倾覆了几次。 3. The boat capsized in heavy seas. 船在大海中倾覆了。 4. A sudden strong wind capsize their boat. 突然一阵强风弄翻了他们的船。', '过去式: capsized 过去分词: capsized 现在分词: capsizing 第三人称单数: capsizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sere', '[sɪə]', 'adj.干枯的；演替系列 =sear.', '1. The desert was edged with sere vegetation. 沙漠周围零星地长着一些干枯的植被。 2. A sere on uncovered rock is a lithosere. 在光秃岩石上的演替系列是岩生演替系列。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elixir', '[ɪ\'lɪksər]', 'n.长生不老药；仙丹妙药', '1. The legend goes that there was a magician who could produce elixir. 相传这里曾有位术士能炼长生不老金丹。 2. He kept the elixir in a box while he went hunting and told his wife not to open it. 当他外出狩猎的时候,他把仙丹放在一个盒子里并且叮嘱他妻子不要打开它。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sybaritic', '[ˌsɪbə\'rɪtɪk]', 'adj.奢侈享乐的', '1. A chinchilla robe of sybaritic lavishness was draped over the bed. 奢华的栗鼠皮毛毯覆盖在床上。 2. Learn to see beyond the appearance of a sybaritic, luxurious dinner table, the masked presence of guts and mutilated cadavers. 学习看到在奢侈豪华的餐桌外表之下的，这个伪装着的贪婪表现着的正是在销毁尸体。 3. Napping is too luxurious, too 9)sybaritic, too unproductive, and it\'s free;pleasures for which we don\'t pay make us anxious. 午睡太奢侈，太逸乐，太浪费时间了，而且，这种享乐是免费的，这可让人心里总觉得不踏实。 4. Beirut, Lebanon. Despite the uncertainty in the air and armed troops on the streets, the city clings tenaciously to its sybaritic appeal. 黎巴嫩的贝鲁特。尽管空气中充满了不确定的气息，街上的有持枪的军队，这座城市吸引人的是他奢华的生活风气。', '副词: sybaritically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('infraction', '[ɪn\'frækʃn]', 'n.违反；违法', '1. You make it sound like a traffic infraction. 你说起来像只是违反了交通规则。 2. He was criticized for his infraction of the discipline. 他因违反纪律而受到了批评。 3. He had just committed a terrible infraction of the law. 他犯了可怕的违法的罪行。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('instrumentalist', '[ˌɪnstrə\'mentəlɪst]', 'n.乐器演奏家；乐器家；工具主义者 adj.工具主义的', '1. My younger brother wants to be an instrumentalist. 我弟弟想当一个器乐演奏家。 2. An instrumentalist believes that ideas are instruments of actions. 工具主义者认为思想是行为的工具。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cactus', '[\'kæktəs]', 'n.仙人掌', '1. We have to water this cactus once a month. 我们必须每月给仙人掌浇一次水。 2. The candy made from cactus tastes strange. 用仙人掌做的糖果味道很怪。', '名词复数: cacti');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('collected', '[kə\'lektɪd]', 'adj.收集成的；镇定的 动词collect的过去式和过去分词.', '1. With Nokia Device Status, you can save all the collected information to a file, and you can send the file to customer care services for closer inspection and analysis. 借由诺基亚装置状态,你能将所有收集到的数据保存到一个文件,并且将文件发送至客户服务部进行进一步的检测分析。 2. If he were insane, he was a very cool and collected insanity. 如果他发了疯，他也是个非常冷静和镇定的疯子。 3. I turned my eyes from him, fixed them on the fire, and tried to assume and maintain a quiet, collected aspect. 我眼睛避开他,去盯着看火,竭力摆出和保持一副安静和镇定的样子。', '副词: collectedly 名词: collectedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imprecise', '[ˌɪmprɪ\'saɪs]', 'adj.不精确的', '1. Their assumptions are imprecise. 他们的假设是不精确的。 2. The terms he used were imprecise. 他用的术语不确切。', '副词: imprecisely 名词: imprecision');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diversity', '[daɪ\'vɜːrsəti]', 'n.多样性；差异', '1. We should get a thorough understanding about the cultural diversity of the United States. 我们应该对美国文化的多样性有一个全面的了解。 2. Diversity is conducive to the learning environment. 多样化对学习环境确有益处。 3. India has huge diversity and could evolve into a trading club and become rich. 印度国内差异巨大,完全可能演变成一个自由贸易俱乐部,最终实现致富。', '名词复数: diversities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('animus', '[\'ænɪməs]', 'n.基本态度；主导精神；敌意；[心理]（女性人格中的）男性基质', '1. They are full of animus towords us. 他们对我们怀有敌意。 2. His criticisms are clearly colored by animus. 批判明显带有敌意。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stylus', '[\'staɪləs]', 'n.铁笔；尖笔；唱针', '1. The stylus is traveling in groove. 唱针正循着唱片纹路移动。', '名词复数: styluses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('demented', '[dɪ\'mentɪd]', 'adj.发狂的；[医]精神错乱状态的', '1. He writes in despair, and the result is a demented book. 他是在绝望中写作的，写出来的是一本疯狂的书。 2. When her child was two hours late, she became quite demented. 她孩子晚了两个小时，她心急如焚。 3. If you can grow new neurons, you might be able to rewire demented brains. 如果病人能够长出新的神经元，那么就有可能给痴呆的大脑更换设施。 4. No one knows for certain the identity of this masked and demented murderer. 没人知道这个带着面具、精神错乱杀手的真实身份。', '副词: dementedly 名词: dementedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('implicate', '[\'ɪmplɪkeɪt]', 'vt.牵涉；意味着；暗示', '1. His enemies tried to implicate him in the murder. 他的仇人竭力想把他牵扯进谋杀案中。 2. He was deeply implicated in the plot. 他与该阴谋牵涉颇深。 3. His absence implicates disagreement. 他的缺席意味着他不同意。 4. The results implicate poor hygiene as one cause of the outbreak. 这些结果说明卫生条件差是疾病流行的一个原因。', '过去式: implicated 过去分词: implicated 现在分词: implicating 第三人称单数: implicates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malleable', '[\'mæliəbl]', 'adj.可塑的；易改变的；有延展性', '1. Lead and tin are malleable metals. 铅和锡是可锻的金属。 2. The human brain is almost infinitely malleable. 人类大脑具有无限的可塑性。 3. The young are more malleable than the old. 年轻人比老年人容易受影响。 4. Every time we recall a long-term memory, it becomes malleable. 每次我们想起一个长期的记忆，它会变得有延展性。', '副词: malleably 名词: malleability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hedgehog', '[\'hedʒhɔːɡ]', 'n.刺猬', '1. We found a little hedgehog in the field. 我们在田里发现了一只小刺猬。 2. A hedgehog often contracts its body into a ball. 刺猬常常把它的身体收缩成一个圆球。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('static', '[\'stætɪk]', 'adj.静态的；静止的；稳定的；静力的；静电的 n.静电；静电干扰', '1. The winking eye is implemented as a series of static images. 眨动的眼睛是用一系列静态图像实现的。 2. Such principles as self-government, or freedom, or social welfare, are not static but dynamic. 自治,自由,或社会福利等原则并非静止,而是变动的。 3. House prices, which have been static for several months, are now rising again. 房价稳定了几个月，现在又上涨了。 4. Static friction is greater than sliding fricton. 静摩擦力大于滑动摩擦力。 5. Her hair was full of static. 她的头发上静电很强。', '形容词: statical 副词: statically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('isotope', '[\'aɪsətoʊp]', 'n.同位素', '1. The isotope ratio is directly used for comparing oils or gases. 同位素比率直接用于比较各种石油或天然气。 2. Changes of nuclear mass and nuclear size cause isotope shifts. 原子核质量和大小的不同引起同位素移动。', '形容词: isotopic 副词: isotopically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tornado', '[tɔːr\'neɪdoʊ]', 'n.龙卷风；飓风；旋风', '1. The entire village was obliterated by the tornado. 整个村庄被龙卷风摧毁了。 2. The tornado cut a swath through the town. 龙卷风袭击该镇,留下一长条破坏的痕迹。 3. When a tornado touches the ground, it does a lot of damage. 当飓风到达地面时，它会带来许多灾难。 4. The ruin of the house was caused by a violent tornado. 一阵猛烈的旋风把房屋卷倒了。', '形容词: tornadic 名词复数: tornadoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('horology', '[hə\'rɑːlədʒi]', 'n.测时法；钟表制造术', '1. One who practices or is skilled in horology. 钟表专家进行钟表制造或精于钟表制造的人 2. The appearance of radio-controlled clock is a revolution in the history of the horology. 电波钟表技术和产品的出现是人类计时历史上的又一次革命。 3. Horology - Functional and non-functional jewels 计时仪器。功能和非功能宝石 4. Precision engineering techniques and horology; 精密机械技术和钟表制造术;', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hemophilia', '[ˌhiːmə\'fɪlɪə]', 'n.血友病', '1. Adapt the World Hemophilia Day theme to further your own needs. 调整世界血友病日的主题以发展你们自己的需求。 2. Another example is the collapse of the Romanov dynasty in Russia, which was due to hemophilia in the family. 另一个例子是俄国罗曼诺夫王朝的灭亡，这也是由于家族中出现了血友病。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lank', '[læŋk]', 'adj.瘦的；细长的；长而柔软的', '1. Lank and floppy hair. 直而松软的长发 2. The old man has lank hair. 那位老人头发稀疏。', '副词: lankly 比较级: lanker 最高级: lankest 名词: lankness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bruit', '[bruːt]', 'vt.散播', '1. Much bruit, little fruit. 讲空话，不办实事。 2. It\'s been bruited about that ... 到处传播 ... 3. The news of the impending marriage was bruited abroad. 婚期临近的消息传遍了各处。', '过去式: bruited 过去分词: bruited 现在分词: bruiting 第三人称单数: bruits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prototype', '[\'proʊtətaɪp]', 'n.原型；范例；雏形', '1. The strange mechanical device is the prototype of modern cars. 这个奇怪的机械装置是现代汽车的原型。 2. Designers have built a working prototype of the car. 设计者已经制造了汽车的工作原型。 3. This is the prototype for future school buildings. 这是未来的学校建筑的蓝本。 4. He is the prototype of good breeding. 他是具有良好教养的典范。', '形容词: prototypal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adhesive', '[əd\'hiːsɪv]', 'adj.有粘性的；难忘的 n.粘着剂', '1. He also invented the adhesive postage stamp. 他还发明了粘性邮票。 2. The adhesive will stick to most clean surfaces. 粘胶剂会粘在非常清洁的表面。 3. You need a strong adhesive to bond wood to metal. 需要强力胶才能把木料粘在金属上。', '副词: adhesively 名词: adhesiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tureen', '[tju\'riːn]', 'n.有盖汤盘', '1. In answer to the ring, appeared a page boy with a silver soup tureen. 按过铃，一个小男仆就捧了一只盛汤的银器进来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('substratum', '[\'sʌbstreɪtəm]', 'n.基础；根据；下层；底层', '1. The story has a substratum of truth. 这故事有事实的基础。 2. There is a substratum of truth in her story. 她叙述中有事实根据. 3. The soil has a substratum of rock. 这土壤下面有层石头。', '形容词: substrative 名词复数: substrata');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('turgid', '[\'tɜːrdʒɪd]', 'adj.(语言或风格等)浮夸而晦涩的；膨胀的', '1. That was really a turgid and incoherent presentation. 那场介绍着实华而不实，语无伦次。 2. The flowers are still crisp and turgid. 花朵尚处于鲜嫩，饱满状态。 3. They were shocked by the turgid waters of the Thames. 上涨的泰晤士河水把他们吓了一跳。', '副词: turgidly 名词: turgidity');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('component', '[kəm\'poʊnənt]', 'n.零部件；元件；组成部分；成分 adj.组成的；构成的', '1. The factory supplies components for the car industry. 该工厂向汽车业供应零部件。 2. Each of the components is useful in its degree. 每一个元件都各有程度不同的用处。 3. The militia is a component of the state\'s armed forces. 民兵是国家武装力量的组成部分。 4. A chemist can seperate a medicine into its components. 化学家能把一种药物的各种成分分解出来。 5. Can you resolve it into its component elements? 你能把它分解为组成它的元素吗?', '形容词: componential');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rewarding', '[rɪ\'wɔːrdɪŋ]', 'adj.有报酬的；有益的；值得的 动词reward的现在分词.', '1. Teaching is not very financially rewarding. 教书不会有很高的报酬。 2. Gardening is a very rewarding pastime. 园艺劳动是非常有益的消遣。 3. It is very rewarding to keep a diary of daily happenings. 把每天发生的事情记一下日记非常有益。 4. She finds motherhood very rewarding. 她认为做母亲得偿所愿。', '副词: rewardingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tattered', '[\'tætərd]', 'adj.破烂的；衣服褴褛的 动词tatter的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. He persists in wearing his tattered overcoat. 他坚持要穿他破烂的大衣。 2. The bum wore a tattered sweater and ripped pants. 那个流浪汉的运动衫和裤子破旧褴褛。 3. Their tattered clothing and broken furniture indicated their poverty. 他们褴褛的衣服和破烂的家具显出他们的贫穷。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('montage', '[ˌmɑːn\'tɑːʒ]', 'n.蒙太奇；混成画；拼集的照片；剪辑 v.运用或结合用蒙太奇手法的', '1. We proposed a montage mesh fusion method based on local Harmonic mapping. 我们提出了一个基于局部调和映射的三维网格蒙太奇融合新方法。', '过去式: montaged 过去分词: montaged 现在分词: montaging 第三人称单数: montages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recourse', '[\'riːkɔːrs]', 'n.依赖；求助；追索权', '1. In the valence bond treatment, explicit recourse is made to classical, localized bond structure. 价键法明显依赖经典的定域结构。 2. You\'d better have recourse to her. 你最好向她求助。 3. Your only recourse is legal action against them. 你只有求助于法律来对付他们。 4. Product protection will give you legal recourse. 对，申请产品保护就得到了合法的追索权。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('consort', '[\'kɑːnsɔːrt]', 'n.<正式>（君王的）配偶；一组(古乐器)；一组(演奏几世纪前音乐的乐师) v.厮混；结交', '1. The queen consort has come together with the king. 王后也随同国王前来。 2. Don\'t consort with criminals. 不要和犯罪分子结交。 3. If Mary and Kate were friends, then to consort with Kate was one way of keeping in touch with Mary. 如果玛丽和凯特是朋友，那么与凯特交往就是与玛丽保持联系的一个途径。', '过去式: consorted 过去分词: consorted 现在分词: consorting 第三人称单数: consorts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vaccinate', '[\'væksɪneɪt]', 'v.接种疫苗；预防接种', '1. She was vaccinate against smallpox as a child. 她小时候就接种了天花疫苗。', '名词: vaccinator 过去式: vaccinated 过去分词: vaccinated 现在分词: vaccinating 第三人称单数: vaccinates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('haft', '[hæft]', 'n.柄；把柄 v.给 ... 装柄', '1. Upon this haft stands the assassin\'s natal autograph, written in the blood of that helpless and unoffending old man who loved you. 这个刀把上留下了凶手的天生标记，这是用那位无力自卫、善良无辜的老人的鲜血印下来的，这位老人很爱你们。', '过去式: hafted 过去分词: hafted 现在分词: hafting 第三人称单数: hafts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('smother', '[\'smʌðər]', 'v.窒息；闷死；用沙等闷住火；忍住；厚厚地或大面积地覆盖', '1. They smother his better instinct. 这些声音窒息了他的良知。 2. He smothered the baby with a pillow. 他用枕头把婴儿闷死了。 3. It\'s better to smother the fire with the earth. 最好用土把火掩熄。 4. Smother the flames from the burning pan with a wet towel. 用湿毛巾把锅里的火扑灭。', '过去式: smothered 过去分词: smothered 现在分词: smothering 第三人称单数: smothers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insouciance', '[ɪn\'suːsiəns]', 'n.漠不关心；无动于衷', '1. She hid her worries behind an air of insouciance. 她掩饰着自己的烦恼，表现得无忧无虑。 2. The government\'s insouciance is perhaps understandable. 政府的漫不经心也许可以理解。 3. I couldn\'t help but believe him;he had too much geeky insouciance to be lying. 我不能不相信西塞尔，因为他实在太洒脱随意了，哪像撒谎的样子啊。 4. The insouciance illustrated his acute observation and positive attitude. 表面上看似漫不经心的叙述反映了他机敏的观察能力和积极的思考态度。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antiseptic', '[ˌænti\'septɪk]', 'n.杀菌剂；防腐剂 adj.杀菌的；防腐的；极为干净整洁的；冷漠的', '1. Antiseptic is used to sterilize the skin before giving an injection. 杀菌剂被用于在注射前给皮肤消毒。 2. They\'re doing tests to evaluate the effectiveness of this herb as an antiseptic. 他们正在检测这种草药作为杀菌剂的有效性。 3. We garantee that no artifical antiseptic in our food. 我们生产的所有食品保证不含人造防腐剂。 4. Ca-propionate was used as antiseptic agent to restrain growth of bacteria and mold. 并通过添加丙酸钙作为防腐剂有效抑制了细菌和霉菌的生长。 5. It is said that marjoram has antiseptic qualities. 据说马郁兰有杀菌的特性。', '副词: antiseptically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rebuke', '[rɪ\'bjuːk]', 'v.指责，斥责 n.指责；谴责', '1. She was roundly rebuked for what she had done. 她做出了这种事因而受到严厉的指责。 2. She rebuked him strongly for his negligence. 她严厉斥责他的疏忽。 3. He received a stern rebuke from his superior. 他受到上司的严厉斥责。 4. The teacher delivered a sharp rebuke to the class. 教师尖刻地指责了全班学生。', '过去式: rebuked 过去分词: rebuked 现在分词: rebuking 第三人称单数: rebukes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('martyr', '[\'mɑːrtər]', 'n.【C】烈士；殉道者；(因病等)长期受苦者 vt.杀害；折磨', '1. He is a martyr of his country. 他为国捐躯。 2. He was posthumously accepted as a martyr. 他被追认为烈士。 3. It is better to be a martyr than a confessor. 与其做忏悔，不如做殉道者。 4. He is a martyr to his rheumatism. 他长期受风湿病折磨。 5. He was martyred by the Romans. 他被罗马人处死而成为殉道者。', '过去式: martyred 过去分词: martyred 现在分词: martyring 第三人称单数: martyrs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('absorb', '[əb\'sɔːrb]', 'vt.吸收；吸引 ... 的注意；吞并；承受', '1. Dry sand absorbs water. 干沙吸收水份。 2. Did you absorb everything the professor said? 教授说的你全部理解了吗? 3. His business absorbs him. 他的业务使他全神贯注。 4. Large nations shouldn\'t absorb smaller ones. 大国不应当吞并小国。', '形容词: absorbable 副词: absorbingly 名词: absorbability 过去式: absorbed 过去分词: absorbed 现在分词: absorbing 第三人称单数: absorbs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('involuntary', '[ɪn\'vɑːlənteri]', 'adj.非自愿的；无意的；不由自主的', '1. All of the involuntary human subject research incorporates torture. 所有的非自愿的人类对象的研究都归入折磨。 2. In the next article in this series I will be covering breeding behaviour, and voluntary and involuntary artificial insemination. 在这一系列的下一篇文章我将会介绍育种行为，以及自愿和非自愿的人工授精。 3. These verbs mean to manifest involuntary vibratory movement. 这些动词意味着显示出不由自主的振动。 4. It\'s an almost involuntary thing and it also tells the person seeing this that he is sick. 这几乎是不由自主的动作，而且也告诉看到这些的人们，这个人病了。', '副词: involuntarily 名词: involuntariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swine', '[swaɪn]', 'n.猪；令人不快的人或事', '1. A swine over fat is the cause of his own bane. 猪因壮死（象以齿焚）。 2. She lived in that gloomy tenement, a place not fit for swine. 她就住在那幢阴暗的,连猪圈都不如的公寓里。 3. Take your hands off me, you filthy swine! 把你的手放开，别碰我，你这个坏蛋！ 4. He\'s an arrogant little swine! 他是个傲慢的小讨厌鬼！', '名词复数: swine');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('annihilate', '[ə\'naɪəleɪt]', 'v.消灭；歼灭；彻底消除；使无效；废止', '1. Identify the enemy you wish to annihilate. 只管标记你要消灭的敌人。 2. The United States cannot annihilate the Chinese nation with its small stack of atom bombs. 美国那点原子弹，消灭不了中国人。 3. We must herd the enemy troops together and annihilate them. 我们必须聚敌而歼灭之。', '形容词: annihilable 名词: annihilability 过去式: annihilated 过去分词: annihilated 现在分词: annihilating 第三人称单数: annihilates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shipshape', '[\'ʃɪpʃeɪp]', 'adj.整洁的；井然有序的', '1. I get the house all shipshape while he is away. 他不在的时候,我把房子打扫得干干净净,整整齐齐。 2. We try to keep the ship shipshape. 我们尽量保持船井井有条。 3. Those books are shipshape on the shelf. 书整齐有序地摆在书架上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rein', '[reɪn]', 'n.缰绳；驾驭；控制 vt.控制；驾驭 vi.驾驭', '1. He pulled at the reins. 他使劲拉住缰绳。 2. The horse responds to the slightest pull on the rein. 只要缰绳稍稍一拉，这匹马就有反应。 3. He gave rein to his imagination. 他纵情想像。 4. It\'s essential to keep a tight rein on public spending. 对公共开支严加控制极为重要。 5. We need to rein back public spending. 我们需要严格控制公共开销。 6. This horse reins well. 这匹马易于驾驭。', '过去式: reined 过去分词: reined 现在分词: reining 第三人称单数: reins');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('approximate', '[ə\'prɑːksɪmət]', 'adj.近似的；大约的 v.接近；约等于', '1. This is just an approximate figure. 这仅仅是个近似值。 2. We are entirely justified in using the approximate theory. 我们用近似理论完全正当。 3. He spent approximate two hours searching the photo. 他用了大约两小时来寻找这张照片. 4. The approximate number of students in the school is 300. 这所学校的学生数大约为300人。 5. Production costs approximate to $100,000 . 生产成本接近十万美元。', '副词: approximately 过去式: approximated 过去分词: approximated 现在分词: approximating 第三人称单数: approximates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hydrant', '[\'haɪdrənt]', 'n.给水栓；水龙头；消火栓', '1. I attached the hose to the hydrant and watered the flowers in the garden. 我把水管接上水龙头，浇了园子里的花。 2. On every floor there is a fire hydrant. 每个楼层都有消火栓。 3. It is not lawful to park in front of a hydrant. 在消火栓前停车是不合法的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('devoid', '[dɪ\'vɔɪd]', 'adj.全无的；缺乏的', '1. In the universe which appears to be uderly devoid of humor.We enjoy the superior luxury. 在一个幽默全无的宇宙里，我们享有这一至高无上的财富。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peery', '[\'pɪərɪ]', '好奇的, 怀疑的', '1. Casual users might notice a difference as well. David Peery says he might give the iPhone another try if it can help him run his real estate business. 普通用户可能会注意到一些不同。DavidPeery说他可能会再试iPhone一次，如果它能帮助他经营他的房地产业务。 2. peery envious eyes 好奇而羡慕的眼光', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('laconic', '[lə\'kɑːnɪk]', 'adj.简洁的；言简意赅的', '1. Her poetic idiom is noted for its laconic brevity, directness and plainness. 她用词简洁,直率,平易。 2. He sent me a laconic private message. 他给我一封简要的私人函件。', '副词: laconically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('extend', '[ɪk\'stend]', 'v.延伸；延长；伸展；扩展；提供；使竭尽全力', '1. Our playing fields extend as far as those trees. 我们的操场延伸到那些树前。 2. Theoretically, a line can extend into infinity. 从理论上来说直线可以无限地延伸。 3. How to extend a visa if it expires? 签证到期后怎样延长签证? 4. Dry-cleaning can extend the life of your clothing. 干洗可以延长衣服的使用寿命。', '形容词: extendable 名词: extendibility 过去式: extended 过去分词: extended 现在分词: extending 第三人称单数: extends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('calligraphy', '[kə\'lɪɡrəfi]', 'n.书法', '1. His calligraphy has reached the acme of perfection. 他的书法已达到出神入化的境界。 2. You can find books about calligraphy on that stack. 您可以在那个书架上找到有关书法的书。', '形容词: calligraphic 名词: calligrapher');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pestle', '[\'pesl]', 'n.杵；乳钵槌', '1. He ground the rock candy with a mortar and pestle. 他自己动手用研钵和杵把冰糖研成粉。 2. A pestle can be ground into a needle and true knowledge comes from perseverance. 想得到真正的学问，必有须磨杵成针的精神。', '过去式: pestled 过去分词: pestled 现在分词: pestling 第三人称单数: pestles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('poseur', '[poʊ\'zɜːr]', 'n.装模作样的人', '1. Some people admired him greatly while others considered him a poseur. 有的人对他佩服得五体投地，而有的人则认为他装腔作势。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gusto', '[\'ɡʌstoʊ]', 'n.爱好；嗜好；由衷的高兴', '1. He started painting with great gusto. 他兴致勃勃地开始作画。 2. I believe in doing lots of things with gusto. 我总是以乐观的态度处理所有的事情。 3. They attacked their meal with gusto. 他们大吃大喝。 4. Much of the region had embraced globalisation with gusto. 该地区大部分国家曾由衷地拥护全球化。', '名词复数: gustoes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verse', '[vɜːrs]', 'n.诗；韵文；诗节 vi.作诗 vt.诗化；在诗中表现；对 ... 精通', '1. There are four verses in each poem. 每首诗有四个诗节。 2. She wrote most of her poetry in blank verse. 她所写的诗大部分都是无韵诗。 3. Most of the scenes are written in verse, but some are in prose. 这场戏大部分内容是用韵文写成的,但也有一些是散文形式的 4. There are four verses in each poem. 每首诗有四个诗节。 5. It was in blank verse that she sang. 她以无韵诗体作诗。', '过去式: versed 过去分词: versed 现在分词: versing 第三人称单数: verses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('base', '[beɪs]', 'n.底部；基地；基础；基数；基线；(棒球)垒；[化]碱 vt.以 ... 作基础 adj.卑鄙的；不道德的', '1. I found a small leaf at the base of the flower. 我在那朵花的底部发现一片小叶。 2. Our mission was over, and went back to our base. 我们的任务结束了,我们返回了基地。 3. Many languages have Latin as their base. 许多语言都以拉丁语为基础。 4. One billion new consumers will double the existing consumer base within the next decade. 未来10年内全球将新增10亿消费者,消费者基数将较现在增加一倍。 5. This novel is based on historical facts. 这部小说是以历史事实为根据的。 6. To betray a friend is a base action. 背叛朋友是卑劣的行为。', '副词: basely 比较级: baser 最高级: basest 过去式: based 过去分词: based 现在分词: basing 第三人称单数: bases');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('choleric', '[\'kɑːlərɪk]', 'adj.易怒的', '1. His pride and choleric temper were to ruin him. 他生性高傲自恃而又易于发怒，这会毁了他的。 2. If your opponent is of choleric temper, seek to irritate him. 用挑逗的方法去激怒敌人，使其失去理智； 3. Choleric people don\'t cry easily or show much emotion at all. 暴躁的人不会轻易哭泣，或显露过多的情绪。', '副词: cholerically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('magnificent', '[mæɡ\'nɪfɪsnt]', 'adj.壮丽的；宏伟的；极好的', '1. The magnificent sights collect a jolly crowd. 壮丽的景色引来欢乐的人群。 2. The Hungarian view is magnificent from the summit of the mountains. 从群山之颠看到的匈牙利景色非常壮丽。 3. Just look at this magnificent autumn landscape! 看看这壮丽的秋景吧！ 4. The Taj Mahal is a magnificent building. 泰姬陵是一座宏伟的建筑。', '副词: magnificently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expansive', '[ɪk\'spænsɪv]', 'adj.易膨胀的；广阔的；滔滔不绝的；健谈的', '1. As a new material, its prospective will be more expansive in the future. 作为一种新型材料，它的发展前景十分广阔。 2. Birdsong\'s answer was expansive. 伯德桑的回答是滔滔不绝的。 3. After he\'d had a few drinks, Charles became very expansive. 查尔斯喝了几杯酒，话就滔滔不绝了。 4. Today Sarah became jovial and expansive. 今天莎拉变得快活而健谈。', '副词: expansively 名词: expansiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aqueduct', '[\'ækwɪdʌkt]', 'n.[建]高架渠；渡槽；[解]导管', '1. The ancient aqueduct stood out against the clear sky. 古代留下来的高架渠在蓝天的映衬之下十分夺目。 2. The aqueduct is the material evidence of mankind civilization development. 高架渠是人类文明发展的主要物证。 3. There is an aqueduct underneath the new house. 这座新房子底下有个导水管。 4. Modern aqueduct systems employ cast iron or steel. 现代输水管道多用钢、铁制成。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('modicum', '[\'mɑːdɪkəm]', 'n.少量；一点点；一小份', '1. They should win, given a modicum of luck. 只要有一点点运气，他们就会赢。 2. There\'s not even a modicum of truth in her statement. 她说的话没有一点是真的。', '名词复数: modicums');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('protocol', '[\'proʊtəkɔːl]', 'n.外交礼仪；草案；协议；规章制度；【医】记录；科学实验报告', '1. It was a gross breach of protocol. 这是粗暴违反外交礼节的行为。 2. He is religious in his observance of protocol. 他十分讲究礼节. 3. The delegates have to be seated according to protocol. 代表们须按礼仪要求就座。 4. The Protocol was signed between Li Hongzhang and the representatives of the eight powers. 这一草案由李鸿章和八国联军的代表签署。', '形容词: protocolar 过去式: protocoled/protocolled 过去分词: protocoled/protocolled 现在分词: protocoling/protocolling 第三人称单数: protocols');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('waver', '[\'weɪvər]', 'v.动摇；摇曳；犹豫；颤抖 n.动摇；踌躇；挥动者；烫发器', '1. They did not waver in their support for him. 他们毫不动摇地支持他。 2. His courage never wavered. 他的勇气从未减弱。 3. The disaster caused him to waver in his faith. 这件灾难使他对信仰发生了动摇。 4. The flame wavered and then died. 火焰摇曳一下就熄灭了。 5. This caused them to waver in their faith. 这件事使他们的信仰动摇了。', '副词: waveringly 名词: waverer 过去式: wavered 过去分词: wavered 现在分词: wavering 第三人称单数: wavers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('subdue', '[səb\'duː]', 'v.使服从；压制；减弱', '1. No one has been able to subdue these areas. 从没有人能够压制这一地区。 2. Soames made a tour of the room, to subdue his rising anger. 索米斯在屋内兜了一圈，压制一下心头升起的怒火。', '形容词: subduable 名词: subduer 过去式: subdued 过去分词: subdued 现在分词: subduing 第三人称单数: subdues');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vernal', '[\'vɜːrnl]', 'adj.春天的；青春的；春天般清新的', '1. Green is vernal colour, also representing vitality and nature. 绿色是春天的色彩，也代表着生命力和大自然。 2. To record industry and company of a few Internet, also smelled in this day it seems that vernal breath. 对于唱片业和一些互联网公司，似乎也在这一天闻到了春天的气息。', '副词: vernally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('depravity', '[dɪ\'prævəti]', 'n.堕落；腐败；邪恶；堕落的行为', '1. Experiencing life does not mean depravity and indulgence. 体验生活并不意味着堕落和放纵。 2. Awe is an essential force to restrain depravity. 敬畏是抑制邪恶的真正力量。 3. People have been tired of the depravities of a corrupt ruler. 人们已经受够了腐败的统治者的堕落行为。', '名词复数: depravities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cadet', '[kə\'det]', 'n.军官学员；培训生；次子；幼子', '1. Mr.Kelly is the only person in the NYPD to go from police cadet to commissioner. 凯利是纽约市警察局中唯一一个从警察学院学生成为警长的人。 2. The authorities sent him to the military academy for study as a cadet. 边区当局将他送进军政大学学习。', '名词: cadetship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tenor', '[\'tenər]', 'n.大意；要旨；常规；男高音；次中音乐器；（票据或支票的）期限 adj.(乐器)次中音的；(组钟中的)最低音的；男高音的 n.[语]本体', '1. I forget the tenor of her reply. 我不记得她回答的大意了。 2. I understood the tenor of their conversation but not the details. 我听懂了他们谈话的大意，但没有听懂其中的细节。 3. I am not competent to catch on the tenor what the lecturer spoke. 我不能明白该讲师所讲的要旨。 4. His appearance disrupted the even tenor of her life. 他的出现打乱她的生活规律。 5. The tenor soloist is unable to appear tonight because of illness. 男高音独唱者因病今晚不能演出。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('feline', '[\'fiːlaɪn]', 'n.猫；猫科动物 adj.猫科的', '1. Now the moonfaced feline can add government envoy to the list. 如今，这只圆脸猫咪又多了一个“政府使节”的新角色。 2. The findings were published in a recent issue of the Journal of Feline Medicine. 该发现发表在最近一期的《猫科医学》杂志。 3. Most feline animals have good hunting skill. 大部分猫科动物都有很好的狩猎技巧。 4. As a result, humans have learned to respect feline independence. 结果是人们已经学会尊重猫的独立性。', '副词: felinely 名词: felineness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malcontent', '[ˌmælkən\'tent]', 'adj.不服的；不满的 n.不满者；反叛者', '1. But she fears the husband is malcontent to this, even rebuff. 但她担心丈夫对此不满，甚至断然拒绝。 2. We must admit that these statistics reflect many malcontent mood. 必须承认，这些统计数字反映了许多不满情绪。 3. The malcontent is gunning for his supervisor. 那个心怀不满的人在伺机加害他的上司。 4. All the trouble is being caused by a handful of malcontents. 这些是非都是由一小撮不满分子搬弄的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('construe', '[kən\'struː]', 'v.解释；翻译；作句法分析', '1. His remarks were wrongly construed. 他的话被错误地解释了。 2. You can construe what he said in a number of different ways. 他的话可以有好几种解释。 3. How do you construe what he did? 你对他之所为作何解释? 4. This sentence is difficult to construe. 这个句子很难翻译。', '过去式: construed 过去分词: construed 现在分词: construing 第三人称单数: construes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nullify', '[\'nʌləˌfaɪ]', 'v.使无效；废除；取消', '1. The election results were nullified because of voter fraud. 因为选民舞弊，选举结果无效。 2. Counterintelligence seeks to nullify the enemy\'s espionage efforts. 反间谍情报之目的是挫败敌人的间谍活动。 3. He has no right to nullify laws. 他无权废除法律。 4. An unhealthy diet will nullify the effects of training. 不健康的饮食会抵消锻炼的效果。', '过去式: nullified 过去分词: nullified 现在分词: nullifying 第三人称单数: nullifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hibernate', '[\'haɪbərneɪt]', 'vi.冬眠；蛰伏；过冬', '1. Bears wake for spring, summer, and fall and hibernate for the winter. 熊在春天、夏天和秋天保持清醒,在冬季冬眠。 2. In the cold weather some of them hibernate. They go to sleep in all kinds of place. 它们有的在寒冷的天气里冬眠了。它们在各种各样的地方睡觉。 3. You should hibernate before I contact with you. 在我与你联系之前，你得潜伏不动。 4. His family often hibernates to the South. 他们家每到冬天都到南方去过冬。', '名词: hibernation 过去式: hibernated 过去分词: hibernated 现在分词: hibernating 第三人称单数: hibernates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exactitude', '[ɪɡ\'zæktɪtuːd]', 'n.正确；严谨', '1. He spoke with pompous exactitude. 他以自视绝对正确的口吻说话。 2. The teacher should pay attention to lead the students exactitude to distinguish the symbol meanings of these phrases under different cultural backgrounds in teaching process. 教师在教学过程中，应注重引导学生正确区分这些词语在不同文化背景下的象征意义。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reed', '[riːd]', 'n.芦苇；芦笛；簧片 Reed：里德（姓氏）.', '1. Hope is a slender reed for a stout man to lean on. 希望是壮汉依靠的一根纤细的芦苇。 2. The river banks were overgrown with reed. 河岸长满了芦苇。 3. Only let me make my life simple and straight, like a flute of reed for thee to fill with music. 只容我把自己的生命归做率真坦荡，象一只芦笛被你盈满乐音。 4. Whether an invaluable Italian violin or a casually-cut reed whistle, when left untouched, remains soundless. 一把价值连城的意大利提琴，和一枝被随手削出的芦笛，不去触动它们，便都是沉默，但沉默的内涵却并不一样。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inscription', '[ɪn\'skrɪpʃn]', 'n.题字；碑铭；铭文 (复数）inscriptions:记名证券.', '1. He carved an inscription on a bench. 他将一则题字刻在长凳上。 2. There was an inscription in Chinese characters over the arch. 牌楼上有汉字题字。 3. The inscription seems to have been worn away. 那块碑铭好像已过磨损。 4. Face B bears what Coedes and Krom describe as an unfinished inscription celebrating a victorious king. 背面刻有戈岱司和克罗姆认为没有完成的碑铭，颂扬一位战胜的国王。', '形容词: inscriptional 副词: inscriptively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('soot', '[sʊt]', 'n.煤烟；烟尘 v.熏以煤烟', '1. The doors and windows were blurred with soot. 那些门窗被煤烟弄得很脏。 2. She is sweeping the soot off the chimney. 她正把烟筒里的黑灰扫掉。 3. One small fire in the kitchen will cover the whole house in soot. 一个厨房里的小火炉就会把整个房子都熏黑。 4. The flue has become sooted up. 烟道里都是黑灰。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aggressor', '[ə\'ɡresər]', 'n.侵略者；攻击者', '1. The aggressor troops still hang on there. 侵略军仍然赖在那里不肯撤走。 2. Our tanks cut in ahead of the escaping aggressors. 我们的坦克抢到前面去拦住那些溃逃的侵略者。 3. It organized an insurrection against the aggressors. 它组织了一个反对侵略者的起义。 4. Baleful aggressor can pass this account to control your computer arbitrarily. 恶意的攻击者可以通过这个账户任意地控制你的计算机。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sinuous', '[\'sɪnjuəs]', 'adj.弯弯曲曲的；蜿蜒的；乖僻的', '1. Self-formed river channels tend to be sinuous. 自动形成的河槽是趋向于弯曲的。 2. The river wound its sinuous way across the plain. 这条河蜿蜒曲折地流过平原。', '副词: sinuously 名词: sinuousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sidesplitting', '[\'saɪdˌsplɪtɪŋ]', 'adj.令人捧腹大笑的', '1. Filled with sidesplitting humor, scary slasher scenes, and plenty of bikini-clad babes, Broken Lizard\'s Club Dread is a comedy to die for! 性感惹火的健身导师；抑或是身材健硕的按摩师？在寻凶“游戏中”，杀人王亦准备将众人逐个吓、逐个杀。 2. a killing joke; sidesplitting antics. 令人捧腹的笑话；令人捧腹的丑态。 3. ”Jialian answered with a sidesplitting laughter,“I will not accept this empty favor 。If only you don\'t blame me ,let alone my blame on you. \"贾琏笑道:\"罢;罢;这空头情我不领.;你不盘察我就够了;我还怪你!\" 4. a sidesplitting comedy. 使人捧腹大笑的喜剧', '副词: sidesplittingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detain', '[dɪ\'teɪn]', 'vt.扣留；拘押；耽搁；延误', '1. You cannot detain the eagle in the forest. 你没有法子将一只老鹰扣留在森林里。 2. We shall have to detain him and question him. 我们只好把他扣起来，讯问他一下。 3. Allow me to detain you for a moment. 请允许我耽搁你一会儿。 4. This matter isn\'t very important, and shouldn\'t detain us very long. 这事不很重要，不该耽搁我们很久。', '名词: detainment 过去式: detained 过去分词: detained 现在分词: detaining 第三人称单数: detains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('postulate', '[\'pɑːstʃəleɪt]', 'n.假定；基本条件 vt.要求；假定', '1. A combinatin of sources of uranium may be the most realistic postulate. 各种铀来源的综合考虑可能是最现实的假说。 2. Authority is a postulate of the moral order and derives from God. 权威是一种道德秩序的主张，并且它来源于上帝。 3. If so we shall have a wave function that satisfies our new postulate . 如果事实确是如此，我们就得到了一个满足新假设的波函数。 4. The school building programme postulates an increase in educational investment. 修建校舍的规划是在增加教育经费的前提下拟定的。', '名词: postulation 过去式: postulated 过去分词: postulated 现在分词: postulating 第三人称单数: postulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fervid', '[\'fɜːrvɪd]', 'adj.炽热的；热情的', '1. It assailed her with all the violence of her fervid imagination. 它以那种她热情想象的全部猛力袭击着她。 2. He was a ready scholar as you are, but more fervid and impatient. 他是一个聪明的学者，跟你一样，不过更加热情而缺乏耐心。 3. Quality is the base of Market, Goodwill erected by fervid service. 以质量拓展市场，热情服务树信誉。 4. Pass by the fervid flowers that press themselves on your sight. 路边的野花直往眼睛里钻。惹她们干哈呀？', '副词: fervidly 名词: fervidness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scrumptious', '[\'skrʌmpʃəs]', 'adj.(食物)很可口的；漂亮的', '1. Those scrumptious chocolates are so hard to resist. 这些令人垂涎三尺的巧克力令人难以抗拒。 2. I saw a scrumptious hair-do in Vogue. 我在妇女杂志上看到一个很优美的发型，', '副词: scrumptiously 名词: scrumptiousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('artery', '[\'ɑːrtəri]', 'n.动脉；干线', '1. Blood was spouting from the severed artery . 血从切断的动脉里喷出来。 2. This widens the inside of the artery, restoring blood flow. 这样会扩展动脉的内腔，达到恢复血流的效果。 3. The Yangtse River is one of the main arteries of traffic in China. 长江是中国的交通要道之一。 4. This is the place where the three main arteries of West London traffic meet. 这是伦敦西区三条主要干线会合的地方。', '名词复数: arteries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appropriate', '[ə\'proʊpriət]', 'adj.适当的；相称的 vt.占用；拨出(款项)', '1. You will be informed of the details at the appropriate time. 在适当的时候将把详情告诉你。 2. It is not easy to choose clothes which are appropriate to your beautiful figure. 选择与你漂亮的体型相称的服装是不容易的。 3. She again entreated his forgiveness for so selfishly appropriating the cottage 她为自己这么自私地占用了这座农舍而再次恳求他的原谅。 4. The government has appropriated some funds for education. 政府拨出了一些款项用作教育基金。', '形容词: appropriative 副词: appropriately 名词: appropriateness 过去式: appropriated 过去分词: appropriated 现在分词: appropriating 第三人称单数: appropriates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illiterate', '[ɪ\'lɪtərət]', 'adj.文盲的；无知的 n.文盲', '1. Dr. Andrew Sneddon is particularly excited by what has been found as it gives a unique insight into the lives of the working but illiterate inhabitants of the city. 安德鲁斯内登博士对于发现到的事物感到非常兴奋，因为可以深入的了解到这城市劳动但文盲的居民生活。 2. The lateral elite is literally illiterate. 边上的杰出人物简直是文盲。 3. I can confirm that you are illiterate in English! 我能确定你是个英语文盲！', '副词: illiterately 名词: illiterateness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scour', '[\'skaʊər]', 'v.擦洗；搜寻；腹泻 n.擦洗；腹泻', '1. He scoured off the dirt from the floor. 他擦去地板上的污垢。 2. This rusted pan does not scour easily. 这只生锈的锅不容易擦乾净。 3. The police scoured the area looking for the lost child. 警方搜遍这个地区寻找这个走失的孩子。 4. The cleaning lady gave it a good scour. 清洁女工将它好好地刷洗了一遍。', '名词: scourer 过去式: scoured 过去分词: scoured 现在分词: scouring 第三人称单数: scours');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('concede', '[kən\'siːd]', 'vt.承认；给予；让步；认输 vi.让步', '1. I concede that you are right. 我承认你是对的。 2. You must concede that I have tried my best. 你必须承认我已经尽力了。 3. The defeated side had to concede some of their territory to the enemy. 战败的一方不得不把一部分领土割让给了敌人。 4. You concede nothing to me and I have to concede everything to you. 你对我无论什么都不肯让步；我对你，可无论什么都得让步。 5. Mike had to concede when he confronted his parents 当面对他的父母,麦克不得不让步。', '副词: concededly 名词: conceder 过去式: conceded 过去分词: conceded 现在分词: conceding 第三人称单数: concedes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spacious', '[\'speɪʃəs]', 'adj.宽敞的；广阔的', '1. The hotel is neither spacious nor comfortable. 这旅馆既不宽敞也不舒服。 2. The systematic arrangement of chairs makes the hall look spacious. 座椅按照顺序排列，这使得礼堂里显得很宽敞。 3. In its spacious halls are displayed over8000 priceless relics. 在它宽敞的大厅里，展出了8000多件珍贵文物。 4. The museum is complemented by a spacious garden. 广大宽阔的庭院为博物馆增色不少。', '副词: spaciously 名词: spaciousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rupture', '[\'rʌptʃər]', 'n.破裂；断裂；[医]疝气 v.（使）破裂', '1. The negotiation came to a rupture. 谈判破裂了。 2. He died of a rupture of blood-vessels. 他血管破裂而死。 3. Failure of the machine may be caused by the rupture of the triangle belt. 这台机器的故障可能是由三角带断裂引起的。 4. I nearly gave myself a rupture lifting that pile of books. 提那一大堆书差点儿让我得了疝气。 5. He\'ll rupture a muscle if he goes on dancing like that! 他要是继续那样跳舞，会跳得皮开肉裂！', '形容词: rupturable 过去式: ruptured 过去分词: ruptured 现在分词: rupturing 第三人称单数: ruptures');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('curmudgeon', '[kɜːr\'mʌdʒən]', 'n.脾气暴躁的人；乖戾的老人', '1. This was taught to me by my pipe-smoking guru, an insufferably grouchy old curmudgeon. 这是我的烟斗导师教给我的，他是一个不苟言笑，脾气乖戾的老头，但他却的确懂得抽烟斗。', '形容词: curmudgeonly 名词: curmudgeonry');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('goad', '[ɡoʊd]', 'v.刺激；激励；驱使 n.刺棒；激励物；刺激物', '1. His persistent questions finally goaded me into an angry reply. 他三番五次地问问题惹得我回答时也没有好气。 2. He kept goading me to fight. 他不断煽动我去打架。 3. Stop goading the poor beast! 别再驱赶那可怜的动物了！ 4. A goad is used for prodding cattle. 刺棒是赶牲畜用的。', '过去式: goaded 过去分词: goaded 现在分词: goading 第三人称单数: goads');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('canopy', '[\'kænəpi]', 'n.天篷；遮篷；苍穹', '1. There is a canopy over the entrance. 入口处有一顶天篷。 2. The enclosed canopy opens upward from the rear to allow for entry and exit. 打开封闭的天篷向上从后方允许入境和出境。 3. The trees formed a leafy canopy above their heads. 树木在他们头顶上空形成了一个枝叶茂盛的遮篷。', '名词复数: canopies 过去式: canopied 过去分词: canopied 现在分词: canopying 第三人称单数: canopies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aquifer', '[\'ækwɪfər]', 'n.含水土层(含水量足以成为井水或泉水)', '1. Recharge areas are necessary for a healthy aquifer. 补给区对于一个正常的含水层来说是必需的。 2. Sometime the term artesian is used to denote a confined aquifer. 有时候人们也用自流含水层这一术语表示承压含水层。', '形容词: aquiferous');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prescience', '[\'presiəns]', 'n.预知；先见', '1. Still he had a strange prescience,an intimation of something yet to come. 不过他有一种奇特的预感，感到了某件事情就要发生！', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exhort', '[ɪɡ\'zɔːrt]', 'vt.劝诫；忠告；勉励 vi.进行规劝（或告诫）', '1. The chairman exhorted the party workers to take action. 主席敦促党的工作人员采取行动。 2. He often exhorts Mary to work harder. 他经常勉励玛丽要更加努力工作。', '名词: exhorter 过去式: exhorted 过去分词: exhorted 现在分词: exhorting 第三人称单数: exhorts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rehearse', '[rɪ\'hɜːrs]', 'vt.预演；排演；预先演习；详述；复述 vi.参加彩排', '1. In most cases, actors rehearse their parts. 在大多数情况下演员要预演他们的角色。 2. Our theatrical company will rehearse and stage a small theatre drama. 我们剧社将排演一出小剧场话剧。 3. They rehearsed how the United States would handle a hypothetical terroris t a ttack. 就美国将如何处理模拟的恐怖分子袭击 4. He rehearsed the events of the day. 他列举当天发生的事情。 5. They rehearse regularly and give periodic concerts. 他们定期排练', '名词: rehearser 过去式: rehearsed 过去分词: rehearsed 现在分词: rehearsing 第三人称单数: rehearses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('authorization', '[ˌɔːθərə\'zeɪʃn]', 'n.授权(书)；批准', '1. May I see your authorization for this? 我可以看看你做这件事的授权书吗? 2. Formal authorization for the trip was given last week. 这次行程上周得到正式批准。 3. You cannot take a day off without authorization. 未经批准你不得休假。 4. It\'s annoying to have to get authorization for spending such piddling amounts of money. 花这么一点钱也要去请示,真烦人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hoist', '[hɔɪst]', 'v.升起；升高；举起 n.起重机；升高', '1. They hoist cargo with a locomobile crane. 他们用自动推进的起重机吊起货物。', '名词: hoister 过去式: hoisted 过去分词: hoisted 现在分词: hoisting 第三人称单数: hoists');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('obstruction', '[əb\'strʌkʃn]', 'n.障碍；妨碍；闭塞；违例阻挡', '1. The road was cleared from obstruction . 那条路已被清除了障碍。 2. The traffic flowed round the obstruction. 车辆绕过障碍行驶。 3. He was arrested for obstruction of a police officer in the execution of his duty. 他因妨碍警察执行公务而被逮捕。 4. These tumors often resulted in stenosis or obstruction of the bronchus. 邻近支气管常有狭窄或闭塞。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('convince', '[kən\'vɪns]', 'vt.使确信；使信服；说服', '1. I try to convince him of the reality of the danger. 我试图使他相信危险的确存在。 2. It took many hours to convince me of his guilt. 研究了许多个小时我才相信他有罪。 3. He convinced me of his sincerity. 他使我确信他的真诚。 4. There was not an atom of evidence to convince him. 没有一点能使他信服的证据。', '形容词: convincible 名词: convincement 过去式: convinced 过去分词: convinced 现在分词: convincing 第三人称单数: convinces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dalliance', '[\'dæliəns]', 'n.戏弄；闲混', '1. It turned out to be his last dalliance with the education system. 这一次竟成了他对教育体制最后的嘲弄。 2. Easy and pleasant as their life at Paris was, it was after all only an idle dalliance and amiable trifling. 他们在巴黎生活得又舒服又有趣，可是终久不过在偷安嬉耍，不是个久远之计。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ecologist', '[i\'kɑːlədʒɪst]', 'n.生态学家', '1. It\'s an ecologist\'s dream but an oil man\'s nightmare. 这是生态学家的梦想，却也是石油商的梦魇。 2. A contemporary ecologist once said: man lives on the earth as a guest of green plants. 一位现代生态学家说：人类是作为绿色植物的客人生活在地球上的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cub', '[kʌb]', 'n.幼兽；年轻人', '1. The cub licked the milk from its mother\'s breast. 这头幼兽吸吮着它妈妈的奶水。 2. A cub takes a playful bite of a relative\'s swishing tail in the African plains. 在非洲平原一个幼兽正咬着它的家族成员的漂亮尾巴玩耍。 3. The cub was wet behind the ears. 这个年轻人还幼稚无知呢。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('simonize', '[\'saɪmənˌaɪz]', 'vt. 给 ... 上蜡； 把 ... 擦亮', '1. Simon is doing very well at school. 西蒙的学习成绩很好。 2. Simon\'s always talking big about his prowess on the golf course. 西蒙总是吹嘘自己在高尔夫球场上的杰出才能。 3. Simon glumly watched TV and went to bed snappy. 西蒙闷闷不乐地看电视，然后没好气地去睡觉。 4. Simon\'s answer disagrees with mine. 西蒙的回答与我的不一致。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('friction', '[\'frɪkʃn]', 'n.摩擦；摩擦力；分歧', '1. Constant friction wore out the heels of my shoes. 不断的摩擦磨损了我的鞋跟。 2. Matches are lighted by friction. 火柴由摩擦而生火。 3. Friction lowers the efficiency of a machine. 摩擦减低机器的效率。 4. Friction causes a rolling ball to stop finally. 摩擦力使滚动的球最终停了下来。', '形容词: frictional 副词: frictionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('insuperable', '[ɪn\'suːpərəbl]', 'adj.（困难）难以克服的；不可逾越的', '1. The difficulties that confront us seem insuperable. 我们面临的困难似乎是不可克服的。 2. The deep river was an insuperable barrier to those who could not swim. 对不会游泳的人来说，这条深河是无法超越的障碍。', '副词: insuperably 名词: insuperability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('permanence', '[\'pɜːrmənəns]', 'n.永久；持久', '1. We no longer talk of the permanence of marriage. 如今，再没有人说婚姻要天长地久了。 2. We believe the permanence of the sun. 我们相信太阳的永恒。 3. The spoken word is immediate but lacks permanence. 口头之言便捷，但缺乏持久性。 4. Consumption was affected by permanence income which is determinant. 持久收入是影响消费的决定因素。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('opiate', '[\'oʊpiət]', 'n.鸦片剂；麻醉剂 adj.安眠的；麻醉的', '1. Music is a beautiful opiate, if you don\'t take it too seriously. 只要不过于沉醉于其中，音乐是一种美丽的麻醉剂。', '过去式: opiated 过去分词: opiated 现在分词: opiating 第三人称单数: opiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shiftiness', '[\'ʃɪfti]', 'adj.诡诈的；不可靠的；（风向）不稳定的；多变的', '1. I didn\'t trust his shifty expression. 他贼眉鼠眼, 我不信任他。 2. He looked like a shifty underworld character. 他看起来是个鬼头鬼脑的下流社会的角色。 3. How about the wind? Is it shifty and steady? 风怎么样？有风摆还是稳定？ 4. Life does shifty things, he is forced to reflect in a most puzzled way. 人生变化无常，他不得不从最难以理解的地方去考虑。', '副词: shiftily 比较级: shiftier 最高级: shiftiest 名词: shiftiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jealousy', '[\'dʒeləsi]', 'n.妒忌', '1. Her admiration for him was tinged with jealousy. 她对他的钦佩带有一点妒忌。 2. Some women have a disposition to jealousy. 有些女人生性爱妒忌。', '名词复数: jealousies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('biped', '[\'baɪped]', 'n.两足动物 adj.两足的', '1. The Library for Character Studio Biped. 两足角色库 2. Or you could even go half way between a quad and a biped model. 或者，你甚至可以在四足和两足模式中各取一半。” 3. Therefore, any biped motion can be evaluated with the method in this paper. 该方法适用于目前常见的两足机器人自由度布置方式，因此具有一定的通用性。 4. Biped robot with heterogeneous legs (BRHL) is a new pattern humanoid robot. 摘要异构双腿行走机器人(BRHL)是一种全新的类人机器人模式。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slippery', '[\'slɪpəri]', 'adj.滑的；狡猾的；不可靠的', '1. A wet road is usually slippery. 潮湿的路往往是滑的。 2. The road was slippery after the rain. 下雨之后道路很滑。 3. Don\'t lend any money to that slippery person. 不要借钱给那个狡猾的家伙。 4. The England striker says the slippery Portuguese winker got him sent off in Saturday\'s World Cup clash. 英格兰前锋说这个狡猾的葡萄牙人在周六的比赛中迫使自己下场后挤眉弄眼。', '比较级: slipperier 最高级: slipperiest 名词: slipperiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('countermand', '[\'kaʊntərmænd]', 'v.取消；撤回；下相反的命令取消', '1. I have now to countermand that order,in consequence of the receipting of the letter this morning. 由于今日上午才收到来函，现在只好取消那份订单。', '过去式: countermanded 过去分词: countermanded 现在分词: countermanding 第三人称单数: countermands');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('endow', '[ɪn\'daʊ]', 'vt.捐助；赋予；使具有某种品质', '1. I can only endow 100 dollors at most. 我充其量只能捐助100美元。 2. He endowed the hospital with a large fortune. 他捐赠一笔巨款给这家医院。 3. She both built and endowed the hospital. 她不仅建了医院还给医院捐赠资金。 4. He is endowed with literary talent. 他有文学天分。', '过去式: endowed 过去分词: endowed 现在分词: endowing 第三人称单数: endows');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clog', '[klɑːɡ]', 'vt.阻塞；妨碍 vi.阻塞；结块；跳木屐舞 n.木屐；障碍', '1. Heavy traffic clogged the freeways. 拥挤的交通堵塞了高速公路 2. Don\'t rinse the leaves out into the sink: you\'ll clog the drain. 不要将叶子冲洗掉进污水槽，会堵塞阴沟的。 3. Sludge can also clog oil passages and prevent normal engine lubrication. 油泥还会阻塞油路，妨碍发动机的正常润滑工作。 4. The pipes are clogging up. 管子渐渐被堵塞。', '过去式: clogged 过去分词: clogged 现在分词: clogging 第三人称单数: clogs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disguise', '[dɪs\'ɡaɪz]', 'vt.掩饰；假装；假扮 n.伪装；伪装物', '1. She could not disguise her amusement at his mistake. 她对他的错误忍俊不禁。 2. It proved difficult to disguise his anxiety. 他的焦虑难以掩饰。 3. She disguised herself as a man, but she couldn\'t disguise her voice. 她把自己乔装成一个男子，但她改变不了自己的声音。 4. He plans to disguise himself as a policeman. 他打算把自己假扮成一个警察。 5. The supposed beggar was really a police officer in disguise. 那个众人眼中的乞丐，其实是化了装的警察。', '副词: disguisedly 名词: disguisement 过去式: disguised 过去分词: disguised 现在分词: disguising 第三人称单数: disguises');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('receptacle', '[rɪ\'septəkl]', 'n.容器；花托；插座', '1. Please find me a receptacle for sugar. 请给我找一个放糖的容器。 2. Learning doesn\'t consist in being an empty receptacle. 学习并不是往空容器里塞东西。 3. Note: this kind of receptacle shell is Au-plated. 注:此类插座壳均为镀金。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ingrate', '[ɪn\'greɪt]', 'adj.忘恩的；忘恩负义的 n.忘恩负义的人', '1. How could you be so ungrateful! Ingrate! 你怎么可以这么无情！忘恩负义的家伙！', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('underutilized', '[ˌʌndər\'juːtəlaɪzd]', '【书】=underused； adj.；未充分使用；是一个非常正式的用词；同\"underused\"', '1. But most PCs used in business are underutilized and expensive. 但业务中使用的大多数PC机都没有得到充分使用，而且也很贵。 2. One underutilized appliance is a conventional countertop blender. 一个没有被充分使用的器具是一般厨房工作台面的搅拌机。 3. Enlacing, wrappage mobile and turning required underutilized. 绑缚时，包装件的安放和转向需靠酬劳举行。 4. The result is that enterprises today often have underutilized storage and CPU. 结果就是现在的企业常常是无法充分利用存储器和CPU。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('generic', '[dʒə\'nerɪk]', 'adj.一般的；普通的；共有的；没有商标的 n.无商标的药品', '1. The generic term for wine, spirits and beer is alcoholic beverages. 葡萄酒、烈性酒、啤酒的通称是酒精类饮料。 2. To run the test now, see Run the Generic Test. 若要立即运行测试,请参见运行一般测试。 3. Instead, it\'s a kind of generic publication that stands for all of the potential publications in your set. 相反,它是一种通用出版物,代表您可能使用的所有出版物。 4. It is designed like a generic Roman basilica, with three aisles and an apse. 它设计得像一座普通的罗马长方形基督教堂，有三条走廊和一个半圆形的后殿。', '副词: generically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('firearm', '[\'faɪərɑːrm]', 'n.火器；枪炮', '1. I want more tough skin to resist all the firearm. 我想有更坚硬的皮肤用它来抵御所有的枪炮。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tiff', '[tɪf]', 'n.一口；小争吵；小口角 vi.小争吵；生气', '1. A petty quarrel or argument; a tiff. 无谓的争吵不重要的争吵或争论; 口角 2. They patched up their tiff. 他们平息了争执。', '过去式: tiffed 过去分词: tiffed 现在分词: tiffing 第三人称单数: tiffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('verbal', '[\'vɜːbl]', 'adj.口头的；用言语的；用文字的；逐字的；动词的 n.动名词', '1. They had made a verbal agreement to sell. 他们达成了口头售货协定。 2. Don\'t be afraid of verbal abuse or criticism. 不要害怕口头上的辱骂或批评。 3. The teacher teaches us the verbal skills. 老师告诉我们使用言辞的技巧。 4. The verbal imagery has hardly changed. 语言文字的意象几乎没有改变。', '副词: verbally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maven', '[\'meɪvn]', 'n.<口语> 专家；行家 =mavin', '1. You\'ll be a negotiating maven if you do this. 掌握了这些要领，你将成为一个谈判高手。 2. The results show that market maven personality is the most important factor. 研究结果显示，市场行家特质是最重要的影响因素。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('palette', '[\'pælət]', 'n.调色板', '1. He picked his brushes and palette. 他提起画笔和调色板。 2. Life is a palette; you put colors on it. 生活是调色板,每个人自己在上面加上颜色。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('strait', '[streɪt]', 'n.海峡；困境 adj.困难的；窘迫的；<古>狭窄的；严格的', '1. We will transit the strait at night. 我们将在夜间通过那个海峡。 2. We passed through the Strait of Magellan. 我们穿过了麦哲伦海峡。 3. I hear you are in poor financial straits. 我听说你处于经济困难之中。 4. The door is rather strait. 这门相当窄。', '副词: straitly 名词: straitness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unprovoked', '[ˌʌnprə\'voʊkt]', 'adj.(生气等)无缘无故的', '1. This malicious and unprovoked attack astounded him. 这个恶意的无端攻击使他吃惊。 2. The boys\' attack on the old woman was quite unprovoked. 那帮男孩对老妇人的袭击完全是无来由的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peculate', '[\'pekjəˌleɪt]', 'vt.挪用（尤指公款）；盗领（钱财）', '1. The accountant began to peculate the public money. 会计开始侵吞公款。 2. They accused him of have peculate the public money. 他们控他侵吞公款。 3. Some lawless users often peculate other\'s IP address in methods of static, dynamic and reworking them. 非法用户常以静、动态和成对修改IP地址的方法盗用局域网IP地址。 4. I found some people in the caboodle of TOEIC .one bottle of coke made me bethink of something that about peculate public money . 找我要人？！', '名词: peculation 过去式: peculated 过去分词: peculated 现在分词: peculating 第三人称单数: peculates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blunt', '[blʌnt]', 'adj.钝的；迟钝的；直率的 v.使迟钝；变钝', '1. Blunt scissors don\'t cut cleanly. 钝剪刀剪不齐。 2. My pencil is blunt, could you lend me a knife to sharpen it? 我的铅笔钝了，你能借我把刀子削一削吗？ 3. It involves systematic yet banal design, and blunt reportage. 它使用系统的，然而平庸的设计和迟钝的新闻报道。 4. He\'s very blunt and will tell you what he thinks about anything. 他的个性非常直率,会把他所想的都说出来。 5. His mind was blunted by boredom. 他的头脑因厌烦而变得迟钝。', '副词: bluntly 比较级: blunter 最高级: bluntest 名词: bluntness 过去式: blunted 过去分词: blunted 现在分词: blunting 第三人称单数: blunts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('centralization', '[ˌsentrəlaɪ\'zeɪʃn]', 'n.集中；中央集权化', '1. This is not simply a problem of financial centralization or decentralization. 这不是个简单的财政集中分散的问题。 2. The most important aspect of centralization and unification is unifying our thinking. 而集中统一，最重要的是思想的统一。 3. To reflect this corporate centralization, the core layer hub-and-spoke configuration establishes the focal point of the data flow as a key site. 为表现公司中央集权化，核心层星型结构建立数据流的汇聚点作为关键站点。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bequeath', '[bɪ\'kwiːð]', 'v.遗赠；遗留；把传下去', '1. I bequeath him this property to have and to hold. 我将此项财产遗赠给他，归他永久享有。 2. Her collection of paintings was bequeathed to the National Gallery when she died. 她去世时，她的全部藏画都遗赠给了国家美术馆。 3. His father bequeathed him a fortune. 他父亲给他留下了一笔遗产。 4. The millionaire will bequeath his colossal fortune to his only son. 这个百万富翁会把他的巨额财产传给他的独子。', '名词: bequeathal 过去式: bequeathed 过去分词: bequeathed 现在分词: bequeathing 第三人称单数: bequeaths');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('Antarctic', '[æn\'tɑːrktɪk]', 'adj.南极的 n.(the A-)南极洲；南极圈', '1. Oh, I have got another cable to send to Antarctic. 哦，我还要发一份去南极的电报。 2. Antarctic exploration begins with Ptolemy. 南极的探险是由普特利姆首先进行的。 3. Antarctic Peninsula has the most moderate climate. 南极洲半岛气候最温和。 4. He always dreams of adventuring in Antarctic. 他总梦想在南极洲进行冒险尝试。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('kiosk', '[\'kiːɑːsk]', 'n.亭；凉亭；报摊', '1. We were eating hamburgers at a kiosk. 我们在一家小亭里吃汉堡包。 2. Customers start using the kiosk without any needed intervention from staff. 用户开始使用亭没有任何必要的干预工作人员。 3. I bought a magazine at the station kiosk. 我在车站报摊上买了一本杂志。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ingrained', '[ɪn\'ɡreɪnd]', 'adj.根深蒂固的；深嵌入纺织品或纤维的 动词ingrain的过去式和过去分词.', '1. Your ingrained prejudice has affected your judgment. 你根深蒂固的偏见已经影响了你的判断力。 2. The belief that one should work hard is ingrained in our culture. 人人都应该努力工作这个信念在我们的文化中根深蒂固。 3. Except for his hands and a circle of his face, his body was grey all over with ancient, ingrained dirt. 除了他的双手和脸上一圈以外，他全身发灰，污秽不堪。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('portable', '[\'pɔːrtəbl]', 'adj.轻便的；手提式的；[计]可移植的 n.便携的东西', '1. The portable device easily knocks down. 这种轻便装置容易拆卸。 2. Portable telephones are very popular nowadays. 现今，移动电话非常普及。 3. She traded her roller-skates for Billy\'s portable radio. 她拿旱冰鞋换了比利的手提收音机。 4. The new portable computers are going like hot cakes. 新的便携式计算机卖得很快。', '副词: portably 名词: portability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('illiberal', '[ɪ\'lɪbərəl]', 'adj.缺乏文化素养的；气量狭小的；吝啬的；思想偏狭的', '1. There are liberal and illiberal pleasures as well as liberal and illiberal arts. 享乐有高雅与粗鄙之分，正如艺术有高雅与粗鄙之别。 2. Butler, deeply illiberal, exerted his rights. 巴特勒心胸狭窄,滥用了自己所拥有的权力。 3. Don\'t not be illiberal in your words to show your love. 不要吝啬自己的语言表达你的情感。 4. The regime has been illiberal and authoritarian. 这样的政体是偏执的以及独裁的。', '副词: illiberally 名词: illiberalism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pathological', '[ˌpæθə\'lɑːdʒɪkl]', 'adj.病理学的', '1. She has a pathological fear of spiders. 她对蜘蛛有一种病态的恐惧。 2. Tumors were diagnosed by neuroimaging and pathological examinatons. 所有病人都经神经影像学和病理学检查确诊。', '副词: pathologically 异体字: pathologic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aggrieve', '[ə\'griːv]', 'vt. 使 ... 受屈； 使 ... 苦恼', '1. I hope I didn\'t aggrieve her feeling. 我希望我并没有伤害到她的感情。 2. The entire population was aggrieve d by the tyranny of the king. 在国王的暴政之下，整个国家都陷入了水深火热之中。 3. They not only aggrieve the parties\' legal procedural rights, but also hinder our country\'s construction of a socialist legal state. 这不但侵害了当事人合法的程序权利，而且阻碍了我国社会主义法治国家的建设进程。 4. In China,however,the controlling stockholders (major stockholders) often departure their fiduciary duty to minority stockholders and take advantage of the controlling over the list companies to aggrieve the benefits of minority stockholders. 我国上市公司控股股东利用对公司的控制 ,违背对中小股东的诚信责任 ,侵害中小股东利益的事件时有发生。', '过去式: aggrieved 过去分词: aggrieved 现在分词: aggrieving 第三人称单数: aggrieves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mercenary', '[\'mɜːrsəneri]', 'adj.唯利是图的；雇佣的 n.唯利是图的人；雇佣兵', '1. The captain of a gnome mercenary company is looking for a good supplier of horses and weapons. 一个唯利是图的侏儒公司的头目正在寻找一个良好的马匹与武器供应源。 2. Mercenary men lust for wealth. 唯利是图的人贪求财富。 3. He sent 4000 mercenary Genoese crossbowmen against the English line.They were cut down by the English longbowmen. 四千个雇佣的热那亚籍十字弓手奉他命令，向英国阵营进攻，不少死在英国长弓手箭下。 4. The captain of a gnome mercenary company is looking for a good supplier of horses and weapons. 一个唯利是图的侏儒公司的头目正在寻找一个良好的马匹与武器供应源。', '副词: mercenarily 名词: mercenariness 名词复数: mercenaries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('approbation', '[ˌæprə\'beɪʃn]', 'n.认可；赞许', '1. The new policy earned the approbation of the people. 新政策得到了人民的认可。 2. The goods are not allowed to be exported without approbation of the customs. 没有海关的许可，这些货物是不允许出口的。 3. The approach he took was given approbation . 他采取的方法得到了称赞。 4. The manager surveyed her report with approbation. 经理赞许地审读了她的报告。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vicinity', '[və\'sɪnəti]', 'n.邻近；周边地区', '1. There\'s a factory in the vicinity of the school. 学校邻近有个工厂。 2. No one was aware of his vicinity. 没有人发现他就在附近。 3. All the ships in the vicinity of the crash joined in the search for survivors. 撞船事故发生地区的所有船只都参加了搜寻幸存者的工作。 4. Pearl Harbor and vicinity had been turned into complete chaos. 珍珠港和附近地区一片混乱。', '名词复数: vicinities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conscript', '[kən\'skrɪpt]', 'v.征兵；征召 n.应征士兵', '1. He\'s a conscript. 他是一名应征士兵。 2. A conscript in a shabby uniform saluted the car. 一个穿着破旧制服的士兵向汽车敬礼。', '过去式: conscripted 过去分词: conscripted 现在分词: conscripting 第三人称单数: conscripts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commune', '[\'kɑːmjuːn]', 'n.公社 v.交换思想、意见或感受；交流', '1. The commune has embarked on a program of reshaping its hills and rivers. 这个公社已开始实施一项重新整治河山的规划。 2. The people\'s commune laid down another20 mu with grass. 这个人民公社在另外二十亩土地上种上了牧草。 3. I will commune with you of your marriage. 我愿推心置腹地与你谈谈你的婚姻问题。 4. I would commune with you of such matters. 我要和你密谈这些事。', '过去式: communed 过去分词: communed 现在分词: communing 第三人称单数: communes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hardihood', '[\'hɑːdɪˌhʊd]', 'n.大胆；鲁莽', '1. Jack have the hardihood to deny what he have do. 杰克厚颜地否认了自己所干的事。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('musicologist', '[ˌmjuːzɪ\'kɒlədʒɪst]', 'n.音乐学者；音乐理论家', '1. She was married to critic and musicologist Aladar Toth (1898-1986); she is buried next to him in Budapest. 她嫁给了评论家和音乐阿拉达尔托特（1898至1986年）;她被安葬在他旁边的布达佩斯。 2. The musical analysis performed by OMRAS is unlike any that a musicologist would recognise. “快变”及其类似产品的工作原理都是将声音和几百万首储存在一个中央数据库中的录音资料加以匹配。 3. Profession (e.g. composer, musicologist, performer, etc. Performers please state instruments. 专业(例如:作曲家;音乐家;演奏家等等.;演奏家请注明演奏乐器 4. An eminent musicologist, mathematician and calendarist, who was honored to be “oriental personage of artistic encyclopedia type”. 明代杰出乐律家、算学家和历学家，被西方赞誉为“东方百科艺术全书式的人物”。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intuitive', '[ɪn\'tuːɪtɪv]', 'adj.直觉的', '1. Are women more intuitive than men? 女子比男子的直觉力更强吗? 2. She is outgoing, naturally cheerful, and intuitive. 她外向、生愉悦以及具备敏锐的直觉。 3. Her perception of the right seemed almost intuitive. 她对正确事物的理解几乎是直觉的。 4. This is an art in which intuitive guessing plays an important part. 这个工作需要技巧，直觉的猜测会起很大的作用', '副词: intuitively 名词: intuitiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('iniquitous', '[ɪ\'nɪkwɪtəs]', 'adj.不正的；不法的；邪恶的', '1. Have you seen this bill? It\'s iniquitous ! 你看见这份帐单了吗?简直是漫天要价! 2. Men of feeling may at any moment be killed outright by the iniquitous and the callous. 多愁善感的人会立即被罪恶的人和无情的人彻底消灭。', '副词: iniquitously 名词: iniquitousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('munch', '[mʌntʃ]', 'v.大声咀嚼', '1. She is munching at an apple. 她正用力咀嚼苹果。 2. Munching the apple as he was, he had an eye for all her movements. 他虽然啃着苹果，但却很留神地监视着她的每一个动作。', '名词: muncher 过去式: munched 过去分词: munched 现在分词: munching 第三人称单数: munches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scintillate', '[\'sɪntlˌeɪt]', 'v.闪烁；发火花', '1. Yet from all these, the unique characteristics of Yuan\'s Ci scintillate. 凡此种种，都体现了遗山词的独特性。 2. These will not only scintillate your palate, but also make for some interesting dinner conversation. 这些葡萄酒不仅让您胃口大开，而且会让餐桌上的对话充满兴趣。 3. The flash of light that accompanies an electric discharge in the atmosphere (or something resembling such a flash),can scintillate for a second or more. 大气中伴随放电现象的闪光或与之类似的闪光，通常可以连续几次放光。 4. The research on the system of Gaogouli Capital City evolution and protection, have leading meaning, Gaogouli Capital City will again scintillate the energy. 都城演变体系研究对今天探讨高句丽都城保护与更新有着指导意义,使高句丽都城再度焕发青春活力。', '副词: scintillatingly 过去式: scintillated 过去分词: scintillated 现在分词: scintillating 第三人称单数: scintillates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rectitude', '[\'rektɪtuːd]', 'n.诚实；正直；操行端正', '1. I do not doubt the rectitude of her motives. 我不怀疑她动机的纯真。 2. I am sure she is a paragon of rectitude. 我可以肯定她是个正直的完人。 3. Alexander is a man of unquestioned moral rectitude. 亚历山大是个品行端正无瑕的人。', '形容词: rectitudinous');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('troupe', '[truːp]', 'n.（演出的）一团；一班 v.巡回演出', '1. The troupe is now on the road. 剧团正在巡回演出。 2. I watched a troupe of travelling actors. 我观看了一个巡回剧团演出。', '过去式: trouped 过去分词: trouped 现在分词: trouping 第三人称单数: troupes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('surgeon', '[\'sɜːrdʒən]', 'n.外科医生', '1. The surgeon has performed the operation. 外科医生做了手术。 2. The surgeon operated on her for appendicitis. 外科医生为她做阑尾切除手术。 3. The surgeon asked him if he felt nervous. 外科医生问他是否感到紧张。 4. He is reputed as the best surgeon in Paris. 他被认为是巴黎最好的外科医生。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('charlatan', '[\'ʃɑːrlətən]', 'n.冒充内行者；骗子', '1. That charlatan is anything but a doctor. 那江湖骗子决不是医生。 2. He was sure that he was dealing with a charlatan. 他真以为自己遇上了江湖骗子。 3. In spite of his boasts of having cured many people, he was nevertheless shown up as a charlatan. 尽管那人夸口说他治好了许多人的病，但他还是被揭穿为一个江湖骗子。', '形容词: charlatanic 名词: charlatanism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('linger', '[\'lɪŋɡər]', 'vi.徘徊；逗留；消磨；漫步', '1. The beautiful melody is lingering in my mind. 美妙的音乐在我心中回荡。 2. She linger after the concert, hoping to meet the star. 音乐会后她徘徊不去，希望能遇见明星。 3. He made excuses to linger on the stairs. 他找借口故意在楼梯口上磨磨蹭蹭。 4. We can\'t linger any more, because we have so many works unfinished. 我们有这么作业还没完成,不能在拖延了。', '副词: lingeringly 名词: lingerer 过去式: lingered 过去分词: lingered 现在分词: lingering 第三人称单数: lingers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('efface', '[ɪ\'feɪs]', 'v.擦掉；抹去；使（自己）不受人注意；忘却', '1. He would have to efface himself before his visitors. 他每每只好在客人面前躲而避之。 2. Time alone will efface those unpleasant memories. 只有时间才能使人淡忘那些不快的记忆。 3. Time and weather had long ago effaced the inscription on the monument. 岁月和风雨早已磨掉纪念碑上的铭文。', '形容词: effaceable 名词: effacement 过去式: effaced 过去分词: effaced 现在分词: effacing 第三人称单数: effaces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('offhand', '[ˌɔːf\'hænd]', 'adj.即时的；未经准备的；唐突无礼的 adv.即时地；未经思索地；随便地', '1. But this offhand explanation was not strictly true. 不过这个搪塞的解释并不完全正确。 2. There was something in his offhand remarks. 他随口说出的话里倒也有些道理。 3. I don\'t like his offhand manner. 我不喜欢他那粗鲁的态度。 4. I can\'t give the answer offhand. 我不能即刻给出答复。', '副词: offhandedly 名词: offhandedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shoot', '[ʃuːt]', 'v.发射；开枪；疾驰；拍照 n.发射；嫩枝 int.哇! 可恶! 哎呀!', '1. This is just a toy gun; it doesn\'t shoot. 这只是玩具枪, 不能发射子弹。 2. He shot the bird with his gun. 他用枪打鸟。 3. The sports car shot past us. 赛车从我们前面飞驰而过。 4. The scene was shot on location. 这个景是实地拍摄的。 5. The enemies made shoots at us. 敌人向我们发起射击。 6. Shoot! My coat is caught in the door. 哇，上衣被车门夹住了。', '名词: shooter 过去式: shot 过去分词: shot 现在分词: shooting 第三人称单数: shoots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fathom', '[\'fæðəm]', 'n.英寻（=6英尺) vi.测量深度 vt.彻底了解；测深', '1. The ship sank in four fathoms. 这条船沉下四英寻。 2. This kind of love is difficult to fathom, but it\'s fundamentally reliable. 虽然很难去测量这种爱有多深，但是它却完全可以信赖。 3. I cannot fathom his meaning. 我不能彻底了解他的意思。 4. He dipped the stick into the water to fathom its depth. 他把棍条浸入水中，试探水的深度。', '形容词: fathomable 名词复数: fathom 过去式: fathomed 过去分词: fathomed 现在分词: fathoming 第三人称单数: fathoms');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drainage', '[\'dreɪnɪdʒ]', 'n.排水；排水系统；污水；【医】引流（法），导液（法）', '1. Bad drainage caused the land to be flooded. 排水不利容易使土地淹水。 2. Make holes through the base to allow for drainage. 在地基中开洞，以便排水。 3. The drainage system has been aged. 排水系统已经老化了。 4. The town\'s drainage is very efficient. 这城市的排水系统很好。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('beet', '[biːt]', 'n.甜菜根；甜菜', '1. Beets are Hank\'s favorite vegetable. 甜菜根是汉克最爱吃的蔬菜。 2. They planted many beets this year. 他们今年种了许多甜菜。 3. Now we are going to unload the beet pulp pellet overside into the barges. 现在我们要把外档的甜菜渣卸到驳船上。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('barn', '[bɑːrn]', 'n.谷仓；牲口棚；车库；大而空荡的农屋', '1. The barn will store five tons of grain. 这个谷仓能放五吨粮食。 2. We took shelter from the storm in a barn. 我们在一个谷仓里躲避暴风雨。 3. The cows were feeding on hay in the barn. 母牛正在牲口棚里吃乾草呢。 4. Another barn has been built there. 另一个牲口棚建在那儿。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inculpate', '[\'ɪnkʌlˌpeɪt]', 'vt.使负罪；控告', '1. inculpate v. 连累；控告；', '形容词: inculpatory 名词: inculpation 过去式: inculpated 过去分词: inculpated 现在分词: inculpating 第三人称单数: inculpates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perverse', '[pər\'vɜːrs]', 'adj.任性的；固执错误的；故意作对的；有悖常理的', '1. We all wanted to go tomorrow, but she had to be perverse and insisted on going today. 我们都想明天去，但她十分任性偏要今天去。 2. I hate his perverse refusal to see a doctor. 我最恨他那拒不就医的固执态度。 3. That perverse guy has been nagging at me all day. 那个故意与我作对的家伙让我终日不得安宁。 4. She gets a perverse satisfaction from making other people embarrassed. 她有一种不正常的心态，以使别人难堪来取乐。', '副词: perversely 名词: perverseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appendage', '[ə\'pendɪdʒ]', 'n.附加物；附属品；附属器官', '1. The amendment is an appendage of that contract. 这个修改案是那个合同的附件。 2. The elephant\'s trunk is a unique appendage. 象的鼻子是一种独特的附肢。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('uninitiated', '[ˌʌnɪ\'nɪʃieɪtɪd]', 'adj.缺乏某种特定知识和经验的；不谙此道的 n.缺乏某种特定经验的人', '1. The labels can be a bit confusing for the uninitiated customers. 对于缺乏经验的顾客来说，这些标签有点令人困惑。 2. To the uninitiated,economics has always been a dismal science. 对门外汉来说，经济学永远是种沉闷无趣的科学。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bibliophile', '[\'bɪbliəfaɪl]', 'n.爱书者；藏书家 =bibliophist.', '1. Ted loves everything about books. He is a real bibliophile. 泰德喜爱所有与书籍有关的事物。他真是一个爱书人。', '形容词: bibliophilistic 异体字: bibliophil 名词: bibliophilism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ravening', '[\'rævənɪŋ]', 'adj.（尤指狼群）贪婪而饥饿的 动词raven的现在分词形式.', '1. It is the ravening lion roaming the earth seeking whom it may devour. 它就像荒野中游荡的狮子，在寻找可以吞食的猎物。 2. Beware of false prophets, which come to you in sheep\'s clothing, but inwardly are ravening wolves. 当心伪先知，他们身着羊皮接近你，但实际上是掠夺的狼。', '副词: raveningly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scutter', '[\'skʌtə]', 'n.疾走 v.疾走', '1. You have to scutter,otherwise you won\'t catch the train. 你得快点跑，不然你就赶不上火车了。', '过去式: scuttered 过去分词: scuttered 现在分词: scuttering 第三人称单数: scutters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('upstart', '[\'ʌpstɑːrt]', 'n.暴发户；傲慢自负之人 adj.暴富的；傲慢的 v.突然跳起', '1. He was a new upstart and a gentleman of the first head. 他是个暴发户，是个新封的贵族。 2. You can\'t marry that young upstart! 你可不能嫁给那个年轻的暴发户！ 3. Lesson those upstart person with a over-confident mind. 狠狠的修理自以为很款很有势的爆发户. 4. He dreaded their upstart ambition. 他惧怕他们的狂妄野心。', '过去式: upstarted 过去分词: upstarted 现在分词: upstarting 第三人称单数: upstarts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aorta', '[eɪ\'ɔːrtə]', 'n.主动脉', '1. The aorta is the largest artery in the body. 主动脉是人体中的最大动脉。', '形容词: aortal 名词复数: aortas');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marbled', '[\'mɑːrbld]', '大理石的,用大理石装饰或建造的', '1. Marbled grey nuance, supplied in kits of 2 mats. 灰色大理石色调，供应的每个套件 ″2 块垫子。 2. Seeds subglobose, ca. 8 mm in diam., brown marbled. 种子近球形的直径约8毫米，棕色大理石纹。 3. Seeds ca. 5 mm in diam., marbled. 种子直径约5毫米，有大理石纹。 4. Esablish i 2000,Lii Marbl & Grai Co. 我公司成立于2000年。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('convalesce', '[ˌkɒnvə\'les]', 'v.渐渐康复；渐愈', '1. She go to the seaside to convalesce after her stay in hospital. 她经过住院治疗後，前往海滨养病。 2. She went to the seaside to convalesce after her stay in hospital. 她经过住院治疗后,前往海滨养病。', '过去式: convalesced 过去分词: convalesced 现在分词: convalescing 第三人称单数: convalesces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commonplace', '[\'kɑːmənpleɪs]', 'adj.平凡的；陈腐的 n.常事；老生常谈；普通的东西', '1. Poets interpret the commonplace freshly. 诗人能把平凡的事物描绘得有声有色。 2. He was an unambitious man destined for a commonplace job. 他是一个没有野心的人，注定要找一个平凡的工作。 3. Soon it will be commonplace for men to travel to the moon. 人们去月球旅行很快就会成为常事。 4. What he has said is a mere commonplace. 他所说的无非是老生常谈而已。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deposit', '[dɪ\'pɑːzɪt]', 'v.放置；(使)沉淀；存储；付(订金等)；寄存 n.存款；定金；堆积物；矿床', '1. She deposited a pile of books on my desk. 她把一摞书放在我的书桌上。 2. Coarse crumb rubber is apt to deposit in asphalt. 粗的橡胶颗粒容易在沥青中沉淀。 3. The Nile floods the fields and deposits mud on them. 尼罗河泛滥，在田野上淤积一层泥。 4. He deposits a sum of money in the bank each month. 他每月在银行存一笔钱。 5. Ten yuan is the minimum initial deposit. 最低的开户存款金额是十元。', '名词: depositor 过去式: deposited 过去分词: deposited 现在分词: depositing 第三人称单数: deposits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('malefactor', '[\'mælɪfæktər]', 'n.罪人；犯人；坏人', '1. Malefactors will be pursued and punished. 作恶的人要予以究治。', '名词: malefaction');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('limerick', '[\'lɪmərɪk]', 'n.五行打油诗', '1. I decided to write a limerick about you! 我想写一首关于你的打油诗。 2. He is full of imagination and can knock off a limerick in a few minutes. 他富于想象力,只几分钟就能写出一首五行打油诗。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('assumption', '[ə\'sʌmpʃn]', 'n.假定；设想；担任(职责等)；假装', '1. The project was predicated on the assumption that the economy was expanding. 这一计划是以经济发展的设想为依据的。 2. The theory is based on a series of wrong assumptions. 这一理论是以一系列错误的设想为依据的。 3. His assumption of power was welcomed by everyone. 他的当权为大家所欢迎。 4. He talked with an assumption of ease. 他装出从容的样子说话。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inimitable', '[ɪ\'nɪmɪtəbl]', 'adj.无法仿效的；不可比拟的', '1. He delivered the speech in his own inimitable style. 他以其无人可模仿的独特风格发表了演说。 2. That was an inimitable feeling when we fell in love with each other. 当我们相爱时，那是一种多么无可比拟的感觉啊。', '副词: inimitably 名词: inimitability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aftermath', '[\'æftərmæθ]', 'n.后果；余波；灾后时期；再生作物', '1. In the aftermath of the hurricane, many people\'s homes were destroyed. 飓风的后果是许多人的房屋被毁。 2. The aftermath of war brought a financial boom. 战争带来了财政经济的兴旺发展。 3. The president visited the region in the immediate aftermath of the disaster. 总统访问个这个刚刚经历灾难的地区。 4. Many people were homeless in the aftermath of the earthquake. 地震之后,许多人无家可归。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cacophonous', '[kə\'kɒfənəs]', 'adj.声音不和谐的；刺耳的', '1. As expected, birds raised in soundproof boxes grew up to sing cacophonous songs. 根据之前的实验，预计在隔声盒中养大的鸟长大后唱的歌将会是刺耳的歌。', '副词: cacophonously');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('custody', '[\'kʌstədi]', 'n.拘留；监禁；监护；羁押', '1. He is in custody awaiting trial. 他已被拘留候审。 2. The criminal was taken into custody. 这个罪犯已被监禁。 3. After their divorce, the father was awarded custody of the son. 离婚以后，孩子由父亲监护。 4. My ex shares custody of the children. 我原先的配偶分担照顾孩子的责任。', '名词复数: custodies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('marine', '[mə\'riːn]', 'adj.海的；海事的；海生的；航海的 n.海运业；船舶；水兵', '1. His father is a marine biologist. 他父亲是位海洋生物学家。 2. Water pollution imperils all kinds of marine life. 水质污染危及所有海洋生物。 3. He works for the marine court. 他为海事法庭工作。 4. The rocks are covered by marine plants. 岩石被海生植物所覆盖。 5. He sought an officer\'s berth in the merchant marine. 他在商船上找了一个高级船员的职位。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('moan', '[moʊn]', 'n.呻吟声；抱怨声 vt.抱怨；呻吟 vi.呻吟；抱怨', '1. Each time she moved her head she let out a moan. 她每转动一下头，就发出一声呻吟。 2. A moan escaped the badly wounded soldier. 那个重伤员不禁呻吟了一声。 3. His constant moan is that no one understands him. 他老是抱怨没有人理解他。 4. She moaned her misfortunes to anyone who would listen. 她向任何乐于听的人哀叹命运不济。 5. Suddenly he began to moan in his sleep. 突然他在睡梦中开始呻吟。', '过去式: moaned 过去分词: moaned 现在分词: moaning 第三人称单数: moans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('contiguous', '[kən\'tɪɡjuəs]', 'adj.邻近的；连续的；接触的', '1. California and Mexico are contiguous. 加利福尼亚和墨西哥相邻。 2. They are two immediately contiguous areas. 他们是紧密接邻的地区。 3. Extents determine how data is striped across multiple containers and ensure that the data pages in a container are contiguous. 区段确定如何跨越多个容器进行数据分段,并确保一个容器里的数据页面是连续的。 4. California and Mexico are contiguous. 加利福尼亚和墨西哥相邻。', '副词: contiguously 名词: contiguousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perch', '[pɜːrtʃ]', 'n.栖木；高位；杆；河鲈鱼 v.栖息；就位；位于', '1. The bird took its perch on a tree branch. 鸟儿栖息在树枝上。 2. The bird flew down from its perch in the cage. 这只鸟从栖息的鸟笼里飞下。 3. The boy sat on the perch and sang lustily. 那个男孩坐在高处起劲地唱。 4. He has a perch in his father\'s bank for as long as he wants it. 他在他父亲的银行里占有一高位，想占多久就多久。 5. The bird perched on the electric wires. 鸟栖息在电线上。', '名词复数: perch 过去式: perched 过去分词: perched 现在分词: perching 第三人称单数: perches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('coagulation', '[kəʊˌæɡju\'leɪʃn]', 'n.凝结', '1. Azoth is often associated with the alchemical principle of coagulation. 水银通常与炼金术中的凝结原理有关。 2. Coagulation of such systems requires rather drastic treatment with massive doses of coagulant salts. 凝聚这种体系时需要用大量凝结剂盐类进行相当激烈的处理。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ennui', '[ɑːn\'wiː]', 'n.怠倦；无聊', '1. You too would suffer from ennui if you had to spend months in a hospital bed. 如果你必须在医院的病床上躺好几个月，那么你也会感到无聊的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('heterogeneous', '[ˌhetərə\'dʒiːniəs]', 'adj.异种的；异质的；由不同成份形成的 [计算机] 非均匀的.', '1. Finally, it is doubtful that such a system could be other than heterogeneous. 最后,这样的系统能不异构很是值得怀疑。 2. The grid is a collection of heterogeneous computing resources. 网格是一组异质计算资源。 3. There is a heterogeneous mass of papers in the teacher\'s office. 老师的办公室里堆满了大批不同的论文。', '副词: heterogeneously 名词: heterogeneousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('upstage', '[ˌʌp\'steɪdʒ]', 'adv.在或向舞台后部地 adj.高傲的；势利的；在后台部的 v.抢风头；势利地对待 n.舞台后部', '1. The dancers were directed to move upstage. 跳舞的人向舞台后部走去。 2. They\'re much too upstage for us these days. 他们近来对我们太势利了。 3. An interpreter mustn\'t upstage the speaker. 翻译不应该抢发言人的风头。 4. He tried to upstage his boss at the meeting. 他在会议期间尽力显得比上司突出。', '名词: upstager 过去式: upstaged 过去分词: upstaged 现在分词: upstaging 第三人称单数: upstages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agitate', '[\'ædʒɪteɪt]', 'v.煽动；搅动；焦虑', '1. They sent agents to agitate the local people. 他们派遣情报人员煽动当地的民众。 2. Agitate the mixture to dissolve the powder. 搅动混合物而使粉末溶化。 3. He was agitated about his wife\'s health. 他为他妻子的健康感到不安。 4. He became quite agitated when he was asked about his criminal past. 当问到他过去的犯罪历史时，他变得十分焦虑不安。', '形容词: agitative 副词: agitatedly 过去式: agitated 过去分词: agitated 现在分词: agitating 第三人称单数: agitates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shun', '[ʃʌn]', 'v.避开；回避；避免', '1. His friends shunned him. 他的朋友都避开他。 2. They shun personal fame and gains. 他们不计个人名利。 3. This recluse shunned all company. 这位隐士不与任何人来往。 4. Wise men love truth, whereas fools shun it. 智者热爱真理,愚者回避真理。', '名词: shunner 过去式: shunned 过去分词: shunned 现在分词: shunning 第三人称单数: shuns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ballot', '[\'bælət]', 'n.投票；投票用纸 vi.投票', '1. We should put it to a ballot. 我们应该对此进行无记名投票。 2. He was elected by ballot. 他是由无记名投票选举的。 3. The new act stipulates that election to union office shall be by secret ballot of members. 新法规定工会职位的选举将由会员秘密投票方式进行。 4. Each voter receives a unique ballot code. 每一个投票人会收到一个独一的选票号码。 5. They decided to ballot for competing lanes. 他们决定抽签选择比赛跑道。', '名词: balloter 过去式: balloted 过去分词: balloted 现在分词: balloting 第三人称单数: ballots');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vengeful', '[\'vendʒfl]', 'adj.复仇心重的；报复的', '1. The whole episode made me vengeful. 整个事件使我一心想复仇。 2. It looked at you with a vengeful aspect. 它用一种报仇雪恨的神情望着你。 3. Meanwhile, the new government should avoid seeming vengeful. 同时，新政府应避免表现出复仇的迹象。', '副词: vengefully 名词: vengefulness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gruesome', '[\'ɡruːsəm]', 'adj.可怕的；令人毛骨悚然的；阴森的', '1. That gruesome story was enough to turn one\'s blood cold. 那个可怕的故事足以使人毛骨悚然。 2. Perform the gruesome task of identifying the dead bodies. 执行辨认尸体这可怕的任务。 3. Death is a gruesome and terrible Arcanum. 死亡是一个恐怖而令人毛骨悚然的奥秘。 4. I heard stories of gruesome tortures in prisons. 我听说过监狱里令人毛骨悚然的刑讯。', '副词: gruesomely 名词: gruesomeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conduct', '[kən\'dʌkt]', 'n.行为；举动；品行 v.引导；指挥；管理 vt.导电；传热', '1. Your conduct is not consistent with what you say. 你的言行不一致。 2. His behavior transgressed the unwritten rules of social conduct. 他的行为违反了不成文的社交规范。 3. His conduct roused the suspicion of the police. 他的举动引起了警察的怀疑。 4. He has good conduct. 他品行端正。 5. The guide conducted us around the ruins of the ancient city. 导游引导我们游览了古城废墟。 6. Most metals can conduct electricity. 大多数金属能导电。', '形容词: conductible 名词: conductibility 过去式: conducted 过去分词: conducted 现在分词: conducting 第三人称单数: conducts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ornery', '[\'ɔːrnəri]', 'adj.脾气坏的；故意刁难的', '1. It is mostly because we\'re mean and ornery. 多半是因为我们小心眼，有点固执。 2. But they seem to be becoming more ornery. 然而他们看起来脾气变得越来越大。 3. Ornery or not,You\'ve been M.I.A for over a month. 贱不贱我不管，你失踪了有一个多月了。 4. I\'m nasty, I\'m old, and a little bit ornery. 我有点儿惹人讨厌，我是老头，有点爱唠叨。', '比较级: ornerier 最高级: orneriest 名词: orneriness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pesticide', '[\'pestɪsaɪd]', 'n.杀虫剂；农药', '1. The crops are regularly sprayed with pesticide. 庄稼定期喷洒杀虫剂。 2. The insects have become resistant to the pesticide. 这些昆虫已经对杀虫剂有抗药性了。 3. The seeds and the pesticide are both ready. 种子跟农药都准备好了。 4. This pesticide is harmless to crops. 这种农药对农作物无害。', '形容词: pesticidal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pulsate', '[\'pʌlseɪt]', 'v.搏动；悸动；有规律的鼓动', '1. The air seemed to pulsate with the bright light. 空气似乎随着亮光而颤动。 2. Hues of purplish, rose and amber begin to pulsate in the sky. 淡紫色的、玫瑰色的和琥珀色的色调开始在天空中微微颤动起来。 3. The air seemed to pulsate with the bright light. 空气似乎随着亮光而颤动。', '过去式: pulsated 过去分词: pulsated 现在分词: pulsating 第三人称单数: pulsates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('emphatic', '[ɪm\'fætɪk]', 'adj.强调的；(人)明确表示的；有目共睹的；[语]语势强的', '1. \"You must go\", she said in an emphatic tone. “你非得去不可”,她用强调的口气说。 2. He refused my offer with an emphatic shake of head. 他用力摇了摇头，拒绝了我的提议。 3. He was emphatic that he could not work with her. 他强调他不能与她共事。 4. He was emphatic about the importance of being punctual. 他强调严守时间的重要性。', '副词: emphatically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pliant', '[\'plaɪənt]', 'adj.易受影响的；易弯的', '1. He was deposed and replaced by a more pliant successor. 他被赶下台，由一个比较容易摆布的继任者取代。 2. New research shows how the pliant animals create such a stiff limb. 新研究显示了这种软梯动物时如何形成这样有力的肢体。', '副词: pliantly 名词: pliancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wield', '[wiːld]', 'v.行使；施加(影响)；使用(武器等)；挥舞', '1. People may wield the power in a democracy. 在民主国家里，人民可以行使权力。 2. She wields a lot of influence. 她是个很有影响力的人。 3. He decides to wield his pitiful weapon. 他决定动用他的可怜的武器了。 4. We must learn to wield the weapon of law effectively. 我们要学会使用和用好法律武器。', '形容词: wieldable 名词: wielder 过去式: wielded 过去分词: wielded 现在分词: wielding 第三人称单数: wields');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ordain', '[ɔːr\'deɪn]', 'vt.任命；授以圣职；命令；注定 vi.颁发命令', '1. He was an ordained priest. 他被委任为牧师。 2. She was ordained the first woman priest of her church. 她被委任为她教会的第一位女牧师。 3. The emperor ordained that all foreigners be expelled. 皇帝下令将所有外国人驱逐出境。 4. The judge ordained that he should pay the debts. 法院判决由他偿还债务。', '名词: ordainer 过去式: ordained 过去分词: ordained 现在分词: ordaining 第三人称单数: ordains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('procreate', '[\'proʊkrieɪt]', 'v.生育；生殖；产生', '1. Why do we breathe,why do we procreate? 我们为什么要呼吸，为什么要生儿育女? 2. To engender(offspring;procreate. 产生（后代）；生育 3. To procreate(offspring)as the male parent. 作为父亲生养（后代） 4. To engender(offspring); procreate. 产生（后代）；生育', '形容词: procreant 名词: procreation 过去式: procreated 过去分词: procreated 现在分词: procreating 第三人称单数: procreates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cling', '[klɪŋ]', 'vi.紧贴；附着；依恋；坚持 n.紧抓；紧贴', '1. The wet clothes clung to his body. 湿衣服紧贴在他身上。 2. He clung to my arm. 他紧抓着我的胳膊。 3. The cat tried to cling to the edge by its claws. 猫用爪子拼命抓住那边缘。 4. Little children always cling to their mothers. 小孩子总是紧依着母亲。 5. The droid used his magnetized rollers to cling tenaciously to the chromed surface of the ship while deadly turbolaser blasts rained overhead. 在致命的雷射光炮不停地打落在太空船上时，他用具有磁性的滚轮紧抓住舰艇铬制的表面。', '形容词: clingy 名词: clinger 过去式: clung 过去分词: clung 现在分词: clinging 第三人称单数: clings');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('odyssey', '[\'ɑːdəsi]', 'n.远行；长途冒险旅行 n.奥德赛(希腊史诗)', '1. Odyssey does not carry instruments that can search for life on Mars. 奥德赛号没有携带可以探索火星存在生物的仪器。 2. Greek Epic poet,two of the greatest works in Western literature,the Iliad and the Odyssey,are attributed to him. 荷马希腊史诗作者创作了西方文学最伟大的两部作品伊利亚特和奥德赛。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sincere', '[sɪn\'sɪr]', 'adj.真诚的；诚挚的', '1. How can I persuade you that I am sincere? 怎样才能使你相信我是真心实意的呢? 2. I will oblige any sincere request. 我会答应任何诚意的请求。 3. I think he is sincere and quite without affectation. 我认为他为人诚挚，毫不做作。 4. Sincere congratulations on your son wedding please convey our best wish. 令郎喜结良缘谨此致以诚挚的祝贺并请转达最美好的祝愿。', '副词: sincerely 比较级: sincerer 最高级: sincerest 名词: sincereness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('incubator', '[\'ɪŋkjubeɪtər]', 'n.孵卵器；早产儿保育器', '1. An incubator is used to hatch chicken. 孵卵器用来孵小鸡。 2. The college campus is an incubator of radical new sociological concepts. 大学校园是产生激进的社会学新概念的温床。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('medium', '[\'miːdiəm]', 'adj.中等的；适中的 n.手段；媒介；媒体', '1. The blue cap is a medium size. 那顶蓝色的帽子就是中号的。 2. The clothes should be washed at medium temperature. 这衣服需以适中温度洗涤。 3. Commercial television is an effective medium for advertising. 商业电视是有效的广告宣传工具。 4. Sound travels through the medium of air. 声音通过空气这一媒介传播。', '名词复数: media');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nascent', '[\'næsnt]', 'adj.新生的；尚不成熟的；尚不发达的', '1. Nascent nanotechnologies are being mashed up with biotechnologies. 新生的纳米技术与生物科技糅合起来。 2. China\'s nascent stock market turned in a stellar performance 中国新生的股票市场取得第一流的表现。 3. The nascent reform has been changing a lot of people\'s life. 尚不成熟的改革改变了很多人的生活。 4. But China is a nascent superpower. 而中国则是一个新兴超级大国。', '名词: nascency');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('modify', '[\'mɑːdɪfaɪ]', 'v.修改；更改；缓和；修饰', '1. We have to modify our plan a little bit. 我们得对我们的计划稍加修改。 2. The policy was agreed by the committee, but only in a modified form. 那项政策经修改后才获得委员会同意。 3. The union has been forced to slightly modify its position. 工会被迫稍稍改变立场。 4. He\'ll have to modify his views if he wants to be elected. 他要想当选就得把观点改得缓和些。', '形容词: modifiable 名词: modifiability 过去式: modified 过去分词: modified 现在分词: modifying 第三人称单数: modifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cone', '[koʊn]', 'n.圆锥体；锥形物；球果 vt.变成锥形', '1. Saw-dust has piled up in a great cone. 锯屑堆积如山。 2. The police have sectioned off the road with traffic cone. 警察用锥形路标把路面分隔开来。 3. The little boy likes to eat the ice-cream cone. 小男孩喜欢吃冰淇淋蛋卷。 4. The staminate cone of pine is male rather than female. 松树雄球果是雄性而非雌性。 5. They coned off a section of motorway during repairs. 他们用锥形标志隔开维修中的一段高速公路。', '过去式: coned 过去分词: coned 现在分词: coning 第三人称单数: cones');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bolster', '[\'boʊlstər]', 'n.长枕；靠垫 vt.支持；鼓励', '1. There is a bolster across the head of the bed. 床头上有一个长枕垫。 2. Both sides offered statistics to bolster their arguments. 双方都拿出统计数字来支持他们的论点。 3. We always bolster up the government in its struggle against terrorism 我们始终支持政府的反恐怖主义的斗争。 4. They bolstered their morale by singing. 他们以唱歌来鼓舞士气。', '名词: bolsterer 过去式: bolstered 过去分词: bolstered 现在分词: bolstering 第三人称单数: bolsters');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crux', '[krʌks]', 'n.关键；难题；[天]十字座；坩埚', '1. Therein lies the crux of the matter. 问题的关键就在那里。 2. Now we come to the crux of the problem. 现在我们来谈问题的症结所在。 3. This is the first main crux of dynamic theory. 这是动态学说第一个主要的难题。', '名词复数: cruxes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pretend', '[prɪ\'tend]', 'v.假装；装作；自以为', '1. She pretends that she likes them so that she can get their help. 她假装很喜欢他们，借以获得他们的帮助。 2. The young actor pretended to be Hamlet. 那个年轻演员扮演哈姆雷特。 3. She closed her eyes and pretended to be asleep. 她闭上眼睛,装作睡着了。 4. Surely he doesn\'t pretend to any understanding of music! 谅他不会自以为懂得什麽音乐吧！', '过去式: pretended 过去分词: pretended 现在分词: pretending 第三人称单数: pretends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('callow', '[\'kæloʊ]', 'adj.未成熟的；缺乏经验的', '1. Callow birds left desert to the skies. 那羽翼未丰的小鸟离开沙漠飞向天空。 2. He was a callow youth when he joined the newspaper. 他进报社时还是个乳臭未干的小子。 3. I believed a lot of things in my callow youth that I don\'t believe now. 在我年轻尚无经验时相信的许多事情，现在我不相信了。', '名词: callowness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bleary', '[\'blɪri]', 'adj.眼睛模糊的；朦胧的；精疲力尽的', '1. A bad cold has made him bleary. 严重的感冒使他视力模糊。 2. Pablo looked at him through his bleary eyes. 巴布罗那双目光呆滞的眼睛望着他。 3. He could only see a bleary view. 他只能看到一个朦胧的景色。 4. She had bleary red eyes from lack of sleep. 她由于缺乏睡眠而双眼昏花，布满血丝。', '副词: blearily 比较级: blearier 最高级: bleariest 名词: bleariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imitative', '[\'ɪmɪteɪtɪv]', 'adj.仿制的；模仿的', '1. Sculpture is an imitative art,ie it copies people,things,etc from real life. 雕刻是模仿的艺术(模刻真实生活中的人、物等). 2. Monkeys are imitative. 猴子爱模仿。 3. This disproves the theory that children are purely imitative. 这证明认为儿童只会单纯地模仿的理论是站不住脚的。', '副词: imitatively 名词: imitativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bracelet', '[\'breɪslət]', 'n.手镯', '1. I like to wear bracelets. 我喜欢戴手镯。 2. Is this bracelet genuine gold? 这个手镯是纯金的吗？ 3. Her bracelet was set with emeralds. 她的手镯上镶著绿宝石。 4. I\'d like you to take this bracelet as a gift. 我希望你把这手镯礼物收下。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intimidate', '[ɪn\'tɪmɪdeɪt]', 'vt.胁迫；威胁；恐吓', '1. Nobody was going to intimidate them. 没有人能胁迫他们。 2. He was intimidated into silence. 他吓得不敢作声。 3. Bob intimidate the witness into silence. 鲍勃威胁证人保持沉默。 4. Your sons don\'t intimidate me. And neither do you. 你的儿子们威胁不了我,你也一样。', '副词: intimidatingly 名词: intimidation 过去式: intimidated 过去分词: intimidated 现在分词: intimidating 第三人称单数: intimidates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aggressive', '[ə\'ɡresɪv]', 'adj.侵略的；进攻性的；好斗的；有进取心的', '1. He has an aggressive manner. 他的态度咄咄逼人。 2. His style of argument in meetings is not so much aggressive as pertinacious. 他在会议上的辩论态度并非锋芒逼人而是坚持己见。 3. Red fire ants are very aggressive and readily attack anything that disturb them. 红火蚁攻击性强,容易攻击任何干扰它们的生物。 4. America has a lot of aggressive weapons now. 美国现在有很多进攻性武器。', '副词: aggressively 名词: aggressiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amoral', '[ˌeɪ\'mɔːrəl]', 'adj.与道德无关的；无从区分是非的', '1. Cats are amoral; they can\'t be censured for killing birds. 猫不受道德约束，它们杀死鸟儿也不会受责难。 2. Unfortunately, television conveys no sense of morality since it is itself amoral. 不幸的是，电视传达的东西没有道德感，因为它本身与道德无关。 3. Young children are amoral. 小孩子是不懂是非的。', '副词: amorally 名词: amoralism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('judicial', '[dʒu\'dɪʃl]', 'adj.司法的；法庭的；公正的；审判上的', '1. He applied for judicial review to quash the order. 他申请司法检查废止该命令。 2. She got a judicial separation from her husband. 她得到法庭判决夫妇分居。 3. He is a man with a judicial mind. 他是个公正的人。 4. In British India, district commissioners had judicial powers. 在过去的英属印度，地区长官有审判权。', '副词: judicially');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('itinerant', '[aɪ\'tɪnərənt]', 'adj.巡回的；流动的 n.巡回者', '1. In the same year an itinerant black preacher arrived in Los Angeles. 就在同一年，一个黑人巡回传教士抵达了洛杉矶。 2. RIM has been stunningly successful, but even it has only around 3 million users, mostly itinerant corporate executives. 然而即使其仅有300万用户，且其中大多为飞来飞去的企业经理，RIM 已经是极其成功了。 3. Itinerant bike repairmen can be found on almost every street. 流动的自行车修理摊几乎在每条街道都可以找到。 4. There is a general debate nowadays about the problem of itinerant workers. 目前，针对流动工人的问题展开了普遍的争论。 5. Going on a trip or changing the apartment, Tiefschlaf is a must for any itinerant. 旅行中或者改变你的公寓,德国睡梦是巡游者的必需品。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cosmos', '[\'kɑːzmoʊs]', 'n.宇宙 (复数）cosmos或cosmoses:大波斯菊.', '1. Our world is but a small part of the cosmos. 我们的世界仅仅是宇宙的一小部分而已。 2. Therefore, God projected the cosmos and souls. 因此，上帝投射了宇宙和灵魂。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('snooze', '[snuːz]', 'v.打盹儿；懒散着打发掉日子 n.打盹儿', '1. Dad is taking a snooze in the other room. 爸爸正在另外一间房间里打盹儿。 2. Dad is taking a snooze in the other room. 爸爸正在另外一间房间里打盹儿。', '过去式: snoozed 过去分词: snoozed 现在分词: snoozing 第三人称单数: snoozes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('expiate', '[\'ekspieɪt]', 'v.赎罪；补偿；<古>结束', '1. He had a chance to confess and expiate his guilt. 他有认错和赎罪的机会。 2. He hoped to expiate his guilt. 他希望为他的过失赎罪。', '名词: expiator 过去式: expiated 过去分词: expiated 现在分词: expiating 第三人称单数: expiates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('citation', '[saɪ\'teɪʃn]', 'n.引用；表扬；(法律)传票', '1. Space does not permit the citation of the examples. 篇幅有限，示例从略。 2. Some dictionary writer use citation to show what word mean. 有些辞典的编纂者用引文作例证以解释词义。 3. He had to sign the proposition for the citation. 他只好在受奖申请书上签了字。 4. What kind of citation you are going to get? 你会得到哪一种表扬呢?', '形容词: citational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brawny', '[\'brɔːni]', 'adj.(人)强壮的', '1. The blacksmith has a brawny arm. 铁匠有强壮的胳膊。 2. A brawny blacksmith made a reach for him. 一个强壮的铁匠伸手过来抓他。', '副词: brawnily 比较级: brawnier 最高级: brawniest 名词: brawniness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thematic', '[θɪ\'mætɪk]', 'adj.主题的；[语]词干的；[音]主旋律的', '1. He has a series of thematic commemorative stamps. 他有一系列专题纪念邮票。 2. Thematic vowels are part of the stem. 词干的元音是词干的一部分。 3. An independent piece written for piano is usually based on a single,short thematic motif. 一首为钢琴所做的独立曲目，通常以一单独的，较短的主旋律为基调。', '副词: thematically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spangle', '[\'spæŋɡl]', 'n.闪光金属片；镶金属小片 v.(使)闪烁发光', '1. A spangle used to ornament a dress or costume. 亮片用来装饰衣服或服装的金属片 2. Surface Finish:regular spangle/skin pass spangle. 表面结构：正常锌花/光整锌花。 3. Flash of spangle in the moonlight! 月光下光芒闪烁！ 4. Spangle dimly their mystic eyes. 使它们神秘的眼睛朦胧闪烁。', '形容词: spangly 过去式: spangled 过去分词: spangled 现在分词: spangling 第三人称单数: spangles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sip', '[sɪp]', 'n.啜饮 v.啜饮；啜', '1. He took one sip of the wine and spat it out. 他抿了一口酒，又吐了出来。 2. He paused to take a sip of water, and then went on with his story. 他停下来呷了一口水，然後继续讲他的事。 3. I sipped at the coffee. 我啜饮咖啡。 4. When you drink your soup, don\'t sip it, but swallow it all in one mouthful. 喝汤时不要啜饮,而应一口吞下去。', '名词: sipper 过去式: sipped 过去分词: sipped 现在分词: sipping 第三人称单数: sips');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fuddle', '[\'fʌdəl]', 'v.使错乱；灌醉；使烂醉 n.混乱', '1. My brain\'s in a fuddle. 我的脑子糊里糊涂的。', '过去式: fuddled 过去分词: fuddled 现在分词: fuddling 第三人称单数: fuddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('protract', '[proʊ\'trækt]', 'vt.延长；托长；伸出', '1. To protract the suspense, he paused for a considerable period of time before telling us the result of the experiment. 为了延长悬念，他在告诉我们实验结果之前停顿了相当一段时间。', '形容词: protractive 副词: protractedly 名词: protractedness 过去式: protracted 过去分词: protracted 现在分词: protracting 第三人称单数: protracts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yokel', '[\'joʊkl]', 'n.乡下佬；土包子；土老帽儿', '1. But George Bailey is not a common,ordinary yokel. 可是，乔治·贝利不是一个普通的粗人。 2. The posters brought in the yokels from fifty miles around every whistle-stop we played. 那些广告把我们演出所在的每一个小镇周围50英里内的乡下佬都引来了。 3. The clothes makes him look like a slack-jaw yokel. 这件衣服让他看起来像个土包子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('destitution', '[ˌdestɪ\'tjuːʃn]', 'n.穷困；缺乏', '1. The people lived in destitution. 民生凋敝。 2. His drinking led him to a life of destitution. 酗酒导致他生活贫穷。 3. The few packages of food seemed a mockery in the face of such enormous destitution. 对于众多赤贫的人们,这几袋食物简直是杯水车薪。 4. In China, physical education in the western regions lags behind that in the east, which mainly is a destitution of an innovation of sports culture. 我国西部体育落后于东部地区，从根本上说，是缺乏体育文化创新。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mawkish', '[\'mɔːkɪʃ]', 'adj.令人作呕的；讨厌的；自作多情的', '1. Mawkish sentimentality, affection, or amorousness. 痴情令人发腻的多愁善感、痴情或韵事 2. Mawkish sentimentality,affection,or amorousness. 痴情令人发腻的多愁善感、痴情或韵事 3. Given to or displaying mawkish affection or amorousness. 给予或者显示出令人作呕的感情或者钟爱 4. Given to or displaying mawkish affectionor amorousness. 给予或者显示出令人作呕的感情或者钟爱。', '副词: mawkishly 名词: mawkishness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hurtle', '[\'hɜːrtl]', 'v.猛冲；猛投；猛烈碰撞 n.碰撞；猛冲', '1. The van hurtled round the corner. 客货车疾驶转过街角。 2. She slipped and went hurtling downstairs. 她一失足咕噜噜跌下楼梯。 3. He\'s hurtled out of the house. 他猛一下被扔出了屋子。 4. He hurtled his empty gun at my face. 他把空枪猛地朝我的脸上投来。', '过去式: hurtled 过去分词: hurtled 现在分词: hurtling 第三人称单数: hurtles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commiserate', '[kə\'mɪzəreɪt]', 'v.怜悯；同情', '1. She commiserated over their failure. 她对他们的失败表示怜悯。 2. I commiserated with her on the loss of her job. 她失去了工作，我很同情她。', '形容词: commiserative 副词: commiseratively 名词: commiserator 过去式: commiserated 过去分词: commiserated 现在分词: commiserating 第三人称单数: commiserates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('strip', '[strɪp]', 'v.剥去；剥夺；脱衣；除去 n.脱衣舞；长条；条状', '1. Elephants strip the leaves from trees. 大象剥去了树上的叶子。 2. It was wrong of him to strip his daughter of the right to education. 他不该剥夺他女儿受教育的权利。 3. Having been stripped of all his titles, he disappeared from public life. 他被剥夺一切荣誉之后，就从公共生活中消声匿迹了。 4. The children stripped off their clothes and jumped into the river. 孩子们脱掉衣服跳进河里。 5. You met me at a strip club. 你和我是在脱衣舞俱乐部里认识的。', '过去式: stripped 过去分词: stripped 现在分词: stripping 第三人称单数: strips');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sturdy', '[\'stɜːrdi]', 'adj.强健的；坚固的；坚决的', '1. The sturdy young man removed the rock without effort. 那个壮实的小伙子没费多大劲便把石块搬开了。 2. His son has grown up into a sturdy hardworking young man. 他的儿子已成长为一个健壮勤劳的小伙子。 3. That chair doesn\'t look very sturdy. 椅子看上其不坚固。 4. Have you any sturdy hiking boots? 有没有耐用的健行靴？', '副词: sturdily 比较级: sturdier 最高级: sturdiest 名词: sturdiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gloat', '[ɡloʊt]', 'v.满足地看；沾沾自喜；幸灾乐祸', '1. Chinese leaders have another reason not to gloat over the KMT\'s victory. 中国领导人亦有其他理由不去满足国民党的选举胜利。 2. Stop gloating just because you won the game! 别因为赢了就扬扬得意！ 3. A friend is someone to gloat with during the good times. 朋友是你得意时和你分享快乐的人. 4. It\'s nothing to gloat about. 没有什麽可幸灾乐祸的。', '名词: gloater 过去式: gloated 过去分词: gloated 现在分词: gloating 第三人称单数: gloats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antic', '[\'æntɪk]', 'n.古怪、滑稽的动作和行为；<古> 小丑 adj.古怪的；滑稽的', '1. We are laughing at the clown\'s silly antics. 我们因小丑笨拙的动作而发笑。 2. I call him an antic old man. 我称他是个古怪的老头。 3. The clown came on with many antic gestures. 小丑上场表演许多滑稽动作。', '副词: antically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('escalation', '[ˌeskə\'leɪʃn]', 'n.逐步扩大；增加', '1. An emergency session of the U. N. Security Council on Friday discussed the dramatic escalation of violence. 周五周五联合国安理会召开了紧急会议，讨论暴力活动的迅速升级局势。 2. There is an escalation in food prices. 食品价格不断增加。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('strident', '[\'straɪdnt]', 'adj.刺耳的；吱吱尖叫的；尖锐的', '1. His strident voice rang through the house. 他那刺耳的嗓音响彻整个房子。 2. People are put off by her strident voice. 人们对她刺耳的嗓音感到十分厌恶。 3. Here we can hear the strident calls of a crane or goose. 这儿我们能听到一只鹤或鹅的尖锐鸣声。 4. The siren is really strident. 警笛声好尖锐啊。', '副词: stridently 名词: stridence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impertinence', '[ɪm\'pɜːtɪnəns]', 'n.无礼；鲁莽；不恰当', '1. Such a remark verges on impertinence. 这种话近于无礼。 2. He will consider it an impertinence. 他会觉得这是无礼的举动。 3. Impertinence does not become you. 鲁莽与你不相称。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ravel', '[\'rævl]', 'v.开线；弄清楚；解决；使纠缠；使错综复杂 n.松开；松开的线；混乱 Ravel. n.拉威尔（人名）', '1. Bind the edge of the rug so that it won\'t ravel. 给地毯镶个边以免开线。 2. I can not ravel this piece of string,it\'s all in knots. 这条绳子打了好多结，我解不开。 3. Ravel a bit of the leftover cloth to mend the tear in vour dress. 拆开一点剩布的线,缝补你的衣服上的撕裂处。 4. We have to ravel the matter out. 我们必须把事情弄个水落石出。', '名词: raveler 过去式: raveled/ravelled 过去分词: raveled/ravelled 现在分词: raveling/ravelling 第三人称单数: ravels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('legislate', '[\'ledʒɪsleɪt]', 'v.制定法律；用立法规定', '1. It is the job of Parliament to legislate. 立法是议会的工作。 2. They promised to legislate to protect people\'s right to privacy. 他们承诺立法保护公民的隐私权。', '过去式: legislated 过去分词: legislated 现在分词: legislating 第三人称单数: legislates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mute', '[mjuːt]', 'n.哑子；弱音器；默音字母 adj.哑的；沉默的；无声的 vt.减音；减弱 vi.(鸟)排泄', '1. He\'s a deaf mute and cannot tell anyone secret. 他是个聋哑人，不会把他们的秘密告诉任何人。 2. He has been passing himself off as a deaf - mute . 他一直装聋作哑。 3. You need get a mute on your guitar to make the tune soft. 你得给吉他安个弱音器好让音柔和一点。 4. The letter \"e\" in \"mouse\" is mute. “mouse”中的字母“e”不发音。 5. He tried to speak but he was still mute. 他尽力想说，却仍然哑口无声。 6. Please mute a music instrument. 请减低乐器的声音。', '副词: mutely 比较级: muter 最高级: mutest 名词: muteness 过去式: muted 过去分词: muted 现在分词: muting 第三人称单数: mutes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('loyal', '[\'lɔɪəl]', 'adj.忠诚的；忠心的', '1. A loyal man stands by his friends in weal or woe. 一个忠诚的人无论祸福都会支持他的朋友。 2. We are loyal to our motherland. 我们忠于祖国。 3. I may say in all sincerity that you have been my most loyal friend. 我可以非常真诚地说，你一直是我最忠实的朋友。 4. The royal destroyer employs lots of loyal employees. 皇家驱逐舰雇佣了很多忠心的雇员。', '副词: loyally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('eviscerate', '[ɪ\'vɪsəreɪt]', 'v.取出内脏；除去精华', '1. Save your cold blood eviscerate as a finisher. 留着你的冷血剔骨做为最后一击。 2. Or a Rogue in 2 Hemos and an Eviscerate. 或者是盗贼两个出血一个剔骨就死了。 3. Lethality will no longer affect the Eviscerate ability. 致命伤不再影响剔骨攻击。 4. Eviscerate demolition meat, cut into the meat section. 拆肉剔骨，将肉切成条。', '名词: evisceration 过去式: eviscerated 过去分词: eviscerated 现在分词: eviscerating 第三人称单数: eviscerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pen', '[pen]', 'n.钢笔；笔；写作；围栏；雌天鹅 v.写；把…关在圈中', '1. The pen slips out of my fingers. 钢笔从我指缝中滑下去了。 2. Put down my pen and stop fiddling! 把我的钢笔放下，别用手玩弄！ 3. He dipped his pen in the ink. 他拿钢笔蘸墨水。 4. She fumbled about in her handbag for a pen. 她在手提袋中搜寻钢笔。 5. She penned a few words of thanks. 她写了几句致谢的话。', '名词: penner 过去式: penned 过去分词: penned 现在分词: penning 第三人称单数: pens');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('applause', '[ə\'plɔːz]', 'n.鼓掌；喝彩；赞许', '1. His speech won the applause of the audience. 他的讲话赢得了听众的掌声。 2. Let\'s have a good round of applause for the next performer. 咱们为下一个表演者热烈鼓掌吧。 3. His speech was frequently interrupted by stormy applause. 他的演说不时被暴风雨般的掌声打断。 4. He waited until the applause had subsided. 他一直等到掌声平息后才继续下去。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('candidacy', '[\'kændɪdəsi]', 'n.候选人的地位；候选资格', '1. He was admitted to candidacy for Ph.D. 他获得了博士候选人资格。 2. The politician declared his candidacy for president. 那位政治家公布了他作为总统候选人的资格。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('peak', '[piːk]', 'n.尖端；山顶；顶峰 v.达到顶峰；使处于顶点 vi.消瘦', '1. In Yersa I noticed a spike on the peak of the pyramid-shaped roof of a church. 在叶拉萨村,我发现一座教堂的金字塔屋顶的尖端有一颗尖钉。 2. The mountain peaks are covered with snow all year. 山顶上终年积雪。 3. Many mountaineers have reached that mountain peak. 许多登山家都登上过那座大山的顶峰。 4. Tourism is at its peak in August. 旅游业在八月份达到高峰。 5. Primary school enrolment will peak this year. 今年小学入学人数将达到最高峰。', '过去式: peaked 过去分词: peaked 现在分词: peaking 第三人称单数: peaks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blurt', '[blɜːrt]', 'vt.冲口说出；突然说出', '1. He blurted out the bad news before I can stop him. 我还没来得及阻止他，他已冲口说出了这个坏消息。 2. You will find yourself able to blurt them out at the right time. 你会发现你终能将它们都脱口而出. 3. What made him blurt out such a remark? 他怎么突然迸出这句话来?', '名词: blurter 过去式: blurted 过去分词: blurted 现在分词: blurting 第三人称单数: blurts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boring', '[\'bɔːrɪŋ]', 'adj.令人厌烦的；乏味的', '1. It is awfully boring. 太叫人厌烦了。 2. It is boring to listen to the same story. 听相同的故事是令人厌烦的。 3. His long boring story made me yawn. 他的冗长的故事听得我直打呵欠。 4. He gave a boring speech full of stale jokes. 他的发言很乏味,满是陈腐的笑话。', '副词: boringly 名词: boringness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('philology', '[fɪ\'lɑːlədʒi]', 'n.语言学；文献学', '1. Professor Smith is recognized to be one of the great scholars in English philology. 史密斯教授被公认为是了不起的英语语言学学者之一。', '形容词: philologic 副词: philologically 名词: philologer');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crust', '[krʌst]', 'n.外壳；坚硬的外壳；面包皮 vt.盖以硬皮 vi.结硬皮', '1. The earth\'s crust is layered.. 地球的外壳是分层的。 2. The crust on the snow was thick enough for us to walk on it. 外层的雪已经冻硬，可以在上面行走。 3. Please cut the bread into slices and remove the crust. 请将面包切片并去除外壳。 4. The crust of the bread is burnt. 这块面包的外皮烤焦了。 5. The snow crusted the lake last night. 昨夜的雪使湖面结了冰。 6. The snow may crust at night, due to outward radiation. 由于外部辐射，晚上雪可能结成雪壳。', '形容词: crustless 过去式: crusted 过去分词: crusted 现在分词: crusting 第三人称单数: crusts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('astrolabe', '[\'æstrəleɪb]', 'n.星盘(古代星位观侧仪)', '1. Other early instruments include the sextant and the astrolabe. 另外的早期仪器还有六分仪和星盘。 2. Mariners were also able to fix their latitude by using an instrument called astrolabe. 海员们还可使用星盘这种仪器确定纬度。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ferrous', '[\'ferəs]', 'adj.含铁的', '1. Mammoth machines are always made of ferrous metal. 大型机械的材质一般是黑色金属。 2. Ferrous iron reduces to ferric iron. 二价铁能还原成三价铁。 3. Retail : nonferrous metals, ferrous materials. 零售：有色、黑色金属材料。 4. Nodules contain a mixture of ferrous and ferrous-oxy leghemoglobin. 根瘤含有亚铁和亚铁一氧化豆血红蛋白的混合物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('succumb', '[sə\'kʌm]', 'v.屈从；死', '1. The mangabeys have been able to resist SIV, while the macaques, much like humans, inevitably succumb to it. 白眉猴已经能够抵抗猴免疫缺陷病毒，而恒河猴，就像人类一样，不可避免地屈从于它。 2. Some advocates of leaving say the presence of Western infidels in Afghanistan is so provocative that it makes Pakistan itself likelier to succumb to the jihadists. 一些赞成撤军的人士声称西方异教者在阿富汗的存在势力太具有挑衅意味而使巴基斯坦自己更有可能屈从与圣战分子。 3. Malnourished children are more likely to succumb to infections. 营养不良的儿童更有可能死于感染。 4. The aged denizen of the forest is doomed to succumb to the woodman\'s stroke! 多年在林中享有权利的香柏树，竟死在樵夫手下！', '过去式: succumbed 过去分词: succumbed 现在分词: succumbing 第三人称单数: succumbs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arraign', '[ə\'reɪn]', 'vt.[律]传讯；审问；指责', '1. He be arraign for high treason . 他被控叛国罪。 2. The man accused of killing a Wesleyan University student was arraign ed Friday. 被指控杀害卫斯廉大学学生的男子周五被起诉。 3. Mao La is again fourth answer: \"Arrived after you are dead Acheron, angel can come arraign you. 毛拉再丁答：“你们死后到了阴间，天使就会来提审你们。 4. Mr Brown is not the first politician to grab credit in good times and deflect the buck in bad ones, nor the only current leader to arraign hostile global forces for domestic woe. 要说繁荣期利用信贷，衰弱期逃避责任，布朗也谈不上开先河；', '名词: arraigner 过去式: arraigned 过去分词: arraigned 现在分词: arraigning 第三人称单数: arraigns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('windfall', '[\'wɪndfɔːl]', 'n.风吹落的果实；意外的收获；侥幸所得', '1. After the storm she gather a basketful of windfall in the apple orchard. 风暴过後，她从苹果园地上拣了满满一篮子苹果。 2. I had a windfall from the football pools. 我从足球比赛赌博中发了一笔横财。 3. He applied the windfall to payment of his mortgage. 他把那笔意外的收入用於偿付抵押。 4. This windfall will eventually dwindle. 此类侥幸所得终将减少。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glide', '[ɡlaɪd]', 'v.滑动；滑翔；溜走 n.滑动；滑过；滑音', '1. The figure skater glided gracefully over the ice. 花样滑冰者在冰上优雅地滑行。 2. The swans glide gracefully on the lake. 天鹅在湖的上空优美地滑翔。 3. The plane managed to glide down to the runway. 飞机终于成功地滑翔降落在跑道上。 4. He glide away from the classroom. 他溜出教室。 5. When a word ends in a vowel sound and the next word begins with a vowel sound, they are connected with a glide between the two vowels. 如果一个单词以元音结束，下一个单词以元音开始的话，两个元音之间用一个滑音连在一起。', '过去式: glided 过去分词: glided 现在分词: gliding 第三人称单数: glides');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('remunerate', '[rɪ\'mjuːnəreɪt]', 'vt.给与报酬；酬劳', '1. The company will remunerate you for your travelling expenses. 公司将给你报销旅费。 2. But Mr Najera Ponce chose a simpler way to remunerate musicians and labels. 但是NajeraPonce先生选择了一种更简单的方法向音乐家和唱片公司支付报酬。 3. Add the sand[ this does not know, however he say if I take you go to have no LIN2 GONG in gram, he will remunerate for me. 加沙[这可不知道，不过他说如果我带你去克里无林宫的话他就会给我报酬。 4. Figures such as these send a clear message that the club wishes to adequately remunerate its stars. 这些数字清楚地表明俱乐部希望充分地回报队中的球星。', '形容词: remunerable 名词: remunerability 过去式: remunerated 过去分词: remunerated 现在分词: remunerating 第三人称单数: remunerates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('torrent', '[\'tɔːrənt]', 'n.激流；山洪；(谩骂、质问等的)连发，爆发', '1. The river was a torrent after the storm. 暴风雨过后，河水成了激流。 2. The torrent scoured a gully down the hillside. 那激流顺山坡而下冲出一条水沟。 3. A torrent of water poured down the mountain. 洪水从山上奔流而下。 4. She attacked him with a torrent of abuse. 她用连珠炮似的谩骂来攻击他。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repose', '[rɪ\'poʊz]', 'n.休息或睡眠；安宁 v.休息；将（信赖等）寄托于', '1. The delightful sofa invites repose. 这么舒适的沙发不由得让人想躺下休息。 2. Her mouth seem always to is smiling,even in repose. 她的嘴角似乎总是挂著微笑,即使在睡眠时也是这样。 3. She went outside seeking a few moments of repose. 她抽空出去休息了一会儿。 4. The owl hunts while you repose in bed. 你躺在床上安然入睡时，猫头鹰却要去觅食。', '名词: reposal 过去式: reposed 过去分词: reposed 现在分词: reposing 第三人称单数: reposes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('velvety', '[\'velvəti]', 'adj.像天鹅绒般柔软光滑的；醇和的', '1. Her skin was admired for its velvety softness. 她的皮肤如天鹅绒般柔软, 令人赞叹。 2. She draped some velvety material over the old sofa. 她把丝绒般柔软的织物罩在旧沙发上。 3. The balance of wood and black fruits creates a velvety, seductively smooth finish. 橡木和黑色水果的风味十分均衡,令此酒醇和柔顺、回味无穷。', '比较级: velvetier 最高级: velvetiest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tawdry', '[\'tɔːdri]', 'adj.廉价而俗丽的；非常华丽的', '1. Everything seemed strange, so tawdry and grotesque. 一切似乎都很新奇，很花哨，而且滑稽可笑。 2. The rare wine world is still recovering from the tawdry affair. 葡萄酒珍品界还对这个俗气的故事心有余悸。 3. The main street has assumed its tawdry prosperity with discomfort. 繁华的大街透着一股不安的气氛。', '副词: tawdrily 比较级: tawdrier 最高级: tawdriest 名词: tawdriness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('perquisite', '[\'pɜːrkwɪzɪt]', 'n.额外补贴；临时津贴', '1. Perquisites include the use of the company car. 福利包括可以使用公司的汽车。 2. Politics in Britain used to be the perquisite of the property-owning classes. 英国的政治以往是有产阶级的特权。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exclusive', '[ɪk\'skluːsɪv]', 'adj.排外的；独占的；唯一的；完整的；奢华的 n.独家新闻；独权', '1. He is part of an exclusive social circle and belongs to an exclusive club. 他所处的社交圈子很排外，而且参加的又是个很排外的社团。 2. The interview is exclusive to this magazine. 本杂志得到独家访问权。 3. Painting has not been her exclusive occupation. 绘画并非她唯一的职业. 4. The teacher tried to gain the students\' exclusive attention. 老师努力试着获得学生的全部注意力。 5. Everyone was surprised by the Times exclusive about the prince\' marriage. 泰晤士报关于王子大婚的独家新闻令很多人惊奇不已。', '副词: exclusively 名词: exclusiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('souse', '[saʊs]', 'v.浸在水中；(使)湿透；腌制；使喝醉 n.浸泡；腌货；酒鬼', '1. Souse fish used to be one of her favorite dish. 腌鱼曾经是她最喜欢吃的菜之一。 2. After lying on the street for two hours the souse sober up and walk home. 在街上躺了两个小时後，酒鬼醒了过来走回家去。', '过去式: soused 过去分词: soused 现在分词: sousing 第三人称单数: souses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('commemorate', '[kə\'meməreɪt]', 'vt.纪念', '1. A monument was built to commemorate the victory. 为了纪念胜利，建造了一座纪念碑。 2. Christmas commemorates the birth of Christ. 圣诞节是为了纪念耶酥的诞生。 3. They reared a monument to commemorate the great musician. 他们建立起一座纪念碑，纪念这位伟大的音乐家。 4. We celebrate this day to commemorate the brave soldiers. 我们庆祝这天，以纪念英勇的士兵。', '名词: commemorator 过去式: commemorated 过去分词: commemorated 现在分词: commemorating 第三人称单数: commemorates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bystander', '[\'baɪstændər]', 'n.旁观者；看热闹的人；局外人', '1. Police warned bystander to keep away from the blazing building. 警察告诫围观者，不要靠近燃烧的建筑物。 2. I was nothing more than an innocent bystander. 我只是一个无辜的看热闹的人而已。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('melodrama', '[\'melədrɑːmə]', 'n.情节剧；音乐剧；传奇剧式的事件', '1. A short 19th-century melodrama is often part of the show. 短小的19世纪式的情景剧常是表演的一部分。 2. When I was 16, I saw a 1978 made-for-TV melodrama called Women at West Point. 我16岁那年看了一部1978年拍摄的有关西点军校女性的情节剧。 3. It had all the elements of melodrama you could want. 这其中你可以找到你想要看的情节紧张剧中的一切要素。 4. The scene in Kauai\'s harbour on August 26th has been followed by more melodrama. 随着8月26日在考艾岛港发生的那场风波之后，一波未平一波又起。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brindled', '[\'brɪndld]', 'adj.有斑纹的 =brindle.', '1. I saw his brindled cow feeding on fish remnants. 我看见他的用鱼杂碎喂养的斑纹奶牛。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rife', '[raɪf]', 'adj.非常多的；盛传的；流行的', '1. His thesis is rife with errors. 他的学位论文错误连篇。 2. Rumours are rife that he is going to resign. 到处都在传，说他要辞职了。 3. It is a country where corruption is rife. 这是个腐败成风的国家。 4. Disease and violence were rife in the city. 这个城市里，疾病流行，暴力成灾。', '比较级: rifer 最高级: rifest');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('palings', '[\'peɪlɪŋz]', 'n.篱笆；木栅栏 名词paling的复数.', '1. A fence made of pales or pickets. 栅栏用桩或尖桩围成的篱笆', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rickety', '[\'rɪkəti]', 'adj.（连接处不牢固导致）摇晃的；患软骨病的', '1. The ladder looks rather rickety. 这梯子看起来不怎么牢固。 2. I was working at a rickety table. 我正在一张摇摇晃晃的桌子边工作。', '比较级: ricketier 最高级: ricketiest 名词: ricketiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blatant', '[\'bleɪtnt]', 'adj.明目张胆的；炫耀的；公然的；喧闹的', '1. I have never encountered such blatant disregard for the Bill of Rights . 我从来没有见过这种明目张胆践踏人权法案的现象。 2. Our teacher is guilty of blatant favouritism. 我们老师有明显的偏心错误。 3. You don\'t have to be blatant about it. 你不必为这事吵吵嚷嚷。', '副词: blatantly 名词: blatancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('corporate', '[\'kɔːrpərət]', 'adj.法人的；公司的；社团的；共同的；全体的', '1. This company is concerned about its corporate image. 这家公司关心它自身的法人形象。 2. The owner opened a corporate checking account at the bank. 公司老板在银行开了一个法人账户。 3. I\'d like to make an appointment to see your Corporate Finance Manager. 我想约见一下你们公司的财务经理。 4. This is our corporate responsibility. 这是我们共同的责任。', '副词: corporately');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('denomination', '[dɪˌnɑːmɪ\'neɪʃn]', 'n.名称；教派；面额', '1. The firm is still operating under another denomination. 这家公司改用了名称仍在继续营业。 2. Today the denomination is worldwide. 目前这个教派已遍布世界各地。 3. This denomination has its origins in Calvinism. 这一教派源自加尔文教。 4. They are mainly credit and debit, some cash for small denomination purchases. 他们主要是信用卡和付款，一些是为小面额现金购买。', '形容词: denominational 副词: denominationally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('projector', '[prə\'dʒektər]', 'n.放映机；探照灯；计划者；投影线', '1. How long will it take to set up the projector? 把这个放映机安放好需要多长时间? 2. The film flew off the spool and wound itself round the projector. 电影胶片从卷轴滑出缠绕在放映机上了。 3. I do not deny that the projector is top quality. 我并不否认放映机质量上乘。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drench', '[drentʃ]', 'v.灌药；使湿透；过分沉溺 n.浸湿；大剂量药液', '1. A heavy shower drench the campers. 一阵骤雨把露营者都淋湿了。 2. We were caught in the storm and got drenched. 我们遇上大雨全都被浇透了。 3. The poster wouldn\'t stick even though I drenched it with glue. 我涂了大量胶水，可那张海报就是贴不住。', '名词: drencher 过去式: drenched 过去分词: drenched 现在分词: drenching 第三人称单数: drenches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('overriding', '[ˌoʊvər\'raɪdɪŋ]', 'adj.最主要的', '1. Minimum weight and volume are almost overriding requirements for any missile servo. 对于任何一种导弹的伺服系统来说，使它的重量为最轻和体积为最小，几乎是最主要的要求了。 2. The overriding U.S. national interest is an open world in which Amierca can thrive. 美国最主要的利益就是建立一个可以蓬勃发展的开放世界。', '副词: overridingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amiss', '[ə\'mɪs]', 'adj.有毛病的；出差错的；有缺点的；不合适的 adv.有毛病地；出差错地；不合适地', '1. Something is amiss when a boy does not eat for days. 一个孩子几天不吃东西一定是有什么毛病了。 2. Everything goes amiss with him,he has certainly bad luck. 他事事不如意，运气真不好。 3. Everything goes amiss with him. He has certainly bad luck. 他事事不如意，运气真不好。 4. Perhaps crop husbandry is amiss. 也许作物管理有缺陷。 5. Nothing has ever gone amiss since he took charge of the school. 自他主管这所学校以来,还从未出过问题。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ursine', '[\'ɜːrsaɪn]', 'adj.熊的；像熊的', '1. Flooey, that animal is not ursine as expected. 糟了，那个动物果然不是熊。 2. Ursine father: \"Foolish the child, you are of course! 熊爸爸：“傻孩子，你当然是啦！ 3. Accordingly, hare bravery already became ursine bravery substitute. 因此，兔胆已成为熊胆替代品。 4. Ursine Fylgja comes into play with four healing counters on it. 熊身守护灵进场时上面有四个医疗指示物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tolerance', '[\'tɑːlərəns]', 'n.宽容；忍耐力；容忍；公差', '1. Tolerance is another name for indifference. 宽容是不关心的别名。 2. My tolerance of your impoliteness is limited. 我对你的无礼的忍耐是有限的。 3. Human beings have limited tolerance of noise. 人类对噪音的忍耐力有限。 4. She had no tolerance for jokes of any kind. 她容不得开任何玩笑。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('refrain', '[rɪ\'freɪn]', 'v.抑制；避免；克制 n.副歌；叠句；重复', '1. Sunlight can refrain the growth of melatonin in the body. 阳光能抑制身体中褪黑激素的生长。 2. I carefully refrained from looking at him. 我留意着避免朝他看。 3. I wish he would refrain from scattering his ash all over the carpet. 我希望他不要将烟灰往地毯上乱弹。 4. You must refrain from smoking in this area. 在这个区域，你必须克制自己不抽烟。 5. Will you all join in singing the refrain, please? 请大家一道来唱副歌好吗?', '名词: refrainer 过去式: refrained 过去分词: refrained 现在分词: refraining 第三人称单数: refrains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('smooth', '[smuːð]', 'adj.光滑的；平稳的；流畅的；圆滑的；可口的；安祥的；均匀的 v.使光滑；消除；安慰；理顺(羽毛)', '1. Her skin is as smooth as silk. 她的皮肤像丝绸一样光滑。 2. The birch has smooth bark and slender branches. 桦树有光滑的皮和细长的枝。 3. At 9:50 the plane began a smooth descent through the cloud-smudged sky to Shanghai. 9点50分,飞机在上海上空开始穿过浓云平稳下降。 4. The process of negotiation was not entirely smooth. 谈判的过程并不十分顺畅。 5. She smoothed out wrinkles out of the tablecloth. 她把桌布上的皱褶弄平。', '副词: smoothly 比较级: smoother 最高级: smoothest 名词: smoother 过去式: smoothed 过去分词: smoothed 现在分词: smoothing 第三人称单数: smoothes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anesthetic', '[ˌænəs\'θetɪk]', 'n.麻醉剂；麻药 adj.麻醉的；无知觉的', '1. Pharmacologically, alcohol is an anesthetic, not a stimulant. 从药理学上讲酒精是麻醉剂，而不是兴奋剂。 2. Egotism is the anesthetic that dulls the pain of stupidity. 自负是为了麻痹因为愚蠢带来痛楚的麻醉剂。 3. The decay is very deep, so I will use a local anesthetic before drilling. 龋洞很深，在钻牙前我将给您打一针麻药。 4. Spinal anesthesia results from the infection of a local anesthetic into the cerebrospinal fluid. 脊椎麻醉将局麻药注入脑脊液。 5. Aldehydes possess anesthetic properties. 醛类具有麻醉的作用。', '副词: anesthetically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lineage', '[\'lɪniɪdʒ]', 'n.家系；直系；血统', '1. Mapmakers hold lineage to those within their species that held such capacities in their lineages. 地图切割者给自己物种内持有这个能力的家系们把握血统。 2. Having emphasised Bush\'s lineage and relationship with old American money, one must qualify this portrayal of him by indicating his rebellious youth. 在着重说明了布什的家系以及其与以前美国上层社会的关系之后，我们必须提及他年轻时的叛逆以便使他的形象更加具体化。 3. She was of aristocratic lineage. 她有贵族的血统。 4. He boasted a lineage of pure blue blood. 他夸耀自己有纯贵族血统。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whimper', '[\'wɪmpər]', 'n.呜咽；啜泣；怨声 v.呜咽；啜泣；抽噎地哭；抱怨', '1. I am listening for a cry or a whimper from upstairs . 我留神听着楼上传来的哭声或呜咽声。 2. He could not possibly have endured a whipping without a whimper. 他不可能一声不吭地忍受鞭打。 3. The animal gave a pathetic little whimper. 这只动物低声哀叫，令人怜悯。 4. She always starts off with a bang but ends with a whimper. 她做事总是虎头蛇尾的。 5. And if he starts to whimper, I\'ll just harmonize with him. 如果他开始呜咽，我就逗他。', '副词: whimperingly 名词: whimperer 过去式: whimpered 过去分词: whimpered 现在分词: whimpering 第三人称单数: whimpers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('patch', '[pætʃ]', 'n.小片；补丁；眼罩；（贴在伤口的）膏药；【生态】斑块 vt.修补；补缀；解决；掩饰', '1. The ground is wet in patches. 地上湿处片片。 2. He reset a patch of land with tomato plants. 他在一小块地上重新种上番茄。 3. She sewed a patch onto the knee of the trousers. 她在裤子的膝部打了个补丁. 4. He would indeed seek to patch things up. 他一定会设法把事情加以补救。', '形容词: patchable 名词: patcher 过去式: patched 过去分词: patched 现在分词: patching 第三人称单数: patches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dirge', '[dɜːrdʒ]', 'n.挽歌；哀乐；庄重悲哀的乐曲', '1. It was to be a funeral dirge, a farewell song to a dead friendship. 这将是一首葬礼挽歌,一首为失去的友谊谱写的告别曲。 2. The stranger, after listening for a moment, joined in the mournful dirge. 听了一会儿后这个陌生人也跟着唱起了悲哀的挽歌。 3. They sang a dirge for the dead person. 他们为那个死去的人唱了哀歌。 4. His songs are full of dirge. 他的歌充满了忧伤。', '形容词: dirgeful');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('evanescent', '[ˌevə\'nesnt]', 'adj.迅速消失的；短暂的', '1. Opinions are easily formed, but are as evanescent as ice in August. 看法很容易形成,但却会像8月的冰雪一样很快消融。 2. The joy and moral stimulation of work no longer must be forgotten in the mad chase of evanescent profits. 务必不能再忘记劳动带来的喜悦和激励，而去疯狂地追逐那转瞬即逝的利润。 3. The evanescent post-war economic boom was quickly followed by a deep recession. 大萧条紧随短暂的战后经济繁荣而来。', '副词: evanescently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('palatial', '[pə\'leɪʃl]', 'adj.宫殿般的；宏伟的', '1. He shares this palatial apartment with me. 他和我合住这间宫殿一般的房间。 2. Palatial office buildings are being constructed in the city. 那个城市正在兴建一些宫殿式办公大楼。 3. But as I stood in the garden of the US ambassador\'s palatial mansion, I heard a very different view. 但是当我站在宏伟的美国大使馆的花园里,听到的却是完全不同的另一种看法。', '副词: palatially 名词: palatialness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lard', '[lɑːrd]', 'n.猪油 v.点缀；涂油于；润色', '1. He likes to eat chips fried in lard. 他喜欢吃猪油煎土豆片。 2. I must render down this fat; we are short of lard. 我得把这块肥肉熬成油，我们正缺猪油。', '形容词: lardy 过去式: larded 过去分词: larded 现在分词: larding 第三人称单数: lards');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arch', '[ɑːrtʃ]', 'n.拱；拱门；拱状物 v.成拱形；拱起 adj.主要的；调皮的', '1. Dip your head under the low arch. 在低矮的门拱下要低头。 2. A pointed arch drawn from two centers within the span. 在跨度内有两个中心点，连接两个中心点的是弧度突出的拱。 3. Have you been to the Triumphal Arch? 你去过凯旋门吗？ 4. The bridge has three arches. 这座桥有三座拱洞。 5. The cat arched its back when it saw the dog. 那猫看见狗时就拱起了背。 6. They considered him their arch opponent. 他们将他看成是主要对手。', '副词: archly 名词: archness 过去式: arched 过去分词: arched 现在分词: arching 第三人称单数: arches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('premeditate', '[prɪ\'medəˌteɪt]', 'vt.预谋；预先计划', '1. Kuang Ziping: This is to premeditate long already, happen to also calculate a coincidence truly to finally. 邝子平： 这是蓄谋已久，到最后真正发生也算一个巧合。 2. And actually, of this enterprise buy the strategy already \" premeditate long already \" . 而其实，该企业的并购战略早已“蓄谋已久”。 3. Before correcting others, premeditate on yourself whether you make mistake first. 要纠正别人之前,先反省自己有没有犯错。 4. The persistence\"four have\" namely has organization, have already premeditate, have confidence and have results to show merit. 坚持\"四有\"即有组织，有预谋，有把握，有成绩。', '形容词: premeditative 名词: premeditator 过去式: premeditated 过去分词: premeditated 现在分词: premeditating 第三人称单数: premeditates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nautical', '[\'nɔːtɪkl]', 'adj.海上的；航海的；船员的', '1. A nautical mile is 1,852 meters. 一海里等于1852米。 2. It is a nautical term, I suppose. 我想，那是航海术语。 3. Captain Gulliver was a middle class, nautical man. 格列佛船长是一个中产阶级的海员。', '副词: nautically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chasm', '[\'kæzəm]', 'n.分歧；深坑；裂口', '1. There is always a vast chasm between rich and poor. 贫富的鸿沟始终存在。 2. The chasm between you and he can not be solved by us. 你和他之间的裂痕不是我们能解决的。 3. There is a chasm between the professor and the schoolmaster. 教授和校长之间出现了分歧。 4. Suddenly a huge chasm opened in the earth. 大地突然裂开，形成一道深坑。', '形容词: chasmal');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prompt', '[prɑːmpt]', 'adj.迅速的；敏捷的；立刻的 vt.激起；促进；推动；提示 vi.提示 n.提示；提示的内容 n.[商]付款期限', '1. The occasion calls for prompt action. 这场合需要迅速的行动。 2. Their prompt actions prevented the fire from spreading. 他们敏捷的行动阻止了火势的蔓延。 3. Thank you for your prompt reply to our telegram. 多谢您对我们电报的即刻答复。 4. His curiosity prompted him to ask questions . 他的好奇心激起他问许多问题。 5. Will you prompt for us at the next performance? 下场演出时你给我们提词好吗? 6. The speaker was rather hesitant and had to be given a frequent prompt by the chairman. 那个发言人讲话结结巴巴的,经常得由主席给个提示。', '副词: promptly 比较级: prompter 最高级: promptest 名词: prompter 过去式: prompted 过去分词: prompted 现在分词: prompting 第三人称单数: prompts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pinpoint', '[\'pɪnpɔɪnt]', 'v.精确地找到；瞄准；使突出 n.极小之物；精确位置 adj.精确的；微小的', '1. It\'s difficult to pinpoint the cause of the accident. 很难清楚地找到事故发生的原因。 2. With this device, we can pinpoint your exact location. 有了这个仪器，我们可以精确地标出你的位置。 3. We need to pinpoint our target market. 我们需要明确指出我们的市场目标。 4. We pinpointed the flaws in his argument. 我们突出他辩论中的错误。 5. There is only a pinpoint of light in the cave. 山洞中只能见到一丝光线。 6. They can control precisely where the nanotube penetrates a cell, for example, and een pinpoint smaller cell structures, such as the nucleus or mitochondrion. 例如他们能精确的控制纳米管插入细胞的位置，甚至能定位到更小的细胞结构如细胞核或线粒体。', '过去式: pinpointed 过去分词: pinpointed 现在分词: pinpointing 第三人称单数: pinpoints');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('greenhorn', '[\'ɡriːnhɔːrn]', 'n.初学者；新手；没经验的人', '1. He is a greenhorn in this field. 他在这个领域还是个新手。 2. A greenhorn who has gotten burned may ask for a guru\'s track record. 一个新手，如果受了伤害，他会找老师要交易记录。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('paradox', '[\'pærədɑːks]', 'n.悖论；似非而是的论点；自相矛盾的话', '1. The gorilla is something of a paradox in the African scene. 在非洲大舞台上大猩猩有点象似是而非的隽语。 2. This paradox cannot be explained, you have to experience it. 这种悖论是不能解释的，你必须经历它。 3. Paradox and irony are characteristics of her style. 她善於运用似非而是的隽语和反语。 4. `More haste, less speed\' is a well-known paradox. ｀欲速不达＇是人所熟知的隽语。', '形容词: paradoxical 副词: paradoxically 名词: paradoxicalness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('anatomical', '[ˌænə\'tɒmɪkl]', 'adj.结构上的；解剖(学)的', '1. In anatomical structure prehistoric man shows close affinity with modern humans. 从解剖结构上看，史前人类与现代人类有着密切的关系。 2. That was an anatomical model of the human body for use in teaching. 那是个用于教学的人体解剖模型。', '副词: anatomically 异体字: anatomic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('whit', '[wɪt]', 'n.些微；一点点', '1. He cares not a whit for public opinion. 他对舆论毫不关心。 2. There\'s not a whit of truth in the statement. 这声明里没有丝毫的真实性。 3. The hostess is every whit as elegant as a lady. 女主人完完全全像贵妇人一样高雅。 4. Linda told her father every whit, and hid nothing from him. 琳达全都告诉了父亲，对他没有一点隐瞒。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apprentice', '[ə\'prentɪs]', 'n.学徒；见习生 v.使当学徒', '1. He began his career as an apprentice. 他以当学徒开始他的职业生涯。 2. The shop is taking on two new apprentices. 这个商店新收了两个学徒。 3. He is an apprentice plumber. 他是个见习水管工人。 4. The two pilots and an apprentice pilot were among those killed. 遇难者中包括两名飞行员和一名见习飞行员。 5. The boy was apprenticed to a carpenter. 这个男孩被送去学木匠。', '名词: apprenticeship 过去式: apprenticed 过去分词: apprenticed 现在分词: apprenticing 第三人称单数: apprentices');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('submit', '[səb\'mɪt]', 'vt.使服从；使屈服；提交；递交；认为 vi.屈从', '1. We will submit ourselves to the court\'s judgement. 我们服从法庭的判决。 2. We have to submit ourselves to discipline. 我们必须遵守纪律。 3. He submitted his proposal for urban development to the city council. 他将城市发展建议提交市议会。 4. Please fill in and submit the form below. 请填写并递交以下表格。 5. They refused to submit to the unjust decision. 他们拒绝服从这个不公正的决定。', '名词: submittal 过去式: submitted 过去分词: submitted 现在分词: submitting 第三人称单数: submits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('collection', '[kə\'lekʃn]', 'n.收集；收取，托收；聚集；收藏品；募捐', '1. The collection of these stamps took ten years. 收集这些邮票花了十年时间。 2. There are two collections a day from this letter box. 这个邮箱每天开两次。 3. Is the collection going to be divided up or sold as a whole? 这批收藏品是零卖还是一起卖? 4. The painting has pride of place in his collection. 这幅画在他的收藏品中最为珍贵', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('smirk', '[smɜːrk]', 'v.假笑；得意地笑 n.假笑；傻笑', '1. Come on, professor, do not smirk at me like that. 拜托！老师，你不要那样对着我假笑。 2. A slight smirk crossed the captain\'s face. 上尉的脸上掠过一丝假笑。 3. He is so embarrassed and try to cover it with smirk. 他很难堪,想用傻笑来掩饰。', '形容词: smirky 副词: smirkingly 名词: smirker 过去式: smirked 过去分词: smirked 现在分词: smirking 第三人称单数: smirks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yarn', '[jɑːrn]', 'n.纱；线；<口>故事 v.讲故事', '1. Wool fibers can be spun into yarn. 羊毛纤维可纺成纱。 2. The tailor was balling the yarn. 裁缝正在把线缠成线团。 3. We stayed up yarning until midnight. 我们讲故事一直讲到半夜才睡。 4. The old mariner liked to yarn about his sea adventures. 老水手喜欢讲他的海上奇遇。', '过去式: yarned 过去分词: yarned 现在分词: yarning 第三人称单数: yarns');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('condiment', '[\'kɒndəmənt]', 'n.调味品；佐料', '1. Fish sauce is a traditional fermented condiment in coastal areas. 鱼露是沿海地区的传统发酵调味品。 2. You then put condiment and a little salt into noodles. 然后你把佐料放进面条里，再加点盐。', '形容词: condimental');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seasoned', '[\'siːznd]', 'adj.经验丰富的；加佐料的；晒干的 动词season的过去式和过去分词形式.', '1. She\'s a seasoned concert performer. 她是富有经验的音乐会演奏家。 2. This football star is a seasoned player. 这位球星身经百战。 3. As a seasoned magician, Liu Qian has a unique understanding of showmanship. 作为一个经验丰富的魔术师，刘谦对魔术表演有着独特的理解。 4. This meat should be seasoned with salt and mustard. 这肉里应该加些盐和芥末。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maturity', '[mə\'tʃʊrəti]', 'n.成熟；(支票等的)到期', '1. My plan has gradually come to maturity. 我的计划逐渐成熟。 2. His performance was full of maturity and poise. 他的表现成熟而稳健。 3. It takes roughly forty years for the trees to reach maturity. 这些树木要花近四十年才能进入成熟期。 4. The interest on term deposit is only due at maturity. 定期存款利息必须到期支付。', '名词复数: maturities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('aseptic', '[ˌeɪ\'septɪk]', 'adj.无菌的；防感染的；冷漠的 n.防腐剂', '1. Sterile equipment and aseptic sampling techniques shall be used when necessary. 必要时须使用无菌设备和灭菌取样措施。 2. She gave me an aseptic smile. 她给了我一个漠然的微笑。', '副词: aseptically 名词: asepticism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('usurp', '[juː\'zɜːrp]', 'v.篡夺；霸占；篡位', '1. Henry IV usurped the throne of England. 亨利四世篡夺了英国的王位。 2. You must not allow it to usurp a disproportionate share of your interest. 你不应让它过多地占据你的兴趣。 3. The assistant began to usurp his boss\'s authority. 助手开始篡夺老板的权力。', '副词: usurpingly 名词: usurper 过去式: usurped 过去分词: usurped 现在分词: usurping 第三人称单数: usurps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('piscatorial', '[ˌpɪskə\'tɔːriəl]', 'adj.渔业的；渔民的', '1. Integrated development uses piscatorial resource can divide for two respects. 渔业资源综合开发利用可分为两个方面。 2. The effect of Ulva Pertusa on the removal of nutrient salt in piscatorial wastewater was studied. 在养殖废水中,利用大型海藻-孔石莼,研究其对各营养盐的吸收情况。 3. Deep-sea fishing gives Zhou Shan piscatorial down to whole economy brings great change. 远洋渔业给舟山渔业以至整个经济带来巨变。 4. Begin as what piscatorial promotion works nevertheless, also reveal an a lot of problems and difficulty. 不过随着渔业推广工作的开展，也暴露出许多问题和困难。', '副词: piscatorially 异体字: piscatory');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sunder', '[\'sʌndər]', 'v.分开；分离', '1. Lightning tore the tree in sunder. 闪电把树劈成两半。 2. Nothing can sunder our friendship. 什么也不能破坏我们的友谊。 3. Time and distance often sunder friends. 朋友久别远离常产生隔阂。', '名词: sunderance 过去式: sundered 过去分词: sundered 现在分词: sundering 第三人称单数: sunders');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('organism', '[\'ɔːrɡənɪzəm]', 'n.有机体；生物体；有机组织', '1. Germs may invade the organism. 细菌会侵入有机体。 2. Organism is the basic study of biology. 生物体是生物研究的基础领域。 3. The ameba is a very simple organism. 变形虫是很简单的生物体。 4. An organism adapts best when stresses are slightly increased. 当压力被稍微地提高时，是生物体适应的最好状况。', '形容词: organismal 副词: organismically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tensile', '[\'tensl]', 'adj.可拉长的；可伸展的；张力的', '1. This dissertationindicated the tensile loads of wire rope should be considered when quantitativelyevaluating the defect by means of MFL. 为此，本文指出利用漏磁密度定量评价钢丝绳缺陷时应充分考虑钢丝绳张力的大小。', '名词: tensility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dwindle', '[\'dwɪndl]', 'v.减少；缩小', '1. Those jobs will dwindle in years to come. 这些工作以后会逐年减少。 2. The number of Internet cafes is starting to dwindle. 网咖的数目正开始逐渐减少中。', '过去式: dwindled 过去分词: dwindled 现在分词: dwindling 第三人称单数: dwindles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('squash', '[skwɑːʃ]', 'n.壁球；摺皱不堪；拥挤嘈杂的人群；浓缩果汁；美国南瓜 vt.压制；压扁 vi.变扁；挤进', '1. I enjoy playing tennis and squash. 我喜欢打网球和壁球。 2. The mine reduced the car to squash. 地雷把汽车炸成一堆烂铁 3. It\'s a squash with five people in this car. 五个人坐在这个小汽车里太挤了。 4. I ordered two squashes. 我要了两杯鲜果汁。 5. The government was quick to squash any hopes of reform. 政府很快消灭了一切改革的希望。 6. The fruit will squash if it is badly packed. 水果如果包装不好会被压扁的。', '名词: squasher 过去式: squashed 过去分词: squashed 现在分词: squashing 第三人称单数: squashes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gullible', '[\'ɡʌləbl]', 'adj.易受骗的；轻信的', '1. Bill\'s so gullible that you could sell him anything. 比尔非常容易上当，你骗他什么他都相信。 2. He must have been pretty gullible to fall for that old trick. 他准是有点儿傻，才落入那惯用的圈套。 3. We \'re so gullible as to believe him. 我们真愚蠢，竟然相信了他。 4. Being gullible and belittling others should both be avoided. 轻信别人的话跟轻看别人都是不好 的。', '副词: gullibly 名词: gullibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tightfisted', '[\'taɪt\'fɪstɪd]', 'adj.吝啬的', '1. His tightfisted employer is unwilling to give him a raise. 他那吝啬的雇主不肯给他加薪。 2. A tightfisted man was standing on the pavement with two heavy suitcases hailing a taxi. 一个吝啬的人带着两只很重的箱子站在人行道上叫出租车。', '名词: tightfistedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pandemic', '[pæn\'demɪk]', 'adj.全国流行的 n.流行病', '1. The risk of pandemic influenza is serious. 全球流感的危险性非常严重。 2. Vaccines effective against a pandemic virus are not yet available. 目前仍没有可有效预防流感大流行的疫苗。 3. The flu was arrested before it became a pandemic. 流感在变成流行病之前被控制住了。 4. The bird flu pandemic is well controlled. 禽流感疫情控制得非常好。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nestling', '[\'nestlɪŋ]', 'n.尚未离巢的小鸟；婴孩 动词nestle的现在分词形式.', '1. One feels good nestling like a baby on its breast. 一个人象婴孩那样地偎依在它的怀中时感觉很舒服。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('calculus', '[\'kælkjələs]', 'n.微积分；算法；结石', '1. It\'s been awhile since I did calculus. 我学微积分已经有一段时间了。 2. I had studied calculus before I got into college. 我在上大学以前,已经学过微积分。 3. Calculus is over the heads of most students. 微积分对大多数学生来说太难学了。 4. This is a problem where calculus won\'t help at all. 对于这一题，微积分一点也用不上。', '名词复数: calculi');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('accuse', '[ə\'kjuːz]', 'v.谴责；控告；指责', '1. How dare you accuse me of lying! 你怎敢谴责我说谎! 2. We resolve not to accuse them to avoid troubles. 我们决定不起诉他们 3. I mustered up enough courage to accuse him. 我鼓起足够的勇气控告他。 4. He was accused of incompetence. 他被指责为不称职。', '副词: accusingly 名词: accuser 过去式: accused 过去分词: accused 现在分词: accusing 第三人称单数: accuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('immense', '[ɪ\'mens]', 'adj.巨大的；广大的；<口>非常好的', '1. They plunged into their work with immense zeal. 他们以极大的热情投入工作。 2. Her contributions to the state have been immense. 她对国家的贡献极大。 3. It\'s almost impossible to find him in the immense ocean. 在无边无际的海洋中要找到他几乎是不可能的。 4. It were the new comers who had cultivated the immense wilderness. 初来此地的人开辟了这片广袤的荒野。', '副词: immensely 名词: immenseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('offensive', '[ə\'fensɪv]', 'adj.令人不快的；冒犯的；侮辱的；与进攻有关的 n.攻势；攻击', '1. His hasty temper made him offensive. 他急躁的脾气使他令人讨厌。 2. His remarks were rather offensive. 他的话非常无礼。 3. The boss kicked him out for an offensive remark. 老板因为他说了一句冒犯的话就把他开除了。 4. She has been greatly annoyed by his offensive remarks. 他出言不逊,这使她很反感。 5. In meetings she always takes the offensive before she can be criticized. 在会上，她不等别人批评她而总是先发制人。', '副词: offensively 名词: offensiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('zenith', '[\'zenɪθ]', 'n.顶点；天顶；全盛', '1. Our spirits rose to their zenith after the victory. 胜利之后我们的士气高昂到极点。 2. Shanghai has not yet reached the zenith of her prosperity. 上海尚未达到繁荣的顶点。 3. The sun reaches its zenith at midday. 太阳在中午升到天顶。 4. It feel as if we have traveled from nadir to zenith. 感觉上我们好像已从天底走到了天顶。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('motley', '[\'mɑːtli]', 'adj.杂色的；混杂的 n.杂色；杂色衣服；混杂；小丑', '1. They are wearing a motley collection of old clothes. 他们穿着各式各样的旧衣服。 2. The people she\'d invited were a pretty motley crew. 她请的人相当杂。 3. The room was soon filled with a motley assemblage. 不多一会儿，屋子里便挤满了形形色色的来开会的人。', '名词复数: motleys');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solitude', '[\'sɑːlətuːd]', 'n.孤独；独居；荒僻之地；幽静的地方', '1. I am not fond of solitude. 我不喜欢孤独。 2. He passed twenty-four years in solitude. 他在孤独中度过了二十四年。 3. I was sociable enough, but I enjoyed solitude too. 我很善于交往，但我也喜欢独居的生活。 4. A person who withdraws from the world to live in seclusion and often in solitude. 隐士逃遁离开这个世界而居住于偏僻之地且常常是独处的人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ugly', '[\'ʌɡli]', 'adj.丑陋的；难看的；令人困窘的；令人不愉快的', '1. Toads have an ugly appearance but they are useful. 蟾蜍外表丑陋，但很有用。 2. You can\'t persuade me to buy this ugly vase! 你不能劝服我买这个丑陋的花瓶！ 3. His face was covered in ugly red blotches. 他脸上有许多难看的红色大斑点。 4. What an ugly mug! 多难看的脸！', '副词: uglily 比较级: uglier 最高级: ugliest 名词: ugliness 名词复数: uglies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('capitation', '[ˌkæpɪ\'teɪʃn]', 'n.人头税；按人计算的补助费', '1. No Capitation, or other direct, Tax shall be laid, unless in Proportion to the Census or enumeration herein before directed to be taken. 除依本宪法前文对人口普查或统计结果规定的比例证税外，不得征收人头税或其它直接税。 2. The vast majority of secondary schools belong to the free education scheme and receive allowances and capitation grants from the State. 绝大部分中学属于免费教育方案,接收国家津贴和按人头计算的补助费。', '形容词: capitative');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('maladroit', '[ˌmælə\'drɔɪt]', 'adj.笨拙的', '1. We knew that he had some problems somewhere from his maladroit movements. 从他笨拙的动作我们就知道了他身体某处有问题。 2. Our new supervisor is clever in matters in which his predecessor was maladroit. 我们的班主任在他的前人做得笨拙的事上很聪明。', '副词: maladroitly 名词: maladroitness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abrasive', '[ə\'breɪsɪv]', 'n.磨料 adj.磨损的；生硬粗暴的；腐蚀的', '1. A trademark can be used for an abrasive of silicon carbide crystals. 金刚砂一种碳化硅晶体磨料的商标名 2. Jeff is usually an abrasive character, but he can be as sweet as honey when he wants something. 杰弗通常是一个生硬粗暴的人，但他想得到某物时，他会象蜜一样甜。 3. An abrasive material is unsuitable for cleaning baths. 有磨蚀作用的材料不适合擦浴缸。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fantasy', '[\'fæntəsi]', 'n.幻想 v.幻想', '1. The young always live in a world of fantasy. 年轻人总是生活在幻想中。 2. He is unable to divorce fantasy from reality. 他不能将幻想与现实分开。 3. He fantasies himself a doctor. 他想像自己是一位医生。', '名词复数: fantasies 过去式: fantasied 过去分词: fantasied 现在分词: fantasying 第三人称单数: fantasies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('belated', '[bɪ\'leɪtɪd]', 'adj.迟来的', '1. It\'s late, but Belated Happy Birthday Han Ji Hye! 现在已经晚了，但迟来的生日快乐韩期金惠！ 2. The award is being made in belated recognition of her services to the industry. 这一奖项是对她为本行业所作贡献的迟来的表彰。', '副词: belatedly 名词: belatedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seamy', '[\'siːmi]', 'adj.丑恶的；有伤痕的；<古>有接缝的', '1. The seamy side of life includes crime and other evils. 生活的阴暗面包括犯罪和其它邪恶事情。', '比较级: seamier 最高级: seamiest 名词: seaminess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('factorable', '[fæk\'təeɪbl]', 'adj.可分解因子的', '1. That\'s a factor which we must not neglect. 这是我们不应忽视的一个因素。 2. I factor ed my uncle\'s estate for three years. 我代管我叔父的财产已有三年了。 3. His experience in social work is a plus factor. 他在社会福利工作方面的经验是一个有利因素。 4. The deciding factor; the deciding vote. 决定性的因素; 决定性的一票', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ulcer', '[\'ʌlsər]', 'n.溃疡；腐坏物；弊病', '1. His ulcer has kicked up again. 他的溃疡又发病了 2. The old man has a stomach ulcer. 那个老人得了胃溃疡。 3. Poverty is an ulcer in our society. 贫穷是我们社会的弊病。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nippers', '[\'nɪpəz]', 'n.钳子；镊子 名词nipper的复数形式.', '1. Here are their lethal poison nippers. 这就是他们致命的毒螯。 2. So what if the little nippers don’t read? 如果这些小家伙不阅读会怎么样？ 3. PONGO: Perdy, we better get these little one nippers off to bed if we\'re going for a W-A-L-K. 柏蒂,亲爱的,我们最好在我们出动散步之前最好选领孩子们上床。 4. The larva takes aim at the snail\'s tentacles.It strikes with its poison nippers. 小萤火虫瞄准了蜗牛的触角，并用自己带毒的螯出击。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exorbitant', '[ɪɡ\'zɔːrbɪtənt]', 'adj.(价格等)过高的；过分的；不合法的', '1. The price of food here is exorbitant. 这儿的食物价格太高。 2. That hotel charges exorbitant prices. 那家旅馆漫天要价。 3. You should be sensible and not make exorbitant demands. 你应该通情达理，不要作过分的要求。', '副词: exorbitantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('batch', '[bætʃ]', 'n.一批；一炉；一次所制之量 v.分批处理', '1. The second batch of sugar is better than the first. 第二批制成的糖比第一批好。 2. There are a batch of tourists over there. 那里有一批旅游者。 3. The first batch of police-women went on duty in Jinan in 1959. 济南第-批女警察是1959年开始值勤。 4. These cakes were baked in batches of twenty. 这些蛋糕是以二十个为一炉烘烤的。', '过去式: batched 过去分词: batched 现在分词: batching 第三人称单数: batches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('timely', '[\'taɪmli]', 'adj.及时的；适时的 adv.及时的', '1. What we expected is nothing less than a timely payment. 及时付款正是我们所盼望的。 2. Had it not been for your timely help, our company would have been on the verge of bankruptcy. 若非你及时伸出援助之手,本公司将会濒临破产。 3. His wife was so poignant and timely. 他的妻子是这样有分寸和适时宜。 4. I think timely rain is good for the crops. 我认为适时地下雨对庄稼生长有好处。 5. I really appreciate your timely help. 真的感谢你及时的帮忙。', '比较级: timelier 最高级: timeliest 名词: timeliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distension', '[dɪ\'stenʃn]', 'n.膨胀 =distention.', '1. Heat causes the distension of gases. 热使气体膨胀。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gentle', '[\'dʒentl]', 'adj.温和的；轻柔的；温顺的；文雅的；出身名门的', '1. We\'ve never met such gentle people. 我们从来没有遇到这样温和的人。 2. My mother is a kind and gentle woman. 我的母亲是一位心地善良、性情温和的妇女。 3. The gentle music can relax him. 轻柔的音乐能使他放松。 4. A gentle breeze stirred the leaves. 微风吹动了树叶。', '副词: gently 比较级: gentler 最高级: gentlest 名词: gentleness 过去式: gentled 过去分词: gentled 现在分词: gentling 第三人称单数: gentles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('declassify', '[ˌdiː\'klæsɪfaɪ]', 'vt.不再当机密文件处理；解密', '1. Plans for nuclear plants have been declassified. 建造核装备的计划已不再保密。', '形容词: declassifiable 名词: declassification 过去式: declassified 过去分词: declassified 现在分词: declassifying 第三人称单数: declassifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('qualified', '[\'kwɑːlɪfaɪd]', 'adj.有资格的；有保留的；有限制的；能胜任的', '1. He\'s not qualified for this job. 他不能胜任这项工作。 2. We need more qualified science worker. 我们需要更多合格的科学工作者。 3. He is well qualified for the work. 他有充分的资格担任该工作。 4. Strictly speaking, he\'s not qualified for the job. 严格说来，他没有资格做这份工作。', '副词: qualifiedly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('slump', '[slʌmp]', 'v.大幅度下跌；猛然瘫坐；使倒下 n.暴跌；低潮状态；(土地)下沉', '1. Sales have slumped in the last month. 上月销售量骤降。 2. Business slumped after the holiday. 节日过后生意下降了。 3. She slumped, exhausted, onto the sofa. 她疲惫之极地倒在沙发上 4. He swayed forward and slumped down in his chair. 他身子向前一歪,猛地倒在靠椅里。 5. The slump hit his business hard. 物价暴跌使他的生意大受打击。', '过去式: slumped 过去分词: slumped 现在分词: slumping 第三人称单数: slumps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ewer', '[\'juːər]', 'n.大口水罐', '1. The ewer is in very good condition with spout restored. 喷口修复后， 水罐还能用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('clamber', '[\'klæmbər]', 'v.（艰难地）爬上；攀登 n.（艰难地）爬；攀登', '1. It was difficult to clamber the mountain. 爬上那座大山是困难的。 2. Stop clambering over my new furniture. 别在我的新家具上爬来爬去。 3. It was easy enough for him to clamber up the gnarled trunk. 他攀上这扭曲的树干，倒还容易。 4. We had a good time of that clamber. 那次攀登让我们很愉快。', '名词: clamberer 过去式: clambered 过去分词: clambered 现在分词: clambering 第三人称单数: clambers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('itinerary', '[aɪ\'tɪnəreri]', 'n.旅行计划，行程表；旅程；游记 adj.旅程的；巡回的；游历的', '1. I need to discuss our itinerary with you. 我得和你讨论我们的旅行计划。 2. For the details of their itinerary, I am all to seek. 关于他们的具体旅程，我毫无所知。 3. He kept a lively itinerary of the trip. 他保留著那次旅行中写的生动日记。 4. But reality is, that change is only endless and hardship is itinerary germinant. 但现实是，那场转变只是一个漫长而艰难旅程的开端。', '名词复数: itineraries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unobtrusive', '[ˌʌnəb\'truːsɪv]', 'adj.不突出的；不显眼的；谦虚的', '1. She\'s a quiet unobtrusive student. 她是个文静而不引人注目的学生。 2. She saw only that he was quiet and unobtrusive, and she liked him for it. 她只知道他沉静而谦逊，并因此而喜欢上他。', '副词: unobtrusively 名词: unobtrusiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ferment', '[\'fɜːrment]', 'n.发酵；酵素；动乱 v.（使）发酵；动乱', '1. He is doing a research in beer ferment. 他正在进行对啤酒发酵的研究。 2. Do health people need edible ferment too? 健康人也需要食用酵素吗？ 3. The country was in ferment. 这个国家处于动荡不安之中。 4. When wine is fermented it gives off bubbles of gas. 酒发酵时会放出气泡。', '形容词: fermentable 名词: fermentability 过去式: fermented 过去分词: fermented 现在分词: fermenting 第三人称单数: ferments');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gangway', '[\'ɡæŋweɪ]', 'n.(上下船的)跳板；（剧场&%2365105; 音乐厅等的）座间甬道；过道', '1. They advanced up the gangway and gained the deck. 他们经舷梯登上甲板。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tramp', '[træmp]', 'n.徒步；流浪汉；淫妇；重脚步声 v.践踏；步行', '1. The boys took a tramp together over the hills. 男孩们一起徒步爬那些山岗。 2. She wants to go for a tramp in the country. 她想去乡间远足。 3. The tramp was benumbed by the cold. 那个流浪汉被冻僵了。 4. A tramp came to the door and asked for food. 一个流浪汉来到门前讨饭吃。 5. One must tramp down the earth over sown seed, which is good for the plants. 播种后一定要踩墒，这样有助于植物的生长。', '形容词: trampish 名词: tramper 过去式: tramped 过去分词: tramped 现在分词: tramping 第三人称单数: tramps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antidote', '[\'æntidoʊt]', 'n.解毒剂；解药；对抗手段', '1. He took an antidote for the poison. 他服了对付那种毒物的解毒剂。 2. Do you have any antidote for a snakebite? 你有治疗毒蛇咬伤的解毒药吗？ 3. Hard work is the best antidote to mischief. 繁忙的工作是防止为非作歹的最好方法。 4. The holiday was a marvellous antidote to the pressures of office work. 那个假日是消除上班工作压力的灵丹妙药。', '形容词: antidotal 副词: antidotally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avocation', '[ˌævoʊ\'keɪʃn]', 'n. <古>娱乐； 消遣； 副业； 嗜好', '1. Make authorship your avocation, not your vocation. 把写作当作你的副业，不要把它当作正业。 2. Louis\' avocation as a ski insspxuctor gradually became his full-time employment. 滑雪教练一职已从路易斯的副业逐渐变成他的全职了。 3. In fact, fishing is my avocation. 事实上，钓鱼是我的一大嗜好。', '形容词: avocational 副词: avocationally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hamper', '[\'hæmpər]', 'vt.妨碍；阻止 n.大篮子', '1. Our progress was hampered by the bad weather. 我们前进时受到了恶劣天气的阻碍。 2. Outdated conventions and bad customs hamper the growth of production. 陈规陋习妨碍生产的发展。 3. The heavy rain hampers the flow of traffic. 大雨阻碍了交通运行。 4. There are some apples in a picnic hamper. 在野餐用的大篮子里有许多苹果。', '过去式: hampered 过去分词: hampered 现在分词: hampering 第三人称单数: hampers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('foreknowledge', '[fɔːr\'nɑːlɪdʒ]', 'n.预知；先见之明', '1. He hasn\'t the least foreknowledge of this matter. 关于此事他事先一点也不知道。 2. Foreknowledge, intuition, and presentiment. 预知，直觉，预感 3. Foreknowledge is prior to predestination . 预知是在预定之前。 4. There is in your complacency no foreknowledge of death nor even of separation. 你自得其乐，对生离死别都无先见之明。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shuffle', '[\'ʃʌfl]', 'v.拖曳；搅乱；推诿；洗牌；移来移去 n.洗牌；搅乱；拖着脚走；搪塞', '1. The prisoners shuffled along the corridor and into their cells. 囚犯们沿着走廊拖着脚步进入牢房。 2. Don\'t shuffle the papers together. 不要把文件混在一起。 3. Don\'t shuffle, give me a clear answer. 别支支吾吾，给我一个明确的答复。 4. He tries to shuffle his work off onto others. 他想把工作推给别人。 5. Give the cards a good shuffle. 把牌好好洗一洗。', '名词: shuffler 过去式: shuffled 过去分词: shuffled 现在分词: shuffling 第三人称单数: shuffles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bare', '[ber]', 'adj.赤裸的；空的；仅有的；贫瘠的，荒芜的 vt.使裸露；暴露', '1. The fierce sun parched the bare earth. 灼热的阳光炙烤着光秃秃的大地。 2. The boy likes to walk on the sand with bare feet. 这男孩喜欢赤脚在沙滩上走。 3. The little room was almost bare of furniture. 这个小房间几乎没有什么家俱。 4. A bare word would be enough for me. 对我来说一句话就够了。 5. He bared the tree of its bark. 他剥光树皮。', '比较级: barer 最高级: barest 名词: bareness 过去式: bared 过去分词: bared 现在分词: baring 第三人称单数: bares');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wreckage', '[\'rekɪdʒ]', 'n.失事；破坏；破减；残骸', '1. Pieces of the wreckage were cast up on the beach. 失事船只的残骸被冲到了沙滩上。 2. Wreckage from the plane was scattered over a wide area. 飞机失事残骸散落在一个广阔地域。 3. For me, therefore, Meursault is not a piece of social wreckage, but a poor and naked man enamored of a sun that leaves no shadows. 因此，对我来说，默尔索不是社会的破坏者，而是一个可怜的人，他怀着一颗赤子之心，迷恋着照不出阴影的阳光。 4. The wreckage slowly drifted away. 残骸慢慢漂走。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inalienable', '[ɪn\'eɪliənəbl]', 'adj.不可剥夺的', '1. Taiwan is an inalienable part of the Chinese territory. 台湾是中国领土不可分割的一部分。 2. Freedom of speech should be an inalienable right. 言论自由应是不可剥夺的权利。', '副词: inalienably 名词: inalienability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pension', '[\'penʃn]', 'n.养老金；退休金；抚恤金；年金；（欧洲等地的）私人小旅店 v.发退休金', '1. He\'s got nothing beyond his state pension. 除了国家发的养老金，他一无所有。 2. He went to the post office to draw his pension. 他到邮局去取退休金了。 3. concede one\'s attention 4. He had stayed at the pension for a fortnight. 他已在那个小旅馆待了两个星期。 5. He was pensioned off and replaced with a younger man. 他被迫退休，由一年轻人接替其职务。', '形容词: pensionable 过去式: pensioned 过去分词: pensioned 现在分词: pensioning 第三人称单数: pensions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('trumpery', '[\'trʌmpəri]', 'n.无价值的杂物；徒有其表的东西；废话 adj.中看不中用的；无价值的', '1. The thing he bought yesterday was trumpery. 他昨天买的只是一件没有什么价值的东西。 2. As usual, a great proportion was trumpery which had begun to accumulate in his father\'s day. 照常，大部分的东西是华而不实的，还是他父亲手里就开始积藏了。 3. In this paper, the training objective and training model of the surveying major are discussed, and some trumpery opinions are presented. 文章主要探讨测绘工程专业的培养目标和培养模式，并提出粗浅的认识。', '名词复数: trumperies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('valorous', '[\'vælərəs]', 'adj.勇敢的；勇武的；刚勇的', '1. And he put the valorous captains in all the fortified cities in Judah. 又在犹大各坚固城内派驻勇敢的军长。', '副词: valorously 名词: valorousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('volition', '[və\'lɪʃn]', 'n.决定；自主；意志力', '1. She offered to help us of her own volition. 她自愿提出要帮助我们。 2. She left entirely of her own volition. 她完全是自愿离开的。 3. I didn\'t ask him to go;he went of his own volition. 我没有要求他去，他是出于自愿的。 4. Such cloudy weather can wear people\'s volition. 这种阴阴的天气最是消磨人的意志。', '形容词: volitional 副词: volitionally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('procession', '[prə\'seʃn]', 'n.队伍；行列 v.列队行进', '1. They watched the procession go past. 他们观看游行队伍经过。 2. The royal procession will be televised. 国王的仪仗行列将由电视播送。 3. The funeral procession choked up Lorna. 那送葬行列使洛娜流下了眼泪。 4. There was a bomb scare during the procession. 在列队行进时因怀疑有炸弹而引起恐慌。', '过去式: processioned 过去分词: processioned 现在分词: processioning 第三人称单数: processions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bracing', '[\'breɪsɪŋ]', 'n.撑杆；支撑 adj.令人振奋的；提神的 动词brace的现在分词.', '1. Transverse bracing was installed between the two shafts. 两根立柱之间设置了横撑。 2. A little bracing roughness is better than spoiling him. 令人精神振作的微弱粗暴比娇宠他要好得多。', '副词: bracingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chapel', '[\'tʃæpl]', 'n.小礼拜堂；礼拜仪式；唱诗班；印刷厂工会；殡仪馆', '1. The chapel was dedicated in 1880. 这座小教堂于1880年举行献堂礼。 2. He built a chapel as a shrine to the memory of his dead wife. 他建了一座小教堂作为悼念亡妻的圣所。 3. The frescos in the Sistine Chapel are world-famous. 西斯廷教堂的壁画举世闻名。 4. The ghost of Lady Margaret is supposed to haunt this chapel. 据说玛格丽特女士的鬼魂常在这个礼拜堂出没。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cascade', '[kæ\'skeɪd]', 'n.瀑布；[电]串联 v.瀑布似地落下；（将 ... ）连结；串联', '1. The water formed a cascade down the mountain. 水沿山泻下，形成一条瀑布。 2. Climbing plants with their bright flowers hung in cascades over the garden wall. 开出鲜艳花朵的爬藤植物瀑布般悬挂在花园墙上。 3. When it rained, water would cascade down the window. 下雨的时候，雨水像瀑布一样沿着窗沿泻下。 4. We can cascade them to determine their overall effect. 我们可以将它们串联起来确定它们的总体影响。', '过去式: cascaded 过去分词: cascaded 现在分词: cascading 第三人称单数: cascades');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('smuggle', '[\'smʌɡl]', 'v.走私；偷运；偷带', '1. They deny conspiring together to smuggle drugs. 他们否认共谋走私毒品。 2. Well, sir, when you smuggle things you lose them. 好了，先生，如果您走私东西，您就要失去这些东西。 3. He tried to smuggle diamonds into Japan. 他企图把钻石偷运进日本。 4. The syndicate collaborated with vice syndicates in the Mainland to smuggle women into Hong Kong for providing sex services. 该集团亦与内地的卖淫集团勾结，偷运女子来港卖淫。', '名词: smuggler 过去式: smuggled 过去分词: smuggled 现在分词: smuggling 第三人称单数: smuggles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('civilian', '[sə\'vɪljən]', 'adj.平民的 n.罗马法专家；平民', '1. He resigned his commission to take up a civilian job. 他辞去军职而从事平民工作。 2. People are indignant by their shooting of innocent civilians. 对于他们枪杀无辜平民，人们感到义愤填膺。 3. A civilian was killed by a stray bullet. 一个平民被流弹打死。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('credulous', '[\'kredʒələs]', 'adj.轻信的；易受骗的', '1. We are less credulous than we used to be. 我们不再像以往那样轻易相信别人了。 2. He always cheats credulous people. 他总是欺骗容易上当的人。 3. John is so credulous that he wil believe what you tell him. 约翰很容易受骗，所有你说的，他都会相信。', '副词: credulously 名词: credulousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ruck', '[rʌk]', 'n.普通人；寻常事物；一大群；大量；皱褶 v.起皱；起褶', '1. He was eager to get out of the ruck and distinguish himself in some way. 他渴望出人头地 2. He pushed his way through the ruck of drinkers to get to the bar. 他从一大群酒鬼中间挤过，到了酒吧。 3. When the police arrived, it soon turned into an ugly ruck. 警察到的时候，人群立刻混乱起来。 4. He smoothed out the rucks in the bedclothes. 他把床单上的褶子抚平了。 5. Your coat\'s all rucked up at the back. 你的外套后面全起皱了。', '过去式: rucked 过去分词: rucked 现在分词: rucking 第三人称单数: rucks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('earring', '[\'ɪrɪŋ]', 'n.耳环；耳饰', '1. She is wearing a small ruby earring. 她戴着一枚红宝石小耳环。 2. I\'ve left my diamond earring in the dressing room. 我的钻石耳环落在了更衣室里。 3. Incidentally, the day after I found the earring the girl asked me if anyone had claimed it. 在我得到那个耳饰后的第二天，那个女孩儿偶然间问我是否有人认领它。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suppliant', '[\'sʌpliənt]', 'adj.哀恳的 n.恳求者', '1. He asked for help in a suppliant attitude. 他以恳求的态度要我帮忙。 2. He knelt as a suppliant at the altar. 他跪在祭坛前祈祷。', '副词: suppliantly 名词: suppliance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vista', '[\'vɪstə]', 'n.街景；展望；回想', '1. The days stretch out in an endless vista. 时日在无穷的展望中延展着。 2. We must face the differences, but let us try to see beyond them down the long vista of the future. 诚然，我们必须正视分歧，但更应努力跨越分歧，展望未来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mollycoddle', '[\'mɑːlikɑːdl]', 'v.溺爱；纵容 n.女性化的男人；娇生惯养的男人', '1. He doesn\'t believe that children should be mollycoddled. 他认为不应溺爱儿童。 2. Let\'s not mollycoddle our students! 我们不能纵容学生。', '名词: mollycoddler 过去式: mollycoddled 过去分词: mollycoddled 现在分词: mollycoddling 第三人称单数: mollycoddles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dictate', '[\'dɪkteɪt]', 'vi.听写 vt.口授；规定；决定，影响 n.命令，支配，主宰；指挥；指令', '1. The teacher dictated a passage to the class. 老师给全班同学听写一段文章。 2. He was dictating a letter to his secretary. 他在向秘书口授信稿。 3. He can\'t write but he can dictate. 他不会写但会说。 4. Businessmen often dictate their letters. 商人常口授信稿令人笔录。 5. If I had the dictatorial power in a dictatorship, I will dictate those IT be kept in detention for appearing too pretentious. 我假如拥有独裁政治的专断权，我会命令把她关起来，罪名是外表炫耀做作。', '过去式: dictated 过去分词: dictated 现在分词: dictating 第三人称单数: dictates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('allergy', '[\'ælərdʒi]', 'n.过敏症；反感；厌恶', '1. I have an allergy to penicillin. 我对青霉素有过敏反应。 2. Some people have an allergy to pollen. 一些人对花粉有过敏反应。 3. She has an allergy to cocktail parties. 她讨厌参加鸡尾酒会。 4. He has an allergy to wine. 他极讨厌酒。', '名词复数: allergies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('brooch', '[broʊtʃ]', 'n.胸针；领针', '1. He bought her a gilt brooch. 他给她买了一枚镀金胸针。 2. That seems a high price for the brooch. 胸针卖这个价钱似乎很贵了。 3. My aunt give me one of her brooches as a keepsake. 我的姑母把她的一只胸针送给我作纪念。 4. Your new black evening gown is beautiful and that gold brooch adds the final touch. 你的新黑色礼服很漂亮,那金胸针又大增其魅力。', '异体字: broach');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('partiality', '[ˌpɑːrʃi\'æləti]', 'n.偏袒；偏心；癖好', '1. He showed no partiality to either side. 他对双方都不偏袒。 2. We think that the court consisting of arbitrators from both sides must be fair and able to handle the dispute without bias or partiality. 我们认为法庭由双方仲裁员组成一定能公平且无偏见或偏袒地解决纠纷。 3. A wise teacher never shows partiality. 聪明的老师从不显露偏心。 4. Show no partiality in your decisions. 作出决定时切勿偏心。', '名词复数: partialities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('well-groomed', '[\'wel\'gruːmd]', 'adj.被小心照料的；梳洗得整洁的', '1. Exceptionally well groomed and presented. 着装整齐，长相端正. 2. They chose him for the job because he always looks so well groomed. 他们选他担任该职务，因为他总是衣冠整齐。 3. They would be turned out agreeable, well groomed and able to take part in intelligent discussion on any subject. 他们将变得举止文雅，修饰得体，能就任何题目进行有见解的讨论。 4. The clothes should be neat, be well groomed, and be dressed right for the job involved. 服装应整齐干净，与所谋求的职业相适应。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('allay', '[ə\'leɪ]', 'v.减轻；使 ... 缓和', '1. There pills will allay your pain. 这药丸可以减轻你的疼痛。 2. More reading may be allaying your doubt. 多读书或许可以减少你的疑惑。 3. The employer was forced to allay the tumult. 雇主被迫缓和骚乱。', '名词: allayer 过去式: allayed 过去分词: allayed 现在分词: allaying 第三人称单数: allays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('strive', '[straɪv]', 'vi.奋斗；努力；力求；斗争', '1. He strove for recognition as an artist. 他为获得艺术家的声誉而奋斗。 2. We should all strive to reunify the motherland. 我们共同努力,实现祖国统一。 3. I strive automatically to bring the world into harmony with my own nature. 我机械地努力以使这世界跟自己的性情协调一致。 4. The scientists strive for a breakthrough in cancer research. 科学家们力争在癌症研究方面有个突破。', '副词: strivingly 名词: striver 过去式: strove 过去分词: striven/strived 现在分词: striving 第三人称单数: strives');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dissipate', '[\'dɪsɪpeɪt]', 'v.驱散；消散；散去；浪费；挥霍；放荡', '1. The sun dissipated the mist. 太阳驱散了雾。 2. Her son\'s letter dissipated all her fears and anxiety. 她儿子的来信消除了她一切恐惧和焦虑。 3. The crowd dissipated soon after the police arrived. 在警察到达之后，人群很快散去了。 4. He soon dissipated his fortune. 他很快就把财产浪费光了。', '形容词: dissipative 名词: dissipater 过去式: dissipated 过去分词: dissipated 现在分词: dissipating 第三人称单数: dissipates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('imminent', '[\'ɪmɪnənt]', 'adj.逼近的；即将发生的', '1. He was faced with imminent death. 他面临逼近的死亡。 2. They are unaware of imminent danger. 他们没意识到逼近的危险。 3. Rumours of an imminent earthquake startled a panic. 谣传即将发生地震引起了一阵恐慌。 4. The black clounds show that a storm is imminent. 乌云预示暴风雨即将来临。', '副词: imminently 名词: imminentness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('amble', '[\'æmbl]', 'n.溜蹄；缓行漫步 v.缓行；溜蹄', '1. The horse is walking at an amble. 这匹马正在溜蹄行走。 2. \"Sure.\" I laugh, slowing to an easy amble. “当然可以，”我笑起来，减下步伐，慢慢地走。 3. He came ambling down the road. 他沿路溜溜达达地来了. 4. Leakey is an infant, but old enough to amble through the canopy on his own. 利基虽然是一个幼龄猩猩，但它也能在属于它自己的丛林上漫步。', '名词: ambler 过去式: ambled 过去分词: ambled 现在分词: ambling 第三人称单数: ambles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diocesan', '[daɪ\'ɒsɪsn]', 'adj.主教管区的 n.管区主教', '1. Approved the Proposal: approve the Parish delegates to Diocesan Annual meeting. 通过提案：追认教区年会代表。 2. Joined the diocesan minor seminary of Ka-ying for his secondary education. 一九四0年：进入嘉应教区修院接受中学教育。 3. Diocesan Girls\'School has a long and distinguished history that goes back 137 years. 拨萃女书院历史悠久，建校已一百三十七年。 4. A two-year diocesan inquiry into Mother Teresa\'s life and evidence of miracles was completed in August this year. 针对德雷莎修女的生平与奇迹证据进行两年的教区调查工作，已在今年八月间完成。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('propensity', '[prə\'pensəti]', 'n.倾向；习性', '1. He showed a propensity for violence. 他表现出暴力倾向。 2. He has a propensity for drinking too much alcohol. 他有酗酒的倾向。 3. This view is based on the propensity of following points. 这个看法基于以下几点倾向。 4. She has a propensity to exaggerate. 她有夸大的习性。', '名词复数: propensities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('muse', '[mjuːz]', 'v.沉思；冥想 n.沉思；[大写]（希腊神话）缪斯；艺术家的灵感；<罕>诗人', '1. It is useless to muse upon past errors. 念念不忘昔日的过错是没有益处的。 2. She lay musing for a while. 她躺着沉思了一会儿。 3. The young girl was lost in a muse. 这女孩陷入了沉思。', '副词: musingly 过去式: mused 过去分词: mused 现在分词: musing 第三人称单数: muses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sinew', '[\'sɪnjuː]', 'n.肌肉；精力；原动力 vt.赋予力量；支持', '1. The special effects first show the skeleton as it is displayed in the museum, then add muscle and sinew, followed by skin. 通过特殊效果，人们先看到的是博物馆了陈列的这副恐龙的骨架，然后出现了肌肉，接着是皮肤。', '过去式: sinewed 过去分词: sinewed 现在分词: sinewing 第三人称单数: sinews');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('epitome', '[ɪ\'pɪtəmi]', 'n.缩影；化身；摘要（古）', '1. The divisions we see in this school are the epitome of those occurring throughout the whole country. 我们在这所学校中看到的各个部门是全国各校的缩影。 2. The Bund is a symbol of Shanghai and an epitome of Shanghai\'s modern history. 外滩是上海的象征，亦是上海近代史的缩影。 3. My cat is the epitome of laziness. 我的猫是懒惰的化身。 4. He is the epitome of diligence. 他是勤勉的典型。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('descend', '[dɪ\'send]', 'v.下降；降临 v.传下来；遗传 v.突然袭击；突然拜访', '1. The sun descended behind the hills. 太阳下山了。 2. I wish that the prices can descend. 但愿物价会下降。 3. I didn\'t expect him to descend to personal abuse. 我没料到他会堕落到对我进行人身攻击的地步。 4. At 6:30 p.m. the tropical darkness descends. 在傍晚六点半的时候,热带地区的黑夜降临。 5. The custom has descended to our day. 这一习俗一直传到今天。 6. Armed thieves descended on the helpless travelers. 一群武装盗贼袭击了无依无靠的旅客。', '形容词: descendible 过去式: descended 过去分词: descended 现在分词: descending 第三人称单数: descends');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('inaugurate', '[ɪ\'nɔːɡjəreɪt]', 'v.举行就职典礼；举行仪式；开始；开创', '1. Mr. Clinton was inaugurated as the President of the U.S.A. 克林顿就职美国总统。 2. The city library was inaugurated by the mayor. 市长主持了市图书馆的落成仪式。 3. Watt inaugurated the age of steam. 瓦特开创了蒸汽时代。', '名词: inaugurator 过去式: inaugurated 过去分词: inaugurated 现在分词: inaugurating 第三人称单数: inaugurates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bullion', '[\'bʊliən]', 'n.金银；金银锭；金银丝花边', '1. Investors world-wide are stashing bullion. 全球投资者都在买进储备黄金。 2. In the London bullion market yesterday, the price of gold was steady. 昨天伦敦金银市场黄金价格稳定。 3. The gold bullion was transported under police escort. 金锭在警方的护送下运走了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('repercussion', '[ˌriːpər\'kʌʃn]', 'n.弹回；反响；后果；反射', '1. The president\'s death had unexpected repercussion. 总统的逝世引起出乎意料的反响。 2. What repercussions will the war have on the economy? 这个战争将给经济带来什么影响?', '形容词: repercussive');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petty', '[\'peti]', 'adj.小的；琐碎的；次要的；狭隘的', '1. The party split into petty factions. 该党分裂成若干小派系。 2. The paymasters of these petty crooks are the big crime syndicates. 操纵这帮小流氓的就是那个大犯罪集团。 3. In his short life he had run the entire gamut of crime, from petty theft to murder. 他在短短的一生中,从小偷小摸到杀人,什么罪都犯过。 4. Don\'t bug me with petty details. 不要讲那些琐碎的细节来烦我。', '副词: pettily 比较级: pettier 最高级: pettiest 名词: pettiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('toss', '[tɔːs]', 'n.投掷；震荡 v.投掷；摇荡；辗转', '1. The decision depended on the toss of a coin. 那项决定是靠掷硬币的方法做出的。 2. The first toss here would appear to favor Candida. 第一次投掷结果看来对坎迪德有利。 3. The children tossed the ball to each other. 孩子们互相把球扔来扔去。 4. My husband was tossing and turning all night. 我丈夫整夜翻来覆去睡不着。', '名词: tosser 过去式: tossed 过去分词: tossed 现在分词: tossing 第三人称单数: tosses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disabuse', '[ˌdɪsə\'bjuːz]', 'v.去除…的错误想法；使省悟', '1. I must disabuse you of your feelings of grandeur. 我必须去消除你的傲气。 2. Let me disabuse of that foolish prejudices. 让我消除那个愚蠢的偏见。 3. Let us disabuse ourselves of the idea that we are invincible. 让我们撤销我们是战无不堪的错误念头。 4. If you think I\'m going to lend you money,I must disabuse you of te wrong idea. 你若认为我会借钱给你，我倒要劝你打消那念头。', '过去式: disabused 过去分词: disabused 现在分词: disabusing 第三人称单数: disabuses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wacky', '[\'wæki]', 'adj.(行为等)古怪的；愚蠢的', '1. Physicists hope to find a new astronomy and test some wacky ideas. 物理学家们试图开展新的天文学来检测一些新奇古怪的想法。 2. They came dressed in wacky costumes for the \"Black Ball\" street parade. 他们身着奇里古怪的衣服参加“黑球”大街的游行。', '副词: wackily 异体字: whacky 比较级: wackier 最高级: wackiest 名词: wackiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('syndrome', '[\'sɪndroʊm]', 'n.症候群；综合症', '1. This patient provides a typical example of the syndrome. 这位患者是这种症候群的典型病例。 2. Poor appetite is one of the symptoms of TV syndrome. 食欲不振是电视综合症的症状之一。 3. This syndrome is associated with frequent coughing. 这种综合症与经常咳嗽有关。', '形容词: syndromic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discount', '[\'dɪskaʊnt]', 'n.折扣；贴现率 vt.打折扣；贴现；不全信；不重视 vi.贴现；减息贷款', '1. These goods will be sold at a discount. 这些货物将减价出售。 2. We give 10 percent discount for cash. 现金付款，我们九折优惠。 3. The discount rate is set by the Fed. 贴现率是由联储决定的。 4. The preferred project in this case depends on the discount rate, not the IRR. 该例中，我们倾向选择哪个项目取决于贴现率，而不是内部收益率。 5. That store does not discount at all. 那家商店出售商品一概不打折。 6. We usually only discount acceptance trade and commercial bills. 我们通常只贴现已承兑的商业票据。', '形容词: discountable 过去式: discounted 过去分词: discounted 现在分词: discounting 第三人称单数: discounts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('moody', '[\'muːdi]', 'adj.易怒的；喜怒无常的；情绪化的 Moody. n.穆迪(人名)', '1. She treated her moody child with indulgence. 她对她那喜怒无常的孩子百依百顺。 2. Moody people are very difficult to deal with. 喜怒无常的人很难对付。 3. The moody Crab is just too difficult for you to handle. 情绪化的蟹子让你很难应付。 4. Harry is taken to Moody\'s office, and is about to be murdered. 哈利被送到穆迪的办公室，即将被杀害。', '副词: moodily 比较级: moodier 最高级: moodiest 名词: moodiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('forward', '[\'fɔːrwərd]', 'adj.向前的；前部的；未来的；将来的；莽撞的；热心的；早熟的 adv.向前地 v.促进；转交；发送 n.[体]前锋', '1. He is forward in his English. 他的英语有进步。 2. We can see the forward part of the ship. 我们可以看见船的前部。 3. A little forward planning at the outset can save you a lot of expense. 一开始就为未来作点打算能节约很多开支。 4. I hope you\'ll apologize that was a very forward thing to do. 我希望你能道歉－－那事你做得太莽撞了。 5. She stepped forward in order to see clearly. 她向前走了一步以便能看得更清楚 6. He\'s hoping to forward his career by this move. 他正希望通过这一举动来促进他的事业。 7. The forward made a foul in the penalty area. 前锋在禁区内犯规了。', '副词: forwardly 名词: forwardness 过去式: forwarded 过去分词: forwarded 现在分词: forwarding 第三人称单数: forwards');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cull', '[kʌl]', 'v.拣选；剔除 n.剔除', '1. The information is culled from various reference books. 这份资料是从各种参考书中摘出的。 2. Each autumn, the villagers will cull the sick members of the herd. 每年秋天，村民们都要挑出畜群里的病弱杀掉。 3. It is usually good practice to cull the poorest prior to field planting. 通常在实践上的好方法是在出圃栽植前挑出最弱的苗木。 4. A seal cut is forbidden. 捕杀海豹是禁止的。', '名词: culler 过去式: culled 过去分词: culled 现在分词: culling 第三人称单数: culls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disposal', '[dɪ\'spoʊzl]', 'n.处理；处置；布置', '1. We placed everything at his disposal. 我们把一切事情都交给他处理。 2. The disposal of rubbish is always a problem. 垃圾的处理总是个难题。 3. The safe disposal of nuclear waste is a major problem. 安全处置核废料是个大问题。 4. The money is at our own disposal. 这钱由我们自由支配使用。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('civility', '[sə\'vɪləti]', 'n.礼貌；谦恭', '1. They greeted us with civility. 他们很有礼貌地迎接了我们。 2. Tom shows his civility before his parents\' friends. 汤姆在他父母的朋友面前表现得很有礼貌。 3. There is nothing that costs less than civility. 世界上没有什么东西比谦恭更不花钱。', '名词复数: civilities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('feasible', '[\'fiːzəbl]', 'adj.可行的；可能的', '1. The plan did not seem feasible. 这个计划似乎没法实行。 2. It\'s quite clear that the electric car is technically feasible. 电动汽车明显在工艺技术上是可行的。 3. It\'s not feasible to follow your proposals. 按照你的建议去做是行不通的。 4. It\'s not feasible to dismiss him. 不可开除他。', '副词: feasibly 名词: feasibility');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('flossy', '[\'flɒsɪ]', 'adj.华丽的；时髦的；丝棉的；柔软的', '1. He wrote flossy articles about the lifestyles of the rich. 他写关于富人生活方式的华丽的文章。', '副词: flossily 比较级: flossier 最高级: flossiest 名词: flossiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('abstract', '[\'æbstrækt]', 'adj.抽象的；理论的；抽象派的 n.摘要；抽象派艺术作品 v.(/æbˈstrækt/)把…抽象出；提取；抽取；转移(注意力等)；做…的摘要；<婉>偷', '1. We may talk of beautiful things, but beauty itself is abstract. 我们尽可谈论美的事物，然而美本身却是抽象的。 2. He has some abstract notion of wanting to change the world. 他有一种要改造世界的空想。 3. Abstract paintings did not appeal to him. 抽象派绘画引不起他的兴趣。 4. The whole text of the abstract shall contain not more than 300 Chinese characters. 摘要文字部分不得超过300个字。 5. She abstracted the main points from the argument. 她把论据概括成要点。', '副词: abstractly 名词: abstracter 过去式: abstracted 过去分词: abstracted 现在分词: abstracting 第三人称单数: abstracts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('felicitate', '[fə\'lɪsəˌteɪt]', 'vt. 祝贺； 庆贺； <古>使开心 adj. <古>使幸福的', '1. I felicitate the day I found you. 我庆幸我找到你的那一天。 2. I felicitate myself on my narrow escape. 我庆幸自己死里逃生。 3. Allow me to felicitate you upon the birth of your daughter. 恭贺你喜得千金。 4. We are the persons who feel felicitate about our single-edged eyelid! 庆幸自己是单眼皮的人们!', '名词: felicitator 过去式: felicitated 过去分词: felicitated 现在分词: felicitating 第三人称单数: felicitates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crackpot', '[\'krækpɑːt]', 'adj.想入非非的；不切实的 n.疯子；怪人；狂想家', '1. That crackpot thinks his neighbors are aliens. 那位疯子认为他的邻居是外星人。 2. Everyone knows Professor Wilkins is a crackpot. 大家都知道教授是个怪人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('duress', '[du\'res]', 'n.强迫；胁迫', '1. There\'s no suggestion that the boys are acting under duress. 没有迹象显示孩子们是被强迫做这些活动。 2. Most Iranians are aware of the duress people suffer in jail. 伊朗人现在意识到人们在狱中遭受种种胁迫。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confection', '[kən\'fekʃən]', 'n.甜食；糖果；糖果剂；调制；精美作品', '1. Her hat was an elaborate confection of satin and net. 她的帽子用缎子和网纱制成，非常精致。', '过去式: confectioned 过去分词: confectioned 现在分词: confectioning 第三人称单数: confections');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disperse', '[dɪ\'spɜːrs]', 'v.分散；散开', '1. The police dispersed the crowd. 警方驱散群众。 2. The wind dispersed the cloud from the sky. 风吹散了天上的云。 3. The enemy had to disperse and hide in caves. 敌人不得不分散藏身于洞穴之中。 4. The crowd dispersed. 人群纷纷散开。', '形容词: dispersible 副词: dispersedly 名词: dispersant 过去式: dispersed 过去分词: dispersed 现在分词: dispersing 第三人称单数: disperses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('generosity', '[ˌdʒenə\'rɑːsəti]', 'n.慷慨；大方；宽大', '1. His generosity to the poor is well known. 他对穷人的慷慨为人所熟知。 2. He hasn\'t a spark of generosity in him. 他一点也不慷慨。 3. His generosity manifests itself in times of difficulties. 他的慷慨在困境中表现了出来。 4. His supposed generosity is merely a form of self-interest. 他貌似慷慨，不过是变相的利己而已。', '名词复数: generosities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sensation', '[sen\'seɪʃn]', 'n.感觉；轰动；激动；知觉', '1. He had a sensation of dizziness. 他有一种晕眩的感觉。 2. I knew the train had stopped, but I had the sensation that it was moving backwards. 我知道火车已经停了，但我觉得火车在倒退。 3. The new discovery caused a great sensation. 这项新发现很轰动。 4. The outrageous book created a sensation. 那部耸人听闻的书曾轰动一时。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('madrigal', '[\'mædrɪɡl]', 'n.牧歌；情歌；小调；合唱曲', '1. Later the Italian madrigal becomes the most distinguished genre. 稍后,意大利牧歌成为最著名的作品。 2. The madrigal he wrote are still sung by people. 他写的情歌仍然还在被人们传唱。', '名词: madrigalist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wangle', '[\'wæŋɡl]', 'v.（用计谋等）得到；取得', '1. He was trying to wangle his way onto the committee. 他千方百计想钻入委员会中。 2. I\'m sure you can wangle the information out of him. 我完全相信你能设法从他的口中套出这项情报来。 3. She managed to wangle an invitation to the reception. 她设法弄到了招待会的请帖。', '名词: wangler 过去式: wangled 过去分词: wangled 现在分词: wangling 第三人称单数: wangles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quaver', '[\'kweɪvər]', 'n.颤音；颤抖 v.用颤声说(唱)；震动；颤抖', '1. You could hear the quaver in her voice. 她的声音中能听出有些颤抖。 2. She quavered an old folk song. 她以震颤声唱一首古老的民谣。 3. The children quavered out their little song. 孩子们颤悠悠地唱出了一支歌。 4. The sign on the wall seemed to quaver under a film of sliding warm water. 墙上的招牌好象在一层浮动的融融的水流下颤动。', '形容词: quavery 副词: quaveringly 过去式: quavered 过去分词: quavered 现在分词: quavering 第三人称单数: quavers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cooperate', '[koʊ\'ɑːpəreɪt]', 'vi.合作；协力；配合', '1. I am so happy to cooperate with you. 很高兴与你合作。 2. I advise you not to cooperate with that deceitful businessman. 我建议你不要和那个不诚实的商人合作。 3. When buyers cooperate, they can make large wholesale purchases at a discount. 如果购买者联合起来,他们可以打折扣买大批的批发商品。 4. We need to cooperate perfectly to win the game. 要想赢得比赛，我们需要密切配合。', '名词: cooperator 过去式: cooperated 过去分词: cooperated 现在分词: cooperating 第三人称单数: cooperates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('acerbity', '[ə\'sɜːbəti]', 'n.涩；酸；刻薄', '1. Before why crying is nose acerbity acerbity? 为什么在哭之前鼻子会酸酸的呢？', '名词复数: acerbities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('untimely', '[ʌn\'taɪmli]', 'adj.不合时宜的；比正常情况早的 adv.不合时宜地；过早地', '1. His untimely intervention annoyed me. 他那不合时宜的干涉让我生气。 2. The accident put an untimely end to the party. 意外事故使聚会匆匆结束了。 3. Her untimely death at 25 made her parents heartbroken. 她25岁时英年早逝使她的父母非常伤心。 4. He was a pure man of letters, untimely born in a world that had no need of letters. 他是个地道的文人，不逢时地生在一个不需要学问的世界里。', '比较级: untimelier 最高级: untimeliest 名词: untimeliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unassuming', '[ˌʌnə\'suːmɪŋ]', 'adj.谦逊的；不装腔作势的', '1. He is emphatically a retiring and unassuming man. 他的确是一个与世无争和谦虚纯朴的人。 2. I found him to be unassuming and easy to get along with. 我发现他没有架子，很好相处。', '副词: unassumingly 名词: unassumingness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stern', '[stɜːrn]', 'adj.严厉的；严峻的；苛刻的；坚决的 n.尾部；船尾', '1. He received a stern rebuke from his superior. 他受到上司的严厉斥责。 2. She had a stern father who never praised her. 她父亲很严厉，他从来没有表扬过她。 3. The teacher\'s stern look reduced him to silence. 教师神情严肃，他便静了下来。 4. He came close to the painter and looked steadfastly into his stern eyes. 他走近画家,并且死死地盯着他那目光严峻的眼睛。 5. Move your stern, I want to sit down. 你把屁股挪一挪，我想坐下。', '副词: sternly 比较级: sterner 最高级: sternest 名词: sternness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cabinet', '[\'kæbɪnət]', 'n.橱柜；内阁 adj.内阁的；秘密的', '1. She needs a cherry cabinet in her room. 她需要在她房里添一个樱桃木的柜子。 2. I put my collection of old glasses in the cabinet. 我把收集的古玻璃器皿放在橱里。 3. The question was discussed in cabinet. 在内阁会议上讨论了这个问题。 4. They have found out the mole in the cabinet. 他们已经发现了内阁中的间谍。 5. He was elevated to cabinet rank. 他被提升到内阁部长级。', '名词: cabinetful');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('saccharin', '[\'sækərɪn]', 'n.糖精', '1. Saccharin is an artificial sweetener. 糖精是一种人工增甜剂。 2. We use saccharin in substitution for sugar. 我们用糖精代替糖。 3. It may replace saccharin as a sugar substitute. 它可以取代糖精作为糖的替代品。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wraith', '[reɪθ]', 'n.鬼魂；死灵；幽灵', '1. He was a wraith-like figure. 他是一个瘦骨嶙峋，面色苍白如鬼魂的人。 2. My only question right now involves the wraith. 我现在唯一的问题是关于幽灵的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confederacy', '[kən\'fedərəsɪ]', 'n.同盟；联邦；共谋 Confederacy. n.（美国南北战争时期的）南部邦联', '1. This bond of kin represented the real basis of the confederacy. 这种血缘亲属关系是联盟的真实基础。 2. The people of the Creek confederacy occupied some 50 towns. 克里克联邦的人占领了大约50个镇子。 3. They believed the Confederacy would fall if the Union won a big military victory early in the war. 他们相信如果联盟在战争初期就取得大捷胜利的话，南部同盟就会士气低落。', '名词复数: confederacies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unspotted', '[ʌn\'spɒtɪd]', 'adj.清白的；无污点的', '1. And gave him a new one all unspotted. 然后递给他一张全新洁白的纸。 2. And gave me a new one all unspotted. 然后递给我全新洁白的一天。 3. The leopard,especially in its black,unspotted form. 豹无斑点的豹，尤指黑背 4. She is a virgin, a most unspotted lily. 她是个纯洁的少女，一朵洁白无瑕的百合花。', '名词: unspottedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('outwit', '[ˌaʊt\'wɪt]', 'v.瞒骗；以智取胜', '1. Two prisoners outwitted their guards and got away. 有两个囚犯设计欺骗了警卫而逃走了。 2. Somehow he always manages to outwit his opponents. 他反正总能设法智胜对手。', '过去式: outwitted 过去分词: outwitted 现在分词: outwitting 第三人称单数: outwits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('guffaw', '[ɡə\'fɔː]', 'n.哄笑；大笑 vi.哄笑；大笑', '1. What he said aroused a blast of guffaw . 他的话引起大家一阵哄笑。 2. All the boys burst out into a guffaw at the joke. 听到这个笑话，男孩子们发出一声狂笑。 3. He laughed, a coarse hearty guffaw 他哈哈笑了起来，一阵粗率、热诚的大笑。 4. The five hunters, in a guffaw, run far, far away. 众人大笑声中，五骑马早去得远了. 5. Many will guffaw at her trashy family. 谈到她家里那些混账事情，不少人会大笑不止。', '过去式: guffawed 过去分词: guffawed 现在分词: guffawing 第三人称单数: guffaws');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('discard', '[dɪs\'kɑːrd]', 'vt.丢弃；抛弃 vi.丢牌 n.丢牌；废牌', '1. He discarded his winter clothing. 他把冬天穿的衣服都丢弃了。 2. My mother-in-law would discard them on the spot. 我的岳母是会当场把它们扔掉的。 3. History discarded him. 他被历史所抛弃。 4. You\'ve got to discard before you can pick up another card. 你得先打出一张牌，才能拿另一张牌。', '形容词: discardable 名词: discarder 过去式: discarded 过去分词: discarded 现在分词: discarding 第三人称单数: discards');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('metrical', '[\'metrɪkl]', 'adj.韵律的；测量的 =metric.', '1. A metrical unit consisting of seven feet. 七韵步由七个音步组成的格律单位 2. A line of verse consisting of five metrical feet. 五音步的每行有五个韵脚的一种诗 3. The substitution of one metrical unit for another, especially the substitution of two short syllables for one long syllable in quantitative verse. 长音节的拆分或替换一个韵律元素替代另一个，尤指在数量韵文中用两个短音节替代一个长音节 4. A metrical unit of quantitative verse consisting of two or more cola. 定量测量单位包括两个或两个以上音行的定量韵律的度量单位', '副词: metrically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('turncoat', '[\'tɜːrnkoʊt]', 'n.背叛者；变节者', '1. Some of the workers began to see him as a turncoat. 有些工人开始认为他是一个叛徒。 2. I\'m a renegade, a turncoat, a Scalawag. 我是个叛徒，变节者，流氓。 3. You\'re still alive, you turncoat? 好哇！原来你这个叛徒还没死？ 4. Wine is a turncoat, first a friend, then a enemy. 酒是叛徒，先是朋友，后是敌人。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lustrous', '[\'lʌstrəs]', 'adj.有光泽的；光辉的；光亮的；皎洁的', '1. Are the cultured pearls as lustrous and beautiful as the natural ones? 人工养殖的珍珠和天然的一样具有光泽和漂亮吗? 2. Cadmium is a lustrous, silver-white, ductile, very malleable metal. 镉是一种有光泽的，银白色的，非常柔软的，延展性很好的金属。 3. She brushed her hair until it fell in lustrous auburn waves. 她把头发梳出光亮的赤褐色波浪。 4. The moon was above, lustrous and serene. 天上的月亮皎洁肃穆。', '副词: lustrously 名词: lustrousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('witch', '[wɪtʃ]', 'n.女巫；巫婆 vt.施巫术 vi.用神杖发现地下水源或矿物', '1. The wedding was in full swing when the witch came in. 当女巫进来时婚礼正进行得热闹。 2. The witch put the princess under a spell, and she fell asleep for ten years. 这女巫使公主中了巫术，沉睡了十年。 3. The witch charmed the prince. 女巫对王子施了魔法。 4. The witch turned the princess into a swan. 巫婆把公主变成了一只天鹅。 5. The little princess was withced. 小公主被施了巫术。', '形容词: witchy 名词: witchery 过去式: witched 过去分词: witched 现在分词: witching 第三人称单数: witches');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grotesque', '[ɡroʊ\'tesk]', 'adj.奇形怪状的；奇怪的；怪诞的；可笑的 n.怪异风格；怪异图案', '1. The fat old man looked grotesque in tight trousers. 那个胖老头穿上绷得紧紧的裤子显得奇形怪状。 2. Tribal dancers were wearing grotesque masks. 部落中跳舞的人戴着古怪的面具。 3. The most grotesque and fantastic conceits haunted him in his bed at night. 夜晚躺在床上的时候，各种离奇怪诞的幻想纷至沓来。 4. The uninhibited mutations and grotesque symbolic language of dreams interrupt the distinct images of contemporary humanity. 现代人的鲜明形象中又穿插了梦境的自由变化和怪诞的象征语言。 5. Hieronymus Bosch was a master of the grotesque in painting. 希罗宁姆斯·博希是怪诞派绘画大师。', '副词: grotesquely 名词: grotesqueness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('knoll', '[noʊl]', 'n.小山；圆丘；<古>丧钟（=knell） v.敲钟', '1. A low mound or ridge of earth; a knoll. 小丘低土丘或圆岗; 小丘 2. There is a bower on the knoll. 小山上有一个凉亭。', '过去式: knolled 过去分词: knolled 现在分词: knolling 第三人称单数: knolls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('girth', '[ɡɜːrθ]', 'n.周围长度；带尺；尺寸；（马等的）肚带；腰带 v.量周长；包围；给 ... 缚上肚带', '1. My girth is increasing. 我的腰围愈来愈大了。 2. He is a man of enormous girth. 他是个腰围粗大的男子。 3. Are you saying that Garth has the perfect girth? 你的意思是盖斯的尺寸非常完美？ 4. Secure the English saddle onto the horse with a girth. 要确保英式马鞍用马肚带固定在马身上。', '过去式: girthed 过去分词: girthed 现在分词: girthing 第三人称单数: girths');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('asset', '[\'æset]', 'n.资产；优点；有用的东西', '1. It was too early to conclude if there was an asset price bubble. 在现阶段下结论,认为出现资产价格泡沫属言之尚早。 2. Private consumption improved and asset prices rose sharply. 私人消费有所改善,资产价格更大幅攀升。 3. The tennis player\'s speed is his great asset. 那个网球运动员动作迅速，这是他的一大优势。 4. A sense of humour is a great asset for a person. 幽默感是一个人的宝贵资产。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('crest', '[krest]', 'n.浪尖；冠；饰章；顶部 v.到达顶部；到达最高点', '1. A surfboard fin sliced the crest of a wave. 冲浪板尾部划破浪尖。 2. The hissing crest of the huge wave bites at your shoulder. 发出啸声的巨浪的浪峰劈头盖脑地向你袭来。 3. The rooster bristled his crest. 公鸡竖起了鸡冠。 4. The redness of her crest makes maples loss color. 她顶冠的艳红让枫叶失去了颜色。 5. As we crested the hill, we saw the castle. 我们登上了山顶,看见了城堡。', '过去式: crested 过去分词: crested 现在分词: cresting 第三人称单数: crests');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('revue', '[rɪ\'vjuː]', 'n.时事讽刺剧', '1. The revue was a showcase for new talent. 这出时事讽刺剧是新秀才能的一次显示。 2. An elaborate theatrical revue consists of music, dance, and skits. 一出精心制作的时事讽刺剧由音乐、舞蹈和讽刺文构成。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sustenance', '[\'sʌstənəns]', 'n.维持生计；营养；食物', '1. He gave money for the sustenance of a poor family. 他把钱给一穷人家维持生活。 2. There isn\'t much sustenance in a cucumber. 黄瓜没有很多营养。 3. She is weak from lack of sustenance. 她因缺乏营养而虚弱。 4. He has gone for a week without sustenance. 他已经一星期未吃食物了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('jeopardy', '[\'dʒepərdi]', 'n.危险', '1. For a moment his life was in jeopardy. 他的生命一度陷入危险中。 2. The security of this entire universe is in jeopardy! 整个宇宙安全都处在危险当中。', '名词复数: jeopardies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('full-bodied', '[fʊl \'bɑːdɪd]', 'adj.醇厚的；魁梧的；浓郁的', '1. Chez Marie has a rich artistic environment and is full of romantic twists. 玛利亚西餐厅具有浓郁的艺术氛围和浪漫的情调。 2. The overall sound remains pure Grado, warm harmonic color, full bodied vocals, excellent dynamics and an ultra smooth top end. 总的声音仍然是纯粹的歌德，温暖和谐的色彩，浓郁的嗓音，出色的动态和超平滑的高端。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exuberance', '[ɪɡ\'zjuːbərəns]', 'n.茂盛；充沛；丰富', '1. The exuberance of nature run riot is a welcome antidote to many of the views on the road from Shanghai, of nature subjugated to economic development. 从上海过来时，一路上有很多绿树缠绕的茂盛景象，这在经济发展正一步步吞噬自然景观的今天实在难得。 2. Jane\'s extraordinary exuberance has produced fabulous results! 简异常充沛的精力创造出了惊人的成效！ 3. What makes the whole thing so marvelous is the exuberance of the participants. 使这一切如此奇妙的是参加者充沛的精力。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impassive', '[ɪm\'pæsɪv]', 'adj.无感情的；无表情的；冷漠的；平静的', '1. He listened with an impassive face. 他面无表情地听着。 2. He was content to stand by as an impassive spectator. 他满足于站在旁边做一个冷漠的旁观者。 3. He still wore the same impassive and preoccupied air. 他仍旧有那种心情缭乱而力自镇静的神气。', '副词: impassively 名词: impassiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spiritual', '[\'spɪrɪtʃuəl]', 'adj.精神的；心灵的；与上帝有关的 n.(尤指美国南部黑人的)圣歌', '1. Many young people could not resist the spiritual pollution. 很多年轻人不能抵制精神污染。 2. I care more about the spiritual life than the substantial life. 和物质生活相比，我更注重精神生活。 3. The monks were arraigned for not teaching things spiritual. 修道士们因不讲授有关心灵的道理而受到指责。', '副词: spiritually 名词: spiritualness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('agitated', '[\'ædʒɪteɪtɪd]', 'adj.激动不安的；焦虑的 动词agitate的过去式和过去分词.', '1. Instead of calming down, she became more and more agitated. 她不但没有平静下来，反而越来越激动。 2. He was agitated about his wife\'s health. 他为他妻子的健康感到不安。 3. He became quite agitated when he was asked about his criminal past. 当问到他过去的犯罪历史时，他变得十分焦虑不安。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('neutron', '[\'nuːtrɑːn]', 'n.中子', '1. Proton and neutron form a charge doublet. 质子和中子构成电荷双重态。 2. Neutron has no charge, either positive or negative. 中子不带电荷,既不带正电荷,也不带负电荷。 3. Let us calculate first how much energy is released when a free neutron decays. 让我们首先来计算一个自由中子的衰变会释放出多少能量。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('hull', '[hʌl]', 'n.外壳；皮；船身；船体；[植]花萼 v.去壳', '1. Some fruits and seeds have hulls. 有些水果和种子有外壳。 2. I\'m hav bad luck,even sliped by a banana hull. 我真倒霉，踩在香蕉皮上滑倒了。 3. An experimental study on the soybean hull modification and the process of treating water with the modified soybean hull was carried out. 对大豆皮的改性方法及其处理水的过程进行了实验研究。 4. The ship\'s hull scraped along the side of the dock. 船行时船身擦着码头的边。 5. Would you help me hull these berries? 你能帮我将这些莓子的蒂梗除去吗?', '名词: huller 过去式: hulled 过去分词: hulled 现在分词: hulling 第三人称单数: hulls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('erstwhile', '[\'ɜːrstwaɪl]', 'adj.从前的；往昔的', '1. His erstwhile friends turned against him. 他先前的朋友转而与他作对。 2. This erstwhile schoolmaster had discovered a way of keeping us quiet in the evenings. 这位往昔的老师找到了一种让我们晚上安静下来的方法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sadistic', '[sə\'dɪstɪk]', 'adj.(性)虐待的；虐待狂的；残酷成性的', '1. Do sadistic films deprave the viewers? 有关性虐待的电影能使观众堕落吗? 2. In prison there are sadistic wardens. 在监狱有虐待狂督导员。 3. He took sadistic pleasure in taunting the boy. 嘲讽这孩子让他感到施虐的快感。 4. The guards were sadistic beasts and their leader was the devil incarnate. 那些警卫都是残暴的野兽，他们的首领是个魔鬼的化身。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('retrieve', '[rɪ\'triːv]', 'vt.恢复；挽回；取回 vi.找回猎物 n.恢复；取回；救出险球', '1. The company is fighting to retrieve its market share. 这个公司正在为恢复其市场份额(占有率)而奋斗。 2. She tried to retrieve the situation by making profuse apologies. 她不住的道歉,力图挽回局面。 3. I should like to retrieve my umbrella which I left in the car. 我想取回我留在车上忘记带走的雨伞。 4. The dog is trained to retrieve. 这狗受过训能找到并带回猎物。 5. This is a loss beyond retrieve. 这是无可挽回的损失。', '形容词: retrievable 副词: retrievably 名词: retrievability 过去式: retrieved 过去分词: retrieved 现在分词: retrieving 第三人称单数: retrieves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('polar', '[\'poʊlər]', 'adj.两极的；对立的 n.极线；极性', '1. Are there any animals in the polar circles? 南极圈和北极圈内有动物存在吗？ 2. The two systems of government are polar opposites. 这两种政体正好相反。 3. The two systems of government are polar opposites. 这两种政体正好相反。 4. Love and hatred are polar feelings. 爱与恨是完全相反的感情。 5. A molecule where the centers do not coincide is called a polar molecule. 正负电荷中心不重合的分子称为极性分子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('chunk', '[tʃʌŋk]', 'n.矮胖的人或物；厚块（片）；相当大的量 vt.（高尔夫球）没击中 vi.发出猛冲的声音', '1. A chunk of the cliff had cracked off in a storm. 山崖上的一块石头在暴风雨中崩塌下来。 2. My mother bought a chunk of meat. 我妈妈买了一大块肉。 3. Sawing another chunk from the log of determination. 我的决心又受到很大的打击。 4. The car repairs took quite a chunk out of her salary. 修理汽车的费用占掉她工资相当大的一笔钱。 5. I listen to the electronic printer chunk along. 我听着电子打字机啪嗒地响个不停。', '过去式: chunked 过去分词: chunked 现在分词: chunking 第三人称单数: chunks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('proceeds', '[\'proʊsiːdz]', 'n.收益 动词proceed的第三人称一般现在时形式.', '1. They donated the proceeds to the local charities. 他们把收益捐给了当地的慈善机构。 2. The proceeds have shored up the balance sheet but the trading picture is grim. 收益减轻了资产负债，但贸易局面是不容乐观的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arabesque', '[ˌærə\'besk]', 'n.蔓藤图饰；阿拉贝斯克舞姿', '1. I like carpets with arabesque patterns. 我喜欢带有阿拉伯式花饰的地毯。 2. That spin in figure skating is performed in an arabesque position. 那是花样滑冰中的一种自旋运动，其舞姿是复杂的阿拉贝斯克图案。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('nostrum', '[\'nɑːstrəm]', 'n.秘方；骗人特效药；万灵药；妙策', '1. He told the patient that he had a nostrum. 他告诉病人他有秘方。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('distant', '[\'dɪstənt]', 'adj.疏远的；遥远的；远房的；陌生的；远行的', '1. His stepson is still very distant towards him. 他的继子对他仍然很疏远。 2. Her manner was cold and distant. 她的态度冷漠而疏远。 3. It snows all the year round in that distant little village. 在那个遥远的小村落里整年下雪。 4. This palmer came from a very distant place. 这个朝圣者来自非常远的地方。', '副词: distantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cram', '[kræm]', 'v.塞满；猛吃；仓促备考 n.仓促备考；挤成一堆的人群 Cram. n.克拉姆(姓氏或男子名)', '1. This box is crammed with Christmas gifts. 这个盒子里塞满了圣诞礼物。 2. He crammed as much candy into his pockets as they would hold. 他把口袋都塞满了糖果。 3. I managed to cram down a few mouthfuls of food. 我好歹狼吞虎咽地吃了几口东西。 4. The teacher tried to cram his pupils. 老师试图用填鸭式教学把知识灌输给学生。 5. My son go to cram school every evening. 我的儿子每晚都去上补习班。 6. Cram ran a fine race to take the gold medal. 克拉姆在赛跑中成绩突出夺得金牌。', '名词: crammer 过去式: crammed 过去分词: crammed 现在分词: cramming 第三人称单数: crams');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bacteria', '[bæk\'tɪriə]', 'n.(复数)细菌', '1. Many diseases are caused by bacteria. 许多疾病是由细菌引起的。 2. Bacteria are too small to see with the naked eye. 细菌太小，肉眼看不见。 3. It is possible to multiply bacteria and other living organisms in the laboratory. 在实验室能够繁殖细菌和其他生物。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('despondent', '[dɪ\'spɑːndənt]', 'adj.失望的；沮丧的；没有精神的', '1. Each time I get despondent,my father will cheer me up. 我每次失望时，父亲总给我打气。 2. He is despondent over his illness. 他对自己的病情感到灰心沮丧。', '副词: despondently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('raconteur', '[ˌrækɑːn\'tɜːr]', 'n.健谈者；善于讲故事的人', '1. Charles Dickens was a raconteur par excellence. 查尔斯·狄更斯是一位非常卓越的健谈者。 2. He used his mental capacity to act as raconteur and juicy gossipmonger. 于是他就扮演一个健谈风趣的大白呼。 3. His grandfather was a fine raconteur, dredging up quite effortlessly, and with a great wealth of detail, scenes and incidents from his early life. 他的祖父是位很会讲故事的人,不费吹灰之力,就把他年轻时事情、场景,极详细地描绘出来。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cyclone', '[\'saɪkloʊn]', 'n.旋风；飓风；气旋；旋风分离器', '1. The cyclone destroyed dozens of houses. 旋风毁坏了好几十户人家。 2. Once the ore is crushed inside the mine, it is transferred to a series of cyclone separators. 只要矿石是在矿区内粉碎，矿石就需要传输到一系列的旋风分离器上。 3. The cyclone has resulted in many thousands of deaths. 飓风已经造成了成千上万的人死亡。 4. Port Hedland experiences a cyclone at least every two years. 海德兰德港至少每两年经受一次飓风。', '形容词: cyclonic');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('thesis', '[\'θiːsɪs]', 'n.毕业论文；论文；论题；论点；命题', '1. Charles is writing his graduation thesis now. 查尔斯正在写毕业论文。 2. He has already started his thesis. 他已经开始写毕业论文了。 3. He wrote his doctoral thesis on electromagnetism. 他写有关电磁的博士论文。 4. He\'s been pegging away at his thesis for months. 他写论文已经忙了几个月了。', '名词复数: theses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stocky', '[\'stɑːki]', 'adj.矮胖的；健壮结实的', '1. Beethoven is a short , stocky man, untidily dressed , with dark and piercing eyes. 贝多芬身材粗短结实，不修边幅，有一双黑色敏锐的眼睛。 2. In the stern is a stocky man dressed in a simple white tunic. 船尾上站着一名健壮的身着朴素白衫的男子。', '副词: stockily 比较级: stockier 最高级: stockiest 名词: stockiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('table', '[\'teɪbl]', 'n.桌子；台子；餐桌；一桌人；表格；目录；（竞赛的）排名榜 vt.搁置；将 ... 放于桌上；提交讨论；列入表中 adj.桌子的', '1. He moved the table over to the center of the room. 他把桌子移到房间中心。 2. Mother told me to lay the table for breakfast. 母亲让我摆好桌子准备吃早饭。 3. We prefer a table besides the window in non-smoking. 我们要不抽烟区靠窗的台子。 4. She spread a cloth on the table. 她用一块布铺在餐桌上。 5. They voted to table the proposal until the following meeting. 他们投票决定把这项建议留到下次会议讨论。', '过去式: tabled 过去分词: tabled 现在分词: tabling 第三人称单数: tables');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gong', '[ɡɑːŋ]', 'n.锣；<俚> 奖章', '1. At six the gong sounded for supper. 6点时，吃晚饭的锣声响了。 2. Then I want to learn how to strike the gong. 那我就学锣吧。 3. In the mid-day the gong sounds at the palace gate. 中午,锣声在庙殿门前敲起。', '过去式: gonged 过去分词: gonged 现在分词: gonging 第三人称单数: gongs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reprieve', '[rɪ\'priːv]', 'v.暂缓处刑；暂时缓解 n.缓刑；缓刑令', '1. The tree that was due to be cut down has been reprieved for six months. 原定砍伐的那棵树已经推迟六个月再砍。 2. The disamed rebels are given a reprieve. 被缴械的叛乱份子获缓刑。 3. He was saved from the gallows by a lastminute reprieve. 最后一刻的缓刑令把他从绞架上解救了下来。', '形容词: reprievable 过去式: reprieved 过去分词: reprieved 现在分词: reprieving 第三人称单数: reprieves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('transmit', '[træns\'mɪt]', 'vt.传达；传染；传送；代代相传 vi.(以无线电或有线电的方式)发送信号', '1. Gypsies frequently transmit recipes orally within the family. 吉普赛人经常以口头形式把秘方世代相传。 2. Please transmit my best regards to your lovely wife. 请转达我向您娇妻的致意。 3. This infection is transmitted by mosquitoes. 这种传染病是由蚊子传染的。 4. The tension soon transmitted itself to all the members of the crowd. 这种紧张情绪很快感染了人群中所有的人。', '形容词: transmittable 过去式: transmitted 过去分词: transmitted 现在分词: transmitting 第三人称单数: transmits');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('arbitrary', '[\'ɑːrbətreri]', 'adj.任意的；专制的；武断的；霸道的', '1. My choice was quite arbitrary. 我的选择相当随意。 2. I\'m not used to your arbitrary standards. 我不习惯你们那些随心所欲的标准。 3. Dictators are arbitrary rulers. 独裁者即独断专横的统治者。 4. This is an arbitrary decision. 这是个武断的决定。', '副词: arbitrarily 名词: arbitrariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('allergic', '[ə\'lɜːrdʒɪk]', 'adj.过敏的；反感的', '1. Ben is allergic to pollen. 班对花粉过敏。 2. I like cats but unfortunately I\'m allergic to them. 我很喜欢猫,但遗憾的是我对猫过敏。 3. Nuts can trigger off a violent allergic reaction. 坚果可以引起严重的过敏反应。 4. He is allergic to having his picture taken. 他讨厌别人给他照相。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mandate', '[\'mændeɪt]', 'n.命令；指令；要求；授权 v.把(某一地区)置于委任管理下', '1. The government gave the police a mandate to reduce crime. 政府命令警方进一步打击犯罪活动。 2. We have a mandate from the union membership to proceed with strike action. 我们获得工会会员同意，继续罢工。 3. You should follow the doctor\'s mandate. 你该听从医师的要求。 4. Our election victory has given us a mandate to reform the economy. 我们在选举中获胜,这就使我们有权进行经济改革。 5. Britain was mandated to govern the former colony of German East Africa. 英国授权代管德国在东非的前殖民地。', '名词: mandator 过去式: mandated 过去分词: mandated 现在分词: mandating 第三人称单数: mandates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('absolve', '[əb\'zɑːlv]', 'vt.宣告...无罪；赦免', '1. The police absolved the suspect. 警方释放了嫌疑犯。 2. He cannot entirely absolve himself of the charge. 他不能完全开脱掉这一指责。 3. I absolve you from your vows. 我解除你的誓约。 4. The captain is absolved from all blame and responsibility for the shipwreck. 那位船长被免除了因船只失事而遭致的非难和罪责。', '形容词: absolvable 名词: absolver 过去式: absolved 过去分词: absolved 现在分词: absolving 第三人称单数: absolves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('descent', '[dɪ\'sent]', 'n.下降；下坡；家世；血统；侵袭；衰落；继承', '1. There was a descent of temperature after rain. 雨后气温下降了。 2. The trail zigzagged down the abrupt descent of the canyon. 这条小路弯弯曲曲的顺着峡谷那陡削的下坡蜿蜒而下。 3. He traces his descent back to an old norman family. 他追踪自己的世系上溯至一个古老的诺曼家族。 4. Many Americans are of English descent. 许多美国人的祖籍是英国。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exhume', '[ɪɡ\'zuːm]', 'v.掘出(尸体以检验)；发掘', '1. When the police exhumed the corpse they discovered traces of poison in it. 警方掘出尸体，发现有中毒的痕迹。 2. He\'s going to ask authorization to exhume the body and have it put somewhere else. 他去请求许可将死者的尸体掘出，移到别的地方。 3. They exhumed for days, but did not find anything. 他们发掘了几天，但什么都没有找到。', '名词: exhumation 过去式: exhumed 过去分词: exhumed 现在分词: exhuming 第三人称单数: exhumes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bathetic', '[bə\'θetɪk]', 'adj.平庸陈腐的；〈语〉顿降的；假作悲伤的', '1. a bathetic novel; maudlin expressons of sympathy; mushy effusiveness; a schmaltzy song; sentimental soap operas; slushy poetry. 矫情的小说；伤感的表示同情；多愁善感的唠叨；伤感的歌曲；多愁善感的肥皂剧；多愁善感的诗歌。 2. 1. a bathetic novel; maudlin expressons of sympathy; mushy effusiveness; a schmaltzy song; sentimental soap operas; slushy poetry. 矫情的小说；伤感的表示同情；多愁善感的唠叨；伤感的歌曲；多愁善感的肥皂剧；多愁善感的诗歌。 3. 3. a bathetic novel; maudlin expressons of sympathy; mushy effusiveness; a schmaltzy song; sentimental soap operas; slushy poetry. 矫情的小说；伤感的表示同情；多愁善感的唠叨；伤感的歌曲；多愁善感的肥皂剧；多愁善感的诗歌。收藏指正 4. a bathetic funeral scene 一个过于夸张哀悼的葬礼场面', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conquer', '[\'kɑːŋkər]', 'vt.征服；克服；战胜 vi.得胜', '1. Conquer the desire, or they will conquer you. 你不战胜欲念，欲念就会征服你。 2. If we want light, we must conquer darkness. 我们要光明，就得征服黑暗。 3. No difficulties can shake their resolve to conquer nature. 环境再艰苦也动摇不了他们征服自然的决心。 4. The only way to conquer a fear is to face it. 克服恐惧的唯一方法是正视恐惧。 5. We have no choice but to conquer. 我们别无选择，只有获胜。', '形容词: conquerable 名词: conqueror 过去式: conquered 过去分词: conquered 现在分词: conquering 第三人称单数: conquers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('intumescence', '[ˌɪntjuː\'mesəns]', 'n.肿大；肿胀；肿块', '1. At the frozen storage of 90 days, some of collagen micro-fibrils in stoma showed intumescence. 冷冻90d时,基质中部分胶原微纤维肿胀; 2. The main fertilizing period was before flower bud differentiation and at alabastrum intumescence stage. 利用温度控制、水分控制和植物生长调节剂对火百合作矮化处理； 3. Approximate solutions were found for the rate of growth of a bubble in the process of intumescence. 得到了膨胀过程中气泡生长速率的近似解。 4. There are lymph gland inflammation,malignant lymphoma and all kinds of metastatio cancer,which often cause intumescence of shallow lymph gland. 淋巴结炎、恶性淋巴瘤,各种转移癌常引起颈部浅表淋巴结肿大。', '形容词: intumescent');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('poisonous', '[\'pɔɪzənəs]', 'adj.有毒的；恶意的', '1. Some mushrooms are poisonous. 有些蘑菇有毒。 2. Some snakes have poisonous fangs. 有些蛇长有毒牙。 3. She gave him a poisonous look. 她恶狠狠地瞪了他一眼。 4. He said some poisonous things to me. 他对我说了一些恶毒的事。', '副词: poisonously 名词: poisonousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('homage', '[\'hɑːmɪdʒ]', 'n.敬意；效忠', '1. Everyone pays homage to the soldiers. 每个人都对军人表示敬意。 2. But they freely concede that they will be there at the end as an act of homage. 但他们不得不勉强的承认他们会满怀敬意的守到最后时刻。 3. The Imperial Guards presented homage to the king. 皇家警卫队向国王宣誓效忠。 4. Investiture is distinct from homage. 授封和效忠不同。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('provocation', '[ˌprɑːvə\'keɪʃn]', 'n.激怒；挑衅；激怒的原因', '1. He flares up at the slightest provocation. 稍一激他，他就大发脾气。 2. She sometimes angers with little or no provocation. 她有时无缘无故就生气。 3. They did not react to this provocation. 他们对这一挑衅未作反应。 4. He hit her after repeated provocations. 她一次次招惹他，他就打了她。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('closed-minded', '[\'kloʊzdˌmɑɪndɪd]', 'adj.保守的', '1. Uncharacteristically, Andrew appeared to have a closed mind. 安德鲁一反常态，显得成见很深。 2. The close minded have baseless claims that have kept us for too long. 有密切的想法毫无根据地声称已经让我们的时间太长。 3. He has a closed mind. 他思想闭塞僵化。 4. The manager has made her decision; she now has a closed mind on the subject and refuses to discuss it further. 经理已经作出了决定，现在她对这题目避而不谈，拒绝作进一步的讨论。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adjunct', '[\'ædʒʌŋkt]', 'n.附属物；附件；修饰语', '1. Are social mission and business activities being mixed in an existing organization as an adjunct to existing profit or social mission goals? 社会使命和商务活动时候是作为现有利润或社会使命目标的附属物而溶入到现有组织的？ 2. When disease is seen as an invader, forced upon the integrity of the self for no reason, then the individual seems powerless and the conscious mind an adjunct. 当疾病被视作侵略者，无缘无故地强加在自我的完整性上时，个人就变得软弱无力，意识头脑也成了附属物。 3. The word is an adjunct of that verb. 这个词是那个动词的修饰语。', '形容词: adjunctive 名词: adjunction');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('watershed', '[\'wɔːtərʃed]', 'n.流域；分水岭；转折点', '1. Zhifanggou Watershed of Ansai is taken as a case study in this paper. 文章试以安塞纸坊沟流域为例，通过航片解译分析流域土地利用现状。 2. The Great Dividing Range is Australia\'s main watershed. 大分水岭是澳大利亚的主要分水岭。 3. The mountain is the watershed of the two rivers of the Yangtze and Qiantang. 黄山是长江和钱塘江两大水系的分水岭。 4. Leaving her first job was a watershed in her life. 辞去她的第一份工作是她生活中的一个转折点。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drain', '[dreɪn]', 'v.排出；排干；喝光；耗尽 n.下水道；消耗', '1. We must dig a trench to drain away the water. 我们必须挖一条沟排水。 2. They drain the swamp and turn it into fertile land. 他们排干沼泽地的水,将它变成了肥沃的土地。 3. They all rose and drained their glasses. 他们都站了起来,一饮而尽。 4. She felt drained of energy. 她感到精疲力竭。 5. We have to call a plumber to unblock the drain. 我们得叫管工来通一通下水道。', '形容词: drainable 名词: drainer 过去式: drained 过去分词: drained 现在分词: draining 第三人称单数: drains');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exaltation', '[ˌeɡzɔːl\'teɪʃn]', 'n.(成功带来的)得意；高兴；抬高或赞美', '1. He was obviously in a state of exaltation. 十分明显，他又得意忘形了。 2. The hallmark of the industrial age has been its exaltation of mechanical design. 工业时代的印记是其机械设计的得意之作。 3. The news filled us with exaltation. 这消息使我们欣喜万分。 4. There was a glow, an exaltation in her eyes. 这时她情绪高涨，眼睛发亮。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pedant', '[\'pednt]', 'n.学究；卖弄学问者；空谈家；墨守成规的人', '1. You are a pedant, my dear fellow. 你是个只会夸夸其谈的学究，亲爱的伙计。 2. The old pedant used so many archaisms that half of what he said was unintelligible. 老学究满口之乎者也，教人半懂不懂。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('festive', '[\'festɪv]', 'adj.欢乐的；节日的；喜庆的', '1. Christmas is often called the festive season. 圣诞节常被称作欢乐的时节。 2. The atmosphere is really festive and friendly. 气氛真是欢乐而友好。 3. The hall looks more festive with all that greenery in pots. 花盆里的绿叶使大厅显得节日气氛更浓。 4. The whole town is in a festive mood. 全镇沉浸在节日的气氛之中。', '副词: festively 名词: festiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('droll', '[droʊl]', 'adj.好笑的；逗趣的；滑稽的 n.离奇古怪；滑稽 adv.离奇古怪地；滑稽地 v.<古>开玩笑', '1. The way of his talking is very droll. 他讲话的方式很可笑。 2. He screwed up his mouth in a droll fashion. 他扭着嘴装出一副可笑的样子。 3. His style is at times droll, satirical, yet sympathetic. 他的写作风格时而滑稽，时而讽刺，有时又饱含同情。 4. His droll expression seemed to say that he had found the secret of contentment. 他那种滑稽可笑的表情似乎在说明他已经发现了知足常乐的秘诀。 5. So he thinks I\'m going to apologize? How droll! 他还以为我要去道歉? 真滑稽!', '副词: drolly 比较级: droller 最高级: drollest 名词: drollness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('effrontery', '[ɪ\'frʌntəri]', 'n.厚颜无耻', '1. He had the effrontery to accuse me of lying! 他竟厚颜无耻地指责我撒谎！ 2. I\'ll see if you have the effrontery to face her. 我倒要看你怎么有脸面对她。', '名词复数: effronteries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('burial', '[\'beriəl]', 'n.埋葬；葬礼；坟墓', '1. His body was brought back to England for burial. 他的遗体已运回英国埋葬。 2. The burial will be on Wednesday. 遗体将在周三被埋葬。 3. He was given an honorable burial. 他的葬礼很体面。 4. The body was placed in bier before burial. 在举行葬礼以前尸体被放在棺材里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('owl', '[aʊl]', 'n.猫头鹰', '1. The owl swooped down on the mouse. 那只猫头鹰向着老鼠猛扑下来。 2. The owl hunts while you repose in bed. 你躺在床上安然入睡时，猫头鹰却要去觅食。 3. The hooting of an owl broke the silence now and again, giving Linda the creeps. 猫头鹰的叫声不时打破寂静，使琳达心惊肉跳。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('phlegmatic', '[fleɡ\'mætɪk]', 'adj.冷静的；冷淡的；冷漠的', '1. Commuting in the rush-hour requires a phlegmatic temperament. 在上下班交通高峰期间乘坐通勤车要有安之若素的心境。 2. No other city in India bears such colossal inconveniences with such phlegmatic grace. 在印度没有哪个城市承受着如此巨大的不便和如此冷淡的宽容。 3. He has a light, phlegmatic smile. 他的脸上挂着淡淡的、冷漠的微笑。 4. The British character is often said to be phlegmatic. 英国人的性格常说成是冷漠的。', '副词: phlegmatically 异体字: phlegmatical');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('locus', '[\'loʊkəs]', 'n.场所；所在地；【数】轨迹，矢量图', '1. The destination or locus of multinational investment has changed. 跨国公司投资的流向地区起了变化。 2. The garden was also an artifact and a locus for material culture and social competition. 亭园也是人为艺品,以及物质文化和社会竞争的场所。 3. Government is the locus of power. 政府是权力的中心。', '名词复数: loci');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('school', '[skuːl]', 'n.学校；学派；院系；鱼群 v.教育；训练；成群地游', '1. She studies in a high school. 她在一所中学学习。 2. Soon, the whole school knew about her win. 不久，全校师生都知道她获胜了。 3. This is the argument of the school. 这就是流行学派的论据。 4. The Prague School has three important points. 布拉格学派有三个至为重要的观点。 5. She should be schooled with her peers. 她应当与她的同龄人一起接受教育。', '过去式: schooled 过去分词: schooled 现在分词: schooling 第三人称单数: schools');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('carpentry', '[\'kɑːrpəntri]', 'n.木工手艺；木工作品', '1. He\'s an adept in carpentry. 他是木工行家。 2. I do not reckon I am any good at carpentry. 我看我对木工一点儿都不在行。 3. His carpentry is really exquisite. He\'s another Lu Ban. 他的木工作品图案精美,不愧为鲁班再世。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('enrage', '[ɪn\'reɪdʒ]', 'vt.激怒；使暴怒', '1. Death Wish and Enrage effects no longer stack. 死愿和激怒的效果不叠加了。 2. He started another matter to enrage me, but I didn\'t care. 他又提出另一问题，想以此激怒我，可我并没在意。', '名词: enragement 过去式: enraged 过去分词: enraged 现在分词: enraging 第三人称单数: enrages');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('economical', '[ˌiːkə\'nɑːmɪkl]', 'adj.节俭的；经济的；合算的', '1. She is an economical housekeeper and feeds her family cheaply. 她是一个节俭的家庭主妇，她全家的花销不大。 2. We are advocate economical life. 我们提倡俭朴的生活。 3. This is not an economical method of heating. 这不是一种经济的取暖方式。 4. She writes novels with economical style. 她以简练的风格写小说。', '副词: economically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('drivel', '[\'drɪvl]', 'n.傻话；胡言；口水 v.胡说；胡写；流口水', '1. I have never heard of such silly drivel in all my life. 我一生中从未听到过这样的傻话。 2. You don\'t believe the drivel you read in the paper. 你不会相信报纸上胡言乱语的。 3. He was drivelling on about the meaning of life. 他喋喋不休地胡诌什麽人生的意义。', '名词: driveler 过去式: driveled/drivelled 过去分词: driveled/drivelled 现在分词: driveling/drivelling 第三人称单数: drivels/drivels');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unscrupulous', '[ʌn\'skruːpjələs]', 'adj.肆无忌惮的；不道德的', '1. You always take part with the unscrupulous man. 你总是袒护那些肆无忌惮的人。 2. He once did me such an unscrupulous shot in the eye. 他曾经如此肆无忌惮地恶意中伤过我。 3. He was utterly unscrupulous in his competition with rival firms. 他与对立公司竞争完全不讲道德。', '副词: unscrupulously 名词: unscrupulousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spruce', '[spruːs]', 'n.赤松；云杉；虎尾枞属的植物 adj.干净的；外表俏丽的 vi.打扮 vt.打扮自己', '1. The orchard is surrounded by spruce forest. 该种子园四周有云杉林环绕。 2. Spruce and pine are evergreen trees. 云杉和松树都是常绿树木。 3. It\'s the ideal time to spruce up for the coming season. 这是为即将到来的一季精心打扮的时刻。', '副词: sprucely 比较级: sprucer 最高级: sprucest 名词: spruceness 过去式: spruced 过去分词: spruced 现在分词: sprucing 第三人称单数: spruces');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('interlocutor', '[ˌɪntər\'lɑːkjətər]', 'n.对话者；谈话者；(代表某人或组织)参加交谈的人', '1. Warren will be the evening\'s sole interlocutor. 沃伦会成为当晚唯一的对话者。 2. He was able to act as interpreter and interlocutor for our group. 他能够作为代表我们组织的口译者和谈话者。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('articulate', '[ɑːr\'tɪkjuleɪt]', 'adj.发音清晰的；善于表达的；有关节的 v.清楚地讲话；发音；以关节连接', '1. Articulate speech is essential for a teacher. 对教师来说,口齿清楚是必不可少的。 2. I\'m a little deaf, please articulate your words carefully. 我有些耳聋，请把话仔细地说清楚。 3. She\'s unusually articulate for a ten-year-old. 作为一个十岁的孩子来说，她的表达力是非常强的。 4. Young people are articulate about the skills they need for everyday life. 年轻人善于表达他们应付日常生活所需的技能。 5. She was too frightened to articulate. 她吓得连话也说不清。', '副词: articulately 名词: articulateness 过去式: articulated 过去分词: articulated 现在分词: articulating 第三人称单数: articulates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('awning', '[\'ɔːnɪŋ]', 'n.雨篷；遮阳篷；甲板上的天蓬', '1. I bought an awning to go over the doorway. 我买了一张可以放在门上的帆布遮篷。 2. My girlfriend has a blue awning on her house. 我的女友的房子上有一顶蓝色的雨篷。 3. There are thousands of awnings on the sea beach. 沙滩上有许多遮阳篷。 4. When we got there, we rolled out the awning and unfolded a small table. 到了那边,我们放下遮阳篷,打开一张小桌子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('spongy', '[\'spʌndʒi]', 'adj.像海绵的；不坚实的', '1. The grass is spongy after the rain. 雨后的草地柔软湿润。 2. Spongy degeneration was apparent with brain biopsy. 脑病理检查表现为海绵状变性。 3. The pulp of this watermelon is too spongy. 这西瓜瓤儿太肉了。 4. There grows some spongy mosson the stone. 石头上长着一些柔软的苔藓。', '比较级: spongier 最高级: spongiest 名词: sponginess');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vegetate', '[\'vedʒəteɪt]', 'v.生长；无所事事；使像植物般生长', '1. This kind of fruit vegetates in many areas. 这种水果香甜可口，生长在世界上许多地方。 2. The vegetables in the garden vegetate vigorously. 园子里的植物在茁壮成长。', '过去式: vegetated 过去分词: vegetated 现在分词: vegetating 第三人称单数: vegetates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('respiration', '[ˌrespə\'reɪʃn]', 'n.呼吸；【生】一次呼吸，呼吸量；植物呼吸作用', '1. He was using his accessory muscles of respiration. 他在用呼吸辅助肌进行呼吸。 2. Respiration is difficult at great heights. 在很高的高原上呼吸很困难。', '形容词: respirational');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('yank', '[jæŋk]', 'v.猛拉；猛拔', '1. You can yank on the rope as a signal. 你可以猛拉一下绳子作为信号。', '过去式: yanked 过去分词: yanked 现在分词: yanking 第三人称单数: yanks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adopt', '[ə\'dɑːpt]', 'v.采用；收养；接受', '1. They adopt new techniques in raising sheep. 他们采用新的养羊技术。 2. The schools must adopt new methods of teaching foreign languages. 学校应采用新的外语教学法。 3. She was left an orphan and a poor peasant woman adopted her. 她成了孤儿，一位贫农妇女收养了她。 4. To adopt the fruits of sin was to give countenance to it. 收养罪恶的果实就等于纵容罪恶。', '形容词: adoptable 名词: adopter 过去式: adopted 过去分词: adopted 现在分词: adopting 第三人称单数: adopts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cursive', '[\'kɜːrsɪv]', 'adj.草书的；草书体的 n.草书；草书原稿', '1. I can\'t remember how to write a capital Z in cursive. 我已经记不得如何去写草书的大写字母Z. 2. A small cursive script developed from uncial. 小写草书体由安色尔字体发展而来。 3. Chinese cursive writing is very difficult to read. 中文的草书体很难读。 4. The third \"n\" looks like an cursive, but this one is not a real cursive. 第三个“n”看起来像草书，但它实际上还不是一个真正的草写体。', '副词: cursively 名词: cursiveness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('impulse', '[\'ɪmpʌls]', 'n.冲动；心血来潮；神经冲动；[物]冲量；[电]脉冲 vt.推动', '1. He bought the house on an impulse. 他凭一时冲动买下了这所房子。 2. We were seized by a sudden impulse to run. 我们身不由己突然想跑。 3. On impulse, I picked up the phone and rang my sister in Australia. 我一时心血来潮，拿起话筒就给在澳大利亚的妹妹打了个电话。 4. He had a sudden impulse to stand up and sing. 他突然心血来潮，想站起来歌唱。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resurge', '[rɪ\'sɜːdʒ]', 'vi.再起；复活；复生', '1. If we met in heaven, would you help me resurge? 假如我们在天堂相见，你会帮我再次重生吗？ 2. We must resurge ecological culture in community and combine it with envi... 为此,在新的时代条件下,我们应重振社区生态文化,将其整合到现代农村环境保护之中。 3. In such joyful moment that everything resurge and thrives, our master Buddha exhibits his fugacious advent. 在这样一个所有生命复苏，乃至满心欢喜的时刻，我们本师佛陀，给我们示现无常的到来。 4. The Renaissance again discovered the world, the man and brought about the resurge of politics. 文艺复兴重新发现了世界,也重新发现了人,并带来了政治学的复兴。', '过去式: resurged 过去分词: resurged 现在分词: resurging 第三人称单数: resurges');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('stab', '[stæb]', 'v.刺；戳；刺伤 n.刺；戳；刺痛；尝试', '1. Good friends stab you in the front. 当面刺痛你的是你的好朋友。 2. He stabbed at the earth with his stick. 他拿手杖戳著地。 3. She stabbed at the air with her finger to emphasize what she was saying. 她手指一戳一戳的，强调她说的话。 4. He stabbed the meat with his fork/stabbed his fork into the meat. 他用叉子叉肉。 5. The hunter made a stab at the wolf, but missed. 猎人向狼刺去，但没有刺中。', '名词: stabber 过去式: stabbed 过去分词: stabbed 现在分词: stabbing 第三人称单数: stabs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('dally', '[\'dæli]', 'v.浪费时间；戏耍；玩弄；赋闲；调情', '1. Come on and don\'t dally. 好了，别浪费时间了。 2. She dallies over her work and rarely finishes it. 她工作吊儿郎当，很少能把工作做完。 3. She merely dallied with his affections. 她只是戏弄他。 4. They dallied with the proposal for days, but finally refused it. 他们把提案拖延了好些天，最后还是拒绝了。', '副词: dallyingly 名词: dallier 过去式: dallied 过去分词: dallied 现在分词: dallying 第三人称单数: dallies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cranky', '[\'kræŋki]', 'adj.怪癖的；不稳的', '1. His mother has been cranky recently. 他的母亲最近常暴躁不安。 2. The baby\'s in a cranky mood today. 婴儿今天爱哭闹。 3. The mass of work made me cranky. 大量的工作使我烦躁。 4. Your network interface(socket) is cranky . 您的网络接口（插座）有毛病。', '副词: crankily 比较级: crankier 最高级: crankiest 名词: crankiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('solemnity', '[sə\'lemnəti]', 'n.庄严；庄重的仪式', '1. The judge took up the gavel with solemnity. 法官严肃地拿起了小木槌。 2. The monument was unveiled with great solemnity. 纪念碑的揭幕庄严而肃穆。 3. All the solemnities of the occasion were observed. 那种场合下应该具有的一切庄重的仪式都举行了。', '名词复数: solemnities');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('manuscript', '[\'mænjuskrɪpt]', 'n.手稿；原稿 adj.手抄的', '1. I read his novel in manuscript. 我看过他小说的手稿。 2. The illumination of the manuscript is delicate. 这个手稿的装饰很精致。 3. The manuscript requires an expert to understand it. 这份手稿只有专家才看得懂。 4. He revised the manuscript of his book before sending it to the publisher. 他对自己那本书的手稿先进行校订，然后才把它交给出版社。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('rosy', '[\'roʊzi]', 'adj.玫瑰色的；美好的', '1. Her normally rosy face took on a deeper hue. 她平常玫瑰色的脸上呈现出更深的色彩。 2. The rosy light yet beamed like a celestial dawn. 玫瑰色的红光依然象天上的朝霞一样绚丽。 3. She painted a rosy picture of the firm\'s future. 她为公司的前景描绘了一幅美好的图画。 4. But life is not rosy for the closeted cross dresser. 但是，对于变装者来说，生活并不是美好的。', '副词: rosily 比较级: rosier 最高级: rosiest 名词: rosiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cement', '[sɪ\'ment]', 'n.水泥；纽带；接合剂；牙骨质；补牙物；基石 vt.用水泥涂；巩固 vi.接合起来', '1. The sack of cement hit the ground with a thump. 水泥袋砰的一声落在地上。 2. Custom was in early days the cement of society. 习俗是早期社会维系的纽带。 3. The floor has been cemented over. 地板上铺了一层水泥。 4. They decided to cement the pavement. 他们决定在人行道上铺上水泥。 5. Snow is cementing. 雪正在凝结。', '名词: cementer 过去式: cemented 过去分词: cemented 现在分词: cementing 第三人称单数: cements');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('avant-garde', '[ˌævɑː̃\'ɡɑːrd]', 'n.先锋派 adj.先锋的；前卫的', '1. Do Westerners Really Understand Chinese Avant Garde Art? 西方人真的了解中国前卫艺术吗? 2. Caracas - Venezuela.Es recomendable para el cambio de fecha tener la fuente [font] Avant Garde Bk Bt. 说明 Elite Model Look Venezuela; concurso de unas de las agencias mas prestigiosas del mundo en Venezuela. 3. As distinctive features, rich avant garde sense, the appearance of a project that was a loving art, a sense of the modern life and pursued. 由于特色鲜明，富有前卫感，项目一经露面，即获得大批爱好前卫艺术、具有现代生活意识的人士的追捧。 4. In essence, resistance of avant garde art is a game, restoring human freedom on the one hand and neutralizing its resistance because of its attitude of game. 先锋艺术的反抗实质上只是一种游戏 ,一方面恢复了人的自由 ,另一方面因游戏态度而消解了反抗功能。', '名词: avant-gardism');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('misanthrope', '[\'mɪsənθroʊp]', 'n.厌恶人类的人；不愿与人来往者', '1. Of, relating to, or characteristic of a misanthrope. 厌恶人类者的厌恶人类者的、与厌恶人类者有关的或有厌恶人类者的特性的 2. Just learned it.) You are not a misanthrope, are you, Daddy? 刚刚学的）长腿叔叔，你不是一个厌世者吧？ 3. Nice try, but you\'re a misanthrope, not a misogynist. ', '不错了;你讨厌的是世界; 不是女人. 4. In the Wine Shop, Soap and The Misanthrope, in Wandering, reflect intellectuals\' life. 在艺术方法上，明显地具有\"淡淡的象征主义色彩\"。');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reprisal', '[rɪ\'praɪzl]', 'n.报复；报仇；报复性劫掠', '1. They made reprisal for what they suffered. 他们为自己所受的苦难进行报复。 2. In those days, objections would only invite reprisals. 在那时候，提出反对意见只会引起报复。 3. Civilian targets were bombed in reprisal . 轰炸了民用目标作为报复. 4. The assassination was in reprisal for invasion. 刺杀行动是为了报复敌人入侵。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('signify', '[\'sɪɡnɪfaɪ]', 'vt.表示；预示；意味着；象征 vi.有重要性', '1. She signifies her disagreement. 她表示她不同意。 2. Do dark clouds signify rain? 有乌云是否显示要下雨? 3. A red sunset signifies fine weather. 红红的晚霞是晴天的预兆。 4. A fever usually signifies that there is something wrong with the body. 发烧通常意味着身体有点毛病。 5. It doesn\'t signify, so you needn\'t worry about it. 这无所谓，你不必担心。', '形容词: signifiable 名词: signifier 过去式: signified 过去分词: signified 现在分词: signifying 第三人称单数: signifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('musty', '[\'mʌsti]', 'adj.发霉的；霉臭的；落伍的', '1. The cottage had a musty smell after being shut up over the winter. 这间村舍关了一个冬天，有一股发霉的气味。 2. The shelves are loaded with old musty books whose pages have become yellowish. 书架上堆着发霉的旧书，书页已经又黄又脆。 3. This room smells a little musty. 这房间闻起来有霉味。 4. A musty odour pervades the room. 房间里弥漫着一股霉臭气。', '副词: mustily 比较级: mustier 最高级: mustiest 名词: mustiness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('linguistic', '[lɪŋ\'ɡwɪstɪk]', 'adj.语言的；语言学的', '1. Gorbachev is a master of linguistic gestures. 戈尔巴乔夫精于语言的动作。 2. Thereafter, his linguistic abilities would decrease as he gets older. 年纪越大，掌握语言的能力相对的也越低。 3. She is pursuing her linguistic researches. 她在从事语言学的研究。 4. Viewed from the perspective of postcolonial translation studies, it is no more a purely aesthetic or linguistic act. 后殖民翻译研究视野中的翻译不再是纯美学的或纯语言学的行为。', '副词: linguistically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('luxuriant', '[lʌɡ\'ʒʊriənt]', 'adj.繁茂的；丰富的；肥沃的；华丽的；奢华的', '1. Luxuriant forests covered the hills. 山上长满茂密的树林。 2. The bees are humming over the luxuriant flowers. 蜜蜂在繁茂的花丛上嗡嗡作响。 3. The backyard of our house has a luxuriant growth of weeds. 我们家的后院长了一大堆杂草。 4. Farming was easy in this luxuriant soil. 在这片沃土上耕种是件易事。', '副词: luxuriantly 名词: luxuriance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('quiescent', '[kwi\'esnt]', 'adj.静止的；寂静的；不活动的', '1. The rapid development of the economy turns the quiescent town into a noisy city. 经济的迅速发展使这个寂静的小镇成为闹市。 2. Stan stared for hours at the quiescent scene of the Japanese rock garden. 斯坦盯着这座宁静的日本岩石花园看了好几个小时。 3. the black holes in our galaxy and others are quiescent. 我们星系和其他星系里的黑洞则是不活跃的。', '副词: quiescently 名词: quiescence');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('riffraff', '[\'rɪfˌræf]', 'n. <贬>乌合之众； 流氓； 渣滓； 垃圾', '1. The army should strictly discipline riffraff. 军队的首长们在广场上点兵阅阵。 2. Haven`t you been told it`s dangerous to drive alone through all that riffraff? 没有人告诉过你一个人通过那段路是很危险的吗? 3. Bleaching and those that you say you are a media riffraff pedophilia! 那些说你漂白和说你是一个娈童痞子的媒体！ 4. \"It\'s terrible.\" and \"It\'s fine.\",\"riffraff\" and \"vanguards of the revolution\" -- here are apt examples. “糟得很”和“好得很”，“痞子”和“革命先锋”，都是适例。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('adherent', '[əd\'hɪrənt]', 'n.追随者；拥护者；信徒 adj.附着的；粘连的', '1. The movement is gaining more and more adherents. 这个运动得到了越来越多的追随者的支持。 2. He is a leader with many adherents. 他是个有众多追随者的领袖。 3. This is a kind of adherent substance. 这是一种粘性物质。', '副词: adherently');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cardinal', '[\'kɑːrdɪnl]', 'n.红衣主教；鲜红色；基数；北美红雀 adj.主要的；深红色的', '1. I\'ve had dinner with Bill and Cardinal Spellman. 我同比尔和斯佩尔曼红衣主教一起吃过晚饭。 2. The cardinal includes 1, 2, 3, etc. 基数词包括1、2、3等等。 3. A cardinal perched momently on the dogwood branch. 一只北美红雀在山茱萸上停留了片刻。 4. Every one suspects himself of at least one of the cardinal virtues. 每个人都认为他自己至少有一种主要的品德。', '名词: cardinalship');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('conservative', '[kən\'sɜːrvətɪv]', 'adj.保守的；守旧的 n.保守派(党)；保守的人', '1. He was very conservative in the estimate. 他的这一估计很保守。 2. Old people are usually more conservative than young people. 老年人通常比年轻人保守。 3. The professor\'s a radical in politics but a conservative dresser. 教授在政治上是激进派,但衣着却很守旧。 4. The man turned from Radical to Conservative. 这人从激进派变成了保守派。', '副词: conservatively 名词: conservativeness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('caress', '[kə\'res]', 'n.爱抚；拥抱 v.爱抚；抚摸；怜爱', '1. The lonely child is longing for the caress of his mother. 这个孤独的孩子渴望母亲的爱抚。 2. She feasted on the caress of the hot spring. 她尽情享受着温泉的抚爱。 3. He prescribed his fiancee\'s reception of his caress. 他要求他的未婚妻接受他的拥抱。 4. He caressed his wife lovingly. 他爱怜地抚摸着他的妻子。', '形容词: caressive 副词: caressingly 名词: caresser 过去式: caressed 过去分词: caressed 现在分词: caressing 第三人称单数: caresses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('antibody', '[\'æntibɑːdi]', 'n.抗体', '1. Our end product is an anti-cancer antibody. 我们的最终产品是一种抗癌抗体。 2. Our bodies produce antibodies to counteract disease. 我们的身体能产生抗体以抵抗疾病。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('monastery', '[\'mɑːnəsteri]', 'n.修道院；寺院', '1. In his youth he had stayed in the monastery. 他年轻时在这个修道院待过。 2. He lived in a monastery for most of his life. 他一生中的大部分时间是在寺院中度过的。 3. An underclass boy named Wusan entered a monastery without revealing his status. 有一个叫无三的孩子出身贱民，只好隐姓埋名进了寺院。', '形容词: monasterial 名词复数: monasteries');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('seraphic', '[sə\'ræfɪk]', 'adj.如天使般的；美丽的', '1. Seraph is of the highest rank of angels in the Bible. 六翼天使是圣经中级别最高的天使。 2. You\'re a seraphic suggestion of attenuated thought. 你的思想是轻灵得如同天使一般的。” 3. Bury the creature if you lose control of Seraph. 如果你不再操控六翼天使，则埋葬此生物。 4. The seraph\'s light will help you. 天使的光芒会帮助你的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('apt', '[æpt]', 'adj.恰当的；聪明的；易于 ... 的 abbr.公寓（=apartment） abbr.才能；天资（=aptitude）', '1. In many ways, the comparison is apt. 在诸多方面，这个对比是恰当的。 2. I imagine that you may deduce an apt moral from my tale. 我觉得你也许能从我的际遇中引出恰当的教训。 3. Henry is an apt student of the practical science. 亨利在实践科学上是个聪明的学生。 4. He is a clever boy but apt to get into mischief. 他是个聪明却很调皮的孩子。 5. He has a handful of intelligent and apt students. 他有许多天资聪颖的学生。', '副词: aptly 名词: aptness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('tumult', '[\'tuːmʌlt]', 'n.骚乱；嘈杂声；烦乱', '1. Presently the tumult died down. 一会儿工夫骚动平息了下来。 2. The employer was forced to allay the tumult. 雇主被迫缓和骚乱。 3. He could hear a great tumult in the street. 他听到街上很响的嘈杂声。 4. One had to shout to be heard above the tumult. 声音嘈杂，得大喊大叫别人才听得见。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('archive', '[\'ɑːrkaɪv]', 'n.档案；档案馆 vt.存档', '1. The multivolume archive was created successfully. 成功创建多卷存档。 2. The repository is the official archive of our work. 库是我们的正式的档案。 3. she went to the city archive this morning. 她今天上午去了市档案馆。 4. It\'s a good idea to archive your files once a week. 一个星期对你的文件存档一次是个不错的主意。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('valiant', '[\'væliənt]', 'adj.勇敢的；英勇的 n.勇士；勇敢的人', '1. Let\'s hail to the valiant victors. 让我们向勇敢的胜利者致敬！ 2. A large reception was held in honor of the valiant explorers. 为勇敢的探险家们举行了一个盛大的招待会。 3. The valiant hero saved the little girl\'s life. 那个英勇的英雄拯救了小女孩的生命。 4. The man put up a valiant fight for victory. 这个人为了赢得胜利进行了英勇的斗争。 5. To a valiant heart nothing is impossible. 勇士面前无难事。', '副词: valiantly 名词: valiancy');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fortify', '[\'fɔːrtɪfaɪ]', 'v.加强；增强；筑防御工事于；（物质或精神上）支持或鼓励', '1. They decided to fortify the coastal areas. 他们决定加强海岸地区的防卫。 2. This country will fortify the coastal areas. 该国将加强沿海地区的防御。 3. Tungsten is used to fortify steel for cars. 钨可以固化钢铁来生产汽车。 4. They fortify the dam against the flood. 他们加固堤坝以防止洪水。', '形容词: fortifiable 副词: fortifyingly 名词: fortifier 过去式: fortified 过去分词: fortified 现在分词: fortifying 第三人称单数: fortifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('glamorous', '[\'ɡlæmərəs]', 'adj.富有魅力的；迷人的', '1. The long red carpet was laid out for this glamorous occasion. 为了这个富有魅力的时刻，地上铺了长长的红地毯。 2. Do not be swayed by glamorous advertisements. 不要为富有迷惑力的广告所左右。 3. The glamorous actress always went shopping with many attendants crowding round her. 那位富有魅力的女演员逛街时总是被前呼后拥地围着。 4. My job is not a very glamorous one but it does have its moments. 我的工作虽不算十分吸引人，但也自有其乐趣所在。', '副词: glamorously 名词: glamorousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detestable', '[dɪ\'testəbl]', 'adj.可憎的；令人厌恶的', '1. All terrorist crime is detestable,whoever the victims. 无论受害者是谁，一切恐怖主义罪行都是可憎的。 2. I thought it a detestable custom. 我觉得这是令人讨厌的习惯。', '副词: detestably 名词: detestability');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gregarious', '[ɡrɪ\'ɡeriəs]', 'adj.爱社交的；群居的', '1. She\'s very outgoing and gregarious. 她非常外向，喜欢交际。 2. Gregarious website is changing the life of people with rapid rate. 社交网站正在以飞快的速度改变着人们的生活。 3. These animals are highly gregarious. 这些动物非常喜欢群居。', '副词: gregariously 名词: gregariousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('petrology', '[pə\'trɑːlədʒi]', 'n.岩石学', '1. Petrology is the science of the rocks. 岩石学是岩石的科学。 2. The branch of petrology that deals with the origin of rocks,especially igneous rocks. 岩石成因说，岩石发展学研究岩石成因的岩石学的一个分支，尤其是火成岩的成因 3. The branch of petrology that deals with the origin of rocks, especially igneous rocks. 岩石成因说，岩石发展学研究岩石成因的岩石学的一个分支，尤其是火成岩的成因 4. The petrology of belt of miarolitic granites in the southeast coast of fujian province and their generation II. 福建沿海晶洞花岗岩带的岩石和成因演化2。', '形容词: petrologic 副词: petrologically 名词: petrologist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('recalcitrant', '[rɪ\'kælsɪtrənt]', 'adj.反抗的；顽强的', '1. The University suspended the most recalcitrant demonstraters. 这所大学把几个反抗性最强的示威者开除了。 2. Donkeys are reputed to be the most recalcitrant animals. 驴被认为是最倔强的牲畜。 3. The university suspended the most recalcitrant demonstrators. 该大学对最为桀骜不驯的学生做了暂令停学的处理。', '名词: recalcitrance');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('riotous', '[\'raɪətəs]', 'adj.暴乱的；狂欢的；放荡的；茂盛的', '1. He was charged with riotous behaviour. 他被控聚众闹事。 2. We spent a riotous night at Christmas. 圣诞节我们度过了一个狂欢之夜。 3. He was expelled from college for riotous conduct. 他因行为放荡而被勒令退学。', '副词: riotously 名词: riotousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scissor', '[\'sɪzər]', 'n.剪刀', '1. To practice scissor skills by cutting out large pictures and shapes. 能正确的使用剪刀，并能用剪刀剪大的形状和图片。', '过去式: scissored 过去分词: scissored 现在分词: scissoring 第三人称单数: scissors');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suspicion', '[sə\'spɪʃn]', 'n.猜疑；怀疑', '1. We regard her behaviour with suspicion. 我们对她的行为有怀疑。 2. \"A science fiction cannot not be regarded as a mere entertainment, but in fact it tells the reader much more.\" \"科幻小说不能简单地看成是供消遣的，而实际上它给读者展示更深刻的内容。\" 3. The talks have resulted in a lessening of suspicion. 谈话消减了彼此的怀疑。 4. His words had sowed the seeds of suspicion in their minds. 他的话已在他们心中播下怀疑的种子。', '形容词: suspicional 过去式: suspicioned 过去分词: suspicioned 现在分词: suspicioning 第三人称单数: suspicions');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('appall', '[ə\'pɔːl]', 'v.使 ... 胆寒；使 ... 惊骇', '1. The prospect of another war appalled us. 想到有可能发生另一场战争，我们不寒而栗。 2. The number of people killed on the roads appalled me. 在路上毙命的人数之多使我胆寒。 3. We were appalled when we heard that the chairman had been murdered. 听说主席被谋杀，我们都吓坏了。 4. We were appalled by the news of the war. 听到战争的消息我们大为震惊。', '过去式: appalled 过去分词: appalled 现在分词: appalling 第三人称单数: appalls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('levelheaded', '[\'levəl\'hedɪd]', 'adj.头脑冷静的', '1. I am knowledgeable and levelheaded. 我知识丰富、头脑冷静。 2. A: I am knowledgeable and levelheaded. I: 说说你的工作经验吧。 3. WSJ: How do you stay levelheaded in the middle of a bubble? 华：在泡沫时期你怎么保持清醒的头脑？ 4. Don\'t get carried away! Be a little more levelheaded. 不要忘乎所以!冷静一点。', '名词: levelheadedness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('grenade', '[ɡrə\'neɪd]', 'n.手榴弹；榴弹', '1. A hand grenade is a missile weapon. 手榴弹是一种投掷武器。 2. He pulled out the pin but the grenade didn\'t work. 他拉了导火索，但是手榴弹并没有响。 3. When fighting in tight hallways I switch to the grenade launcher to defend myself. 当在狭窄的通道迎战，我会换到榴弹发射器来保卫自己。 4. The cook, with her leg broken by the bursting grenade, had been carried into the kitchen. 榴弹碎片打伤了厨娘的大腿，有人把她抬到厨房里。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('document', '[\'dɑːkjumənt]', 'n.文件；公文；文档 vt.记载；(用文件等)证明', '1. She signed her name to the document. 她在文件上签了名。 2. He persuaded her to sign the document by guile. 他用欺骗手段说服她在文件上签字。 3. The official document was misworded. 这公文的措词不当。 4. A document issued to sub-branches shall be sealed by all the issuers. 联合下发的公文，发文机关都应当加盖印章。 5. The history of this area is very well documented. 这个地区的历史档案保存得很好。', '形容词: documental 名词: documenter 过去式: documented 过去分词: documented 现在分词: documenting 第三人称单数: documents');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('lean', '[liːn]', 'v.倾斜；倾向；依靠；倚；屈身 adj.瘦的；贫乏的；无脂肪的 n.瘦肉；倾斜，倾向', '1. The trees leant in the wind. 树在风中倾斜。 2. Kids today lean toward casual clothes. 今天的孩子倾向于穿随便的衣服。 3. I lean towards letting him go alone. 我倾向于让他一个人去。 4. We lean on our friends when we are in trouble. 我们遇到困难时依靠朋友帮助。 5. The little girl only eats lean pork. 这个小女孩只吃瘦肉。', '副词: leanly 比较级: leaner 最高级: leanest 名词: leanness 过去式: leaned 过去分词: leaned 现在分词: leaning 第三人称单数: leans');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('awry', '[ə\'raɪ]', 'adj.扭曲的；歪曲的 adv.错误地；出岔子；歪；斜', '1. Her clothes were all awry. 她的衣服全都歪歪扭扭的。 2. It is no use to blame the looking glass if your face is awry. 假如你的脸是长歪的，责怪镜子是没有用的。 3. Our plans went awry. 我们的计划出岔子了。 4. Children are easy to go awry without parental control. 孩子没有父母的照管容易走上邪路。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('boost', '[buːst]', 'v.提高；增加；鼓励；举起；为...做宣传 n.增加；推进；鼓励', '1. This new technique will boost food production. 这种新工艺将会提高食品产量。 2. The publication of this book boost my confidence. 这本书的出版增强了我的信心。 3. The change of management has boosted morale throughout the company. 管理层的变更使整个公司士气大振。 4. Boost me up the tree and I\'ll get the apple. 把我托上树,我就能摘到那只苹果了。 5. Last month saw a tremendous boost in sales. 上个月的销售额激增。', '过去式: boosted 过去分词: boosted 现在分词: boosting 第三人称单数: boosts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sonnet', '[\'sɑːnɪt]', 'n.十四行诗', '1. I am able to recite all shakespeare\'s sonnet. 我能背诵莎士比亚的全部十四行诗。 2. He read us a sonnet that celebrates love. 他给我们读了一首歌颂爱情的十四行诗。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('denouement', '[ˌdeɪnuː\'mɑː̃]', 'n.(小说、戏剧等的)结尾；结局', '1. Cowperwood was in no way pleased by this rough denouement. 这样草草收场，柯帕乌绝不会高兴的。 2. In a surprising denouement, she becomes a nun. 结局出人意表，她当修女了。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('combat', '[\'kɑːmbæt]', 'n.战斗；试图解决 v.战斗；与 ... 斗争；试图解决 adj.战斗的', '1. The fighter planes quickly disengaged from the combat. 歼击机很快从战斗中撤出了。 2. He is stuck in the combat against this problem. 他在解决这个难题的过程中遇到了障碍。 3. The nation will combat all invaders. 这个民族将同所有的入侵者战斗。 4. The ship is combating the wind and waves. 那只船正与风浪搏斗。 5. The soldiers are ready to fly the 50 combat mission. 战士们已经准备好了执行第50号战斗任务。', '过去式: combated/combatted 过去分词: combated/combatted 现在分词: combating/combatting 第三人称单数: combats/combats');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('furnace', '[\'fɜːrnɪs]', 'n.炉子；熔炉；闷热地带；严峻考验', '1. This room is like a furnace. 这屋子热得象火炉一样。 2. Would you please fire the furnace? 你去给炉子添加燃料好吗? 3. The metal glowed in the furnace. 金属在熔炉里发出灼热的光。 4. He endured the furnace of his friends\'blame after the accident. 事故发生之后,他遭朋友指责的考验', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('deduct', '[dɪ\'dʌkt]', 'vt.扣除；演绎', '1. Nowadays income tax is normally deducted from a person\'s wages. 现在，所得税通常是在发工资前就已经扣除了。 2. Tax is deducted from your salary. 税金从你的薪金中扣除。 3. You may deduct your families health insurance. 你可以扣除你的家庭健康保险. 4. It is not the bank\'s policy to deduct interest on withdrawal. 提款需扣除利息这并非是本银行的政策。', '过去式: deducted 过去分词: deducted 现在分词: deducting 第三人称单数: deducts');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('license', '[\'laɪsns]', 'n.许可证；执照；特许 vt.发许可证给；特许', '1. We contemplate obtaining a technical license. 我们希望获得一项技术许可证。 2. His license was suspended for six months. 他的执照被吊销6个月。 3. The designers were allowed a lot of creative license. 那些设计者们获得了很多创意许可。 4. Are you licensed to drive? 你得到驾车的执照了吗？', '形容词: licensable 名词: licenser 过去式: licensed 过去分词: licensed 现在分词: licensing 第三人称单数: licenses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diverse', '[daɪ\'vɜːrs]', 'adj.不同的；多种多样的', '1. They are the people from diverse cultures. 他们是些有着不同文化背景的人。 2. Since then，she has played a diverse range of roles. 从那时起,她出演了各种不同的角色。 3. Her interests are very diverse. 她的兴趣非常广泛。 4. Their way of life is rich, diverse and rooted. 他们的生活方式丰富多彩,多种多样,扎根传统。', '副词: diversely 名词: diverseness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('confess', '[kən\'fes]', 'v.承认；供认；告解；听取忏悔', '1. I confess you are right on one point. 我承认你在某一点上是正确的。 2. Now, I must confess that I\'m at my wit\'s end. 现在我必须承认我已毫无办法。 3. He confessed that he had never seen her before. 他承认以前从未见过她。 4. He refused to confess to his crime. 他拒绝认罪。', '形容词: confessable 副词: confessedly 过去式: confessed 过去分词: confessed 现在分词: confessing 第三人称单数: confesses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('array', '[ə\'reɪ]', 'n.一系列；大批；数组；陈列，列队；盛装 vt.排列；部署；打扮', '1. The era also gave birth to a whole array of new social problems. 那个时代还产生了一系列新的社会问题。 2. We have quite an array of leather shoes. 我们有一大批各类皮鞋。 3. Today\'s vehicles offer an array of advanced safety features. 现在的汽车都提供了大量先进的安全设备。 4. Our troops were drawn up in battle array. 我们的部队已严阵以待。 5. I want to array this specimen mount in the display window. 我想把这个标本架放到橱窗里。', '过去式: arrayed 过去分词: arrayed 现在分词: arraying 第三人称单数: arrays');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('banal', '[bə\'nɑːl]', 'adj.陈腐的；平庸的', '1. Chris\' banal advice was no help to us in solving our problem. 克里斯陈腐的劝告对于解决我们的问题完全没有帮助。 2. Even if you are saying something banal, it will seem original if you make it vague, open-ended, and sphinxlike. 哪怕你是在说一些很平庸陈腐的东西，说得越模糊，越显得独创而有哲理。 3. It involves systematic yet banal design, and blunt reportage. 它使用系统的，然而平庸的设计和迟钝的新闻报道。', '副词: banally 动词: banalize');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('outshine', '[ˌaʊt\'ʃaɪn]', 'v.优于；使相形见拙；光亮强过；发光', '1. You can never be afraid that someone\'s going to outshine you. 你决不能害怕将有人会超越你。 2. You\'re going to outshine the rest. 你会使其他人显得相形见绌。 3. The young girl violinist outshone (ie was much better than) all the other competitors. 那年轻姑娘演奏小提琴使所有的竞争者相形见绌。 4. She is lovely enough to outshine the moon and put the flowers to shame. 她有沉鱼落雁之容,闭月羞花之貌。', '过去式: outshone 过去分词: outshone 现在分词: outshining 第三人称单数: outshines');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('metamorphose', '[ˌmetə\'mɔːrfoʊz]', 'v.改变形状；使变成', '1. The caterpillar will eventually metamorphose into a butterfly. 毛毛虫最终将蜕变成一只蝴蝶。 2. A larva metamorphoses into a chrysalis and then into a butterfly. 幼虫变为蛹，然后再变成蝴蝶。 3. The magician metamorphosed the frog into a prince. 魔术师把青蛙变成了王子。', '过去式: metamorphosed 过去分词: metamorphosed 现在分词: metamorphosing 第三人称单数: metamorphoses');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('applaud', '[ə\'plɔːd]', 'vi.拍手喝彩 vt.称赞；赞成；鼓掌', '1. He leaped to his feet and began to applaud. 他跳起来开始鼓掌。 2. Please don\'t applaud until everyone has performed. 请在每个人表演完毕后再鼓掌。 3. Should I applaud my husband or chastise him? 我是该称赞还是责罚我的丈夫呢？ 4. Before I begin to flame anything, I would like to applaud a few folks. 在我开始对任何事激动之前,我想称赞一些人。', '形容词: applaudable 副词: applaudably 名词: applauder 过去式: applauded 过去分词: applauded 现在分词: applauding 第三人称单数: applauds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('refectory', '[rɪ\'fektri]', 'n.餐厅', '1. Anyway, I had found the refectory. 我总算找到了餐厅。 2. They eat most days in the college refectory. 他们多数都是在学院的餐厅里吃饭。 3. The meal of the school refectory is healthy and delicious. 学校食堂做的饭菜卫生可口。', '名词复数: refectories');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('pending', '[\'pendɪŋ]', 'adj.待定的；即将发生或来临的 prep.直到；等待 ... 的时候；在 ... 期间', '1. The lawsuit was then pending. 那件讼案因而尚未解决。 2. A climax is pending. 高潮即将来到。 3. A decision on this matter is pending. 此事即将作出决定。 4. Series The command has been accepted, but the requested action is on hold, pending receipt of further information. 命令被接受,但是被要求的行动被保留,直到收到索取补充材料。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('disruptive', '[dɪs\'rʌptɪv]', 'adj.分裂的；破坏性的；制造混乱的', '1. We should be alert to the potentially disruptive elements in society. 我们应该警惕社会上潜在的破坏分子。 2. It is more about evolution not disruptive innovations now. 重要的是，这是一种进化的过程，而非是破坏性的创新。 3. The impact of Western civilization has been highly disruptive. 西方文化的影响具有高度的破坏性。 4. He has a disruptive influence on the other children. 他能影响别的孩子使他们失控。', '副词: disruptively');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fossilize', '[\'fɑːsəlaɪz]', 'vt.使成化石；使陈腐 vi.变成化石；变陈腐；固定化', '1. He found a piece of fossil of an ancient bird. 他发现一块古代鸟类的化石。 2. This fossil may be over 2 million years old. 这化石可能超过二百万年了。 3. Can you date the fossil exactly? 你能确定这化石的确切年代吗? 4. Isn\'t Professor Bell an old fossil? 贝尔教授真是个老顽固。', '名词: fossilization 过去式: fossilized 过去分词: fossilized 现在分词: fossilizing 第三人称单数: fossilizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('skimp', '[skɪmp]', 'v.舍不得给；节省；克扣；敷衍 adj.少的；不足的', '1. Don\'t skimp the butter when you make cakes. 你做蛋糕时不要吝惜用奶油。 2. They have to skimp on fuel in winter. 冬天他们得节省燃料。 3. Higher officials always skimp on the salaries of their staff. 上级长官总是克扣下属们的薪饷。 4. Don\'t skimp on your employment section. 一定要详细阐述你的工作 经验。', '过去式: skimped 过去分词: skimped 现在分词: skimping 第三人称单数: skimps');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('gorgeous', '[\'ɡɔːrdʒəs]', 'adj.华丽的；灿烂的；极好的', '1. The gorgeous costume added to the brilliance of the dance. 华丽的服装使舞蹈更加光彩夺目。 2. In the evening the rosy clouds were gorgeous. 傍晚的云霞绚丽多彩。 3. The garden is gorgeous with peonies. 花园里盛开着绚丽的牡丹花。 4. What a gorgeous day! 多美好的一天啊!', '副词: gorgeously 名词: gorgeousness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exuberant', '[ɪɡ\'zuːbərənt]', 'adj.兴高采烈的；繁茂的；丰富的', '1. She gave an exuberant account of the party. 她生动地介绍了那一聚会的情形. 2. All those mother trees in the garden are exuberant. 果园里的那些母树都长得十分茂盛。 3. The nation enjoyed exuberant prosperity. 这个国家极度繁荣。', '副词: exuberantly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('sane', '[seɪn]', 'adj.心智健全的；明智的', '1. A sane healthy mind can get momentarily off the rails. 正常健全的头脑也会一时失常。 2. It\'s hard to stay sane under such awful pressure. 处于这种可怕的压力之下，不疯才怪呢。 3. He made a sane choice. 他做了一个明智的选择。 4. She has a sane attitude toward diving and never goes too fast. 她对于跳水的态度很明智，从不操之过急。', '副词: sanely 比较级: saner 最高级: sanest 名词: saneness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shove', '[ʃʌv]', 'v.推挤；撞；乱塞；乱放 n.推；挤', '1. Don\'t try to shove all the work onto me! 别把工作都推给我！ 2. He dragged her out of the door and shoved her into the street. 他把她拖到门口，猛地把她推到马路上。 3. Then suddenly, Old Grizzly gave Brown Bear a big shove. 突然间，老灰熊给棕色熊一个重重的推撞。 4. Bunt was probably a nickname given to him at school, for going around with his head lowered, ready to bump and shove anybody aside. 铁头可能是他上学时得的绰号，那时他总低着头走路，一副准备随时一头把人撞到一边的架势。 5. The car won\'t start. Can you give it a shove? 这车子启动不了。你能不能推它一把?', '名词: shover 过去式: shoved 过去分词: shoved 现在分词: shoving 第三人称单数: shoves');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('suffocate', '[\'sʌfəkeɪt]', 'vt.使窒息；使缺氧；阻碍 vi.窒息；窒息而亡；阻碍发展', '1. But they do suffocate from a lack of air. 但它们确实也会因为缺少空气而窒息。 2. The stale air made us suffocate. 浑浊的空气使我们感到窒息。', '形容词: suffocative 副词: suffocatingly 名词: suffocation 过去式: suffocated 过去分词: suffocated 现在分词: suffocating 第三人称单数: suffocates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('wardrobe', '[\'wɔːrdroʊb]', 'n.衣橱，衣柜；全部服装', '1. The wardrobe takes up too much space. 这衣橱太占地方了。 2. All the shirts hang together in the same wardrobe. 所有的衬衫都挂在同一个衣橱里。 3. Such an outfit would be a useful addition to my wardrobe. 在我的服装中添置这一套会有用的。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('cryptic', '[\'krɪptɪk]', 'adj.隐秘的；秘密的；用密码的；隐晦的', '1. A cryptic message said France needs to pull troops out of Afghanistan. 一个神秘消息要求法国需要从阿富汗撤军。 2. I don\'t know what this cryptic remark is intended to convey. 我不知道这句暗藏玄机的评语是要表示什麽。 3. Before the day was over, Henry issued a cryptic memo to top executives. 亨利赶着在当天就向高级职员发出了一份使人费解的内部通知。 4. She made a cryptic comment about how the film mirrored her life. 她隐晦地表示说这部电影是她人生的写照。', '副词: cryptically 异体字: cryptical 名词: crypticness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('vitrify', '[\'vɪtrɪfaɪ]', 'v.（使）变成玻璃；（使）玻璃化', '1. Dry powder insulation mortar produced by vitrify micro beads material, have excellent insulation and fire proof heat resistant properties, never crack whith high strength. 玻化微珠材料生产的干粉保温砂浆。具有优良的保温隔热性能和防火耐热抗老化性能，不空鼓开裂。 2. \"Earthenware is the oldest and simplest form;stoneware is fired at a high temperature to cause it to vitrify and harden;and porcelain is a fine, generally translucent form of pottery. 陶器是最古老和简单的陶瓷形式,而石陶器则是在高温下形成的玻璃状硬器皿,瓷器则是一种精致半透明的陶瓷。 3. Keywords heavy slags;vitrify;decorate material;molten slags;decorate properties; 重矿渣;玻化;饰面材料;熔渣;装饰性能; 4. vitrify micro beads 玻化微珠', '形容词: vitrifiable 名词: vitrifiability 过去式: vitrified 过去分词: vitrified 现在分词: vitrifying 第三人称单数: vitrifies');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('belongings', '[bɪ\'lɔːŋɪŋz]', 'n.财产；所有物；物件；东西', '1. She lost all her belongings in the fire. 她在那场火灾中失去了所有的财产。 2. He pointed his belongings towards the police. 他向警察出示了自己的所有东西。 3. She tied up her few belongings into a bundle. 她把她仅有的一些所有物绑成一捆。 4. Parents owe their children privacy and respect for their personal belongings. 父母亲应允许孩子们有个人的秘密，要尊重他们的私人物件。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('countenance', '[\'kaʊntənəns]', 'n.面容；面部表情；支持 v.赞成；支持', '1. He is a young man of handsome countenance. 他是一个拥有英俊面容的年轻人。 2. He kept his countenance when he was in danger. 在这个危险的处境中他表现得镇定自若。 3. Horror was depicted on every countenance. 每一张脸上都现出骇愕的表情。 4. I would not give countenance to such a plan. 我不赞同这样的计划。 5. We will not countenance any aggressive violence. 我们不会支持任何挑衅性暴力行动。', '名词: countenancer 过去式: countenanced 过去分词: countenanced 现在分词: countenancing 第三人称单数: countenances');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('growl', '[ɡraʊl]', 'n.吠声；咆哮声 v.怒吠；咆哮；吼', '1. I kicked the dog, which responded by growling/with a growl. 我踢了那条狗，它便狂吠起来。 2. The dog evinced its dislike of stranger by growl. 犬以咆哮表示憎恶生人。 3. He answered the question with growl. 他咆哮着回答了这个问题。 4. Each time I moved in her direction, a menacing growl rumbled in her throat. 我每次朝她那方向走，她喉咙里就响起威胁的咆哮声。 5. The dog growled at me. 那狗向我咆哮。', '形容词: growly 过去式: growled 过去分词: growled 现在分词: growling 第三人称单数: growls');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('bridle', '[\'braɪdl]', 'n.马笼头，缰绳；约束，约束物 v.给 ... 套笼头；控制（感情等）；动怒', '1. He was leading a horse by the bridle. 他牵着马的缰绳。 2. It is the bridle and spur that makes a good horse. 要把马练好，缰绳靴刺少不了。 3. Her common sense is a bridle to her quick temper. 她的常识是对她急脾气的抑制。 4. Jane bridled her favourite horse yesterday. 昨天简给她心爱的马装上了马鞍。', '名词: bridler 过去式: bridled 过去分词: bridled 现在分词: bridling 第三人称单数: bridles');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('asparagus', '[ə\'spærəɡəs]', 'n.芦笋', '1. We have some asparagus for lunch. 我们午饭有些芦笋。 2. There is even?a bonus disc?for creating asparagus. 还有一个附赠的做芦笋的碟子。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('doggerel', '[\'dɔːɡərəl]', 'n.打油诗 adj.(诗)拙劣的；不含诗律的；滑稽的', '1. Neither it nor his other theological versetreatises rise far above doggerel. 跟他的其他有关神学的议论诗一样，这不比拙劣的打油诗高明多少。', '异体字: doggrel');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('reprobate', '[\'reprəbeɪt]', 'n.堕落的人；恶棍；被神遗弃的人 adj.堕落的；邪恶的 v.斥责；非难', '1. He has always been a bit of a reprobate. 他一向不很规矩. 2. Far from being the drunken reprobate of popular legend,they found him punctual and hard-working. 远非流传的那样他是一个烂醉的恶棍，他们发现他既守时又勤奋。 3. Theses boys have reprobate tendencies. 这些孩子有堕落的倾向。 4. Don\'t reprobate a weak and foolish girl\'s ignorance. 不要谴责一个软弱而又愚蠢的姑娘的无知。', '形容词: reprobative 名词: reprobation 过去式: reprobated 过去分词: reprobated 现在分词: reprobating 第三人称单数: reprobates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('digit', '[\'dɪdʒɪt]', 'n.数字；位数；手指；脚趾', '1. One digit always precedes the decimal point. 小数点前总有一个数字。 2. John\'s money quickly melted away as the double - digit inflation rate continued to soar. 随着两位数的通货膨胀率继续上升，约翰的钱很快就花光了。 3. Swipe the said digit across the scanner and the transaction will appear to go through as normal even as the bank is alerted that something fishy is going on. 大幅度地挥动这个惊慌手指通过扫描仪，即使银行得到可以现象的警报，交易会像正常情况下一样显示通过。 4. She put a dressing on the mangled digit. 她包扎了被砍伤的脚趾。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('exterminate', '[ɪk\'stɜːrmɪneɪt]', 'vt.消灭；扑灭；根绝', '1. This spray will exterminate the termites. 这种喷剂能消灭白蚁。 2. We must exterminate every mistake. 我们必须消除一切错误。 3. Taiwan\'s government has made it a priority to exterminate the fire ants. 台湾政府已将扑杀火蚁列为第一要务。 4. Would Mother Nature really exterminate mankind? 大自然会根除人类吗？', '形容词: exterminative 名词: extermination 过去式: exterminated 过去分词: exterminated 现在分词: exterminating 第三人称单数: exterminates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('ignite', '[ɪɡ\'naɪt]', 'vi.着火；燃烧 vt.点燃；使 ... 燃烧；引发', '1. Large pieces of wood do not ignite easily. 大块木材是不易着火的。 2. Ammonia-air mixtures are quite difficult to ignite. 氨与空气的混合气体不易燃烧。 3. The burning gases can ignite the lean mixture. 燃烧着的气体能点燃稀的混合气。 4. What can you do to ignite your own passion? 有什么办法可以点燃你的热情？', '形容词: ignitable 名词: igniter 过去式: ignited 过去分词: ignited 现在分词: igniting 第三人称单数: ignites');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('horizontal', '[ˌhɔːrə\'zɑːntl]', 'adj.水平的；横的 n.水平线；水平面', '1. The vertical line meets the horizontal one here. 垂直线与水平线在此相交。 2. The sun rises from the horizontal line. 太阳从地平线上升起。 3. Please draw a horizontal line on the page. 请在这一页画条横线。 4. The bottom of the door is out of the horizontal. 这扇门底部不成水平。', '副词: horizontally');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('graphic', '[\'ɡræfɪk]', 'adj.生动的；图表的 n.图表', '1. The general gave a graphic account of the battle. 将军对战斗作了生动的描述。 2. He was a man of many words and many graphic gestures. 他是一个话多的人，还不停比划着生动的手势。 3. The newspaper article gave a graphic description of the earthquake. 报纸文章生动地描述了地震的情况。 4. The principal kept a graphic record of school attendance. 校长用图表记录学生的出席率。 5. Please help me to make a graphic. 请帮我做份图表。', '副词: graphically 名词: graphicness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('guileless', '[\'ɡaɪlləs]', 'adj.不狡猾的；诚实的', '1. He is a guileless young man. 他是个诚实的年轻人。 2. He was very guileless in affiliating with people. 与人交往，他非常朴实。 3. She gave him a guileless look, but he knew he couldn\'t really trust her. 她朝他诚恳地看了一眼，但是他知道他不能真正地相信她。', '副词: guilelessly 名词: guilelessness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('fumigate', '[\'fjuːmɪɡeɪt]', 'v.以烟熏消毒', '1. The hospital wards were fumigated after the outbreak of typhus. 发现斑疹伤寒以后，医院的病房进行了烟熏消毒。', '名词: fumigation 过去式: fumigated 过去分词: fumigated 现在分词: fumigating 第三人称单数: fumigates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('scooter', '[\'skuːtər]', 'n.踏板车；小型摩托车', '1. For sale: small motor scooter. Enquire within. 待售：小型摩托车，请进内询问。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('zesty', '[\'zesti]', 'adj.兴致很高的', '1. The palate is zesty and lively with great length of flavour. 酒质生动，收结悠长且充满芳香。 2. Juicy Beef, plump Tomatoes, fresh Potatoes & zesty Onions make a hearty feed. 上选特质牛肉，配以新鲜番茄、土豆、洋葱等蔬菜煨制，用料精细讲究，营养健康。 3. This refreshing Sauvignon Blanc is bursting with zesty, citrus characters. 此款苏维翁白葡萄酒充满明快的柑桔气息，清爽怡人。 4. Prepare as directed, using KRAFT Light Zesty Italian Reduced Fat Dressing. 准备的指示，用牛皮轻zesty意大利减少脂肪敷料。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('mien', '[miːn]', 'n.风采；态度；外表', '1. He is a man of proud mien. 他是个态度傲慢的人。 2. She maintained her serious mien until the interview was over. 直到访问结束她一直保持严肃的态度。 3. He left the room with a saddened mien. 他神情黯然地离开了房间。 4. The young girl in the picture has a thoughtful and solemn mien. 画中的年轻女孩带着一副沉思而又严肃的神态。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('prestige', '[pre\'stiːʒ]', 'n.[U]威望；声望 adj.有威信的；名贵的', '1. She enjoyed high prestige among the masses. 她在群众中享有很高威信。 2. He is an author of international prestige. 他是有国际声望的作家。 3. The old universities of Oxford and Cambridge still have a lot of prestige. 历史悠久的牛津大学和剑桥大学仍然享有很高的声望。 4. The company would do anything but risk their prestige at stake. 公司绝不愿将自己的信誉孤注一掷。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('undergird', '[ˌʌndə\'gɜːd]', 'vt.从底层加固；加强', '1. We took measures to undergird the ship. 我们采取措施将船的底部加固。 2. We took measures to undergird the ship. 我们采取措施将船的底部加固。 3. And when they had hoisted it up, they used supports to undergird the ship. 17既把小艇拉上来，就用缆绳捆绑船底； 4. Acts 27:17 And when they had hoisted it up, they used supports to undergird the ship. 徒二七17既把小艇拉上来，就用缆绳捆绑船底；', '过去式: undergirded/undergirt 过去分词: undergirded/undergirt 现在分词: undergirding 第三人称单数: undergirds');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('swagger', '[\'swæɡər]', 'v.大摇大摆地走；吹嘘 n.大摇大摆；吹牛', '1. He emerged with a macho swagger. 他大摇大摆地走了出来。 2. He emerged with a macho swagger. 他大摇大摆地走了出来。 3. Now she was going to make up for this, she wanted to swagger around the streets and markets enjoying herself with Xiangzi. 现在，她要捞回来这点缺欠，要大摇大摆的在街上，在庙会上，同着祥子去玩。', '副词: swaggeringly 名词: swaggerer 过去式: swaggered 过去分词: swaggered 现在分词: swaggering 第三人称单数: swaggers');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('blissful', '[\'blɪsfl]', 'adj.极快乐的；幸福的；有福的', '1. We have blissful memories of a summer vacation. 暑假里的快乐时光仍留在我们的记忆中。 2. We have a blissful life. 我们拥有幸福的生活。 3. I like a stronge plumply man,I feel they are honest,virtuous,adult,blissful. 我喜欢有点胖的男人,觉得他们淳朴,善良,成熟,稳重,有福气。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('longing', '[\'lɔːŋɪŋ]', 'n.渴望；憧憬 adj.渴望的', '1. I am longing to see my friend Jack again. 我渴望再见到我的朋友杰克。 2. An inexplicable longing consumes them. 一种无法言寓的渴望吸引着他们。 3. I have a great longing for a bright future. 我对未来充满了憧憬。 4. Let it go back into the gloaming , and gad with a lot of longing. 就让他回到暮色中，满怀憧憬地游荡吧。 5. The fire hot red lips longing for your almsgiving. 火辣的红唇渴望的等待你的施舍。', '副词: longingly');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('galvanize', '[\'ɡælvənaɪz]', 'v.镀锌；刺激；激励', '1. It is more usual to complete the weldment first and then to galvanize it. 常用的方法是先把钢板焊起来再镀锌。 2. The manager\'s arrival galvanized the workers into activity. 经理一来，工人闻风而动。 3. And unlike in the past, carry traders now have options, as central banks worldwide have hammered down rates in a concerted effort to galvanize the economy. 与以往不同，这类交易者现在有了多种选择，因为世界各国的央行为刺激经济都在下调利率。 4. How can we galvanize the students into taking the responsibility for their work? 我们怎样才能激励学生对他们的作业负起责任来呢？', '名词: galvanization 过去式: galvanized 过去分词: galvanized 现在分词: galvanizing 第三人称单数: galvanizes');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('withstand', '[wɪð\'stænd]', 'vt.对抗；经得起；承受', '1. He slew all who dared to withstand him. 他把敢于对抗他的人都斩尽杀绝。 2. Explorers have to withstand hardships. 探险者得忍受艰苦。 3. They could not withstand the fierceness of attack of those soldiers. 他们抵挡不住那些士兵猛烈的进攻。 4. This dress material will withstand repeated washing. 这种衣料经得住反复洗涤。', '名词: withstander 过去式: withstood 过去分词: withstood 现在分词: withstanding 第三人称单数: withstands');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('convenience', '[kən\'viːnjəns]', 'n.便利；舒适；适宜；便利设施；方便的时间', '1. It\'s a great convenience to live in town. 住在城市里有很大的方便。 2. I stock upon grocery at the convenience store. 我到便利商店买食品备用。 3. The hotel combines comfort with convenience. 这家旅馆既舒适又方便。 4. Analyzed experiment data, the best one is ultrasonic in the light of convenience, quick, especially avoid sample color disturbing and hydrargyrum pollution. 通过实验得出数据，进行分析，确定了超声法为最适宜样品前处理方法。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('detour', '[\'diːtʊr]', 'n.绕路；便道 v.绕路而行', '1. During the construction we had to take a detour. 施工期间，我们不得不绕路而行。 2. It actually saves time to take this detour. 走这条便道反而省时间。 3. The detour was a dirt road that led through banana fields, orange orchards and a graveyard. 这条便道是一条穿过几个香蕉田，橘子园和一块墓地的泥泞小路。 4. During the construction we had to take a detour. 施工期间，我们不得不绕路而行。', '过去式: detoured 过去分词: detoured 现在分词: detouring 第三人称单数: detours');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elocution', '[ˌelə\'kjuːʃn]', 'n.演说术；朗诵法', '1. Lawyers have to study elocution. 律师须研究演讲术。 2. With every advantage of lungs and elocution, the effect is singularly vapid. 然而扯着嗓子、抑扬顿挫地朗诵,其结果却是令听者兴味索然。', '形容词: elocutionary 名词: elocutionist');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('debate', '[dɪ\'beɪt]', 'n.辩论；讨论 vt.争论；思考 vi.辩论', '1. After a long debate, the house of commons approved the bill. 经过长时间的辩论，下议院通过了议案。 2. We had a long debate as to whether we should spend so much money on space technology. 至于我们要否花那么多钱在太空技术上,我们辩论了很久。 3. Her resignation caused much public debate. 她辞职一事引起群众议论纷纷。 4. There has been heated debate about whether the film should be allowed. 关于这场电影是否该通过,人们展开了热烈的讨论。 5. I don\'t wish to debate my opinions with you. 我不想就我的看法同你辩论。 6. This is a question that they have often debated. 这是个他们常讨论的问题。', '名词: debatement 过去式: debated 过去分词: debated 现在分词: debating 第三人称单数: debates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('liberty', '[\'lɪbərti]', 'n.自由；自由权；冒失', '1. Those prisoners are dreaming of liberty. 这些囚犯们梦想着获得自由。 2. Everybody is at liberty to air his views. 每个人都有发表意见的自由。 3. Women used to have little liberty. 过去妇女没有多少自由。 4. I am afraid that I am not at liberty to discuss this matter. 对不起，我无权讨论这个问题。', '名词复数: liberties');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('elementary', '[ˌelɪ\'mentri]', 'adj.基本的；初级的；元素的', '1. He is ignorant of even the most elementary facts. 他连最基本的事实都不知道。 2. They lack the most elementary sanitary facilities. 他们缺乏最基本的卫生设备。 3. This is the elementary rules of social conduct. 这是社会行为的基本原则。 4. This elementary school is affiliated to a university. 这所小学附属于一所大学。', '副词: elementarily 名词: elementariness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('resilience', '[rɪ\'zɪliəns]', 'n.适应力；弹性', '1. She has shown great resilience to stress. 她对压力表现出了极大的适应能力。 2. Further tests of the market\'s resilience will come later this week. 进一步的试验市场的适应能力将在本周晚些时候。 3. Rubber has more resilience than wood. 橡胶有比木头更大的弹性。 4. It also reflects the resilience of domestic demand. 调整过程也反映出国内需求的弹性。', 'none');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('doff', '[dɑːf]', 'vt.脱；丢弃；废除', '1. Doff your stupid habits and live. 抛弃你的坏习惯好好生活吧。 2. To doff(one\'s hat)as a token of respect or submission. 脱下脱下（某人的帽子）以表示敬意或顺从 3. EXAMPLE: On Monday mornings I sometimes feel a little doff. 我有时在周一的早上感觉脑子发木。 4. Fie, doff this habit, shame to your estate, An eye-sore to our solemn festival! 快把这身衣服换一换，它太不合您的身分，而且在这样郑重的婚礼中间，也会让人瞧着笑话的。', '过去式: doffed 过去分词: doffed 现在分词: doffing 第三人称单数: doffs');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('shuck', '[ʃʌk]', 'n.(植物的)壳；夹；无用之物 v.剥皮；脱掉；欺骗 int.呸！无聊！可恶', '1. Shuck these ears of corn and put them into the boiling water. 把玉米叶剥下來后将玉米放到沸水里。 2. Shuck your dirty shirt and put on a new one. 把你的脏衬衣脱了，换一件干净的。 3. You should not shuck a little child. 你不应该去欺骗一个小孩。', '名词: shucker 过去式: shucked 过去分词: shucked 现在分词: shucking 第三人称单数: shucks');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('unseemly', '[ʌn\'siːmli]', 'adj.不体面的；不相配的；不适宜的 adv.不适当地', '1. Everyone was shocked by his unseemly conduct. 大家都被他不得体的举动震惊了。 2. His social position allows him of no unseemly behaviour in public. 他的社会地位不容许他在公共场合有行为不妥之处。', '比较级: unseemlier 最高级: unseemliest 名词: unseemliness');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('initial', '[ɪ\'nɪʃl]', 'n.(词)首字母 adj.开始的；最初的；字首的 vt.签姓名的首字母于', '1. This is a letter paper personalized with his initials. 这是一张有他姓名首字母的信纸。 2. After the initial cheers,the noise of the crowd began to die away as the group started playing. 开始的欢呼声结束以后，乐队开始演奏，人们的喧闹声也随之逐渐消失。 3. We are through the initial testing period. 我们通过了最初的考试阶段 4. The word “hour” is pronounced without an initial aspirate. hour一词的首字母h不发送气音。 5. She initialed a handkerchief and gave it to that young man. 她在手帕上绣上姓名的首字母，把它送给了那个年轻人。', '副词: initially 名词: initialness 过去式: initialed/initialled 过去分词: initialed/initialled 现在分词: initialing/initialling 第三人称单数: initials/initials');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('liberate', '[\'lɪbəreɪt]', 'v.解放；使获得自由；释出；放出', '1. The country was liberated in 1966. 这个国家是在1966年解放的。 2. Our army had liberated many occupied areas. 我们的军队解放了许多地区。 3. This small software can liberate your fingers! 这个小软件可以解放你的手指啦！ 4. They can liberate us from the limitations of our thoughts and feelings. 他们可以使我们从思想与感受解放。', '副词: liberatingly 名词: liberator 过去式: liberated 过去分词: liberated 现在分词: liberating 第三人称单数: liberates');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('diplomatic', '[ˌdɪplə\'mætɪk]', 'adj.外交的；古字体的；老练的', '1. He has diplomatic immunity. 他有外交豁免权。 2. The exercise of patience is essential in diplomatic negotiations. 在外交谈判中，重要的是要有耐性。 3. He tried to be diplomatic when he refused their invitation. 他在拒绝他们的邀请时，尽可能地婉转些。 4. John was as diplomatic as Mary when talking to the press. 约翰在与媒体打交道时和玛丽一样老练。', '副词: diplomatically');
INSERT INTO `gre` VALUES ('submission', '[səb\'mɪʃn]', 'n.提交；服从；屈服；[律]意见', '1. They prepared a report for submission to the council. 他们准备了一份报告要提交给理事会。 2. Tomorrow is the last date for submission of entries for the competition. 明天是提交参赛表格的最后期限。 3. They bowed to the king with all due submission. 他们必恭必敬地向国王鞠躬。 4. They believe that submission in no way implies inferiority. 他们认为服从决不意味着低人一等。', 'none');
